/* Card data extracted from the China Modern History (1800-1947) Anki deck. */
window.CARD_DATA = [{"id":"cnh-001","num":"一","category":"China · History","question":"A group of mythological rulers and culture-heroes said to have reigned in remote antiquity before the first dynasties, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> — credited with inventing things like agriculture, writing and medicine — are recorded in the <i>Records of the Grand Historian</i> and stand at the dawn of Chinese mythology and history.","answer":"Three Sovereigns and Five Emperors","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">三皇五帝 ('three sovereigns and five emperors'), legendary culture-heroes</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"三皇五帝","pinyin":"Sānhuáng Wǔdì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Sānhuáng Wǔdì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Three Sovereigns and Five Emperors</b> is a collective designation for a series of mythological rulers and culture-heroes traditionally held to have governed the dawn of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_mythology\">Chinese mythology</span> and proto-history, occupying the long semi-legendary epoch that preceded the founding of China's first hereditary dynasty. The earlier triad of \"sovereigns\" most commonly comprised <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fuxi\">Fuxi</span>, the creator-goddess <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nüwa\">Nüwa</span></b>, and the divine farmer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shennong\">Shennong</span>, although competing catalogues substituted alternative beings such as the fire-bringer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Suiren\">Suiren</span> or an abstract trinity of the Heavenly, Earthly, and Human Sovereigns. The succeeding rank of \"emperors\" was canonised by the Han historian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Qian\">Sima Qian</span> as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_Emperor\">Yellow Emperor</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuanxu\">Zhuanxu</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Ku\">Emperor Ku</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Yao\">Yao</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Shun\">Shun</span>, a genealogy with which he opened the 130-chapter <i><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Records_of_the_Grand_Historian\">Records of the Grand Historian</span></i>. Completed around 94 BCE, that work pointedly commenced its narrative with the Yellow Emperor rather than the more fabulous sovereigns, whom Sima Qian considered too legendary to admit into sober history, and it went on to furnish the model for the entire series of dynastic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Twenty-Four_Histories\">Twenty-Four Histories</span>. Traditional chronologies preserved in texts like the <i><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bamboo_Annals\">Bamboo Annals</span></i> assign the Yellow <b>Emperor's reign to around 2697 BCE</b> and carry the combined age down to the legendary flood-tamer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yu_the_Great\">Yu the Great</span>, whose establishment of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xia_dynasty\">Xia dynasty</span> the state-backed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xia–Shang–Zhou_Chronology_Project\">Xia–Shang–Zhou Chronology Project</span> <b>dated to approximately 2070 BCE</b>. <br> <br> Each of these figures was remembered for bestowing a foundational gift upon nascent civilisation, Fuxi for devising the divinatory trigrams of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bagua\">bagua</span> and supplanting knotted cords with written symbols, Shennong for the plough and a herbal pharmacopoeia he assembled after reputedly tasting hundreds of plants, and Nüwa for fashioning the first human beings from yellow clay. The Yellow Emperor attracted an especially dense cluster of attributions, among them the creation of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_characters\">Chinese script</span> by his minister <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cangjie\">Cangjie</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sexagenary_cycle\">sexagenary calendar</span>, the compass-chariot, and the canonical medical dialogue of the <i><b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huangdi_Neijing\">Huangdi Neijing</span></b></i>, while his wife <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Leizu\">Leizu</span> was credited with discovering <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sericulture\">sericulture</span>. Under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span> the emperors were systematically integrated into the cosmology of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuxing_(Chinese_philosophy)\">Five Phases</span>, each being paired with one of the elements, a direction, a season, and a colour, an arrangement that assigned the Yellow Emperor to earth and the central position from which his very title derives. The sovereigns by contrast were admitted to the orthodox canon only belatedly, when the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang dynasty</span> scholar <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Zhen\">Sima Zhen</span></b> appended a supplementary \"Annals of the Three Sovereigns\" to the <i>Records</i> during the 8th century, harmonising scattered traditions found in earlier compendia like the <i><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huainanzi\">Huainanzi</span></i> and the mythographic <i><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Classic_of_Mountains_and_Seas\">Classic of Mountains and Seas</span></i>. Among modern scholars the whole succession is understood not as a literal royal chronicle but as a layered mythological and ideological construction, frequently <b>analysed through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Euhemerism\">euhemerism</span></b> and linked to the virtue-based <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Abdication\">abdications</span> later invoked to justify the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mandate_of_Heaven\">Mandate of Heaven</span>, even as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Neolithic\">Neolithic</span> archaeology keeps testing how much faint historical memory, if any, these venerable legends might enclose.","citation":"","answerText":"Three Sovereigns and Five Emperors"},{"id":"cnc-008","num":"八","category":"China · Culture","question":"A mythical bird sometimes called the Chinese phoenix and traditionally paired with the dragon to symbolise the imperial consort and marriage, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> represents virtue and grace in Chinese mythology.","answer":"Fenghuang","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">凤凰 (Fènghuáng): 凤 the male and 凰 the female phoenix</span></div>","traditional":"鳳凰","hanzi":"凤凰","pinyin":"Fènghuáng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Fènghuáng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>fenghuang</b> is a mythical bird of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_mythology\">Chinese mythology</span></b>, frequently rendered in English as the Chinese phoenix and revered as the sovereign of all <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bird\">birds</span>. The name originally denoted a pair, the male <i>feng</i> and the female <i>huang</i>, which were later fused into a single, largely feminine creature emblematic of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yin_and_yang\">yin</span> when set opposite the masculine <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_dragon\">dragon</span></b>. Classical descriptions, among them those in the ancient dictionary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Erya\"><i>Erya</i></span>, portray it as a composite of many animals, blending the head of a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Golden_pheasant\">golden pheasant</span>, the tail of a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peafowl\">peacock</span></b>, and the legs of a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Red-crowned_crane\">crane</span>, its plumage radiant in five symbolic colours. Those colours were said to embody the cardinal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> virtues, so that the bird came to stand for virtue, grace, and harmony, quite unlike the Western <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Phoenix_(mythology)\">phoenix</span></b> with which it is loosely identified, for the fenghuang is no creature reborn from its own ashes. It ranks among the auspicious numinous animals of tradition alongside the dragon, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qilin\">qilin</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Black_Tortoise\">tortoise</span>, and is sometimes conflated with the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vermilion_Bird\">Vermilion Bird</span></b>, one of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Symbols\">Four Symbols</span> that guard the four quarters of the heavens. <br> <br> Paired with the dragon, the fenghuang became the supreme emblem of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_of_China\">emperor</span> and his <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empress\">empress</span></b>, and the dragon-and-phoenix motif grew into the most familiar symbol of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marriage\">marital</span> union and conjugal harmony in Chinese culture. As the empress's special device the bird adorned imperial regalia, most notably the elaborate <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fengguan\">phoenix crown</span></b> worn by empresses and, by long custom, by brides on their <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_marriage\">wedding</span> day. Its appearance was reckoned a rare and joyful omen, manifesting only in ages of peace and good government and thus serving as a celestial endorsement of a virtuous ruler holding the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mandate_of_Heaven\">Mandate of Heaven</span>. The creature is among the oldest in Chinese lore, with bird motifs appearing as early as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Neolithic\">Neolithic</span> and later flourishing on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shang_dynasty\">Shang</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_dynasty\">Zhou</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_ritual_bronzes\">ritual bronzes</span>, while it is celebrated in early texts such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Classic_of_Poetry\"><i>Classic of Poetry</i></span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Book_of_Rites\"><i>Book of Rites</i></span>, and the fantastical <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Classic_of_Mountains_and_Seas\"><i>Classic of Mountains and Seas</i></span>. From China the image spread across the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"East_Asian_cultural_sphere\">East Asian cultural sphere</span>, becoming the Korean <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bonghwang\">bonghwang</span> and the Japanese hō-ō, and it endures as a ubiquitous motif in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_art\">Chinese art</span>, architecture, and place names across <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Fenghuang"},{"id":"cnc-074","num":"七十四","category":"China · Culture","question":"Presiding over a celestial bureaucracy that mirrors the earthly imperial court, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is honoured at the New Year and figures in many popular legends.","answer":"Jade Emperor","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">玉皇大帝 (Yùhuáng Dàdì, 'Jade August Emperor')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"玉皇大帝","pinyin":"Yùhuáng Dàdì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Yùhuáng Dàdì</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Jade August Emperor”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Jade Emperor</b> is the supreme sovereign of Heaven in <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_folk_religion\">Chinese folk religion</span></b> and one of the most revered deities of religious <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Taoism</span>. From his throne he is held to preside over a vast <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tian\">celestial</span> bureaucracy that mirrors the earthly imperial court, governing gods, mortals, and the spirits of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Diyu\">underworld</span> alike through graded ranks of divine officials. In formal Taoist theology he stands just below the primordial <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Pure_Ones\">Three Pure Ones</span></b>, yet in popular devotion he effectively absorbed the role of the archaic sky god <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shangdi\">Shangdi</span>, also known as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Haotian_Shangdi\">Haotian Shangdi</span>. His sprawling court embraces the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dragon_King\">Dragon Kings</span> who command the rains and seas, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tudigong\">earth gods</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"City_God_(China)\">city gods</span>, and the household <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kitchen_God\">kitchen god</span></b> who reports on human conduct, together with divine servants such as the warrior <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Erlang_Shen\">Erlang Shen</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight_Immortals\">Eight Immortals</span>. Often paired with the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Queen_Mother_of_the_West\">Queen Mother of the West</span></b>, he is depicted in temples as an enthroned monarch in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_dragon\">dragon</span>-embroidered robes and a bead-fringed imperial crown, clasping a ceremonial tablet in the manner of a human <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_of_China\">emperor</span>. <br> <br> Although divine sky-rulers are ancient, the Jade Emperor emerged as a distinct supreme deity only in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song</span> periods, his cult raised to the summit of the pantheon when the Song emperors <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Zhenzong\">Zhenzong</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Huizong\">Huizong</span></b> conferred upon him grand official titles. He is honoured especially at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_New_Year\">New Year</span>, his birthday falling on the 9th day of the first month of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_calendar\">lunar calendar</span>, shortly after the kitchen god ascends to report each family's deeds before his throne. He figures prominently in popular legend, most famously in the novel <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Journey_to_the_West\"><i>Journey to the West</i></span>, where the unruly <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Wukong\">Monkey King</span></b> throws his celestial court into chaos and is subdued only through the intervention of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gautama_Buddha\">Buddha</span>. Other tales cast him as the stern grandfather of the heavenly <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Weaver_Girl_and_the_Cowherd\">Weaver Girl</span>, whose enforced separation from her mortal husband is mourned and celebrated each year at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qixi_Festival\">Qixi Festival</span></b>. Among <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hokkien\">Hokkien</span> communities, particularly in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span>, he is reverently addressed as the Heavenly Grandfather, and across <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> and its diaspora he endures as one of the central figures of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_mythology\">Chinese mythology</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Jade Emperor"},{"id":"cnc-003","num":"三","category":"China · Culture","question":"Prized above gold for thousands of years and carved into ritual discs, burial suits and ornaments, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> symbolised purity, virtue and immortality, treasured from the Neolithic Liangzhu culture through every imperial dynasty.","answer":"jade","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">English 'jade' from Spanish 'piedra de ijada' ('stone of the flank')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"玉","pinyin":"yù","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">yù</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Jade</b> is the hard, lustrous stone that Chinese civilization prized above gold for thousands of years as a symbol of purity, virtue, and immortality, the term covering chiefly <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nephrite\">nephrite</span></b>, since gem <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jadeite\">jadeite</span> entered China only in the 18th century. The classic supply came from the rivers of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hotan\">Hotan</span>, where boulders of \"mutton-fat\" white stone washed down the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yurungkash_River\">White Jade River</span> from the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kunlun_Mountains\">Kunlun Mountains</span></b>, traveling east along routes older than the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk_Road\">Silk Road</span>. <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Neolithic\">Neolithic</span> peoples already treated it as numinous, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hongshan_culture\">Hongshan culture</span> coiling it into dragons and <b>the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liangzhu_culture\">Liangzhu culture</span> of about 3300–2300 BCE</b> burying elites under hundreds of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bi_(jade)\">bi</span> discs and square-tubed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cong_(vessel)\">cong</span>, emblems of heaven and earth. Under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shang_dynasty\">Shang dynasty</span> the consort <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fu_Hao\">Fu Hao</span> was <b>interred around 1200 BCE</b> with 755 jade objects, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_dynasty\">Zhou</span> codified 6 ritual jades for worshipping the quarters of the cosmos in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rites_of_Zhou\"><i>Rites of Zhou</i></span>. Moralists completed the stone's apotheosis, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Book_of_Rites\"><i>Book of Rites</i></span> recording <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucius\">Confucius</span> comparing its qualities to the 11 virtues of the gentleman, who should never be without it. <br> <br> Belief that the stone halted decay culminated in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jade_burial_suit\">jade burial suits</span>, and the suit of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Sheng,_Prince_of_Zhongshan\">Liu Sheng</span>, <b>excavated in 1968</b>, stitched 2,498 plaques with about 1.1 kilograms (2.4 lb) of gold wire. Politically no jade outranked the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"He_Shi_Bi\">He Shi Bi</span>, the disc once valued at 15 cities, which <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_Shi_Huang\">Qin Shi Huang</span> reputedly had carved into the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heirloom_Seal_of_the_Realm\">Heirloom Seal of the Realm</span></b>, the talisman of legitimate rule for a millennium. Because nephrite reaches 6 to 6.5 on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mohs_scale\">Mohs scale</span>, it cannot be cut like ordinary stone but must be ground with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Quartz\">quartz</span> sand, a slow abrasion that made every vessel a monument of labor, none grander than the boulder of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yu_the_Great\">Yu the Great</span> taming the flood, over 5 tonnes (5.5 tons) of Hotan stone finished for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qianlong_Emperor\">Qianlong Emperor</span> in 1787 under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span>. That same reign opened the age of emerald-green \"feicui\" jadeite, mined at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hpakant\">Hpakant</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Myanmar\">Myanmar</span> and carried in through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yunnan\">Yunnan</span>, which conquered the court and still commands records, a 27-bead necklace once owned by <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Barbara_Hutton\">Barbara Hutton</span></b> fetching 27.4 million US dollars at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sotheby's\">Sotheby's</span> in 2014. The reverence endures in the People's Republic, which inlaid the medals of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2008_Summer_Olympics\">2008 Summer Olympics</span> with rings of the stone, wedding 5,000 years of the \"stone of heaven\" to the modern nation's self-image.","citation":"","answerText":"jade"},{"id":"cnc-004","num":"四","category":"China · Culture","question":"A benevolent, serpentine creature associated with water, rain and imperial power rather than menace, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> adorned the robes of the emperor, lends its name to one of the signs of the zodiac, and is paraded in festival dances.","answer":"Chinese dragon","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">龙 (lóng), the Chinese dragon, a benevolent water deity</span></div>","traditional":"龍","hanzi":"龙","pinyin":"lóng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">lóng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Chinese dragon</b> is a benevolent, serpentine creature of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_mythology\">Chinese mythology</span> associated with water, rain, and imperial authority, a sharp contrast to the treasure-hoarding menace of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"European_dragon\">European dragon</span></b>. Its pedigree is <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Neolithic\">Neolithic</span>, attested by a shell-mosaic dragon laid beside a burial at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Puyang\">Puyang</span> around 4400 BCE and by the coiled <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jade\">jade</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pig_dragon\">pig-dragons</span> of <b>the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hongshan_culture\">Hongshan culture</span> of roughly 4700–2900 BCE</b>, while the character for <i>long</i> already appears on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Oracle_bone\">oracle bones</span> over 3,000 years old. A <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han</span>-era formula describes it as a composite of 9 likenesses—antlers of a deer, head of a camel, eyes of a demon, neck of a snake, belly of a clam, scales of a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Carp\">carp</span>, claws of an eagle, paws of a tiger, and ears of an ox—able to shrink to a silkworm or swell to fill heaven and earth. As master of the waters it sends rain, dwells in rivers and wells, and rules the seas through the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dragon_King\">Dragon Kings</span></b> of the 4 directions, with the winged <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yinglong\">Yinglong</span> credited with aiding the floods' taming. Cosmologically the dragon is pure <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yin_and_yang\">yang</span>, governing the east and spring as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Azure_Dragon\">Azure Dragon</span></b>, 1 of the 4 great constellation-<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Symbols\">symbols</span> of the Chinese sky. <br> <br> Imperial ideology made the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_of_China\">emperor</span> the \"true dragon\" and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Son_of_Heaven\">Son of Heaven</span>, so that under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> the 5-clawed dragon was reserved for the sovereign's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dragon_robe\">dragon robes</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dragon_Throne\">Dragon Throne</span>, lesser nobles wearing 4-clawed beasts, while screens such <b>as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nine-Dragon_Wall\">Nine-Dragon Wall</span> of 1756</b> and the carved terraces of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Forbidden_City\">Forbidden City</span> multiplied the motif by the hundred. The dragon is the 5th and only mythical animal among the 12 signs of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_zodiac\">Chinese zodiac</span>, and its prestige is measurable in demography, Singapore's births leaping roughly 25 percent in <b>the Dragon year of 1988</b>, with comparable booms recurring across Chinese societies in 2000, 2012, and 2024. At festivals the creature literally comes alive in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dragon_dance\">dragon dance</span>, in which teams animate a sinuous body, often of 9 sections, beneath lanterns at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_New_Year\">Chinese New Year</span>, while paddlers race dragon-headed craft at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dragon_Boat_Festival\">Dragon Boat Festival</span> in memory of the poet <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qu_Yuan\">Qu Yuan</span>. The image traveled with Chinese civilization, fathering the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japanese_dragon\">Japanese</span> and Vietnamese dragons and returning home as an ethnic emblem, canonized by the 1978 anthem <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Descendants_of_the_Dragon\">\"Descendants of the Dragon.\"</span></b> Sensitive to the beast's fearsome reputation abroad, Beijing passed over it for the 2008 Olympic mascots, and state media in the Dragon year 2024 even campaigned to rebrand it in English as the \"loong,\" guarding the benevolence of a symbol now 6 millennia old.","citation":"","answerText":"Chinese dragon"},{"id":"cnc-005","num":"五","category":"China · Culture","question":"Produced by unwinding the cocoons of mulberry silkworms in a process kept secret for centuries, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was so prized abroad that the overland trade routes carrying it westward came to be called the Silk Road, a foundation of early Chinese commerce.","answer":"silk","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">English 'silk', via Greek sērikón, from the Seres (the Chinese)</span></div>","traditional":"絲","hanzi":"丝","pinyin":"sī","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">sī</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Silk</b> is the lustrous protein fiber unwound from cocoons of the domesticated mulberry silkworm <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bombyx_mori\">Bombyx mori</span></b>, a luxurious fabric whose manufacture China kept secret for centuries and whose westward trade named the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk_Road\">Silk Road</span>. Legend credits the discovery to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Leizu\">Leizu</span>, wife of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_Emperor\">Yellow Emperor</span>, when a cocoon unraveled in <b>her hot tea around 2700 BCE</b>, while archaeology pushes the craft at least that far back through woven fragments of the 3rd millennium BCE and a 2016 study reporting silk proteins in 8,500-year-old tombs at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiahu\">Jiahu</span>. <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sericulture\">Sericulture</span> demands feeding the <b>worms exclusively on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Morus_(plant)\">mulberry</span></b> leaves and steaming the cocoons before the moth can break the thread, since each holds a single continuous filament up to 900 meters (3,000 ft) long. By the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shang_dynasty\">Shang dynasty</span> silk clothed ritual and rank, and it later served as a writing surface, as in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mawangdui_Silk_Texts\">Mawangdui silk texts</span>, and even as money, with taxes and salaries reckoned in bolts. Exports under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span> reached the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Roman_Empire\">Roman Empire</span>, where moralists denounced the transparent stuff and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pliny_the_Elder\">Pliny the Elder</span></b> groaned that the Eastern luxury trade drained 100 million sesterces a year. <br> <br> The monopoly leaked along the road itself, first, legend says, through a Chinese princess who smuggled eggs in her headdress to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hotan\">Hotan</span>, and decisively in 552, when monks reportedly carried silkworm eggs in hollow canes to <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Justinian_I\">Justinian I</span></b>, founding <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Byzantine_silk\">Byzantine silk</span>. China nonetheless kept the summit of the art through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song</span>, weaving figured brocades on the great <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Drawloom\">drawloom</span> in centers such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Suzhou\">Suzhou</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hangzhou\">Hangzhou</span>, and the fabric even bought peace, <b>the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chanyuan_Treaty\">Chanyuan Treaty</span> of 1005</b> obliging the Song to send the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liao_dynasty\">Liao</span> 200,000 bolts a year. Sericulture then naturalized in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Italy\">Italy</span> and at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lyon\">Lyon</span> in France, where in 1804 the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jacquard_machine\">Jacquard machine</span> automated figured weaving with punched cards that helped inspire computing. The 20th century brought rivals, above all <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nylon\">nylon</span> stockings <b>from 1938</b>, yet silk kept its prestige, and today China again reels well over half the world's raw silk, far ahead of 2nd-place <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"India\">India</span>, while Beijing trades on the old glamour by branding its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Belt_and_Road_Initiative\">Belt and Road Initiative</span> a new Silk Road. Science has opened a further career, spinning the protein <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fibroin\">fibroin</span> into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Surgical_suture\">sutures</span> and tissue scaffolds, so that the thread of emperors now stitches wounds as once it stitched empires to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">Chinese commerce</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"silk"},{"id":"cng-021","num":"二十一","category":"China · Geography","question":"A vast, deeply eroded upland of yellowish wind-blown soil around the middle Yellow River, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is a cradle of early Chinese farming but suffers severe gully erosion.","answer":"Loess Plateau","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">黄土高原 ('yellow-earth plateau')</span></div>","traditional":"黃土高原","hanzi":"黄土高原","pinyin":"Huángtǔ Gāoyuán","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Huángtǔ Gāoyuán</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“yellow-earth plateau”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Loess Plateau</b> is a highland of roughly 640,000 square kilometers (250,000 sq mi) around the middle reaches of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_River\">Yellow River</span></b>, sprawling across <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shaanxi\">Shaanxi</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanxi\">Shanxi</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gansu\">Gansu</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ningxia\">Ningxia</span> as the largest <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Loess\">loess</span> deposit on earth. Its mantle of yellowish silt, on average 50–100 meters (160–330 ft) thick and exceeding 300 meters (980 ft) near <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lanzhou\">Lanzhou</span>, accumulated through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Aeolian_processes\">aeolian</span> deposition as winter <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"East_Asian_Monsoon\">monsoon</span> winds carried dust from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gobi_Desert\">Gobi</span> and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mu_Us_Desert\">Mu Us Desert</span></b> over the past 2.6 million years of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Quaternary\">Quaternary</span>, leaving one of the world's finest archives of ancient climate. Because the unconsolidated soil dissolves under torrential summer rains, the plateau became one of the most erodible landscapes known, historically delivering about 1.6 billion tonnes (<b>1800 million</b> tons) of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sediment\">sediment</span> a year, roughly 90 percent of the river's load, with losses in the worst districts surpassing 10,000 tonnes (11,000 tons) per square kilometer annually. The surface is consequently dissected by hundreds of thousands of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gully\">gullies</span> and ravines, the silt-choked river thunders ochre through <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hukou_Waterfall\">Hukou Waterfall</span></b>, and downstream deposition raised the channel bed to cause the floods that earned the river the name \"China's Sorrow.\" Since the 1950s terracing and tens of thousands of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Check_dam\">check dams</span>, capped by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Grain_for_Green\">Grain for Green</span> program <b>launched in 1999</b>, have roughly doubled vegetation cover to above 60 percent and cut the sediment flux by more than 4 fifths. <br> <br> Despite its fragility, the plateau ranks among the cradles of Chinese agriculture, where <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Neolithic\">Neolithic</span> communities domesticated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foxtail_millet\">foxtail</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Proso_millet\">proso millet</span> by around 6000 BCE</b> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangshao_culture\">Yangshao culture</span> left painted-pottery villages such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Banpo\">Banpo</span> near modern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi'an\">Xi'an</span>. Along its southern margin the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wei_River\">Wei River</span> valley of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guanzhong\">Guanzhong</span> nourished the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_dynasty\">Zhou dynasty</span> from the 11th century BCE and then the state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_(state)\">Qin</span>, which unified China in 221 BCE on the strength of the easily tilled yellow earth. Generations of inhabitants carved <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yaodong\">yaodong</span> cave dwellings into the loess cliffs, sheltering as many as 40 million people in the 20th century, though the same geology magnified the 1556 <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1556_Shaanxi_earthquake\">Shaanxi earthquake</span></b>, whose collapsing caves contributed to a toll of about 830,000, the deadliest earthquake ever recorded. The plateau's northern fringe long marked the contested boundary between farmers and steppe herders, fortified by successive lines of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Wall_of_China\">Great Wall</span>. In modern times its gullied hills around <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yan'an\">Yan'an</span> sheltered the communist leadership after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Long_March\">Long March</span> ended there in 1935, and the cave-dwelling years of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> fixed the yellow plateau in revolutionary iconography even as it has since become a global showcase for ecological restoration.","citation":"","answerText":"Loess Plateau"},{"id":"cng-022","num":"二十二","category":"China · Geography","question":"A fine, fertile, yellowish sediment deposited by the wind over thousands of years, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> blankets a huge plateau of northern China, tints the Yellow River, and erodes easily into steep gullies.","answer":"Loess","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">黄土 (huángtǔ, 'yellow earth')</span></div>","traditional":"黃土","hanzi":"黄土","pinyin":"huángtǔ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">huángtǔ</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“yellow earth”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Loess</b> is a clastic, predominantly <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silt\">silt</span></b>-sized sediment formed by the accumulation of wind-blown dust, typically with grains of 20 to 50 micrometres bound loosely by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Calcium_carbonate\">calcium carbonate</span> into a homogeneous, unstratified blanket. Its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Porosity\">porosity</span> near 50 percent and tendency toward vertical jointing allow it to stand in sheer cliffs, yet the same open fabric collapses when saturated, making loess country prone to subsidence and destructive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Landslide\">landslides</span>. Deposits of this <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Aeolian_processes\">aeolian</span> material cover roughly a tenth of Earth’s land surface, from glacially ground sheets along the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rhine\">Rhine</span></b>, the lower <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mississippi_River\">Mississippi</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Palouse\">Palouse</span> to the desert-derived mantles of northern China, and they weather into famously fertile soils such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chernozem\">chernozem</span> belt of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ukraine\">Ukraine</span>. The term entered geology in the 1820s through <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Karl_Cäsar_von_Leonhard\">Karl Cäsar von Leonhard</span></b>’s work on Rhine valley exposures, while <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ferdinand_von_Richthofen\">Ferdinand von Richthofen</span>, travelling China in the 1870s, established the now accepted wind-blown origin. Because dusty glacial intervals alternate with soil-forming warm phases, stacked loess and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paleosol\">paleosol</span></b> layers constitute one of the finest land archives of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Quaternary\">Quaternary</span> climate and of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"East_Asian_monsoon\">East Asian monsoon</span>, a field pioneered by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Tungsheng\">Liu Tungsheng</span>, who received the <b>2002 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tyler_Prize_for_Environmental_Achievement\">Tyler Prize</span></b> for the work. <br> <br> Nowhere is the deposit grander than on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Loess_Plateau\">Loess Plateau</span> of some 640,000 square kilometres (250,000 sq mi) along the middle <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_River\">Yellow River</span>, where thicknesses of 50 to 100 metres (160 to 330 ft) are routine and exceed 300 metres (980 ft) near <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lanzhou\">Lanzhou</span>, the deepest dust pile on the planet. Winter winds have swept this material from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gobi_Desert\">Gobi</span> and the margins of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taklamakan_Desert\">Taklamakan</span> for about 2.6 million years, atop older red clays that carry the dust record back toward the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Miocene\">Miocene</span>. The soft, self-fertilizing ground nurtured <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Millet\">millet</span> farming as early as the 7th millennium BCE at sites of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cishan_culture\">Cishan</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dadiwan_culture\">Dadiwan</span> cultures, later villages of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangshao_culture\">Yangshao culture</span> such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Banpo\">Banpo</span>, and a tradition of carved <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yaodong\">yaodong</span> cave dwellings that has sheltered tens of millions of people. Yet the same softness makes the plateau among the most erodible landscapes on Earth, dissected by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gully\">gullies</span> losing upward of 10,000 tonnes (11,000 tons) per square kilometre annually, feeding the Yellow River a historical load near 1.6 billion tonnes (<b>1800 million</b> tons) of silt a year, and amplifying the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1556_Shaanxi_earthquake\">1556 Shaanxi earthquake</span>, whose collapse of cave homes killed perhaps 830,000 people in the deadliest quake on record. Since 1999 the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Grain_for_Green_Program\">Grain for Green Program</span>, together with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Terrace_(earthworks)\">terracing</span> and tens <b>of thousands of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Check_dam\">check dams</span></b>, has roughly doubled vegetation cover and cut the river’s sediment load by the better part of 90 percent.","citation":"","answerText":"Loess"},{"id":"cng-023","num":"二十三","category":"China · Geography","question":"The 2nd-longest river in the country and traditionally seen as the cradle of Chinese civilisation, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> earned the grim nickname \"China's Sorrow\" for its floods before emptying into the Bohai Sea across the North China Plain.","answer":"Yellow River","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">黄河 (Huáng Hé, 'yellow river'), for its loess silt</span></div>","traditional":"黃河","hanzi":"黄河","pinyin":"Huáng Hé","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Huáng Hé</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Yellow River</b> is the 2nd-longest river in China at about 5,464 kilometers (3,395 mi), rising in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bayan_Har_Mountains\">Bayan Har Mountains</span></b> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qinghai\">Qinghai</span> on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_Plateau\">Tibetan Plateau</span> and crossing 9 provinces before reaching the sea. From the first major city on its banks at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lanzhou\">Lanzhou</span> it sweeps north around the great <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ordos_Loop\">Ordos Loop</span></b>, then saws south through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Loess_Plateau\">Loess Plateau</span>, plunging over <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hukou_Waterfall\">Hukou Waterfall</span> and receiving the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wei_River\">Wei River</span> before turning east toward the lowlands. Scouring the friable <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Loess\">loess</span>, it became the most <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sediment\">sediment</span>-laden major river on earth, historically carrying some 1.6 billion tonnes (<b>1800 million</b> tons) of silt a year at average concentrations near 35 kilograms (77 lb) per cubic meter, the ochre burden that gives the river its name. Across the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"North_China_Plain\">North China Plain</span> this silt settled between man-made dikes until the channel became a \"hanging river\" perched as much as 10 meters (33 ft) above the surrounding fields near <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kaifeng\">Kaifeng</span>, primed for catastrophic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Avulsion_(river)\">avulsions</span> that repeatedly flung the mouth between the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bohai_Sea\">Bohai Sea</span> and the Yellow Sea, most recently in <b>the great shift of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1855_Yellow_River_flood\">1855</span></b> that fixed the present delta in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shandong\">Shandong</span>. More than 1,500 recorded floods earned it the epithet \"China's Sorrow,\" with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1887_Yellow_River_flood\">1887 flood</span> killing on the order of 900,000 people and the deliberate dike breach <b>ordered by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1938_Yellow_River_flood\">1938</b></span>, during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Sino-Japanese_War\">Second Sino-Japanese War</span>, drowning several hundred thousand more. <br> <br> The river's middle valley is traditionally regarded as the cradle of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_civilization\">Chinese civilisation</span>, nurturing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangshao_culture\">Yangshao</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Longshan_culture\">Longshan</span> cultures, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Erlitou_culture\">Erlitou</span> sites often linked to the legendary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xia_dynasty\">Xia dynasty</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shang_dynasty\">Shang</span> capital near <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anyang\">Anyang</span>. The myth of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yu_the_Great\">Yu the Great</span>, who tamed the floods by dredging channels around the 21st century BCE, made river control the very foundation of political legitimacy, and imperial capitals such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luoyang\">Luoyang</span> rose nearby, linked southward after the early 7th century by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Grand_Canal_(China)\">Grand Canal</span>. For over 2,000 years dynasties staked their mandate on the dikes, and breakdowns of control, like the disastrous floods of the 1340s and 1850s, fed the rebellions that helped topple ruling houses. The People's Republic answered with engineering, from the silt-plagued <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sanmenxia_Dam\">Sanmenxia Dam</span></b> of 1960 to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiaolangdi_Dam\">Xiaolangdi Dam</span> completed around 2001, whose annual flushing operations now manage the silt, while overuse once left the lower river dry for 226 days in 1997 before unified regulation restored continuous flow after 1999. Today the basin supplies water to roughly 12 percent of China's population and a comparable share of its farmland from only a small fraction of national runoff, a strain the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South–North_Water_Transfer_Project\">South–North Water Transfer Project</span></b> and a 2023 protection law seek to ease for the waterway still honored as the Mother River.","citation":"","answerText":"Yellow River"},{"id":"cng-033","num":"三十三","category":"China · Geography","question":"The longest river in Asia and the 3rd-longest in the world, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> rises on the Tibetan Plateau and crosses the country to reach the sea at Shanghai, draining the most populous river basin in China.","answer":"Yangtze","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">长江 (Cháng Jiāng, 'long river'); 'Yangtze' from the Yangzi ferry reach</span></div>","traditional":"長江","hanzi":"长江","pinyin":"Cháng Jiāng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Cháng Jiāng</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Long River”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Yangtze</b> is the longest river in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Asia\">Asia</span> and the 3rd-longest in the world after the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nile\">Nile</span></b> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Amazon_River\">Amazon</span>, flowing about 6,300 kilometers (3,900 mi) entirely within one country from glacier-fed headstreams in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tanggula_Mountains\">Tanggula Mountains</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qinghai\">Qinghai</span> on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_Plateau\">Tibetan Plateau</span>. Its upper course, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jinsha_River\">Jinsha</span>, plunges through the canyons of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yunnan\">Yunnan</span>, including <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tiger_Leaping_Gorge\">Tiger Leaping Gorge</span></b> within the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Parallel_Rivers\">Three Parallel Rivers</span> World Heritage area, before hooking north and east to skirt the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan_Basin\">Sichuan Basin</span> past <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chongqing\">Chongqing</span>. Bursting through the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Gorges\">Three Gorges</span></b>, it winds across the central lake country, exchanging floodwaters with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dongting_Lake\">Dongting</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Poyang_Lake\">Poyang</span>, China's 2 largest freshwater lakes, passing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuhan\">Wuhan</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span> before reaching the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"East_China_Sea\">East China Sea</span> through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze_Delta\">delta</span> at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span>. Discharging roughly 30,000 cubic meters per second, it drains a basin of 1.8 million square kilometers (690,000 sq mi) that houses over 400 million people, about a 3rd of the national population, generates more than 40 percent of GDP, and carries upward of 3 billion tonnes (3300 million tons) of cargo a year as the busiest inland waterway on earth. That bounty has come with peril, for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1931_China_floods\"><b>1931 floods</span> rank</b> among the deadliest natural disasters ever recorded, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1954_Yangtze_River_floods\">1954 floods</span> killed some 30,000 people, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1998_China_floods\">1998 deluge</span> displaced millions. <br> <br> Flood control and power justified the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Gorges_Dam\">Three Gorges Dam</span>, completed in stages <b>between 2003</b> and 2012 as the world's largest power station at 22,500 megawatts, backing up a 600-kilometer (370 mi) reservoir that required relocating about 1.3 million people, while upstream the Jinsha cascade added giants such as the 16,000-megawatt <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Baihetan_Dam\">Baihetan Dam</span>. The engineered river paid an ecological price, as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Baiji\">baiji</span> dolphin was <b>declared functionally extinct in 2007</b> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_paddlefish\">Chinese paddlefish</span> extinct by 2022, leaving the critically endangered <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_sturgeon\">Chinese sturgeon</span> and roughly 1,200 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze_finless_porpoise\">Yangtze finless porpoises</span> to benefit from a 10-year fishing ban imposed in 2021. Long before, the valley cradled civilization in its own right, domesticating <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rice\">rice</span> by the 7th millennium BCE at sites of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hemudu_culture\">Hemudu culture</span></b> and raising the moated jade metropolis of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liangzhu_culture\">Liangzhu</span> around 3300–2300 BCE. Its waters decided empires at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Red_Cliffs\">Battle of Red Cliffs</span> in 208 CE, fed the capitals via the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Grand_Canal_(China)\">Grand Canal</span>, and after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Nanking\">Treaty of Nanking</span> in 1842 carried foreign gunboats deep into the interior. The communist crossing of 1949 sealed the civil war on its banks, and since the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuhan_Yangtze_River_Bridge\">Wuhan Yangtze River Bridge</span> first spanned the stream in 1957 more than 100 crossings have stitched together the \"golden waterway\" that remains the central artery of Chinese life.","citation":"","answerText":"Yangtze"},{"id":"cnh-002","num":"二","category":"China · History","question":"Honoured as a legendary sovereign and the mythical ancestor of the Han Chinese, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is traditionally said to have defeated rival tribes, founded civilisation and even fathered Chinese medicine, and is counted among the earliest rulers.","answer":"Yellow Emperor","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Reigned</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. 2697–2597 BCE</span></div>","traditional":"黃帝","hanzi":"黄帝","pinyin":"Huángdì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Huángdì</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Yellow Thearch”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Yellow Emperor</b> was a legendary sovereign and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Culture_hero\">culture hero</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_mythology\">Chinese mythology</span> who is</b> revered as a founding ancestor of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Chinese\">Han Chinese</span> and counted among the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Sovereigns_and_Five_Emperors\">Three Sovereigns and Five Emperors</span> placed at the dawn of recorded history. His epithet derives from the colour yellow, which in the system of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuxing_(Chinese_philosophy)\">Five Phases</span> corresponds to the element earth and to the loess soils of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_River\">Yellow River</span> heartland, where the early Chinese state is traditionally said to have coalesced on the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Plain_(China)\">Central Plain</span></b>. According to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Qian\">Sima Qian</span>, whose <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Records_of_the_Grand_Historian\"><i>Records of the Grand Historian</i></span> opens its narrative of antiquity with him, he rose to power by defeating the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yan_Emperor\">Yan Emperor</span> at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Banquan\">Battle of Banquan</span></b> and then crushing the monstrous warlord <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiyou\">Chiyou</span> at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Zhuolu\">Battle of Zhuolu</span>, conflicts later mythologized as the formative struggles of the Chinese people. Tradition credits his roughly 100-year reign with an extraordinary outpouring of inventions and institutions, including the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_characters\">Chinese writing system</span> devised by his minister <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cangjie\">Cangjie</span>, the cultivation of silkworms and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sericulture\">sericulture</span> attributed to his consort <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Leizu\">Leizu</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sexagenary_cycle\">sexagenary calendar</span> used to reckon years and days. He is likewise honoured as a father of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Traditional_Chinese_medicine\">traditional Chinese medicine</span> through the foundational dialogues of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huangdi_Neijing\"><i>Huangdi Neijing</i></span>, and is said to have introduced boats, carts, music, and the direction-finding <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South-pointing_chariot\">south-pointing chariot</span></b> deployed in his campaigns. <br> <br> Modern scholarship regards the figure as largely a product of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warring_States_period\">Warring States period</span>, when competing thinkers retrojected an idealized founder onto the distant past, and many historians read the surviving accounts through the lens of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Euhemerism\">euhemerism</span>, by which an originally divine being was reinterpreted as a human ruler. By the early <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span> his name had become attached to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huang–Lao\">Huang–Lao</span> current of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Daoism</span>, which paired him with the sage <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Laozi\">Laozi</span> and promoted doctrines of cosmic harmony and minimal governance that guided court policy for several decades. Later genealogists made him the progenitor of the subsequent sage-kings <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuanxu\">Zhuanxu</span>, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Ku\">Emperor Ku</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Yao\">Yao</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Shun\">Shun</span>, while the ruling houses of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_dynasty\">Zhou</span> and later dynasties traced their descent back to him, embedding him at the root of a sprawling mythical genealogy. A sacrificial cult developed around a grand <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mausoleum_of_the_Yellow_Emperor\">mausoleum</span></b> on Mount Qiao in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shaanxi\">Shaanxi</span>, where state ceremonies honouring the ancestor have been performed intermittently for more than 2,000 years and continue to the present day. In the late Qing era and <b>during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinhai_Revolution\">Xinhai Revolution</span> of 1911</b> he was invoked by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_nationalism\">Han nationalists</span> as the shared ancestor of the nation, with reformers even proposing to reckon the calendar from his reign in an era then numbered at more than 4,600 years, and the enduring phrase \"descendants of Yan and Huang\" still expresses the identity of a Han population that today exceeds 1.3 billion people, close to 18 percent of the world's total.","citation":"","answerText":"Yellow Emperor"},{"id":"cnh-003","num":"三","category":"China · History","question":"Celebrated for taming a catastrophic flood of the Yellow River by dredging channels rather than building dams, and for labouring so hard he passed his own home without entering, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was rewarded with the throne and is regarded as the founder of the first dynasty.","answer":"Yu the Great","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Reigned</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. 2123–2025 BCE</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"大禹","pinyin":"Dà Yǔ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Dà Yǔ</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Yu the Great</b> was a legendary <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sage_king\">sage-king</span> of remote Chinese antiquity</b>, conventionally placed at the close of the era of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Sovereigns_and_Five_Emperors\">Three Sovereigns and Five Emperors</span> and celebrated above all for subduing a catastrophic deluge and founding the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xia_dynasty\">Xia dynasty</span>. According to the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gun-Yu_myth\">flood myth</span></b> preserved in early texts, the labour of controlling the waters had first fallen to his father <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gun_(Chinese_mythology)\">Gun</span>, who struggled in vain for nine years by raising <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Levee\">dikes</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dam\">earthen dams</span> before being put to death. Inheriting the commission, Yu reversed his father's strategy of blockage and instead dredged outlets and deepened watercourses to lead the floods toward the sea, a feat he is said to have achieved over 13 years of ceaseless effort during which he passed his own door three times without once entering. His triumph was construed as a moral as much as a hydraulic one, exemplifying the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"De_(Chinese)\">virtue</span> for which the sovereign <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Shun\">Shun</span>—who had himself received power from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Yao\">Yao</span> through the idealized practice of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Abdication\">abdication</span> to the most worthy candidate—selected Yu as successor in preference to his own son. After ascending the throne, Yu is credited with dividing the land into nine provinces and casting the emblematic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nine_Tripod_Cauldrons\">Nine Tripod Cauldrons</span>, and on his death he passed his power to his son <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qi_of_Xia\">Qi</span>, whose accession transformed the meritocratic succession of the sage-kings into a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hereditary_monarchy\">hereditary monarchy</span></b>.<br> <br>Although later enshrined in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> tradition—<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucius\">Confucius</span> himself extolled Yu's selfless devotion in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Analects\"><i>Analects</i></span>—the figure long antedates the surviving classics, and no contemporary documents attest to his existence. The earliest known reference appears on the Bin Gong xu, a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Western_Zhou\">Western Zhou</span> <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_ritual_bronzes\">ritual bronze</span> vessel of around 900 BCE</b>, whose 98-character inscription opens by proclaiming that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mandate_of_Heaven\">Heaven</span> had charged Yu with spreading out the land and channelling the rivers. Fuller narratives surface only centuries afterward, in works such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Book_of_Documents\"><i>Book of Documents</i></span>, whose <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yu_Gong\"><i>Tribute of Yu</i></span> chapter maps the nine provinces and their products, and in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Records_of_the_Grand_Historian\"><i>Records of the Grand Historian</i></span> <b>compiled by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Qian\">Sima Qian</span> around 100 BCE</b>. Modern scholarship remains divided over the historicity of Yu and the Xia alike, with many archaeologists tentatively linking the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Erlitou_culture\">Erlitou culture</span>—a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bronze_Age\">Bronze Age</span> society that flourished roughly between 1900 and 1500 BCE, immediately preceding the firmly attested <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shang_dynasty\">Shang dynasty</span>—to the polity he is supposed to have founded, even as the state-sponsored <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xia–Shang–Zhou_Chronology_Project\">Xia–Shang–Zhou Chronology Project</span> dated the dynasty to <b>between about 2070 and 1600 BCE</b>. A striking new line of evidence emerged in 2016, when a study in the journal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Science_(journal)\"><i>Science</i></span> reported geological traces, dated by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Radiocarbon_dating\">radiocarbon</span>, of a colossal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Landslide_dam\">landslide-dam</span> outburst flood on the upper river around 1920 BCE—its peak discharge estimated at 300,000 to 500,000 cubic metres per second, ranking among the largest floods of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Holocene\">Holocene</span></b>—offering a possible natural seed for the enduring legend of the man who mastered the waters.","citation":"","answerText":"Yu the Great"},{"id":"cnh-004","num":"四","category":"China · History","question":"Traditionally said to have been founded by Yu the Great around <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> BCE, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is described in later texts but remains hard to confirm, with some scholars linking it to the Bronze-Age Erlitou culture.","answer":"Xia dynasty","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">traditionally c. &lt;b&gt;2070&lt;/b&gt;–&lt;b&gt;1600 BCE&lt;/b&gt;</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"夏朝","pinyin":"Xià cháo","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Xià cháo</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Xia dynasty</b> is conventionally regarded as the first dynasty in traditional <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_historiography\">Chinese historiography</span></b>, said to have been established by the sage-king <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yu_the_Great\">Yu the Great</span> after he tamed the catastrophic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Flood_(China)\">Great Flood</span> that had ravaged the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_River\">Yellow River</span> basin. According to legend Yu had himself received the throne through the meritocratic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Abdication\">abdication</span> by which his predecessor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Shun\">Shun</span> had chosen the worthiest successor, but upon his death his son <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qi_of_Xia\">Qi</span> seized power and inaugurated the <b>principle of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hereditary_monarchy\">hereditary monarchy</span></b> that would define every subsequent Chinese dynasty. Later sources such as the <i><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Records_of_the_Grand_Historian\">Records of the Grand Historian</span></i> compiled by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Qian\">Sima Qian</span>, together with the <i><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bamboo_Annals\">Bamboo Annals</span></i> and the <i><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Book_of_Documents\">Book of Documents</span></i>, preserve a king-list of 17 rulers spanning roughly 14 generations and about 470 years. These traditions locate the dynasty's heartland in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Plain_(China)\">Central Plain</span></b> of modern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Henan\">Henan</span>, with an early capital remembered as Yangcheng near present-day <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dengfeng\">Dengfeng</span>, in a region long celebrated as a cradle of Chinese civilisation. The line is said to have ended under the tyrannical last king <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jie_of_Xia\">Jie</span>, who was overthrown by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_of_Shang\">Tang</span> at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Mingtiao\">Battle of Mingtiao</span></b>, an upheaval that founded the succeeding <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shang_dynasty\">Shang dynasty</span> and furnished a paradigmatic precedent for the later doctrine of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mandate_of_Heaven\">Mandate of Heaven</span>. <br> <br> Despite this rich textual tradition the dynasty's very existence remains contested, since no contemporaneous written records survive and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Oracle_bone_script\">oracle bone</span> inscriptions excavated at the Shang capital of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yinxu\">Yinxu</span>, which constitute the earliest known Chinese writing, contain no reference to any preceding Xia state. In the absence of such documentation, many Chinese archaeologists have identified the dynasty with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bronze_Age\">Bronze Age</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Erlitou_culture\">Erlitou culture</span>, a sophisticated society of the middle Yellow River valley whose type site near <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luoyang\">Luoyang</span> was first <b>investigated in 1959</b> by the archaeologist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xu_Xusheng\">Xu Xusheng</span> while he was deliberately searching for the ruins of the lost dynasty. Flourishing approximately between 1900 and 1500 BCE, the Erlitou settlement grew to cover some 300 hectares (740 acres) and contained China's earliest known palace foundations of pounded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rammed_earth\">rammed earth</span>, large-scale bronze foundries, and elite tombs furnished with early <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_ritual_bronzes\">ritual bronze</span> vessels and an intricate dragon plaque assembled from more than 2,000 pieces of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Turquoise\">turquoise</span>. The state-sponsored <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xia–Shang–Zhou_Chronology_Project\">Xia–Shang–Zhou Chronology Project</span>, working partly from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Radiocarbon_dating\">radiocarbon dating</span>, concluded in 2000 that the dynasty endured from about 2070 to 1600 BCE and tentatively assigned its later phases to the Erlitou horizon. Many Western historians nevertheless remain sceptical, cautioning that the equation of an archaeological culture with a named textual polity is unproven and suggesting that the dynasty may be in part a retrospective construction of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_dynasty\">Zhou dynasty</span> fashioned to provide a historical mirror for its own conquest of the Shang, so that the question of whether the first dynasty was a genuine kingdom or a foundational legend remains genuinely open.","citation":"","answerText":"Xia dynasty"},{"id":"cnh-005","num":"五","category":"China · History","question":"Identified at a major archaeological site in Henan with large palace foundations and early bronze workshops, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is considered by many to be the material remains of the semi-legendary first dynasty.","answer":"Erlitou culture","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1900–1500 BCE</span></div>","traditional":"二里頭文化","hanzi":"二里头文化","pinyin":"Èrlǐtóu wénhuà","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Èrlǐtóu wénhuà</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Erlitou culture</b> was an early <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bronze_Age\">Bronze Age</span> society and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Archaeological_culture\">archaeological culture</span></b> that flourished across the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Loess\">loess</span> lands of the middle <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_River\">Yellow River</span> valley in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Henan\">Henan</span> <b>from roughly 1900</b> to <b>1500 BCE</b>. It takes its name from its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Type_site\">type site</span> near <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yanshi\">Yanshi</span> in the city of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luoyang\">Luoyang</span>, which was first <b>identified in 1959</b> during a survey explicitly searching for traces of the legendary first dynasty and has since been excavated by teams of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Academy_of_Social_Sciences\">Chinese Academy of Social Sciences</span>, revealing an urban centre that at its height spread across some 3 square kilometres (1.2 sq mi). At its core lay a planned palace precinct of more than 10 hectares (25 acres), within which excavators uncovered the earliest known <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rammed_earth\">rammed-earth</span> palatial foundations in China, including large courtyard compounds whose layout set an architectural template echoed by later dynasties. Adjacent workshops cast China's first <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_ritual_bronzes\">ritual bronzes</span>, among them slender wine vessels of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jue_(vessel)\">jue</span> type, demonstrating a <b>command of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bronze\">bronze</span></b> metallurgy that would remain central to elite ceremony for the next millennium. The settlement also sustained specialized <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Turquoise\">turquoise</span> and pottery industries, most famously yielding an inlaid <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_dragon\">dragon</span> object more than 70 centimetres (28 in) long and assembled from over 2,000 individual pieces, a find that <b>points to pronounced <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Social_stratification\">social stratification</span></b> and centralized control of luxury craft production. <br> <br> Emerging from the late <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Neolithic\">Neolithic</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Longshan_culture\">Longshan culture</span> and overlapping with the succeeding <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Erligang_culture\">Erligang culture</span> centred on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhengzhou\">Zhengzhou</span>, it is widely regarded as the first state-level polity in East Asia and a pivotal step in the transition toward the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shang_dynasty\">Shang</span> civilization, whose later royal capital lay at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yinxu\">Yinxu</span>. Because its dates and location broadly match traditional accounts of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xia_dynasty\">Xia dynasty</span>—the semi-legendary realm said to have been founded by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yu_the_Great\">Yu the Great</span> and chronicled by the historian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Qian\">Sima Qian</span> in texts such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Records_of_the_Grand_Historian\"><i>Records of the Grand Historian</i></span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bamboo_Annals\"><i>Bamboo Annals</i></span>—many Chinese scholars treat it as the material remains of that first dynasty. This identification was reinforced by the state-sponsored <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xia–Shang–Zhou_Chronology_Project\">Xia–Shang–Zhou Chronology Project</span></b>, which between 1996 and 2000 combined <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Radiocarbon_dating\">radiocarbon dating</span> with textual analysis to date the Xia to approximately 2070 to 1600 BCE and to correlate its later phases with the central settlement. Many Western archaeologists remain cautious, noting that no contemporaneous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Oracle_bone\">oracle-bone</span> inscriptions or other writing securely tie the remains to the name \"Xia,\" and warning that the dynastic label was projected onto the material record rather than derived from it. Whatever its dynastic identity, the culture is recognized as a foundational chapter in the rise of early Chinese statehood, and continuing excavations across the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"North_China_Plain\">North China Plain</span> keep refining understanding of how <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Complex_society\">complex society</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Urban_planning\">urban planning</span>, and bronze ritual first took shape in the region.","citation":"","answerText":"Erlitou culture"},{"id":"cnh-006","num":"六","category":"China · History","question":"The earliest dynasty firmly attested by writing and archaeology, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is known for lavish royal tombs, human sacrifice and divination recorded in the oracle bone script, and was overthrown by the Zhou invoking the Mandate of Heaven.","answer":"Shang dynasty","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">16th–11th c. BCE</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"商朝","pinyin":"Shāng cháo","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Shāng cháo</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Shang dynasty</b> was the earliest Chinese state firmly documented by both written records and archaeology, a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bronze_Age\">Bronze Age</span></b> civilization that flourished in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_River\">Yellow River</span> valley across roughly the 16th to 11th centuries BCE. Traditional histories hold that it was founded when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_of_Shang\">Tang</span> overthrew the dissolute <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jie_of_Xia\">Jie</span>, last ruler of the preceding <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xia_dynasty\">Xia</span>, thereby establishing a line of some 30 kings spread over about 17 generations. An earlier walled capital, associated with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Erligang_culture\">Erligang culture</span> at present-day Zhengzhou, preceded the move that the <b>king <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pan_Geng\">Pan Geng</span> made around 1300 BCE</b> to Yin, beside modern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anyang\">Anyang</span>, whose ruins—the renowned <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yinxu\">Yinxu</span>—furnished the dynasty its alternative name. At the apex of its power under the long-reigning <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Ding\">Wu Ding</span>, the Shang theocracy revolved around the monarch's role as supreme priest, who <b>through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Veneration_of_the_dead\">ancestor veneration</span></b> and appeals to the high god <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shangdi\">Di</span> mediated between the living and the powers governing harvest, weather, and war. The dynasty fell when its last and reputedly tyrannical king, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Zhou_of_Shang\">Di Xin</span>, was defeated by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Wu_of_Zhou\">King Wu</span> at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Muye\">Battle of Muye</span>, conventionally <b>dated to 1046 BCE</b>.<br> <br>Knowledge of the Shang was transformed by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Oracle_bone\">oracle bones</span>—ox scapulae and turtle shells used in pyromantic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Divination\">divination</span>—which the scholar <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Yirong\">Wang Yirong</span> recognized as ancient <b>writing in 1899</b>, and of which more than 150,000 inscribed fragments have since been recovered. The graphs they bear, numbering around 4,000 distinct characters of which only some 1,500 have been confidently deciphered, constitute the direct ancestor of modern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_characters\">Chinese characters</span>, and in 1917 the polymath <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Guowei\">Wang Guowei</span> demonstrated that the royal genealogy they preserved closely matched the king list transmitted in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Records_of_the_Grand_Historian\"><i>Records of the Grand Historian</i></span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Qian\">Sima Qian</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bamboo_Annals\"><i>Bamboo Annals</i></span>. Systematic excavation of Yinxu, begun in 1928 under the auspices of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Academia_Sinica\">Academia Sinica</span>, laid bare enormous cruciform royal tombs, pits interring sacrificed horses and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chariot\">chariots</span>, and a royal cemetery of more than 1,200 sacrificial burials that testifies to the dynasty's pervasive practice of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Human_sacrifice\">human sacrifice</span>. Shang artisans achieved extraordinary mastery of piece-mould bronze casting, producing the ritual <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_ritual_bronzes\">vessels</span> for which the era is celebrated, among them the colossal Houmuwu <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ding_(vessel)\">ding</span></b>, which at about 833 kilograms (1,840 lb) remains the heaviest piece of ancient bronzework ever unearthed. The unlooted tomb of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fu_Hao\">Fu Hao</span>, a royal consort and military commander excavated in 1976, yielded more than 1,500 objects—including over 400 bronzes, hundreds of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jade\">jade</span> carvings, and nearly 7,000 cowrie <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shell_money\">shells</span></b>—while inscriptions credit her with leading armies of 13,000 troops; on such accumulated evidence the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xia–Shang–Zhou_Chronology_Project\">Xia–Shang–Zhou Chronology Project</span> placed the dynasty's founding at around 1600 BCE.","citation":"","answerText":"Shang dynasty"},{"id":"cnc-001","num":"一","category":"China · Culture","question":"Evolving over more than 3,000 years from ancient pictographs into the logographic script used across East Asia, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> — later split into traditional and simplified forms — represents words and morphemes rather than sounds.","answer":"Chinese characters","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">汉字 (hànzì, 'Han characters'), after the Han dynasty</span></div>","traditional":"漢字","hanzi":"汉字","pinyin":"hànzì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">hànzì</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Chinese characters</b> are the logographic graphemes that constitute the principal writing system of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_language\">Chinese language</span></b>, in which each unit ordinarily corresponds to a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Morpheme\">morpheme</span> or whole word rather than to an isolated sound. The script descends from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Oracle_bone_script\">oracle bone script</span> incised on turtle plastrons and ox scapulae for divination during <b>the late <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shang_dynasty\">Shang dynasty</span> around 1250 BCE</b>, a corpus that preserves more than 4,000 distinct graphs, of which roughly 1,200 have been securely deciphered. Over the following millennia the forms passed through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_bronze_inscriptions\">bronze inscriptions</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Seal_script\">seal script</span> before the chancellor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Si\">Li Si</span> imposed a standardized <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Small_seal_script\">small seal script</span> upon the unification of China <b>by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_dynasty\">Qin dynasty</span> in 221 BCE</b>, after which the more fluid <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Clerical_script\">clerical script</span> and ultimately the modern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Regular_script\">regular script</span> took shape. Lexicographers progressively catalogued this expanding inventory, as when the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span> scholar <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xu_Shen\">Xu Shen</span> analysed 9,353 characters in <b>his <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shuowen_Jiezi\"><i>Shuowen Jiezi</i></span> of around 100 CE</b> and arranged them under 540 semantic headers, while the imperially commissioned <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kangxi_Dictionary\"><i>Kangxi Dictionary</i></span> of 1716 listed some 47,035 graphs beneath 214 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kangxi_radical\">radicals</span>. Estimates of the total stock of characters ever devised reach far higher, with the 1994 <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhonghua_Zihai\"><i>Zhonghua Zihai</i></span></b> recording about 85,568 distinct forms, although the overwhelming majority are obsolete variants that a literate adult never encounters.<br> <br>Beyond China the script radiated across the wider <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sinosphere\">Sinosphere</span>, where it was adapted to write <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japanese_language\">Japanese</span> as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kanji\">kanji</span>, Korean as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hanja\">hanja</span>, and Vietnamese as the now-defunct <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chữ_Nôm\">chữ Nôm</span>. Mastery has always demanded sustained effort, since functional literacy in modern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Standard_Chinese\">Standard Chinese</span> requires command of roughly 3,000 to 4,000 characters, and the official <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Table_of_General_Standard_Chinese_Characters\">Table of General Standard Chinese Characters</span> promulgated in 2013 fixes a working set of 8,105. To raise literacy, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span> introduced rounds of character simplification in 1956 and 1964 that altered the structure of more than 2,000 commonly used graphs, whereas <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Traditional_Chinese_characters\">traditional characters</span> have remained standard in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Macau\">Macau</span>. Because the graphs encode meaning rather than pronunciation, auxiliary phonetic systems arose to teach and transcribe speech, most prominently <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pinyin\">Hanyu Pinyin</span></b>, the romanization adopted in 1958, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bopomofo\">Bopomofo</span>, the phonetic notation still taught in Taiwan. Far more than a utilitarian tool, the script underpins the venerated art of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_calligraphy\">Chinese calligraphy</span>, practised in flowing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cursive_script_(East_Asia)\">cursive</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Semi-cursive_script\">semi-cursive</span> styles prized for their expressive line, and in the digital age more than 90,000 of its characters have been encoded as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"CJK_Unified_Ideographs\">CJK Unified Ideographs</span></b> within the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Unicode\">Unicode</span> standard.","citation":"","answerText":"Chinese characters"},{"id":"cnc-006","num":"六","category":"China · Culture","question":"Cast in piece-moulds with intricate <i>taotie</i> motifs and used for offerings of food and wine to ancestors, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> often bear early inscriptions valued by historians.","answer":"Chinese ritual bronzes","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">青铜器 (qīngtóngqì, 'bronze ware')</span></div>","traditional":"青銅器","hanzi":"青铜器","pinyin":"qīngtóngqì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">qīngtóngqì</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“bronze ware”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Chinese ritual bronzes</b> are cast metal vessels and objects produced for ceremonial use during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bronze_Age\">Bronze Age</span> in China, above all under the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shang_dynasty\">Shang</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_dynasty\">Zhou</span> dynasties. Cast from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bronze\">bronze</span>, an alloy of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Copper\">copper</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tin\">tin</span>, they served chiefly to present offerings of food and wine to the spirits of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_ancestral_worship\">ancestors</span>, binding the living lineage to its dead through solemn sacrificial rites. Unlike the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lost-wax_casting\">lost-wax</span></b> methods favoured elsewhere, Chinese founders perfected an elaborate piece-mould technique built from assembled ceramic sections, a process that lent itself to the crisp, deeply cut ornament for which the vessels are renowned. Their surfaces teem with stylised zoomorphic designs dominated by the enigmatic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taotie\">taotie</span> mask, accompanied by coiling <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kui_(Chinese_mythology)\">dragons</span>, cicadas, and dense spiral grounds of thunder pattern. They took dozens of specialised forms classified by function, from the tripod food cauldron known as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ding_(vessel)\">ding</span> and the grain-serving <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gui_(vessel)\">gui</span> to wine vessels such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jue_(vessel)\">jue</span> and ringing sets of bronze <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bianzhong\">bells</span>, the ding in particular becoming a potent emblem of political authority. <br> <br> Many vessels carry cast <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_bronze_inscriptions\">inscriptions</span></b> in an early script that historians prize as primary records of conquests, royal appointments, and land grants, the writing marking a crucial stage in the evolution of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Large_seal_script\">large seal script</span>. Among the most celebrated examples is the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Gong_ding\">Mao Gong ding</span></b>, whose interior bears one of the longest known bronze inscriptions, while other vessels record the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Muye\">Zhou conquest of Shang</span>, an event thereby dated <b>by some scholars to 1046 BCE</b>. The tradition reaches back to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Erlitou_culture\">Erlitou</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Erligang_culture\">Erligang</span> cultures and attained extraordinary heights at the late Shang capital of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yinxu\">Yinxu</span>, where the <b>undisturbed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tomb_of_Fu_Hao\">tomb of Fu Hao</span></b> yielded hundreds of bronzes, while the uncanny figures of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sanxingdui\">Sanxingdui</span> reveal a strikingly different regional style. The colossal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Houmuwu_ding\">Houmuwu ding</span>, weighing some 832 kilograms (1,830 lb), ranks as the heaviest ancient bronze ever found, and the number of vessels a noble might display was strictly regulated by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sumptuary_law\">sumptuary</span> rule, while the legendary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nine_Tripod_Cauldrons\">Nine Tripod Cauldrons</span> attributed to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yu_the_Great\">Yu the Great</span> came to embody the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mandate_of_Heaven\">Mandate of Heaven</span> itself. Long after such rites faded, the bronzes became objects of antiquarian study, catalogued by collectors of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song dynasty</span> and treasured today in institutions such as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_Museum\">Shanghai Museum</span></b> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Museum_of_China\">National Museum of China</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Chinese ritual bronzes"},{"id":"cnc-007","num":"七","category":"China · Culture","question":"Expressed through home altars, grave-sweeping at Qingming and offerings of food and burnt spirit money, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> honours deceased forebears as continuing members of the family, reflecting the deep value placed on filial piety.","answer":"Chinese ancestral worship","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">敬祖 (jìngzǔ, 'reverence for ancestors')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"敬祖","pinyin":"jìngzǔ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">jìngzǔ</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“reverence for ancestors”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Chinese ancestral worship</b> is the practice of honouring deceased forebears as continuing members of the family, sustained through home altars, grave offerings, and burnt <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joss_paper\">spirit money</span></b>, and grounded in the cardinal virtue of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Filial_piety\">filial piety</span>. Its roots reach the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shang_dynasty\">Shang dynasty</span>, whose kings addressed dead ancestors through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Oracle_bone\">oracle-bone</span> divination as intercessors with the high god <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shangdi\">Shangdi</span>, feeding them lavish sacrifices attested in the royal tombs of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yinxu\">Yinxu</span>. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_dynasty\">Zhou dynasty</span> regularized the cult around ancestral temples and <b>inscribed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Spirit_tablet\">spirit tablets</span></b>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucius\">Confucius</span> gave it ethical depth, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Analects\"><i>Analects</i></span> urging that one sacrifice to the dead as if they were present. Classical psychology explained the double cult by the 2 souls of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hun_and_po\">hun and po</span>, the ethereal hun lodging in the tablet on the family altar while the earthly po rested with the body at the grave, and the neglected dead <b>degenerating into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hungry_ghost\">hungry ghosts</span></b>. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song</span> master <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_Xi\">Zhu Xi</span> codified domestic rites for 4 generations of ancestors in his <i>Family Rituals</i>, and after <b>a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span> edict of 1536</b> permitted commoners to build <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ancestral_shrine\">ancestral halls</span>, lineage temples multiplied across south China. <br> <br> The ritual year still turns on the ancestors: graves are swept and food offered at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qingming_Festival\">Qingming Festival</span> in early April, the wandering dead are fed at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ghost_Festival\">Ghost Festival</span> of the 7th lunar month, ascents honour them at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Double_Ninth_Festival\">Double Ninth Festival</span></b>, and tablets receive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Incense\">incense</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kowtow\">kowtows</span>, and a place at the reunion feast of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_New_Year\">Chinese New Year</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dongzhi_Festival\">winter solstice</span>. Offerings of paper houses, cars, and banknotes burned for the beyond continue a logic of provisioning the dead now updated with cardboard smartphones. The cult once crowned the state itself, emperors serving their forebears at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_Ancestral_Temple\">Imperial Ancestral Temple</span>, and it triggered the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Rites_controversy\">Chinese Rites controversy</span>, in which Rome, rejecting the tolerant line of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Matteo_Ricci\">Matteo Ricci</span>, banned Catholic converts <b>from ancestral rites in 1715</b> and relented only in 1939. Lineage halls and genealogies were smashed during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span>, yet since the 1980s the practice has rebounded vigorously in provinces such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fujian\">Fujian</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangdong\">Guangdong</span>, and <b>in 2008</b> the People's Republic restored Qingming as a national public holiday that now sets over 100 million people travelling to family graves. Embedded alike in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> ethics, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Taoist</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Buddhism\">Buddhist</span> liturgy, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_folk_religion\">folk religion</span>, and carried worldwide by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Overseas_Chinese\">overseas Chinese</span>, ancestral worship remains the most durable thread of Chinese religious life.","citation":"","answerText":"Chinese ancestral worship"},{"id":"cng-024","num":"二十四","category":"China · Geography","question":"A huge, densely populated lowland built up over ages from silt dropped by the Yellow River, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the agricultural and historical heartland around Beijing and a major wheat-growing region.","answer":"North China Plain","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">华北平原 ('north-China plain')</span></div>","traditional":"華北平原","hanzi":"华北平原","pinyin":"Huáběi Píngyuán","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Huáběi Píngyuán</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>North China Plain</b> is an <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Alluvial_plain\">alluvial plain</span> of roughly 410,000 square</b> kilometres (160,000 sq mi), the largest in China, built from silt laid down by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_River\">Yellow River</span> together with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huai_River\">Huai</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hai_River\">Hai</span> rivers. Rarely rising 50 metres (160 ft) above sea level, it spreads from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taihang_Mountains\">Taihang Mountains</span> on the west and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yan_Mountains\">Yan Mountains</span></b> on the north past the hills of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shandong\">Shandong</span> to the shores of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bohai_Sea\">Bohai</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_Sea\">Yellow seas</span>. Continual silting has perched the Yellow River’s bed as much as 10 metres (33 ft) above the surrounding fields near <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kaifeng\">Kaifeng</span>, and over the past 2 millennia the stream has burst its dikes some 1,500 times and shifted course in about 26 major <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Avulsion_(river)\">avulsions</span>, most recently swinging from the Yellow Sea back <b>to the Bohai in 1855</b>, calamities that earned it the name “China’s Sorrow.” Watered by a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Monsoon\">monsoon</span> climate delivering 500 to 800 millimetres (20 to 31 in) of mostly summer rain, the plain is double-cropped in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Winter_wheat\">winter wheat</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maize\">maize</span>, yields over half of the national wheat harvest, and supports a population exceeding 300 million at densities far above the Chinese average. That intensity has produced some of the severest <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Groundwater\">groundwater</span> depletion on Earth, with falling water tables, land <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Subsidence\">subsidence</span>, transfers of tens of billions of cubic metres northward through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South–North_Water_Transfer_Project\">South–North Water Transfer Project</span> <b>since 2014</b>, and projections that irrigation-enhanced humidity could push future <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wet-bulb_temperature\">wet-bulb temperatures</span> toward lethal extremes. <br> <br> Known historically as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhongyuan\">Zhongyuan</span> or Central Plain, the lowland is a cradle of Chinese civilization, holding the palatial <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Erlitou\">Erlitou</span> site of about 1900 BCE</b> that many scholars tie to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xia_dynasty\">Xia dynasty</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shang_dynasty\">Shang</span> capital of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yinxu\">Yinxu</span> at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anyang\">Anyang</span>, where <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Oracle_bone\">oracle bones</span> from around 1250 BCE preserve the earliest Chinese writing. Dynasty after dynasty seated its power here, the saying ran that whoever held the Central Plain held all China, and under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song dynasty</span> Kaifeng grew by the 11th century into a metropolis of perhaps 1 million people, then among the largest cities in the world. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sui_dynasty\">Sui</span> emperors began threading the plain with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Grand_Canal_(China)\">Grand Canal</span> from 605, an artery eventually stretching 1,794 kilometres (1,115 mi) to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hangzhou\">Hangzhou</span> that hauled southern grain to northern capitals for over a thousand years. The plain’s flatness also invited tragedy, never more than in 1938, when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span>’s forces deliberately breached the dikes at Huayuankou in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1938_Yellow_River_flood\">1938 Yellow River flood</span></b>, drowning perhaps half a million people and displacing millions more until the river was resealed in 1947. Today the expanse anchors megacities from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tianjin\">Tianjin</span> to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhengzhou\">Zhengzhou</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shijiazhuang\">Shijiazhuang</span></b>, knit together by the densest stretch of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"High-speed_rail_in_China\">high-speed rail in China</span> and augmented since 2017 by the planned city of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiong'an\">Xiong’an</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"North China Plain"},{"id":"cng-067","num":"六十七","category":"China · Geography","question":"A broad region centred on the North China Plain and the capital, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> — including provinces such as Hebei and Shandong — is the historic wheat-and-millet heartland north of the Qinling–Huai line.","answer":"North China","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">华北 (Huáběi, 'north of China proper')</span></div>","traditional":"華北","hanzi":"华北","pinyin":"Huáběi","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Huáběi</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“northern China”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>North China</b> is a broad geographic and cultural region of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> centred on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"North_China_Plain\">North China Plain</span> and the national capital, lying north of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qinling–Huaihe_Line\">Qinling–Huaihe Line</span></b> that traditionally separates the country’s north from its south. Definitions of the region vary, but it generally embraces the municipalities of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tianjin\">Tianjin</span> together with the provinces of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hebei\">Hebei</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanxi\">Shanxi</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shandong\">Shandong</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Henan\">Henan</span>, and often the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Inner_Mongolia\">Inner Mongolian</span> steppe to the north. Its core is the flat alluvial plain built by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_River\">Yellow River</span>, flanked on the west by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Loess_Plateau\">Loess Plateau</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taihang_Mountains\">Taihang Mountains</span> and shading northward into the dry margins of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gobi_Desert\">Gobi</span>, under a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Monsoon\">monsoon</span> climate of cold dry winters and hot, often dust-laden summers. Agriculturally it is the <b>historic heartland of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Winter_wheat\">winter wheat</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maize\">maize</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Millet\">millet</span> — the grain on which northern farming was founded long before wheat spread — in sharp contrast to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rice\">rice</span> economy of the south, though chronic water shortages now strain its fields. The same divide shapes the table, the north favouring wheaten staples such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Noodle\">noodles</span>, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mantou\">steamed buns</span></b>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiaozi\">dumplings</span> over rice, and the region is home overwhelmingly to northern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Chinese\">Han Chinese</span> and to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mandarin_Chinese\">Mandarin</span> speech from which the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Standard_Chinese\">national standard language</span> is drawn. <br> <br> North China is the cradle of Chinese civilization, where Neolithic villages of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangshao_culture\">Yangshao culture</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Longshan_culture\">Longshan culture</span> gave way to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bronze_Age\">Bronze Age</span> states of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shang_dynasty\">Shang dynasty</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_dynasty\">Zhou dynasty</span> along the middle Yellow River. This was the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhongyuan\">Central Plain</span></b> long regarded as the seat of legitimate rule, and successive dynasties raised their capitals here, among them ancient <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chang'an\">Chang’an</span> near modern Xi’an, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luoyang\">Luoyang</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kaifeng\">Kaifeng</span>, before the focus shifted to Beijing in the north. Exposed to the steppe, the region was repeatedly invaded by nomadic peoples — the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiongnu\">Xiongnu</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xianbei\">Xianbei</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khitan_people\">Khitan</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jurchen_people\">Jurchen</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongols\">Mongols</span> — and often fell under conquest dynasties such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Wei\">Northern Wei</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jin_dynasty_(1115–1234)\">Jin</span>, against whom the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Wall_of_China\">Great Wall</span> was raised as a northern bulwark. In modern times the region has become an industrial and energy core, its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Coal\">coal</span> seams, above all in Shanxi and Inner Mongolia, fuelling much of the nation’s power and heavy industry, including major <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Steelmaking\">steel</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Petroleum\">oil</span> production. Yet this dominance comes at a cost, for the densely settled plain suffers severe <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Groundwater\">groundwater</span> depletion and notorious <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Air_pollution_in_China\">air pollution</span></b>, problems addressed by the vast <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South–North_Water_Transfer_Project\">South–North Water Transfer Project</span> and by efforts to weld Beijing, Tianjin, and Hebei into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jingjinji\">Jingjinji</span> megalopolis.","citation":"","answerText":"North China"},{"id":"cnc-002","num":"二","category":"China · Culture","question":"Inscribed on turtle shells and ox shoulder blades used for divination during the Shang dynasty, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was rediscovered by scholars only at the end of the 19th century.","answer":"oracle bone script","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. 1250–1050 BCE</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"甲骨文","pinyin":"jiǎgǔwén","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">jiǎgǔwén</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“shell and bone script”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Oracle bone script</b> is the oldest known fully developed system of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_characters\">Chinese characters</span></b>, a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Logogram\">logographic</span> script incised onto the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Turtle_shell\">plastrons</span> of turtles and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Scapula\">scapulae</span> of oxen during the late <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shang_dynasty\">Shang dynasty</span>. These texts arose from the royal practice of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pyromancy\">pyromantic</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Divination\">divination</span>, in forms known as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Scapulimancy\">scapulimancy</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Plastromancy\">plastromancy</span></b>, in which diviners applied intense heat to a prepared bone until it cracked, the resulting fissures being read as answers from royal ancestors and the high god <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shangdi\">Shangdi</span>. The charges inscribed beside the cracks concerned matters vital to the Shang court — the prospects of the harvest, the outcome of military campaigns and royal hunts, the meaning of dreams, the conduct of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sacrifice\">sacrifices</span> within the cult of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_ancestor_worship\">ancestor veneration</span>, and the causes of the king's afflictions, and many bones preserved not only the question but also the king's prognostication and a later note verifying the outcome. Surviving inscriptions date overwhelmingly from the closing phase of the dynasty, <b>approximately 1250</b> to 1050 BCE, beginning in the long reign of the warrior-king <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Ding\">Wu Ding</span>, and almost all were produced at the final Shang capital of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yinxu\">Yinxu</span>, near the modern city of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anyang\">Anyang</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Henan\">Henan</span> province. Already a mature system exhibiting the principal methods of word formation later codified as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_character_classification\">six categories of Chinese characters</span></b>, its graphs nonetheless remained strongly <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pictogram\">pictographic</span> and highly variable in form, and the script is recognised as the direct forerunner of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_bronze_inscriptions\">bronze inscriptions</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Seal_script\">seal script</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Clerical_script\">clerical script</span> from which all later Chinese writing descends. <br> <br> Although its descendant scripts endured, the oracle bones themselves lay unrecognised for nearly 3,000 years <b>until 1899</b>, when the senior official and antiquarian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Yirong\">Wang Yirong</span> is traditionally said to have identified ancient writing on the fragments of bone that pharmacies were grinding up as the \"dragon bones\" of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Traditional_Chinese_medicine\">traditional Chinese medicine</span>. His associate <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_E\">Liu E</span> published the first catalogue of rubbings, <i>Tieyun canggui</i>, <b>in 1903</b>, after which the script was steadily deciphered by pioneers such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Yirang\">Sun Yirang</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luo_Zhenyu\">Luo Zhenyu</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Guowei\">Wang Guowei</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dong_Zuobin\">Dong Zuobin</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guo_Moruo\">Guo Moruo</span>, the last four of whom came to be honoured as the “four masters” of the field. Systematic archaeological excavation of the ruins at Yinxu commenced in 1928 under the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Institute_of_History_and_Philology\">Institute of History and Philology</span></b> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Academia_Sinica\">Academia Sinica</span>, with the work directed in part by the archaeologist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Ji_(archaeologist)\">Li Ji</span>, and it brought to light tens of thousands of inscribed fragments alongside palace foundations and royal tombs. Excavations have since recovered more than 150,000 inscribed pieces bearing over 4,000 distinct graphs, of which fewer than 1,500 have been securely deciphered, a gap so stubborn that museums in Anyang have offered rewards of 100,000 yuan for the convincing interpretation of a single previously unread character. Today the corpus is prized as a primary source for the early <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"History_of_China\">history of China</span> and for reconstructing the archaic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_language\">Chinese language</span>, and in recognition of that importance the inscriptions were entered on UNESCO's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Memory_of_the_World\">Memory of the World</span> register in 2017, while the Yinxu site itself had been designated a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Heritage_Site\">World Heritage Site</span> as early as 2006.","citation":"","answerText":"oracle bone script"},{"id":"cnh-007","num":"七","category":"China · History","question":"The longest-lasting dynasty in Chinese history, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> overthrew the Shang in the 11th century BCE, justified its rule by the Mandate of Heaven, and presided over the era when Confucius and the other classical philosophers lived.","answer":"Zhou dynasty","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. &lt;b&gt;1046&lt;/b&gt;–&lt;b&gt;256 BCE&lt;/b&gt;</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"周朝","pinyin":"Zhōu cháo","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōu cháo</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Zhou dynasty</b> was the longest-enduring ruling house in Chinese history, lasting nearly 800 years from the <b>moment its founder <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Wu_of_Zhou\">King Wu</span></b> shattered the armies of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shang_dynasty\">Shang dynasty</span> at the decisive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Muye\">Battle of Muye</span> around 1046 BCE. Rising from a frontier power in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wei_River\">Wei River</span> valley whose fortunes had been built by King Wu's father <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Wen_of_Zhou\">King Wen</span>, the new regime legitimised its violent seizure of power through the enduring political theology of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mandate_of_Heaven\">Mandate of Heaven</span>, a doctrine elaborated by the statesman <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Duke_of_Zhou\">Duke of Zhou</span> during his regency for the youthful <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Cheng_of_Zhou\">King Cheng</span></b>. This conception held that Heaven conferred the right to rule on the virtuous and stripped it from the corrupt, a principle that retrospectively justified the conquest of the dissolute final Shang king and would anchor the Chinese notion of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dynastic_cycle\">dynastic cycle</span> for nearly 3,000 years thereafter. To govern its enormous new territory the dynasty parcelled out land to royal kinsmen and allied lords under the decentralised <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fengjian\">fengjian</span> system, traditionally said to have created 71 vassal states of which 53 were granted to members of the royal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ji_(surname_姬)\">Ji clan</span>, an order reinforced by the patriarchal lineage law of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zongfa\">zongfa</span> that bound the nobility into a ritual hierarchy of ancestral obligation. This first phase, known as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Western_Zhou\">Western Zhou</span> and centred on the twin capital of Haojing near modern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi'an\">Xi'an</span>, <b>collapsed in 771 BCE</b> when the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Quanrong\">Quanrong</span> tribes sacked the city and killed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_You_of_Zhou\">King You</span>, forcing the court to flee eastward to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luoyang\">Luoyang</span>. <br> <br> The ensuing Eastern Zhou period saw real authority drain away from the increasingly ceremonial kings toward a shifting constellation of rival states competing for supremacy, and it is conventionally subdivided into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Spring_and_Autumn_period\">Spring and Autumn period</span> and the bloodier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warring_States_period\">Warring States period</span> that consumed the centuries leading to final unification. Paradoxically, this era of political fragmentation produced the most creative age of Chinese thought, the so-called <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hundred_Schools_of_Thought\">Hundred Schools of Thought</span>, during which <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucius\">Confucius</span> founded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucianism</span> and was followed by figures such as the Daoist sage <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Laozi\">Laozi</span>, the universalist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mozi\">Mozi</span>, and the authoritarian theorists of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Legalism_(Chinese_philosophy)\">Legalism</span>. These thinkers and their many successors, among them <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mencius\">Mencius</span> and the Daoist visionary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuang_Zhou\">Zhuangzi</span>, composed or inspired a large share of the foundational texts later canonised as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Books_and_Five_Classics\">Five Classics</span>, a corpus that included the divinatory <i><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"I_Ching\">I Ching</span></i> and the ancient poetic anthology of the <i><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Classic_of_Poetry\">Classic of Poetry</span></i> and that would shape East Asian scholarship and statecraft for millennia. The same centuries witnessed sweeping material transformation, as the <b>spread of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cast_iron\">cast iron</span></b> tools and ox-drawn ploughs revolutionised agriculture, the first metal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ancient_Chinese_coinage\">coinage</span> in the form of spade and knife money entered circulation, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Crossbow\">crossbow</span> reshaped the scale and lethality of warfare. After centuries of dwindling to a tiny ceremonial enclave, the royal house was finally extinguished in 256 BCE when the ascendant state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_(state)\">Qin</span> deposed the last king, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Nan_of_Zhou\">King Nan</span>, and seized the sacred <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nine_Tripod_Cauldrons\">Nine Tripod Cauldrons</span></b>, clearing the way for Qin's unification of China in 221 BCE under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_dynasty\">Qin dynasty</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Zhou dynasty"},{"id":"cnh-008","num":"八","category":"China · History","question":"Defeating the last Shang king at the Battle of Muye, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> founded a new dynasty and was later idealised by Confucians as a model of righteous kingship who had received the Mandate of Heaven.","answer":"King Wu of Zhou","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Reigned</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. 1046–1043 BCE</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"周武王","pinyin":"Zhōu Wǔwáng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōu Wǔwáng</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Martial King of Zhou”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>King Wu of Zhou</b> was the founding monarch of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_dynasty\">Zhou dynasty</span></b>, the longest-lasting royal house in Chinese history, a dynasty that would endure for nearly 800 years. Born Ji Fa into the royal Ji clan of a Zhou vassal state in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wei_River\">Wei River</span> valley of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guanzhong\">Guanzhong</span> basin, he inherited leadership of the anti-Shang cause from his father <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Wen_of_Zhou\">King Wen</span>, who had been imprisoned by the Shang court yet steadily expanded Zhou influence before dying with the great campaign still unlaunched. Aided by his brother the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Duke_of_Zhou\">Duke of Zhou</span></b> and the veteran strategist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Ziya\">Jiang Ziya</span>, he marched against the tyrannical last <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shang_dynasty\">Shang</span> king, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Zhou_of_Shang\">King Zhou</span>, and shattered his army at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Muye\">Battle of Muye</span>, conventionally <b>dated to 1046 BCE</b>. Traditional accounts describe a Zhou host of some 45,000 troops supported by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chariot\">chariots</span> overwhelming a far larger Shang force whose conscripts and slaves defected en masse, after which the defeated monarch fled and perished by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Self-immolation\">self-immolation</span> at his palace beside the Shang capital of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yinxu\">Yin</span>. To legitimize the overthrow of a once-sanctioned house, Zhou ideologues advanced the doctrine of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mandate_of_Heaven\">Mandate of Heaven</span>, holding that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tian\">Heaven</span> conferred the right to rule on the virtuous and stripped it from the corrupt, a principle of conditional, virtue-based sovereignty that would underpin the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dynastic_cycle\">dynastic cycle</span> and justify changes of ruling house for the next 3,000 years. <br> <br> King Wu survived his triumph by only about 3 years, <b>dying around 1043 BCE</b> and bequeathing the throne to his young son <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Cheng_of_Zhou\">King Cheng</span>, on whose behalf the Duke of Zhou governed as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Regent\">regent</span> for roughly 7 years before returning full authority to the king. He and his successors organized the conquered territory under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fengjian\">fengjian</span> system, parcelling out domains to royal kinsmen, allied clans, and surviving Shang nobles in order to hold a realm far too vast to administer directly from the twin capitals at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fenghao\">Fenghao</span>, near modern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi'an\">Xi'an</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shaanxi\">Shaanxi</span>. The fragile new order was nearly undone soon after his death by the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rebellion_of_the_Three_Guards\">Rebellion of the Three Guards</span></b>, an uprising in which his own brothers joined Shang loyalists against the regency, but its forceful suppression secured the dynasty and consolidated the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Western_Zhou\">Western Zhou</span> period that would endure until its capital <b>fell in 771 BCE</b>. Later tradition, and especially <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucianism</span>, transformed him together with his father into paragons of righteous kingship, with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucius\">Confucius</span> invoking the early Zhou as a golden age and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mencius\">Mencius</span> citing the conquest to argue that a ruler who forfeits virtue may justly be deposed. His deeds are commemorated in classical texts including the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Book_of_Documents\"><i>Book of Documents</i></span> and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Classic_of_Poetry\"><i>Classic of Poetry</i></span></b>, and were later compiled by the historian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Qian\">Sima Qian</span> in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Records_of_the_Grand_Historian\"><i>Records of the Grand Historian</i></span>, ensuring that the founder of a house which survived through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Spring_and_Autumn_period\">Spring and Autumn</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warring_States_period\">Warring States</span> eras until 256 BCE remained a touchstone of Chinese political thought.","citation":"","answerText":"King Wu of Zhou"},{"id":"cnh-010","num":"十","category":"China · History","question":"The decentralised order of the early Zhou, under which the king granted territories to relatives and allies who ruled as hereditary lords in exchange for loyalty and military service, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> — often compared to European feudalism — broke down into the wars of the Spring and Autumn period.","answer":"Fengjian","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">封建 (fēngjiàn, 'enfeoffment and establishment')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"封建","pinyin":"Fēngjiàn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Fēngjiàn</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“enfeoffment and establishment”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Fengjian</b> was the decentralised sociopolitical order of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_dynasty\">Zhou dynasty</span>, under which the king, ruling as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Son_of_Heaven\">Son of Heaven</span></b> by virtue of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mandate_of_Heaven\">Mandate of Heaven</span>, parcelled out territory to kinsmen and allies who governed as hereditary lords in return for tribute, ritual allegiance, and military service. The system was first instituted on a large scale after the conquest <b>of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shang_dynasty\">Shang dynasty</span> around 1046 BCE</b>, when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Wu_of_Zhou\">King Wu</span> and his brother the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Duke_of_Zhou\">Duke of Zhou</span> are recorded in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zuo_zhuan\"><i>Zuozhuan</i></span> to have invested 71 vassal states, 53 of them granted to the royal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ji_(surname_姬)\">Ji clan</span>, in order to garrison a realm far too vast to administer directly. At the apex stood the Zhou monarch, beneath whom a graded aristocracy of regional rulers <b>held ranks of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_nobility\">nobility</span></b> conventionally rendered as duke, marquis, earl, viscount, and baron, supported in turn by ministerial great officers and the lower warrior-scholar class of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shi_(class)\">shi</span>. This pyramid was bound together less by formal contract than by the patrilineal lineage law of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zongfa\">zongfa</span>, which channelled succession through the eldest son of the principal wife under a <b>rule of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Primogeniture\">primogeniture</span></b>, while the agrarian ideal codified in texts such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rites_of_Zhou\"><i>Rites of Zhou</i></span> was the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Well-field_system\">well-field system</span>, a grid of 9 plots in which 8 peasant households jointly tilled a central field for their lord. Although later observers, and especially 20th-century scholars, frequently likened the arrangement to medieval European <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Feudalism\">feudalism</span>, the comparison is imperfect, since Zhou lordship rested far more heavily on shared ancestral cult and clan kinship than on the personal homage and fief-for-service contracts characteristic of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vassal\">vassalage</span> of the West. <br> <br> Over successive generations the kinship bonds that underpinned the system inevitably loosened, and after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Western_Zhou\">Western Zhou</span> capital fell <b>to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Quanrong\">Quanrong</span> in 771 BCE</b>, an assault in which <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_You_of_Zhou\">King You</span> was killed, the surviving kings retained only ceremonial prestige while real power drained to the regional states. During the ensuing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Spring_and_Autumn_period\">Spring and Autumn period</span> the strongest lords assumed the role of hegemon, the so-called <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five_Hegemons\">Five Hegemons</span> who convened the nobility and waged war in the king's name, while relentless annexation steadily devoured a patchwork once numbering well over 100 polities. By the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warring_States_period\">Warring States period</span> only about 7 major kingdoms survived, each ruled by a sovereign who had usurped the royal title of king and abandoned even nominal deference to the now powerless Zhou court. The order was ultimately swept away by the centralising reforms pioneered in the state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_(state)\">Qin</span> by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Legalism_(Chinese_philosophy)\">Legalist</span> statesman <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shang_Yang\">Shang Yang</span>, and after the <b>unification of China in 221 BCE</b> the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_dynasty\">Qin dynasty</span> under the first emperor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_Shi_Huang\">Qin Shi Huang</span> abolished hereditary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fief\">fiefs</span> altogether, dividing the realm instead into 36 directly governed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Commandery_(China)\">commanderies</span> subdivided into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"County_(China)\">counties</span>. The tension between this decentralised model and the centralised commandery system became a recurring theme of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_historiography\">Chinese historiography</span>, debated by statesmen for nearly 2,000 years, and in the 20th century the very word was repurposed by <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marxist_historiography\">Marxist historiography</span></b>, which controversially applied <i>fengjian</i> in the sense of \"feudal society\" to almost the entire span of imperial China down to 1912.","citation":"","answerText":"Fengjian"},{"id":"cnc-009","num":"九","category":"China · Culture","question":"Invoked by the Zhou dynasty to justify overthrowing the Shang, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> held that a just ruler governed by divine approval, which could be withdrawn — through disasters or rebellion — from a corrupt emperor.","answer":"Mandate of Heaven","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">天命 (tiānmìng, 'Heaven's decree')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"天命","pinyin":"tiānmìng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">tiānmìng</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Heaven's decree”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Mandate of Heaven</b> was the foundational doctrine of legitimate rule in China, holding that the impersonal supreme power known as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tian\">Heaven</span> conferred upon a virtuous sovereign the right to govern the realm, or <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tianxia\">all under Heaven</span></b>, as its earthly deputy. The concept emerged in the 11th century BCE as a theological innovation of the Zhou conquerors, who transformed the earlier Shang devotion to the high god <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shangdi\">Shangdi</span> into a more abstract and moral authority that weighed a ruler's worthiness rather than his ancestry, thereby supplying a principled explanation for why one royal house might rightfully supplant another. This rationale was given concrete force when <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Wu_of_Zhou\">King Wu of Zhou</span></b>, completing the design of his revered father <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Wen_of_Zhou\">King Wen</span>, overthrew the dissolute last Shang king, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Zhou_of_Shang\">King Zhou</span>, <b>at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Muye\">Battle of Muye</span> around 1046 BCE</b>, an act the victors justified as Heaven's transfer of its favour from a tyrant to a more worthy line. The doctrine was most fully articulated by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Duke_of_Zhou\">Duke of Zhou</span>, the regent during the early <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Western_Zhou\">Western Zhou</span>, and was enshrined in canonical texts such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Book_of_Documents\"><i>Book of Documents</i></span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Classic_of_Poetry\"><i>Classic of Poetry</i></span>, both later numbered among the Confucian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five_Classics\">Five Classics</span>. Crucially, the mandate was conditional rather than purely hereditary, resting on the ruler's moral charisma or <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"De_(Chinese)\">virtue</span> and entitling him to the title <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Son_of_Heaven\">Son of Heaven</span>, so that floods, famines, earthquakes, and popular uprisings could all be read as portents that Heaven had begun to withdraw its favour.<br> <br>During the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warring_States_period\">Warring States period</span> the philosopher <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mencius\">Mencius</span> sharpened the idea into an explicit <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Right_of_revolution\">right of rebellion</span></b>, contending that a tyrant forfeited his legitimacy and that Heaven perceived through the eyes of the common people, a humane reading that entered the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> mainstream descended from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucius\">Confucius</span> in the earlier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Spring_and_Autumn_period\">Spring and Autumn period</span>. In this respect the mandate differed sharply from the European <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Divine_right_of_kings\">divine right of kings</span></b>, which made monarchy unconditional and irrevocable, whereas the Chinese theory furnished a built-in justification for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dynastic_cycle\">dynastic cycle</span> of rise, decline, and replacement. Every successful founder accordingly claimed the mandate to legitimize his accession, from the peasant-born <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Gaozu_of_Han\">Liu Bang</span>, who <b>established the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span> in 202 BCE</b>, to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hongwu_Emperor\">Zhu Yuanzhang</span>, who founded the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming dynasty</span> in 1368 after expelling the Mongol <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan dynasty</span>. Rulers of later dynasties such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span> treated such portents with great seriousness, maintaining bureaus of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_astronomy\">court astronomers</span> to watch the skies, since comets, eclipses, droughts, and floods alike could be construed as Heaven's commentary on the conduct of the throne. Invoked continuously for nearly 3,000 years, the doctrine endured through every change of dynasty down to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> and lost its binding force only <b>with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinhai_Revolution\">Xinhai Revolution</span> of 1911</b> and the abdication of the child emperor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Puyi\">Puyi</span> in 1912, which together brought the entire imperial order to an end.","citation":"","answerText":"Mandate of Heaven"},{"id":"cnc-011","num":"十一","category":"China · Culture","question":"An ancient divination manual built on 64 hexagrams formed from broken and unbroken lines, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> — also a font of cosmological philosophy — is closely tied to the interplay of yin and yang.","answer":"I Ching","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">易经 (Yìjīng, 'Classic of Changes')</span></div>","traditional":"易經","hanzi":"易经","pinyin":"Yìjīng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Yìjīng</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Classic of Changes”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b><i>I Ching</i></b> is one of the oldest of the Chinese classics, an <b>ancient manual of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Divination\">divination</span></b> that gradually accrued a body of philosophical commentary making it a cornerstone of East Asian cosmological thought. Each of its 64 hexagrams is a figure of 6 stacked lines, every one either broken or unbroken, generated by combining the 8 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bagua\">trigrams</span> in pairs, and the constant alternation between the broken and unbroken lines embodies the interplay of the complementary cosmic forces of yin and yang. Tradition ascribes the original 8 trigrams to the legendary culture hero <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fuxi\">Fu Xi</span></b>, the arrangement and judgement texts of the 64 hexagrams to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Wen_of_Zhou\">King Wen of Zhou</span> during his imprisonment, and the appended line statements to his son the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Duke_of_Zhou\">Duke of Zhou</span>. A later stratum of philosophical appendices known as the Ten Wings, conventionally attributed to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucius\">Confucius</span> but now dated by scholars to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warring_States_period\">Warring States period</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span>, recast the work as a treatise on cosmic process, deriving the manifold of phenomena from the undifferentiated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiji_(philosophy)\">Supreme Ultimate</span>. The oldest core, compiled during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Western_Zhou\">Western Zhou</span> around the <b>9th century BCE</b>, was honoured among the Confucian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five_Classics\">Five Classics</span> and escaped the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Burning_of_books_and_burying_of_scholars\">burning of books</span> <b>ordered by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_Shi_Huang\">Qin Shi Huang</span> in 213 BCE only</b> because it was spared as a practical divination manual, while in the 3rd century CE the commentary of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Bi\">Wang Bi</span> established its enduring philosophical interpretation.<br> <br>Beyond divination the classic became a wellspring of Chinese philosophy, informing both the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> tradition and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Taoist</span> conception of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tao\">Dao</span>, shaping the metaphysics of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Neo-Confucianism\">Neo-Confucianism</span>, and lending conceptual scaffolding to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Feng_shui\">feng shui</span>, the theory of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuxing_(Chinese_philosophy)\">Five Phases</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Traditional_Chinese_medicine\">traditional Chinese medicine</span>. In practice, consultation traditionally proceeded by the laborious sorting of 50 dried <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yarrow\">yarrow</span> stalks, a procedure later simplified into the tossing of 3 coins, with the resulting hexagram and its commentary read as guidance. The text drew European <b>attention as early as 1703</b>, when the philosopher <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gottfried_Wilhelm_Leibniz\">Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz</span>, shown the hexagram diagrams by the Jesuit missionary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joachim_Bouvet\">Joachim Bouvet</span>, recognized in them a striking correspondence to his own <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Binary_number\">binary arithmetic</span>, equating the broken line with 0 and the unbroken line with 1. Scholarly translation followed in the 19th and 20th centuries, beginning with the sinologist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"James_Legge\">James Legge</span>, whose 1882 English version appeared in the monumental <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sacred_Books_of_the_East\"><i>Sacred Books of the East</i></span></b>, and continuing with the influential 1923 German rendering by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Richard_Wilhelm_(sinologist)\">Richard Wilhelm</span>. Through Wilhelm's edition the book reached a wide Western readership and influenced the psychologist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Carl_Jung\">Carl Jung</span>, who drew on it in formulating his notion of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Synchronicity\">synchronicity</span>, while the avant-garde composer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"John_Cage\">John Cage</span> adopted its method of casting hexagrams to generate <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Aleatoric_music\">chance music</span></b>, testimony to the enduring reach of a text more than 2,500 years old.","citation":"","answerText":"I Ching"},{"id":"cnh-009","num":"九","category":"China · History","question":"Serving as loyal regent for his young nephew and suppressing a rebellion to secure the new dynasty, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is revered in Confucian tradition as the paragon of the virtuous minister, credited with shaping the rituals of the early Zhou and admired by Confucius himself.","answer":"Duke of Zhou","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">fl. c. 1042–1036 BCE</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"周公","pinyin":"Zhōu Gōng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōu Gōng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Duke of Zhou</b> was an early <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_dynasty\">Zhou</span> statesman, the fourth son of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Wen_of_Zhou\">King Wen</span></b> and younger brother of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Wu_of_Zhou\">King Wu</span>, whose conquest of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shang_dynasty\">Shang</span> he had helped to bring about. When King Wu died only a few years after the decisive victory <b>at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Muye\">Battle of Muye</span> of 1046 BCE</b>, leaving the throne to his young son <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Cheng_of_Zhou\">King Cheng</span>, the duke took up the role of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Regent\">regent</span> and effective ruler of the fledgling state from its western capital of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Haojing\">Haojing</span>. His authority was almost immediately challenged by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rebellion_of_the_Three_Guards\">Rebellion of the Three Guards</span>, in which several of his own brothers, allied with the <b>Shang prince <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Geng\">Wu Geng</span></b>—son of the vanquished <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Zhou_of_Shang\">Di Xin</span>—and the eastern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dongyi\">Yi</span> peoples, rose against the court. Over a punishing three-year eastern campaign the duke crushed the revolt, putting Wu Geng and the foremost of the rebel brothers to death, and in its wake he resettled the Shang populace and founded the eastern capital of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chengzhou\">Chengzhou</span>, beside modern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luoyang\">Luoyang</span>, to secure Zhou mastery of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhongyuan\">central plains</span>. After roughly seven years, once King Cheng had come of age, the duke—who had ruled in concert with his colleague the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Duke_of_Shao\">Duke of Shao</span></b>—voluntarily relinquished his powers and resumed the station of a subject, an act of self-effacing loyalty that did more for his lasting renown than any of his victories.<br> <br>Beyond preserving the dynasty, the duke is traditionally credited with devising many of its foundational institutions, above all the system of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fengjian\">enfeoffment</span> that parcelled out territory to royal kinsmen and allies such <b>as the strategist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Ziya\">Jiang Ziya</span></b>, who received the state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qi_(state)\">Qi</span>; the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xunzi_(book)\"><i>Xunzi</i></span> later records the founding of 71 such fiefs, 53 of them held by his own Ji clan. One of these domains, the state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lu_(state)\">Lu</span>, was conferred upon his son <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bo_Qin\">Bo Qin</span></b> and would centuries afterward become the home state of Confucius, a connection that helped enshrine the duke as the supreme exemplar of the minister who wields power yet never usurps it. He is revered, too, as the architect of the Zhou order of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_(Confucianism)\">rites</span> and ceremonial <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yayue\">music</span>, the idealized scheme later set down—and much elaborated—in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rites_of_Zhou\"><i>Rites of Zhou</i></span></b>, while the speeches attributed to him in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Book_of_Documents\"><i>Book of Documents</i></span> gave enduring expression to the doctrine that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tian\">Heaven</span> grants its mandate only to the virtuous. Tradition further ascribes to him the line statements of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"I_Ching\"><i>I Ching</i></span>, ranking him among the venerated authors of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Books_and_Five_Classics\">Confucian classics</span> whose authority thinkers from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mencius\">Mencius</span> onward would invoke for more than two millennia. His memory was enshrined above all by Confucius, who took the duke as his very model of the sage in office and, in a celebrated lament preserved in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Analects\"><i>Analects</i></span>, gauged his own waning vigour by how long it had been since he last dreamed of the Duke of Zhou; the fullest account of his statecraft, in turn, survives in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Records_of_the_Grand_Historian\"><i>Records of the Grand Historian</i></span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Qian\">Sima Qian</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Duke of Zhou"},{"id":"cnh-013","num":"十三","category":"China · History","question":"A once-peripheral western state that grew mighty through the harsh Legalist reforms of Shang Yang, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> rivals during the Warring States era before unifying the whole country.","answer":"Qin","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. &lt;b&gt;897&lt;/b&gt;–&lt;b&gt;221 BCE&lt;/b&gt;</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"秦","pinyin":"Qín","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Qín</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Qin</b> was a frontier state on the western marches of the Chinese world that rose from obscurity to unify the entire realm, originating as a fief in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wei_River\">Wei River</span></b> valley and the strategically sheltered <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guanzhong\">Guanzhong</span> basin of present-day <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shaanxi\">Shaanxi</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gansu\">Gansu</span>. Tradition traces the ruling Ying clan to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Feizi\">Feizi</span>, a horse-breeder granted the town of Qin around 897 BCE by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Xiao_of_Zhou\">King Xiao of Zhou</span>, and the domain was elevated to a <b>full vassal state in 770 BCE</b> when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Duke_Xiang_of_Qin\">Duke Xiang</span> escorted the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_dynasty\">Zhou</span> court eastward after the sack of its capital. Long dismissed by the central plain as a semi-barbarian power steeped in the culture of the neighbouring <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xirong\">Western Rong</span>, the state nonetheless expanded vigorously, and under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Duke_Mu_of_Qin\">Duke Mu</span> it came to be reckoned among the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five_Hegemons\">Five Hegemons</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Spring_and_Autumn_period\">Spring and Autumn period</span>. Its decisive transformation came under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Duke_Xiao_of_Qin\">Duke Xiao</span>, who from 356 BCE empowered the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Legalism_(Chinese_philosophy)\">Legalist</span> statesman <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shang_Yang\">Shang Yang</span></b> to enact radical reforms, abolishing the old aristocratic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Well-field_system\">well-field</span> land system, permitting the free sale of land, and replacing hereditary privilege with a ladder of 20 ranks awarded for battlefield merit. Shang Yang further organised the populace into mutually liable groups of 5 and 10 households, standardised weights and measures, relocated the capital to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xianyang\">Xianyang</span> in 350 BCE, and reorganised the territory into centrally governed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"County_(China)\">counties</span>, forging a disciplined war-state whose principles he set down in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Book_of_Lord_Shang\"><i>Book of Lord Shang</i></span>. <br> <br> Although Shang Yang himself was torn apart by chariots in 338 BCE once his royal patron died, his rigorously enforced system long outlived him, and the promise of land and rank in exchange for grain and valour filled the conscript armies that drove relentless expansion through the centuries of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warring_States_period\">Warring States period</span>. A turning point arrived in 316 BCE with the conquest of the wealthy southwestern states of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shu_(state)\">Shu</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ba_(state)\">Ba</span> in modern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan\">Sichuan</span>, a granary made vastly more productive by hydraulic works such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dujiangyan\">Dujiangyan</span> irrigation scheme completed around 256 BCE by the engineer <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Bing_(engineer)\">Li Bing</span></b> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhengguo_Canal\">Zhengguo Canal</span> of 246 BCE. The state's growing military supremacy was demonstrated with terrible force at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Changping\">Battle of Changping</span> in 260 BCE, among the deadliest engagements of the ancient world, where the general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bai_Qi\">Bai Qi</span> shattered the army of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhao_(state)\">Zhao</span> and, according to the histories, put to death some 400,000 surrendered prisoners. Guided by ministers such as the chancellor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Si\">Li Si</span> and exploiting the shifting diplomatic coalitions among its enemies, the state launched its final <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin's_wars_of_unification\">wars of unification</span> under King Zheng between 230 and 221 BCE, extinguishing the rival kingdoms of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_(Warring_States)\">Han</span>, Zhao, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wei_(state)\">Wei</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chu_(state)\">Chu</span>, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yan_(state)\">Yan</span></b>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qi_(state)\">Qi</span> one after another. With the last of these conquered in 221 BCE, King Zheng styled himself <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_Shi_Huang\">Qin Shi Huang</span>, the First Emperor, and founded the short-lived but epochal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_dynasty\">Qin dynasty</span>, an empire whose very name is widely thought to have travelled westward along the trade routes to become the European word for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Names_of_China\">China</span> itself.","citation":"","answerText":"Qin"},{"id":"cnc-010","num":"十","category":"China · Culture","question":"The oldest surviving collection of Chinese poetry, gathering more than 300 folk songs, hymns and odes from the Zhou era, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> became one of the Five Classics revered in Confucianism.","answer":"Classic of Poetry","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">11th–7th c. BCE</span></div>","traditional":"詩經","hanzi":"诗经","pinyin":"Shījīng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Shījīng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b><i>Classic of Poetry</i></b>, also known in English as the <b><i>Book of Songs</i></b>, is the oldest surviving anthology of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_poetry\">Chinese poetry</span></b> and a foundational text of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_literature\">Chinese literary</span> tradition. Comprising 305 poems—together with 6 further pieces preserved only by their titles—the collection gathers compositions dating from roughly the <b>11th</b> to <b>7th centuries BCE</b>, spanning the early <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Western_Zhou\">Western Zhou</span> period to the middle of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Spring_and_Autumn_period\">Spring and Autumn period</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_dynasty\">Zhou</span> dynasty, and its rhyme patterns remain a principal source for reconstructing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Old_Chinese\">Old Chinese</span> phonology. It is conventionally arranged in 4 sections: the 160 \"Airs of the States,\" folk songs drawn from 15 regional domains; the Minor and Major Court Hymns, comprising 74 and 31 pieces; and 40 \"Eulogies,\" stately temple verses sung at ancestral <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sacrifice\">sacrifices</span> within the <b>cult of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_ancestor_worship\">ancestor veneration</span></b> and accompanied by the ritual court music known as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yayue\">yayue</span>. The Airs preserve some of the earliest literary glimpses of ordinary life in ancient China—treating courtship, marriage, farming, soldiering and complaint against harsh rulers—while the grander hymns recount the legendary rise of the Zhou house and celebrate the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mandate_of_Heaven\">Mandate of Heaven</span> conferred on founders such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Wen_of_Zhou\">King Wen</span> and the statesman <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Duke_of_Zhou\">Duke of Zhou</span>. Most of its verse is cast in lines of 4 characters and deploys the 3 expressive modes—plain narration, explicit comparison, and the evocative \"stirring\" image—that later critics enshrined among the <b>fundamental techniques of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Classical_Chinese_poetry\">classical Chinese poetry</span></b>, establishing the work as the fountainhead of the enduring <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shi_(poetry)\">shi</span> poetic form. <br> <br> Tradition long credited <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucius\">Confucius</span> with selecting these 305 poems from an older corpus said to have numbered some 3,000, although most modern scholars treat that story as legendary and regard the anthology as the cumulative work of Zhou court musicians and officials. Confucius nonetheless prized the poems above almost all other learning, asserting in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Analects\"><i>Analects</i></span> that their spirit could be captured in the phrase \"thoughts without depravity\" and that one ignorant of the Odes would be unfit to converse, an esteem that helped fix the text at the heart of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> curriculum. Like other ancient writings it was condemned during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_dynasty\">Qin</span> regime in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Burning_of_books_and_burying_of_scholars\">burning of the books</span> <b>ordered by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_Shi_Huang\">Qin Shi Huang</span> in 213 BCE</b>, yet it survived largely intact because scholars had committed its verses to memory and its rhymed, song-like form lent itself to oral preservation. Under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span> the text passed through 4 rival schools of interpretation—the Lu, Qi, Han and Mao traditions—of which only the Mao recension survived complete, its prefaces and the commentary of the Eastern Han scholar <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zheng_Xuan\">Zheng Xuan</span> shaping its reading for centuries afterward. Honoured as one of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five_Classics\">Five Classics</span></b>—together with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Book_of_Documents\"><i>Book of Documents</i></span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Book_of_Rites\"><i>Book of Rites</i></span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"I_Ching\"><i>Book of Changes</i></span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Spring_and_Autumn_Annals\"><i>Spring and Autumn Annals</i></span>—and absorbed into the wider canon of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Books_and_Five_Classics\">Four Books and Five Classics</span>, it was memorised by candidates for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examinations</span> and reinterpreted by figures such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song</span>-dynasty <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Neo-Confucianism\">Neo-Confucian</span> master <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_Xi\">Zhu Xi</span>, exerting an influence on Chinese verse that has endured for more than 2,500 years.","citation":"","answerText":"Classic of Poetry"},{"id":"cnc-012","num":"十二","category":"China · Culture","question":"Represented by a circle split into swirling dark and light halves, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> describes how seemingly opposite forces — such as shadow and light, female and male — are in fact complementary and interdependent in Taoist and broader Chinese thought, underpinning traditional medicine.","answer":"Yin and yang","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">阴阳 (yīnyáng, 'shadow and light'), the shaded and sunlit sides of a hill</span></div>","traditional":"陰陽","hanzi":"阴阳","pinyin":"yīnyáng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">yīnyáng</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“shadow and light”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Yin and yang</b> is a foundational concept of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_philosophy\">Chinese philosophy</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Taoist</span> cosmology, describing how seemingly opposite forces—such as dark and light or female and male—are in reality complementary, interdependent, and continually giving rise to one another. Its best-known emblem is the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taijitu\">taijitu</span>, a circle split by a curving line into a dark yin half and a bright yang half, each bearing a dot of the opposite colour, an image that in <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiji_(philosophy)\">Supreme Ultimate</span></b> cosmology depicts the primordial unity from which both principles emerge out of the undifferentiated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuji_(philosophy)\">Wuji</span>, or limitless void. Yin is conventionally linked with darkness, the moon, the feminine, cold, water, and stillness, whereas yang corresponds to light, the sun, the masculine, heat, fire, and activity, the former aligned with the receptive Earth and the latter with creative <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tian\">Heaven</span>, a scheme of correspondences that extends to the seasons, the directions, and the flow of vital <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qi\">qi</span> through the body. Rather than static opposites, the pair forms a dynamic <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dualistic_cosmology\">dualism</span></b> in which each waxes as the other wanes, each depends upon the other for its very definition, and each turns into its opposite upon reaching its extreme, so that the deepest midnight already holds the first stirring of dawn. Although the paired terms appear in early inscriptions merely denoting the shady and sunny sides of a hill, their philosophical elaboration is rooted in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"I_Ching\"><i>Book of Changes</i></span>, whose broken and solid lines combine into the 8 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bagua\">trigrams</span> and 64 <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hexagram_(I_Ching)\">hexagrams</span></b>, and in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tao_Te_Ching\"><i>Tao Te Ching</i></span> attributed to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Laozi\">Laozi</span>, which holds that the myriad things carry yin and embrace yang. <br> <br> During the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warring_States_period\">Warring States period</span> the concept was systematised by the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"School_of_Naturalists\">School of Yin-Yang</span></b>, whose leading figure <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zou_Yan\">Zou Yan</span> fused it with the doctrine of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuxing_(Chinese_philosophy)\">Five Phases</span>—wood, fire, earth, metal, and water—to account for natural cycles and the rise and fall of dynasties. Under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span> these ideas were woven into an elaborate correlative cosmology by thinkers such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dong_Zhongshu\">Dong Zhongshu</span>, who aligned the alternation of yin and yang with the calendar, the conduct of government, and a moral order binding <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> ethics to the patterns of nature. Centuries later the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song</span>-dynasty <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Neo-Confucianism\">Neo-Confucian</span> philosopher <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Dunyi\">Zhou Dunyi</span></b> placed this alternation at the heart of his celebrated diagram of the Supreme Ultimate, supplying a metaphysical framework that would shape orthodox Chinese thought for generations. In <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Traditional_Chinese_medicine\">traditional Chinese medicine</span>, codified in the ancient canon known as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huangdi_Neijing\"><i>Huangdi Neijing</i></span>, health is understood as a harmonious balance of yin and yang within the body's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zang-fu\">organ systems</span>, while disease signals an excess or deficiency that practitioners aim to correct through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Acupuncture\">acupuncture</span>, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_herbology\">herbal medicine</span></b>, dietary regulation, and the management of qi along the body's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Meridian_(Chinese_medicine)\">meridians</span>. Beyond medicine, the polarity pervades Chinese cultural life—from the geomancy of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Feng_shui\">feng shui</span> and the slow paired movements of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tai_chi\">tai chi</span> to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_astrology\">astrological</span> calculation and the relativistic vision of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuangzi_(book)\"><i>Zhuangzi</i></span>—so that a single circle of intertwined dark and light has come to stand among the most recognisable symbols of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tao\">the Dao</span> and of Chinese thought across the world.","citation":"","answerText":"Yin and yang"},{"id":"cnc-013","num":"十三","category":"China · Culture","question":"A fivefold scheme of agents — wood, fire, earth, metal and water — that generate and overcome one another in cycles, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> pervades Chinese medicine, geomancy and astrology.","answer":"Wu Xing","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">五行 (wǔxíng, 'five phases')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"五行","pinyin":"wǔxíng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">wǔxíng</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Five Phases”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Wu Xing</b> is the fivefold conceptual scheme that, together with the <b>polarity of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yin_and_yang\">yin and yang</span></b> and the vital breath of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qi\">qi</span>, forms the backbone of traditional Chinese correlative cosmology. Its five agents—wood, fire, earth, metal, and water—are conceived less as static substances than as dynamic phases of transformation, linked in a generating cycle in which wood feeds fire, fire produces the ash that becomes earth, earth yields metal, metal collects water, and water in turn nourishes wood. In a complementary cycle of conquest the phases also overcome one another, as wood parts the earth, earth dams and absorbs water, water extinguishes fire, fire melts metal, and metal cuts through wood, the opposed cycles of generation and restraint together producing a self-regulating balance. The scheme was given systematic form during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warring_States_period\">Warring States period</span> by the cosmologist <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zou_Yan\">Zou Yan</span></b>, founder of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"School_of_Naturalists\">School of Naturalists</span> among the contending <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hundred_Schools_of_Thought\">Hundred Schools of Thought</span>, and was later fused with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucianism</span> by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span> scholar <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dong_Zhongshu\">Dong Zhongshu</span>. Elements of the doctrine appear as early as the \"Great Plan\" chapter of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Book_of_Documents\"><i>Book of Documents</i></span> and were elaborated in encyclopaedic compilations such as <b>the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lüshi_Chunqiu\"><i>Lüshi Chunqiu</i></span> of about 239 BCE</b> and the later <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huainanzi\"><i>Huainanzi</i></span>, which matched the five phases to the seasons, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cardinal_direction\">cardinal directions</span>, colours, flavours, and many other categories of experience.<br> <br>Politically, Zou Yan applied the phases to dynastic legitimacy in his theory of the five powers, holding that each ruling house governed under the aegis of one phase and that the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mandate_of_Heaven\">Mandate of Heaven</span> passed along the cycle, so that on <b>unifying China in 221 BCE</b> the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_dynasty\">Qin dynasty</span> proclaimed itself the black phase of water in succession to the fire of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_dynasty\">Zhou dynasty</span>, a logic that underpinned the broader <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dynastic_cycle\">dynastic cycle</span>. The system became foundational to Chinese medicine through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huangdi_Neijing\"><i>Huangdi Neijing</i></span>, the canonical text attributed to the legendary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_Emperor\">Yellow Emperor</span>, which correlated the five principal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zang-fu\">visceral organs</span>—the liver with wood, the heart with fire, the spleen with earth, the lungs with metal, and the kidneys with water—so that the generating and controlling relations could guide diagnosis and therapy. It likewise structured the reckoning of time and fate, pairing the five phases with the 10 <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heavenly_Stems\">Heavenly Stems</span></b> that, in combination with the 12 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Earthly_Branches\">earthly branches</span>, generate the 60-year <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sexagenary_cycle\">sexagenary cycle</span> underlying the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_calendar\">Chinese calendar</span>, geomancy, and horoscopy alike. Its reach extended into the arts and beyond, governing the five notes of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pentatonic_scale\">pentatonic scale</span></b>, lending its structure to internal martial arts such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xingyiquan\">Xingyiquan</span>, and even supplying the Chinese names of the five visible planets—<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jupiter\">Jupiter</span> for wood, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mars\">Mars</span> for fire, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Saturn\">Saturn</span> for earth, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Venus\">Venus</span> for metal, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mercury_(planet)\">Mercury</span> for water. Unlike the four <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Classical_element\">classical elements</span></b> posited by the Greek philosopher <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empedocles\">Empedocles</span>, which were understood as the static stuff of which matter is composed, the five phases describe processes and relations of mutual production and restraint, a distinctively dynamic conception that has shaped East Asian thought from antiquity to the present day.","citation":"","answerText":"Wu Xing"},{"id":"cnc-014","num":"十四","category":"China · Culture","question":"A 7-stringed zither plucked to produce soft, subtle tones, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was the favoured companion of scholar-officials and is counted among the \"four arts\" alongside calligraphy, painting and the strategy game Go.","answer":"Guqin","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">古琴 (gǔqín, 'ancient zither')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"古琴","pinyin":"gǔqín","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">gǔqín</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“ancient qin”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Guqin</b> is a plucked, 7-stringed Chinese <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zither\">zither</span></b> celebrated for its soft, subtle, and introspective tone. Long the favoured instrument of the cultivated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Scholar-official\">scholar-official</span>, it stands first among the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_arts\">four arts</span> that defined the accomplished gentleman, ranked beside <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_calligraphy\">calligraphy</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ink_wash_painting\">painting</span>, and the board game <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Go_(game)\">Go</span>. Rather than a vehicle for public display, it was played quietly for personal <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Self-cultivation\">self-cultivation</span></b> or before a single sympathetic listener, in keeping with the contemplative ideals of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Taoism</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucianism</span>. Its long <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lacquer\">lacquered</span> soundbox of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paulownia\">paulownia</span> wood carries 7 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk\">silk</span> strings and a row of 13 <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nacre\">mother-of-pearl</span></b> studs marking the harmonic nodes, while tradition reads cosmic meaning into its very dimensions, the original 5 strings standing for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuxing_(Chinese_philosophy)\">five phases</span> before two more were added by the Zhou kings <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Wen_of_Zhou\">Wen</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Wu_of_Zhou\">Wu</span>. The player draws sharply contrasting timbres from it — open strings, stopped notes, and ethereal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Harmonic\">harmonics</span> — guided by a distinctive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Musical_notation\">tablature</span> that prescribes finger techniques and string positions rather than fixed pitches. <br> <br> Among the most venerable instruments in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Music_of_China\">music of China</span></b>, the qin has been played for some 3,000 years and was, by tradition, mastered by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucius\">Confucius</span> himself. Its lore brims with tales of true friendship, above all that of the legendary player <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boya\">Boya</span>, who is said to have smashed his instrument and never played again after the one friend who truly understood his music died. The philosopher <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ji_Kang\">Xi Kang</span>, one of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Seven_Sages_of_the_Bamboo_Grove\">Seven Sages of the Bamboo Grove</span></b>, is famed for performing the piece <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangling_San\"><i>Guangling San</i></span> before his execution, while earlier masters such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Xiangru\">Sima Xiangru</span> and <b>the poet <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cai_Wenji\">Cai Wenji</span></b> were celebrated for their artistry upon it. Playable instruments survive from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang dynasty</span>, and the oldest surviving written music for the qin, preserved in a Tang copy of the melody <i>Jieshi Diao Youlan</i>, ranks among the earliest notated compositions in the world. Its music was proclaimed by <b>UNESCO a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Masterpieces_of_the_Oral_and_Intangible_Heritage_of_Humanity\">Masterpiece of the Oral and Intangible Heritage of Humanity</span> in 2003</b>, and a recording of the piece <i>Flowing Water</i> played by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guan_Pinghu\">Guan Pinghu</span> was carried into interstellar space aboard the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Voyager_Golden_Record\">Voyager Golden Record</span>, a lasting emblem of the refined art of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Guqin"},{"id":"cnc-015","num":"十五","category":"China · Culture","question":"Flourishing during the turbulent Spring and Autumn and Warring States periods, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> produced rival philosophies — among them Confucianism, Daoism, Mohism and Legalism — competing to bring order to a divided land.","answer":"Hundred Schools of Thought","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">诸子百家 ('the many masters and hundred schools')</span></div>","traditional":"諸子百家","hanzi":"诸子百家","pinyin":"Zhūzǐ Bǎijiā","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhūzǐ Bǎijiā</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“the various masters and hundred schools”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Hundred Schools of Thought</b> denotes the <b>great efflorescence of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_philosophy\">philosophy</span></b> and political theory that unfolded in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> from roughly the 6th to the 3rd centuries BCE. The ferment coincided with the breakdown of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_dynasty\">Zhou dynasty</span> order during the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Spring_and_Autumn_period\">Spring and Autumn</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warring_States_period\">Warring States</span> periods, when the erosion of the old <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fengjian\">feudal</span> aristocracy threw open careers to itinerant scholars known as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shi_(class)\">shi</span>. Rival lords seeking advantage patronised these wandering advisers, most famously at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jixia_Academy\">Jixia Academy</span></b> in the state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qi_(state)\">Qi</span>, which at its height is said to have hosted hundreds of resident masters. The phrase itself derives from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han</span> historian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Qian\">Sima Qian</span> and the bibliographic treatise of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ban_Gu\">Ban Gu</span></b>, whose <i><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Book_of_Han\">Book of Han</span></i> classified the welter of thinkers into a canonical scheme of competing lineages. Although tradition speaks of a hundred, the surviving record centres on perhaps a dozen identifiable currents whose debates over ethics, government, and the cosmos would shape East Asian civilisation for two millennia. <br> <br> Foremost among them was <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucianism</span>, founded by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucius\">Confucius</span> and elaborated by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mencius\">Mencius</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xunzi_(philosopher)\">Xunzi</span>, which located social harmony in ritual propriety, filial duty, and the cultivation of virtue. Against it stood <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Daoism</span>, associated with the figures <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Laozi\">Laozi</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuangzi_(philosopher)\">Zhuangzi</span></b>, which counselled accord with the spontaneous patterns of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tao\">Dao</span> and distrust of artificial striving. The utilitarian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mohism\">Mohists</span>, following <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mozi\">Mozi</span>, preached universal love and condemned offensive warfare, while the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Legalism_(Chinese_philosophy)\">Legalists</span> theorised by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Fei\">Han Fei</span> and implemented by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shang_Yang\">Shang Yang</span> staked everything on strict law, reward, and punishment. Lesser currents proliferated alongside them, including the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"School_of_Names\">School of Names</span> with its logical paradoxes, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"School_of_Naturalists\">School of Yin-Yang</span> exploring cosmic correspondences, the diplomatic strategists of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"School_of_Diplomacy\">School of Diplomacy</span></b>, and the agrarian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Agriculturalism\">Agriculturalists</span>. The contest narrowed sharply after <b>the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_dynasty\">Qin</span> unification of 221 BCE</b> imposed Legalist orthodoxy and reportedly carried out a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Burning_of_books_and_burying_of_scholars\">burning of books</span>, yet the ideas endured to be synthesised under the Han, when Confucianism was elevated to the doctrine of state.","citation":"","answerText":"Hundred Schools of Thought"},{"id":"cnc-016","num":"十六","category":"China · Culture","question":"A semi-legendary sage said to have been an archivist of the Zhou court who left society riding an ox, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is traditionally credited with authoring the seminal text of Taoism and is venerated as a deity in popular religion.","answer":"Laozi","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">trad. 6th c. BCE</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"老子","pinyin":"Lǎozǐ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Lǎozǐ</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Old Master”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Laozi</b> was a semi-legendary <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_philosophy\">philosopher</span></b> and writer revered as the founder of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Taoism</span>. According to the earliest surviving account, preserved in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Records_of_the_Grand_Historian\"><i>Records of the Grand Historian</i></span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Qian\">Sima Qian</span>, his personal name was Li Er and he hailed from the southern state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chu_(state)\">Chu</span>, serving as keeper of the archives at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_dynasty\">Zhou</span> royal court in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luoyang\">Luoyang</span>. Tradition holds that the younger <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucius\">Confucius</span> once sought him out to ask about ritual and came away likening the elder to an unfathomable dragon, an anecdote later cherished by Taoists as evidence of their school's seniority over <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucianism</span>. Disheartened by the decay of the realm, he is said to have departed westward riding an ox, and at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hangu_Pass\">Hangu Pass</span></b> the gatekeeper <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yinxi\">Yinxi</span> entreated him to set down his teaching before he vanished from history. The result was the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tao_Te_Ching\"><i>Tao Te Ching</i></span>, a terse work of roughly 5,000 characters in 81 brief chapters that expounds the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tao\">Dao</span>, or Way, the cultivation of inner power or <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"De_(Chinese)\">de</span>, and the <b>ideal of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_wei\">wu wei</span></b>, effortless action attuned to the natural order. <br> <br> Modern scholarship treats Laozi as a likely composite or legendary figure, observing that Sima Qian himself confessed uncertainty and that the received text more plausibly coalesced during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warring_States_period\">Warring States</span> period of the 4th to 3rd centuries BCE, near the era of the philosopher <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuangzi_(philosopher)\">Zhuangzi</span>. Excavated manuscripts have reshaped understanding of the work, the silk copies recovered <b>from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mawangdui_Silk_Texts\">Mawangdui</span> in 1973</b> and the bamboo slips unearthed at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guodian_Chu_Slips\">Guodian</span> around 300 BCE preserving recensions older than any previously available. As Taoism matured into an organised religion, Laozi was progressively deified, worshipped under the title <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taishang_Laojun\">Taishang Laojun</span> and ranked among the supreme <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Pure_Ones\">Three Pure Ones</span></b>, becoming a god of great consequence in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_folk_religion\">Chinese folk religion</span>. The earliest organised Taoist movement, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Way_of_the_Celestial_Masters\">Way of the Celestial Masters</span> founded by <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Daoling\">Zhang Daoling</span></b> in the 2nd century CE, claimed direct revelation from him, and centuries afterward the rulers of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang dynasty</span>, sharing his reputed surname <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_(surname_李)\">Li</span>, proclaimed him their divine ancestor. His influence radiated widely, drawing an early commentary from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Legalism_(Chinese_philosophy)\">Legalist</span> thinker <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Fei\">Han Fei</span> and later inspiring the polemical <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huahujing\"><i>Huahujing</i></span></b>, which claimed he had travelled west to instruct the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gautama_Buddha\">Buddha</span>, while the <i>Tao Te Ching</i> endured to become among the most frequently translated works in all of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>'s literary heritage.","citation":"","answerText":"Laozi"},{"id":"cnc-017","num":"十七","category":"China · Culture","question":"Centred on living in harmony with an ineffable cosmic Way and the principle of effortless action, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> — both a philosophy and an organised religion with its own deities and rituals — traces its roots to Laozi.","answer":"Taoism","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">道教 (Dàojiào, 'teaching of the Way')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"道教","pinyin":"Dàojiào","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Dàojiào</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“teaching of the Way”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Taoism</b> is a tradition centred on living in harmony with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tao\">Tao</span>, the ineffable source and pattern of the cosmos, through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_wei\">wu wei</span> or effortless action, and it traces its roots to <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Laozi\">Laozi</span></b>, a possibly legendary archivist of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_dynasty\">Zhou dynasty</span> court traditionally dated to the 6th century BCE. The foundational scripture attributed to him, the roughly 5,000-character <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tao_Te_Ching\"><i>Tao Te Ching</i></span> in 81 brief chapters, celebrates spontaneity, softness, and rulership so unobtrusive that the people say \"we did it ourselves,\" and its earliest excavated copies, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guodian_Chu_Slips\">Guodian bamboo slips</span>, <b>date to around 300 BCE</b>. A 2nd major stream flows from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuang_Zhou\">Zhuang Zhou</span> (4th century BCE), whose eponymous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuangzi_(book)\"><i>Zhuangzi</i></span> uses parables such as the philosopher dreaming he is a butterfly to dissolve fixed distinctions, securing the school a place among the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hundred_Schools_of_Thought\">Hundred Schools of Thought</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warring_States_period\">Warring States period</span>. Its vocabulary of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ziran\">ziran</span> (naturalness), <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yin_and_yang\">yin and yang</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qi\">qi</span> shaped early imperial statecraft, and the syncretic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huang–Lao\">Huang–Lao</span> teaching guided ministers of the early <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span> before <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucianism</span> <b>became orthodoxy in 136 BCE</b>. By the 2nd century CE Laozi had been deified as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taishang_Laojun\">Taishang Laojun</span>, receiving imperial sacrifice from Emperor Huan in 165 CE. <br> <br> Organized religious Taoism began in 142 CE, when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Daoling\">Zhang Daoling</span> reported a revelation from the deified Laozi and founded the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Way_of_the_Celestial_Masters\">Way of the Celestial Masters</span></b>, whose tithe of 5 pecks of rice supported a virtual theocracy in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan\">Sichuan</span>. New revelations produced the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shangqing_School\">Shangqing</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lingbao_School\">Lingbao</span> scriptural corpora in the 4th century CE, while seekers of immortality as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xian_(Taoism)\">xian</span> pursued the elixirs catalogued by <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ge_Hong\">Ge Hong</span></b> and later the meditative \"inner alchemy\" of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Neidan\">neidan</span>. The tradition developed a vast pantheon headed by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Pure_Ones\">Three Pure Ones</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jade_Emperor\">Jade Emperor</span>, and its canon, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Daozang\">Daozang</span>, reached about 1,400 works in the <b>printing of 1445</b>, having enjoyed lavish patronage from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang dynasty</span> emperors, who claimed descent from Laozi himself. Since the 12th century 2 schools have predominated: the monastic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Quanzhen_School\">Quanzhen</span> order, headquartered at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"White_Cloud_Temple\">White Cloud Temple</span> in Beijing, and the householder priests of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhengyi_Dao\">Zhengyi</span>, heirs of the Celestial Masters. Though temples were devastated during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span>, Taoism is today 1 of 5 state-recognized religions overseen by the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Taoist_Association\">Chinese Taoist Association</span></b>, with surveys counting roughly 12 million self-identified adherents, while practices it nourished—<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Traditional_Chinese_medicine\">traditional medicine</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Feng_shui\">feng shui</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tai_chi\">tai chi</span>—touch hundreds of millions more.","citation":"","answerText":"Taoism"},{"id":"cnc-018","num":"十八","category":"China · Culture","question":"A short, cryptic work of about 81 brief chapters in verse, traditionally ascribed to Laozi, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> teaches the elusive Way and the value of non-action.","answer":"Tao Te Ching","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. 4th c. BCE</span></div>","traditional":"道德經","hanzi":"道德经","pinyin":"Dàodéjīng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Dàodéjīng</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Classic of the Way and Virtue”</span></div>","abstract":"<b><i>Tao Te Ching</i></b> is the foundational scripture of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Taoism</span>, traditionally attributed to the semi-legendary sage <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Laozi\">Laozi</span>. Its title joins the words for the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tao\">Dao</span></b>, the ineffable Way, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"De_(Chinese)\">de</span>, inner virtue or power, and the work comprises roughly 5,000 characters of terse <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Classical_Chinese\">Classical Chinese</span> arranged in 81 short chapters. Conventionally it falls into two parts, the Dao section spanning the first 37 chapters and the De section comprising the remainder, a sequence that the archaeological manuscripts would later be found to reverse. Composed in a cryptic, aphoristic verse rich in paradox, it celebrates the <b>supreme value of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_wei\">wu wei</span></b>, or non-action, alongside the related ideals of naturalness, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ziran\">ziran</span>, and the simplicity of the uncarved block, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pu_(Taoism)\">pu</span>. Recurring images of water, the yielding feminine, and the empty vessel illustrate how softness overcomes hardness, while the ideal <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sage_(philosophy)\">sage</span></b>-ruler is said to govern best through restraint, attuned to the cosmic balance of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yin_and_yang\">yin and yang</span>. <br> <br> Although a tradition recorded by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Qian\">Sima Qian</span> places its composition in the 6th century BCE, most scholars now date the received text to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warring_States_period\">Warring States</span> period of the 4th to 3rd centuries BCE, regarding it as an accreted anthology roughly contemporary with the writings of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuangzi_(book)\"><i>Zhuangzi</i></span>. This later dating is reinforced by the oldest known witnesses, the bamboo slips <b>excavated at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guodian_Chu_Slips\">Guodian</span> around 300 BCE</b> and the two silk manuscripts unearthed at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mawangdui_Silk_Texts\">Mawangdui</span> in 1973, both differing markedly from the transmitted version. Generations of interpretation followed celebrated commentaries, the cosmological reading ascribed to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heshang_Gong\">Heshang Gong</span> under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han</span>, the philosophical gloss of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Bi\">Wang Bi</span> in the 3rd century CE, and the religious <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiang'er\">Xiang'er</span> commentary tied to the early <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Way_of_the_Celestial_Masters\">Celestial Masters</span></b>, who absorbed the scripture into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Daozang\">Taoist canon</span>. Its authority radiated across rival traditions, prompting an early commentary from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Legalism_(Chinese_philosophy)\">Legalist</span> thinker <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Fei\">Han Fei</span>, shaping the development of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chan_Buddhism\">Chan Buddhism</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Neo-Confucianism\">Neo-Confucianism</span>, and even attracting an imperial exegesis from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span> emperor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Xuanzong_of_Tang\">Xuanzong</span>. Beyond <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> it became one of the most frequently translated works in world literature, carried into Western languages by scholars such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"James_Legge\">James Legge</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Arthur_Waley\">Arthur Waley</span>, with English renderings alone numbering in the hundreds and its worldwide circulation frequently said to trail only that of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bible\">Bible</span></b>.","citation":"","answerText":"Tao Te Ching"},{"id":"cnc-019","num":"十九","category":"China · Culture","question":"A central Taoist ideal sometimes rendered as \"effortless action\" or \"non-doing\", the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> counsels acting in spontaneous accord with the natural flow of things rather than through forced striving, a theme explored at length in the writings attributed to Zhuang Zhou.","answer":"Wu wei","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">无为 (wúwéi, 'non-action')</span></div>","traditional":"無為","hanzi":"无为","pinyin":"wúwéi","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">wúwéi</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“non-action”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Wu wei</b> is a central ideal of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Taoism</span> that counsels acting in spontaneous accord with the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tao\">Tao</span></b>, the natural flow of things, rather than through forced and self-assertive striving. The concept pervades the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tao_Te_Ching\"><i>Tao Te Ching</i></span> attributed to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Laozi\">Laozi</span>, whose 81 chapters paradoxically promise that \"the Way does nothing, yet nothing is left undone,\" compare the sage to water that benefits all things without contending, and advise ruling a great state as one cooks a small fish, so lightly that the people say \"we did it ourselves.\" Its richest illustrations come in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuangzi_(book)\"><i>Zhuangzi</i></span> attributed to <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuang_Zhou\">Zhuang Zhou</span></b> (4th century BCE), where a butcher carves oxen for 19 years without dulling his blade by following the natural seams, and a swimmer survives a cataract by yielding to the water's own course, embodying perfected skill as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ziran\">ziran</span> or self-so spontaneity. The ideal was not exclusively Taoist, for even the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Analects\"><i>Analects</i></span> reports <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucius\">Confucius</span> praising the sage-king <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Shun\">Shun</span> for governing by wu wei, merely facing south with reverence. As practical statecraft it triumphed under the syncretic <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huang–Lao\">Huang–Lao</span></b> teaching of the early <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span>, when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Wen_of_Han\">Emperor Wen</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Jing_of_Han\">Emperor Jing</span> presided over the frugal <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rule_of_Wen_and_Jing\">Rule of Wen and Jing</span></b>, cutting the land tax to 1/30th of the harvest. <br> <br> Even the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Legalism_(Chinese_philosophy)\">Legalist</span> theorist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Fei\">Han Fei</span> (3rd century BCE) appropriated the term, urging the ruler to remain still and inscrutable while his ministers exhaust themselves, and the 2nd-century BCE compendium <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huainanzi\"><i>Huainanzi</i></span> recast wu wei as acting only in alignment with circumstance. Commentators such as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heshang_Gong\">Heshang Gong</span></b>, the prodigy <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Bi\">Wang Bi</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guo_Xiang\">Guo Xiang</span> of the 3rd-century CE <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xuanxue\">Xuanxue</span> movement refined it into a metaphysics of non-purposive action, while religious Taoists cultivated it through meditative practices like <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zuowang\">zuowang</span></b>, \"sitting in forgetfulness.\" The ideal flowed into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chan_Buddhism\">Chan Buddhism</span> and thence into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zen\">Zen</span>, informing the Japanese aesthetic of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mushin_(mental_state)\">mushin</span> or \"no-mind\" and the bodily training of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tai_chi\">tai chi</span>. Western interpreters from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joseph_Needham\">Joseph Needham</span>, who glossed it as refraining from action contrary to nature, to the popularizer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Alan_Watts\">Alan Watts</span> carried the notion abroad, and psychologists compare it to the absorbed state that <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mihaly_Csikszentmihalyi\">Mihaly Csikszentmihalyi</span></b> termed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Flow_(psychology)\">flow</span>. The sinologist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Edward_Slingerland\">Edward Slingerland</span> has even framed wu wei through cognitive science as the paradox of \"trying not to try,\" evidence that a concept first articulated some 2,400 years ago still poses live questions about effort, skill, and spontaneity.","citation":"","answerText":"Wu wei"},{"id":"cnc-022","num":"二十二","category":"China · Culture","question":"Stressing that the supreme skill is to subdue an enemy without fighting, and emphasising deception, terrain and spies, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> has profoundly shaped thinking on strategy far beyond warfare.","answer":"The Art of War","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. 5th c. BCE</span></div>","traditional":"孫子兵法","hanzi":"孙子兵法","pinyin":"Sūnzǐ Bīngfǎ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Sūnzǐ Bīngfǎ</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Master Sun's Military Methods”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b><i>The Art of War</i></b> is an ancient <b>Chinese treatise on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"War\">warfare</span></b> attributed to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Tzu\">Sun Tzu</span>, a general said to have come from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qi_(state)\">Qi</span> and served <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Helü_of_Wu\">King Helü</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_(state)\">Wu</span> in the late 6th century BCE, near the end of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Spring_and_Autumn_period\">Spring and Autumn period</span>. Modern scholarship places its compilation in the 5th century BCE, early in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warring_States_period\">Warring States period</span>, as a compact text of 13 chapters running to roughly 6,000 characters. Its teaching begins from 5 fundamental factors—the moral <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tao\">Way</span>, heaven, earth, command, and method—calculated in the temple before a single soldier moves, and it insists that the highest skill lies in subduing the enemy without fighting, since prolonged campaigns ruin states and a besieged city is the worst of all options. Declaring that \"all warfare is based on deception,\" it counsels feigned weakness, formlessness like water, mastery of terrain, and speed, closing with a chapter on the 5 kinds of agents used in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Espionage\">espionage</span>, on whom foreknowledge wholly depends. Doubts about the author's historicity were <b>reshaped in 1972</b>, when a tomb sealed between about 140 and 118 BCE at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yinqueshan_Han_Slips\">Yinqueshan</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shandong\">Shandong</span> yielded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bamboo_and_wooden_slips\">bamboo slips</span> of the text alongside a long-lost companion treatise by the <b>later strategist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Bin\">Sun Bin</span></b>, proving the 2 works distinct. <br> <br> The warlord <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cao_Cao\">Cao Cao</span> wrote the earliest surviving commentary in the 3rd century CE, and under <b>the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song dynasty</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Shenzong_of_Song\">Emperor Shenzong</span> in 1080</b> placed the work first among the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Seven_Military_Classics\">Seven Military Classics</span>, the canon of the empire's military <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">examinations</span>. The book reached <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japan\">Japan</span> by around 760 and saturated the strategy of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sengoku_period\">Sengoku period</span>, most visibly in the banner of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Takeda_Shingen\">Takeda Shingen</span>, whose motto \"wind, forest, fire, mountain\" quotes chapter 7. Europe met the text through a French rendering by <b>the Jesuit <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jean_Joseph_Marie_Amiot\">Jean Joseph Marie Amiot</span> in 1772</b>, reputedly known to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Napoleon\">Napoleon</span>, while the influential English version of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lionel_Giles\">Lionel Giles</span> followed in 1910. Its maxims on deception and protracted war guided <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>'s guerrilla doctrine and the campaigns of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Võ_Nguyên_Giáp\">Võ Nguyên Giáp</span> in Vietnam, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States_Marine_Corps\">United States Marine Corps</span> placed the book on its professional reading list, with commanders such as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Norman_Schwarzkopf\">Norman Schwarzkopf</span></b> citing it during the 1991 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gulf_War\">Gulf War</span>. Translated into more than 30 languages, it is now mined far beyond the battlefield—by theorists of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Strategic_management\">strategic management</span>, litigators, athletes, and even the fictional corporate raider of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wall_Street_(1987_film)\"><i>Wall Street</i></span>—making a 2,400-year-old field manual one of the most <b>quoted books on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Strategy\">strategy</span></b> ever written.","citation":"","answerText":"The Art of War"},{"id":"cnc-023","num":"二十三","category":"China · Culture","question":"Compiled by followers after their master's death, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was memorised by generations preparing for the examinations as one of the Four Books.","answer":"Analects","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">5th c. BCE</span></div>","traditional":"論語","hanzi":"论语","pinyin":"Lúnyǔ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Lúnyǔ</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“selected sayings”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b><i>Analects</i></b> is a compilation of aphorisms and short dialogues recording the teachings of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucius\">Confucius</span></b> and his immediate disciples, long regarded as the foundational scripture of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucianism</span>. Rather than the work of a single hand, it was assembled gradually by followers after <b>the master's death in 479 BCE</b>, accreting successive layers across the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Spring_and_Autumn_period\">Spring and Autumn</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warring_States_period\">Warring States</span> periods before approaching its received form under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span>. In its standard arrangement the work comprises 20 chapters containing roughly 500 brief passages and some 15,900 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_characters\">Chinese characters</span>, many of them introduced by the recurring formula “the Master said.” During the Han three distinct recensions circulated — the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lu_(state)\">Lu</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qi_(state)\">Qi</span> versions transmitted by separate lineages and an “Old Text” recension reputedly recovered from a wall of Confucius's former house — until the scholar Zhang Yu fused them into the conflated edition that later became standard. Archaeology has illuminated this early history most strikingly through bamboo-strip fragments <b>unearthed in 1973</b> from a tomb at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dingzhou\">Dingzhou</span> sealed in 55 BCE, which preserve a recension predating the modern vulgate. <br> <br> The teachings recorded in the work revolve around the cultivation of moral character, foregrounding the virtues of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ren_(Confucianism)\">ren</span>, or humaneness, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_(Confucianism)\">li</span>, the ritual propriety governing conduct, as the means by which an ordinary person becomes a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Junzi\">junzi</span> or exemplary individual. Allied ideals such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Filial_piety\">filial piety</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yi_(Confucianism)\">righteousness</span></b> recur throughout, alongside the conviction that a ruler governs best through moral example rather than coercion, and one celebrated passage frames an early version of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Golden_Rule\">Golden Rule</span>, enjoining that one should not impose on others what one does not desire for oneself. Generations of scholars layered commentary upon the terse original, from the collected glosses assembled by <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"He_Yan\">He Yan</span></b> under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cao_Wei\">Cao Wei</span> state to the magisterial rereading of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song</span> philosopher <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_Xi\">Zhu Xi</span>, whose <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Neo-Confucianism\">Neo-Confucian</span> interpretation became orthodox. It was Zhu Xi who in the 12th century grouped the text with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Learning\"><i>Great Learning</i></span>, the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Doctrine_of_the_Mean\"><i>Doctrine of the Mean</i></span></b>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mencius_(book)\"><i>Mencius</i></span> to form the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Books\">Four Books</span>, the core curriculum that candidates committed to memory for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examinations</span> <b>until their abolition in 1905</b>. Beyond <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> the work shaped governance and learning across the wider <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"East_Asian_cultural_sphere\">East Asian cultural sphere</span>, taking deep root in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Korea\">Korea</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japan\">Japan</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vietnam\">Vietnam</span>, while landmark English renderings by the missionary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"James_Legge\">James Legge</span> and later the sinologist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Arthur_Waley\">Arthur Waley</span> carried its ethical vocabulary to readers in the West.","citation":"","answerText":"Analects"},{"id":"cnc-025","num":"二十五","category":"China · Culture","question":"A cardinal virtue expressed in the Chinese term <i>xiao</i>, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> demands respect, obedience and care toward one's parents and ancestors, lies at the heart of Confucian ethics, and is tied to the practice of ancestor veneration and the wider family order.","answer":"Filial piety","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">孝 (xiào): the graph shows a child supporting an elder</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"孝","pinyin":"xiào","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">xiào</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Filial piety</b> is the cardinal virtue of reverence, obedience, and devoted care owed to one's parents, elders, and ancestors, occupying the central position in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> ethics. The character 孝 pictures a child supporting an aged parent by fusing the graphic elements for “old” and “son,” and the notion is already <b>attested in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Oracle_bone_script\">oracle bone</span></b> and bronze inscriptions of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_dynasty\">Zhou dynasty</span> well before its philosophical systematisation. <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucius\">Confucius</span> treated filial conduct as the very root of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ren_(Confucianism)\">ren</span>, or humaneness, and as a <b>natural expression of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yi_(Confucianism)\">righteousness</span></b>, while the later philosopher <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mencius\">Mencius</span> made it the bedrock of a moral order extending from the household to the realm. Bound tightly to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_(Confucianism)\">li</span>, the ritual propriety governing conduct, and to the <b>practice of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_ancestral_worship\">ancestor veneration</span></b>, the duty received its classic statement in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Classic_of_Filial_Piety\"><i>Classic of Filial Piety</i></span>, a short dialogue traditionally ascribed to Confucius and his disciple <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zengzi\">Zengzi</span> and later counted among the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Thirteen_Classics\">Thirteen Classics</span></b>. Within the hierarchical scheme of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Fundamental_Bonds_and_Five_Constant_Virtues\">Five Relationships</span> the bond between father and son mirrored that between ruler and subject, so that a dutiful son was held to mature naturally into a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Loyalty\">loyal</span> servant of the throne. <br> <br> During the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span> the ideal gained institutional force through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiaolian\">xiaolian</span> system of recruitment, under which local officials nominated men reputed to be “filial and incorrupt” for entry into the bureaucracy. The duty likewise shaped an elaborate culture of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mourning\">mourning</span>, most demandingly the customary three-year withdrawal observed for a deceased parent, together with the annual tomb-sweeping of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qingming_Festival\">Qingming Festival</span>. Imperial endorsement deepened across later ages, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span> emperor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Xuanzong_of_Tang\">Xuanzong</span> composing a celebrated commentary on the canonical text, while popular instruction leaned on the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Twenty-four_Filial_Exemplars\"><i>Twenty-four Filial Exemplars</i></span></b> assembled under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan dynasty</span> and was later reinforced by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Neo-Confucianism\">Neo-Confucian</span> moralists. The spread of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Buddhism_in_China\">Buddhism</span>, whose monastic celibacy seemed to imperil the continuity of the family line, prompted accommodations such as the legend of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mulian_Rescues_His_Mother\"><i>Mulian Rescues His Mother</i></span></b> and the rites of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ghost_Festival\">Ghost Festival</span>, which recast monastic merit as repayment of parental kindness. Carried throughout the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"East_Asian_cultural_sphere\">East Asian cultural sphere</span>, the virtue became a pillar of social order in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Korea\">Korea</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japan\">Japan</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vietnam\">Vietnam</span>, and it retains legal resonance in modern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>, where a <b>2013 revision</b> of the law protecting the elderly even obliges adult children to visit their aging parents.","citation":"","answerText":"Filial piety"},{"id":"cnc-027","num":"二十七","category":"China · Culture","question":"Advocating \"impartial care\" for all people equally and condemning offensive warfare and lavish ritual, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> rivalled Confucianism before fading from influence.","answer":"Mohism","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">墨家 (Mòjiā, 'School of Mo'), after the philosopher Mozi</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"墨家","pinyin":"Mòjiā","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Mòjiā</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“School of Mo”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Mohism</b> was an influential philosophical movement of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warring_States_period\">Warring States</span> period founded by <b>the thinker <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mozi\">Mozi</span></b> in the 5th century BCE. Numbered among the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hundred_Schools_of_Thought\">Hundred Schools of Thought</span>, it stood for a time as the foremost rival of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucianism</span>, the two being paired by later writers as the most prominent doctrines of the age. Its central teaching was impartial care, the conviction that one should extend equal concern to all people rather than the graded affection favoured by Confucians, from which followed a vigorous condemnation of offensive <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"War\">warfare</span></b> as the gravest harm a state could inflict. Mohists likewise denounced the lavish <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ritual\">ritual</span>, elaborate <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Funeral\">funerals</span>, and costly court <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yayue\">music</span> prized by the elite, while upholding the moral <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tian\">Will of Heaven</span>, the existence of percipient <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ghosts_in_Chinese_culture\">spirits</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Meritocracy\">elevation of the worthy</span> to office regardless of birth, and the <b>rejection of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fatalism\">fatalism</span></b>. Underlying these positions was a strongly <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Consequentialism\">consequentialist</span> ethic that judged every practice by its tangible benefit to the common people, a stance some modern <b>scholars liken to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Utilitarianism\">utilitarianism</span></b>. <br> <br> The Mohists were organised as a tightly disciplined order under a leader titled the Juzi, or Grand Master, and were renowned as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Military_engineering\">military engineers</span> who placed their expertise at the <b>service of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Siege\">defensive siege</span></b> warfare rather than aggression. A celebrated episode recounts how Mozi walked for 10 days to dissuade the state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chu_(state)\">Chu</span> from attacking <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_(state)\">Song</span>, besting the <b>famed artisan <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lu_Ban\">Lu Ban</span></b> in a simulated contest of siege engines and counter-defences. The school's writings were gathered in the <i>Mozi</i>, whose later chapters, the work of the so-called Later Mohists, advanced sophisticated investigations of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Logic\">logic</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Epistemology\">epistemology</span>, geometry, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Optics\">optics</span>, including what is regarded as the earliest known description of a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Camera_obscura\">camera obscura</span></b>. Its doctrine of impartial care drew fierce criticism from the Confucian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mencius\">Mencius</span>, who charged that treating strangers like kin amounted to a denial of one's own father, and the school was scrutinised too by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Legalism_(Chinese_philosophy)\">Legalist</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Fei\">Han Fei</span>, who ranked it beside Confucianism as one of the two eminent learnings. Mohism declined sharply after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_dynasty\">Qin</span> unification and all but vanished once <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Wu_of_Han\">Emperor Wu of Han</span>, advised by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dong_Zhongshu\">Dong Zhongshu</span>, established Confucianism as state orthodoxy, though its texts won renewed scholarly attention during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> and among modern philosophers in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Mohism"},{"id":"cnc-029","num":"二十九","category":"China · Culture","question":"Filled with parables, paradoxes and humour — including a famous dream of being a butterfly — the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> named for its supposed author, prizes spontaneity and the relativity of human judgements, complementing the <i>Tao Te Ching</i>.","answer":"Zhuangzi","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">庄子 (Zhuāngzǐ, 'Master Zhuang'), after its author</span></div>","traditional":"莊子","hanzi":"庄子","pinyin":"Zhuāngzǐ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhuāngzǐ</span></div>","abstract":"<b><i>Zhuangzi</i></b> is, alongside the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tao_Te_Ching\"><i>Tao Te Ching</i></span></b> ascribed to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Laozi\">Laozi</span>, one of the two foundational texts of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Taoism</span>. It takes its name from its principal author, the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warring_States_period\">Warring States</span> philosopher <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuang_Zhou\">Zhuang Zhou</span></b>, a native of the town of Meng in the state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_(state)\">Song</span> traditionally dated to the 4th century BCE. The received version, comprising 33 chapters, is conventionally divided into the 7 Inner Chapters regarded as the genuine work of Zhuang Zhou, 15 Outer Chapters, and 11 Miscellaneous Chapters assembled by later hands. Unlike the gnomic verse of its companion classic, the book unfolds through a profusion of anecdotes, fables, and imaginary dialogues laced with wit, hyperbole, and deliberate absurdity, and is prized as one of the supreme achievements of early <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_literature\">Chinese literature</span>. Among its most celebrated passages are the dream in which the narrator becomes a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Butterfly\">butterfly</span></b> and awakens unsure whether he is a man who dreamt he was a butterfly or a butterfly now dreaming it is a man, the giant fish that transforms into the soaring <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peng_(mythology)\">Peng</span> bird, and the cook <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cook_Ding\">Ding</span></b> whose blade glides effortlessly through an ox. <br> <br> Philosophically the text prizes spontaneity and the relativity of all human judgements, a stance often described as a form of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Relativism\">relativism</span>, urging accord with the spontaneous flow of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tao\">Dao</span> through effortless <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_wei\">wu wei</span> and naturalness, or <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ziran\">ziran</span>. Its searching <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Philosophical_skepticism\">skepticism</span> about language and fixed categories is dramatised in playful debates with the logician <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hui_Shi\">Hui Shi</span></b> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"School_of_Names\">School of Names</span>, most famously their exchange over whether one can truly know the happiness of fish. The text that survives owes its present shape to the scholar <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guo_Xiang\">Guo Xiang</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jin_dynasty_(266–420)\">Jin dynasty</span>, who pruned an originally larger compilation down to its 33 chapters and supplied an influential commentary central to the current of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xuanxue\">Xuanxue</span>, or Mysterious Learning. Under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang dynasty</span> the emperor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Xuanzong_of_Tang\">Xuanzong</span> elevated it to canonical rank as the <i>Nanhua zhenjing</i>, the True Classic of Southern Florescence, while Zhuang Zhou himself came to be revered as a perfected being in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_folk_religion\">popular religion</span>. Its imaginative vision left a deep imprint on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chan_Buddhism\">Chan Buddhism</span>, on the poetry of figures such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Bai\">Li Bai</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tao_Yuanming\">Tao Yuanming</span></b>, and on the tradition of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shan_shui\">landscape painting</span>, while modern renderings by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Burton_Watson\">Burton Watson</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Herbert_Giles\">Herbert Giles</span>, and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Angus_Charles_Graham\">A. C. Graham</span></b> have made it a touchstone of comparative philosophy far beyond <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Zhuangzi"},{"id":"cnc-030","num":"三十","category":"China · Culture","question":"Often translated as \"vital energy\" or \"life force\", the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is believed to flow through the body along channels called meridians, and its balance is the aim of acupuncture, tai chi and other practices.","answer":"Qi","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">气 (qì, 'breath, vital energy')</span></div>","traditional":"氣","hanzi":"气","pinyin":"qì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">qì</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“breath”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Qi</b> is the vital energy or life force that traditional Chinese thought holds to constitute and animate the cosmos, circulating through the human body <b>along channels called <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Meridian_(Chinese_medicine)\">meridians</span></b>, whose balanced flow is the aim of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Acupuncture\">acupuncture</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tai_chi\">tai chi</span>, and allied practices. The graph originally pictured rising vapor, and by the 4th century BCE the \"Neiye\" chapter of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guanzi_(text)\"><i>Guanzi</i></span></b> taught its cultivation through posture and breathing, while <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mencius\">Mencius</span> spoke of nourishing a \"flood-like qi\" fed by moral conduct. Cosmologically, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tao_Te_Ching\"><i>Tao Te Ching</i></span> describes the 10,000 things blending qi between <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yin_and_yang\">yin and yang</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuangzi_(book)\"><i>Zhuangzi</i></span> defines life as qi condensing and death as its dispersal, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han</span> correlative thought meshed it with the 5 phases of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuxing_(Chinese_philosophy)\">wuxing</span>. Medicine systematized these ideas in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huangdi_Neijing\"><i>Huangdi Neijing</i></span> (2nd–1st centuries BCE), which mapped 12 primary meridians linking the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zang-fu\">zang-fu</span> organs and a classical 365 acupoints where the flow could be adjusted with needles. Bodily disciplines kept pace, from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Daoyin\">daoyin</span> gymnastics depicted in 44 exercising figures on a silk chart <b>buried at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mawangdui\">Mawangdui</span> around 168 BCE</b> to the breath-work that evolved into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Taoist</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Neidan\">inner alchemy</span> and modern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qigong\">qigong</span>. <br> <br> In <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Neo-Confucianism\">Neo-Confucian</span> philosophy, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Zai\">Zhang Zai</span></b> (11th century) built a monism in which all reality is condensing and dispersing qi, while <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_Xi\">Zhu Xi</span> paired it with immaterial principle as the 2 constituents of every thing, and the concept suffused aesthetics through the 6th-century critic <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xie_He_(art_historian)\">Xie He</span></b>, whose <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Six_principles_of_Chinese_painting\">6 principles of painting</span> rank \"spirit resonance\" of qi first. The notion remains the theoretical core of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Traditional_Chinese_medicine\">traditional Chinese medicine</span> and of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_martial_arts\">Chinese martial arts</span>, and it traveled abroad as Japanese <i>ki</i> and Korean <i>gi</i>. Modern science, however, has identified no anatomical or physiological correlate for qi or the meridians, leading mainstream sources to class the framework as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vitalism\">vitalism</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pseudoscience\">pseudoscience</span>, a judgment sharpened <b>by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"German_acupuncture_trials\">German acupuncture trials</span> of 2002–2007</b>, in which more than 1,100 low-back-pain patients responded as well to sham needling at non-points (44.2 percent) as to genuine acupuncture (47.6 percent), both beating conventional care (27.4 percent) and implying a powerful <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Placebo\">placebo</span> component rather than a detectable energy, a reading echoed in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cochrane_(organisation)\">Cochrane</span> reviews. None of this has dimmed qi's cultural force, which propelled a \"qigong fever\" of an estimated 60–100 million practitioners in 1980s–1990s China until the state, alarmed by movements such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Falun_Gong\">Falun Gong</span>, <b>banned the largest in 1999</b>, and which still guides everyday arts from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Feng_shui\">feng shui</span> to calligraphy.","citation":"","answerText":"Qi"},{"id":"cnc-031","num":"三十一","category":"China · Culture","question":"Holding that human nature is selfish and that order requires strict laws, harsh punishments and a powerful ruler, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> provided the governing philosophy of the unifying Qin dynasty under its ruthless minister Li Si and the emperor Qin Shi Huang.","answer":"Legalism","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">法家 (Fǎjiā, 'School of Law')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"法家","pinyin":"Fǎjiā","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Fǎjiā</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“School of Law”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Legalism</b> was a pragmatic school of political philosophy that arose during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warring_States_period\">Warring States</span> period and ranked among the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hundred_Schools_of_Thought\">Hundred Schools of Thought</span>. Its mature theory, synthesised by <b>the philosopher <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Fei\">Han Fei</span></b> in the 3rd century BCE, rested on a triad of interlocking instruments of rule: clear and impartial law, or <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fa_(concept)\">fa</span>, the administrative techniques by which a ruler controlled his ministers, and the raw positional power of the throne. Han Fei drew together strands developed by earlier statesmen, the codified law associated with <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shang_Yang\">Shang Yang</span></b> and the early legal code of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Kui_(legalist)\">Li Kui</span>, the bureaucratic methods of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shen_Buhai\">Shen Buhai</span>, and the doctrine of authority elaborated by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shen_Dao\">Shen Dao</span>. The school took a starkly <b>pessimistic view of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Human_nature\">human nature</span></b>, holding that people are fundamentally self-interested, in pointed contrast to the optimism of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mencius\">Mencius</span> and echoing instead the teaching of the Confucian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xunzi_(philosopher)\">Xunzi</span>, who counted both Han Fei and the <b>future chancellor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Si\">Li Si</span></b> among his pupils. Order, the Legalists insisted, depended not on moral cultivation but on a powerful sovereign wielding the “two handles” of generous reward and severe punishment through laws applied uniformly to noble and commoner alike, a programme sharply opposed to the ritual ethics of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucianism</span> and the universal love preached by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mohism\">Mohism</span>. <br> <br> The doctrine first proved its power in the state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_(state)\">Qin</span>, where <b>from 356 BCE Shang</b> Yang imposed sweeping reforms, instituting household registration, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Collective_punishment\">collective responsibility</span> for crime, and a hierarchy of ranks awarded for military and agricultural achievement rather than birth. These measures forged the formidable war machine that enabled <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_Shi_Huang\">Qin Shi Huang</span> to <b>complete the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin's_wars_of_unification\">conquest of the warring states</span> in 221 BCE</b>, founding the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_dynasty\">Qin dynasty</span> with Li Si as his chancellor and chief Legalist architect. Under their rule the empire standardised the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Small_seal_script\">script</span>, weights, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ban_Liang\">currency</span>, yet enforced ideological conformity through the notorious <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Burning_of_books_and_burying_of_scholars\">burning of books and burying of scholars</span> aimed at Confucian and other rival learning. The dynasty's severity bred widespread rebellion and it collapsed within 15 years of unification, its chancellor Li Si falling to the intrigues of the eunuch <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhao_Gao\">Zhao Gao</span>, after which the succeeding <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span> publicly repudiated Legalism in favour of Confucian orthodoxy while quietly preserving much of its centralised <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bureaucracy\">bureaucratic</span> machinery. Often likened by later observers to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Realpolitik\">realpolitik</span>, to the statecraft of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Niccolò_Machiavelli\">Machiavelli</span>, and even to modern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Totalitarianism\">totalitarianism</span>, Legalist principles continued to shape the administration of imperial <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> for two millennia, and the school's foundational writings survive in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Feizi\"><i>Han Feizi</i></span> and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Book_of_Lord_Shang\"><i>Book of Lord Shang</i></span></b>.","citation":"","answerText":"Legalism"},{"id":"cnc-033","num":"三十三","category":"China · Culture","question":"An anthology of richly imaginative, shamanistic verse from the southern state of Chu, much of it attributed to Qu Yuan, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> stands alongside the <i>Classic of Poetry</i> as a fountainhead of the Chinese poetic tradition.","answer":"Chu Ci","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">楚辞 (Chǔcí, 'Verses of Chu')</span></div>","traditional":"楚辭","hanzi":"楚辞","pinyin":"Chǔcí","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Chǔcí</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Verses of Chu”</span></div>","abstract":"<b><i>Chu Ci</i></b> is an anthology of ancient <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_poetry\">Chinese poetry</span></b> arising from the southern state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chu_(state)\">Chu</span> during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warring_States_period\">Warring States period</span>, attributed in large part to the poet-statesman <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qu_Yuan\">Qu Yuan</span></b>. Where the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Classic_of_Poetry\"><i>Classic of Poetry</i></span> gathered the measured airs of the northern plains, this collection breathes the lush religiosity of the middle <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span>, steeped in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shamanism\">shamanic</span> rites of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_(shaman)\">wu</span> spirit-mediums who flourished in the regions of modern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hunan\">Hunan</span>. The received text of 17 sections took shape over centuries, first assembled by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han</span> bibliographer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Xiang_(scholar)\">Liu Xiang</span> in the 1st century BCE and fixed with commentary by <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Yi_(librarian)\">Wang Yi</span></b> in the 2nd century CE. Its crowning piece is the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Sao\"><i>Li Sao</i></span>, an allegorical lament of some 373 lines in which a slandered nobleman soars on a celestial quest past the mythic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kunlun_(mythology)\">Kunlun</span> peaks, while the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiu_Ge\"><i>Nine Songs</i></span></b> preserve liturgies to deities such as the goddesses of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiang_River\">Xiang River</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heavenly_Questions\"><i>Heavenly Questions</i></span> interrogates <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_mythology\">myth</span> and cosmos in more than 170 riddling queries. Composed in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Classical_Chinese\">Classical Chinese</span> lines longer and freer than the old 4-beat metre, marked by the sighing particle <i>xi</i> and dense with fragrant flora and spirit-flights like the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_You\"><i>Far-off Journey</i></span></b>, the anthology founded what later ages called the sao style. <br> <br> Tradition remembers Qu Yuan as a loyal minister of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Huai_of_Chu\">King Huai of Chu</span> who was driven from court by slander, and holds that upon learning that the capital <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ying_(Chu)\">Ying</span> had <b>fallen to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_(state)\">Qin</span> in 278 BCE</b> he drowned himself in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Miluo_River\">Miluo River</span>. His death is commemorated each year at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dragon_Boat_Festival\">Dragon Boat Festival</span>, when racing crews re-enact the search for his body and people eat the wrapped rice dumplings called <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zongzi\">zongzi</span>, said to have been thrown into the water to keep the fish from his corpse. The anthology's idiom became the seedbed of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fu_(literature)\">fu</span> rhapsody that dominated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_poetry\">Han poetry</span>, cultivated by admirers such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jia_Yi\">Jia Yi</span>, who composed a famous lament for Qu Yuan in exile, and the court poet <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Xiangru\">Sima Xiangru</span>. Its allegory of fragrant plants and the spurned worthy supplied later literature with an enduring language of political loyalty, echoing through poets from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tao_Yuanming\">Tao Yuanming</span> to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Bai\">Li Bai</span>. Wang Yi's annotated edition carried the corpus to posterity, modern scholars continue to debate how much of it truly came from Qu Yuan's hand, and the complete English version by the sinologist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"David_Hawkes_(sinologist)\">David Hawkes</span>, <b>published in 1985</b> as <i>The Songs of the South</i>, confirmed its standing beside its northern counterpart as a twin fountainhead of the poetry of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Chu Ci"},{"id":"cnc-034","num":"三十四","category":"China · Culture","question":"Falling on the 5th day of the 5th lunar month and commemorating the drowned poet-statesman Qu Yuan, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> features races of long, ornately carved boats and the eating of pyramid-shaped rice parcels.","answer":"Dragon Boat Festival","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">端午节 ('festival of the upright fifth'), on the fifth day of the fifth month</span></div>","traditional":"端午節","hanzi":"端午节","pinyin":"Duānwǔ jié","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Duānwǔ jié</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“festival of the upright fifth”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Dragon Boat Festival</b> is a traditional celebration held on the 5th day of the 5th month of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_calendar\">Chinese calendar</span></b>, falling between late May and the middle of June. Its ruling legend honours <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qu_Yuan\">Qu Yuan</span>, the poet-statesman of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chu_(state)\">Chu</span> in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warring_States_period\">Warring States period</span> who drowned himself <b>in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Miluo_River\">Miluo River</span> in 278 BCE</b>, whereupon villagers raced out in boats, beat the water to scare the fish, and threw in rice, a story firmly attached to the day by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span>. From that rice grew <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zongzi\">zongzi</span>, <b>pyramids of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Glutinous_rice\">glutinous rice</span></b> bound in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bamboo\">bamboo</span> or reed leaves, sweetened with jujubes in the north and stuffed with pork and salted egg yolk in the south, offered, the tales say, to feed the fish or appease the river dragon. Other regions remember other dead, the wronged minister <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Zixu\">Wu Zixu</span> along the lower Yangtze and the filial daughter <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cao_E\">Cao E</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhejiang\">Zhejiang</span>, while scholars trace the racing itself to far older dragon-totem rites of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Baiyue\">Baiyue</span> peoples of the watery south. The craft of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dragon_boat\">dragon boat</span> remains gloriously theatrical, a long, narrow hull fitted with the carved head and tail of a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_dragon\">Chinese dragon</span>, wakened by dotting its eyes, and driven by 20 or more paddlers stroking to the beat of an onboard <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Drum\">drum</span>. <br> <br> Falling near the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Summer_solstice\">summer solstice</span></b>, the double fifth was anciently feared as a pestilent “evil month,” so doors are hung with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mugwort\">mugwort</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Acorus_calamus\">calamus</span>, children wear fragrant sachets and five-poison charms, and the curious try <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Egg_balancing\">egg balancing</span></b> at noon, when upright forces are held strongest. Adults once drank or daubed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Realgar_wine\">realgar wine</span> against vermin, the very draught that, in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Legend_of_the_White_Snake\">Legend of the White Snake</span>, forces the heroine to reveal her serpent form on this day. The races have meanwhile become a global sport, organised internationally <b>from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span> after 1976</b> and governed since 1991 by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"International_Dragon_Boat_Federation\">International Dragon Boat Federation</span>, with tens of millions of paddlers and regattas on every continent. The day was restored to the <b>calendar of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Public_holidays_in_China\">public holidays in China</span> in 2008</b>, is likewise kept in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span>, and in 2009 became the first Chinese festival inscribed by UNESCO as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Intangible_cultural_heritage\">intangible cultural heritage</span>. Cousins mark the season elsewhere, Korea's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gangneung_Danoje_Festival\">Gangneung Danoje Festival</span> earning its own UNESCO listing in 2005 amid lively debate, and Japan's fifth-of-the-fifth evolving into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Children's_Day_(Japan)\">Children's Day</span>, while in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> the drums, leaves, and racing dragons still make Duanwu the great water rite of early summer.","citation":"","answerText":"Dragon Boat Festival"},{"id":"cng-025","num":"二十五","category":"China · Geography","question":"A hilly arm of land jutting into the sea between the Bohai and Yellow seas, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> holds the major port of Qingdao and lies across the water from Korea.","answer":"Shandong Peninsula","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">山东 (Shāndōng, 'east of the [Taihang] mountains')</span></div>","traditional":"山東半島","hanzi":"山东半岛","pinyin":"Shāndōng Bàndǎo","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Shāndōng Bàndǎo</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Shandong Peninsula</b>, also called the Jiaodong Peninsula, is the largest peninsula in China, the hilly eastern arm of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shandong\">Shandong</span> province thrusting between the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bohai_Sea\">Bohai Sea</span></b> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_Sea\">Yellow Sea</span>, separated from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liaodong_Peninsula\">Liaodong Peninsula</span> by the roughly 106-kilometer (65.9 mi) <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bohai_Strait\">Bohai Strait</span> and facing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Korean_Peninsula\">Korean Peninsula</span> only about 190 kilometers (120 mi) across the water. Its terrain of weathered granite hills meets the sea in rocky capes and bays, culminating in 1,133-meter (3,717 ft) <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mount_Lao\">Mount Lao</span> beside <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiaozhou_Bay\">Jiaozhou Bay</span></b>, often cited as the highest peak on China's entire coastline. The shore is studded with major cities, above all <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qingdao\">Qingdao</span> with some 10 million people, together with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yantai\">Yantai</span>, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Weihai\">Weihai</span></b>, and inland <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Weifang\">Weifang</span>, famed for its kites. A warm-temperate monsoon climate makes the uplands China's premier orchard country, leading the nation in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Apple\">apples</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peanut\">peanuts</span>, while coastal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Aquaculture\">aquaculture</span> of kelp and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sea_cucumber\">sea cucumber</span> ranks among the largest on earth and Yantai's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Changyu\">Changyu</span> winery, <b>founded in 1892</b>, is the country's oldest. Modern engineering has matched this bounty, for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Port_of_Qingdao\">Port of Qingdao</span> now handles cargo volumes among the half-dozen busiest in the world, home appliances from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Haier\">Haier</span> ship globally, and the 26.7-kilometer (16.6 mi) <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiaozhou_Bay_Bridge\">Jiaozhou Bay Bridge</span> spans the bay as one of the longest sea crossings ever built. <br> <br> In antiquity the peninsula was home to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dongyi\">Dongyi</span> peoples before the state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qi_(state)\">Qi</span> grew rich on its salt and fish from the 11th century BCE, and after unification <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_Shi_Huang\">Qin Shi Huang</span> toured its capes, dispatching the magician <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xu_Fu\">Xu Fu</span> with thousands of youths to seek the elixir of life beyond the waves. Those waters bred the legend of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mount_Penglai\">Mount Penglai</span>, island paradise of the immortals, where the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight_Immortals\">Eight Immortals</span> were said to cross the sea and where mirages still draw crowds to the cliff-top <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Penglai_Pavilion\">Penglai Pavilion</span></b>. Under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang dynasty</span> its harbors anchored the busiest sea lanes to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silla\">Silla</span> Korea and Japan, hosting resident Korean merchant communities. The peninsula then became a stage for imperial collapse when <b>the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Weihaiwei\">Battle of Weihaiwei</span> in 1895</b>, during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Sino-Japanese_War\">First Sino-Japanese War</span>, annihilated the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beiyang_Fleet\">Beiyang Fleet</span> in its home port. Germany seized Jiaozhou Bay in 1898 as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kiautschou_Bay_Leased_Territory\">Kiautschou leased territory</span>, <b>founding the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tsingtao_Brewery\">Tsingtao Brewery</span> in 1903</b>, and after Japan took the colony in the 1914 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Siege_of_Tsingtao\">Siege of Tsingtao</span>, the postwar <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shandong_Problem\">Shandong Problem</span> ignited the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"May_Fourth_Movement\">May Fourth Movement</span> of 1919 that reshaped modern Chinese politics.","citation":"","answerText":"Shandong Peninsula"},{"id":"cng-035","num":"三十五","category":"China · Geography","question":"A large, shrinking floodplain lake in northern Hunan that swells and contracts with the seasons as it buffers floodwaters of the Yangtze, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> gives its name to the province lying to its south.","answer":"Dongting Lake","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">洞庭湖 (Dòngtíng Hú)</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"洞庭湖","pinyin":"Dòngtíng Hú","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Dòngtíng Hú</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Dongting Lake</b> is a great <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Floodplain\">floodplain</span></b> lake on the middle <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span> in northern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hunan\">Hunan</span>, so dominant in regional geography that Hunan means \"south of the lake\" and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hubei\">Hubei</span> \"north of the lake.\" A classic river-connected lake, it breathes with the seasons, contracting below 1,000 square kilometers (390 sq mi) in winter and swelling beyond 2,600 in summer, though in the early 19th century under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> it spread over roughly 6,000 square kilometers (2,300 sq mi) as China's largest freshwater body before <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sediment\">sediment</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Land_reclamation\">reclamation</span> behind <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Polder\">polder</span></b> dikes cut its area nearly in half, leaving it 2nd to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Poyang_Lake\">Poyang Lake</span>. It works as the Yangtze's natural detention basin, swallowing floodwaters through several inlet channels and the \"four waters\" of Hunan, led by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiang_River\">Xiang</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_River\">Yuan</span></b>, then returning the flow to the river at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yueyang\">Yueyang</span>, shaving billions of cubic meters off flood peaks. Its marshes, protected under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ramsar_Convention\">Ramsar Convention</span> <b>since 1992</b>, winter most of the world's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lesser_white-fronted_goose\">lesser white-fronted geese</span>, shelter on the order of 120 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze_finless_porpoise\">Yangtze finless porpoises</span>, and support a free-ranging herd of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Père_David's_deer\">Père David's deer</span> descended from animals that escaped during the <b>1998 flood</b>. The lake has also bred afflictions, from the snail-borne <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Schistosomiasis\">schistosomiasis</span> fought in mass campaigns since the 1950s to a plague of some 2 billion mice flushed from its islets in 2007, while the record drought of 2022 shrank its waters to historic lows. <br> <br> Few landscapes loom larger in classical letters, for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Meng_Haoran\">Meng Haoran</span> in the 8th century pictured its mists swallowing heaven, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Du_Fu\">Du Fu</span> in 768 wrote one of the most celebrated of all Chinese poems upon finally climbing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yueyang_Tower\">Yueyang Tower</span> above its outlet. That pavilion, one of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Great_Towers_of_Jiangnan\">Three Great Towers of Jiangnan</span>, <b>inspired <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fan_Zhongyan\">Fan Zhongyan</span>'s 1046 essay</b> <i>Memorial to Yueyang Tower</i>, whose injunction to be first in worrying about the world and last in enjoying its pleasures became a creed of Chinese statecraft. Offshore lies <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Junshan_Island\">Junshan Island</span>, source of the rare <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Junshan_Yinzhen\">Junshan Yinzhen</span> tea, where spotted bamboo is said to bear the tear-stains of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ehuang_and_Nüying\">Ehuang and Nüying</span></b>, consorts of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Shun\">Emperor Shun</span> who drowned themselves in grief and became goddesses of the lake. Into these same waters flows the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Miluo_River\">Miluo</span>, where the poet <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qu_Yuan\">Qu Yuan</span> drowned himself in 278 BCE, an act commemorated in the racing boats of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dragon_Boat_Festival\">Dragon Boat Festival</span>, and Tang storytellers added the tale of a scholar bearing a letter to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dragon_King\">Dragon King</span> of Dongting's underwater palace. History intruded as well, when rebel lake fleets were crushed here in 1135 by the loyalist general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yue_Fei\">Yue Fei</span>, yet through every age the shrinking lake has remained the flooded heart of a \"land of fish and rice.\"","citation":"","answerText":"Dongting Lake"},{"id":"cng-037","num":"三十七","category":"China · Geography","question":"A broad, shallow lake on the Yangtze Delta between Jiangsu and Zhejiang, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is dotted with islands, famed for the ornamental \"scholar's rocks\" dredged from it, and ringed by historic garden cities.","answer":"Lake Tai","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">太湖 (Tài Hú, 'grand lake')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"太湖","pinyin":"Tài Hú","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Tài Hú</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Grand Lake”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Lake Tai</b> is a broad, shallow lake of roughly 2,250 square kilometers (869 sq mi) on the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze_Delta\">Yangtze Delta</span></b>, the 3rd-largest freshwater lake in China, lying mainly in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiangsu\">Jiangsu</span> with its southern shore touching <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhejiang\">Zhejiang</span>, yet averaging barely 2 meters (6.6 ft) deep and scattered with about 90 islands. Its origin remains debated, with most geologists favoring a silted coastal lagoon while others have proposed an ancient <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Impact_crater\">impact crater</span></b>, a hypothesis drawn from shocked minerals reported around its rim. The lake feeds <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Suzhou_Creek\">Suzhou Creek</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huangpu_River\">Huangpu River</span> that flows through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span>, links to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Grand_Canal_(China)\">Grand Canal</span>, and anchors a basin that on a fraction of one percent of China's land yields on the order of a 10th of its economic output around cities such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuxi\">Wuxi</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Suzhou\">Suzhou</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huzhou\">Huzhou</span>. From its waters came the perforated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Limestone\">limestone</span> <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taihu_stone\">Taihu stones</span></b>, scholar's rocks sculpted by waves and prized since the Tang, so coveted that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Huizong_of_Song\">Emperor Huizong</span>'s ruinous flower-and-rock convoys of the early 12th century helped ignite the <b>rebellion of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fang_La\">Fang La</span> in 1120</b>. The finest specimens still crown the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Classical_Gardens_of_Suzhou\">Classical Gardens of Suzhou</span>, inscribed as World Heritage in 1997, where rockeries of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lion_Grove_Garden\">Lion Grove Garden</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Humble_Administrator's_Garden\">Humble Administrator's Garden</span> recreate the lake's craggy islets in miniature. <br> <br> On the orchard-clad Dongting hills rising from the eastern shore grows <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Biluochun\">Biluochun</span>, a spiral-leafed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Green_tea\">green tea</span> counted among China's 10 most famous since imperial times. The lake's fishery was equally storied, built on the \"three whites\" of translucent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Salangidae\">icefish</span>, whitefish, and white shrimp, supplemented by the autumn harvest of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_mitten_crab\">Chinese mitten crabs</span></b> and by pens that long made the region a center of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultured_freshwater_pearls\">cultured freshwater pearls</span>. Legend reaches back to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Spring_and_Autumn_period\">Spring and Autumn period</span>, when the strategist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fan_Li\">Fan Li</span> and the beauty <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Shi\">Xi Shi</span>, having engineered the fall of the <b>kingdom of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_(state)\">Wu</span> in 473 BCE</b>, were said to have vanished together in a small boat upon these waters. Modern prosperity nearly killed the lake, as effluent from thousands of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Township_and_village_enterprises\">township and village enterprises</span> and farm runoff drove severe <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eutrophication\">eutrophication</span>, culminating in a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cyanobacteria\">cyanobacterial</span> <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Algal_bloom\">bloom</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Microcystis\">Microcystis</span> in 2007</b> that fouled the taps of around 2 million Wuxi residents and triggered a cleanup costing tens of billions of yuan. The blooms still return in warm summers, yet the lake endures as the scenic heart of the delta, its sails, stone bridges, and garden cities preserving the watery aesthetic that once defined Jiangnan.","citation":"","answerText":"Lake Tai"},{"id":"cnh-011","num":"十一","category":"China · History","question":"Named after a chronicle traditionally edited by Confucius, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> saw royal authority wither as powerful states fought for dominance and the first of the great philosophers of the Hundred Schools began to teach.","answer":"Spring and Autumn period","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">770–476 BCE</span></div>","traditional":"春秋時代","hanzi":"春秋时代","pinyin":"Chūnqiū shídài","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Chūnqiū shídài</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Spring and Autumn period</b> was the first major phase of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eastern_Zhou\">Eastern Zhou</span></b>, conventionally dated <b>from 770</b> to <b>476 BCE</b> and named for a court chronicle traditionally said to have been edited by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucius\">Confucius</span>. It opened in the aftermath of 771 BCE, when nomadic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Quanrong\">Quanrong</span> invaders sacked the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Western_Zhou\">Western Zhou</span> capital and killed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_You_of_Zhou\">King You</span>, prompting his successor <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Ping_of_Zhou\">King Ping</span></b> to move the seat of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_dynasty\">Zhou dynasty</span> eastward to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chengzhou\">Chengzhou</span> near present-day <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luoyang\">Luoyang</span>, an eastward shift in 770 BCE that gives the era its conventional starting point. Stripped of much of its territory and prestige, the Zhou king endured as a ceremonial <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Son_of_Heaven\">Son of Heaven</span> while real power devolved to the regional lords of a crumbling <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fengjian\">fengjian</span> order, so that more than 100 statelets gradually consolidated into a smaller number of aggressive territorial powers such as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jin_(Chinese_state)\">Jin</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qi_(state)\">Qi</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chu_(state)\">Chu</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_(state)\">Qin</span>. To fill the resulting vacuum, dominant rulers assumed the role of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five_Hegemons\">hegemon</span>, beginning with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Duke_Huan_of_Qi\">Duke Huan of Qi</span>, who with his reforming minister <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guan_Zhong\">Guan Zhong</span> rallied the states under the slogan of honouring the king and repelling outside threats, a precedent soon followed by figures such as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Duke_Wen_of_Jin\">Duke Wen of Jin</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Zhuang_of_Chu\">King Zhuang of Chu</span>. Interstate conflict in this era was still bound by aristocratic ritual and waged with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chariot\">chariot</span>-borne nobility, punctuated by sworn covenants and grand conferences that maintained a precarious balance among the contending courts, even as the number of recognized polities steadily shrank toward the handful that would dominate the succeeding age. <br> <br> The era derives its name from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Spring_and_Autumn_Annals\"><i>Spring and Autumn Annals</i></span>, a terse year-by-year record of the state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lu_(state)\">Lu</span> covering <b>the years 722 to 481 BCE</b> across the reigns of 12 dukes of Lu, a record that tradition ascribes to the editorial hand of Confucius. Because the chronicle is so laconic, it was transmitted alongside expansive commentaries, most importantly the narrative-rich <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zuo_Zhuan\"><i>Zuo Zhuan</i></span> and the more interpretive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gongyang_Commentary\"><i>Gongyang Commentary</i></span>, which together preserve much of what is known about the period's politics and diplomacy. Intellectually the age witnessed the dawn of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hundred_Schools_of_Thought\">Hundred Schools of Thought</span>, for it was during its closing decades that Confucius founded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucianism</span> with its emphasis on ritual propriety and benevolent government, and that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Laozi\">Laozi</span> was traditionally credited with inspiring <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Daoism</span>. Military theory likewise matured, as the strategist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Tzu\">Sun Tzu</span>, traditionally placed in the southern state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_(state)\">Wu</span> during its rivalry with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yue_(state)\">Yue</span>, is credited with the foundational treatise <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Art_of_War\"><i>The Art of War</i></span>, while the spread of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Iron\">iron</span> tools began to transform agriculture and warfare alike. The period gave way to the more ruthless <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warring_States_period\">Warring States period</span>, a shift often marked by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Partition_of_Jin\">partition of Jin</span> around 453 BCE, leaving an enduring legacy in which the moral and political debates first raised under a fading Zhou monarchy would shape Chinese civilization for the next 2,000 years.","citation":"","answerText":"Spring and Autumn period"},{"id":"cnc-020","num":"二十","category":"China · Culture","question":"A teacher and minor official of the 6th–5th centuries BCE from the state of Lu, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the thinker whose ideas on virtue, ritual and proper relationships, transmitted by his disciples, became the foundation of a tradition shaping the civil service examinations and statecraft of imperial China.","answer":"Confucius","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">551–479 BCE</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"孔子","pinyin":"Kǒngzǐ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Kǒngzǐ</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Master Kong”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Confucius</b>, personal name <b>Kong Qiu</b>, was a teacher and minor official from the state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lu_(state)\">Lu</span> during the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Spring_and_Autumn_period\">Spring and Autumn period</span></b> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_dynasty\">Zhou dynasty</span>, whose ethical and political thought became the foundation of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucianism</span>. Born near <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qufu\">Qufu</span> into the lower aristocratic class of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shi_(class)\">shi</span>, he served as a keeper of granaries and livestock before traditionally rising to <b>minister of crime around 501–497 BCE</b>, then spent some 14 years traveling among rival states in a fruitless search for a ruler who would implement his ideas. His teaching centered on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ren_(philosophy)\">ren</span> (humaneness), <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_(Confucianism)\">li</span> (ritual propriety), <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Filial_piety\">filial piety</span>, and the cultivation of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Junzi\">junzi</span> or exemplary person, framed as a restoration of the moral order attributed to the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Duke_of_Zhou\">Duke of Zhou</span></b> and including a negative formulation of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Golden_Rule\">Golden Rule</span>. Tradition credits him with 3,000 disciples, of whom 72 mastered his teachings, and his sayings were compiled by followers over subsequent generations into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Analects\"><i>Analects</i></span>. <b>After his death in 479 BCE</b>, thinkers such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mencius\">Mencius</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xunzi_(philosopher)\">Xunzi</span> developed competing interpretations of his legacy amid the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hundred_Schools_of_Thought\">Hundred Schools of Thought</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warring_States_period\">Warring States period</span>. <br> <br> Under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Wu_of_Han\">Emperor Wu</span> established academic chairs <b>for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five_Classics\">Five Classics</span> in 136 BCE</b>, elevating the Confucian canon to state orthodoxy, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Qian\">Sima Qian</span> honored the master with a hereditary-house biography in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Records_of_the_Grand_Historian\"><i>Records of the Grand Historian</i></span> around 94 BCE. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examinations</span>, instituted under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sui_dynasty\">Sui dynasty</span> in 605 and expanded by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span>, tested mastery of this canon, while state-sponsored <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Temple_of_Confucius\">temples of Confucius</span> spread to every county seat of the empire. During the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song dynasty</span> the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Neo-Confucianism\">Neo-Confucian</span> synthesis of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_Xi\">Zhu Xi</span></b> reorganized the curriculum around the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Books_and_Five_Classics\">Four Books</span>, which from 1313 until the examinations' abolition in 1905 defined the intellectual formation of China's governing elite. Successive courts heaped posthumous titles upon the sage, granting his descendants the hereditary dignity of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Duke_Yansheng\">Duke Yansheng</span></b> in 1055, and the Kong genealogy now registers more than 2 million descendants across 83 generations. Though attacked by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Culture_Movement\">New Culture Movement</span> in the 1910s and vilified during the 1973–1976 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Criticize_Lin,_Criticize_Confucius\">Criticize Lin, Criticize Confucius</span> campaign, his thought shaped statecraft and education across <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"East_Asia\">East Asia</span> for 2 millennia, and since 2004 the Chinese government has invoked his name through hundreds of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucius_Institute\">Confucius Institutes</span> worldwide.","citation":"","answerText":"Confucius"},{"id":"cnc-024","num":"二十四","category":"China · Culture","question":"Emphasising filial piety, ritual propriety, benevolence and hierarchical social harmony, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> founded on the teachings of a 6th-century-BCE sage became the dominant state ideology of imperial China, later revived as Neo-Confucianism under the Song dynasty.","answer":"Confucianism","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">551–479 BCE (Confucius)</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"儒家","pinyin":"Rújiā","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Rújiā</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“school of the scholars”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Confucianism</b> is the ethical, social, and political tradition founded on the teachings of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucius\">Confucius</span> (<b>551–479 BCE</b>), a sage of the state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lu_(state)\">Lu</span> whose vision of moral self-cultivation became the dominant ideology of imperial China. Its core values—<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ren_(philosophy)\">ren</span> (benevolence), <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_(Confucianism)\">li</span> (ritual propriety), <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yi_(philosophy)\">yi</span> (righteousness), and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Filial_piety\">filial piety</span></b>—were transmitted in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Analects\"><i>Analects</i></span> and ordered society through 5 hierarchical relationships binding ruler and subject, father and son, husband and wife, elder and younger brother, and friends. During the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warring_States_period\">Warring States period</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mencius\">Mencius</span> (4th century BCE) argued that human nature was innately good and that the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mandate_of_Heaven\">Mandate of Heaven</span> could pass from unworthy rulers, while <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xunzi_(philosopher)\">Xunzi</span> (3rd century BCE) countered that goodness required deliberate shaping by ritual, defining 2 enduring wings of the school amid the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hundred_Schools_of_Thought\">Hundred Schools of Thought</span></b>. The tradition nearly perished when the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_dynasty\">Qin dynasty</span>, governing by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Legalism_(Chinese_philosophy)\">Legalist</span> principles, <b>ordered the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Burning_of_books_and_burying_of_scholars\">burning of books</span> in 213 BCE</b>. Fortunes reversed under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span> when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Wu_of_Han\">Emperor Wu</span>, advised by the synthesizer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dong_Zhongshu\">Dong Zhongshu</span>, established academic chairs <b>for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five_Classics\">Five Classics</span> in 136 BCE</b> and made Confucian learning the orthodoxy of the state. <br> <br> The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examinations</span>, begun under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sui_dynasty\">Sui dynasty</span> in 605, tied office-holding to mastery of the Confucian canon for 1,300 years, recruiting the scholar-official elite that administered every subsequent dynasty until the system's abolition in 1905. After centuries of competition from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Buddhism\">Buddhism</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Taoism</span>, thinkers of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song dynasty</span> forged the revival known as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Neo-Confucianism\">Neo-Confucianism</span>, which grounded ethics in a metaphysics of principle (<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_(neo-Confucianism)\">li</span>) and vital force (<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qi\">qi</span>). Its greatest systematizer, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_Xi\">Zhu Xi</span> (1130–1200), elevated the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Books_and_Five_Classics\">Four Books</span> to the heart of the curriculum, and from 1313 his commentaries defined examination orthodoxy, later challenged by the idealist school of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Yangming\">Wang Yangming</span></b> (1472–1529) under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span>. The tradition radiated across <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"East_Asia\">East Asia</span>, serving as state ideology of Korea's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joseon\">Joseon</span> dynasty for 5 centuries after 1392, informing governance in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Edo_period\">Edo</span>-period Japan, and sustaining civil examinations in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vietnam\">Vietnam</span> until 1919. Denounced by the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Culture_Movement\">New Culture Movement</span></b> in the 1910s and again during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span> of 1966–1976, Confucian thought has nonetheless been rehabilitated by 20th-century <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Confucianism\">New Confucianism</span> and invoked by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> itself as a pillar of national identity.","citation":"","answerText":"Confucianism"},{"id":"cnc-021","num":"二十一","category":"China · Culture","question":"Traditionally placed in the Spring and Autumn era and revered as a master strategist, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is credited with a celebrated treatise on strategy that is still studied in military academies and business schools worldwide.","answer":"Sun Tzu","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">traditionally c. 544</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. 496 BCE</span></div>","traditional":"孫子","hanzi":"孙子","pinyin":"Sūnzǐ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Sūnzǐ</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Master Sun”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Sun Tzu</b> was a Chinese general and military theorist traditionally placed in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Spring_and_Autumn_period\">Spring and Autumn</span> period. He is celebrated as the author of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Art_of_War\"><i>The Art of War</i></span></b>, a concise treatise of 13 chapters that ranks among the most influential works of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Military_strategy\">military strategy</span> ever composed. According to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Records_of_the_Grand_Historian\"><i>Records of the Grand Historian</i></span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Qian\">Sima Qian</span>, he served <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Helü\">King Helü</span></b> of the southern state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_(state)\">Wu</span> alongside the general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Zixu\">Wu Zixu</span>, helping it prevail over its rival <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yue_(state)\">Yue</span> and the great southern power of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chu_(state)\">Chu</span>. A famous anecdote relates how he demonstrated his methods by drilling the king's palace concubines into disciplined ranks, executing two of the monarch's favourites to enforce obedience and prove that firm command could impose order on any body of troops. The treatise stresses that warfare is fundamentally an art of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Military_deception\">deception</span>, that the supreme achievement is to subdue an enemy without fighting, and that victory flows from foreknowledge, adaptability, mastery of terrain, and the disciplined use of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Espionage\">spies</span>. <br> <br> Modern scholars debate his historicity, and many contend that the received text reached its final form during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warring_States_period\">Warring States</span> period of the 5th to 4th centuries BCE rather than in Sun Tzu's supposed lifetime. For centuries some doubted whether he was distinct from his descendant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Bin\">Sun Bin</span>, a question <b>resolved in 1972</b> when the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yinqueshan_Han_Slips\">Yinqueshan Han Slips</span> yielded separate bamboo copies of <i>The Art of War</i> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Bin's_Art_of_War\"><i>Sun Bin's Art of War</i></span> in a single tomb. The work was later enshrined as the foremost of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Seven_Military_Classics\">Seven Military Classics</span></b> canonised under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song dynasty</span>, attracted an influential commentary from the warlord <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cao_Cao\">Cao Cao</span>, and shaped warfare across East Asia, inspiring the battle standard <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fūrinkazan\">Fūrinkazan</span> of the Japanese daimyo <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Takeda_Shingen\">Takeda Shingen</span>. It reached Europe through a <b>1772 French</b> translation by the Jesuit <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jean_Joseph_Marie_Amiot\">Jean Joseph Marie Amiot</span> and a widely read 1910 English rendering by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lionel_Giles\">Lionel Giles</span>, and its precepts are credited with influencing commanders from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Napoleon\">Napoleon</span> to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ho_Chi_Minh\">Ho Chi Minh</span></b>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Võ_Nguyên_Giáp\">Võ Nguyên Giáp</span>. Mao in particular wove it into his theory of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guerrilla_warfare\">guerrilla warfare</span>, and today the text is studied not only at institutions such as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States_Military_Academy\">United States Military Academy</span></b> but also in the fields of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Strategic_management\">business strategy</span>, law, and sport far beyond <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Sun Tzu"},{"id":"cnh-012","num":"十二","category":"China · History","question":"Following the breakup of the old order, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> saw 7 major states wage total war with mass infantry and crossbows, even as the rival thinkers of the Hundred Schools flourished, until all were conquered by Qin.","answer":"Warring States period","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">475–221 BCE</span></div>","traditional":"戰國時代","hanzi":"战国时代","pinyin":"Zhànguó shídài","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhànguó shídài</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Warring States period</b> was the turbulent final phase of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_dynasty\">Zhou dynasty</span>, conventionally dated <b>from about 475</b> to <b>221 BCE</b>, during which a handful of rival kingdoms battled for mastery over the wreckage of the old feudal order. It is usually held to have begun with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Partition_of_Jin\">Partition of Jin</span>, the <b>carving up around 453 BCE</b> of the once-dominant state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jin_(Chinese_state)\">Jin</span> into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_(Warring_States)\">Han</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhao_(state)\">Zhao</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wei_(state)\">Wei</span>, a usurpation the powerless Zhou king was forced to ratify in 403 BCE. These three successors, together with Qin in the far west, sprawling <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chu_(state)\">Chu</span> in the south, eastern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qi_(state)\">Qi</span>, and northern <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yan_(state)\">Yan</span></b>, made up the seven great powers whose rulers soon cast off all deference to the Zhou throne and assumed the royal title of king for themselves. The relentless demands of such warfare drove sweeping reform, most thoroughly in Qin, where the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Legalism_(Chinese_philosophy)\">Legalist</span> measures of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shang_Yang\">Shang Yang</span> from about 356 BCE forged a centralized and regimented state—its rationale later distilled by the philosopher <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Fei\">Han Fei</span>—that bent every subject to the twin obligations of farming and fighting. On the battlefield aristocratic chariotry gave way to vast armies of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Infantry\">infantry</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cavalry\">cavalry</span>—the latter introduced when <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Wuling_of_Zhao\">King Wuling of Zhao</span></b> took up nomad horsemanship around 307 BCE—wielding iron weapons and the crossbow, and the slaughter reached its height at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Changping\">Battle of Changping</span> in 260 BCE, after which the Qin commander <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bai_Qi\">Bai Qi</span> is said to have buried alive some 400,000 surrendered Zhao troops.<br> <br>Amid the unceasing conflict the period became the most fertile age of Chinese thought, as the masters of the so-called Hundred Schools competed for influence at the courts: the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucians</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mencius\">Mencius</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xun_Kuang\">Xunzi</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Daoist</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuang_Zhou\">Zhuangzi</span>, and the disciplined adherents of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mohism\">Mohism</span> each set forth a rival path to social order. Equally characteristic was the febrile diplomacy of the vertical and horizontal alliances, in which itinerant persuaders like <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Su_Qin\">Su Qin</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Yi_(Warring_States_period)\">Zhang Yi</span> assembled or shattered coalitions that arrayed the eastern states against Qin or bound them to it, intrigues later anthologized in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhanguo_Ce\"><i>Strategies of the Warring States</i></span></b> from which the era takes its name. Beneath the political turmoil the economy was reshaped by the spread of iron tools and ox-drawn ploughing, by growing cities and circulating <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ancient_Chinese_coinage\">bronze coinage</span>, and by monumental public works such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dujiangyan\">Dujiangyan</span> irrigation system and the long frontier ramparts that foreshadowed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Wall_of_China\">Great Wall</span>. The balance tilted irreversibly toward Qin, which in 256 BCE deposed <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Nan_of_Zhou\">King Nan</span></b> and thereby extinguished the last shadow of Zhou authority altogether. Between 230 and 221 BCE the Qin king then conquered the six surviving states one after another in his <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin's_wars_of_unification\">wars of unification</span>, and on completing the conquest he proclaimed himself <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_Shi_Huang\">Qin Shi Huang</span>, first emperor of the centralized <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_dynasty\">Qin dynasty</span> that now replaced the vanished world of contending kingdoms.","citation":"","answerText":"Warring States period"},{"id":"cnc-026","num":"二十六","category":"China · Culture","question":"A craftsman-turned-philosopher of the 5th century BCE who preached universal love and frugality, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> founded a disciplined movement whose members were noted for helping cities defend against sieges, opposing the war-making of rival states during the Warring States age of the Hundred Schools.","answer":"Mozi","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. 470–391 BCE</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"墨子","pinyin":"Mòzǐ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Mòzǐ</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Master Mo”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Mozi</b>, personal name Mo Di, was a craftsman-turned-philosopher, probably from the state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lu_(state)\">Lu</span>, who founded <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mohism\">Mohism</span></b>, the first organized rival to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucianism</span> among the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hundred_Schools_of_Thought\">Hundred Schools of Thought</span> at the dawn of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warring_States_period\">Warring States period</span>. Reportedly trained in the teachings of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucius\">Confucius</span> before rejecting them as extravagant, he preached \"impartial care,\" the doctrine that one should love all people as one's own kin, grounding it in the will of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tian\">Heaven</span> and the watchfulness of spirits, and judging every practice by its benefit to the people in a system often called the world's earliest <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Consequentialism\">consequentialism</span></b>. From this calculus he condemned offensive war, lavish funerals with 3-year mourning, and courtly music, while championing frugality, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Asceticism\">ascetic</span> discipline, and the elevation of the worthy regardless of birth, an early statement of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Meritocracy\">meritocracy</span>. He proposed 3 tests for any doctrine—its precedent among the sage-kings, the evidence of people's eyes and ears, and its practical benefit when applied in government. His followers formed a tightly disciplined order under a Grand Master, and sources claim he commanded 180 disciples who would walk through fire or tread on sword blades at his order. <br> <br> Because they opposed aggression in practice as well as theory, Mohists became renowned engineers of city defense, and 11 surviving chapters of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mozi_(book)\"><i>Mozi</i></span>—a corpus originally of 71 chapters, of which 53 remain—detail <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fortification\">fortification</span>, counter-tunneling, and <b>incendiary tactics against <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Siege_engine\">siege engines</span></b>. The most famous tale recounts Mozi defeating the master artisan <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lu_Ban\">Lu Ban</span> in 9 simulated assaults at the court of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chu_(state)\">Chu</span>, thereby talking the king out of invading <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_(state)\">Song</span>. The later \"Mohist Canons\" pioneered Chinese <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Optics\">optics</span></b>, mechanics, and geometry, including a 4th-century BCE description of the inverted image in a pinhole or <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Camera_obscura\">camera obscura</span>, alongside a rigorous semantics that, with the rival <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"School_of_Names\">School of Names</span>, marks the high point of early <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Logic_in_China\">Chinese logic</span></b>. Though <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mencius\">Mencius</span> denounced impartial care as denying one's own father, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuangzi_(book)\"><i>Zhuangzi</i></span> conceded Mozi was \"one of the best men in the world,\" the school withered after <b>the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_dynasty\">Qin</span> unification of 221 BCE</b> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han</span> turn to Confucian orthodoxy, effectively disappearing within a century. The text survived largely through inclusion in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Daozang\">Daozang</span> of 1445, was philologically restored in <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Yirang\">Sun Yirang</span>'s commentary of 1893</b> under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span>, won praise from historians of science such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joseph_Needham\">Joseph Needham</span>, and lent the sage's name in 2016 to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Quantum_Experiments_at_Space_Scale\">Micius</span>, the world's first quantum-communications satellite.","citation":"","answerText":"Mozi"},{"id":"cnh-014","num":"十四","category":"China · History","question":"A ruthless Legalist minister whose reforms in the 4th century BCE organised the western state for war by rewarding farming and soldiering and punishing collectively, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> strengthened Qin so much that he was torn apart by chariots after his patron died during the Warring States era.","answer":"Shang Yang","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. 390–338 BCE</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"商鞅","pinyin":"Shāng Yāng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Shāng Yāng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Shang Yang</b> was a statesman and reformer of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warring_States_period\">Warring States period</span></b> and a leading exponent of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Legalism_(Chinese_philosophy)\">Legalist</span> school, whose stress on strict law and centralized power stood opposed to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucianism</span> amid the wider ferment of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hundred_Schools_of_Thought\">Hundred Schools of Thought</span>. Born a minor scion of the small state of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wey_(state)\">Wey</span></b> and originally known as Gongsun Yang, he found his talents overlooked in the state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wei_(state)\">Wei</span> and so migrated west to offer his services to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Duke_Xiao_of_Qin\">Duke Xiao of Qin</span>, an ambitious ruler determined to strengthen his realm. Granted sweeping authority in successive waves of reform <b>beginning in 356 BCE</b>, he dismantled the privileges of the hereditary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Aristocracy\">aristocracy</span> and replaced them with a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Meritocracy\">meritocratic</span> ladder of 20 noble ranks awarded almost entirely for battlefield achievement, channelling the population into the twin pursuits of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Agriculture\">farming</span> and war and binding able-bodied men to military <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Conscription\">conscription</span>. He bound the populace into mutual-responsibility units of 5 and <b>10 households under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Collective_punishment\">collective punishment</span></b>, in which failing to report a neighbour's crime was punished as harshly as the crime itself, while reorganizing the countryside into some 31 centrally governed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"County_(China)\">counties</span> and relocating the capital to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xianyang\">Xianyang</span> in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guanzhong\">Guanzhong</span> heartland. Among his most consequential measures were the abolition of the ancient <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Well-field_system\">well-field system</span> in favour of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Private_property\">private landholding</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Standardization\">standardization</span> of weights and measures, and to prove the state would honour its word he famously offered 50 gold to whoever would move a pole from one city gate to another, paying out the moment a sceptic complied. <br> <br> His reforms transformed <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_(state)\">Qin</span></b> from a peripheral power into the most disciplined and militarized state of the age, laying the institutional groundwork for the eventual <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin's_wars_of_unification\">unification</span> of <b>China under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_Shi_Huang\">Qin Shi Huang</span> in 221 BCE</b>. Rewarded for his successes with a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fief\">fief</span> of 15 towns in the Shang region of present-day <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shaanxi\">Shaanxi</span>, from which he drew his honorific title, he nonetheless amassed bitter enemies among the elite, above all by punishing the tutors of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Crown_prince\">crown prince</span> when the heir himself transgressed the new laws. When his protector Duke Xiao <b>died in 338 BCE</b>, that former crown prince ascended as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Huiwen_of_Qin\">King Huiwen of Qin</span> and, nursing his old grievance, charged the minister with treason and ordered his arrest. In a celebrated irony, the fleeing reformer was reportedly refused shelter at an inn because his own registration laws forbade lodging unidentified travellers, and after his capture he was condemned to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capital_punishment\">execution</span> by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dismemberment\">dismemberment</span>—his body torn apart by chariots—while his entire clan was exterminated. Yet his harsh machinery of law outlived him and continued to drive Qin's ascendancy, and his ideas, preserved in the treatise <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Book_of_Lord_Shang\"><i>The Book of Lord Shang</i></span> and later sharpened by Legalists such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Fei\">Han Fei</span> and the chancellor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Si\">Li Si</span>, were recorded for posterity by the historian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Qian\">Sima Qian</span> in his <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Records_of_the_Grand_Historian\"><i>Records of the Grand Historian</i></span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Shang Yang"},{"id":"cnc-028","num":"二十八","category":"China · Culture","question":"Regarded as the most important Confucian thinker after the founder himself, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is innately good and that a ruler who neglects the people's welfare forfeits the Mandate of Heaven, lending his name to one of the Four Books.","answer":"Mencius","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">traditionally c. 372–289 BCE</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"孟子","pinyin":"Mèngzǐ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Mèngzǐ</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Master Meng”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Mencius</b>, personal name Meng Ke, was a philosopher of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warring_States_period\">Warring States period</span> from the small state of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zou_(state)\">Zou</span></b>, regarded as the most important <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> thinker after <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucius\">Confucius</span> himself. Raised by a widowed mother whose 3 changes of residence in search of a proper environment made the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mencius's_mother\">Mother of Mencius</span> a byword for maternal devotion, he reportedly studied under followers of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zisi\">Zisi</span>, the master's grandson. For decades he traveled among courts, debating <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Hui_of_Wei\">King Hui of Wei</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Xuan_of_Qi\">King Xuan of Qi</span> and residing at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jixia_Academy\">Jixia Academy</span>, where he urged \"benevolent government\" guaranteeing livelihoods—mulberry groves so that 70-year-olds might wear silk and eat meat, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Well-field_system\">well-field system</span> in which 8 families jointly tilled the 9th, public, plot. Against rivals he insisted that <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Human_nature\">human nature</span></b> is innately good, identifying 4 inborn \"sprouts\" of virtue—compassion flowering into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ren_(philosophy)\">ren</span>, shame into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yi_(philosophy)\">yi</span>, deference into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_(Confucianism)\">li</span>, and moral discernment into wisdom—famously arguing that anyone seeing a child about to fall into a well feels spontaneous alarm. Declaring that the people rank first, the altars of state second, and the ruler last, he taught that a king who neglects the people's welfare forfeits the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mandate_of_Heaven\">Mandate of Heaven</span>, so that killing a tyrant like <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Zhou_of_Shang\">King Zhou of Shang</span> is merely punishing \"a fellow,\" while he denounced the egoist <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yang_Zhu\">Yang Zhu</span></b> and the universalist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mohism\">Mohists</span> as beasts who denied father and sovereign. <br> <br> His conversations were compiled into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mencius_(book)\"><i>Mencius</i></span>, 7 books totaling roughly 35,000 characters, the longest of the early Confucian classics, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Qian\">Sima Qian</span> accorded him a brief biography in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Records_of_the_Grand_Historian\"><i>Records of the Grand Historian</i></span>. Within the school his optimism was contested by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xunzi_(philosopher)\">Xunzi</span> (3rd century BCE), who held that goodness must be acquired through ritual, and through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span> the text remained respected but uncanonical. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span> essayist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Yu\">Han Yu</span> hailed Mencius as the last true transmitter of the Way, and under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song dynasty</span> the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Neo-Confucianism\">Neo-Confucian</span> master <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_Xi\">Zhu Xi</span> <b>grouped the work in 1190</b> with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Analects\"><i>Analects</i></span> and 2 ritual chapters as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Books_and_Five_Classics\">Four Books</span>. These became the core of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examinations</span> from 1313, and <b>in 1330</b> the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan dynasty</span> canonized him as the \"Second Sage,\" whose descendants maintained the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Temple_of_Mencius\">Temple of Mencius</span> at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zoucheng\">Zoucheng</span>. His populism so alarmed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hongwu_Emperor\">Hongwu Emperor</span> of <b>the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span> that in 1394</b> he ordered 85 passages expurgated from examination editions, yet the full text survived to inspire reformers across East Asia into the 20th century.","citation":"","answerText":"Mencius"},{"id":"cnc-032","num":"三十二","category":"China · Culture","question":"A loyal minister and poet of the state of Chu who, in despair at his kingdom's decline, is said to have drowned himself in a river around <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> BCE, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is mourned with dragon-boat races and rice dumplings each year.","answer":"Qu Yuan","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. 340–278 BCE</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"屈原","pinyin":"Qū Yuán","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Qū Yuán</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Qu Yuan</b> was a loyal minister and poet of the southern state of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chu_(state)\">Chu</span></b> during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warring_States_period\">Warring States period</span>, the first Chinese poet known by name, whose despairing suicide is mourned each year with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dragon_boat\">dragon-boat</span> races and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zongzi\">rice dumplings</span>. A kinsman of the royal house, he rose high in the counsels of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Huai_of_Chu\">King Huai of Chu</span></b>, urging internal reform and alliance with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qi_(state)\">Qi</span> against the predatory <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_(state)\">Qin</span>, until rivals seduced by the Qin envoy <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Yi\">Zhang Yi</span> slandered him into disgrace. Banished to the wilds south of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span>, he watched his warnings come true as King Huai was <b>lured to Qin in 299 BCE</b> and died a captive, while the new king exiled the poet once more. The end came in 278 BCE, when the Qin general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bai_Qi\">Bai Qi</span> sacked the Chu capital of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ying_(Chu)\">Ying</span>, and Qu Yuan, clasping a stone to his breast, drowned himself in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Miluo_River\">Miluo River</span> in present-day <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hunan\">Hunan</span>. <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Qian\">Sima Qian</span> enshrined the story in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Records_of_the_Grand_Historian\"><i>Records of the Grand Historian</i></span>, including the famous exchange in which a fisherman counsels compromise and the poet answers, \"all the world is muddy, I alone am clear.\" <br> <br> Qu Yuan stands at the head of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chu_Ci\"><i>Chu Ci</i></span></b>, the \"Songs of the South\" anthologized under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han</span>, whose shamanic imagery opened Chinese verse to flights among gods and constellations and fathered the rhapsodic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fu_(poetry)\">fu</span>. His masterpiece, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Sao\"><i>Li Sao</i></span> or \"Encountering Sorrow,\" runs to about 373 lines, the longest early Chinese poem, an allegorical self-portrait of the slandered minister adorned with fragrant orchids of virtue, while the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nine_Songs\"><i>Nine Songs</i></span> preserve hymns to river goddesses and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heavenly_Questions\"><i>Heavenly Questions</i></span> hurl more than 170 riddles at the cosmos, a title China <b>revived in 2020</b> for its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tianwen-1\">Tianwen-1</span> Mars mission. Legend holds that villagers paddled out to save him and scattered rice so the fish would spare his body, the remembered origin of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dragon_Boat_Festival\">Dragon Boat Festival</span> on the 5th day of the 5th lunar month, with its drumming boat races and leaf-wrapped zongzi. The festival became a public holiday of <b>the People's Republic in 2008</b> and in 2009 the first Chinese festival inscribed by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"UNESCO\">UNESCO</span> as intangible cultural heritage. The poet's afterlife has been equally political, for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Peace_Council\">World Peace Council</span> named him 1 of 4 world cultural celebrities in 1953 beside <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nicolaus_Copernicus\">Copernicus</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"François_Rabelais\">Rabelais</span>, and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"José_Martí\">José Martí</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guo_Moruo\">Guo Moruo</span>'s wartime drama of 1942 made him a patriot for a nation under invasion, and pilgrims still honor him at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zigui_County\">Zigui</span>, his reputed birthplace above the river gorges.","citation":"","answerText":"Qu Yuan"},{"id":"cnc-036","num":"三十六","category":"China · Culture","question":"A prince of the state of Han and the leading theorist of Legalism, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> synthesised ideas of law, statecraft and authority into a manual of rule that influenced Qin Shi Huang before he died in prison.","answer":"Han Fei","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. 280–233 BCE</span></div>","traditional":"韓非","hanzi":"韩非","pinyin":"Hán Fēi","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Hán Fēi</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Han Fei</b>, honorifically <b>Han Feizi</b> or \"<b>Master Han Fei</b>,\" was a prince of the state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_(Warring_States)\">Han</span> and the leading theorist of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Legalism_(Chinese_philosophy)\">Legalism</span></b> in the final decades of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warring_States_period\">Warring States period</span>. A stammerer who compensated with a brilliant pen, he studied under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> master <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xunzi_(philosopher)\">Xunzi</span> alongside <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Si\">Li Si</span></b>, the future Qin chancellor, and when the Han court ignored his memorials he poured his frustration into essays such as \"Solitary Indignation.\" His system fused 3 earlier strands—the impartial published law (<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fa_(concept)\">fa</span>) of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shang_Yang\">Shang Yang</span>, the administrative techniques (<i>shu</i>) of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shen_Buhai\">Shen Buhai</span></b>, and the positional power (<i>shi</i>) of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shen_Dao\">Shen Dao</span>—wielded through the \"2 handles\" of reward and punishment by a ruler who remains still and inscrutable in a Legalist adaptation of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_wei\">wu wei</span>. Assuming with Xunzi that people act from self-interest, he argued that history advances and that venerating ancient kings is as foolish as the farmer in his parable who, having once seen a rabbit break its neck on a stump, abandoned his plow to wait for another. The 55-chapter <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Feizi\"><i>Han Feizi</i></span> teems with such stories—including the spear-and-shield vendor whose boasts gave Chinese its word for \"contradiction\"—and contains the oldest surviving commentaries on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tao_Te_Ching\"><i>Tao Te Ching</i></span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Laozi\">Laozi</span>. <br> <br> In the essay \"5 Vermin\" he branded scholars, rhetoricians, knights-errant or <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Youxia\">youxia</span>, courtiers, and merchants as parasites on the productive farmer-soldier, also dismissing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mohism\">Mohist</span> and Confucian moralism as useless to a state. The young king of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_(state)\">Qin</span>—the future <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_Shi_Huang\">Qin Shi Huang</span>—reportedly exclaimed after reading these essays that he could die without regret if only he met their author, yet when Han Fei arrived <b>as an envoy in 233 BCE</b>, the jealous Li Si engineered his imprisonment and forced him to drink poison. <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Qian\">Sima Qian</span> recorded the irony in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Records_of_the_Grand_Historian\"><i>Records of the Grand Historian</i></span>, grouping his biography with those of Laozi and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuang_Zhou\">Zhuang Zhou</span>, while Qin proceeded <b>to unify China in 221 BCE</b> on broadly Han Feian lines, dividing the empire into 36 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Commandery_(China)\">commanderies</span>, standardizing script and measures, and in 213 BCE ordering the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Burning_of_books_and_burying_of_scholars\">burning of books</span>. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span> formally repudiated Legalism even as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Xuan_of_Han\">Emperor Xuan</span></b> admitted his house mixed the kingly and hegemonic ways, fixing a 2,000-year pattern often summarized as \"Confucian outside, Legalist inside.\" Long compared to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Niccolò_Machiavelli\">Machiavelli</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Prince\"><i>The Prince</i></span>, he was praised by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>, exalted during the <b>1973–1976 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Criticize_Lin,_Criticize_Confucius\">Criticize Lin, Criticize Confucius</span></b> campaign, and is quoted approvingly by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span>, whose 2014 borrowing of the line \"no state is forever strong or forever weak\" returned the prison-slain prince to the center of Chinese statecraft.","citation":"","answerText":"Han Fei"},{"id":"cnh-016","num":"十六","category":"China · History","question":"Proclaiming himself the \"First Emperor\" after unifying the realm in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> BCE, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> linked frontier walls into the Great Wall, built a colossal tomb guarded by the Terracotta Army, and ruled through harsh Legalist methods.","answer":"Qin Shi Huang","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">259–210 BCE</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"秦始皇","pinyin":"Qín Shǐhuáng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Qín Shǐhuáng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Qin Shi Huang</b> was the founder of imperial China and its first emperor, born the prince Zheng in the city of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Handan\">Handan</span> while his father was held as a hostage in the rival state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhao_(state)\">Zhao</span>. He inherited the <b>throne of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_(state)\">Qin</span> in 246 BCE</b> as a boy of about 13, ruling at first under the regency of the powerful merchant-minister <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lü_Buwei\">Lü Buwei</span> before assuming personal control and, with the aid of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Legalism_(Chinese_philosophy)\">Legalist</span> chancellor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Si\">Li Si</span>, completing the conquest of the <b>warring states in 221 BCE</b>. To mark his unprecedented achievement he discarded the title of king and fashioned a grander style, <i>huangdi</i> or <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_of_China\">emperor</span>, fusing the words for the mythic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Sovereigns_and_Five_Emperors\">Three Sovereigns and Five Emperors</span> to signal a dignity surpassing all earlier rulers. Abolishing the old decentralised order of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fengjian\">fengjian</span>, he reorganised the empire into 36 directly governed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Commandery_(China)\">commanderies</span> subdivided into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"County_(China)\">counties</span> and staffed by appointed officials answerable to the centre. His regime imposed a sweeping standardisation across the realm, unifying the written language in a common <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Seal_script\">seal script</span> promoted by Li Si, replacing the diverse regional currencies with a single round <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ban_Liang\">bronze coin</span>, and fixing uniform <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_units_of_measurement\">weights and measures</span></b> as well as a standard axle-width so that carts could run in the same wheel-ruts on every road. <br> <br> On the northern frontier he set hundreds of thousands of conscripts under the general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Meng_Tian\">Meng Tian</span> to link and extend the older state ramparts into a continuous defensive barrier against the nomadic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiongnu\">Xiongnu</span>, an early version of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Wall_of_China\">Great Wall</span> said to have stretched more than 5,000 kilometres (3,100 mi). His rule grew increasingly absolutist, culminating in the notorious <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Burning_of_books_and_burying_of_scholars\">burning of books and burying of scholars</span>, an episode in which many <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> and historical texts were consigned <b>to the flames in 213 BCE</b> and, according to tradition, some 460 scholars were executed the following year. Even more colossal was the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mausoleum_of_the_First_Qin_Emperor\">mausoleum</span> he ordered at the foot of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mount_Li\">Mount Li</span> near modern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi'an\">Xi'an</span>, a subterranean complex on which the historian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Qian\">Sima Qian</span> reports in his <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Records_of_the_Grand_Historian\"><i>Records of the Grand Historian</i></span> that 700,000 labourers toiled and which legend held to contain rivers of flowing <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mercury_(element)\">mercury</span></b>, a detail seemingly corroborated by the abnormally high mercury readings later measured in the surrounding soil. Guarding the tomb stands the famous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Terracotta_Army\">Terracotta Army</span>, an underground host of roughly 8,000 individually modelled life-size soldiers rediscovered by well-diggers in 1974, while the emperor's own obsessive quest for physical immortality led him to dispatch the alchemist <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xu_Fu\">Xu Fu</span></b> across the sea and to ingest mercury-laced <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Elixir_of_life\">elixirs</span> that may well have hastened his death. When he died suddenly while touring the east in 210 BCE, his chief eunuch <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhao_Gao\">Zhao Gao</span> concealed the death long enough to install the pliable younger son <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_Er_Shi\">Qin Er Shi</span></b> and force the suicide of the rightful heir <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fusu\">Fusu</span>, yet the brittle <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_dynasty\">Qin dynasty</span> he had founded, lasting a mere 15 years in all, disintegrated soon afterward amid the popular revolts that ushered in the succeeding <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span>, even as the centralised imperial template he created would shape Chinese governance for the next 2,000 years.","citation":"","answerText":"Qin Shi Huang"},{"id":"cnh-021","num":"二十一","category":"China · History","question":"Born a peasant and rising through rebellion to defeat his aristocratic rival in the contest for power, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> kept much of the Qin administrative system while easing its harshest Legalist laws.","answer":"Emperor Gaozu of Han","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Reigned</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. 256 – 195 BCE</span></div>","traditional":"劉邦","hanzi":"高祖","pinyin":"Gāozǔ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Gāozǔ</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Emperor Gaozu of Han</b> was the founder and first emperor of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span>, and one of the very few rulers in the history of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> to rise from peasant origins to supreme imperial power after the swift collapse of the preceding Qin. Born in the district of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pei_County\">Pei</span></b>, within the former <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warring_States_period\">Warring States</span> kingdom of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chu_(state)\">Chu</span>, he was a man of common stock who served only as a minor patrol officer under the centralized regime that the First Emperor, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_Shi_Huang\">Qin Shi Huang</span>, had forged. When that regime fractured under the misrule of the Second Emperor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_Er_Shi\">Qin Er Shi</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dazexiang_uprising\">peasant revolt</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Sheng\">Chen Sheng</span> ignited rebellion <b>across the land in 209 BCE</b>, Liu Bang abandoned his post, gathered a following, and emerged as a regional warlord known as the Lord of Pei. In 206 BCE he became the first rebel commander to reach the Qin heartland of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guanzhong\">Guanzhong</span>, entering the capital <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xianyang\">Xianyang</span> and accepting the surrender of the last Qin ruler, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ziying\">Ziying</span>, whereupon he won wide popularity by sparing the city and replacing the draconian Qin code with a famous covenant of just three articles. His success alarmed the <b>aristocratic warlord <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiang_Yu\">Xiang Yu</span></b>, who nearly had him killed at the celebrated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Feast_at_Hong_Gate\">Feast at Hong Gate</span> before carving the realm into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eighteen_Kingdoms\">Eighteen Kingdoms</span> and banishing Liu Bang to the remote southwest as King of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hanzhong\">Han</span>, a fief that would lend its name to the future dynasty.<br> <br>From this base Liu Bang launched a protracted civil war against Xiang Yu, prevailing over four years of fighting through the talents of three indispensable <b>subordinates—the strategist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Liang_(Western_Han)\">Zhang Liang</span></b>, the brilliant general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Xin\">Han Xin</span>, and the master administrator <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiao_He\">Xiao He</span>. The struggle was decided <b>at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Gaixia\">Battle of Gaixia</span> in 202 BCE</b>, where Xiang Yu was encircled and, in despair, took his own life, leaving Liu Bang to proclaim himself emperor and to establish his capital at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chang'an\">Chang'an</span>, near the ruins of the old Qin metropolis. As ruler he pursued a deliberately conciliatory course, keeping the efficient Qin system of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Commandery_(China)\">commanderies</span> and counties yet tempering it with semi-autonomous kingdoms granted to kinsmen and allies, relaxing the savage Legalist penal code and slashing land taxes to roughly 1/15 of the harvest, and—though personally scornful of scholars—eventually embracing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> court ritual devised for him by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shusun_Tong\">Shusun Tong</span>. His later years were shadowed by the menace of the steppe, <b>for in 200 BCE</b> the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiongnu\">Xiongnu</span> under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Modu_Chanyu\">Modu Chanyu</span> nearly trapped him at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Baideng\">Battle of Baideng</span>, prompting the appeasing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heqin\">heqin</span> policy of marriage alliances, while at home he and his formidable consort, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empress_Lü\">Empress Lü</span>, destroyed the over-mighty generals who had won him the throne, most notably Han Xin. When he died in 195 BCE he was succeeded by his son, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Hui_of_Han\">Emperor Hui of Han</span></b>, and the dynasty he had founded would endure, with one brief interruption, for over four centuries until 220 CE, give its name to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Chinese\">Han Chinese</span>, and find its first great chronicler in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Qian\">Sima Qian</span>, whose <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Records_of_the_Grand_Historian\"><i>Records of the Grand Historian</i></span> preserves the fullest account of his rise.","citation":"","answerText":"Emperor Gaozu of Han"},{"id":"cnh-015","num":"十五","category":"China · History","question":"A decade-long series of campaigns ending in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> BCE, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> saw the western state of Qin systematically annihilate the other 6 Warring States, bringing all of China under one ruler and ending the long age of division.","answer":"Qin's wars of unification","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">秦灭六国之战 ('the Qin destroys the six states'), 230–221 BCE</span></div>","traditional":"秦滅六國之戰","hanzi":"秦灭六国之战","pinyin":"Qín miè liù guó zhī zhàn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Qín miè liù guó zhī zhàn</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Qin's wars of unification</b> were the decade-long series of military campaigns, waged <b>between 230</b> and <b>221 BCE</b>, through which the western state of Qin destroyed its six surviving rivals and brought the whole of the Chinese world under a single sovereign for the first time. The campaigns built on advantages accumulated over the previous century, above all the rigorous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Legalism_(Chinese_philosophy)\">Legalist</span> reforms enacted by <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shang_Yang\">Shang Yang</span></b> in the 4th century BCE and a series of devastating victories, most infamously the reported massacre of some 400,000 surrendered <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhao_(state)\">Zhao</span> soldiers at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Changping\">Battle of Changping</span> around 260 BCE under the general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bai_Qi\">Bai Qi</span>. Directed by the ambitious Qin king Ying Zheng and guided by advisers such as the chancellor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Si\">Li Si</span>, the offensive opened with the rapid conquest of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_(Warring_States)\">Han</span></b> in 230 BCE and the fall of Zhao's capital <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Handan\">Handan</span> in 228 BCE, the latter hastened after the brilliant Zhao commander <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Mu\">Li Mu</span> had been removed through Qin-sponsored slander. Resistance briefly stiffened when, in 227 BCE, the assassin <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jing_Ke\">Jing Ke</span>—dispatched by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Crown_Prince_Dan\">Crown Prince Dan</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yan_(state)\">Yan</span>—failed in a celebrated attempt on the Qin king's life, yet the advance pressed on, and <b>in 225 BCE</b> the general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Ben_(Qin_dynasty)\">Wang Ben</span> reduced the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wei_(state)\">Wei</span> capital of Daliang by breaching the dikes of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_River\">Yellow River</span> to flood it. The conquest of the vast southern state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chu_(state)\">Chu</span> proved the hardest, for an overconfident thrust by the young general Li Xin with 200,000 men collapsed before the veteran <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Jian_(Qin_dynasty)\">Wang Jian</span> was recalled, raised a force reputed at 600,000, and destroyed the <b>Chu commander <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiang_Yan\">Xiang Yan</span></b> by 223 BCE.<br> <br>With its northern and central rivals eliminated, Qin extinguished the last remnants of Yan—whose court had fled to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liaodong_Peninsula\">Liaodong</span>—in 222 BCE, and the following year the easternmost state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qi_(state)\">Qi</span> capitulated almost without a fight in 221 BCE, its king having been lulled into passivity by Qin diplomacy and bribery. In 221 BCE the victorious Ying Zheng cast aside the title of king and proclaimed himself <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_Shi_Huang\">Qin Shi Huang</span>, the \"First Emperor,\" claiming the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mandate_of_Heaven\">Mandate of Heaven</span>, ending the centuries of fragmentation that had followed the decline of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_dynasty\">Zhou dynasty</span>, and founding both the short-lived <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_dynasty\">Qin dynasty</span> and the enduring imperial office of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_of_China\">Emperor of China</span>. The new emperor and his chancellor Li Si swept away the old <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fengjian\">feudal</span> order, replacing hereditary fiefs with a centralized network of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Commandery_(China)\">commanderies</span> and counties run by appointed officials, while standardizing the writing system into a uniform <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Seal_script\">seal script</span>, unifying weights and measures, and replacing the patchwork of regional coinages with the round <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ban_Liang\">Ban Liang</span> cash. To defend and glorify the new realm, the regime linked existing northern ramparts into a forerunner of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Wall_of_China\">Great Wall of China</span>, mobilized enormous conscript armies, and entombed the First Emperor alongside the famous <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Terracotta_Army\">Terracotta Army</span></b> of more than 8,000 life-sized figures, even as it crushed intellectual dissent through the notorious <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Burning_of_books_and_burying_of_scholars\">burning of books and burying of scholars</span>. Although the unified empire spanned an immense territory, its punishing exactions provoked widespread rebellion soon after Qin Shi Huang's death in 210 BCE, and the dynasty collapsed in 206 BCE after barely 15 years; even so, the centralized imperial framework forged by the wars proved remarkably durable, becoming the template that the succeeding <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span> and later regimes would sustain for more than two millennia.","citation":"","answerText":"Qin's wars of unification"},{"id":"cnh-017","num":"十七","category":"China · History","question":"Though it lasted only about 15 years before collapsing into revolt, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> created the centralised imperial system — dividing the land into commanderies run by appointed officials — that dynasties from the Han onward inherited from its founder Qin Shi Huang, and gave the West the name \"China\".","answer":"Qin dynasty","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">221–206 BCE</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"秦朝","pinyin":"Qín cháo","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Qín cháo</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Qin dynasty</b> was the first imperial dynasty of China, <b>founded in 221 BCE</b> by <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_Shi_Huang\">Qin Shi Huang</span></b> and lasting a mere 15 years <b>before its collapse in 206 BCE</b>, yet in that brief span it inaugurated a centralized imperial model that would endure for more than 2,000 years. It grew out of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Legalism_(Chinese_philosophy)\">Legalist</span>-reformed state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_(state)\">Qin</span>, which between 230 and 221 BCE <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin's_wars_of_unification\">conquered</span> its rival kingdoms one after another to end the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warring_States_period\">Warring States period</span>, whereupon its king assumed the new title of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_of_China\">emperor</span> to signal a sovereignty grander than any earlier ruler's. Rejecting the old <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fengjian\">feudal</span> order, the regime carved the empire into 36 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Commandery_(China)\">commanderies</span> subdivided into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"County_(China)\">counties</span> and staffed by centrally appointed, salaried officials rather than hereditary lords, establishing a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bureaucracy\">bureaucratic</span> template that every dynasty from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han</span> onward would inherit largely intact. Under the guidance of his chancellor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Si\">Li Si</span>, the First Emperor standardized the written language into a unified <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Seal_script\">seal script</span>, replaced the coinages of the conquered states with a single round <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ban_Liang\">Ban Liang</span> currency, and fixed uniform weights, measures, and cart-axle widths across the realm, binding commerce and communication under a single set of standards. Vast conscript armies were mobilized to link existing ramparts into the northern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Wall_of_China\">Great Wall</span> against the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiongnu\">Xiongnu</span>, to cut the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lingqu_Canal\">Lingqu Canal</span> through the south, and to raise a colossal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mausoleum_of_the_First_Qin_Emperor\">mausoleum</span> guarded by the some 8,000 figures of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Terracotta_Army\">Terracotta Army</span>, <b>rediscovered only in 1974</b>. <br> <br> The dynasty's methods were brutally coercive, most notoriously in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Burning_of_books_and_burying_of_scholars\">burning of books and burying of scholars</span> of 213 to 212 BCE, when texts deemed subversive were destroyed and, by tradition, around 460 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> scholars were executed. When Qin Shi Huang died in 210 BCE while touring his empire in search of an elixir of immortality—a quest that may itself have hastened his end through mercury poisoning—his death was concealed by Li Si and the <b>scheming eunuch <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhao_Gao\">Zhao Gao</span></b>, who suppressed his true wishes for the succession. The conspirators forced the capable heir <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fusu\">Fusu</span> and the frontier general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Meng_Tian\">Meng Tian</span> to take their own lives, installing instead the pliable younger son <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_Er_Shi\">Qin Er Shi</span> as a puppet Second Emperor whose incompetence and Zhao Gao's continued intrigues only hastened the dynasty's ruin. Misgovernment and crushing burdens soon ignited the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dazexiang_Uprising\">Dazexiang Uprising</span> of 209 BCE under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Sheng\">Chen Sheng</span>, the first great popular revolt in Chinese history, and as rebellion engulfed the country the rival commanders <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiang_Yu\">Xiang Yu</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Bang\">Liu Bang</span></b> closed in until the last Qin ruler <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ziying\">Ziying</span> surrendered in 206 BCE and the capital <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xianyang\">Xianyang</span> was put to the torch. The ensuing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chu–Han_Contention\">Chu–Han Contention</span> ended with Liu Bang's victory and the founding of the long-lived Han, which preserved the centralized machinery of the Qin while tempering its harshest laws, and the very <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Names_of_China\">name \"China\"</span></b> is widely thought to descend, by way of Persian and Sanskrit intermediaries, from that of this brief but foundational regime.","citation":"","answerText":"Qin dynasty"},{"id":"cnc-037","num":"三十七","category":"China · Culture","question":"Standardised across the realm after Qin Shi Huang unified the country and abolished regional variants, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>, with its evenly curved strokes, survives today mainly on name seals and in calligraphy.","answer":"seal script","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">篆书 (zhuànshū, 'seal script')</span></div>","traditional":"篆書","hanzi":"篆书","pinyin":"zhuànshū","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">zhuànshū</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Seal script</b> is an ancient style of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_characters\">Chinese writing</span></b> that flourished before the imperial era and endures as one of the principal scripts of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_calligraphy\">Chinese calligraphy</span>. It is conventionally divided into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Large_seal_script\">large seal script</span>, a loose term for the diverse archaic forms of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_dynasty\">Zhou</span> era, and the more regular <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Small_seal_script\">small seal script</span> that succeeded it. The earlier forms descend ultimately from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Oracle_bone_script\">oracle bone script</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shang_dynasty\">Shang</span> and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_bronze_inscriptions\">bronze inscriptions</span></b> cast on ritual vessels, exemplified in the engraved <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stone_Drums_of_Qin\">Stone Drums of Qin</span>. After <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_Shi_Huang\">Qin Shi Huang</span> <b>unified the realm in 221 BCE</b>, his chancellor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Si\">Li Si</span> oversaw a sweeping reform that abolished the divergent scripts of the conquered <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warring_States_period\">Warring States</span> and imposed the small seal as a single empire-wide standard. This policy of “writing in the same script” was propagated through model primers such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cangjiepian\"><i>Cangjiepian</i></span>, named for the legendary scribe <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cangjie\">Cangjie</span></b>, and the resulting forms are marked by elongated, symmetrical characters built from evenly curved <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stroke_(CJK_character)\">strokes</span> of nearly uniform thickness. <br> <br> Because its careful curves were slow to execute, the small seal was soon supplanted for everyday use by the simpler <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Clerical_script\">clerical script</span></b>, which spread under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_dynasty\">Qin</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han</span> and in turn gave rise to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Regular_script\">regular script</span> still in use today. The seal forms nonetheless retained great prestige, and <b>around 100 CE</b> the scholar <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xu_Shen\">Xu Shen</span> adopted them as the basis of his pioneering character dictionary, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shuowen_Jiezi\"><i>Shuowen Jiezi</i></span>, which dissected the structure of thousands of graphs. Although banished from daily writing, the script enjoyed periodic revivals among calligraphers, notably under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span>, and inspired ornamental variants such as the decorative <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bird-worm_seal_script\">bird-worm seal script</span>. Today it survives chiefly as an artistic and ceremonial form, engraved on the personal name <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Seal_(East_Asia)\">seals</span>, or chops, that authenticate documents and artworks, struck on early coins like the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ban_Liang\">Ban Liang</span>, and prized by practitioners of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_seal_carving\">seal carving</span> across <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>. The art of seal engraving was <b>inscribed in 2009</b> on the UNESCO list of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Intangible_cultural_heritage\">intangible cultural heritage</span>, and the script remains one of the five canonical styles studied in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"East_Asian_calligraphy\">East Asian calligraphy</span> alongside the clerical, regular, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Semi-cursive_script\">running</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cursive_script_(East_Asia)\">cursive</span> hands.","citation":"","answerText":"seal script"},{"id":"cnc-038","num":"三十八","category":"China · Culture","question":"Built and rebuilt over many centuries to keep out northern nomads, with the surviving brick sections largely dating from the Ming dynasty, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> stretches thousands of kilometres and is among the most recognisable World Heritage symbols of the country.","answer":"Great Wall of China","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">万里长城 ('ten-thousand-li long wall')</span></div>","traditional":"萬里長城","hanzi":"万里长城","pinyin":"Wànlǐ Chángchéng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Wànlǐ Chángchéng</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“10,000-li long wall”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Great Wall of China</b> is the system of fortifications built and rebuilt across northern China for over 2,000 years to manage the horse-borne peoples of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eurasian_Steppe\">Eurasian Steppe</span></b>, and a comprehensive state survey announced in 2012 measured walls of all eras at a combined 21,196 kilometers (13,171 mi). Its ancestors were the separate ramparts of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warring_States_period\">Warring States</span> kingdoms such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhao_(state)\">Zhao</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yan_(state)\">Yan</span>, which <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_Shi_Huang\">Qin Shi Huang</span> ordered joined <b>after his unification of 221 BCE</b>, sending the general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Meng_Tian\">Meng Tian</span> with a reported 300,000 men to raise ramparts of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rammed_earth\">rammed earth</span>. The project's human cost passed into legend as the tale of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lady_Meng_Jiang\">Lady Meng Jiang</span>, whose weeping for a husband conscripted to death cracked the wall open to yield his bones. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span> drove the line far westward along the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hexi_Corridor\">Hexi Corridor</span> to <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yumen_Pass\">Yumen Pass</span></b>, screening the new <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk_Road\">Silk Road</span> from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiongnu\">Xiongnu</span> with watchposts whose beacon signals could outpace any rider. Later dynasties added their own lines, though the frontier worked less as an impermeable barrier than as a graded obstacle, customs gate, and signal network, and under the Mongol <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan dynasty</span>, which ruled both sides, building lapsed altogether. <br> <br> The brick-and-stone wall in the modern imagination is the work of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming dynasty</span>, which turned to massive fortification <b>after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tumu_Crisis\">Tumu Crisis</span> of 1449</b>, when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongols\">Mongol</span> horsemen captured the reigning emperor barely 2 days' ride from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>. A 2009 survey put the Ming system at 8,850 kilometers (5,500 mi), studded with thousands of watchtowers and anchored by great passes, from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanhai_Pass\">Shanhai Pass</span>, where the \"Old Dragon's Head\" wades into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bohai_Sea\">Bohai Sea</span>, through showpiece <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Badaling\">Badaling</span></b> to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiayu_Pass\">Jiayu Pass</span> at the desert's edge. Even this colossus fell not to assault but to politics, when the Ming general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Sangui\">Wu Sangui</span> opened <b>the Shanhai gates in 1644</b> to the Manchus, whose <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> ruled the steppe directly and let the wall decay. Reborn as national symbol, it framed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>'s line that one is no true man until one reaches it and the photographs of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Richard_Nixon\">Richard Nixon</span>'s 1972 visit, though the cherished belief that it is visible from space has been refuted by astronauts themselves. Inscribed as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Heritage_Site\">World Heritage Site</span> in 1987 and voted among the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_7_Wonders_of_the_World\">New 7 Wonders of the World</span></b> in 2007, it now draws some 10 million visitors a year to Badaling alone, even as surveys warn that roughly 30 percent of the Ming wall has already crumbled away.","citation":"","answerText":"Great Wall of China"},{"id":"cng-001","num":"一","category":"China · Geography","question":"The <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> stretches some 5,000 km (3,100 mi) from the Pamirs in the west to the Pacific coast in the east and shares land borders with 14 nations.","answer":"China","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">中国 (Zhōngguó, 'central state / Middle Kingdom')</span></div>","traditional":"中國","hanzi":"中国","pinyin":"Zhōngguó","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōngguó</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Middle Kingdom”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>China</b>, officially the <b>People's Republic of China</b>, is a country in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"East_Asia\">East Asia</span> that spans roughly 9.6 million square kilometers (3.7 million sq mi), ranking as the 3rd- or 4th-largest nation in the world by total area. Its territory extends some 5,000 kilometers (3,100 mi) from the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pamir_Mountains\">Pamir Mountains</span></b> in the west to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pacific_Ocean\">Pacific</span> coast in the east, embracing terrain that ranges from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Himalayas\">Himalayas</span> and vast plateaus to fertile river valleys, and it shares land frontiers with 14 countries, tying <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russia\">Russia</span> for the most of any nation. Among the world's oldest continuous civilizations, China traces its roots to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Neolithic\">Neolithic</span> cultures along the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_River\">Yellow River</span>, a region long regarded as one of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cradle_of_civilization\">cradles of civilization</span>. Its first unified empire was <b>forged in 221 BCE</b> by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_Shi_Huang\">Qin Shi Huang</span>, founder of the short-lived <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_dynasty\">Qin dynasty</span>, inaugurating a succession of imperial dynasties that ruled the country for over 2,000 years. That imperial order endured until the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> was toppled <b>in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinhai_Revolution\">Xinhai Revolution</span> of 1911</b>, which gave rise to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)\">Republic of China</span> the following year and brought thousands of years of dynastic rule to an end. <br> <br> After decades of warlordism, Japanese invasion, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">civil war</span> between Nationalists and Communists, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Proclamation_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">proclaimed the new republic</span> on October 1, <b>1949</b>, establishing a state led by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span>. Today it is governed as a unitary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"One-party_state\">one-party</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialist_state\">socialist republic</span> in which the party's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"General_Secretary_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">general secretary</span>, currently <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span>—who is also <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"President_of_China\">state president</span> and the country's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paramount_leader\">paramount leader</span>—wields predominant authority, while <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Qiang\">Li Qiang</span> has <b>served as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Premier_of_the_State_Council\">premier</span></b> since 2023. The country is administratively organized into 23 provinces—including <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span>, which it claims but does not control—alongside 5 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Autonomous_regions_of_China\">autonomous regions</span>, 4 directly governed municipalities, and 2 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Special_administrative_regions_of_China\">special administrative regions</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Macau\">Macau</span>, with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_People's_Congress\">National People's Congress</span> as its constitutional legislature and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> as its capital. Beginning with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">market reforms</span> launched by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> in 1978, China achieved decades of rapid growth that transformed it into the world's largest manufacturer and exporter and the 2nd-largest national economy by nominal output, anchored by industrial and financial hubs such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span>. With a population of roughly 1.41 billion, China was the world's most populous country for centuries until it was overtaken by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"India\">India</span> in 2023, and its numbers have since begun to fall amid one of the lowest birth rates on record; as a recognized nuclear-weapon state and a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Permanent_members_of_the_United_Nations_Security_Council\">permanent member of the United Nations Security Council</span></b>, it remains one of the most consequential powers of the 21st century.","citation":"","answerText":"China"},{"id":"cng-026","num":"二十六","category":"China · Geography","question":"The innermost and shallowest of China's seas, a gulf almost enclosed by the Liaodong and Shandong peninsulas, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> receives the Yellow River and rings the capital region.","answer":"Bohai Sea","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">渤海 (Bó Hǎi), an enclosed gulf of the Yellow Sea</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"渤海","pinyin":"Bó Hǎi","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Bó Hǎi</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Bohai Sea</b> is the innermost and shallowest of China’s seas, a nearly landlocked gulf of about 77,000 square kilometres (30,000 sq mi) whose waters average only some 18 metres (59 ft) in depth. It is embraced by the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liaodong_Peninsula\">Liaodong</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shandong_Peninsula\">Shandong</span> peninsulas, communicates with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_Sea\">Yellow Sea</span> through the roughly 105-kilometre-wide (65.2 mi) <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bohai_Strait\">Bohai Strait</span>, and divides internally into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liaodong_Bay\">Liaodong</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bohai_Bay\">Bohai</span>, and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Laizhou_Bay\">Laizhou</span></b> bays. Into Laizhou Bay pours the silt-laden <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_River\">Yellow River</span>, whose advancing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_River_Delta\">delta</span> has at times grown by kilometres in a decade, while the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hai_River\">Hai</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luan_River\">Luan</span>, and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liao_River\">Liao</span></b> rivers freshen the gulf to salinities near 30 parts per thousand, winter ice sheets form across Liaodong Bay, and those northern waters host China’s only breeding colony of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Spotted_seal\">spotted seal</span>. Beneath the seabed lie rich hydrocarbons, and the offshore complex operated by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"CNOOC\">CNOOC</span> surpassed <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Daqing\">Daqing</span> around 2021</b> as the country’s largest crude oil producer at more than 30 million tonnes (33 million tons) a year, though the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2011_Bohai_Bay_oil_spill\">2011 Bohai Bay oil spill</span> exposed the risks. Heavy effluent from surrounding industry and sweeping <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Land_reclamation\">land reclamation</span> have meanwhile made this one of the most stressed seas on Earth, erasing tidal flats critical to shorebirds of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"East_Asian–Australasian_Flyway\">East Asian–Australasian Flyway</span>. <br> <br> In Chinese myth these waters concealed the immortal isles of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mount_Penglai\">Penglai</span>, and <b>around 219 BCE <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_Shi_Huang\">Qin Shi Huang</span></b> dispatched the magician <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xu_Fu\">Xu Fu</span> from this coast with thousands of youths to seek the elixir of life, a quest from which none returned. The sea’s name later travelled north when the Manchurian-Korean kingdom of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Balhae\">Balhae</span>, founded in 698, adopted the same characters for its state. Guarding the maritime approach to the capital, the gulf became a battleground of the imperial twilight, as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taku_Forts\">Taku Forts</span> at the Hai’s mouth were stormed by foreign fleets during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Opium_War\">Second Opium War</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boxer_Rebellion\">Boxer Rebellion</span>, while the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beiyang_Fleet\">Beiyang Fleet</span>’s base at Port Arthur on the strait <b>witnessed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Port_Arthur_massacre_(China)\">Port Arthur massacre</span> of 1894</b> in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Sino-Japanese_War\">First Sino-Japanese War</span> and the great <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Siege_of_Port_Arthur\">siege</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russo-Japanese_War\">Russo-Japanese War</span> a decade later. Today the shoreline anchors the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bohai_Economic_Rim\">Bohai Economic Rim</span>, where <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tianjin\">Tianjin</span> handles on the order of 20 million <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Twenty-foot_equivalent_unit\">containers</span> annually and the coal and ore wharves of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tangshan\">Tangshan</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qinhuangdao\">Qinhuangdao</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dalian\">Dalian</span> rank among the busiest on the planet by tonnage. The same shore endured the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1976_Tangshan_earthquake\">1976 Tangshan earthquake</span></b> that killed some 242,000 people, and planners still debate a roughly 123-kilometre (76.4 mi) <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Undersea_tunnel\">undersea tunnel</span> from Dalian to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yantai\">Yantai</span> that would be the longest ever bored beneath a sea.","citation":"","answerText":"Bohai Sea"},{"id":"cng-031","num":"三十一","category":"China · Geography","question":"A fertile, densely settled lowland ringed by mountains in the southwest, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> — drained by tributaries of the Yangtze and centred on Chengdu and Chongqing — enjoys a mild, misty climate ideal for rice and rapeseed.","answer":"Sichuan Basin","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">四川 (Sìchuān, 'four circuits')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"四川盆地","pinyin":"Sìchuān Péndì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Sìchuān Péndì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Sichuan Basin</b>, nicknamed the Red Basin by <b>the geographer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ferdinand_von_Richthofen\">Ferdinand von Richthofen</span></b> for its purple-red <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sandstone\">sandstone</span> hills, is a lowland of some 165,000 square kilometers (63,700 sq mi) in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan\">Sichuan</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chongqing\">Chongqing</span>, walled in by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qinling\">Qinling</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Daba_Mountains\">Daba Mountains</span></b> to the north, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Mountains\">Wu Mountains</span> to the east, and the rampart of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_Plateau\">Tibetan Plateau</span> to the west. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span> traces its southern rim, gathering the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Min_River_(Sichuan)\">Min</span></b>, Tuo, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jialing_River\">Jialing</span> rivers before escaping eastward through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Gorges\">Three Gorges</span>. Sheltered from northern cold, the basin enjoys a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Humid_subtropical_climate\">humid subtropical climate</span> with nearly frost-free winters but ranks among the cloudiest places in China, receiving only about 1,000–1,300 hours of sunshine a year, a murk so proverbial that dogs of Shu were said to bark at the sun. Its warmth, mists, and fertile purple soils sustain intensive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rice\">rice</span> and nation-leading <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rapeseed\">rapeseed</span> cultivation, along with citrus and the country's largest pig herd, supporting on the order of 100 million people at extraordinary rural densities. The agricultural heart is the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chengdu_Plain\">Chengdu Plain</span>, watered <b>since 256 BCE</b> by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dujiangyan\">Dujiangyan</span> irrigation works of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Bing\">Li Bing</span>, which still serve hundreds of thousands of hectares and earned the region its ancient title of \"Land of Abundance.\" <br> <br> Civilization here reaches deep into the Bronze Age, when the enigmatic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shu_(kingdom)\">Shu kingdom</span> cast the colossal masks of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sanxingdui\">Sanxingdui</span> around the 12th century BCE, sharing the basin with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ba_(state)\">Ba</span> until <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_(state)\">Qin</span> <b>annexed both in 316 BCE</b>. Behind its mountain walls the basin repeatedly became a redoubt, most famously as the realm of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shu_Han\">Shu Han</span> founded by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Bei\">Liu Bei</span> and counseled by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuge_Liang\">Zhuge Liang</span> from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chengdu\">Chengdu</span> in the 3rd century CE, while the poet <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Bai\">Li Bai</span> immortalized the perilous cliff galleries in <i>The Road to Shu Is Hard</i>. At <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zigong\">Zigong</span> drillers tapping brine pioneered deep-well technology, burning piped <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Natural_gas\">natural gas</span> to boil <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Salt_in_Chinese_history\">salt</span> for roughly 2 millennia and sinking the first borehole past 1,000 meters (3,300 ft) <b>in 1835</b>, a legacy continued today as the basin yields China's richest conventional gas and its first major <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shale_gas\">shale gas</span> field, opened in 2012. The fortress geography told again in the Second World War, when Chongqing served as the bombed wartime capital from 1937 to 1945, enduring the years-long <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bombing_of_Chongqing\">Bombing of Chongqing</span>, and once more in the 1960s when the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Third_Front_(China)\">Third Front</span> hid strategic industry among its hills. Nature exacted its own price along the western rim, where the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Longmenshan_Fault\">Longmenshan Fault</span></b> unleashed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2008_Sichuan_earthquake\">2008 Sichuan earthquake</span> that killed about 87,000 people on the mountainous edge that also shelters the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Giant_panda\">giant panda</span>, yet the basin thrives as a twin-engine megaregion celebrated worldwide for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan_cuisine\">Sichuan cuisine</span> and fiery <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Baijiu\">baijiu</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Sichuan Basin"},{"id":"cng-041","num":"四十一","category":"China · Geography","question":"The major river system of the south, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> formed by the joining of the West, North and East rivers empties through a densely urbanised delta past Guangzhou, Hong Kong and Macau.","answer":"Pearl River","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">珠江 (Zhū Jiāng, 'pearl river')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"珠江","pinyin":"Zhū Jiāng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhū Jiāng</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“pearl river”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Pearl River</b> is the principal river system of southern China, formed where the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_River\">West River</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bei_River\">North River</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dong_River\">East River</span> converge before pouring into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South_China_Sea\">South China Sea</span>. Measured along its longest headstream it runs about 2,400 kilometres (1,500 mi), ranking as the country’s 3rd-longest river and its 2nd by volume, draining a basin of roughly 450,000 square kilometres (170,000 sq mi) that reaches into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yunnan\">Yunnan</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guizhou\">Guizhou</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangxi\">Guangxi</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangdong\">Guangdong</span>, and a corner of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vietnam\">Vietnam</span>. The dominant branch, the West River, rises on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yunnan–Guizhou_Plateau\">Yunnan–Guizhou Plateau</span> as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanpan_River\">Nanpan River</span></b> and gathers most of the system’s flow, while the name “Pearl” derives from the Haizhu Stone, a long-vanished islet of smooth rock once washed by the current at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou\">Guangzhou</span>. Near the sea the river fans into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pearl_River_Delta\">Pearl River Delta</span>, discharging through eight principal mouths, the easternmost and most storied being the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bocca_Tigris\">Bocca Tigris</span></b>, the narrow “Tiger’s Gate” guarding the approach to Guangzhou. That delta has swollen into one of the most densely urbanised regions on Earth, a manufacturing powerhouse often dubbed the world’s factory, anchoring the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangdong–Hong_Kong–Macau_Greater_Bay_Area\">Greater Bay Area</span> that knits together Guangzhou, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Special_economic_zones_of_China\">special economic zones</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shenzhen\">Shenzhen</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuhai\">Zhuhai</span>, the export city of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dongguan\">Dongguan</span>, and the territories of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Macau\">Macau</span> into a conurbation of more than 70 million people. <br> <br> <b>In 214 BCE</b> the armies of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_Shi_Huang\">Qin Shi Huang</span> pushed south into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lingnan\">Lingnan</span> by way of the newly cut <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lingqu_Canal\">Lingqu Canal</span>, which joined the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiang_River\">Xiang River</span> of the Yangtze basin to the Pearl’s headwaters, and after the dynasty fell the region flowered as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanyue\">Nanyue</span> kingdom ruled from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Panyu_District\">Panyu</span>, forerunner of modern Guangzhou. Guangzhou had long been a terminus of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maritime_Silk_Road\">Maritime Silk Road</span>, and <b>in 1557</b> the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Portuguese_Empire\">Portuguese</span> obtained a permanent trading base at Macau, the first lasting European foothold on the China coast. From 1757 the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> court funnelled all Western maritime commerce through Guangzhou under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Canton_System\">Canton System</span>, confining foreign merchants to the riverside <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Thirteen_Factories\">Thirteen Factories</span> and their ships to the anchorage at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Whampoa_anchorage\">Whampoa</span>. Tensions over the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Opium\">opium</span> trade erupted when the imperial commissioner <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lin_Zexu\">Lin Zexu</span> destroyed more than 1,000 tonnes (1,100 tons) of the <b>drug at Humen in 1839</b>, igniting the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Opium_War\">First Opium War</span> that ended with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Nanking\">Treaty of Nanking</span> of 1842 and the cession of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_Island\">Hong Kong Island</span> to Britain. The delta later seeded the Chinese republican movement as the home region of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Yat-sen\">Sun Yat-sen</span> and site of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Whampoa_Military_Academy\">Whampoa Military Academy</span> founded in 1924, and after Hong Kong and Macau returned to Chinese rule under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"One_country,_two_systems\">one country, two systems</span> in 1997 and 1999 the estuary was spanned in 2018 by the 55-kilometre (34 mi) <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong–Zhuhai–Macau_Bridge\">Hong Kong–Zhuhai–Macau Bridge</span></b>, the longest sea crossing in the world.","citation":"","answerText":"Pearl River"},{"id":"cng-047","num":"四十七","category":"China · Geography","question":"Rising in Shandong, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the foremost of the country's Five Great Mountains, a place where emperors performed grand sacrifices to heaven and a long-revered site of pilgrimage.","answer":"Mount Tai","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">泰山 (Tài Shān, 'supreme / peaceful mountain')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"泰山","pinyin":"Tài Shān","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Tài Shān</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“supreme mountain”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Mount Tai</b> is a mountain in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shandong\">Shandong</span> province rising to 1,545 metres (5,069 ft) at its <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jade_Emperor\">Jade Emperor</span></b> Peak, and the foremost of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sacred_Mountains_of_China\">Five Great Mountains</span>, the cardinal sacred peaks of imperial China and of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Taoism</span>. Rising abruptly above the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"North_China_Plain\">North China Plain</span> near the city of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tai'an\">Tai’an</span>, it is the eastern member of that quintet and has from antiquity symbolised sunrise, birth, and renewal, drawing pilgrims to watch the dawn break over a sea of clouds from its summit. The mountain is venerated as the seat of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"God_of_Mount_Tai\">Great Emperor of the Eastern Peak</span></b>, a deity governing life and death, and of his daughter <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bixia_Yuanjun\">Bixia Yuanjun</span>, the Goddess of the Azure Clouds whose summit shrine has long attracted women praying for children, while <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Buddhism\">Buddhism</span> too left temples along its slopes. The classic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pilgrimage\">pilgrimage</span> ascent begins at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dai_Temple\">Dai Temple</span></b> in Tai’an, where the imperial rites traditionally opened, and climbs a stone stairway of roughly 7,000 steps that steepens at the Eighteen Bends before reaching the cloud-wreathed Southern Gate to Heaven. Geologically the massif exposes some of the oldest rocks in eastern China, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Archean\">Archean</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gneiss\">gneisses</span> around 2.5 billion years old, and its ancient <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cypress\">cypress</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pinus\">pine</span> groves and thousands of carved inscriptions <b>earned it inscription in 1987</b> as a mixed cultural and natural <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Heritage_Site\">World Heritage Site</span>. <br> <br> Mount Tai is above all the stage of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Feng_and_Shan_sacrifices\">feng and shan sacrifices</span>, the most solemn of imperial rites, in which a ruler ascended to offer thanks to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tian\">heaven</span> on the summit and to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Houtu\">earth</span> at the foot, a ceremony bound up with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mandate_of_Heaven\">Mandate of Heaven</span> and first performed in unified <b>China by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_Shi_Huang\">Qin Shi Huang</span> in 219 BCE</b>. Only a handful of later dynasts deemed their reigns worthy to repeat it, among them <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Wu_of_Han\">Emperor Wu of Han</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span>’s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Gaozong_of_Tang\">Gaozong</span> accompanied by the future empress <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Zetian\">Wu Zetian</span>, and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song</span> ruler <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Zhenzong\">Emperor Zhenzong</span> in 1008</b>, the last sovereign ever to perform the full sacrifice. The sages reinforced its prestige, for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucius\">Confucius</span> hailed from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qufu\">Qufu</span> in the nearby state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lu_(state)\">Lu</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mencius\">Mencius</span> recorded the master’s saying that, having climbed Mount Tai, he found the whole world small. Its rocks bear thousands of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_calligraphy\">calligraphic</span> inscriptions accumulated over 2,000 years, including a celebrated carving of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Diamond_Sutra\">Diamond Sutra</span> and a blank “Wordless Stele” traditionally ascribed to Emperor Wu, and the historian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Qian\">Sima Qian</span> lent the peak proverbial weight by writing that a death might be heavier than Mount Tai or lighter than a feather. So deeply did the mountain enter the language that being “as stable as Mount Tai” became a byword for permanence, and today the ancient pilgrim route is paralleled by an <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Aerial_tramway\">aerial tramway</span></b> installed in 1983 that helps carry millions of visitors a year up one of the most revered <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tourism_in_China\">tourist</span> sites in China.","citation":"","answerText":"Mount Tai"},{"id":"cng-059","num":"五十九","category":"China · Geography","question":"A sprawling southwestern municipality, by some measures the most populous in the world within its vast administrative area, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> sits where the Jialing meets the Yangtze and served as China's capital during the war against Japan.","answer":"Chongqing","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">重庆 (Chóngqìng, 'double celebration')</span></div>","traditional":"重慶","hanzi":"重庆","pinyin":"Chóngqìng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Chóngqìng</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“double celebration”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Chongqing</b> is a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Direct-administered_municipalities_of_China\">directly governed municipality</span></b> in southwestern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>, administering a vast area of some 82,000 square kilometres (32,000 sq mi) that, with a population around 32 million, is by some reckonings the most populous city in the world. The city proper rises on steep hills around the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuzhong_District\">peninsula</span></b> at the confluence of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jialing_River\">Jialing River</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span>, a setting that has earned it the nicknames “Mountain City” and, for its persistent winter mists, the “Fog Capital.” Carved <b>out of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan\">Sichuan</span> in 1997</b> to become China’s youngest and largest municipality, it was charged in part with resettling the more than a million people displaced by the rising reservoir of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Gorges_Dam\">Three Gorges Dam</span> downstream, whose backwaters reach the city along the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Gorges\">Three Gorges</span>. Its dramatic vertical landscape of bridges, cliff-side towers, and a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chongqing_Rail_Transit\">monorail</span> threading through an apartment block has made it an internet emblem of the futuristic “8D city,” anchored by sights such as the stilted <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hongya_Cave\">Hongyadong</span> complex, while its sweltering <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Humid_subtropical_climate\">humid summers</span> rank it among the Yangtze’s notoriously hot “furnace cities.” Industrially the municipality is a heavyweight, producing a large share of the world’s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Laptop\">laptops</span> and ranking among China’s biggest makers of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Automotive_industry_in_China\">automobiles</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Motorcycle\">motorcycles</span>, even as it is celebrated nationwide for its fiery <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chongqing_hot_pot\">hot pot</span></b> seasoned with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan_pepper\">Sichuan pepper</span>. <br> <br> The site was the heart of the ancient state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ba_(state)\">Ba</span>, <b>absorbed by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_(state)\">Qin</span> in 316 BCE</b>, and bore the names Jiangzhou and Yuzhou before acquiring its present name in 1189, when the future <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Guangzong_of_Song\">Emperor Guangzong</span> marked his enfeoffment and accession as a “double celebration.” In 1259 the nearby cliff fortress at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hechuan_District\">Hechuan</span> withstood a Mongol siege during which the Great Khan <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Möngke_Khan\">Möngke</span> died, an event that helped halt the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongol_Empire\">Mongol Empire</span>’s expansion and is remembered as the place “where God broke his whip.” Chongqing was opened to foreign trade <b>as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_ports\">treaty port</span> in 1891</b>, becoming the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span>’s commercial gateway to the upper Yangtze and the far southwest. Its greatest historical moment came in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Sino-Japanese_War\">Second Sino-Japanese War</span>, when the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Nationalist</span> government of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span> made it China’s wartime capital from 1938, enduring years of devastating Japanese air raids in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bombing_of_Chongqing\">Bombing of Chongqing</span> before hosting the failed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chongqing_Negotiations\">Chongqing Negotiations</span> between Chiang and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> in 1945, talks attended by the Communist envoy <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span>. In the reform era it grew into an engine of western development and a twin metropolis with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chengdu\">Chengdu</span>, though it drew global headlines in 2012 when its ambitious Party chief <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bo_Xilai\">Bo Xilai</span> fell in a sensational <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Lijun_incident\">murder-and-defection scandal</span></b>, while within its borders the medieval <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dazu_Rock_Carvings\">Dazu Rock Carvings</span> endure as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Heritage_Site\">World Heritage Site</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Chongqing"},{"id":"cng-066","num":"六十六","category":"China · Geography","question":"A southern autonomous region bordering Vietnam and famed for the dramatic karst pinnacles around Guilin, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was established for the Zhuang, the country's largest ethnic minority.","answer":"Guangxi","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">广西 (Guǎngxī, 'western expanse')</span></div>","traditional":"廣西","hanzi":"广西","pinyin":"Guǎngxī","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Guǎngxī</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Guangxi</b>, formally the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, is a southern region of 237,600 square kilometers (91,740 sq mi) and 50.1 million people in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2020_Chinese_census\">2020 census</span></b>, bordering <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vietnam\">Vietnam</span> and fronting the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gulf_of_Tonkin\">Gulf of Tonkin</span> as the only one of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Autonomous_regions_of_China\">autonomous regions</span> with a seacoast, established on 5 March 1958 for the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuang_people\">Zhuang</span></b>, China's largest ethnic minority with some 19.6 million people nationwide, roughly a 3rd of the region's population. Its scenery is defined by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Karst\">karst</span>, from the pinnacles of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guilin\">Guilin</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangshuo_County\">Yangshuo</span> mirrored in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_River\">Li River</span> to the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ban_Gioc–Detian_Falls\">Ban Gioc–Detian Falls</span></b> shared with Vietnam, Asia's largest transnational cataract, while <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao'er_Mountain\">Mao'er Mountain</span> rises to 2,141 meters (7,024 ft) as the highest point in South China. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_River\">Xi River</span>, trunk stream of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pearl_River\">Pearl River</span> system, drains the region and was joined to the Yangtze <b>basin as early as 214 BCE</b> by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lingqu\">Lingqu</span>, often called the world's oldest contour canal. Zhuang culture remains vivid, carried in a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kra–Dai_languages\">Kra–Dai language</span> akin to Thai written historically in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sawndip\">sawndip</span> character script, in 2,000-year-old <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bronze_drum\">bronze drums</span>, in the cliff paintings of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zuojiang_Huashan_Rock_Art_Cultural_Landscape\">Huashan rock art</span>, some 1,900 figures created between the 5th century BCE and the 2nd century CE and <b>listed by UNESCO in 2016</b>, and in the song-fairy <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Sanjie\">Liu Sanjie</span> honored at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Double_Third_Festival\">Double Third Festival</span>. Economically the region grows over 60 percent of China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sugarcane\">sugarcane</span>, exports the cult snail-noodle dish <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luosifen\">luosifen</span> from industrial <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liuzhou\">Liuzhou</span>, hosts the annual expo binding <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanning\">Nanning</span> to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"ASEAN\">ASEAN</span> <b>since 2004</b>, and is digging the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pinglu_Canal\">Pinglu Canal</span>, begun in 2022 at some 72.7 billion yuan as the People's Republic's first great new canal to the sea. <br> <br> In antiquity the land of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Baiyue\">Baiyue</span> was annexed by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_dynasty\">Qin dynasty</span> in 214 BCE on the logistics of the Lingqu, passed through the breakaway kingdom of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanyue\">Nanyue</span>, and took its name from the \"Guangnan West\" circuit of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song dynasty</span>. Modern history erupted here in January 1851, when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Xiuquan\">Hong Xiuquan</span> proclaimed his heavenly kingdom at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jintian_Uprising\">Jintian Uprising</span> in a Guangxi village, igniting the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiping_Rebellion\">Taiping Rebellion</span> that consumed perhaps 20–30 million lives over 14 years. On this frontier Chinese troops won the celebrated victory at Zhennan Pass in 1885 during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-French_War\">Sino-French War</span>, and in the Republican era the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Guangxi_clique\">New Guangxi clique</span> of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Zongren\">Li Zongren</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bai_Chongxi\">Bai Chongxi</span> ran a famed \"model province\" whose armies bled heavily against Japan. The People's Republic brought autonomy in 1958 but also catastrophe, for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangxi_Massacre\">Guangxi Massacre</span> of the Cultural Revolution killed an estimated 100,000–150,000 people amid documented atrocities, and in 1979 the region served as a staging ground for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-Vietnamese_War\">Sino-Vietnamese War</span>. From embattled borderland the region has since recast itself as China's bridge to Southeast Asia, its drums and karst towers presiding over a frontier of commerce rather than war.","citation":"","answerText":"Guangxi"},{"id":"cng-068","num":"六十八","category":"China · Geography","question":"A warm, humid region taking in Guangdong and the Pearl River basin, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is associated with rice paddies, Cantonese speech and a long tradition of overseas emigration.","answer":"South China","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">华南 (Huánán, 'southern China')</span></div>","traditional":"華南","hanzi":"华南","pinyin":"Huánán","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Huánán</span></div>","abstract":"<b>South China</b> is the conventional region embracing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangdong\">Guangdong</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangxi\">Guangxi</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hainan\">Hainan</span> together with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Macau\">Macau</span>, overlapping the older cultural realm of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lingnan\">Lingnan</span>, \"south of the ranges,\" beyond the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanling_Mountains\">Nanling Mountains</span></b> watershed. Its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Humid_subtropical_climate\">humid subtropical</span> to tropical climate delivers 1,500 to over 2,000 millimeters (79 in) of rain and regular <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Typhoon\">typhoons</span>, sustaining the flooded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rice\">rice</span> paddies whose <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Multiple_cropping\">double and even triple cropping</span> long made the region a byword for abundance. Economic life centers on the basin of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pearl_River_(China)\">Pearl River</span>, whose <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pearl_River_Delta\">delta</span> became the \"factory of the world\" and now anchors the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Greater_Bay_Area\">Greater Bay Area</span></b> of some 86 million people and nearly 2 trillion dollars of output, linking ancient <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou\">Guangzhou</span> with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shenzhen\">Shenzhen</span>, a fishing district of 30,000 <b>transformed after its 1980 designation</b> among the first <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Special_economic_zones_of_China\">special economic zones</span> into a metropolis of 17 million. The region speaks its own tongues, above all the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yue_Chinese\">Yue</span> family whose <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cantonese\">Cantonese</span> standard counts on the order of 85 million speakers and is mutually unintelligible with Mandarin. Its tastes traveled with its people, for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cantonese_cuisine\">Cantonese cuisine</span> defines Chinese food to much of the world, and the region's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lychee\">lychees</span> were once relayed by imperial courier to please a Tang consort. <br> <br> Anciently the home of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Baiyue\">Baiyue</span>, the south was annexed <b>by the Qin in 214 BCE</b> and then ruled from Guangzhou by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhao_Tuo\">Zhao Tuo</span>'s breakaway kingdom of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanyue\">Nanyue</span> from 204 BCE, absorbing wave after wave of northern migrants over the following millennium. <b>Under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Canton_System\">Canton System</span> of 1757–1842 Guangzhou</b> served as the empire's sole legal port for Western trade, until the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Opium_Wars\">Opium Wars</span> pried open the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_ports\">treaty ports</span> and detached Hong Kong and Macau as colonies. From these crowded counties flowed the great 19th-century emigration, as Cantonese and Taishanese men joined the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"California_gold_rush\">California gold rush</span></b>, supplied the roughly 15,000–20,000 laborers who built the western <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Transcontinental_Railroad\">First Transcontinental Railroad</span>, and endured the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Coolie\">coolie</span> trade, planting the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinatown\">Chinatowns</span> in which Cantonese long remained the lingua franca, so that the majority of today's tens of millions of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Overseas_Chinese\">overseas Chinese</span> trace their roots to this coast. Remittances flowed back to the emigrant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qiaoxiang\">qiaoxiang</span> districts, financing marvels like the fortified <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kaiping_diaolou\">Kaiping diaolou</span></b> towers listed by UNESCO in 2007, while <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taishan,_Guangdong\">Taishan</span> still claims more descendants abroad than residents at home. Openness bred upheaval as well, for the native son <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Yat-sen\">Sun Yat-sen</span> organized revolution from these shores until the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinhai_Revolution\">Xinhai Revolution</span> of 1911 toppled the empire, and 7 decades later the same region led China back into the world economy.","citation":"","answerText":"South China"},{"id":"cng-071","num":"七十一","category":"China · Geography","question":"The most populous and one of the wealthiest provinces, lying on the southern coast around the Pearl River Delta, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> contains the metropolis of Guangzhou and borders Hong Kong.","answer":"Guangdong","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">广东 (Guǎngdōng, 'eastern expanse')</span></div>","traditional":"廣東","hanzi":"广东","pinyin":"Guǎngdōng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Guǎngdōng</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“expanse east”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Guangdong</b> is the most populous province of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>, with some 126 million inhabitants, and <b>by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"List_of_Chinese_administrative_divisions_by_GDP\">economic output</span></b> its wealthiest, lying along the southern coast around the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pearl_River_Delta\">Pearl River Delta</span> on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South_China_Sea\">South China Sea</span>. Its abbreviation Yue recalls the ancient <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Baiyue\">Yue</span> peoples of the south, and it is the homeland of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cantonese\">Cantonese</span> language and of the broader <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lingnan\">Lingnan</span> culture, distinct from that of the Chinese heartland to the north. Its delta forms one of the world’s mightiest manufacturing zones, the “factory of the world,” built up <b>since 1980 around</b> the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Special_economic_zones_of_China\">special economic zones</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shenzhen\">Shenzhen</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuhai\">Zhuhai</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shantou\">Shantou</span>, and now bordering the territories of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Macau\">Macau</span> within the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangdong–Hong_Kong–Macau_Greater_Bay_Area\">Greater Bay Area</span></b>. Beyond the capital and ancient port of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou\">Guangzhou</span>, the province encompasses the export hub of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dongguan\">Dongguan</span> and the manufacturing city of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foshan\">Foshan</span>, and its booming factories have drawn the largest flow of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Floating_population\">internal migrants</span> in history from poorer inland provinces. Culturally it is celebrated for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cantonese_cuisine\">Cantonese cuisine</span> and its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dim_sum\">dim sum</span> teahouses, while its humid subtropical climate, swept by summer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Typhoon\">typhoons</span>, ripens crops such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lychee\">lychee</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sugarcane\">sugarcane</span>. <br> <br> In antiquity the region lay beyond the Chinese world until the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_dynasty\">Qin</span> <b>pushed south around 214 BCE</b>, after which it became the heart of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanyue\">Nanyue</span> kingdom ruled from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Panyu_District\">Panyu</span>, absorbed into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span> empire in 111 BCE. Its capital grew into a great maritime port, a southern terminus of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maritime_Silk_Road\">Maritime Silk Road</span> and, <b>from 1757</b>, the sole gateway for Western trade under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Canton_System\">Canton System</span>, a monopoly whose disputes over <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Opium\">opium</span> helped ignite the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Opium_War\">First Opium War</span> of 1839–1842. From the 19th century the province became the great source of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Overseas_Chinese\">Chinese diaspora</span>, as Cantonese emigrants flowed out to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinatown\">Chinatowns</span> across <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Southeast_Asia\">Southeast Asia</span>, the Americas, and Australia, <b>drawn by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"California_Gold_Rush\">gold rushes</span></b> and railway labour. Guangdong was also a cradle of modern revolution, the birthplace of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Yat-sen\">Sun Yat-sen</span> and the base from which the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Whampoa_Military_Academy\">Whampoa Military Academy</span> trained officers and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Expedition\">Northern Expedition</span> set out to unify China, while the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hakka_people\">Hakka</span> visionary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Xiuquan\">Hong Xiuquan</span>, founder of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiping_Rebellion\">Taiping Rebellion</span>, hailed from a village near Guangzhou. After 1978 the province spearheaded China’s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">reform and opening</span>, its Shenzhen zone transformed from a fishing town into a megacity, a course reaffirmed by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> during his celebrated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping's_southern_tour\">1992 southern tour</span> and propelling Guangdong to the front rank of the world’s <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manufacturing\">manufacturing</span></b> economies.","citation":"","answerText":"Guangdong"},{"id":"cng-072","num":"七十二","category":"China · Geography","question":"A huge southern port on the Pearl River and capital of Guangdong, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> — known to Westerners as Canton — was for centuries China's main gateway for foreign commerce.","answer":"Guangzhou","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">广州 (Guǎngzhōu, 'broad prefecture')</span></div>","traditional":"廣州","hanzi":"广州","pinyin":"Guǎngzhōu","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Guǎngzhōu</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Guangzhou</b> is the capital of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangdong\">Guangdong</span> and a metropolis of 18.7 million in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2020_Chinese_census\"><b>2020</b> census</span> at the head of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pearl_River_Delta\">Pearl River Delta</span>, founded as Panyu in 214 BCE and trading continuously on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pearl_River_(China)\">Pearl River</span> for some 2,200 years as the eastern terminus of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maritime_Silk_Road\">Maritime Silk Road</span>. <b>From 204 BCE</b> it reigned as capital of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhao_Tuo\">Zhao Tuo</span>'s kingdom of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanyue\">Nanyue</span>, whose jade-shrouded ruler was rediscovered in 1983 in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mausoleum_of_the_Nanyue_King\">Mausoleum of the Nanyue King</span> beneath the modern city. Under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang dynasty</span> tens of thousands of Arab and Persian merchants filled a foreign quarter served by the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huaisheng_Mosque\">Huaisheng Mosque</span></b>, by tradition founded in 627 as one of the oldest on earth, until the rebel <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huang_Chao\">Huang Chao</span> sacked the port in 879 and, by one Arab account, slaughtered some 120,000 foreigners. The city's most famous role came <b>under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Canton_System\">Canton System</span> of 1757–1842</b>, when it was the empire's sole legal port for Western trade, conducted through the riverside <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Thirteen_Factories\">Thirteen Factories</span> under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cohong\">Cohong</span> merchant guild, whose chief <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Howqua\">Howqua</span> was reckoned the richest commoner in the world. The system died by fire and cannon after <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lin_Zexu\">Lin Zexu</span>'s 1839 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Destruction_of_opium_at_Humen\">destruction of opium at Humen</span> triggered the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Opium_War\">First Opium War</span>, and after occupation in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Opium_War\">Second Opium War</span> the islet of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shamian\">Shamian</span> became a colonnaded Anglo-French concession. <br> <br> Canton then became the forge of revolution, where <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Yat-sen\">Sun Yat-sen</span> based his governments between 1917 and 1925, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Whampoa_Military_Academy\">Whampoa Military Academy</span> opened in 1924 with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span> as commandant and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span> in its political department, the 16-month <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Canton–Hong_Kong_strike\">Canton–Hong Kong strike</span></b> of 1925–1926 strangled British commerce, and the communist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou_Uprising\">Guangzhou Uprising</span> of December 1927 was drowned in blood within days. Through the isolation after 1949 the city stayed China's shop window via the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Canton_Fair\">Canton Fair</span>, held twice yearly since 1957 as the country's oldest and largest trade exposition. Reform restored the old vocation on a vast scale, so that the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Port_of_Guangzhou\">Port of Guangzhou</span> now ranks among the world's busiest, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou_Baiyun_International_Airport\">Baiyun airport</span></b> has led global passenger counts in some years, the 600-meter (2,000 ft) <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Canton_Tower\">Canton Tower</span> has marked the skyline since the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2010_Asian_Games\">2010 Asian Games</span>, and municipal output approaches 3 trillion yuan. The city remains the metropolis of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cantonese\">Cantonese</span> speech and of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cantonese_cuisine\">Cantonese cuisine</span>, proverbially the place to eat in China, where mornings begin with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yum_cha\">yum cha</span> and heritage endures in the carved <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Clan_Ancestral_Hall\">Chen Clan Ancestral Hall</span></b>, the granite Gothic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sacred_Heart_Cathedral_(Guangzhou)\">Sacred Heart Cathedral</span> of 1888, and the pagoda of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Temple_of_the_Six_Banyan_Trees\">Temple of the Six Banyan Trees</span>. Legend says 5 immortals on rams brought the first rice ears to the site, and the City of Rams they blessed has scarcely paused for breath as a gateway in the 2 millennia since.","citation":"","answerText":"Guangzhou"},{"id":"cng-075","num":"七十五","category":"China · Geography","question":"A laid-back, fast-growing metropolis on the fertile Sichuan plain and capital of its province, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is renowned for spicy cuisine, teahouses, and as a base for breeding the giant panda.","answer":"Chengdu","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">成都 (Chéngdū, 'to become a capital')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"成都","pinyin":"Chéngdū","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Chéngdū</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Chengdu</b> is the capital of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan\">Sichuan</span></b> province and the great metropolis of southwestern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>, a fast-growing city of roughly 21 million people spread across the fertile western <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan_Basin\">Sichuan Basin</span>. It occupies the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chengdu_Plain\">Chengdu Plain</span>, a land so productive it has been called the “Land of Abundance,” its fields watered for over 2,200 years by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dujiangyan\">Dujiangyan</span> irrigation system, an engineering marvel <b>built around 256 BCE</b> by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_(state)\">Qin</span> governor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Bing_(Qin)\">Li Bing</span> that still functions and is honoured as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Heritage_Site\">World Heritage Site</span>. The city is famed for an unhurried culture of bamboo-chair teahouses, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mahjong\">mahjong</span>, and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan_opera\">Sichuan opera</span></b> art of face-changing, and as a cradle of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan_cuisine\">Sichuan cuisine</span>, whose numbing-hot marriage of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan_pepper\">Sichuan pepper</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chili_pepper\">chili</span> in dishes like <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mapo_tofu\">mapo tofu</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kung_Pao_chicken\">kung pao chicken</span> <b>earned it recognition in 2010</b> as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"UNESCO\">UNESCO</span> City of Gastronomy. On its northern outskirts the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chengdu_Research_Base_of_Giant_Panda_Breeding\">Chengdu Research Base of Giant Panda Breeding</span>, founded in 1987 with 6 rescued animals and now home to more than 200, anchors global efforts to conserve the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Giant_panda\">giant panda</span>, emblem of the nearby mountains. The modern city is an engine of China’s “Go West” development, hosting a major <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Semiconductor\">electronics</span> industry where a large share of the world’s <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"IPad\">iPads</span></b> have been assembled, the twin-towered headquarters quarter around the colossal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Century_Global_Center\">New Century Global Center</span>, and twin international airports linked by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Railway_Express\">freight trains</span> running to Europe. <br> <br> Chengdu is among the few great Chinese cities never to have changed its name or site since its <b>founding around 311 BCE</b>, and the nearby <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sanxingdui\">Sanxingdui</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jinsha_site\">Jinsha</span> sites reveal that the enigmatic bronze-casting <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shu_(kingdom)\">Shu</span> civilization flourished here over 3,000 years ago. Under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span> its workshops made it the centre of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Brocade\">brocade</span> weaving, the “Brocade City,” and in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Kingdoms\">Three Kingdoms</span> era it served as capital of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shu_Han\">Shu Han</span>, whose ruler <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Bei\">Liu Bei</span> and chancellor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuge_Liang\">Zhuge Liang</span> are venerated at the Wuhou Shrine. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span> poet <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Du_Fu\">Du Fu</span> wrote some 240 poems at his thatched cottage here, and under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song</span> the city’s merchants issued the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiaozi_(currency)\">jiaozi</span>, the world’s first government-backed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Banknote\">paper money</span>, in the early 11th century. Catastrophe struck in the 17th century when <b>the rebel <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Xianzhong\">Zhang Xianzhong</span></b> made it his capital amid massacres that helped empty Sichuan and prompted a vast resettlement, and in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Sino-Japanese_War\">war against Japan</span> the city served as a rear base from which American <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boeing_B-29_Superfortress\">B-29s</span> first bombed the Japanese home islands in 1944. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Railway_Protection_Movement\">Railway Protection Movement</span> that erupted here in 1911 helped trigger the revolution that toppled the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span>, and the modern city, shaken but largely spared by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2008_Sichuan_earthquake\">2008 Sichuan earthquake</span> in the mountains to its northwest, has grown into a hub of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Aerospace_industry_of_China\">aerospace</span>, software, and pop culture often ranked among China’s most livable and creative cities.","citation":"","answerText":"Chengdu"},{"id":"cnh-019","num":"十九","category":"China · History","question":"An infamous act of intellectual repression under Qin Shi Huang, urged by his chancellor Li Si, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> reportedly destroyed many texts of the rival philosophical schools — especially the Confucian classics — and persecuted scholars who criticised the regime.","answer":"Burning of books and burying of scholars","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">213–212 BCE</span></div>","traditional":"焚書坑儒","hanzi":"焚书坑儒","pinyin":"fénshū kēngrú","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">fénshū kēngrú</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>burning of books and burying of scholars</b> was a notorious episode of intellectual repression carried out under the <b>First Emperor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_Shi_Huang\">Qin Shi Huang</span></b> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_dynasty\">Qin dynasty</span> at the urging of his <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Legalism_(Chinese_philosophy)\">Legalist</span> chancellor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Si\">Li Si</span>. The crisis was sparked at <b>a court banquet in 213 BCE</b> when a scholar advocated reviving the decentralised <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fengjian\">fengjian</span> order of antiquity, prompting Li Si to argue that independent scholars who invoked the past to criticise the present and disparage the new system of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Commandery_(China)\">commanderies</span> posed an intolerable threat to imperial authority. On Li Si's recommendation the emperor decreed that the historical chronicles of every state except Qin — the genre exemplified by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Spring_and_Autumn_Annals\"><i>Spring and Autumn Annals</i></span> — together with all privately held copies of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Classic_of_Poetry\"><i>Classic of Poetry</i></span></b>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Book_of_Documents\"><i>Book of Documents</i></span>, and the writings of the rival <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hundred_Schools_of_Thought\">Hundred Schools of Thought</span> were to be surrendered and burned within 30 days. Specifically exempted from the flames were the volumes in the imperial library and works of immediate practical value, namely treatises on medicine, agriculture, and divination such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"I_Ching\"><i>I Ching</i></span>, together with the chronicles of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_(state)\">Qin</span></b> state itself. Because these texts were laboriously inscribed on perishable <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bamboo_and_wooden_slips\">bamboo slips</span>, the destruction was severe, and the accompanying penalties were ferocious, with offenders who failed to comply branded and condemned to hard labour on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Wall_of_China\">Great Wall</span> and anyone caught discussing the proscribed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Books_and_Five_Classics\">classics</span> liable to execution. <br> <br> The second and <b>grislier phase came in 212 BCE</b>, when the emperor, enraged that a pair of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fangshi\">alchemists</span> who had failed to procure an <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Elixir_of_life\">elixir of immortality</span> then fled while slandering him, ordered an inquisition in the capital <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xianyang\">Xianyang</span> that ended, according to tradition, with some 460 scholars being buried alive. When the heir apparent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fusu\">Fusu</span> protested against the cruelty of the executions, he was banished to the northern frontier to serve under the general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Meng_Tian\">Meng Tian</span>, a dismissal that would later prove fatal to his claim on the throne. Almost everything known of the affair derives from a single near-contemporary source, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Records_of_the_Grand_Historian\"><i>Records of the Grand Historian</i></span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Qian\">Sima Qian</span>, and the loss of learning was compounded a few years afterward when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiang_Yu\">Xiang Yu</span> sacked and torched the <b>Qin imperial <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Epang_Palace\">palaces</span> around 206 BCE</b>, destroying the official archive that had preserved the only sanctioned copies. These twin catastrophes deprived later generations of much pre-imperial literature and forced scholars of the succeeding <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span>, which under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Wu_of_Han\">Emperor Wu</span> would enshrine <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucianism</span> as state orthodoxy, to reconstruct the classics of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucius\">Confucius</span> from memory and from texts hidden away during the persecution. Although modern historians caution that the traditional account is probably exaggerated and that many of the victims may have been occultists rather than orthodox scholars, the episode endured as the archetypal emblem of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anti-intellectualism\">anti-intellectual</span> tyranny and state <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Censorship_in_China\">censorship</span> in Chinese memory, and it was pointedly invoked in the 20th century when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> compared his own regime favourably to the Qin during the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Criticize_Lin,_Criticize_Confucius_Campaign\">Criticise Lin, Criticise Confucius campaign</span></b>.","citation":"","answerText":"Burning of books and burying of scholars"},{"id":"cnc-039","num":"三十九","category":"China · Culture","question":"Discovered by well-diggers in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> near Xi'an, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was buried to guard the tomb of Qin Shi Huang, who unified China under the Qin dynasty.","answer":"Terracotta Army","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. 210 BCE</span></div>","traditional":"兵馬俑","hanzi":"兵马俑","pinyin":"Bīngmǎyǒng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Bīngmǎyǒng</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“soldier-and-horse funerary figures”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Terracotta Army</b> is a vast array of life-sized <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Terracotta\">terracotta</span> sculptures portraying the armies of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_Shi_Huang\">Qin Shi Huang</span></b>, founder of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_dynasty\">Qin dynasty</span>, buried to protect the emperor in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Afterlife\">afterlife</span> in place of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Human_sacrifice\">human sacrifices</span> of earlier ages. The figures came <b>to light in March 1974</b>, when farmers digging a well in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lintong,_Xi'an\">Lintong</span> on the outskirts of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi'an\">Xi'an</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shaanxi\">Shaanxi</span> province struck fragments of pottery about 1.5 kilometres (0.93 mi) east of the burial mound at the foot of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mount_Li\">Mount Li</span>. They guard the eastern approach to the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mausoleum_of_Qin_Shi_Huang\">Mausoleum of Qin Shi Huang</span></b>, a funerary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Necropolis\">necropolis</span> spreading over some 98 square kilometres (38 sq mi), which the historian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Qian\">Sima Qian</span> records was built by 700,000 conscripts <b>between 246 and 208 BCE</b>. Three great pits hold the army proper, the largest measuring roughly 230 by 62 metres (750 by 200 ft) and containing the main infantry force, with the whole array estimated at about 8,000 soldiers accompanied by 130 wooden <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chariot\">chariots</span>, 520 draught horses, and 150 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cavalry\">cavalry</span> mounts. Standing between about 175 and 200 centimetres (68.9 and 79 in) tall, each warrior was built from mould-made parts on a kind of ancient <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Assembly_line\">assembly line</span></b> yet individually finished, so that faces, hairstyles, and armour differ from figure to figure, while foremen stamped their names into the clay as a measure of quality control. <br> <br> The soldiers were originally painted in vivid colours over a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lacquer\">lacquer</span> ground that included the synthetic pigment <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_purple_and_Han_blue\">Han purple</span>, though much of the colour curled away within minutes of exposure during early <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Excavation_(archaeology)\">excavation</span>, a loss that has made conservation a central concern. The figures bore functional <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bronze\">bronze</span></b> weapons, among them swords, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dagger-axe\">dagger-axes</span>, and tens of thousands of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Crossbow\">crossbow</span> triggers and bolts, whose fine preservation was long credited to ancient <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chrome_plating\">chromium plating</span> until a <b>2019 study</b> traced the chromium to lacquer contamination. Neighbouring pits have yielded terracotta <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Acrobatics\">acrobats</span>, strongmen, musicians, and civil officials together with bronze waterfowl, and in 1980 two exquisite half-scale bronze chariots with drivers and teams of four horses were unearthed beside the mound. The tomb chamber itself remains deliberately unopened, for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Records_of_the_Grand_Historian\"><i>Records of the Grand Historian</i></span> describes a buried palace coursing with rivers of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mercury_(element)\">mercury</span>, an account lent credence by soil readings far above natural levels, while scorched timbers in the pits accord with the tradition that the rebel <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiang_Yu\">Xiang Yu</span> plundered the complex after the dynasty's fall. Inscribed as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Heritage_Site\">World Heritage Site</span> in 1987 and popularly hailed as an <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eighth_Wonder_of_the_World\">Eighth Wonder of the World</span>, the army now anchors the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Qinshihuang's_Mausoleum_Site_Museum\">Emperor Qinshihuang's Mausoleum Site Museum</span>, drawing millions of visitors each year, and travelling figures broke attendance records at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"British_Museum\">British Museum</span> in 2008, fixing the discovery as a global icon of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> and its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_art\">art</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Terracotta Army"},{"id":"cnh-018","num":"十八","category":"China · History","question":"The brilliant and ruthless Legalist chancellor who helped Qin Shi Huang centralise the empire and standardise the script, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is blamed for advising the notorious suppression of dissenting books and scholars, before being executed in a power struggle after the emperor's death.","answer":"Li Si","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. 280</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">208 BCE</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"李斯","pinyin":"Lǐ Sī","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Lǐ Sī</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Li Si</b> was a Legalist statesman who rose from obscure beginnings to become <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chancellor_(China)\">chancellor</span> of the state of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_(state)\">Qin</span></b> and the principal architect of the centralized administration of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_dynasty\">Qin dynasty</span>, the first unified empire in Chinese history. Born into a family of modest means in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shangcai_County\">Shangcai</span>, then part of the southern state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chu_(state)\">Chu</span>, he studied statecraft under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> philosopher <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xunzi\">Xunzi</span> alongside his gifted fellow student <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Fei\">Han Fei</span>. Seeking advancement in the most powerful of the warring kingdoms, he entered the household of the Qin minister <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lü_Buwei\">Lü Buwei</span>, and <b>around 237 BCE</b>, after the unmasking of the hydraulic engineer behind the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhengguo_Canal\">Zhengguo Canal</span> as a foreign agent provoked an edict expelling all officials of foreign origin, Li Si reversed the decree with a celebrated memorial defending the recruitment of talent from rival states. As his influence deepened, he helped orchestrate the methodical conquest of the rival states that closed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warring_States_period\">Warring States period</span>, and tradition holds that, gnawed by envy, he engineered the imprisonment and death of Han Fei, the most original theorist of their shared doctrine. After the empire was <b>unified in 221 BCE</b>, Li Si stood as its dominant minister and the chief engineer of its centralization, abolishing the old <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fengjian\">feudal</span> order in favour of a uniform grid of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Commandery_(China)\">commanderies</span>, extending the harsh statecraft pioneered a century earlier by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shang_Yang\">Shang Yang</span>, and imposing a single standard on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_characters\">written script</span>—which he is also traditionally credited with refining as a master of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_calligraphy\">calligraphy</span>—as well as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ban_Liang\">Ban Liang</span> coinage and the empire's weights and measures.<br> <br><b>In 213 BCE</b> Li Si delivered the advice for which he is most reviled, urging the throne to suppress private learning and to burn the texts of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hundred_Schools_of_Thought\">Hundred Schools of Thought</span> that had flourished since the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Spring_and_Autumn_period\">Spring and Autumn period</span>, lest scholars invoke the past to censure the present, and the following year this <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Burning_of_books_and_burying_of_scholars\">campaign of burning books and burying scholars</span> reputedly culminated in the live burial of some 460 men of learning across <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>. When the First Emperor died unexpectedly in 210 BCE while touring the east, Li Si joined the powerful <b>court <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eunuch\">eunuch</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhao_Gao\">Zhao Gao</span></b> in concealing the death and forging the imperial testament. Together they enthroned the pliable younger son as the Second Emperor, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_Er_Shi\">Qin Er Shi</span>, and dispatched a forged order compelling the rightful heir <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fusu\">Fusu</span> and the <b>eminent general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Meng_Tian\">Meng Tian</span></b> to take their own lives. The alliance soon curdled, for Zhao Gao turned upon his accomplice, and after being slandered, imprisoned, and tortured into a confession, Li Si was put to death in 208 BCE in the capital <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xianyang\">Xianyang</span>—subjected to the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five_Punishments\">Five Punishments</span></b> and cut in half at the waist, while his clan was exterminated. His tumultuous career survives chiefly through the account in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Qian\">Sima Qian</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Records_of_the_Grand_Historian\"><i>Records of the Grand Historian</i></span>, and although the Qin collapsed amid rebellion in 206 BCE—soon swept away by the founder of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Gaozu_of_Han\">Liu Bang</span>—the centralized bureaucratic state that Li Si did so much to build endured as the template of Chinese imperial governance for the next two thousand years.","citation":"","answerText":"Li Si"},{"id":"cnh-020","num":"二十","category":"China · History","question":"A 4-year civil war that broke out after the collapse of the Qin, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> pitted the aristocratic warrior Xiang Yu against the commoner-born Liu Bang, ending with the latter's victory and the founding of a new dynasty.","answer":"Chu–Han Contention","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">206–202 BCE</span></div>","traditional":"楚漢相爭","hanzi":"楚汉相争","pinyin":"Chǔ–Hàn Xiāngzhēng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Chǔ–Hàn Xiāngzhēng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Chu–Han Contention</b> was the roughly 4-year <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Civil_war\">civil war</span></b>, lasting <b>from 206</b> to <b>202 BCE</b>, that filled the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Interregnum\">interregnum</span> between the fall of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_dynasty\">Qin dynasty</span> and the rise of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han</span> and determined who would inherit the unified empire the Qin had created. The conflict pitted the brilliant but autocratic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Aristocracy\">aristocrat</span> <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiang_Yu\">Xiang Yu</span></b>, scion of a noble line of the old state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chu_(state)\">Chu</span> who had crushed the main Qin armies at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Julu\">Battle of Julu</span>, against the pragmatic, commoner-born <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Gaozu_of_Han\">Liu Bang</span>, a minor local official of humble origins. After Liu Bang was the first rebel commander to enter the Qin heartland of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guanzhong\">Guanzhong</span> and accept the surrender of the last Qin king <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ziying\">Ziying</span> in 206 BCE, the two leaders met at the tense <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Feast_at_Hong_Gate\">Feast at Hong Gate</span></b>, where Xiang Yu's adviser <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fan_Zeng\">Fan Zeng</span> urged his master to assassinate the rival who nonetheless slipped away unharmed. As the dominant warlord, Xiang Yu styled himself Hegemon-King of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Western_Chu\">Western Chu</span> and carved the realm into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eighteen_Kingdoms\">Eighteen Kingdoms</span>, banishing his rival to the remote southwestern region of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hanzhong\">Hanzhong</span> as the mere King of Han, in violation of an earlier pledge that whoever first entered Guanzhong should rule it. Soon afterward Xiang Yu had the figurehead <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Yi_of_Chu\">Emperor Yi of Chu</span></b> murdered, an act that helped Liu Bang cast his own cause as just when he burst back out of his mountain exile to seize Guanzhong and open the long struggle for supremacy. <br> <br> Liu Bang's ultimate triumph owed much to a trio of gifted subordinates—the strategist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Liang_(Western_Han)\">Zhang Liang</span>, the logistician <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiao_He\">Xiao He</span>, and above all the peerless general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Xin\">Han Xin</span>—whose talents he employed far more readily than his prouder opponent, an openness to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Meritocracy\">merit</span> that proved decisive. Although Xiang Yu routed him in a devastating defeat <b>at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Pengcheng\">Battle of Pengcheng</span> in 205 BCE</b>, Liu Bang recovered, and as the two main armies ground each other down in a long central stalemate, Han Xin's sweeping campaigns subdued the northern and eastern states one by one and gradually encircled the Chu forces. The war was decided at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Gaixia\">Battle of Gaixia</span> in 202 BCE, where converging Han armies trapped Xiang Yu and unnerved his men by singing the songs of his homeland, the despairing scene of his midnight farewell to his consort <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Consort_Yu\">Consort Yu</span> becoming one of the most famous episodes in Chinese literature. Breaking out with a dwindling band of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cavalry\">cavalry</span> and finally reduced to 28 riders, Xiang Yu refused a ferryman's offer of escape across the Wu River and took his own life on its bank, ashamed to face the elders of the homeland he had led to ruin, whereupon Liu Bang proclaimed himself <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_of_China\">emperor</span> and founded the Han dynasty with its capital eventually at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chang'an\">Chang'an</span>. The new dynasty would rule for some 400 years and give its name to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Chinese\">Han Chinese</span> majority, while the dramatic struggle—immortalized by the historian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Qian\">Sima Qian</span> in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Records_of_the_Grand_Historian\"><i>Records of the Grand Historian</i></span>—left an enduring imprint on the language through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chengyu\">idioms</span> and even survives in the divided river that separates the two sides of a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiangqi\">Chinese chess</span> board.","citation":"","answerText":"Chu–Han Contention"},{"id":"cnh-022","num":"二十二","category":"China · History","question":"Ruling for some 4 centuries and considered a golden age so formative that the majority ethnic group still calls itself by its name, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> made Confucianism the basis of the state, expanded along the Silk Road, and battled the nomadic Xiongnu.","answer":"Han dynasty","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">&lt;b&gt;206 BCE&lt;/b&gt;–&lt;b&gt;220 CE&lt;/b&gt;</span></div>","traditional":"漢朝","hanzi":"汉朝","pinyin":"Hàncháo","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Hàncháo</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Han dynasty</b> was the imperial dynasty that succeeded the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_dynasty\">Qin</span> in governing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>, an era so culturally formative that the country's majority ethnic group still calls itself the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Chinese\">Han Chinese</span> and its logographic script remains widely known as Han characters. Its founding followed the Qin's abrupt disintegration in 206 BCE, which plunged the realm into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chu–Han_Contention\">Chu–Han Contention</span>, a civil war lasting <b>until 202 BCE</b> from which the commoner-born <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Gaozu_of_Han\">Liu Bang</span> emerged triumphant over the aristocratic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiang_Yu\">Xiang Yu</span> and proclaimed himself emperor with his capital at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chang'an\">Chang'an</span>. Under the long and assertive reign of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Wu_of_Han\">Emperor Wu</span>, the throne elevated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucianism</span> into the official basis of the state, drawing on the cosmological synthesis of the scholar <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dong_Zhongshu\">Dong Zhongshu</span> and founding in 124 BCE an Imperial University, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taixue\">Taixue</span>, whose enrolment reportedly swelled to some 30,000 students by the 2nd century CE. Emperor Wu further dispatched the envoy <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Qian\">Zhang Qian</span> into the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Western_Regions\">Western Regions</span></b> from 138 BCE, missions that pried open the trans-Eurasian caravan routes later called the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk_Road\">Silk Road</span> and linked the markets of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Asia\">Central Asia</span>, and eventually the distant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Roman_Empire\">Roman Empire</span>, to the Chinese court. Much of this outward thrust unfolded amid a prolonged contest with the nomadic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiongnu\">Xiongnu</span> confederation along the northern steppe, whose raids the early emperors had long appeased through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heqin\">heqin</span> policy of marriage alliances and tribute before Emperor Wu launched the sustained <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han–Xiongnu_War\">Han–Xiongnu War</span></b>, an effort that secured the western corridors and led to the founding of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Protectorate_of_the_Western_Regions\">Protectorate of the Western Regions</span> around 60 BCE. <br> <br> The dynasty is conventionally divided into an earlier and a later phase by the usurpation of the regent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Mang\">Wang Mang</span>, whose short-lived <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xin_dynasty\">Xin dynasty</span> broke the line during the interregnum of 9 to 23 CE before loyalist armies restored the imperial house and transferred the capital eastward to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luoyang\">Luoyang</span> under <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Guangwu_of_Han\">Emperor Guangwu</span></b> in 25 CE. Han letters reached remarkable heights, embodied by the court astrologer and historian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Qian\">Sima Qian</span>, whose <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Records_of_the_Grand_Historian\"><i>Records of the Grand Historian</i></span> set the template for the next 2,000 years of dynastic historiography, even as the canonisation of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Books_and_Five_Classics\">Five Classics</span> fixed the Confucian corpus that would later anchor China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examination</span> system. Technological and scientific achievement flourished in parallel, as the official <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cai_Lun\">Cai Lun</span> won lasting fame for refining <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Papermaking\">papermaking</span> around 105 CE, the polymath <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Heng\">Zhang Heng</span></b> constructed an ingenious bronze <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Seismometer\">seismometer</span> in 132 CE, and Han workshops mass-produced cast-iron tools and the formidable <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Repeating_crossbow\">repeating crossbow</span>. Administratively the empire ruled a population of nearly 58 million spread across more than 12 million households, enumerated in the strikingly detailed census of 2 CE, through a hybrid framework of directly governed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Commandery_(China)\">commanderies</span> and semi-autonomous kingdoms staffed by a salaried bureaucracy of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Scholar-official\">scholar-officials</span>, its treasury reinforced by state monopolies on salt and iron. Sapped from the late 2nd century CE by bitter factional strife between palace <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eunuch\">eunuchs</span> and Confucian officials, by the millenarian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_Turban_Rebellion\">Yellow Turban Rebellion</span> of 184 CE, and by the ascent of regional warlords such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cao_Cao\">Cao Cao</span>, the dynasty at last dissolved in 220 CE upon the abdication of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Xian_of_Han\">Emperor Xian</span>, fragmenting the realm into the rival states of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Kingdoms\">Three Kingdoms</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Han dynasty"},{"id":"cnh-023","num":"二十三","category":"China · History","question":"A powerful confederation of horse-riding nomads to the north whose raids prompted the building of border walls, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> launched aggressive campaigns against them across the steppe.","answer":"Xiongnu","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">匈奴 (Xiōngnú), a Chinese transcription of the confederation's name</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"匈奴","pinyin":"Xiōngnú","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Xiōngnú</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Xiongnu</b> were a powerful confederation of nomadic, horse-riding <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pastoralism\">pastoralists</span></b> who dominated the eastern Eurasian steppe from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongolian_Plateau\">Mongolian Plateau</span> between the <b>3rd century BCE</b> and the <b>1st century CE</b>, forming the most formidable northern adversary of early imperial <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>. Fighting as superb <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mounted_archery\">mounted archers</span>, their seasonal raids on the settled farming states had long prompted the building of defensive walls, and <b>around 215 BCE</b> the Qin general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Meng_Tian\">Meng Tian</span>, acting for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_Shi_Huang\">Qin Shi Huang</span>, drove them from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ordos_Plateau\">Ordos</span> loop and joined these ramparts into the early <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Wall_of_China\">Great Wall</span>. The scattered tribes were forged into a formidable empire around 209 BCE by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Modu_Chanyu\">Modu Chanyu</span>, who murdered his father <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Touman\">Touman</span>, subjugated the neighbouring <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Donghu_people\">Donghu</span> and drove the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuezhi\">Yuezhi</span> westward, and ruled from the <b>supreme office of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chanyu\">chanyu</span></b>. In 200 BCE Modu sprang a trap at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Baideng\">Battle of Baideng</span>, encircling the Han founder <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Gaozu_of_Han\">Emperor Gaozu</span> and his army with a cavalry host the histories number at some 400,000 horsemen. To buy peace the early Han adopted the conciliatory <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heqin\">heqin</span> policy, dispatching imperial princesses as brides to successive chanyus together with lavish annual tribute of silk, grain, and wine, an arrangement of nominal equality that endured for some 60 years.<br> <br>This humiliating accommodation was ultimately reversed by the martial Emperor Wu, who first dispatched the envoy <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Qian\">Zhang Qian</span> in 138 BCE to seek allies against the Xiongnu among the exiled Yuezhi—a mission that failed in its purpose yet opened the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Western_Regions\">Western Regions</span> and the trade arteries later known as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk_Road\">Silk Road</span>. From the abortive ambush at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Mayi\">Mayi</span> in 133 BCE, he committed the empire to the protracted <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han–Xiongnu_War\">Han–Xiongnu War</span>, abandoning appeasement for relentless offensives across the northern frontier. The decisive blows fell through the brilliant cavalry generals <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wei_Qing\">Wei Qing</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huo_Qubing\">Huo Qubing</span>, who wrested the strategic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hexi_Corridor\">Hexi Corridor</span> from the Xiongnu by 121 BCE and, at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Mobei\">Battle of Mobei</span></b> in 119 BCE, crossed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gobi_Desert\">Gobi</span> to shatter their main forces and drive them deep into the north. Weakened and divided, the Xiongnu saw the chanyu <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huhanye\">Huhanye</span> submit to the Han in 51 BCE and accept the celebrated bride <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Zhaojun\">Wang Zhaojun</span> in 33 BCE, after which the confederation split into a southern branch that became Han vassals and a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Xiongnu\">northern branch</span></b> that was finally broken in 89 CE by the general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dou_Xian\">Dou Xian</span>, leaving the rising <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xianbei\">Xianbei</span> to absorb much of what remained. Much of what is known of the Xiongnu derives from the Chinese chronicles, above all the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Records_of_the_Grand_Historian\"><i>Records of the Grand Historian</i></span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Qian\">Sima Qian</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Book_of_Han\"><i>Book of Han</i></span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ban_Gu\">Ban Gu</span>, and although their language and ethnic make-up remain debated, some scholars have controversially linked them to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huns\">Huns</span> who later descended upon Europe.","citation":"","answerText":"Xiongnu"},{"id":"cnh-026","num":"二十六","category":"China · History","question":"Selected increasingly for learning in the Confucian classics rather than birth, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> — the \"mandarins\" of Western parlance — staffed the imperial bureaucracy and dominated society for 2 millennia, embodying the ideal of the gentleman.","answer":"Scholar-official","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">士大夫 (shìdàfū, 'scholar grandees'); called 'mandarins' in the West</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"士大夫","pinyin":"shìdàfū","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">shìdàfū</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Scholar-officials</b>, known in the West as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mandarin_(bureaucrat)\">mandarins</span></b> and often called the <b>literati</b>, were the educated elite who staffed the imperial <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bureaucracy\">bureaucracy</span></b> and dominated Chinese government and culture for roughly 2,000 years, selected increasingly for their command of learning rather than for noble birth. The class grew out of the lettered servitors of antiquity but took definitive shape under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span>, when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Wu_of_Han\">Emperor Wu</span>, advised by the scholar <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dong_Zhongshu\">Dong Zhongshu</span>, made <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucianism</span> the state orthodoxy and founded the Imperial Academy, or <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taixue\">Taixue</span>, <b>in 124 BCE</b> to train officials in classical learning. Recruitment by learning rather than by birth was institutionalized through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examination</span> established under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sui_dynasty\">Sui dynasty</span> around 605, refined under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span>, and made the principal road to office under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song dynasty</span>, displacing the hereditary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Aristocracy\">aristocracy</span> and the earlier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nine-rank_system\">nine-rank system</span> with a partly <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Meritocracy\">meritocratic</span> civil service open, in principle, to talented men of modest origin. Candidates devoted their lives to mastering the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucian_classics\">Confucian classics</span></b>, above all the canon of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Books_and_Five_Classics\">Four Books and Five Classics</span>, and under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> their essays were forced into the rigid form known as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight-legged_essay\">eight-legged essay</span>. Success was rare and fiercely contested, as aspirants advanced through grueling stages to win the provincial <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Juren\">juren</span> rank and ultimately the prized <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jinshi\">jinshi</span> degree, with only a few hundred of the many thousands who sat the highest examinations passing in each cycle, a contest so punishing that many studied into old age and others never succeeded at all. <br> <br> Beyond administrative skill, the scholar-official was expected to embody the Confucian ideal of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Junzi\">junzi</span>, or gentleman, a morally cultivated person who, in the vision of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucius\">Confucius</span>, governed less by force than by personal virtue and example, ruling through moral suasion as much as through law. Such a man was to cultivate the cardinal virtues of benevolence, or <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ren_(Confucianism)\">ren</span>, and ritual propriety, or <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_(Confucianism)\">li</span>, <b>together with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Filial_piety\">filial piety</span></b>, serving simultaneously as a competent administrator and a moral exemplar for the society beneath him, even bearing a duty to remonstrate with the throne when it strayed from virtue. The ideal scholar was also a man of refined accomplishment, expected to be versed in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_calligraphy\">calligraphy</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_painting\">painting</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_poetry\">poetry</span>, so that the elite that ruled the empire also shaped its highest artistic and literary culture through the distinctive tradition of literati art. Degree-holders enjoyed tax and legal privileges and formed the local <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gentry\">gentry</span></b>, giving China a remarkably stable and literate ruling class whose competitive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Civil_service\">civil service</span> later impressed and partly inspired reformers in the West, even as it allowed a measure of social mobility unusual in the pre-modern world. The institution finally dissolved when the civil examinations were <b>abolished in 1905</b> and the imperial order itself fell in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinhai_Revolution\">Xinhai Revolution</span> of 1911, ending a scholar-bureaucratic tradition that had shaped Chinese civilization for close to 2,000 years.","citation":"","answerText":"Scholar-official"},{"id":"cnc-035","num":"三十五","category":"China · Culture","question":"Literally \"wind-water\" and rooted in ideas of <i>qi</i>, <i>yin and yang</i> and the five phases, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> aims to harmonise people with their surroundings for good fortune.","answer":"Feng shui","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">风水 (fēngshuǐ, 'wind and water')</span></div>","traditional":"風水","hanzi":"风水","pinyin":"fēngshuǐ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">fēngshuǐ</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“wind-water”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Feng shui</b> is the traditional Chinese art of arranging buildings, graves, cities, and furniture so that people harmonize with their surroundings and prosper, drawing on the cosmology of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qi\">qi</span>, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yin_and_yang\">yin and yang</span></b>, and the 5 phases of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuxing_(Chinese_philosophy)\">wuxing</span>. The name derives from the 4th-century CE <i>Book of Burial</i> attributed to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guo_Pu\">Guo Pu</span> (<b>276–324 CE</b>), which teaches that vital qi disperses when it rides the wind and halts when bounded by water, so the skilled diviner gathers it for the dead and the living alike. The impulse is far older, visible in the south-facing dwellings <b>of Neolithic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Banpo\">Banpo</span> around 4000 BCE</b>, and its theory absorbed the trigrams of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"I_Ching\"><i>I Ching</i></span> arranged as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bagua\">bagua</span>, while <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han</span> diviners' south-pointing lodestone spoons—ancestors of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Compass\">compass</span>, as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joseph_Needham\">Joseph Needham</span> emphasized—evolved into the practitioner's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luopan\">luopan</span> with its 36 or more concentric rings. Two broad methods emerged, a Form school reading landforms where the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Azure_Dragon\">Azure Dragon</span> ridge should rise to the east and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"White_Tiger_(mythology)\">White Tiger</span> to the west of an armchair-shaped site, and a Compass school calculating directions and timings. Emperors employed both, siting the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_tombs\">Ming tombs</span> in their auspicious valley <b>from 1409</b> and aligning the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Forbidden_City\">Forbidden City</span> on the 7.8-kilometer (4.8 mi) <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing_Central_Axis\">Central Axis of Beijing</span>, inscribed as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Heritage_Site\">World Heritage Site</span> in 2024. <br> <br> In the 19th century geomancers famously obstructed railways and telegraph lines for wounding the \"dragon veins\" of the land, <b>prompting the missionary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ernst_Johann_Eitel\">Ernst Johann Eitel</span></b> to publish the first Western study of the system in 1873. The People's Republic condemned the art as feudal superstition, and practitioners suffered during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span>, but the tradition thrived in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span>, and Southeast Asia. Hong Kong supplied its most famous modern theatre, where <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Norman_Foster\">Norman Foster</span></b>'s HSBC headquarters was vetted by masters, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"I._M._Pei\">I. M. Pei</span>'s knife-edged <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bank_of_China_Tower_(Hong_Kong)\">Bank of China Tower</span> of 1990 was accused of slashing its neighbors with hostile qi, and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_Disneyland\">Hong Kong Disneyland</span></b> rotated its front gate by 12 degrees on geomantic advice before opening in 2005. Western readers often label the system Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Geomancy\">geomancy</span>, and because controlled studies find no measurable effect of qi or orientation on fortune, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Scientific_skepticism\">skeptics</span> classify its claims as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pseudoscience\">pseudoscience</span>, even while geographers credit its landscape readings with practical wisdom about drainage, sunlight, and shelter. None of this has slowed a multibillion-dollar global consulting trade whose clients have ranged from Asian banks to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Donald_Trump\">Donald Trump</span> in the 1990s, carrying the old grave-siting art from Bronze Age hillsides into Manhattan boardrooms.","citation":"","answerText":"Feng shui"},{"id":"cnc-040","num":"四十","category":"China · Culture","question":"Combining gentle movement, controlled breathing and focused meditation to cultivate vital energy, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is rooted in traditional medicine and was at the centre of a mass health craze in the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>s and <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>s.","answer":"Qigong","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">气功 (qìgōng, 'qi work')</span></div>","traditional":"氣功","hanzi":"气功","pinyin":"qìgōng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">qìgōng</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“qi work”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Qigong</b> is the family of practices combining gentle movement, <b>controlled <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Breathing\">breathing</span></b>, and focused <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Meditation\">meditation</span> to cultivate and circulate <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qi\">qi</span>, rooted in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Traditional_Chinese_medicine\">traditional Chinese medicine</span> and in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Taoist</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Buddhism\">Buddhist</span> self-cultivation. Its ancestry is ancient, for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuangzi_(book)\"><i>Zhuangzi</i></span> already mocks longevity-seekers doing \"bear strides and bird stretches,\" and a silk chart of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Daoyin\">daoyin</span> gymnastics <b>buried at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mawangdui\">Mawangdui</span> around 168 BCE depicts</b> 44 exercising figures, while tradition credits the physician <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hua_Tuo\">Hua Tuo</span> with the animal-mimicking Five Frolics. Over the centuries the streams multiplied, from the meditative inner alchemy of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Neidan\">neidan</span> to martial breath-training and standardized sets like the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Baduanjin\">Eight Brocades</span></b> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yijin_Jing\">Yijin Jing</span>. The umbrella word itself is modern, fixed in the 1950s when the cadre-healer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Guizhen\">Liu Guizhen</span>, cured of ulcers by breathing practice, founded a sanatorium program at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tangshan\">Tangshan</span> and installed \"qigong\" in the socialist health system. Practitioners distinguish dynamic routines from motionless \"standing post\" and sitting work, and masters of the era increasingly claimed to emit external qi from their palms to heal others, a claim that set the stage for both mass enthusiasm and scientific scandal. <br> <br> The result was the qigong fever of the 1980s and 1990s, when an estimated 60 to 200 million Chinese practiced in parks and stadiums, the celebrity master <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yan_Xin\">Yan Xin</span> filled arenas with \"qi-emission\" lectures and co-authored experiments at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tsinghua_University\">Tsinghua University</span> purporting to alter molecules thousands of kilometers away, and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Hongbao\">Zhang Hongbao</span></b>'s Zhonggong network claimed tens of millions of members. The craze enjoyed high patronage, most remarkably from the rocket scientist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qian_Xuesen\">Qian Xuesen</span>, who promoted a \"somatic science\" of latent human powers, while debunkers like <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Nan\">Sima Nan</span></b> exposed stage tricks and skeptics labeled the field <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pseudoscience\">pseudoscience</span>. The largest movement of all, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Falun_Gong\">Falun Gong</span>, <b>founded by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Hongzhi\">Li Hongzhi</span> in 1992</b>, so alarmed the leadership after some 10,000 adherents silently surrounded the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhongnanhai\">Zhongnanhai</span> compound in April 1999 that the state banned it that July and launched the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Persecution_of_Falun_Gong\">persecution</span> documented since by human-rights organizations, dissolving rival qigong empires in the same sweep. What survived was domesticated, the authorities issuing <b>from 2003</b> a sanitized \"Health Qigong\" canon of 4 routines, later expanded to 9, now taught in universities and parks, while abroad the practice settled into the wellness mainstream, where <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Meta-analysis\">meta-analyses</span> report modest, low-certainty benefits for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hypertension\">blood pressure</span>, balance, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anxiety\">anxiety</span>, leaving the old breath-art, like its sibling <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tai_chi\">tai chi</span>, quietly outliving the gurus who once electrified it.","citation":"","answerText":"Qigong"},{"id":"cnc-041","num":"四十一","category":"China · Culture","question":"Based on the language of late Zhou texts and remaining the medium of scholarship and literature for over 2,000 years, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> differed sharply from everyday speech and was finally displaced by writing in the vernacular in the early 20th century, after the New Culture Movement.","answer":"Classical Chinese","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">文言文 (wényánwén, 'literary-language writing')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"文言文","pinyin":"wényánwén","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">wényánwén</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“literary-language writing”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Classical Chinese</b>, also called Literary Chinese, is the terse written form based on the language of late <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_dynasty\">Zhou dynasty</span></b> texts of the 5th–3rd centuries BCE, which remained the medium of Chinese scholarship, administration, and high literature for more than 2,000 years. Its model corpus includes the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Analects\"><i>Analects</i></span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mencius_(book)\"><i>Mencius</i></span>, the narrative <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zuo_zhuan\"><i>Zuo zhuan</i></span></b>, and, as a later exemplar, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Records_of_the_Grand_Historian\"><i>Records of the Grand Historian</i></span>. The style prizes extreme economy—largely 1-syllable words, no inflection, and a small kit of grammatical particles—while its fixity in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_characters\">Chinese characters</span> detached it from the evolving sounds of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Old_Chinese\">Old Chinese</span></b>, so that readers of any era or dialect could parse texts whose pronunciation had vanished. Already under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span> the written norm diverged sharply from everyday speech, and vernacular intrusions surfaced mainly at the margins, in translations of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Buddhist_canon\">Buddhist canon</span> and in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang dynasty</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bianwen\">bianwen</span> storytelling recovered from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dunhuang\">Dunhuang</span>. As the learned lingua franca of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"East_Asian_cultural_sphere\">East Asian cultural sphere</span>, it was read and composed for centuries as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kanbun\">kanbun</span> in Japan, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hanmun\">hanmun</span> in Korea, and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chữ_Hán\">chữ Hán</span></b> in Vietnam. <br> <br> The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examinations</span> welded the language to power, requiring candidates to memorize the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Books_and_Five_Classics\">Four Books and Five Classics</span> and, from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span> through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span>, to compose the rigid 8-part <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight-legged_essay\">eight-legged essay</span>. Within the tradition, stylistic battles raged, most famously when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Yu\">Han Yu</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Zongyuan\">Liu Zongyuan</span></b> championed plain \"ancient prose\" against ornate <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Parallel_prose\">parallel prose</span>, founding the lineage of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight_Great_Prose_Masters_of_the_Tang_and_Song\">8 Great Prose Masters of the Tang and Song</span>. Meanwhile a vernacular literature flourished beneath official notice, culminating in 18th-century novels such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dream_of_the_Red_Chamber\"><i>Dream of the Red Chamber</i></span>, yet government, scholarship, and the press still wrote wenyan into the 1910s. The decisive assault came with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Culture_Movement\">New Culture Movement</span>, when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Shih\">Hu Shih</span> published an 8-point program for literary reform in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Duxiu\">Chen Duxiu</span><b>'s journal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Youth\"><i>New Youth</i></span> in 1917</b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lu_Xun\">Lu Xun</span> issued the first great vernacular story, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"A_Madman's_Diary\"><i>A Madman's Diary</i></span>, in 1918, and amid the ferment of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"May_Fourth_Movement\">May Fourth Movement</span> the Ministry of Education ordered primary <b>schools onto <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Written_vernacular_Chinese\">written vernacular Chinese</span> in 1920</b>. The old language nonetheless saturates <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Standard_Chinese\">Standard Chinese</span> through thousands of 4-character <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chengyu\">chengyu</span> and formal registers, and since 2017 mainland primary textbooks have assigned 124 classical poems and essays, keeping schoolchildren on speaking terms with a 2,500-year-old idiom.","citation":"","answerText":"Classical Chinese"},{"id":"cnc-042","num":"四十二","category":"China · Culture","question":"Built on theories of <i>qi</i>, <i>yin and yang</i> and the five phases, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> employs herbal remedies, acupuncture, massage and dietary therapy, and is practised alongside Western medicine in modern China.","answer":"Traditional Chinese medicine","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">中医 (zhōngyī, 'Chinese medicine')</span></div>","traditional":"中醫","hanzi":"中医","pinyin":"zhōngyī","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">zhōngyī</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Chinese medicine”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Traditional Chinese medicine</b> is the healing system built on theories of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qi\">qi</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yin_and_yang\">yin and yang</span>, and the 5 phases of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuxing_(Chinese_philosophy)\">wuxing</span>, employing herbal remedies, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Acupuncture\">acupuncture</span>, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tui_na\">tui na</span></b> massage, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_food_therapy\">dietary therapy</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Moxibustion\">moxibustion</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cupping_therapy\">cupping</span>, and practised alongside Western medicine in modern China. Its theoretical charter is the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huangdi_Neijing\"><i>Huangdi Neijing</i></span> of the 2nd–1st centuries BCE, which maps the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zang-fu\">zang-fu</span> organ systems and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Meridian_(Chinese_medicine)\">meridians</span> and grounds the diagnostic arts of questioning, observation of the tongue, and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pulse_diagnosis\">pulse reading</span></b> that classify each patient's \"pattern of disharmony.\" The pharmacy grew across 2 millennia, from the 365 drugs of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shennong_Ben_Cao_Jing\"><i>Shennong Ben Cao Jing</i></span>, ascribed to the herb-tasting sage <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shennong\">Shennong</span>, through the cold-damage formulas of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Zhongjing\">Zhang Zhongjing</span><b>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghan_Lun\"><i>Shanghan Lun</i></span> of about 200 CE</b>, still prescribed today, to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Shizhen\">Li Shizhen</span>'s 1578 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Compendium_of_Materia_Medica\"><i>Compendium of Materia Medica</i></span>, cataloguing 1,892 substances and 11,096 prescriptions. Marginalized by early modernizers, the tradition was rehabilitated in the 1950s as a national \"treasure-house,\" and roughly 1 million <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Barefoot_doctor\">barefoot doctors</span> carried its needles and herbs through the countryside in the 1960s and 1970s. Today the People's Republic protects it by a dedicated law in force <b>since 2017</b>, runs thousands of TCM hospitals beside biomedical ones, and saw the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Health_Organization\">World Health Organization</span> controversially add traditional-medicine diagnoses to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"ICD-11\">ICD-11</span> in 2019. <br> <br> The tradition's proudest gift to world health came when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tu_Youyou\">Tu Youyou</span>, combing classical texts for an antimalarial, found in a 4th-century CE handbook by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ge_Hong\">Ge Hong</span> the cold-extraction hint that yielded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Artemisinin\">artemisinin</span>, the drug that has saved millions from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Malaria\">malaria</span> and won the <b>2015 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nobel_Prize_in_Physiology_or_Medicine\">Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine</span></b>. Beyond that triumph the evidence is thinner, for qi and meridians have no identified physical basis, large sham-controlled trials suggest much of acupuncture's benefit is non-specific, and systematic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cochrane_(organisation)\">Cochrane</span> reviews of herbal formulas are routinely inconclusive, leading many scientists to class the underlying theory as pre-scientific or outright <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pseudoscience\">pseudoscience</span> even while individual plants repay study. Safety has scarred the record too, most gravely the kidney failure and urinary-tract cancers traced in the 1990s to herbs containing <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Aristolochic_acid\">aristolochic acid</span></b>, alongside heavy-metal contamination and herb-drug interactions. Demand for animal materia medica has bled into conservation crises over <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tiger\">tiger</span> bone, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rhinoceros\">rhinoceros</span> horn, and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pangolin\">pangolin</span></b> scales, prompting China's 1993 trade bans and the pangolin's removal from the official pharmacopoeia in 2020. Yet by WHO count the system is now used in more than 180 countries, and in any large Chinese hospital patients move matter-of-factly between the infusion ward and the herb dispensary, citizens of 2 medicines at once.","citation":"","answerText":"Traditional Chinese medicine"},{"id":"cnc-043","num":"四十三","category":"China · Culture","question":"A pear-shaped, 4-stringed lute held upright and played with the fingers, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> — entering China along the Silk Road — became a mainstay of court and folk music and features in much Tang poetry.","answer":"Pipa","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">琵琶 (pípá), naming the outward and inward plucking strokes</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"琵琶","pinyin":"pípá, the 2 syllables naming the outward and inward plucking strokes","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">pípá, the 2 syllables naming the outward and inward plucking strokes</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Pipa</b> is a pear-shaped, <b>4-stringed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lute\">lute</span></b> held upright and played with the fingers, a mainstay of court and folk <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Music_of_China\">Chinese music</span> for some 2,000 years. <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han</span>-era sources already use the name for a round-bodied native lute, ancestor of today's <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ruan\">ruan</span></b>, but the bent-necked, pear-shaped instrument descends from the Persian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Barbat_(lute)\">barbat</span>, carried east along the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk_Road\">Silk Road</span> by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sogdia\">Sogdian</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kucha\">Kuchean</span> musicians and naturalized in north China by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Wei\">Northern Wei</span> of the 4th–5th centuries CE. Under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span> it reigned over banquet music, held sideways and struck with a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Plectrum\">plectrum</span></b> by celebrated Central Asian virtuosos, while painters of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mogao_Caves\">Mogao Caves</span> immortalized a dancing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Apsara\">apsara</span> playing the instrument behind her back. Tang poets made it the very voice of feeling, above all <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bai_Juyi\">Bai Juyi</span>, whose <i>Song of the Pipa</i> of 816 hears a former courtesan's notes fall like large and small pearls onto a jade plate. The Tang instrument even survives physically, for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shōsōin\">Shōsōin</span> treasury in Japan preserves an 8th-century 5-stringed specimen inlaid with a camel-riding lutenist in mother-of-pearl, cousin to the Japanese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Biwa\">biwa</span> that the pipa fathered. <br> <br> Between the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> the instrument assumed its modern form, raised fully upright, plucked with the fingernails of the right hand, and fitted with ever more <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fret\">frets</span>, today numbering about 30 across neck and belly. Its repertoire divides into lyrical \"civil\" pieces and programmatic \"martial\" ones, none more famous than <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ambush_from_Ten_Sides\"><i>Ambush from Ten Sides</i></span></b>, a one-instrument battle scene of clashing arms and cries recreating the defeat of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiang_Yu\">Xiang Yu</span> <b>at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Gaixia\">Battle of Gaixia</span> in 202 BCE</b>, and the tradition was fixed in print when the first published pipa anthology appeared in 1819. The 20th century brought conservatory standardization, with steel strings supplanting twisted <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk\">silk</span> in the 1950s and fret placement <b>adjusted to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Equal_temperament\">equal temperament</span></b> so the instrument could anchor the plucked section of the modern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_orchestra\">Chinese orchestra</span>. It also remains the lifeblood of regional genres such as Suzhou <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pingtan\">pingtan</span> storytelling, where singers accompany themselves through whole evenings of narrative. Ambassadors like <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Man\">Wu Man</span>, collaborating with the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kronos_Quartet\">Kronos Quartet</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yo-Yo_Ma\">Yo-Yo Ma</span>'s Silk Road Ensemble, have carried the lute from oasis caravans to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Carnegie_Hall\">Carnegie Hall</span>, completing a migration begun 15 centuries ago.","citation":"","answerText":"Pipa"},{"id":"cnc-044","num":"四十四","category":"China · Culture","question":"The most important festival of the year, marking the start of the lunisolar calendar with family reunions, firecrackers and the giving of money-filled red packets, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is also known as the Spring Festival.","answer":"Chinese New Year","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">春节 (Chūnjié, 'Spring Festival')</span></div>","traditional":"春節","hanzi":"春节","pinyin":"Chūnjié","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Chūnjié</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Spring Festival”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Chinese New Year</b> is the most important festival of the Chinese year, marking the first day of the first month of the traditional <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lunisolar_calendar\">lunisolar</span></b> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_calendar\">Chinese calendar</span> and falling on a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_moon\">new moon</span> between 21 January and 20 February. Festivities stretch from the eve to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lantern_Festival\">Lantern Festival</span> on the 15th night, and their roots reach back to <b>year-end offerings of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_ancestral_worship\">ancestral worship</span></b> in antiquity, overlaid by the legend of the monster <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nian\">Nian</span>, driven off by red, fire, and noise. The festival's gravitational pull homeward produces <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chunyun\">chunyun</span>, often called the largest annual human migration, with roughly 3 billion passenger trips recorded across the travel season in peak years, all converging on the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Reunion_dinner\">reunion dinner</span> of New Year's Eve</b>. The table itself speaks in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Homophonic_puns_in_Mandarin_Chinese\">homophonic puns</span>, northern families folding ingot-shaped <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiaozi\">jiaozi</span> dumplings, a whole fish promising yearly surplus, the sticky cake <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nian_gao\">nian gao</span></b> punning on a rising year, and round <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tangyuan_(food)\">tangyuan</span> standing for family unity. Households are swept clean beforehand so that no luck is brushed away on the day itself, doorways are dressed in red <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Antithetical_couplet\">antithetical couplets</span></b> and the character <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fu_(character)\">fu</span> pasted upside down so that fortune “arrives,” the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kitchen_God\">Kitchen God</span> is sent heavenward days earlier with honeyed lips, and each new year installs the next animal of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_zodiac\">Chinese zodiac</span>. <br> <br> Midnight erupts in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Firecracker\">firecrackers</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fireworks\">fireworks</span>, streets fill with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lion_dance\">lion dance</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dragon_dance\">dragon dance</span>, children appear in new clothes, and married elders hand the young money-filled <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Red_envelope\">red envelopes</span> against the year's evils. Modern ritual has its own centrepiece in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"CCTV_New_Year's_Gala\">CCTV New Year's Gala</span>, broadcast every eve <b>since 1983</b> to audiences approaching 700 million, among the most-watched programmes on earth, while the state grants one of the year's great <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Golden_Week_(China)\">Golden Week</span> holidays. The same lunisolar reckoning underlies the wider family of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lunar_New_Year\">Lunar New Year</span> feasts, from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tết\">Tết</span> in Vietnam to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Seollal\">Seollal</span> in Korea, and the day is a public holiday in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Singapore\">Singapore</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Malaysia\">Malaysia</span>, and beyond. Carried worldwide by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Overseas_Chinese\">overseas Chinese</span>, it floods every <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinatown\">Chinatown</span> with parades, the procession in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"San_Francisco\">San Francisco</span> dating to the 19th century as one of the oldest outside Asia. <b>In 2024</b> the Spring Festival was inscribed by UNESCO as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Intangible_cultural_heritage\">intangible cultural heritage</span> of humanity, fitting recognition for a celebration that gathers more than a billion people of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> and its diaspora around one table.","citation":"","answerText":"Chinese New Year"},{"id":"cnc-047","num":"四十七","category":"China · Culture","question":"Staged by manipulating flat, jointed puppets of leather or paper behind a backlit cloth screen, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> told folk tales and legends to musical accompaniment, and is considered an ancestor of animated film.","answer":"Shadow play","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">皮影戏 (píyǐngxì, 'leather-shadow theatre')</span></div>","traditional":"皮影戲","hanzi":"皮影戏","pinyin":"píyǐngxì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">píyǐngxì</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“leather-shadow theatre”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Shadow play</b> is the <b>ancient form of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Theatre\">theatre</span></b> in which flat, jointed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Puppet\">puppets</span> of translucent leather or paper are manipulated against a backlit cloth screen, acting out folk tales and legends to song and percussion. Chinese tradition traces it to the court of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Wu_of_Han\">Emperor Wu</span> <b>of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span> around 120 BCE</b>, when a magician consoled the grieving sovereign by conjuring the moving shadow of his dead consort behind a curtain. Securely documented troupes appear in the entertainment quarters of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kaifeng\">Kaifeng</span> under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song dynasty</span> in the 11th century, by which time carvers had moved from paper to durable hide. A classic figure is scraped from donkey or cow <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Leather\">leather</span></b> until it glows, pierced with hundreds of ornamental cuts, dyed, and assembled from about 11 jointed pieces worked on slender <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bamboo\">bamboo</span> rods, with celebrated regional styles from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tangshan\">Tangshan</span> in the northeast to Huaxian in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shaanxi\">Shaanxi</span>. A troupe of about 5 could stage whole epic cycles, gods and demons from the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Investiture_of_the_Gods\"><i>Investiture of the Gods</i></span></b> or the pilgrims of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Journey_to_the_West\"><i>Journey to the West</i></span> flying across a lamp-lit screen for village audiences night after night. <br> <br> The art travelled widely, carried west in the wake of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongol_Empire\">Mongol Empire</span> toward <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Iran\">Iran</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Turkey\">Turkey</span>, where it fed the bawdy <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Karagöz_and_Hacivat\">Karagöz</span> tradition, while <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Indonesia\">Indonesia</span>'s venerable <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wayang_kulit\">wayang kulit</span></b> represents a parallel and possibly older lineage. Europe embraced the \"<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ombres_chinoises\">ombres chinoises</span>\" in the 18th century, fashionable from Parisian boulevards to the amateur stage of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Johann_Wolfgang_von_Goethe\">Goethe</span>, who mounted shadow <b>plays at Weimar in 1781</b>. Film historians count the screen of moving silhouettes an ancestor of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Animation\">animated</span> cinema, most directly in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lotte_Reiniger\">Lotte Reiniger</span>'s cut-out <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Adventures_of_Prince_Achmed\"><i>Adventures of Prince Achmed</i></span> of 1926</b>, the earliest surviving animated feature, while the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_Animation_Film_Studio\">Shanghai Animation Film Studio</span> later turned shadow and paper-cut styles into a national school. In China itself the tradition was battered by war and condemned during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span>, a fate dramatized in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Yimou\">Zhang Yimou</span>'s film <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"To_Live_(1994_film)\"><i>To Live</i></span> of 1994, whose hero's puppet chest is finally burned. Surviving masters, many now elderly, won global recognition when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"UNESCO\">UNESCO</span> inscribed Chinese shadow puppetry as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Intangible_cultural_heritage\">intangible cultural heritage</span> in 2011, and visitors to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi'an\">Xi'an</span> and other old towns can still watch a lamp, a screen, and 5 pairs of hands summon armies out of light.","citation":"","answerText":"Shadow play"},{"id":"cnc-048","num":"四十八","category":"China · Culture","question":"Assigning each year in a repeating 12-year cycle an animal — rat, ox, tiger, rabbit, dragon and so on — the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is used to reckon a person's birth sign, is celebrated each New Year, and draws on the same sexagenary cycle as the traditional calendar.","answer":"Chinese zodiac","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">生肖 (shēngxiào, 'birth likeness')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"生肖","pinyin":"shēngxiào","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">shēngxiào</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“born resembling”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Chinese zodiac</b> is a classification scheme rooted in the traditional <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_calendar\">Chinese calendar</span> that assigns an animal and its reputed attributes to each year in a repeating 12-year cycle, forming the foundation of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_astrology\">Chinese astrology</span></b>. The canonical sequence runs <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rat_(zodiac)\">Rat</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ox_(zodiac)\">Ox</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tiger_(zodiac)\">Tiger</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rabbit_(zodiac)\">Rabbit</span>, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dragon_(zodiac)\">Dragon</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Snake_(zodiac)\">Snake</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Horse_(zodiac)\">Horse</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Goat_(zodiac)\">Goat</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Monkey_(zodiac)\">Monkey</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rooster_(zodiac)\">Rooster</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dog_(zodiac)\">Dog</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pig_(zodiac)\">Pig</span>, the Dragon alone being a creature of myth. Each animal corresponds to one of the 12 <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Earthly_Branches\">Earthly Branches</span></b>, which pair with the 10 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heavenly_Stems\">Heavenly Stems</span> to generate the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sexagenary_cycle\">sexagenary cycle</span> of 60 year-names that has ordered Chinese chronology for more than 2 millennia. Because the stems carry the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuxing_(Chinese_philosophy)\">five phases</span> of wood, fire, earth, metal, and water, while the branches alternate between <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yin_and_yang\">yin and yang</span>, every birth year acquires a compound character, and a full 60 years must pass before, for instance, one Fire Horse year yields to the next. The same animals also label the <b>12 double-hours of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Traditional_Chinese_timekeeping\">traditional timekeeping</span></b> as well as months and days, so that a person's birth sign, refined by these finer reckonings, long furnished material for fortune-telling and for judging compatibility in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_marriage\">marriage</span> matchmaking. <br> <br> The system's origins reach back at least to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warring_States_period\">Warring States period</span>, for bamboo slips recovered at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shuihudi_Qin_bamboo_texts\">Shuihudi</span> from a tomb <b>sealed about 217 BCE already</b> match the branches with animals, while the list in its received order first appears in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lunheng\"><i>Lunheng</i></span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han</span> skeptic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Chong\">Wang Chong</span> in the 1st century CE. Popular legend instead explains the order through a great race convened by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jade_Emperor\">Jade Emperor</span>, or in Buddhist retellings by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gautama_Buddha\">Buddha</span>, in which the cunning Rat rode across the river on the Ox's head to claim first place while the Cat, tricked into missing the summons, was excluded forever. The signs remain woven into custom, each <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_New_Year\">Chinese New Year</span> ushering in a new animal, while people whose own sign returns traditionally appease the year-god <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tai_Sui\">Tai Sui</span> and wear red through their inauspicious zodiac year. Belief measurably shapes demography, for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Birth_rate\">birth rates</span> in communities such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Singapore\">Singapore</span> climb appreciably in favoured <b>Dragon years such as 2012</b>, whereas in Japan the Fire Horse year of 1966, shadowed by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hinoeuma\">hinoeuma</span> superstition, saw births plunge by roughly 25 percent. Carried along the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk_Road\">Silk Road</span> and through centuries of exchange, the cycle took root across Asia in variant forms, the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vietnamese_zodiac\">Vietnamese zodiac</span></b> substituting the Cat for the Rabbit and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_calendar\">Tibetan calendar</span> adapting it likewise, and today the animals are celebrated by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Overseas_Chinese\">Chinese communities worldwide</span> and honoured on commemorative <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Postage_stamp\">stamps</span> issued far beyond <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Chinese zodiac"},{"id":"cnc-049","num":"四十九","category":"China · Culture","question":"Arriving along the Silk Road in the Han era and flourishing under the Tang, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> blended Indian teachings with local thought, inspiring grotto temples, pilgrimages and schools such as Pure Land and Chan.","answer":"Chinese Buddhism","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">汉传佛教 ('Han-transmission Buddhism')</span></div>","traditional":"漢傳佛教","hanzi":"汉传佛教","pinyin":"Hànchuán Fójiào","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Hànchuán Fójiào</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Han-transmission Buddhism”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Chinese Buddhism</b> is the East Asian form of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mahayana\">Mahayana</span></b> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Buddhism\">Buddhism</span> that arrived along the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk_Road\">Silk Road</span> in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han</span> era and was gradually adapted to native <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Taoist</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> thought. Legend credits a dream of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Ming_of_Han\">Emperor Ming</span></b> with the founding of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"White_Horse_Temple\">White Horse Temple</span> at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luoyang\">Luoyang</span> in 68 CE, and historically attested monastic communities appear by the 1st century CE. Translation drove assimilation, from the Parthian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"An_Shigao\">An Shigao</span> in the 2nd century CE, whose circle borrowed Taoist vocabulary to \"match concepts,\" to the Kuchean master <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kumārajīva\">Kumarajiva</span>, who <b>reached Chang'an in 401 CE</b> and with a bureau of hundreds rendered some 300 scroll-volumes, including the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lotus_Sutra\"><i>Lotus Sutra</i></span>. Chinese pilgrims reversed the route, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Faxian\">Faxian</span> traveling to India between 399 and 414 CE and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xuanzang\">Xuanzang</span> returning in 645 with 657 texts, of which he translated 75 works in 1,335 fascicles, a journey later mythologized in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Journey_to_the_West\"><i>Journey to the West</i></span>. Imperial patronage carved the colossal grottoes of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yungang_Grottoes\">Yungang</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Longmen_Grottoes\">Longmen</span> under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Wei\">Northern Wei</span> and the painted <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mogao_Caves\">Mogao Caves</span> at Dunhuang, while by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sui_dynasty\">Sui</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span> distinctively Chinese schools had crystallized, among them <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tiantai\">Tiantai</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huayan\">Huayan</span>, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pure_Land_Buddhism\">Pure Land</span></b>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chan_Buddhism\">Chan</span>. <br> <br> The Tang marked the apex, when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Zetian\">Wu Zetian</span> championed Huayan metaphysics and dedicated Longmen's 17-meter (56 ft) Vairocana in 675, and pilgrims thronged the 4 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sacred_Mountains_of_China\">sacred Buddhist mountains</span> such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mount_Wutai\">Mount Wutai</span>. Monastic wealth provoked the backlash of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Wuzong_of_Tang\">Emperor Wuzong</span>, whose <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huichang_persecution_of_Buddhism\">Huichang persecution</span></b> of 845 reportedly destroyed 4,600 monasteries and 40,000 shrines and returned 260,500 monks and nuns to lay life. The scholastic schools never fully recovered, but practice-oriented Chan and Pure Land flourished into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song</span>, and Buddhist devotion propelled print culture, from the world's earliest dated printed book, a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Diamond_Sutra\"><i>Diamond Sutra</i></span> of 868, to the first woodblock <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Buddhist_canon\">Buddhist canon</span>, cut on some 130,000 blocks by 983. The synthesis radiated outward, shaping <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Korean_Buddhism\">Korean Buddhism</span></b>, Japanese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zen\">Zen</span>, and Vietnamese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Thiền\">Thiền</span>, while at home it settled into the syncretism of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_teachings\">3 teachings</span>. After the reformer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taixu\">Taixu</span> launched <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Humanistic_Buddhism\">Humanistic Buddhism</span></b> in the early 20th century and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span> shuttered nearly every temple, a striking revival has followed, with surveys suggesting on the order of 200 million Buddhists in China today—around 1 in 5 adults—making it the country's largest organized faith.","citation":"","answerText":"Chinese Buddhism"},{"id":"cnc-052","num":"五十二","category":"China · Culture","question":"Held on the 15th day of the 1st lunar month to close out the New Year celebrations, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is marked by eating sweet glutinous rice balls called <i>tangyuan</i> beneath the 1st full moon of the year.","answer":"Lantern Festival","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">元宵节 (Yuánxiāojié, 'festival of the first full-moon night')</span></div>","traditional":"元宵節","hanzi":"元宵节","pinyin":"Yuánxiāojié","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Yuánxiāojié</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“festival of the prime night”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Lantern Festival</b> falls on the 15th day of the 1st lunar month of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_calendar\">Chinese calendar</span>, closing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_New_Year\">New Year</span> season beneath the year's 1st full <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Moon\">moon</span></b> with glowing lanterns, riddles, and sweet glutinous rice balls. Its origins braid several threads of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span>: <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Wu_of_Han\">Emperor Wu</span>'s night-long torchlit worship of the supreme star deity, the lamps that <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Ming_of_Han\">Emperor Ming</span></b>, reigning 58–75 CE, ordered lit in honor of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Buddhism\">Buddhist</span> relics on the full-moon night, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Taoist</span> birthday of the Heavenly Official who confers blessings. The spectacle peaked under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span>, when the nightly <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Curfew\">curfew</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chang'an\">Chang'an</span> was suspended</b> for 3 nights so crowds could roam beneath towering lantern wheels, an indulgence the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song</span> stretched to 5 nights and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span> to as many as 10. Because respectable women could walk abroad those evenings, the festival doubled as a night of courtship, immortalized in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xin_Qiji\">Xin Qiji</span>'s lyric of searching the crowd a hundred times before finding his beloved where the lantern light burned low, while guessing the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Riddle\">riddles</span></b> pasted on lanterns sharpened wits, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lion_dance\">lion</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dragon_dance\">dragon dances</span> shook the streets. The essential taste is the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tangyuan\">tangyuan</span>, boiled rice-flour spheres filled with black <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sesame\">sesame</span>, peanut, or <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Adzuki_bean\">red-bean</span> paste, whose roundness puns on the word for family reunion. <br> <br> Regional celebrations grew into wonders of their own, from the lantern fair on <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qinhuai_River\">Qinhuai River</span></b>, held since the Ming, to the colossal illuminated tableaux of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zigong\">Zigong</span>, China's self-styled lantern capital, which draw millions each season. On <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span> the night takes to the air and the battlefield alike, thousands of wish-inscribed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sky_lantern\">sky lanterns</span> rising over the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pingxi_Sky_Lantern_Festival\">Pingxi Sky Lantern Festival</span> while daredevils at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yanshui_Beehive_Fireworks_Festival\">Yanshui Beehive Fireworks Festival</span></b> stand in armor amid volleys of bottle rockets fired for luck. Southeast Asian communities keep the date as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cap_Go_Meh\">Cap Go Meh</span>, Hokkien for the \"15th night,\" with parades from Indonesia to Malaysia. As the \"Upper Prime\" festival it heads a Taoist trio of moonlit observances that continues with the 7th-month <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ghost_Festival\">Ghost Festival</span>, and its snack once brushed politics, <b>for in 1916 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_Shikai\">Yuan Shikai</span></b>, hearing in \"yuanxiao\" a pun on \"Yuan extinguished,\" ordered the dumplings called tangyuan instead. Two thousand years on, the mainland gives the day no public holiday, yet temple fairs, television galas, and now drone-lit skies still end the New Year as it began, with the whole family round, like the moon and the dumplings, under the year's first full light.","citation":"","answerText":"Lantern Festival"},{"id":"cnc-053","num":"五十三","category":"China · Culture","question":"Practised with brush, ink, paper and inkstone — the Four Treasures of the Study — the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> treats the writing of characters as a form of self-expression and is ranked alongside painting among the highest visual arts.","answer":"Chinese calligraphy","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">书法 (shūfǎ, 'the method of writing')</span></div>","traditional":"書法","hanzi":"书法","pinyin":"shūfǎ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">shūfǎ</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“the way of writing”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Chinese calligraphy</b> is the artistic practice of writing <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_characters\">Chinese characters</span></b> with brush and ink, esteemed as one of the highest of the visual arts. It is executed with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Treasures_of_the_Study\">Four Treasures of the Study</span> — the animal-hair <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ink_brush\">brush</span></b>, the pine-soot <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Inkstick\">inkstick</span> ground with water, the absorbent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xuan_paper\">paper</span>, and the carved <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Inkstone\">inkstone</span> upon which the ink is prepared. Sharing both its implements and its <b>expressive brushwork with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ink_wash_painting\">ink wash painting</span></b>, the two were traditionally held to spring from a common source and ranked together at the summit of cultivated accomplishment. The art encompasses five canonical styles that evolved over many centuries, the archaic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Seal_script\">seal script</span>, the squared <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Clerical_script\">clerical script</span>, the standard <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Regular_script\">regular script</span></b>, the fluid <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Semi-cursive_script\">running script</span>, and the dynamic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cursive_script_(East_Asia)\">cursive script</span>. These forms emerged from the earliest <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Oracle_bone_script\">oracle bone</span> inscriptions and matured into a self-conscious art during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jin_dynasty_(266–420)\">Jin</span> dynasties, when the brushwork of individual masters began to be collected and revered. <br> <br> The towering figure of the tradition is <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Xizhi\">Wang Xizhi</span>, honoured as the Sage of Calligraphy, whose <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lantingji_Xu\"><i>Preface to the Orchid Pavilion</i></span> of 353 CE</b> is celebrated as the supreme example of running script. Under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang dynasty</span> the regular script attained its classical perfection in the hands of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yan_Zhenqing\">Yan Zhenqing</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ouyang_Xun\">Ouyang Xun</span>, while the unconventional <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Xu\">Zhang Xu</span></b> and the monk <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huaisu\">Huaisu</span> drove cursive writing toward exuberant abstraction. Later generations added their own voices, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song</span> scholar-artists <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Su_Shi\">Su Shi</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mi_Fu\">Mi Fu</span> prizing personal feeling over imitation, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan</span> master <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhao_Mengfu\">Zhao Mengfu</span> reviving the elegance of the ancients. Bound up with the world of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Scholar-official\">scholar-officials</span>, fine handwriting carried real weight in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examinations</span> and was prized above all as a direct trace of the writer's inner character, captured in the maxim that the brush reveals the person. The art radiated throughout East Asia as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japanese_calligraphy\">Japanese</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Korean_calligraphy\">Korean</span> calligraphy, later stirred the imagination of Western <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Abstract_expressionism\">abstract expressionists</span>, and <b>in 2009</b> was inscribed by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> on the UNESCO list of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Intangible_cultural_heritage\">intangible cultural heritage</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Chinese calligraphy"},{"id":"cnc-057","num":"五十七","category":"China · Culture","question":"Encompassing the worship of a vast pantheon of gods, immortals and ancestors, along with geomancy and local festivals, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> — without a single founder or scripture — remains the most widely practised belief system among Han Chinese.","answer":"Chinese folk religion","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">中国民间信仰 ('Chinese popular belief')</span></div>","traditional":"中國民間信仰","hanzi":"中国民间信仰","pinyin":"Zhōngguó mínjiān xìnyǎng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōngguó mínjiān xìnyǎng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Chinese folk religion</b> is the diffuse, indigenous religious tradition of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Chinese\">Han Chinese</span>, possessing neither a single founder nor a defining scripture nor any formal membership. Thoroughly <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Polytheism\">polytheistic</span>, it venerates an <b>immense pantheon of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shen_(Chinese_religion)\">gods</span></b>, deified heroes, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xian_(Taoism)\">immortals</span>, headed by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jade_Emperor\">Jade Emperor</span> and including such beloved figures as the sea goddess <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mazu\">Mazu</span>, the warrior <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guan_Yu\">Guan Yu</span>, and the merciful <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guanyin\">Guanyin</span>. Alongside these great deities stand countless local guardians, the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tudigong\">earth gods</span></b>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"City_God_(China)\">city gods</span>, and the household <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kitchen_God\">kitchen god</span>, together with the spirits of the family <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_ancestral_worship\">ancestors</span> honoured at domestic altars. Its worldview rests on the interplay of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yin_and_yang\">yin and yang</span> and the vital breath of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qi\">qi</span>, on a moralised <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tian\">Heaven</span></b>, and on a vision of the afterlife as an underworld <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Diyu\">bureaucracy</span> mirroring the imperial state, in which deities might be promoted or demoted according to their merit. In practice it blends seamlessly with the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_teachings\">three teachings</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucianism</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Taoism</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Buddhism\">Buddhism</span>, borrowing deities, clergy, and rites from each without demanding exclusive allegiance to any. <br> <br> The tradition's roots reach into deep antiquity, to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shang_dynasty\">Shang</span> worship of the high god <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shangdi\">Shangdi</span> attested on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Oracle_bone_script\">oracle bones</span> and to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_dynasty\">Zhou</span> cult of Heaven and ancestors. Its everyday observance centres on offerings of incense and <b>burned <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joss_paper\">spirit money</span></b>, on divination by casting crescent-shaped <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiaobei\">moon blocks</span>, on the siting of graves and buildings according to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Feng_shui\">geomancy</span>, and on the <b>trance work of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tongji_(spirit_medium)\">spirit mediums</span></b>. Communal life turns on a calendar of festivals, among them <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_New_Year\">Chinese New Year</span>, the tomb-sweeping of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qingming_Festival\">Qingming</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ghost_Festival\">Ghost Festival</span>, celebrated at innumerable village temples and lineage halls through processions and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Temple_fair\">temple fairs</span></b>. Long disparaged by modernising reformers and savagely repressed as feudal superstition during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span>, the religion revived vigorously after the economic reforms of the late 20th century, when temples were rebuilt across the countryside. Today it flourishes in mainland <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>, is especially pervasive in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span>, and travels with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Overseas_Chinese\">overseas Chinese</span> diaspora, with scholarly estimates of its adherents ranging from several hundred million to more than 400 million, making it by far the most widely practised faith among the Han.","citation":"","answerText":"Chinese folk religion"},{"id":"cng-011","num":"十一","category":"China · Geography","question":"The largest inland basin in the country, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is a great endorheic lowland of southern Xinjiang ringed by the Tian Shan and Kunlun ranges and filled largely by a vast sand desert.","answer":"Tarim Basin","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">from a Turkic name for the basin's river</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"塔里木盆地","pinyin":"Tǎlǐmù Péndì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Tǎlǐmù Péndì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Tarim Basin</b> is the largest <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Endorheic_basin\">endorheic basin</span></b> in China, an interior lowland of southern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinjiang\">Xinjiang</span> covering roughly 530,000 to over 1,000,000 square kilometers (390,000 sq mi) depending on definition, enclosed by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tian_Shan\">Tian Shan</span> to the north, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kunlun_Mountains\">Kunlun Mountains</span> to the south, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pamir_Mountains\">Pamirs</span> to the west. Its floor lies between roughly 800 and 1,300 meters (2,600 and 4,300 ft) above sea level and receives generally less than 100 millimeters (3.9 in) of rain annually, conditions that sustain the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taklamakan_Desert\">Taklamakan Desert</span>, a sand sea of about 337,000 square kilometers (130,000 sq mi) often ranked as the world's 2nd-largest shifting-sand desert. The basin is drained internally by the roughly 2,000-kilometer (1,200 mi) <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tarim_River\">Tarim River</span>, China's longest inland watercourse, which gathers the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yarkand_River\">Yarkand</span> and other glacier-fed streams and formerly terminated in the <b>salt lake <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lop_Nur\">Lop Nur</span></b>, which dried up by the 1970s after upstream diversions. Geologically the lowland rests on an ancient <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Precambrian\">Precambrian</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Craton\">craton</span> buried under kilometers of sediment, and its deep strata hold some of China's richest <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Petroleum\">petroleum</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Natural_gas\">natural gas</span> reserves, estimated at well over 10 billion tonnes (11000 million tons) of oil equivalent and tapped <b>since 2004</b> by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"West–East_Gas_Pipeline\">West–East Gas Pipeline</span>. Human settlement clings to a ring of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Oasis\">oases</span> such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kashgar\">Kashgar</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hotan\">Hotan</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Korla\">Korla</span>, which support irrigated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cotton\">cotton</span> and fruit cultivation, while the Lop Nur wastes hosted China's first nuclear detonation, <b>the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Project_596\">596 test</span> of 1964</b>. <br> <br> The basin's deep past was illuminated by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tarim_mummies\">Tarim mummies</span>, naturally desiccated remains from sites like the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiaohe_Cemetery\">Xiaohe Cemetery</span> dated to roughly 2100–1700 BCE, whose genomes were shown in a 2021 study to derive largely from <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ancient_North_Eurasian\">Ancient North Eurasian</span></b> populations rather than from migrants. By the 1st millennium BCE its rim supported city-states such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Loulan_Kingdom\">Loulan</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kucha\">Kucha</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kingdom_of_Khotan\">Kingdom of Khotan</span>, several of which spoke the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tocharian_languages\">Tocharian languages</span></b>, the easternmost branch of the Indo-European family. The northern and southern arms of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk_Road\">Silk Road</span> diverged around the desert, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span> asserted control by establishing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Protectorate_of_the_Western_Regions\">Protectorate of the Western Regions</span> in 60 BCE. <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Buddhism\">Buddhism</span> flourished in the oasis kingdoms for the next millennium, anchored under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang dynasty</span> by the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Garrisons_of_Anxi\">Four Garrisons of Anxi</span></b>, before the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kara-Khanid_Khanate\">Kara-Khanid Khanate</span> began the region's gradual conversion to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Islam\">Islam</span> in the 10th century. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> annexed the basin in the 1750s after destroying the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dzungar_Khanate\">Dzungar Khanate</span>, and today it remains the demographic heartland of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Uyghurs\">Uyghur</span> people.","citation":"","answerText":"Tarim Basin"},{"id":"cng-012","num":"十二","category":"China · Geography","question":"Occupying most of the Tarim Basin, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> — one of the largest sandy deserts on Earth — was skirted by the oasis towns of the ancient Silk Road.","answer":"Taklamakan Desert","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Turkic; popularly read as 'place of no return'</span></div>","traditional":"塔克拉瑪干沙漠","hanzi":"塔克拉玛干沙漠","pinyin":"Tǎkèlāmǎgān Shāmò","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Tǎkèlāmǎgān Shāmò</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Taklamakan Desert</b> is a vast sandy desert of about 337,000 square kilometres (130,000 sq mi) filling most of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tarim_Basin\">Tarim Basin</span></b> in southern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinjiang\">Xinjiang</span>, often ranked as the largest desert of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> and the world’s second largest expanse of shifting sands. Walled off by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kunlun_Mountains\">Kunlun Mountains</span> to the south, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pamir_Mountains\">Pamirs</span> to the west, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tian_Shan\">Tian Shan</span> to the north, it lies in a profound <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rain_shadow\">rain shadow</span> where annual precipitation ranges from roughly 10 to 40 millimetres (0.39 to 1.6 in), earning it the Chinese epithet “Sea of Death.” Around 85 percent of its surface consists of mobile <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dune\">dunes</span></b>, some rising 200 to 300 metres (660 to 980 ft), and its harsh <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Desert_climate\">cold desert climate</span> swings from winter lows near −20 °C (−4 °F) to summer highs around 40 °C (104 °F), with a rare snowfall blanketing <b>the entire desert in 2008</b>. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tarim_River\">Tarim River</span> traces the northern margin while the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hotan_River\">Hotan River</span> seasonally threads the sands toward it, and historic drainage once terminated in the wandering salt lake of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lop_Nur\">Lop Nur</span> on the eastern fringe. Ferocious spring <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dust_storm\">dust storms</span></b>, known locally as black hurricanes, loft sediment that contributes to the deposits of the distant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Loess_Plateau\">Loess Plateau</span>. <br> <br> The desert’s extreme aridity preserved the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tarim_mummies\">Tarim mummies</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bronze_Age\">Bronze Age</span> burials such as the so-called Beauty of Loulan <b>dating to nearly 1800 BCE</b>, which testify to early settlement along the rivers. In later antiquity the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk_Road\">Silk Road</span> split into northern and southern branches that skirted the sands through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Oasis\">oasis</span> towns including <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kashgar\">Kashgar</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kingdom_of_Khotan\">Khotan</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kucha\">Kucha</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Loulan_Kingdom\">Loulan</span>, channels through which <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Buddhism\">Buddhism</span> entered China and along which the pilgrim <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xuanzang\">Xuanzang</span> travelled in the 7th century. Sand-buried settlements such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Niya_ruins\">Niya ruins</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dandan_Oilik\">Dandan Oilik</span> were <b>rediscovered around 1900</b> by the explorers <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sven_Hedin\">Sven Hedin</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Aurel_Stein\">Aurel Stein</span>, whose excavations recovered documents in scripts like <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kharosthi\">Kharosthi</span>. Beneath the dunes lie major reserves of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Petroleum\">petroleum</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Natural_gas\">natural gas</span> that since 2004 have fed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"West–East_Gas_Pipeline\">West–East Gas Pipeline</span>, prompting construction of the 552-kilometre (343 mi) <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tarim_Desert_Highway\">Tarim Desert Highway</span></b> in 1995, shielded by an irrigated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Windbreak\">windbreak</span> of drought-tolerant shrubs. Completion of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hotan–Ruoqiang_railway\">Hotan–Ruoqiang railway</span> in 2022 closed a 2,712-kilometre (1,685 mi) rail loop around the desert, and in 2024 workers finished a 3,046-kilometre (1,893 mi) green belt encircling the sands under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three-North_Shelter_Forest_Program\">Three-North Shelter Forest Program</span>, the first attempt in history to hem in an entire drifting desert.","citation":"","answerText":"Taklamakan Desert"},{"id":"cng-013","num":"十三","category":"China · Geography","question":"Containing the lowest point in the country at well over 150 m (490 ft) below sea level, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is famed for its grapes and for the underground <i>karez</i> channels that irrigate its oases.","answer":"Turpan Depression","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">from the Uyghur place name Turpan</span></div>","traditional":"吐魯番盆地","hanzi":"吐鲁番盆地","pinyin":"Tǔlǔfān Péndì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Tǔlǔfān Péndì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Turpan Depression</b>, also rendered Turfan, is a <b>fault-bounded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Graben\">graben</span></b> of roughly 50,000 square kilometers (19,000 sq mi) in eastern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinjiang\">Xinjiang</span>, pressed against the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bogda_Shan\">Bogda Shan</span> spur of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tian_Shan\">Tian Shan</span>, with some 4,000 square kilometers (1,500 sq mi) of its floor lying below sea level. At its center the <b>salt lake <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ayding_Lake\">Ayding Lake</span></b> sits about 154 meters (505 ft) below sea level, the lowest point in China and among the lowest exposed land surfaces on earth after the shores of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dead_Sea\">Dead Sea</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sea_of_Galilee\">Sea of Galilee</span>. Locked in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rain_shadow\">rain shadow</span> of the surrounding ranges, the basin is the hottest place in China, recording 52.2 °C (126 °F) <b>in July 2023</b>, while annual precipitation of barely 16 millimeters (0.63 in) is dwarfed by potential evaporation approaching 3,000 millimeters (120 in), and the red sandstone <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Flaming_Mountains\">Flaming Mountains</span> radiate surface temperatures said to exceed 70 °C (158 °F). Agriculture survives on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Snowmelt\">snowmelt</span> delivered through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Turpan_water_system\">karez</span>, gravity-fed underground galleries related to the Persian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qanat\">qanat</span>, of which more than 1,000 systems totaling on the order of 5,000 kilometers (3,100 mi) were dug over roughly 2,000 years. This water sustains an <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Oasis\">oasis</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Viticulture\">viticulture</span> famed since antiquity, whose seedless <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sultana_(grape)\">sultana</span> grapes, dried in latticed mud-brick barns, make the district one of the leading sources of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Raisin\">raisins</span> in the country. <br> <br> The depression entered history as the seat of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jushi_Kingdom\">Jushi Kingdom</span></b>, whose capital at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiaohe_ruins\">Jiaohe</span>, founded in the 1st millennium BCE on a loess island between two ravines, ranks among the oldest and largest earthen cities in the world. After the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span> wrested the area from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiongnu\">Xiongnu</span> in the 1st century BCE, the walled city of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gaochang\">Gaochang</span> rose as the basin's chief <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk_Road\">Silk Road</span> entrepôt, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang dynasty</span> annexed it in 640, leaving the nearby <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Astana_Cemetery\">Astana Cemetery</span></b> filled with thousands of dated documents and desiccated burials. From the 9th century the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kingdom_of_Qocho\">Kingdom of Qocho</span>, founded by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Uyghurs\">Uyghur</span> migrants, presided over a cosmopolitan society in which <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Buddhism\">Buddhism</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manichaeism\">Manichaeism</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Church_of_the_East\">Church of the East</span> coexisted, its art preserved in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bezeklik_Caves\">Bezeklik cave temples</span></b>. Early in the 20th century German expeditions under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Albert_von_Le_Coq\">Albert von Le Coq</span> sawed away many Bezeklik murals, a large share of which were destroyed in Allied bombing during the Second World War. The basin also holds a place in literature, since the Flaming Mountains figure in the 16th-century novel <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Journey_to_the_West\"><i>Journey to the West</i></span>, and today the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lanzhou–Xinjiang_high-speed_railway\">Lanzhou–Xinjiang high-speed railway</span></b> carries visitors across a landscape where vineyards flourish below sea level.","citation":"","answerText":"Turpan Depression"},{"id":"cng-014","num":"十四","category":"China · Geography","question":"A long, narrow string of oases running northwest between mountains and desert in Gansu, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was the vital gateway of the Silk Road linking the Chinese heartland to Central Asia.","answer":"Hexi Corridor","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">河西走廊 ('corridor west of the [Yellow] river')</span></div>","traditional":"甘肅走廊","hanzi":"河西走廊","pinyin":"Gānsù Zǒuláng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Gānsù Zǒuláng</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“corridor west of the river”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Hexi Corridor</b>) is a chain of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Oasis\">oases</span> stretching roughly 1,000 kilometres (620 mi) northwest through <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gansu\">Gansu</span></b> province, taking its name from its position west of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_River\">Yellow River</span> and forming the natural passage between the Chinese heartland, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinjiang\">Xinjiang</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Asia\">Central Asia</span>. The corridor, in places only a few kilometres wide and elsewhere nearly 100, is pinned between the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qilian_Mountains\">Qilian Mountains</span>, whose summits exceed 5,500 metres (18,000 ft), and the arid ranges fronting the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gobi_Desert\">Gobi</span>, the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Badain_Jaran_Desert\">Badain Jaran</span></b>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tengger_Desert\">Tengger</span> sands to the north. Annual precipitation on the corridor floor falls below 200 millimetres (7.9 in), so settlement depends on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Glacier\">glacier</span>-fed streams such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shiyang_River\">Shiyang</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ruo_Shui\">Ruo Shui</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shule_River\">Shule River</span>, which die away in desert terminal basins. These waters sustain the historic oasis cities of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuwei,_Gansu\">Wuwei</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhangye\">Zhangye</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiuquan\">Jiuquan</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dunhuang\">Dunhuang</span>, home today to several million people and to striped badlands like those of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhangye_National_Geopark\">Zhangye National Geopark</span></b>. The Qilian ice fields that feed the corridor have lost a substantial share of their area since the 1950s, making water scarcity a growing constraint on its irrigated agriculture. <br> <br> The corridor entered history when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Qian\">Zhang Qian</span> traversed it on diplomatic missions <b>between 138 and 126 BCE</b>, after which <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Wu_of_Han\">Emperor Wu of Han</span> sent the young general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huo_Qubing\">Huo Qubing</span> to drive out the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiongnu\">Xiongnu</span> in 121 BCE and founded 4 garrison commanderies along its length. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span> extended the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Wall_of_China\">Great Wall</span> to the corridor’s far end at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yumen_Pass\">Yumen Pass</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangguan\">Yangguan</span>, fixing the route along which <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk_Road\">Silk Road</span> caravans and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Buddhism\">Buddhism</span> itself entered China. Near Dunhuang the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mogao_Caves\">Mogao Caves</span>, <b>begun in 366 CE</b> and eventually numbering 735 grottoes, preserved a sealed library of some 50,000 manuscripts rediscovered in 1900, among them a copy of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Diamond_Sutra\"><i>Diamond Sutra</i></span> dated 868, the oldest securely dated printed book in the world. Control later passed to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_Empire\">Tibetan Empire</span>, the loyalist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guiyi_Circuit\">Guiyi Circuit</span> from 848, the Tangut <b>state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Western_Xia\">Western Xia</span> after 1036</b>, and the Mongols whose roads <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marco_Polo\">Marco Polo</span> described, until the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming dynasty</span> anchored its frontier at the 1372 fortress of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiayu_Pass\">Jiayu Pass</span>. The same trough now carries the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lanzhou–Xinjiang_railway\">Lanzhou–Xinjiang railway</span></b> of 1962 and a 1,776-kilometre (1,104 mi) <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lanzhou–Urumqi_high-speed_railway\">high-speed line</span> opened in 2014, while the multi-gigawatt <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gansu_Wind_Farm\">Gansu Wind Farm</span> near Jiuquan ranks among the largest on Earth, reviving the corridor’s old role as artery of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Belt_and_Road_Initiative\">Belt and Road Initiative</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Hexi Corridor"},{"id":"cng-028","num":"二十八","category":"China · Geography","question":"An east–west mountain range cutting across the middle of the country, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> shields the Sichuan Basin from northern cold, separates the Yangtze watershed from the north, and shelters the wild giant panda.","answer":"Qinling","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">秦岭 ('mountains of Qin'), after the ancient Qin state</span></div>","traditional":"秦嶺","hanzi":"秦岭","pinyin":"Qínlǐng, “mountains of Qin,” after the ancient state of <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Qin_(state","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Qínlǐng, “mountains of Qin,” after the ancient state of &lt;a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Qin_(state</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Qinling</b>\">Qin</a>) is an east–west mountain system running some 1,600 kilometres (990 mi) from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gansu\">Gansu</span> across southern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shaanxi\">Shaanxi</span> into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Henan\">Henan</span>, crowned by <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mount_Taibai\">Mount Taibai</span></b> at 3,767 metres (12,360 ft), the highest summit in China east of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_Plateau\">Tibetan Plateau</span>. Together with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huai_River\">Huai River</span> it defines the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qinling–Huaihe_Line\">Qinling–Huaihe Line</span>, the customary divide of China that tracks the 0 °C (32 °F) January isotherm and the 800-millimetre rainfall contour, separating the subtropical <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rice\">rice</span> lands of the south from the dry wheat country of the north. The wall of peaks blocks Siberian cold from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan_Basin\">Sichuan Basin</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hanzhong\">Hanzhong</span> valley while parting the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wei_River\">Wei River</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guanzhong\">Guanzhong</span> plain around <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi'an\">Xi’an</span> from the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_River_(Hanshui)\">Han River</span></b>, the longest tributary of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span>. Its cloud forests shelter the “four treasures” of the range, namely a distinct Qinling subspecies of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Giant_panda\">giant panda</span> numbering around 345 animals and including rare brown-and-white individuals, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Golden_snub-nosed_monkey\">golden snub-nosed monkey</span>, the golden <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Takin\">takin</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Crested_ibis\">crested ibis</span>, <b>refound in 1981</b> as a final flock of just 7 birds in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yang_County\">Yang County</span> and since restored to many thousands. At the eastern end rises <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mount_Hua\">Mount Hua</span>, 2,154 metres (7,067 ft) of sheer granite counted among the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sacred_Mountains_of_China\">Five Great Mountains</span>, while the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhongnan_Mountains\">Zhongnan</span> section has harboured religious hermits for 2 millennia. <br> <br> From antiquity the barrier was threaded by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shu_Roads\">Shu Roads</span>, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gallery_road\">gallery roads</span> of timber bolted</b> to cliff faces along routes such as Chencang and Ziwu, paths whose terrors <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Bai\">Li Bai</span> immortalized in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shu_Dao_Nan\"><i>Shu Dao Nan</i></span> as harder than climbing to heaven. Strategy turned on these planks, for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Gaozu_of_Han\">Liu Bang</span> <b>burned them in 206 BCE</b> to feign retreat before secretly recrossing at Chencang, a ruse remembered as a proverb, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuge_Liang\">Zhuge Liang</span>’s repeated northern expeditions over the range ended with his death on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Wuzhang_Plains\">Wuzhang Plains</span> in 234 CE. Tradition also makes the northern foothills a cradle of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Taoism</span>, since <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Laozi\">Laozi</span> is said to have composed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tao_Te_Ching\"><i>Tao Te Ching</i></span> at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Louguantai\">Louguantai</span> before vanishing into the west. Modern engineering finally tamed the crossing with the first railway from <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Baoji\">Baoji</span> to Chengdu in 1958</b>, the 18-kilometre (11 mi) <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhongnanshan_Tunnel\">Zhongnanshan Tunnel</span> of 2007, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi'an–Chengdu_high-speed_railway\">Xi’an–Chengdu high-speed railway</span> of 2017 that runs almost entirely in tunnels and viaducts within the range, and a 98-kilometre (61 mi) water tunnel holed through in 2022 to carry Han River water north to the Wei. The mountains even shook national politics when, after 6 directives from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span>, authorities in 2018 demolished about 1,185 illegal villas built on protected slopes, a scandal that helped bring <b>former governor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhao_Zhengyong\">Zhao Zhengyong</span></b> a suspended death sentence and made the Qinling a national symbol of ecological discipline.","citation":"","answerText":"Qinling"},{"id":"cng-043","num":"四十三","category":"China · Geography","question":"A large tropical island in the South China Sea, separated from the mainland by the narrow Qiongzhou Strait, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is a beach-resort destination and the home region of the Li people.","answer":"Hainan","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">海南 (Hǎinán, 'south of the sea')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"海南","pinyin":"Hǎinán","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Hǎinán</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“south of the sea”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Hainan</b> is the southernmost province of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>, consisting chiefly of a tropical island in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South_China_Sea\">South China Sea</span> separated from the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Leizhou_Peninsula\">Leizhou Peninsula</span></b> of the mainland by the roughly 30-kilometre (19 mi) <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qiongzhou_Strait\">Qiongzhou Strait</span>. At about 33,900 square kilometres (13,100 sq mi) the island is the second largest in China after <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span>, home to some 10 million inhabitants, with the provincial capital <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Haikou\">Haikou</span> on its northern shore and the beach resort of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sanya\">Sanya</span></b> at its tropical southern tip. The island is the historic homeland of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_people\">Li people</span>, an indigenous population of around 1.5 million who speak a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hlai_languages\">Hlai</span> tongue of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kra–Dai_languages\">Kra–Dai</span> family, and it also shelters <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Miao_people\">Miao</span> communities and the small Muslim <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Utsuls\">Utsuls</span> of Sanya, whose <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chamic_languages\">Chamic</span> speech descends from the medieval kingdom of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Champa\">Champa</span>. Its mountainous interior culminates in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mount_Wuzhi\">Mount Wuzhi</span> at 1,840 metres (6,040 ft) and is <b>mantled by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tropical_rainforest\">tropical rainforest</span></b> preserved in a national park, the last refuge of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hainan_gibbon\">Hainan gibbon</span>, which with only around 40 individuals ranks among the rarest <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Primate\">primates</span> and indeed the rarest <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ape\">ape</span> on Earth. Its warm climate underpins <b>extensive plantations of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Natural_rubber\">natural rubber</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Coconut\">coconut</span>, and tropical fruit, yet the modern economy leans heavily on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tourism\">tourism</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Duty-free_shop\">duty-free</span> retail, expanded after the island was <b>designated a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hainan_Free_Trade_Port\">Hainan Free Trade Port</span> in 2018</b> to draw mainland visitors to its resorts. <br> <br> Imperial China reached the island in 110 BCE, when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Wu_of_Han\">Emperor Wu of Han</span> established the commanderies of Zhuya and Dan’er, though indigenous resistance led the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han</span> to abandon direct rule for long stretches. Remote and malarial, Hainan became a notorious place of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Exile\">exile</span> for disgraced officials, most famously the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song</span>-era poet <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Su_Shi\">Su Shi</span>, banished to Danzhou <b>from 1097</b>, while in later centuries it produced the upright <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span> censor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hai_Rui\">Hai Rui</span>. <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empire_of_Japan\">Japan</span> occupied the island from 1939 to 1945 and stripped its iron and other resources, and after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">civil war</span> the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army\">People’s Liberation Army</span> wrested Hainan from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Nationalist</span> forces in <b>the amphibious <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Landing_Operation_on_Hainan_Island\">Landing Operation on Hainan Island</span> of 1950</b>. Administered as part of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangdong\">Guangdong</span> for most of its modern history, Hainan was separated to become China’s youngest province in 1988 and simultaneously its largest <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Special_economic_zones_of_China\">special economic zone</span>, a status championed during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">reforms</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>. Today the province anchors strategic assets far larger than its size, including the coastal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wenchang_Space_Launch_Site\">Wenchang Space Launch Site</span> from which heavy <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Long_March_5\">Long March 5</span> rockets and lunar and Mars probes ascend, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yulin_Naval_Base\">Yulin Naval Base</span> near Sanya that harbours China’s nuclear-powered <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Submarine\">submarines</span>; its surrounding waters drew global attention in the 2001 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hainan_Island_incident\">Hainan Island incident</span> involving a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States\">US</span> spy plane, even as the seaside town of Boao now hosts the annual <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boao_Forum_for_Asia\">Boao Forum for Asia</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Hainan"},{"id":"cng-048","num":"四十八","category":"China · Geography","question":"A set of revered peaks central to traditional religion, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> comprises the Five Great Mountains tied to Taoism and imperial ritual, alongside the celebrated Four Sacred Mountains of Chinese Buddhism.","answer":"Sacred Mountains of China","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">五岳 ('five great peaks') and 四大佛教名山 ('four Buddhist mountains')</span></div>","traditional":"五嶽 and 四大佛教名山","hanzi":"五岳 and 四大佛教名山","pinyin":"Wǔyuè, \"Five Great Mountains,\" and Sìdà Fójiào Míngshān, \"Four Great Buddhist Mountains\"","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Wǔyuè, \"Five Great Mountains,\" and Sìdà Fójiào Míngshān, \"Four Great Buddhist Mountains\"</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Sacred Mountains of China</b> together form the classic grouping of 9 revered peaks that anchor the country's sacred geography, the first set tied to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Taoism</span> and the imperial cult and arranged by the directional cosmology of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuxing_(Chinese_philosophy)\">Five Phases</span>. Foremost is the eastern peak, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mount_Tai\">Mount Tai</span></b> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shandong\">Shandong</span>, only 1,545 meters (5,069 ft) high yet climbed by some 72 ancient rulers according to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Qian\">Sima Qian</span>, where <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_Shi_Huang\">Qin Shi Huang</span> <b>performed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Feng_and_Shan_sacrifices\">Feng and Shan sacrifices</span> in 219 BCE</b> as one of only 6 emperors ever to do so, the last being <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Zhenzong\">Zhenzong</span> in 1008, and where <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucius\">Confucius</span> was said to have found the world small from the summit reached today by roughly 6,600 steps. The other cardinal peaks are <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mount_Hua\">Mount Hua</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shaanxi\">Shaanxi</span>, at 2,154 meters (7,067 ft) the loftiest and most precipitous with its notorious cliff-side plank walk, the southern <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mount_Heng_(Hunan)\">Mount Heng</span></b> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hunan\">Hunan</span>, and the northern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mount_Heng_(Shanxi)\">Mount Heng</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanxi\">Shanxi</span>, near the cliff-pinned <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hanging_Temple\">Hanging Temple</span>. At the center stands <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mount_Song\">Mount Song</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Henan\">Henan</span>, whose <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shaolin_Monastery\">Shaolin Monastery</span>, founded in 495, became the wellspring of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chan_Buddhism\">Chan Buddhism</span> and of legendary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_martial_arts\">martial arts</span>, recognized within <b>a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Heritage_Site\">World Heritage</span> ensemble in 2010</b>. Conceived as cosmic pillars and stations of imperial inspection tours, the Five Great Mountains were later matched by Taoism's own sacred quartet headed by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wudang_Mountains\">Wudang Mountains</span>. <br> <br> The companion set comprises the 4 great mountains of Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Buddhism\">Buddhism</span>, each venerated as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bodhimaṇḍa\">bodhimaṇḍa</span>, or earthly seat, of a bodhisattva. <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mount_Wutai\">Mount Wutai</span> in Shanxi, rising to 3,061 meters (10,040 ft) as the roof of north China and <b>listed by UNESCO in 2009</b>, belongs to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manjushri\">Mañjuśrī</span> of wisdom and preserves Tang wooden halls, including <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foguang_Temple\">Foguang Temple</span> of 857, famously re-identified by the architect <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liang_Sicheng\">Liang Sicheng</span> in 1937. <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mount_Emei\">Mount Emei</span> in Sichuan, 3,099 meters (10,170 ft) and home to what tradition calls the country's first Buddhist temple of the 1st century CE, is the seat of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Samantabhadra\">Samantabhadra</span> and was inscribed in 1996 together with the 71-meter (230 ft) <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Leshan_Giant_Buddha\">Leshan Giant Buddha</span></b> carved in the 8th century. The island peak of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mount_Putuo\">Mount Putuo</span> off Zhejiang draws the faithful of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guanyin\">Guanyin</span>, while <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mount_Jiuhua\">Mount Jiuhua</span> in Anhui honors <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kshitigarbha\">Kṣitigarbha</span> through the Korean prince-monk <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kim_Gyo-gak\">Kim Gyo-gak</span></b>, who died there in 794 and whose successors left a tradition of mummified \"flesh-body\" monks. Millions still make the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pilgrimage\">pilgrimage</span> circuits each year, and the travel writer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xu_Xiake\">Xu Xiake</span> supplied the enduring verdict that one who returns from the Five Great Mountains looks at no others, while one returning from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huangshan\">Huangshan</span> looks not even at those.","citation":"","answerText":"Sacred Mountains of China"},{"id":"cng-070","num":"七十","category":"China · Geography","question":"A vast, arid region taking in Gansu, Xinjiang and the high deserts, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> lies west of the densely populated population line and formed the corridor of the ancient Silk Road.","answer":"Northwest China","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">西北 (Xīběi, 'northwest')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"西北","pinyin":"Xīběi","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Xīběi</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“northwest”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Northwest China</b> is the conventional region comprising <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shaanxi\">Shaanxi</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gansu\">Gansu</span>, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qinghai\">Qinghai</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ningxia\">Ningxia</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinjiang\">Xinjiang</span>, some 3.1 million square kilometers (1.2 million sq mi) or nearly a 3rd of the national territory, yet home to only about 104 million people in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2020_Chinese_census\"><b>2020</b> census</span>, the sparse western world beyond the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heihe–Tengchong_Line\">Heihe–Tengchong Line</span>. Its frame is built of closed basins and high walls, with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tarim_Basin\">Tarim</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Junggar_Basin\">Junggar</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qaidam_Basin\">Qaidam</span> depressions holding the sands of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taklamakan_Desert\">Taklamakan</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gurbantünggüt_Desert\">Gurbantünggüt</span></b> between the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tian_Shan\">Tian Shan</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kunlun_Mountains\">Kunlun</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Altai_Mountains\">Altai</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qilian_Mountains\">Qilian</span> ranges, under skies that grant most districts less than 200–400 millimeters (7.9–16 in) of rain. Settlement threads the oases, above all the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hexi_Corridor\">Hexi Corridor</span>, a thousand-kilometer passage between Qilian snowmelt and desert that funneled the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk_Road\">Silk Road</span> westward from the capital at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chang'an\">Chang'an</span>. Beneath the aridity lies wealth, from the oilfields <b>opened at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Karamay\">Karamay</span> in 1955</b> and the gas of the Tarim to Qaidam's lithium and potash brines, Xinjiang's fields growing about 90 percent of China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cotton\">cotton</span>, roughly a 5th of the world crop, and the desert mega-bases that have made the region the vanguard of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wind_power_in_China\">wind</span> and solar power. The caravan corridor has been reborn in steel, as China–Europe freight rolls along the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eurasian_Land_Bridge\">Eurasian Land Bridge</span>, the 1,776-kilometer (1,104 mi) <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lanzhou–Xinjiang_high-speed_railway\">Lanzhou–Xinjiang high-speed railway</span> <b>opened in 2014</b> from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lanzhou\">Lanzhou</span> to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ürümqi\">Ürümqi</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Belt_and_Road_Initiative\">Belt and Road Initiative</span>, unveiled in 2013 in the very language of a new Silk Road. <br> <br> The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span> stitched the region to China after the cavalry campaigns of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huo_Qubing\">Huo Qubing</span> in 121 BCE, planting the 4 garrison commanderies of the corridor and guarding the caravan exit at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yumen_Pass\">Yumen Pass</span>. At the corridor's far end, the oasis of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dunhuang\">Dunhuang</span> accumulated the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mogao_Caves\">Mogao Caves</span>, 735 grottoes painted from 366 onward, whose walled-up Library Cave, opened in 1900 with some 50,000 manuscripts, was dispersed to the world by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Aurel_Stein\">Aurel Stein</span> and his rivals. The Ming pulled the frontier back to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiayu_Pass\">Jiayu Pass</span> fortress of 1372, the western terminus of the Great Wall, while the region became the heartland of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hui_people\">Hui</span> and of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Islam_in_China\">Islam in China</span>, scarred by the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dungan_Revolt_(1862–1877)\">Dungan Revolt</span></b> of 1862–1877 that cost millions of lives before Ningxia gained its Hui autonomous region in 1958. Xinjiang, made a province in 1884 and an autonomous region for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Uyghurs\">Uyghurs</span> in 1955, has dominated recent attention, as deadly riots in Ürümqi in 2009 gave way after 2017 to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinjiang_internment_camps\">Xinjiang internment camps</span>, where researchers estimated around a million detainees and a 2022 UN report found possible crimes against humanity, charges Beijing rejects as counter-extremism policy. The northwest is finally the nation's water tower, for the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sanjiangyuan\">Sanjiangyuan</span></b> headwaters of the Yangtze, Yellow, and Mekong rise on its Qinghai plateau, so that the old corridor of camels now serves at once as energy bank, ecological reserve, and the land bridge of a continent.","citation":"","answerText":"Northwest China"},{"id":"cng-083","num":"八十三","category":"China · Geography","question":"Nicknamed the \"Spring City\" for its mild year-round climate, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> sits high on the southwestern plateau near Dian Lake and serves as a gateway to Southeast Asia.","answer":"Kunming","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">昆明 (Kūnmíng), after an ancient local people</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"昆明","pinyin":"Kūnmíng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Kūnmíng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Kunming</b> is the capital of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yunnan\">Yunnan</span> province and the metropolis of China’s southwest, a city of roughly 8.5 million people lying at about 1,890 metres (6,200 ft) on the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yunnan–Guizhou_Plateau\">Yunnan–Guizhou Plateau</span></b>, whose perpetually mild weather has earned it the nickname “Spring City.” It spreads along the northern shore of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dian_Lake\">Dian Lake</span>, at some 300 square kilometres (120 sq mi) the largest lake of the plateau, framed by the temple-studded Western Hills, though decades of urban effluent turned the water <b>infamously green with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Algal_bloom\">algal blooms</span></b> that tens of billions of yuan in cleanup have only partly tamed. The eternal spring sustains a vast <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Floriculture\">floriculture</span> industry whose Dounan market, the largest in Asia, trades billions of cut stems a year, and the city’s green credentials led it to host the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2021_United_Nations_Biodiversity_Conference\"><b>2021</b> United Nations Biodiversity Conference</span>, opening the process that produced the Kunming–Montreal framework on nature protection. Within day-trip distance rise the limestone pinnacles of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stone_Forest\">Stone Forest</span>, inscribed in 2007 as part of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South_China_Karst\">South China Karst</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Heritage_Site\">World Heritage Site</span>, while the city itself, seat of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yunnan_University\">Yunnan University</span></b>, mixes Han residents with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yi_people\">Yi</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hui_people\">Hui</span>, and other peoples of China’s most ethnically diverse province. Above all Kunming is the country’s gateway to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Southeast_Asia\">Southeast Asia</span>, the starting point of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China–Laos_railway\">China–Laos railway</span></b> opened in 2021 to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vientiane\">Vientiane</span> and the hub of the projected <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kunming–Singapore_railway\">Kunming–Singapore railway</span> network at the heart of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Belt_and_Road_Initiative\">Belt and Road Initiative</span>. <br> <br> The lakeshore was home to the bronze-working <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dian_Kingdom\">Dian Kingdom</span>, whose ruler submitted <b>to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span> in 109 BCE</b> and received from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Wu_of_Han\">Emperor Wu</span> a golden royal seal that archaeologists unearthed beside the lake in 1956. The city proper traces itself to a stronghold founded by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanzhao\">Nanzhao</span> kingdom in 765, and after the Mongols of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kublai_Khan\">Kublai Khan</span> conquered <b>the successor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dali_Kingdom\">Dali Kingdom</span> in 1253</b>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan</span> governor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sayyid_Ajall_Shams_al-Din_Omar\">Sayyid Ajall Shams al-Din</span>, a Central Asian Muslim praised for founding both mosques and Confucian schools, made the town the provincial capital that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marco_Polo\">Marco Polo</span> soon described. From a Muslim family of nearby Jinning on the lake came the great <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span> admiral <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zheng_He\">Zheng He</span>, while darker chapters followed when the turncoat general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Sangui\">Wu Sangui</span>, ruling from Kunming, had the last <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Southern_Ming\">Southern Ming</span> claimant, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yongli_Emperor\">Yongli Emperor</span>, strangled here in 1662, and an anti-Muslim massacre in the city in 1856 ignited the devastating <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Panthay_Rebellion\">Panthay Rebellion</span>. The French linked the city to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Haiphong\">Haiphong</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"French_Indochina\">French Indochina</span> by a mountain railway completed in 1910, the general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cai_E\">Cai E</span> launched the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Protection_War\">National Protection War</span> against <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_Shikai\">Yuan Shikai</span> from Kunming in 1915, and in the war against Japan the city became the terminus of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Burma_Road\">Burma Road</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Hump\">the Hump</span> airlift, the base of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Flying_Tigers\">Flying Tigers</span>, and the refuge of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Southwestern_Associated_University\">National Southwestern Associated University</span>, whose wartime students included the future Nobel laureate <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yang_Chen-Ning\">Yang Chen-Ning</span>. The city suffered the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2014_Kunming_attack\">2014 Kunming attack</span>, a mass stabbing at its railway station that killed 31 people, yet it continues to grow as the commercial, scientific, and tourist springboard of the entire southwest.","citation":"","answerText":"Kunming"},{"id":"cng-087","num":"八十七","category":"China · Geography","question":"Making up over 90% of the country's population and named after an early dynasty, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the largest in the world, sharing a common writing system across many spoken varieties and forming the majority almost everywhere except Tibet and Xinjiang.","answer":"Han Chinese","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">汉族 (Hànzú), named after the Han dynasty</span></div>","traditional":"漢族","hanzi":"汉族","pinyin":"Hànzú","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Hànzú</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Han Chinese</b> are the largest ethnic group in the world, numbering some 1.4 billion people, taking their name from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span> and constituting about 91 percent of the population of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> and nearly a fifth of all humanity. They also form overwhelming majorities in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span> and a dominant share in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Singapore\">Singapore</span>, anchor a worldwide <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Overseas_Chinese\">diaspora</span> of tens of millions, and predominate in every province-level division of China except <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibet_Autonomous_Region\">Tibet</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinjiang\">Xinjiang</span>. Linguistically they speak the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sinitic_languages\">Sinitic languages</span></b> — <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mandarin_Chinese\">Mandarin</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cantonese\">Cantonese</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Chinese\">Wu</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Min_Chinese\">Min</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hakka_Chinese\">Hakka</span>, and others — varieties often as different as separate languages, yet bound together by a shared <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Logogram\">logographic</span> <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Written_Chinese\">writing system</span></b>, historically by the literary medium of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Classical_Chinese\">Classical Chinese</span>, and today by the promotion of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Standard_Chinese\">Standard Mandarin</span>. Beneath the common name lies great regional diversity of subgroups and customs, though genetic studies reveal a broadly coherent population grading from north to south along the paths of ancient migrations. Common threads of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> ethics, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_ancestor_veneration\">ancestor veneration</span></b>, and festivals such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_New_Year\">Chinese New Year</span> sustain identity, expressed in self-descriptions as descendants of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yan_Emperor\">Yan</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_Emperor\">Yellow</span> emperors, as “descendants of the dragon,” or, among many southerners and emigrants whose <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinatown\">Chinatowns</span> are literally “Tang people’s streets,” as people of the Tang. <br> <br> The group’s ancestors were the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huaxia\">Huaxia</span> communities of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_River\">Yellow River</span> basin in the 2nd millennium BCE, organised under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shang_dynasty\">Shang</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_dynasty\">Zhou</span> dynasties, who defined themselves against “barbarian” neighbours, and the ethnonym crystallised under <b>the Han dynasty of 206 BCE</b> to 220 CE, which consolidated the unification begun by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_dynasty\">Qin</span>. Over the following 1,500 years successive waves of southward migration, fleeing steppe invasions and dynastic collapse, carried Han settlers across the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span> into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lingnan\">Lingnan</span>, absorbing the indigenous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Baiyue\">Baiyue</span> and other peoples and turning the south into the demographic heart of the Han world. The Han were themselves twice ruled by conquest dynasties, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongols\">Mongol</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_people\">Manchu</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span>, the latter compelling Han men to wear the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Queue_(hairstyle)\">queue</span>, and resentment of Manchu rule fed the Han nationalism that helped drive the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1911_Revolution\"><b>1911</b> Revolution</span>. The republic of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Yat-sen\">Sun Yat-sen</span> proclaimed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five_Races_Under_One_Union\">Five Races Under One Union</span>, and the People’s Republic counts the Han as one of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"List_of_ethnic_groups_in_China\">56 official ethnic groups</span> within the overarching concept of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhonghua_minzu\">Zhonghua minzu</span></b>, though policy has treated them distinctly, from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"One-child_policy\">one-child policy</span> applied most strictly to Han families to state-organised Han settlement of frontier regions through bodies like the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinjiang_Production_and_Construction_Corps\">Xinjiang Production and Construction Corps</span>. In recent decades a youthful <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hanfu\">Hanfu</span> revival and debates over <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_chauvinism\">Han chauvinism</span></b> have made Han identity itself a subject of public argument, even as the group’s vast population has begun to age and shrink.","citation":"","answerText":"Han Chinese"},{"id":"cnh-024","num":"二十四","category":"China · History","question":"Reigning for over 50 years and hugely expanding the empire into Central Asia, Korea and the south, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> established Confucianism as state orthodoxy, created a government salt-and-iron monopoly, and sent an envoy to seek allies against the Xiongnu.","answer":"Emperor Wu of Han","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">156–87 BCE</span></div>","traditional":"漢武帝","hanzi":"汉武帝","pinyin":"Hàn Wǔdì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Hàn Wǔdì</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Emperor Wu of Han</b> was the 7th emperor of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span>, a son of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Jing_of_Han\">Emperor Jing</span></b> whose reign of 141 to 87 BCE endured for some 54 years and ranked among the longest in Chinese imperial history. Early in that reign he adopted the counsel of the scholar <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dong_Zhongshu\">Dong Zhongshu</span> to suppress the rival doctrines of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hundred_Schools_of_Thought\">Hundred Schools of Thought</span> and elevate <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucianism</span> into the orthodox ideology of the state, a momentous reorientation reinforced by his establishment of the Imperial University, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taixue\">Taixue</span>, <b>in 124 BCE</b>. Ruling from the populous capital of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chang'an\">Chang'an</span>, he is conventionally credited as the earliest Chinese sovereign to adopt formal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_era_name\">era names</span>, inaugurating the practice with the Jianyuan era proclaimed in 140 BCE that would structure imperial chronology for the next 2,000 years. To finance his ambitions he overhauled state finance alongside the merchant-official <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sang_Hongyang\">Sang Hongyang</span>, nationalising the lucrative manufacture of salt and iron, standardising <b>the bronze <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Zhu\">wuzhu coin</span> in 118 BCE</b>, and imposing price-stabilising trade controls whose contested merits were later dissected in the celebrated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Discourses_on_Salt_and_Iron\"><i>Discourses on Salt and Iron</i></span>. This concentrated wealth funded a decisive abandonment of the defensive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heqin\">heqin</span> policy of marriage alliances by which earlier emperors had placated the frontier, as Emperor Wu instead committed the empire to decades of open warfare against the nomadic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiongnu\">Xiongnu</span> confederation to the north. <br> <br> His renowned generals <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wei_Qing\">Wei Qing</span> and the youthful <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huo_Qubing\">Huo Qubing</span> struck deep into the steppe during the protracted <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han–Xiongnu_War\">Han–Xiongnu War</span>, expelling the enemy from the strategic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hexi_Corridor\">Hexi Corridor</span> and securing the northwestern road toward <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Asia\">Central Asia</span>. In search of allies against the Xiongnu he had earlier sent the <b>envoy <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Qian\">Zhang Qian</span> westward in 138 BCE</b> to find the displaced <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuezhi\">Yuezhi</span>, and although that alliance never materialised, the resulting reconnaissance of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Western_Regions\">Western Regions</span> opened the trans-Eurasian trade arteries later known as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk_Road\">Silk Road</span>. A coveting of the prized <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ferghana_horse\">heavenly horses</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dayuan\">Dayuan</span> in the Ferghana Valley provoked the gruelling <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"War_of_the_Heavenly_Horses\">War of the Heavenly Horses</span></b> around 104 to 101 BCE, in which his general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Guangli\">Li Guangli</span> marched armies across thousands of kilometres of desert to wrest tribute and breeding stock from the remote kingdom. The emperor projected power in nearly every other direction as well, annexing the northern Korean realm of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gojoseon\">Gojoseon</span> in 108 BCE and planting the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Commanderies_of_Han\">Four Commanderies of Han</span></b> such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lelang_Commandery\">Lelang</span>, while to the south he conquered the kingdom of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanyue\">Nanyue</span> in 111 BCE and absorbed neighbouring <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Minyue\">Minyue</span>. His court patronised the grand historian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Qian\">Sima Qian</span>, author of the monumental <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Records_of_the_Grand_Historian\"><i>Records of the Grand Historian</i></span>, yet the reign darkened toward its close amid the crushing expense of war, the emperor's obsessive quest for an <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Elixir_of_life\">elixir of immortality</span>, and the bloody witchcraft purge of 91 BCE that consumed his heir apparent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Ju\">Liu Ju</span> before his death in 87 BCE delivered the throne to the child <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Zhao_of_Han\">Emperor Zhao</span></b>.","citation":"","answerText":"Emperor Wu of Han"},{"id":"cnh-025","num":"二十五","category":"China · History","question":"Dispatched westward by Emperor Wu to find allies and held captive by the Xiongnu for years, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> returned with the first detailed reports of the lands of Central Asia, helping to open the great trade routes to the west.","answer":"Zhang Qian","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">died 114 BCE</span></div>","traditional":"張騫","hanzi":"张骞","pinyin":"Zhāng Qiān","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhāng Qiān</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Zhang Qian</b> was an imperial envoy and explorer of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span>, born in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hanzhong\">Hanzhong</span>, whose journeys into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Asia\">Central Asia</span> earned him lasting fame as a pioneer of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk_Road\">Silk Road</span> and as one of the first Chinese to bring home reliable knowledge of the world beyond the empire's western marches. <b>Around 139 BCE</b> the expansionist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Wu_of_Han\">Emperor Wu</span> dispatched him westward to seek an alliance with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuezhi\">Yuezhi</span>, a people driven from their homeland by the formidable <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nomad\">nomadic</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiongnu\">Xiongnu</span> confederation—whose ruler was said to have made a drinking cup of the slain Yuezhi king's skull—that menaced the Han along its northern frontier. Almost immediately he was captured by the Xiongnu and held for some 10 years, during which he took a Xiongnu wife and fathered a son, yet he never relinquished the staff of authority that marked him as the emperor's envoy before at last escaping westward to resume his mission. Pressing on through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Western_Regions\">Western Regions</span>, he passed the kingdom of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dayuan\">Dayuan</span> in the Ferghana valley and the realm of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kangju\">Kangju</span> before reaching the Yuezhi, now settled prosperously in <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bactria\">Bactria</span></b> and no longer willing to wage a war of revenge against their old enemy, so that the embassy's original aim came to nothing. Captured once more on his homeward route, he escaped amid a Xiongnu succession crisis and at last returned to <b>the capital <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chang'an\">Chang'an</span> in 126 BCE</b> after roughly 13 years abroad, with only 2 of the 100 men who had originally set out returning home alive. <br> <br> His report furnished the Han court with its first detailed picture of these distant lands, describing the cities and customs of Central Asia, the prized <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ferghana_horse\">heavenly horses</span> of Ferghana, the great kingdom of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Parthian_Empire\">Parthia</span></b> to the west, and rumours of a wealthy land of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"India\">India</span> beyond, an account preserved by the historian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Qian\">Sima Qian</span> in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Records_of_the_Grand_Historian\"><i>Records of the Grand Historian</i></span>. After Han armies under the generals <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wei_Qing\">Wei Qing</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huo_Qubing\">Huo Qubing</span> had broken Xiongnu power in the north, he was sent <b>out once more around 119 BCE</b> at the head of a large mission to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wusun\">Wusun</span>, dispatching subordinate envoys still farther afield to Ferghana, Bactria, and Parthia to establish relations with the peoples he had earlier described. These embassies helped open the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hexi_Corridor\">Hexi Corridor</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Oasis\">oasis</span> routes skirting the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tarim_Basin\">Tarim Basin</span> through the frontier town of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dunhuang\">Dunhuang</span>, knitting together the caravan network of desert way-stations that later generations would call the Silk Road. Along these arteries Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk\">silk</span> flowed westward while horses, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Grape\">grapes</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Alfalfa\">alfalfa</span>, and other novelties travelled east, inaugurating a sustained exchange of goods, peoples, religions, and ideas across <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eurasia\">Eurasia</span> that would reshape both China and its neighbours for centuries. Ennobled as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marquis\">marquis</span> for his services, he died in 114 BCE not long after his final journey, remembered ever since as the intrepid <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Exploration\">explorer</span></b> whose <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Diplomacy\">diplomacy</span> first linked China to the wider world and opened the long age of contact between East and West.","citation":"","answerText":"Zhang Qian"},{"id":"cnc-046","num":"四十六","category":"China · Culture","question":"Covering some 2,000 years from the legendary Yellow Emperor to the Han, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> set the model — with its annals and biographies — for the official histories of later dynasties.","answer":"Records of the Grand Historian","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. 94 BCE</span></div>","traditional":"史記","hanzi":"史记","pinyin":"Shǐjì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Shǐjì</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Historical Records”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b><i>Records of the Grand Historian</i></b> is a monumental work of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_historiography\">Chinese historiography</span></b> compiled by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han</span> court scholar <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Qian\">Sima Qian</span>. The project had been begun by his father <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Tan\">Sima Tan</span></b>, who held the office of grand astrologer, and was carried to completion by Sima Qian around 94 BCE. Its narrative spans well over two millennia, opening with the reign of the legendary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_Emperor\">Yellow Emperor</span>, counted among the mythical <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Sovereigns_and_Five_Emperors\">Five Emperors</span></b>, and descending through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xia_dynasty\">Xia</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shang_dynasty\">Shang</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_dynasty\">Zhou</span> dynasties to the author's own age under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Wu_of_Han\">Emperor Wu of Han</span>. The completed text runs to 130 chapters and roughly 526,000 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_characters\">characters</span>, a colossal labour that drew on royal archives, earlier chronicles of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warring_States_period\">Warring States</span>, and the author's own extensive travels. Its most enduring innovation was a five-part organisation comprising 12 basic annals of rulers, 10 chronological tables, 8 topical treatises on matters such as ritual, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yayue\">music</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_calendar\">calendar</span>, 30 accounts of hereditary noble houses, and 70 ranked biographies of notable individuals. <br> <br> This annals-and-biography format became the template for nearly all subsequent official histories, the long series eventually known as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Twenty-Four_Histories\">Twenty-Four Histories</span>, beginning with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Book_of_Han\"><i>Book of Han</i></span> compiled by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ban_Gu\">Ban Gu</span>. The history was finished under extraordinary personal duress, for Sima Qian had defended the <b>defeated general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Ling_(Han_dynasty)\">Li Ling</span></b> after his surrender to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiongnu\">Xiongnu</span>, an act that brought upon him the punishment of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Castration\">castration</span>. Choosing this humiliation over death so that he might fulfil his father's charge, he set down his resolve in a celebrated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Letter_to_Ren_An\">letter to Ren An</span>, a document long admired as a meditation on duty and posterity. Beyond its sheer scope the work is prized as a masterpiece of prose, its vivid <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Biography\">biographies</span> of figures like</b> the first emperor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_Shi_Huang\">Qin Shi Huang</span>, the rebel <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiang_Yu\">Xiang Yu</span>, and the founder <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Gaozu_of_Han\">Emperor Gaozu</span> during the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chu–Han_Contention\">Chu–Han Contention</span></b> conveying sharp character through dramatic incident and reported speech. Sima Qian consciously measured himself against the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Spring_and_Autumn_Annals\"><i>Spring and Autumn Annals</i></span> attributed to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucius\">Confucius</span>, and his achievement has since been honoured as the foundational classic of historical writing in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>, made accessible to English readers above all through the translations of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Burton_Watson\">Burton Watson</span></b>.","citation":"","answerText":"Records of the Grand Historian"},{"id":"cnc-045","num":"四十五","category":"China · Culture","question":"Enduring the punishment of castration rather than abandon his life's work, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is honoured as the father of Chinese historiography for compiling a monumental history of the country up to his own emperor's reign.","answer":"Sima Qian","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. 145</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. 86 BCE</span></div>","traditional":"司馬遷","hanzi":"司马迁","pinyin":"Sīmǎ Qiān","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Sīmǎ Qiān</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Sima Qian</b> was a court astrologer, scribe, and historian of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span> under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Wu_of_Han\">Emperor Wu</span>, honoured as the father of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_historiography\">Chinese historiography</span></b> for compiling the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Records_of_the_Grand_Historian\"><i>Records of the Grand Historian</i></span>. Born at Xiayang, modern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hancheng\">Hancheng</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shaanxi\">Shaanxi</span>, he was the son of the <b>Grand Historian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Tan\">Sima Tan</span></b>, and at 20 he toured the empire, tracing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span>, mourning the poet <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qu_Yuan\">Qu Yuan</span> at the river where he drowned, and visiting the home of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucius\">Confucius</span> at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qufu\">Qufu</span>. When his dying father, excluded from <b>the great <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Feng_Shan\">Feng and Shan sacrifices</span> of 110 BCE</b> on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mount_Tai\">Mount Tai</span>, charged him to complete a universal history worthy of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Spring_and_Autumn_Annals\"><i>Spring and Autumn Annals</i></span>, Sima Qian inherited the office in 108 BCE and in 104 BCE helped reform the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_calendar\">calendar</span>. Disaster struck in 99 BCE, when he alone <b>defended the general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Ling_(general)\">Li Ling</span></b>, whose 5,000 infantry had surrendered to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiongnu\">Xiongnu</span> only after their arrows ran out, and the enraged emperor condemned the historian, who, unable to pay the commutation fine, chose <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Castration\">castration</span> in 98 BCE over honourable suicide so that his book might live. In the celebrated <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Letter_to_Ren_An\">Letter to Ren An</span></b> he explained that a death can weigh more than Mount Tai or less than a feather, and he endured life as a palace <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eunuch\">eunuch</span> secretary to finish the work around 91 BCE. <br> <br> The completed history runs to 130 chapters and roughly 526,500 characters, narrating more than 2,000 years from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_Emperor\">Yellow Emperor</span> to his own sovereign's reign. Its 5-part architecture—12 basic annals, 10 chronological tables, 8 treatises on matters from rites to the economy, 30 hereditary houses, and 70 ranked biographies—created the annals-biography form imitated by every one of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Twenty-Four_Histories\">Twenty-Four Histories</span> of imperial China. His judgments could be daring, granting the failed rebel <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiang_Yu\">Xiang Yu</span> a basic annal alongside emperors, scrutinizing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_Shi_Huang\">Qin Shi Huang</span>, and devoting biographies to assassins, merchants, jesters, and the Xiongnu themselves, while his treatise on the heavens preserved early <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_astronomy\">Chinese astronomy</span></b>. A copy guarded by his daughter was published a generation later under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Xuan_of_Han\">Emperor Xuan</span>, and the model was institutionalized when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ban_Gu\">Ban Gu</span> shaped the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Book_of_Han\"><i>Book of Han</i></span> upon it. Later ages enshrined him in a temple above the Yellow River, the writer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lu_Xun\">Lu Xun</span> hailed the work as the historians' crowning song, a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Sao\"><i>Li Sao</i></span> without rhyme, and through translations such as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Burton_Watson\">Burton Watson</span></b>'s the castrated scribe's vow to comprehend the changes of past and present still speaks across 21 centuries.","citation":"","answerText":"Sima Qian"},{"id":"cnh-028","num":"二十八","category":"China · History","question":"A reform-minded official who seized the throne in _ CE and founded a brief dynasty between the 2 halves of the Han, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> tried radical measures such as nationalising land and freeing slaves, only to be overwhelmed by floods, famine and the Red Eyebrows rebellion.","answer":"Wang Mang","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">45 BCE</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">23 CE</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"王莽","pinyin":"Wáng Mǎng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Wáng Mǎng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Wang Mang</b> was a Han official and consort-kin politician who usurped the throne in 9 CE to found the short-lived <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xin_dynasty\">Xin dynasty</span></b>, the brief interregnum that separated the Western and Eastern phases of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span>. He owed his ascent to the powerful Wang consort clan and above all to his aunt <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Zhengjun\">Wang Zhengjun</span>, the long-lived grand empress dowager and consort of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Yuan_of_Han\">Emperor Yuan</span></b>, whose family had dominated the court since the reign of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Cheng_of_Han\">Emperor Cheng</span>. Cultivating a carefully managed reputation for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> humility and frugality, he was appointed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Regent\">regent</span> for the boy-king <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Ping_of_Han\">Emperor Ping</span></b> and then for the infant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ruzi_Ying\">Ruzi Ying</span>, before discarding the fiction of stewardship and proclaiming himself emperor of a new dynasty he named Xin, signifying renewal. Drawing inspiration from the idealised institutions of the ancient <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_dynasty\">Zhou dynasty</span> and the classical <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rites_of_Zhou\"><i>Rites of Zhou</i></span>, he launched a sweeping programme of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Land_reform\">land reform</span> in 9 CE that nationalised great estates as \"king's fields,\" sought to revive the egalitarian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Well-field_system\">well-field system</span>, and forbade the private sale of land and of human beings under fresh curbs on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Slavery_in_China\">slavery</span>. His monetary policy proved especially destabilising, as repeated reissues of debased coinage and the revival of archaic <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Knife_money\">knife money</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Spade_money\">spade money</span>—at one point comprising some 28 separate denominations—threw commerce into chaos, while new state monopolies and a thicket of renamed offices and territories alienated officials and commoners alike across his capital at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chang'an\">Chang'an</span>. <br> <br> Abroad his insistence on archaic protocol soured relations with neighbouring peoples, for he humiliatingly downgraded the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiongnu\">Xiongnu</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chanyu\">chanyu</span> and demoted the rulers of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Goguryeo\">Goguryeo</span>, provoking border wars that further drained an already strained treasury. Calamity deepened when the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_River\">Yellow River</span> burst its dykes and shifted its course around 11 CE, unleashing devastating floods and famine across the densely settled <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"North_China_Plain\">North China Plain</span> that uprooted and impoverished millions of peasants. From this misery erupted vast popular uprisings, most famously the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Red_Eyebrows\">Red Eyebrows</span></b>, who rose in the east from around 18 CE under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fan_Chong\">Fan Chong</span> and painted their foreheads crimson to mark themselves in battle, alongside the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lulin\">Lulin</span> rebels of the south who threw their weight behind a restoration of the Han. The Lulin elevated the Han scion <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gengshi_Emperor\">Liu Xuan</span> to the throne in 23 CE, and after an immense Xin army—numbered by traditional sources in the hundreds of thousands—was annihilated at the decisive <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Kunyang\">Battle of Kunyang</span></b> by the future <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Guangwu_of_Han\">Emperor Guangwu</span>, rebel troops stormed Chang'an and slew the usurper that same year within his <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Weiyang_Palace\">Weiyang Palace</span>. Condemned for nearly 2,000 years as the archetypal <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Usurper\">usurper</span></b> in the hostile biography preserved in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ban_Gu\">Ban Gu</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Book_of_Han\"><i>Book of Han</i></span>, Wang Mang has nonetheless been reassessed by some modern scholars such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Shih\">Hu Shih</span> as a visionary if disastrously impractical reformer, whose abrupt fall in 23 CE cleared the way for the Han revival under the Eastern dynasty at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luoyang\">Luoyang</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Wang Mang"},{"id":"cnc-051","num":"五十一","category":"China · Culture","question":"A court eunuch of the Han dynasty traditionally credited around <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> CE with perfecting and standardising paper from bark, hemp and rags, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> spread a cheap writing material across the world.","answer":"Cai Lun","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. 62 – 121 CE</span></div>","traditional":"蔡倫","hanzi":"蔡伦","pinyin":"Cài Lún","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Cài Lún</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Cai Lun</b>, courtesy name Jingzhong, was a court <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eunuch\">eunuch</span> of the Eastern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span> traditionally <b>credited in 105 CE</b> with perfecting and standardizing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Papermaking\">papermaking</span>, the innovation that gave the world its first cheap writing material. Born at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Leiyang\">Leiyang</span> in modern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hunan\">Hunan</span>, he entered palace service about 75 CE, rose under <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_He_of_Han\">Emperor He</span></b> to head the imperial workshops, and won repute for improving weapons and instruments before turning to writing materials. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Book_of_the_Later_Han\"><i>Book of the Later Han</i></span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fan_Ye_(historian)\">Fan Ye</span> records that, since <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk\">silk</span> was costly and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bamboo_and_wooden_slips\">bamboo slips</span> heavy, Cai pulped tree bark—especially the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Broussonetia_papyrifera\">paper mulberry</span></b>—together with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hemp\">hemp</span> waste, rags, and old fishing nets, presenting the resulting sheets to the throne in 105 CE to imperial acclaim. Archaeology shows he was a perfecter rather than sole inventor, for crude hemp sheets predate him by centuries, including a paper map from a tomb <b>at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fangmatan\">Fangmatan</span> of roughly 179–141 BCE</b>, yet his standardized process spread so fast that good paper was simply called \"Marquis Cai's paper.\" Ennobled as a marquis in 114, he was destroyed by palace politics, and in 121, summoned to answer for his long-ago role in the persecution of the grandmother of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_An_of_Han\">Emperor An</span>, he bathed, dressed in his finest robes, and drank poison. <br> <br> His material conquered Asia within centuries, reaching Korea and Vietnam in late antiquity and, tradition holds, carried to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japan\">Japan</span> in 610 by the Korean monk <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Damjing\">Damjing</span>. Islam met the craft at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Talas\">Battle of Talas</span> in 751, after which captive Chinese papermakers reputedly set up shop in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Samarkand\">Samarkand</span>, and a mill opened at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Baghdad\">Baghdad</span> in 793 to feed the bureaucratic and bookish <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Abbasid_Caliphate\">Abbasid Caliphate</span></b>. Europe received the art through Muslim Spain, with the famous mill at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xàtiva\">Xàtiva</span> recorded in the 11th century, and through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fabriano\">Fabriano</span> in Italy from the 13th, where cheap rag paper displaced <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Parchment\">parchment</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Papyrus\">papyrus</span> and made the 1450s revolution of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Johannes_Gutenberg\">Gutenberg</span>'s <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Printing_press\">printing press</span></b> economically possible. Paper accordingly heads the canonical <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Great_Inventions\">4 Great Inventions</span> of China, and when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Michael_H._Hart\">Michael H. Hart</span> <b>compiled his 1978</b> ranking <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_100:_A_Ranking_of_the_Most_Influential_Persons_in_History\"><i>The 100</i></span>, he placed Cai Lun 7th among the most influential people who ever lived. Papermakers long worshipped him as their patron, pilgrims still visit his tomb at Leiyang, and his homeland, now turning out well over 100 million tonnes (110 million tons) of paper and board a year, remains the largest producer on earth.","citation":"","answerText":"Cai Lun"},{"id":"cnh-030","num":"三十","category":"China · History","question":"A brilliant, ruthless warlord and poet who seized control of the Han court and the northern plains, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was checked at the Red Cliffs, and is portrayed as the cunning villain of the <i>Romance of the Three Kingdoms</i>.","answer":"Cao Cao","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">155–220 CE</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"曹操","pinyin":"Cáo Cāo","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Cáo Cāo</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Cao Cao</b> was a warlord, statesman and poet who rose amid the disintegration of the Eastern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span> to dominate northern China and lay the foundations of the state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cao_Wei\">Cao Wei</span>, one of the rival powers of the ensuing <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Kingdoms\">Three Kingdoms</span></b> period. Born in 155 CE to a family of middling rank—his father, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cao_Song\">Cao Song</span>, was the adopted son of the influential palace <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eunuch\">eunuch</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cao_Teng\">Cao Teng</span>—he first won distinction helping to suppress the millenarian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_Turban_Rebellion\">Yellow Turban Rebellion</span> that <b>erupted in 184 CE</b> and shattered the authority of the imperial centre. Amid the warlord anarchy that followed, he joined the coalition against the tyrant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dong_Zhuo\">Dong Zhuo</span> and steadily enlarged his own power base before executing his masterstroke in 196 CE, when he took the fugitive boy-sovereign <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Xian_of_Han\">Emperor Xian</span> under his protection and removed the court to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xuchang\">Xuchang</span>, thereafter wielding imperial legitimacy to overawe rival lords. His decisive victory over the far larger forces of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_Shao\">Yuan Shao</span> <b>at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Guandu\">Battle of Guandu</span> in 200 CE left</b> him master of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"North_China_Plain\">North China Plain</span>, a supremacy he cemented by destroying the remnants of Yuan's house and subduing the northern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuhuan\">Wuhuan</span> tribes by 207 CE. His ambition to reunify the entire empire foundered in the winter of 208 CE at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Red_Cliffs\">Battle of Red Cliffs</span>, where the allied armies of the southern warlords <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Quan\">Sun Quan</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Bei\">Liu Bei</span>, directed by the strategists <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Yu\">Zhou Yu</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuge_Liang\">Zhuge Liang</span>, burned his fleet on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span> and sealed the lasting tripartite division of the realm. <br> <br> Although he amassed almost total <b>authority—appointed imperial <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chancellor_(China)\">chancellor</span> in 208 CE</b>, ennobled as Duke of Wei in 213 CE, and raised to King of Wei in 216 CE with his court centred on the northern city of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yecheng\">Ye</span>—he never deposed the powerless emperor nor seized the throne in his own name. As an administrator he showed himself a formidable reformer, resettling displaced refugees and feeding his armies through the state-managed military farms of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tuntian\">tuntian</span></b> system, and issuing edicts that selected officials for ability and talent in defiance of conventional demands for moral reputation and pedigree. Cao Cao was moreover an accomplished poet who, together with his sons <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cao_Pi\">Cao Pi</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cao_Zhi\">Cao Zhi</span>, stood at the forefront of the influential <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jian'an_poetry\">Jian'an poetry</span></b> movement, his surviving work—among it the celebrated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Short_Song_Style\"><i>Short Song Style</i></span>—prized for its austere force and brooding reflections on mortality and ambition. His death in 220 CE cleared the way for Cao Pi to force the abdication of the last Han ruler and proclaim himself emperor of Wei, a regime that posthumously honoured its founder as Emperor Wu, even as the rival kingdoms of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shu_Han\">Shu Han</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eastern_Wu\">Eastern Wu</span> completed the tripartite settlement. Judged by the historian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Shou\">Chen Shou</span> in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Records_of_the_Three_Kingdoms\"><i>Records of the Three Kingdoms</i></span> to be a man of exceptional ability, Cao Cao was recast a millennium afterward by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luo_Guanzhong\">Luo Guanzhong</span> in the 14th-century novel <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Romance_of_the_Three_Kingdoms\"><i>Romance of the Three Kingdoms</i></span> as the archetypal cunning and treacherous villain, an ambivalent legacy distilled in the apocryphal boast that he would sooner wrong the world than let the world wrong him.","citation":"","answerText":"Cao Cao"},{"id":"cnh-031","num":"三十一","category":"China · History","question":"Renowned as the supremely wise chancellor and strategist of the kingdom of Shu, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> became the very symbol of cunning and loyalty in Chinese culture, his exploits embellished in the <i>classic novel</i>.","answer":"Zhuge Liang","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">181–234 CE</span></div>","traditional":"諸葛亮","hanzi":"诸葛亮","pinyin":"Zhūgě Liàng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhūgě Liàng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Zhuge Liang</b> was the chancellor and military strategist of the kingdom of Shu during the era of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Kingdoms\">Three Kingdoms</span></b>, and he has endured ever since as the supreme emblem of wisdom, ingenuity, and unswerving loyalty in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_culture\">Chinese culture</span>. Born in what is now <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shandong\">Shandong</span> during the twilight of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span>, he was orphaned young and grew up to live as a reclusive scholar-farmer at Longzhong near <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiangyang\">Xiangyang</span>, where his evident brilliance earned him the sobriquet <b>\"Crouching Dragon.\" Around 207 CE</b> the warlord Liu Bei sought him out in the famous episode of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Visits_to_the_Thatched_Cottage\">Three Visits to the Thatched Cottage</span>, and Zhuge Liang responded with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Longzhong_Plan\">Longzhong Plan</span>, a grand strategy to seize <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jing_Province\">Jing</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yi_Province\">Yi</span> provinces, ally with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Quan\">Sun Quan</span> against the dominant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cao_Cao\">Cao Cao</span>, and ultimately restore the imperial house. He helped cement the alliance that destroyed Cao Cao <b>at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Red_Cliffs\">Battle of Red Cliffs</span> in 208 CE</b>, after which Liu Bei occupied the rich basin of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan\">Sichuan</span> and the foundations of a separate southwestern state were laid. When Liu Bei established Shu Han in 221 CE, Zhuge Liang became its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chancellor_(China)\">chancellor</span>, and upon Liu Bei's <b>death at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Baidicheng\">Baidicheng</span> in 223 CE</b> he was entrusted with the realm as regent for the youthful and ineffectual <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Shan\">Liu Shan</span>, governing in all but name.<br> <br>As regent he first secured the home front in his <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuge_Liang's_Southern_Campaign\">southern campaign</span> of 225 CE, subduing the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanman\">frontier peoples</span></b> and, in a celebrated tale of magnanimity, capturing and releasing their chieftain <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Meng_Huo\">Meng Huo</span> seven times until he gave his allegiance. He then devoted his final years to restoring Han rule, submitting to Liu Shan the celebrated memorial known as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chu_Shi_Biao\"><i>Chu Shi Biao</i></span> in 227 CE before launching five <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuge_Liang's_Northern_Expeditions\">Northern Expeditions</span> against the rival state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cao_Wei\">Wei</span> between 228 and 234 CE, ventures for which he is credited with devising the rapid-firing <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Repeating_crossbow\">repeating crossbow</span></b> and ingenious supply machines. His advances were repeatedly checked by the patient Wei commander <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Yi\">Sima Yi</span>, whose caution inspired the most famous of his legends, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empty_fort_strategy\">Empty Fort Strategy</span>, in which he supposedly bluffed a superior army into retreat by flinging open his undefended city's gates and calmly playing a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guqin\">zither</span>. Worn down by illness and the strain of command, Zhuge Liang died in 234 CE in the midst of his fifth expedition at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Wuzhang_Plains\">Battle of Wuzhang Plains</span>, leaving his protégé <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Wei\">Jiang Wei</span> to carry on the doomed struggle. Revered thereafter as the very paragon of loyalty and strategic genius, he was honoured at temples such as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuhou_Shrine\">Wuhou Shrine</span></b> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chengdu\">Chengdu</span>, recorded soberly in the 3rd-century <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Records_of_the_Three_Kingdoms\"><i>Records of the Three Kingdoms</i></span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Shou\">Chen Shou</span>, and transformed into a near-magical sage by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luo_Guanzhong\">Luo Guanzhong</span> in the 14th-century classic novel, while popular tradition even credits him with inventions ranging from the repeating crossbow to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sky_lantern\">sky lantern</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Zhuge Liang"},{"id":"cnh-029","num":"二十九","category":"China · History","question":"Erupting in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> CE and led by Taoist faith healers who promised a new age of peace, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> gave ambitious generals like Cao Cao the chance to seize power.","answer":"Yellow Turban Rebellion","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">184 CE</span></div>","traditional":"黃巾之亂","hanzi":"黄巾之乱","pinyin":"Huángjīn zhī Luàn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Huángjīn zhī Luàn</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Yellow Turban Rebellion</b> was a massive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peasant\">peasant</span> uprising that erupted across the <b>late <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han</span> empire in 184 CE</b>, taking its name from the yellow scarves its followers bound about their heads and ranking among the largest popular revolts in Chinese history. It was led by the faith healer <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Jiao\">Zhang Jiao</span></b>, founder of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Taoist</span> sect known as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Way_of_the_Supreme_Peace\">Way of the Supreme Peace</span>, who won a vast following through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Faith_healing\">faith healing</span> with charms and holy water at a time of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Famine\">famine</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Epidemic\">epidemic</span>, and grinding misgovernment that had left the countryside desperate and receptive to his promise of a coming age of Great Peace. Drawing on the scripture of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiping_Jing\"><i>Taiping Jing</i></span></b>, his <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Millenarianism\">millenarian</span> movement proclaimed that the azure heaven of the Han was dead and a new yellow heaven would arise, a doctrine rooted in the cycle of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuxing_(Chinese_philosophy)\">Five Phases</span>, by which the fire-red virtue of the reigning dynasty was destined to yield to an earth-yellow successor whose colour his adherents wore upon their heads. The sect was organized into 36 regional divisions embracing several hundred thousand believers across 8 provinces, and when a disciple's betrayal exposed the plot it rose prematurely in 184 CE, convulsing the provinces of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"North_China_Plain\">North China Plain</span> in a matter of weeks. The court of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Ling_of_Han\">Emperor Ling</span></b> mobilized generals such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huangfu_Song\">Huangfu Song</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lu_Zhi_(Han_dynasty)\">Lu Zhi</span> to meet the threat, and although Zhang Jiao soon died of illness and the main revolt was crushed within a year, scattered bands and fresh outbreaks smouldered on for nearly 20 more years. <br> <br> To contain the emergency, the throne devolved sweeping military and fiscal authority on regional governors and local strongmen, turning provincial inspectors into powerful territorial lords in a fateful decentralization that armed the very <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warlord\">warlords</span> who would soon carve up the empire. At the same time the dynasty was paralyzed by a venomous feud between the palace <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eunuch\">eunuchs</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ten_Attendants\">Ten Attendants</span> and the general-in-chief <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"He_Jin\">He Jin</span>, a struggle whose <b>bloody climax in 189 CE left</b> a power vacuum at the heart of the state and laid bare how the rebellion had hollowed out central authority. Into that vacuum stepped the brutal warlord <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dong_Zhuo\">Dong Zhuo</span>, who seized the capital <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luoyang\">Luoyang</span>, and ambitious commanders such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cao_Cao\">Cao Cao</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Bei\">Liu Bei</span> rose from the chaos, Cao Cao in particular <b>cementing his power around 192 CE</b> by absorbing some 300,000 surrendered Yellow Turban fighters of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_Province\">Qing Province</span> into his army. A kindred Daoist movement, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five_Pecks_of_Rice\">Five Pecks of Rice</span> led by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Lu_(Han_dynasty)\">Zhang Lu</span>, carved out an autonomous theocracy in the mountains of the southwest during these same years, underscoring how religious rebellion had become a recurring symptom of the dynasty's decay. The convulsions set in motion by the uprising culminated in 220 CE, when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cao_Pi\">Cao Pi</span> deposed the last emperor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Xian_of_Han\">Emperor Xian</span> and ushered in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Kingdoms\">Three Kingdoms</span></b>, an age chronicled in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Book_of_the_Later_Han\"><i>Book of the Later Han</i></span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Records_of_the_Three_Kingdoms\"><i>Records of the Three Kingdoms</i></span> and immortalized as the opening drama of the classic novel <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Romance_of_the_Three_Kingdoms\"><i>Romance of the Three Kingdoms</i></span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Yellow Turban Rebellion"},{"id":"cnh-032","num":"三十二","category":"China · History","question":"A decisive naval clash of <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> CE on the Yangtze, in which the allied southern forces used fire ships to destroy the much larger fleet of Cao Cao, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> thwarted his bid to conquer the south and helped set the stage for the division into three kingdoms.","answer":"Battle of Red Cliffs","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">208 CE</span></div>","traditional":"赤壁之戰","hanzi":"赤壁之战","pinyin":"Chìbì zhī zhàn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Chìbì zhī zhàn</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Battle of Red Cliffs</b> was a decisive <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Naval_warfare\">naval</span></b> battle fought in the <b>winter of 208 CE</b> along the middle <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span> during the final disintegration of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span>, and it ranks among the most consequential battles in Chinese history for the political order it ushered in. Having conquered the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"North_China_Plain\">north</span> and seized control of the puppet <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Xian_of_Han\">Emperor Xian</span>, <b>the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warlord\">warlord</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cao_Cao\">Cao Cao</span></b> drove southward in 208 to reunify the empire, absorbing a large fleet and many trained sailors when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jing_Province\">Jing Province</span> surrendered to him after the death of its governor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Biao\">Liu Biao</span>, so that he now commanded the river as well as the land. Against this advance the <b>southeastern warlord <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Quan\">Sun Quan</span></b> and the displaced <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Bei\">Liu Bei</span> forged an alliance—brokered by the strategist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuge_Liang\">Zhuge Liang</span> and the adviser <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lu_Su\">Lu Su</span>—and entrusted their combined armies to the brilliant commander <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Yu\">Zhou Yu</span>, who assured the hesitant Sun Quan that Cao Cao's exhausted and disease-ridden host could be broken despite its overwhelming numbers. Cao Cao's host was far larger—he boasted of 800,000 men, though the true figure was probably fewer than 240,000 against perhaps 50,000 allies—yet his northern soldiers, more at home with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cavalry\">cavalry</span> than with ships, were weakened by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Epidemic\">epidemic</span>, prompting him to chain his warships together bow to stern to steady them against the seasickness of his unseasoned troops. Exploiting this fatal arrangement, Zhou Yu's veteran officer <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huang_Gai\">Huang Gai</span></b> approached under a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Military_deception\">feigned surrender</span> with vessels packed with kindling and oil, and when a southeasterly wind rose he loosed these blazing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fire_ship\">fire ships</span> into the linked fleet, engulfing it in flames that leapt to the shore encampment. <br> <br> The result was a catastrophic defeat, as fire, disease, and panic shattered Cao Cao's armament and forced him to burn his remaining ships and retreat north, abandoning his ambition of conquering the south and leaving the field with only a fraction of the army he had brought. The victory secured the survival of the <b>regimes of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South_China\">southern China</span></b> and tilted the balance of power so decisively that it foreclosed any swift reunification, setting the stage for the empire's lasting division into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Kingdoms\">Three Kingdoms</span>, a tripartite balance that would endure for some 60 years. Over the following years <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cao_Pi\">Cao Pi</span> deposed the last Han emperor to found the northern <b>state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cao_Wei\">Cao Wei</span> in 220 CE</b>, while Liu Bei proclaimed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shu_Han\">Shu Han</span> in the southwestern basin of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yi_Province\">Yi Province</span> in 221 CE and Sun Quan declared <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eastern_Wu\">Eastern Wu</span> along the lower Yangtze a few years afterward. Remembered as one of the most celebrated engagements in Chinese history, the battle was fought at a riverside site near the modern city of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chibi,_Hubei\">Chibi</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hubei\">Hubei</span> whose precise location historians still dispute. It was set down by the historian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Shou\">Chen Shou</span> in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Records_of_the_Three_Kingdoms\"><i>Records of the Three Kingdoms</i></span>, later dramatized as a centerpiece of the novel <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Romance_of_the_Three_Kingdoms\"><i>Romance of the Three Kingdoms</i></span>, and immortalized in verse by the Song poet <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Su_Shi\">Su Shi</span> in his celebrated <i>Rhapsody on the Red Cliff</i>, where the long-vanished battle becomes a meditation on the impermanence of human glory.","citation":"","answerText":"Battle of Red Cliffs"},{"id":"cnh-033","num":"三十三","category":"China · History","question":"Following the final collapse of the Han, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> saw the land divided among the rival realms of Wei, Shu and Wu, an age of warfare and heroism later romanticised in one of the great classic novels.","answer":"Three Kingdoms","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">220–280 CE</span></div>","traditional":"三國","hanzi":"三国","pinyin":"Sānguó","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Sānguó</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Three Kingdoms</b> was the turbulent period, lasting <b>from roughly 220</b> to <b>280 CE</b>, during which the territory of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> fractured after the fall of the Han into three contending states—<b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cao_Wei\">Wei</span></b> in the north, Shu in the southwest, and Wu in the southeast—in an age of incessant warfare and martial heroism. The period was born from the disintegration of the Han state, hastened by the great <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_Turban_Rebellion\">Yellow Turban Rebellion</span> of 184 CE and the warlord struggles of the dynasty's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"End_of_the_Han_dynasty\">final decades</span>, in the course of which the formidable <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cao_Cao\">Cao Cao</span></b> seized control of the north while keeping the powerless <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Xian_of_Han\">Emperor Xian</span> as a puppet. In 208 CE the southern warlords <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Bei\">Liu Bei</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Quan\">Sun Quan</span>—the latter heir to a southeastern domain built by his late brother <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Ce\">Sun Ce</span>—joined forces to destroy Cao Cao's invading fleet and army at the decisive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Red_Cliffs\">Battle of Red Cliffs</span>, a defeat that wrecked his hopes of reunification and made a threefold partition all but certain. The division became formal in 220 CE, when Cao Cao's son <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cao_Pi\">Cao Pi</span> deposed Emperor Xian and enthroned himself over Wei from the old capital of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luoyang\">Luoyang</span>; Liu Bei <b>answered in 221 CE</b> by founding Shu Han in the fastness of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan\">Sichuan</span>, with its seat at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chengdu\">Chengdu</span>, and in 229 CE Sun Quan proclaimed himself emperor of Wu along the lower <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span>, ruling from Jianye, the modern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span>. Each realm became celebrated for its champions—Wei for Cao Cao and the <b>cunning general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Yi\">Sima Yi</span></b>; Shu for its sage chancellor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuge_Liang\">Zhuge Liang</span> and the sworn brothers <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guan_Yu\">Guan Yu</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Fei\">Zhang Fei</span>, bound to Liu Bei by the legendary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Oath_of_the_Peach_Garden\">Oath of the Peach Garden</span>; and Wu for Sun Quan and the strategist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Yu\">Zhou Yu</span>, victor at Red Cliffs.<br> <br>Much of the era's drama lay in the campaigns of Zhuge Liang, whose repeated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuge_Liang's_Northern_Expeditions\">Northern Expeditions</span> against Wei pitted him against Sima Yi until his death in the field at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Wuzhang_Plains\">Battle of Wuzhang Plains</span> in 234 CE. The balance finally broke when Wei overran Shu in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Conquest_of_Shu_by_Wei\">conquest</span> of 263 CE, after which Sima Yi's grandson <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Yan\">Sima Yan</span> usurped the Wei throne to found the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jin_dynasty_(266–420)\">Jin dynasty</span> in 266 CE and then conquered Wu in 280 CE, reuniting the empire and bringing the period to a close. The cost in human life was staggering, for the registered population, which the Han had once numbered at some 56 million, is recorded as having fallen to roughly 16 million by the time of reunification, a collapse driven by decades of war, famine, and mass displacement. The principal historical record of these events is the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Records_of_the_Three_Kingdoms\"><i>Records of the Three Kingdoms</i></span>, compiled in the 3rd century CE by the historian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Shou\">Chen Shou</span> and enriched roughly two centuries later by the copious annotations of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pei_Songzhi\">Pei Songzhi</span>. Yet the era owes its enduring fame above all to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Romance_of_the_Three_Kingdoms\"><i>Romance of the Three Kingdoms</i></span>, the sprawling 14th-century novel attributed to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luo_Guanzhong\">Luo Guanzhong</span> and counted <b>among China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Great_Classical_Novels\">Four Great Classical Novels</span></b>, a work so artfully blending record and invention that it has long been described as seven parts fact and three parts fiction.","citation":"","answerText":"Three Kingdoms"},{"id":"cnh-034","num":"三十四","category":"China · History","question":"Briefly reuniting the country in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> CE after the era of three kingdoms, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> soon fell into the ruinous War of the Eight Princes and lost the north to nomadic invaders, forcing the court to flee south of the Yangtze.","answer":"Jin dynasty","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">266–420 CE</span></div>","traditional":"晉朝","hanzi":"晋朝","pinyin":"Jìncháo","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Jìncháo</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Jin dynasty</b> was the imperial dynasty, founded by the Sima family, that supplanted the state of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cao_Wei\">Cao Wei</span></b> and briefly reunified China at the close of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Kingdoms\">Three Kingdoms</span> era before being driven into a southern rump state by nomadic invaders. Its founder, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Wu_of_Jin\">Sima Yan</span>, was the grandson of the formidable Wei regent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Yi\">Sima Yi</span> and the son of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Zhao\">Sima Zhao</span>, the <b>conqueror of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shu_Han\">Shu Han</span> in 263 CE</b>, and in 266 CE he compelled the last Wei ruler to abdicate and enthroned himself as Emperor Wu at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luoyang\">Luoyang</span>. Reunification was completed in 280 CE when Jin forces overran the southern kingdom of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eastern_Wu\">Eastern Wu</span>, yet a census taken that year recorded only some 16 million people across the realm, a stark gauge of the depopulation left by generations of warfare. Seeking to avoid the dynastic isolation that had doomed Wei, the founder granted his many kinsmen extensive fiefs and private armies, but after his death this very policy proved catastrophic, as his developmentally impaired successor, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Hui_of_Jin\">Emperor Hui</span>, became the helpless prize in a savage contest among the over-mighty Sima princes. That rivalry erupted into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"War_of_the_Eight_Princes\">War of the Eight Princes</span> <b>between 291 and 306 CE</b>, a sprawling civil war whose campaigns ravaged the heartland, exhausted the imperial armies, and fatally weakened the defences of the northern frontier. <br> <br> Into this vacuum surged the nomadic and semi-nomadic peoples later grouped as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five_Barbarians\">Five Barbarians</span>, among them the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiongnu\">Xiongnu</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jie_people\">Jie</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xianbei\">Xianbei</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Di_(Five_Barbarians)\">Di</span>, whose incursions inaugurated the fractured age of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sixteen_Kingdoms\">Sixteen Kingdoms</span> throughout the north. In the calamity remembered as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Disaster_of_Yongjia\">Disaster of Yongjia</span>, the Xiongnu-led state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han-Zhao\">Han-Zhao</span> sacked the capital and <b>captured <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Huai_of_Jin\">Emperor Huai</span> in 311 CE</b>, and after the fall of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chang'an\">Chang'an</span> and the seizure of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Min_of_Jin\">Emperor Min</span> in 316 CE the Western Jin collapsed altogether. A surviving prince, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Yuan_of_Jin\">Sima Rui</span>, re-established the dynasty in 317 CE south of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span> with its capital at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiankang\">Jiankang</span>, the modern Nanjing, founding the southern regime conventionally called the Eastern Jin. Authority in the southern court rested heavily on great émigré aristocratic clans—so dominant that <b>the chancellor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Dao\">Wang Dao</span></b> and his family were said to share the realm with the emperor himself—and the dynasty's very survival was secured in 383 CE at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Fei_River\">Battle of Fei River</span>, where a modest Jin army routed the vast host of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fu_Jiān\">Fu Jian</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Former_Qin\">Former Qin</span>, reportedly numbering several hundred thousand. For all its political fragility the era fostered a brilliant high culture—the abstruse metaphysics of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xuanxue\">Xuanxue</span>, the <b>leisured wit of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pure_conversation\">pure conversation</span></b>, and the peerless brushwork of the calligrapher <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Xizhi\">Wang Xizhi</span>—but in 420 CE the general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Wu_of_Liu_Song\">Liu Yu</span> deposed the final emperor and proclaimed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Song\">Liu Song</span>, opening the protracted age of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_and_Southern_dynasties\">Northern and Southern dynasties</span> later chronicled in the Tang-era <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Book_of_Jin\"><i>Book of Jin</i></span></b>.","citation":"","answerText":"Jin dynasty"},{"id":"cnh-035","num":"三十五","category":"China · History","question":"A chaotic era when northern China fractured into a shifting patchwork of mostly non-Chinese states founded by peoples such as the Xiongnu and Xianbei, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> followed the loss of the north by the Jin and lasted until the north was reunified by the Northern Wei.","answer":"Sixteen Kingdoms","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">304–439 CE</span></div>","traditional":"十六國","hanzi":"十六国","pinyin":"Shíliù Guó","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Shíliù Guó</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Sixteen Kingdoms</b> was the turbulent era <b>from 304</b> to <b>439 CE</b> during which northern China splintered into a shifting patchwork of mostly short-lived states, the majority founded by non-Han peoples collectively remembered as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five_Barbarians\">Five Barbarians</span></b>. The chaos followed the unraveling of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Western_Jin\">Western Jin</span>, which had briefly reunified China only a generation earlier but whose authority was then shattered by the ruinous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"War_of_the_Eight_Princes\">War of the Eight Princes</span>, a civil war among imperial kinsmen that bled the realm and left its frontiers defenceless. Seizing the moment, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiongnu\">Xiongnu</span> chieftain <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Yuan_(Han-Zhao)\">Liu Yuan</span></b> proclaimed the state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han-Zhao\">Han-Zhao</span> in 304 CE, and his successors sacked <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luoyang\">Luoyang</span> in 311 CE in the catastrophe known as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Disaster_of_Yongjia\">Disaster of Yongjia</span>, carrying off the Jin emperor, before taking <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chang'an\">Chang'an</span> in 316 CE and driving the surviving Jin court to flee south and re-establish itself as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eastern_Jin\">Eastern Jin</span></b> at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiankang\">Jiankang</span>, near modern Nanjing. The states arose chiefly among the frontier and steppe peoples—the Xiongnu, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xianbei\">Xianbei</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jie_people\">Jie</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Di_(Five_Barbarians)\">Di</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qiang_(historical_people)\">Qiang</span>—many of whom had already settled inside the empire as soldiers and tributaries before turning against it. Although a later chronicle fixed the conventional total at 16, in reality more than 20 regimes rose and fell, among them the Jie-ruled <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Later_Zhao\">Later Zhao</span></b> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shi_Le\">Shi Le</span>, the Xianbei <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Former_Yan\">Former Yan</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cheng-Han\">Cheng-Han</span> kingdom in the southwest, and a handful were actually founded by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Chinese\">Han Chinese</span> rather than by the steppe newcomers, few of these states outlasting a single generation. <br> <br> The nearest approach to reunification came when the Di-led <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Former_Qin\">Former Qin</span>, under the able ruler Fu Jian and his celebrated minister <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Meng_(Former_Qin)\">Wang Meng</span>, brought almost the whole of the north under a <b>single throne by about 376 CE</b>, leaving only the Eastern Jin to hold the south. His attempt to conquer the south as well ended in disaster at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Fei_River\">Battle of Fei River</span> in 383 CE, where a far smaller Eastern Jin army routed his enormous host, after which Former Qin swiftly disintegrated and the north shattered once more into rival kingdoms, undoing in a single campaign the unity it had taken him years to build. Beneath the incessant warfare and the great southward migration of Han families, the era also saw the steady <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sinicization\">sinicization</span> of its alien rulers and a remarkable flowering of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Buddhism\">Buddhism</span>, advanced by the translator <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kumarajiva\">Kumarajiva</span>, brought to Chang'an by the Qiang-led <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Later_Qin\">Later Qin</span>, and by the first carving of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mogao_Caves\">Mogao Caves</span> near Dunhuang in 366 CE. The long fragmentation was finally ended by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tuoba\">Tuoba</span> branch of the Xianbei, whose state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Wei\">Northern Wei</span>, founded in 386 CE and led under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Taiwu_of_Northern_Wei\">Emperor Taiwu</span>, conquered the last surviving northern kingdom and reunified the region in 439 CE. That reunification opened the era of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_and_Southern_dynasties\">Northern and Southern dynasties</span>, a further phase of the long age of disunion between the fall of the Han and the eventual reunification of China under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sui_dynasty\">Sui</span>, even as centuries of intermingling left a lasting imprint of steppe culture, Buddhism, and ethnic fusion upon the Chinese north.","citation":"","answerText":"Sixteen Kingdoms"},{"id":"cnh-036","num":"三十六","category":"China · History","question":"Founded by the Xianbei Tuoba clan and reuniting the north, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> sponsored magnificent Buddhist cave temples, pursued sweeping sinicisation reforms under Emperor Xiaowen, and introduced a land-distribution scheme later inherited by reunified China.","answer":"Northern Wei","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">&lt;b&gt;386&lt;/b&gt;–&lt;b&gt;534&lt;/b&gt;</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"北魏","pinyin":"Běi Wèi","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Běi Wèi</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Northern Wei</b> was a dynasty founded by the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xianbei\">Xianbei</span></b> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tuoba\">Tuoba</span> clan that grew into the most powerful and enduring of the regimes making up the northern half of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_and_Southern_dynasties\">Northern and Southern Dynasties</span> period of Chinese history. Established in 386 CE by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Daowu_of_Northern_Wei\">Tuoba Gui</span>, who took the throne as Emperor Daowu, the young state was first centred on its capital at <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pingcheng\">Pingcheng</span></b>, in present-day <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Datong\">Datong</span> in the province of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanxi\">Shanxi</span>. Under the militant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Taiwu_of_Northern_Wei\">Emperor Taiwu</span> its armies overran the patchwork of states left by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sixteen_Kingdoms\">Sixteen Kingdoms</span> and, by <b>destroying the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Liang\">Northern Liang</span> in 439 CE</b>, brought the whole of northern China under a single ruler for the first time in well over a century. Although Taiwu himself unleashed a violent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Disasters_of_Wu\">suppression of Buddhism</span> in 446 CE at the urging of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Daoist</span> master <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kou_Qianzhi\">Kou Qianzhi</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> statesman Cui Hao, his successors swiftly reversed the policy and made <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Buddhism\">Buddhism</span> a central pillar of imperial legitimacy. That devotion found its grandest expression at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yungang_Grottoes\">Yungang Grottoes</span> near Pingcheng, where the monk <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tan_Yao\">Tan Yao</span> oversaw the carving of colossal cliff-face sanctuaries from around 460 CE, a complex that still preserves roughly 252 caves and niches and more than 51,000 statues, the largest of them towering some 17 metres (56 ft) high. <br> <br> The dynasty's most consequential reign was that of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Xiaowen_of_Northern_Wei\">Emperor Xiaowen</span> (471–499 CE), who, first under the regency of his grandmother <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empress_Dowager_Feng\">Empress Dowager Feng</span></b> and afterwards in his own right, pressed an ambitious campaign of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sinicization\">sinicisation</span> designed to bind the Xianbei ruling caste to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Chinese\">Han Chinese</span> majority it governed. Among the most durable of these measures was the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Equal-field_system\">equal-field system</span>, promulgated in 485 CE to grant cultivable land to peasant households in return for grain taxes and corvée labour, a framework of state landholding that was later inherited and refined by the reunified <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sui_dynasty\">Sui</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span> dynasties. In 493 CE the emperor moved the capital south to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luoyang\">Luoyang</span>, where work soon began on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Longmen_Grottoes\">Longmen Grottoes</span>, and he decreed that Xianbei dress, speech, and surnames be abandoned at court in favour of Chinese ones, the imperial Tuoba house itself adopting the surname Yuan. The southward drift of wealth and prestige toward the Luoyang court, however, embittered the Xianbei troops still manning the northern frontier, whose mounting grievances erupted in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rebellion_of_the_Six_Garrisons\">Rebellion of the Six Garrisons</span></b> from 523 and plunged the dynasty into ruinous internal war. Amid the ensuing chaos the warlord <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Erzhu_Rong\">Erzhu Rong</span> seized Luoyang and slaughtered much of the aristocracy in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heyin_Massacre\">Heyin Massacre</span> of 528, after which the crippled empire fractured into the rival <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eastern_Wei\">Eastern Wei</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Western_Wei\">Western Wei</span>, successor regimes whose own heirs, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Qi\">Northern Qi</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Zhou\">Northern Zhou</span>, would prepare the ground for the reunification of China under the Sui.","citation":"","answerText":"Northern Wei"},{"id":"cnh-037","num":"三十七","category":"China · History","question":"An age of division lasting from the late 4th to the late 6th century, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> saw a succession of mostly non-Chinese regimes rule the north while Han Chinese courts held the south, a period that nonetheless saw the deep spread of Buddhism across the country.","answer":"Northern and Southern dynasties","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">420–589 CE</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"南北朝","pinyin":"Nánběicháo","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Nánběicháo</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Northern and Southern dynasties</b> was an age of political division that splintered <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> for more than a century and a half, during which a succession of mostly non-Han dynasties governed the north while Han Chinese courts held the south, following the collapse of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jin_dynasty_(266–420)\">Jin</span></b> and ending only with the reunification achieved by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sui_dynasty\">Sui</span>. The fragmentation followed the brief reunification under the Jin, whose authority dissolved amid the ruinous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"War_of_the_Eight_Princes\">War of the Eight Princes</span> and the risings of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five_Barbarians\">Five Barbarians</span>, until the sack of the capital <b>in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Disaster_of_Yongjia\">Disaster of Yongjia</span> of 311 CE drove</b> the imperial court south and left the north to splinter into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sixteen_Kingdoms\">Sixteen Kingdoms</span>. In the south, beginning with the founding <b>of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Song_dynasty\">Liu Song</span> in 420 CE</b>, a sequence of four short-lived Han Chinese dynasties—Liu Song, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Southern_Qi\">Southern Qi</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liang_dynasty\">Liang</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_dynasty\">Chen</span>—ruled from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiankang\">Jiankang</span> in a refined, aristocratic continuation of the so-called <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Six_Dynasties\">Six Dynasties</span>. In the north, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tuoba\">Tuoba</span> clan of the Xianbei, having built the powerful <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Wei\">Northern Wei</span></b>, reunified the entire region by 439 CE, an order briefly shaken by the violent anti-Buddhist persecution of 446 CE under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Taiwu_of_Northern_Wei\">Emperor Taiwu</span> before imperial favour toward the faith was restored. From this base the Northern Wei became a lavish patron of religion and a bold reformer, carving the colossal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yungang_Grottoes\">Yungang Grottoes</span> from the 460s CE, instituting the redistributive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Equal-field_system\">equal-field system</span> in 485 CE, and opening the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Longmen_Grottoes\">Longmen Grottoes</span>—which together with Yungang preserve well over 100,000 carved Buddhist images—around 493 CE, shortly before the reforming <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Xiaowen_of_Northern_Wei\">Emperor Xiaowen</span> moved the capital to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luoyang\">Luoyang</span> in 494 CE as part of a sweeping <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sinicization\">sinicization</span> that imposed Han surnames, dress, and speech.<br> <br>Throughout these centuries Buddhism struck ever deeper roots across the land, so that by the early 6th century the north reportedly held some 30,000 monasteries, the devout <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Wu_of_Liang\">Emperor Wu of Liang</span></b> lavished patronage on the faith in the south, and the legendary arrival of the monk <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bodhidharma\">Bodhidharma</span> gave rise to the meditative school of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chan_Buddhism\">Chan</span> and its enduring association with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shaolin_Monastery\">Shaolin Monastery</span>. The age was also one of profound cultural fusion, blending the martial traditions of the steppe peoples with Han civilization in the north, while the southern courts cultivated a brilliant literary culture—epitomized by the landscape poetry of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xie_Lingyun\">Xie Lingyun</span>—and a flourishing of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Daoism</span>, even as the economic centre of gravity shifted decisively toward the fertile <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span> south. Political stability nonetheless proved elusive in the north, where the Northern Wei eventually broke apart into the rival <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eastern_Wei\">Eastern Wei</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Western_Wei\">Western Wei</span>, soon supplanted by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Qi\">Northern Qi</span> and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Zhou\">Northern Zhou</span></b>, the latter of which absorbed its eastern neighbour in 577. The long division was finally ended when the Northern Zhou general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Wen_of_Sui\">Yang Jian</span> seized the throne to found the Sui in 581 and, <b>in 589</b>, conquered the southern Chen, reuniting the whole of China for the first time in centuries. Though politically chaotic, the era proved deeply formative, for the synthesis of nomadic and Chinese institutions that matured under its northern regimes, together with the spiritual and artistic ferment of Buddhism, supplied the very foundations on which the reunified <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span> would build one of the golden ages of Chinese civilization.","citation":"","answerText":"Northern and Southern dynasties"},{"id":"cnh-038","num":"三十八","category":"China · History","question":"First introduced under the Northern Wei and used by later dynasties, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> periodically allotted plots to peasant households and reclaimed them on death, aiming to ensure tax revenue and curb great estates while supporting the militia armies.","answer":"Equal-field system","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">均田制 (jūntián zhì, 'equal-field system')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"均田制","pinyin":"jūntián zhì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">jūntián zhì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>equal-field system</b> was a <b>scheme of state-directed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Land_tenure\">land tenure</span></b> first instituted by the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Wei\">Northern Wei</span> under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Xiaowen_of_Northern_Wei\">Emperor Xiaowen</span> in 485 CE</b> and inherited by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Qi\">Northern Qi</span> and later regimes down to the mid-<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span>, forming one of the central institutions of medieval Chinese statecraft. Asserting <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_ownership\">state ownership</span></b> over much of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Arable_land\">cultivable land</span> left vacant by generations of war, the government allotted standardized plots to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peasant\">peasant</span> households according to their members and periodically redistributed them, reviving the egalitarian ideal of the ancient <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Well-field_system\">well-field system</span> while harnessing it to the practical ends of revenue and control. Allotments fell into distinct classes: <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Grain\">grain</span></b>-growing fields granted for the holder's working life and reclaimed by the state upon his death or old age, and hereditary plots planted with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mulberry\">mulberry</span> for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sericulture\">silk</span> or with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hemp\">hemp</span> that a family could keep across the generations. Under the Tang, for example, an able-bodied adult male was entitled to 100 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mu_(unit)\">mu</span> of land, of which 80 mu reverted to the state at his death while 20 mu passed permanently to his heirs, with smaller grants extended to women, the aged, and in the Northern Wei even to a household's draught oxen. The design aimed to secure a broad base of tax-paying <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Smallholding\">smallholders</span>, to keep cultivators settled and entered in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huji_system\">household registers</span></b>, and to check the engrossment of land into the great estates of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Aristocracy\">aristocratic</span> clans, whose sprawling manors the throne regarded as a drain on its revenues and its manpower alike. <br> <br> Bound up with the allotments was a tripartite levy on each registered adult—a tax in grain, a tax in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Textile\">cloth</span>, and a term of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Corvée\">corvée</span> labour—through which the equal holdings translated directly into reliable <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taxation\">revenue</span></b> for the throne, rendered in kind from every plot. The same landed households also sustained the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fubing_system\">fubing</span> militia, a self-supporting soldiery <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Conscription\">conscripted</span> in rotation that farmed in peacetime and furnished its own equipment, sparing the dynasty the cost of a large <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Standing_army\">standing army</span>—an arrangement pioneered under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Western_Wei\">Western Wei</span> and carried on by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Zhou\">Northern Zhou</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sui_dynasty\">Sui</span>, and the Tang. The system could function only so long as the state held ample land to grant and maintained an accurate <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Census\">census</span></b>, conditions made possible by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Population_decline\">depopulation</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_and_Southern_dynasties\">Northern and Southern dynasties</span> but ever harder to sustain as peace returned, the population swelled, and powerful families quietly enlarged their holdings. Across the course of the Tang, rising numbers, the relentless accumulation of land by officials, aristocrats, and Buddhist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Monastery\">monasteries</span>, and the decay of registration steadily undermined the allotments, a collapse completed when the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"An_Lushan_Rebellion\">An Lushan Rebellion</span> wrecked both the census and the treasury. Around 780 the government formally abandoned the scheme in favour of a twice-yearly tax assessed on actual property, an acceptance of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Private_property\">private landownership</span> that, together with the dissolution of the militia into professional armies, closed an institution that had anchored the fiscal and military order of medieval China for nearly 300 years and shaped the agrarian foundations of the Sui-Tang empire.","citation":"","answerText":"Equal-field system"},{"id":"cnh-039","num":"三十九","category":"China · History","question":"Reunifying China in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> after centuries of division, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> launched the examination system and the Grand Canal, but exhausted the people with vast projects and disastrous wars in Korea, collapsing after only 2 reigns.","answer":"Sui dynasty","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">581–618 CE</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"隋朝","pinyin":"Suí cháo","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Suí cháo</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Sui dynasty</b> was the short-lived but pivotal dynasty that <b>reunified <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> in 589</b>, bringing to a close the long division of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_and_Southern_dynasties\">Northern and Southern dynasties</span></b> and laying the institutional foundations on which the succeeding <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span> would build its golden age. Its founder, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Wen_of_Sui\">Emperor Wen</span>—born Yang Jian, a powerful general of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Zhou\">Northern Zhou</span> and a scion of the mixed Chinese–Xianbei <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guanlong_Group\">Guanlong aristocracy</span></b>—seized the throne from his infant grandson in 581 and, eight years later, extinguished the southern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_dynasty\">Chen</span> to reunite the empire under a single ruler. He set about rebuilding centralized government, establishing the enduring framework of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Departments_and_Six_Ministries\">Three Departments and Six Ministries</span>, reviving the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Equal-field_system\">equal-field system</span> of landholding and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fubing_system\">fubing</span> militia, codifying a more lenient body of law, and inaugurating the merit-based examination system that, by recruiting <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Scholar-official\">scholar-officials</span>, would shape Chinese government for nearly 1,300 years. He laid out a magnificent new capital at Daxing, on the site of the future <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chang'an\">Chang'an</span>, reformed the currency around the standard <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuzhu\">Wuzhu</span> coin, and presided over the prosperous era remembered as the Government of Kaihuang, during which a population ravaged by centuries of war recovered to some 46 million and the state granaries overflowed. The throne then passed in 604 to his son <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Yang_of_Sui\">Emperor Yang</span></b>, who by tradition murdered his way to power, a ruler of boundless ambition whose grandiose projects would ultimately break the dynasty he had inherited.<br> <br>His most enduring achievement was the colossal Grand Canal, begun around 605, which harnessed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Corvée\">forced labour</span> of some 5 million conscripts to link the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_River\">Yellow River</span> with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span> and bind the rice-rich south, reaching as far as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hangzhou\">Hangzhou</span>, to the political north. He compounded these burdens by rebuilding <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luoyang\">Luoyang</span> as a sumptuous eastern capital, repairing long stretches of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Wall_of_China\">Great Wall</span>, raising immense state <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Granary\">granaries</span>, and touring his realm in extravagant flotillas, exactions that drove millions of peasants into ruinous toil. Most ruinous of all were his three massive invasions of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Goguryeo\">Goguryeo</span> on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Korean_Peninsula\">Korean Peninsula</span> between 612 and 614, the first of which mustered well over a million men yet ended in annihilation at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Salsu\">Battle of Salsu</span></b>, where the Goguryeo general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eulji_Mundeok\">Eulji Mundeok</span> destroyed a Sui army from which only a few thousand are said to have returned. Crushed by taxation, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Conscription\">conscription</span>, and military catastrophe, the empire dissolved into a sprawling <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Transition_from_Sui_to_Tang\">rebellion</span>, and Emperor Yang fled south to Jiangdu, the modern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangzhou\">Yangzhou</span>, where <b>in 618</b> he was strangled in a coup led by <b>his general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuwen_Huaji\">Yuwen Huaji</span></b>, even as the aristocrat <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Gaozu_of_Tang\">Li Yuan</span> seized the capital and proclaimed the Tang. Thus the dynasty endured a mere two reigns and some 37 years, yet its canal, its laws, and its institutions of governance passed almost intact to the Tang, in a turn of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dynastic_cycle\">dynastic cycle</span> that closely echoed how the short-lived <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_dynasty\">Qin</span> had once prepared the ground for the long and glorious <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Sui dynasty"},{"id":"cnh-040","num":"四十","category":"China · History","question":"Seizing power and then conquering the southern Chen to end nearly 300 years of disunion, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> built huge grain reserves, laying foundations the succeeding Tang would inherit.","answer":"Emperor Wen of Sui","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">541–604</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"隋文帝","pinyin":"Suí Wéndì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Suí Wéndì</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Emperor Wen of Sui</b>, personal name <b>Yang Jian</b>, was the founder and first ruler of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sui_dynasty\">Sui dynasty</span>, a member of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Chinese\">Han Chinese</span> Yang family that had risen within the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xianbei\">Xianbei</span>-dominated military aristocracy of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guanzhong\">Guanzhong</span> region under the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Zhou\">Northern Zhou</span></b>. Acting as regent for the child emperor who had inherited the Northern Zhou throne, Yang Jian, already ennobled as Duke of Sui, steadily concentrated both military and civil power in his own hands, and in 581 he induced the young ruler to abdicate, eliminated much of the deposed Yuwen ruling house, and proclaimed himself emperor of an entirely new dynasty. He adopted the era name <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_era_name\">Kaihuang</span>, which would lend its name to a reign later celebrated as a period of exceptional prosperity, and he was honoured after death with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Temple_name\">temple name</span> Gaozu and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Posthumous_name\">posthumous name</span></b> Wen, even as he ordered the building of a vast new capital, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Daxingcheng\">Daxingcheng</span>, on the site of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chang'an\">Chang'an</span> near present-day <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi'an\">Xi'an</span>. Laid out from 582 on a grand grid plan by the <b>master architect <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuwen_Kai\">Yuwen Kai</span></b>, this metropolis grew into one of the largest cities in the world and would be inherited largely intact by the succeeding <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span>. His crowning achievement came in 589, when his armies crossed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span> and overran the southern <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_dynasty\">Chen dynasty</span></b> at its capital <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiankang\">Jiankang</span>, the site of modern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span>, reunifying China for the first time since the fall of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Western_Jin\">Western Jin</span> and ending nearly 300 years of division spanning the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_and_Southern_dynasties\">Northern and Southern Dynasties</span>. <br> <br> In governing his reunified realm, the new emperor overhauled the imperial administration, institutionalising the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Departments_and_Six_Ministries\">Three Departments and Six Ministries</span></b> at the centre while pruning the bloated provincial apparatus into a leaner two-tier hierarchy of prefectures and counties that curbed the cost and autonomy of local officialdom. He curtailed the entrenched <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nine-rank_system\">nine-rank system</span> of aristocratic appointment in favour of recruiting officials on merit, an innovation that anticipated the later <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examination</span>, and he issued a humane legal code, forerunner of the celebrated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_Code\">Tang Code</span>, that slashed the number of capital offences and abolished many of the cruelest punishments. His fiscal administration revived the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Equal-field_system\">equal-field system</span> of land allotment and standardised the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Zhu\">five-zhu coinage</span></b>, while sweeping household registrations drew millions of concealed taxpayers onto the tax rolls and helped lift the empire's recorded population toward some 46 million people across nearly 9 million households at the dynasty's height. He amassed enormous state <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Granary\">grain reserves</span> in fortified granaries, stockpiles reportedly so vast that early Tang officials claimed they had not been exhausted decades after the dynasty fell, and, having himself been raised by a Buddhist nun, he became a fervent patron of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Buddhism\">Buddhism</span>, reviving the religion after its harsh suppression under <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Wu_of_Northern_Zhou\">Emperor Wu of Northern Zhou</span></b> while continuing to honour <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucianism</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Daoism</span>. Devoted to his formidable empress, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empress_Dugu_Qieluo\">Dugu Qieluo</span>, he died in 604 amid enduring suspicion that he was murdered by his son <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Yang_of_Sui\">Yang Guang</span>, whose ruinous campaigns against <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Goguryeo\">Goguryeo</span> and lavish public works would topple the dynasty within little more than a decade, yet the centralised institutions, codified laws, and economic foundations laid by Emperor Wen endured to sustain the long golden age of the Tang.","citation":"","answerText":"Emperor Wen of Sui"},{"id":"cnh-041","num":"四十一","category":"China · History","question":"Built on a colossal scale under the Sui by conscripting millions of labourers, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> — the longest in the world — linked the rice-rich Yangtze south with the northern capitals, becoming a vital artery for shipping grain and taxes for over 1,000 years.","answer":"Grand Canal","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">completed 609</span></div>","traditional":"大運河","hanzi":"大运河","pinyin":"Dà Yùnhé","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Dà Yùnhé</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Grand Canal</b> is the longest artificial waterway in the world, a vast <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Canal\">canal</span> system linking northern and southern China by joining the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hai_River\">Hai</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_River\">Yellow</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huai_River\">Huai</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qiantang_River\">Qiantang</span> river systems into a single navigable network that remains the longest and among the oldest canal systems ever built. Although stretches of canal had existed since antiquity—one section between the Huai and the Yangtze was <b>dug as early as 486 BCE</b> by the ancient state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_(state)\">Wu</span>—it was welded into a single system on a colossal scale under the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sui_dynasty\">Sui</span> emperor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Yang_of_Sui\">Emperor Yang</span></b> between 605 and 610, building on works lately begun by his father <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Wen_of_Sui\">Emperor Wen</span>. The works conscripted <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Corvée\">corvée</span> labour on a staggering scale, with more than a million men and women toiling on a single section and countless thousands perishing, a burden that, together with Emperor Yang's ruinous <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Goguryeo–Sui_War\">wars in Korea</span></b>, helped provoke the revolts that destroyed the short-lived dynasty within a decade of the canal's completion. Its purpose was to bind the prosperous, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rice\">rice</span>-growing south of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiangnan\">Jiangnan</span>—by now the empire's most productive region—to the political and military centres of the north, allowing the state to move <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Grain\">grain</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taxation\">taxes</span>, and troops in bulk between the northern and southern halves of the empire. In its Sui form the <b>canal ran for roughly 2,500 kilometres (1,600 mi)</b> through several great branches reaching from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luoyang\">Luoyang</span> toward both the Yangtze and the far north, channeling the agricultural surplus of the south to feed the capitals and their armies and knitting the empire's northern and southern economies together as never before. <br> <br> For more than 1,000 years the canal served as the economic lifeline of successive dynasties, indispensable to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song</span>, whose capital at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kaifeng\">Kaifeng</span> stood upon it precisely to receive the southern tribute grain that a vast state transport service shipped north each year. It also drove remarkable feats of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hydraulic_engineering\">hydraulic engineering</span>, including the world's first <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pound_lock\">pound lock</span>, built along its course in 984 to raise and lower vessels between stretches of differing water level and so greatly improve the flow of traffic. Under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kublai_Khan\">Kublai Khan</span> had the waterway re-routed in the 1290s to run directly to his new capital at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>—a final section engineered by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guo_Shoujing\">Guo Shoujing</span>—creating the nearly 1,800-kilometre (1,100 mi) line that still runs south through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangzhou\">Yangzhou</span> to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hangzhou\">Hangzhou</span> and abandoning the older Sui loop through the central plains. From the late imperial era the canal declined as silting, the diversion of tribute grain to faster <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> sea routes, a catastrophic shift in the course of the Yellow River, and the coming of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rail_transport\">railway</span> progressively reduced its importance until long northern stretches fell silent and dry. Even so, its southern reaches remain busy with traffic, parts have been absorbed into the modern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South–North_Water_Transfer_Project\">South–North Water Transfer Project</span>, and <b>in 2014</b> the whole was inscribed as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Heritage_Site\">World Heritage Site</span> in recognition of more than 2,000 years of continuous engineering and use.","citation":"","answerText":"Grand Canal"},{"id":"cnh-045","num":"四十五","category":"China · History","question":"Refined under the Sui and Tang and copied across East Asia, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> split the work of drafting, reviewing and carrying out policy among separate offices, with the executive arm overseeing ministries for personnel, revenue, rites, war, justice and public works.","answer":"Three Departments and Six Ministries","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">三省六部 ('three departments, six ministries')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"三省六部","pinyin":"sān shěng liù bù","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">sān shěng liù bù</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Three Departments and Six Ministries</b> was the principal structure of <b>central government in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Political_systems_of_Imperial_China\">imperial China</span></b>, an administrative framework that deliberately separated the drafting, review, and implementation of policy among distinct offices and was emulated, with local variations, throughout East Asia. At its apex stood the three departments—the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhongshu_Sheng\">Secretariat</span>, which composed imperial edicts, the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Menxia_Sheng\">Chancellery</span></b>, which scrutinized those edicts and could return or reject them, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Department_of_State_Affairs\">Department of State Affairs</span>, which carried approved policy into effect and supervised the executive ministries. Subordinate to the Department of State Affairs were the six ministries—those of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ministry_of_Personnel\">Personnel</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ministry_of_Revenue_(imperial_China)\">Revenue</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ministry_of_Rites\">Rites</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ministry_of_War_(imperial_China)\">War</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ministry_of_Justice_(imperial_China)\">Justice</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ministry_of_Works_(imperial_China)\">Works</span>—each of which was itself subdivided into four bureaus, yielding 24 specialized bureaus across the administration. These ministries respectively governed civil appointments and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Civil_service\">civil service</span>, the census and taxation, state ceremonies and the recruitment examinations, the armed forces, law and punishment, and public construction, while the heads of the Secretariat and the Department of State Affairs were <b>styled <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chancellor_of_China\">chancellors</span></b> and ranked second only to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_of_China\">emperor</span>. By distributing executive authority among separate organs rather than concentrating it in a single chief minister, the arrangement institutionalized a form of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Separation_of_powers\">separation of powers</span> within the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bureaucracy\">bureaucracy</span> and furnished the administrative skeleton for a state increasingly staffed through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examinations</span> by a class of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Scholar-official\">scholar-officials</span>.<br> <br>The system superseded the older <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Lords_and_Nine_Ministers\">Three Lords and Nine Ministers</span> arrangement of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Legalism_(Chinese_philosophy)\">Legalist</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_dynasty\">Qin dynasty</span> (<b>221–206 BCE</b>), under which a small group of senior officials had served the throne directly, though the constituent departments of the new structure first took embryonic shape during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span> (206 BCE–220 CE). The Secretariat as a distinct edict-drafting body was instituted under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cao_Wei\">Cao Wei</span> state (<b>220–265 CE</b>) by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cao_Pi\">Cao Pi</span>, while the reviewing role of the Chancellery emerged during the Jin and the subsequent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_and_Southern_dynasties\">Northern and Southern dynasties</span>, when it frequently became the most powerful organ of state. It was consolidated into its mature form by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Wen_of_Sui\">Emperor Wen of Sui</span>, who instituted the three-department structure in 581, the year he founded his dynasty, and it was further elaborated under the succeeding Tang dynasty (618–907), most notably during the reign of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Taizong_of_Tang\">Emperor Taizong</span>, when the coordinated cycle of drafting, review, and execution reached its classic articulation. From the Tang period onward the model was exported across East Asia as a template for centralized monarchy, being adopted by the Korean states of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Balhae\">Balhae</span> (698–926) and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Goryeo\">Goryeo</span> (918–1392), retained in modified form by the later <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joseon\">Joseon</span> dynasty, and imitated by successive dynasties in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"History_of_Vietnam\">Vietnam</span>. Within China itself the Secretariat and Chancellery were periodically fused into a single <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Secretariat-Chancellery\">Secretariat-Chancellery</span> from the late Tang through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song dynasty</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan</span> transferred control of the six ministries to the Central Secretariat, and after <b>the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Weiyong\">Hu Weiyong</span> affair of 1380</b> the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hongwu_Emperor\">Hongwu Emperor</span> abolished the departments and the chancellorship outright, leaving the six ministries to report directly to the throne and to endure through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> dynasties until the early 20th century.","citation":"","answerText":"Three Departments and Six Ministries"},{"id":"cnh-042","num":"四十二","category":"China · History","question":"A competitive system of written tests on the classics, formalised under the Sui and refined by later dynasties, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> selected officials by merit rather than birth, opening a path to power for talented men and producing the class of scholar-officials.","answer":"imperial examination","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">from c. 605 CE</span></div>","traditional":"科舉","hanzi":"科举","pinyin":"kējǔ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">kējǔ</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>imperial examination</b> was the competitive system of written tests, centred on the Confucian classics, through which imperial <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> recruited its <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Civil_service\">civil service</span></b> on the basis of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Meritocracy\">merit</span> rather than birth, serving as the principal pathway to office for some 1,300 years. Its roots lay in the recruitment practices of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span>, when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Wu_of_Han\">Emperor Wu</span> <b>founded the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taixue\">Imperial Academy</span> in 124 BCE</b> and officials were chosen largely by recommendation, a practice later overshadowed by the aristocratic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nine-rank_system\">nine-rank</span> regime that reserved high office for great families. The examination proper was formalized <b>under the Sui around 605</b>, when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Yang_of_Sui\">Emperor Yang</span> established the prestigious <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jinshi_(imperial_examination)\">jinshi</span></b> degree as a route into government, breaking decisively with hereditary privilege. It was elaborated under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang dynasty</span>, which developed distinct examination categories, while the empress <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Zetian\">Wu Zetian</span> broadened access, personally sponsored candidates, and is credited with instituting both the military examination and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Palace_examination\">palace examination</span></b>. Under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song dynasty</span> the system reached maturity and became the overwhelming route into the imperial <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bureaucracy\">bureaucracy</span>, as the court multiplied the number of degrees conferred, guarded against fraud by concealing candidates' names and recopying their papers, and harnessed the spread of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Woodblock_printing\">woodblock printing</span> to disseminate the texts on which the tests were based.<br> <br>The curriculum rested on the Confucian classics, reshaped from the Song onward by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Neo-Confucianism\">Neo-Confucian</span> orthodoxy of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_Xi\">Zhu Xi</span> and codified in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Books_and_Five_Classics\">Four Books and Five Classics</span>, until under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> dynasties the rigidly formulaic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight-legged_essay\">eight-legged essay</span> came to dominate the tests. By the late imperial era the examinations formed a daunting ladder of ascending degrees, rising from the local licentiate, or <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiucai\">xiucai</span>, through the provincial <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Juren\">juren</span> to the metropolitan and palace examinations that conferred the coveted jinshi, the very first of whom was honoured as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuangyuan\">zhuangyuan</span>, or principal graduate. The ordeal was extraordinarily severe, with candidates sealed for days at a time into row upon row of tiny brick cells—the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiangnan_Examination_Hall\">Jiangnan Examination Hall</span></b> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span> alone held more than 20,000 of them—and success rates at the higher levels often amounted to less than 1 percent, so that many men sat the tests repeatedly into old age. In principle the system offered <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Social_mobility\">social mobility</span> to talented men of humble birth and, in producing the scholarly <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mandarin_(bureaucrat)\">mandarins</span> who staffed the bureaucracy, it created an educated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_gentry\">gentry</span> class and bound the empire's elite firmly to the state and to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> ideology. The Chinese model inspired comparable systems abroad, such as Korea's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gwageo\">gwageo</span>, and is often regarded as a forerunner of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northcote–Trevelyan_Report\">Northcote–Trevelyan reforms</span> that established merit-based recruitment in 19th-century Britain, before the institution was finally abolished by the Qing <b>court under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empress_Dowager_Cixi\">Empress Dowager Cixi</span> in 1905</b> as part of its sweeping <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Policies\">New Policies</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"imperial examination"},{"id":"cnh-043","num":"四十三","category":"China · History","question":"Widely regarded as a high point of cosmopolitan civilisation, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> ruled a vast, outward-looking empire from Chang'an, then the world's largest city, presiding over a golden age of poetry and welcoming foreign religions along the Silk Road.","answer":"Tang dynasty","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">&lt;b&gt;618&lt;/b&gt;–&lt;b&gt;907&lt;/b&gt;</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"唐朝","pinyin":"Táng cháo","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Táng cháo</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Tang dynasty</b> was an imperial dynasty of China, founded by <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Gaozu_of_Tang\">Li Yuan</span></b> amid the collapse of the short-lived <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sui_dynasty\">Sui dynasty</span>, and is traditionally regarded as a high point of Chinese civilisation and a golden age of cosmopolitan culture. Its second emperor, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Taizong_of_Tang\">Taizong</span>, seized the throne through the bloody <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xuanwu_Gate_Incident\">Xuanwu Gate Incident</span> of 626 and presided over the model administration remembered as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Reign_of_Zhenguan\">Reign of Zhenguan</span>, crushing the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eastern_Turkic_Khaganate\">Eastern Turkic Khaganate</span></b> in 630 and accepting the steppe title of Heavenly Khaghan as Tang power pushed deep into Central Asia. In 690 the empress dowager <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Zetian\">Wu Zetian</span> usurped the throne and founded her own <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Zhou\">Zhou dynasty</span> until 705, becoming the only woman in Chinese history to rule as emperor in her own right, after which the restored dynasty reached its cultural and territorial zenith under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Xuanzong_of_Tang\">Emperor Xuanzong</span>, whose long reign from 712 is celebrated as the Kaiyuan golden age. The dynasty refined the institutions it had inherited, expanding the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examination</span> system, sustaining the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Equal-field_system\">equal-field</span> system of land allotment, and governing through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Departments_and_Six_Ministries\">Three Departments and Six Ministries</span>, while its meticulous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_Code\">Tang Code</span> became the model for the legal systems of neighbouring <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silla\">Silla</span>, Japan, and Vietnam. This zenith was shattered by the catastrophic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"An_Lushan_Rebellion\">An Lushan Rebellion</span> of 755–763, an uprising led by the <b>frontier general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"An_Lushan\">An Lushan</span></b> that so devastated the empire that the registered population, tallied at roughly 52.9 million before the war, had collapsed to about 16.9 million by 764, a fall reflecting both massive loss of life and the wholesale breakdown of state registration. <br> <br> At its height the empire was governed from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chang'an\">Chang'an</span>, then the largest city on earth with perhaps a million inhabitants, a cosmopolitan terminus of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk_Road\">Silk Road</span> thronged with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sogdia\">Sogdian</span>, Persian, and Arab merchants, while a secondary capital flourished at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luoyang\">Luoyang</span>. Religious life was strikingly plural, as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Buddhism\">Buddhism</span> flourished in new schools such as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chan_Buddhism\">Chan</span></b> and was enriched by the Indian travels of the pilgrim-monk <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xuanzang\">Xuanzang</span>, the ruling Li family promoted <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Daoism</span> and claimed descent from its sage Laozi, and foreign creeds such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Church_of_the_East\">Nestorian Christianity</span>—recorded on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nestorian_Stele\">Nestorian Stele</span> of 781—together with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manichaeism\">Manichaeism</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zoroastrianism\">Zoroastrianism</span> were tolerated until the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Anti-Buddhist_Persecution\">great persecution</span> of 845 under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Wuzong_of_Tang\">Emperor Wuzong</span></b>. The era is above all remembered as the golden age of Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_poetry\">poetry</span>, producing masters such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Bai\">Li Bai</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Du_Fu\">Du Fu</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bai_Juyi\">Bai Juyi</span>, whose works fill the later anthology <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Quan_Tangshi\"><i>Quan Tangshi</i></span> with nearly 49,000 surviving poems, while artisans perfected <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sancai\">sancai</span> tricolour ceramics and printers produced the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Diamond_Sutra\">Diamond Sutra</span> of 868, the world's earliest dated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Woodblock_printing\">printed</span> book. In the rebellion's long aftermath, real power drained to autonomous regional military governors known as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiedushi\">jiedushi</span> and to palace <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eunuch\">eunuchs</span>, and the enfeebled court was further battered by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huang_Chao\">Huang Chao</span> Rebellion of 874–884, which sacked both Chang'an and the southern port of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou\">Guangzhou</span>. The dynasty finally fell in 907, when the warlord <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_Wen\">Zhu Wen</span> deposed the last Tang emperor and founded the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Later_Liang_(Five_Dynasties)\">Later Liang</span>, opening the fragmented <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five_Dynasties_and_Ten_Kingdoms_period\">Five Dynasties and Ten Kingdoms</span> period, yet the splendour of its verse, its open cities, and its imperial model would echo through East Asian civilisation for the next thousand years.","citation":"","answerText":"Tang dynasty"},{"id":"cnh-044","num":"四十四","category":"China · History","question":"Coming to power after killing his brothers in a palace coup, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is celebrated for the prosperous Reign of Zhenguan, for heeding frank advisers, and for crushing the Eastern Turks to extend Chinese power across Central Asia.","answer":"Emperor Taizong of Tang","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Reigned</span><span class=\"dt-v\">626–649</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"唐太宗","pinyin":"Táng Tàizōng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Táng Tàizōng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Emperor Taizong of Tang</b> was the second emperor of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang dynasty</span> and is traditionally ranked among the greatest rulers in Chinese history, a soldier-statesman whose reign is remembered as the model <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Golden_age\">golden age</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Reign_of_Zhenguan\">Reign of Zhenguan</span></b>. The second son of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Gaozu_of_Tang\">Emperor Gaozu</span>, who founded the Tang in 618 amid the collapse of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sui_dynasty\">Sui</span>, he had been the dynasty's foremost general, sealing its mastery of the realm with a decisive victory at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Hulao\">Battle of Hulao</span></b> in 621, where he crushed the rival warlords <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Shichong\">Wang Shichong</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dou_Jiande\">Dou Jiande</span> in a single campaign to reunite the empire under Tang rule. Locked in a deadly rivalry with his brothers, the <b>crown prince <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Jiancheng\">Li Jiancheng</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Yuanji\">Li Yuanji</span>, he ambushed and killed them both in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xuanwu_Gate_Incident\">Xuanwu Gate Incident</span> of 626, a palace <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Coup_d'état\">coup</span> after which he compelled his father first to name him heir and then, within months, to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Abdication\">abdicate</span> the throne to him. As emperor he presided over an era of frugal and effective government—lowering taxes, codifying law in the influential <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_Code\">Tang Code</span></b>, and expanding recruitment through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examinations</span>—that later generations idealized as the high point of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> statecraft and an age of recovering prosperity and rare domestic peace. He was especially celebrated for soliciting and tolerating candid criticism, above all from his blunt <b>remonstrating minister <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wei_Zheng\">Wei Zheng</span></b> and the able chancellors <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fang_Xuanling\">Fang Xuanling</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Du_Ruhui\">Du Ruhui</span>, and he is said to have mourned Wei Zheng's death as the loss of a mirror in which he could see his own faults, his court's exemplary dialogues being later gathered in the compendium <i>Zhenguan Zhengyao</i>. <br> <br> Abroad, Taizong shattered the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eastern_Turkic_Khaganate\">Eastern Turkic Khaganate</span> in 630, when his general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Jing_(Tang_dynasty)\">Li Jing</span> captured its khan, a triumph that led the steppe peoples to hail him as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heavenly_Khagan\">Heavenly Khagan</span></b>, supreme overlord of Chinese and nomad alike. He then pushed Tang power deep into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Asia\">Central Asia</span>, subduing the oasis kingdoms of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Western_Regions\">Western Regions</span>—conquering <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gaochang\">Gaochang</span> in 640—and pressing back the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Western_Turkic_Khaganate\">Western Turks</span></b> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tuyuhun\">Tuyuhun</span> to command the trade routes toward the west. In foreign affairs he wove marriage alliances as well, dispatching <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Princess_Wencheng\">Princess Wencheng</span> in 641 to wed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Songtsen_Gampo\">Songtsen Gampo</span>, the king of the rising <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_Empire\">Tibetan Empire</span>, an alliance that carried Chinese culture and Buddhism onto the Tibetan plateau. A patron of learning and religion, he welcomed the pilgrim <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xuanzang\">Xuanzang</span> back from India in 645 and supported his translation of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Buddhism\">Buddhist</span> scriptures, while his cosmopolitan capital at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chang'an\">Chang'an</span> grew into the largest and most diverse city on earth, thronged with merchants, pilgrims, and envoys from across Asia. Under his rule the Tang became one of the most powerful and open empires of its age, and although he is also thought to have shaped the court records of his bloody rise to the throne, later tradition enshrined him as the very model of the wise and virtuous emperor.","citation":"","answerText":"Emperor Taizong of Tang"},{"id":"cnh-046","num":"四十六","category":"China · History","question":"A devout monk who made an epic 17-year pilgrimage overland to India to obtain authentic Buddhist texts, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> returned to a hero's welcome under the Tang and spent his remaining years translating scriptures, his journey later inspiring the fantasy novel <i>Journey to the West</i>.","answer":"Xuanzang","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. 602</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">664</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"玄奘","pinyin":"Xuánzàng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Xuánzàng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Xuanzang</b> was a Chinese Buddhist <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bhikkhu\">monk</span></b>, scholar, and translator of the early Tang period, born into a family of Confucian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Scholar-official\">scholar-officials</span> near <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luoyang\">Luoyang</span> in present-day <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Henan\">Henan</span>. Dissatisfied with the inconsistent and incomplete Chinese translations of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Buddhist_texts\">Buddhist scripture</span></b> then available, and following in the tradition of earlier pilgrims such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Faxian\">Faxian</span>, he resolved to seek authentic texts at their source and, defying an imperial prohibition on foreign travel, set out westward along the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk_Road\">Silk Road</span>. His route carried him across the wastes of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gobi_Desert\">Gobi Desert</span> and the oasis kingdoms of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Asia\">Central Asia</span>, over the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hindu_Kush\">Hindu Kush</span></b> into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gandhara\">Gandhara</span>, and at last into the Buddhist heartland of northern India, where he was received by the powerful emperor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Harsha\">Harsha</span>. There he spent more than a decade in study and pilgrimage, venerating sacred sites such as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bodh_Gaya\">Bodh Gaya</span></b> and immersing himself above all in the great monastic university of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nalanda_mahavihara\">Nālandā</span> in present-day <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bihar\">Bihar</span>, where he was tutored in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mahayana\">Mahāyāna</span> and especially <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yogachara\">Yogācāra</span> doctrine for several years by its venerable abbot <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Śīlabhadra\">Śīlabhadra</span>, then reputedly 106 years old. After roughly seventeen years abroad he returned to the Tang capital of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chang'an\">Chang'an</span> in 645, bearing 657 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sanskrit\">Sanskrit</span> manuscripts packed in 520 cases and carried by a caravan of 20 packhorses, and was met with a tumultuous welcome by Emperor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Taizong_of_Tang\">Taizong</span>, who offered him a high ministerial post that he respectfully declined.<br> <br>For the remaining 19 years of his life he gave himself to translation, founding an imperially sponsored bureau that by his death had rendered roughly 75 works into some 1,335 fascicles of Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sutra\">sūtras</span> and treatises, among them 600 fascicles of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Prajnaparamita\">Perfection of Wisdom</span></b> literature and the brief but celebrated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heart_Sutra\"><i>Heart Sutra</i></span>. His versions were prized for their fidelity to the originals, while his own study and commentary upon the Consciousness-Only teachings gave rise to the short-lived but influential Faxiang school of East Asian Buddhism, perpetuated by his foremost disciple <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuiji\">Kuiji</span>. At the emperor's behest he also compiled the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Records_of_the_Western_Regions\"><i>Records of the Western Regions</i></span></b>, a meticulous description of the 110 kingdoms he had traversed and 28 further lands known only by report, which endures as an indispensable source for the history and geography of 7th-century India and Central Asia. To shelter the hundreds of manuscripts he had carried home, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Giant_Wild_Goose_Pagoda\">Giant Wild Goose Pagoda</span> was raised at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Daci'en_Temple\">Daci'en Temple</span></b> in Chang'an in 652 under Emperor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Gaozong_of_Tang\">Gaozong</span>, a towering brick monument that survives in modern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi'an\">Xi'an</span>. When he died in 664 the Tang court is said to have ordered three days of mourning, yet his most enduring popular memorial came in the 16th century, when his arduous quest was transmuted into a beloved fantasy novel in which he appears as the pilgrim <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_Sanzang\">Tang Sanzang</span>, the \"<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tripitaka\">Tripitaka</span> of Tang,\" escorted along the road by the irrepressible Monkey King <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Wukong\">Sun Wukong</span> and given lasting form by the novelist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Cheng'en\">Wu Cheng'en</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming dynasty</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Xuanzang"},{"id":"cnh-047","num":"四十七","category":"China · History","question":"The earliest Chinese legal code to survive largely intact and a model for the laws of Japan, Korea and Vietnam, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> blended Legalist punishments with Confucian principles of graded social relationships.","answer":"Tang Code","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">唐律 (Táng lǜ, 'the Tang statutes')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"唐律","pinyin":"Táng lǜ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Táng lǜ</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Tang Code</b> was the penal code of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang dynasty</span> and the earliest Chinese legal code to survive largely intact, a synthesis of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Legalism_(Chinese_philosophy)\">Legalist</span> penal severity and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> social ethics whose authority made it the model for the laws of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japan\">Japan</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Korea\">Korea</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vietnam\">Vietnam</span>. Its provisions descended from a long tradition of codified statute, traced to the Legalist thinker <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Kui_(legalist)\">Li Kui</span> and his Canon <b>of Laws of around 400 BCE</b> and refined through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Qi\">Northern Qi</span> code of 564 and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sui_dynasty\">Sui</span> Kaihuang code, before being promulgated under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Gaozu_of_Tang\">Emperor Gaozu</span> as the Wude Code of 624 and revised under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Taizong_of_Tang\">Emperor Taizong</span> as the Zhenguan Code of 637. The definitive recension, the Code with Subcommentary, was <b>completed in 653</b> by a commission headed by <b>the statesman <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhangsun_Wuji\">Zhangsun Wuji</span></b> under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Gaozong_of_Tang\">Emperor Gaozong</span>, whose appended official commentary carried the full force of law and clarified the statutes through a systematic question-and-answer exegesis that effectively turned the work into a comprehensive legal treatise. In its received form the code comprised 502 articles distributed across 12 sections, opening with a chapter of general principles that fixed the scale of punishments, enumerated the gravest offences, and laid down the doctrines governing the entire compilation. Its penalties followed a graduated scale of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five_Punishments\">Five Punishments</span>—beating with the light or heavy rod, <b>terms of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Penal_labour\">penal servitude</span></b> of one to three years, banishment to fixed distances of up to 3,000 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_(unit)\">li</span>, and death by either strangulation or <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Decapitation\">decapitation</span>—a markedly less mutilating system than the amputations of earlier ages. <br> <br> The Confucian dimension appeared most clearly in the rule that punishment varied with the social relationship between offender and victim, so that a junior who struck a senior relative—their bond measured by the five degrees of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mourning\">mourning</span> kinship and the duties of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Filial_piety\">filial piety</span>—could face death, whereas a senior chastising a junior was treated with leniency, all in keeping with the hierarchy of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five_Bonds\">Five Bonds</span>. At the summit of the code's gravity stood the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ten_Abominations\">Ten Abominations</span></b>, a class of the most heinous crimes—above all rebellion and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treason\">treason</span> against the throne, together with grave breaches of family duty such as plotting against or striking a parent—which were barred from the periodic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Amnesty\">amnesties</span> and could never be commuted. Conversely, the code wove social rank into its very operation, allowing nobles, officials, and their kin to reduce or redeem penalties through the so-called eight deliberations and graduated payments of copper, a calibration of justice by status from which ordinary commoners were wholly excluded. Beyond China its influence radiated across <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"East_Asia\">East Asia</span>, furnishing the chief model for the Japanese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ritsuryō\">ritsuryō</span> system embodied in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taihō_Code\">Taihō Code</span></b> of 701 and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yōrō_Code\">Yōrō Code</span> of 718, shaping the statutes of the Korean kingdoms of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Goryeo\">Goryeo</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joseon\">Joseon</span>, and informing the dynastic law of Vietnam. Within China itself its framework was carried forward almost unchanged by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song</span> penal code of 963 and supplied the structural template for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Ming_Code\">Great Ming Code</span> and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Qing_Legal_Code\">Great Qing Legal Code</span></b> that governed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_law\">Chinese law</span> into the early 20th century, a longevity that secured its standing as the most influential body of statute in the premodern East Asian world.","citation":"","answerText":"Tang Code"},{"id":"cnh-048","num":"四十八","category":"China · History","question":"Beginning as a concubine and rising to dominate the court through 2 Tang emperors, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> eventually took the throne in her own name and founded a short-lived dynasty, becoming the only female to rule China as emperor in her own right, and a patron of Buddhism.","answer":"Wu Zetian","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. 624–705</span></div>","traditional":"武則天","hanzi":"武则天","pinyin":"Wǔ Zétiān","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Wǔ Zétiān</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Wu Zetian</b> was the only woman in Chinese history to rule as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_of_China\">emperor</span> in her own right, a formidable figure who founded her own short-lived dynasty in the midst of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span>, an achievement without parallel in more than 2,000 years of imperial history. She entered the palace as a low-ranking <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Concubinage\">concubine</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Taizong_of_Tang\">Emperor Taizong</span>, and on his death she was sent to a Buddhist convent in the customary fashion, only to be recalled by his son and successor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Gaozong_of_Tang\">Emperor Gaozong</span>, whose favour she won so completely that she <b>supplanted his consort <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empress_Wang_(Tang_dynasty)\">Empress Wang</span></b> and was raised to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empress\">empress</span> in 655. As Gaozong's health failed she increasingly governed in his stead, the pair ruling jointly as the so-called Two Sages, and she destroyed rivals such as the powerful chancellor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhangsun_Wuji\">Zhangsun Wuji</span> while brushing aside the accusations of murderous intrigue that her enemies and later chroniclers heaped upon her. After Gaozong died in 683 she dominated the <b>state as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empress_dowager\">empress dowager</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Regent\">regent</span>, installing and deposing her own sons—<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Zhongzong_of_Tang\">Emperor Zhongzong</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Ruizong_of_Tang\">Emperor Ruizong</span>—as puppet rulers whom she raised and cast down at will. In 690 she cast aside the last pretence, deposing Ruizong to take the throne herself and proclaiming the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Zhou\">Zhou dynasty</span></b>, governing with genuine ability—promoting talented men of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Meritocracy\">merit</span> through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examinations</span>—but also through a feared network of informers and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Secret_police\">secret police</span>. <br> <br> She moved her capital from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chang'an\">Chang'an</span> to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luoyang\">Luoyang</span> and ran a vigorous administration that recruited officials widely, even from humble origins, though she did not hesitate to set agents such as the notorious <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lai_Junchen\">Lai Junchen</span></b> upon any whom she suspected of disloyalty. A devoted patron of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Buddhism\">Buddhism</span>, she leaned on it to legitimize a female sovereign in defiance of a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> tradition that allowed no place for a woman on the throne, having herself proclaimed an incarnation of the future Buddha <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maitreya\">Maitreya</span> and a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cakravartin\">cakravartin</span> through the specially produced <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Cloud_Sutra\"><i>Great Cloud Sutra</i></span></b>. Her piety and her ambition together funded grand religious works and the translation of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Buddhist_canon\">Buddhist canon</span>, most spectacularly the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Longmen_Grottoes\">Longmen Grottoes</span> near Luoyang, where a colossal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vairocana\">Vairocana</span> Buddha was carved under her patronage and is traditionally said to bear her own features, a towering sculptural statement of her power. In 705, old and ailing, she was forced from power in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shenlong_coup\">Shenlong coup</span></b> led by the chancellor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Jianzhi\">Zhang Jianzhi</span>, who restored her son Zhongzong and with him the Tang, ending her Zhou dynasty after some 15 years, and she died later that same year. Reviled by later Confucian historians as a ruthless usurper yet acknowledged as a decisive and capable ruler who held the empire steady between the golden ages of her predecessors and of her grandson <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Xuanzong_of_Tang\">Emperor Xuanzong</span>, she lies buried beside Gaozong at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qianling_Mausoleum\">Qianling Mausoleum</span></b> beneath the famous uninscribed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wordless_Stele\">Wordless Stele</span>, as if leaving the final verdict on her extraordinary reign to posterity.","citation":"","answerText":"Wu Zetian"},{"id":"cnh-049","num":"四十九","category":"China · History","question":"Presiding over the cultural zenith of his dynasty before his reign ended in catastrophe, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is remembered for his doomed love of the concubine Yang Guifei and for the devastating rebellion that erupted after he neglected government, a tragedy echoed in the verse of the Tang poets.","answer":"Emperor Xuanzong of Tang","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Reigned</span><span class=\"dt-v\">685 – 3</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"唐玄宗","pinyin":"Táng Xuánzōng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Táng Xuánzōng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Emperor Xuanzong of Tang</b>, personal name <b>Li Longji</b> and also styled <b>Emperor Ming of Tang</b>, was the longest-reigning emperor of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang dynasty</span>, presiding over what later historians regarded as the political and cultural zenith of the imperial house. He came to the throne amid a decade of palace turmoil that followed the unprecedented reign of the empress regnant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Zetian\">Wu Zetian</span>, leading a coup in 710 that crushed the faction of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empress_Wei_(Tang_dynasty)\">Empress Wei</span></b> after she had poisoned his uncle <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Zhongzong_of_Tang\">Emperor Zhongzong</span>, thereby restoring his father <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Ruizong_of_Tang\">Emperor Ruizong</span> to power. Two years later he ascended in his own right and soon eliminated his formidable aunt <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Princess_Taiping\">Princess Taiping</span>, inaugurating the celebrated Kaiyuan era in which capable chief ministers such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yao_Chong\">Yao Chong</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_Jing\">Song Jing</span>, and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Jiuling\">Zhang Jiuling</span></b> presided over fiscal reform, frontier consolidation, and an efficient bureaucracy recruited partly through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examination</span>. Under his patronage the capital of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chang'an\">Chang'an</span> swelled into one of the most populous and cosmopolitan cities on earth, home to perhaps a million people within its walls and serving as the eastern terminus of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk_Road\">Silk Road</span>, where Persian merchants, Central Asian musicians, foreign monks, and tributary envoys mingled in its sprawling markets. A devotee of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Taoism</span> and a passionate connoisseur of music and dance, he founded the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pear_Garden\">Pear Garden</span> academy that later ages honoured as the cradle of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_opera\">Chinese opera</span>, while the poets <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Bai\">Li Bai</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Du_Fu\">Du Fu</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Wei_(Tang_dynasty)\">Wang Wei</span> carried <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_poetry\">Tang poetry</span> to its classical summit during his long reign. <br> <br> In his later years the aging sovereign grew enamoured of <b>the consort <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yang_Guifei\">Yang Guifei</span></b>, numbered among the legendary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Beauties\">Four Beauties</span> of Chinese tradition, and increasingly surrendered the business of government to the corrupt chancellor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Linfu\">Li Linfu</span> and afterwards to her ambitious cousin <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yang_Guozhong\">Yang Guozhong</span>. This protracted neglect allowed the <b>frontier general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"An_Lushan\">An Lushan</span></b>, a commander of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sogdia\">Sogdian</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Turkic_peoples\">Turkic</span> descent who had ingratiated himself at court and accumulated three northern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiedushi\">military governorships</span> together with perhaps 150,000 seasoned troops, to amass dangerous and unchecked power along the empire's vulnerable borders. In December 755 An Lushan launched the catastrophic <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"An_Lushan_rebellion\">An Lushan Rebellion</span></b>, overran the eastern capital of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luoyang\">Luoyang</span> and then Chang'an itself, and drove the court into flight toward <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan\">Sichuan</span>, where mutinous imperial guards at the Mawei post station compelled Yang Guifei to take her own life in 756. Stripped of real authority, the broken ruler became a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taishang_Huang\">retired emperor</span> while his son was proclaimed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Suzong_of_Tang\">Emperor Suzong</span>, and though the dynasty ultimately survived, the war proved devastating, the census of 754 recording roughly 52.9 million registered persons against fewer than 17 million a decade later, a collapse that reflected administrative breakdown and mass displacement as much as outright death. His doomed romance with Yang Guifei passed into enduring legend, immortalised above all in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bai_Juyi\">Bai Juyi</span>'s long <b>narrative poem <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chang_hen_ge\"><i>Song of Everlasting Sorrow</i></span></b>, whose lament for a love sundered by rebellion shaped the literary and popular memory of his reign for more than a millennium.","citation":"","answerText":"Emperor Xuanzong of Tang"},{"id":"cnh-051","num":"五十一","category":"China · History","question":"A failed examination candidate turned salt smuggler whose massive rebellion of <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>–<span class=\"blank\">_____</span> sacked the great cities of Chang'an and Guangzhou, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> dealt the dying Tang a blow from which it never recovered.","answer":"Huang Chao","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. 835</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">884</span></div>","traditional":"黃巢","hanzi":"黄巢","pinyin":"Huáng Cháo","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Huáng Cháo</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Huang Chao</b> was a Chinese rebel leader, born into a prosperous <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Salt_in_Chinese_history\">salt</span></b>-trading family of Cao Prefecture in present-day <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heze\">Heze</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shandong\">Shandong</span>, whose failure to pass the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examinations</span> turned him from salt smuggling toward the great uprising that bears his name. The dynasty he confronted had been in decline since the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"An_Lushan_Rebellion\">An Lushan Rebellion</span> of 755–763, its authority sapped by autonomous regional <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiedushi\">military governors</span> and by powerful court <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eunuch\">eunuchs</span>, and in the 870s a ruinous drought and famine across <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Henan\">Henan</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hebei\">Hebei</span>, and the eastern provinces drove multitudes of starving peasants into banditry. He joined the revolt raised in 874 by his fellow salt bootlegger <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Xianzhi_(rebel)\">Wang Xianzhi</span></b> the following year, and when Wang was defeated and killed in 878 he absorbed the remnants of that army to become the rebellion's paramount leader, his ranks swelling with destitute farmers until his forces were said to approach 600,000 men. Sweeping southward across the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span>, in 879 his army stormed the great maritime emporium of Guangzhou and carried out the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou_massacre\">Guangzhou massacre</span></b>, in which tens of thousands of foreign traders—<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Muslims\">Muslims</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jews_in_China\">Jews</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Christians_in_China\">Christians</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zoroastrianism\">Zoroastrians</span>—were slaughtered, the Arab writers <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Abu_Zayd_al-Sirafi\">Abu Zayd al-Sirafi</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Al-Masudi\">al-Mas'udi</span> placing the toll as high as 200,000. From the south he turned north, capturing the eastern capital of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luoyang\">Luoyang</span> late in 880 before breaking through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tong_Pass\">Tong Pass</span> to seize the imperial capital Chang'an early in 881, whereupon <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Xizong_of_Tang\">Emperor Xizong</span></b> fled to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chengdu\">Chengdu</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan\">Sichuan</span>.<br> <br>In the captured capital he proclaimed himself <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_of_China\">emperor</span> of a new dynasty styled the Great Qi, taking the throne on 16 January 881 under the era name Jintong, with his <b>veteran commander <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shang_Rang\">Shang Rang</span></b> installed among his chancellors. His authority scarcely reached beyond the capital region, however, for the powerful provincial commanders, notably <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gao_Pian\">Gao Pian</span>, held back their armies while Tang loyalist forces <b>under the chancellor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Duo\">Wang Duo</span></b> gradually closed in, and the protracted occupation, racked by famine and reprisal, reduced the once-magnificent metropolis to ruin. Decisive in the counteroffensive was the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shatuo\">Shatuo</span> Turkic chieftain <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Keyong\">Li Keyong</span>, whose cavalry helped the dynasty recover Chang'an in 883 and drive the rebel emperor into headlong retreat toward the east. Pursued into his native Shandong, he was run down and killed in the summer of 884 at Langhu Valley in present-day <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Laiwu\">Laiwu</span>, bringing his rebellion of 875–884 to its end. The blow proved mortal: the Tang lingered as a hollow shell until 907, when one of his own former lieutenants, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_Wen\">Zhu Wen</span>, deposed the last emperor and founded the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Later_Liang_(Five_Dynasties)\">Later Liang</span>, inaugurating the fractured <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five_Dynasties_and_Ten_Kingdoms_period\">Five Dynasties and Ten Kingdoms</span> era.","citation":"","answerText":"Huang Chao"},{"id":"cnc-055","num":"五十五","category":"China · Culture","question":"A complex of hundreds of grottoes near the oasis town of Dunhuang on the Silk Road, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> preserves a millennium of Buddhist murals and statues, along with a hidden library of ancient manuscripts sealed for centuries.","answer":"Mogao Caves","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">莫高窟 (Mògāo kū, 'peerless caves')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"莫高窟","pinyin":"Mògāo kū","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Mògāo kū</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“peerless caves”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Mogao Caves</b> is a complex of Buddhist cave temples carved into a desert cliff some 25 kilometres (16 mi) southeast of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Oasis\">oasis</span> town of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dunhuang\">Dunhuang</span></b> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gansu\">Gansu</span>, at a crossroads of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk_Road\">Silk Road</span>, comprising 735 grottoes of which 492 are decorated. Tradition holds that the monk Le Zun, granted a vision of a thousand radiant Buddhas, excavated <b>the first sanctuary in 366 CE</b>, and over the following millennium pilgrims, merchants, and ruling families sponsored ever grander shrines in this masterpiece of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rock-cut_architecture\">rock-cut architecture</span>. Construction continued from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sixteen_Kingdoms\">Sixteen Kingdoms</span> through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Wei\">Northern Wei</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sui_dynasty\">Sui</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span> to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan</span>, embracing the decades of occupation by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_Empire\">Tibetan Empire</span> after 781 and the patronage of the local <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guiyi_Circuit\">Guiyi Circuit</span> warlords and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Western_Xia\">Western Xia</span>. The caves preserve roughly 45,000 square metres of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mural\">murals</span> and more than 2,400 painted clay sculptures, an unrivalled gallery of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Buddhist_art\">Buddhist art</span></b> teeming with paradise scenes, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jataka_tales\">jataka tales</span>, donor portraits, and soaring <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Apsara\">apsaras</span>. Among the most imposing works is the seated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maitreya\">Maitreya</span> of Cave 96, a colossus about 35.5 metres (116 ft) high completed in 695 during the reign of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Zetian\">Wu Zetian</span> and still sheltered behind the landmark nine-storey facade. <br> <br> Early in the 11th century a small side chamber now numbered Cave 17 was packed with documents and sealed behind a plastered wall, perhaps against feared invasion, and forgotten for nearly 900 years. As overland trade withered after the Yuan and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span> turned commerce to the sea, the site fell into neglect, its lower grottoes drifting full of sand from the encroaching dunes. <b>In 1900</b> the resident Taoist caretaker <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Yuanlu\">Wang Yuanlu</span> chanced upon the hidden chamber and its hoard of up to 50,000 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dunhuang_manuscripts\">manuscripts</span>, paintings, and printed scrolls in Chinese, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sanskrit\">Sanskrit</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sogdian_language\">Sogdian</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Old_Uyghur\">Old Uyghur</span>, and other tongues, including even a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hebrew_language\">Hebrew</span> prayer sheet. Foreign expeditions soon carried much of it away, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Aurel_Stein\">Aurel Stein</span> securing thousands of items for <b>a modest payment in 1907</b>, among them the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Diamond_Sutra\"><i>Diamond Sutra</i></span> of 868, the world's earliest dated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Woodblock_printing\">printed</span> book now in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"British_Library\">British Library</span>, followed by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paul_Pelliot\">Paul Pelliot</span> in 1908 for the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bibliothèque_nationale_de_France\">Bibliothèque nationale de France</span></b>, by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sergey_Oldenburg\">Sergei Oldenburg</span> for Russia, and by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Langdon_Warner\">Langdon Warner</span>, who peeled away fragments of mural in 1924. The dispersal gave birth to the international field of Dunhuang studies, and the site has since passed into careful stewardship, protected by the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dunhuang_Academy\">Dunhuang Academy</span></b> founded in 1944, inscribed as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Heritage_Site\">World Heritage Site</span> in 1987, conserved with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Getty_Conservation_Institute\">Getty Conservation Institute</span>, and reunited digitally through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"International_Dunhuang_Project\">International Dunhuang Project</span> as one of the supreme cultural treasures of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Mogao Caves"},{"id":"cnc-056","num":"五十六","category":"China · Culture","question":"Originally the male bodhisattva Avalokiteśvara of Indian Buddhism, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> came to be widely worshipped in China in female form as the \"Goddess of Mercy\", venerated in both temples and folk religion.","answer":"Guanyin","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">观音 (Guānyīn, 'perceiver of the world's sounds')</span></div>","traditional":"觀音","hanzi":"观音","pinyin":"Guānyīn, short for Guanshiyin","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Guānyīn, short for Guanshiyin</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Perceiver of the World's Sounds”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Guanyin</b> is the Chinese form of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bodhisattva\">bodhisattva</span></b> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Avalokiteśvara\">Avalokiteśvara</span>, the embodiment of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Karuṇā\">compassion</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mahayana\">Mahayana</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Buddhism\">Buddhism</span>, who came to be venerated across China in female form as the \"Goddess of Mercy.\" Devotion rests above all on chapter 25 of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lotus_Sutra\"><i>Lotus Sutra</i></span>, <b>translated by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kumārajīva\">Kumarajiva</span> in 406 CE</b>, which promises rescue from fire, flood, and sword to all who call the name and lists 33 manifestations, several of them female, in which the bodhisattva preaches. The abbreviated name spread partly because the syllable <i>shi</i> fell under the naming taboo of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Taizong_of_Tang\">Emperor Taizong</span>, even though the pilgrim <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xuanzang\">Xuanzang</span> insisted the correct rendering was Guanzizai, \"the Lord who gazes down.\" Imagery remained male, often mustached, through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span>, turned graceful and ambiguous under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song</span>, and was almost wholly feminine by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span>, a shift scholars link to the savior-goddess <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tara_(Buddhism)\">Tara</span>, indigenous mother deities, and the bodhisattva's child-granting powers. The transformation was sealed by the legend of Princess <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Miaoshan\">Miaoshan</span>, first attested <b>in an inscription of 1100</b>, who gave her own eyes and arms to cure her cruel father and was revealed as Guanyin of the Thousand Arms. <br> <br> Iconography multiplied accordingly, from the thousand-armed, thousand-eyed form invoked through the Great Compassion <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nīlakaṇṭha_Dhāraṇī\">dharani</span> to the White-Robed lady with willow branch and vase of sweet dew, the bringer of sons merged with <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Songzi_Niangniang\">Songzi Niangniang</span></b>, and the sea-borne Guanyin of the South attended by the dragon girl <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Longnü\">Longnü</span> and the boy pilgrim <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sudhana\">Sudhana</span>. In the devotional triad of the Western <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sukhavati\">Pure Land</span></b> she stands beside <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Amitābha\">Amitābha</span> with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mahāsthāmaprāpta\">Mahāsthāmaprāpta</span>, escorting the dying to rebirth. Her island seat of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mount_Putuo\">Mount Putuo</span> off <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhejiang\">Zhejiang</span>, 1 of the 4 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sacred_Mountains_of_China\">sacred Buddhist mountains</span>, still draws millions of pilgrims yearly to festivals on the 19th day of the 2nd, 6th, and 9th lunar months, beneath a 33-meter (110 ft) bronze South Sea Guanyin <b>erected in 1997</b>. Beyond the monasteries she pervades <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_folk_religion\">folk religion</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Taoist</span> pantheon, protects sailors alongside the sea goddess <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mazu\">Mazu</span>, and repeatedly rescues the pilgrims of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Journey_to_the_West\"><i>Journey to the West</i></span>. Her cult shaped all <b>East Asia—Kyoto's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sanjūsangen-dō\">Sanjūsangen-dō</span></b> alone houses 1,001 images of the thousand-armed form—while in China her name graces <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tieguanyin\">Tieguanyin</span> tea and the 108-meter (354 ft) <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guanyin_of_Nanshan\">Guanyin of Nanshan</span>, completed in 2005 as one of the tallest statues on earth.","citation":"","answerText":"Guanyin"},{"id":"cnc-059","num":"五十九","category":"China · Culture","question":"Emphasising direct insight and meditation over scripture and ritual, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was later transmitted to Japan, where it became known as Zen.","answer":"Chan Buddhism","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">禅宗 (Chánzōng); 禅 renders Sanskrit dhyāna ('meditation')</span></div>","traditional":"禪宗","hanzi":"禅宗","pinyin":"Chánzōng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Chánzōng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Chan Buddhism</b> is a school of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mahayana\">Mahayana</span> Buddhism that developed within <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Buddhism\">Chinese Buddhism</span> and <b>placed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Meditation\">meditation</span></b> and direct insight at the heart of practice. Its adherents characterised the tradition as a special transmission outside the scriptures, pointing directly to the mind so as to awaken the practitioner to an innate <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Buddha-nature\">Buddha-nature</span>, often in a <b>flash of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Subitism\">sudden enlightenment</span></b>. The school traced its origin to the semi-legendary Indian monk <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bodhidharma\">Bodhidharma</span>, said to have reached China early in the 6th century and to have spent years in wall-gazing meditation at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shaolin_Monastery\">Shaolin Monastery</span></b>. In doctrine it fused the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yogachara\">Yogācāra</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Madhyamaka\">Madhyamaka</span> currents of Indian thought with the emptiness teaching of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Prajnaparamita\">Prajñāpāramitā</span>, while drawing temperamentally on the spontaneity prized by Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Taoism</span>. By privileging wordless realisation over the study of texts and the performance of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ritual\">ritual</span>, it offered a deliberately iconoclastic alternative to the more scholastic and devotional forms of the faith. <br> <br> A line of patriarchs running from Bodhidharma through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dazu_Huike\">Huike</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Daman_Hongren\">Hongren</span> culminated in the 6th patriarch <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huineng\">Huineng</span>, whose southern teaching of sudden awakening eclipsed the gradualist northern school of his rival <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shenxiu\">Shenxiu</span>. Huineng's words were enshrined in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Platform_Sutra\"><i>Platform Sutra</i></span></b>, the only Chinese Buddhist work to bear the honorific title of <i>sutra</i> and a foundational scripture of the mature tradition. During the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song</span> dynasties the school flowered into its classical form, the masters <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mazu_Daoyi\">Mazu Daoyi</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Linji_Yixuan\">Linji Yixuan</span></b> teaching through shouts, blows, and the baffling riddles later codified as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kōan\">kōans</span>, as the lineage divided into the so-called <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five_Houses_of_Chán\">Five Houses</span>. These encounters were gathered in celebrated anthologies such as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Blue_Cliff_Record\"><i>Blue Cliff Record</i></span></b> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Gateless_Barrier\"><i>Gateless Gate</i></span>, and the teaching spread abroad to become <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Korean_Seon\">Seon</span> in Korea, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Thiền\">Thiền</span> in Vietnam, and the renowned <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zen\">Zen</span> of Japan. There the monk <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eisai\">Eisai</span> transmitted the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rinzai_school\">Rinzai</span> line and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dōgen\">Dōgen</span> the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sōtō\">Sōtō</span> line, whose sensibilities shaped <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ink_wash_painting\">ink painting</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japanese_tea_ceremony\">tea ceremony</span>, and garden design, while in the 20th century writers such as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"D._T._Suzuki\">D. T. Suzuki</span></b> carried Zen to a wide Western audience.","citation":"","answerText":"Chan Buddhism"},{"id":"cnc-060","num":"六十","category":"China · Culture","question":"Evolving from the Indian stupa as Buddhism spread eastward, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was often built to house relics or scriptures and became a distinctive feature of the skyline.","answer":"Chinese pagoda","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">塔 (tǎ), a clipping of Sanskrit stūpa</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"塔","pinyin":"tǎ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">tǎ</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Chinese pagoda</b> is a tiered tower with multiple projecting eaves, developed in China as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Buddhism\">Buddhism</span></b> spread eastward and built chiefly to enshrine relics and scriptures, becoming the most distinctive vertical accent of the East Asian skyline. The faith arrived under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span> along the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk_Road\">Silk Road</span> in the 1st century CE, by tradition first housed at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"White_Horse_Temple\">White Horse Temple</span></b>, and early builders of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Buddhism\">Chinese Buddhism</span> fused the hemispherical Indian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stupa\">stupa</span> with the native multi-storey watchtowers known from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Que_(tower)\">que</span> gate-pillars and tomb models. Like its Indian ancestor, the tower served to hold the cremation relics called <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Śarīra\">śarīra</span> together with precious copies of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sutra\">sutras</span>, its storeys almost always odd in number, since odd digits belonged to the auspicious realm of heaven. The first examples rose in timber upon intricate <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dougong\">dougong</span> bracket sets and have largely perished, so the oldest survivor is of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Brick\">brick</span>, the 12-sided <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Songyue_Pagoda\">Songyue Pagoda</span></b> of 523 on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mount_Song\">Mount Song</span>, raised under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Wei\">Northern Wei</span> and standing about 40 metres (130 ft). Under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span> the square plan prevailed, exemplified by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Giant_Wild_Goose_Pagoda\">Giant Wild Goose Pagoda</span> erected at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi'an\">Xi'an</span> in 652 to store the scriptures carried home from India by the pilgrim <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xuanzang\">Xuanzang</span>, before the octagon became standard in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song</span> era. <br> <br> Carpentry reached its summit in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pagoda_of_Fogong_Temple\">Pagoda of Fogong Temple</span>, <b>completed in 1056</b> under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liao_dynasty\">Liao</span>, which at 67.31 metres (221 ft) remains the world's oldest and tallest ancient wooden tower, its frame joined without iron nails and surviving repeated earthquakes. Masonry kept pace, the so-called <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Iron_Pagoda\">Iron Pagoda</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kaifeng\">Kaifeng</span>, <b>finished in 1049</b>, rising 56.88 metres (187 ft) in iron-hued glazed brick, while the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liuhe_Pagoda\">Liuhe Pagoda</span> above <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hangzhou\">Hangzhou</span> doubled as a lighthouse for river sailors. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Porcelain_Tower_of_Nanjing\">Porcelain Tower of Nanjing</span>, built by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yongle_Emperor\">Yongle Emperor</span> in the early 15th century and sheathed in gleaming white tiles to a height of nearly 79 metres (260 ft), was counted by European travellers among the wonders of the world until the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiping_Rebellion\">Taiping Rebellion</span> <b>destroyed it in 1856</b>, while the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Leifeng_Pagoda\">Leifeng Pagoda</span>, famed from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Legend_of_the_White_Snake\">Legend of the White Snake</span>, collapsed in 1924 and was rebuilt in 2002. The form travelled outward with the faith, begetting the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japanese_pagoda\">Japanese pagoda</span> and the stone towers of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Korea\">Korea</span>, even as towers at home shed their Buddhist purpose, towns raising <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Feng_shui\">feng shui</span> towers to mend the fortunes of the landscape and bless examination candidates. Europe caught the fashion through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinoiserie\">chinoiserie</span>, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"William_Chambers_(architect)\">William Chambers</span></b> raising his 10-storey Great Pagoda at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kew_Gardens\">Kew Gardens</span> in 1762, and thousands of historic towers still punctuate the hills and rivers of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>, beloved emblems of its skyline.","citation":"","answerText":"Chinese pagoda"},{"id":"cnc-062","num":"六十二","category":"China · Culture","question":"Regarded as the golden age of Chinese verse and preserved in anthologies of some 50,000 surviving poems, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> includes the work of celebrated masters such as Li Bai and Du Fu.","answer":"Tang poetry","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">618–907 (Tang)</span></div>","traditional":"唐詩","hanzi":"唐诗","pinyin":"Tángshī","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Tángshī</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Tang poetry</b> is the body of verse composed under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang dynasty</span> of 618–907, regarded as the golden age of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_poetry\">Chinese poetry</span></b> and preserved on a staggering scale, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Quan_Tangshi\"><i>Complete Tang Poems</i></span> commissioned <b>by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kangxi_Emperor\">Kangxi Emperor</span> in 1705</b> gathering some 48,900 poems by more than 2,200 authors. Its master form was the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shi_(poetry)\">shi</span> lyric in lines of 5 or 7 characters, ranging from free \"old-style\" <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gushi_(poetry)\">gushi</span> to the <b>tonally patterned <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Regulated_verse\">regulated verse</span></b> of 8 lines and the 4-line <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jueju\">jueju</span> quatrain. Verse-writing was tested in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examinations</span> and practiced from palace banquets in million-strong <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chang'an\">Chang'an</span> to garrisons on the steppe, where <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cen_Shen\">Cen Shen</span> and the frontier poets sang of sand and snow. The High Tang produced the canonical trio of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Bai\">Li Bai</span>, the \"Banished Immortal\" toasting the moon in roughly 1,000 surviving poems, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Du_Fu\">Du Fu</span></b>, the \"Poet-Sage\" whose 1,400 poems chronicle his age with Confucian conscience, and the Buddhist painter-poet <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Wei_(Tang_dynasty)\">Wang Wei</span>, beside quieter voices like <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Meng_Haoran\">Meng Haoran</span>. The catastrophe of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"An_Lushan_Rebellion\">An Lushan Rebellion</span> of 755–763 cleaved the era, and Du Fu's laments over a state shattered while hills and rivers endure fixed the standard for poetry as witness. <br> <br> Mid-Tang writing turned demotic and reformist with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bai_Juyi\">Bai Juyi</span>, whose new <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuefu\">yuefu</span> ballads protested misrule and whose <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_of_Everlasting_Regret\"><i>Song of Everlasting Regret</i></span></b>, on the doomed love of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Xuanzong_of_Tang\">Emperor Xuanzong</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yang_Guifei\">Yang Guifei</span>, was reportedly chanted by singing girls and herd-boys alike. The Late Tang refined a darker music in the veiled, allusive love poems of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Shangyin\">Li Shangyin</span>, the elegant quatrains of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Du_Mu\">Du Mu</span>, and the ghost-haunted genius of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_He\">Li He</span>, dead at 26. Transmission never ceased, from manuscript copies sealed in the caves of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dunhuang\">Dunhuang</span> to the <b>1763 schoolroom</b> anthology <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Hundred_Tang_Poems\"><i>Three Hundred Tang Poems</i></span>, whose preface promised that memorizing its roughly 310 selections would make even a dullard chant. Abroad, the corpus became the model for Sino-Japanese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kanshi_(poetry)\">kanshi</span>, while <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ezra_Pound\">Ezra Pound</span>'s 1915 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cathay_(poetry_collection)\"><i>Cathay</i></span></b> and the versions of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Arthur_Waley\">Arthur Waley</span> carried Li Bai and Du Fu into the bloodstream of modernist English verse. In China the poems remain a living possession, with Li Bai's 20-character <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Quiet_Night_Thought\"><i>Quiet Night Thought</i></span> on moonlight and homesickness still the first classic most children learn, 12 centuries after it was written.","citation":"","answerText":"Tang poetry"},{"id":"cnc-063","num":"六十三","category":"China · Culture","question":"Performed by two dancers sharing a vivid costume to mimic the beast's movements, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is staged to bring good luck and drive off evil at the New Year and at shop openings, accompanied by clashing cymbals, gongs and drums.","answer":"lion dance","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">舞狮 (wǔshī, 'dancing lion')</span></div>","traditional":"舞獅","hanzi":"舞狮","pinyin":"wǔshī","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">wǔshī</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>lion dance</b> is a traditional Chinese performance in which 2 dancers animate a single vivid costume, one steering the great blinking head and the other the rump, mimicking a lion's prowls, scratches, and leaps to summon good fortune and drive off evil at <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_New_Year\">Chinese New Year</span></b>, shop openings, and weddings. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lion\">lion</span> itself is no native of China, arriving instead as exotic tribute along the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk_Road\">Silk Road</span> during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span> from realms such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Parthian_Empire\">Parthian Empire</span>, after which the beast's image fused with the sacred lion of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Buddhism\">Buddhism</span> and the stone <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_guardian_lions\">guardian lions</span></b> flanking gates. Masked lion mummery was already a court spectacle under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span>, whose five-direction lion troupes performed in coloured shags, and the poet <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bai_Juyi\">Bai Juyi</span> left a vivid 9th-century sketch of a western dancer's lion with carved head, silken tail, and ears that flapped. Two grand families of the art endure, the Northern lion of the old capitals wearing a shaggy red-and-gold coat, often paired or trailed by a cub, and given to playful <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Acrobatics\">acrobatics</span> with an embroidered ball. The Southern lion of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangdong\">Guangdong</span> instead sports a horned papier-mâché head with mirrored brow and snapping lids, its faces colour-keyed to the oath-brothers <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Bei\">Liu Bei</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guan_Yu\">Guan Yu</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Fei\">Zhang Fei</span>, and its steps grew up inside <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_martial_arts\">martial arts</span> halls such as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hung_Ga\">Hung Ga</span></b> schools of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foshan\">Foshan</span>. <br> <br> Every routine rides on a thunderous trio, the great <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Drum\">drum</span> leading <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gong\">gong</span> and clashing <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cymbal\">cymbals</span></b> amid volleys of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Firecracker\">firecrackers</span>, while a new costume is brought to life in an eye-dotting rite that touches the pupils with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cinnabar\">cinnabar</span>. The signature act is the plucking of the green, in which a head of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lettuce\">lettuce</span> tied to a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Red_envelope\">red envelope</span> of money is hung</b> high, the lion devouring the prize and spraying shredded leaves over the crowd to scatter prosperity, the din and colour recalling the noise-fearing monster <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nian\">Nian</span> of New Year legend. Modern troupes have pushed the athleticism to extremes, bounding between steel jong poles up to 3 metres (9.8 ft) tall, and <b>since 1994</b> the strongest teams have contested world championships at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Genting_Highlands\">Genting Highlands</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Malaysia\">Malaysia</span>. Carried abroad by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Overseas_Chinese\">overseas Chinese</span>, the dance enlivens <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinatown\">Chinatowns</span> on every continent and claims cousins across Asia, from the shishi-mai of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japan\">Japan</span> to the múa lân that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vietnam\">Vietnam</span> stages at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mid-Autumn_Festival\">Mid-Autumn Festival</span></b>, while remaining distinct from the many-bodied <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dragon_dance\">dragon dance</span>. Inscribed in national registers of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Intangible_cultural_heritage\">intangible cultural heritage</span> and practised today by men and women alike, the leaping lion remains the most joyous herald of festivity in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"lion dance"},{"id":"cnc-064","num":"六十四","category":"China · Culture","question":"A romantic, wine-loving wanderer of the 8th century famed for spontaneous, exuberant verse, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is, by legend, said to have drowned trying to embrace the moon's reflection, and is paired with Du Fu as the greatest of Chinese poets.","answer":"Li Bai","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">701–762</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"李白","pinyin":"Lǐ Bái","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Lǐ Bái</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Li Bai</b> was a poet of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang dynasty</span> regarded, together with his friend <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Du_Fu\">Du Fu</span></b>, as the greatest of all Chinese poets. Nicknamed the Poet Immortal for the seemingly effortless brilliance of his verse, he cultivated a romantic persona as a wine-loving, sword-bearing wanderer steeped in the mysticism of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Taoism</span>. He was said to have been born far to the west at <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Suyab\">Suyab</span></b> in Central Asia before being raised in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan\">Sichuan</span> near present-day <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiangyou\">Jiangyou</span>, and from his youth he roamed widely rather than pursue the conventional path of the examination official. Roughly a thousand of his poems survive, ranging across the free <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gushi_(poetry)\">old-style verse</span></b>, the folk-flavoured <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuefu\">yuefu</span> ballad, and the compact <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jueju\">quatrain</span>, their imagery dwelling on the moon, wine, rivers, and mountains in a tradition reaching back to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chu_Ci\"><i>Chu Ci</i></span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qu_Yuan\">Qu Yuan</span>. Among his best-loved pieces is the wistful <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Quiet_Night_Thought\"><i>Quiet Night Thought</i></span></b>, and he moved in a circle of fellow writers including <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Meng_Haoran\">Meng Haoran</span> and the elder <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"He_Zhizhang\">He Zhizhang</span>, who on meeting him reportedly hailed the younger man as a banished immortal. <br> <br> Around 742 he was summoned to the capital <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chang'an\">Chang'an</span> to serve the emperor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Xuanzong_of_Tang\">Xuanzong</span> in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hanlin_Academy\">Hanlin Academy</span>, but his irreverence, embodied in a legend that he made the <b>powerful eunuch <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gao_Lishi\">Gao Lishi</span></b> pull off his boots, soon cost him his place. When the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"An_Lushan_Rebellion\">An Lushan Rebellion</span> convulsed the empire after 755, Li Bai attached himself to a prince whose cause was branded treasonous, and he was condemned to exile toward distant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yelang\">Yelang</span> before a timely amnesty set him free. He died in 762, and although he most likely succumbed to illness at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dangtu_County\">Dangtu</span> in the care of his kinsman <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Yangbing\">Li Yangbing</span>, who gathered his scattered works, romantic tradition holds that he drowned in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span> while drunkenly reaching to embrace the moon's reflection. His prodigious love of drink earned him a place among the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight_Immortals_of_the_Wine_Cup\">Eight Immortals of the Wine Cup</span></b> celebrated in a poem by Du Fu, and intoxication became inseparable from his poetic legend. His influence has been immense, shaping later <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_poetry\">Chinese poetry</span> and the wider canon of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_poetry\">Tang poetry</span> and, in the 20th century, reaching the West through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Arthur_Waley\">Arthur Waley</span> and through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ezra_Pound\">Ezra Pound</span>, whose collection <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cathay_(poetry_collection)\"><i>Cathay</i></span> reworked his verse from the notes of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ernest_Fenollosa\">Ernest Fenollosa</span></b>, carrying his fame far beyond <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Li Bai"},{"id":"cnc-065","num":"六十五","category":"China · Culture","question":"Celebrated under the brightest full moon of the year with family gatherings and gazing at the sky, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is associated with the legend of the moon goddess Chang'e and with the sharing of rich, round pastries.","answer":"Mid-Autumn Festival","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">中秋节 (Zhōngqiūjié, 'mid-autumn festival')</span></div>","traditional":"中秋節","hanzi":"中秋节","pinyin":"Zhōngqiūjié","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōngqiūjié</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Mid-Autumn Festival</b> is the harvest festival held on the 15th day of the 8th lunar month, when families gather under the brightest full <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Moon\">moon</span> of the year</b> for reunion dinners, moon-gazing, and the sharing of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mooncake\">mooncakes</span>, a celebration 2nd only to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_New_Year\">Chinese New Year</span>. Royal autumn sacrifices to the moon are recorded from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_dynasty\">Zhou dynasty</span>, moonlit revels and palace legends flourished under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span>, and by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song</span> the night had become a fixed popular festival of wine, markets, and verse, crowned by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Su_Shi\">Su Shi</span>'s lyric wishing that loved ones a thousand li apart might share the same fair moon. Its presiding myth tells how the archer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Houyi\">Houyi</span>, who shot down 9 of the 10 scorching suns, received an elixir of immortality from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Queen_Mother_of_the_West\">Queen Mother of the West</span>, and how his wife <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chang'e\">Chang'e</span> swallowed it and floated to the moon, where she dwells forever with the elixir-pounding <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Moon_rabbit\">Jade Rabbit</span></b> and the woodcutter <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Gang\">Wu Gang</span>, condemned to fell a self-healing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Osmanthus_fragrans\">osmanthus</span> tree. The round mooncake embodies reunion, classically dense with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lotus_seed\">lotus-seed</span> paste around a golden <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Salted_duck_egg\">salted duck-egg</span></b> yolk for a moon, and legend even credits cakes with smuggling the messages that timed the revolt of the future <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hongwu_Emperor\">Hongwu Emperor</span> <b>against the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan</span> in 1368</b>. Around the table go <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pomelo\">pomelos</span> and osmanthus wine, children in the south parade paper <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lantern\">lanterns</span>, and in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span> the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tai_Hang_fire_dragon_dance\">Tai Hang fire dragon</span>, some 67 meters (220 ft) long and bristling with tens of thousands of lit incense sticks, weaves through the lanes for 3 nights. <br> <br> The full moon of the 8th month gathers in neighbors as well, as Vietnam's child-centered <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tết_Trung_Thu\">Tết Trung Thu</span></b>, Korea's great 3-day harvest thanksgiving <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chuseok\">Chuseok</span>, and Japan's quiet moon-viewing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tsukimi\">Tsukimi</span>. In the People's Republic the festival entered the national <b>register of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Intangible_cultural_heritage\">intangible cultural heritage</span> in 2006</b> and the calendar of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Public_holidays_in_China\">public holidays</span> in 2008, unleashing one of the year's great travel waves. Commerce keeps pace, with mooncake sales running on the order of 20 billion yuan a year, novelty fillings from custard lava to ice cream, the chilled <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Snow_skin_mooncake\">snow-skin mooncake</span> popularized from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Singapore\">Singapore</span> and Hong Kong, and periodic austerity drives against gold-boxed gift extravagance, while nutritionists note a single double-yolk cake can approach 1,000 calories. The legend has even gone back to its source, for China named its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Lunar_Exploration_Program\">lunar exploration program</span> Chang'e and its rovers <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yutu_(rover)\">Yutu</span>, the Jade Rabbit, landing on <b>the far side in 2019</b> and returning moon samples in 2020. So the goddess who fled to the moon now lends her name to spacecraft that touch it, while below, families still look up together, finding in one bright circle the old promise that the parted share a single sky.","citation":"","answerText":"Mid-Autumn Festival"},{"id":"cnc-066","num":"六十六","category":"China · Culture","question":"Living through the devastating An Lushan rebellion and writing with compassion about war, poverty and duty, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> — often called the \"poet-sage\" — is ranked alongside Li Bai at the summit of the tradition.","answer":"Du Fu","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">712–770</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"杜甫","pinyin":"Dù Fǔ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Dù Fǔ</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Du Fu</b>, courtesy name Zimei, was a poet of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang dynasty</span> revered as the \"Poet-Sage,\" who stands with his friend <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Bai\">Li Bai</span></b> at the summit of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_poetry\">Chinese poetry</span>. Grandson of the court poet <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Du_Shenyan\">Du Shenyan</span> and raised near <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luoyang\">Luoyang</span>, he failed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examination</span> in 735 and again in the notorious test of 747, when the chief minister <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Linfu\">Li Linfu</span> passed no one, though his wanderings brought the consolation of meeting Li Bai in 744. After a threadbare decade petitioning at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chang'an\">Chang'an</span> under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Xuanzong_of_Tang\">Emperor Xuanzong</span>, he received a minor post in 755 just as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"An_Lushan_Rebellion\">An Lushan rebellion</span> exploded, was trapped in the fallen capital, and escaped in 756 to the refugee court of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Suzong_of_Tang\">Emperor Suzong</span></b>, only to be demoted for impolitic loyalty to a disgraced minister. Resigning amid famine in 759, he trekked west through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tianshui\">Tianshui</span> to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chengdu\">Chengdu</span>, where in the years 760–765 the modest <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Du_Fu_Thatched_Cottage\">Thatched Cottage</span></b> sheltered some of his gentlest work, including the poem in which, his own roof torn off by autumn wind, he wishes for a mansion of 10,000 rooms to shelter all the poor scholars of the world. Drifting down the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span>, he spent 766–768 above the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Gorges\">Three Gorges</span> at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Baidicheng\">Baidicheng</span> in his most prolific period, producing over 400 poems including the 8-poem cycle <i>Autumn Meditations</i>, before dying on a riverboat on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiang_River\">Xiang River</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hunan\">Hunan</span> at 58. <br> <br> About 1,400 of his poems survive, supreme above all in the 8-line <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Regulated_verse\">regulated verse</span></b>, whose paired couplets he charged with unprecedented density, while his old-style <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gushi_(poetry)\">gushi</span> ballads of conscripts, tax collectors, and partings earned him the title \"poet-historian.\" <i>Spring View</i>, written in occupied Chang'an, compresses the age into its opening—the state shattered, mountains and rivers remaining—and exemplifies the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> compassion for war, poverty, and duty that pervades his work, alongside self-mocking domestic humor and a craftsman's vow not to rest until his words startled. Strangely, contemporary anthologies largely ignored him, and his fame was built posthumously, beginning when <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_Zhen\">Yuan Zhen</span></b>'s epitaph of 813 ranked him even above Li Bai and completed when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song</span> editors and admirers such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Su_Shi\">Su Shi</span> canonized him as the model for all later poets. Schoolchildren still meet him through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Hundred_Tang_Poems\"><i>Three Hundred Tang Poems</i></span>, which includes more of his work than of any other writer's. Abroad, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kenneth_Rexroth\">Kenneth Rexroth</span></b> judged him among the greatest poets to survive in any language, the sinologist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stephen_Owen_(sinologist)\">Stephen Owen</span> published a complete English translation of nearly 3,000 pages <b>in 6 volumes in 2016</b>, and a 2020 BBC film presented by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Michael_Wood_(historian)\">Michael Wood</span> introduced him to new audiences simply as China's greatest poet.","citation":"","answerText":"Du Fu"},{"id":"cnc-067","num":"六十七","category":"China · Culture","question":"Shaped over millennia and elevated into an art by the Tang scholar Lu Yu in a classic treatise, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> surrounds the growing, preparation and ceremonial serving of tea with deep ritual and etiquette.","answer":"Chinese tea culture","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">茶文化 (chá wénhuà, 'tea culture')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"茶文化","pinyin":"chá wénhuà","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">chá wénhuà</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“tea culture”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Chinese tea culture</b> is the tradition surrounding the growing, preparation, and ceremonial serving of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tea\">tea</span> with deep ritual and etiquette, shaped over millennia in the plant's homeland and elevated into an art under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span>. <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Camellia_sinensis\">Camellia sinensis</span></b> grows wild in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yunnan\">Yunnan</span>, where some tea trees exceed 1,000 years of age, legend credits the herb-tasting <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shennong\">Shennong</span> with <b>discovering the leaf in 2737 BCE</b>, and archaeology found actual tea in the tomb of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han</span> ruler <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Jing_of_Han\">Emperor Jing</span>, who died in 141 BCE. The decisive elevation came from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lu_Yu_(sage_of_tea)\">Lu Yu</span>, whose <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Classic_of_Tea\"><i>Classic of Tea</i></span></b> of about 760, in 3 scrolls and 10 chapters cataloguing everything from water grades to a service of 24 implements, made tea a discipline of connoisseurship and earned its author deification as the sage of tea. Fashions then evolved by dynasty, the Tang boiling powdered cake-tea with a pinch of salt, while the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song</span> whisked powdered tea to a froth judged in competitions against the black glaze of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jian_ware\">Jian ware</span> bowls, an art so courtly that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Huizong_of_Song\">Emperor Huizong</span> himself wrote a <b>treatise on it in 1107</b> and whose whisked style fathered <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Matcha\">matcha</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japanese_tea_ceremony\">Japanese tea ceremony</span>. Modern steeping was born by decree, when the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hongwu_Emperor\">Hongwu Emperor</span> banned <b>labor-devouring tribute cakes in 1391</b>, turning China to loose leaf brewed in the lidded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gaiwan\">gaiwan</span> and the prized purple-clay <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yixing_clay_teapot\">Yixing teapot</span>. <br> <br> Connoisseurship now spans 6 classes by processing—green, white, yellow, oolong, black, and dark—crowned by famous leaves such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Longjing_tea\">Longjing</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tieguanyin\">Tieguanyin</span>, age-worthy <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pu'er_tea\">pu-erh</span>, and the cliff-grown <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Da_Hong_Pao\">Da Hong Pao</span>, 20 grams from whose mother bushes fetched 208,000 yuan at a 2002 auction. The most elaborate etiquette lives in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gongfu_tea_ceremony\">gongfu tea ceremony</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chaozhou\">Chaozhou</span></b>, tiny pots and cups refilled through many infusions, while in rites of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_marriage\">marriage</span> the couple's tea served kneeling to parents seals the union. Around the cup grew a public world, from the bamboo-chair teahouses of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chengdu\">Chengdu</span> where retirees idle over endless refills to the Beijing establishment immortalized when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lao_She\">Lao She</span> compressed half a century of Chinese history into his 1957 play <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Teahouse_(play)\"><i>Teahouse</i></span>. The leaf also moved history, bartered for war horses along the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tea_Horse_Road\">Tea Horse Road</span>, draining British silver until opium and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Opium_War\">First Opium War</span> answered, and finally stolen outright when <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Robert_Fortune\">Robert Fortune</span></b> smuggled plants and skills to India in 1848. China remains the leaf's superpower, producing over 3 million tonnes (3.3 million tons) a year, nearly half the world's tea, and in 2022 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"UNESCO\">UNESCO</span> inscribed its traditional tea processing and customs as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Intangible_cultural_heritage\">intangible cultural heritage</span>, formal honor for a civilization that learned, 12 centuries ago, to read its soul in a cup.","citation":"","answerText":"Chinese tea culture"},{"id":"cnc-070","num":"七十","category":"China · Culture","question":"Used to produce the world's earliest dated printed book — a copy of the Buddhist <i>Diamond Sutra</i> from <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> — the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> long preceded the movable type later devised by Bi Sheng.","answer":"Woodblock printing","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">雕版印刷 (diāobǎn yìnshuā, 'carved-block printing')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"雕版印刷","pinyin":"diāobǎn yìnshuā","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">diāobǎn yìnshuā</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“carved-block printing”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Woodblock printing</b> is the technique of carving text and images in relief on wooden blocks, inking the surface, and rubbing paper against it, the world's first true printing method and the dominant one in East Asia for a millennium before and after the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Movable_type\">movable type</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bi_Sheng\">Bi Sheng</span></b>. A fair copy on thin <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paper\">paper</span> was pasted face-down on a plank of pear or <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jujube\">jujube</span>, the blank wood cut away, and pages pulled with water-based <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Inkstick\">ink</span> and a dry brush, a practiced printer turning out 1,500 or more sheets a day from a single block. The earliest survivors are Buddhist charms of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span> era and its neighbors, including a dharani found at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bulguksa\">Bulguksa</span> in Korea printed before 751 and the 1 million miniature prayer <b>scrolls of Japan's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hyakumantō_Darani\">Hyakumantō Darani</span></b> of 764–770. The masterpiece is the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Diamond_Sutra\"><i>Diamond Sutra</i></span> dated 868, a 5-meter (16 ft) scroll of 7 sheets with a superb frontispiece, commissioned by one Wang Jie for free distribution, sealed in a cave at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dunhuang\">Dunhuang</span>, <b>removed by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Aurel_Stein\">Aurel Stein</span> in 1907</b>, and now in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"British_Library\">British Library</span>. Demand came from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Buddhism\">Buddhist</span> merit-making, from almanacs of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_calendar\">Chinese calendar</span> so profitable that <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Wenzong_of_Tang\">Emperor Wenzong</span></b> banned private printing of them in 835, and soon from the textual needs of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examinations</span>. <br> <br> Under state sponsorship the craft exploded, <b>the minister <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Feng_Dao\">Feng Dao</span></b> completing the first printed edition of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five_Classics\">Confucian classics</span> in 953, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song dynasty</span> cutting some 130,000 blocks by 983 for the first printed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Buddhist_canon\">Buddhist canon</span>, while commercial publishers drove book prices down by an order of magnitude. <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shen_Kuo\">Shen Kuo</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dream_Pool_Essays\"><i>Dream Pool Essays</i></span> describes Bi Sheng's clay movable type of the 1040s, yet for a script of thousands of characters whole-block carving remained cheaper and handsomer, and woodblock ruled Chinese publishing into the 19th century. The medium also became an art, yielding multi-block color printing, the auspicious New Year <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nianhua\">nianhua</span> pasted on village doors, and in Japan the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ukiyo-e\">ukiyo-e</span> school whose summit is <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hokusai\">Hokusai</span><b>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Great_Wave_off_Kanagawa\"><i>Great Wave</i></span> of about 1831</b>. Korea answered with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tripitaka_Koreana\">Tripitaka Koreana</span>, 81,258 blocks carved in the 13th century and still intact, and Europe's 15th-century <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Block_book\">block books</span> show the idea active in the West on the eve of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Johannes_Gutenberg\">Gutenberg</span>. Honored among China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Great_Inventions\">4 Great Inventions</span> as the root of printing, the craft was inscribed by <b>UNESCO as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Intangible_cultural_heritage\">intangible cultural heritage</span> in 2009</b> and is still practiced by master carvers today.","citation":"","answerText":"Woodblock printing"},{"id":"cnc-072","num":"七十二","category":"China · Culture","question":"A 2-stringed fiddle played with a bow whose hair passes between the strings, producing a plaintive, voice-like sound, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is a staple of Chinese opera orchestras and folk music, sometimes nicknamed the Chinese violin.","answer":"Erhu","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">二胡 (èrhú, 'two-stringed hu fiddle')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"二胡","pinyin":"èrhú","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">èrhú</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“two-stringed hu”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Erhu</b> is a <b>2-stringed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bowed_string_instrument\">bowed</span></b> fiddle, the most widespread member of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huqin\">huqin</span> family in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Music_of_China\">music of China</span> and often nicknamed the Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Violin\">violin</span> in the West. Its name joins the numeral for its pair of strings to the prefix <i>hu</i>, which anciently marked things borrowed from the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eurasian_nomads\">nomadic peoples</span> of the frontier</b>, and its ancestry is traced to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiqin_(instrument)\">xiqin</span>, a fiddle attributed to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kumo_Xi\">Xi people</span> and documented under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song dynasty</span> in the 11th century. The instrument consists of a slender neck bearing two tuning pegs but no <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fingerboard\">fingerboard</span>, set into a small hexagonal sound box of dense wood such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rosewood\">rosewood</span>, its face stretched with the skin of a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pythonidae\">python</span></b> upon which a tiny wooden <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bridge_(instrument)\">bridge</span> rests. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Horsehair\">horsehair</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bow_(music)\">bow</span>, coated with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rosin\">rosin</span>, passes permanently between the two strings, which are tuned a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Perfect_fifth\">perfect fifth</span></b> apart, customarily to D and A, so that the player sounds either string by pressing the hair against it from opposite sides. Because the strings are stopped by the fingers in mid-air rather than against a board, the instrument commands supple <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Portamento\">slides</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vibrato\">vibrato</span> across a range of three or more <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Octave\">octaves</span>, producing the plaintive, voice-like tone for which it is celebrated. <br> <br> In ensemble the fiddle is a staple of the orchestras of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_opera\">Chinese opera</span>, where its piercing cousin the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jinghu_(instrument)\">jinghu</span> leads <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peking_opera\">Peking opera</span> while the brighter <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gaohu\">gaohu</span> colours <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cantonese_opera\">Cantonese opera</span> in the south. It is equally at home in folk traditions, above all the silk-and-bamboo chamber music of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiangnan_sizhu\">Jiangnan sizhu</span></b> cultivated in teahouses of the lower <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span>, and in the modern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_orchestra\">Chinese orchestra</span>, where massed players joined by the deeper <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhonghu\">zhonghu</span> fill the role of a violin section. Its elevation into a solo concert instrument owes most to <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Tianhua\">Liu Tianhua</span></b>, a reformer teaching at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peking_University\">Peking University</span> in the 1920s, who introduced systematic technique and composed 10 solo works, among them <i>Birdsong in the Desolate Mountain</i>. Equally cherished is the legacy of the blind street musician <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Abing\">Abing</span>, whose haunting <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Erquan_Yingyue\"><i>Erquan Yingyue</i></span>, <b>recorded in 1950 shortly</b> before his death, has become the instrument's signature piece. Later virtuosi such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Min_Huifen\">Min Huifen</span> carried the repertoire to international stages, arrangements of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Butterfly_Lovers'_Violin_Concerto\"><i>Butterfly Lovers' Violin Concerto</i></span> now pass freely between erhu and violin, and since trade in python skin came under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"CITES\">CITES</span> regulation, makers in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> have increasingly fitted synthetic membranes to instruments destined for export.","citation":"","answerText":"Erhu"},{"id":"cng-076","num":"七十六","category":"China · Geography","question":"An ancient walled city in Shaanxi that, as Chang'an, served as the capital of many dynasties and the eastern terminus of the Silk Road, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is now famous for the nearby Terracotta Army.","answer":"Xi'an","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">西安 (Xī'ān, 'western peace')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"西安","pinyin":"Xī'ān","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Xī'ān</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Western Peace”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Xi'an</b> is the capital of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shaanxi\">Shaanxi</span>, a city of 12.95 million in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2020_Chinese_census\"><b>2020 census</b></span><b> set</b> in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guanzhong\">Guanzhong</span> basin of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wei_River\">Wei River</span>, which as Chang'an served 13 dynasties across some 1,100 years and ranks first among the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Historical_capitals_of_China\">great ancient capitals</span>. The royal lineage began nearby with the Zhou seat of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Haojing\">Haojing</span> in the 11th century BCE and the Qin court at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xianyang\">Xianyang</span> across the river, before the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span> <b>founded Chang'an proper in 202 BCE</b>, the eastern terminus from which <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk_Road\">Silk Road</span> caravans first set out in the 2nd century BCE. Under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sui_dynasty\">Sui</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span> the rebuilt grid city of 84 walled square kilometers and roughly a million residents was the largest metropolis on earth, governed from the vast <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Daming_Palace\">Daming Palace</span></b> and so cosmopolitan that the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nestorian_Stele\">Nestorian Stele</span> of 781 records a flourishing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Church_of_the_East\">Church of the East</span>. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Giant_Wild_Goose_Pagoda\">Big Wild Goose Pagoda</span>, raised in 652, housed the sutras that the monk <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xuanzang\">Xuanzang</span> carried back from India, travels later transfigured into the novel <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Journey_to_the_West\"><i>Journey to the West</i></span>. Even the city's prehistory runs deep, from the Neolithic village of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Banpo\">Banpo</span> on its outskirts to the far older fossils of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lantian_Man\">Lantian Man</span> in the county hills. <br> <br> Global fame <b>returned on 29 March 1974</b>, when farmers digging a well 35 kilometers (22 mi) east struck the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Terracotta_Army\">Terracotta Army</span>, an estimated 8,000 life-size soldiers with 130 chariots and 670 horses guarding the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mausoleum_of_Qin_Shi_Huang\">Mausoleum of Qin Shi Huang</span>, the unifier who died in 210 BCE, whose unopened tumulus, according to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Qian\">Sima Qian</span>, contains rivers of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mercury_(element)\">mercury</span>, a claim supported by soil readings, with the complex inscribed as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Heritage_Site\">World Heritage Site</span> in 1987. The living city is ringed by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fortifications_of_Xi'an\">fortifications</span> rebuilt by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span> in the 1370s, a 13.7-kilometer (8.51 mi) circuit 12 meters (39 ft) high that is the most complete ancient wall in China, centered on the 1384 <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bell_Tower_of_Xi'an\">Bell Tower</span></b>. Beside it the Muslim Quarter of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hui_people\">Hui</span> surrounds the courtyard <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Mosque_of_Xi'an\">Great Mosque</span>, traditionally dated to 742, and feeds pilgrims of another sort with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Roujiamo\">roujiamo</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Biangbiang_noodles\">biangbiang noodles</span></b>, whose name requires a 58-stroke character. History crowds the suburbs, from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huaqing_Pool\">Huaqing Pool</span> where the Tang emperor bathed with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yang_Guifei\">Yang Guifei</span>, and where in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi'an_Incident\">Xi'an Incident</span> of December 1936 the marshal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Xueliang\">Zhang Xueliang</span> kidnapped <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span> to force a united front against Japan, to the crypt of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Famen_Temple\">Famen Temple</span></b>, which in 1987 yielded a venerated finger-bone relic of the Buddha. Today the city builds aircraft and memory chips, educates tens of thousands at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi'an_Jiaotong_University\">Xi'an Jiaotong University</span>, and watches young visitors in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hanfu\">hanfu</span> promenade beneath Tang-style eaves, an ancient capital contentedly playing itself.","citation":"","answerText":"Xi'an"},{"id":"cnh-050","num":"五十","category":"China · History","question":"Launched in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> by a powerful frontier general of Sogdian and Turkic descent, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> nearly toppled the Tang, depopulated whole regions, and marked the beginning of the dynasty's long decline, a calamity mourned in the poetry of Du Fu.","answer":"An Lushan Rebellion","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">755–763 CE</span></div>","traditional":"安史之亂","hanzi":"安史之乱","pinyin":"Ān-Shǐ zhī luàn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Ān-Shǐ zhī luàn</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>An Lushan Rebellion</b> was a devastating <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Civil_war\">civil war</span></b> that convulsed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span> empire <b>from 755</b> to <b>763</b> and is reckoned the great turning point after which the once-glorious dynasty slid into permanent decline. It was launched by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"An_Lushan\">An Lushan</span>, a powerful frontier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiedushi\">military governor</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sogdia\">Sogdian</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Turkic_peoples\">Turkic</span></b> descent who as commander of 3 border regions led perhaps 150,000 troops, and who had risen high in the favour of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Xuanzong_of_Tang\">Emperor Xuanzong</span> and his beloved consort <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yang_Guifei\">Yang Guifei</span>. By then the aging Xuanzong had withdrawn from affairs, leaving power to chancellors such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Linfu\">Li Linfu</span> and the grasping <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yang_Guozhong\">Yang Guozhong</span></b>, whose rivalry with An Lushan, together with the dangerous concentration of troops in the frontier commands, set the stage for revolt. Rising at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fanyang\">Fanyang</span> near modern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> late in 755 on the pretext of purging Yang Guozhong, his rebel host swept south to seize the eastern capital <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luoyang\">Luoyang</span>, where he proclaimed himself emperor of a rival Yan dynasty, before pressing on to take the great capital <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chang'an\">Chang'an</span>. As the rebels neared, Xuanzong fled toward <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan\">Sichuan</span>, but at the Mawei post station his mutinous guards forced him to have Yang Guozhong killed and his cherished Yang Guifei strangled, a tragedy long retold in Chinese letters, after which the broken emperor abdicated in favour of his son <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Suzong_of_Tang\">Emperor Suzong</span>. <br> <br> Suzong rallied the loyalist cause, and with the generals <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guo_Ziyi\">Guo Ziyi</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Guangbi\">Li Guangbi</span> and the cavalry of the allied <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Uyghur_Khaganate\">Uyghur Khaganate</span> the Tang recaptured both capitals in 757, though the revolt dragged on under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shi_Siming\">Shi Siming</span>—after An Lushan was murdered by his own son <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"An_Qingxu\">An Qingxu</span>—until it was finally crushed in 763. The human cost was staggering, for the registered population recorded by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Census\">census</span> plummeted from around 53 million before the war to under 17 million afterward, a collapse that, however much it reflected lost records as well as death and flight, ranks the conflict among the most ruinous in all of human history. The Tang never recovered its former strength, as the frontier governors hardened into autonomous, often hereditary warlords—above all in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hebei\">Hebei</span>, which slipped almost wholly from imperial control—the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Equal-field_system\">equal-field</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fubing_system\">militia</span> systems disintegrated, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_Empire\">Tibetan Empire</span> overran the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Western_Regions\">Western Regions</span>, leaving the dynasty to limp through roughly 150 more years of decline before its final fall in 907. Beyond its political wreckage, the rebellion shattered the brilliant cosmopolitan civilization of the high Tang, scattering its artists and scholars—among them the wandering poet <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Bai\">Li Bai</span>—and casting a long shadow of loss over the flowering of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_poetry\">Tang poetry</span>. That sorrow found its most enduring voice in the verse of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Du_Fu\">Du Fu</span>, who lived through the upheaval and mourned its ruined cities and broken families in some of the most celebrated poems in the language, while the doomed love of Xuanzong and Yang Guifei was later immortalized by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bai_Juyi\">Bai Juyi</span> in his celebrated <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_of_Everlasting_Sorrow\"><i>Song of Everlasting Sorrow</i></span></b>.","citation":"","answerText":"An Lushan Rebellion"},{"id":"cnh-052","num":"五十二","category":"China · History","question":"Lasting from <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> to <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> after the final collapse of the Tang, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> saw 5 short-lived regimes rapidly succeed one another in the north while numerous kingdoms held the south, even as the Khitan rose on the frontier, until the land was reunified by the Song.","answer":"Five Dynasties and Ten Kingdoms","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">&lt;b&gt;907&lt;/b&gt;–&lt;b&gt;979&lt;/b&gt;</span></div>","traditional":"五代十國","hanzi":"五代十国","pinyin":"Wǔdài Shíguó","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Wǔdài Shíguó</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Five Dynasties and Ten Kingdoms</b> was an era of intense political fragmentation in China that followed the final disintegration of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang dynasty</span> and culminated in the reunification of the empire under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song dynasty</span>. The disorder stemmed from the entrenched power of regional military governors known as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiedushi\">jiedushi</span>, whose autonomy had steadily hollowed out central authority during the late Tang, and the period opened in 907 when the warlord <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_Wen\">Zhu Wen</span> deposed the last Tang ruler, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Ai_of_Tang\">Emperor Ai</span>, and proclaimed the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Later_Liang_(Five_Dynasties)\">Later Liang</span></b>. Across the north, five short-lived dynasties succeeded one another in rapid and frequently violent turnover, the Later Liang yielding to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shatuo\">Shatuo</span>-led <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Later_Tang\">Later Tang</span>, then to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Later_Jin_(Five_Dynasties)\">Later Jin</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Later_Han_(Five_Dynasties)\">Later Han</span>, and finally the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Later_Zhou\">Later Zhou</span></b>, together spanning barely five decades yet enthroning more than a dozen emperors. Most of these regimes governed from the strategic city of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kaifeng\">Kaifeng</span> on the North China Plain, but their hold on power was precarious, and in 938 the Later Jin founder <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shi_Jingtang\">Shi Jingtang</span> ceded the densely settled <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sixteen_Prefectures\">Sixteen Prefectures</span> surrounding the future Beijing to a steppe ally in return for military backing. That ally was the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khitan_people\">Khitan</span>, a steppe people whose chieftain <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Taizu_of_Liao\">Abaoji</span> had earlier forged the empire that would become known as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liao_dynasty\">Liao dynasty</span>, and these strategically vital lost lands would remain a festering grievance that even the later Song would try and fail to recover. <br> <br> While the north convulsed, the south and west fractured into a shifting array of regional states conventionally numbered as ten kingdoms, among them the wealthy <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Southern_Tang\">Southern Tang</span></b>, the prosperous coastal realm of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuyue\">Wuyue</span> centred on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hangzhou\">Hangzhou</span>, the successive Sichuan-based kingdoms of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Former_Shu\">Former Shu</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Later_Shu\">Later Shu</span>, and lesser powers such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Min_(Ten_Kingdoms)\">Min</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Southern_Han\">Southern Han</span>, and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chu_(Ten_Kingdoms)\">Chu</span></b>. Largely sheltered from the incessant warfare of the north, several of these southern courts enjoyed relative stability and grew into flourishing centres of commerce, agriculture, and the arts, with the Southern Tang ruler <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Yu_(Southern_Tang)\">Li Yu</span> celebrated as one of the supreme masters of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ci_(poetry)\">ci</span> lyric poetry, a song-form whose plaintive cadences he brought to new emotional depth. The age likewise produced enduring cultural and technological achievements, most famously the first state-sponsored printing of the Confucian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_classics\">classics</span> through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Woodblock_printing\">woodblock printing</span>, a monumental undertaking carried out between 932 and 953 under the minister <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Feng_Dao\">Feng Dao</span>, who held high office under several successive and rival dynasties and came to embody the era's fluid, opportunistic politics. The drive toward reunification gathered momentum under the reforming Later Zhou emperor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Shizong_of_Later_Zhou\">Chai Rong</span>, but it was <b>his general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Taizu_of_Song\">Zhao Kuangyin</span></b> who seized the throne in 960 to found the Song and then systematically absorbed the surviving kingdoms one after another. The long division finally closed in 979, when Song armies overran the Liao-protected <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Han\">Northern Han</span>, the last of the ten kingdoms and the only one rooted in the north, an outcome that ended more than seven decades of fragmentation and ushered in a centralised, examination-based imperial order destined to shape the remainder of China's dynastic history.","citation":"","answerText":"Five Dynasties and Ten Kingdoms"},{"id":"cnh-053","num":"五十三","category":"China · History","question":"A nomadic people of Manchuria and Mongolia who founded the Liao dynasty, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the likely origin of \"Cathay\", the old European word for China, before they were conquered by the rising Jurchens.","answer":"Khitan people","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">契丹 (Qìdān), the source of the name 'Cathay'</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"契丹","pinyin":"Qìdān","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Qìdān</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Khitan people</b> were a nomadic and seminomadic people who inhabited the grasslands of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchuria\">Manchuria</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Inner_Mongolia\">Inner Mongolia</span>, and the wider <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongolian_Plateau\">Mongolian Plateau</span></b>, centered on the valley of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liao_River\">Liao River</span>. Probably descended from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xianbei\">Xianbei</span> branch of the ancient <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Donghu_people\">Donghu</span> and closely related to the neighboring <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kumo_Xi\">Kumo Xi</span>, they first appear in Chinese sources under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Wei\">Northern Wei</span> in the 4th century CE and spoke the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Para-Mongolic_languages\">para-Mongolic</span> <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khitan_language\">Khitan language</span></b>, later recorded in distinctive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khitan_large_script\">large</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khitan_small_script\">small scripts</span> that remain only partly deciphered. Organized into a confederation of 8 tribes whose <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khan_(title)\">khan</span> was traditionally chosen every 3 years, they were welded into a centralized state by <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Taizu_of_Liao\">Yelü Abaoji</span></b>, who consolidated power from 907 and proclaimed himself emperor in 916, founding the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liao_dynasty\">Liao dynasty</span> that would rule for some 218 years. Expanding into northern China, the Liao seized the strategic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sixteen_Prefectures\">Sixteen Prefectures</span> ceded by the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Later_Jin_(Five_Dynasties)\">Later Jin</span></b> in 938 and governed their mixed realm through a pioneering dual administration that ruled nomads and settled <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">Chinese</span> subjects under separate systems. After decades of warfare with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song dynasty</span>, <b>the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Chanyuan\">Treaty of Chanyuan</span> in 1005</b> secured the Khitan an enormous annual tribute of 100,000 taels of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silver\">silver</span> and 200,000 bolts of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk\">silk</span>, underwriting a flourishing court culture and a devout <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Buddhism\">Buddhism</span> exemplified by the <b>great wooden <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pagoda_of_Fogong_Temple\">Pagoda of Fogong Temple</span> of 1056</b>. <br> <br> The Khitan name, transmitted westward across the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eurasian_Steppe\">Eurasian steppe</span> by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Turkic_peoples\">Turkic</span> and Mongol intermediaries, became the basis of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cathay\">Cathay</span>, the medieval European designation for northern China popularized by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marco_Polo\">Marco Polo</span>, and survives today in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russian_language\">Russian</span> word for the country. Khitan dominance was broken when their formerly subordinate <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jurchen_people\">Jurchen</span> vassals, united under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Taizu_of_Jin\">Wanyan Aguda</span>, rose in rebellion and <b>founded the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jin_dynasty_(1115–1234)\">Jin dynasty</span> in 1115</b>, overrunning the Liao within a decade and extinguishing it by 1125. A surviving prince, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yelü_Dashi\">Yelü Dashi</span>, led a remnant westward and established the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qara_Khitai\">Qara Khitai</span>, or Western Liao, which came to rule much of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Asia\">Central Asia</span> until it was absorbed into the expanding <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongol_Empire\">Mongol Empire</span> in 1218. That final Khitan polity fell after the Naiman usurper <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuchlug\">Kuchlug</span> seized its throne and was in turn crushed by the forces of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Genghis_Khan\">Genghis Khan</span>, after which the dispersed Khitan were gradually assimilated into surrounding populations. Many entered Mongol service as administrators and soldiers, while modern scholarship often identifies the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Daur_people\">Daur people</span> of northeastern China as their likeliest descendants, leaving the Khitan remembered as the founders of a durable steppe empire and the source of one of the oldest Western names for China.","citation":"","answerText":"Khitan people"},{"id":"cnh-055","num":"五十五","category":"China · History","question":"A leading general famously draped in the imperial yellow robe by his own troops in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> ended the era of disunion and then defused the threat of military coups by persuading his top commanders to retire \"over a cup of wine\", favouring civilian officials instead.","answer":"Emperor Taizu of Song","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">March 21, 927</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">November 14, 976</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"宋太祖","pinyin":"Sòng Tàizǔ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Sòng Tàizǔ</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Emperor Taizu of Song</b>, personal name <b>Zhao Kuangyin</b>, was the military commander who founded the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song dynasty</span> and reunified most of China after decades of political fragmentation. Born in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luoyang\">Luoyang</span> into a family of professional soldiers, he rose to high command in the army of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Later_Zhou\">Later Zhou</span></b>, the last of the northern regimes of the chaotic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five_Dynasties_and_Ten_Kingdoms_period\">Five Dynasties and Ten Kingdoms period</span>, and earned the trust of the able reformer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Shizong_of_Later_Zhou\">Emperor Shizong of Later Zhou</span>. When Shizong died in 959 and left the throne to his young son, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Gong_of_Later_Zhou\">Emperor Gong</span></b>, the senior officers engineered the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chenqiao_Mutiny\">Chenqiao Mutiny</span> in early 960, draping Zhao Kuangyin in the imperial yellow robe at a post station outside the capital and hailing him as emperor. He took power with comparatively little bloodshed, fixed his capital at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kaifeng\">Kaifeng</span>, and claimed the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mandate_of_Heaven\">Mandate of Heaven</span></b> for a new dynasty that would go on to rule China for more than 300 years. Resolved to end the cycle of usurpation that had brought down one short-lived regime after another in roughly half a century, he methodically subdued the surviving southern states, absorbing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jingnan\">Jingnan</span> in 963, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Later_Shu\">Later Shu</span> in 965, the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Southern_Han\">Southern Han</span></b> in 971, and the wealthy <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Southern_Tang\">Southern Tang</span> of the celebrated poet-ruler <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Yu_(Southern_Tang)\">Li Yu</span>, taken for him by the general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cao_Bin\">Cao Bin</span>, in 975. <br> <br> To stop his own commanders from one day repeating his <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Coup_d'état\">coup</span>, in 961 he is said to have gathered his leading generals, including <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shi_Shouxin\">Shi Shouxin</span></b>, at a banquet and persuaded them to give up their commands \"over a cup of wine\" in return for titles, estates, and a comfortable retirement. Guided by his chief <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Grand_chancellor_(China)\">chancellor</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhao_Pu\">Zhao Pu</span>, he stripped the regional military governors, or <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiedushi\">jiedushi</span>, of the autonomy that had shattered the late <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang dynasty</span>, concentrating the finest troops in a central palace army under direct imperial command. Reversing the militarism of the preceding age, he raised civilian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Scholar-official\">scholar-officials</span> above the generals, broadened the competitive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examinations</span> and the coveted <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jinshi\">jinshi</span> degree as the principal route to office, and was traditionally remembered for an ancestral pledge against executing officials and outspoken scholars. This civil emphasis, grounded in a revived <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucianism</span> that would later flower into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Neo-Confucianism\">Neo-Confucianism</span>, brought lasting domestic stability but left the dynasty strategically defensive, never recovering the vital <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sixteen_Prefectures\">Sixteen Prefectures</span></b> controlled by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liao_dynasty\">Khitan Liao</span> along the northern frontier. He died abruptly in 976 at the age of 49, amid later tales of fratricide known as the \"shadows of a candle and sound of an axe,\" and was succeeded not by a son but by his brother, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Taizong_of_Song\">Emperor Taizong</span></b>, who finished the reunification by absorbing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuyue\">Wuyue</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Han\">Northern Han</span>—a contested succession the official <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"History_of_Song\"><i>History of Song</i></span> would seek to legitimize through the disputed Golden Casket testament.","citation":"","answerText":"Emperor Taizu of Song"},{"id":"cnh-057","num":"五十七","category":"China · History","question":"Emerging among merchants in Sichuan during the Song and then taken over by the government, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> are regarded as the world's first paper money, made practical by advances in printing.","answer":"Jiaozi","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">交子 (jiāozǐ), an early note of exchange in Song Sichuan</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"交子","pinyin":"jiāozǐ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">jiāozǐ</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Jiaozi</b> were a <b>form of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Promissory_note\">promissory note</span></b> that circulated in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan\">Sichuan</span> region under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song dynasty</span> and are widely regarded as the world's first true <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Banknote\">paper money</span>. Their emergence was driven by the peculiar monetary conditions of Sichuan, where the authorities relied on bulky <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cash_(Chinese_coin)\">iron cash</span></b> rather than the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Copper\">copper</span> coinage used elsewhere, so that even modest purchases demanded strings of low-value coins weighing many kilograms and rendering large transactions impractical. To ease this burden, wealthy <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Merchant\">merchants</span></b> in the prosperous capital of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chengdu\">Chengdu</span> began around the turn of the 11th century to accept coin deposits and issue redeemable printed receipts, an innovation that echoed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span>-era remittance instruments known as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Flying_cash\">flying cash</span>. After private over-issue and disputes threatened confidence, the imperial government suppressed the merchant notes and assumed a monopoly during the reign of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Renzong_of_Song\">Emperor Renzong</span>, establishing a state Bureau of Exchange Notes at Chengdu that printed official jiaozi <b>from 1024</b>. Their production was made practical by the maturity of Song <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Woodblock_printing\">woodblock printing</span>, alongside the contemporaneous invention of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Movable_type\">movable type</span> by the artisan <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bi_Sheng\">Bi Sheng</span>, with intricately engraved plates and multiple colors used to frustrate <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Counterfeit_money\">counterfeiting</span></b>. <br> <br> The official notes were issued in fixed multi-year series and were in principle convertible into coin, backed by a cash reserve that for the first government issue is recorded at roughly 360,000 strings against an authorized circulation of about 1.26 million strings, a reserve ratio of roughly 28 percent. Over the following century the system spread and evolved, giving rise to successor instruments such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huizi_(currency)\">huizi</span> of the Southern Song and parallel issues by the rival <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jin_dynasty_(1115–1234)\">Jin dynasty</span> to the north, as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_the_Song_dynasty\">Song commercial expansion</span></b> increasingly relied on credit and circulating notes. The model reached its fullest development under the Mongol <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan dynasty</span>, when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kublai_Khan\">Kublai Khan</span> made paper currency the principal legal tender across his empire, a system the Venetian traveler <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marco_Polo\">Marco Polo</span> marveled at and recorded for European readers in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Travels_of_Marco_Polo\"><i>The Travels of Marco Polo</i></span>. Yet the temptation to print beyond reserves repeatedly undermined these currencies, producing bouts of severe <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Inflation\">inflation</span> as notes lost their convertibility and drifted toward an unbacked, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fiat_money\">fiat</span> status, a pattern that recurred under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming dynasty</span> before paper money was largely abandoned in favor of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silver\">silver</span>. As the earliest documented government-issued banknotes, jiaozi mark a milestone in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Numismatics\">numismatics</span> and in the <b>wider history of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Money\">money</span></b>, demonstrating how innovations in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Printing\">printing</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Credit_(finance)\">credit</span> could transform a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Medium_of_exchange\">medium of exchange</span> centuries before comparable notes appeared in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Europe\">Europe</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Jiaozi"},{"id":"cnh-058","num":"五十八","category":"China · History","question":"A state founded in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> by the Tangut people in the arid north-west astride the Silk Road, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> developed its own complex script and held off its neighbours for nearly 2 centuries before being annihilated by the Mongols.","answer":"Western Xia","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">西夏 (Xī Xià, 'Western Xia'), as named in Chinese sources</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"西夏","pinyin":"Xī Xià","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Xī Xià</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Western Xia</b> was an empire <b>proclaimed in 1038</b> along the arid frontiers of north-western China by the Tangut, a people speaking a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-Tibetan_languages\">Sino-Tibetan</span></b> tongue and descended from the nomadic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qiang_(historical_people)\">Qiang</span>. Its ruling house, the Tuoba clan, had migrated from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ordos_Plateau\">Ordos</span> region and accumulated power over generations, receiving the imperial surname Li from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang dynasty</span> before the warlord <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Jiqian\">Li Jiqian</span> wrested effective autonomy from the Chinese court, a foundation upon which his grandson <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Yuanhao\">Li Yuanhao</span> declared himself emperor. Two years before that proclamation, <b>in 1036</b>, Li Yuanhao had promulgated a distinctive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tangut_script\">Tangut script</span>, a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Logogram\">logographic</span> system of roughly 6,000 characters that, though superficially resembling <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_characters\">Chinese characters</span>, was structurally independent and used to render the now-extinct <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tangut_language\">Tangut language</span>. From its capital at Zhongxing, on the site of modern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yinchuan\">Yinchuan</span> in present-day <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ningxia\">Ningxia</span>, the kingdom governed a population estimated at some 3 million and grew wealthy by taxing the caravans that crossed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hexi_Corridor\">Hexi Corridor</span> through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gansu\">Gansu</span>, where <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Buddhism\">Buddhism</span>—much of it inflected by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_Buddhism\">Tibetan</span> traditions—flourished alongside a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> bureaucracy. Surrounded by powerful rivals, the Tanguts survived for generations by playing the Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song dynasty</span> against the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khitan_people\">Khitan</span>-led <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liao_dynasty\">Liao dynasty</span> and, later, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jurchen_people\">Jurchen</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jin_dynasty_(1115–1234)\">Jin dynasty</span>, extracting lavish annual subsidies of silver, silk, and tea from the Song after a series of border wars culminating in the peace settlement of 1044.<br> <br>At its height the realm spanned roughly 800,000 square kilometres (310,000 sq mi) of desert, steppe, and oasis, and across nearly 2 centuries it was governed by a line of ten emperors who poured resources into Buddhist temples and into a monumental <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Western_Xia_Imperial_Tombs\">imperial necropolis</span></b>—nine great mausoleums and roughly 250 lesser tombs spread over some 50 square kilometres (19 sq mi) at the foot of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Helan_Mountains\">Helan Mountains</span>—that modern observers have likened to the pyramids of Egypt. This long equilibrium was shattered by the rise of the Mongols under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Genghis_Khan\">Genghis Khan</span>, whose forces first raided the kingdom in 1205 and, in the campaign of 1209–1210, besieged Zhongxing and attempted to inundate it by diverting the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_River\">Yellow River</span>, compelling the Tangut court to accept vassalage. When the Tangut ruler subsequently refused to supply troops for the Mongol war against the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khwarazmian_Empire\">Khwarazmian Empire</span></b> in 1219, Genghis Khan resolved to destroy the kingdom outright, and a final campaign <b>extinguished Western Xia in 1227</b>—the very year of the conqueror's own death—amid the sack of its cities and the slaughter of much of its people. Because the conquering <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan dynasty</span> compiled no separate dynastic chronicle for the Tanguts among the official <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Twenty-Four_Histories\">Twenty-Four Histories</span>, and because their cities lay ruined and their script gradually fell silent, the civilization was nearly erased from memory, its language surviving only in scattered relics such as Buddhist inscriptions carved as late as 1502. The empire was recovered for scholarship largely by chance, when the <b>Russian explorer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pyotr_Kozlov\">Pyotr Kozlov</span></b> excavated the abandoned fortress-city of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khara-Khoto\">Khara-Khoto</span> in 1908–1909 and unearthed thousands of manuscripts, a trove soon supplemented by the explorations of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Aurel_Stein\">Aurel Stein</span> and decoded by orientalists such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nikolai_Nevsky\">Nikolai Nevsky</span>, whose patient reconstruction of the lost tongue laid the foundations of modern Tangut studies.","citation":"","answerText":"Western Xia"},{"id":"cnh-060","num":"六十","category":"China · History","question":"A semi-nomadic people of the north-eastern forests who founded the Jin dynasty and sacked the Northern Song capital, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> found the dynasty that ruled China into the 20th century.","answer":"Jurchen people","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">女真 (Nǚzhēn), a transcription of 'Jurchen'</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"女真","pinyin":"Nǚzhēn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Nǚzhēn</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Jurchen people</b> were a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tungusic_peoples\">Tungusic</span></b>-speaking, semi-nomadic people of the forests, rivers, and mountains of northeastern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchuria\">Manchuria</span> who lived by hunting, fishing, farming, and horse-breeding. Tracing their roots to the ancient <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sushen\">Sushen</span></b> recorded in Chinese texts as early as the 1st millennium BCE and more directly to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mohe_people\">Mohe</span> tribes who had built the kingdom of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Balhae\">Balhae</span>, they emerged as a distinct group around the 10th century while subject to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khitan_people\">Khitan</span> rulers of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liao_dynasty\">Liao dynasty</span>. In the early 12th century the chieftain <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Taizu_of_Jin\">Wanyan Aguda</span></b> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wanyan\">Wanyan</span> clan united the Jurchen tribes, rebelled against Liao overlordship, and <b>founded the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jin_dynasty_(1115–1234)\">Jin dynasty</span> in 1115</b>, naming it with the Chinese word for gold. Within a decade his armies had annihilated the Liao, and in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jingkang_Incident\">Jingkang Incident</span> of 1127 they stormed and sacked <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kaifeng\">Kaifeng</span>, the capital of the Northern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song</span>, carrying off the captured emperors <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Huizong_of_Song\">Huizong</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Qinzong_of_Song\">Qinzong</span> into northern captivity. The surviving Song court fled south to establish a rump regime at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hangzhou\">Hangzhou</span>, while the Jin ruled northern China for over a century, devising their own <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jurchen_script\">script</span> and growing steadily <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sinicization\">sinicized</span> before the dynasty was destroyed <b>by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongol_Empire\">Mongols</span> in 1234</b>. <br> <br> After the fall of the Jin, the Jurchen fragmented for centuries until the chieftain <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nurhaci\">Nurhaci</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Aisin_Gioro\">Aisin Gioro</span> clan reunited the tribes, organized them into the formidable <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight_Banners\">Eight Banners</span>, and proclaimed a <b>revived <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Later_Jin_(1616–1636)\">Later Jin</span> state in 1616</b>. His son <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Taiji\">Hong Taiji</span> renamed the people <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_people\">Manchu</span> in 1635 and the following year redesignated the dynasty the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span>, deliberately discarding the older Jurchen identity in favor of a broader imperial one. When the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming dynasty</span> collapsed amid rebellion and the rebel <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Zicheng\">Li Zicheng</span> seized Beijing, the Manchus were admitted through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanhai_Pass\">Shanhai Pass</span> in 1644 and, under the regent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dorgon\">Dorgon</span>, occupied <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> to begin their conquest of China. As a small ruling minority governing a vast Han majority, the Qing expanded to its greatest territorial extent and endured until the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinhai_Revolution\">Xinhai Revolution</span>, when the child emperor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Puyi\">Puyi</span> abdicated in 1912, ending more than 2,000 years of imperial rule. The Jurchen language survived as the ancestor of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_language\">Manchu language</span></b>, and the people themselves persist today as the officially recognized Manchu nationality, leaving these forest tribes of the northeast remembered as the founders of both the Jin and, in their Manchu guise, the Qing, among the most powerful conquest dynasties in Chinese history.","citation":"","answerText":"Jurchen people"},{"id":"cnc-050","num":"五十","category":"China · Culture","question":"A patriotic shorthand celebrated for China's contributions to world civilisation, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> comprises papermaking, gunpowder, the compass and printing.","answer":"Four Great Inventions","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">四大发明 ('four great inventions')</span></div>","traditional":"四大發明","hanzi":"四大发明","pinyin":"sìdà fāmíng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">sìdà fāmíng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Four Great Inventions</b> is a patriotic shorthand celebrating four contributions of ancient <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> to world civilisation: <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Papermaking\">papermaking</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Printing\">printing</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gunpowder\">gunpowder</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Compass\">compass</span>. The <b>making of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paper\">paper</span></b> is traditionally credited to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han</span> court eunuch <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cai_Lun\">Cai Lun</span>, who in 105 CE presented an improved process using bark, hemp, and rags, though archaeologists have recovered still earlier specimens, including a paper map from a tomb at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fangmatan\">Fangmatan</span> dating to the 2nd century BCE. Printing matured under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span>, whose <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Woodblock_printing\">woodblock</span> craft produced the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Diamond_Sutra\"><i>Diamond Sutra</i></span> of 868, the world's earliest dated printed book, before the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song</span> artisan <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bi_Sheng\">Bi Sheng</span> devised ceramic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Movable_type\">movable type</span> around the 1040s, a technique refined in <b>wood by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Zhen_(inventor)\">Wang Zhen</span> about 1298</b> and in metal in Korea, where the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jikji\"><i>Jikji</i></span> of 1377 survives. Gunpowder emerged from the elixir experiments of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_alchemy\">Chinese alchemy</span> in the 9th century, and its earliest recorded formulas of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Potassium_nitrate\">saltpetre</span>, sulphur, and charcoal appear in the <b>military compendium <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wujing_Zongyao\"><i>Wujing Zongyao</i></span> of 1044</b>, by which time the mixture was already arming <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fire_lance\">fire lances</span>, bombs, and rockets. The compass evolved from Han <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lodestone\">lodestone</span> divination into the magnetised needle described by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shen_Kuo\">Shen Kuo</span> <b>in his <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dream_Pool_Essays\"><i>Dream Pool Essays</i></span> of 1088</b>, and by 1119 the writer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_Yu_(author)\">Zhu Yu</span> recorded its use aboard ships sailing from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou\">Guangzhou</span>, a decisive advance for long-range <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Navigation\">navigation</span>. <br> <br> The grouping itself descends from European admiration, for <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Francis_Bacon\">Francis Bacon</span></b> observed in his <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Novum_Organum\"><i>Novum Organum</i></span> of 1620 that printing, gunpowder, and the magnet had changed the whole face of the world, unaware of their Chinese origins, a judgement later echoed by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Karl_Marx\">Karl Marx</span>. Paper was joined to Bacon's three by scholars building on the reports of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jesuit_China_missions\">Jesuit missions</span>, and the four-fold canon was cemented in the 20th century, above all through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joseph_Needham\">Joseph Needham</span> and his monumental <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Science_and_Civilisation_in_China\"><i>Science and Civilisation in China</i></span></b>. Westward transmission ran along the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk_Road\">Silk Road</span> and through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongol_Empire\">Mongol Empire</span>, papermaking reaching the Islamic world after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Talas\">Battle of Talas</span> in 751, gunpowder arriving in Europe by the 13th century, and the needle guiding the mariners of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Age_of_Discovery\">Age of Discovery</span>. Abroad these seeds bore famous fruit, most visibly the press of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Johannes_Gutenberg\">Johannes Gutenberg</span> in the 1450s, while at home the four became fixtures of schoolbooks and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_nationalism\">national pride</span>, dramatised before a worldwide audience at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2008_Summer_Olympics_opening_ceremony\">2008 Summer Olympics opening ceremony</span></b>. Historians caution that the formula obscures a far longer roll of achievements, from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk\">silk</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Porcelain\">porcelain</span> to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cast_iron\">cast iron</span>, recorded in the sprawling <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"List_of_Chinese_inventions\">list of Chinese inventions</span>, yet the quartet endures as the most familiar emblem of the country's inventive genius.","citation":"","answerText":"Four Great Inventions"},{"id":"cnc-061","num":"六十一","category":"China · Culture","question":"Achieving such refinement that fine white porcelain became known in the West simply as \"china\", the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> reached famous heights with celadon glazes and the cobalt blue-and-white wares produced at the kilns of Jingdezhen and exported along the trade routes.","answer":"Chinese ceramics","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">陶瓷 (táocí, 'pottery and porcelain')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"陶瓷","pinyin":"táocí, \"pottery and porcelain\"","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">táocí, \"pottery and porcelain\"</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Chinese ceramics</b> constitute a craft of such antiquity and refinement that fine white <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Porcelain\">porcelain</span></b> became known in the West simply as \"china,\" and the tradition begins astonishingly early, with shards from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xianrendong_Cave\">Xianrendong Cave</span> dated to about 18,000 BCE, the oldest pottery yet found anywhere. <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Neolithic\">Neolithic</span> villagers of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangshao_culture\">Yangshao culture</span> painted bold spirals on burial urns, while the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Longshan_culture\">Longshan culture</span></b> threw black \"eggshell\" goblets with walls scarcely 1 millimeter thick. True porcelain, fired from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kaolinite\">kaolin</span> clays at around 1,300 degrees Celsius (2,372 °F), emerged in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhejiang\">Zhejiang</span> by the late <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span> in the 2nd century CE, and under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span> the palette ran from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sancai\">sancai</span> tomb glazes to trade bowls, some 60,000 of which sank with a single Arab dhow, the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Belitung_shipwreck\">Belitung shipwreck</span></b>, around 830. Connoisseurs crown the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song dynasty</span> the classic age, when the 5 great kilns produced the ivory <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ding_ware\">Ding</span>, flambé <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jun_ware\">Jun</span>, and sky-blue <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ru_ware\">Ru</span> wares, of which fewer than 100 complete Ru pieces survive, alongside the jade-green <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Celadon\">celadons</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Longquan_celadon\">Longquan</span>. <b>In 1004</b> an obscure river town took the reign-name of the era as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jingdezhen\">Jingdezhen</span>, beginning its 1,000-year career as the porcelain capital of the world. <br> <br> Under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan dynasty</span>, Persian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cobalt\">cobalt</span> painted under the glaze created <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Blue_and_white_pottery\">blue-and-white</span> porcelain, <b>mature by 1351</b>, the year inscribed on the celebrated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"David_Vases\">David Vases</span>. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming dynasty</span> installed imperial kilns at Jingdezhen, whose reign-marked masterpieces set standards still unmatched, while <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kraak_ware\">kraak</span> export ware sailed west in Portuguese and then Dutch hulls, the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dutch_East_India_Company\">Dutch East India Company</span></b> alone shipping over 30 million pieces during the 17th century along the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maritime_Silk_Road\">maritime silk road</span>. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> kilns of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kangxi_Emperor\">Kangxi Emperor</span> and his successors added the enamelled palettes of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Famille_rose\">famille rose</span>, and Europe's hunger turned to espionage, the Jesuit <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"François_Xavier_d'Entrecolles\">François Xavier d'Entrecolles</span> mailing home <b>detailed kiln secrets in 1712</b>, shortly after <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Meissen_porcelain\">Meissen</span> had fired Europe's first true porcelain in 1710. Imperial wares now dominate the art market, a tiny Ming <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chicken_cup\">chicken cup</span> bringing 36 million US dollars at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sotheby's\">Sotheby's</span> in 2014. Jingdezhen still employs tens of thousands of potters, and the everyday English word for tableware quietly commemorates the country that taught the world to make it.","citation":"","answerText":"Chinese ceramics"},{"id":"cnc-068","num":"六十八","category":"China · Culture","question":"Using only black ink in varied dilutions applied with a brush, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> — sharing tools and aesthetics with calligraphy — sought to capture the spirit rather than the mere likeness of landscapes, bamboo and birds, flourishing under the Song dynasty.","answer":"Ink wash painting","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">水墨画 (shuǐmòhuà, 'water-and-ink painting')</span></div>","traditional":"水墨畫","hanzi":"水墨画","pinyin":"shuǐmòhuà","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">shuǐmòhuà</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“water-and-ink painting”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Ink wash painting</b> is an East Asian style of brush painting that uses black <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ink\">ink</span> in varied dilutions to model form, tone, and atmosphere. It is created with the same <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Treasures_of_the_Study\">Four Treasures of the Study</span></b> as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_calligraphy\">calligraphy</span> — the supple <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ink_brush\">brush</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Inkstick\">inkstick</span> ground upon an <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Inkstone\">inkstone</span></b>, and absorbent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xuan_paper\">paper</span> or <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk\">silk</span> — so that the two arts share a common vocabulary of expressive line. Its guiding ambition, articulated as early as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Six_principles_of_Chinese_painting\">six principles</span></b> set down by the critic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xie_He_(painter)\">Xie He</span>, was to seize the living spirit or breath of a subject rather than its mere outward likeness. Favoured subjects accordingly carried symbolic weight, from sweeping <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shan_shui\">landscapes</span> and the noble <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Gentlemen\">bamboo and plum</span></b> to studies of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bird-and-flower_painting\">birds and flowers</span>, each rendered with economy and an eloquent use of empty space. Such restraint resonated with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Taoist</span> reverence for nature and the spontaneity prized by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chan_Buddhism\">Chan Buddhism</span>, lending the finest works an air of meditative suggestion. <br> <br> The monochrome manner took shape under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span>, when the poet-painter <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Wei_(Tang_dynasty)\">Wang Wei</span> was later honoured as a founder of pure ink landscape. It reached its first great flowering under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song</span>, the towering Northern Song landscapes of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fan_Kuan\">Fan Kuan</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guo_Xi\">Guo Xi</span> yielding to the misty, asymmetric “one-corner” compositions of the Southern Song masters <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ma_Yuan_(painter)\">Ma Yuan</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xia_Gui\">Xia Gui</span>. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Scholar-official\">scholar-official</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Su_Shi\">Su Shi</span> championed an amateur ideal that prized painting as personal expression akin to poetry, while the eccentric <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liang_Kai\">Liang Kai</span> pared his Chan-inspired figures down to a few abbreviated, spontaneous strokes. Under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan</span> the literati style triumphed in the hands of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Masters_of_the_Yuan_dynasty\">Four Masters</span></b>, among them <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huang_Gongwang\">Huang Gongwang</span>, whose handscroll <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dwelling_in_the_Fuchun_Mountains\"><i>Dwelling in the Fuchun Mountains</i></span> is counted among the supreme achievements of Chinese art. Later individualists such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bada_Shanren\">Bada Shanren</span> pushed the idiom toward terse abstraction, and the art spread across East Asia as Korean <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Korean_painting\">ink painting</span></b> and the Japanese tradition perfected by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sesshū_Tōyō\">Sesshū Tōyō</span>, remaining to this day a defining art form of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Ink wash painting"},{"id":"cnc-069","num":"六十九","category":"China · Culture","question":"Stumbled upon by Taoist alchemists seeking an elixir of immortality, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was first used for fireworks and later for early firearms and bombs under the Song.","answer":"gunpowder","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">火药 (huǒyào, 'fire medicine'), from alchemists' elixir experiments</span></div>","traditional":"火藥","hanzi":"火药","pinyin":"huǒyào","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">huǒyào</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“fire medicine”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Gunpowder</b> is an <b>explosive mixture of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Potassium_nitrate\">saltpetre</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sulfur\">sulphur</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Charcoal\">charcoal</span>, classically combined in proportions near 75, 10, and 15 percent, and the first chemical explosive known to humanity. It was stumbled upon in 9th-century <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span> China by adepts of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Taoist</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_alchemy\">alchemy</span> searching for an <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Elixir_of_life\">elixir of immortality</span>, and a treatise of about 850 preserved in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Daozang\">Taoist canon</span> already warned that mixing these ingredients had singed beards and burned down houses. Military men soon harnessed the discovery, fitting incendiary packets to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fire_arrow\">fire arrows</span> by 904 and devising the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fire_lance\">fire lance</span></b>, a spear-mounted flame tube depicted on a silk banner from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dunhuang\">Dunhuang</span> around 950. The earliest surviving formulas appear <b>in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wujing_Zongyao\"><i>Wujing Zongyao</i></span> of 1044</b>, a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song</span> military compendium giving three low-nitrate recipes for incendiaries, and as nitrate content rose the mixture turned truly explosive, thunderclap bombs helping repel invaders <b>at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Caishi\">Battle of Caishi</span> in 1161</b>. Iron-cased <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Thunder_crash_bomb\">thunder crash bombs</span> traded between the Song, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jin_dynasty_(1115–1234)\">Jin</span>, and the Mongols devastated defenders <b>at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongol_siege_of_Kaifeng\">siege of Kaifeng</span> in 1232</b>, while the evolution of the fire lance into the metal-barrelled <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hand_cannon\">hand cannon</span> is attested by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heilongjiang_hand_cannon\">Heilongjiang specimen</span> of 1288, among the oldest guns in existence. <br> <br> The mature arsenal was catalogued in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huolongjing\"><i>Huolongjing</i></span>, a 14th-century compendium associated with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiao_Yu\">Jiao Yu</span> that describes <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Land_mine\">land mines</span>, naval mines, multistage <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rocket\">rockets</span>, and exploding cannonballs. Knowledge of the powder travelled with the conquests of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongol_Empire\">Mongol Empire</span>, whose forces hurled ceramic bombs during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongol_invasions_of_Japan\">invasions of Japan</span> in 1274 and 1281, while the Syrian writer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hasan_al-Rammah\">Hasan al-Rammah</span> recorded over a hundred recipes for the Islamic world around 1280. In Europe the friar <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Roger_Bacon\">Roger Bacon</span> described the marvel by 1267, the first true <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cannon\">cannon</span></b> appear in illustrations of the 1320s, and English guns saw service at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Crécy\">Battle of Crécy</span> in 1346, opening the long transformation of Western warfare. At home the powder filled peaceful uses as well, supplanting the burning <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bamboo\">bamboo</span> of antiquity with the paper <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Firecracker\">firecracker</span> and elaborate <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fireworks\">fireworks</span> that still mark <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_New_Year\">Chinese New Year</span>, and securing its place among the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Great_Inventions\">Four Great Inventions</span>. Black powder reigned on battlefields for some <b>9 centuries until <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Smokeless_powder\">smokeless powder</span></b> displaced it in the 1880s, yet it endures in pyrotechnics, fuses, and ceremonial salutes, the most consequential chemical discovery to issue from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"gunpowder"},{"id":"cnc-071","num":"七十一","category":"China · Culture","question":"Famed for balancing flavour, aroma, colour and texture and for techniques like stir-frying in a wok, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> spans many regional styles and is eaten with chopsticks across the world.","answer":"Chinese cuisine","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">中国菜 (Zhōngguó cài, 'Chinese dishes')</span></div>","traditional":"中國菜","hanzi":"中国菜","pinyin":"Zhōngguó cài","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōngguó cài</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Chinese cuisine</b> is the culinary tradition of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>, famed for judging every dish by the union of colour, aroma, and flavour together with texture, and for structuring the meal around a grain staple attended by accompanying dishes. Its prestige is ancient, the legendary cook <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yi_Yin\">Yi Yin</span></b> rising to minister by likening statecraft to seasoning, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucius\">Confucius</span> voicing exacting standards at table, new crops arriving along the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk_Road\">Silk Road</span> under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han</span>, and the cities of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song</span>, above all <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hangzhou\">Hangzhou</span>, nurturing what historians count among the world's first true <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Restaurant\">restaurants</span></b>. Technique centres on the command of fire, from lightning-fast <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stir_frying\">stir-frying</span> in the round-bottomed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wok\">wok</span>, prized for the smoky “breath” it imparts, to gentle <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Steaming\">steaming</span>, the slow <b>soy braise of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Red_cooking\">red cooking</span></b>, and virtuoso knife work that cuts every ingredient to match its cooking time. The pantry divides broadly between the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rice\">rice</span> of the south and the wheaten north of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Noodle\">noodles</span>, steamed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mantou\">mantou</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiaozi\">jiaozi</span>, <b>united by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soy_sauce\">soy sauce</span></b>, black vinegars, fermented pastes, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tea\">tea</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tofu\">tofu</span>, whose invention legend assigns to the Han prince <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_An\">Liu An</span>. Underlying it all runs a dietetic philosophy of the 5 flavours and <b>of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_food_therapy\">food therapy</span></b>, balancing heating and cooling foods according to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yin_and_yang\">yin and yang</span>. <br> <br> Convention maps the tradition into 8 great regional schools, the cuisines of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shandong_cuisine\">Shandong</span>, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan_cuisine\">Sichuan</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cantonese_cuisine\">Canton</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiangsu_cuisine\">Jiangsu</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhejiang_cuisine\">Zhejiang</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fujian_cuisine\">Fujian</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hunan_cuisine\">Hunan</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anhui_cuisine\">Anhui</span>. Their temperaments diverge sharply, Sichuan's numbing-hot málà marrying the native <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan_pepper\">Sichuan pepper</span> to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chili_pepper\">chili</span> that reached China through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Columbian_exchange\">Columbian exchange</span> in the 16th century, while Canton prizes pristine freshness and the teahouse parade of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dim_sum\">dim sum</span>. Certain creations have become national emblems, lacquered <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peking_duck\">Peking duck</span> carved tableside, the soup-filled <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiaolongbao\">xiaolongbao</span> of the Yangtze delta, and the convivial bubbling <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hot_pot\">hot pot</span> shared in every province. Eaten with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chopsticks\">chopsticks</span> and carried abroad by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Overseas_Chinese\">overseas Chinese</span>, the cuisine now counts hundreds of thousands of restaurants worldwide, the roughly 45,000 in the United States alone outnumbering the largest burger chains combined and begetting an <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"American_Chinese_cuisine\">American Chinese</span></b> offshoot famous for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"General_Tso's_chicken\">General Tso's chicken</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fortune_cookie\">fortune cookie</span>. Having long seasoned the kitchens of its neighbours across the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"East_Asian_cultural_sphere\">East Asian cultural sphere</span>, it stands today, by most reckonings, among the 2 or 3 most widely eaten cuisines on earth.","citation":"","answerText":"Chinese cuisine"},{"id":"cnc-073","num":"七十三","category":"China · Culture","question":"A lyric verse form with lines of irregular length set to fixed musical tunes, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> reached its height under the Song dynasty in the hands of writers such as Li Qingzhao and Su Shi.","answer":"Ci","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">词 (cí, 'song lyric')</span></div>","traditional":"詞","hanzi":"词","pinyin":"cí, \"song lyric\"","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">cí, \"song lyric\"</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Ci</b> is a Chinese lyric verse form with lines of irregular length composed to fixed musical tunes, which rose from entertainment song to high art and reached its summit under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song dynasty</span>. A poet did not invent a stanza but \"filled in\" a named tune pattern or <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cipai\">cipai</span>, each prescribing line lengths, tones, and rhymes, and <b>the imperial register of 1715</b> catalogued 826 such tunes in 2,306 variant forms, a prosody far more intricate than the even lines of classical <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shi_(poetry)\">shi</span>. The genre began among the singing girls and banquet music of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span>, nourished by Central Asian melodies from oasis kingdoms like <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kucha\">Kucha</span>, and manuscripts from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dunhuang\">Dunhuang</span> preserve some 500 anonymous popular lyrics, while <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wen_Tingyun\">Wen Tingyun</span> in the 9th century made the boudoir lyric a literati craft gathered in the 940 anthology <i>Huajian ji</i>. Its first tragic master was <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Yu_(Southern_Tang)\">Li Yu</span></b>, last ruler of the Southern Tang, whose captive laments asking how much sorrow a man can hold turned the form toward the soul. In the pleasure quarters of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kaifeng\">Kaifeng</span> the Northern Song perfected it, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Yong_(poet)\">Liu Yong</span></b> writing long lyrics sung, it was said, wherever there was well water, the statesman <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ouyang_Xiu\">Ouyang Xiu</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yan_Shu\">Yan Shu</span> polishing the short form, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Su_Shi\">Su Shi</span> bursting its romantic bounds with his \"heroic abandon\" on history and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mid-Autumn_Festival\">Mid-Autumn</span> moon, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Bangyan\">Zhou Bangyan</span> refining its music. <br> <br> The form's supreme woman poet, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Qingzhao\">Li Qingzhao</span> (<b>1084–1155</b>), defended the lyric as a separate discipline in her essay \"On Ci\" and distilled the delicate-restraint style, her late masterpiece piling doubled syllables of searching and asking how the single word \"sorrow\" could suffice. Her life was broken <b>by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jingkang_incident\">Jingkang catastrophe</span> of 1127</b>, when the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jin_dynasty_(1115–1234)\">Jin</span> seized the north, and the Southern Song lyric turned patriotic in the 629 surviving ci of the swordsman-poet <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xin_Qiji\">Xin Qiji</span> and the verse of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lu_You\">Lu You</span>, while the composer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Kui\">Jiang Kui</span> left <b>17 tunes in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gongche_notation\">gongche notation</span></b>, the only Song ci whose actual music survives. Under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan</span> the livelier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sanqu\">sanqu</span> displaced it on stage, but <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> scholars revived and canonized the genre, and the modern compendium <i>Quan Song ci</i> gathers about 19,900 lyrics by more than 1,330 Song authors. The tradition never died, for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> cast his famous 1936 poem \"Snow\" as a ci, and in 1983 <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Teresa_Teng\">Teresa Teng</span></b> set Li Yu and Su Shi to pop melodies that all <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_poetry\">Chinese poetry</span> lovers can hum. Paired forever with Tang shi in the schoolroom formula \"Tang poems, Song lyrics,\" the form still carries tune titles like \"Butterflies Lingering over Flowers\" for melodies silent these 800 years.","citation":"","answerText":"Ci"},{"id":"cnc-075","num":"七十五","category":"China · Culture","question":"First developed using lodestone spoons for divination and geomancy before being adapted with a magnetised needle for navigation by the Song era, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> indicates direction by aligning with the Earth's magnetic field.","answer":"compass","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">指南针 (zhǐnánzhēn, 'south-pointing needle')</span></div>","traditional":"指南針","hanzi":"指南针","pinyin":"zhǐnánzhēn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">zhǐnánzhēn</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“south-pointing needle”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>compass</b> is an instrument that indicates the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cardinal_direction\">cardinal directions</span></b> by aligning a magnetised pointer with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Earth's_magnetic_field\">Earth's magnetic field</span>. Its earliest form took shape in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han</span> China as a spoon of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lodestone\">lodestone</span>, the naturally magnetic ore <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Magnetite\">magnetite</span>, balanced upon a bronze diviner's board, a device described in the 1st century CE in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lunheng\"><i>Lunheng</i></span> of the <b>skeptical philosopher <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Chong\">Wang Chong</span></b>. For roughly a millennium the pointer served not sailors but practitioners of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Divination\">divination</span> and the siting art of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Feng_shui\">feng shui</span>, an inheritance preserved in the elaborately ringed geomantic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luopan\">luopan</span>, while the mechanical <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South-pointing_chariot\">south-pointing chariot</span> of legend worked</b> by gears rather than magnetism. The decisive advance is recorded by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song</span> polymath <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shen_Kuo\">Shen Kuo</span>, whose <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dream_Pool_Essays\"><i>Dream Pool Essays</i></span> of 1088 explains</b> how rubbing a steel needle on lodestone magnetises it, compares mountings by float, fingernail, and silk thread, and notes the needle's slight deviation from true south, the first known observation of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Magnetic_declination\">magnetic declination</span>, some 4 centuries before Europe. Soon afterward the writer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_Yu_(author)\">Zhu Yu</span>, in his <i>Pingzhou Table Talks</i> <b>of 1119</b>, supplied the earliest account anywhere of the needle's use in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Navigation\">navigation</span>, reporting that pilots sailing from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou\">Guangzhou</span> consulted it in dark or overcast weather. <br> <br> Knowledge of the floating needle travelled swiftly along the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maritime_Silk_Road\">Maritime Silk Road</span>, <b>surfacing in Europe by 1190</b> in the writings of the English monk <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Alexander_Neckam\">Alexander Neckam</span> and among Islamic and Persian authors during the 13th century. Mariners of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mediterranean_Sea\">Mediterranean</span> refined the instrument into a dry, pivoted needle fixed beneath a 32-point <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Compass_rose\">compass rose</span>, an innovation tradition assigns to the port of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Amalfi\">Amalfi</span>, and the new confidence it gave extended the sailing season into winter and multiplied the voyages a ship could make each year. In China the needle guided the grandest expeditions of the age, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_treasure_voyages\">treasure voyages</span> of the admiral <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zheng_He\">Zheng He</span> between 1405 and 1433 steering by recorded compass bearings across the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Indian_Ocean\">Indian Ocean</span>, while in the West it underpinned the oceanic crossings of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Age_of_Discovery\">Age of Discovery</span>. Scientific understanding followed practice when <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"William_Gilbert_(physician)\">William Gilbert</span></b> argued in his <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"De_Magnete\"><i>De Magnete</i></span> of 1600 that the Earth is itself a vast magnet, after which navigators systematically corrected their readings toward <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"True_north\">true north</span>. Honoured among the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Great_Inventions\">Four Great Inventions</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>, the magnetic needle has since been joined by the spinning <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gyrocompass\">gyrocompass</span> and the solid-state <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Magnetometer\">magnetometers</span> embedded in every <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Smartphone\">smartphone</span>, yet the principle of a needle swinging toward the pole remains unchanged after a thousand years.","citation":"","answerText":"compass"},{"id":"cnc-078","num":"七十八","category":"China · Culture","question":"Reviving and reinterpreting classical ethics with a deeper metaphysics partly in response to Buddhism and Taoism, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> became the orthodox basis of the imperial examinations for centuries.","answer":"Neo-Confucianism","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">理学 (lǐxué, 'learning of principle')</span></div>","traditional":"道學","hanzi":"理学","pinyin":"lǐxué","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">lǐxué</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“learning of principle”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Neo-Confucianism</b>, \"learning of the Way\") is the movement that revived and reinterpreted classical <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> ethics with a deeper <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Metaphysics\">metaphysics</span></b>, framed consciously against <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Buddhism\">Buddhism</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Taoism</span>, and crystallizing under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song dynasty</span>. Its prophet was the Tang polemicist <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Yu\">Han Yu</span></b>, who in 819 denounced imperial veneration of a Buddha relic and claimed a transmission of the Way broken since Mencius, a lineage the Song \"5 Masters\" set out to restore: <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Dunyi\">Zhou Dunyi</span> with his diagram of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiji_(philosophy)\">Supreme Ultimate</span>, the cosmologist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shao_Yong\">Shao Yong</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Zai\">Zhang Zai</span>, whose \"Western Inscription\" declared all people his siblings, and the brothers <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cheng_Hao\">Cheng Hao</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cheng_Yi\">Cheng Yi</span></b>. Their key was <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_(neo-Confucianism)\">li</span>, the principle inherent in every thing, realized in the stuff of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qi\">qi</span>, so that the originally good nature is merely clouded and can be polished through the \"investigation of things\" taught in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Learning\"><i>Great Learning</i></span>. <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_Xi\">Zhu Xi</span> (<b>1130–1200</b>) forged the synthesis, writing the standard commentaries on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Books_and_Five_Classics\">Four Books</span>, restoring the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"White_Deer_Grotto_Academy\">White Deer Grotto Academy</span> in 1179, and codifying family ritual, yet he <b>died in 1200</b> with his teaching officially proscribed as \"false learning.\" Vindication was total, for in 1313 the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan</span> court made his Four Books the canon of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examinations</span>, where it defined orthodoxy for nearly 600 years <b>until 1905</b>. <br> <br> A rival idealist wing began with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lu_Jiuyuan\">Lu Jiuyuan</span>, who proclaimed the universe his own mind, and triumphed in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span> with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Yangming\">Wang Yangming</span>, who, after famously failing to grasp principle by staring at bamboo for 7 days, located it in innate moral knowing and preached the unity of knowledge and action. The movement became East Asia's common philosophy, ruling Korea's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joseon\">Joseon</span> dynasty for 5 centuries through masters like <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yi_Hwang\">Yi Hwang</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yi_I\">Yi I</span></b>, who gaze today from the 1,000- and 5,000-<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South_Korean_won\">won</span> banknotes, and serving the shoguns of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Edo_period\">Edo</span> Japan as official learning. Within China the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> philologists of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kaozheng\">kaozheng</span> evidential research punctured its speculative readings, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dai_Zhen\">Dai Zhen</span> charged that men now \"killed with principle\" as once with law. Critics of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Culture_Movement\">New Culture Movement</span> went further, blaming its ritualism—especially the widow-chastity ideal descending from Cheng Yi's dictum that starving is a small matter beside losing virtue—for a tradition that, they said, devoured the young and the female. Yet the system was reborn abroad and at home as 20th-century <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Confucianism\">New Confucianism</span>, with thinkers like <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mou_Zongsan\">Mou Zongsan</span> reading Zhu Xi beside Kant, testimony that a philosophy built to out-think the Buddhists still frames how East Asia reasons about mind and morals.","citation":"","answerText":"Neo-Confucianism"},{"id":"cng-027","num":"二十七","category":"China · Geography","question":"Named for the silt that tints its waters, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> lies between mainland China and the Korean Peninsula, washing the shores of Shandong and Jiangsu.","answer":"Yellow Sea","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">黄海 (Huáng Hǎi, 'yellow sea'), for river silt</span></div>","traditional":"黃海","hanzi":"黄海","pinyin":"Xī Hǎi","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Xī Hǎi</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Yellow Sea</b> in Korea) is a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marginal_sea\">marginal sea</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pacific_Ocean\">Pacific Ocean</span></b> of roughly 380,000 square kilometers (150,000 sq mi) lying between mainland China, where it washes <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shandong\">Shandong</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiangsu\">Jiangsu</span>, and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Korean_Peninsula\">Korean Peninsula</span></b>. It occupies a drowned <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Continental_shelf\">continental shelf</span> averaging only about 44 meters (140 ft) deep and nowhere much beyond 150 meters (490 ft), opening northwest through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bohai_Strait\">Bohai Strait</span> into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bohai_Sea\">Bohai Sea</span>, north into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Korea_Bay\">Korea Bay</span> at the mouth of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yalu_River\">Yalu</span>, and south into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"East_China_Sea\">East China Sea</span> along a line from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span> estuary to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jeju_Island\">Jeju Island</span>. Its name comes from the ochre silt that clouds its waters, supplied by windblown dust and by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_River\">Yellow River</span>, which actually emptied into this sea <b>between 1194</b> and 1855 and built much of the Jiangsu coast. During the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Last_Glacial_Maximum\">Last Glacial Maximum</span> about 20,000 years ago, when sea level stood some 120 meters (390 ft) lower, the entire basin was an exposed plain linking China and Korea by land. Today its margins host <b>one of the world's largest <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tidal_range\">tidal ranges</span></b>, approaching 10 meters (33 ft) near <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Incheon\">Incheon</span>, sustaining immense <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mudflat\">mudflats</span> such as the Korean <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Getbol\">getbol</span> and the marshes of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yancheng\">Yancheng</span>, inscribed <b>as World Heritage in 2021</b> and 2019 as critical refueling grounds on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"East_Asian–Australasian_Flyway\">East Asian–Australasian Flyway</span> for species like the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Spoon-billed_sandpiper\">spoon-billed sandpiper</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Red-crowned_crane\">red-crowned crane</span>. <br> <br> The shallow, nutrient-rich waters long ranked among the most productive fishing grounds of Asia, but decades of intense <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Overfishing\">overfishing</span> by fleets of several nations have stripped out large predatory fish and favored swarms of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nomura's_jellyfish\">Nomura's jellyfish</span> weighing up to 200 kilograms (440 lb) each. <b>Since 2007</b> the sea has also produced the largest recorded green tides on earth, as mats of the alga <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ulva_prolifera\">Ulva prolifera</span> spreading over tens of thousands of square kilometers wash annually onto the beaches of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qingdao\">Qingdao</span>. The basin has likewise been an arena of naval history, witnessing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_the_Yalu_River_(1894)\">Battle of the Yalu River</span> in 1894 during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Sino-Japanese_War\">First Sino-Japanese War</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_the_Yellow_Sea\">Battle of the Yellow Sea</span> in 1904 during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russo-Japanese_War\">Russo-Japanese War</span>. In 1950 the great amphibious gamble of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Inchon\">Incheon landing</span> turned the course of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Korean_War\">Korean War</span> from these tide-swept approaches. The sea remains strategically tense, with China and South Korea yet to settle their overlapping <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Exclusive_economic_zone\">exclusive economic zones</span>, disputes simmering over the submerged <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socotra_Rock\">Socotra Rock</span></b>, and the 2010 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"ROKS_Cheonan_sinking\">sinking of the corvette Cheonan</span> underscoring how heavily armed these silt-tinted waters remain.","citation":"","answerText":"Yellow Sea"},{"id":"cng-030","num":"三十","category":"China · Geography","question":"Flowing between the Yellow and Yangtze rivers, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> lends its name — together with the Qinling mountains — to the conventional line dividing northern from southern China.","answer":"Huai River","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">淮河 (Huái Hé), a central river giving its name to the line</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"淮河","pinyin":"Huái Hé","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Huái Hé</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Huai River</b> is a major waterway of about 1,110 kilometres (690 mi) flowing midway between the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_River\">Yellow River</span></b> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span>, draining a basin of roughly 270,000 square kilometres (100,000 sq mi) across <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Henan\">Henan</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anhui\">Anhui</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiangsu\">Jiangsu</span>, and joining the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qinling\">Qinling</span> range to define the conventional boundary between northern and southern China along the 0 °C (32 °F) January isotherm and the 800-millimetre rainfall line. Rising in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tongbai_Mountains\">Tongbai Mountains</span></b>, it marked a felt climatic frontier already in the 6th century BCE, when the statesman <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yan_Ying\">Yan Ying</span> famously quipped that oranges planted south of the Huai stay oranges but north of it turn into bitter <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Trifoliate_orange\">trifoliate fruit</span>. The river once reached the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_Sea\">Yellow Sea</span> on its own, but after <b>a great <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Avulsion_(river)\">avulsion</span> in 1194</b> the silt-laden Yellow River usurped its lower course until 1855, choking the old mouth and ponding the waters back into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hongze_Lake\">Hongze Lake</span>, at about 1,960 square kilometres (757 sq mi) now the 4th largest freshwater lake in China. Ever since, most of the flow has escaped southward through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gaoyou_Lake\">Gaoyou Lake</span> to the Yangtze, supplemented by a 1950s irrigation canal and a 163-kilometre (101 mi) flood channel to the sea <b>opened in 2003</b>. Trapped on an almost gradientless plain under a monsoonal rainfall regime, the basin has suffered chronic inundation, from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1931_China_floods\">1931 floods</span> that killed hundreds of thousands at minimum, through major deluges in 1954, 1991, 2007, and 2020, to the night in 1975 when rains from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Typhoon_Nina_(1975)\">Typhoon Nina</span> burst the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Banqiao_Dam\">Banqiao Dam</span> and dozens of others on Huai tributaries, drowning tens of thousands outright and perhaps 100,000 or more in the aftermath, the deadliest dam disaster in history. <br> <br> Some 165 million people crowd the basin, one of the densest agrarian landscapes on Earth, which produces on the order of a sixth of China’s grain from a small fraction of its land. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Grand_Canal_(China)\">Grand Canal</span> crosses the river at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huai'an\">Huai’an</span>, where <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> governments stationed their river-conservancy chiefs to manage the treacherous junction of canal, Huai, and Yellow River on which the empire’s grain transport depended. Under the People’s Republic the valley became the proving ground of mass hydraulics after <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> <b>proclaimed in 1951</b> that the Huai must be harnessed, a campaign that mobilized millions of labourers and eventually studded the basin with thousands of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Reservoir\">reservoirs</span> and modern control works such as the Linhuaigang project of the 2000s. Breakneck industrialization then made the Huai a byword for filth, as 1990s accidents sent black, foaming water past dead fisheries, tributaries like the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shaying_River\">Shaying</span> became associated with <b>clusters of so-called <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cancer_village\">cancer villages</span></b>, and the river was singled out for China’s first basin-wide pollution regulations in 1995. Along its banks today rise industrial cities such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bengbu\">Bengbu</span>, coal-rich <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huainan\">Huainan</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fuyang\">Fuyang</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinyang\">Xinyang</span>, while the old divide lives on in policy, since free winter <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"District_heating\">district heating</span> was historically provided only north of the Huai line, and studies in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Proceedings_of_the_National_Academy_of_Sciences_of_the_United_States_of_America\">Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences</span></b> have linked the resulting coal smoke to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Air_pollution\">air pollution</span> severe enough to cut northern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Life_expectancy\">life expectancy</span> by roughly 3 to 5 years.","citation":"","answerText":"Huai River"},{"id":"cng-046","num":"四十六","category":"China · Geography","question":"A range of red sandstone peaks and gorges in northern Fujian, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> are celebrated for their biodiversity and as the source of prized oolong and black teas.","answer":"Wuyi Mountains","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">武夷山 (Wǔyí Shān)</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"武夷山","pinyin":"Wǔyí Shān","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Wǔyí Shān</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Wuyi Mountains</b> are a range of red <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sandstone\">sandstone</span> peaks and gorges along the border of northern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fujian\">Fujian</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiangxi\">Jiangxi</span>, <b>inscribed in 1999</b> as one of China's rare mixed cultural and natural <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Heritage_Site\">World Heritage Sites</span> across roughly 1,000 square kilometers (390 sq mi). Their scenery is a textbook <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Danxia_landform\">Danxia landform</span>, where 36 sheer-walled peaks rise above the Nine-Bend Stream, a 9.5-kilometer (5.9 mi) gorge that visitors still descend on bamboo rafts beneath cliffs of rust-colored stone. Behind this front the range climbs to 2,158-meter (7,080 ft) <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mount_Huanggang\">Mount Huanggang</span>, the highest summit in mainland southeastern China, protected <b>since 1987</b> under UNESCO's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Man_and_the_Biosphere_Programme\">Man and the Biosphere Programme</span>. The slopes carry what conservationists rank as the largest and best-preserved subtropical evergreen broadleaf forest on earth, sheltering more than 2,500 plant and some 5,000 insect species, and 19th-century naturalists collected here so intensively that the mountains became the type locality for nearly 1,000 species. Flagship inhabitants include <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cabot's_tragopan\">Cabot's tragopan</span></b>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_giant_salamander\">Chinese giant salamander</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Black_muntjac\">black muntjac</span>, while the forests were among the last haunts claimed for the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South_China_tiger\">South China tiger</span></b>. <br> <br> Human history clings to the cliffs as well, from the boat-shaped <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hanging_coffins\">hanging coffins</span> lodged in crevices by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Baiyue\">Baiyue</span> peoples over 3,000 years ago, among the oldest known, to the excavated 1st-century BCE capital of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Minyue\">Minyue</span> kingdom destroyed by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han</span>. The philosopher <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_Xi\">Zhu Xi</span> spent some 5 decades here, founding a famous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shuyuan\">shuyuan</span> academy <b>beside the stream in 1183</b>, which led UNESCO to call the range the cradle of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Neo-Confucianism\">Neo-Confucianism</span>, while <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Taoist</span> temples and over 400 cliff inscriptions layer the gorges with devotion. Above all the mountains are holy ground for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tea\">tea</span>, since bushes of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Camellia_sinensis\">Camellia sinensis</span> rooted in mineral cliff soils yield the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuyi_tea\">Wuyi rock teas</span></b>, the original <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Oolong\">oolongs</span> prized for their \"rock rhyme,\" crowned by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Da_Hong_Pao\">Da Hong Pao</span>, whose 6 mother bushes, over 300 years old and off-limits to picking since 2006, once saw 20 grams auctioned for 208,000 yuan. In the village of Tongmu around the 17th century, pine-smoke withering created <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lapsang_souchong\">Lapsang souchong</span></b>, ancestor of all <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Black_tea\">black tea</span>, which as \"Bohea\" dominated the cargoes of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"East_India_Company\">East India Company</span> and gained a luxury descendant in 2005 with bud-only <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jin_Jun_Mei\">Jin Jun Mei</span>. The mountains even seeded their rivals, for in 1849 the plant hunter <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Robert_Fortune\">Robert Fortune</span> smuggled Wuyi tea plants and skilled workers to British India, helping found industries from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Darjeeling\">Darjeeling</span> outward, while today high-speed trains deliver pilgrims of scenery and tea alike to the gateway city of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuyishan\">Wuyishan</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Wuyi Mountains"},{"id":"cng-065","num":"六十五","category":"China · Geography","question":"A small autonomous region carved out along the upper Yellow River in the arid northwest, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was established for the Muslim Hui people and mixes irrigated farmland with stretches of the Gobi.","answer":"Ningxia","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">宁夏 (Níngxià, 'pacified Xia')</span></div>","traditional":"寧夏","hanzi":"宁夏","pinyin":"Níngxià","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Níngxià</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“pacified Xia”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Ningxia</b> is a small <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Autonomous_regions_of_China\">autonomous region</span></b> in the arid northwest of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>, the smallest of the country’s five such regions at about 66,000 square kilometres (25,000 sq mi). Its name, meaning “pacified Xia,” recalls the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Western_Xia\">Western Xia</span> empire crushed by the Mongols, and the region was <b>established in 1958</b> for the Muslim <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hui_people\">Hui</span>, a Chinese-speaking minority who today make up roughly a third of its 7 million people alongside a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Chinese\">Han</span> majority, governed from the capital <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yinchuan\">Yinchuan</span>. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_River\">Yellow River</span> crosses the territory, sustaining a fertile irrigated plain long praised as a “Jiangnan beyond the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Wall_of_China\">Great Wall</span>,” which is sheltered on the west by the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Helan_Mountains\">Helan Mountains</span></b> and hemmed by the sands of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tengger_Desert\">Tengger Desert</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gobi_Desert\">Gobi</span>, while the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Loess_Plateau\">Loess Plateau</span> rises to the south. Islam shapes daily life across the region, its towns dotted with mosques and its Hui communities tracing their roots to <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Islam_in_China\">Muslim</span></b> traders and soldiers who settled along the medieval trade routes, making Ningxia a stronghold of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sufism\">Sufism</span> and Chinese-Muslim culture. Yellow River irrigation lets the plain grow <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rice\">rice</span> and wheat in a desert setting, and the region is China’s foremost producer of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wolfberry\">goji berry</span></b>, increasingly renowned for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_wine\">vineyards</span> of its Helan foothills and underlain by major <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Coal\">coal</span> reserves at Ningdong. <br> <br> Ningxia has been a contested frontier since antiquity, when the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_dynasty\">Qin</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han</span> pushed back the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiongnu\">Xiongnu</span> and dug irrigation canals from the Yellow River that remain among the oldest in China, while the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk_Road\">Silk Road</span> threaded through the southern city of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guyuan\">Guyuan</span> past the Buddhist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xumishan_Grottoes\">Xumishan Grottoes</span>. <b>From 1038</b> the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tangut_people\">Tangut</span> empire centred its power here, raising its capital on the site of modern Yinchuan and leaving the monumental <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Western_Xia_Imperial_Tombs\">Western Xia Imperial Tombs</span> known as the “pyramids of China,” until <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Genghis_Khan\">Genghis Khan</span> <b>annihilated the state in 1227</b> in a campaign during which the conqueror himself died. The Hui descend largely from Arab, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Persians\">Persian</span>, and Central Asian Muslims who came as merchants and, under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan dynasty</span>, as the privileged <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Semu\">Semu</span> administrators, gradually intermarrying with the Han and adopting the Chinese language while keeping their faith. The region’s Muslim population was convulsed by the great <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dungan_Revolt_(1862–1877)\">Dungan Revolt</span> of the 1860s and 1870s, and Ningxia, briefly a separate province from 1928, was merged into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gansu\">Gansu</span> before being re-created as an autonomous region in 1958. In the arid south the once desperately poor highlands around Xihaigu, deemed by one assessment barely fit for habitation, have been transformed by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Poverty_in_China\">poverty-relief</span> resettlement and a Fujian-aided development model, while at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shapotou_District\">Shapotou</span> pioneering straw-checkerboard barriers along the railway have become a global model for halting <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Desertification\">desert encroachment</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Ningxia"},{"id":"cng-078","num":"七十八","category":"China · Geography","question":"A scenic city at the southern end of the Grand Canal and capital of Zhejiang, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>, celebrated for its West Lake, was the glittering capital of the Southern Song and is today a base for tech giants.","answer":"Hangzhou","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">杭州 (Hángzhōu)</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"杭州","pinyin":"Hángzhōu","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Hángzhōu</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Hangzhou</b> is the capital of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhejiang\">Zhejiang</span>, a city of 11.9 million in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2020_Chinese_census\"><b>2020 census</span></b> beside the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qiantang_River\">Qiantang River</span> at the southern terminus of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Grand_Canal_(China)\">Grand Canal</span>, completed under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sui_dynasty\">Sui</span> in 609, and paired with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Suzhou\">Suzhou</span> in the proverb that heaven lies above while these 2 cities lie below. Its roots run 5,000 years to the jade metropolis of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liangzhu_culture\">Liangzhu culture</span>, inscribed <b>as World Heritage in 2019</b> within the city's own district, while the kingdom of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuyue\">Wuyue</span> under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qian_Liu\">Qian Liu</span> beautified the lake from 907 and raised the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liuhe_Pagoda\">Liuhe Pagoda</span> in 970 to becalm the river's tides. Glory peaked when the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song dynasty</span>, driven south, made the city its capital Lin'an <b>from 1138</b> to 1276, probably the largest and richest city on earth with well over a million inhabitants, and after it fell in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongol_conquest_of_the_Song_dynasty\">Mongol conquest</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marco_Polo\">Marco Polo</span> still pronounced \"Quinsay\" the finest and noblest city in the world. <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"West_Lake\">West Lake</span></b>, itself listed in 2011, distills that civilization in the causeways built by the poet-governors <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bai_Juyi\">Bai Juyi</span> in the 820s and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Su_Shi\">Su Shi</span> in 1090, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Leifeng_Pagoda\">Leifeng Pagoda</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Legend_of_the_White_Snake\"><i>Legend of the White Snake</i></span>, the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lingyin_Temple\">Lingyin Temple</span></b> founded in 326 beneath the carved grottoes of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Feilai_Feng\">Feilai Feng</span>, and the tomb of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yue_Fei\">Yue Fei</span>, before which iron effigies of the traitor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_Hui\">Qin Hui</span> have knelt for centuries. The river answers with the planet's greatest <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tidal_bore\">tidal bore</span></b>, a wall of water approaching 9 meters (30 ft) that has drawn autumn crowds since the Tang. <br> <br> From the lakeside hills comes <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Longjing_tea\">Longjing tea</span>, the most celebrated of green teas, whose 18 bushes the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qianlong_Emperor\">Qianlong Emperor</span> designated imperial, while the city's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk\">silk</span> traveled the canal north for a millennium. Catastrophe struck when sieges of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiping_Rebellion\">Taiping Rebellion</span> in 1860–1862 ruined the city and killed a large share of its people, yet it rebuilt as the republic's favorite resort. The modern resurrection has been digital, for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jack_Ma\">Jack Ma</span> founded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Alibaba_Group\">Alibaba</span> in a lakeside apartment in 1999, seeding an e-commerce and fintech empire with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ant_Group\">Ant Group</span> that made the digital economy the city's pillar. A 2nd wave crowned it China's startup darling, as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"DeepSeek\">DeepSeek</span> stunned the AI world from Hangzhou in 2025 and the hometown studio behind <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Black_Myth:_Wukong\"><i>Black Myth: Wukong</i></span> sold over 20 million copies in 2024, earning the city its nickname as home of the \"6 little dragons.\" Having hosted the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2016_G20_Hangzhou_summit\">2016 G20 summit</span></b> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2022_Asian_Games\">2022 Asian Games</span>, and bound to Shanghai by a 45-minute bullet train, the old paradise now runs on code as smoothly as it once ran on silk.","citation":"","answerText":"Hangzhou"},{"id":"cnh-059","num":"五十九","category":"China · History","question":"A brilliant and controversial chancellor of the Northern Song, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> launched a sweeping \"New Policies\" programme of state loans to farmers, a graduated land tax and a militia system, splitting the court into bitter factions and drawing the opposition of conservatives like Sima Guang.","answer":"Wang Anshi","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">8 December 1021</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">21 May 1086</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"王安石","pinyin":"Wáng Ānshí","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Wáng Ānshí</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Wang Anshi</b>, courtesy name <b>Jiefu</b>, was a Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Scholar-official\">scholar-official</span>, economist, poet, and essayist of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Song\">Northern Song</span></b> who rose to serve as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Grand_chancellor_(China)\">chancellor</span> and became one of the most consequential and divisive reformers in imperial Chinese history. Born into a family of modest officials at Linchuan in present-day <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiangxi\">Jiangxi</span>, he passed the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examination</span> with distinction in 1042</b> to earn the prestigious <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jinshi\">jinshi</span> degree, then built a reputation as an unusually capable administrator across a succession of provincial posts. In 1058 he submitted a celebrated \"Myriad Word <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Memorial_to_the_throne\">Memorial</span>\" to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Renzong_of_Song\">Emperor Renzong</span> calling for far-reaching institutional change, and although it was set aside at the time, his proposals found an eager patron when the ambitious young <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Shenzong_of_Song\">Emperor Shenzong</span> raised him <b>to high office in 1069</b>. From that vantage Wang launched the sweeping <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Policies_(Song_dynasty)\">New Policies</span>, a coordinated programme designed to enrich the treasury, strengthen the army against the rival <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Western_Xia\">Western Xia</span> and Khitan <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liao_dynasty\">Liao</span>, and curb the dominance of great landlords and merchants, enacted chiefly during the Xining era <b>between 1069 and 1076</b>. Its centrepiece measures included the Green Sprouts law, under which the state advanced planting-season <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Usury\">loans</span> to peasant farmers at roughly 20 percent interest in order to free them from private moneylenders, a \"square fields\" land survey that assessed taxes by the size and fertility of holdings, and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Baojia_(China)\">baojia</span></b> system, which organised rural households into mutual-responsibility units that doubled as a local <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Militia\">militia</span>. <br> <br> Further measures commuted compulsory labour <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Corvée\">service</span> into a graduated cash payment, billeted government <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cavalry\">cavalry</span> horses with peasant households, created state offices to regulate commerce and steady prices, and recast the examination syllabus around Wang's own commentaries on the Confucian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_classics\">classics</span>, above all the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rites_of_Zhou\"><i>Rites of Zhou</i></span>. The programme ignited fierce resistance and cleaved the bureaucracy into a reformist camp and a conservative opposition, the latter led by the <b>great historian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Guang\">Sima Guang</span></b>, compiler of the monumental chronicle <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zizhi_Tongjian\"><i>Zizhi Tongjian</i></span>, and including such figures as the veteran statesman <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Qi\">Han Qi</span>, the philosopher <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cheng_Yi_(philosopher)\">Cheng Yi</span>, a founder of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Neo-Confucianism\">Neo-Confucianism</span>, and the poet <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Su_Shi\">Su Shi</span>. Opponents charged that the New Policies expanded state coercion, often burdened the very farmers they were meant to relieve, and concentrated dangerous authority in a single minister, and the ensuing partisan warfare would poison court politics at the capital of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kaifeng\">Kaifeng</span> for decades to come. Twice driven from power, Wang withdrew for good in 1076 to a quiet retirement near <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Jiangning</span>, and after Shenzong's death in 1085 the regency governing for the child <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Zhezong_of_Song\">Emperor Zhezong</span></b> recalled Sima Guang, who moved at once to dismantle almost the whole reform edifice. Wang died the next year, reportedly broken by the unravelling of his life's work, yet his reputation as a literary master endured, for he was numbered among the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight_Great_Prose_Masters_of_the_Tang_and_Song\">Eight Great Prose Masters of the Tang and Song</span> beside contemporaries such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ouyang_Xiu\">Ouyang Xiu</span>, and his terse, allusive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Classical_Chinese_poetry\">poetry</span> and forceful prose have been admired down the centuries even by those who deplored his politics.","citation":"","answerText":"Wang Anshi"},{"id":"cnc-077","num":"七十七","category":"China · Culture","question":"A towering Song dynasty polymath also known as Su Dongpo — a poet, essayist, painter and calligrapher repeatedly exiled for his politics — the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is remembered for a famous ode on the Red Cliffs of the Yangtze and even for a style of braised pork.","answer":"Su Shi","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1037–1101</span></div>","traditional":"蘇軾","hanzi":"苏轼","pinyin":"Sū Shì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Sū Shì</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Su Shi</b> was a poet, essayist, statesman, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_calligraphy\">calligrapher</span></b>, painter, and gastronome of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song dynasty</span>, ranked among the supreme figures of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_poetry\">Chinese letters</span>. Born at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Meishan\">Meishan</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan\">Sichuan</span>, he <b>passed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examination</span> in 1057</b> at the age of 19, astonishing the chief examiner <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ouyang_Xiu\">Ouyang Xiu</span>, and together with his father <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Su_Xun\">Su Xun</span> and brother <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Su_Zhe\">Su Zhe</span> he stands among the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight_Great_Prose_Masters_of_the_Tang_and_Song\">Eight Great Prose Masters of the Tang and Song</span>. A pioneer of the bold, expansive manner in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ci_(poetry)\">ci</span> lyric, he <b>composed in 1076</b> the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shuidiao_Getou\"><i>Shuidiao Getou</i></span> for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mid-Autumn_Festival\">Mid-Autumn Festival</span>, addressed in longing to his distant brother and still sung today. His mocking opposition to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Policies_(Song_dynasty)\">New Policies</span> of the reformer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Anshi\">Wang Anshi</span> brought catastrophe <b>in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Crow_Terrace_Poetry_Trial\">Crow Terrace Poetry Trial</span> of 1079</b>, when he was imprisoned for months, narrowly escaped execution, and was banished to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huangzhou_District\">Huangzhou</span>. There, farming a plot he called the Eastern Slope, from which he took the name Dongpo, he wrote in 1082 his two rhapsodies on the Red Cliffs of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span>, meditations on transience evoking the ancient <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Red_Cliffs\">Battle of Red Cliffs</span> that rank among the glories of Chinese prose-poetry. <br> <br> Restored to favour, he governed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hangzhou\">Hangzhou</span>, where in 1089 he dredged <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"West_Lake\">West Lake</span> and raised from the spoil the 2.8-kilometre (1.7 mi) <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Su_Causeway\">Su Causeway</span></b>, while local legend credits him with the braised <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dongpo_pork\">Dongpo pork</span> that bears his name. Renewed factional vengeance drove him in 1094 to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huizhou\">Huizhou</span> in the far south and in 1097 across the strait to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Danzhou\">Danzhou</span> on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hainan\">Hainan</span>, the remotest banishment then conceivable, where he taught local students until an amnesty recalled him, only for death to overtake him at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Changzhou\">Changzhou</span> in 1101. As a calligrapher he is grouped with <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huang_Tingjian\">Huang Tingjian</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mi_Fu\">Mi Fu</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cai_Xiang\">Cai Xiang</span> as one of the four masters of the Song, his manuscript of poems written for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cold_Food_Festival\">Cold Food Festival</span> at Huangzhou treasured in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Palace_Museum\">National Palace Museum</span> as one of the most celebrated scrolls in existence. In painting he favoured gnarled rocks and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bamboo\">bamboo</span> in the manner of his friend <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wen_Tong\">Wen Tong</span>, and his insistence that art should capture spirit rather than outward likeness became the founding <b>creed of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Literati_painting\">literati painting</span></b>. Roughly 2,700 poems and some 350 lyrics survive from his brush, along with essays, letters, and inscriptions that generations have memorised, securing him a place in the affection of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> that few writers have ever rivalled.","citation":"","answerText":"Su Shi"},{"id":"cnc-076","num":"七十六","category":"China · Culture","question":"A humble artisan of the Song who, around <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>, fashioned individual characters from baked clay that could be arranged and reused, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is credited with creating the world's first movable type, centuries before Gutenberg.","answer":"Bi Sheng","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. 972</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1051</span></div>","traditional":"畢昇","hanzi":"毕昇","pinyin":"Bì Shēng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Bì Shēng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Bi Sheng</b> was a commoner artisan of the Northern Song who, during the Qingli era (1041–1048) under <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Renzong_of_Song\">Emperor Renzong</span></b>, created the world's first <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ceramic\">ceramic</span> movable type for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Printing\">printing</span>, fashioning individual characters from baked clay that could be arranged and reused. His method, as later recorded, was to carve characters into sticky <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Clay\">clay</span></b> as thin as the edge of a coin and harden them in fire, then arrange them in an iron frame upon a plate coated with pine <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Resin\">resin</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wax\">wax</span>, and paper ash, which was warmed to bind the type into a single solid block and reheated afterward to free the pieces for reuse. Almost everything known of him derives from a single source, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dream_Pool_Essays\"><i>Dream Pool Essays</i></span> <b>compiled around 1088</b> by the Northern Song polymath <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shen_Kuo\">Shen Kuo</span>, which preserves the earliest surviving account of the technique and observes that the rest of his life passed almost without record. Shen Kuo related that the process was tedious for a handful of copies but marvelously fast for hundreds or thousands, the artisan keeping a pair of formes working in alternation and casting more than 20 pieces of type for each frequently used <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_characters\">character</span>, all stored in wooden cases sorted by rhyme. Printing itself was no novelty in China, where <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Woodblock_printing\">woodblock printing</span> on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paper\">paper</span></b>—the latter perfected centuries earlier by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cai_Lun\">Cai Lun</span>—was long established, but the principle of reusable type marked a revolutionary advance, and printing would be counted among the celebrated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Great_Inventions\">Four Great Inventions</span> of ancient China alongside <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gunpowder\">gunpowder</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Compass\">compass</span>.<br> <br>Reusable type nonetheless remained a marginal technology in China, for the immense <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Written_Chinese\">character set</span> of written Chinese, numbering many thousands of symbols, made the carving and sorting of individual sorts far more cumbersome than for an alphabet, and woodblock printing continued to dominate. He had likewise experimented with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wood_type\">wooden type</span>, but abandoned it because the grain warped and the surface grew uneven once soaked in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ink\">ink</span>, leaving baked clay as his preferred material. After his death the ceramic technique appears to have spread to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tangut_people\">Tangut</span> kingdom of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Western_Xia\">Western Xia</span>, where a printed copy of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vimalakirti_Sutra\"><i>Vimalakirti Sutra</i></span></b> bearing the marks of clay type was recovered at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuwei,_Gansu\">Wuwei</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gansu\">Gansu</span>, while metal type was used under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jin_dynasty_(1115–1234)\">Jin dynasty</span> to print <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paper_money\">paper money</span>. Movable type was steadily refined thereafter: the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan</span> official <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Zhen_(inventor)\">Wang Zhen</span> perfected practical <b>wooden movable type around 1297</b> with a revolving typecase, bronze type flourished under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span> in the work of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hua_Sui\">Hua Sui</span>, and in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Goryeo\">Korea</span> metal type <b>produced the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jikji\"><i>Jikji</i></span> of 1377</b>, the oldest surviving book printed with movable metal type. Although movable type never supplanted the woodblock in China, the invention anticipated the European <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Printing_press\">printing press</span> of Johannes Gutenberg by roughly 400 years, and a tomb attributed to the inventor, unearthed in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hubei\">Hubei</span> in 1990, has helped secure his standing as the originator of one of history's most transformative technologies.","citation":"","answerText":"Bi Sheng"},{"id":"cnh-064","num":"六十四","category":"China · History","question":"A brilliant general of the Southern Song who won victories against the Jurchens, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was recalled and executed on trumped-up charges by the treacherous minister Qin Hui, and is revered ever since as a model of patriotic loyalty.","answer":"Yue Fei","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">March 24, 1103</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">January 28, 1142</span></div>","traditional":"岳飛","hanzi":"岳飞","pinyin":"Yuè Fēi","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Yuè Fēi</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Yue Fei</b> was a military general of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Southern Song</span> who is honored as one of the greatest patriots and military commanders in <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"History_of_China\">Chinese history</span></b>. Born into a poor farming family in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tangyin_County\">Tangyin</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Henan\">Henan</span>, he came of age as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jurchen_people\">Jurchen</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jin_dynasty_(1115–1234)\">Jin dynasty</span> overran the north <b>in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jingkang_Incident\">Jingkang Incident</span> of 1127</b>, carried off the captive emperor and his retired father, and drove the shattered Song court into southern exile under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Gaozong_of_Song\">Emperor Gaozong</span>. Rising through merit in the ensuing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jin–Song_Wars\">Jin–Song Wars</span>, he built a famously disciplined force known as the Yue Family Army, whose troops were said to \"freeze to death rather than loot and starve to death rather than plunder,\" while tradition holds that his mother <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tattoo\">tattooed</span> onto his back the injunction to \"serve the country with utmost loyalty.\" Through the 1130s he recovered broad stretches of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Plain_(China)\">Central Plains</span>, and <b>at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Yancheng\">Battle of Yancheng</span> in 1140</b> he routed the elite armored <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cavalry\">cavalry</span> of the Jin commander <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wanyan_Zongbi\">Wuzhu</span>, advancing to within reach of the lost capital at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kaifeng\">Kaifeng</span> and vowing to press on to the Jin heartland. Just as outright victory seemed within grasp, he was abruptly <b>recalled in 1141</b> by 12 urgent gold-lettered orders from a court that had resolved to negotiate rather than fight on. <br> <br> The peace faction was dominated by the chief councillor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_Hui\">Qin Hui</span>, who had the general stripped of command, imprisoned, and in early 1142 put to death at the age of 39 together with his son <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yue_Yun_(general)\">Yue Yun</span>, on fabricated charges that the <b>veteran commander <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Shizhong\">Han Shizhong</span></b> openly denounced and that the minister could justify only with the evasive phrase \"perhaps so.\" Yue Fei's removal cleared the way for the humiliating <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Shaoxing\">Treaty of Shaoxing</span>, under which the Southern Song accepted vassal status, fixed its frontier with the Jin along the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huai_River\">Huai River</span>, and agreed to pay an annual tribute of 250,000 taels of silver and 250,000 bolts of silk. In 1162 <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Xiaozong_of_Song\">Emperor Xiaozong</span></b> posthumously exonerated and rehabilitated him, restoring his rank, granting honorary titles, and ordering his remains reburied with full ceremony. His tomb and a memorial temple stand beside <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"West_Lake\">West Lake</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hangzhou\">Hangzhou</span>, where kneeling iron statues of Qin Hui and his wife have for centuries been reviled and spat upon by visitors, fixing the minister in popular memory as the archetypal traitor. Celebrated in the patriotic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ci_(poetry)\">ci</span> lyric <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manjianghong\"><i>Manjianghong</i></span> traditionally ascribed to him, in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_opera\">opera</span>, and in the later novel <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Story_of_Yue_Fei\"><i>The Story of Yue Fei</i></span>, he endures across the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Chinese\">Han Chinese</span> world as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Folk_hero\">folk hero</span> and the <b>supreme embodiment of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Patriotism\">patriotic</span></b> loyalty grounded in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> virtue.","citation":"","answerText":"Yue Fei"},{"id":"cnh-061","num":"六十一","category":"China · History","question":"Established by the Jurchens who had overthrown their former Khitan overlords, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> conquered northern China and captured the Song capital, only to be destroyed a century later by the Mongols.","answer":"Jin dynasty","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">&lt;b&gt;1115&lt;/b&gt;–&lt;b&gt;1234&lt;/b&gt;</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"金朝","pinyin":"Jīn Cháo","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Jīn Cháo</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“gold”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Jin dynasty</b> was a dynasty of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tungusic_peoples\">Tungusic</span> <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jurchen_people\">Jurchen</span></b> people that ruled northern China for over a century after toppling their former overlords, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liao_dynasty\">Liao dynasty</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khitan_people\">Khitan</span>. The Jurchens were a semi-sedentary forest and river people of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchuria\">Manchuria</span>, and under the chieftain <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Taizu_of_Jin\">Wanyan Aguda</span> of the ruling <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wanyan\">Wanyan</span> clan they rose in revolt and proclaimed their own dynasty in 1115, choosing the name \"gold\" to signify a permanence that base metals lacked. Allied with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Song\">Northern Song</span> through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Alliance_Conducted_at_Sea\">Alliance Conducted at Sea</span>, the Jurchens <b>crushed the Liao by 1125</b>, destroying in barely a decade an empire that had stood for two centuries, but they soon turned on their erstwhile partner and drove deep into the Song heartland. In the catastrophic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jingkang_incident\">Jingkang incident</span> of 1127 they stormed the Song capital of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kaifeng\">Kaifeng</span> and carried off the retired emperor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Huizong_of_Song\">Huizong</span>, his son <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Qinzong_of_Song\">Qinzong</span>, and thousands of the imperial household into captivity in the north. A surviving prince fled south to refound the imperial line as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Southern_Song\">Southern Song</span></b> under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Gaozong_of_Song\">Emperor Gaozong</span>, eventually fixing a new capital at Lin'an, the modern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hangzhou\">Hangzhou</span>, while the Jurchen state consolidated its hold over the whole of north China and the millions of subjects who lived there. <br> <br> Protracted warfare with the Southern Song was eventually halted by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Shaoxing\">Treaty of Shaoxing</span> in 1142, which fixed the frontier along the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huai_River\">Huai River</span>, reduced the southern court to a tribute-paying vassal, and was sealed by the judicial murder of the celebrated Song general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yue_Fei\">Yue Fei</span>. Ruling a Han majority that vastly outnumbered the Jurchens, the dynasty grew steadily more <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sinicization\">sinicized</span>, embracing Chinese bureaucratic methods and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examination</span> even as it promoted a new <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jurchen_script\">Jurchen script</span> to safeguard an ancestral tongue that nonetheless steadily lost ground to Chinese. In 1153 the ambitious usurper <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wanyan_Liang\">Wanyan Liang</span></b> shifted the principal capital south to Zhongdu, the site of modern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>, and the long, prosperous reigns of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Shizong_of_Jin\">Emperor Shizong</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Zhangzong_of_Jin\">Emperor Zhangzong</span> are often regarded as the cultural high point of the regime. Religious and intellectual life thrived, most notably in the rapid spread of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Quanzhen_School\">Quanzhen School</span> of Daoism founded by <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Chongyang\">Wang Chongyang</span></b>, while a census of 1207 counted a populous realm of more than 53 million people, the overwhelming majority of them Han governed by a small Jurchen elite. From 1211 the Mongols of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Genghis_Khan\">Genghis Khan</span> assailed the dynasty relentlessly, seizing Zhongdu in 1215 and driving the court to take refuge at Kaifeng, until the armies of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ögedei_Khan\">Ögedei Khan</span>, once more in concert with the Southern Song, cornered the last emperor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Aizong_of_Jin\">Aizong</span> at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Caizhou\">siege of Caizhou</span>, where the realm founded by Aguda was extinguished in 1234 and absorbed into the rising <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongol_Empire\">Mongol Empire</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Jin dynasty"},{"id":"cnh-054","num":"五十四","category":"China · History","question":"Founded by the nomadic Khitan in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> and controlling a swathe of the north including 16 prefectures coveted by the Chinese, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> ruled a dual administration over both steppe and settled peoples and long menaced the Song.","answer":"Liao dynasty","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">&lt;b&gt;916&lt;/b&gt;–&lt;b&gt;1125&lt;/b&gt;</span></div>","traditional":"遼朝","hanzi":"辽朝","pinyin":"Liáo Cháo","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Liáo Cháo</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Liao dynasty</b> was a multiethnic empire of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khitan_people\">Khitan</span></b> people that ruled across what is now northern China, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchuria\">Manchuria</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Inner_Mongolia\">Inner Mongolia</span> for more than two centuries, ranking among the most powerful states of medieval East Asia. It was founded in 916 by the chieftain <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Taizu_of_Liao\">Yelü Abaoji</span>, who welded the eight <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nomad\">nomadic</span> Khitan tribes of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liao_River\">Liao River</span> basin into a single state and proclaimed himself emperor, before enlarging his domain by destroying the neighbouring kingdom of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Balhae\">Balhae</span> in 926. His son <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Taizong_of_Liao\">Emperor Taizong</span></b> pushed the empire southward, gaining in 938 the strategically vital <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sixteen_Prefectures\">Sixteen Prefectures</span> of densely settled Han Chinese territory ceded by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shi_Jingtang\">Shi Jingtang</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Later_Jin_(Five_Dynasties)\">Later Jin</span>, and it was under him that the state adopted the Chinese-style dynastic name \"Great Liao.\" These prefectures, which embraced the future cities of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Datong\">Datong</span>, brought a vast agricultural and urban population under Khitan rule and were governed within a distinctive network of five regional capitals spread across the empire's varied terrain. To rule peoples of radically different ways of life, the Liao devised a celebrated dual administration, a Northern bureau that governed the Khitan and other steppe tribes by traditional nomadic custom and a Southern bureau that administered the sedentary Han and former Balhae subjects through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span>-style institutions, a defining feature of what historians call a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Conquest_dynasty\">conquest dynasty</span></b>. <br> <br> Although profoundly shaped by Chinese statecraft, the Khitan elite preserved a distinct identity, devising two original writing systems, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khitan_large_script\">Khitan large script</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khitan_small_script\">Khitan small script</span>, to record their own <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khitan_language\">language</span>, and maintaining a mobile court that migrated seasonally between hunting camps rather than ruling from a single fixed throne. <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Buddhism\">Buddhism</span> flourished under lavish imperial patronage, leaving enduring monuments such as the soaring wooden <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pagoda_of_Fogong_Temple\">Pagoda of Fogong Temple</span>, <b>erected in 1056</b> and still the oldest and tallest surviving timber pagoda in China. Militarily the dynasty long overshadowed its southern neighbour, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song</span>, beating back repeated Song campaigns to retake the lost prefectures and, under the formidable regent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiao_Chuo\">Empress Dowager Xiao</span> acting for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Shengzong_of_Liao\">Emperor Shengzong</span>, forcing them to accept the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Chanyuan\">Treaty of Chanyuan</span></b> in 1005. Under that settlement the Song recognised the Liao as a diplomatic equal and paid an annual subsidy of 100,000 taels of silver and 200,000 bolts of silk, purchasing a peace that lasted roughly 120 years, while the dynasty simultaneously waged protracted wars against the Korean kingdom of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Goryeo\">Goryeo</span> and managed a shifting, often hostile relationship with the Tangut <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Western_Xia\">Western Xia</span>. In the early 12th century the once-subject <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jurchen_people\">Jurchens</span> under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Taizu_of_Jin\">Aguda</span> founded the rival <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jin_dynasty_(1115–1234)\">Jin dynasty</span> and, in alliance with the Song, overthrew the Khitan by 1125, after which the prince <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yelü_Dashi\">Yelü Dashi</span> led a remnant westward to establish the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qara_Khitai\">Qara Khitai</span> in Central Asia, a successor state that endured until the rise of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongol_Empire\">Mongols</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Liao dynasty"},{"id":"cnh-062","num":"六十二","category":"China · History","question":"A humiliating catastrophe of <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> when Jurchen armies captured Kaifeng and carried off 2 emperors and the imperial clan into captivity, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> ended the Northern Song and drove the survivors to refound the dynasty in the south.","answer":"Jingkang Incident","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1127</span></div>","traditional":"靖康之變","hanzi":"靖康之变","pinyin":"Jìngkāng zhī biàn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Jìngkāng zhī biàn</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Jingkang Incident</b> refers to the catastrophic conquest of the <b>Northern Song capital in 1127</b> by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jurchen_people\">Jurchen</span>, an event named for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_era_name\">era name</span> then borne by the reigning Chinese sovereign. Its origins lay in the <b>ill-fated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Alliance_Conducted_at_Sea\">Alliance Conducted at Sea</span> of 1120</b>, by which the Song joined the rising Jurchen state in destroying the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khitan_people\">Khitan</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liao_dynasty\">Liao dynasty</span> in hopes of recovering the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sixteen_Prefectures\">Sixteen Prefectures</span> lost in the 10th century. The joint campaign instead laid bare the dynasty's military feebleness, and once the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Tianzuo_of_Liao\">last Liao emperor</span> had been <b>captured in 1125</b>, the triumphant Jin turned upon their erstwhile ally under the reigning <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Taizong_of_Jin\">Emperor Taizong</span>. A first Jin assault late in 1125 so panicked <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Huizong_of_Song\">Emperor Huizong</span> that he abdicated in favour of his son <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Qinzong_of_Song\">Emperor Qinzong</span>, whose defenders, led by <b>the minister <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Gang_(Song_dynasty)\">Li Gang</span></b>, held the walls of Bianjing long enough to negotiate a withdrawal in exchange for a staggering ransom of five million taels of gold and fifty million of silver. When the court reneged on the cession of three northern prefectures and dismissed Li Gang, the generals <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wanyan_Zonghan\">Wanyan Zonghan</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wanyan_Zongwang\">Wanyan Zongwang</span></b> returned in force later in 1126, and the capital fell in the first month of 1127 after a deluded reliance on a charlatan who promised to repel the besiegers with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Daoist</span> sorcery ended in ruin.<br> <br>In the spring of 1127 the conquerors deposed both emperors and herded them north out of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_River\">Yellow River</span> heartland of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Chinese\">Han Chinese</span> civilization, together with some 3,000 members of the imperial clan—empresses, consorts, princes, and princesses—and thousands of officials, artisans, and palace women, as well as the dynasty's regalia, libraries, and accumulated treasure. Conveyed into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchuria\">Manchuria</span> and saddled with mocking titles, the two captive sovereigns never returned—Huizong died in exile in 1135 and his son endured imprisonment for decades more—while the <b>former minister <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Bangchang\">Zhang Bangchang</span></b>, installed as a figurehead, briefly headed a Jin <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Puppet_state\">puppet</span> regime in the ravaged capital. One of Huizong's sons, the Prince of Kang, had eluded the catastrophe, and in 1127 he was acclaimed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Gaozong_of_Song\">Emperor Gaozong</span> at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shangqiu\">Yingtian</span>, refounding the realm as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Southern_Song\">Southern Song</span></b> and ultimately fixing his capital at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hangzhou\">Hangzhou</span>, safely south of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span>. The ensuing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jin–Song_Wars\">Jin–Song Wars</span> dragged on until the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Shaoxing\">Treaty of Shaoxing</span> of 1141 fixed the frontier along the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huai_River\">Huai River</span>, abandoned the entire <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"North_China_Plain\">North China Plain</span> to the Jin, and bound the Southern Song to annual <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tribute\">tribute</span> of 250,000 taels of silver and an equal number of bolts of silk. The settlement was sealed only after the patriotic general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yue_Fei\">Yue Fei</span>, who had fought to reconquer the north, was judicially murdered in 1142 at the instigation of the chancellor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_Hui\">Qin Hui</span>, yet the trauma of 1127—enshrined in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ci_(poetry)\">ci</span> lyric traditionally ascribed to Yue Fei, <i>Manjianghong</i>, with its vow to wipe away the \"shame of Jingkang\"—lingered for centuries as the very archetype of national humiliation, persisting until the Jin fell in 1234 and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongol_conquest_of_the_Song_dynasty\">Mongol conquest</span> at last extinguished the Southern Song in 1279.","citation":"","answerText":"Jingkang Incident"},{"id":"cnh-063","num":"六十三","category":"China · History","question":"Re-established in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> with its capital at Hangzhou after the loss of the north, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> presided over a brilliant flowering of art, commerce and maritime trade even as it paid tribute to the Jin, before falling at last to Kublai Khan.","answer":"Southern Song","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">&lt;b&gt;1127&lt;/b&gt;–&lt;b&gt;1279&lt;/b&gt;</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"南宋","pinyin":"Nán Sòng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Nán Sòng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Southern Song</b> was the latter phase of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song dynasty</span>, a Chinese imperial regime that ruled the lands south of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huai_River\">Huai River</span> after the catastrophic loss of the north Chinese heartland to invading nomads. It arose directly from the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jingkang_incident\">Jingkang Incident</span></b> of 1127, when the armies of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jin_dynasty_(1115–1234)\">Jin dynasty</span>, founded by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jurchen_people\">Jurchen</span> people of the northeast, sacked the Northern Song capital at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kaifeng\">Kaifeng</span> and carried the retired <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Huizong_of_Song\">Emperor Huizong</span> and his son <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Qinzong_of_Song\">Emperor Qinzong</span> into captivity. A surviving prince was enthroned as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Gaozong_of_Song\">Emperor Gaozong</span></b> and, after years of flight from pursuing cavalry, fixed his court at the prosperous southern city of Lin'an, present-day <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hangzhou\">Hangzhou</span>, which swelled into one of the most populous cities on earth with perhaps more than a million inhabitants. The general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yue_Fei\">Yue Fei</span> won renown campaigning to recover the lost provinces, but the court, dominated by the chief councillor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_Hui\">Qin Hui</span>, instead sought accommodation and had him <b>executed in 1142</b> on fabricated charges. That settlement was sealed by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Shaoxing\">Treaty of Shaoxing</span>, which fixed the frontier along the Huai River and obliged the dynasty to remit an annual tribute of 250,000 taels of silver and 250,000 bolts of silk while acknowledging the Jin emperor as its nominal superior. <br> <br> Despite its truncated borders, the regime presided over a remarkable <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_the_Song_dynasty\">commercial expansion</span>, issuing the government-backed paper currency known as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huizi_(currency)\">huizi</span> and drawing a substantial share of state revenue from a booming overseas commerce centred on the great ports of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Quanzhou\">Quanzhou</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou\">Guangzhou</span>. Maritime merchants ranged across the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Indian_Ocean\">Indian Ocean</span> aboard ocean-going <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Junk_(ship)\">junks</span> guided by the magnetic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Compass\">compass</span>, while military engineers developed early <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gunpowder\">gunpowder</span> weapons and the empire's prized <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Longquan_celadon\">celadon</span> wares travelled as far as East Africa. Intellectual life was no less vibrant, for the philosopher <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_Xi\">Zhu Xi</span> synthesised the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Neo-Confucianism\">Neo-Confucian</span> tradition that would shape East Asian thought for centuries, while court painters such as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ma_Yuan_(painter)\">Ma Yuan</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xia_Gui\">Xia Gui</span> perfected an evocative, asymmetrical style of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shan_shui\">landscape painting</span>. The lyric <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ci_(poetry)\">ci</span> verse of poets like <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xin_Qiji\">Xin Qiji</span> reached new heights in the same period, yet the dynasty's security steadily eroded after it joined the rising <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongol_Empire\">Mongol Empire</span> to destroy the Jin in 1234, only to watch the Mongols turn their formidable armies southward. The resulting <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongol_conquest_of_the_Song_dynasty\">decades-long war</span></b> saw <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kublai_Khan\">Kublai Khan</span> proclaim the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan dynasty</span> in 1271 and prevail in the gruelling six-year siege of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Xiangyang\">Xiangyang</span> that ended in 1273, after which his forces took Hangzhou in 1276 and extinguished the last Song resistance at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Yamen\">Battle of Yamen</span> in 1279, where the boy emperor drowned alongside his loyal minister in the sea.","citation":"","answerText":"Southern Song"},{"id":"cnc-079","num":"七十九","category":"China · Culture","question":"The most influential Neo-Confucian thinker, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> systematised the tradition, fixed the Four Books as the core curriculum, and shaped orthodox learning across East Asia for 700 years.","answer":"Zhu Xi","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1130–1200</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"朱熹","pinyin":"Zhū Xī","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhū Xī</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Zhu Xi</b> was a philosopher, historian, and educator of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song dynasty</span>, born in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fujian\">Fujian</span>, whose synthesis of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Neo-Confucianism\">Neo-Confucianism</span> made him the most influential figure in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> thought after the ancient masters themselves. He <b>passed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examination</span> in 1148</b> when only 18, yet spent barely 9 years in provincial office and a famous 46 days at court, devoting his life instead to scholarship and teaching. Building on the brothers <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cheng_Hao\">Cheng Hao</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cheng_Yi\">Cheng Yi</span>, whose lineage his own became known as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cheng–Zhu_school\">Cheng–Zhu school</span>, and on the Supreme Ultimate, or <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiji_(philosophy)\">taiji</span>, of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Dunyi\">Zhou Dunyi</span></b>, he articulated a cosmos in which immaterial principle, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_(Neo-Confucianism)\">li</span>, joins with vital force, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qi\">qi</span>, to form all things, offering Confucians a metaphysics to rival <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Buddhism\">Buddhism</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Taoism</span>. The heart of his programme lay in the investigation of things and the cultivation of the mind, and <b>in 1190</b> he published together the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Analects\"><i>Analects</i></span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mencius_(book)\"><i>Mencius</i></span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Learning\"><i>Great Learning</i></span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Doctrine_of_the_Mean\"><i>Doctrine of the Mean</i></span>, fixing these <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Books_and_Five_Classics\">Four Books</span> with his commentaries as the gateway to all learning. A tireless builder of the private academies called <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shuyuan\">shuyuan</span>, he <b>restored the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"White_Deer_Grotto_Academy\">White Deer Grotto Academy</span> in 1179</b> and gave it articles of instruction copied for centuries, debated the intuitionist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lu_Jiuyuan\">Lu Jiuyuan</span> at Goose Lake in 1175, and with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lü_Zuqian\">Lü Zuqian</span> compiled the anthology <i>Reflections on Things at Hand</i>. <br> <br> His industry extended to history and ritual, for he condensed the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zizhi_Tongjian\"><i>Zizhi Tongjian</i></span></b> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Guang\">Sima Guang</span> into a moralised outline and composed the <i>Family Rituals</i> that standardised weddings, funerals, and ancestral rites across East Asia. His final years passed under persecution, <b>the chancellor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Tuozhou\">Han Tuozhou</span></b> proscribing his teaching as false learning in 1196, and he died in 1200 with his doctrines still banned, though nearly a thousand followers braved official displeasure to attend his funeral. Vindication came swiftly, his tablet entering the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Temple_of_Confucius\">Temple of Confucius</span> in 1241, and after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan</span> restored the examinations in 1313 his commentaries served as the orthodox standard for some 6 centuries until the system's abolition in 1905. Beyond China his school became the state creed of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joseon\">Joseon</span> Korea, expounded by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yi_Hwang\">Yi Hwang</span>, shaped <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Edo_period\">Edo</span> Japan through scholars such as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hayashi_Razan\">Hayashi Razan</span></b>, and guided the examinations of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vietnam\">Vietnam</span>, ordering learning throughout the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"East_Asian_cultural_sphere\">East Asian cultural sphere</span> for 700 years. Even the great challenge of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Yangming\">Wang Yangming</span>'s school of the mind defined itself against him, and with works ranging from his commentaries to the 140 chapters of recorded conversations in the <i>Zhuzi yulei</i>, he remains, by common consent, the most consequential thinker <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> produced in the 2nd millennium.","citation":"","answerText":"Zhu Xi"},{"id":"cnh-065","num":"六十五","category":"China · History","question":"Born Temüjin and proclaimed \"universal ruler\" in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> after uniting the warring Mongol tribes, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> forged history's largest contiguous land empire, his armies smashing the Western Xia and the Jin in the course of his campaigns.","answer":"Genghis Khan","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. 1162–1227</span></div>","traditional":"鐵木真","hanzi":"成吉思汗","pinyin":"Tiěmùzhēn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Tiěmùzhēn</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Genghis Khan</b>; c. <b>1162</b> – 1227) was the founder and first <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khagan\">khagan</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongol_Empire\">Mongol Empire</span>, born into the aristocratic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Borjigin\">Borjigin</span> clan beside the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Onon_River\">Onon River</span> on the eastern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongolian_Plateau\">Mongolian Plateau</span>. His childhood was scarred by hardship after his father, the chieftain <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yesugei\">Yesügei</span></b>, was poisoned by rival <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tatar_confederation\">Tatars</span> and the family was cast out to destitution, yet the young Temüjin rebuilt his fortunes through shrewd alliances—most notably with his father's sworn brother <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Toghrul\">Toghrul</span> of the Kereit and his own blood-brother <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jamukha\">Jamukha</span></b>—and by recovering his abducted wife <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Börte\">Börte</span> in a daring raid. Over the following two decades he outmaneuvered and subdued the steppe's great confederations—the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Keraites\">Keraites</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Naimans\">Naimans</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Merkit\">Merkits</span>—and finally broke the power of Jamukha, until no rival remained to dispute his mastery of the eastern grasslands. <b>In 1206</b> a grand <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kurultai\">kurultai</span> of the assembled chieftains acclaimed him by the title \"Genghis Khan,\" widely rendered as universal ruler, and confirmed the birth of a unified Mongol nation forged from once-warring clans. To govern the new realm he reorganized his followers into a decimal hierarchy of units numbering ten, a hundred, a thousand, and ten thousand, raised an elite bodyguard called the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Keshig\">Keshig</span>, codified customary law in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yassa\">Yassa</span>, adopted a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongolian_script\">written script</span> for the Mongolian language, and bound his territories together through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yam_(route)\">Yam</span> relay network while extending notable tolerance to the empire's many faiths.<br> <br>Now master of the steppe, he turned his cavalry outward, reducing the Tangut state of Western <b>Xia to vassalage by 1210</b>, storming the Jurchen Jin and seizing their central capital of Zhongdu—modern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>—in 1215, and extinguishing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qara_Khitai\">Qara Khitai</span> through his general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jebe\">Jebe</span> in 1218. When the governor of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khwarazmian_Empire\">Khwarazmian Empire</span> massacred a Mongol trade caravan at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Otrar\">Otrar</span> in 1218, Genghis Khan launched a devastating invasion of Central Asia between 1219 and 1221, razing fabled cities such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Samarkand\">Samarkand</span> and driving the fugitive Shah <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Muhammad_II_of_Khwarazm\">Muhammad II</span></b> to die in flight on an island in the Caspian. While the main host turned homeward, a long-range reconnaissance led by the brilliant strategist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Subutai\">Subutai</span> swept around the Caspian and through the Caucasus, annihilating a combined <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kievan_Rus'\">Rus'</span> and Cuman army at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_the_Kalka_River\">Kalka River</span> in 1223 before rejoining the khan in the east. His final campaign was directed against Western Xia, which had refused to furnish troops for the western war, and it was during this expedition that Genghis Khan died in 1227—reportedly buried in secret somewhere near the sacred peak of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Burkhan_Khaldun\">Burkhan Khaldun</span></b>—having already apportioned his conquests among his four sons by Börte: <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jochi\">Jochi</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chagatai_Khan\">Chagatai</span>, the designated heir <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ögedei_Khan\">Ögedei</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tolui\">Tolui</span>. The empire he founded swelled under his heirs into history's largest contiguous land power, reaching at its height some 24 million square kilometres (9.3 million sq mi)—about a sixth of the world's land area—and though the conquests he unleashed may have cost tens of millions of lives, they also opened the trans-Eurasian peace later termed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pax_Mongolica\">Pax Mongolica</span>; his grandson <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kublai_Khan\">Kublai Khan</span> ultimately ruled China as founder of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan dynasty</span>, and a 2003 genetic study famously estimated that some 16 million men alive today bear a Y-chromosome lineage traceable to his patriline.","citation":"","answerText":"Genghis Khan"},{"id":"cnh-066","num":"六十六","category":"China · History","question":"Stretching at its height from Korea to Eastern Europe, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> founded by Genghis Khan eventually fragmented into rival khanates, the easternmost of which conquered all of China.","answer":"Mongol Empire","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">&lt;b&gt;1206&lt;/b&gt;–&lt;b&gt;1368&lt;/b&gt;</span></div>","traditional":"蒙古帝國","hanzi":"蒙古帝国","pinyin":"Měnggǔ Dìguó","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Měnggǔ Dìguó</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Great Mongol State”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Mongol Empire</b> was the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"List_of_largest_empires\">largest contiguous land empire</span></b> in history, at its zenith spanning roughly 24 million square kilometres (9.3 million sq mi), or about 16% of the earth's land surface, and holding sway over a population estimated at more than 100 million people. It was forged on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eurasian_Steppe\">Eurasian steppe</span> by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Genghis_Khan\">Genghis Khan</span>, who in 1206 united the fractious <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongols\">Mongol</span> and Turkic tribes at a great <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kurultai\">kurultai</span> and was acclaimed supreme <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khagan\">khagan</span> of a newly consolidated steppe confederation. Its astonishing expansion rested on a disciplined cavalry army <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongol_military_tactics_and_organization\">organised by a decimal system</span></b> into units culminating in the 10,000-strong <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tumen_(unit)\">tumen</span>, whose mounted archers wielded the powerful <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Composite_bow\">composite bow</span> and employed feigned retreats, encirclement, and calculated terror with devastating effect. Genghis first subjugated the Tangut <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Western_Xia\">Western Xia</span> and invaded the Jurchen <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jin_dynasty_(1115–1234)\">Jin dynasty</span> of northern China before unleashing a catastrophic assault on the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khwarazmian_Empire\">Khwarazmian Empire</span></b> of Central Asia and Persia, where entire cities were razed and their inhabitants massacred. Under his successors the onslaught continued, for during the reign of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ögedei_Khan\">Ögedei Khan</span> the general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Batu_Khan\">Batu</span> overran <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kievan_Rus'\">Kievan Rus'</span> and shattered European armies at <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Legnica\">Legnica</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Mohi\">Mohi</span> in 1241</b>, while in 1258 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hulagu_Khan\">Hulagu</span> sacked <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Siege_of_Baghdad_(1258)\">Baghdad</span> and extinguished the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Abbasid_Caliphate\">Abbasid Caliphate</span>. <br> <br> The unified empire did not long survive the death of the Great Khan <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Möngke_Khan\">Möngke</span> in 1259, for the ensuing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Toluid_Civil_War\">Toluid Civil War</span> between <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kublai_Khan\">Kublai Khan</span> and his brother <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ariq_Böke\">Ariq Böke</span> shattered central authority and left the realm divided among four rival khanates. These comprised the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Golden_Horde\">Golden Horde</span></b> astride the Russian steppes, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chagatai_Khanate\">Chagatai Khanate</span> in Central Asia, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ilkhanate\">Ilkhanate</span> in Persia, and the dominant eastern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan dynasty</span>, which Kublai proclaimed in 1271 as the imperial successor in China. From his capital at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khanbaliq\">Khanbaliq</span>, modern Beijing, Kublai completed the conquest of the wealthy <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Southern_Song\">Southern Song</span> in 1279, bringing all of China under foreign rule for the first time and making the Yuan the easternmost and richest of the successor states. Across these domains the so-called <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pax_Mongolica\">Pax Mongolica</span> secured the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk_Road\">Silk Road</span> and a continent-spanning <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yam_(route)\">courier relay network</span>, fostering an unprecedented exchange of goods, technologies, and ideas that drew travellers such as the Venetian merchant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marco_Polo\">Marco Polo</span> deep into Asia. Yet the same arteries of trade also carried the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Black_Death\">Black Death</span> westward in the 14th century, and as the khanates succumbed to internal strife and assimilation, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming dynasty</span> expelled the Yuan from China in 1368, driving its remnants back onto the steppe as the rump <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Yuan\">Northern Yuan</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Mongol Empire"},{"id":"cnh-067","num":"六十七","category":"China · History","question":"A grandson of Genghis Khan who completed the conquest of China and moved his capital to the site of modern Beijing, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> founded a new dynasty, adopted Chinese forms of government, and received the Venetian traveller Marco Polo at his court.","answer":"Kublai Khan","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1215–1294</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"忽必烈","pinyin":"Hūbìliè","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Hūbìliè</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Kublai Khan</b> was the fifth <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khagan\">khagan</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongol_Empire\">Mongol Empire</span></b> and the founder of China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan dynasty</span>, presiding over the transformation of a nomadic conquest state into a settled East Asian empire. A grandson of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Genghis_Khan\">Genghis Khan</span> through the latter's youngest son <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tolui\">Tolui</span></b>, he was raised under the influence of his mother <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sorghaghtani_Beki\">Sorghaghtani Beki</span>, an able Nestorian Christian noblewoman whose four sons all rose to rule major portions of the Mongol world. When his elder brother <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Möngke_Khan\">Möngke</span> <b>became Great Khan in 1251</b>, Kublai was entrusted with the administration of the conquered territories of northern China, where he gathered Chinese advisers and built a summer capital at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shangdu\">Shangdu</span>, the fabled Xanadu of later European legend. Möngke's death in 1259 during the campaign against the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Southern_Song\">Southern Song</span> precipitated a succession crisis, and <b>in 1260 Kublai</b> had himself proclaimed Great Khan at his Chinese power base, touching off the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Toluid_Civil_War\">Toluid Civil War</span> against his younger brother <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ariq_Böke\">Ariq Böke</span>. His victory by 1264 confirmed his supremacy but effectively severed the eastern realm from the western khanates, shifting the empire's centre of gravity away from the old steppe capital of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Karakorum\">Karakorum</span> toward the agrarian wealth of China. <br> <br> <b>In 1271</b> he proclaimed the Yuan dynasty, adopting a dynastic title drawn from the classic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"I_Ching\"><i>I Ching</i></span> and signalling his claim to be a legitimate Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_of_China\">emperor</span>, and he raised a magnificent new capital, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khanbaliq\">Dadu</span>, on the site of present-day <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>. By 1279 his armies had crushed the last Southern Song resistance at the naval <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Yamen\">battle off Yamen</span>, reuniting all of China under one throne for the first time since the fall of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang dynasty</span> and establishing the first foreign regime ever to rule the entire country. Although he embraced Chinese bureaucratic forms, issued a single empire-wide <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Banknote\">paper currency</span>, and adopted the trappings of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> imperial rule, Kublai suspended the traditional <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">civil-service examinations</span> and entrenched a rigid ethnic hierarchy that placed Mongols and Central Asian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Semu\">Semu</span> above the far more numerous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Chinese\">Han Chinese</span> and southern populations. He extended notable patronage to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_Buddhism\">Tibetan Buddhism</span>, elevating the lama <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Drogön_Chögyal_Phagpa\">Phagpa</span> as his imperial preceptor and commissioning a universal <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"'Phags-pa_script\">'Phags-pa script</span></b>, and his cosmopolitan court famously welcomed the Venetian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marco_Polo\">Marco Polo</span>, whose later account spread the dynasty's fame across Europe. His later reign was marred by ruinously expensive overseas ventures, <b>including two failed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongol_invasions_of_Japan\">invasions of Japan</span></b> in 1274 and 1281 whose fleets were wrecked by the typhoons the Japanese revered as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kamikaze_(typhoon)\">kamikaze</span>, as well as draining campaigns against <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Đại_Việt\">Đại Việt</span> in the south, so that when he died in 1294 he bequeathed a unified but overstretched realm that his successors would lose to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span> within a century.","citation":"","answerText":"Kublai Khan"},{"id":"cnh-070","num":"七十","category":"China · History","question":"A decades-long struggle finally completed in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> overcame fierce resistance — including the long siege of Xiangyang — to subjugate the wealthy Southern Song, bringing all of China under the rule of Kublai Khan.","answer":"Mongol conquest of the Song dynasty","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1235–1279</span></div>","traditional":"蒙宋戰爭","hanzi":"蒙宋战争","pinyin":"Méng-Sòng Zhànzhēng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Méng-Sòng Zhànzhēng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Mongol conquest of the Song dynasty</b> was the protracted, multi-generational war through which the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongol_Empire\">Mongol Empire</span> subjugated the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Southern_Song\">Southern Song</span>, the last independent Chinese state and the wealthiest realm of 13th-century <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"East_Asia\">East Asia</span>, in a contest that stretched <b>from roughly 1235</b> to 1279 and ranks among the longest and costliest of all the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongol_invasions_and_conquests\">Mongol campaigns</span>. Open hostilities erupted soon after the Mongols and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song</span> had jointly <b>destroyed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jin_dynasty_(1115–1234)\">Jin dynasty</span> in 1234</b>, and the opening invasions ordered by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ögedei_Khan\">Ögedei Khan</span> fell heavily on the fertile basin of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan\">Sichuan</span>, a region whose registered population would collapse over the ensuing decades of campaigning. The war escalated under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Möngke_Khan\">Möngke Khan</span>, who personally led an army into the southwest but <b>died in 1259 while</b> besieging the mountaintop fortress of Diaoyucheng near present-day <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chongqing\">Chongqing</span>, a death that compelled a Mongol withdrawal and touched off the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Toluid_Civil_War\">Toluid Civil War</span> between his brothers. The eventual victor, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kublai_Khan\">Kublai Khan</span>, overcame his rival <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ariq_Böke\">Ariq Böke</span></b>, proclaimed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan dynasty</span> in 1271, and pressed the offensive with vastly greater resources from his new northern capital at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khanbaliq\">Khanbaliq</span>. The decisive obstacle lay on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span> approaches, where the siege of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Xiangyang\">Xiangyang</span> dragged on for roughly 6 years before falling in 1273, broken only after Persian engineers from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ilkhanate\">Ilkhanate</span> introduced massive counterweight <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Trebuchet\">trebuchets</span> whose stone projectiles shattered the defenses and induced the <b>Song commander <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lü_Wenhuan\">Lü Wenhuan</span></b> to surrender and defect. <br> <br> With the river barrier broken, the Mongol general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bayan_of_the_Baarin\">Bayan of the Baarin</span> drove down the Yangtze and seized the Song capital of Lin'an, modern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hangzhou\">Hangzhou</span>, in 1276, where the child <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Gong_of_Song\">Emperor Gong of Song</span> and the regency surrendered after the discredited chancellor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jia_Sidao\">Jia Sidao</span> had been blamed for the dynasty's ruin. A core of loyalist officials led by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wen_Tianxiang\">Wen Tianxiang</span> refused to submit, fleeing southward to enthrone a succession of boy-emperors and to rally the surviving fragments of the imperial fleet and court along the coast. This last resistance was annihilated at the naval <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Yamen\">Battle of Yamen</span> in 1279, where the Yuan commander <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Hongfan\">Zhang Hongfan</span> destroyed the Song armada and the grand councillor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lu_Xiufu\">Lu Xiufu</span> leapt into the sea clutching the last Song sovereign, the child <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Bing_of_Song\">Emperor Bing of Song</span></b>, with traditional chronicles claiming that more than 100,000 loyalists perished in the waters. The campaign reunited the whole of China under one throne for the first time in centuries and made the Yuan the first foreign-led dynasty to govern the entire country, supplanting the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Scholar-official\">scholar-official</span> elite that had administered the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Chinese\">Han Chinese</span> heartland under the Song. Census figures preserved in <b>the official <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"History_of_Yuan\"><i>History of Yuan</i></span></b> indicate that the registered population of the realm fell by tens of millions across the era of conquest, a demographic shock that scholars ascribe to a mixture of warfare, famine, and disrupted record-keeping, even as the reunified empire soon drew foreign travelers such as the Venetian merchant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marco_Polo\">Marco Polo</span> to the Yuan court.","citation":"","answerText":"Mongol conquest of the Song dynasty"},{"id":"cnh-069","num":"六十九","category":"China · History","question":"A merchant from Venice who, by his own account, spent years in the service of Kublai Khan, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> saw.","answer":"Marco Polo","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. 1254</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">January 8, 1324</span></div>","traditional":"馬可·波羅","hanzi":"马可·波罗","pinyin":"Mǎkě Bōluó","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Mǎkě Bōluó</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Marco Polo</b> was a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_Venice\">Venetian</span></b> merchant, explorer, and writer whose account of his travels across Asia became one of the most influential works of medieval European literature. Born into a trading family during the era of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongol_Empire\">Mongol Empire</span>'s greatest extent, he was <b>about 17 when in 1271</b> he set out for the East with his father and uncle, the merchants <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Niccolò_and_Maffeo_Polo\">Niccolò and Maffeo Polo</span>, who had already reached the Mongol court once before. Their overland route followed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk_Road\">Silk Road</span> through the Middle East and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ilkhanate\">Persia</span>, across the high <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pamir_Mountains\">Pamir Mountains</span> and the forbidding <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gobi_Desert\">Gobi Desert</span>, until after a grueling trek of several years they reached <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kublai_Khan\">Kublai Khan</span> at his summer <b>capital of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shangdu\">Shangdu</span> around 1275</b>. By his own telling, Marco entered the Khan's service and spent some 17 years in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan</span> realm, undertaking missions that he claimed carried him as far as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangzhou\">Yangzhou</span>, a city he said he governed, and the southern provinces beyond. He marveled at the wealth of the empire's cities, above all the capital at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khanbaliq\">Khanbaliq</span>, present-day Beijing, and the southern metropolis of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hangzhou\">Hangzhou</span>, which he called Quinsai and described as the finest city in the world, crossed by a fabled 12,000 bridges. <br> <br> The Polos <b>finally left China around 1292</b>, escorting a young Mongol princess named <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kököchin\">Kököchin</span> by sea toward Persia as a bride for the Ilkhanid ruler <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Arghun\">Arghun</span>, a voyage that by Marco's account set out with 14 ships and hundreds of travelers yet ended with only 18 survivors. Returning to Venice around 1295 after nearly 24 years abroad, he was soon taken prisoner by the rival <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_Genoa\">Republic of Genoa</span></b>, traditionally said to have been captured following the naval <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Curzola\">Battle of Curzola</span>, and while imprisoned he dictated his recollections to a fellow captive, the romance writer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rustichello_da_Pisa\">Rustichello da Pisa</span>. The resulting book, known in English as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Travels_of_Marco_Polo\"><i>The Travels of Marco Polo</i></span> and originally composed in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Old_French\">Old French</span> under titles such as <i>Le Devisement du Monde</i> and the nickname <i>Il Milione</i>, recounted the riches of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cathay\">Cathay</span>, the use of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Banknote\">paper money</span>, and the rumored island of Cipangu, or <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japan\">Japan</span>. Copied into perhaps 150 surviving manuscripts and rendered into many languages, it shaped European geographic thinking for centuries, informing the famous <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Catalan_Atlas\">Catalan Atlas</span></b> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fra_Mauro_map\">Fra Mauro map</span> and supplying the heavily annotated copy that helped inspire <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Christopher_Columbus\">Christopher Columbus</span> to seek a western route to the East. He was released around 1299, resumed life as a prosperous Venetian merchant, and died in 1324, leaving a reputation contested ever since, for while skeptics such <b>as the historian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Frances_Wood\">Frances Wood</span></b> have stressed his silence on features like the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Wall_of_China\">Great Wall of China</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foot_binding\">foot binding</span> and have questioned how much of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sumatra\">Sumatra</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"India\">India</span>, and inland China he truly saw, defenders cite his precise descriptions of Mongol administration as evidence that he reached the Khan's domains.","citation":"","answerText":"Marco Polo"},{"id":"cnh-068","num":"六十八","category":"China · History","question":"Proclaimed in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> by Kublai Khan, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> governed China for under a century, ranking its subjects in a hierarchy that placed Han Chinese near the bottom, before being overthrown by the peasant rebellions that founded the Ming.","answer":"Yuan dynasty","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1271–1368</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"元朝","pinyin":"Yuáncháo","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Yuáncháo</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Yuan dynasty</b> was the Mongol-ruled imperial dynasty of China <b>proclaimed in 1271</b> by Kublai Khan, a grandson of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Genghis_Khan\">Genghis Khan</span></b>, who adopted the grandiose dynastic name \"Great Yuan\" from a phrase in the ancient <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"I_Ching\"><i>I Ching</i></span> and would govern the country for fewer than a hundred years. Conceived as the eastern, China-based heart of the wider <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongol_Empire\">Mongol Empire</span>, the new state left its founder claiming the supreme title of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khagan\">khagan</span> over the now largely autonomous western khanates—the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Golden_Horde\">Golden Horde</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ilkhanate\">Ilkhanate</span>, and <b>the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chagatai_Khanate\">Chagatai Khanate</span>—and in 1279</b> it completed the unification of China by destroying the last of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Southern_Song\">Southern Song</span>. Kublai fixed his principal capital at Dadu, the \"Great Capital\" also known as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khanbaliq\">Khanbaliq</span> on the site of modern Beijing, kept a summer seat at the storied <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shangdu\">Shangdu</span>, and governed through a Chinese-style bureaucracy whose <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Provinces_of_China\">provincial</span> divisions still underlie the administrative map of China today. Society was ordered into a four-tier hierarchy that set the ruling Mongols above the Central Asian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Semu\">Semu</span>, ranked the northern Han beneath them, and consigned the conquered southern Chinese to the very bottom, while the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examinations</span> were suspended until 1315, leaving the displaced Confucian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Scholar-official\">scholar-officials</span> embittered and largely shut out of power. The regime granted broad religious tolerance, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_Buddhism\">Tibetan Buddhism</span> gained particular favour at court under the Imperial Preceptor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Drogön_Chögyal_Phagpa\">Phagpa</span>, who devised the universal <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Phags-pa_script\">Phags-pa script</span></b>; meanwhile <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Banknote\">paper money</span> became the empire's dominant currency, and the security of the Mongol peace drew Eurasian travellers such as the Venetian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marco_Polo\">Marco Polo</span> to Kublai's court.<br> <br>Kublai's reign also brought ruinous military overreach, for his two great seaborne invasions of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japan\">Japan</span> in 1274 and 1281 were annihilated by the typhoons that the Japanese revered as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kamikaze_(typhoon)\">kamikaze</span>, or divine winds, while repeated assaults on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Đại_Việt\">Đại Việt</span> foundered against the resistance of <b>the general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Trần_Hưng_Đạo\">Trần Hưng Đạo</span></b>. After Kublai died in 1294 the throne grew unstable, passing through a rapid series of emperors amid court intrigue and corruption, while reckless over-printing of banknotes touched off the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hyperinflation\">hyperinflation</span> that hollowed out an economy already straining to feed a population the census of 1290 had numbered at roughly 59 million. Disaster compounded misrule when the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_River\">Yellow River</span> burst its banks and the forced conscription of some 150,000 labourers to control it—coinciding with famine and plague—helped ignite the millenarian <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Red_Turban_Rebellions\">Red Turban Rebellions</span></b> from 1351, movements rooted in the secret <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"White_Lotus\">White Lotus</span> Buddhist society. Out of the rebel chaos rose the peasant-born former monk Zhu Yuanzhang, the future <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hongwu_Emperor\">Hongwu Emperor</span>, who crushed his chief rival <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Youliang\">Chen Youliang</span> at the immense <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Lake_Poyang\">Battle of Lake Poyang</span> in 1363, proclaimed the Ming at <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span> in 1368</b>, and that same year sent his armies to take Dadu, driving the last Yuan ruler, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Toghon_Temür\">Toghon Temür</span>, in flight to the steppe. The exiled court regrouped on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongolia\">Mongolian</span> grasslands as the rump <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Yuan\">Northern Yuan</span>, yet the brief dynasty left an enduring imprint—Beijing as an imperial capital, the provincial framework of Chinese government, and a China knitted as never before into the commerce and culture of Eurasia—having become, in less than a century, the first foreign power to rule the whole of the Chinese world.","citation":"","answerText":"Yuan dynasty"},{"id":"cnh-072","num":"七十二","category":"China · History","question":"A Latin term for the relative stability the Mongol Empire imposed across Eurasia, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> made the overland trade routes safer for merchants, missionaries and ideas — and, less happily, helped the plague travel west.","answer":"Pax Mongolica","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">13th–14th c.</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"蒙古治世","pinyin":"Měnggǔ Zhìshì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Měnggǔ Zhìshì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Pax Mongolica</b> is a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Historiography\">historiographical</span> term, modelled on the earlier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pax_Romana\">Pax Romana</span>, denoting the era of relative stability that the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongol_Empire\">Mongol Empire</span> imposed across much of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eurasia\">Eurasia</span></b> during the <b>13th</b> and <b>14th centuries</b>. Although the unified empire fractured into four rival khanates after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Toluid_Civil_War\">Toluid Civil War</span> of the 1260s, the parallel rule of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan dynasty</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Golden_Horde\">Golden Horde</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chagatai_Khanate\">Chagatai Khanate</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ilkhanate\">Ilkhanate</span> sustained a largely connected sphere of commerce and travel for roughly a century. This security rested in part on the mounted <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yam_(route)\">yam</span> relay system, a vast network of post stations that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marco_Polo\">Marco Polo</span> claimed numbered some 10,000 stations supplied with around 200,000 horses, allowing messages and merchants to move swiftly along the revived <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk_Road\">Silk Road</span>. Under its protection a remarkable array of long-distance travellers crossed the continent, among them the Moroccan jurist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ibn_Battuta\">Ibn Battuta</span>, the Franciscan envoy <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Giovanni_da_Pian_del_Carpine\">Giovanni da Pian del Carpine</span></b>, and the Flemish friar <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"William_of_Rubruck\">William of Rubruck</span>, all of whom left detailed accounts of the Mongol world. The Mongols' notable religious tolerance encouraged exchange among Christians, Muslims, and Buddhists alike, so that the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Church_of_the_East\">Church of the East</span> monk <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rabban_Bar_Sauma\">Rabban Bar Sauma</span></b> journeyed from China as far as Rome and Paris, while the missionary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"John_of_Montecorvino\">John of Montecorvino</span> was installed as the first Catholic archbishop of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khanbaliq\">Khanbaliq</span>. <br> <br> The integration of Eurasian routes also accelerated the westward diffusion of Chinese innovations such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gunpowder\">gunpowder</span>, the navigational <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Compass\">compass</span>, and block <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Printing\">printing</span>, even as Persian cobalt travelled east to inspire the celebrated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Blue_and_white_pottery\">blue-and-white porcelain</span> of the period. Diplomatic horizons widened as well, with the Ilkhanate repeatedly seeking a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Franco-Mongol_alliance\">Franco-Mongol alliance</span></b> against the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mamluk_Sultanate\">Mamluk Sultanate</span>, and European powers dispatching embassies to the Mongol courts in hopes of military cooperation and conversion. The same open arteries, however, carried catastrophe, for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bubonic_plague\">bubonic plague</span> spread westward out of Inner Asia to the Genoese-held port of Caffa in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Crimea\">Crimea</span>, where <b>the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Siege_of_Caffa\">besieging Mongol army</span> of 1346</b> is reputed to have catapulted plague-ridden corpses over the city walls. From there the contagion, remembered as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Black_Death\">Black Death</span>, reached Europe by 1347 and within a few years killed an estimated one-third of its population, perhaps 75 to 200 million people across <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Afro-Eurasia\">Afro-Eurasia</span> as a whole. The Mongol peace ultimately unravelled amid this upheaval, as the western khanates splintered and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming dynasty</span> expelled the Yuan from China in 1368, bringing to a close what some historians regard as an early experiment in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Archaic_globalization\">Eurasian globalisation</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Pax Mongolica"},{"id":"cnc-080","num":"八十","category":"China · Culture","question":"Combining song, mime, acrobatics, elaborate costume and stylised gesture rather than realistic acting, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> exists in hundreds of regional forms, from the refined <i>Kunqu</i> to the boisterous Peking variety, often accompanied by the <i>erhu</i>.","answer":"Chinese opera","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">戏曲 (xìqǔ, 'theatrical song')</span></div>","traditional":"戲曲","hanzi":"戏曲","pinyin":"xìqǔ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">xìqǔ</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“theatrical song”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Chinese opera</b> is the broad performing-arts tradition that fuses song, mime, acrobatics, elaborate costume, and stylised gesture in place of realistic acting, surviving today in more than 300 regional forms, from the refined <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kunqu\">Kunqu</span></b> to the boisterous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peking_opera\">Peking opera</span>, sung to fiddles like the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Erhu\">erhu</span> amid clashing gongs. Court patronage is as old as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span>, whose <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Xuanzong_of_Tang\">Emperor Xuanzong</span> founded the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pear_Garden\">Pear Garden</span></b> academy in 714, bequeathing actors their enduring title \"children of the Pear Garden.\" Full-blown music drama matured in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zaju\">zaju</span> of the 13th and 14th centuries, when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guan_Hanqing\">Guan Hanqing</span> wrote the wronged-widow tragedy <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Injustice_to_Dou_E\"><i>The Injustice to Dou E</i></span></b> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Romance_of_the_Western_Chamber\"><i>Romance of the Western Chamber</i></span> perfected romantic comedy. Under the Ming the elegant Kunqu style, its Kunshan melodies refined in the 16th century, carried the literary drama to its peak in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_Xianzu\">Tang Xianzu</span><b>'s 55-scene <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Peony_Pavilion\"><i>Peony Pavilion</i></span> of 1598</b>, its author dying in 1616, the very year as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"William_Shakespeare\">Shakespeare</span>. The boisterous metropolitan style was born when the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Great_Anhui_Troupes\">4 Great Anhui Troupes</span> came to Beijing from 1790 for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qianlong_Emperor\">Qianlong Emperor</span>'s 80th birthday and stayed to forge Peking opera. <br> <br> Every form shares a grammar of convention: 4 role types—the male sheng, the female <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dan_(Chinese_opera)\">dan</span>, the painted-face <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jing_(Chinese_opera)\">jing</span></b>, and the clown chou—each mastering the 4 skills of song, speech, dance-acting, and combat, on a bare stage where a whip is a horse, a circuit is a journey, and face-paint colors broadcast character, red for loyalty and white for treachery. Its supreme modern star was the dan master <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mei_Lanfang\">Mei Lanfang</span>, whose <b>1930 American</b> tour charmed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Charlie_Chaplin\">Charlie Chaplin</span> and whose 1935 Moscow performances helped inspire <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bertolt_Brecht\">Bertolt Brecht</span>'s theory of the alienation effect. Beneath the Peking style's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jinghu_(instrument)\">jinghu</span> fiddle thrives a continent of regional voices, from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cantonese_opera\">Cantonese opera</span> and the all-female <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yue_opera\">Yue opera</span> of Shaoxing to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan_opera\">Sichuan opera</span> with its lightning mask-switching art of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bian_lian\">bian lian</span>. The tradition bent to politics during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span>, when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Qing\">Jiang Qing</span> reduced the national stage for a decade to 8 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Revolutionary_opera\">revolutionary model works</span>. Recognition followed trauma, Kunqu opening <b>UNESCO's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Intangible_cultural_heritage\">intangible heritage</span> honors in 2001</b> with Cantonese and Peking opera inscribed in 2009 and 2010, while the Palme d'Or–winning film <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Farewell_My_Concubine_(film)\"><i>Farewell My Concubine</i></span> of 1993 carried the painted faces to the world even as the art now labors to win audiences younger than its melodies.","citation":"","answerText":"Chinese opera"},{"id":"cng-039","num":"三十九","category":"China · Geography","question":"A rugged upland of the southwest covering much of Yunnan and Guizhou, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is renowned for its dramatic karst scenery, deep valleys and great ethnic diversity.","answer":"Yunnan–Guizhou Plateau","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">云贵高原 ('Yunnan–Guizhou plateau')</span></div>","traditional":"雲貴高原","hanzi":"云贵高原","pinyin":"Yúnguì Gāoyuán","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Yúnguì Gāoyuán</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Yunnan–Guizhou Plateau</b> is one of China's 4 great plateaus, a rugged upland of roughly 500,000 square kilometers (190,000 sq mi) tilting from about 2,000 meters (6,600 ft) in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yunnan\">Yunnan</span> down to 1,000–1,500 meters (3,300–4,900 ft) in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guizhou\">Guizhou</span>, descending from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hengduan_Mountains\">Hengduan</span> ramparts of the Tibetan Plateau toward the southeastern hills. Its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Limestone\">limestone</span> heart forms the core of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South_China_Karst\">South China Karst</span>, inscribed as World Heritage <b>from 2007</b>, embracing the pinnacles of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stone_Forest\">Stone Forest</span>, the cone <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Karst\">karst</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Libo_County\">Libo</span>, cave chambers in Guizhou measured near 10.8 million cubic meters, the largest known on earth, and a natural sinkhole that <b>since 2016</b> has cradled the 500-meter (1,600 ft) dish of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five-hundred-meter_Aperture_Spherical_Telescope\">FAST telescope</span>. Great rivers entrench the surface, from the parallel gorges of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jinsha_River\">Jinsha</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mekong\">Mekong</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Salween_River\">Salween</span> in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Parallel_Rivers\">Three Parallel Rivers</span> reserve to the headwaters of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pearl_River\">Pearl River</span>, while the 77.8-meter (255 ft) <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huangguoshu_Waterfall\">Huangguoshu Waterfall</span></b> ranks as China's largest. Fault-basin lakes such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dian_Lake\">Dian</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Erhai\">Erhai</span> moderate a famously gentle climate, giving <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kunming\">Kunming</span> its title of Spring City and supporting biodiversity so rich that Yunnan alone harbors roughly half of China's plant and animal species, from the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yunnan_snub-nosed_monkey\">Yunnan snub-nosed monkey</span></b> to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Asian_elephant\">Asian elephants</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xishuangbanna_Dai_Autonomous_Prefecture\">Xishuangbanna</span>. Farmers answered the broken terrain with sculpture, most spectacularly the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Honghe_Hani_Rice_Terraces\">Honghe Hani Rice Terraces</span>, carved over some 1,300 years and <b>listed by UNESCO in 2013</b>. <br> <br> No region of China is more ethnically diverse, for Yunnan counts about 25 recognized minorities, including the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yi_people\">Yi</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bai_people\">Bai</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hani_people\">Hani</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dai_people\">Dai</span>, the matrilineal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mosuo\">Mosuo</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Naxi_people\">Naxi</span> with their pictographic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dongba_symbols\">Dongba script</span>, while Guizhou's valleys shelter the drum towers and silver finery of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Miao_people\">Miao</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dong_people\">Dong</span></b>. Indigenous states flourished early, from the bronze-casting <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dian_Kingdom\">Dian Kingdom</span> of the 2nd century BCE to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanzhao\">Nanzhao</span> in the 8th century and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dali_Kingdom\">Dali Kingdom</span> of 937–1253, which fell only when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kublai_Khan\">Kublai Khan</span> outflanked the Song across these highlands. For a millennium mule caravans on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tea_Horse_Road\">Tea Horse Road</span> exchanged compressed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pu'er_tea\">Pu'er tea</span> for Tibetan horses along cliff trails threading the gorges. During the Second World War some 200,000 laborers hacked out the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Burma_Road\">Burma Road</span> to Kunming in 1937–1938, the lifeline later defended from Yunnan airfields by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Flying_Tigers\">Flying Tigers</span>. Long synonymous with poverty and isolation, the plateau now leaps its own canyons, as Guizhou hosts data centers and nearly half of the world's highest bridges, crowned by the 565-meter (1,850 ft) <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Duge_Bridge\">Duge Bridge</span> and the 625-meter (2,050 ft) <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huajiang_Grand_Canyon_Bridge\">Huajiang Grand Canyon Bridge</span></b>, opened in 2025 as the tallest on earth.","citation":"","answerText":"Yunnan–Guizhou Plateau"},{"id":"cng-056","num":"五十六","category":"China · Geography","question":"Serving as the national capital and seat of the central government, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> contains the Forbidden City and has been an imperial capital for much of the past 8 centuries.","answer":"Beijing","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">北京 (Běijīng, 'northern capital')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"北京","pinyin":"Běijīng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Běijīng</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Northern Capital”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Beijing</b> is the capital of the People's Republic, a direct-administered municipality of 21.9 million people recorded in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2020_Chinese_census\"><b>2020 census</span></b> across 16,410 square kilometers (6,336 sq mi) at the northwestern corner of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"North_China_Plain\">North China Plain</span>, sheltered by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yan_Mountains\">Yan</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taihang_Mountains\">Taihang</span> ranges. Human presence reaches back some 700,000 years to the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peking_Man\">Peking Man</span></b> fossils of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhoukoudian\">Zhoukoudian</span>, and a walled city named Ji served as capital of the state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yan_(state)\">Yan</span> by the 11th century BCE. Its imperial career began when the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liao_dynasty\">Liao dynasty</span> made it a secondary capital in 938 and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jin_dynasty_(1115–1234)\">Jin</span> <b>their central capital in 1153</b>, after which the city sacked by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Genghis_Khan\">Genghis Khan</span> in 1215 rose again from 1267 as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khanbaliq\">Khanbaliq</span>, the Yuan capital of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kublai_Khan\">Kublai Khan</span> that dazzled <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marco_Polo\">Marco Polo</span>. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yongle_Emperor\">Yongle Emperor</span> fixed the pattern by transferring the <b>Ming capital here in 1421</b> after raising the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Forbidden_City\">Forbidden City</span> between 1406 and 1420, a 980-building palace of 72 hectares (180 acres) that remained the throne of Ming and Qing emperors and makes the city an imperial capital for most of the past 8 centuries. That legacy gives Beijing 8 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Heritage_Site\">World Heritage Sites</span>, more than any other city, including the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Temple_of_Heaven\">Temple of Heaven</span></b>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Summer_Palace\">Summer Palace</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_tombs\">Ming tombs</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Badaling\">Badaling</span> stretch of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Wall_of_China\">Great Wall</span>, and the 7.8-kilometer (4.8 mi) <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing_Central_Axis\">Central Axis</span> inscribed in 2024. <br> <br> Modern history has played out at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tiananmen\">Tiananmen</span>, where students launched the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"May_Fourth_Movement\">May Fourth Movement</span> in 1919, Mao Zedong delivered the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Proclamation_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">proclamation of the People's Republic</span></b> on 1 October 1949, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1989_Tiananmen_Square_protests_and_massacre\">1989 protests</span> were crushed by the army. The leadership now governs from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhongnanhai\">Zhongnanhai</span> beside the old palace, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_People's_Congress\">National People's Congress</span> convenes in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Hall_of_the_People\">Great Hall of the People</span>, and the surviving lanes of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hutong\">hutongs</span> and courtyard <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Siheyuan\">siheyuan</span> shelter old Beijing beneath the towers. The city is equally the national brain and boardroom, home to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peking_University\">Peking</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tsinghua_University\">Tsinghua</span> universities, the tech district of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhongguancun\">Zhongguancun</span>, and more headquarters of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fortune_Global_500\">Fortune Global 500</span> than any other city on earth. Spectacle has kept pace, as Beijing became the only city to host both the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2008_Summer_Olympics\">2008 Summer</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2022_Winter_Olympics\">2022 Winter Olympics</span>, opened the starfish-shaped <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing_Daxing_International_Airport\">Daxing airport</span></b> in 2019, and runs a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing_Subway\">subway</span> exceeding 800 kilometers (500 mi), among the world's longest. The capital has even tamed its notorious air, cutting fine-particle <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Particulates\">pollution</span> by roughly two-thirds between 2013 and 2023, while water piped north through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South–North_Water_Transfer_Project\">South–North Water Transfer Project</span> sustains a metropolis whose population planners cap at 23 million.","citation":"","answerText":"Beijing"},{"id":"cng-092","num":"九十二","category":"China · Geography","question":"One of the most widely dispersed minorities, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> are largely indistinguishable from the Han majority in language and appearance but are defined by their faith, and are most concentrated in the autonomous region of Ningxia.","answer":"Hui people","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">回族 (Huízú), from 回回 (Huíhui)</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"回族","pinyin":"Huízú","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Huízú</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Hui people</b> are China's Sinophone Muslim nationality, numbering 11.38 million in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2020_Chinese_census\"><b>2020</b> census</span> and the most widely dispersed of all minorities, with communities in nearly every county yet the greatest concentration in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ningxia\">Ningxia</span> Hui Autonomous Region created in 1958, followed by Gansu, Qinghai, Henan, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yunnan\">Yunnan</span>. Unlike other minorities they are defined by faith rather than language, speaking <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mandarin_Chinese\">Mandarin</span> or local dialects salted with Arabic and Persian loanwords and resembling the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Chinese\">Han</span> in most respects, while standing apart through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sunni_Islam\">Sunni</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hanafi\">Hanafi</span> practice of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Islam_in_China\">Islam in China</span>, the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Halal\">halal</span></b> discipline of \"pure and true\" food, and the white caps and headscarves of observant dress. Their origins lie with Arab and Persian merchants who settled the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span> and Song ports of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou\">Guangzhou</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Quanzhou\">Quanzhou</span>, massively reinforced under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan dynasty</span> by Central Asian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Semu\">semu</span> administrators such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sayyid_Ajjal_Shams_al-Din_Omar\">Sayyid Ajall Shams al-Din</span>, governor of Yunnan <b>until 1279</b>, whose soldier-settlers married local women and raised Chinese-speaking Muslim lineages. Integration deepened under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span>, which counted the great admiral <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zheng_He\">Zheng He</span>, a Yunnan Hui, among its servants, while mosques took Chinese temple form, as at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Mosque_of_Xi'an\">Great Mosque of Xi'an</span> and <b>Beijing's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Niujie_Mosque\">Niujie Mosque</span></b>, founded in 996. Devotional life grew its own landscape of old-teaching congregations, Sufi <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Menhuan\">menhuan</span> orders within <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sufism\">Sufism</span> such as the often-rebellious <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jahriyya\">Jahriyya</span>, and the 20th-century reformist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yihewani\">Yihewani</span>, with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Linxia_Hui_Autonomous_Prefecture\">Linxia</span> revered as the \"little Mecca\" of the northwest. <br> <br> Qing-era frictions exploded into 2 of the 19th century's bloodiest wars, <b>the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Panthay_Rebellion\">Panthay Rebellion</span> of 1856–1873</b>, in which <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Du_Wenxiu\">Du Wenxiu</span> ruled a sultanate from Dali before Yunnan lost perhaps a million people, and the northwestern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dungan_Revolt_(1862–1877)\">Dungan Revolt</span> of 1862–1877, whose millions of dead and fleeing survivors planted the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dungan_people\">Dungan people</span></b> across Central Asia. In the republican era the Muslim warlords of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ma_clique\">Ma clique</span>, led by figures like <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ma_Bufang\">Ma Bufang</span>, governed the northwest, and where the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span> classed the Hui as merely religious Han, the communists recognized them as a nationality, winning durable loyalty. The reform decades brought a halal economy and culinary ubiquity, as Hui-run <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lamian\">lamian</span> shops serving Lanzhou beef noodles spread to every Chinese city beside classics like Xi'an's <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangrou_paomo\">yangrou paomo</span></b>, while Hui scholars such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bai_Shouyi\">Bai Shouyi</span> wrote the community's history into the national story. Recent years have tested the accommodation, as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sinicization\">Sinicization</span> campaign stripped domes and Arabic signage from mosques and provoked standoffs at Weizhou in 2018 and in Yunnan in 2023, milder than the repression in Xinjiang yet a reminder that the Hui's 13-century balancing act, as the most Chinese of Muslims and the most Muslim of Chinese, continues under watchful eyes.","citation":"","answerText":"Hui people"},{"id":"cng-093","num":"九十三","category":"China · Geography","question":"Descendants of the steppe horsemen who once ruled all of China, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> still speak the Mongolian language and herd on the grasslands.","answer":"Mongols in China","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">蒙古族 (Měnggǔzú)</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"蒙古族","pinyin":"Měnggǔzú","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Měnggǔzú</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Mongols in China</b> are an ethnic group numbering around 6.3 million, more than live in independent <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongolia\">Mongolia</span></b> itself, descended from the steppe horsemen who under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Genghis_Khan\">Genghis Khan</span> once forged the largest contiguous land empire in history. Within <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> they form a minority of barely 0.4 percent of the national population, the bulk of them concentrated in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Inner_Mongolia\">Inner Mongolia</span></b> Autonomous Region, with sizeable communities in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liaoning\">Liaoning</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinjiang\">Xinjiang</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongghul\">Tu</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dongxiang_people\">Dongxiang</span> kin-groups counted separately. Many still speak the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongolian_language\">Mongolian language</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongolic_languages\">Mongolic family</span>, and in a notable divergence from the republic to the north, which adopted the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cyrillic_script\">Cyrillic</span> alphabet, the Mongols of China still write it in the vertical <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongolian_script\">traditional script</span> descended from the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Old_Uyghur_alphabet\">Old Uyghur alphabet</span></b>. Their pastoral heritage of herding sheep, horses, and camels across the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Steppe\">grasslands</span> survives in the felt tents called <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yurt\">ger</span>, the summer festival of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Naadam\">Naadam</span> with its “three manly games” of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongolian_wrestling\">wrestling</span>, archery, and horse racing, the long-song and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khoomei\">throat-singing</span> traditions, and a diet of mutton and dairy. Religion blends the indigenous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tengrism\">Tengri</span> sky-worship and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shamanism\">shamanism</span> with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_Buddhism\">Tibetan Buddhism</span> embraced en masse from the 16th century, when the title <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dalai_Lama\">Dalai Lama</span> was itself conferred by the Mongol ruler <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Altan_Khan\">Altan Khan</span>. <br> <br> The Mongols burst onto the world stage when Genghis Khan united <b>the steppe tribes in 1206</b>, and his grandson <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kublai_Khan\">Kublai Khan</span> completed the conquest of China, founding the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan dynasty</span> in 1271 that ruled the whole country until its expulsion <b>by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span> in 1368</b>. Driven back to the steppe, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Yuan\">Northern Yuan</span> and its successors splintered into rival confederations, the eastern groups gradually submitting to the rising Manchu <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> through the 17th century while the western <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dzungar_Khanate\">Dzungars</span> were annihilated in the 1750s. Under the Qing the Mongol lands were partitioned into \"inner\" and \"outer\" zones and organised into the banner-and-league system that still shapes Inner Mongolia’s map, even as Han farmers pushed steadily onto the pastures. When the dynasty <b>fell in 1911 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Outer_Mongolia\">Outer Mongolia</span></b> broke away to become today’s independent state, but the inner territories remained tied to China, and after a brief Japanese-sponsored regime under Prince <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Demchugdongrub\">Demchugdongrub</span>, the Communists established the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Inner_Mongolia_Autonomous_Region\">Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region</span></b> in 1947, the earliest of China’s autonomous regions. Decades of Han migration have since made the Mongols a small minority of about a sixth in their own region, and though herding, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Genghis_Khan_Mausoleum\">cult of Genghis Khan</span>, and a vibrant music scene endure, recent moves to reduce <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2020_Inner_Mongolia_protests\">Mongolian-language instruction</span> in schools sparked rare public protests in 2020 over the future of the mother tongue.","citation":"","answerText":"Mongols in China"},{"id":"cnh-056","num":"五十六","category":"China · History","question":"Reunifying China in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> and presiding over a commercial and technological revolution — with the world's first paper money, widespread printing and gunpowder weapons — the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> prized civilian scholar-officials over generals and refined Neo-Confucianism, yet repeatedly lost ground to northern nomads.","answer":"Song dynasty","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">&lt;b&gt;960&lt;/b&gt;–&lt;b&gt;1279&lt;/b&gt;</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"宋朝","pinyin":"Sòng cháo","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Sòng cháo</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Song dynasty</b> was an imperial dynasty founded in 960 by <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Taizu_of_Song\">Emperor Taizu</span></b>, who seized the throne from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Later_Zhou\">Later Zhou</span> and within two decades reunified most of China, bringing the turbulent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five_Dynasties_and_Ten_Kingdoms_period\">Five Dynasties and Ten Kingdoms</span> period to a close. Determined to prevent the warlordism that had destroyed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span>, its founders subordinated the military to a civil administration staffed by scholars chosen through a greatly expanded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examination</span> system, and the court nurtured a revival of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> philosophy that the scholar <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_Xi\">Zhu Xi</span> would later forge into a lasting orthodoxy. Beneath this civilian order the economy underwent a commercial revolution, as a monetized, market-driven society arose around teeming cities like the capital <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kaifeng\">Kaifeng</span>, whose population neared a million, supported by a realm that swelled past 100 million inhabitants and by foundries reckoned by some estimates to have produced as much as 125,000 tonnes (138,000 tons) of iron a year by the 1070s. The age generated a cascade of innovations: it produced the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiaozi_(currency)\">jiaozi</span>, the world's first government-issued <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Banknote\">paper money</span>, first circulated in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan\">Sichuan</span> in the early 11th century, saw <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Woodblock_printing\">woodblock printing</span> spread alongside the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Movable_type\">movable type</span> <b>devised by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bi_Sheng\">Bi Sheng</span> around 1040</b>, harnessed the magnetic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Compass\">compass</span> for seafaring, and fielded gunpowder armaments such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fire_lance\">fire lance</span>. Learning flourished in step with commerce, producing the polymath <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shen_Kuo\">Shen Kuo</span>, whose <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dream_Pool_Essays\"><i>Dream Pool Essays</i></span> of 1088 ranged across science and technology, the historian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Guang\">Sima Guang</span>, who compiled the monumental <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zizhi_Tongjian\"><i>Zizhi Tongjian</i></span></b>, the reform minister <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Anshi\">Wang Anshi</span>, and the great poet <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Su_Shi\">Su Shi</span>.<br> <br>For all its wealth and sophistication, the Song proved chronically unable to match the cavalry powers of the steppe, and it never recovered the northern frontier lands, including the strategic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sixteen_Prefectures\">Sixteen Prefectures</span>, that lay in the hands of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khitan_people\">Khitan</span>-led <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liao_dynasty\">Liao dynasty</span>. By the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chanyuan_Treaty\">Treaty of Chanyuan</span></b> of 1005 the dynasty bought peace with the Liao by paying an annual tribute of 100,000 taels of silver and 200,000 bolts of silk, and it entered comparable arrangements with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tangut_people\">Tangut</span> state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Western_Xia\">Western Xia</span> on its northwestern flank. Disaster followed when the Song joined the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jurchen_people\">Jurchen</span>-led <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jin_dynasty_(1115–1234)\">Jin dynasty</span> in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Alliance_Conducted_at_Sea\">alliance</span> that destroyed the Liao, only to be turned upon by their erstwhile allies, who stormed Kaifeng in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jingkang_Incident\">Jingkang Incident</span></b> of 1127 and carried off the retired emperor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Huizong_of_Song\">Huizong</span> and his son <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Qinzong_of_Song\">Qinzong</span> into captivity, extinguishing the Northern Song. The court fled south and re-established itself at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hangzhou\">Hangzhou</span>, where the Southern Song (1127–1279) presided over a brilliant maritime and cultural flowering, its great port of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Quanzhou\">Quanzhou</span> trading across the Indian Ocean, even as the celebrated general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yue_Fei\">Yue Fei</span> waged his campaigns to recover the lost north against the Jin. The dynasty's long resistance ended only when the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongols\">Mongols</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kublai_Khan\">Kublai Khan</span>, having founded the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan dynasty</span>, annihilated the last Song loyalists at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Yamen\">Battle of Yamen</span> in 1279, closing a remarkable era that had lasted 319 years.","citation":"","answerText":"Song dynasty"},{"id":"cnh-071","num":"七十一","category":"China · History","question":"A decisive naval engagement of <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> off the southern coast, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> ended the Southern Song when, with defeat certain, a loyal official leapt into the sea clutching the boy emperor, completing the Mongol conquest and ushering in the Yuan.","answer":"Battle of Yamen","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1279</span></div>","traditional":"崖門戰役","hanzi":"崖门战役","pinyin":"Yámén zhànyì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Yámén zhànyì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Battle of Yamen</b>, also called the <b>Battle of Yashan</b>, was the <b>decisive naval engagement of 1279</b>, fought in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pearl_River_Delta\">Pearl River Delta</span></b> on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South_China_Sea\">South China Sea</span> off the coast of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangdong\">Guangdong</span>, that destroyed the last remnant of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song dynasty</span> and completed the Mongol conquest of China. The conquest had advanced by grim stages: the Great Khan <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Möngke_Khan\">Möngke</span> died while warring <b>on the Song in 1259</b>, his brother <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kublai_Khan\">Kublai Khan</span> then broke the dynasty's defenses along the middle <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span> by capturing the fortress of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Xiangyang\">Xiangyang</span> in 1273, and in 1276 his general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bayan_of_the_Baarin\">Bayan</span> took the capital of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hangzhou\">Lin'an</span>, where the child <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Gong_of_Song\">Emperor Gong</span> surrendered. A band of irreconcilable loyalists—the chancellor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lu_Xiufu\">Lu Xiufu</span>, <b>the admiral <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Shijie\">Zhang Shijie</span></b>, and the scholar-general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wen_Tianxiang\">Wen Tianxiang</span>—fought on, proclaiming at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fuzhou\">Fuzhou</span> the boy <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Duanzong_of_Song\">Emperor Duanzong</span>, who died in 1278, and then his seven-year-old half-brother <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhao_Bing\">Zhao Bing</span>, as the refugee court fled ever farther south by sea. By 1279 this fugitive court had gathered at the strait of Yamen near modern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiangmen\">Jiangmen</span>, southwest of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou\">Guangzhou</span>, where it mustered a floating refuge of perhaps a thousand <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Junk_(ship)\">war junks</span> bearing some 200,000 soldiers, officials, and civilians, though the earlier defection of the maritime magnate <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pu_Shougeng\">Pu Shougeng</span></b> at the great port of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Quanzhou\">Quanzhou</span> had already gutted Song sea power. The Yuan admiral <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Hongfan\">Zhang Hongfan</span> sealed off the inlet and severed its fresh water, leaving the trapped crews to sicken on brine, while Zhang Shijie fatefully chained his ships together around the imperial vessel—surrendering all mobility—so that when the attackers struck with the tide on 19 March 1279 the immobilized fleet was swiftly overwhelmed.<br> <br>With annihilation certain, the Grand Councilor Lu Xiufu would not let the child sovereign be taken alive, and—having bound the dynasty's <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heirloom_Seal_of_the_Realm\">imperial seal</span></b> to his own waist and arrayed the boy in robes of state—he hoisted the young emperor onto his back and plunged into the sea, an example soon followed by the mass self-drowning of consorts, ministers, and troops. The dynastic history relates that more than 100,000 corpses afterward drifted upon the waves, and the handful who escaped fared scarcely better, for Zhang Shijie perished in a storm within weeks, while the captured Wen Tianxiang, having spurned every inducement to change sides, was put to death at the Yuan <b>capital of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khanbaliq\">Khanbaliq</span> in 1283</b> and venerated ever after as the supreme exemplar of loyalty. The disaster snuffed out a dynasty that had ruled for 319 years since 960 and, more momentously still, marked the first occasion on which the whole of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_proper\">China proper</span> passed under the dominion of a non-<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Chinese\">Han</span> people, the steppe horsemen of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongol_Empire\">Mongol Empire</span>. Yet the fallen Song had presided over a golden age of Chinese civilization—an era of flourishing maritime trade and the world's first government-issued paper <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiaozi_(currency)\">money</span>, of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gunpowder\">gunpowder</span> weaponry and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Movable_type\">movable-type printing</span>, of a meritocratic bureaucracy recruited through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examinations</span>, and of the intellectual revival later called <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Neo-Confucianism\">Neo-Confucianism</span>. Remembered ever since as the ultimate emblem of both dynastic ruin and unyielding devotion, the battle gave rise to the much-debated later saying that \"after Yashan there is no more China\"—a lament, contested by modern historians, for a vanished classical order—even as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mandate_of_Heaven\">Mandate of Heaven</span> passed to a Mongol throne that, for all the savagery of its triumph, briefly drew China into the trans-Eurasian peace of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pax_Mongolica\">Pax Mongolica</span> before holding the realm for a mere 89 years.","citation":"","answerText":"Battle of Yamen"},{"id":"cnh-074","num":"七十四","category":"China · History","question":"Born a destitute peasant who survived famine as a wandering monk before rising through the rebellion, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> drove out the Mongols, ruled with autocratic ferocity, and abolished the post of chancellor to concentrate power in his own hands.","answer":"Hongwu Emperor","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">October 21, 1328</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">June 24, 1398</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"洪武","pinyin":"Hóngwǔ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Hóngwǔ</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“vastly martial”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Hongwu Emperor</b> was the <b>founder of China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming dynasty</span></b> and one of only a handful of rulers in Chinese history to ascend from genuine peasant poverty to the imperial throne. Born to a destitute farming family in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fengyang_County\">Fengyang</span> in what is now <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anhui\">Anhui</span> province, he was <b>orphaned in 1344</b> when famine and plague carried off most of his relatives, after which he survived by entering a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Buddhist_monasticism\">Buddhist monastery</span> and then roaming the countryside as a mendicant beggar. Around 1352 he joined the anti-Mongol <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Red_Turban_Rebellion\">Red Turban Rebellion</span> under the warlord <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guo_Zixing\">Guo Zixing</span>, whose adopted daughter, the future <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empress_Ma_(Hongwu)\">Empress Ma</span>, he married, and he rose so <b>quickly that by 1356</b> he had seized <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span> as the base of his growing movement. He then destroyed his chief rivals for control of the south, annihilating the fleet of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Youliang\">Chen Youliang</span> at <b>the colossal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Lake_Poyang\">Battle of Lake Poyang</span> in 1363</b>, an engagement frequently ranked among the largest naval battles in history, before eliminating <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Shicheng\">Zhang Shicheng</span> at Suzhou in 1367. Proclaiming the Ming dynasty and the Hongwu era in 1368, he sent the generals <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xu_Da\">Xu Da</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chang_Yuchun\">Chang Yuchun</span></b> to expel the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan</span> from their capital at Dadu, modern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>, driving the Mongol court back onto the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongolian_Plateau\">steppe</span> as the rump <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Yuan\">Northern Yuan</span>. <br> <br> As emperor he ruled with notorious severity, and in 1380, after <b>charging his chancellor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Weiyong\">Hu Weiyong</span></b> with treason, he permanently abolished the ancient office of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Grand_chancellor_(China)\">chancellor</span> and took direct command of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Six_Ministries\">Six Ministries</span> of government. The Hu Weiyong affair, together with the later treason case of <b>the general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lan_Yu_(general)\">Lan Yu</span></b>, unleashed sweeping purges that, by many estimates, claimed tens of thousands of lives, and he institutionalized the surveillance of officialdom through the secret-police corps known as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jinyiwei\">Jinyiwei</span>. He nonetheless laid durable administrative foundations, promulgating the comprehensive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Ming_Code\">Great Ming Code</span>, reorganizing rural society and taxation through detailed household and land registers, reviving an agriculture devastated by decades of war, and imposing a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Haijin\">maritime prohibition</span> on private overseas commerce. Steeped in a conservative <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> vision of a self-sufficient agrarian state, he distrusted merchants and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eunuch\">eunuchs</span> and issued ancestral injunctions intended to bind his heirs, consciously recalling the precedent of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Bang\">Liu Bang</span>, the peasant founder of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span>. When his heir apparent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_Biao\">Zhu Biao</span> died in 1392 he designated a grandson, the future <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jianwen_Emperor\">Jianwen Emperor</span>, as his successor, and after his own death in 1398 and entombment at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_Xiaoling_Mausoleum\">Ming Xiaoling Mausoleum</span> that fragile arrangement collapsed into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jingnan_campaign\">Jingnan campaign</span>, a civil war that elevated his son the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yongle_Emperor\">Yongle Emperor</span> to a throne his dynasty would retain until 1644.","citation":"","answerText":"Hongwu Emperor"},{"id":"cnh-073","num":"七十三","category":"China · History","question":"A wave of uprisings beginning in the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>s, fuelled by famine, flooding of the Yellow River and millenarian White Lotus beliefs, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> produced the rebel leader who would found the next dynasty.","answer":"Red Turban Rebellion","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">&lt;b&gt;1351&lt;/b&gt;–&lt;b&gt;1368&lt;/b&gt;</span></div>","traditional":"紅巾起義","hanzi":"红巾起义","pinyin":"Hóngjīn qǐyì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Hóngjīn qǐyì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Red Turban Rebellion</b> was a vast wave of popular uprisings against the Mongol <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan dynasty</span> that ultimately toppled it and brought to power the founder of the succeeding <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming dynasty</span>. Its outbreak was driven by a convergence of catastrophes, as repeated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Famine\">famines</span> and the disastrous flooding of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_River\">Yellow River</span> coincided with ruinous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hyperinflation\">hyperinflation</span> of the Yuan's paper currency and deep resentment of Mongol rule among the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Chinese\">Han Chinese</span> majority. The immediate spark came around 1351, when the court of the last Yuan emperor, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Toghon_Temür\">Toghon Temür</span></b>, conscripted some 150,000 labourers into brutal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Corvée\">corvée</span> service to redirect the flooded river, concentrating a vast body of desperate and embittered men along its banks. The revolt drew its fervour from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Millenarianism\">millenarian</span> religion, above all the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"White_Lotus\">White Lotus</span> societies, which fused <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pure_Land_Buddhism\">Buddhist</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manichaeism\">Manichaean</span> ideas into a prophecy that the future Buddha <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maitreya\">Maitreya</span> would descend to overthrow a corrupt age and usher in a new era of light. In 1351 the preacher <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Shantong\">Han Shantong</span></b> and his lieutenant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Futong\">Liu Futong</span> raised the standard of revolt, their followers marked out by the red turbans that gave the movement its name, and after Han Shantong's capture and execution they installed his son <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Lin'er\">Han Lin'er</span> as the figurehead emperor of a restored <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song</span> dynasty. <br> <br> The rising spread rapidly across the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span> valley and the northern plains, splintering into rival Red Turban factions, among them the southern movement of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xu_Shouhui\">Xu Shouhui</span></b>, while northern bands ranged so far as to sack the Yuan summer capital of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shangdu\">Shangdu</span>. It was within this turmoil that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hongwu_Emperor\">Zhu Yuanzhang</span>, an orphaned former Buddhist novice of peasant stock from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anhui\">Anhui</span>, joined a Red Turban band under <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guo_Zixing\">Guo Zixing</span> in 1352</b> and rose swiftly through its ranks to command his own army from a base at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span>. As the rebel leaders turned on one another, Zhu annihilated the fleet of his greatest rival, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Youliang\">Chen Youliang</span>, at the colossal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Lake_Poyang\">Battle of Lake Poyang</span> in 1363, one of the largest naval engagements in history. He went on to crush the <b>wealthy warlord <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Shicheng\">Zhang Shicheng</span></b>, who held the rich lower-Yangtze region around <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Suzhou\">Suzhou</span>, and the puppet emperor Han Lin'er conveniently drowned in 1366 while in Zhu's custody, removing the last rival claim to leadership of the cause. In 1368 Zhu proclaimed himself the Hongwu Emperor and founder of the Ming, claiming the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mandate_of_Heaven\">Mandate of Heaven</span>, and his armies drove the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongols\">Mongols</span> out of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khanbaliq\">Dadu</span> and back onto the steppe, where the shattered dynasty lingered as the rump <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Yuan\">Northern Yuan</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Red Turban Rebellion"},{"id":"cnh-077","num":"七十七","category":"China · History","question":"Seizing the throne from his nephew in a bloody civil war, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> moved the capital to Beijing and built the Forbidden City, commissioned a colossal encyclopedia, and dispatched grand naval expeditions across the seas.","answer":"Yongle Emperor","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1360</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1424</span></div>","traditional":"永樂帝","hanzi":"永乐帝","pinyin":"Yǒnglè dì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Yǒnglè dì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Yongle Emperor</b> was the third emperor of the Ming dynasty, the fourth son of the dynasty's founder, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hongwu_Emperor\">Hongwu Emperor</span>, who reigned <b>from 1402</b> to 1424 under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_era_name\">era name</span> Yongle and is honoured by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Temple_name\">temple name</span> Chengzu. Originally enfeoffed as the Prince of Yan and based at Beiping, the future <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>, he spent years defending the northern frontier against the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongols\">Mongols</span>, but <b>on Hongwu's death in 1398</b> the throne passed over him to his young nephew, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jianwen_Emperor\">Jianwen Emperor</span>. When the new emperor began stripping the imperial princes of their power, Zhu Di rose in armed revolt in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jingnan_campaign\">Jingnan Campaign</span> of 1399–1402, storming the capital at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span>, where the palace burned and his nephew vanished without trace, after which the victor purged the defeated faction with ferocity, notably executing the scholar <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fang_Xiaoru\">Fang Xiaoru</span> along with his entire kin. Distrusting the southern capital, he resolved to rule from Beijing, raising there <b>between 1406</b> and 1420 the vast palace complex of the Forbidden City—a labour said to have employed up to a million workers—reopening the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Grand_Canal_(China)\">Grand Canal</span> to ship southern grain northward, and in 1421 formally proclaiming the northern city his imperial capital. His court also sponsored prodigious scholarship and reorganized government, compiling the enormous <i>Yongle Encyclopedia</i>—completed in 1408 in some 11,000 volumes by more than 2,000 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Scholar-official\">scholars</span>—while he leaned heavily on palace <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eunuch\">eunuchs</span>, created the advisory <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Grand_Secretariat\">Grand Secretariat</span>, and in 1420 established the eunuch-run <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eastern_Depot\">Eastern Depot</span></b> as a secret police.<br> <br>His most celebrated undertaking was the series of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_treasure_voyages\">treasure voyages</span>, six of them launched during his reign from 1405 under the Muslim eunuch admiral <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zheng_He\">Zheng He</span>, whose armadas of some 300 vessels and 27,000 men ranged across the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South_China_Sea\">South China Sea</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Indian_Ocean\">Indian Ocean</span> in an unrivalled projection of maritime power. These towering <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_treasure_ship\">treasure ships</span></b> reached <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sri_Lanka\">Ceylon</span>, the harbours of Arabia, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Swahili_coast\">Swahili coast</span> of East Africa, returning laden with tribute and curiosities, most famously a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Giraffe\">giraffe</span> that the astonished court greeted as the auspicious <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qilin\">qilin</span>. On land he was no less ambitious, personally leading five campaigns against the Mongols of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Yuan\">Northern Yuan</span> across the steppe and annexing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Đại_Việt\">Đại Việt</span> as a Ming province in 1406–1407—a conquest the rebel <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lê_Lợi\">Lê Lợi</span> would later undo—while the death of the would-be conqueror <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Timur\">Timur</span></b> in 1405 spared the empire a threatened assault from his <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Timurid_Empire\">Timurid</span> realm. Diplomacy flourished alongside conquest, as the throne exchanged embassies across Asia and drew neighbours such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joseon\">Joseon</span> Korea into China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tributary_system_of_China\">tributary</span> order, though the staggering expense of palaces, fleets, and armies steadily drained the imperial treasury. The emperor died in 1424 while returning from his final expedition into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongolia\">Mongolia</span> and was entombed at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_tombs\">Ming tombs</span> north of Beijing, leaving the throne to his son the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hongxi_Emperor\">Hongxi Emperor</span></b> and soon his grandson the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xuande_Emperor\">Xuande Emperor</span>, under whom the great voyages were curtailed and then abandoned, even as his reign endured in memory as the most expansive and dynamic age of the Ming.","citation":"","answerText":"Yongle Emperor"},{"id":"cnh-075","num":"七十五","category":"China · History","question":"Ruling from <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> to <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> after expelling the Mongols, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> oversaw a flourishing of porcelain and vernacular novels before falling to rebellion and invasion.","answer":"Ming dynasty","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">&lt;b&gt;1368&lt;/b&gt;–&lt;b&gt;1644&lt;/b&gt;</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"明朝","pinyin":"Míng cháo","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Míng cháo</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Ming dynasty</b> was the imperial dynasty that ruled China for 276 years after expelling the Mongol <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan dynasty</span>, and it was the last dynasty governed by the ethnic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Chinese\">Han Chinese</span> before the Manchu conquest. It was founded by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hongwu_Emperor\">Zhu Yuanzhang</span>, a destitute orphan and former Buddhist novice who rose through the anti-Mongol <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Red_Turban_Rebellion\">Red Turban Rebellion</span></b> to proclaim himself the Hongwu Emperor at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span> in 1368, thereafter ruling as an autocrat who abolished the office of chancellor to concentrate power in the throne. His son the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yongle_Emperor\">Yongle Emperor</span> seized the throne from a nephew in a bloody civil war and moved the capital north to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>, where <b>between 1406</b> and 1420 he raised the vast palace complex of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Forbidden_City\">Forbidden City</span>, with its roughly 980 buildings spread across some 72 hectares (180 acres). Under Yongle the dynasty projected its power abroad through the seven great <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_treasure_voyages\">treasure voyages</span> of the admiral <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zheng_He\">Zheng He</span> between 1405 and 1433, whose fleets of some 300 vessels and 27,000 men reached as far as Arabia and the East African coast, while scholars compiled the colossal <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yongle_Encyclopedia\"><i>Yongle Encyclopedia</i></span></b> of over 11,000 volumes. To guard against renewed nomadic incursions from the steppe, later Ming emperors rebuilt the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Wall_of_China\">Great Wall</span> in brick and stone along its northern frontier, and the surviving Ming sections stretch for roughly 8,850 kilometres (5,500 mi), forming the bulk of the wall seen by visitors today. <br> <br> The Ming economy grew increasingly commercialised and monetised, as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Single_whip_law\">Single Whip reform</span></b> consolidated taxes into payments of silver drawn from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manila_galleon\">Manila galleon</span> trade with Spanish America, and New World crops introduced by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Columbian_exchange\">Columbian Exchange</span> helped the population swell to perhaps 150 million or more by the dynasty's final century. Its craftsmen achieved international renown above all for porcelain, the imperial kilns at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jingdezhen\">Jingdezhen</span> producing the cobalt <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Blue_and_white_pottery\">blue-and-white wares</span></b> that were exported in enormous quantities across Asia and, later, to Europe. The period likewise witnessed the maturing of the Chinese vernacular novel, producing enduring classics such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Water_Margin\"><i>Water Margin</i></span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Romance_of_the_Three_Kingdoms\"><i>Romance of the Three Kingdoms</i></span>, and the fantastical <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Journey_to_the_West\"><i>Journey to the West</i></span>. Intellectual and bureaucratic life centred on a revived <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Neo-Confucianism\">Neo-Confucianism</span>, challenged by the introspective philosophy of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Yangming\">Wang Yangming</span>, and on a rigorous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">civil-service examination</span> in which the rigid <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight-legged_essay\">eight-legged essay</span> became the prescribed literary form. By the early 17th century, however, court factionalism, ruinous military costs, and the famines of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Little_Ice_Age\">Little Ice Age</span> had gravely weakened the state, and in 1644 the rebel <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Zicheng\">Li Zicheng</span> seized Beijing, prompting the last <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chongzhen_Emperor\">Chongzhen Emperor</span> to hang himself, after which the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_people\">Manchus</span>, admitted through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanhai_Pass\">Shanhai Pass</span> by the turncoat general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Sangui\">Wu Sangui</span>, swept south to found the succeeding <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Ming dynasty"},{"id":"cnh-076","num":"七十六","category":"China · History","question":"A policy enforced at times by the Ming that banned private maritime trade and coastal settlement, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was meant to curb piracy but pushed many merchants into the very pirate activity it sought to stop, and left the coast facing inward after the great voyages ended.","answer":"Haijin","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">海禁 (hǎijìn, 'sea ban')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"海禁","pinyin":"Hǎijìn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Hǎijìn</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“sea ban”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Haijin</b> was a <b>series of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Isolationism\">isolationist</span></b> policies, enforced at intervals by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span> and later the early <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span>, that prohibited private maritime trade and restricted coastal settlement and seafaring. The policy was first imposed by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hongwu_Emperor\">Hongwu Emperor</span> <b>from around 1371</b>, partly to deny support to coastal pirates and the maritime followers of his defeated rival <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fang_Guozhen\">Fang Guozhen</span></b>, and partly to channel all foreign commerce through the state-controlled <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tributary_system_of_China\">tributary system</span>. So sweeping was the prohibition that subjects were at times forbidden to put a single plank to sea, yet by criminalising legitimate <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Smuggling\">trade</span></b> the ban drove countless coastal merchants and fishermen into the very <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Piracy\">piracy</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wokou\">wokou</span> raiding it was meant to suppress. The restriction on private shipping coexisted with grand state-sponsored seafaring, for under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yongle_Emperor\">Yongle Emperor</span> the admiral <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zheng_He\">Zheng He</span> led the spectacular <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_treasure_voyages\">treasure voyages</span> across the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Indian_Ocean\">Indian Ocean</span> <b>between 1405</b> and 1433. When those voyages were abruptly halted after 1433, official Chinese seafaring ceased while the haijin endured, leaving a once outward-looking maritime power turned increasingly inward and once-great ports such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Quanzhou\">Quanzhou</span> to wither as the great ocean-going <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Junk_(ship)\">junks</span> fell idle. <br> <br> The ban grew harshest during the 16th-century pirate crisis under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiajing_Emperor\">Jiajing Emperor</span>, especially after a bloody clash between rival <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japan\">Japanese</span> tribute <b>missions at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ningbo\">Ningbo</span> in 1523</b> prompted a further tightening of maritime controls. Recognising at last that prohibition had bred the very disorder it opposed, the court of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Longqing_Emperor\">Longqing Emperor</span> lifted most of the ban in 1567, legalising private overseas trade through a designated port in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fujian\">Fujian</span> and so draining the pirate economy of its recruits. The reopening tied the Chinese coast into a booming global commerce, drawing in vast quantities of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silver\">silver</span> carried by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manila_galleon\">Manila galleons</span> from Spanish America in exchange for silk and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_export_porcelain\">porcelain</span>. The Manchu conquerors revived the policy in even harsher form, ordering the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Clearance\">Great Clearance</span></b> of 1661, which forcibly evacuated the southeastern coastline inland by tens of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_(unit)\">li</span> to starve out the Ming loyalist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kingdom_of_Tungning\">Kingdom of Tungning</span> that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Koxinga\">Koxinga</span> had founded on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span>. Only after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kangxi_Emperor\">Kangxi Emperor</span> conquered Taiwan in 1683 was the coast resettled and maritime trade reopened, though European commerce was later again funnelled through the single port of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou\">Canton</span> under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Canton_System\">Canton System</span>, an enduring insularity that historians often contrast with the outward thrust of Europe's contemporaneous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Age_of_Discovery\">Age of Discovery</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Haijin"},{"id":"cnh-080","num":"八十","category":"China · History","question":"A rigid and highly stylised composition with 8 prescribed sections that candidates had to master to pass the civil-service examinations, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> drilled scholars in the Confucian classics but was later blamed for stifling original and practical thought.","answer":"Eight-legged essay","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">八股文 ('eight-legged essay'), for its eight prescribed parts</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"八股文","pinyin":"bāgǔwén","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">bāgǔwén</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>eight-legged essay</b> was a rigidly stylized prose form that served as the prescribed format for answering questions in the Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examinations</span> under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> dynasties. Its name derived from the 4 pairs of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Antithesis\">antithetical</span> passages of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Parallel_prose\">parallel prose</span></b>—the famous 8 \"legs\"—at the core of the essay, framed by a fixed sequence of opening, transitional, and concluding sections. Candidates were required to expound a brief quotation drawn from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Books_and_Five_Classics\">Four Books and Five Classics</span>, such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Analects\">Analects</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mencius\">Mencius</span>, interpreting it strictly according to the orthodox <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Neo-Confucianism\">Neo-Confucian</span> commentaries of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_Xi\">Zhu Xi</span> and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cheng–Zhu_school\">Cheng–Zhu school</span></b>. A defining rule obliged the writer to compose entirely \"in the voice of the sage,\" ventriloquizing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucius\">Confucius</span> or the ancient worthies rather than voicing any personal opinion, and the whole essay was held to a strict length, capped in the Qing at roughly 700 characters of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Classical_Chinese\">Classical Chinese</span>. Growing out of the classics-exegesis essays promoted under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song dynasty</span> by the reformer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Anshi\">Wang Anshi</span>, the form crystallized in the late 15th century under the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chenghua_Emperor\">Chenghua Emperor</span></b>, and for more than 400 years mastery of it was indispensable to anyone climbing from the provincial <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Juren\">juren</span> degree to the coveted <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jinshi\">jinshi</span> and entry into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Scholar-official\">scholar-official</span> elite and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hanlin_Academy\">Hanlin Academy</span>. <br> <br> Although the discipline instilled deep familiarity with the canonical texts and a shared elite culture, the eight-legged essay was widely condemned, then and since, for fostering rote formalism while stifling originality, practical knowledge, and independent thought. The <b>Ming scholar <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gu_Yanwu\">Gu Yanwu</span></b> famously charged that its intellectual harm rivaled that of the notorious <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Burning_of_books_and_burying_of_scholars\">burning of the books</span> under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_dynasty\">Qin dynasty</span>, and the examination culture it dominated was savagely satirized in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Jingzi\">Wu Jingzi</span>'s <b>celebrated novel <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Scholars_(novel)\"><i>The Scholars</i></span></b>. Generations of aspirants nonetheless devoted years, often decades, to drilling its rigid conventions and memorizing thousands of model essays, since success was the surest path to office, wealth, and social prestige in late imperial China. Reformers finally moved against it <b>during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hundred_Days'_Reform\">Hundred Days' Reform</span> of 1898</b>, when the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangxu_Emperor\">Guangxu Emperor</span>, prompted by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kang_Youwei\">Kang Youwei</span>, abolished the form, though the coup of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empress_Dowager_Cixi\">Empress Dowager Cixi</span> soon restored it. The entire examination system was finally <b>abolished in 1905</b> on the urging of statesmen such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_Shikai\">Yuan Shikai</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Zhidong\">Zhang Zhidong</span>, yet the term lived on as a byword for hollow, formulaic prose, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>'s 1942 essay <i>Oppose Stereotyped Party Writing</i> would later assail the dogmatic \"party eight-legged\" writing of his own movement.","citation":"","answerText":"Eight-legged essay"},{"id":"cnh-081","num":"八十一","category":"China · History","question":"Bands of raiders — despite a name implying they were all Japanese, in fact often led by Chinese — the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> ravaged the southern coast in the 16th century, their depredations worsened by the Ming ban on maritime trade.","answer":"Wokou","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">倭寇 (Wōkòu, 'Japanese pirates')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"倭寇","pinyin":"Wōkòu","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Wōkòu</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Japanese pirates”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Wokou</b> were <b>bands of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Piracy\">pirates</span></b> and armed smugglers who raided the coasts of China, Korea, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japan\">Japan</span> around the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"East_China_Sea\">East China Sea</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South_China_Sea\">South China Sea</span> from the 13th to the 16th century. An earlier wave, most active in the 14th century and dominated by raiders from the Japanese islands of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tsushima_Island\">Tsushima</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kyushu\">Kyushu</span>, fell heavily upon the Korean kingdoms of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Goryeo\">Goryeo</span> and early <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joseon\">Joseon</span> as well as the Chinese coast. The far larger second wave struck the southern Chinese provinces of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhejiang\">Zhejiang</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fujian\">Fujian</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangdong\">Guangdong</span> during the 16th century, and despite the term's implication of Japanese authorship, Ming officials themselves reckoned that perhaps seven in ten of these raiders were in fact Chinese. Their depredations were greatly aggravated by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span> policy of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Haijin\">haijin</span>, a prohibition on private overseas commerce that criminalised the livelihoods of coastal merchants and drove once-legitimate <b>trading networks into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Smuggling\">smuggling</span></b> and armed raiding. This wave reached its destructive climax in the 1550s during the long reign of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiajing_Emperor\">Jiajing Emperor</span>, when, in the wake of a violent clash between rival Japanese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tributary_system_of_China\">tribute missions</span> at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ningbo\">Ningbo</span>, large fleets penetrated deep into the wealthy <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiangnan\">Jiangnan</span> region. <br> <br> The most formidable of the raiders were often Chinese smuggler-chieftains such as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Zhi_(pirate)\">Wang Zhi</span></b>, who commanded a vast trading-and-raiding network from bases in the Japanese port of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hirado,_Nagasaki\">Hirado</span>, leading mixed crews of Chinese, Japanese, and even <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Portuguese_Empire\">Portuguese</span> adventurers. The phenomenon drew strength from wider currents of the day, recruiting masterless <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rōnin\">rōnin</span> set adrift by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sengoku_period\">Sengoku</span>-period wars, during which the enfeebled <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ashikaga_shogunate\">Ashikaga shogunate</span></b> could neither control its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Daimyo\">daimyo</span> nor police the seas, and it was through these same networks that the first European <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tanegashima_(gun)\">firearms</span> had reached Japan aboard <b>a Chinese junk in 1543</b>. The Ming court eventually mounted a vigorous suppression under the supreme commander <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Zongxian\">Hu Zongxian</span>, who combined military pressure with stratagems that lured Wang Zhi to his execution around 1560. Decisive victories were won in the field by the celebrated general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qi_Jiguang\">Qi Jiguang</span>, whose rigorously drilled \"Qi family army\" and innovative small-unit formations, together with the campaigns of his fellow commander <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yu_Dayou\">Yu Dayou</span>, had largely broken the raiders by the mid-1560s. The threat finally receded after the new <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Longqing_Emperor\">Longqing Emperor</span> partially lifted <b>the maritime ban in 1567</b> and permitted licensed private trade once more, a relaxation that fed the surging <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manila_galleon\">silver trade</span> and drained the smuggling economy of the recruits on which the coastal raiders had depended, bringing their great age to a close.","citation":"","answerText":"Wokou"},{"id":"cnh-082","num":"八十二","category":"China · History","question":"A major fiscal reform of the late Ming that consolidated the many separate labour and grain levies into a single payment made in silver, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> reflected the flood of New World silver entering the economy through trade.","answer":"Single Whip reform","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">16th c. (Ming)</span></div>","traditional":"一條鞭法","hanzi":"一条鞭法","pinyin":"yī tiáo biān fǎ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">yī tiáo biān fǎ</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“single whip law”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Single Whip reform</b> was a sweeping fiscal reorganization of the mid-to-late <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming dynasty</span> that merged a tangle of separate land taxes, labor services, and miscellaneous levies into a single annual <b>assessment paid in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silver\">silver</span></b> rather than in grain or unpaid labor. It replaced an early-Ming system, rooted in the institutions of the founding <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hongwu_Emperor\">Hongwu Emperor</span>, under which households owed twice-yearly grain quotas alongside burdensome <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Corvée\">corvée</span> labor obligations administered through village tax units. By the 16th century these registers had grown hopelessly outdated and inequitable, and reform-minded officials—among them the famously upright <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hai_Rui\">Hai Rui</span></b>—began experimenting with consolidated silver assessments in the southern provinces during the long reign of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiajing_Emperor\">Jiajing Emperor</span>. The measure was extended <b>across the empire around 1581</b> by the powerful <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Grand_Secretariat\">Grand Secretary</span> <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Juzheng\">Zhang Juzheng</span></b> during the reign of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wanli_Emperor\">Wanli Emperor</span>, who paired it with a sweeping nationwide <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cadastre\">land survey</span> intended to bring the tax rolls back into line with actual holdings. Its colloquial name punned on a near-homophone meaning to \"combine into one,\" aptly capturing how the reform commuted labor duties into cash, merged scattered surcharges into a single bill, transferred collection from village headmen to salaried officials, and pushed China decisively toward a de facto <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silver_standard\">silver standard</span>. <br> <br> The reform both reflected and intensified a massive monetization of the Chinese economy fed by the early-modern <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Global_silver_trade_in_the_Early_Modern_Period\">global silver trade</span></b>, as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bullion\">bullion</span> poured in from Japanese mines such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Iwami_Ginzan_Silver_Mine\">Iwami</span> and, above all, from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Spanish_Empire\">Spanish Americas</span>. Much of this New World metal, struck into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Spanish_dollar\">Spanish dollar</span> in the mints of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Spain\">New Spain</span> and hewn from the great silver mountain of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Potosí\">Potosí</span>, crossed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pacific_Ocean\">Pacific</span> from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Acapulco\">Acapulco</span> aboard the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manila_galleon\">Manila galleon</span> to <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manila\">Manila</span></b>, where it was traded for Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk\">silk</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_export_porcelain\">porcelain</span>. Silver was drawn eastward partly because its purchasing power in China was exceptionally high, the gold-to-silver ratio standing at roughly 1 to 6 there against about 1 to 12 in Europe, and by some estimates the empire ultimately absorbed a third or more of all the silver mined in the Americas, the same flood that drove Europe's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Price_revolution\">price revolution</span>. This dependence on imported silver simplified administration and swelled state revenues, yet it also tethered the dynasty's finances to forces far beyond its frontiers, so that when bullion inflows contracted in the 1630s the ensuing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deflation\">deflation</span> and fiscal distress helped <b>precipitate the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Transition_from_Ming_to_Qing\">fall of the Ming</span> in 1644</b>, when rebel armies under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Zicheng\">Li Zicheng</span> seized the capital. The principle of a single, silver-denominated levy nevertheless endured and was carried further under the succeeding <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span>, whose <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kangxi_Emperor\">Kangxi</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yongzheng_Emperor\">Yongzheng</span> emperors in the early 18th century folded the lingering head tax into the land tax, completing a long simplification of Chinese fiscal practice that the reform had set in motion.","citation":"","answerText":"Single Whip reform"},{"id":"cnc-054","num":"五十四","category":"China · Culture","question":"Operated by sliding beads along rods within a frame and known in Chinese as the <i>suanpan</i>, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is still taught for mental-maths training.","answer":"Abacus","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">算盘 (suànpán, 'calculating tray')</span></div>","traditional":"算盤","hanzi":"算盘","pinyin":"suànpán","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">suànpán</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“calculating tray”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Abacus</b> is the ancient device of beads sliding on rods within a frame that enabled rapid <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Arithmetic\">arithmetic</span> for some 2,000 years before the electronic <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Calculator\">calculator</span></b>. Bead-and-board reckoning is far older than China, attested from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mesopotamia\">Mesopotamia</span> to the grooved <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Roman_abacus\">Roman abacus</span>, while Chinese calculators of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warring_States_period\">Warring States period</span> onward <b>worked with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Counting_rods\">counting rods</span></b>, whose strict <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Positional_notation\">place-value</span> layout, codified in manuals such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sunzi_Suanjing\"><i>Sunzi Suanjing</i></span>, prepared the way. A \"ball arithmetic\" is first mentioned by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han</span> <b>writer Xu Yue around 190 CE</b>, a shop counter in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Zeduan\">Zhang Zeduan</span>'s 12th-century scroll <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Along_the_River_During_the_Qingming_Festival\"><i>Along the River During the Qingming Festival</i></span> appears to show one, and by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span> the instrument was universal, illustrated in <b>a children's primer of 1371</b> and systematized in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cheng_Dawei\">Cheng Dawei</span>'s best-selling manual of 1592. The classic suanpan carries 2 beads above the beam and 5 below on each rod, letting merchants reckon not only in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Decimal\">decimal</span> but in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hexadecimal\">hexadecimal</span> weights of 16 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tael\">taels</span> to the catty, often jotting results in the cursive <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Suzhou_numerals\">Suzhou numerals</span></b>. Exported eastward, it was slimmed in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japan\">Japan</span> into the 1-and-4-bead <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soroban\">soroban</span>, the form most refined for speed. <br> <br> That speed was famously demonstrated in <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tokyo\">Tokyo</span> on 12 November 1946</b>, when a contest sponsored by the newspaper <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stars_and_Stripes_(newspaper)\"><i>Stars and Stripes</i></span> pitted a Japanese postal clerk's soroban against a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States_Army\">United States Army</span> electric calculating machine, the beads winning 4 events to 1. Across East Asia the frame clicked on shop counters and bank desks deep into the late 20th century, and Chinese schoolchildren drilled on it until a 2001 curriculum reform made instruction optional. Its strangest legacy is the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mental_abacus\">mental abacus</span>, in which trained children manipulate an imagined instrument, a skill whose champions sum 15 flashed 3-digit numbers in under 2 seconds and whose practitioners, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Neuroimaging\">neuroimaging</span> studies report, shift calculation from language circuits to visuospatial networks of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Parietal_lobe\">parietal lobe</span></b>, making it a popular form of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mental_calculation\">mental-maths training</span>. In 2013 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"UNESCO\">UNESCO</span> inscribed Chinese zhusuan, the knowledge and practice of suanpan reckoning, on its list of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Intangible_cultural_heritage\">intangible cultural heritage</span>. Adapted as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cranmer_abacus\">Cranmer abacus</span> it still serves blind students worldwide, and tens of thousands of children in East Asia attend after-school bead academies, keeping an ancient calculator alive in the smartphone age.","citation":"","answerText":"Abacus"},{"id":"cnc-058","num":"五十八","category":"China · Culture","question":"Collectively known in the West as kung fu and grouped into hard \"external\" and soft \"internal\" approaches, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> are linked with the Shaolin Monastery, cultivate <i>qi</i>, and have spread worldwide through cinema.","answer":"Chinese martial arts","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">武术 (wǔshù, 'martial arts')</span></div>","traditional":"武術","hanzi":"武术","pinyin":"wǔshù","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">wǔshù</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Chinese martial arts</b> are the hundreds of fighting traditions of China, conventionally grouped into hard \"external\" and soft \"internal\" approaches, linked in legend with the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shaolin_Monastery\">Shaolin Monastery</span></b>, devoted to cultivating <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qi\">qi</span>, and carried worldwide by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Martial_arts_film\">cinema</span>. Combat skill was lettered early, from the swordswoman <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuenü\">Yuenü</span></b> lecturing King <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Goujian\">Goujian</span> on the way of the blade to the Han imperial bibliography's chapters on unarmed combat, and the Ming general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qi_Jiguang\">Qi Jiguang</span> codified 32 boxing postures for soldiers in the 1560s. Shaolin, <b>founded in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Henan\">Henan</span> in 495 CE</b>, owes its martial halo partly to the legend that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bodhidharma\">Bodhidharma</span> taught the monks strengthening exercises and solidly to a stele recording how 13 cudgel-wielding monks aided the future <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Taizong_of_Tang\">Emperor Taizong</span> in 621, while their staff method won fame against 16th-century pirates. The internal–external division was <b>coined in 1669</b>, when the scholar <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huang_Zongxi\">Huang Zongxi</span> opposed a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Neijia\">neijia</span> \"internal school\" of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wudang_Mountains\">Wudang Mountains</span> to Shaolin's hard school, a family later filled by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tai_chi\">tai chi</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xingyiquan\">xingyiquan</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Baguazhang\">baguazhang</span>. Around them spreads a galaxy of styles—long-range northern legwork, close southern fists like <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wing_Chun\">Wing Chun</span>, animal imitations, and the classical 18 weapons from saber to spear. <br> <br> Modern nationalism reorganized the arts, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chin_Woo_Athletic_Association\">Jingwu Athletic Association</span> <b>founded in Shanghai in 1909 around</b> the legend of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huo_Yuanjia\">Huo Yuanjia</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Guoshu_Institute\">Central Guoshu Institute</span> of 1928 staging national examinations, before the People's Republic distilled performance-oriented <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wushu_(sport)\">sport wushu</span>, showcased at a special tournament of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2008_Summer_Olympics\">2008 Olympics</span> and admitted to the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Youth_Olympic_Games\">Youth Olympic Games</span></b> of 2026. Cinema made the arts a world language, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shaw_Brothers_Studio\">Shaw Brothers</span> spectacles preparing the ground for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bruce_Lee\">Bruce Lee</span>, whose <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Enter_the_Dragon\"><i>Enter the Dragon</i></span></b> of 1973 ignited a global craze, followed by the comic genius of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jackie_Chan\">Jackie Chan</span> and the lyrical <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Crouching_Tiger,_Hidden_Dragon\"><i>Crouching Tiger, Hidden Dragon</i></span>, which took 4 Academy Awards in 2001. The film <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shaolin_Temple_(1982_film)\"><i>Shaolin Temple</i></span> of 1982 resurrected the half-ruined monastery itself, around which academies such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shaolin_Tagou_Martial_Arts_School\">Tagou school</span> now drill on the order of 35,000 students, while the abbot franchises the brand abroad. The internet age has tested the legends, full-contact <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sanda_(sport)\">sanda</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mixed_martial_arts\">mixed martial arts</span> exposing stage masters and pushing traditionalists toward honest pressure-testing, yet the deepest claim survives in the word gongfu itself, which means not fighting but skill won through time and effort.","citation":"","answerText":"Chinese martial arts"},{"id":"cnc-081","num":"八十一","category":"China · Culture","question":"Distilled from sorghum and other grains into a clear, potent spirit, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> — the most consumed in the world by volume — is central to banquets and toasts, with brands such as Moutai commanding extraordinary prices.","answer":"Baijiu","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">白酒 (báijiǔ, 'white liquor')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"白酒","pinyin":"báijiǔ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">báijiǔ</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“white liquor”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Baijiu</b> is the clear, potent Chinese spirit distilled chiefly from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sorghum\">sorghum</span> and other grains, the <b>most consumed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liquor\">liquor</span></b> on earth by volume, outselling <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Whisky\">whisky</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vodka\">vodka</span>, gin, rum, and tequila combined on roughly US$100 billion in annual sales. Its method is unlike Western distilling: steamed grain is inoculated with <i>qū</i>, bricks of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wheat\">wheat</span> teeming with wild yeasts and molds, then undergoes solid-state <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fermentation\">fermentation</span></b> in earthen pits or jars before <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Distillation\">distillation</span> in pot-still-like steamers (<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pot_still\">pot stills</span> of the Chinese type), yielding spirits of 35 to 60 percent <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Alcohol_by_volume\">alcohol by volume</span></b>, classically 53. Distilled \"burnt wine\" is generally traced to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan dynasty</span> of the 13th century, as the physician <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Shizhen\">Li Shizhen</span> recorded in his <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Compendium_of_Materia_Medica\"><i>Compendium of Materia Medica</i></span>, though some scholars argue for earlier stills. Connoisseurs sort the spirit by aroma: \"strong\" styles from continuously used mud pits, supremely those of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luzhou_Laojiao\">Luzhou Laojiao</span>, in service <b>since 1573</b>, and of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuliangye\">Wuliangye</span> at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yibin\">Yibin</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan\">Sichuan</span>; clean \"light\" spirits like <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fenjiu\">Fenjiu</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanxi\">Shanxi</span>; mild \"<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rice\">rice</span>\" aromas of the south; and the funky \"sauce\" aroma of Guizhou. Its king is <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kweichow_Moutai\">Kweichow Moutai</span></b>, brewed on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chishui_River\">Chishui River</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guizhou\">Guizhou</span> through a year-long cycle of 9 steamings, 8 fermentations, and 7 pressings, then blended from long-aged stocks. <br> <br> Socially the spirit rules the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Banquet\">banquet</span>, drunk in thimble cups drained to cries of <i>ganbei</i> in toasts that map hierarchy, seal contracts, and test stamina. Moutai's mystique is political, fed by tales of Red Army soldiers on the <b>1935 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Long_March\">Long March</span></b> disinfecting wounds with the local liquor and sealed when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span> poured it for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Richard_Nixon\">Richard Nixon</span> at the 1972 state banquet, after which <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Henry_Kissinger\">Henry Kissinger</span> joked that with enough Maotai \"we can solve anything.\" Markets agreed, Kweichow Moutai <b>overtaking <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Diageo\">Diageo</span> in 2017</b> as the world's most valuable distiller, its flagship bottle officially priced at 1,499 yuan yet commonly fetching double on the street, while rare vintages trade like liquid gold at auction. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anti-corruption_campaign_under_Xi_Jinping\">anti-corruption campaign</span> launched in 2012 briefly crushed extravagant gifting before consumer demand roared back, and in 2023 a Moutai-spiked latte from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luckin_Coffee\">Luckin Coffee</span> sold 5.42 million cups on its first day, recruiting young drinkers to an elders' spirit. The great paradox remains its passport: less than 1 percent is exported, leaving the planet's best-selling liquor, central to a billion toasts, still a stranger at most of the world's bars.","citation":"","answerText":"Baijiu"},{"id":"cnc-082","num":"八十二","category":"China · Culture","question":"A grouping of the most celebrated works of pre-modern Chinese vernacular fiction, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> comprises a sprawling war epic, a tale of outlaw heroes, a fantastical pilgrimage and a melancholy chronicle of a great family's decline, all written under the Ming and Qing.","answer":"Four Great Classical Novels","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">四大名著 ('four great masterworks')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"四大名著","pinyin":"sì dà míngzhù","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">sì dà míngzhù</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“4 great masterworks”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Four Great Classical Novels</b> is the canonical grouping of the most celebrated works of pre-modern Chinese <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vernacular_Chinese\">vernacular</span></b> fiction, comprising a war epic, an outlaw saga, a fantastic pilgrimage, and a family chronicle written under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span>. The eldest is the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Romance_of_the_Three_Kingdoms\"><i>Romance of the Three Kingdoms</i></span>, attributed to the 14th-century <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luo_Guanzhong\">Luo Guanzhong</span>, whose 120 chapters dramatize the <b>wars of 184 to 280 CE</b> among the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Kingdoms\">Three Kingdoms</span>, famously \"7 parts history, 3 parts invention,\" and made cultural immortals of the strategist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuge_Liang\">Zhuge Liang</span> and the deified <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guan_Yu\">Guan Yu</span>. The <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Water_Margin\"><i>Water Margin</i></span></b>, attributed to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shi_Nai'an\">Shi Nai'an</span>, gathers the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"108_Stars_of_Destiny\">108 outlaw heroes</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_Jiang\">Song Jiang</span> in the marshes of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mount_Liang\">Mount Liang</span></b>, a rough brotherhood of forced rebels that emperors periodically banned as sedition. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Journey_to_the_West\"><i>Journey to the West</i></span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Cheng'en\">Wu Cheng'en</span>, <b>printed in 1592</b>, transmutes the historical pilgrimage of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xuanzang\">Xuanzang</span> into a comic allegory of 81 tribulations starring the irrepressible Monkey King <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Wukong\">Sun Wukong</span>. Crowning the set is the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dream_of_the_Red_Chamber\"><i>Dream of the Red Chamber</i></span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cao_Xueqin\">Cao Xueqin</span>, left unfinished <b>at his death around 1763</b> and published in 1791 with 40 chapters completed by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gao_E\">Gao E</span>, a melancholy, semi-autobiographical chronicle of the Jia clan's decline with a cast of several hundred that sustains an entire scholarly industry, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Redology\">Redology</span>. <br> <br> The grouping itself has a history, for late-Ming critics spoke of \"4 masterworks\" that included the erotic <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jin_Ping_Mei\"><i>Jin Ping Mei</i></span></b>, displaced by the Red Chamber in the canon fixed by modern publishers. Editor-critics shaped the texts we read, most radically <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jin_Shengtan\">Jin Shengtan</span>, whose 1641 recension cut the <i>Water Margin</i> to 70 chapters and praised it as genius, while the novels in turn fed the repertoire of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peking_opera\">Peking opera</span> and stocked the language with proverbs. Politics read along, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> mining the <i>Three Kingdoms</i> for strategy and launching a national campaign in 1975 to criticize Song Jiang's \"capitulationism.\" Translators carried the quartet abroad, from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pearl_S._Buck\">Pearl S. Buck</span>'s 1933 outlaw version and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Arthur_Waley\">Arthur Waley</span>'s 1942 <i>Monkey</i> to the 5-volume <i>Story of the Stone</i> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"David_Hawkes_(sinologist)\">David Hawkes</span> and his successor in 1973–1986. Their afterlife is inexhaustible, spanning the beloved 1986 and 1987 television serials, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dynasty_Warriors\">Dynasty Warriors</span> games, the Monkey-inspired <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dragon_Ball\">Dragon Ball</span>, and the 2024 blockbuster <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Black_Myth:_Wukong\"><i>Black Myth: Wukong</i></span>, which sold more than 20 million copies in its first month, proof that the 4 old books remain the shared imaginative DNA of the Chinese world.","citation":"","answerText":"Four Great Classical Novels"},{"id":"cnc-083","num":"八十三","category":"China · Culture","question":"Dramatising the wars and intrigues that followed the collapse of the Han, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> immortalised figures such as the warlord Cao Cao and remains a wellspring of strategy and drama.","answer":"Romance of the Three Kingdoms","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">14th c. (Ming)</span></div>","traditional":"三國演義","hanzi":"三国演义","pinyin":"Sānguó Yǎnyì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Sānguó Yǎnyì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b><i>Romance of the Three Kingdoms</i></b> is a <b>sweeping work of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Historical_fiction\">historical fiction</span></b> attributed to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luo_Guanzhong\">Luo Guanzhong</span> of the 14th century, among the earliest and grandest novels written in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Written_vernacular_Chinese\">vernacular Chinese</span> on the eve of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span>. Opening <b>amid the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_Turban_Rebellion\">Yellow Turban Rebellion</span> of 184 CE</b> and the tyranny of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dong_Zhuo\">Dong Zhuo</span>, it dramatises the disintegration of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span> into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Kingdoms\">Three Kingdoms</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cao_Wei\">Wei</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shu_Han\">Shu</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eastern_Wu\">Wu</span> under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cao_Cao\">Cao Cao</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Bei\">Liu Bei</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Quan\">Sun Quan</span>, closing only with reunification <b>under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jin_dynasty_(266–420)\">Jin</span> in 280 CE</b>. Across 120 chapters, roughly 800,000 characters of text, and a cast approaching 1,000 named figures, it weaves court intrigue, battlefield stratagem, and oaths of brotherhood into a meditation on loyalty and the rise and fall of states. Its emotional core is the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Oath_of_the_Peach_Garden\">Oath of the Peach Garden</span> binding Liu Bei to the warriors <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guan_Yu\">Guan Yu</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Fei\">Zhang Fei</span>, joined by the strategist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuge_Liang\">Zhuge Liang</span>, whose borrowed arrows and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empty_Fort_Strategy\">Empty Fort Strategy</span></b> became proverbial. Against them the novel sets the magnificent villainy of Cao Cao, the doomed warrior <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lü_Bu\">Lü Bu</span> ensnared by the beauty <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Diaochan\">Diaochan</span>, and the allied fire-ships that shatter Cao Cao's fleet <b>at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Red_Cliffs\">Battle of Red Cliffs</span> in 208 CE</b>. <br> <br> The narrative grew from the sober <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Records_of_the_Three_Kingdoms\"><i>Records of the Three Kingdoms</i></span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Shou\">Chen Shou</span>, enriched by the annotations of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pei_Songzhi\">Pei Songzhi</span> and by centuries of storytellers' scripts and stage plays. The oldest surviving edition was printed in 1522, while the standard text descends from the 1660s revision of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zonggang\">Mao Zonggang</span></b>, who added the famous opening on empires long divided uniting and long united dividing, and the scholar <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Xuecheng\">Zhang Xuecheng</span> later judged the whole to be 7 parts fact and 3 parts invention. Honoured among the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Classic_Chinese_Novels\">Classic Chinese Novels</span> beside the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Water_Margin\"><i>Water Margin</i></span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Journey_to_the_West\"><i>Journey to the West</i></span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dream_of_the_Red_Chamber\"><i>Dream of the Red Chamber</i></span>, it seeded everyday speech with sayings such as “speak of Cao Cao and Cao Cao arrives,” while Guan Yu ascended into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_folk_religion\">folk religion</span> as a god of loyalty and wealth. Its episodes furnish a standing repertoire of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peking_opera\">Peking opera</span> and an endless stream of retellings, from the Japanese novelisation of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eiji_Yoshikawa\">Eiji Yoshikawa</span> and a celebrated 84-episode television serial of 1994 to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"John_Woo\">John Woo</span>'s film <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Red_Cliff_(film)\"><i>Red Cliff</i></span></b> of 2008 and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dynasty_Warriors\"><i>Dynasty Warriors</i></span> video games. Studied by generals and entrepreneurs as a manual of stratagem and carried into English most fully by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Moss_Roberts\">Moss Roberts</span> in 1991, the novel remains a wellspring of drama for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> and the wider <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"East_Asian_cultural_sphere\">East Asian cultural sphere</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Romance of the Three Kingdoms"},{"id":"cnc-084","num":"八十四","category":"China · Culture","question":"Recounting how 108 outlaws driven by injustice gather as righteous bandits at Liangshan Marsh before being offered amnesty, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> celebrates loyalty and rebellion against corrupt officials.","answer":"Water Margin","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">14th c. (Ming)</span></div>","traditional":"水滸傳","hanzi":"水浒传","pinyin":"Shuǐhǔ Zhuàn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Shuǐhǔ Zhuàn</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Chronicle of the Water Margin”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b><i>Water Margin</i></b> is a rollicking vernacular novel of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span>, attributed to <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shi_Nai'an\">Shi Nai'an</span></b>, with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luo_Guanzhong\">Luo Guanzhong</span> often named as reviser, which recounts how 108 outlaws driven by injustice gather as righteous bandits at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liangshan_Marsh\">Liangshan Marsh</span> before accepting imperial <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Amnesty\">amnesty</span>. Its seed was a real bandit chief, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_Jiang\">Song Jiang</span></b>, who roamed the north with 36 men in 1119–1121 under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Huizong_of_Song\">Emperor Huizong</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song</span>, and whom 2 centuries of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huaben\">huaben</span> storytelling and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zaju\">zaju</span> drama inflated into the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"108_Stars_of_Destiny\">108 Stars of Destiny</span></b>, 36 Heavenly Spirits and 72 Earthly Fiends arrayed against villains like the football-playing favorite <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gao_Qiu\">Gao Qiu</span>. The early chapters chain together unforgettable origins—the framed instructor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lin_Chong\">Lin Chong</span>, whose persecution coined the idiom \"forced up Mount Liang\" for having no way out, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Song\">Wu Song</span></b> punching a tiger to death after 18 bowls of wine, the tattooed monk <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lu_Zhishen\">Lu Zhishen</span> uprooting a willow tree, the black whirlwind <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Kui_(Water_Margin)\">Li Kui</span> with twin axes, and 3 women generals including <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Sanniang\">Hu Sanniang</span> of the steel daggers. United first under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chao_Gai\">Chao Gai</span> and then under Song Jiang, the brotherhood robs the corrupt in Heaven's name while insisting on loyalty to a misled throne, their destiny sealed when a stone tablet in chapter 71 reveals their starry ranks. In the full 100- and 120-chapter versions amnesty proves a slow execution, the band dying off in campaigns against the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liao_dynasty\">Liao</span> and the rebel <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fang_La\">Fang La</span> until the poisoned Song Jiang loyally drains his cup. <br> <br> The earliest complete editions appeared late, a 100-chapter text <b>prefaced in 1589</b> and the famous Rongyutang printing of 1610 carrying commentary in the name of the iconoclast <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Zhi_(philosopher)\">Li Zhi</span>, who exalted this bandit book as sincere literature. In 1641 the critic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jin_Shengtan\">Jin Shengtan</span> cut the novel to 70 chapters, ending it with a dream of execution, and his recension ruled for 3 centuries even as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> authorities repeatedly banned the work for teaching brigandage, folk wisdom agreeing that the young should not read it. Modern critics led by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lu_Xun\">Lu Xun</span> enthroned it in the vernacular canon, and its gravitational pull had already produced the great domestic novel <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jin_Ping_Mei\"><i>Jin Ping Mei</i></span>, spun out of the Wu Song episode. Japan devoured it from a translation <b>begun in 1757</b>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Edo_period\">Edo</span> Suikoden craze making <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Utagawa_Kuniyoshi\">Utagawa Kuniyoshi</span>'s fame with his warrior prints of 1827 and later christening the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Suikoden\">Suikoden</span> video-game saga, while English readers met the outlaws through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pearl_S._Buck\">Pearl S. Buck</span>'s <i>All Men Are Brothers</i> <b>in 1933</b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sidney_Shapiro\">Sidney Shapiro</span>'s <i>Outlaws of the Marsh</i> in 1980. Even <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> conscripted the book, launching a 1975 campaign against Song Jiang's \"capitulationism,\" and the lavish 43-episode <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Water_Margin_(1998_TV_series)\">1998 television series</span> keeps the marsh's defiant brotherhood alive for each new generation.","citation":"","answerText":"Water Margin"},{"id":"cnc-085","num":"八十五","category":"China · Culture","question":"Prepared by air-drying and roasting the bird until the skin turns crisp and glossy, then carving it to be wrapped in thin pancakes with spring onion and sweet bean sauce, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was once served at the imperial court in the capital.","answer":"Peking duck","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">北京烤鸭 ('Beijing roast duck')</span></div>","traditional":"北京烤鴨","hanzi":"北京烤鸭","pinyin":"Běijīng kǎoyā","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Běijīng kǎoyā</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Beijing roast duck”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Peking duck</b> is the most celebrated dish of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> and a crown jewel of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_cuisine\">Chinese cuisine</span></b>, a whole <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Duck\">duck</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Roasting\">roasted</span> until its skin turns crisp, glossy, and mahogany-red. Roast duck already won praise in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan</span> dietary classic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yinshan_Zhengyao\"><i>Yinshan Zhengyao</i></span> <b>compiled by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Sihui\">Hu Sihui</span> in 1330</b>, and the art matured at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span> before travelling north with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yongle_Emperor\">Yongle Emperor</span>'s court, becoming a fixture of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> imperial kitchens within the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Forbidden_City\">Forbidden City</span>. Two restaurant lineages carried the dish to the public, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bianyifang\">Bianyifang</span>, <b>founded in 1416</b> and famous for its closed-oven method, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Quanjude\">Quanjude</span>, founded in 1864, whose ducks hang in open ovens over smouldering <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jujube\">jujube</span> and other fruitwoods. Preparation is exacting, a plump <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"American_Pekin\">Pekin</span> duck having air pumped beneath the skin to loosen it, then being scalded, lacquered with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maltose\">maltose</span> syrup, air-dried for up to 24 hours, and roasted for roughly 40 minutes until the fat has basted the flesh and the skin shatters like caramel. A carver then draws some 90 paper-thin slices, which diners wrap at table in gossamer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bing_(bread)\">bing</span> pancakes with slivered <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Scallion\">scallion</span>, batons of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cucumber\">cucumber</span>, and a <b>smear of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sweet_bean_sauce\">sweet bean sauce</span></b>, often replaced abroad by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hoisin_sauce\">hoisin</span>, while the carcass returns later as a milky <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soup\">soup</span>. <br> <br> The dish has long served the <b>purposes of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Culinary_diplomacy\">culinary diplomacy</span></b>, for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span> set it before foreign guests again and again, a duck luncheon famously easing the secret <b>talks of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Henry_Kissinger\">Henry Kissinger</span> in 1971</b> and the banquets of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1972_visit_by_Richard_Nixon_to_China\">1972 visit by Richard Nixon</span> fixing the image of the lacquered bird in the world's eye. The breed itself had already emigrated, a small flock shipped to America in 1873 founding the duck farms of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Long_Island\">Long Island</span> and, with them, the global supply of Pekin ducks. At home Quanjude grew into a chain roasting millions of birds a year, while a newer generation of chefs renders the duck leaner and lighter, several houses in Beijing and beyond earning stars from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Michelin_Guide\">Michelin Guide</span>. Its standing approaches that of a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_dish\">national dish</span></b>, enshrined in the saying that no visit to the capital is complete without climbing the Great Wall and eating roast duck. From the emperor's table to neighbourhood ovens and airport counters, the dish remains the single most famous plate to come out of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Peking duck"},{"id":"cnc-086","num":"八十六","category":"China · Culture","question":"Built in the early 15th century as the imperial palace at the heart of Beijing, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> housed the Ming and Qing emperors and is now a vast museum.","answer":"Forbidden City","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">紫禁城 (Zǐjìnchéng, 'purple forbidden city')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"紫禁城","pinyin":"Zǐjìnchéng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zǐjìnchéng</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Purple Forbidden City,”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Forbidden City</b> is the vast imperial palace at the heart of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>, home to 24 emperors of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> dynasties and now the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Palace_Museum\">Palace Museum</span></b>. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yongle_Emperor\">Yongle Emperor</span>, shifting his capital north from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span>, built it between 1406 and 1420 with a reported 1,000,000 laborers and 100,000 artisans, floating colossal <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Phoebe_zhennan\">nanmu</span></b> timbers from the southwest and \"golden bricks\" fired at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Suzhou\">Suzhou</span> up the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Grand_Canal_(China)\">Grand Canal</span>. The walled rectangle measures 961 by 753 meters (3,150 by 2,470 ft), some 72 hectares (180 acres) ringed by a 52-meter (170 ft) moat and 10-meter (33 ft) walls, and legend credits it with 9,999.5 rooms, just short of heaven's 10,000, though the real count is about 8,700 bays. Ceremony filled the Outer Court along the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing_Central_Axis\">central axis of Beijing</span>, culminating in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hall_of_Supreme_Harmony\">Hall of Supreme Harmony</span></b>, China's largest surviving timber hall, while the emperor's family lived behind in the Inner Court around the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Palace_of_Heavenly_Purity\">Palace of Heavenly Purity</span>. Everything proclaimed cosmic rank, from the south-facing plan guarded at the rear by the artificial hill of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jingshan_Park\">Jingshan</span>, heaped from moat soil, to the emperor-only yellow glazed tiles crowned with processions of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_roof_decoration\">roof figurines</span>, to the 5-bayed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Meridian_Gate\">Meridian Gate</span> through which only the Son of Heaven passed at center. <br> <br> Lightning burned the 3 great halls within months of the <b>1420 inauguration</b>, the first of many fires and rebuildings, and in 1644 the rebel <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Zicheng\">Li Zicheng</span> briefly seized the palace before the Qing moved in, later luminaries of the compound ranging from the collector-emperor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qianlong_Emperor\">Qianlong</span> to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empress_Dowager_Cixi\">Empress Dowager Cixi</span>. The last emperor, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Puyi\">Puyi</span>, <b>abdicated in 1912</b> but lingered in the Inner Court until the warlord <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Feng_Yuxiang\">Feng Yuxiang</span> expelled him in 1924, and on 10 October 1925 the palace opened as a museum. War scattered its treasures, more than 13,000 crates evacuated south in 1933 ahead of the Japanese, of which 2,972 crates <b>crossed to Taipei in 1948–1949</b> to seed the rival <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Palace_Museum\">National Palace Museum</span>, though Beijing's collection still numbers about 1.86 million objects. The compound survived the Cultural Revolution behind gates that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span> ordered shut and garrisoned in 1966, gazes south over <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tiananmen\">Tiananmen</span> with its portrait of Mao, and entered the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Heritage_Site\">World Heritage</span> list in 1987, the same year <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bernardo_Bertolucci\">Bernardo Bertolucci</span></b> filmed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Last_Emperor\"><i>The Last Emperor</i></span> inside and carried off 9 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Academy_Awards\">Academy Awards</span>. Now capped at 80,000 visitors a day after drawing about 19 million in 2019, the world's most visited museum has even relitigated modernity on its own terms, evicting a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Starbucks\">Starbucks</span> from its precincts in 2007 after a nationalist outcry, 6 centuries after the first emperor took up residence.","citation":"","answerText":"Forbidden City"},{"id":"cnc-087","num":"八十七","category":"China · Culture","question":"A masterpiece of Ming architecture in Beijing centred on a circular, triple-eaved hall of prayer, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is where emperors performed solemn rites and sacrifices to Heaven to ensure good harvests.","answer":"Temple of Heaven","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">天坛 (Tiāntán, 'altar of Heaven')</span></div>","traditional":"天壇","hanzi":"天坛","pinyin":"Tiāntán","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Tiāntán</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Altar of Heaven”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Temple of Heaven</b> is an imperial sacrificial complex in southern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> where the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_of_China\">emperors</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> dynasties offered solemn <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sacrifice\">sacrifices</span> to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tian\">Heaven</span> for a bountiful <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Harvest\">harvest</span>. It was raised <b>between 1406</b> and 1420 by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yongle_Emperor\">Yongle Emperor</span> in tandem with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Forbidden_City\">Forbidden City</span>, and its walled park in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dongcheng,_Beijing\">Dongcheng</span> spreads over some 273 hectares (675 acres), several times the area of the palace itself. The plan embodies the ancient cosmology of a round heaven over a square earth, the northern walls curving and the southern running straight, the principal buildings strung along a north–south axis beneath deep-blue tiles amid groves of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cypress\">cypresses</span>, some more than 600 years old. Its centrepiece, the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hall_of_Prayer_for_Good_Harvests\">Hall of Prayer for Good Harvests</span></b>, is a circular, triple-eaved tower of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_architecture\">Chinese architecture</span> at its most refined, about 38 metres (120 ft) tall and 36 metres (120 ft) across, framed wholly in timber without a single <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nail_(fastener)\">nail</span></b>, its 28 columns symbolising the 4 seasons, the 12 months, and the 12 double-hours of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Traditional_Chinese_timekeeping\">traditional timekeeping</span>. South along the axis stand the Imperial Vault of Heaven, ringed by the whispering Echo Wall, and the open-air Circular Mound Altar <b>added in 1530</b>, whose 3 marble terraces are laid out in multiples of the celestial number 9 around the Heart of Heaven stone. <br> <br> Each <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Winter_solstice\">winter solstice</span> the emperor, as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Son_of_Heaven\">Son of Heaven</span>, processed from the palace through silenced streets, purified himself by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fasting\">fasting</span> in the Palace of Abstinence, and reported to the supreme deity <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shangdi\">Shangdi</span>, a rite upon which the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mandate_of_Heaven\">Mandate of Heaven</span> itself was felt to rest. Under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiajing_Emperor\">Jiajing Emperor</span> the worship of the cosmic powers was divided in 1530 among new altars, the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Temple_of_Earth\">Temple of Earth</span></b> in the north and the temples of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Temple_of_the_Sun_(Beijing)\">Sun</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Temple_of_the_Moon_(Beijing)\">Moon</span> to east and west, while the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qianlong_Emperor\">Qianlong Emperor</span> enlarged and refaced the southern altar in the 18th century. <b>Disaster struck in 1889</b> when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lightning\">lightning</span> burned the great hall to the ground, but it was rebuilt to the old design by 1890 under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangxu_Emperor\">Guangxu Emperor</span>. The last sacrifice in the imperial manner was performed at the winter solstice of 1914 by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_Shikai\">Yuan Shikai</span> during his short-lived bid to found the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empire_of_China_(1915–1916)\">Empire of China</span></b>, and in 1918 the precinct opened to the public as a park. Inscribed as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Heritage_Site\">World Heritage Site</span> in 1998 and embraced within the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing_Central_Axis\">Beijing Central Axis</span> listing of 2024, it now receives millions of visitors a year and fills each dawn with practitioners of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tai_chi\">tai chi</span> beneath the old trees, enduring as one of the most beloved architectural emblems of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Temple of Heaven"},{"id":"cnc-088","num":"八十八","category":"China · Culture","question":"Designed to evoke an idealised miniature landscape with winding paths, rocks, ponds and pavilions, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> — exemplified by the classical examples of Suzhou — sought to harmonise human structures with nature.","answer":"Chinese garden","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">园林 (yuánlín, 'gardens and groves')</span></div>","traditional":"園林","hanzi":"园林","pinyin":"yuánlín","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">yuánlín</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Chinese garden</b> is the art of landscape design that composes winding paths, eroded rocks, ponds, and pavilions into an idealized miniature landscape, seeking to harmonize <b>human structures with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nature\">nature</span></b> rather than impose upon it. Its imperial root was the vast hunting park, transformed when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Wu_of_Han\">Emperor Wu of Han</span> dug a palace lake with 3 islets imitating the immortals' isle of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mount_Penglai\">Penglai</span>, fixing the \"1 pool, 3 mountains\" formula that gardens repeated for 2,000 years. Alongside this <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Taoist</span> dream of paradise ran the scholar's ideal, nourished by the pastoral verse of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tao_Yuanming\">Tao Yuanming</span></b>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shan_shui\">shanshui</span> landscape painting tradition, and retreats like the estate of the poet-painter <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Wei_(Tang_dynasty)\">Wang Wei</span>, so that a garden became a 3-dimensional painting to be strolled. Obsession could turn ruinous, as when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Huizong_of_Song\">Emperor Huizong</span> raised the artificial <b>mountain of Genyue in 1117–1122</b>, his convoys of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taihu_stone\">Taihu stones</span> so burdening the south that they helped sink his dynasty. The mature art deployed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Borrowed_scenery\">borrowed scenery</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Moon_gate\">moon gates</span> and lattice windows framing views, symbolic plantings of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bamboo\">bamboo</span>, pine, and plum—the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Friends_of_Winter\">3 Friends of Winter</span>—and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nelumbo_nucifera\">lotus</span> pools, all <b>theorized in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ji_Cheng\">Ji Cheng</span>'s 1631 manual</b> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuanye\"><i>Yuanye</i></span>, whose ideal is work \"made by man, yet as if born of heaven.\" <br> <br> The classic flowering came in the canal-laced merchant and scholar city of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Suzhou\">Suzhou</span> in the prosperous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiangnan\">Jiangnan</span> region, which at its height counted over 200 private gardens, 9 of them <b>inscribed in 1997</b> and 2000 as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Classical_Gardens_of_Suzhou\">Classical Gardens of Suzhou</span> World Heritage ensemble. Among them are the 5.2-hectare (13 acres) <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Humble_Administrator's_Garden\">Humble Administrator's Garden</span> of 1509, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lingering_Garden\">Lingering Garden</span>, the jewel-like <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Master_of_the_Nets_Garden\">Master of the Nets Garden</span></b>, and the rockery labyrinth of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lion_Grove_Garden\">Lion Grove</span>, beloved of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qianlong_Emperor\">Qianlong Emperor</span>. The north answered with imperial parklands, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Summer_Palace\">Summer Palace</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chengde_Mountain_Resort\">Chengde Mountain Resort</span> scaling the scholar's pond to lake size, while the fabled <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Old_Summer_Palace\">Old Summer Palace</span>, the \"Garden of Gardens,\" was burned by Anglo-French troops in 1860 and remains a national wound. Abroad the art seeded the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japanese_garden\">Japanese garden</span></b> and bewitched 18th-century Europe, where <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"William_Chambers_(architect)\">William Chambers</span> raised a 10-story Chinese pagoda at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kew_Gardens\">Kew</span> in 1762 amid the fashion for irregular \"Anglo-Chinese\" parks. The tradition still travels and renews itself, Suzhou craftsmen assembling a courtyard garden inside New York's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Metropolitan_Museum_of_Art\">Metropolitan Museum of Art</span> in 1980 and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"I._M._Pei\">I. M. Pei</span> distilling whitewashed walls and water into his 2006 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Suzhou_Museum\">Suzhou Museum</span>, proof that one may still build a landscape to walk through as one walks through a painting.","citation":"","answerText":"Chinese garden"},{"id":"cnc-089","num":"八十九","category":"China · Culture","question":"Originating in the Suzhou region around the 16th century and prized for its elegant melodies and poetic librettos, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was recognised by UNESCO as a masterpiece of intangible heritage.","answer":"Kunqu","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">昆曲 (Kūnqǔ, 'song of Kunshan')</span></div>","traditional":"崑曲","hanzi":"昆曲","pinyin":"Kūnqǔ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Kūnqǔ</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“song of Kunshan”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Kunqu</b> is the refined and ancient form of Chinese opera that arose around the 16th century in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Suzhou\">Suzhou</span> region, prized for elegant melodies and poetic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Libretto\">librettos</span> and honored by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"UNESCO\">UNESCO</span> as a masterpiece of humanity's heritage. Its local tune, traced to <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kunshan\">Kunshan</span></b> singers of the late <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan</span>, was transformed in the 1540s when the musician <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wei_Liangfu\">Wei Liangfu</span> spent a decade \"water-polishing\" it into melismatic smoothness, floated on the breathy bamboo <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dizi_(instrument)\">dizi</span> rather than fiddles and drums. The style conquered the stage when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liang_Chenyu\">Liang Chenyu</span> set the full-length drama <i>Washing Gauze</i> <b>to it around 1566</b>, and for the next 200 years Kunqu was the national theatre of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span> and early <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> elite, sung by household troupes in the gardens of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiangnan\">Jiangnan</span>. Upon it the literati lavished their greatest plays, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_Xianzu\">Tang Xianzu</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Peony_Pavilion\"><i>Peony Pavilion</i></span> of 1598</b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Sheng\">Hong Sheng</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Palace_of_Eternal_Life\"><i>Palace of Eternal Life</i></span> of 1688, and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kong_Shangren\">Kong Shangren</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Peach_Blossom_Fan\"><i>Peach Blossom Fan</i></span> of 1699</b>. Musically the form strings together hundreds of fixed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qupai\">qupai</span> tunes whose strict prosody binds poetry to pitch, while dance-like gesture, water sleeves, and whispered refinement set the standard that earned Kunqu the title \"teacher of the hundred operas.\" <br> <br> Fashion turned in the 18th and 19th centuries, when the \"flowery\" popular styles, above all <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peking_opera\">Peking opera</span>, drove the \"elegant\" Kunqu from the boards, and by the early Republic the art survived chiefly through about 50 boys trained from 1921 at a Suzhou institute, the famous \"Chuan\" generation, alongside admirers such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mei_Lanfang\">Mei Lanfang</span>. Salvation arrived in 1956, when a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhejiang\">Zhejiang</span> troupe's staging of the courtroom comedy <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fifteen_Strings_of_Cash\"><i>Fifteen Strings of Cash</i></span></b> delighted <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span> and the press hailed how \"one play saved an entire genre,\" prompting the founding of the state companies, today 8 strong, in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span>, Beijing, and beyond. Silenced again during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span>, the tradition was rebuilt in the 1980s and crowned in 2001, when UNESCO placed Kunqu among the inaugural 19 Masterpieces of the Oral and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Intangible_cultural_heritage\">Intangible Heritage</span> of Humanity. International fame followed daring productions, from <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Shi-Zheng\">Chen Shi-Zheng</span></b>'s complete 55-scene <i>Peony Pavilion</i>, some 19 hours long, premiered at New York's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lincoln_Center\">Lincoln Center</span> in 1999 after Shanghai authorities barred the original cast, to the 9-hour \"Young Lovers' Edition\" curated by <b>the novelist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pai_Hsien-yung\">Pai Hsien-yung</span></b> in 2004, which has toured campuses worldwide through hundreds of performances. Six centuries after the first Kunshan songs, the once-dying art again fills theatres with students queuing to hear a flute carry a ghost story of love stronger than death.","citation":"","answerText":"Kunqu"},{"id":"cnc-091","num":"九十一","category":"China · Culture","question":"Born from a stone and armed with a magic staff that can shrink to needle size, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> wreaks havoc in Heaven before escorting the monk Xuanzang westward.","answer":"Sun Wukong","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">16th c.</span></div>","traditional":"孫悟空","hanzi":"孙悟空","pinyin":"Sūn Wùkōng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Sūn Wùkōng</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Monkey Awakened to Emptiness”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Sun Wukong</b>, the Monkey King, is the rebellious, shape-shifting hero of the 1592 novel <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Journey_to_the_West\"><i>Journey to the West</i></span> attributed to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Cheng'en\">Wu Cheng'en</span>, a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Monkey\">monkey</span></b> hatched from a stone who storms <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heaven\">Heaven</span> before escorting the monk <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xuanzang\">Xuanzang</span> to India. Born from a rock atop the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mount_Huaguo\">Mountain of Flowers and Fruit</span> and crowned king of its monkeys, he seeks immortality from the sage <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Subhuti\">Subhuti</span>, mastering 72 transformations and a cloud-somersault of 108,000 li. From the undersea palace of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dragon_King\">Dragon King</span> he extorts the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ruyi_Jingu_Bang\">Ruyi Jingu Bang</span></b>, a 13,500-catty iron pillar that shrinks to needle size behind his ear, then strikes his name from the ledgers of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yama\">Yama</span>'s underworld and bullies the court of heaven into titling him \"Great Sage Equal to Heaven.\" Insulted, he devours the immortality peaches of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Queen_Mother_of_the_West\">Queen Mother of the West</span> and the elixir pills of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Laozi\">Laozi</span>, routs the celestial host including the prince <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nezha\">Nezha</span> and the god <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Erlang_Shen\">Erlang Shen</span></b>, and emerges from 49 days in Laozi's furnace with fiery golden eyes, until the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gautama_Buddha\">Buddha</span> wins a wager—the pillars at the world's edge prove to be his fingers—and pins the ape under a mountain for 500 years. Released through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guanyin\">Guanyin</span>'s design to guard Xuanzang through 81 tribulations, his anarchic genius checked by a golden headband that tightens at the monk's chant, he embodies the restless \"<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mind_monkey\">monkey of the mind</span>\" that the pilgrimage gradually tames. <br> <br> Scholars have long argued over his ancestry, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Shih\">Hu Shih</span> <b>proposing in 1923</b> a debt to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hanuman\">Hanuman</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ramayana\"><i>Ramayana</i></span>, while <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lu_Xun\">Lu Xun</span> championed native river-demon lore, and a monkey pilgrim already stars in a 13th-century storyteller's booklet and <b>in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zaju\">zaju</span></b> drama long before the novel. He is also a god in earnest, worshipped as the Great Sage in temples of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fujian\">Fujian</span> and among emigrant communities from Taiwan to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Singapore\">Singapore</span>, where spirit mediums still take on his grimacing persona. Modern media multiplied him without end, <b>through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Arthur_Waley\">Arthur Waley</span>'s 1942 translation</b> <i>Monkey</i>, the classic animation <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Havoc_in_Heaven\"><i>Havoc in Heaven</i></span> of 1961–1964, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Journey_to_the_West_(1986_TV_series)\">1986 television series</span> whose reruns in China are counted in the thousands, while his whiskered acrobatics remain a showpiece of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peking_opera\">Peking opera</span>. Japan's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dragon_Ball\">Dragon Ball</span> built its hero Son <b>Goku upon him in 1984</b>, and in 2024 the game <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Black_Myth:_Wukong\"><i>Black Myth: Wukong</i></span> sold over 20 million copies in a month on the strength of his legend. Even Chinese science claims him, christening its 2015 dark-matter satellite <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dark_Matter_Particle_Explorer\">\"Wukong\"</span> for eyes that see what others cannot, a fitting orbit for the stone-born trickster who once out-leapt the gods.","citation":"","answerText":"Sun Wukong"},{"id":"cng-036","num":"三十六","category":"China · Geography","question":"The largest freshwater lake in the country, lying in Jiangxi and connected to the Yangtze, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is a vital wintering ground for migratory cranes.","answer":"Poyang Lake","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">鄱阳湖 (Póyáng Hú), after Mount Poyang</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"鄱阳湖","pinyin":"Póyáng Hú","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Póyáng Hú</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Poyang Lake</b> is the largest freshwater lake in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>, occupying a low basin in northern <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiangxi\">Jiangxi</span></b> province where it drains into the middle <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span>. Its surface fluctuates more dramatically than that of almost any comparable lake, swelling beyond 4,000 square kilometres (1,500 sq mi) at the height of the summer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Monsoon\">monsoon</span> floods yet contracting to a maze of channels covering only a few hundred square kilometres in the winter dry season. The lake gathers the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gan_River\">Gan River</span> together with the Fu, Xin, Rao, and Xiu rivers that drain most of Jiangxi, discharging their combined flow northward into the Yangtze at <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hukou_County\">Hukou County</span></b>, where the great river’s summer surge can reverse the current and pond floodwaters back into the basin. Those seasonally exposed mudflats make the lake East Asia’s premier waterbird refuge, wintering the bulk of the world population of the critically endangered <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Siberian_crane\">Siberian crane</span>, some 4,000 birds, alongside <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"White-naped_crane\">white-naped cranes</span></b>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Swan_goose\">swan goose</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tundra_swan\">tundra swans</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Oriental_stork\">Oriental stork</span>, while its open water shelters several hundred <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze_finless_porpoise\">Yangtze finless porpoises</span>, among the last of a species now numbering barely a thousand. Protected <b>since 1983</b> as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nature_reserve\">nature reserve</span> and listed under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ramsar_Convention\">Ramsar Convention</span> in 1992 as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wetland\">wetland</span> of international importance, the lake has nonetheless seen its dry-season lows deepen sharply, a trend tied to downstream regulation by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Gorges_Dam\">Three Gorges Dam</span>, to intensive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sand_mining\">sand mining</span> that has scoured its outflow channel, and to severe <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Drought\">droughts</span> <b>such as that of 2022</b>, when the water fell to record depths months ahead of schedule. <br> <br> In 1363 the lake became the stage for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Lake_Poyang\">Battle of Lake Poyang</span>, reckoned among the largest <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Naval_warfare\">naval battles</span> in history, in which the <b>rebel leader <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_Yuanzhang\">Zhu Yuanzhang</span></b> destroyed the larger fleet of his rival <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Youliang\">Chen Youliang</span> amid the collapse of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan dynasty</span>. Chen’s death in the fighting cleared Zhu’s path to <b>proclaim the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming dynasty</span> in 1368</b>, making the engagement a decisive turning point in the founding of imperial China’s last Han-led dynasty. When the waters retreat each winter they lay bare a Ming-era stone causeway, the so-called Thousand-Eye Bridge near <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Duchang_County\">Duchang County</span>, and expose the shoals off Laoye Temple, a notoriously treacherous stretch sometimes dubbed China’s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bermuda_Triangle\">Bermuda Triangle</span> for the many vessels lost there. The basin is rimmed by the provincial capital <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanchang\">Nanchang</span> on the Gan, the Yangtze port of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiujiang\">Jiujiang</span>, and the scenic heights of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mount_Lu\">Mount Lu</span>, its fertile shores having supported dense settlement since antiquity in one of the country’s foremost <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rice\">rice</span>-growing regions. To curb the worsening dry-season shrinkage, provincial authorities have for years proposed a controversial <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sluice\">sluice</span>-gate barrage across the lake’s narrow neck near Hukou, a plan that conservationists warn could strand the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bird_migration\">migratory flocks</span> and the finless porpoise, leaving the lake’s future poised at the centre of a protracted struggle between <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Water_resources\">water management</span> and ecology.","citation":"","answerText":"Poyang Lake"},{"id":"cng-040","num":"四十","category":"China · Geography","question":"A type of landscape formed where slightly acidic water dissolves limestone into caves, sinkholes and pinnacles, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> produces the iconic pillar-like hills around Guilin and across the plateaus of Guizhou.","answer":"Karst","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">from the Kras plateau of Slovenia, the type-region for the landform</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"喀斯特","pinyin":"kāsītè","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">kāsītè</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Karst</b> is a landscape produced where slightly acidic water dissolves soluble bedrock, above all <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Limestone\">limestone</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dolomite_(rock)\">dolomite</span>, as rain and soil water <b>charged with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Carbon_dioxide\">carbon dioxide</span></b> form weak <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Carbonic_acid\">carbonic acid</span> that eats the rock along joints over millions of years. The result is a distinctive suite of features, from fluted <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Karren\">karren</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sinkhole\">sinkholes</span>, flat-floored <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Polje\">poljes</span>, and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Losing_stream\">losing streams</span></b> on the surface to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cave\">caves</span> and giant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Spring_(hydrology)\">springs</span> below, where dripwater builds <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stalactite\">stalactites</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stalagmite\">stalagmites</span>, and other <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Speleothem\">speleothems</span>. Such terrain covers roughly 15 percent of the planet's ice-free land, and karst <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Aquifer\">aquifers</span> supply drinking water to perhaps a quarter of humanity, while dissolution has hollowed systems as vast as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mammoth_Cave_National_Park\">Mammoth Cave</span></b>, surveyed beyond 680 kilometers (420 mi). The name comes from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kras\">Kras</span> plateau of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Slovenia\">Slovenia</span>, whose stony hills supplied the type examples when the geographer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jovan_Cvijić\">Jovan Cvijić</span> founded the scientific study of <b>the phenomenon with his 1893 monograph</b>. Because speleothems lock in chemical signatures as they grow, cave deposits have become premier archives of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paleoclimatology\">paleoclimatology</span>, with Chinese stalagmites famously reconstructing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"East_Asian_Monsoon\">East Asian monsoon</span> across 640,000 years. <br> <br> China is the world's foremost karst country, with soluble rocks underlying some 3.4 million square kilometers (1.3 million sq mi), and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South_China_Karst\">South China Karst</span>, <b>inscribed by UNESCO in 2007</b> and 2014, forms the largest subtropical karst expanse on earth at around half a million square kilometers. Its most celebrated expression is the tower karst around <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guilin\">Guilin</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangshuo_County\">Yangshuo</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangxi\">Guangxi</span>, where pillar-like hills rising from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_River\">Li River</span> adorn the 20-yuan note of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Renminbi\">renminbi</span> and echo through a millennium of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shan_shui\">shan shui</span> painting, while clustered cone karst blankets <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guizhou\">Guizhou</span>, pinnacles bristle in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stone_Forest\">Stone Forest</span>, and drowned towers form Vietnam's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hạ_Long_Bay\">Hạ Long Bay</span> offshore. The region also holds the superlatives of the underworld, including the giant collapse dolines called <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tiankeng\">tiankeng</span>, led by the 662-meter-deep (2,170 ft) <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiaozhai_Tiankeng\">Xiaozhai Tiankeng</span></b>, the natural bridges of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wulong_Karst\">Wulong</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shuanghe_Cave\">Shuanghe Cave</span>, mapped past 400 kilometers (250 mi) as Asia's longest. Chinese inquiry came early, for the late-Ming traveler <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xu_Xiake\">Xu Xiake</span> systematically described caves and <b>stone forests around 1638</b>, recording observations in <i>The Travel Diaries of Xu Xiake</i> centuries before European karstology. Yet the same geology breeds fragility, since thin soils stripped from bare rock have driven rocky <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Desertification\">desertification</span> across more than 100,000 square kilometers (39,000 sq mi) of the southwest, and sudden collapses and easily poisoned groundwater make living on dissolving stone a continuing national challenge.","citation":"","answerText":"Karst"},{"id":"cng-042","num":"四十二","category":"China · Geography","question":"A large, strategically vital sea south of the mainland bordered by Vietnam, the Philippines and Borneo, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> contains the contested Spratly and Paracel islands and some of the world's busiest shipping lanes.","answer":"South China Sea","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">南海 (Nán Hǎi, 'south sea')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"南海","pinyin":"Nán Hǎi","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Nán Hǎi</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“South Sea”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>South China Sea</b> is a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marginal_sea\">marginal sea</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pacific_Ocean\">Pacific Ocean</span> covering</b> roughly 3.5 million square kilometers (1.4 million sq mi), stretching from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan_Strait\">Taiwan</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luzon_Strait\">Luzon</span> straits to the approaches of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Strait_of_Malacca\">Strait of Malacca</span></b>, bounded by the Chinese mainland and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hainan\">Hainan</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Philippines\">Philippines</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Borneo\">Borneo</span>'s coasts in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Malaysia\">Malaysia</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Brunei\">Brunei</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Indonesia\">Indonesia</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vietnam\">Vietnam</span>. Broad continental shelves and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gulf_of_Tonkin\">Gulf of Tonkin</span></b> fringe a central abyssal basin plunging past 5,000 meters (16,000 ft), across which <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Typhoon\">typhoons</span> track every summer and autumn. Through these waters passes about a 3rd of global maritime commerce, valued near 3.4 trillion dollars a year, including the bulk of the oil and a major share of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liquefied_natural_gas\">liquefied natural gas</span></b> bound for East Asia. The sea's own wealth is immense, for its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fishery\">fisheries</span> yield on the order of 12 percent of the world catch and sustain millions of livelihoods, while estimates credit the seabed with roughly 11 billion barrels of oil and 190 trillion cubic feet of gas. Hundreds of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Coral_reef\">coral reefs</span> and atolls make it a biodiversity treasury, though dredging and the plunder of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Giant_clam\">giant clams</span> have destroyed reef on a scale measured in dozens of square kilometers. <br> <br> For 2 millennia these monsoon waters formed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maritime_Silk_Road\">Maritime Silk Road</span>, linking Chinese ports with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Champa\">Champa</span> and the spice routes, traversed most famously by the treasure fleets of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zheng_He\">Zheng He</span> <b>between 1405</b> and 1433. Sovereignty is now the world's most tangled maritime dispute, as China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nine-dash_line\">nine-dash line</span>, inherited from a 1947 map, overlaps the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_Nations_Convention_on_the_Law_of_the_Sea\">UNCLOS</span> zones of five neighbors, with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Spratly_Islands\">Spratly Islands</span> claimed in whole or part by 6 parties, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paracel_Islands\">Paracels</span> seized from South Vietnam in the <b>1974 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_the_Paracel_Islands\">Battle of the Paracel Islands</span></b>, and 64 Vietnamese sailors killed in the 1988 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Johnson_South_Reef_Skirmish\">Johnson South Reef Skirmish</span>. After 2013 China dredged some 13 square kilometers (5 sq mi) of new land onto 7 Spratly reefs, crowning <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fiery_Cross_Reef\">Fiery Cross</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mischief_Reef\">Mischief</span> reefs with 3,000-meter (9,800 ft) runways, radars, and missile shelters. In the case of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Philippines_v._China\">Philippines v. China</span>, a tribunal under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Permanent_Court_of_Arbitration\">Permanent Court of Arbitration</span> <b>ruled in 2016</b> that the nine-dash claim had no legal basis, a verdict Beijing rejected outright, just as it had held <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Scarborough_Shoal\">Scarborough Shoal</span> after the 2012 standoff. With American <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Freedom_of_navigation\">freedom-of-navigation</span> patrols, water-cannon confrontations around Philippine outposts, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"ASEAN\">ASEAN</span> code-of-conduct talks inching along since 2002, the sea remains the most combustible stretch of water on earth.","citation":"","answerText":"South China Sea"},{"id":"cng-058","num":"五十八","category":"China · Geography","question":"A major northern port and municipality on the Bohai coast serving as the maritime gateway to nearby Beijing, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was carved into foreign concessions in the 19th century and remains a hub of industry and shipping.","answer":"Tianjin","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">天津 (Tiānjīn, 'ford of Heaven')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"天津","pinyin":"Tiānjīn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Tiānjīn</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Ford of Heaven”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Tianjin</b> is a direct-administered municipality of 13.87 million people in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2020_Chinese_census\"><b>2020</b> census</span>, set on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hai_River\">Hai River</span> where the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Grand_Canal_(China)\">Grand Canal</span> meets the sea lanes of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bohai_Sea\">Bohai</span>, roughly 120 kilometers (75 mi) southeast of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>, whose maritime gateway it has been for 6 centuries. The city owes its name to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yongle_Emperor\">Yongle Emperor</span>, who forded <b>the river here in 1400</b> during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jingnan_campaign\">Jingnan campaign</span> that won him the throne and in 1404 walled the site as the Tianjin Guard, after which it grew rich on salt and canal grain. Defeat in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Opium_War\">Second Opium War</span> <b>brought the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Tientsin\">Treaty of Tientsin</span> in 1858</b> and opening as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_ports\">treaty port</span> in 1860, and eventually 9 foreign <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Concessions_in_Tianjin\">concessions</span>, including Italy's only one in Asia, carved up the riverfront, more than in any other Chinese city, leaving the European streetscapes still strolled today at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wudadao\">Wudadao</span>. Foreign privilege bred violence, from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tianjin_Massacre\">Tianjin Massacre</span> of 1870 to the storming of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taku_Forts\">Taku Forts</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Tientsin\">Battle of Tientsin</span> during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boxer_Rebellion\">Boxer Rebellion</span> in 1900, after which the victors razed the city walls. Yet the same exposure made Tianjin the laboratory of modernization, where <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Hongzhang\">Li Hongzhang</span> based his projects, China's first modern university opened in 1895 as the ancestor of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tianjin_University\">Tianjin University</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nankai_University\">Nankai University</span> educated the young <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span> after 1919, the deposed emperor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Puyi\">Puyi</span> idled in the Japanese concession from 1925 to 1931, and the People's Liberation Army finally took the city in a 29-hour assault of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pingjin_campaign\">Pingjin campaign</span> in January 1949. <br> <br> Modern Tianjin remains above all a working port, for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Port_of_Tianjin\">Port of Tianjin</span> is the largest in northern China and ranks among the world's 10 busiest, handling over 20 million <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Twenty-foot_equivalent_unit\">TEU</span> a year. Industry concentrates in the seaside <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Binhai\">Binhai</span></b> New Area, where an <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Airbus_A320_family\">Airbus A320</span> final assembly line has operated since 2008 as the first outside Europe, rockets stage through the port for coastal launch sites, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tianhe-1A\">Tianhe-1A</span> supercomputer briefly ranked as the world's fastest in 2010. The boom has known shocks, from the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2015_Tianjin_explosions\">2015 port explosions</span></b> that killed 173 people to the 2017 admission that Binhai's output had been overstated by roughly a 3rd, ushering in leaner years. Connectivity compensates, since the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing–Tianjin_intercity_railway\">Beijing–Tianjin intercity railway</span> of 2008 inaugurated 350-kilometer (220 mi)-per-hour service in China and now links the cities in about half an hour, while landmarks like the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tianjin_Eye\">Tianjin Eye</span> ferris wheel and the futuristic <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tianjin_Binhai_Library\">Binhai Library</span></b> of 2017 give the skyline flair. The city's soul stays droll and well fed, as the cradle of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiangsheng\">xiangsheng</span> comic crosstalk, the home of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Goubuli\">Goubuli</span> steamed buns and the breakfast <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jianbing\">jianbing</span>, and the source of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Year_picture\">New Year pictures</span></b> of Yangliuqing that once papered half of northern China.","citation":"","answerText":"Tianjin"},{"id":"cng-061","num":"六十一","category":"China · Geography","question":"A small, densely packed peninsula and islands on the western side of the Pearl River Delta, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> returned to China in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> and has become the world's biggest gambling hub.","answer":"Macau","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">澳门 (Àomén, 'bay gate'); 'Macau' from the A-Ma temple</span></div>","traditional":"澳門","hanzi":"澳门","pinyin":"Àomén","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Àomén</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Macau</b> is a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Special_administrative_regions_of_China\">special administrative region</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> on the western side of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pearl_River_Delta\">Pearl River Delta</span>, a former Portuguese territory returned <b>to Chinese rule in 1999</b>. Covering barely 33 square kilometres (13 sq mi) yet home to about 680,000 residents, it is the most densely populated territory on Earth, comprising the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Macau_Peninsula\">Macau Peninsula</span> attached to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuhai\">Zhuhai</span> on the mainland together with the islands of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taipa\">Taipa</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Coloane\">Coloane</span>, now joined by the reclaimed <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cotai\">Cotai</span></b> strip. It faces <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span> across the mouth of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pearl_River_(China)\">Pearl River</span>, the two now linked by the 55-kilometre (34 mi) <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong–Zhuhai–Macau_Bridge\">Hong Kong–Zhuhai–Macau Bridge</span> <b>opened in 2018</b>, and like Hong Kong it keeps its own legal system, government, and currency, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Macanese_pataca\">Macanese pataca</span>. The territory’s economy revolves overwhelmingly around <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gambling_in_Macau\">casino gaming</span>, legal here since the 19th century and concentrated since the 2000s along the Cotai strip, where gaming revenue overtook the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Las_Vegas_Strip\">Las Vegas Strip</span> around 2006 and peaked near 7 times that of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Las_Vegas\">Las Vegas</span></b>, helping give Macau one of the highest <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"List_of_countries_by_GDP_(PPP)_per_capita\">incomes per head</span> in the world. Beyond its casinos the city preserves a distinctive Eurasian heritage recognised in 2005 as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Historic_Centre_of_Macau\">Historic Centre of Macau</span>, a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Heritage_Site\">World Heritage Site</span> whose landmarks include the soaring façade of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ruins_of_St._Paul's\">Ruins of St. Paul’s</span></b> and the seaside <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"A-Ma_Temple\">A-Ma Temple</span>, while its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Macanese_cuisine\">Macanese cuisine</span> and the street-racing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Macau_Grand_Prix\">Macau Grand Prix</span> round out a culture found nowhere else. <br> <br> The name Macau is thought to derive from A-Ma-Gau, the “Bay of A-Ma,” after the sea goddess <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mazu\">Mazu</span> whose shrine greeted the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Portuguese_Empire\">Portuguese navigators</span> who reached this coast in the 16th century. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming dynasty</span> permitted them to establish a permanent <b>trading post around 1557</b>, the oldest European settlement in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"East_Asia\">East Asia</span>, which flourished as the linchpin of a lucrative commerce carrying <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silver\">silver</span> and silk between China, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanban_trade\">Japan</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Portuguese_India\">Goa</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lisbon\">Lisbon</span>. Macau also became the gateway for Catholic missions to the region, a base for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Society_of_Jesus\">Jesuits</span> such as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Matteo_Ricci\">Matteo Ricci</span></b> bound for the imperial court, though the colony declined after Japan closed itself off and the rise of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"British_Hong_Kong\">British Hong Kong</span> in the 1840s eclipsed its trade. To revive its fortunes the Portuguese administration legalised <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gambling\">gambling</span> in 1847, and from 1962 a monopoly held by the tycoon <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stanley_Ho\">Stanley Ho</span> built the modern casino industry, until the market was opened to foreign operators in 2002 and the Las Vegas-style resorts of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Venetian_Macao\">Venetian</span> and its rivals transformed Cotai. Under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-Portuguese_Joint_Declaration\">Sino-Portuguese Joint Declaration</span> of 1987, Portugal returned Macau to China on 20 December 1999, the last European colony in Asia, where it now governs itself under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"One_country,_two_systems\">one country, two systems</span> until 2049, a politically quiescent region that draws the bulk of its millions of visitors from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mainland_China\">mainland</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Macau"},{"id":"cng-077","num":"七十七","category":"China · Geography","question":"A historic city on the lower Yangtze and capital of Jiangsu, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> served as the seat of dynasties and of the Republican government, and suffered a notorious massacre in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>.","answer":"Nanjing","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">南京 (Nánjīng, 'southern capital')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"南京","pinyin":"Nánjīng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Nánjīng</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“southern capital”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Nanjing</b> is a historic metropolis on the lower <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span></b> and the capital of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiangsu\">Jiangsu</span> province, home to roughly 9.5 million people. Among the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Historical_capitals_of_China\">Four Great Ancient Capitals</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>, it has served as the seat of some 10 dynasties and regimes, a record that <b>began in 229 CE</b> when the state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eastern_Wu\">Eastern Wu</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Kingdoms\">Three Kingdoms</span> made the city, then called Jianye, its capital. Through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Six_Dynasties\">Six Dynasties</span> era it flourished as the cultured southern counterweight to a war-torn north, perhaps the world’s largest city under the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liang_dynasty\">Liang</span></b> in the 6th century, sheltered by its setting among hills such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Purple_Mountain\">Purple Mountain</span> beside the great river. The founder of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming dynasty</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hongwu_Emperor\">Hongwu Emperor</span>, made it <b>the imperial capital in 1368</b> and girdled it with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"City_Wall_of_Nanjing\">City Wall of Nanjing</span>, at about 35 kilometres (22 mi) the longest city wall ever built, before his son moved the court to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> in 1421, leaving the tomb complex of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_Xiaoling_Mausoleum\">Ming Xiaoling</span> as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Heritage_Site\">World Heritage Site</span>. From its shipyards the eunuch admiral <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zheng_He\">Zheng He</span> launched his 7 great <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_treasure_voyages\">treasure voyages</span> <b>between 1405</b> and 1433, and the city remains a centre of learning anchored by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing_University\">Nanjing University</span>, its skyline now mixing Republican-era plane-tree boulevards with towers beside one of the Yangtze’s oldest modern crossings, the 1968 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing_Yangtze_River_Bridge\">Nanjing Yangtze River Bridge</span>. <br> <br> Modern history has repeatedly pivoted on the city, beginning with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Nanking\">Treaty of Nanking</span> signed aboard a British warship here in 1842 to end the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Opium_War\">First Opium War</span>, the first of the unequal treaties. From 1853 to 1864 the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiping_Rebellion\">Taiping Rebellion</span> made Nanjing its Heavenly Capital under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Xiuquan\">Hong Xiuquan</span>, until imperial forces retook and devastated the city in a war that ranks among the deadliest ever fought. After the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1911_Revolution\">1911 Revolution</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Yat-sen\">Sun Yat-sen</span> was inaugurated here as provisional president of the new <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)\">Republic of China</span>, and in 1927 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span> established the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nationalist_government\">Nationalist government</span> in the city, inaugurating the “Nanjing decade” of state-building crowned by the hillside <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Yat-sen_Mausoleum\">Sun Yat-sen Mausoleum</span></b>. Catastrophe followed in December 1937, when Japanese troops captured the capital in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Sino-Japanese_War\">Second Sino-Japanese War</span> and perpetrated the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing_Massacre\">Nanjing Massacre</span>, weeks of mass killing and rape in which China puts the death toll at 300,000, a trauma commemorated at the city’s memorial hall and witnessed by foreigners such as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"John_Rabe\">John Rabe</span></b>, who sheltered civilians in a safety zone. The Nationalists restored their capital here after Japan’s defeat, but in April 1949 the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army\">People’s Liberation Army</span> crossed the Yangtze and took the city in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">Chinese Civil War</span>, ending Nanjing’s career as a national capital, though it thrives today as an educational, petrochemical, and electronics hub of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze_Delta\">Yangtze Delta</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Nanjing"},{"id":"cnh-078","num":"七十八","category":"China · History","question":"A Muslim eunuch admiral of enormous stature, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> led 7 great treasure voyages for the Yongle Emperor, sailing huge fleets as far as East Africa and the Persian Gulf in the early 15th century.","answer":"Zheng He","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. 1371</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1433</span></div>","traditional":"鄭和","hanzi":"郑和","pinyin":"Zhèng Hé","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhèng Hé</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Zheng He</b> was a Chinese mariner, diplomat, and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eunuch\">eunuch</span></b> admiral who commanded the great <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_treasure_voyages\">treasure voyages</span> of the early <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming dynasty</span>. Born into a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hui_people\">Hui</span> Muslim family in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yunnan\">Yunnan</span> whose father and grandfather had completed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hajj\">hajj</span> to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mecca\">Mecca</span>, he was captured and castrated as a boy of about 11 <b>during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_conquest_of_Yunnan\">Ming conquest of Yunnan</span> around 1382</b> and assigned to the household of the prince who would become the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yongle_Emperor\">Yongle Emperor</span>. After serving his master with distinction in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jingnan_campaign\">Jingnan campaign</span> that won the throne in 1402, he was rewarded with the surname Zheng and elevated to the senior eunuch directorship from which he would oversee the imperial fleet. <b>Between 1405</b> and 1433 he led 7 expeditions across the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Indian_Ocean\">Indian Ocean</span>, the inaugural voyage alone reportedly numbering some 317 vessels and nearly 28,000 men, a fleet that dwarfed any contemporary European force and that over the years called on more than 30 states across Asia and Africa. At their heart sailed the immense <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_treasure_ship\">treasure ships</span></b>, which traditional Chinese sources describe as exceeding 120 metres (390 ft), or some 400 feet, in length—dimensions that would have made them the largest wooden vessels ever constructed and that modern scholars still dispute as physically plausible. <br> <br> His armadas called at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Champa\">Champa</span>, the Javanese realm of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Majapahit\">Majapahit</span>, the wealthy port of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Malacca_Sultanate\">Malacca</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sumatra\">Sumatra</span> before ranging westward to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sri_Lanka\">Sri Lanka</span>, the Indian emporium of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kozhikode\">Calicut</span>, the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Persian_Gulf\">Persian Gulf</span></b>, and the Arabian port of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Aden\">Aden</span>. The fleets reached as far as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Swahili_coast\">Swahili coast</span> of East Africa, touching <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mogadishu\">Mogadishu</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Malindi\">Malindi</span>, from which a giraffe was carried home and presented at court as an auspicious <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qilin\">qilin</span>. Though chiefly diplomatic, the voyages projected hard power as well, crushing the pirate <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Zuyi\">Chen Zuyi</span> at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Palembang\">Palembang</span> in 1407</b> and carrying off a defiant Sinhalese king from Ceylon in 1411, while he honored the sea goddess <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mazu\">Mazu</span> and erected commemorative steles such as the trilingual <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Galle_Trilingual_Inscription\">inscription at Galle</span>. After the Yongle Emperor's death in 1424 the costly enterprise was suspended by the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hongxi_Emperor\">Hongxi Emperor</span></b>, but the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xuande_Emperor\">Xuande Emperor</span> revived it for a 7th and final voyage in 1431, in the course of which the aging admiral is believed to have died around 1433. Thereafter the Ming turned away from the oceans, reviving the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Haijin\">maritime ban</span> as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> officials condemned the voyages' expense, with one administrator, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Daxia\">Liu Daxia</span>, later reputed to have suppressed their records, so that the fleets which had reached Africa nearly a century before <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vasco_da_Gama\">Vasco da Gama</span> rounded it were never rebuilt.","citation":"","answerText":"Zheng He"},{"id":"cnh-079","num":"七十九","category":"China · History","question":"A series of 7 vast maritime expeditions between <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> and <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> commanded by the admiral Zheng He, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> projected the power and prestige of the Ming across the Indian Ocean, only to be abruptly halted and never resumed.","answer":"Ming treasure voyages","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1405–1433</span></div>","traditional":"鄭和下西洋","hanzi":"郑和下西洋","pinyin":"Zhèng Hé xià Xīyáng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhèng Hé xià Xīyáng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Ming treasure voyages</b> were a series of seven grand maritime expeditions launched <b>between 1405</b> and <b>1433</b>, commissioned chiefly by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yongle_Emperor\">Yongle Emperor</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming dynasty</span> and commanded by <b>the admiral <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zheng_He\">Zheng He</span></b>. Zheng He was a Muslim <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eunuch\">eunuch</span> from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yunnan\">Yunnan</span>, born into a family of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Islam_in_China\">Central Asian Muslim</span> descent and taken into imperial service as a boy, who rose to become one of the emperor's most trusted lieutenants and an exceptionally capable naval and diplomatic commander. The fleets were of unprecedented size, the first reportedly comprising some 317 vessels manned by nearly 28,000 sailors and soldiers, and they were led by the enormous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_treasure_ship\">treasure ships</span>, nine-masted <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Junk_(ship)\">junks</span> that traditional accounts describe as well over 100 metres (330 ft) long, dwarfing any European vessel of the age. Sailing from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span> and the southern coast, the expeditions ranged across the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Indian_Ocean\">Indian Ocean</span></b> to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Malacca_Sultanate\">Malacca</span>, the Indian port of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kozhikode\">Calicut</span>, the Persian Gulf at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ormus\">Hormuz</span>, and the Arabian harbour of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Aden\">Aden</span>, before reaching the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Swahili_coast\">Swahili coast</span> of East Africa. Their purpose was less conquest than the projection of imperial grandeur and the enrolment of distant rulers into the Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tributary_system_of_China\">tributary system</span>, though some accounts also tie the earliest voyage to a search for the vanished <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jianwen_Emperor\">Jianwen Emperor</span> whom Yongle had usurped. <br> <br> Although largely peaceful, the voyages did employ force on occasion, as when Zheng He crushed the pirate fleet of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Zuyi\">Chen Zuyi</span> near <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Palembang\">Palembang</span> in 1407</b> and later intervened in a succession dispute on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sri_Lanka\">Ceylon</span>, carrying the captured king of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kingdom_of_Kotte\">Kotte</span> back to the Ming court. Among the marvels the fleets brought home was a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Giraffe\">giraffe</span> obtained by way of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bengal_Sultanate\">Bengal</span> in 1414, which courtiers hailed as the auspicious <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qilin\">qilin</span> of legend, an omen affirming the virtue of the emperor's reign. The seventh and final voyage, undertaken under the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xuande_Emperor\">Xuande Emperor</span></b> and ending around 1433, proved to be the last, for the ruinous expense and the opposition of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Scholar-official\">Confucian scholar-officials</span> who distrusted eunuch power coincided with a strategic refocusing on the northern land frontier against the resurgent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongols\">Mongols</span>. In the decades that followed the court enforced increasingly strict maritime prohibitions known as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Haijin\">haijin</span>, the great shipyards fell idle, and the official archives of the expeditions were reportedly destroyed by hostile officials such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Daxia\">Liu Daxia</span> to forestall any revival. As a result China turned away from the oceans just as Europe prepared to embark upon its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Age_of_Discovery\">Age of Discovery</span>, for Zheng He's armadas had crossed the Indian Ocean more than half a century before the far smaller fleets of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Christopher_Columbus\">Christopher Columbus</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vasco_da_Gama\">Vasco da Gama</span> first ventured beyond European waters.","citation":"","answerText":"Ming treasure voyages"},{"id":"cnh-084","num":"八十四","category":"China · History","question":"An Italian Jesuit who mastered the language and won the respect of scholars by adopting their dress, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> introduced European mathematics, astronomy and world maps to the late-Ming court while seeking to reconcile Christianity with Confucian tradition.","answer":"Matteo Ricci","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">October 6, 1552</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">May 11, 1610</span></div>","traditional":"利瑪竇","hanzi":"利玛窦","pinyin":"Lì Mǎdòu","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Lì Mǎdòu</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Matteo Ricci</b> was an Italian <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jesuits\">Jesuit</span></b> priest and one of the founding figures of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jesuit_China_missions\">Jesuit mission to China</span> during the late <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming dynasty</span>. Born in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Macerata\">Macerata</span> in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Papal_States\">Papal States</span>, he joined the <b>Society of Jesus in 1571</b> and studied mathematics and astronomy at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Roman_College\">Roman College</span> under the celebrated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Christopher_Clavius\">Christopher Clavius</span> before sailing east in 1578. After several years at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Goa\">Goa</span> in Portuguese India, he reached the trading <b>enclave of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Macau\">Macau</span> in 1582</b>, where alongside <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Michele_Ruggieri\">Michele Ruggieri</span> he began the arduous study of Chinese. Settling on the mainland at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhaoqing\">Zhaoqing</span> in 1583, the missionaries at first dressed as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Buddhism\">Buddhist</span> monks, but Ricci soon abandoned that guise for the silk robes and manners of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Scholar-official\">scholar-officials</span>, judging the literati to command far greater prestige. Moving steadily northward through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span>, he <b>gained permission in 1601</b> to reside in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>, where chiming clocks and other curiosities won him standing at the court of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wanli_Emperor\">Wanli Emperor</span>, who accepted his gifts though emperor and missionary never met face to face. <br> <br> At the heart of his strategy lay the introduction of European learning, most famously the great Chinese-language world map known as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kunyu_Wanguo_Quantu\">Kunyu Wanguo Quantu</span> of 1602, a large multi-panel chart that revealed to Chinese readers the Americas and the true extent of the continents and oceans. With his foremost convert, the official <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xu_Guangqi\">Xu Guangqi</span>, he produced the first Chinese rendering of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Euclid\">Euclid</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Euclid's_Elements\"><i>Elements</i></span> in 1607, founding the study of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Euclidean_geometry\">Euclidean geometry</span></b> in East Asia, and he further astonished the literati with the Western mnemonic system of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Method_of_loci\">memory palace</span>. Pursuing a strategy of cultural accommodation, he immersed himself in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Books_and_Five_Classics\">Confucian classics</span> and argued in his dialogue <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_True_Meaning_of_the_Lord_of_Heaven\"><i>The True Meaning of the Lord of Heaven</i></span></b> that the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Christianity\">Christian</span> God could be identified with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shangdi\">Shangdi</span> of the ancient Chinese texts, presenting <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucianism</span> as a moral philosophy compatible with the faith. He won a small but influential circle of converts, among them the scholar-official <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Zhizao\">Li Zhizao</span>, and on his death in Beijing in 1610 he became the first Westerner granted an imperial burial plot in the capital, interred at what is now the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhalan_Cemetery\">Zhalan Cemetery</span></b>. His method of reconciling Christian doctrine with Confucian rite, propagated in Europe through journals edited by his confrère <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nicolas_Trigault\">Nicolas Trigault</span>, shaped Western perceptions of China for generations but also sowed the seeds of the bitter <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Rites_controversy\">Chinese Rites controversy</span> that would later divide the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Catholic_Church\">Catholic Church</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Matteo Ricci"},{"id":"cnh-085","num":"八十五","category":"China · History","question":"A chieftain who united the Jurchen tribes of the north-east and declared war on the Ming with his \"Seven Grievances\", the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> organised his people into the banner system that would carry his descendants to the conquest of China.","answer":"Nurhaci","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1559–1626</span></div>","traditional":"努爾哈赤","hanzi":"努尔哈赤","pinyin":"Nǔ'ěrhāchì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Nǔ'ěrhāchì</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Nurhaci</b> was a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jurchen_people\">Jurchen</span></b> chieftain of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Aisin_Gioro\">Aisin Gioro</span> clan whose conquests laid the foundations of the dynasty that would later rule China as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span>. A leader of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jianzhou_Jurchens\">Jianzhou Jurchens</span> in the forests of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchuria\">Manchuria</span>, he <b>began his career in 1583</b> after his father and grandfather were killed during a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span> military expedition, reportedly inheriting only 13 suits of armour with which to avenge them. Over the following three decades he subjugated the rival Jurchen tribes one by one, and to administer his growing realm he commissioned the creation of <b>a new <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_alphabet\">Manchu script</span> in 1599</b>, adapted from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongolian_script\">Mongolian script</span>. He reorganised his people into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight_Banners\">Eight Banners</span>, a system of hereditary military-civilian units that mobilised the entire population for war and would become the institutional backbone of Manchu power for the next three centuries. <b>In 1616</b> he proclaimed himself <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khan_(title)\">khan</span> and founded the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Later_Jin_(1616–1636)\">Later Jin</span> state, deliberately invoking the earlier Jurchen <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jin_dynasty_(1115–1234)\">Jin dynasty</span>, and adopted the reign title Tianming, meaning the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mandate_of_Heaven\">Mandate of Heaven</span>. <br> <br> In 1618 he openly declared war on the Ming by issuing the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Seven_Grievances\">\"Seven Grievances\"</span></b>, a manifesto cataloguing his complaints against the empire, and promptly stormed the frontier garrison of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fushun\">Fushun</span>. His decisive triumph came in 1619 at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Sarhū\">Battle of Sarhū</span>, where his banner armies annihilated a far larger Ming-led coalition dispatched by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wanli_Emperor\">Wanli Emperor</span> in four separate columns, shattering Ming power in the northeast. He went on to seize the great cities of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liaodong_Peninsula\">Liaodong</span> region, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liaoyang\">Liaoyang</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shenyang\">Shenyang</span>, in 1621, and in 1625 he transferred his capital to the latter, known to the Manchus as Mukden, where he began construction of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mukden_Palace\">imperial palace</span>. His advance was finally checked in 1626 at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Ningyuan\">Battle of Ningyuan</span></b>, where the Ming general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_Chonghuan\">Yuan Chonghuan</span> repelled the assault with European-style <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cannon\">cannon</span>, inflicting on Nurhaci the first major defeat of his career, and he died a few months later. His son and successor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Taiji\">Hong Taiji</span> renamed the people the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_people\">Manchus</span> and the dynasty the Qing, and in 1644 the banner armies Nurhaci had forged, led by the regent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dorgon\">Dorgon</span> on behalf of the child <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shunzhi_Emperor\">Shunzhi Emperor</span>, poured through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanhai_Pass\">Shanhai Pass</span> to seize <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> and complete the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Transition_from_Ming_to_Qing\">conquest</span> he had begun.","citation":"","answerText":"Nurhaci"},{"id":"cnh-087","num":"八十七","category":"China · History","question":"The most notorious eunuch in Chinese history, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> dominated the late-Ming court under a negligent emperor, built a vast network of spies, savagely purged the reformist Donglin faction, and even had temples erected in his own honour before his sudden fall.","answer":"Wei Zhongxian","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1568–1627</span></div>","traditional":"魏忠賢","hanzi":"魏忠贤","pinyin":"Wèi Zhōngxián","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Wèi Zhōngxián</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Wei Zhongxian</b> was a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eunuch\">eunuch</span></b> official who became the most powerful man at the late <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span> court and is traditionally reviled as the most notorious eunuch in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"History_of_China\">Chinese history</span>. Born into a poor family in what is now <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hebei\">Hebei</span>, he was an illiterate commoner and habitual <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gambling\">gambler</span> who, ruined by debt, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Castration\">castrated</span> himself and entered the imperial <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Forbidden_City\">palace</span> as a menial servant late in the 16th century. The late Ming was already enfeebled by decades of neglect under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wanli_Emperor\">Wanli Emperor</span>, and Wei's fortunes were transformed when the young <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tianqi_Emperor\">Tianqi Emperor</span> <b>took the throne in 1620</b>, a ruler who preferred <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Woodworking\">carpentry</span> to governing and left affairs to Wei and the emperor's former wet nurse, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Madame_Ke\">Madame Ke</span>. As head of the chief eunuch directorate he controlled the flow of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Memorial_to_the_throne\">memorials</span> reaching the throne and <b>issued <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rescript\">rescripts</span></b> in the emperor's name, effectively usurping the authority of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Grand_Secretariat\">Grand Secretariat</span> and the regular bureaucracy of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Scholar-official\">scholar-officials</span>. To enforce his will he commanded the dreaded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eastern_Depot\">Eastern Depot</span>, a eunuch-run <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Secret_police\">secret police</span>, and worked alongside the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Embroidered_Uniform_Guard\">Embroidered Uniform Guard</span></b> to weave a vast web of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Espionage\">informers</span>, secret prisons, and torturers that spread terror through officialdom. <br> <br> Wei reserved his fiercest hostility for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Donglin_movement\">Donglin movement</span>, a circle of reformist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> moralists, schooled through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examinations</span> and centred on the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Donglin_Academy\">Donglin Academy</span></b> near <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuxi\">Wuxi</span>, who denounced eunuch corruption and demanded a return to upright government. After the official <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yang_Lian_(Ming_dynasty)\">Yang Lian</span> submitted a <b>celebrated memorial in 1624 listing</b> 24 great crimes against him, Wei retaliated savagely, having Yang and other leading Donglin partisans arrested on fabricated charges and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Torture\">tortured</span> to death in prison. At the height of his dominance he enjoyed an extraordinary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cult_of_personality\">cult of personality</span>, as sycophantic officials raised living shrines in his honour across the provinces and hailed him as the \"Nine Thousand Years,\" a title just beneath the emperor's own \"Ten Thousand Years,\" while some even proposed that he be venerated alongside <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucius\">Confucius</span>. His ascendancy collapsed with startling speed when the Tianqi Emperor <b>died childless in 1627</b> and was succeeded by his brother the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chongzhen_Emperor\">Chongzhen Emperor</span>, who within months stripped Wei of his offices and ordered him banished to guard an imperial tomb at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fengyang_County\">Fengyang</span>. Learning en route that he was to be seized and tried, Wei hanged himself before the year was out, whereupon his corpse was dismembered and displayed at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>, his eunuch faction was purged, and the martyred Donglin scholars were posthumously honoured, even as the venomous factionalism of his era continued to corrode the dynasty until its final <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Transition_from_Ming_to_Qing\">collapse</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Wei Zhongxian"},{"id":"cnh-083","num":"八十三","category":"China · History","question":"Triggered when the warlord Toyotomi Hideyoshi invaded Korea in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> as a stepping stone to China, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> drew in huge Ming armies to defend their tributary ally, draining a treasury in a war that helped weaken the dynasty.","answer":"Imjin War","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">&lt;b&gt;1592&lt;/b&gt;–&lt;b&gt;1598&lt;/b&gt;</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"","pinyin":"","translations":"","abstract":"The <b>Imjin War</b> was a devastating conflict fought on the Korean peninsula when the Japanese ruler <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Toyotomi_Hideyoshi\">Toyotomi Hideyoshi</span></b> twice invaded the kingdom of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joseon\">Joseon</span>, drawing in the armies of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span> China. Named for the cyclical year 1592 in which it began, the war sprang from Hideyoshi's grandiose ambition, fresh from unifying the warring states of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sengoku_period\">Sengoku</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japan\">Japan</span>, to conquer Ming China, with Korea to serve as a mere stepping stone after the Joseon court refused him passage. In 1592 a Japanese army of some 158,000 men, armed with European-style <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tanegashima_(gun)\">matchlock</span> muskets and led by commanders such as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Konishi_Yukinaga\">Konishi Yukinaga</span></b>, crossed from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tsushima_Island\">Tsushima</span> to land at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Busan\">Busan</span> and swept north, seizing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Seoul\">Seoul</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pyongyang\">Pyongyang</span> within months and driving King <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Seonjo_of_Joseon\">Seonjo</span> to the northern frontier. Korean resistance crystallised at sea, where <b>the admiral <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yi_Sun-sin\">Yi Sun-sin</span></b> deployed armoured <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Turtle_ship\">turtle ships</span> to win crushing victories such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Hansan_Island\">Battle of Hansan Island</span> that severed Japanese supply lines, while civilian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Righteous_army\">righteous armies</span> harried the invaders on land. Honouring its obligation to a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tributary_system_of_China\">tributary</span> ally, the court of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wanli_Emperor\">Wanli Emperor</span> dispatched large armies that joined the Koreans to <b>retake Pyongyang in early 1593</b>, after which the front congealed into a bloody stalemate. <br> <br> Years of fruitless peace negotiations collapsed, and in 1597 Hideyoshi launched a second invasion, its armies again led by veterans like <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Katō_Kiyomasa\">Katō Kiyomasa</span>, during which the Korean navy was nearly annihilated at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Chilcheollyang\">Battle of Chilcheollyang</span> under the inept <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Won_Gyun\">Won Gyun</span>. Hastily reinstated, Yi Sun-sin salvaged the situation with one of history's most celebrated naval feats, routing a far larger enemy fleet with only 13 ships at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Myeongnyang\">Battle of Myeongnyang</span></b>. The Japanese effort foundered with the death of Hideyoshi in 1598, and as their forces withdrew the allied Ming and Korean fleets, jointly commanded by Yi and the Ming admiral <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Lin_(Ming_dynasty)\">Chen Lin</span>, fell upon them at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Noryang\">Battle of Noryang</span>, a final clash in which Yi Sun-sin was killed at the moment of victory. Korea emerged shattered, its population ravaged and its countryside laid waste, and among the spoils carried off to Japan were thousands of Korean <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Korean_pottery_and_porcelain\">potters</span> whose skills helped found celebrated Japanese ceramic traditions such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Satsuma_ware\">Satsuma</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imari_porcelain\">Arita</span> ware. For the Ming the war was ruinously expensive, consuming millions of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tael\">taels</span> of silver and so straining the treasury that it helped hasten the dynasty's decline and the eventual rise of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_people\">Manchus</span>, who would <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Transition_from_Ming_to_Qing\">conquer</span> China within decades, while in Japan the Toyotomi collapse soon gave way to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tokugawa_shogunate\">Tokugawa shogunate</span> after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Sekigahara\">Battle of Sekigahara</span> of 1600.","citation":"","answerText":"Imjin War"},{"id":"cnc-090","num":"九十","category":"China · Culture","question":"Loosely based on the real pilgrimage of the monk Xuanzang to fetch Buddhist scriptures from India, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> follows a holy traveller and his mischievous animal-spirit disciples, attributed to Wu Cheng'en.","answer":"Journey to the West","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. 1592</span></div>","traditional":"西遊記","hanzi":"西游记","pinyin":"Xīyóujì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Xīyóujì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b><i>Journey to the West</i></b> is a comic and fantastical novel of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming dynasty</span>, <b>published anonymously in 1592</b> and attributed to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Cheng'en\">Wu Cheng'en</span>, the crowning work of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gods_and_demons_fiction\">gods-and-demons</span> genre. It takes its frame from history, the 17-year pilgrimage of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span> monk <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xuanzang\">Xuanzang</span>, who between 629 and 645 crossed deserts and mountains to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"India\">India</span> in search of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Buddhism\">Buddhist</span> scriptures and recorded his travels in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Tang_Records_on_the_Western_Regions\"><i>Great Tang Records on the Western Regions</i></span></b>. In the novel the gentle master, called <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_Sanzang\">Tang Sanzang</span>, is escorted at the bidding of the bodhisattva <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guanyin\">Guanyin</span> by 4 supernatural penitents, the monkey king <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Wukong\">Sun Wukong</span>, the gluttonous pig-spirit <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_Bajie\">Zhu Bajie</span>, the river ogre <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sha_Wujing\">Sha Wujing</span>, and a dragon prince transformed into the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"White_Dragon_Horse\">White Dragon Horse</span></b>. The irrepressible Monkey, hatched from a stone, has mastered 72 transformations and a cloud-somersault of 108,000 li, wields the size-changing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ruyi_Jingu_Bang\">Ruyi Jingu Bang</span> wrested from the dragon king <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ao_Guang\">Ao Guang</span>, and once stole the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peaches_of_Immortality\">Peaches of Immortality</span></b> and routed the hosts of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jade_Emperor\">Jade Emperor</span> before the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gautama_Buddha\">Buddha</span> pinned him beneath a mountain for 500 years. Across the novel's 100 chapters the pilgrims must survive 81 ordained tribulations, fending off demons who crave the monk's flesh as a charm of immortality, among them the fiery child <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Red_Boy\">Red Boy</span> and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bull_Demon_King\">Bull Demon King</span></b> with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Princess_Iron_Fan\">Princess Iron Fan</span>, whose magic fan alone can quench the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Flaming_Mountains\">Flaming Mountains</span>. <br> <br> Beneath the slapstick and marvels readers have always found allegory, the unruly Monkey embodying the restless “mind-ape” to be tamed on the road to enlightenment, the narrative braiding Buddhist karma with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Taoist</span> vocabulary of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Neidan\">internal alchemy</span>. The book stands among the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Classic_Chinese_Novels\">Classic Chinese Novels</span> beside the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Romance_of_the_Three_Kingdoms\"><i>Romance of the Three Kingdoms</i></span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Water_Margin\"><i>Water Margin</i></span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dream_of_the_Red_Chamber\"><i>Dream of the Red Chamber</i></span>. Its episodes long ago entered the repertoire of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peking_opera\">Peking opera</span>, animated the celebrated film <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Havoc_in_Heaven\"><i>Havoc in Heaven</i></span> of the early 1960s, and reached vast audiences through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Journey_to_the_West_(1986_TV_series)\"><b>1986</b> television serial</span>, rebroadcast thousands of times. Abroad the tale travelled as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Arthur_Waley\">Arthur Waley</span>'s beloved 1942 abridgement <i>Monkey</i>, in the complete 4-volume translation of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anthony_C._Yu\">Anthony C. Yu</span> finished in 1983, through the cult Japanese series <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Monkey_(TV_series)\"><i>Monkey</i></span></b> of 1978, and into the DNA of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dragon_Ball\"><i>Dragon Ball</i></span>, whose hero Son Goku is the Monkey King reborn. The pilgrimage shows no sign of ending, for the 2024 video game <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Black_Myth:_Wukong\"><i>Black Myth: Wukong</i></span> sold tens of millions of copies worldwide, confirming the stone monkey as the most exuberant ambassador of the imagination of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Journey to the West"},{"id":"cnh-088","num":"八十八","category":"China · History","question":"A former postal worker who became the most successful rebel leader amid the famine and chaos of the dying Ming, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> captured Beijing in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> and proclaimed his own dynasty, only to be swept away within weeks by the Manchu invasion.","answer":"Li Zicheng","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">September 22, 1606</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1645</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"李自成","pinyin":"Lǐ Zìchéng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Lǐ Zìchéng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Li Zicheng</b> was the most successful of the peasant rebels of the late <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming dynasty</span>, a leader who briefly toppled the empire and founded the short-lived <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shun_dynasty\">Shun dynasty</span></b>. Born to a poor family in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mizhi_County\">Mizhi County</span> in drought-stricken northern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shaanxi\">Shaanxi</span>, he worked as a herdsman and then at a government postal relay station, only to be cast <b>out of work around 1629</b> when the cash-strapped Ming abolished many such posts. Driven into the rebellions then convulsing the famine-ravaged northwest under the climatic stress of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Little_Ice_Age\">Little Ice Age</span>, he rose among the insurgents—a movement led also by the rival warlord <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Xianzhong\">Zhang Xianzhong</span>—and after the rebel chief <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gao_Yingxiang\">Gao Yingxiang</span> was <b>executed in 1636</b>, he inherited his sobriquet of \"Dashing King.\" Though Ming commanders such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Chuanting\">Sun Chuanting</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Chengchou\">Hong Chengchou</span> repeatedly battered his forces, the rebellion revived spectacularly around 1640, when advisers like <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Niu_Jinxing\">Niu Jinxing</span> helped him win mass support with promises to abolish grain taxes and discipline armies that reportedly swelled into the hundreds of thousands. He <b>stormed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luoyang\">Luoyang</span> in 1641</b> and killed its bloated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_Changxun\">Prince of Fu</span>, saw his siege of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kaifeng\">Kaifeng</span> end in 1642 amid a catastrophic breach of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_River\">Yellow River</span> dikes, and seized <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi'an\">Xi'an</span> in 1643, where early in 1644 he proclaimed himself emperor of the Great Shun. <br> <br> Marching swiftly through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanxi\">Shanxi</span> on the capital, his armies entered <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> in April 1644, whereupon the last Ming sovereign, the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chongzhen_Emperor\">Chongzhen Emperor</span></b>, hanged himself on the hill of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jingshan_Park\">Jingshan</span> behind the palace as the rebels poured in. His brief mastery of the city was fatally undermined when his commanders extorted the Ming elite and seized the family and concubine, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Yuanyuan\">Chen Yuanyuan</span></b>, of the frontier general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Sangui\">Wu Sangui</span>, who in fury opened the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanhai_Pass\">Shanhai Pass</span> to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_people\">Manchus</span>. Marching out to confront them, Li was crushed at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Shanhai_Pass\">Battle of Shanhai Pass</span></b> by the combined armies of Wu and the Qing regent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dorgon\">Dorgon</span>, and after barely 6 weeks in Beijing he hastily had himself enthroned, looted the palaces, and fled westward as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span>, under the boy <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shunzhi_Emperor\">Shunzhi Emperor</span>, occupied the capital. Harried relentlessly southward, he lost his strongholds within a year and met his end in 1645 in the mountains of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hubei\">Hubei</span>, reportedly killed by local militiamen, so that his Great Shun endured scarcely a single year. Though he had extinguished the Ming, his failure to consolidate his conquest opened the way for the Manchu seizure of China in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Transition_from_Ming_to_Qing\">Ming–Qing transition</span>, and his swift downfall later furnished the historian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guo_Moruo\">Guo Moruo</span> with a celebrated 1944 essay that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> prescribed as a warning to his own party against the complacency of victory.","citation":"","answerText":"Li Zicheng"},{"id":"cnh-089","num":"八十九","category":"China · History","question":"Inheriting a bankrupt and faction-ridden state and unable to halt its collapse despite his diligence, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> hanged himself on a hill behind the palace in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> as the rebel Li Zicheng entered the capital.","answer":"Chongzhen Emperor","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">February 6, 1611</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">April 25, 1644</span></div>","traditional":"崇禎","hanzi":"崇祯","pinyin":"Chóngzhēn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Chóngzhēn</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“lofty auspiciousness”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Chongzhen Emperor</b> was the last emperor of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming dynasty</span> to rule a unified China from Beijing. He <b>ascended the throne in 1627</b> at about 16, succeeding his negligent brother the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tianqi_Emperor\">Tianqi Emperor</span>, and his first decisive act was to break the dreaded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eunuch\">eunuch</span> dictator <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wei_Zhongxian\">Wei Zhongxian</span>, who was soon driven to suicide. Yet the empire he inherited, already weakened by the long misrule of his grandfather the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wanli_Emperor\">Wanli Emperor</span>, was riven by factional strife between the eunuch clique and the reformist <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Donglin_movement\">Donglin movement</span></b>, drained by an empty treasury, and battered by the climatic shocks of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Little_Ice_Age\">Little Ice Age</span>, which loosed catastrophic droughts, famines, and epidemics across the north. Caught between foreign invasion and internal rebellion, he confronted the rising <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_people\">Manchu</span> power forged by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nurhaci\">Nurhaci</span> and led by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Taiji\">Hong Taiji</span> along the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liaodong\">Liaodong</span> frontier, even as famine-stricken <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shaanxi\">Shaanxi</span> erupted into the peasant revolts of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Zicheng\">Li Zicheng</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Xianzhong\">Zhang Xianzhong</span>. Diligent and frugal but deeply suspicious, he rotated through dozens of chief ministers of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Grand_Secretariat\">Grand Secretariat</span> and fatally crippled <b>his own defenses in 1630</b> by having the able frontier general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_Chonghuan\">Yuan Chonghuan</span> put to death by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lingchi\">slow slicing</span> on a false charge of treason. <br> <br> To finance the wars he levied crushing surtaxes that only deepened rural misery and swelled the rebel ranks, while a devastating outbreak of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bubonic_plague\">plague</span> ravaged <b>Beijing in 1643</b>, hollowing out its garrison on the very eve of the crisis. Early in 1644 Li Zicheng proclaimed his own <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shun_dynasty\">Shun dynasty</span> and marched on the capital, whose demoralized and unpaid defenders offered little resistance as the rebel army closed in that April. On the night the city fell, the emperor reportedly killed or ordered the deaths of his own family before climbing the hill of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jingshan_Park\">Jingshan</span> behind the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Forbidden_City\">Forbidden City</span>, where he hanged himself beside his <b>faithful eunuch <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Cheng'en\">Wang Cheng'en</span></b>, leaving a final note that reproached his ministers yet implored the conquerors to spare the common people. His death ended 276 years of Ming rule, but Li Zicheng held Beijing only briefly, for the frontier general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Sangui\">Wu Sangui</span> opened the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanhai_Pass\">Shanhai Pass</span> to the Manchus, whose regent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dorgon\">Dorgon</span> shattered the rebels at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Shanhai_Pass\">Battle of Shanhai Pass</span></b> and enthroned the boy <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shunzhi_Emperor\">Shunzhi Emperor</span> of the new <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> in the capital. Loyalists rallied around a succession of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Southern_Ming\">Southern Ming</span> courts that prolonged the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Transition_from_Ming_to_Qing\">Ming–Qing transition</span> for nearly 20 years, while the Qing, seeking legitimacy, granted the dead emperor an honorable burial among the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_tombs\">Ming tombs</span>, and posterity has remembered him as a conscientious but doomed ruler whose own indecision deepened a ruin he had inherited.","citation":"","answerText":"Chongzhen Emperor"},{"id":"cnh-090","num":"九十","category":"China · History","question":"A Ming general guarding the strategic pass where the Great Wall meets the sea, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> — enraged at the rebel Li Zicheng — opened the gate to let the Manchu armies through in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>, and later rose against the new dynasty himself.","answer":"Wu Sangui","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1612</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">October 2, 1678</span></div>","traditional":"吳三桂","hanzi":"吴三桂","pinyin":"Wú Sānguì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Wú Sānguì</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Wu Sangui</b> was a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming dynasty</span> general whose decision to admit the Manchus through <b>the Great Wall in 1644</b> helped seal the fate of the empire. Commanding the elite northeastern army from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liaodong\">Liaodong</span> frontier, he was charged with holding the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanhai_Pass\">Shanhai Pass</span>, the fortified gateway where the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Wall_of_China\">Great Wall</span></b> descends to meet the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bohai_Sea\">Bohai Sea</span>. When the rebel <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Zicheng\">Li Zicheng</span> seized Beijing in April 1644 and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chongzhen_Emperor\">Chongzhen Emperor</span> took his own life, Wu found himself trapped <b>between the rebel <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shun_dynasty\">Shun</span></b> regime to his west and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_people\">Manchu</span> banners to his east. According to a famous tradition, he turned against Li Zicheng on learning that his family had been seized and his celebrated concubine <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Yuanyuan\">Chen Yuanyuan</span></b> carried off by the rebel commander <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Zongmin\">Liu Zongmin</span>, an episode later immortalized in the poet <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Weiye\">Wu Weiye</span>'s <i>Song of Yuanyuan</i>, though strategic calculation surely weighed as heavily as rage. Throwing open the pass to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight_Banners\">Manchu armies</span> under the regent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dorgon\">Dorgon</span>, he joined them in routing the rebels at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Shanhai_Pass\">Battle of Shanhai Pass</span></b>, after which the victors installed the boy <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shunzhi_Emperor\">Shunzhi Emperor</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> in the capital. <br> <br> Richly rewarded for his services, Wu was enfeoffed as the Prince Who Pacifies the West and dispatched to subdue the southwest, where he pursued the last <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Southern_Ming\">Southern Ming</span> claimant, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yongli_Emperor\">Yongli Emperor</span>, into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Myanmar\">Burma</span> and had him strangled at <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kunming\">Kunming</span> in 1662</b>, extinguishing the last Ming claim to the throne. As semi-independent ruler of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yunnan\">Yunnan</span>, he became the most powerful of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Feudatories\">Three Feudatories</span>, the trio of Han generals—alongside <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shang_Kexi\">Shang Kexi</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Geng_Jingzhong\">Geng Jingzhong</span>—who governed the conquered south almost as private kingdoms. <b>In 1673</b>, when the young <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kangxi_Emperor\">Kangxi Emperor</span> moved to dismantle these fiefs, Wu rose in open revolt, igniting the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Revolt_of_the_Three_Feudatories\">Revolt of the Three Feudatories</span>, a protracted civil war that became the gravest internal threat the early Qing dynasty would face. Overrunning much of southern China, he proclaimed a new imperial dynasty he called the Great Zhou and declared himself emperor at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hengyang\">Hengzhou</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hunan\">Hunan</span> in 1678, only to die of illness within months. His grandson <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Shifan\">Wu Shifan</span> carried on the doomed cause until its final suppression in 1681, and Wu Sangui has been remembered in Chinese tradition as the archetypal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hanjian\">traitor</span>, a man who betrayed first the Ming and then the very dynasty he had helped to enthrone.","citation":"","answerText":"Wu Sangui"},{"id":"em-004","num":"四","category":"Late Qing · Rulers &amp; Identity","question":"Originating in the forests of Manchuria and conquering China in 1644, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> ruled the empire as a minority elite, imposing the queue hairstyle on Han Chinese men while gradually adopting much of the culture they governed.","answer":"Manchu people","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Origin</span><span class=\"dt-v\">ethnonym “Manju” proclaimed by Hong Taiji, 1635 (replacing Jurchen)</span></div>","traditional":"滿族","hanzi":"满族","pinyin":"Mǎnzú","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Mǎnzú</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Manchu</span><span class=\"tr-ov\">ᠮᠠᠨᠵᡠ</span> <span class=\"tr-rom\">Manju</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Manchu people</b> are a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tungusic_peoples\">Tungusic</span></b> ethnic group native to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northeast_China\">Northeast China</span>, descended from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jurchen_people\">Jurchen</span> tribes who had earlier <b>founded the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jin_dynasty_(1115–1234)\">Jin dynasty</span> of 1115–1234</b>. Their political ascent began in the late 16th century, when the chieftain <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nurhaci\">Nurhaci</span> unified the rival Jurchen tribes, commissioned a new <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_alphabet\">Manchu script</span> in 1599, and in 1616 proclaimed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Later_Jin_(1616–1636)\">Later Jin</span> state. His successor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Taiji\">Hong Taiji</span> reorganised society into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight_Banners\">Eight Banners</span>, a hereditary military and civil structure, and <b>in 1635</b> replaced the older Jurchen name with \"Manju,\" declaring the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> the following year. The dynasty's opportunity came amid the collapse of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming dynasty</span>, when the rebel <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Zicheng\">Li Zicheng</span> seized <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> in 1644</b> and the Ming general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Sangui\">Wu Sangui</span> opened the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanhai_Pass\">Shanhai Pass</span>, allowing the regent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dorgon\">Dorgon</span> to install the young <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shunzhi_Emperor\">Shunzhi Emperor</span> on the throne. Although the conquering Manchus probably numbered fewer than 1 million against a subject population of well over 100 million, they consolidated control throughout the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Transition_from_Ming_to_Qing\">Ming–Qing transition</span> and enforced the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Queue_Order\">queue order</span> of 1645, whose brutal imposition provoked fierce resistance and atrocities such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangzhou_massacre\">Yangzhou massacre</span>.<br> <br>Under the long reigns of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kangxi_Emperor\">Kangxi Emperor</span>, whose 61 years on the throne remain the longest of any Chinese sovereign, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yongzheng_Emperor\">Yongzheng Emperor</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qianlong_Emperor\">Qianlong Emperor</span>, the empire expanded to its greatest territorial extent during the prosperous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"High_Qing_era\">High Qing era</span>. The ruling <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Aisin_Gioro\">Aisin Gioro</span> clan presented itself simultaneously as Confucian emperors, steppe khans, and patrons of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_Buddhism\">Tibetan Buddhism</span>, governing a composite realm that reached deep into <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Inner_Asia\">Inner Asia</span></b> and absorbed extensive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongols\">Mongol</span> and Tibetan domains. Whether the dynasty gradually dissolved into Chinese civilisation through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sinicization\">sinicisation</span> or deliberately preserved a separate identity has become the central question of the revisionist <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Qing_History\">New Qing History</span></b>, whose proponents stress the regime's enduring reliance on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_language\">Manchu language</span> in confidential administration. Anti-Manchu sentiment, distilled in the revolutionary call to expel the foreign rulers championed by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Yat-sen\">Sun Yat-sen</span>, helped propel the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinhai_Revolution\">Xinhai Revolution</span> of 1911, which forced the abdication of the child emperor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Puyi\">Puyi</span> in 1912 and ended 268 years of imperial rule. Today recognised as one of the 56 official <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"List_of_ethnic_groups_in_China\">ethnic groups of China</span>, the Manchus numbered roughly 10.4 million at the 2010 census, yet their ancestral tongue has all but vanished—sustained in writing chiefly by the related <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xibe_people\">Xibe people</span></b>—even as the overwhelming majority now speak <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mandarin_Chinese\">Mandarin</span> and live fully integrated into wider Chinese society.","citation":"","answerText":"Manchu people"},{"id":"cnc-094","num":"九十四","category":"China · Culture","question":"A collection of nearly 500 supernatural tales of fox spirits, ghosts and scholars compiled by Pu Songling, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> used the uncanny to satirise the corruption and absurdities of Qing society.","answer":"Strange Stories from a Chinese Studio","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1640–1715 (Pu Songling)</span></div>","traditional":"聊齋誌異","hanzi":"聊斋志异","pinyin":"Liáozhāi zhìyì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Liáozhāi zhìyì</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“strange tales from the studio of leisure”</span></div>","abstract":"<b><i>Strange Stories from a Chinese Studio</i></b> is a collection of nearly 500 supernatural tales by <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pu_Songling\">Pu Songling</span></b> (1640–1715), the masterpiece of short fiction of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span>. Its author spent his life near <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zibo\">Zibo</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shandong\">Shandong</span>, where, after youthful distinction, he failed the provincial <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examination</span> repeatedly and earned his bread for decades as a tutor in a gentry household, receiving an honorary degree only at the age of 71. He gathered and polished his tales across some 40 years, <b>completing a preface in 1679 yet</b> adding stories into the early 1700s, and the work circulated in manuscript long after his death until its first printing in 1766. Composed in a dense, allusive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Classical_Chinese\">Classical Chinese</span> rare for fiction, it fuses the laconic anomaly records of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhiguai_xiaoshuo\">zhiguai</span></b> tradition with the romance of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chuanqi_(short_story)\">chuanqi</span>, each tale often capped by the author's verdict as the self-styled Historian of the Strange, a bow to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sima_Qian\">Sima Qian</span> that won the admiration of <b>the poet <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Shizhen_(Qing_dynasty)\">Wang Shizhen</span></b>. Its world teems with seductive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huli_jing\">fox spirits</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ghosts_in_Chinese_culture\">ghosts</span> who console poor scholars, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Taoist</span> exorcists, and venal magistrates, the uncanny serving as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Satire\">satire</span>, as in <i>The Cricket</i>, where a boy's soul enters a champion insect to satisfy a court craze for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cricket_fighting\">cricket fighting</span>. <br> <br> Among its most celebrated pieces are <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Painted_Skin\"><i>The Painted Skin</i></span>, whose lovely woman proves a demon wearing human hide, the ghost bride <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nie_Xiaoqian\"><i>Nie Xiaoqian</i></span></b>, and the laughing fox-girl <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yingning\"><i>Yingning</i></span>, tales in which monsters often show more humanity than mandarins. Writing from the margins of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Scholar-official\">scholar-official</span> world he could never enter, Pu turned foxes and ghosts into instruments of protest, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guo_Moruo\">Guo Moruo</span> later praised him for excelling all in writing of spirits while flaying greed and corruption to the bone. The book's success begat rivals and rejoinders, from the urbane collection of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_Mei\">Yuan Mei</span> to the pointed anecdotes of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ji_Yun\">Ji Yun</span>, who faulted its novelistic embroidery of the unseen. The West first met it through the prudishly <b>trimmed 1880 selection</b> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Herbert_Giles\">Herbert Giles</span>, while <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"John_Minford\">John Minford</span>'s 2006 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Penguin_Classics\">Penguin Classics</span> version restored its sly erotic and ironic edge. Its tales feed an unending stream of opera, television, and film, <i>Nie Xiaoqian</i> becoming the <b>beloved <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"A_Chinese_Ghost_Story\"><i>A Chinese Ghost Story</i></span> of 1987</b>, the swordswoman tale <i>Xianü</i> inspiring <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Hu\">King Hu</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"A_Touch_of_Zen\"><i>A Touch of Zen</i></span>, honoured at Cannes in 1975, and the 2008 blockbuster <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Painted_Skin_(2008_film)\"><i>Painted Skin</i></span> spawning sequels, so that the studio's strange guests remain among the liveliest spirits in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_folklore\">folklore</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Strange Stories from a Chinese Studio"},{"id":"em-003","num":"三","category":"Late Qing · The Dynasty","question":"Ruling from 1644 until 1912 as the last imperial dynasty, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was founded by the Manchus and presided over China's territorial peak before declining through the 19th century under pressure from rebellion and Western powers.","answer":"Qing dynasty","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Founded</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1644 · Manchu conquest of Beijing</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Ended</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1912 · abdication of Puyi</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"清","pinyin":"Qīng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Qīng</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Manchu</span><span class=\"tr-rom\">Daicing gurun</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Qing dynasty</b> was the last imperial dynasty of China, ruling <b>from 1644</b> to <b>1912</b> and tracing its origins to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jurchen_people\">Jurchen</span> chieftain <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nurhaci\">Nurhaci</span>, who unified the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_people\">Manchu</span> tribes of the northeast and founded <b>the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Later_Jin_(1616–1636)\">Later Jin</span> state in 1616</b>. His son <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Taiji\">Hong Taiji</span> proclaimed the new dynastic name in 1636 and organised Manchu society into the military-civil <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight_Banners\">Eight Banners</span>, and in 1644 the collapse of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming dynasty</span> under the rebel <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Zicheng\">Li Zicheng</span> allowed the defecting general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Sangui\">Wu Sangui</span> to open the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanhai_Pass\">Shanhai Pass</span> and admit the Manchu armies. Under the regent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dorgon\">Dorgon</span>, the boy <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shunzhi_Emperor\">Shunzhi Emperor</span></b> was installed in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>, and the conquering regime imposed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Queue_(hairstyle)\">queue</span> on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Chinese\">Han Chinese</span> population while retaining the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> bureaucracy and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examination</span> system that had administered earlier dynasties. During the prolonged peace and prosperity that accompanied the long reigns of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kangxi_Emperor\">Kangxi Emperor</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yongzheng_Emperor\">Yongzheng Emperor</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qianlong_Emperor\">Qianlong Emperor</span>, the empire reached its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"High_Qing_era\">demographic and economic apex</span>, with the population swelling from roughly 150 million in the early period to more than 400 million by the early 19th century. Through campaigns such as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ten_Great_Campaigns\">Ten Great Campaigns</span></b> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dzungar_genocide\">subjugation of the Dzungars</span>, the dynasty incorporated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinjiang\">Xinjiang</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibet\">Tibet</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongolia\">Mongolia</span>, expanding to govern more than 13 million square kilometres (5 million square miles) at its territorial height around 1790. <br> <br> The 19th century brought mounting crises, beginning with the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"White_Lotus_Rebellion\">White Lotus Rebellion</span></b> and culminating in defeat by Britain in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Opium_War\">First Opium War</span>, which ended in 1842 with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Nanking\">Treaty of Nanking</span>, the cession of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span>, and the first of many <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Unequal_treaty\">unequal treaties</span>. Further humiliation followed in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Opium_War\">Second Opium War</span>, while internally the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiping_Rebellion\">Taiping Rebellion</span> led by the millenarian <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Xiuquan\">Hong Xiuquan</span></b> raged from 1850 to 1864 and left an estimated 20 to 30 million people dead, ranking among the deadliest conflicts in human history. Reformist officials launched the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Self-Strengthening_Movement\">Self-Strengthening Movement</span> to modernise the military and industry, but the catastrophic loss to Japan in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Sino-Japanese_War\">First Sino-Japanese War</span> of 1894–1895 forced the cession of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span> under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Shimonoseki\">Treaty of Shimonoseki</span> and exposed the limits of reform. Court politics in these decades were dominated by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empress_Dowager_Cixi\">Empress Dowager Cixi</span>, who suppressed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hundred_Days'_Reform\">Hundred Days' Reform</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangxu_Emperor\">Guangxu Emperor</span> in 1898, and whose tacit support for the anti-foreign <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boxer_Rebellion\">Boxer Rebellion</span> provoked an invasion by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight-Nation_Alliance\">Eight-Nation Alliance</span> and the crushing indemnity imposed by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boxer_Protocol\">Boxer Protocol</span>, set at 450 million taels of silver. Belated constitutional reforms failed to restore the dynasty's legitimacy, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinhai_Revolution\">Xinhai Revolution</span> of 1911 swept it away, ending with the abdication of the child emperor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Puyi\">Puyi</span> in February 1912 and the establishment of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)\">Republic of China</span> under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Yat-sen\">Sun Yat-sen</span>, closing more than 2,000 years of dynastic imperial rule.","citation":"","answerText":"Qing dynasty"},{"id":"em-005","num":"五","category":"Qing Foreign Relations · World Order","question":"Framing foreign relations as a hierarchy in which neighbouring states sent envoys bearing gifts and performed the kowtow in exchange for trade and recognition, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> placed the Chinese emperor at the centre of the civilised world — an idea strained by Western diplomats demanding equality.","answer":"tributary system","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Coined</span><span class=\"dt-v\">J. K. Fairbank & Teng Ssu-yu, early 1940s</span></div>","traditional":"朝貢體系","hanzi":"朝贡体系","pinyin":"cháogòng tǐxì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">cháogòng tǐxì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>tributary system</b> was the hierarchical, China-centred framework of foreign relations through which successive Chinese dynasties managed their dealings with surrounding peoples, placing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_of_China\">emperor</span> at the apex of a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sinocentrism\">Sinocentric</span> world order</b>. Grounded in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> ideas of graded hierarchy and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hua–Yi_distinction\">distinction between the civilised and the barbarian</span>, the arrangement cast the ruler as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Son_of_Heaven\">Son of Heaven</span>, holder of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mandate_of_Heaven\">Mandate of Heaven</span>, whose authority was imagined to extend over <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tianxia\">all under Heaven</span>. In practice, foreign envoys travelled to the capital bearing local <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tribute\">tribute</span>, performed the <b>ritual <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kowtow\">kowtow</span> before the throne</b>, and received in return lavish counter-gifts, formal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Investiture\">investiture</span>, and the right to trade, a bond of nominal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Suzerainty\">suzerainty</span> rather than direct imperial rule. Elements of the practice appeared as early as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span> and were elaborated under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song</span> dynasties, but it reached its most codified form under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span>, whose statutes regulated the frequency, routes, and size of missions from dozens of states across Asia. Among the most faithful participants was <b>Korea's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joseon\">Joseon</span> dynasty</b>, which sent several embassies a year, joined by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ryukyu_Kingdom\">Ryukyu Kingdom</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Đại_Việt\">Đại Việt</span>, the Siamese <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ayutthaya_Kingdom\">Ayutthaya Kingdom</span></b>, and at times the shoguns of Japan's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ashikaga_shogunate\">Ashikaga</span> court, while the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_treasure_voyages\">treasure voyages</span> of the admiral <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zheng_He\">Zheng He</span>, 7 expeditions launched <b>between 1405 and 1433 </b>with fleets of up to 300 ships and nearly 28,000 men, carried the system across the Indian Ocean. <br> <br> Although couched in the language of submission, the order operated as much as a commercial and diplomatic mechanism, for the court routinely bestowed return gifts exceeding the value of the tribute it received, and accompanying merchants used the missions to conduct exchange that the dynasty otherwise tightly restricted. The framework was later systematised by the historian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"John_King_Fairbank\">John King Fairbank</span> and his collaborators, notably in the 1968 volume <i>The Chinese World Order</i>, although subsequent scholars have questioned how coherently the varied practices it groups together ever functioned as a single institution. Friction with European states centred on their insistence on diplomatic equality, most famously when the <b>British <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Macartney_Embassy\">Macartney Embassy</span></b> of 1793 refused to perform the full ritual of 3 kneelings and 9 prostrations before the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qianlong_Emperor\">Qianlong Emperor</span>, who answered with an edict to King <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"George_III\">George III</span> rejecting British requests and declaring that the empire possessed all things and needed nothing. The strain intensified as Western traders chafed under the restrictive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Canton_System\">Canton System</span>, and military defeat in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Opium_War\">First Opium War</span> produced the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Nanking\">Treaty of Nanking</span> of 1842 and a cascade of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Unequal_treaty\">unequal treaties</span> that imposed Western diplomatic norms by force. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Tientsin\">Treaty of Tianjin</span> of 1858 won foreign envoys the right to reside in the capital, and the establishment of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zongli_Yamen\">Zongli Yamen</span> in 1861 marked a reluctant turn towards the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Westphalian_sovereignty\">Westphalian</span> principle of sovereign equality, a transformation that by the early 20th century had replaced the old hierarchy with the <b>modern practice of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Diplomacy\">diplomacy</span></b> among formally equal states.","citation":"","answerText":"tributary system"},{"id":"em-008","num":"八","category":"Opium Wars · Trade &amp; Drugs","question":"Growing into a corrosive problem as British traders smuggled it to balance their purchases of tea, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> drained silver from the country and bred mass addiction, provoking the crackdown that led to war.","answer":"Opium","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Greek ὄπιον (ópion, ‘poppy juice’), via Latin opium</span></div>","traditional":"鴉片","hanzi":"鸦片","pinyin":"yāpiàn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">yāpiàn</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Opium</b> is a narcotic substance prepared from the dried latex of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Opium_poppy\">opium poppy</span>, rich in the alkaloids <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Morphine\">morphine</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Codeine\">codeine</span>, that had been used medicinally in China since the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang dynasty</span> before recreational smoking spread widely during the 18th century. Its commercial significance grew explosively once the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"East_India_Company\">East India Company</span> began cultivating the drug in <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bengal_Presidency\">Bengal</span></b> and smuggling it through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou\">Canton</span> to offset a chronic trade deficit, since European demand for Chinese tea, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk\">silk</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Porcelain\">porcelain</span> had to be paid in bullion under the restrictive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Canton_System\">Canton System</span> and its monopolistic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cohong\">Cohong</span> merchants. Annual imports surged from a <b>few thousand chests around 1800</b> to roughly 40,000 chests—each weighing some 63 kilograms (140 pounds)—by the late 1830s, a flood that reversed the long-standing inflow of silver and bred dependence on a mass scale. Alarmed by addiction running into the millions and by the resulting drain of bullion counted in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tael\">taels</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> court under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Daoguang_Emperor\">Daoguang Emperor</span> dispatched the commissioner <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lin_Zexu\">Lin Zexu</span>, who <b>in 1839</b> confiscated and publicly destroyed more than 20,000 chests at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Destruction_of_opium_at_Humen\">Humen</span>. Britain answered the seizure with military force in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Opium_War\">First Opium War</span> of 1839–1842, whose lopsided outcome was sealed by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Nanking\">Treaty of Nanking</span>, the first of the so-called <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Unequal_treaty\">unequal treaties</span>, which ceded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span> Island, opened five <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_ports\">treaty ports</span>, and imposed an indemnity of 21 million silver dollars.<br> <br>A second conflict, <b>the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Opium_War\">Second Opium War</span> of 1856–1860</b> waged by Britain and France—triggered by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Arrow_incident\">Arrow incident</span> as the dynasty was simultaneously convulsed by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiping_Rebellion\">Taiping Rebellion</span>—yielded the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Tientsin\">Treaty of Tientsin</span> and then the punitive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Convention_of_Peking\">Convention of Peking</span>, which together legalised the import, extended <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Extraterritoriality\">extraterritoriality</span>, and were attended by the burning of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Old_Summer_Palace\">Old Summer Palace</span></b> and the cession of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kowloon\">Kowloon</span>. Far from curbing consumption, legalisation spurred a vast expansion of domestic cultivation in provinces such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yunnan\">Yunnan</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan\">Sichuan</span>, until home-grown opium came to eclipse the imported supply entirely. By the turn of the 20th century the number of habitual users is thought to have climbed into the tens of millions, prompting a sweeping domestic suppression launched by imperial edict in 1906 and an international response at the 1909 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"International_Opium_Commission\">International Opium Commission</span> in Shanghai. Although consumption persisted through the warlord era and the early Republic, the newly founded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic</span> mounted a draconian anti-narcotics campaign between 1950 and 1952 that, through mass treatment, relentless propaganda, and the execution of major traffickers, all but eradicated the habit within a few years. Remembered as the catalyst of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Century_of_humiliation\">century of humiliation</span></b> and a spur to the reformist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Self-Strengthening_Movement\">Self-Strengthening Movement</span>, the trade survives in official historiography as a foundational parable of national weakness, foreign predation, and the enduring necessity of a strong central state.","citation":"","answerText":"Opium"},{"id":"em-016","num":"十六","category":"Foreign Imperialism · The Treaty System","question":"Among the most resented privileges won by the powers, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> exempted foreign nationals from Chinese courts, so that a Briton or American accused of a crime in a treaty port would be tried by his own consul.","answer":"Extraterritoriality","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Latin extra (‘outside’) + territorium; legal usage from the 19th c.</span></div>","traditional":"治外法權","hanzi":"治外法权","pinyin":"zhìwài fǎquán","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">zhìwài fǎquán</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Extraterritoriality</b> is the legal principle by which foreign nationals residing in a host country are exempted from its <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jurisdiction\">jurisdiction</span></b> and remain answerable instead to the laws and courts of their own state, in effect carrying their home legal order with them wherever they go. In China it became one of the most galling features of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Unequal_treaty\">unequal treaties</span>, first conceded to Britain <b>in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_the_Bogue\">Treaty of the Bogue</span> of 1843</b> after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Opium_War\">First Opium War</span> and quickly extended to the United States and France through the treaties of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Wanghia\">Wanghia</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Whampoa\">Whampoa</span> in 1844. Because each accord carried <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Most_favoured_nation\">most-favoured-nation</span> guarantees, the privilege spread automatically, and by the early 20th century the nationals of as many as 19 foreign powers enjoyed immunity from the courts of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> across the network of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_port\">treaty ports</span>. In practice a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Consul_(representative)\">consul</span></b> or a dedicated consular tribunal heard cases against his countrymen, an arrangement formalised in institutions such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"British_Supreme_Court_for_China\">British Supreme Court for China</span>, <b>established at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span> in 1865</b>, and the later <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States_Court_for_China\">United States Court for China</span> of 1906. Within the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_International_Settlement\">Shanghai International Settlement</span>, cases involving both Chinese and foreigners were handled by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_Mixed_Court\">Mixed Court</span>, a hybrid body whose proceedings increasingly slipped from Chinese control and came to symbolise the broader erosion of national sovereignty. <br> <br> The principle was not unique to China, drawing on the older <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capitulations_of_the_Ottoman_Empire\">capitulations</span> granted by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ottoman_Empire\">Ottoman Empire</span> and finding parallels in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empire_of_Japan\">Japan</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Thailand\">Siam</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mixed_Courts_of_Egypt\">Mixed Courts of Egypt</span>, yet it became most closely bound up with national humiliation in East Asia. Japan succeeded in shedding its own extraterritorial servitude through treaty revision that <b>took effect in 1899</b>, while in China the system endured for a century and became a rallying cry for rising <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_nationalism\">Chinese nationalism</span> and a defining grievance of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Century_of_humiliation\">century of humiliation</span>. The retreat of the privilege came piecemeal, as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"German_Empire\">Germany</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Austria-Hungary\">Austria-Hungary</span> forfeited their rights after defeat in the First World War and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Soviet Union</span> renounced its own in 1924 in a calculated bid to court Chinese goodwill. The remaining powers finally relinquished extraterritoriality in China through a <b>pair of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_for_the_Relinquishment_of_Extraterritorial_Rights_in_China\">relinquishment treaties</span></b> signed in January 1943 with the wartime <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)\">Nationalist government</span> as an Allied gesture during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_War_II\">Second World War</span>. Although the colonial form vanished, related forms of extraterritorial exemption persist in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Diplomatic_immunity\">diplomatic immunity</span></b> codified by the 1961 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vienna_Convention_on_Diplomatic_Relations\">Vienna Convention on Diplomatic Relations</span>, in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Status_of_forces_agreement\">status-of-forces agreements</span> that govern soldiers stationed abroad, and in the immunities extended to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"International_organization\">international organisations</span> and their officials.","citation":"","answerText":"Extraterritoriality"},{"id":"em-017","num":"十七","category":"Foreign Imperialism · The Treaty System","question":"Territories leased or carved out within Chinese cities and administered by foreign powers, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> — with their own police, courts and municipal councils — sprang up in ports such as Tianjin and Hankou after the unequal treaties.","answer":"concessions","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Latin concessio (‘a granting’); foreign-leased zones, 19th c.</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"租界","pinyin":"zūjiè","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">zūjiè</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>concessions</b>&nbsp; were enclaves within Chinese cities that were leased or granted to foreign powers and administered by them as virtually self-governing states, complete with their own police forces, law courts, and elected municipal councils, that proliferated in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_ports\">treaty ports</span> opened after the unequal treaties, beginning with the <b>1842</b> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Nanking\">Treaty of Nanking</span>. Their existence rested on the principle of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Extraterritoriality\">extraterritoriality</span>, which removed foreign residents from Chinese jurisdiction, and they ranged from single-power concessions administered by an individual nation's consul to multinational international settlements governed jointly by several of the treaty powers. The archetype was <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span>, where a British settlement <b>established in 1845</b>, soon administered by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_Municipal_Council\">Shanghai Municipal Council</span> created in 1854, merged with the American quarter in 1863 to form the celebrated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_International_Settlement\">Shanghai International Settlement</span>, while the adjacent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_French_Concession\">French Concession</span> kept its own separate administration. Such districts operated as miniature city-states, raising their own taxes, maintaining police bodies such as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_Municipal_Police\">Shanghai Municipal Police</span></b>, adjudicating cases through tribunals like the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_International_Mixed_Court\">Mixed Court</span>, and lining their riverfronts with imposing commercial architecture, most famously along the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Bund\">Bund</span>. Beyond Shanghai, foreign quarters multiplied along the coast and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span>: the city of Tianjin alone eventually contained 9 separate concessions, the river port of Hankou held 5, and smaller enclaves arose on <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shamian_Island\">Shamian Island</span></b> at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou\">Canton</span> and on the islet of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gulangyu\">Gulangyu</span> off <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiamen\">Amoy</span>.<br> <br>At their height these enclaves were held by a roster of powers that included Britain, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"France\">France</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empire_of_Japan\">Empire of Japan</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russian_Empire\">Russian Empire</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"German_Empire\">German Empire</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Austria-Hungary\">Austria-Hungary</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kingdom_of_Italy\">Kingdom of Italy</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Belgium\">Belgium</span>, each transplanting its own architecture and institutions onto Chinese soil. Cosmopolitan, prosperous, and beyond the reach of Chinese law, the largest settlements drew merchants, adventurers, and capital from across the globe and became havens for the displaced—from <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"White_émigré\">White Russian émigrés</span></b> fleeing revolution to refugees of many other nations—while a comparable foreign enclave, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing_Legation_Quarter\">Beijing Legation Quarter</span>, entrenched itself in the imperial capital. Their retreat began during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_War_I\">First World War</span>, when China declared war and seized the German and <b>Austro-Hungarian concessions in 1917</b>, and accelerated under pressure from the rising <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Nationalist</span> movement, which in 1927 obliged Britain to surrender its concessions at Hankou and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiujiang\">Jiujiang</span>. The system was shattered by the Second World War, as Japan seized the foreign settlements after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Attack_on_Pearl_Harbor\">attack on Pearl Harbor</span> in 1941—even while Japanese-held Shanghai sheltered the Jewish refugees of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_Ghetto\">Shanghai Ghetto</span>—and the surviving privileges were formally surrendered in 1943, when the United States and Britain renounced extraterritoriality and the Japanese-sponsored <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Jingwei_regime\">Wang Jingwei regime</span></b> nominally recovered the rest. Though the enclaves themselves have long since vanished, their imprint endures in the grand European facades that still line the waterfronts and avenues of cities such as Shanghai, where they persist in official memory as one of the most vivid symbols of the foreign domination that defined China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Century_of_humiliation\">century of humiliation</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"concessions"},{"id":"em-040","num":"四十","category":"Foreign Imperialism · Economy","question":"Borrowed from Portuguese, the term <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> named the Chinese manager who served as the indispensable go-between for a foreign firm in a treaty port, often growing rich, while later Marxist writers used the word as an insult for capitalists tied to imperialism.","answer":"Comprador","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Portuguese comprador (‘buyer’); in East-Asia trade from the 16th c.</span></div>","traditional":"買辦","hanzi":"买办","pinyin":"mǎibàn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">mǎibàn</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Comprador</b> (from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Portuguese_language\">Portuguese</span> <i>comprador</i>, \"buyer\") was the term for the Chinese manager and intermediary who handled the local business of a foreign trading house or bank in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> China. The word entered usage through the Portuguese enclave of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Macau\">Macau</span> and gradually displaced the older intermediaries of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Canton_System\">Canton System</span>, under which Sino-Western trade had been funneled through the monopoly guild of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cohong\">Cohong</span> merchants at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou\">Canton</span> <b>between 1757</b> and 1842. After the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Opium_War\">First Opium War</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Nanking\">Treaty of Nanking</span> of 1842 abolished that monopoly and opened a string of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_port\">treaty ports</span>, Western firms began engaging compradors directly to recruit Chinese staff, vouch for the credit of local merchants, and manage transactions settled in silver <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sycee\">sycee</span>. Posting a substantial security bond and drawing both a salary and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Commission_(remuneration)\">commissions</span>, the comprador bridged formidable barriers of language, currency, and custom while pursuing lucrative private ventures of his own, so that the position became a celebrated avenue to fortune. Indispensable to the great <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_(business)\">hongs</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span> such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jardine_Matheson\">Jardine Matheson</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dent_&amp;_Co.\">Dent &amp; Co.</span>, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russell_&amp;_Company\">Russell &amp; Company</span></b>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"HSBC\">Hongkong and Shanghai Banking Corporation</span>, the comprador class amassed enormous capital, with the historian Hao Yen-p'ing estimating that its members earned roughly 530 million <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tael\">taels</span> <b>between 1842</b> and 1894. <br> <br> Many of the most prominent compradors hailed from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangdong\">Guangdong</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ningbo\">Ningbo</span>, and although the class may have numbered around 10,000 by the end of the 19th century, individual figures such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tong_King-sing\">Tong King-sing</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zheng_Guanying\">Zheng Guanying</span></b> began their careers in the trade before redirecting their wealth and expertise into native industry. Such men channeled comprador capital into pioneering modern enterprises, including the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Merchants_Steam_Navigation_Company\">China Merchants' Steam Navigation Company</span> and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kaiping_Mines\">Kaiping coal mines</span></b>, making the class an important early engine of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Self-Strengthening_Movement\">Self-Strengthening Movement</span> and of Chinese industrialisation. In <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marxism\">Marxist</span> and especially <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marxism–Leninism\">Marxist–Leninist</span> analysis, however, the word took on a sharply pejorative cast, designating a \"comprador bourgeoisie\" of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capitalism\">capitalists</span> whose interests were bound to foreign <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperialism\">imperialism</span> rather than to national development. <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> gave this usage <b>lasting currency in his 1926 essay</b> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Analysis_of_the_Classes_in_Chinese_Society\"><i>Analysis of the Classes in Chinese Society</i></span>, branding the comprador class an enemy of revolution in contrast to the more ambivalent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_bourgeoisie\">national bourgeoisie</span>, and the epithet <b>later spread through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dependency_theory\">dependency theory</span></b> to describe intermediary elites across the colonial world. The institution itself gradually waned as Chinese merchants mastered direct commercial dealings, and it vanished altogether after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> came to power in 1949, by which point \"comprador\" had hardened from a job title into one of the gravest accusations in the new state's political vocabulary.","citation":"","answerText":"Comprador"},{"id":"cnh-086","num":"八十六","category":"China · History","question":"A military-social structure created by Nurhaci that organised Manchu households into hereditary units identified by coloured flags, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> formed the elite army of the conquest and a privileged caste that received state stipends for generations.","answer":"Eight Banners","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">八旗 (Bāqí, 'eight banners'), the Manchu military divisions</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"八旗","pinyin":"Bāqí","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Bāqí</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Eight Banners</b> were the hereditary military and social divisions into which the early <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_people\">Manchu</span></b> state organised its population, each identified by a distinctively coloured flag and forming the bedrock of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> power. They were created by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nurhaci\">Nurhaci</span>, founder of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Later_Jin_(1616–1636)\">Later Jin</span>, who built upon the traditional <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jurchen_people\">Jurchen</span> hunting company, or niru, first <b>establishing four banners around 1601</b> and expanding them to eight by 1615, distinguished by plain and bordered flags of yellow, white, red, and blue. Far more than an army, each banner was simultaneously a military formation, an administrative unit, and a social framework to which every <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Conscription\">conscript</span> household permanently belonged, mobilising the whole people for war. Under his son <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Taiji\">Hong Taiji</span> the system was broadened by the addition of parallel <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongols\">Mongol</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hanjun\">Han Chinese</span></b> banners, eventually numbering 24 in all, and the banner population coalesced into a distinct hereditary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Caste\">caste</span> set apart from ordinary subjects. It was these disciplined banner armies that formed the spearhead of the Manchu <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Transition_from_Ming_to_Qing\">conquest</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span> China, having first proven their power <b>at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Sarhū\">Battle of Sarhū</span> in 1619</b> before pouring through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanhai_Pass\">Shanhai Pass</span> in 1644 under the regent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dorgon\">Dorgon</span>, acting for the child <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shunzhi_Emperor\">Shunzhi Emperor</span>, to seize the empire. <br> <br> After the conquest the banners were quartered as permanent garrisons, the bulk of them concentrated around the capital at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> and the rest stationed in walled enclaves within strategic cities such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi'an\">Xi'an</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hangzhou\">Hangzhou</span>, where they lived apart from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Chinese\">Han Chinese</span> majority. As a privileged warrior estate, bannermen and their families received hereditary state <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stipend\">stipends</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rice\">rice</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silver\">silver</span></b> together with allotments of land, and were generally forbidden to engage in trade or farming so as to remain a standing martial class. Over the generations, however, a swelling banner population and the soaring cost of its stipends became a crushing fiscal burden that vexed emperors from the time of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qianlong_Emperor\">Qianlong Emperor</span>, while the once-formidable troops grew idle, impoverished, and militarily ineffective through a creeping <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sinicization\">sinicisation</span> and loss of martial vigour. By the 19th century the banner forces could no longer carry the empire's wars, proving largely ineffective in conflicts such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Opium_War\">First Opium War</span>, and the dynasty leaned ever more on the Han <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Green_Standard_Army\">Green Standard Army</span></b> and, during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiping_Rebellion\">Taiping Rebellion</span>, on new regional forces such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiang_Army\">Xiang</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huai_Army\">Huai</span> armies. Despite their decay, the banner system and its stipends endured until the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinhai_Revolution\">revolution</span> that <b>toppled the Qing in 1912</b>, after which the bannermen abruptly lost their state support, and many of them, including the once-exalted <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Aisin_Gioro\">Aisin Gioro</span> clan, fell into poverty or concealed their ancestry amid a wave of anti-Manchu feeling.","citation":"","answerText":"Eight Banners"},{"id":"cnh-091","num":"九十一","category":"China · History","question":"Decades of warfare during which the Manchus and their Chinese collaborators overcame the rebels, the remnants of the Ming and loyalists such as Koxinga on Taiwan, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> established a new ruling house over all of China by the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>s.","answer":"Transition from Ming to Qing","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">明清易代 ('the Ming–Qing change of mandate')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"明清易代","pinyin":"Míng-Qīng yìdài","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Míng-Qīng yìdài</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>transition from Ming to Qing</b> denotes the decades of devastating warfare, <b>spanning roughly 1618</b> to <b>1683</b>, during which the Manchu-led <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> supplanted the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span> as the ruling house of China. The conflict had its origins on the northeastern frontier, where <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nurhaci\">Nurhaci</span> had welded the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_people\">Manchu</span> tribes into a formidable state, and where his son <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Taiji\">Hong Taiji</span> proclaimed <b>the Qing dynasty in 1636 while</b> subduing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joseon\">Korea</span> and the Mongol borderlands. The Ming, meanwhile, was crumbling from within under famine, fiscal exhaustion, and vast peasant uprisings led by rebels such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Zicheng\">Li Zicheng</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Xianzhong\">Zhang Xianzhong</span>, and in 1644 Li captured <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>, driving the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chongzhen_Emperor\">Chongzhen Emperor</span> to take his own life. Rather than submit to the rebels, the <b>Ming general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Sangui\">Wu Sangui</span></b> opened the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanhai_Pass\">Shanhai Pass</span> to the Manchus, and the regent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dorgon\">Dorgon</span>, acting for the boy <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shunzhi_Emperor\">Shunzhi Emperor</span>, routed Li Zicheng and installed the Qing on the throne in Beijing. The imposition of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Queue_Order\">queue order</span>, which compelled <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Chinese\">Han Chinese</span> men to shave their foreheads and braid their hair on pain of death, provoked fierce resistance that was answered with atrocities such as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangzhou_massacre\">Yangzhou massacre</span></b> of 1645. <br> <br> Resistance nonetheless persisted for decades, as a succession of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Southern_Ming\">Southern Ming</span> regimes rallied around surviving princes, the last of whom, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yongli_Emperor\">Yongli Emperor</span>, fled into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Myanmar\">Burma</span> before being handed over and executed by Wu Sangui in 1662. The most celebrated loyalist was <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Koxinga\">Koxinga</span>, son of the merchant-admiral <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zheng_Zhilong\">Zheng Zhilong</span></b>, who after years of resistance along the southeast coast and a failed assault on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span> expelled the Dutch from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span> in 1662 and founded the Ming-loyalist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kingdom_of_Tungning\">Kingdom of Tungning</span> there. The gravest threat to the new order came from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Revolt_of_the_Three_Feudatories\">Revolt of the Three Feudatories</span> between 1673 and 1681, when Wu Sangui and two fellow Chinese collaborators, granted vast semi-autonomous fiefs in the south, rose against the young <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kangxi_Emperor\">Kangxi Emperor</span>. Kangxi crushed the uprising after eight years of hard fighting, and in 1683 his admiral <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shi_Lang\">Shi Lang</span> destroyed the Zheng fleet at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Penghu\">Battle of Penghu</span>, compelling the surrender of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zheng_Keshuang\">Zheng Keshuang</span></b> and bringing Taiwan under Qing rule. With the fall of Taiwan the conquest was complete, leaving the Manchu <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Aisin_Gioro\">Aisin Gioro</span> house masters of all China, and though the upheaval had cost the lives of many millions through battle, massacre, and famine, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight_Banners\">banner</span> regime it established would endure until the fall of imperial China in 1912.","citation":"","answerText":"Transition from Ming to Qing"},{"id":"cnh-098","num":"九十八","category":"China · History","question":"A series of frontier wars trumpeted by the Qianlong Emperor as proof of his glory, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> extended control over Xinjiang — destroying the Dzungars — and intervened in Tibet, Burma and Vietnam, draining the treasury despite their grand reputation.","answer":"Ten Great Campaigns","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">十全武功 ('ten complete military victories'), Qianlong's own count</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"十全武功","pinyin":"Shíquán wǔgōng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Shíquán wǔgōng</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“ten complete military victories”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Ten Great Campaigns</b> were a series of frontier wars waged by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> during the long 18th-century reign of the Qianlong Emperor, who counted them among his <b>proudest achievements and in 1792</b> styled himself the \"Old Man of the Ten Perfect Victories.\" The most far-reaching were the campaigns of 1755–1757 that shattered the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dzungar_Khanate\">Dzungar Khanate</span> of the western Mongols and were followed by a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dzungar_genocide\">systematic extermination</span> in which warfare, massacre, famine, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Smallpox\">smallpox</span> annihilated perhaps four-fifths of the Dzungar people. Pressing on, his generals subdued <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dzungaria\">Dzungaria</span> and then <b>crushed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Revolt_of_the_Altishahr_Khojas\">revolt of the Altishahr Khojas</span> in 1758–1759</b>, conquering the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Uyghurs\">Uyghur</span> oasis cities of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tarim_Basin\">Tarim Basin</span> and welding the whole vast territory into the dominion that Qianlong named Xinjiang, the \"New Frontier.\" Disproportionately ruinous were the two <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jinchuan_campaigns\">Jinchuan campaigns</span>, <b>begun as early as 1747</b> and renewed in 1771–1776 against tiny <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_people\">Tibetan</span> hill chieftaincies in the mountains of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan\">Sichuan</span>, the second of which devoured tens of millions of silver <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tael\">taels</span> for a sliver of rugged territory. Closer to home, another of the ten put down the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lin_Shuangwen_rebellion\">Lin Shuangwen rebellion</span></b> of 1787–1788, an uprising of the secret <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tiandihui\">Tiandihui</span> brotherhood on the island of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span>.<br> <br>The remaining campaigns reached well beyond the empire's borders and proved far less glorious, for the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-Burmese_War_(1765–1769)\">four invasions of Burma</span></b> between 1765 and 1769 failed to subdue the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Konbaung_dynasty\">Konbaung dynasty</span> and cost the Qing dearly in lives and treasure, yielding only a face-saving <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tributary_system_of_China\">tributary</span> gesture from the kings of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Myanmar\">Burma</span>. In 1788–1789 a Qing army marched into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_invasion_of_Đại_Việt\">Vietnam</span> to restore the deposed <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Later_Lê_dynasty\">Lê dynasty</span></b>, only to be routed during the lunar new year by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tây_Sơn_dynasty\">Tây Sơn</span> ruler <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nguyễn_Huệ\">Nguyễn Huệ</span>, whose victory was likewise glossed over once he tendered nominal submission. Only the final intervention ended in clear success, when the general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fuk'anggan\">Fuk'anggan</span> answered a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gurkha\">Gurkha</span> invasion of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibet\">Tibet</span> in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-Nepalese_War\">Sino-Nepalese War</span> of 1788–1792, driving the armies of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kingdom_of_Nepal\">Kingdom of Nepal</span></b> back almost to Kathmandu and reducing it to tributary status. These wars were borne by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_people\">Manchu</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight_Banners\">Eight Banners</span> alongside the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Green_Standard_Army\">Green Standard Army</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Chinese\">Han Chinese</span> troops, and although they roughly doubled the empire and brought it to its greatest extent, their combined cost—well over 100 million taels of silver—steadily drained a treasury that several of the supposed triumphs had done little to enrich. For all the grandeur Qianlong attached to his \"ten perfect victories,\" the staggering fiscal toll of these wars, compounded by the rampant corruption of his favourite <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heshen\">Heshen</span>, helped to sap the dynasty's strength on the very eve of the upheavals of the 19th century.","citation":"","answerText":"Ten Great Campaigns"},{"id":"cnc-092","num":"九十二","category":"China · Culture","question":"Practised the world over as a slow, flowing sequence of postures for health and meditation, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> aims to cultivate and balance <i>qi</i> through relaxed, continuous movement.","answer":"Tai chi","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">太极拳 (tàijíquán, 'supreme-ultimate boxing')</span></div>","traditional":"太極拳","hanzi":"太极拳","pinyin":"tàijíquán","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">tàijíquán</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“supreme-ultimate boxing”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Tai chi</b> is the \"internal\" <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_martial_arts\">Chinese martial art</span></b>, grounded in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Taoist</span> philosophy, that cultivates and balances <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qi\">qi</span> through slow, relaxed, continuous sequences of postures, practised today by an estimated 250 million people as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Meditation\">meditation</span> in motion. Its name invokes the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiji_(philosophy)\">taiji</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"I_Ching\"><i>I Ching</i></span> tradition</b>, the polarity of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yin_and_yang\">yin and yang</span>, and its classics teach yielding over force, promising that \"4 ounces deflects 1,000 pounds,\" principles it shares with the other <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Neijia\">neijia</span> internal arts. Legend ascribes the art to the immortal <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Sanfeng\">Zhang Sanfeng</span></b> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wudang_Mountains\">Wudang Mountains</span>, inspired by a snake's evasion of a crane, but historians trace it to the garrison village of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chenjiagou\">Chenjiagou</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Henan\">Henan</span>, where <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Wangting\">Chen Wangting</span></b> codified spiraling \"silk-reeling\" boxing in the 17th century. The art left the clan when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yang_Luchan\">Yang Luchan</span>, nicknamed \"the Invincible,\" carried it to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> in the 1850s, founding the gentler Yang style from which the Wu, Wu (Hao), and Sun schools branched into today's 5 major lineages. Practice spans solo routines from the <b>state-designed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"24-form_tai_chi_chuan\">24-form</span> of 1956</b> to the traditional 108-posture Yang set, the sensitivity drill of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pushing_hands\">pushing hands</span>, and weapons, most gracefully the double-edged <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jian\">jian</span>. <br> <br> Modern medicine has examined the slow art with unusual rigor, randomized trials showing it cuts <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Falls_in_older_adults\">falls in older adults</span> by roughly 20 to 40 percent, improves balance in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Parkinson's_disease\">Parkinson's disease</span>, <b>as a landmark 2012 trial</b> reported, and matched or beat aerobic exercise for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fibromyalgia\">fibromyalgia</span> in a 2018 study, findings that have put it into fall-prevention programs endorsed by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Centers_for_Disease_Control_and_Prevention\">Centers for Disease Control and Prevention</span>. Mass diffusion owed much to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yang_Chengfu\">Yang Chengfu</span>, whose large-frame teaching in the 1920s and 1930s opened the art to the public, to the People's Republic's promotion of simplified forms as national exercise, and to emigré masters like <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cheng_Man-ch'ing\">Cheng Man-ch'ing</span>, whose 37-posture short form seeded the Western boom from 1960s New York. Its softer cousin practices blur into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qigong\">qigong</span>, while the athletic wing competes in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wushu_(sport)\">wushu</span> taolu events of leaping, theatrical taijiquan. Prestige <b>peaked in December 2020</b>, when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"UNESCO\">UNESCO</span> inscribed taijiquan as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Intangible_cultural_heritage\">intangible cultural heritage</span>, even as combat credibility took blows at home, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mixed_martial_arts\">mixed-martial-arts</span> fighter <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xu_Xiaodong\">Xu Xiaodong</span> flattening a self-styled master in about 10 seconds in a viral 2017 bout that forced debate over fantasy and function. The art's deepest victory needs no referee, visible at first light in any park on earth, where rows of practitioners breathe through the same unhurried river of movement.","citation":"","answerText":"Tai chi"},{"id":"cnc-093","num":"九十三","category":"China · Culture","question":"Renowned for bold, fiery and numbing flavours produced by liberal use of chilli and the tingling Sichuan pepper, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> gave the world dishes such as mapo tofu and kung pao chicken.","answer":"Sichuan cuisine","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">川菜 (Chuāncài, 'Sichuan dishes')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"川菜","pinyin":"Chuāncài","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Chuāncài</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Sichuan dishes”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Sichuan cuisine</b> is one of the great regional traditions of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_cuisine\">Chinese cuisine</span></b>, rooted in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan\">Sichuan</span> province and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chongqing\">Chongqing</span> and renowned for the bold, fiery, and numbing sensation of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mala_(seasoning)\">mala</span>, built on liberal <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chili_pepper\">chili</span></b> and the tingling <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan_pepper\">Sichuan pepper</span>. The humid <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan_Basin\">Sichuan Basin</span> is popularly said to demand sweat-inducing spice, yet the signature heat is young, for chilies reached China only through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Columbian_exchange\">Columbian exchange</span> and are documented in Sichuan kitchens under the early <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span>, where they married the native pepper whose <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hydroxy_alpha_sanshool\">sanshool</span> molecules buzz the lips—a vibration that volunteers in a <b>2013 study</b> matched to about 50 hertz—against the burn of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capsaicin\">capsaicin</span>. Cooks boast that with 1 dish comes 1 style and with 100 dishes 100 flavors, codifying some 23 compound profiles such as the chili-garlic \"fish-fragrant\" <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuxiang\">yuxiang</span> and the sesame-laced \"strange flavor,\" all anchored by the fermented broad-bean chili paste <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Doubanjiang\">doubanjiang</span> of Pixian, now a protected <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Geographical_indication\">geographical indication</span>. The classics carry stories: <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mapo_tofu\">mapo tofu</span>, the pockmarked grandmother's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tofu\">tofu</span>, traces to <b>a Chengdu eatery of 1862</b>, while <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kung_Pao_chicken\">kung pao chicken</span> with its scorched chilies and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peanut\">peanuts</span> honors <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ding_Baozhen\">Ding Baozhen</span>, the province's reforming governor of the 1870s and 1880s, by his palace title. Beyond these stand street and table icons—<b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dandan_noodles\">dan dan noodles</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Twice-cooked_pork\">twice-cooked pork</span>, bubbling Chongqing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hot_pot\">hot pot</span>—though banquet cooking prizes restraint too, from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhangcha_duck\">tea-smoked duck</span> to a deceptively plain \"boiled cabbage\" in crystal consommé served at state dinners. <br> <br> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chengdu\">Chengdu</span> was named a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"UNESCO\">UNESCO</span> <b>City of Gastronomy in 2010</b>, the first in Asia, formal recognition of a food culture whose teahouses and \"fly restaurants\" are a way of life. History stirred the pot as well, for the wartime removal of the national capital to Chongqing during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Sino-Japanese_War\">Second Sino-Japanese War</span> of 1937–1945 mixed refugee palates into the local fire, and post-1980s migration carried mala to every Chinese city, Chongqing alone now claiming on the order of 30,000 hot-pot establishments. Abroad, \"Szechuan\" entered the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States\">American</span> vocabulary in the 1970s even while the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Food_and_Drug_Administration\">Food and Drug Administration</span></b>, fearing citrus canker, banned genuine Sichuan peppercorns from 1968 until 2005, so a generation tasted the cuisine without its tingle. Authenticity found champions such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fuchsia_Dunlop\">Fuchsia Dunlop</span>, trained at Chengdu's cooking institute, whose books from 2001 taught Western kitchens the grammar of flavors, while the hot-pot chain <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Haidilao\">Haidilao</span> grew past 1,300 restaurants worldwide. Repeated surveys now rank this once-provincial style the most popular cuisine in China itself, proof that a marriage of New World fire and ancient native spice could conquer first a basin, then a nation, then the world's tongue.","citation":"","answerText":"Sichuan cuisine"},{"id":"cnc-095","num":"九十五","category":"China · Culture","question":"Tracing the doomed romance of Jia Baoyu and the decline of an aristocratic clan in exquisite detail, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is widely regarded as the greatest work of Chinese fiction and spawned its own field of scholarship, Redology.","answer":"Dream of the Red Chamber","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">18th c.</span></div>","traditional":"紅樓夢","hanzi":"红楼梦","pinyin":"Hónglóumèng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Hónglóumèng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b><i>Dream of the Red Chamber</i></b> is an 18th-century novel of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span>, widely regarded as the supreme achievement of fiction in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Written_vernacular_Chinese\">vernacular Chinese</span>. Its author <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cao_Xueqin\">Cao Xueqin</span> wrote it in poverty in the decades <b>before his death in 1763</b>, distilling his own family's fate, for the Caos had grown rich as imperial textile commissioners at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span> under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kangxi_Emperor\">Kangxi Emperor</span> only to be ruined by confiscation <b>under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yongzheng_Emperor\">Yongzheng Emperor</span> in 1727</b>. A mythic frame opens the tale, in which a sentient stone left over from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nüwa\">Nüwa</span>'s mending of the sky is carried into the mortal world by a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Buddhism\">Buddhist</span> monk and a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Taoist</span>, to be born as the heir <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jia_Baoyu\">Jia Baoyu</span> with a piece of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jade\">jade</span> in his mouth and a temperamental loathing for the careerism of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examinations</span>. At the story's heart lies his doomed love for his frail, brilliant cousin <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lin_Daiyu\">Lin Daiyu</span>, set against the poised <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xue_Baochai\">Xue Baochai</span>, whom he is tricked into marrying as Daiyu dies, a betrayal that finally drives him to renounce the world as a monk. Around the triangle Cao unfolds the slow decline of the aristocratic Jia clan in exquisite detail, from the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Daguanyuan\">Grand View Garden</span></b> built for the visit of the imperial consort <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jia_Yuanchun\">Jia Yuanchun</span> to the schemes of the manager <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Xifeng\">Wang Xifeng</span> and the comic visits of rustic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Granny_Liu\">Granny Liu</span>, peopling 120 chapters with several hundred characters in a supple <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing_dialect\">Beijing-dialect</span> prose studded with poems. <br> <br> The novel first circulated in hand-copied versions of 80 chapters bearing the intimate commentaries of the mysterious <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhiyanzhai\">Zhiyanzhai</span>, or Red Inkstone, until a <b>printed edition of 1791–92</b> added 40 concluding chapters edited or composed by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gao_E\">Gao E</span>, whose authenticity scholars dispute to this day. So vast is the interpretive literature that it constitutes a discipline of its own, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Redology\">Redology</span>, transformed in 1921 when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Shih\">Hu Shih</span> established the autobiographical reading, convulsed in 1954 by a political campaign against the critic <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yu_Pingbo\">Yu Pingbo</span></b>, and graced by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>'s boast of having read the book 5 times. First among the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Classic_Chinese_Novels\">Classic Chinese Novels</span>, it is treasured as a virtual encyclopedia of its civilisation, recording cuisine, medicine, gardens, dress, and ritual with anthropological fineness. English readers know it above all through the 5-volume <i>The Story of the Stone</i> translated by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"David_Hawkes_(sinologist)\">David Hawkes</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"John_Minford\">John Minford</span></b> for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Penguin_Classics\">Penguin Classics</span> between 1973 and 1986, alongside the complete version by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yang_Xianyi\">Yang Xianyi</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gladys_Yang\">Gladys Yang</span>. Its afterlife flourishes in a <b>beloved <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dream_of_the_Red_Chamber_(1987_TV_series)\">1987 television adaptation</span></b>, in the repertoire of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yue_opera\">Yue opera</span>, and in replica Grand View Gardens built for pilgrims of the book, securing its place as the novel by which <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> measures all others.","citation":"","answerText":"Dream of the Red Chamber"},{"id":"cnc-097","num":"九十七","category":"China · Culture","question":"Emerging in the capital in the late 18th century by blending several regional styles, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is famed for its painted-face role types, falsetto singing and dazzling acrobatic combat, and was reshaped during the Cultural Revolution into model works.","answer":"Peking opera","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">19th c.</span></div>","traditional":"京劇","hanzi":"京剧","pinyin":"Jīngjù","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Jīngjù</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“capital drama”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Peking opera</b> is the most celebrated form of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_opera\">Chinese opera</span></b>, a synthesis of regional styles that took shape in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> in the late 18th century under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span>. Its conventional birth date is 1790, when the Four Great Troupes of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anhui\">Anhui</span> arrived in the capital for the 80th birthday of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qianlong_Emperor\">Qianlong Emperor</span>, and over the following half-century their tunes fused with melodies brought by players from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hubei\">Hubei</span>, with refinements borrowed from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kunqu\">Kunqu</span> and the clapper style of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qinqiang\">Qinqiang</span>, maturing by about 1845. Performers fall into 4 great role types, the male <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sheng_(Chinese_opera)\">sheng</span>, the female <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dan_(Chinese_opera)\">dan</span>, the painted-face <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jing_(Chinese_opera)\">jing</span></b>, and the comic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chou_(Chinese_opera)\">chou</span>, the jing's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lianpu\">lianpu</span> make-up speaking a colour code in which red proclaims the loyalty of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guan_Yu\">Guan Yu</span>, white the treachery of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cao_Cao\">Cao Cao</span>, and black the blunt integrity of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Fei\">Zhang Fei</span>. Training unites the 4 skills of song, declamation, dance-acting, and combat, <b>joining a stylised <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Falsetto\">falsetto</span></b>, above all in the dan roles, to dazzling <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Acrobatics\">acrobatic</span> battle, while on a nearly bare stage a flourished whip signifies a galloping horse and a circuit of the boards a journey of a thousand miles. The drama rides on a small ensemble led by the piercing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jinghu_(instrument)\">jinghu</span> fiddle with the plucked <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yueqin\">yueqin</span>, as drums, clappers, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gong\">gongs</span> cue every entrance, glance, and blow. <br> <br> Adored at court by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empress_Dowager_Cixi\">Empress Dowager Cixi</span>, the form built a repertoire of some 1,400 works drawn from history, legend, and the classic novels. Its stars became national idols, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tan_Xinpei\">Tan Xinpei</span> appearing in the first Chinese film, the <b>1905 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dingjun_Mountain_(film)\"><i>Dingjun Mountain</i></span></b>, while the supreme dan <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mei_Lanfang\">Mei Lanfang</span> carried the art to the United States in 1930 and the Soviet Union in 1935, leaving a deep mark on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Konstantin_Stanislavski\">Stanislavski</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bertolt_Brecht\">Brecht</span>. During the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span> the traditional repertoire was banned outright, and <b>from 1966</b> the stage belonged to the revolutionary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Model_opera\">model operas</span> championed by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Qing\">Jiang Qing</span>, 8 sanctioned works such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Legend_of_the_Red_Lantern\"><i>The Legend of the Red Lantern</i></span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taking_Tiger_Mountain_by_Strategy\"><i>Taking Tiger Mountain by Strategy</i></span> replacing emperors and fox-spirits with soldiers and railway workers for a decade. The old plays <b>returned after 1976</b>, state companies and academies rebuilt the tradition on both sides of the strait, including in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span>, and in 2010 the art entered the UNESCO list of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Intangible_cultural_heritage\">intangible cultural heritage</span>. Its backstage world reached global audiences through <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Kaige\">Chen Kaige</span></b>'s film <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Farewell_My_Concubine_(film)\"><i>Farewell My Concubine</i></span>, winner of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Palme_d'Or\">Palme d'Or</span> in 1993, and though its audience greys, the painted faces remain the theatrical signature of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Peking opera"},{"id":"cnc-098","num":"九十八","category":"China · Culture","question":"Played by 4 people drawing and discarding engraved tiles to assemble winning hands amid much clattering, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is a fixture of family gatherings and gambling dens alike.","answer":"Mahjong","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">麻将 (májiàng); the name is often linked to 麻雀 ('sparrow')</span></div>","traditional":"麻將","hanzi":"麻将","pinyin":"májiàng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">májiàng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Mahjong</b> is the immensely popular <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tile-based_game\">tile-based game</span></b> in which 4 players draw and discard to assemble winning hands, a contest of skill, strategy, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luck\">luck</span> equally at home at family reunions and in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gambling\">gambling</span> dens. A standard set holds 144 tiles, once <b>carved from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bone\">bone</span></b> backed with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bamboo\">bamboo</span> and now molded plastic or collectible <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bakelite\">Bakelite</span>: 108 suit tiles of dots, bamboos, and characters numbered 1 to 9, plus winds, dragons, and 8 flowers and seasons. Play whirls through \"washing\" the tiles, building walls, and racing to complete 4 sets and a pair, the clatter so constant that the sparrows of the nickname seem to be quarreling on the table. The game is younger than its legends, for the tale that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucius\">Confucius</span> invented it is fantasy, and historians instead derive it <b>from money-suited <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Playing_card\">card</span></b> games like <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Madiao\">madiao</span> crossed with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dominoes\">domino</span>-style tiles, crystallizing around the 1850s in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ningbo\">Ningbo</span>–<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span> region in the turbulent years of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiping_Rebellion\">Taiping Rebellion</span>. It conquered late-<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> society from teahouse to mansion, was banned as gambling after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Republic_of_China\">People's Republic</span> <b>arrived in 1949</b>, and returned in force in the 1980s, until an official \"Guobiao\" competition rulebook of 1998 recast the pastime as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mind_sport\">mind sport</span> claimed by hundreds of millions of players. <br> <br> The game's strangest journey was westward, after <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joseph_Park_Babcock\">Joseph Park Babcock</span> of Standard Oil simplified the rules and shipped sets to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States\">United States</span> <b>from 1920</b>, igniting a craze that moved over 1.5 million sets by 1923 and put bone tiles in flapper-era parlors. The American line matured into a tradition of its own, organized since 1937 by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Mah_Jongg_League\">National Mah Jongg League</span> with its 152-tile sets, jokers, and an annually changing card of hands, cherished especially among <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"American_Jews\">Jewish American</span></b> women. <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japan\">Japan</span> forged the cerebral riichi school of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japanese_mahjong\">Japanese mahjong</span>, sustaining thousands of parlors and millions of devotees, while the lightning 13-tile game rules <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span> and the diaspora. The table has become a literary and cinematic stage, structuring <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Amy_Tan\">Amy Tan</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Joy_Luck_Club\"><i>The Joy Luck Club</i></span> and supplying the duel that crowns the <b>2018 film</b> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Crazy_Rich_Asians_(film)\"><i>Crazy Rich Asians</i></span>. Science has even pulled up a chair, with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Randomized_controlled_trial\">randomized trials</span> among nursing-home elders reporting modest gains in memory and executive function and observational studies linking regular play to slower cognitive decline and lower <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dementia\">dementia</span> risk, a respectable excuse, as automatic shuffling tables hum and the sparrows clatter on, for one more round.","citation":"","answerText":"Mahjong"},{"id":"cnc-099","num":"九十九","category":"China · Culture","question":"A Cantonese tradition of eating an array of small steamed and fried dishes — dumplings, buns and rolls — from bamboo baskets, typically served with tea in a custom known as <i>yum cha</i>, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is especially popular for late-morning meals.","answer":"Dim sum","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">点心 (diǎnxīn, 'touch the heart'); 'dim sum' is the Cantonese reading</span></div>","traditional":"點心","hanzi":"点心","pinyin":"diǎnxīn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">diǎnxīn</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“touch the heart”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Dim sum</b> is the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cantonese_cuisine\">Cantonese</span></b> tradition of eating an array of small steamed and fried dishes—<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dumpling\">dumplings</span>, buns, and rolls served in stacked <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bamboo\">bamboo</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Food_steamer\">steamer</span> baskets—taken with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tea\">tea</span> in the <b>custom of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yum_cha\">yum cha</span></b>, \"drinking tea,\" beloved above all as a late-morning <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Brunch\">meal</span>. The word anciently meant any snack, but the modern institution grew in the 19th-century <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Teahouse\">teahouses</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou\">Guangzhou</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pearl_River_Delta\">Pearl River Delta</span>, where porters and merchants rested over \"1 cup and 2 pieces.\" Its canon runs from translucent shrimp <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Har_gow\">har gow</span>, whose wrapper a proud chef pleats at least 7 and often 10 or more times, and open-topped <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shumai\">siu mai</span>, to fluffy barbecue-pork <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cha_siu_bao\">char siu bao</span></b>, silky <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rice_noodle_roll\">rice noodle rolls</span>, braised <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chicken_feet\">chicken feet</span> styled \"phoenix claws,\" lotus-leaf parcels of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lo_mai_gai\">lo mai gai</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Egg_tart\">egg tart</span>, cousin of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pastel_de_nata\">pastel de nata</span></b> by way of colonial bakeries. Ritual surrounds the pot as much as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Steaming\">steamingfinger kowtow</span> of thanks, a courtesy legend traces to companions of the incognito <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qianlong_Emperor\">Qianlong Emperor</span>, and an opened lid silently requests more <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pu'er_tea\">pu-erh</span> or <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chrysanthemum_tea\">chrysanthemum tea</span></b>. For Cantonese families the weekend yum cha is a standing multigenerational appointment, the trolley ladies of old calling their wares as carts of bamboo towers steamed past. <br> <br> Twentieth-century <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span> polished the craft into a high art and exported it with every wave of emigration, making dim sum the Sunday heartbeat of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinatown\">Chinatowns</span> from San Francisco to Sydney. Recognition followed appetite, <b>for in 2009</b> the city's Cantonese flagship <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lung_King_Heen\">Lung King Heen</span> became the first Chinese restaurant awarded 3 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Michelin_Guide\">Michelin</span> stars, while the humble dim sum shop <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tim_Ho_Wan\">Tim Ho Wan</span> won a star <b>of its own in 2010</b> and was hailed as the cheapest Michelin-starred restaurant on earth before multiplying across Asia. The old style endures precariously at survivors like the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lin_Heung_Tea_House\">Lin Heung Tea House</span>, pouring tea since 1928 amid clattering carts, even as order sheets, central kitchens, and supermarket freezers carry the dumplings into modern life. Abroad the word has stretched generously, so that Jiangnan's soup-filled <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiaolongbao\">xiaolongbao</span> now shares the menu, alongside vegan and halal reinventions from London to Jakarta. However it travels, the form keeps its founding promise, an unhurried morning of small dishes and refilled cups meant, as the name says, to touch the heart.","citation":"","answerText":"Dim sum"},{"id":"cnc-100","num":"一百","category":"China · Culture","question":"A small packet of bright red paper, the colour of luck, used to present a gift of money, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is observed at New Year, weddings and birthdays, and has migrated into digital form on messaging apps.","answer":"red envelope","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">红包 (hóngbāo, 'red packet')</span></div>","traditional":"紅包","hanzi":"红包","pinyin":"hóngbāo","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">hóngbāo</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>red envelope</b> is a small packet of bright red paper used to present a <b>gift of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Money\">money</span></b> at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_New_Year\">Chinese New Year</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wedding\">weddings</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Birthday\">birthdays</span>, and other joyful occasions, red being the supreme color of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luck\">luck</span> in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Color_in_Chinese_culture\">Chinese color scheme</span></b>. New Year money is properly <i>yasuiqian</i>, \"age-suppressing money,\" from the tale of a demon called Sui who stroked sleeping children until coins wrapped in red by the bed flashed and drove it off, a charm with real ancestors in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yansheng_coin\">yansheng amulet coins</span></b> strung on red thread since the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span>. Etiquette is governed by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Numbers_in_Chinese_culture\">number lore</span>: crisp new <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Renminbi\">renminbi</span> notes in even, auspicious sums rich in 8s, such as 88 or 888, never amounts containing the deathly 4 shunned under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tetraphobia\">tetraphobia</span>, given and received with both hands and not opened before the giver. The married give to children and the unmarried at New Year, wedding guests present envelopes scaled to cover their seat at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_marriage\">marriage</span> banquet and duly recorded in the family ledger, while odd sums in white envelopes belong to the inverse world of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Funeral\">funeral</span>. The custom rings the region, as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span> lai see, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vietnam\">Vietnam</span>'s <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lì_xì\">lì xì</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japan\">Japan</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Otoshidama\">otoshidama</span>, and the green packets that Muslims in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Malaysia\">Malaysia</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Singapore\">Singapore</span> give at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eid_al-Fitr\">Eid</span>. <br> <br> The packet then leapt onto the smartphone, when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tencent\">Tencent</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"WeChat\">WeChat</span> launched digital red packets for <b>the New Year of 2014</b>, a flanking strike on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Alipay\">Alipay</span> so effective that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jack_Ma\">Jack Ma</span> called it \"a Pearl Harbor attack\" on his company. A shake-your-phone partnership <b>with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"CCTV_New_Year's_Gala\">CCTV New Year's Gala</span> in 2015</b> detonated the habit, and Chinese users exchanged more than 8 billion digital packets over the 2016 holiday and a staggering 14 billion on New Year's Eve of 2017 alone. The genius lay in gamification, group packets splitting a sum into random \"lucky\" shares that friends race to grab, which strapped hundreds of millions of bank cards to chat apps and, with the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"QR_code\">QR code</span></b>, helped vault China into a near-cashless world of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mobile_payment\">mobile payment</span>. The same red wrapper has a shadow side, for envelopes pressed on doctors, teachers, or officials shade into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bribery\">bribery</span>, drawing strict caps and bans in anti-corruption rules. Even so, elders still prize the paper original, a blessing one can hold, so the custom now glows in 2 forms at once, crimson paper across the dinner table and crimson pixels across a billion screens.","citation":"","answerText":"red envelope"},{"id":"cng-002","num":"二","category":"China · Geography","question":"Often called the \"Roof of the World\" and the source of many of Asia's great rivers, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> dominates the country's southwest, walled off to the south by the Himalayas and forming most of Tibet and Qinghai.","answer":"Tibetan Plateau","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">青藏高原 ('Qinghai–Tibet plateau')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"青藏高原","pinyin":"Qīngzàng Gāoyuán","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Qīngzàng Gāoyuán</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Qinghai–Tibet Plateau”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Tibetan Plateau</b> is the highest and most extensive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Plateau\">plateau</span> on Earth, an immense upland in the southwest of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> long celebrated as the \"<b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Roof_of_the_World\">Roof of the World</span></b>.\" Covering roughly 2.5 million square kilometres (970,000 sq mi) and averaging around 4,500 metres (15,000 ft) in elevation — well in excess of the 4,000 metres (13,000 ft) of common reckoning — it stretches some 2,500 kilometres (1,600 mi) from west to east. It is rimmed by some of the planet's mightiest mountain ranges, walled off to the south by the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Himalayas\">Himalayas</span></b>, flanked to the west by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Karakoram\">Karakoram</span>, and bounded to the north by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kunlun_Mountains\">Kunlun</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qilian_Mountains\">Qilian</span> mountains and to the east by the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hengduan_Mountains\">Hengduan Range</span></b>. Holding the largest store of ice outside the polar regions, it is often dubbed the \"<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Third_Pole\">Third Pole</span>,\" and the thousands of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Glacier\">glaciers</span> locked across its ranges have been <b>retreating rapidly under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Climate_change\">climate change</span></b> as its frozen <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Permafrost\">permafrost</span> soils thaw. The plateau is the great water tower of Asia, giving rise to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_River\">Yellow River</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mekong\">Mekong</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Brahmaputra_River\">Brahmaputra</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Salween_River\">Salween</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Indus_River\">Indus</span>, rivers on which more than a billion people downstream depend. <br> <br> The plateau owes its existence to the slow-motion collision of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Indian_Plate\">Indian</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eurasian_Plate\">Eurasian</span> tectonic plates, a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Continental_collision\">continental collision</span></b> that began some 50 million years ago and continues to thrust the land upward today. Its sheer bulk and altitude profoundly shape the climate of the region, helping to drive the seasonal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Monsoon\">monsoon</span> that waters much of southern and eastern Asia. Politically the highland forms the bulk of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibet_Autonomous_Region\">Tibet Autonomous Region</span> and the province of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qinghai\">Qinghai</span></b>, spilling over as well into western <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan\">Sichuan</span> and neighbouring provinces and into territory disputed with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"India\">India</span>. Centred on the city of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lhasa\">Lhasa</span>, historic seat of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dalai_Lama\">Dalai Lama</span>, it is the homeland of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_people\">Tibetan people</span>, many of whom still practise the high-altitude <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pastoralism\">pastoralism</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Domestic_yak\">yak</span> herding across its grasslands. Sparsely peopled and ecologically distinctive, the plateau shelters wildlife such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_antelope\">Tibetan antelope</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Snow_leopard\">snow leopard</span> and cradles vast saline lakes including <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qinghai_Lake\">Qinghai Lake</span></b>, even as questions of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibet\">Tibetan</span> autonomy and Chinese rule keep this remote expanse at the centre of enduring political dispute.","citation":"","answerText":"Tibetan Plateau"},{"id":"cng-003","num":"三","category":"China · Geography","question":"Straddling the border between China and Nepal and known in Chinese as Qomolangma, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the highest mountain on Earth at about 8,849 m (29,030 ft) above sea level.","answer":"Mount Everest","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Tibetan Chomolungma ('holy mother peak'); English after surveyor George Everest</span></div>","traditional":"珠穆朗瑪峰","hanzi":"珠穆朗玛峰","pinyin":"Zhūmùlǎngmǎ Fēng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhūmùlǎngmǎ Fēng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Mount Everest</b> is the highest mountain on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Earth\">Earth</span> as measured above sea level, a peak of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Himalayas\">Himalayas</span> that rises to 8,848.86 metres (29,032 ft)</b> on the frontier between <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nepal\">Nepal</span></b>. Known to Tibetans as Chomolungma, rendered in Chinese as Qomolangma, and to Nepalis as Sagarmatha, it acquired its English name only in 1865, when it was christened in honour of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"George_Everest\">Sir George Everest</span>, a former <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Surveyor_General_of_India\">Surveyor General of India</span>. It had earlier been catalogued merely as \"Peak XV\" by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Trigonometrical_Survey\">Great Trigonometrical Survey</span> of India, whose computations — credited to the mathematician <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Radhanath_Sikdar\">Radhanath Sikdar</span> — first <b>identified it in 1852</b> as the world's loftiest summit, a finding later formalised by the surveyor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Andrew_Scott_Waugh\">Andrew Waugh</span>. The mountain stands in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mahalangur_Himal\">Mahalangur Himal</span> sub-range, its summit bisected by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China–Nepal_border\">China–Nepal border</span> between the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibet_Autonomous_Region\">Tibet Autonomous Region</span> to the north and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Solukhumbu_District\">Solukhumbu</span> district of Nepal to the south. Its uppermost rocks are marine <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Limestone\">limestone</span> laid down on an ancient seabed and bearing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fossil\">fossils</span>, thrust skyward by the collision of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Indian_Plate\">Indian</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eurasian_Plate\">Eurasian</span> plates that still nudges the peak slowly upward and to the northeast. <br> <br> The summit was first <b>reached on 29 May 1953</b> by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Edmund_Hillary\">Edmund Hillary</span> of New Zealand and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sherpa_people\">Sherpa</span> mountaineer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tenzing_Norgay\">Tenzing Norgay</span>, members of a British expedition led by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"John_Hunt,_Baron_Hunt\">John Hunt</span> that ascended from the Nepalese side. Climbers today follow chiefly two routes, the southeast ridge over the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South_Col\">South Col</span> from Nepal and the north ridge over the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"North_Col\">North Col</span> from Tibet, both of which thread the so-called <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Death_zone\">death zone</span> above 8,000 metres (26,000 ft) where the air can no longer sustain human life. Most expeditions rely on bottled oxygen, a dependence broken in 1978 when <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Reinhold_Messner\">Reinhold Messner</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peter_Habeler\">Peter Habeler</span> made the first ascent without supplementary supplies, a feat once thought physiologically impossible. <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mountaineering\">Commercial mountaineering</span> has since transformed the peak, where more than 6,000 people have now stood on the top while over 300 have perished, among them the 8 climbers lost in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1996_Mount_Everest_disaster\">storm disaster</span> of 1996</b> and the many killed by avalanches in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2015_Nepal_earthquake\">Nepal earthquake</span> of 2015. The climbing economy depends heavily on Sherpa guides and porters who shoulder the gravest risks on the treacherous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khumbu_Icefall\">Khumbu Icefall</span> and high camps, and the surge of visitors has left the slopes above <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Everest_Base_Camp\">Base Camp</span> — much of it <b>within Nepal's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sagarmatha_National_Park\">Sagarmatha National Park</span></b> — strewn with refuse, prompting periodic clean-up campaigns on the world's most coveted summit.","citation":"","answerText":"Mount Everest"},{"id":"cng-004","num":"四","category":"China · Geography","question":"Formed by the slow collision of the Indian and Eurasian plates, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> marks the southern rim of the Tibetan Plateau and contains the planet's highest peaks.","answer":"Himalayas","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Sanskrit himālaya ('abode of snow')</span></div>","traditional":"喜馬拉雅山脈","hanzi":"喜马拉雅山脉","pinyin":"Xǐmǎlāyǎ Shānmài","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Xǐmǎlāyǎ Shānmài</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“abode of snow”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Himalayas</b> are the highest mountain system on Earth, forming a roughly 2,400-kilometer (1,500 mi) arc across <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Asia\">Asia</span> that separates the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Indian_subcontinent\">Indian subcontinent</span></b> from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_Plateau\">Tibetan Plateau</span>. They were thrust upward by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Continental_collision\">continental collision</span> of the northward-moving <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Indian_Plate\">Indian Plate</span> with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eurasian_Plate\">Eurasian Plate</span>, a <b>process of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Plate_tectonics\">plate tectonics</span></b> that began roughly 40 to 50 million years ago, when the two landmasses converged and progressively closed the ancient <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tethys_Ocean\">Tethys Ocean</span> that had once divided them. Because both plates carried buoyant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Continental_crust\">continental crust</span>, neither could fully subduct, so the compression instead crumpled and stacked the rock skyward in the orogenic episode known as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Himalayan_orogeny\">Himalayan orogeny</span>, part of the wider <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Alpine_orogeny\">Alpine orogeny</span></b> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cenozoic\">Cenozoic</span> era. The collision has shortened the Indian crust by an estimated 500 kilometers (310 mi), and the convergence continues today, with the Indian Plate advancing northward at about 5 centimeters (2 in) per year and forcing the range higher by roughly 5 millimeters (0.2 in) annually, and locally by as much as 7 to 10 millimeters (0.28 to 0.39 in) a year. Evidence of this slow uplift is preserved in beds of marine limestone and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ammonoidea\">ammonite</span> fossils found near the summit of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mount_Everest\">Mount Everest</span></b>, rock that once lay on the floor of the Tethys Sea before being lifted more than 8,000 meters (26,000 ft) above sea level. <br> <br> The range is crowned by Mount Everest, which at 8,848.86 meters (29,032 ft) is the highest point on the planet, and it harbors 10 of the world's 14 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight-thousander\">eight-thousanders</span>, including <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kangchenjunga\">Kangchenjunga</span>, the 3rd-highest summit on Earth, while the other 4 rise in the neighboring <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Karakoram\">Karakoram</span> range. Stretching from <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanga_Parbat\">Nanga Parbat</span></b> in the west to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Namcha_Barwa\">Namcha Barwa</span> in the east, the system spans or borders 5 countries—<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pakistan\">Pakistan</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"India\">India</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nepal\">Nepal</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bhutan\">Bhutan</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>—and after <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Annapurna\">Annapurna</span> became the first eight-thousander to be <b>climbed in 1950</b>, the first confirmed ascent of Everest followed in 1953 by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Edmund_Hillary\">Edmund Hillary</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tenzing_Norgay\">Tenzing Norgay</span>. The Himalayan snow and ice feed several of the great river systems of Asia—among them the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Indus_River\">Indus</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ganges\">Ganges</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Brahmaputra_River\">Brahmaputra</span>—whose meltwater and monsoon-fed flow sustains the agriculture and drinking water of well over a billion people across South and East Asia. Because the range and the adjoining plateau hold the largest reserves of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Glacier\">glacial</span> ice outside the polar regions, they are frequently called the \"Third Pole,\" a vast frozen store of tens of thousands of glaciers that has been shrinking rapidly under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Climate_change\">climate change</span>. The ongoing tectonic stress also makes the region one of the most <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Earthquake\">earthquake</span>-prone on Earth, as shown by the <b>devastating <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"April_2015_Nepal_earthquake\">Nepal earthquake</span> of 2015</b>, even as the mountains have for millennia held deep spiritual meaning in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hinduism\">Hinduism</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Buddhism\">Buddhism</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jainism\">Jainism</span>, with peaks such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mount_Kailash\">Mount Kailash</span> revered as the abode of the gods.","citation":"","answerText":"Himalayas"},{"id":"cng-005","num":"五","category":"China · Geography","question":"Rising in western Tibet and carving the world's deepest canyon before bending sharply south to become the Brahmaputra, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> runs eastward across the high plateau.","answer":"Yarlung Tsangpo","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Tibetan ('the river of the Yarlung valley')</span></div>","traditional":"雅魯藏布江","hanzi":"雅鲁藏布江","pinyin":"Yǎlǔ Zàngbù Jiāng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Yǎlǔ Zàngbù Jiāng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Yarlung Tsangpo</b> is the great river of southern <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibet\">Tibet</span></b> and the upper course of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Brahmaputra_River\">Brahmaputra</span>, the highest major river on Earth by mean elevation. It rises from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Glacier\">glaciers</span> in far western Tibet, near the sacred massif of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mount_Kailash\">Mount Kailash</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lake_Manasarovar\">Lake Manasarovar</span></b>, and then flows generally eastward for more than 1,500 kilometres (930 mi) across the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_Plateau\">Tibetan Plateau</span> at elevations mostly above 3,000 metres (9,800 ft). Along its valley lie the town of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shigatse\">Shigatse</span> and, on the tributary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lhasa_River\">Lhasa River</span>, the regional capital <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lhasa\">Lhasa</span>, the fertile basin forming the agricultural heartland of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_people\">Tibetan people</span>. Approaching the towering peak of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Namcha_Barwa\">Namcha Barwa</span></b> and its neighbour <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gyala_Peri\">Gyala Peri</span>, the river swings through a vast horseshoe bend and gouges the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yarlung_Tsangpo_Grand_Canyon\">Yarlung Tsangpo Grand Canyon</span>, the deepest <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Canyon\">canyon</span></b> on the planet, plunging more than 5,000 metres (16,000 ft) and reaching some 6,000 metres (20,000 ft) at its deepest. Beyond the canyon it bends sharply south and descends into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"India\">India</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Arunachal_Pradesh\">Arunachal Pradesh</span> as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Siang_River\">Siang</span>, becoming the Brahmaputra across <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Assam\">Assam</span> before joining the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ganges\">Ganges</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bangladesh\">Bangladesh</span> and emptying into the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bay_of_Bengal\">Bay of Bengal</span></b>. <br> <br> Its middle reaches cradle the birthplace of Tibetan civilisation, the Yarlung Valley from which both the river and the early <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_Empire\">Tibetan monarchy</span> took their name, where tradition places the first king <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nyatri_Tsenpo\">Nyatri Tsenpo</span></b> and the ancient fortress of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yumbulagang\">Yumbulagang</span>. The deep gorge around Namcha Barwa is revered in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_Buddhism\">Tibetan Buddhism</span> as a hidden sacred land, its near-impenetrable rainforest long shielding the region from outside intrusion. In recent decades the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">Chinese</span> state has begun to harness the river's enormous fall for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hydroelectricity\">hydroelectric power</span>, completing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zangmu_Dam\">Zangmu Dam</span> on <b>the main stream in 2015</b> as the first of several planned barrages. In 2024 Beijing approved a far more ambitious scheme near the Great Bend in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mêdog_County\">Mêdog County</span>, a project expected to become the world's largest power plant with a capacity perhaps 3 times that of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Gorges_Dam\">Three Gorges Dam</span>. Because the same waters sustain hundreds of millions of people downstream — feeding the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jamuna_River_(Bangladesh)\">Jamuna</span> and the Ganges delta — China's tightening grip on this transboundary source has stoked persistent anxiety over <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Water_conflict\">water security</span> in India and Bangladesh, making the Yarlung Tsangpo as much a strategic asset as a natural wonder.","citation":"","answerText":"Yarlung Tsangpo"},{"id":"cng-006","num":"六","category":"China · Geography","question":"One of the longest mountain chains in Asia, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> forms the northern edge of the Tibetan Plateau and rises over the southern rim of the Tarim Basin, looming large in Chinese myth.","answer":"Kunlun Mountains","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">昆仑山, a range of ancient Chinese cosmology</span></div>","traditional":"崑崙山","hanzi":"昆仑山","pinyin":"Kūnlún Shān","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Kūnlún Shān</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Kunlun Mountains</b> form one of the longest mountain chains in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Asia\">Asia</span>, stretching roughly 3,000 kilometers (1,900 mi) eastward from the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pamir_Mountains\">Pamir Mountains</span></b> along the northern edge of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_Plateau\">Tibetan Plateau</span> and the southern rim of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tarim_Basin\">Tarim Basin</span>. The range traverses <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinjiang\">Xinjiang</span>, the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibet_Autonomous_Region\">Tibet Autonomous Region</span></b>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qinghai\">Qinghai</span>, rising abruptly above the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taklamakan_Desert\">Taklamakan Desert</span> before grading eastward into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Altyn-Tagh\">Altyn-Tagh</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qilian_Mountains\">Qilian Mountains</span></b>, with crest elevations commonly between 5,500 and 6,000 meters (18,000 and 20,000 ft). Its highest summit, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liushi_Shan\">Liushi Shan</span>, reaches 7,167 meters (23,510 ft), while the remote <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ulugh_Muztagh\">Ulugh Muztagh</span>, once estimated at over 7,700 meters (25,000 ft), was <b>remeasured in 1985</b> at about 6,973 meters (22,880 ft). Geologically the chain incorporates <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paleozoic\">Paleozoic</span> basement rocks uplifted anew by the collision of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Indian_Plate\">Indian Plate</span> with Eurasia, and the 1,600-kilometer (990 mi) strike-slip <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kunlun_fault\">Kunlun fault</span> <b>produced the magnitude 7.8 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2001_Kunlun_earthquake\">2001 Kunlun earthquake</span></b>, whose surface rupture extended some 450 kilometers (280 mi). Glaciers and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Permafrost\">permafrost</span> feed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Karakash_River\">Karakash</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yurungkash_River\">Yurungkash</span> rivers, which have carried <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nephrite\">nephrite</span> jade to the oases of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hotan\">Hotan</span> for over 3,000 years, while the headwaters of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_River\">Yellow River</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span> emerge near the eastern reaches, where the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qinghai–Tibet_railway\">Qinghai–Tibet railway</span> crosses the 4,767-meter (15,640 ft) <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kunlun_Mountain_Pass\">Kunlun Mountain Pass</span></b>. <br> <br> In <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_mythology\">Chinese mythology</span> the range lent its name to the legendary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kunlun_(mythology)\">Mount Kunlun</span>, an <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Axis_mundi\">axis mundi</span> linking heaven and earth and the paradise of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Queen_Mother_of_the_West\">Queen Mother of the West</span>, described in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Classic_of_Mountains_and_Seas\"><i>Classic of Mountains and Seas</i></span>, compiled between the 4th century BCE and the early centuries CE. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"King_Mu_of_Zhou\">King Mu of Zhou</span> (reigned c. <b>976–922 BCE</b>) was said to have journeyed there to meet the goddess, a tale elaborated in the 4th-century BCE narrative <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tale_of_King_Mu,_Son_of_Heaven\"><i>Tale of King Mu, Son of Heaven</i></span>. During the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span>, after the explorations of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Qian\">Zhang Qian</span> in the 2nd century BCE, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Wu_of_Han\">Emperor Wu</span> formally identified the jade-bearing mountains south of Hotan with the mythical Kunlun, fixing the name to its present geography. In <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Taoism</span> the mountain became a celestial realm of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xian_(Taoism)\">immortals</span>, and it endures in popular culture as the home of the Kunlun School in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuxia\">wuxia</span> fiction. The historical range was equally consequential in commerce, since the southern branch of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk_Road\">Silk Road</span> ran along its northern foot, threading oasis towns that for centuries exchanged Chinese silk for the white \"mutton-fat\" jade prized by every dynasty from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shang_dynasty\">Shang</span> onward.","citation":"","answerText":"Kunlun Mountains"},{"id":"cng-007","num":"七","category":"China · Geography","question":"A vast, arid depression of salt flats and oilfields lying high on the northeastern Tibetan Plateau within Qinghai province, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is hemmed in by the Kunlun and Qilian ranges.","answer":"Qaidam Basin","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Mongolian Tsaidam ('salt marsh')</span></div>","traditional":"柴達木盆地","hanzi":"柴达木盆地","pinyin":"Cháidámù Péndì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Cháidámù Péndì</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“salt marsh”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Qaidam Basin</b> is a hyper-arid <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Endorheic_basin\">endorheic</span></b> depression of roughly 120,000 square kilometres (46,000 sq mi) in northwestern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qinghai\">Qinghai</span> province, ranking among the largest intermontane basins of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>. Enclosed by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kunlun_Mountains\">Kunlun Mountains</span> to the south, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qilian_Mountains\">Qilian Mountains</span> to the northeast, and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Altyn-Tagh\">Altun Mountains</span></b> to the northwest, its floor lies at 2,600 to 3,000 metres (8,500 to 9,800 ft) on the northeastern margin of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_Plateau\">Tibetan Plateau</span>, making it the highest large basin in the country. Structurally it is a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cenozoic\">Cenozoic</span> <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foreland_basin\">foreland basin</span></b> whose sedimentary fill, locally exceeding 12,000 metres (39,000 ft) in thickness, records mountain-building driven by the collision of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Indian_plate\">Indian Plate</span> with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eurasian_plate\">Eurasia</span>. Aridity deepened through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Quaternary\">Quaternary</span>, and today annual precipitation averages under 100 millimetres (3.9 in) against potential evaporation above 2,500 millimetres (98 in), leaving about a quarter of the floor <b>mantled in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dry_lake\">playas</span></b> and saline lakes, the greatest being the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qarhan_Playa\">Qarhan</span> salt crust of some 5,800 square kilometres (2,200 sq mi). Relentless northwesterly winds have meanwhile sculpted one of Earth’s most extensive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yardang\">yardang</span> fields across the western basin, terrain so barren that scientists study it as an analogue for the surface of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mars\">Mars</span>. <br> <br> The basin historically carried a southern branch of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk_Road\">Silk Road</span>, and from the 4th to the 7th centuries it formed the heartland of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tuyuhun\">Tuyuhun</span> kingdom, a state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xianbei\">Xianbei</span> origin that fell to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_Empire\">Tibetan Empire</span> around 663. Mongol pastoralists settled the steppe fringes under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> dynasties, and the region is now governed as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Haixi_Mongol_and_Tibetan_Autonomous_Prefecture\">Haixi Mongol and Tibetan Autonomous Prefecture</span></b>, whose scattered population of roughly half a million clusters in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Delingha\">Delingha</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Golmud\">Golmud</span>. Geological surveys <b>begun in 1954</b> located <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Petroleum\">petroleum</span> at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lenghu\">Lenghu</span> and near <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mangnai\">Mangnai</span>, also a centre of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Asbestos\">asbestos</span> mining, and the Qinghai Oilfield now yields on the order of 7 million tonnes (7.7 million tons) of oil and gas equivalent annually, with the Sebei field sending <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Natural_gas\">natural gas</span> by pipeline to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lanzhou\">Lanzhou</span>. Even greater wealth lies in brines holding China’s largest reserves of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Potash\">potash</span> alongside major stores of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lithium\">lithium</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Magnesium\">magnesium</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boron\">boron</span>, supporting output of about 5 million tonnes (5.5 million tons) of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Potassium_chloride\">potassium chloride</span> a year and a rising share of the nation’s battery-grade <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lithium_carbonate\">lithium carbonate</span>. <b>Since 2006 Golmud</b> has served as the junction where the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qinghai–Tibet_railway\">Qinghai–Tibet railway</span> climbs toward <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lhasa\">Lhasa</span>, while intense solar radiation has turned the basin into a showcase of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Photovoltaic_power_station\">photovoltaic power stations</span> measured in multiple gigawatts.","citation":"","answerText":"Qaidam Basin"},{"id":"cng-008","num":"八","category":"China · Geography","question":"The largest lake in the country, a vast saline body sitting at over 3,000 m (9,800 ft) on the northeastern Tibetan Plateau, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> gives its name to the surrounding province and draws migratory birds to its shores.","answer":"Qinghai Lake","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">青海湖 (Qīnghǎi Hú, 'blue-green sea lake')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"青海湖","pinyin":"Qīnghǎi Hú","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Qīnghǎi Hú</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“azure sea”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Qinghai Lake</b> is the largest lake of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>, a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Salt_lake\">saline</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Endorheic_basin\">endorheic</span> water body spreading across more than 4,500 square kilometres (1,700 sq mi) of the northeastern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_Plateau\">Tibetan Plateau</span>. Its surface stands near 3,200 metres (10,000 ft) above sea level, its waters reach depths beyond 25 metres (82 ft), and inflow arrives from roughly 23 rivers and streams, of which the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Buha_River\">Buha River</span></b> alone contributes close to half. The lake is <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Brackish_water\">brackish</span> to saline at about 12 to 14 grams of dissolved salts per litre, and despite this salinity it freezes over for roughly 3 months each winter. During the 20th century the water level fell by more than 3 metres (9.8 ft) and the area shrank to about 4,240 square kilometres (1,640 sq mi) <b>by 2004</b>, but a warmer and wetter regional <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Climate_change\">climate</span> has since driven an expansion past 4,600 square kilometres (1,800 sq mi). The lake sustains the endemic naked carp <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gymnocypris_przewalskii\"><i>Gymnocypris przewalskii</i></span>, protected by fishing moratoria since the early 2000s, while surrounding steppes shelter <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Przewalski's_gazelle\">Przewalski’s gazelle</span></b>, and its islets, designated under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ramsar_Convention\">Ramsar Convention</span>, host over 100,000 <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bird_migration\">migratory birds</span> such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bar-headed_goose\">bar-headed geese</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pallas's_gull\">Pallas’s gulls</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_cormorant\">great cormorants</span>, a colony struck by a <b>notorious <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Influenza_A_virus_subtype_H5N1\">H5N1</span> outbreak in 2005</b>. <br> <br> Chinese sources of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span> called the lake Xihai, the “Western Sea,” and the regent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Mang\">Wang Mang</span> founded a short-lived Xihai Commandery on its shores in 4 CE. The basin later became a battleground between the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tuyuhun\">Tuyuhun</span> kingdom and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_Empire\">Tibetan Empire</span>, and legend holds that the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Princess_Wencheng\">Princess Wencheng</span> gazed back toward home from the nearby Sun and Moon Pass in 641 while travelling to marry the Tibetan ruler <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Songtsen_Gampo\">Songtsen Gampo</span>. <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khoshut\">Khoshut</span> Mongols under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Güshi_Khan\">Güshi Khan</span> dominated the grasslands from the 1630s until the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> crushed the <b>revolt of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lobzang_Danjin\">Lobzang Danjin</span> in 1724</b> and ruled the region through officials at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xining\">Xining</span>, and in 1928 the surrounding territory was organized as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qinghai\">Qinghai</span> province, taking its name from the lake. In <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_Buddhism\">Tibetan Buddhist</span> tradition the lake remains a sacred site whose <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kora_(pilgrimage)\">kora</span> circumambulation covers some 360 kilometres (220 mi), a route now paralleled by millions of tourists, a lakeside <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nature_reserve\">nature reserve</span> established in the 1990s, and the international <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tour_of_Qinghai_Lake\">Tour of Qinghai Lake</span> cycling race held annually since 2002.","citation":"","answerText":"Qinghai Lake"},{"id":"cng-009","num":"九","category":"China · Geography","question":"Meaning \"Celestial Mountains\", the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> stretches across Xinjiang and on into Central Asia, separating the Junggar basin to its north from the Tarim to its south.","answer":"Tian Shan","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">天山 (Tiān Shān, 'celestial mountains')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"天山","pinyin":"Tiān Shān","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Tiān Shān</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Celestial Mountains”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Tian Shan</b> is one of the great ranges of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Asia\">Central Asia</span></b>, extending roughly 2,800 kilometers (1,700 mi) from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinjiang\">Xinjiang</span> westward into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kyrgyzstan\">Kyrgyzstan</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kazakhstan\">Kazakhstan</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Uzbekistan\">Uzbekistan</span>, dividing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Junggar_Basin\">Junggar Basin</span> to its north from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tarim_Basin\">Tarim Basin</span> to its south. Its loftiest summits cluster near the Kyrgyz–Chinese border, where <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jengish_Chokusu\">Jengish Chokusu</span></b> (Victory Peak) rises to 7,439 meters (24,410 ft) and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khan_Tengri\">Khan Tengri</span> reaches 7,010 meters (23,000 ft), making them the northernmost peaks on earth to exceed 7,000 meters (23,000 ft). The range supports several thousand glaciers covering on the order of 10,000 square kilometers (3,900 sq mi), including the roughly 60-kilometer (37 mi) <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Engilchek_Glacier\">Engilchek Glacier</span></b>, though studies indicate the ice has lost about a quarter of its mass since the 1960s amid regional warming. Meltwater feeds the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Naryn_River\">Naryn</span>, principal headstream of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Syr_Darya\">Syr Darya</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ili_River\">Ili River</span> flowing to <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lake_Balkhash\">Lake Balkhash</span></b>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Aksu_River_(China)\">Aksu</span> feeding the Tarim, while the range also cradles <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Issyk-Kul\">Issyk-Kul</span>, a 668-meter-deep (2,190 ft) lake at 1,607 meters (5,272 ft) that ranks among the largest mountain lakes in the world. Built on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paleozoic\">Paleozoic</span> crust accreted around ancient <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kazakhstania\">Kazakhstania</span> and rejuvenated by the distant collision of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Indian_Plate\">Indian Plate</span> with Eurasia, the chain remains seismically violent, as shown <b>by the magnitude 8 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1911_Kebin_earthquake\">1911 Kebin earthquake</span></b>, and its Chinese and western sections were inscribed as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Heritage_Site\">World Heritage Sites</span> in 2013 and 2016. <br> <br> The name first appears in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span> sources of the 2nd century BCE, possibly translating an older designation used by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiongnu\">Xiongnu</span>, for whom the mountains held sacred significance. The northern and middle branches of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk_Road\">Silk Road</span> skirted and crossed the range through passes such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Torugart_Pass\">Torugart</span>, linking oasis cities like <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kucha\">Kucha</span> with the steppe domains of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wusun\">Wusun</span> and later nomadic powers. The <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heavenly_Lake_of_Tianshan\">Heavenly Lake</span></b> beneath 5,445-meter (17,860 ft) <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bogda_Peak\">Bogda Peak</span> became identified in Chinese tradition with the jade pool of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Queen_Mother_of_the_West\">Queen Mother of the West</span>, while the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang dynasty</span> in the 7th century projected power along both flanks of the range. Its valleys and high pastures sustain the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Transhumance\">transhumant</span> herding traditions of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kyrgyz_people\">Kyrgyz</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kazakhs\">Kazakhs</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Uyghurs\">Uyghurs</span>, and the slopes shelter one of the most important remaining populations of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Snow_leopard\">snow leopard</span>. Today the contrast between summit and basin is starkest near <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ürümqi\">Ürümqi</span>, where peaks above 5,000 meters (16,000 ft) stand barely 100 kilometers (62 mi) from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Turpan_Depression\">Turpan Depression</span>, which plunges to 154 meters (505 ft) below sea level.","citation":"","answerText":"Tian Shan"},{"id":"cng-010","num":"十","category":"China · Geography","question":"A large, semi-arid basin in northern Xinjiang enclosed by the Tian Shan to the south and the Altai to the north, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> holds grasslands, rich oilfields and the Gurbantünggüt sands.","answer":"Junggar Basin","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Mongolian Dzungar ('left hand', i.e. the western wing)</span></div>","traditional":"準噶爾盆地","hanzi":"准噶尔盆地","pinyin":"Zhǔngá'ěr Péndì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhǔngá'ěr Péndì</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“left hand”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Junggar Basin</b> is a semi-arid <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Endorheic_basin\">endorheic</span></b> lowland of roughly 380,000 square kilometres (150,000 sq mi) in northern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinjiang\">Xinjiang</span>, second in size among the great interior basins of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> only to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tarim_Basin\">Tarim Basin</span>. It is framed by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tian_Shan\">Tian Shan</span> on the south, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Altai_Mountains\">Altai Mountains</span> on the northeast, and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dzungarian_Alatau\">Dzungarian Alatau</span></b> on the west, where the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dzungarian_Gate\">Dzungarian Gate</span> admits moist westerly air that gives the floor 100 to 200 millimetres (3.9 to 7.9 in) of annual precipitation, enough to sustain <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Steppe\">steppe</span> grasslands rather than absolute desert. The centre is nonetheless occupied by the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gurbantünggüt_Desert\">Gurbantünggüt Desert</span></b>, China’s second largest at about 48,800 square kilometres (18,800 sq mi), whose dunes are mostly fixed by vegetation, while the basin’s lowest point lies at saline <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lake_Ebinur\">Lake Ebinur</span>, only 189 metres (620 ft) above sea level. Drainage is largely internal, although the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Irtysh_River\">Irtysh River</span></b> crosses the northern rim as the only Chinese river to reach the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Arctic_Ocean\">Arctic Ocean</span>. Beneath the surface, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Carboniferous\">Carboniferous</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Permian\">Permian</span> source rocks under as much as 15,000 metres (49,000 ft) of sediment have generated abundant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Petroleum\">petroleum</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jurassic\">Jurassic</span> strata along the margins have yielded celebrated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dinosaur\">dinosaur</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pterosaur\">pterosaur</span> fossils such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dsungaripterus\"><i>Dsungaripterus</i></span>. <br> <br> The basin corresponds to the historical region of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dzungaria\">Dzungaria</span></b>, prized pastureland that became the core of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dzungar_Khanate\">Dzungar Khanate</span>, the last great nomadic empire of Inner Asia, in the 17th and 18th centuries. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qianlong_Emperor\">Qianlong Emperor</span> destroyed that state in the 1750s amid the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dzungar_genocide\">Dzungar genocide</span>, after which the depopulated grasslands were resettled by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kazakhs\">Kazakhs</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hui_people\">Hui</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Chinese\">Han Chinese</span> migrants. <b>Since 1949</b> the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinjiang_Production_and_Construction_Corps\">Xinjiang Production and Construction Corps</span> has converted oasis belts along streams such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manas_River\">Manas River</span> into irrigated farms of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cotton\">cotton</span> and grain, anchoring new cities on the basin’s southern rim near <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ürümqi\">Ürümqi</span>. Discovery of <b>oil at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Karamay\">Karamay</span> in 1955 gave</b> the People’s Republic its first large oilfield, an operation of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_National_Petroleum_Corporation\">China National Petroleum Corporation</span> that now lifts on the order of 13 million tonnes (14 million tons) of oil equivalent annually, while the Zhundong field in the east holds <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Coal\">coal</span> reserves estimated near 390 billion tonnes (430000 million tons). Rail lines through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Alashankou\">Alashankou</span> to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kazakhstan\">Kazakhstan</span> have meanwhile made the basin a corridor of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eurasian_Land_Bridge\">Eurasian Land Bridge</span> and a strategic axis of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Belt_and_Road_Initiative\">Belt and Road Initiative</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Junggar Basin"},{"id":"cng-015","num":"十五","category":"China · Geography","question":"A range in the far northwest where China meets Mongolia, Russia and Kazakhstan, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> lend their name to a great language family and feed the headwaters of the Irtysh.","answer":"Altai Mountains","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Mongolian-Turkic altan ('gold')</span></div>","traditional":"阿爾泰山脈","hanzi":"阿尔泰山脉","pinyin":"Ā'ěrtài Shānmài","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Ā'ěrtài Shānmài</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“gold”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Altai Mountains</b> are a mountain system running some 2,000 kilometres (1,200 mi) from northwest to southeast through the meeting ground of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russia\">Russia</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kazakhstan\">Kazakhstan</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongolia\">Mongolia</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinjiang\">Xinjiang</span> region of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>. The range culminates at 4,506 metres (14,780 ft) on <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Belukha_Mountain\">Belukha Mountain</span></b> in Russia, while the glaciated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tavan_Bogd\">Tavan Bogd</span> massif at the Chinese–Mongolian frontier rises to 4,374 metres (14,350 ft) at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khüiten_Peak\">Khüiten Peak</span>, known on the Chinese side as Friendship Peak. Altai snows feed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Irtysh_River\">Irtysh</span>, which rises on the range’s southern slopes in China, as well as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khovd_River\">Khovd</span> and the headstreams of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ob_River\">Ob</span>, into which the Irtysh flows on a course of more than 4,200 kilometres (2,600 mi) toward the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Arctic_Ocean\">Arctic Ocean</span></b>. Their slopes carry the southernmost outliers of Siberian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiga\">taiga</span>, dominated by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Larch\">larch</span> and sheltering <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Snow_leopard\">snow leopards</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Argali\">argali</span> sheep, while glacial troughs hold waters such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kanas_Lake\">Kanas Lake</span>, nearly 190 metres (620 ft) deep and ringed by villages of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tuvans\">Tuvans</span>. The Russian core of the range, spanning more than 16,000 square kilometres (6,200 sq mi), was <b>inscribed in 1998</b> as the Golden Mountains of Altai <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Heritage_Site\">World Heritage Site</span>. <br> <br> The range lent its name in the 19th century to the proposed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Altaic_languages\">Altaic</span> family uniting the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Turkic_languages\">Turkic</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongolic_languages\">Mongolic</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tungusic_languages\">Tungusic</span> languages, a grouping most linguists now treat as a zone of contact rather than common descent. Human depths here are extraordinary, for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Denisova_Cave\">Denisova Cave</span> on the Russian flank yielded the finger bone from which the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Denisovan\">Denisovans</span> were <b>identified in 2010</b>, along with a roughly 90,000-year-old girl born to a Denisovan father and Neanderthal mother. Frozen <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kurgan\">kurgans</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pazyryk_culture\">Pazyryk culture</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Scythians\">Scythian</span> horsemen of the 5th to 3rd centuries BCE, preserved tattooed bodies such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Siberian_Ice_Maiden\">Siberian Ice Maiden</span> <b>excavated in 1993</b>. Medieval tradition placed the original <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Göktürks\">Göktürks</span> in these mountains as iron smiths serving the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rouran_Khaganate\">Rouran Khaganate</span> before their 6th-century rise, and the slopes today are home chiefly to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kazakhs\">Kazakhs</span> on the Chinese side, where <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Altay_Prefecture\">Altay Prefecture</span></b> counts roughly 670,000 inhabitants. True to the golden name, the mountains have long been mined, most famously at the No. 3 pegmatite pit of Koktokay in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fuyun_County\">Fuyun County</span>, whose <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beryllium\">beryllium</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lithium\">lithium</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tantalum\">tantalum</span> helped repay Soviet-era debts during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-Soviet_split\">Sino-Soviet split</span>, while ancient rock paintings near Altay City are cited by some researchers as evidence that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Skiing\">skiing</span> itself was born beneath these peaks perhaps 10,000 years ago.","citation":"","answerText":"Altai Mountains"},{"id":"cng-016","num":"十六","category":"China · Geography","question":"A high, grassy tableland of the north straddling the border with Mongolia and covering much of Inner Mongolia, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was long home to nomadic herders.","answer":"Mongolian Plateau","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">蒙古高原 ('Mongolian plateau')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"蒙古高原","pinyin":"Měnggǔ Gāoyuán","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Měnggǔ Gāoyuán</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Mongolian Plateau</b> is a vast inland tableland of some 2.6 million square kilometers (1 million sq mi) in the heart of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"East_Asia\">East Asia</span>, lying mostly between 1,000 and 1,500 meters (3,300 and 4,900 ft) in elevation and embracing the state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongolia\">Mongolia</span> together with much of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Inner_Mongolia\">Inner Mongolia</span>. It is framed by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Greater_Khingan\">Greater Khingan</span> range on the east, the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yin_Mountains\">Yin Mountains</span></b> on the south, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Altai_Mountains\">Altai</span> on the west, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khangai_Mountains\">Khangai</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khentii_Mountains\">Khentii</span> uplands toward Siberia, while its <b>center grades from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Steppe\">steppe</span></b> grassland into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gobi_Desert\">Gobi Desert</span>, itself roughly 1.3 million square kilometers (500,000 sq mi). The climate is among the most continental on earth, with winter readings below −40 °C (−40 °F), and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ulaanbaatar\">Ulaanbaatar</span> ranking as the coldest national capital, while periodic winter disasters known as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zud\">zud</span> killed about 10 million <b>head of livestock in 2009–2010 alone</b>. Drainage is largely interior, yet the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Orkhon_River\">Orkhon</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Selenga_River\">Selenga</span> rivers carry the plateau's waters north to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lake_Baikal\">Lake Baikal</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kherlen_River\">Kherlen</span> ends in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hulun_Lake\">Hulun Lake</span>. The grasslands still support immense herds of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongolian_gazelle\">Mongolian gazelle</span></b>, but thawing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Permafrost\">permafrost</span>, overgrazing, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Desertification\">desertification</span> have degraded a large share of the pasture and feed the spring dust storms that reach <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>. <br> <br> For roughly 3,000 years the plateau has been the <b>homeland of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nomadic_pastoralism\">nomadic pastoralists</span></b> who move felt <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yurt\">yurts</span> between seasonal pastures and herd the \"five snouts\" of sheep, goats, cattle, camels, and the hardy <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongol_horse\">Mongol horse</span>. It was here that the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiongnu\">Xiongnu</span> under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Modu_Chanyu\">Modu Chanyu</span> forged the first <b>great steppe empire around 209 BCE</b>, an example followed by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xianbei\">Xianbei</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rouran_Khaganate\">Rouran Khaganate</span>. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Turkic_Khaganate\">Turkic Khaganate</span> arose in 552 and left the 8th-century <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Orkhon_inscriptions\">Orkhon inscriptions</span>, the oldest known Turkic texts, before the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Uyghur_Khaganate\">Uyghur Khaganate</span> dominated the steppe from 744 to 840. <b>In 1206 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Genghis_Khan\">Genghis Khan</span></b> united the tribes and launched the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongol_Empire\">Mongol Empire</span>, history's largest contiguous land empire, governed for a time from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Karakorum\">Karakorum</span> in the Orkhon valley and later from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan dynasty</span> capital in China. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> absorbed the plateau in the 17th century and administered <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Outer_Mongolia\">Outer Mongolia</span> separately from the inner banks, a division that hardened after 1911 into today's contrast between a sovereign nation of about 3.5 million people and a Chinese autonomous region of roughly 24 million.","citation":"","answerText":"Mongolian Plateau"},{"id":"cng-017","num":"十七","category":"China · Geography","question":"A vast cold desert of gravel plains and bare rock spanning northern China and southern Mongolia, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> lies in the rain shadow of the Himalayas and has yielded famous dinosaur fossils.","answer":"Gobi Desert","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Mongolian gobi ('waterless place')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"戈壁","pinyin":"Gēbì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Gēbì</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“waterless place”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Gobi Desert</b> is a great arid expanse of roughly 1.3 million square kilometers (500,000 sq mi) arcing some 1,600 kilometers (990 mi) across southern <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongolia\">Mongolia</span></b> and northern China, including much of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Inner_Mongolia\">Inner Mongolia</span>, making it the largest desert in Asia and among the half-dozen largest on earth. Perched at 900 to 1,500 meters (3,000 to 4,900 ft) between the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Altai_Mountains\">Altai Mountains</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hexi_Corridor\">Hexi Corridor</span>, it owes its dryness to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rain_shadow\">rain shadow</span> cast by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Himalayas\">Himalayas</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_Plateau\">Tibetan Plateau</span>, which block moisture from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Monsoon\">monsoon</span> and hold annual precipitation to roughly 50–200 millimeters (2–7.9 in). As a classic cold <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Desert_climate\">desert climate</span></b>, it endures temperature swings from below −40 °C (−40 °F) in winter to above 40 °C (104 °F) in summer, sometimes shifting tens of degrees within a single day. Contrary to popular image, only around 5 percent of its surface is sand, exemplified by the 300-meter (980 ft) singing dunes of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khongoryn_Els\">Khongoryn Els</span></b> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gobi_Gurvansaikhan_National_Park\">Gobi Gurvansaikhan National Park</span>, while most of the terrain is bare rock and gravel <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Desert_pavement\">desert pavement</span> dotted with drought-hardy <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Saxaul\">saxaul</span> and sheltering the last roughly 1,000 <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wild_Bactrian_camel\">wild Bactrian camels</span></b>, a few dozen <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gobi_bear\">Gobi bears</span>, and herds of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongolian_wild_ass\">Mongolian wild ass</span>. Overgrazing and drought have pushed the desert's margins outward by thousands of square kilometers of lost grassland per year at the worst of the crisis, feeding the springtime <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Asian_Dust\">Asian dust</span> storms that blanket <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> and prompting China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three-North_Shelter_Forest_Program\">Three-North Shelter Forest Program</span>, <b>begun in 1978</b>. <br> <br> The Gobi's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cretaceous\">Cretaceous</span> sediments rank among the richest <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dinosaur\">dinosaur</span> graveyards in the world, first exploited scientifically in the 1920s when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Roy_Chapman_Andrews\">Roy Chapman Andrews</span> led <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"American_Museum_of_Natural_History\">American Museum of Natural History</span></b> expeditions to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Flaming_Cliffs\">Flaming Cliffs</span>. There his teams unearthed the first widely recognized fossil <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dinosaur_egg\">dinosaur eggs</span> along with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Protoceratops\">Protoceratops</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Oviraptor\">Oviraptor</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Velociraptor\">Velociraptor</span>, and later Polish–Mongolian work recovered the <b>famous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fighting_Dinosaurs\">Fighting Dinosaurs</span> specimen in 1971</b> and giant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tarbosaurus\">Tarbosaurus</span> skeletons from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nemegt_Formation\">Nemegt Formation</span>. Humans have long skirted and braved the waste, for caravans of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk_Road\">Silk Road</span> threaded its southern oases, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marco_Polo\">Marco Polo</span> in the 13th century described a month-long crossing haunted by phantom voices. Modern transit came with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Trans-Mongolian_Railway\">Trans-Mongolian Railway</span>, completed in the 1950s to join Beijing with Ulaanbaatar and Moscow across the gravel plains. In the 21st century the desert has become an economic frontier as well, anchored by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Oyu_Tolgoi_mine\">Oyu Tolgoi mine</span>, one of the largest known copper–gold deposits on the planet, whose expansion now rivals herding as the emblem of Gobi life.","citation":"","answerText":"Gobi Desert"},{"id":"cng-018","num":"十八","category":"China · Geography","question":"A long, forested range running north to south through Inner Mongolia and the northeast, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> separate the Mongolian Plateau from the plains of Manchuria and hold some of the country's largest timber reserves.","answer":"Greater Khingan","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">大兴安岭 ('greater Khingan range')</span></div>","traditional":"大興安嶺","hanzi":"大兴安岭","pinyin":"Dà Xīng'ān Lǐng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Dà Xīng'ān Lǐng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Greater Khingan</b> is a forested range stretching roughly 1,200 kilometres (750 mi) from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Amur_River\">Amur River</span> in northern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heilongjiang\">Heilongjiang</span> south through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Inner_Mongolia\">Inner Mongolia</span> toward the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xar_Moron_River\">Xar Moron River</span></b>, marking the great divide between the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongolian_Plateau\">Mongolian Plateau</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northeast_China_Plain\">Northeast China Plain</span>. Its relief is gentle, averaging 1,200 to 1,300 metres (3,900 to 4,300 ft) and peaking at 2,029 metres (6,657 ft) on Huanggangliang in <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hexigten_Banner\">Hexigten Banner</span></b>, with volcanic craters and hot springs clustered around <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Arxan\">Arxan</span>. The climate is the harshest in China, for the town of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mohe_City\">Mohe</span> at the range’s northern tip registered −53 °C (−63 °F) <b>in 2023</b>, and the uplands carry the country’s southernmost extensive belt of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Permafrost\">permafrost</span>. Upon this cold foundation grows the largest contiguous forest region of China, more than 8 million hectares (20 million acres) of state forest dominated by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Larix_gmelinii\">Dahurian larch</span> mixed with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Birch\">birch</span> and Mongolian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Scots_pine\">Scots pine</span>, long the nation’s premier timber reserve. The crest parts the waters of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Argun_(Amur)\">Argun</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hailar_River\">Hailar</span> on the west from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nen_River\">Nen River</span> draining east toward the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Songhua_River\">Songhua</span>, and the woods shelter <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Moose\">moose</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sable\">sable</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Reindeer\">reindeer</span> herds of China’s last herding community of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Evenks\">Evenks</span> at Aoluguya. <br> <br> The range has been a cradle of steppe peoples, a memory <b>confirmed in 1980</b> when archaeologists at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gaxian_Cave\">Gaxian Cave</span> found an inscription recording sacrifices that a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Wei\">Northern Wei</span> embassy offered in 443 CE at the ancestral grotto of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xianbei\">Xianbei</span>. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shiwei\">Shiwei</span> tribes, counted among the ancestors of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongols\">Mongols</span>, later roamed its western valleys, while the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khitan_people\">Khitans</span> on its southeastern flank founded the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liao_dynasty\">Liao dynasty</span> in 907. Under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span>, hunting peoples such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Oroqen_people\">Oroqen</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Daur_people\">Daur</span> were organized into frontier banners, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Eastern_Railway\">Chinese Eastern Railway</span> pierced the crest with a 3-kilometre (1.9 mi) tunnel <b>completed in 1903</b>, a corridor later incorporated into the Hingan provinces of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchukuo\">Manchukuo</span>. After 1949 the People’s Republic turned the range into its main <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Logging\">logging</span> base administered from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jagdaqi\">Jagdaqi</span>, an era scarred in May 1987 when the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Black_Dragon_Fire\">Black Dragon Fire</span></b> consumed over 1 million hectares (2.5 million acres), killed about 200 people, and ranked among the worst wildfires of the 20th century. Conservation programs launched after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1998_China_floods\">1998 floods</span> culminated in a complete commercial logging ban in 2015, redirecting the region toward <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ecotourism\">ecotourism</span> anchored by attractions such as the Arxan <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"UNESCO_Global_Geoparks\">UNESCO Global Geopark</span></b>.","citation":"","answerText":"Greater Khingan"},{"id":"cng-019","num":"十九","category":"China · Geography","question":"The largest plain in the country, a broad expanse of fertile black soil in historic Manchuria, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> drained by the Songhua and Liao rivers is a major producer of maize, soybeans and grain.","answer":"Northeast China Plain","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">东北平原 ('northeast plain')</span></div>","traditional":"東北平原","hanzi":"东北平原","pinyin":"Dōngběi Píngyuán","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Dōngběi Píngyuán</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Northeast China Plain</b>, also called the Manchurian or Songliao Plain, is the largest plain in China, spreading over roughly 350,000 square kilometers (140,000 sq mi) of historic <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchuria\">Manchuria</span></b> across <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heilongjiang\">Heilongjiang</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jilin\">Jilin</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liaoning\">Liaoning</span> between the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Greater_Khingan\">Greater Khingan</span>, the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lesser_Khingan\">Lesser Khingan</span></b>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Changbai_Mountains\">Changbai Mountains</span>, opening southward to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liaodong_Bay\">Liaodong Bay</span>. Mostly lying below 200 meters (660 ft), it comprises the central Songnen lowland of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Songhua_River\">Songhua</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nen_River\">Nen</span> rivers, the valley of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liao_River\">Liao River</span> in the south, and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sanjiang_Plain\">Sanjiang Plain</span></b> in the far northeast where the Songhua meets the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Amur_River\">Amur</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ussuri_River\">Ussuri</span>. Its celebrated black earth belongs to one of the world's few great <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chernozem\">chernozem</span> belts, though decades of plowing and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soil_erosion\">erosion</span> have thinned a humus layer once commonly 60–100 centimeters (24–39 in) deep to 20–30 centimeters (7.9–12 in) in many fields, prompting a national <b>black-soil protection law in 2022</b>. Despite a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Humid_continental_climate\">humid continental climate</span> that permits only a single harvest and brings winters below −20 °C (−4 °F), the plain anchors a region producing over a 5th of China's grain, leading the nation in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maize\">maize</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soybean\">soybeans</span>, and premium <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japonica_rice\">japonica rice</span></b> in a zone often compared to the American <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Corn_Belt\">Corn Belt</span>. The Sanjiang section, long known as the Great Northern Wilderness, was converted after the 1950s by soldier-settlers and state farms into millions of hectares of cropland, at the cost of roughly 4 fifths of its original wetlands. <br> <br> The plain also conceals mineral wealth, most famously the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Daqing_Field\">Daqing Field</span> <b>discovered in 1959</b>, China's largest oilfield, which sustained output around 50 million tonnes (55 million tons) annually for some 27 years. Historically the lowland was the cradle of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jurchen_people\">Jurchen</span>, founders <b>of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jin_dynasty_(1115–1234)\">Jin dynasty</span> in 1115</b>, and of their <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_people\">Manchu</span> descendants, whose <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> long fenced the homeland behind the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Willow_Palisade\">Willow Palisade</span> to restrict Han settlement. When the ban dissolved in the late 19th century, the migration known as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chuang_Guandong\">Chuang Guandong</span> drew tens of millions of farmers from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shandong\">Shandong</span> and Hebei onto the black earth in one of the largest population movements of the era. Railways built by Russia and Japan, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Eastern_Railway\">Chinese Eastern</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South_Manchuria_Railway\">South Manchuria</span> lines, knitted the plain into industrial circuits, and after the 1931 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mukden_Incident\">Mukden Incident</span> the puppet state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchukuo\">Manchukuo</span> made it Japan's continental workshop. The People's Republic inherited that base, placing its first auto plant under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"FAW_Group\">FAW</span> at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Changchun\">Changchun</span> in 1953, and although cities such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Harbin\">Harbin</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shenyang\">Shenyang</span> later suffered rust-belt decline addressed by the 2003 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northeast_Area_Revitalization_Plan\">revitalization plan</span>, the plain remains the indispensable granary of a region of about 100 million people.","citation":"","answerText":"Northeast China Plain"},{"id":"cng-020","num":"二十","category":"China · Geography","question":"Forming much of the long northeastern border between China and Russia, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> — known in Chinese as the Heilongjiang, or \"Black Dragon River\" — was the subject of the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> Treaty of Nerchinsk and gives its name to a province.","answer":"Amur River","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">黑龙江 (Hēilóng Jiāng, 'black dragon river')</span></div>","traditional":"黑龍江","hanzi":"黑龙江","pinyin":"Hēilóng Jiāng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Hēilóng Jiāng</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Black Dragon River”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Amur River</b> is the world’s 10th longest river system, flowing about 2,824 kilometres (1,755 mi) from the junction of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shilka_River\">Shilka</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Argun_(Amur)\">Argun</span> rivers, or some 4,440 kilometres (2,760 mi) when measured from headstreams such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Onon_River\">Onon</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongolia\">Mongolia</span>. Its basin of roughly 1.86 million square kilometres (718,000 sq mi) spans <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russia\">Russia</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>, and Mongolia, and for well over 1,500 kilometres (930 mi) the main stream itself traces the Sino-Russian frontier. From the north it receives the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zeya_River\">Zeya</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bureya_River\">Bureya</span>, from the south the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Songhua_River\">Songhua</span>, its largest tributary, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ussuri_River\">Ussuri</span>, before emptying into the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Strait_of_Tartary\">Strait of Tartary</span></b> opposite <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sakhalin\">Sakhalin</span>, an island whose very name echoes the river’s Manchu title. Unusually for a great river, the Amur main stem remains undammed, supporting more than 120 fish species, among them runs of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chum_salmon\">chum salmon</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kaluga_(fish)\">kaluga</span> sturgeon, which can approach 1,000 kilograms (2,200 lb) and ranks among the largest freshwater fishes on Earth. Its wetlands and forested margins shelter the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Siberian_tiger\">Siberian tiger</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Amur_leopard\">Amur leopard</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Red-crowned_crane\">red-crowned crane</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Oriental_stork\">Oriental stork</span>, while <b>record floods in 2013</b> reminded both banks of the river’s power. <br> <br> The valley is the ancient home of Tungusic and other fishing peoples such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanai_people\">Nanai</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nivkh_people\">Nivkh</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Daur_people\">Daur</span>, and in the 1410s the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span> eunuch admiral <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yishiha\">Yishiha</span> descended to the estuary, raising temple steles at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tyr,_Russia\">Tyr</span> to proclaim Chinese suzerainty. <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cossacks\">Cossack</span> <b>bands under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vassili_Poyarkov\">Vassili Poyarkov</span> in 1643</b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yerofey_Khabarov\">Yerofey Khabarov</span> after 1649 pillaged the valley, provoking <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> counterattacks at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Albazino\">Albazin</span> that ended <b>with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Nerchinsk\">Treaty of Nerchinsk</span> in 1689</b>, which barred Russia from the basin for nearly 170 years. The governor-general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nikolay_Muravyov-Amursky\">Nikolay Muravyov-Amursky</span> reversed that verdict through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Aigun\">Treaty of Aigun</span> of 1858 and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Convention_of_Peking\">Convention of Peking</span> of 1860, transferring about 1 million square kilometres (390,000 sq mi) of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Outer_Manchuria\">Outer Manchuria</span> to Russia, planting cities like <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Blagoveshchensk\">Blagoveshchensk</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khabarovsk\">Khabarovsk</span>, and setting the stage for the drowning of several thousand Chinese residents in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Blagoveshchensk_massacre\">Blagoveshchensk massacre</span> of 1900 during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boxer_Rebellion\">Boxer Rebellion</span>. Armed clashes flared again in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-Soviet_border_conflict\">Sino-Soviet border conflict</span> of 1969, yet a 2004 agreement dividing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bolshoy_Ussuriysky_Island\">Bolshoy Ussuriysky Island</span> finally settled the line, and after toxic benzene from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2005_Jilin_chemical_plant_explosions\">2005 Jilin chemical plant explosions</span> drifted down the Songhua past <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Harbin\">Harbin</span> into the Amur, the two states deepened cooperation that produced the first road bridge across the river, opened between Blagoveshchensk and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heihe\">Heihe</span> in 2022.","citation":"","answerText":"Amur River"},{"id":"cng-032","num":"三十二","category":"China · Geography","question":"A cluster of high, parallel ranges and deep gorges where the southeastern Tibetan Plateau drops toward Yunnan, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> funnel the Mekong, Salween and upper Yangtze through a famously biodiverse region.","answer":"Hengduan Mountains","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">横断山脉 ('mountains that cut crosswise')</span></div>","traditional":"橫斷山脈","hanzi":"横断山脉","pinyin":"Héngduàn Shānmài","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Héngduàn Shānmài</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“to cut crosswise”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Hengduan Mountains</b> are a system of parallel north–south ranges and deep gorges along the southeastern margin of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_Plateau\">Tibetan Plateau</span>, spanning western <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan\">Sichuan</span>, northwestern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yunnan\">Yunnan</span>, and southeastern <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibet_Autonomous_Region\">Tibet</span></b>. They culminate in the glacier-clad pyramid of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gongga_Shan\">Gongga Shan</span>, also called Minya Konka, at 7,556 metres (24,790 ft) — the highest summit in China east of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Himalayas\">Himalayas</span> — and in the sacred, still-unclimbed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kawagarbo\">Kawagarbo</span> of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Meili_Snow_Mountains\">Meili Snow Mountains</span></b> at 6,740 metres (22,100 ft). The ranges famously compress the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span>, here the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jinsha_River\">Jinsha River</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mekong\">Mekong</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Salween_River\">Salween</span> into nearly parallel courses within roughly 70 kilometres (43 mi) of one another, a spectacle protected <b>since 2003</b> as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Parallel_Rivers_of_Yunnan_Protected_Areas\">Three Parallel Rivers of Yunnan Protected Areas</span>, a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Heritage_Site\">World Heritage Site</span> of about 1.7 million hectares (4.2 million acres). Their constituent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gaoligong_Mountains\">Gaoligong Mountains</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shaluli_Mountains\">Shaluli Mountains</span>, and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Daxue_Mountains\">Daxue Mountains</span></b> are cleft by canyons such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tiger_Leaping_Gorge\">Tiger Leaping Gorge</span> on the Jinsha, where the river runs some 3,000 metres (9,800 ft) below the crest of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jade_Dragon_Snow_Mountain\">Yulong Snow Mountain</span>. Wrung by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Monsoon\">monsoon</span> moisture across an immense altitudinal range, the mountains form one of Earth’s richest temperate <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Biodiversity_hotspot\">biodiversity hotspots</span></b>, a center of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rhododendron\">rhododendron</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Primula\">Primula</span> diversity and a realm of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Giant_panda\">giant panda</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Red_panda\">red panda</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Black_snub-nosed_monkey\">Yunnan snub-nosed monkey</span>, while a <b>2020 study</b> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Science_(journal)\">Science</span> dated their alpine flora to roughly 30 million years ago as perhaps the oldest sustained alpine biota on the planet. <br> <br> The gorges have long sheltered a remarkable ethnic mosaic of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_people\">Tibetan</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Naxi_people\">Naxi</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yi_people\">Yi</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lisu_people\">Lisu</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bai_people\">Bai</span> peoples, and carried the southwestern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tea_Horse_Road\">Ancient Tea Horse Road</span> that bore <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pu'er_tea\">Pu’er tea</span> from Yunnan toward <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lhasa\">Lhasa</span>. At <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lijiang\">Lijiang</span> the Naxi preserved the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dongba_symbols\">Dongba script</span>, the world’s only living pictographic writing system, while the nearby shores of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lugu_Lake\">Lugu Lake</span> remain home to the matrilineal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mosuo\">Mosuo</span>. <b>In May 1935</b> the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Red_Army\">Red Army</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Long_March\">Long March</span> forced a passage over the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dadu_River\">Dadu River</span> at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Luding_Bridge\">Battle of Luding Bridge</span>, a celebrated feat of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">Chinese Civil War</span>. The region’s flora drew Western <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Plant_collecting\">plant collectors</span> such as the Scottish <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"George_Forrest_(botanist)\">George Forrest</span>, the English <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Frank_Kingdon-Ward\">Frank Kingdon-Ward</span>, and the Austrian-American <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joseph_Rock\">Joseph Rock</span>, whose decades around Lijiang for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Geographic_Society\">National Geographic Society</span> are sometimes credited with inspiring the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shangri-La\">Shangri-La</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"James_Hilton_(novelist)\">James Hilton</span>’s 1933 novel <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lost_Horizon\"><i>Lost Horizon</i></span>. Today the steep, fast-falling rivers anchor some of the world’s largest <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hydroelectricity\">hydroelectricity</span> projects, among them the 16,000-megawatt <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Baihetan_Dam\">Baihetan Dam</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wudongde_Dam\">Wudongde Dam</span> on the Jinsha, even as the seismically restless terrain produced the deadly <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2022_Luding_earthquake\">2022 Luding earthquake</span> and confronts engineers driving the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan–Tibet_railway\">Sichuan–Tibet railway</span> through the heart of the range.","citation":"","answerText":"Hengduan Mountains"},{"id":"cng-038","num":"三十八","category":"China · Geography","question":"Lying off the central coast between the mainland, Taiwan and the Japanese Ryukyu Islands, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> receives the Yangtze and contains the disputed Senkaku, or Diaoyu, islands.","answer":"East China Sea","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">东海 (Dōnghǎi, 'east sea')</span></div>","traditional":"東海, also 東中國海","hanzi":"东海, also 东中国海","pinyin":"Dōnghǎi","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Dōnghǎi</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“east sea”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>East China Sea</b> is a marginal sea of the western <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pacific_Ocean\">Pacific Ocean</span></b> covering roughly 770,000 square kilometres (300,000 sq mi) between the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"East_Asia\">East Asian</span> mainland, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span>, the Japanese island of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kyushu\">Kyushu</span>, and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ryukyu_Islands\">Ryukyu Islands</span></b>. Much of it overlies one of the world’s broadest <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Continental_shelf\">continental shelves</span>, shallower than 200 metres (660 ft) across vast stretches, before plunging along its eastern margin into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Okinawa_Trough\">Okinawa Trough</span>, a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Back-arc_basin\">back-arc basin</span></b> reaching depths beyond 2,300 metres (7,500 ft). Into it pours the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span>, China’s greatest river, whose sediment plume and nutrients enrich its waters, while the warm <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuroshio_Current\">Kuroshio Current</span>, a powerful boundary stream whose name means “black tide,” sweeps northeastward past the Ryukyus and spins off the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tsushima_Current\">Tsushima Current</span> into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sea_of_Japan\">Sea of Japan</span>. This confluence long made the sea among the most productive fishing grounds on Earth, centred on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhoushan_Archipelago\">Zhoushan Archipelago</span> of some 1,390 islands, though decades of overfishing have devastated stocks such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Large_yellow_croaker\">large yellow croaker</span>, and among those islands rises <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mount_Putuo\">Mount Putuo</span>, one of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sacred_Mountains_of_China\">sacred Buddhist mountains</span> devoted to the bodhisattva <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guanyin\">Guanyin</span>. On its western shore stand some of the busiest ports on the planet, the container hub of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span> at the Yangtze’s mouth and the cargo colossus of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ningbo\">Ningbo</span>–Zhoushan, linked across the silt-laden <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hangzhou_Bay\">Hangzhou Bay</span></b> by the 36-kilometre (22 mi) <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hangzhou_Bay_Bridge\">Hangzhou Bay Bridge</span>, one of the longest sea crossings ever built. <br> <br> Across these waters ran a busy arm of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maritime_Silk_Road\">Maritime Silk Road</span>, by which <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span>- and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song</span>-era China exchanged ceramics and silk with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japan\">Japan</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Korea\">Korea</span>, and along which Buddhist pilgrims ferried scriptures between the coasts. From the 14th to the 16th centuries the same sea lanes were terrorized by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wokou\">Wokou</span>, pirate fleets of mixed Japanese and Chinese origin whose raids on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span> coast were finally curbed by generals such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qi_Jiguang\">Qi Jiguang</span>. After the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Opium_War\">First Opium War</span>, the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Nanking\">Treaty of Nanking</span> of 1842</b> forced open coastal cities including Shanghai and Ningbo as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_ports\">treaty ports</span>, drawing foreign merchants and gunboats onto the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> empire’s eastern seaboard. During the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pacific_War\">Pacific War</span> the sea saw fierce fighting, <b>culminating in April 1945</b> when American carrier aircraft sank the battleship <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japanese_battleship_Yamato\">Yamato</span>, the largest ever built, as it steamed toward <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Okinawa_Prefecture\">Okinawa</span> on a one-way sortie. Today the sea ranks among Asia’s tensest maritime arenas, where Japan, China, and Taiwan all claim the uninhabited <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Senkaku_Islands\">Senkaku Islands</span>, known in Chinese as the Diaoyu, a quarrel <b>inflamed by Japan’s 2012 purchase</b> of several islets, by disputed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Exclusive_economic_zone\">exclusive economic zone</span> boundaries over seabed gas reserves, and by Beijing’s declaration of an <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Air_defense_identification_zone\">air defense identification zone</span> across much of the sea in 2013.","citation":"","answerText":"East China Sea"},{"id":"cng-044","num":"四十四","category":"China · Geography","question":"Known within China as the Lancang, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> rises on the Tibetan Plateau and flows through Yunnan before crossing Southeast Asia to become one of the world's most important international rivers.","answer":"Mekong","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Chinese 澜沧江 ('turbulent river'); 'Mekong' from Mae Nam Khong</span></div>","traditional":"瀾滄江","hanzi":"","pinyin":"Láncāng Jiāng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Láncāng Jiāng</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“turbulent river”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Mekong</b> is the longest river of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Southeast_Asia\">Southeast Asia</span></b> at roughly 4,350 kilometers (2,700 mi), rising above 5,200 meters (17,000 ft) in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qinghai\">Qinghai</span> on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_Plateau\">Tibetan Plateau</span>. Nearly half its course lies in China, where it knifes through the gorges of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yunnan\">Yunnan</span> within the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Parallel_Rivers\">Three Parallel Rivers</span> World Heritage area, shedding some 4,500 meters (15,000 ft) of elevation before leaving China at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Golden_Triangle_(Southeast_Asia)\">Golden Triangle</span></b>, where <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Myanmar\">Myanmar</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Laos\">Laos</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Thailand\">Thailand</span> meet. Along the Lao reaches it braids through the 4,000 islands of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Si_Phan_Don\">Si Phan Don</span> and plunges over <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khone_Phapheng_Falls\">Khone Phapheng Falls</span>, the broadest cataract complex on earth and the barrier that has always blocked through-navigation. In <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cambodia\">Cambodia</span> the monsoon flood performs a famous hydraulic trick, reversing the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tonlé_Sap\">Tonlé Sap</span></b> river so that the great lake swells to around 5 times its dry-season size and yields most of the nation's animal protein. The river then fans across <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vietnam\">Vietnam</span> as the \"Nine Dragons\" of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mekong_Delta\">Mekong Delta</span>, a 40,000-square-kilometer rice bowl of some 17 million people that grows about half of Vietnam's rice, before discharging roughly 475 cubic kilometers a year into the sea. <br> <br> Only the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Amazon_River\">Amazon</span> exceeds the Mekong in freshwater biodiversity, for its waters hold over 1,100 fish species, including the 300-kilogram (660 lb) <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mekong_giant_catfish\">Mekong giant catfish</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Giant_freshwater_stingray\">giant freshwater stingray</span> that set <b>a world record in 2022</b>, and a remnant of about 90 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Irrawaddy_dolphin\">Irrawaddy dolphins</span>, all sustaining the planet's largest inland <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fishery\">fishery</span> at around 2.6 million tonnes (2.9 million tons) a year, perhaps a quarter of the global freshwater catch. That abundance is now squeezed by dams, as China's Lancang cascade, begun <b>with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manwan_Dam\">Manwan Dam</span> in 1995</b> and crowned by the 292-meter (958 ft) <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiaowan_Dam\">Xiaowan</span> and the 5,850-megawatt <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nuozhadu_Dam\">Nuozhadu</span>, joined Lao projects like <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xayaburi_Dam\">Xayaburi</span> in 2019 to trap the bulk of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sediment\">sediment</span> that once built the delta, which now sinks through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Subsidence\">subsidence</span> aggravated by rampant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sand_mining\">sand mining</span>. Governance splits along the same line, with the 4 downstream states cooperating in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mekong_River_Commission\">Mekong River Commission</span> since 1995 while Beijing convenes its own <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lancang-Mekong_Cooperation\">Lancang–Mekong Cooperation</span> <b>from 2016</b>, an arrangement strained by the record droughts of 2019–2020. Civilizations have always drunk from the river, from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Funan\">Funan</span> entrepôt of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Óc_Eo\">Óc Eo</span> in the early centuries CE to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khmer_Empire\">Khmer Empire</span>, whose capital at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Angkor\">Angkor</span> fed perhaps a million people on Tonlé Sap's bounty. The French expedition of 1866–1868 under <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Francis_Garnier\">Francis Garnier</span></b> proved at Khone that the river could never be a trade route to China, redirecting the ambitions of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"French_Indochina\">French Indochina</span>, and after the delta's canals saw riverine combat in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vietnam_War\">Vietnam War</span>, the Mekong settled into its present role as the contested lifeline of some 70 million people.","citation":"","answerText":"Mekong"},{"id":"cng-049","num":"四十九","category":"China · Geography","question":"A roughly 130 km-wide (81 mi) channel separating the mainland province of Fujian from the island of Taiwan, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> connects the East China Sea with the South China Sea and is one of the world's most sensitive maritime flashpoints.","answer":"Taiwan Strait","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">台湾海峡 ('Taiwan strait')</span></div>","traditional":"臺灣海峽","hanzi":"台湾海峡","pinyin":"Táiwān Hǎixiá","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Táiwān Hǎixiá</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Taiwan Strait</b> is a channel of the western <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pacific_Ocean\">Pacific Ocean</span></b> separating the island of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span> from the mainland province of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fujian\">Fujian</span>, linking the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"East_China_Sea\">East China Sea</span> in the north with the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South_China_Sea\">South China Sea</span></b> in the south. Roughly 130 kilometres (81 mi) across at its narrowest and some 400 kilometres (250 mi) long, it is shallow over most of its breadth, lying on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Continental_shelf\">continental shelf</span> where depths typically fall below 100 metres (330 ft). During <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pleistocene\">Pleistocene</span> glacial periods lowered sea levels turned this shelf into a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Land_bridge\">land bridge</span></b> by which animals and early humans reached Taiwan, a past attested by the archaic “Penghu 1” jawbone dredged from the seabed near the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Penghu\">Penghu Islands</span> that lie midway across the channel. Just off the Fujian coast sit the islands of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kinmen\">Kinmen</span> and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Matsu_Islands\">Matsu Islands</span></b>, held by Taiwan within sight of the mainland, while the strait’s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Monsoon\">monsoon</span>-driven winds and rich currents make it both a productive fishery and one of the world’s premier sites for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Offshore_wind_power\">offshore wind power</span>. Above all the strait is one of the busiest and most strategically vital waterways on Earth, traversed by a large share of global maritime <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Trade\">trade</span> and lying athwart the routes that carry the advanced <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Semiconductor\">semiconductors</span> produced in Taiwan, above all by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"TSMC\">TSMC</span>, whose dominance lends the channel outsized importance to the world economy. <br> <br> For centuries <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Chinese\">Han</span> migrants from Fujian braved the strait’s treacherous currents, the so-called Black Ditch, to settle Taiwan, and <b>in 1661</b> the Ming loyalist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Koxinga\">Koxinga</span> crossed it with a great fleet to expel the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dutch_Formosa\">Dutch</span> from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fort_Zeelandia_(Taiwan)\">Fort Zeelandia</span>. His descendants ruled the island as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kingdom_of_Tungning\">Kingdom of Tungning</span> until the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> admiral <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shi_Lang\">Shi Lang</span> won <b>the decisive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Penghu\">Battle of Penghu</span> in 1683</b> and annexed Taiwan to the empire. Two centuries later defeat in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Sino-Japanese_War\">First Sino-Japanese War</span> forced the Qing to cede Taiwan to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empire_of_Japan\">Japan</span> under the 1895 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Shimonoseki\">Treaty of Shimonoseki</span>, placing the strait between a Japanese-ruled island and the mainland for half a century. After losing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">Chinese Civil War</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span> government of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span> retreated <b>across the water in 1949</b> to rule the island as the rival Republic of China, and when the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Korean_War\">Korean War</span> erupted in 1950 the United States <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States_Seventh_Fleet\">Seventh Fleet</span> moved into the strait to forestall an invasion. The channel became a recurring flashpoint of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cold_War\">Cold War</span> through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Taiwan_Strait_Crisis\">First Taiwan Strait Crisis</span> of 1954–1955, the massive 1958 bombardment of Kinmen in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Taiwan_Strait_Crisis\">Second Taiwan Strait Crisis</span>, and the missile tests of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Third_Taiwan_Strait_Crisis\">Third Taiwan Strait Crisis</span> of 1995–1996, and it endures as one of the most dangerous standoffs in the world as Chinese forces increasingly cross the unofficial median line amid disputes over the island’s status.","citation":"","answerText":"Taiwan Strait"},{"id":"cng-057","num":"五十七","category":"China · Geography","question":"The most populous city proper in the country and its leading commercial centre, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> grew from a treaty port into a global metropolis, its Pudong district bristling with skyscrapers along the Huangpu.","answer":"Shanghai","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">上海 (Shànghǎi, 'upon the sea')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"上海","pinyin":"Shànghǎi","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Shànghǎi</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“upon the sea”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Shanghai</b> is the most populous city proper in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> and a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Direct-administered_municipalities_of_China\">directly governed municipality</span></b>, home to roughly 25 million people and serving as the country’s foremost commercial and financial centre. It lies on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze_Delta\">Yangtze Delta</span> where the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span> empties into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"East_China_Sea\">East China Sea</span>, straddling the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huangpu_River\">Huangpu River</span></b> a short way upstream from the great river’s mouth. The Huangpu divides the city between the older western districts, where the colonnaded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Bund\">Bund</span> recalls its foreign past, and the eastern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pudong\">Pudong</span>, whose <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lujiazui\">Lujiazui</span> financial quarter bristles with towers including the 632-metre (2,070 ft) <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_Tower\">Shanghai Tower</span>, the tallest building in China. Its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Port_of_Shanghai\">Port of Shanghai</span> has ranked as the world’s busiest container port <b>since 2010</b>, handling well over 47 million <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Twenty-foot_equivalent_unit\">containers</span> a year, much of it through the offshore <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangshan_Port\">Yangshan Port</span> reached by the 32-kilometre (20 mi) <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Donghai_Bridge\">Donghai Bridge</span>. A magnet for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Multinational_corporation\">multinational corporations</span> and a rival to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span> as a financial capital, the city hosts the reborn <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_Stock_Exchange\">Shanghai Stock Exchange</span>, <b>pioneered the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_(Shanghai)_Pilot_Free-Trade_Zone\">first mainland free-trade zone</span> in 2013</b>, and links its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_Pudong_International_Airport\">airport</span> to the centre by a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_maglev_train\">magnetic-levitation train</span> that reaches 430 kilometres per hour (270 mph). <br> <br> Shanghai began as a fishing and market settlement, growing into a county seat <b>under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan dynasty</span> in 1292</b> and gaining a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Defensive_wall\">city wall</span> in 1553 to fend off the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wokou\">Japanese pirates</span> who raided the coast. Its modern transformation began after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Opium_War\">First Opium War</span>, when the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Nanking\">Treaty of Nanking</span> of 1842 opened it as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_ports\">treaty port</span>, and foreign powers carved out the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_International_Settlement\">Shanghai International Settlement</span> and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_French_Concession\">French Concession</span></b> beyond Chinese jurisdiction. By the early 20th century the cosmopolitan port had become the financial hub of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"East_Asia\">East Asia</span> and a byword for glamour and vice as the “Paris of the East,” and in 1921 a clandestine gathering in the French Concession founded the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span>. War shattered this golden age, as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Shanghai\">Battle of Shanghai</span> of 1937 brought ferocious fighting in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Sino-Japanese_War\">Second Sino-Japanese War</span> and a brutal occupation, during which the city sheltered tens of thousands of Jewish refugees in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_Ghetto\">Shanghai Ghetto</span>. After the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Revolution\">Communist victory</span> of 1949 Shanghai became an industrial powerhouse yet lost its old international flair, until the development of the Pudong New Area from 1990, accelerated by the reforms of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>, restored it to the <b>front rank of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Global_city\">global cities</span></b>, a resurgence crowned by its hosting of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Expo_2010\">Expo 2010</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Shanghai"},{"id":"cng-060","num":"六十","category":"China · Geography","question":"A dazzling financial centre on the southern coast beside the Pearl River Delta, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> returned to Chinese sovereignty in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> and is governed as a special administrative region with its own currency and laws.","answer":"Hong Kong","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">香港 (Xiānggǎng, 'fragrant harbour')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"香港","pinyin":"Xiānggǎng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Xiānggǎng</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Fragrant Harbour”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Hong Kong</b> is a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Special_administrative_regions_of_China\">special administrative region</span> of about 7.4 million</b> people on 1,114 square kilometers (430 sq mi) beside the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pearl_River_Delta\">Pearl River Delta</span>, comprising <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_Island\">Hong Kong Island</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kowloon\">Kowloon</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Territories\">New Territories</span>, and over 260 islands clustered around the deep anchorage of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Victoria_Harbour\">Victoria Harbour</span>. The colony was assembled in 3 bites, as Britain <b>took the island in 1842</b> under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Nanking\">Treaty of Nanking</span> ending the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Opium_War\">First Opium War</span>, Kowloon in 1860 under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Convention_of_Peking\">Convention of Peking</span>, and the New Territories on a 99-year lease in 1898 under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Convention_for_the_Extension_of_Hong_Kong_Territory\">Convention for the Extension of Hong Kong Territory</span>. After <b>the brutal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japanese_occupation_of_Hong_Kong\">Japanese occupation</span> of 1941–1945</b>, waves of mainland refugees multiplied a population of around 600,000 into the millions, fueling a textile-and-toys boom that matured into a services powerhouse. The expiring lease drove the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-British_Joint_Declaration\">Sino-British Joint Declaration</span> of 1984, and at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Handover_of_Hong_Kong\">handover</span> on 1 July 1997</b> a century and a half of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"British_Hong_Kong\">British Hong Kong</span> ended under the formula of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"One_country,_two_systems\">one country, two systems</span>, with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_Basic_Law\">Basic Law</span> promising the territory's way of life unchanged for 50 years. Its autonomy remains tangible in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Common_law\">common law</span> courts, a separate customs territory, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_dollar\">Hong Kong dollar</span>, pegged near 7.8 to the US dollar since 1983. <br> <br> The city consistently ranks around 3rd worldwide on the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Global_Financial_Centres_Index\">Global Financial Centres Index</span></b>, hosts the multitrillion-dollar <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_Stock_Exchange\">Hong Kong Stock Exchange</span>, runs the world's busiest air-cargo hub at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_International_Airport\">Hong Kong International Airport</span>, moves the vast majority of daily trips on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"MTR\">MTR</span>, and bristles with more <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Skyscraper\">skyscrapers</span> than any other city on earth. Yet beneath the towers climbed by the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Victoria_Peak\">Victoria Peak</span></b> tram and crossed by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Star_Ferry\">Star Ferry</span>, both running since 1888, housing is the least affordable in the world and a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gini_coefficient\">Gini coefficient</span> around 0.54 marks one of the developed world's widest wealth gaps. Culturally the territory speaks <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cantonese\">Cantonese</span> and exports its synthesis of East and West through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cinema_of_Hong_Kong\">cinema</span> that gave the world <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bruce_Lee\">Bruce Lee</span>, through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cantopop\">Cantopop</span>, and through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dim_sum\">dim sum</span> houses and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cha_chaan_teng\">cha chaan teng</span></b> diners. Politics has dominated recent decades, from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Umbrella_Movement\">Umbrella Movement</span> of 2014 to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2019–2020_Hong_Kong_protests\">2019–2020 protests</span> that drew marches estimated up to 2 million, answered by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2020_Hong_Kong_national_security_law\">2020 national security law</span> under which opposition figures were jailed and elections restricted to vetted \"patriots\" from 2021. More than 150,000 residents have since emigrated on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"British_National_(Overseas)\">British National (Overseas)</span> pathways, yet with institutions like the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"University_of_Hong_Kong\">University of Hong Kong</span> still ranked among Asia's best, the city continues its high-wire act as China's world city while the 2047 horizon draws near.","citation":"","answerText":"Hong Kong"},{"id":"cng-062","num":"六十二","category":"China · Geography","question":"A long, narrow autonomous region sweeping across the north along the border with Mongolia, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is rich in coal and rare earths and home to many ethnic Mongols.","answer":"Inner Mongolia","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">内蒙古 (Nèi Měnggǔ, 'inner Mongolia')</span></div>","traditional":"內蒙古","hanzi":"内蒙古","pinyin":"Nèi Měnggǔ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Nèi Měnggǔ</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Inner Mongolia</b>, formally the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region, is the 3rd-largest of China's provincial units and the oldest of its <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Autonomous_regions_of_China\">autonomous regions</span></b>, sweeping some 2,400 kilometers (1,500 mi) along the borders of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongolia\">Mongolia</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russia\">Russia</span> across 1.18 million square kilometers (456,000 sq mi), about 12 percent of the national territory. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2020_Chinese_census\"><b>2020</b> census</span> counted 24.05 million residents, including roughly 4.2 million ethnic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongols_in_China\">Mongols</span>, more than live in independent Mongolia, though Han Chinese form nearly 4 fifths of the population. Its landscapes run from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hulunbuir\">Hulunbuir</span> and Xilingol steppes of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongolian_Plateau\">Mongolian Plateau</span>, among the finest grasslands on earth, through the forests of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Greater_Khingan\">Greater Khingan</span> and the irrigated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hetao\">Hetao</span> bend of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_River\">Yellow River</span>, to the sands of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gobi_Desert\">Gobi</span>, the 460-meter (1,500 ft) mega-dunes of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Badain_Jaran_Desert\">Badain Jaran</span></b>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kubuqi_Desert\">Kubuqi</span>, showcased as a model of desert greening. Underground wealth defines the economy, for the region has led the nation in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Coal_in_China\">coal</span> with output around 1.2 billion tonnes (<b>1300 million</b> tons) in 2022, while <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bayan_Obo\">Bayan Obo</span> near <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Baotou\">Baotou</span> holds the world's largest deposit of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rare-earth_element\">rare-earth elements</span>, the bedrock of China's global dominance in those strategic metals. Above ground the capital <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hohhot\">Hohhot</span>, founded by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Altan_Khan\">Altan Khan</span> in the 1570s, styles itself China's dairy capital as home of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yili_Group\">Yili</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mengniu\">Mengniu</span> giants, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ordos_City\">Ordos</span></b> spins much of the world's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cashmere_wool\">cashmere</span> atop its coal boom, and wind and solar farms now stride across the steppe. <br> <br> The grasslands carry deep imperial memory, having nurtured the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liao_dynasty\">Liao dynasty</span> and hosted <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shangdu\">Shangdu</span>, the summer capital of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kublai_Khan\">Kublai Khan</span> immortalized as Xanadu and <b>listed by UNESCO in 2012</b>. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> organized the southern Mongol tribes into \"inner\" leagues and banners distinct from Outer Mongolia, and uniquely the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"League_(China)\">league</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Banner_(Inner_Mongolia)\">banner</span> survive today as official administrative tiers found nowhere else in China. In the 20th century Japan sponsored the puppet state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mengjiang\">Mengjiang</span> under Prince <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Demchugdongrub\">Demchugdongrub</span> from 1939 to 1945, before the communist Mongol leader <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ulanhu\">Ulanhu</span> proclaimed the autonomous region on 1 May 1947, more than 2 years ahead of the People's Republic itself. Autonomy has known wounds, above all the Cultural Revolution purge remembered as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Inner_Mongolia_incident\">Inner Mongolia incident</span>, which by official count killed 16,222 people and persecuted some 346,000, and friction resurfaced in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2020_Inner_Mongolia_protests\">2020 protests</span> against reducing Mongolian-language schooling. Yet Mongol culture remains visible everywhere, from the vertical <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongolian_script\">Mongolian script</span> preserved here while Mongolia adopted Cyrillic, to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Naadam\">Naadam</span> games, the horse-head <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Morin_khuur\">morin khuur</span>, and the incense kept burning for 8 centuries at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mausoleum_of_Genghis_Khan\">shrine of Genghis Khan</span></b> in Ordos.","citation":"","answerText":"Inner Mongolia"},{"id":"cng-063","num":"六十三","category":"China · Geography","question":"The largest provincial-level unit by area, a vast autonomous region in the far northwest containing the Tarim Basin, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the homeland of the Turkic Uyghurs and a key link on the old Silk Road.","answer":"Xinjiang","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">新疆 (Xīnjiāng, 'new frontier')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"新疆","pinyin":"Xīnjiāng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Xīnjiāng</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“new frontier”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Xinjiang</b> is the largest provincial-level unit of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> by area, an <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Autonomous_regions_of_China\">autonomous region</span> of roughly 1.66 million</b> square kilometres (641,000 sq mi) occupying the country’s far northwest. Covering about a sixth of China’s territory, it shares borders with 8 countries — among them <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongolia\">Mongolia</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kazakhstan\">Kazakhstan</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kyrgyzstan\">Kyrgyzstan</span>, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tajikistan\">Tajikistan</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Afghanistan\">Afghanistan</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pakistan\">Pakistan</span> — more international frontiers than any other part of the country. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tian_Shan\">Tian Shan</span> range bisects the region into the southern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tarim_Basin\">Tarim Basin</span>, filled by the great <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taklamakan_Desert\">Taklamakan Desert</span>, and the northern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Junggar_Basin\">Junggar Basin</span>, while the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Turpan_Depression\">Turpan Depression</span></b> in the east sinks to about 154 metres (505 ft) below sea level — the lowest and one of the hottest places in China — and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Karakoram\">Karakoram</span> along the southwestern rim culminates in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"K2\">K2</span>, the world’s second-highest peak. Beneath its deserts lie China’s largest reserves of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Petroleum\">petroleum</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Natural_gas\">natural gas</span> along with vast <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Coal\">coal</span> deposits, and its irrigated oases make Xinjiang the source of around 90 percent of the nation’s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cotton\">cotton</span>, roughly a fifth of the world’s supply. Its population of around 26 million is led by the Turkic, mostly Muslim <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Uyghurs\">Uyghurs</span> and a large <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Chinese\">Han Chinese</span> minority that has grown sharply <b>since 1949</b>, alongside <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kazakhs\">Kazakhs</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hui_people\">Hui</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kyrgyz_people\">Kyrgyz</span>, most professing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Islam_in_China\">Islam</span> and many speaking the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Uyghur_language\">Uyghur language</span>, and centred on the capital <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ürümqi\">Ürümqi</span> and historic oasis cities such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kashgar\">Kashgar</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hotan\">Hotan</span>. <br> <br> Xinjiang lay at the heart of the ancient <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk_Road\">Silk Road</span>, its oasis kingdoms drawn under Chinese influence when the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span> established the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Protectorate_of_the_Western_Regions\">Protectorate of the Western Regions</span> in 60 BCE, an era whose desert-preserved <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tarim_mummies\">Tarim mummies</span> and flourishing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Buddhism\">Buddhism</span> left rich remains. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang dynasty</span> governed the region through the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Protectorate_General_to_Pacify_the_West\">Anxi Protectorate</span></b>, and after the rise of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Uyghur_Khaganate\">Uyghur Khaganate</span> and the gradual conversion of the oases to Islam under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kara-Khanid_Khanate\">Kara-Khanid Khanate</span> from the 10th century, the area passed through Mongol and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chagatai_Khanate\">Chagatai</span> hands. The Buddhist Mongol <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dzungar_Khanate\">Dzungar Khanate</span> dominated the north until the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> destroyed it in the 1750s amid the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dzungar_genocide\">Dzungar genocide</span> and annexed the whole region, naming it “Xinjiang,” and after suppressing the rebellion of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yaqub_Beg\">Yaqub Beg</span> the Qing reorganised it as <b>a full province in 1884</b>. During the turbulent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)\">Republican</span> decades the region saw two short-lived <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"East_Turkestan\">East Turkestan</span> republics before the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army\">People’s Liberation Army</span> incorporated it into the new People’s Republic in 1949, after which the paramilitary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinjiang_Production_and_Construction_Corps\">Xinjiang Production and Construction Corps</span> settled waves of Han migrants and the autonomous region was formally <b>established in 1955</b>. In recent decades ethnic tensions have flared, from the deadly <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"July_2009_Ürümqi_riots\">July 2009 Ürümqi riots</span> to a wave of violence in the early 2010s, and since 2017 the government’s mass detention of Uyghurs and other Muslims in a network of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinjiang_internment_camps\">internment camps</span> — described by Beijing as vocational and counter-terrorism centres but condemned by many foreign governments as grave human-rights abuses — has made the region intensely contested, even as it remains a pivotal corridor of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Belt_and_Road_Initiative\">Belt and Road Initiative</span> toward Central Asia.","citation":"","answerText":"Xinjiang"},{"id":"cng-064","num":"六十四","category":"China · Geography","question":"Occupying the southwestern bulk of the high Tibetan Plateau with its capital at Lhasa, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the heartland of Tibetan Buddhism and was incorporated into the People's Republic in the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>s.","answer":"Tibet Autonomous Region","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">西藏 (Xīzàng, 'western Tsang')</span></div>","traditional":"西藏自治區","hanzi":"西藏自治区","pinyin":"Xīzàng Zìzhìqū","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Xīzàng Zìzhìqū</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Tibet Autonomous Region</b> covers 1.23 million square kilometers (475,000 sq mi) of the southwestern <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_Plateau\">Tibetan Plateau</span></b>, about an 8th of China and its 2nd-largest provincial unit, averaging some 4,500 meters (15,000 ft) in elevation yet holding only 3.65 million people in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2020_Chinese_census\">2020 census</span>, the country's lowest density at roughly 3 per square kilometer, of whom about 86 percent are Tibetan. Its territory carries the planet's superlatives, including the north face of 8,849-meter (29,030 ft) <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mount_Everest\">Mount Everest</span>, the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yarlung_Tsangpo\">Yarlung Tsangpo</span></b>, which knifes through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yarlung_Tsangpo_Grand_Canyon\">deepest canyon on earth</span> before becoming the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Brahmaputra_River\">Brahmaputra</span>, and the pilgrim goals of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mount_Kailash\">Mount Kailash</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lake_Manasarovar\">Lake Manasarovar</span></b>, sacred to 4 religions. The region is the heartland of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_Buddhism\">Tibetan Buddhism</span>, dominated by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gelug\">Gelug</span> school of the Dalai and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Panchen_Lama\">Panchen</span> lineages, centered on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lhasa\">Lhasa</span>, where the 7th-century <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jokhang\">Jokhang</span> is the holiest shrine and the 13-story, thousand-room <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Potala_Palace\">Potala Palace</span>, <b>begun in 1645</b> and listed by UNESCO in 1994, crowns the city. Daily life remains distinctive, carried in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetic_languages\">Tibetic languages</span>, barley tsampa and butter tea, herds of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Domestic_yak\">yak</span> on the high pastures, and funerary customs such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sky_burial\">sky burial</span>. Notably the region comprises only about half of cultural Tibet, since the eastern provinces of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kham\">Kham</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Amdo\">Amdo</span> lie largely in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qinghai\">Qinghai</span>, Sichuan, and neighboring provinces, a distinction central to the political dispute. <br> <br> The plateau's golden age was the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_Empire\">Tibetan Empire</span> of the 7th to 9th centuries, founded by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Songtsen_Gampo\">Songtsen Gampo</span>, who wed the Tang <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Princess_Wencheng\">Princess Wencheng</span> and whose successors briefly seized the Chinese capital in 763, after which Tibet passed through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan</span> patronage and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> oversight exercised through resident <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Amban\">ambans</span> from the 1720s. Following the Qing collapse, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"13th_Dalai_Lama\">13th Dalai Lama</span> ruled a de facto independent state <b>from 1913</b> until the People's Liberation Army's victory at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Chamdo\">Battle of Chamdo</span> in 1950 compelled the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Seventeen_Point_Agreement\">Seventeen Point Agreement</span> of 1951, an incorporation Beijing terms peaceful liberation and the exile community calls annexation. The <b>failed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1959_Tibetan_uprising\">1959 uprising</span> sent</b> the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"14th_Dalai_Lama\">14th Dalai Lama</span> into exile at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dharamshala\">Dharamshala</span>, where the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Tibetan_Administration\">Central Tibetan Administration</span> still sits, while the region was formally constituted in 1965, saw most of its thousands of monasteries wrecked in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span>, and in 1995 watched Beijing detain the 6-year-old <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gedhun_Choekyi_Nyima\">Gedhun Choekyi Nyima</span></b>, the Dalai Lama's Panchen choice, and install its own. Recent decades pair conspicuous development with tight control, as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qinghai–Tibet_railway\">Qinghai–Tibet railway</span> crested a 5,072-meter (16,640 ft) pass in 2006, subsidies and tens of millions of tourists transformed Lhasa, foreigners still require special permits, UN experts in 2023 estimated that around a million Tibetan children attend state boarding schools, and in 2024 China announced on the Yarlung Tsangpo what would be the world's largest hydropower project. The region is also a military frontier, for the Himalayan boundary disputed since the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-Indian_War\">Sino-Indian War</span> of 1962, including Indian-held <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Arunachal_Pradesh\">Arunachal Pradesh</span> claimed by Beijing as South Tibet, makes the sacred plateau equally a geopolitical bastion.","citation":"","answerText":"Tibet Autonomous Region"},{"id":"cng-069","num":"六十九","category":"China · Geography","question":"A historic region of the northeast, the homeland of the Manchus, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was occupied by Japan and later made a base of the early socialist economy.","answer":"Manchuria","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">满洲 (Mǎnzhōu), the homeland of the Manchu</span></div>","traditional":"滿洲","hanzi":"满洲","pinyin":"Mǎnzhōu","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Mǎnzhōu</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Manchuria</b> is a historic region of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northeast_China\">Northeast China</span></b> and the ancestral homeland of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_people\">Manchus</span>, an area now more commonly called the Northeast, or Dongbei, and comprising the provinces of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liaoning\">Liaoning</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jilin\">Jilin</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heilongjiang\">Heilongjiang</span>. Its heart is the broad, fertile <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northeast_China_Plain\">Northeast China Plain</span></b> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chernozem\">black soil</span>, ringed by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Greater_Khingan\">Greater Khingan</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lesser_Khingan\">Lesser Khingan</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Changbai_Mountains\">Changbai Mountains</span> and watered by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Amur_River\">Amur</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Songhua_River\">Songhua</span>, and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liao_River\">Liao</span></b> rivers, under a climate of long, severe winters. Its cities include <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shenyang\">Shenyang</span>, the old Manchu capital once known as Mukden, the Russian-founded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Harbin\">Harbin</span> in the north, the auto-making centre of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Changchun\">Changchun</span>, and the ice-free port of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dalian\">Dalian</span> on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liaodong_Peninsula\">Liaodong Peninsula</span>. The black-earth plains have made the region one of China’s great granaries, a leading producer of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maize\">maize</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soybean\">soybeans</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japonica_rice\">rice</span> grown through a single long season. From the mid-20th century it became the cradle of Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heavy_industry\">heavy industry</span> and the “eldest son of the Republic,” home to the giant oilfield at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Daqing\">Daqing</span>, the steelworks of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anshan\">Anshan</span>, and the country’s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"FAW_Group\">first automobile works</span>, though the decline of its state factories later turned it into a struggling <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rust_belt\">rust belt</span></b>. <br> <br> The region was long home to forest and steppe peoples such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mohe_people\">Mohe</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jurchen_people\">Jurchens</span>, who founded the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jin_dynasty_(1115–1234)\">Jin dynasty</span>, and from these the Manchus <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nurhaci\">arose</span> in the early 17th century, renaming themselves and proclaiming the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> that would conquer <b>all of China in 1644</b>. As the Qing homeland the area was for a time closed to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Chinese\">Han Chinese</span> settlement behind the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Willow_Palisade\">Willow Palisade</span>, but the bars eventually fell, unleashing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chuang_Guandong\">Chuang Guandong</span> migration in which tens of millions of land-hungry peasants from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shandong\">Shandong</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hebei\">Hebei</span> poured into the northeast. <b>By 1900</b> the region had become an arena of imperial rivalry, as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russian_Empire\">Russia</span> drove the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Eastern_Railway\">Chinese Eastern Railway</span> across it and clashed with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empire_of_Japan\">Japan</span> <b>in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russo-Japanese_War\">Russo-Japanese War</span> of 1904–1905</b>, after which the warlord <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Zuolin\">Zhang Zuolin</span> rose to dominate it. In 1931 Japan seized the whole territory after the staged <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mukden_Incident\">Mukden Incident</span> and erected the puppet state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchukuo\">Manchukuo</span> under the last Qing emperor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Puyi\">Puyi</span>, a regime notorious for the biological-warfare atrocities of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Unit_731\">Unit 731</span> near Harbin, until the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_invasion_of_Manchuria\">Soviet invasion of Manchuria</span> swept it away in 1945. The region then became a decisive battleground of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">Chinese Civil War</span> in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liaoshen_campaign\">Liaoshen campaign</span> of 1948, and with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Soviet</span> aid it was rebuilt in the 1950s into a foundation of the planned economy, today a largely Han land that still shelters a sizeable <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Koreans_in_China\">Korean</span> minority in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yanbian_Korean_Autonomous_Prefecture\">Yanbian</span> borderland.","citation":"","answerText":"Manchuria"},{"id":"cng-074","num":"七十四","category":"China · Geography","question":"A sprawling industrial and transport hub of central China formed from 3 towns where the Han joins the Yangtze, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was the site of the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> uprising that toppled the empire.","answer":"Wuhan","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">武汉, a contraction of Wuchang, Hankou and Hanyang</span></div>","traditional":"武漢","hanzi":"武汉","pinyin":"Wǔhàn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Wǔhàn</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Wuhan</b> is the capital of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hubei\">Hubei</span> and, with 12.3 million people in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2020_Chinese_census\"><b>2020</b> census</span>, the metropolis of central China, created in 1927 by merging the 3 towns of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuchang_District\">Wuchang</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hankou\">Hankou</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hanyang_District\">Hanyang</span> that face one another where the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_River_(Yangtze_River_tributary)\">Han River</span> joins the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span>, a junction so commanding that the city is proverbially the \"thoroughfare of 9 provinces.\" Strewn with some 166 lakes, including <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"East_Lake_(Wuhan)\">East Lake</span></b>, among the largest urban lakes in China, and infamous as one of the Yangtze \"furnace\" cities, the site has been strategic since the Shang outpost of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Panlongcheng\">Panlongcheng</span> rose nearby 3,500 years ago, while the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_Crane_Tower\">Yellow Crane Tower</span>, first <b>built in 223 CE</b> and celebrated in verses answered by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Bai\">Li Bai</span>, remains its poetic emblem. Opened as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_ports\">treaty port</span> in 1861, Hankou sprouted 5 foreign concessions and grew rich shipping brick tea to Russia, earning the nickname \"Chicago of China.\" In the 1890s the reforming viceroy <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Zhidong\">Zhang Zhidong</span> planted Asia's first great ironworks in Hanyang alongside the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hanyang_Arsenal\">Hanyang Arsenal</span>, whose rifles armed Chinese soldiers for half a century. The city's supreme moment <b>came on 10 October 1911</b>, when an accidental bomb blast exposed a revolutionary cell and the garrison's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuchang_Uprising\">Wuchang Uprising</span> that night ignited the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinhai_Revolution\">Xinhai Revolution</span>, toppling 2 millennia of empire within months. <br> <br> Revolution kept returning, as the left-Kuomintang government of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Jingwei\">Wang Jingwei</span> ruled from the tri-cities in 1927, and in 1938 Wuhan served as the wartime capital whose defense in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Wuhan\">Battle of Wuhan</span>, engaging over a million combatants, was the largest clash of the early <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Sino-Japanese_War\">Second Sino-Japanese War</span>. Under the People's Republic the city withstood the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1954_Yangtze_River_floods\">1954 floods</span></b>, carried the first rail crossing of the river on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuhan_Yangtze_River_Bridge\">Wuhan Yangtze River Bridge</span> in 1957, watched <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> take his famous 1966 swim in the Yangtze on the eve of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span>, and a year later saw the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuhan_incident\">Wuhan incident</span> bring armed factions to the brink of civil war. Reform remade the hub, concentrating China's <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Optical_fiber\">optical fiber</span></b> industry in the Optics Valley district, hosting <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dongfeng_Motor_Corporation\">Dongfeng</span> automobiles, and educating some 1.3 million university students, more than any other city on earth, at campuses like cherry-blossomed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuhan_University\">Wuhan University</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huazhong_University_of_Science_and_Technology\">HUST</span>, while the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuhan–Guangzhou_high-speed_railway\">Wuhan–Guangzhou high-speed railway</span> of 2009 restored the old role of national crossroads at 350 kilometers per hour (220 mph). The city entered world consciousness when the first cluster of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"COVID-19_pandemic\">COVID-19 pandemic</span> emerged in December 2019, prompting the unprecedented 76-day lockdown of 11 million people from 23 January 2020 and the construction of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huoshenshan_Hospital\">Huoshenshan Hospital</span></b> in 10 days. Recovery came with characteristic appetite, announced over steaming bowls of the breakfast <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hot_dry_noodles\">hot dry noodles</span> that no siege has ever dislodged from the Wuhan morning.","citation":"","answerText":"Wuhan"},{"id":"cng-079","num":"七十九","category":"China · Geography","question":"The largest city of the far northeast and capital of Heilongjiang, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> shaped by Russian railway builders is known for bitter winters and a famous annual ice and snow festival.","answer":"Harbin","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">哈尔滨, from Manchu, said to mean 'place for drying nets'</span></div>","traditional":"哈爾濱","hanzi":"哈尔滨","pinyin":"Hā'ěrbīn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Hā'ěrbīn</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Harbin</b> is the capital of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heilongjiang\">Heilongjiang</span> province and the largest city of the far northeast of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>, a metropolis of roughly 10 million people on the banks of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Songhua_River\">Songhua River</span></b>. It is the coldest major city in the country, dubbed the “Ice City,” where January means plunge to around −20 °C (−4 °F) and below, a climate that powers the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Harbin_International_Ice_and_Snow_Sculpture_Festival\">Harbin International Ice and Snow Sculpture Festival</span>, <b>launched in 1985</b> and now the largest event of its kind on Earth, its palaces of river ice and snow drawing millions of visitors each winter. The city is equally famed for its Russian face, crowned by the green-domed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Saint_Sophia_Cathedral_(Harbin)\">Saint Sophia Cathedral</span> of 1907 and the cobbled shopping promenade of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhongyang_Street\">Zhongyang Street</span></b>, lined with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Art_Nouveau\">Art Nouveau</span> façades that earned it the nickname “Moscow of the East.” Local culture still carries that imprint in foods such as the smoked red sausage modelled on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lithuania\">Lithuanian</span> recipes and the city’s own <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Harbin_Brewery\">Harbin Brewery</span>, <b>founded in 1900</b> as China’s first beer maker, while its conservatory tradition led <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"UNESCO\">UNESCO</span> to name Harbin a City of Music in 2010. Economically the city anchors the old industrial northeast with power-equipment, aircraft, and food industries, hosts the hub <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Harbin_Institute_of_Technology\">Harbin Institute of Technology</span>, one of China’s premier engineering universities, and serves as a gateway for trade with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russia\">Russia</span>. <br> <br> Though the region had ancient roots as the cradle of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jurchen_people\">Jurchen</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jin_dynasty_(1115–1234)\">Jin dynasty</span>, whose first capital rose <b>at nearby Acheng in 1115</b>, modern Harbin was born in 1898 as a construction headquarters of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Eastern_Railway\">Chinese Eastern Railway</span>, the shortcut the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russian_Empire\">Russian Empire</span> drove across <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchuria\">Manchuria</span> toward <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vladivostok\">Vladivostok</span>. The railway boomtown drew settlers of dozens of nationalities, and after the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russian_Revolution\">Russian Revolution</span></b> of 1917 it swelled with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"White_émigré\">White émigrés</span> into the largest Russian city outside Russia, while its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"History_of_the_Jews_in_Harbin\">Jewish community</span>, at its height some 20,000 strong, built synagogues that still stand. Darker chapters followed under Japanese rule after 1932, when Harbin fell within the puppet state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchukuo\">Manchukuo</span> and the nearby Pingfang district concealed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Unit_731\">Unit 731</span>, the germ-warfare command whose human experiments killed thousands and whose site is now a memorial museum. The city also produced heroes of the resistance, among them the <b>guerrilla commander <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhao_Shangzhi\">Zhao Shangzhi</span></b> and the martyred poet-fighter <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhao_Yiman\">Zhao Yiman</span>, and it was among the first major cities taken in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_invasion_of_Manchuria\">Soviet invasion of Manchuria</span> in 1945, then held by Communist forces as a rear base during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">Chinese Civil War</span>. After 1949 Soviet-aided plants made it a bastion of the planned economy, and though the rust-belt decades and a notorious <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2005_Jilin_chemical_plant_explosions\">benzene spill</span> that cut the city’s water for days in 2005 tested it, Harbin has lately reinvented itself through winter <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tourism_in_China\">tourism</span>, its ice festival fuelling record-breaking visitor booms in the mid-2020s.","citation":"","answerText":"Harbin"},{"id":"cng-080","num":"八十","category":"China · Geography","question":"The largest city of the northeast and capital of Liaoning, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> — once the Manchu capital of Mukden with its own imperial palace — sits at the heart of China's old heavy-industry belt.","answer":"Shenyang","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">沈阳 (Shěnyáng, 'north of the Shen river')</span></div>","traditional":"瀋陽","hanzi":"沈阳","pinyin":"Shěnyáng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Shěnyáng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Shenyang</b> is the capital of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liaoning\">Liaoning</span> and the metropolis of the Northeast, counting 9.07 million people in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2020_Chinese_census\"><b>2020</b> census</span> on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hun_River\">Hun River</span>, where settlement reaches back some 7,200 years to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinle_culture\">Xinle culture</span>. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_people\">Manchu</span> founder <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nurhaci\">Nurhaci</span> seized the <b>Ming garrison town in 1625</b> and made it capital of his <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Later_Jin_(1616–1636)\">Later Jin</span> state, after which he and his son <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Taiji\">Hong Taiji</span> raised the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mukden_Palace\">Mukden Palace</span> between 1625 and 1636, a 300-room complex blending Manchu and Chinese forms that joined the <b>World Heritage list in 2004</b>, and here in 1636 Hong Taiji proclaimed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span>. After the conquest of 1644 the city remained the dynasty's revered secondary capital, with both founders entombed in pine-shaded mausolea now inscribed among the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_Tombs_of_the_Ming_and_Qing_Dynasties\">Imperial Tombs of the Ming and Qing Dynasties</span>. The railway age made Mukden a prize, fought over in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Mukden\">Battle of Mukden</span></b> of February–March 1905, the climactic land battle of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russo-Japanese_War\">Russo-Japanese War</span> with over 600,000 combatants, the largest the world had then seen in a century. From here the warlord <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Zuolin\">Zhang Zuolin</span> and his <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fengtian_clique\">Fengtian clique</span> dominated the Northeast until Japanese officers murdered him in the 1928 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huanggutun_incident\">Huanggutun incident</span>, whereupon his son <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Xueliang\">Zhang Xueliang</span> raised the republic's flag over the city. <br> <br> On 18 September 1931 Japanese troops staged an explosion on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South_Manchuria_Railway\">South Manchuria Railway</span> in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mukden_Incident\">Mukden Incident</span>, seized the city overnight, and built the puppet state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchukuo\">Manchukuo</span>, a wound the city marks each anniversary with wailing sirens. The decisive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liaoshen_campaign\">Liaoshen campaign</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">Chinese Civil War</span> closed with Shenyang's fall on 2 November 1948, sealing the Northeast for the communists and tilting the war itself. The new state then made the city the \"eldest son of the republic,\" loading the first of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five-year_plans_of_China\">five-year plans</span> into the smokestacks of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tiexi_District,_Shenyang\">Tiexi District</span></b>, the \"Ruhr of the East,\" where machine-tool works and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shenyang_Aircraft_Corporation\">Shenyang Aircraft Corporation</span>, builder of China's jet fighters since the 1950s, anchored the national <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heavy_industry\">heavy-industry</span> belt. The 1990s brought rust-belt collapse and millions of layoffs, elegized in the 9-hour documentary <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tie_Xi_Qu:_West_of_the_Tracks\"><i>Tie Xi Qu: West of the Tracks</i></span></b>, before the 2003 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northeast_Area_Revitalization_Plan\">revitalization plan</span> and new investment turned the tide, so that the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"BMW\">BMW</span> joint venture with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Brilliance_Auto\">Brilliance</span> has grown into that automaker's largest production base in the world. Today imperial roofs glint among the mills, the Xita quarter thrums as a hub of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Koreans_in_China\">Koreans in China</span>, and the earthy Northeastern humor popularized by <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhao_Benshan\">Zhao Benshan</span></b> gives the old Manchu capital its unmistakably gritty warmth.","citation":"","answerText":"Shenyang"},{"id":"cng-081","num":"八十一","category":"China · Geography","question":"Sitting at over 3,600 m (12,000 ft) in a high valley, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the historic and religious capital of Tibet, dominated by the towering Potala Palace, former seat of the Dalai Lama.","answer":"Lhasa","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Tibetan Lhasa ('place of the gods')</span></div>","traditional":"拉薩","hanzi":"拉萨","pinyin":"Lāsà","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Lāsà</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“place of the gods”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Lhasa</b> is the historic and religious capital of Tibet and the seat of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibet_Autonomous_Region\">Tibet Autonomous Region</span>, lying at about 3,650 metres (12,000 ft) in the valley of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lhasa_River\">Lhasa River</span>, a tributary of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yarlung_Tsangpo\">Yarlung Tsangpo</span></b>, which makes it one of the highest cities on Earth. The skyline is commanded by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Potala_Palace\">Potala Palace</span>, the fortress-monastery of about 1,000 rooms rising 13 storeys from the Red Hill that served as winter seat of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dalai_Lama\">Dalai Lamas</span> and was inscribed <b>as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Heritage_Site\">World Heritage Site</span> in 1994</b>, an ensemble later extended to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jokhang\">Jokhang</span> temple and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Norbulingka\">Norbulingka</span> summer palace. The 7th-century Jokhang enshrines a revered statue of the young <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gautama_Buddha\">Buddha</span>, the holiest image in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_Buddhism\">Tibetan Buddhism</span>, around which pilgrims still prostrate along the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Barkhor\">Barkhor</span> circuit in the ritual clockwise <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kora_(pilgrimage)\">kora</span>. Ringing the city stand the three great seats of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gelug\">Gelug</span> school, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ganden_Monastery\">Ganden</span> <b>founded in 1409</b> by the reformer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Je_Tsongkhapa\">Tsongkhapa</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Drepung_Monastery\">Drepung</span> of 1416, once the largest monastery in the world with perhaps 10,000 monks, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sera_Monastery\">Sera</span> of 1419, famed for its debating courtyards. Basking in roughly 3,000 hours of sunshine a year as the “sunlit city,” modern Lhasa holds under a million people and has been bound to the rest of China <b>since 2006</b> by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qinghai–Tibet_railway\">Qinghai–Tibet railway</span>, joined in 2021 by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lhasa–Nyingchi_railway\">Lhasa–Nyingchi railway</span>, arteries that feed a tourism boom now numbering millions of visitors annually. <br> <br> The city rose to greatness around 633, when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Songtsen_Gampo\">Songtsen Gampo</span> made it the capital of the expanding <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_Empire\">Tibetan Empire</span>, raised a palace on the Red Hill, and founded the Jokhang to house sacred images associated with his Nepali bride <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bhrikuti\">Bhrikuti</span> and his <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span> bride <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Princess_Wencheng\">Princess Wencheng</span>. After the empire’s collapse in the 9th century Lhasa languished for centuries, until the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"5th_Dalai_Lama\">5th Dalai Lama</span></b>, backed by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khoshut\">Khoshut</span> Mongol ruler <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Güshi_Khan\">Güshi Khan</span>, unified Tibet in 1642, established the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ganden_Phodrang\">Ganden Phodrang</span> government, and in 1645 began the Potala that restored the city’s primacy. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> expelled an occupying force of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dzungar_Khanate\">Dzungar Khanate</span> in 1720 and from 1727 stationed resident <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Amban\">ambans</span> in the city, while in 1904 the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"British_expedition_to_Tibet\">British expedition</span></b> under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Francis_Younghusband\">Francis Younghusband</span> fought its way to Lhasa and dictated a treaty in the Potala’s shadow. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army\">People’s Liberation Army</span> arrived after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Seventeen_Point_Agreement\">Seventeen Point Agreement</span> of 1951, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1959_Tibetan_uprising\">1959 Tibetan uprising</span> that erupted around the Norbulingka ended with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"14th_Dalai_Lama\">14th Dalai Lama</span> fleeing into exile at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dharamshala\">Dharamshala</span>. Lhasa has since seen waves of unrest, from the protests that brought martial law in 1989 to the deadly riots of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2008_Tibetan_unrest\">2008 Tibetan unrest</span></b>, and it remains the contested heart of Tibet, transformed by Han migration, development, and pilgrimage alike beneath the unchanged white-and-crimson mass of the Potala.","citation":"","answerText":"Lhasa"},{"id":"cng-084","num":"八十四","category":"China · Geography","question":"A breezy port city on the Shandong Peninsula with red-roofed German colonial architecture, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is famous for the beer founded there in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>.","answer":"Qingdao","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">青岛 (Qīngdǎo, 'green island')</span></div>","traditional":"青島","hanzi":"青岛","pinyin":"Qīngdǎo","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Qīngdǎo</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Azure Island”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Qingdao</b> is a port city of 10.07 million in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2020_Chinese_census\">2020 census</span> on the southern shore of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shandong_Peninsula\">Shandong Peninsula</span>, wrapped around <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiaozhou_Bay\">Jiaozhou Bay</span></b> where the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_Sea\">Yellow Sea</span> breezes cool its slogan-famous red tiles, green trees, and azure water. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"German_Empire\">German Empire</span> seized the <b>fishing harbor in 1897</b> after the murder of 2 missionaries in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Juye_Incident\">Juye Incident</span>, extracting the 99-year <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kiautschou_Bay_Leased_Territory\">Kiautschou lease</span> in 1898 and building a model colony of planned boulevards, the villa quarter of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Badaguan\">Badaguan</span>, hilltop churches later joined by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"St._Michael's_Cathedral,_Qingdao\">St. Michael's Cathedral</span>, and a railway to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jinan\">Jinan</span> <b>opened in 1904</b>. In 1903 Anglo-German investors founded the Germania brewery that became <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tsingtao_Brewery\">Tsingtao Brewery</span>, brewing with spring water credited to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mount_Lao\">Mount Lao</span> into China's most famous export label. The colony fell in the <b>1914 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Siege_of_Tsingtao\">Siege of Tsingtao</span></b>, when Japanese and British forces stormed the forts while seaplanes from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japanese_seaplane_carrier_Wakamiya\">Wakamiya</span> flew some of history's first carrier-launched air raids. Japan's refusal to return the territory created the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shandong_Problem\">Shandong Problem</span> that ignited the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"May_Fourth_Movement\">May Fourth Movement</span> in 1919, and only the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Washington_Naval_Conference\">Washington Naval Conference</span> restored Qingdao to China in 1922, a deliverance the city commemorates in its central May Fourth Square. <br> <br> Between the wars the breezy town drew China's literati, with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lao_She\">Lao She</span> writing his masterpiece <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rickshaw_Boy\"><i>Rickshaw Boy</i></span></b> here in 1936 and the aged reformer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kang_Youwei\">Kang Youwei</span> spending his final years above the bay. The deep harbor now serves the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army_Navy\">People's Liberation Army Navy</span>, whose northern forces are headquartered here and whose first aircraft carrier, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_aircraft_carrier_Liaoning\">Liaoning</span>, is homeported nearby. Commerce matches the fleet, for the city headquarters the appliance giants <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Haier\">Haier</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hisense\">Hisense</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Port_of_Qingdao\">Port of Qingdao</span> ranks around 5th among the world's container harbors at some 26 million TEU, the 26.7-kilometer (16.6 mi) <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiaozhou_Bay_Bridge\">Jiaozhou Bay Bridge</span> spans the bay, and the city hosted the sailing regattas of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2008_Summer_Olympics\">2008 Summer Olympics</span> and the 2018 summit of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_Cooperation_Organisation\">Shanghai Cooperation Organisation</span></b>. Beer remains the civic religion, celebrated since 1991 at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qingdao_International_Beer_Festival\">Qingdao International Beer Festival</span>, Asia's largest, while locals famously carry fresh draft home in plastic bags to pour over plates of clams. The newest identity is cinematic, since UNESCO named Qingdao a City of Film in its <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Creative_Cities_Network\">Creative Cities Network</span></b> in 2017 and blockbusters like <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Wandering_Earth\"><i>The Wandering Earth</i></span> were shot on its vast new soundstages, so that a town of Bavarian gables now manufactures Chinese science fiction between sips of its own lager.","citation":"","answerText":"Qingdao"},{"id":"cnh-092","num":"九十二","category":"China · History","question":"A decree imposed on the conquered Han Chinese population requiring all men, on pain of death, to shave the front of the head and wear the hair in a long braided queue in the Manchu style, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> provoked fierce resistance and massacres in the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>s.","answer":"Queue Order","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1645</span></div>","traditional":"剃髮令","hanzi":"剃发令","pinyin":"tìfàlìng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">tìfàlìng</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“order to shave the hair”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Queue Order</b> was a series of decrees by which the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> compelled the conquered <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Chinese\">Han Chinese</span> male population to adopt the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_people\">Manchu</span></b> hairstyle on pain of death. The mandated style required men to shave the front of the head—a forced <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tonsure\">tonsure</span>—and to braid the remaining hair into a single long <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Queue_(hairstyle)\">queue</span>, a fashion utterly alien to Han custom. It struck at the heart of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> values, for the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Classic_of_Filial_Piety\"><i>Classic of Filial Piety</i></span></b> taught that the body and hair were received from one's parents and must not be harmed, so that Han men had long grown their hair and bound it in a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Topknot\">topknot</span> as a mark of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Filial_piety\">filial piety</span>. An initial order issued after the <b>1644 capture</b> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>, secured through the defection of the general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Sangui\">Wu Sangui</span>, was withdrawn amid outrage, but in 1645, after the fall of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Southern_Ming\">Southern Ming</span> during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Transition_from_Ming_to_Qing\">Manchu conquest</span>, the regent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dorgon\">Dorgon</span>, governing for the boy <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shunzhi_Emperor\">Shunzhi Emperor</span>, reimposed it with merciless rigor. Pressed by the Han collaborator <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Zhixie\">Sun Zhixie</span>, the decree was enforced under the chilling slogan that a man might keep his hair or keep his head, and it was soon coupled with orders to replace traditional <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hanfu\">Han clothing</span> with Manchu dress. <br> <br> The <b>1645 enforcement</b> ignited ferocious resistance, above all in the wealthy <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiangnan\">Jiangnan</span> region of the lower <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span>, and was answered with savage reprisals by the Qing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight_Banners\">Banner armies</span> against the towns that defied it. At Yangzhou the loyalist commander <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shi_Kefa\">Shi Kefa</span>, defending the court of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hongguang_Emperor\">Hongguang Emperor</span></b>, was overwhelmed, and the Qing prince <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dodo,_Prince_Yu\">Dodo</span> unleashed the 10-day <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangzhou_massacre\">Yangzhou massacre</span>, whose traditional death toll—almost certainly exaggerated—was reckoned in the hundreds of thousands. The town of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiangyin\">Jiangyin</span> held out in a famous 81-day siege before being put to the sword, while nearby Jiading was massacred repeatedly by the <b>turncoat general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Chengdong\">Li Chengdong</span></b> in the episodes remembered as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiading_massacre\">Three Massacres of Jiading</span>. Once imposed, the queue became the inescapable badge of submission to Qing rule and a standing test of loyalty for nearly 270 years, so that to cut it off was an act of open rebellion, as it was among the long-haired insurgents of the later <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiping_Rebellion\">Taiping Rebellion</span>. The hated hairstyle was finally cast off only with the collapse of the dynasty <b>in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinhai_Revolution\">Xinhai Revolution</span> of 1911</b>, when the mass cutting of queues across the country became a potent emblem of liberation from Manchu rule and of the new <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)\">Republic</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Queue Order"},{"id":"cnh-093","num":"九十三","category":"China · History","question":"Ascending the throne as a child and reigning for 61 years — among the longest in history — the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> crushed the Revolt of the Three Feudatories, annexed Taiwan, fixed the Russian border, and sponsored a great dictionary of Chinese characters.","answer":"Kangxi Emperor","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">May 4, 1654</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">December 20, 1722</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"康熙","pinyin":"Kāngxī","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Kāngxī</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“peaceful and flourishing”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Kangxi Emperor</b> was an emperor of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> whose reign of 61 years remains the longest of any sovereign in Chinese history. A son of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shunzhi_Emperor\">Shunzhi Emperor</span>, he came <b>to the throne in 1661</b> at the age of 7, reportedly chosen in part because he had already survived <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Smallpox\">smallpox</span>, and a council of regents governed in his name until he asserted personal rule in 1669 by arresting the overbearing regent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Oboi\">Oboi</span>. He then secured the young dynasty against its gravest internal challenge, doggedly suppressing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Revolt_of_the_Three_Feudatories\">Revolt of the Three Feudatories</span> led by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Sangui\">Wu Sangui</span> in a war that raged <b>from 1673</b> to 1681 and at its height engulfed most of southern China. In 1683 his admiral <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shi_Lang\">Shi Lang</span> destroyed the fleet of the Ming-loyalist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kingdom_of_Tungning\">Kingdom of Tungning</span>, founded by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Koxinga\">Koxinga</span>, at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Penghu\">Battle of Penghu</span></b>, bringing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span> under direct imperial rule for the first time. Turning to the frontiers, he checked Tsarist expansion along the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Amur\">Amur</span> <b>through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Nerchinsk\">Treaty of Nerchinsk</span> of 1689</b>—China's first treaty with a European power—and personally led campaigns that crushed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dzungar_Khanate\">Dzungar</span> chieftain <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Galdan_Boshugtu_Khan\">Galdan</span> at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Jao_Modo\">Battle of Jao Modo</span> in 1696. <br> <br> His campaigns drew the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khalkha_Mongols\">Khalkha Mongols</span></b> of the north under Qing protection and culminated in an expedition that expelled rival Mongols from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibet\">Tibet</span> and installed a friendly Dalai Lama at Lhasa, extending Qing overlordship across Inner Asia. A learned patron of scholarship, he ordered the compilation of the monumental <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kangxi_Dictionary\"><i>Kangxi Dictionary</i></span></b>, which between 1710 and 1716 catalogued more than 47,000 characters arranged under 214 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kangxi_radical\">radicals</span>, and he likewise sponsored the vast poetry anthology <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Quan_Tangshi\"><i>Quan Tangshi</i></span> and championed orthodox <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Neo-Confucianism\">Neo-Confucianism</span>. Intensely curious about Western learning, he employed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jesuits\">Jesuit</span> savants such <b>as the astronomer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ferdinand_Verbiest\">Ferdinand Verbiest</span></b> and for a time tolerated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Christianity\">Christianity</span>, until the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Rites_controversy\">Chinese Rites controversy</span> over ancestral veneration soured his relations with the papacy. At home he lightened taxes, undertook major works to tame the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_River\">Yellow River</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Grand_Canal_(China)\">Grand Canal</span>, toured the prosperous south to court its elites, and famously capped the empire's poll-tax quota in a measure that eased the burden on a fast-growing population. His later years were clouded by a ferocious struggle for the succession among his many sons, which led him twice to depose his heir apparent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yinreng\">Yinreng</span>, and on his death in 1722 the throne passed amid controversy to his 4th son, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yongzheng_Emperor\">Yongzheng Emperor</span>, inaugurating with the later reign of his grandson the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qianlong_Emperor\">Qianlong Emperor</span> the flourishing era known as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"High_Qing_era\">High Qing</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Kangxi Emperor"},{"id":"cnh-094","num":"九十四","category":"China · History","question":"A dangerous rebellion of the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>s led by Wu Sangui and other Chinese generals granted vast semi-autonomous fiefs in the south for aiding the conquest, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was suppressed by the young Kangxi Emperor, consolidating Manchu control of the south.","answer":"Revolt of the Three Feudatories","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1673–1681</span></div>","traditional":"三藩之亂","hanzi":"三藩之乱","pinyin":"Sānfān zhī luàn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Sānfān zhī luàn</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Revolt of the Three Feudatories</b> was a dangerous rebellion against the early <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span>, mounted by three powerful <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Chinese\">Han Chinese</span> generals who had been granted vast semi-autonomous domains in southern China. The three were <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Sangui\">Wu Sangui</span></b>, the dominant figure, who held <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yunnan\">Yunnan</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guizhou\">Guizhou</span>; <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shang_Kexi\">Shang Kexi</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangdong\">Guangdong</span>; and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Geng_Jingzhong\">Geng Jingzhong</span></b> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fujian\">Fujian</span>. All three had defected from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span> and earned their fiefs by aiding the Manchu <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Transition_from_Ming_to_Qing\">conquest</span> of the south, Wu Sangui most notoriously having <b>opened the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanhai_Pass\">Shanhai Pass</span> in 1644</b> and later hunting down the last <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Southern_Ming\">Southern Ming</span> claimant, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yongli_Emperor\">Yongli Emperor</span>. Within their <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fief\">fiefs</span> the three commanded their own armies, levied their own taxes, and ruled almost as independent kings, and their upkeep is said to have devoured a large share of the revenue of the Qing court at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>. The young <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kangxi_Emperor\">Kangxi Emperor</span>, who had already asserted his personal rule by purging the regent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Oboi\">Oboi</span>, resolved to dismantle these overmighty domains, and <b>in 1673</b> he ordered the abolition of all three. <br> <br> Wu Sangui rose in revolt late in 1673 and was quickly joined by Geng Jingzhong and by Shang Kexi's son <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shang_Zhixin\">Shang Zhixin</span>, their forces overrunning much of the south and southwest from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hunan\">Hunan</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan\">Sichuan</span> to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangxi\">Guangxi</span>, while the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kingdom_of_Tungning\">Kingdom of Tungning</span> under <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zheng_Jing\">Zheng Jing</span></b> raided the Fujian coast from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span>. Refusing all compromise, the emperor marshalled the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Green_Standard_Army\">Green Standard Army</span> of Han troops alongside the Manchu <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight_Banners\">banners</span> and directed a patient, methodical counter-offensive. The rebel coalition gradually fractured, for Wu Sangui hesitated to push north across the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span>, and the hard-pressed Geng Jingzhong and Shang Zhixin abandoned the rebellion and submitted to the Qing. In a final bid for legitimacy Wu Sangui proclaimed himself emperor of a <b>new Zhou dynasty in 1678</b>, but he died of illness only months later, leaving the cause to his grandson <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Shifan\">Wu Shifan</span>. Wu Shifan proved unable to hold the rump rebellion together and took his own life as imperial troops stormed the Yunnan capital of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kunming\">Kunming</span> in 1681, a victory that cemented direct <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_people\">Manchu</span> control over the south, opened the way to the conquest of Taiwan at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Penghu\">Battle of Penghu</span></b> in 1683, and ushered in the prosperous era historians call the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"High_Qing_era\">High Qing</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Revolt of the Three Feudatories"},{"id":"cnh-096","num":"九十六","category":"China · History","question":"A hardworking and ruthless ruler who came to power amid a bitter succession struggle, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> tightened central control by creating a secret Grand Council and cracking down on corruption, bringing his father Kangxi's era of expansion into a period of stern consolidation before passing the throne to his son.","answer":"Yongzheng Emperor","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">December 13, 1678</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">October 8, 1735</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"雍正","pinyin":"Yōngzhèng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Yōngzhèng</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“harmonious and upright”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Yongzheng Emperor</b> was the 4th son of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kangxi_Emperor\">Kangxi Emperor</span></b> and an emperor of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> whose brief but transformative reign formed a crucial link in the flourishing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"High_Qing_era\">High Qing era</span>, bridging the long rules of his father and his own son. He seized the throne on <b>his father's death in 1722</b> amid a vicious contest among Kangxi's numerous sons, the so-called struggle that had already seen the crown prince <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yinreng\">Yinreng</span> twice deposed, and persistent rumors held that he had tampered with the imperial will. Once enthroned, he ruthlessly neutralized his rival brothers, foremost among them the 8th prince <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yinsi\">Yinsi</span>, stripping them of rank, imposing degrading new names, and confining several until their deaths. To forestall such crises in the future, he devised a system of secret succession, sealing the name of his chosen heir in a box concealed behind a plaque in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Forbidden_City\">Forbidden City</span> rather than naming a crown prince openly. He tightened central authority above all by establishing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Grand_Council_(Qing_dynasty)\">Grand Council</span>, a small inner cabinet that soon eclipsed the older <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Grand_Secretariat\">Grand Secretariat</span>, and by expanding the use of confidential <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Palace_memorial\">palace memorials</span></b> that let him monitor officials directly. <br> <br> A relentless worker who pored over state papers late into the night, he pressed vigorous campaigns against official corruption, granted bureaucrats generous salary supplements to discourage graft, completed the great fiscal reform that folded the per-head poll tax into the land tax, and rebuilt a depleted treasury whose silver reserve reportedly climbed to roughly 60 million <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tael\">taels</span> by the end of his short reign. On the frontiers he prosecuted his father's war against the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dzungar_Khanate\">Dzungar Khanate</span>, asserted firmer control over <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibet\">Tibet</span> by stationing resident <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Amban\">ambans</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lhasa\">Lhasa</span>, and in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guizhou\">Guizhou</span> and the wider southwest pressed the <b>policy of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gaitu_Guiliu\">gaitu guiliu</span></b>, replacing hereditary native <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tusi\">chieftains</span> with appointed officials and suppressing revolts among the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Miao_people\">Miao</span>. A devout student of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chan_Buddhism\">Chan Buddhism</span>, he nonetheless upheld <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> orthodoxy by promulgating an amplified version of his father's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sacred_Edict_of_the_Kangxi_Emperor\">Sacred Edict</span>, and <b>in 1724</b> he banned <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Christianity\">Christianity</span> in the wake of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Rites_controversy\">Chinese Rites controversy</span>, expelling most missionaries while retaining a few <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jesuits\">Jesuits</span> for their technical skills. When the scholar <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zeng_Jing\">Zeng Jing</span>, inspired by the anti-Manchu writings of the late-Ming loyalist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lü_Liuliang\">Lü Liuliang</span>, was caught in a seditious plot, the emperor remarkably engaged him in debate and published the treatise <i>Dayi Juemi Lu</i> in defense of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_people\">Manchu</span> rule, even as his reign saw the early stirrings of the Qing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Literary_inquisition\">literary inquisition</span>. He <b>died suddenly in 1735</b>, possibly poisoned by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Daoist</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_alchemy\">elixirs</span> he had taken in search of longevity, and his sealed succession edict passed the throne smoothly to his son the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qianlong_Emperor\">Qianlong Emperor</span>; buried at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Western_Qing_tombs\">Western Qing tombs</span></b>, he is remembered as an austere and exacting reformer who left a strengthened state and a full treasury.","citation":"","answerText":"Yongzheng Emperor"},{"id":"cnh-095","num":"九十五","category":"China · History","question":"Signed in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> and negotiated with help from Jesuit interpreters, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> — the first between China and a European power on equal terms — fixed the border with Russia along the Amur region, halting Russian expansion southward.","answer":"Treaty of Nerchinsk","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1689</span></div>","traditional":"尼布楚條約","hanzi":"尼布楚条约","pinyin":"Níbùchǔ Tiáoyuē","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Níbùchǔ Tiáoyuē</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Treaty of Nerchinsk</b> was an agreement between the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> of China and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tsardom_of_Russia\">Tsardom of Russia</span></b>, the first accord China ever signed with a European power on terms of genuine equality. It arose from decades of friction as Russian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cossacks\">Cossacks</span> and settlers pushed eastward across <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Siberia\">Siberia</span> into the basin of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Amur_River\">Amur River</span>, encroaching on territory claimed by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_people\">Manchu</span> rulers in their homeland of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchuria\">Manchuria</span>. The flashpoint was the Russian fort of Albazin, which the armies of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kangxi_Emperor\">Kangxi Emperor</span> reduced <b>in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Siege_of_Albazin\">sieges of Albazin</span> of 1685</b> and 1686, after which both sides agreed to negotiate. The talks <b>convened in 1689</b> at the Siberian town of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nerchinsk\">Nerchinsk</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Transbaikal\">Transbaikalia</span>, where the Qing envoy <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Songgotu\">Songgotu</span> faced the Russian plenipotentiary <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fyodor_Golovin\">Fyodor Golovin</span></b>, then acting for the regency of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sophia_Alekseyevna\">Sophia Alekseyevna</span> and the young tsar <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peter_the_Great\">Peter the Great</span>. Because neither delegation could speak the other's tongue, a pair of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jesuits\">Jesuit</span> missionaries at the Qing court, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jean-François_Gerbillon\">Jean-François Gerbillon</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tomás_Pereira\">Tomás Pereira</span>, served as interpreters and mediators, conducting the proceedings in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Latin\">Latin</span>. <br> <br> Under its terms Russia abandoned the Amur valley and the fort of Albazin, and the frontier between Qing China and Russia—the first defined <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China–Russia_border\">Sino-Russian border</span></b>—was fixed along the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Argun_River_(Asia)\">Argun River</span> and the watershed of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stanovoy_Range\">Stanovoy Range</span>, leaving the whole Amur basin, the Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heilongjiang\">Heilongjiang</span>, in Qing hands. The authoritative text was drafted in Latin, with parallel versions in Russian and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_language\">Manchu</span>, and the agreement also regulated cross-border trade and the surrender of fugitives. Remarkably, the treaty was negotiated outside China's usual <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tributary_system_of_China\">tributary framework</span> and on a footing of equality, in sharp contrast to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Unequal_treaty\">unequal treaties</span> that foreign powers would impose on a weakened Qing in the 19th century. By pacifying the northern border it freed the Kangxi Emperor to turn his full attention against the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dzungar_Khanate\">Dzungar Khanate</span>, and it was <b>complemented in 1727</b> by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Kyakhta_(1727)\">Treaty of Kyakhta</span>, which delimited the frontier farther west across <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongolia\">Mongolia</span>. The settlement held for some 170 years until a militarily eclipsed China was forced to cede the Amur lands to Russia by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Aigun\">Treaty of Aigun</span> of 1858 and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Convention_of_Peking\">Convention of Peking</span> of 1860, yet Nerchinsk endures as a landmark of early-modern diplomacy and of the Qing empire at its zenith.","citation":"","answerText":"Treaty of Nerchinsk"},{"id":"cnh-097","num":"九十七","category":"China · History","question":"Presiding over the territorial and cultural zenith of his dynasty during a reign of 60 years, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> sponsored a colossal literary compilation, yet saw corruption fester and rebuffed the British envoy who sought trade in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>.","answer":"Qianlong Emperor","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1711–1799</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"乾隆","pinyin":"Qiánlóng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Qiánlóng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Qianlong Emperor</b> was the fourth emperor of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_people\">Manchu</span> <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span></b> dynasty to reign over China proper, presiding over the territorial and cultural zenith of his house during the period known as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"High_Qing_era\">High Qing</span>. A grandson of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kangxi_Emperor\">Kangxi Emperor</span> and son of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yongzheng_Emperor\">Yongzheng Emperor</span>, he ruled <b>from 1735</b> until 1796, when he formally abdicated after exactly 60 years so as not to surpass his revered grandfather, though he retained real power as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taishang_Huang\">retired emperor</span> until his death. He prosecuted a series of expensive frontier wars that he celebrated as his <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ten_Great_Campaigns\">Ten Great Campaigns</span>, the most consequential of which destroyed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dzungar_Khanate\">Dzungar Khanate</span> in a campaign so ruthless that it amounted to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dzungar_genocide\">genocide</span>, and annexed the vast oasis lands of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tarim_Basin\">Tarim Basin</span>. These conquests incorporated the new dominion of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinjiang\">Xinjiang</span> and roughly doubled the size of the empire, while further expeditions into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jinchuan_campaigns\">Jinchuan</span> highlands, against the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Konbaung_dynasty\">Burmese</span>, and in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-Nepalese_War\">Gurkha war</span></b> confirmed Qing mastery over <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibet\">Tibet</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongolia\">Mongolia</span> at the empire's greatest territorial extent. An avid patron of letters and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_painting\">painting</span>, he commissioned the monumental <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Siku_Quanshu\"><i>Siku Quanshu</i></span></b>, a compendium of some 3,400 works running to roughly 36,000 manuscript volumes, even as the same project served as a vast <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Literary_Inquisition\">literary inquisition</span> in which thousands of texts judged seditious were censored or destroyed. <br> <br> The latter decades of his reign were nonetheless corroded by rampant corruption, epitomised by his favourite <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heshen\">Heshen</span>, who exploited the emperor's indulgence to amass a private fortune reputedly worth hundreds of millions of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tael\">taels</span> of silver, perhaps the equal of years of state revenue. <b>In 1793</b> he received the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Macartney_Embassy\">Macartney Embassy</span>, the first major British diplomatic mission to China, whose envoy <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"George_Macartney,_1st_Earl_Macartney\">George Macartney</span> sought expanded trade and a permanent legation in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>. After a dispute over whether Macartney would perform the ritual <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kowtow\">kowtow</span>, the emperor rebuffed these overtures in a celebrated edict to King <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"George_III\">George III</span></b> that insisted China possessed all things and had no need of British manufactures, confining foreign commerce to the tightly regulated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Canton_System\">Canton System</span> of the Qing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tributary_system_of_China\">tributary</span> order. Beneath the splendour, however, the empire was strained by a population that had roughly doubled to some 300 million over the 18th century and by the decay of the once-formidable <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight_Banners\">banner</span> armies, while his final years were troubled by the outbreak of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"White_Lotus_Rebellion\">White Lotus Rebellion</span>. He <b>died in 1799</b> as one of the longest-lived rulers in Chinese history, and his son the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiaqing_Emperor\">Jiaqing Emperor</span> at once forced Heshen to commit suicide and confiscated his colossal estate, yet the corruption and complacency of the late Qianlong era are widely seen as the point at which the fortunes of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Aisin_Gioro\">Aisin Gioro</span> dynasty began their long decline.","citation":"","answerText":"Qianlong Emperor"},{"id":"cnc-096","num":"九十六","category":"China · Culture","question":"Born into a once-wealthy family that fell from imperial favour, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> poured his memories of vanished splendour into a sprawling, semi-autobiographical novel he left unfinished at his death, the masterpiece of Chinese vernacular literature.","answer":"Cao Xueqin","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. 1715</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. 1763</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"曹雪芹","pinyin":"Cáo Xuěqín","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Cáo Xuěqín</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Cao Xueqin</b> was an impoverished <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> writer who poured his memories of vanished splendour into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dream_of_the_Red_Chamber\"><i>Dream of the Red Chamber</i></span>, the unfinished, semi-autobiographical <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Novel\">novel</span></b> acclaimed as the masterpiece of Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vernacular_Chinese\">vernacular</span> literature. His family were Han <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Booi_Aha\">bondservants</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight_Banners\">Eight Banners</span> raised to dazzling fortune when his great-grandmother nursed the future <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kangxi_Emperor\">Kangxi Emperor</span>, and his grandfather <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cao_Yin\">Cao Yin</span></b> ran the lucrative imperial <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk\">silk</span> manufactory at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span>, hosting the emperor 4 times on his southern tours of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiangnan\">Jiangnan</span> and supervising the printing <b>of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Quan_Tangshi\"><i>Complete Tang Poems</i></span> in 1705</b>. The glory ended abruptly when the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yongzheng_Emperor\">Yongzheng Emperor</span> confiscated the family's property in 1727–1728 for deficits and factional taint, exiling the clan to straitened obscurity in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>. The adult Cao lived poor in the city's western hills near the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fragrant_Hills\">Fragrant Hills</span>, selling paintings of rocks and trading verses with banner friends who recall him eating porridge and buying wine on credit, while by his own account he spent 10 years on his book through 5 revisions. He <b>died around 1763</b>, reportedly broken by his young son's death, leaving 80 chapters circulating in hand copies annotated by the mysterious intimate commentator known as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhiyanzhai\">Zhiyanzhai</span>, \"Red Inkstone.\" <br> <br> The novel, also titled <i>The Story of the Stone</i> after the sentient stone left over from the goddess <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nüwa\">Nüwa</span>'s repair of heaven, <b>reached print only in 1791–1792</b>, when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gao_E\">Gao E</span> and his partner issued 120 chapters, the last 40 of contested authorship. Within its hundreds of characters revolves the triangle of the pampered heir <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jia_Baoyu\">Jia Baoyu</span>, the brilliant, dying <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lin_Daiyu\">Lin Daiyu</span>, and the dutiful <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xue_Baochai\">Xue Baochai</span> amid the poetry clubs of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Grand_View_Garden\">Grand View Garden</span></b>, the whole suffused with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Buddhism\">Buddhist</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taoism\">Taoist</span> intimations that splendour is dream. The Jia mansion's rise, raid, and ruin so mirror the Cao family's that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Shih\">Hu Shih</span>'s pioneering studies of 1921, armed with the Zhiyanzhai manuscripts, established author and autobiography at the heart of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Redology\">Redology</span>, the scholarly industry the book sustains. The author had foreseen mixed readings, opening with the quatrain confessing \"pages full of idle words, a handful of bitter tears.\" His tears conquered <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_literature\">Chinese literature</span> and beyond, through the 5-volume English version begun by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"David_Hawkes_(sinologist)\">David Hawkes</span> for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Penguin_Classics\">Penguin Classics</span>, the <b>beloved 36-episode <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dream_of_the_Red_Chamber_(1987_TV_series)\">1987 television series</span></b>, and the homage of readers from scholars to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>, who claimed to have read the novel 5 times.","citation":"","answerText":"Cao Xueqin"},{"id":"em-007","num":"七","category":"Qing Foreign Relations · Maritime Trade","question":"A guild of licensed Chinese merchants granted a monopoly over foreign trade at Canton, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> alone was permitted to deal with European firms such as the East India Company and was held responsible for the conduct of the foreign traders.","answer":"Cohong","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Cantonese 公行 (gōngháng, ‘official merchant guild’); formed 1720</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"公行","pinyin":"gōngháng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">gōngháng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Cohong</b> was the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guild\">guild</span> of licensed Chinese merchant</b> houses that held a government-sanctioned <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Monopoly\">monopoly</span> over all foreign maritime trade conducted at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou\">Canton</span> during the late <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> period. First <b>organised in 1720</b> under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kangxi_Emperor\">Kangxi Emperor</span> and made central after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qianlong_Emperor\">Qianlong Emperor</span> confined all Western commerce to the single <b>port of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangdong\">Guangdong</span> in 1757</b>, the guild anchored the so-called <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Canton_System\">Canton System</span>, the regulatory regime that channeled China's dealings with Europe outside the formal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tributary_system_of_China\">tributary system</span>. Its members were the only Chinese permitted to deal with foreign firms such as the British <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"East_India_Company\">East India Company</span></b>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dutch_East_India_Company\">Dutch East India Company</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Swedish_East_India_Company\">Swedish East India Company</span>, along with the American houses of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Old_China_Trade\">Old China Trade</span>, and they alone could lawfully sell <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tea\">tea</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk\">silk</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_export_porcelain\">export porcelain</span> to the West. The number of licensed firms typically hovered around 13, lending its name to the riverside row of foreign <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Factory_(trading_post)\">factories</span> known as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Thirteen_Factories\">Thirteen Factories</span>, which crowded the banks of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pearl_River_(China)\">Pearl River</span> just beyond the city walls. Serving as brokers, guarantors, and collectors of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Customs\">customs</span> duties, the merchants were held jointly responsible for the debts and personal conduct of the foreigners, who were barred from approaching officials directly and were hemmed in by restrictive rules that limited their movements, excluded their women, and obliged them to depart once the trading season had closed. <br> <br> Several hong merchants amassed colossal fortunes, the most celebrated being <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Howqua\">Howqua</span>, whose assets were estimated at roughly 26 million silver dollars in the 1830s and who was reputed to rank among the wealthiest individuals in the world, while the earlier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Puankhequa\">Puankhequa</span> had been instrumental in organising and leading the guild. Commerce flowed heavily in China's favour, as European and American firms carried home more than 30 million pounds of tea a year and paid for it largely in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Spanish_dollar\">silver dollars</span>, while the everyday transactions of the waterfront were conducted in the hybrid jargon of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Pidgin_English\">Chinese Pidgin English</span></b>. This balance began to tip after the East India Company lost its China monopoly in 1834 and private merchants flooded the market with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Opium\">opium</span> to reverse the outflow of silver, a crisis that drove the imperial commissioner <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lin_Zexu\">Lin Zexu</span> to confiscate and destroy more than 20,000 chests of the drug at the port in 1839. British merchants had long resented the constraints of the system, a grievance already voiced by the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Macartney_Embassy\">Macartney Embassy</span></b> of 1793, and the dispute over opium escalated into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Opium_War\">First Opium War</span>, which the Qing decisively lost. The resulting <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Nanking\">Treaty of Nanking</span> of 1842</b> abolished the guild's monopoly, ceded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span> to Britain, and opened 5 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_ports\">treaty ports</span> such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span> to direct foreign commerce, and the old factory district was itself consumed by fire during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Opium_War\">Second Opium War</span> in 1856.","citation":"","answerText":"Cohong"},{"id":"em-006","num":"六","category":"Qing Foreign Relations · Maritime Trade","question":"Confining European merchants from 1757 to a single southern port and forbidding them direct contact with officials, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> channelled all foreign commerce through licensed monopoly merchants at Canton, a regime resented by British traders seeking to sell more opium.","answer":"Canton System","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Began</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1757 · trade confined to Canton</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Ended</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1842 · Treaty of Nanking</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"一口通商","pinyin":"yīkǒu tōngshāng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">yīkǒu tōngshāng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Canton System</b> was the restrictive commercial framework through which the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> regulated and confined Western maritime trade <b>between 1757</b> and <b>1842</b>, channelling all European seaborne commerce through the single southern port of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou\">Canton</span> on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pearl_River_(China)\">Pearl River</span> delta. Maritime trade had been permitted at several coastal customs houses after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kangxi_Emperor\">Kangxi Emperor</span> <b>reopened foreign commerce in 1684</b>, but in 1757 the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qianlong_Emperor\">Qianlong Emperor</span> abruptly closed the ports of Amoy, Ningbo, and others, restricting Westerners to Canton alone out of concern for coastal security and cultural contamination. All transactions were funnelled through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cohong\">Cohong</span>, a state-licensed guild of roughly a dozen Chinese merchant houses who alone were permitted to trade with and stand surety for foreigners, the latter being confined to a cramped riverside enclave of warehouses and lodgings known as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Thirteen_Factories\">Thirteen Factories</span>. A code of restrictive regulations forbade foreign merchants from learning Chinese, bringing women or warships upriver, or contacting officials directly, and required them to withdraw to Portuguese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Macau\">Macau</span> once the autumn trading season had ended. The Westerners came chiefly for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tea\">tea</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk\">silk</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_export_porcelain\">porcelain</span>, paying overwhelmingly in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Spanish_dollar\">silver coin</span>, so that the system long generated an enormous favourable balance for China and drew vast quantities of bullion into the empire through the wider <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Global_silver_trade_from_the_16th_to_19th_centuries\">global silver trade</span>. <br> <br> <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"British_Empire\">British</span></b> trade, dominated until 1834 by the monopoly of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"East_India_Company\">East India Company</span>, came to overshadow that of all other nations, and the duties levied on imported tea alone supplied roughly a tenth of the revenue of the British treasury by the early 19th century. To redress the resulting outflow of silver, British and other traders aggressively expanded the smuggling of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Opium\">opium</span> grown in <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bengal\">Bengal</span></b>, whose imports surged from about 4,000 chests around 1800 to some 40,000 chests by the late 1830s and reversed the bullion flow against China. Repeated British attempts to loosen the system foundered on the Qing insistence that foreigners conform to its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tributary_system_of_China\">tributary</span> protocol, as when the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Macartney_Embassy\">Macartney Embassy</span> of 1793, led by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"George_Macartney,_1st_Earl_Macartney\">George Macartney</span>, and the later mission of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"William_Amherst,_1st_Earl_Amherst\">William Amherst</span></b> in 1816 both failed amid disputes over the ritual <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kowtow\">kowtow</span> before the emperor. After the Company's monopoly lapsed in 1834, the influx of independent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Free_trade\">free-trade</span> merchants intensified friction, and the abortive mission of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"William_Napier,_9th_Lord_Napier\">Lord Napier</span> to deal directly with Canton's authorities ended in humiliating failure that hardened demands in London for an end to the old <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mercantilism\">mercantilist</span> restrictions. The escalating crisis culminated when the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Daoguang_Emperor\">Daoguang Emperor</span> dispatched the commissioner <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lin_Zexu\">Lin Zexu</span>, whose <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Destruction_of_opium_at_Humen\">destruction of confiscated opium at Humen</span></b> in 1839 helped precipitate the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Opium_War\">First Opium War</span>, a conflict whose victorious British dictated the 1842 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Nanking\">Treaty of Nanking</span>, which abolished the Cohong, ceded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span>, and replaced the entire regime with a network of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_ports\">treaty ports</span> governed under foreign <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Extraterritoriality\">extraterritoriality</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Canton System"},{"id":"cng-082","num":"八十二","category":"China · Geography","question":"One of the most landlocked major cities on Earth, lying far from any sea at the foot of the Tian Shan, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is a key crossroads between the Chinese heartland and Central Asia.","answer":"Ürümqi","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">known from 1763 to 1954 as Dihua</span></div>","traditional":"烏魯木齊","hanzi":"乌鲁木齐","pinyin":"Wūlǔmùqí","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Wūlǔmùqí</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Ürümqi</b> is the capital of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinjiang\">Xinjiang</span>, a city of 4.05 million in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2020_Chinese_census\"><b>2020</b> census</span> lying at about 800 meters (2,600 ft) on the rim of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Junggar_Basin\">Junggar Basin</span> at the northern foot of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tian_Shan\">Tian Shan</span>, beneath the snows of 5,445-meter (17,860 ft) <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bogda_Peak\">Bogda Peak</span>. No major city on earth lies farther from the ocean, roughly 2,500 kilometers (1,600 mi) from the nearest coast, with the Eurasian <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pole_of_inaccessibility\">pole of inaccessibility</span></b> only a few hundred kilometers away. Its population has been transformed by migration, with Han Chinese now around 3 quarters of residents alongside <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Uyghurs\">Uyghurs</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hui_people\">Hui</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kazakhs\">Kazakhs</span>, and daily life runs on double clocks, since many keep unofficial <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinjiang_Time\">Xinjiang Time</span> 2 hours behind Beijing. The economy turns on its crossroads position, refining crude from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Karamay\">Karamay</span>, harvesting the gales of the Dabancheng gap in one of China's pioneering <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wind_farm\">wind-farm</span> corridors, trading through the domed halls of the International Grand <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bazaar\">Bazaar</span> <b>opened in 2003</b>, and dispatching China–Europe freight along the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eurasian_Land_Bridge\">Eurasian Land Bridge</span> via <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Alashankou\">Alashankou</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khorgas\">Khorgas</span>, while <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Southern_Airlines\">China Southern</span> jets link the city to the capitals of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Asia\">Central Asia</span>. Even its water tells of fragility, drawn from the headwater <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Glacier\">glacier</span> of the Ürümqi River, a world benchmark of ice study that split into 2 <b>shrinking halves in 1993</b>. <br> <br> Tang garrisons stood nearby in the 7th and 8th centuries, but the modern city began as Dihua, \"to civilize,\" founded in 1763 after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> conquest of the steppe that culminated in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dzungar_genocide\">Dzungar genocide</span>, and it recovered its Mongol-derived name only in 1954. In the 20th century the <b>Soviet-leaning warlord <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sheng_Shicai\">Sheng Shicai</span></b> ruled from here through purges between 1933 and 1944, before the People's Liberation Army arrived in 1949 and the city became capital of the new autonomous region in 1955. Recent decades brought violence and clampdown, from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"July_2009_Ürümqi_riots\">July 2009 riots</span> that officially killed 197 people to the bombings and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"May_2014_Ürümqi_attack\">May 2014 market attack</span></b> that killed 43, answered by checkpoints, surveillance, and the post-2017 network of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinjiang_internment_camps\">internment camps</span> that made the city a byword for securitization. History pivoted here again on 24 November 2022, when the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2022_Ürümqi_fire\">Ürümqi apartment fire</span> killed 10 people under lockdown and grief ignited the nationwide <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2022_COVID-19_protests_in_China\">white-paper protests</span> that helped end zero-COVID within weeks. Through it all the caravan city keeps its table and its memory, displaying the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tarim_mummies\">Tarim mummies</span> in its regional museum and feeding all comers <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lagman\">lagman</span> noodles, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pilaf\">polo pilaf</span>, tandoor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Naan\">naan</span>, and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Big_plate_chicken\">big-plate chicken</span></b> that Xinjiang gave to the world.","citation":"","answerText":"Ürümqi"},{"id":"cne-034","num":"三十四","category":"China · Economics","question":"An early-modern doctrine favouring exports, trade surpluses and the accumulation of bullion or reserves, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the outlook critics accuse China of practising through an undervalued currency and support for exporters, a charge central to disputes with the United States over its trade surplus.","answer":"Mercantilism","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Coined</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Named the 'mercantile system' by Adam Smith, 1776</span></div>","traditional":"重商主義","hanzi":"重商主义","pinyin":"zhòngshāng zhǔyì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">zhòngshāng zhǔyì</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Mercantilism</b> was the dominant body of economic thought and state policy across Europe between the 16th and 18th centuries, holding that a nation's power and prosperity depended on amassing <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Precious_metal\">precious metals</span></b> such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gold\">gold</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silver\">silver</span> through a persistently favourable balance of trade within what its proponents treated as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zero-sum_game\">zero-sum</span> contest among rival states. Its strictest expression, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bullionism\">bullionism</span>, was nourished by the flood of New World treasure extracted at mines such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Potosí\">Potosí</span> by the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Spanish_Empire\">Spanish Empire</span></b>, whose colonies furnished roughly 80 percent of the world's silver and helped to ignite the inflationary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Price_revolution\">price revolution</span> of the 16th century. To engineer the coveted surpluses, governments levied protective <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tariff\">tariffs</span> and export bounties in a programme of systematic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Protectionism\">protectionism</span>, while granting monopolies to chartered ventures such as the English <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"East_India_Company\">East India Company</span></b> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dutch_East_India_Company\">Dutch East India Company</span> to dominate trade with distant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Colonialism\">colonies</span>. The doctrine advanced hand in hand with the consolidation of the early-modern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nation_state\">nation state</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Absolute_monarchy\">absolute monarchy</span>, finding expression in the English <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Navigation_Acts\">Navigation Acts</span> first <b>passed in 1651</b> and in the dirigiste reforms of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jean-Baptiste_Colbert\">Jean-Baptiste Colbert</span>, controller-general of finances under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Louis_XIV\">Louis XIV</span>, whose methods lent their name to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Colbertism\">Colbertism</span>. Among its foremost expositors stood the English merchant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Thomas_Mun\">Thomas Mun</span>, a director of the East India Company whose posthumously published <i>England's Treasure by Forraign Trade</i> <b>of 1664</b> contended that the kingdom must annually sell more to foreigners than it bought from them.<br> <br>Mercantilist reasoning came under sustained attack from the Scottish philosopher <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"David_Hume\">David Hume</span>, whose 1752 exposition of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Price–specie_flow_mechanism\">price–specie flow mechanism</span> demonstrated that an inflow of bullion would raise domestic prices and automatically erode the very trade surplus that had attracted it. Drawing on the earlier objections of the French <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Physiocracy\">physiocrats</span> led by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"François_Quesnay\">François Quesnay</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Adam_Smith\">Adam Smith</span> denounced the \"mercantile <b>system\" in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Wealth_of_Nations\"><i>The Wealth of Nations</i></span> of 1776</b>, a work that both fixed the term in common usage and inaugurated the tradition of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Classical_economics\">classical economics</span> championing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Free_trade\">free trade</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Laissez-faire\">laissez-faire</span>. The ascendancy of liberal commerce that followed—reinforced by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"David_Ricardo\">David Ricardo</span>'s theory of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Comparative_advantage\">comparative advantage</span> and symbolised by Britain's repeal of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Corn_Laws\">Corn Laws</span> in 1846—drove mercantilist policy into retreat for much of the 19th century. Its core assumptions nonetheless endured, resurfacing in <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Friedrich_List\">Friedrich List</span></b>'s case for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Infant_industry_argument\">infant-industry</span> protection and, in the 20th century, in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Neomercantilism\">neomercantilism</span> of developmental states that combined <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Export-oriented_industrialization\">export-oriented industrialization</span> with the deliberate accumulation of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foreign_exchange_reserves\">foreign exchange reserves</span>. Critics have increasingly attached the label to contemporary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>, citing an allegedly undervalued <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Renminbi\">renminbi</span>, generous support for exporters, and reserves that approached $4 trillion in 2014, grievances that helped fuel the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China–United_States_trade_war\">China–United States trade war</span> and led Washington to formally designate Beijing a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Currency_intervention\">currency manipulator</span> in 2019.","citation":"","answerText":"Mercantilism"},{"id":"em-010","num":"十","category":"Opium Wars · The Court","question":"Reigning from 1820 and alarmed by the silver outflow and addiction caused by opium, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> dispatched a special commissioner to Canton to stamp out the trade, a decision that triggered war with Britain.","answer":"Daoguang Emperor","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">16 September 1782 · Beijing</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">25 February 1850 (age 67) · Beijing</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"道光","pinyin":"Dàoguāng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Dàoguāng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Daoguang Emperor</b> (September 16, 1782 – February 25, 1850) was the 6th <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> sovereign to rule over China proper, reigning <b>from 1820</b> to 1850 over a dynasty that, after the prosperity of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"High_Qing_era\">High Qing era</span>, was entering visible decline. A son of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiaqing_Emperor\">Jiaqing Emperor</span> and a member of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_people\">Manchu</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Aisin-Gioro\">Aisin-Gioro</span> clan, he is known by the personal name Minning and conventionally by his era name, carrying the posthumous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Temple_name\">temple name</span> Xuanzong, while his reign was beset by fiscal strain, official corruption, the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jahangir_Khoja\">Jahangir Khoja</span></b> revolt in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinjiang\">Xinjiang</span>, and recurrent flooding of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_River\">Yellow River</span> alongside silting of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Grand_Canal_(China)\">Grand Canal</span> that carried tribute grain to the capital. The defining challenge of his rule was the surging illicit import of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Opium\">opium</span>, largely shipped by British merchants to offset their purchases of Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tea\">tea</span>, which grew from a few thousand <b>chests a year around 1800</b> to roughly 40,000 chests by the late 1830s and produced an addicted population numbering in the millions. The traffic reversed China's long-standing trade surplus and drained tens of millions of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Spanish_dollar\">silver dollars</span> from the economy, sharpening a debate at court between officials who urged legalising and taxing the drug and a prohibitionist faction that demanded its outright suppression. Siding with the hardliners, <b>the emperor in 1839</b> dispatched the upright official <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lin_Zexu\">Lin Zexu</span> to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou\">Canton</span> as imperial commissioner, where he blockaded the foreign factories of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Canton_System\">Canton System</span> and compelled the surrender and destruction of more than 20,000 chests of opium. <br> <br> The crackdown precipitated the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Opium_War\">First Opium War</span> of 1839–1842, as the British superintendent of trade <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Charles_Elliot\">Charles Elliot</span></b> withdrew his nationals and London sent an expeditionary force that, though numbering fewer than 20,000 men, used steam warships and modern artillery to overwhelm the empire's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight_Banners\">Eight Banners</span> and coastal defences. The decisive defeat forced the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Nanking\">Treaty of Nanking</span> in 1842, which ceded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span> to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_Kingdom\">Britain</span>, abolished the monopoly of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cohong\">Cohong</span> guild, opened 5 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_ports\">treaty ports</span>, and imposed an indemnity of 21 million silver dollars. Supplementary agreements such as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_the_Bogue\">Treaty of the Bogue</span></b> granted <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Extraterritoriality\">extraterritorial</span> privileges and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Most_favoured_nation\">most-favoured-nation</span> status to foreign powers, inaugurating the era of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Unequal_treaty\">unequal treaties</span> that historians link to China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Century_of_humiliation\">century of humiliation</span>. Daoguang died in 1850, leaving the throne to his son the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xianfeng_Emperor\">Xianfeng Emperor</span></b>, who almost immediately confronted the catastrophic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiping_Rebellion\">Taiping Rebellion</span> amid continued foreign encroachment. Often remembered for his personal frugality, the emperor is generally judged by historians as a well-meaning but irresolute sovereign whose failure to grasp the scale of the Western challenge left the empire dangerously exposed, marking the point at which the dynasty's long decline became all but irreversible.","citation":"","answerText":"Daoguang Emperor"},{"id":"em-011","num":"十一","category":"Opium Wars · Officials","question":"Appointed imperial commissioner in 1838 and famous for confiscating and destroying vast stocks of opium at Humen, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> provoked the British with his action against the smugglers, which became the immediate trigger for war.","answer":"Lin Zexu","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">30 August 1785 · Fuzhou, Fujian</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">22 November 1850 (age 65) · Puning, Guangdong</span></div>","traditional":"林則徐","hanzi":"林则徐","pinyin":"Lín Zéxú","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Lín Zéxú</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Lin Zexu</b> (1785–1850) was a Chinese <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Scholar-official\">scholar-official</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span></b>, born into a modest literati family in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fuzhou\">Fuzhou</span> in the southeastern province of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fujian\">Fujian</span>. Having attained the prestigious rank of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jinshi\">jinshi</span> <b>in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examinations</span> of 1811</b> and entered the elite <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hanlin_Academy\">Hanlin Academy</span>, he climbed through provincial posts to the rank of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Viceroy_of_Huguang\">Viceroy of Huguang</span>, where a reputation for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> rectitude and incorruptibility was matched by an uncompromising campaign against narcotics. Persuaded by Lin's forceful memorial advocating total prohibition, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Daoguang_Emperor\">Daoguang Emperor</span> appointed him <b>imperial commissioner in late 1838</b> and dispatched him to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou\">Canton</span>, the sole port for Western commerce under the restrictive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Canton_System\">Canton System</span>, where he arrived in March 1839. Moving swiftly, he blockaded the foreign merchants within the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Thirteen_Factories\">Thirteen Factories</span> and compelled the British superintendent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Charles_Elliot\">Charles Elliot</span> to surrender more than 20,000 chests of the contraband drug held by traders such as the firm of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jardine_Matheson\">Jardine Matheson</span>. Over some <b>23 days in June 1839</b>, Lin had this haul—amounting to roughly 1,000 tonnes (1,100 tons)—dissolved in pits of lime and saltwater near the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bocca_Tigris\">Bocca Tigris</span> at the mouth of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pearl_River_(China)\">Pearl River</span>, an act he accompanied with a celebrated open letter appealing to the conscience of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Queen_Victoria\">Queen Victoria</span></b>.<br> <br>His uncompromising stand handed the war faction in London, urged on by lobbyists such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"William_Jardine_(merchant)\">William Jardine</span> and endorsed by Foreign Secretary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lord_Palmerston\">Lord Palmerston</span>, the pretext to dispatch an expeditionary fleet, igniting the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Opium_War\">First Opium War</span> of 1839–1842. As British forces overwhelmed the coastal defences, the emperor made Lin a scapegoat, stripping him of office in 1840 and banishing him in 1842 to remote <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinjiang\">Xinjiang</span>, even as the conflict was concluded by the humiliating <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Nanking\">Treaty of Nanking</span>, the first of China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Unequal_treaty\">unequal treaties</span>, which ceded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span> to Britain. During this exile he supervised land reclamation and irrigation works in the oases around <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Turpan\">Turpan</span> and urged the study of Western science and weaponry, an outlook that informed the scholar <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wei_Yuan_(scholar)\">Wei Yuan</span>'s influential <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Illustrated_Treatise_on_the_Maritime_Kingdoms\"><i>Illustrated Treatise on the Maritime Kingdoms</i></span></b> and anticipated the later <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Self-Strengthening_Movement\">Self-Strengthening Movement</span>. Eventually pardoned and restored to high office, he was recalled in 1850 to help suppress the incipient <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiping_Rebellion\">Taiping Rebellion</span> but fell ill and died that November while travelling through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangdong\">Guangdong</span>. Commemorated ever since as an incorruptible patriot and an early martyr to foreign aggression, he endures in modern Chinese memory as a pioneer of the struggle against narcotics and as a defining figure at the dawn of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Century_of_humiliation\">century of humiliation</span></b>.","citation":"","answerText":"Lin Zexu"},{"id":"cnh-099","num":"九十九","category":"China · History","question":"Sent by Britain in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> to seek expanded trade and a permanent ambassador, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was rebuffed with the claim that China needed nothing from abroad.","answer":"Macartney Embassy","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1793</span></div>","traditional":"馬戛爾尼使團","hanzi":"马戛尔尼使团","pinyin":"Mǎjiáʼěrní Shǐtuán","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Mǎjiáʼěrní Shǐtuán</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Macartney Embassy</b> was a British diplomatic mission to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> China <b>between 1792</b> and <b>1794</b>, led by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"George_Macartney,_1st_Earl_Macartney\">George Macartney</span> and dispatched by the government of King <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"George_III\">George III</span> under <b>Prime Minister <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"William_Pitt_the_Younger\">William Pitt</span></b>, with the backing of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"East_India_Company\">East India Company</span>. Its objectives were to expand British commerce beyond the single southern port of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou\">Canton</span>, to establish a permanent British ambassador at the court in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>, and to secure a small island near <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhoushan\">Zhoushan</span> for use as a trading base. The mission reflected mounting British frustration with the restrictive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Canton_System\">Canton System</span>, under which a soaring demand for Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tea\">tea</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk\">silk</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_export_porcelain\">porcelain</span> drained British <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silver\">silver</span> in a chronic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Balance_of_trade\">trade deficit</span>, while Chinese buyers showed little interest in European goods. Sailing from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kingdom_of_Great_Britain\">Britain</span> in 1792 with an entourage of several hundred and some 600 cases of gifts, including clocks, scientific <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Orrery\">instruments</span>, and other showpieces of British industry, the embassy was accompanied by Macartney's deputy <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"George_Leonard_Staunton\">George Staunton</span></b> and Staunton's young son, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"George_Thomas_Staunton\">Thomas Staunton</span>, who learned enough Chinese to address the emperor. The Chinese received the visitors as bearers of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tributary_system_of_China\">tribute</span> rather than as equals, and after landing near <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tianjin\">Tianjin</span> Macartney was finally granted an audience with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qianlong_Emperor\">Qianlong Emperor</span> at the imperial summer retreat <b>of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chengde\">Chengde</span> in September 1793</b>. <br> <br> The encounter was nearly derailed by a dispute over the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kowtow\">kowtow</span>, the elaborate ritual of prostration expected of all who approached the emperor, which Macartney, as the envoy of a sovereign he deemed China's equal, refused to perform before the watchful chief minister <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heshen\">Heshen</span>, reportedly compromising by kneeling on one knee. The emperor rejected every British request, and in a now-famous edict to the British king he declared that the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Celestial_Empire\">Celestial Empire</span></b> possessed all things in abundance and had no need of foreign manufactures, an attitude rooted in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sinocentrism\">Sinocentric</span> worldview that admitted no equal sovereigns. With no concession won, British trade remained shackled to Canton, and the episode exposed the widening gulf between an industrialising Britain transformed by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Industrial_Revolution\">Industrial Revolution</span> and a self-sufficient agrarian empire serenely confident of its own superiority. Macartney privately likened the Qing state to an aged, dilapidated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Man-of-war\">man-of-war</span> that might float on for a while but would be wrecked once poorly steered, and members of his suite such as the writer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"John_Barrow,_1st_Baronet\">John Barrow</span> brought home a trove of detailed observations about the empire. A second British attempt, the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Amherst_Embassy\">Amherst Embassy</span></b> of 1816, foundered on the same ceremonial rock, and the deepening impasse over trade and the spread of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Opium\">opium</span> would erupt within decades in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Opium_War\">First Opium War</span>, which shattered the old order the Qianlong court had so confidently defended.","citation":"","answerText":"Macartney Embassy"},{"id":"em-009","num":"九","category":"Late Qing · Rebellions","question":"Erupting in 1794 among impoverished settlers and inspired by a millenarian Buddhist sect, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> drained the Qing treasury and exposed the decline of the once-formidable Banner armies at the turn of the 19th century.","answer":"White Lotus Rebellion","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Began</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1794 · uprising in central China</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Ended</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1804 · suppressed by the Qing</span></div>","traditional":"白蓮教起義","hanzi":"白莲教起义","pinyin":"Báiliánjiào Qǐyì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Báiliánjiào Qǐyì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>White Lotus Rebellion</b> was a major popular uprising that convulsed the mountainous interior of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> China <b>between 1794</b> and <b>1804</b>, marking a violent close to the long prosperity of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"High_Qing_era\">High Qing era</span></b>. It drew its name and inspiration from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"White_Lotus\">White Lotus</span>, a clandestine and syncretic tradition rooted in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_folk_religion\">Chinese folk religion</span> and heterodox <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Buddhism\">Buddhism</span>, whose adherents venerated an Eternal Mother deity and awaited the imminent advent of the future buddha <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maitreya\">Maitreya</span> and a coming age of cosmic renewal. As a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Millenarianism\">millenarian</span> movement promising deliverance to the faithful, the sect also <b>nursed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Messianism\">messianic</span></b> hopes of overthrowing the ruling <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_people\">Manchu</span> dynasty and restoring the fallen <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span>, a subversive message that repeatedly invited official persecution. The revolt erupted among impoverished and landless <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Human_migration\">migrants</span> who had crowded into the rugged <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Daba_Mountains\">Daba Mountains</span></b> along the borders of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hubei\">Hubei</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan\">Sichuan</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shaanxi\">Shaanxi</span>, frontier regions where surging <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Population_growth\">population growth</span>, acute land hunger, and the extortions of local <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tax\">tax</span> collectors had bred widespread desperation. Official harassment and the heavy-handed suppression of sectarians touched off open insurrection in 1794, which <b>by 1796</b> had flared into a full-scale rebellion spreading through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_River_(Hubei)\">Han River</span> highlands and into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gansu\">Gansu</span>, drawing in tens of thousands of peasant fighters and adherents of related <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_salvationist_religions\">salvationist sects</span> across at least five provinces. <br> <br> The campaign against it was crippled by the rampant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Political_corruption\">corruption</span> of the late reign of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qianlong_Emperor\">Qianlong Emperor</span>, whose powerful favourite <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heshen\">Heshen</span> embezzled military appropriations on a colossal scale; when he was forced to take his own life in 1799, his confiscated assets were reckoned at some 800 million <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tael\">taels</span> of silver, a hoard exceeding a decade of the empire's annual revenue. Real authority passed to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiaqing_Emperor\">Jiaqing Emperor</span> only after Qianlong's death that same year, whereupon the new sovereign purged Heshen's clique, seized his estate for the treasury, and pressed the prosecution of the war with renewed vigour. The protracted conflict exposed the alarming decay of the hereditary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight_Banners\">Eight Banners</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Green_Standard_Army\">Green Standard Army</span>, whose poorly led troops, though mobilised in the hundreds of thousands, repeatedly failed to subdue lightly armed bands moving through familiar mountain terrain. Suppression came instead <b>through locally raised <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tuanlian\">militia</span></b> and a methodical policy of herding the rural population into fortified <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stockade\">stockades</span> while laying waste the surrounding country, a near-<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Scorched_earth\">scorched-earth</span> approach that, together with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Famine\">famine</span> and disease, claimed hundreds of thousands of lives before the last rebels were hunted down in 1804. Estimated to have cost the dynasty between 100 and 200 million taels and to have consumed the vast fiscal surplus amassed under Qianlong, the rebellion shattered the myth of Banner invincibility and foreshadowed the militia-based, gentry-led pacification on which the empire would come to depend decades later during the far greater <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiping_Rebellion\">Taiping Rebellion</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"White Lotus Rebellion"},{"id":"em-029","num":"二十九","category":"Self-Strengthening · Statesmen","question":"A Confucian scholar-official who raised a personal provincial force, the Xiang Army, when the regular Banner troops failed, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is credited with saving the dynasty by defeating the Taiping rebels.","answer":"Zeng Guofan","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">26 November 1811 · Xiangxiang, Hunan</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">12 March 1872 (age 60) · Nanjing</span></div>","traditional":"曾國藩","hanzi":"曾国藩","pinyin":"Zēng Guófān","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zēng Guófān</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Zeng Guofan</b> (1811–1872) was a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Scholar-official\">scholar-official</span> and general of the late <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> from <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hunan\">Hunan</span></b> who is widely credited with rescuing the dynasty by crushing the greatest rebellion of the age. After earning the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jinshi\">jinshi</span> degree <b>in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examinations</span> of 1838</b> and entering the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hanlin_Academy\">Hanlin Academy</span>, he rose through the central ministries in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>, all the while cultivating the austere self-discipline of a devout <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Neo-Confucianism\">Neo-Confucian</span>. When the Taiping uprising overwhelmed the hereditary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight_Banners\">Eight Banners</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Green_Standard_Army\">Green Standard Army</span>, the throne authorised officials to raise local militia, and <b>in 1853</b>, while in mourning for his mother in Hunan, Zeng was charged with organising such a force. The army he built was a radically new kind of regional force, recruited from Hunanese villagers, bound by ties of personal loyalty and native place, better paid and drilled than the imperial troops, financed through its own channels, and backed by a flotilla that contested control of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span>. Eventually swelling to roughly 120,000 men, this force battled the rebels for a decade up and down the river, retaking <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuchang_District\">Wuchang</span> and, after a grinding siege, capturing the strategic city of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anqing\">Anqing</span> in 1861</b>.<br> <br>The campaign reached its climax when Zeng's younger brother <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zeng_Guoquan\">Zeng Guoquan</span> besieged and stormed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span> in July 1864, extinguishing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiping_Heavenly_Kingdom\">Taiping Heavenly Kingdom</span> of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Xiuquan\">Hong Xiuquan</span></b> in a final bloodbath that left much of the lower Yangtze in ruins. In the process Zeng nurtured a remarkable cohort of subordinates, foremost among them <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Hongzhang\">Li Hongzhang</span>, who modelled his own <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huai_Army\">Huai Army</span> on the Hunanese template, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zuo_Zongtang\">Zuo Zongtang</span>, and together they steered the conservative reform known as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tongzhi_Restoration\">Tongzhi Restoration</span>. A pioneer of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Self-Strengthening_Movement\">Self-Strengthening Movement</span>, he urged the adoption of Western arms and industry, helping to found the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiangnan_Arsenal\">Jiangnan Arsenal</span> at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span> in 1865 and sponsoring the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Educational_Mission\">Chinese Educational Mission</span></b> that dispatched young students to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States\">United States</span>. Rewarded with the highest offices, including the viceroyalties of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Viceroy_of_Liangjiang\">Liangjiang</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Viceroy_of_Zhili\">Zhili</span>, he saw his reputation tarnished by his conciliatory handling of the anti-foreign <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tianjin_Massacre\">Tianjin Massacre</span></b> of 1870, and he died in 1872 while still in imperial service. Revered ever since as a paragon of Confucian statecraft and self-cultivation—his collected letters still studied as guides to discipline and leadership, and admired by figures as different as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>—he is nonetheless faulted for the savagery of his campaigns and for pioneering the personal regional armies that would later fuel the country's descent into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warlord_Era\">warlordism</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Zeng Guofan"},{"id":"em-035","num":"三十五","category":"Self-Strengthening · Statesmen","question":"A general who had helped suppress the Taiping and promoted self-strengthening by founding a shipyard, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is best remembered for the costly military campaign that reconquered the far-western region of Xinjiang for the dynasty.","answer":"Zuo Zongtang","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">10 November 1812 · Xiangyin, Hunan</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">5 September 1885 (age 72) · Fuzhou, Fujian</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"左宗棠","pinyin":"Zuǒ Zōngtáng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zuǒ Zōngtáng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Zuo Zongtang</b> (1812–1885) was a general and statesman of the late <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hunan\">Hunan</span>, best remembered for leading the arduous campaign that recovered the vast northwestern frontier for the empire. A gifted but unconventional scholar, he passed the <b>provincial <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Juren\">juren</span> examination in 1832 yet</b> repeatedly failed the metropolitan <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">examinations</span>, after which he abandoned the orthodox career path to immerse himself in the practical studies of geography, agriculture, and statecraft. He first won distinction as a military strategist during the Taiping upheaval, then raised his own Hunanese Chu Army, with which he cleared the rebels from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhejiang\">Zhejiang</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fujian\">Fujian</span> and rose to the rank of viceroy. A committed advocate of self-strengthening, <b>in 1866</b> he founded the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foochow_Arsenal\">Foochow Arsenal</span> at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fuzhou\">Fuzhou</span>, one of China's earliest modern shipyards and naval academies, built with the help of the French officer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Prosper_Giquel\">Prosper Giquel</span>. Transferred to the northwest as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Viceroy_of_Shaan-Gan\">Viceroy of Shaan-Gan</span></b>, he then waged a ferocious campaign to crush the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dungan_Revolt_(1862–1877)\">Dungan Revolt</span>, a series of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hui_people\">Hui</span> Muslim uprisings that had convulsed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shaanxi\">Shaanxi</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gansu\">Gansu</span> with enormous loss of life.<br> <br>By the time he turned to the far west, much of the region had been seized by the Central Asian adventurer <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yaqub_Beg\">Yaqub Beg</span></b>, whose state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yettishar\">Yettishar</span> won recognition from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"British_Empire\">Britain</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ottoman_Empire\">Ottoman Empire</span>, while the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russian_Empire\">Russian Empire</span> had occupied the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ili_River\">Ili</span> valley, prompting a celebrated court debate in which <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Hongzhang\">Li Hongzhang</span> urged abandoning the territory for coastal defence and Zuo insisted on its recovery. Prevailing in the debate, Zuo mounted a meticulous reconquest <b>between 1876</b> and 1878, advancing slowly while establishing military farms and supply depots—and, by legend, lines of willow trees—and financing the enormous cost through foreign loans arranged by the banker <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Xueyan\">Hu Xueyan</span> from Western houses such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"HSBC\">HSBC</span>, crushing the invader's forces and recovering nearly the whole territory after Yaqub Beg's death in 1877. The recovery of the Russian-held Ili required a further diplomatic struggle, the disastrous <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Livadia\">Treaty of Livadia</span></b> of 1879, negotiated by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chonghou\">Chonghou</span>, being repudiated and replaced by the more favourable <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Saint_Petersburg_(1881)\">Treaty of Saint Petersburg</span>, negotiated by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zeng_Jize\">Zeng Jize</span>, in 1881, which Zuo backed by massing troops in readiness for war. Largely on his recommendation, Xinjiang was formally constituted as a province in 1884, the same year Zuo, by then a member of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Grand_Council_(Qing_dynasty)\">Grand Council</span>, was dispatched to organise the defence of the southeast in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-French_War\">Sino-French War</span>, during which he died at Fuzhou in 1885. By securing for China a northwestern frontier of some 1.6 million square kilometres (620,000 square miles), Zuo earned a lasting place among the foremost statesmen of the late empire, alongside <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zeng_Guofan\">Zeng Guofan</span>, even as to much of the outside world his name now survives, incongruously, in the popular American-Chinese dish <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"General_Tso's_chicken\">General Tso's chicken</span></b>, with which he had no connection.","citation":"","answerText":"Zuo Zongtang"},{"id":"em-020","num":"二十","category":"Mid-Qing Crisis · Rebel Leaders","question":"A village schoolteacher who, after failing the civil-service examinations and reading Christian tracts, came to believe he was the younger brother of Jesus, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> launched a massive mid-19th-century rebellion against the ruling dynasty.","answer":"Hong Xiuquan","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1 January 1814 · Guangzhou, Guangdong</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1 June 1864 (age 50) · Nanjing</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"洪秀全","pinyin":"Hóng Xiùquán","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Hóng Xiùquán</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Hong Xiuquan</b> (1814–1864) was a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hakka_people\">Hakka</span></b> village schoolteacher from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangdong\">Guangdong</span> who founded the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiping_Heavenly_Kingdom\">Taiping Heavenly Kingdom</span> and led the most devastating uprising of 19th-century China against the ruling <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span>. Born near <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou\">Canton</span> under the name Hong Huoxiu, he repeatedly failed the lowest rung of the imperial civil-service examinations, and after <b>one such defeat in 1837 fell</b> into a feverish delirium in which he beheld visions of a bearded old man and a younger figure who commanded him to sweep away demons. Only in 1843, after yet another failure, did he link these visions to a Christian tract he had earlier received, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liang_Fa\">Liang Fa</span>'s <i>Good Words to Admonish the Age</i>, concluding that he was a son of the Christian God and a younger brother of Jesus, dispatched to cleanse China of idolatry and of its alien <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_people\">Manchu</span> rulers. Together with his kinsman <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Feng_Yunshan\">Feng Yunshan</span></b>, Hong founded the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"God_Worshipping_Society\">God Worshipping Society</span>, a militant religious movement that won thousands of converts among the impoverished Hakka, miners, and charcoal-burners of mountainous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangxi\">Guangxi</span>. <b>In January 1851</b> he proclaimed the rebellion at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jintian_Uprising\">Jintian Uprising</span>, assuming the title of Heavenly King, and by 1853 his armies had swept down the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span> to capture <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span>, which he renamed Tianjing, the \"Heavenly Capital,\" and made the seat of his new kingdom.<br> <br>The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiping_Rebellion\">Taiping Rebellion</span> sought to build a puritanical theocracy that outlawed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Opium\">opium</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foot_binding\">foot binding</span>, gambling, and prostitution, proclaimed a radical communal land system, advanced an unusual degree of formal equality for women, and waged iconoclastic war on the temples and texts of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucianism</span>, Buddhism, and folk religion. Real power soon devolved onto a circle of subordinate \"kings,\" among them the domineering <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yang_Xiuqing\">Yang Xiuqing</span>, whose assassination touched off <b>the fratricidal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tianjing_Incident\">Tianjing Incident</span> of 1856</b> that slaughtered tens of thousands and crippled the movement, after which Hong withdrew into religious seclusion and entrusted reform to his cousin <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Rengan\">Hong Rengan</span>. The Qing eventually turned the tide not through its decaying banner forces but through new provincial armies, above all the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiang_Army\">Xiang Army</span> raised by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zeng_Guofan\">Zeng Guofan</span> and the forces of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Hongzhang\">Li Hongzhang</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zuo_Zongtang\">Zuo Zongtang</span>, aided near <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span> by the Western-officered <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ever_Victorious_Army\">Ever Victorious Army</span> first led by <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Frederick_Townsend_Ward\">Frederick Townsend Ward</span></b> and later by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Charles_George_Gordon\">Charles Gordon</span>. With the Heavenly Capital under crippling siege, Hong died in June 1864—of illness, possibly hastened by eating wild plants during the famine—and Nanjing fell weeks later in the climactic <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Third_Battle_of_Nanking\">battle for the city</span></b> in July 1864, a massacre that exterminated its defenders, while his teenage son and successor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Tianguifu\">Hong Tianguifu</span> was swiftly captured and executed. With a death toll estimated at 20 to 30 million, the conflict ranks among the bloodiest in human history, and though Hong has been condemned as a deluded fanatic, he was later recast by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Yat-sen\">Sun Yat-sen</span> and by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Communism\">Communist</span> historians as a proto-revolutionary nationalist, his vast revolt having fatally weakened the Qing and helped open the way to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Self-Strengthening_Movement\">Self-Strengthening Movement</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Hong Xiuquan"},{"id":"cne-021","num":"二十一","category":"China · Economics","question":"A core idea of David Ricardo holding that nations gain by specialising where their relative costs are lowest, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> helps explain why China first exported labour-intensive textiles and toys before moving up the value chain into electronics and advanced manufacturing.","answer":"Comparative advantage","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Coined</span><span class=\"dt-v\">David Ricardo, in 'On the Principles of Political Economy', 1817</span></div>","traditional":"比較優勢","hanzi":"比较优势","pinyin":"bǐjiào yōushì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">bǐjiào yōushì</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Comparative advantage</b> is a foundational principle of economics holding that a party <b>can gain from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"International_trade\">trade</span></b> by specialising in whatever it produces at the lowest <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Opportunity_cost\">opportunity cost</span>, even if a rival is more efficient at producing everything. The idea was set <b>out by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"David_Ricardo\">David Ricardo</span> in 1817</b> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"On_the_Principles_of_Political_Economy_and_Taxation\"><i>On the Principles of Political Economy and Taxation</i></span>, using a celebrated example of England and Portugal exchanging cloth and wine, and it refined the notion of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Absolute_advantage\">absolute advantage</span> advanced earlier by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Adam_Smith\">Adam Smith</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Wealth_of_Nations\"><i>The Wealth of Nations</i></span>. By demonstrating that mutual <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gains_from_trade\">gains from trade</span></b> arise from relative rather than absolute costs, the principle provided the central theoretical case for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Division_of_labour\">specialisation</span> of national economies and for free exchange between them, and it remains one of the most influential and counter-intuitive ideas in the discipline. Later economists, notably <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eli_Heckscher\">Eli Heckscher</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bertil_Ohlin\">Bertil Ohlin</span>, extended it in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heckscher–Ohlin_model\">Heckscher–Ohlin model</span>, which attributes a country's comparative advantage to its abundant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Factors_of_production\">factors of production</span>, so that a labour-rich economy tends to export labour-intensive goods. <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paul_Samuelson\">Paul Samuelson</span></b> famously cited it as one of the few economic propositions that is both true and non-obvious, though the theory was complicated by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Leontief_paradox\">Leontief paradox</span> identified by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wassily_Leontief\">Wassily Leontief</span> and later supplemented by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_trade_theory\">new trade theory</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paul_Krugman\">Paul Krugman</span>, which stressed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economies_of_scale\">economies of scale</span>. <br> <br> The principle helps explain the trajectory of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> after <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">reform and opening up</span> <b>began in 1978</b>, when its enormous reserve of low-cost rural labour gave it a pronounced comparative advantage in labour-intensive goods such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Textile\">textiles</span>, garments, footwear, plastic toys, and the assembly of simple consumer products. Channelled through the coastal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Special_economic_zones_of_China\">special economic zones</span> and financed by waves of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foreign_direct_investment\">foreign direct investment</span>, this <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Export-oriented_industrialization\">export-oriented</span> model exploited that advantage on a vast scale and turned the country into the workshop of the world within a single generation. As incomes and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wage\">wages</span> rose, China steadily moved up the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Value_chain\">value chain</span> from simple assembly into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Electronics\">electronics</span>, machinery, and increasingly sophisticated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manufacturing\">manufacturing</span>, illustrating how comparative advantage can shift and be deliberately cultivated over time. This dynamic, sometimes likened to the \"<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Flying_geese_paradigm\">flying geese</span>\" pattern of East Asian development and accelerated by entry <b>into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Trade_Organization\">World Trade Organization</span> in 2001</b>, helped make China the world's largest goods exporter from 2009 and the source of roughly 30 percent of global manufacturing output. More recently, rising labour costs have pushed the lowest-value production toward cheaper economies such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vietnam\">Vietnam</span>, while Beijing's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Made_in_China_2025\">Made in China 2025</span> strategy seeks to build new advantages in high-technology industries, underscoring that a nation's place in the global division of labour is never fixed but evolves with its endowments, policies, and the wider <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">Chinese economy</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Comparative advantage"},{"id":"em-034","num":"三十四","category":"Self-Strengthening · Statesmen","question":"The empire's leading statesman and diplomat in the late 19th century, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> built the Beiyang Fleet and launched industrial ventures, yet bore the blame for the disastrous peace with Japan that he was sent to negotiate.","answer":"Li Hongzhang","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">15 February 1823 · Hefei, Anhui</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">7 November 1901 (age 78) · Beijing</span></div>","traditional":"李鴻章","hanzi":"李鸿章","pinyin":"Lǐ Hóngzhāng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Lǐ Hóngzhāng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Li Hongzhang</b> (February 15, 1823 – November 7, 1901) was a Chinese statesman, general, and diplomat who dominated the foreign and military affairs of the late <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> through much of the latter half of the 19th century. Born into a scholar-official family near <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hefei\">Hefei</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anhui\">Anhui</span> province, he earned the <b>prestigious <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">jinshi</span> degree in 1847</b> and became a protégé of the influential official <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zeng_Guofan\">Zeng Guofan</span>. He rose to prominence by organising the provincial <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huai_Army\">Huai Army</span> around 1862 to help crush the massive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiping_Rebellion\">Taiping Rebellion</span>, a civil war that claimed an estimated 20 to 30 million lives, and he later assisted in suppressing the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nian_Rebellion\">Nian Rebellion</span></b> while cooperating with the foreign-led <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ever_Victorious_Army\">Ever Victorious Army</span> commanded by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Charles_George_Gordon\">Charles George Gordon</span>. Appointed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Viceroy_of_Zhili\">Viceroy of Zhili</span> and Commissioner of <b>the Northern Ports in 1870</b>, a post he held from his base at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tianjin\">Tianjin</span> for some 25 years, he became the foremost champion of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Self-Strengthening_Movement\">Self-Strengthening Movement</span> that sought to graft Western technology onto the imperial order. Under his patronage arose a string of pioneering enterprises, <b>including the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Merchants_Steam_Navigation_Company\">China Merchants' Steam Navigation Company</span> in 1872</b>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kaiping_Mines\">Kaiping coal mines</span>, arsenals, telegraph lines, and cotton mills, as well as the powerful <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beiyang_Fleet\">Beiyang Fleet</span>, which by the early 1890s ranked among the strongest navies in Asia. <br> <br> Centred on a pair of German-built <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ironclad_warship\">ironclads</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_ironclad_Dingyuan\">Dingyuan</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_ironclad_Zhenyuan\">Zhenyuan</span>, each displacing more than 7,000 tons, that fleet was nonetheless annihilated in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Sino-Japanese_War\">First Sino-Japanese War</span> of 1894–1895, notably at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_the_Yalu_River_(1894)\">Battle of the Yalu River</span> and the fall of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Weihaiwei\">Weihaiwei</span>. Dispatched to sue for peace, he negotiated and signed the punishing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Shimonoseki\">Treaty of Shimonoseki</span> with <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Itō_Hirobumi\">Itō Hirobumi</span></b> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empire_of_Japan\">Japan</span> in April 1895, ceding <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Penghu\">Penghu Islands</span>, surrendering the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liaodong_Peninsula\">Liaodong Peninsula</span>, and agreeing to an indemnity of 200 million <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tael\">taels</span> of silver. During the talks he was shot in the face by a Japanese assailant, an outrage that shamed Tokyo into softening its terms, and the seized peninsula was soon disgorged after the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Triple_Intervention\">Triple Intervention</span></b> by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russian_Empire\">Russia</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"France\">France</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"German_Empire\">German Empire</span> in exchange for a further 30 million taels. Made the scapegoat for the catastrophe yet still deemed indispensable, he embarked on a world tour spanning roughly 190 days in 1896 that carried him through Europe and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States\">United States</span>, concluded the secret <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li–Lobanov_Treaty\">Li–Lobanov Treaty</span></b> granting Russia rights to build the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Eastern_Railway\">Chinese Eastern Railway</span> across Manchuria, and was lionised abroad as the \"Bismarck of the East\" in tribute to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Otto_von_Bismarck\">Otto von Bismarck</span>. Recalled to service after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boxer_Rebellion\">Boxer Rebellion</span> and the occupation of the capital by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight-Nation_Alliance\">Eight-Nation Alliance</span>, he negotiated the ruinous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boxer_Protocol\">Boxer Protocol</span> of 1901, which imposed an indemnity of 450 million taels, and he died in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> later that same year, leaving a contested legacy as both a far-sighted moderniser and the architect of national humiliation.","citation":"","answerText":"Li Hongzhang"},{"id":"em-022","num":"二十二","category":"Mid-Qing Crisis · The Court","question":"Coming to the throne in 1850 and facing both the Taiping upheaval and a new war with the Western powers, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> fled the capital as foreign troops approached, dying in 1861 and leaving power to his widow, the future Empress Dowager Cixi.","answer":"Xianfeng Emperor","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">17 July 1831 · Beijing</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">22 August 1861 (age 30) · Chengde (Rehe)</span></div>","traditional":"咸豐","hanzi":"咸丰","pinyin":"Xiánfēng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Xiánfēng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Xianfeng Emperor</b> (July 17, 1831 – August 22, 1861) was the 7th <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> sovereign to rule over China proper, a son of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Daoguang_Emperor\">Daoguang Emperor</span> who came <b>to the throne in 1850</b> at a moment of deepening dynastic crisis. Born Yizhu into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_people\">Manchu</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Aisin-Gioro\">Aisin-Gioro</span> house and later honoured with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Temple_name\">temple name</span> Wenzong, he inherited an empire already reeling from the catastrophic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiping_Rebellion\">Taiping Rebellion</span> in the south and the simultaneous <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nian_Rebellion\">Nian Rebellion</span></b> across the north China plain. His government, its hereditary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight_Banners\">Eight Banners</span> overwhelmed, came to depend on the new provincial forces of Han officials such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zeng_Guofan\">Zeng Guofan</span> and his <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiang_Army\">Xiang Army</span>, even as the imperial treasury was drained by years of relentless civil war that would eventually claim tens of millions of lives. Compounding these disasters, a fresh conflict with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Opium_War\">Western powers</span> erupted <b>after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Arrow_Incident\">Arrow Incident</span> of 1856</b>, as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_Kingdom\">Britain</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_French_Empire\">France</span> launched a joint expedition to force wider concessions from the court. The defeat of Qing forces <b>produced the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Tientsin\">Treaty of Tientsin</span> in 1858</b>, but the emperor's reluctance to honour its humiliating terms, including the residence of foreign envoys in the capital, reignited the fighting and brought the allied armies to the gates of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>. <br> <br> In 1860 the Anglo-French force seized Beijing and, on the orders of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"James_Bruce,_8th_Earl_of_Elgin\">Lord Elgin</span>, looted and burned the magnificent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Old_Summer_Palace\">Old Summer Palace</span> over several days in October 1860, while the emperor abandoned his capital and fled some 200 kilometres (120 miles) north to the imperial retreat at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chengde_Mountain_Resort\">Chengde Mountain Resort</span>. He left his brother <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Prince_Gong\">Prince Gong</span></b> to negotiate the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Convention_of_Peking\">Convention of Peking</span>, which confirmed the earlier treaty, ceded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kowloon\">Kowloon</span> to Britain, legalised the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Opium\">opium</span> trade, and admitted permanent foreign legations and Christian missionaries. Seizing the moment, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russian_Empire\">Russian Empire</span> extracted roughly 1 million square kilometres (390,000 square miles) of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Outer_Manchuria\">Outer Manchuria</span> through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Aigun\">Treaty of Aigun</span> and the Peking settlement, one of the largest territorial losses in Chinese history. Broken in health and spirit, the emperor died at Chengde in 1861 at the age of 30 without ever returning to Beijing, leaving the throne to his only surviving son, the 5-year-old <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tongzhi_Emperor\">Tongzhi Emperor</span></b>, under a regency of 8 ministers headed by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sushun_(Qing_dynasty)\">Sushun</span>. Within weeks the boy's mother, a former <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Concubinage\">concubine</span>, joined Prince Gong and the senior consort <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empress_Dowager_Ci'an\">Ci'an</span> to overthrow the regents in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinyou_Coup\">Xinyou Coup</span></b>, inaugurating the long ascendancy of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empress_Dowager_Cixi\">Empress Dowager Cixi</span>, who would dominate the empire for nearly half a century and preside with Prince Gong over the reforms of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tongzhi_Restoration\">Tongzhi Restoration</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Xianfeng Emperor"},{"id":"em-030","num":"三十","category":"Late Qing · The Court","question":"Rising from imperial concubine to the dominant figure at court for nearly 50 years after a coup in 1861, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> ruled from \"behind the curtain\" through child emperors and is often blamed for diverting navy funds to rebuild the Summer Palace and resisting the reforms that might have saved the Qing.","answer":"Empress Dowager Cixi","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">29 November 1835 · Beijing</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">15 November 1908 (age 72) · Beijing</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"慈禧太后","pinyin":"Cíxǐ Tàihòu","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Cíxǐ Tàihòu</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Empress Dowager Cixi</b> (29 November 1835 – 15 November 1908) was a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_people\">Manchu</span> noblewoman of the Yehe Nara clan who effectively controlled the government of the late <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> for nearly half a century, exercising power from behind the throne through a succession of child emperors. Having entered the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_Chinese_harem_system\">imperial harem</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xianfeng_Emperor\">Xianfeng Emperor</span> as a <b>low-ranking concubine around 1852</b>, she rose swiftly after giving birth to his only surviving son in 1856, the boy who would reign as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tongzhi_Emperor\">Tongzhi Emperor</span>. When the emperor died in 1861 at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chengde_Mountain_Resort\">Chengde Mountain Resort</span>, to which the court had fled during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Opium_War\">Second Opium War</span>, Cixi <b>joined Empress <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empress_Dowager_Ci'an\">Ci'an</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yixin,_Prince_Gong\">Prince Gong</span> in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinyou_Coup\">Xinyou Coup</span> to oust the eight regents headed by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sushun_(Qing_dynasty)\">Sushun</span>. As co-regent for her young son she instituted the practice of \"ruling from behind the curtain,\" and after the Tongzhi Emperor <b>died of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Smallpox\">smallpox</span> in 1875</b> at the age of 18 without an heir she broke dynastic convention by installing her three-year-old nephew as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangxu_Emperor\">Guangxu Emperor</span>, thereby prolonging her own regency. The death of the co-regent Ci'an in 1881 left Cixi the unchallenged power behind the throne, even as reform-minded statesmen such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Hongzhang\">Li Hongzhang</span> pressed forward with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Self-Strengthening_Movement\">Self-Strengthening Movement</span>, an effort to modernise the empire's military and industry along Western lines. <br> <br> Cixi's reputation is darkened by the enduring accusation that she diverted funds intended for the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beiyang_Fleet\">Beiyang Fleet</span></b> to reconstruct the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Summer_Palace\">Summer Palace</span>, where the ornamental <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marble_Boat\">Marble Boat</span> survives as a symbol of the extravagance many historians link to China's humiliating defeat <b>in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Sino-Japanese_War\">First Sino-Japanese War</span> of 1894–1895</b>. When the Guangxu Emperor backed the sweeping <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hundred_Days'_Reform\">Hundred Days' Reform</span> of 1898, championed by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kang_Youwei\">Kang Youwei</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liang_Qichao\">Liang Qichao</span>, Cixi mounted a counter-coup after just 103 days, placed the emperor under house arrest on the islet of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yingtai\">Yingtai</span>, and had reformers including <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tan_Sitong\">Tan Sitong</span> executed. Two years later she threw her support behind the anti-foreign <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boxer_Rebellion\">Boxer Rebellion</span> and declared war on the foreign powers, a catastrophic gamble that brought the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight-Nation_Alliance\">Eight-Nation Alliance</span> to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>, forced her flight to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi'an\">Xi'an</span>, and culminated in the punishing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boxer_Protocol\">Boxer Protocol</span> of 1901, which imposed an indemnity of 450 million <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tael\">taels</span> of silver. Chastened by these disasters, Cixi belatedly sanctioned the very kind of changes she had earlier crushed, enacting the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Late_Qing_reforms\">Late Qing reforms</span></b> after 1901 and abolishing the millennium-old <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examination</span> system in 1905. She died on 15 November 1908, only a day after the Guangxu Emperor, whose remains a 2008 forensic investigation found to contain lethal concentrations of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Arsenic_poisoning\">arsenic</span>, deepening long-standing suspicions about her role; having named the infant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Puyi\">Puyi</span> as her final successor, she left a contested legacy that recent biographers such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jung_Chang\">Jung Chang</span> have sought to rehabilitate against the lurid portrait popularised by the forger <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Edmund_Backhouse,_2nd_Baronet\">Edmund Backhouse</span></b>.","citation":"","answerText":"Empress Dowager Cixi"},{"id":"em-012","num":"十二","category":"Opium Wars · The First War","question":"Fought from 1839 to 1842 after the destruction of opium stocks at Canton, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> pitted the Royal Navy's steam-powered gunboats against an outmatched Qing military and ended in a humiliating Chinese defeat.","answer":"First Opium War","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Began</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1839 · Lin Zexu’s opium seizure</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Ended</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1842 · Treaty of Nanking</span></div>","traditional":"第一次鴉片戰爭","hanzi":"第一次鸦片战争","pinyin":"Dìyīcì Yāpiàn Zhànzhēng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Dìyīcì Yāpiàn Zhànzhēng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>First Opium War</b> was an armed conflict fought between <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_Kingdom\">Britain</span></b> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> empire <b>from 1839</b> to <b>1842</b>, the first of the great collisions between China and the industrialising powers of the West and a foundational episode in the modern history of Sino-Western relations. Its roots lay in the spiralling British traffic in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Opium\">opium</span>, which merchants smuggled into China in defiance of an imperial ban to offset the silver they spent on tea, a contraband trade that approached 40,000 chests a year by the late 1830s under the restrictive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Canton_System\">Canton System</span> at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou\">Canton</span>. Determined to halt the resulting drain of bullion and the social ravages of addiction, the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Daoguang_Emperor\">Daoguang Emperor</span></b> dispatched the commissioner <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lin_Zexu\">Lin Zexu</span>, whose <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Destruction_of_opium_at_Humen\">destruction of confiscated opium at Humen</span> in 1839 — some 1,000 tons amounting to roughly 20,000 chests — followed his confinement of the foreign merchants in their riverside factories and supplied the war's immediate trigger. The British superintendent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Charles_Elliot\">Charles Elliot</span> had induced his traders to surrender those stocks under a government pledge of compensation, and the ensuing demand for reimbursement and redress prompted the foreign secretary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Henry_John_Temple,_3rd_Viscount_Palmerston\">Lord Palmerston</span> to send a punitive expedition, a decision the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"House_of_Commons_of_the_United_Kingdom\">House of Commons</span> <b>endorsed in 1840</b> by a margin of only nine votes. Backed by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"East_India_Company\">East India Company</span> and stiffened by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sepoy\">sepoy</span> troops from British India, the expedition swelled to roughly 20,000 soldiers and sailors borne by a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Royal_Navy\">Royal Navy</span> fleet of warships and armed steamers that blockaded the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pearl_River_(China)\">Pearl River</span> and seized the offshore island of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhoushan\">Zhoushan</span> in 1840. <br> <br> British superiority in arms proved overwhelming, as the iron paddle-steamer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nemesis_(1839)\">Nemesis</span> and other <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Steamship\">steam</span></b> warships, mounting heavy cannon and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Congreve_rocket\">Congreve rockets</span>, shattered the Qing's wooden war <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Junk_(ship)\">junks</span> and crumbling shore batteries manned by soldiers still equipped with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Matchlock\">matchlocks</span>, bows, and antiquated gingals. After storming the forts of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_the_Bogue\">Bogue</span> early in 1841, the British exacted the ransom of Canton for six million <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Spanish_dollar\">silver dollars</span></b> in May and went on to seize the southern port of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Amoy\">Amoy</span> that August. Renewed operations in 1842, following the winter occupation of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ningbo\">Ningbo</span>, carried the fleet up the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span>, where the bloody storming of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Chinkiang\">Chinkiang</span> — defended to the death by its Manchu garrison — severed the empire's vital grain artery along the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Grand_Canal_(China)\">Grand Canal</span> and brought British guns within reach of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span>. The human cost of the fighting was starkly asymmetrical, with Chinese dead numbering perhaps 18,000 to 20,000 against roughly 500 British fatalities, of whom only about 70 fell in action while the remainder succumbed to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Malaria\">malaria</span> and dysentery. The war was concluded by the 1842 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Nanking\">Treaty of Nanking</span>, the first of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Unequal_treaty\">unequal treaties</span>, which ceded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_Island\">Hong Kong Island</span>, abolished the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cohong\">Cohong</span> monopoly, opened five <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_ports\">treaty ports</span>, and levied an indemnity of 21 million silver dollars for the destroyed opium, war costs, and old debts, while a supplementary accord soon secured for Britain the privilege of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Extraterritoriality\">extraterritoriality</span>; the catastrophe ushered in what later generations would bitterly remember as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Century_of_humiliation\">century of humiliation</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"First Opium War"},{"id":"em-052","num":"五十二","category":"Historical Memory · Nationalism","question":"A phrase later embraced by both Nationalists and Communists to frame the era from the Opium Wars onward, the \"<span class=\"blank\">_____</span>\" casts the period of defeats, unequal treaties and foreign encroachment as a national trauma whose reversal became a central goal of modern Chinese nationalism.","answer":"century of humiliation","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Began</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1839 · First Opium War</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Ended</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1949 · founding of the PRC</span></div>","traditional":"百年國恥","hanzi":"百年国耻","pinyin":"bǎinián guóchǐ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">bǎinián guóchǐ</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Hundred Years of National Humiliation”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>century of humiliation</b> is the term used in modern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_nationalism\">Chinese nationalist</span> historiography for the era of foreign intervention and internal decline that began with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Opium_War\">First Opium War</span> and is conventionally held to have ended with the founding of <b>the People's Republic in 1949</b>. The phrase itself emerged among nationalist intellectuals in the 1910s, gaining wide currency around 1915 amid outrage over Japan's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Twenty-One_Demands\">Twenty-One Demands</span>, and it recast roughly a century of military defeats and territorial losses as a single coherent national trauma. Its narrative typically opens with the defeat <b>of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> in 1842</b> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Nanking\">Treaty of Nanking</span>, the earliest of the so-called <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Unequal_treaty\">unequal treaties</span>, which ceded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span>, opened several <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_port\">treaty ports</span>, and imposed an indemnity of 21 million silver dollars. The account continues through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Opium_War\">Second Opium War</span>, during which Anglo-French forces looted and burned <b>the imperial <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Old_Summer_Palace\">Old Summer Palace</span> in 1860</b> before the dynasty was compelled to sign the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Convention_of_Peking\">Convention of Peking</span>, an episode that endures as a potent symbol of Western depredation in Chinese memory. It further encompasses the disastrous loss to Japan in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Sino-Japanese_War\">First Sino-Japanese War</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Shimonoseki\">Treaty of Shimonoseki</span> of 1895 that surrendered <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span>, and the subsequent carving of the empire into competing foreign <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sphere_of_influence\">spheres of influence</span>. <br> <br> After the suppression of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boxer_Rebellion\">Boxer Rebellion</span> by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight-Nation_Alliance\">Eight-Nation Alliance</span>, the punitive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boxer_Protocol\">Boxer Protocol</span> of 1901 levied an indemnity of 450 million taels of silver, roughly one for every subject of the empire, payable with interest over 39 years. Further grievances accumulated with the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Versailles\">Treaty of Versailles</span></b>, which in 1919 transferred former German rights in Shandong to Japan in the so-called <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shandong_Problem\">Shandong Problem</span> and ignited the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"May_Fourth_Movement\">May Fourth Movement</span>, and the narrative builds towards the Japanese seizure of Manchuria after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mukden_Incident\">Mukden Incident</span> of 1931 and the full-scale <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Sino-Japanese_War\">Second Sino-Japanese War</span>. That conflict, which left an estimated 14 to 20 million Chinese dead and produced atrocities such as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing_Massacre\">Nanjing Massacre</span></b> of 1937, in which between 200,000 and 300,000 civilians and surrendered soldiers were killed, fixed Japan as the supreme antagonist of the humiliation narrative. The framework was embraced by both the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span>, notably in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span>'s wartime tract <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China's_Destiny\"><i>China's Destiny</i></span></b>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span>, whose leader <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> proclaimed in 1949 that the Chinese people had at last stood up, presenting the founding of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Republic_of_China\">People's Republic</span> as the humiliation's reversal. Since the 1990s the memory has been deliberately cultivated through the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Patriotic_Education_Campaign\">Patriotic Education Campaign</span></b> begun in 1991, and the imperative of finally erasing that humiliation underpins contemporary slogans of national rejuvenation such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Dream\">Chinese Dream</span> promoted by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"century of humiliation"},{"id":"em-013","num":"十三","category":"Opium Wars · Treaties","question":"Signed in 1842 aboard a British warship to end the war provoked by the opium crackdown, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> forced China to pay an indemnity, open five ports to trade, abolish the monopoly merchants, and cede Hong Kong Island to Britain.","answer":"Treaty of Nanking","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Signed</span><span class=\"dt-v\">29 August 1842 · Nanjing (ended the First Opium War)</span></div>","traditional":"南京條約","hanzi":"南京条约","pinyin":"Nánjīng Tiáoyuē","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Nánjīng Tiáoyuē</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Treaty of Nanking</b> was the agreement that ended the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Opium_War\">First Opium War</span></b> between the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> empire and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_Kingdom\">Britain</span>, and the first of the accords later condemned as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Unequal_treaty\">unequal treaties</span>. It was <b>signed on August 29, 1842</b>, aboard the British warship <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"HMS_Cornwallis_(1813)\">HMS Cornwallis</span></b> as the fleet lay on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span> threatening <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span>, with the plenipotentiary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Henry_Pottinger\">Henry Pottinger</span> negotiating for the British and the imperial commissioners <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qiying_(official)\">Qiying</span></b> and Yilibu conceding terms for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Daoguang_Emperor\">Daoguang Emperor</span>. Its 13 articles compelled China to pay an indemnity of 21 million <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Spanish_dollar\">silver dollars</span>, a sum that included 6 million for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Opium\">opium</span> destroyed by the imperial crackdown, 3 million for the debts of the hong merchants, and 12 million to cover Britain's war expenses. It opened 5 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_ports\">treaty ports</span>—<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou\">Canton</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiamen\">Amoy</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fuzhou\">Foochow</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ningbo\">Ningpo</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span>—to foreign residence and commerce, and it abolished the monopoly of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cohong\">Cohong</span> guild that had channeled all trade through the old <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Canton_System\">Canton System</span>. Most consequentially, it ceded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_Island\">Hong Kong Island</span> to the British crown in perpetuity, while an accompanying schedule of duties fixed China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tariff\">tariff</span> at roughly 5% and stripped the empire of control over its own customs revenue, laying the basis for a foreign-managed maritime customs service in later decades. <br> <br> The settlement was extended the following year by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_the_Bogue\">Treaty of the Bogue</span>, which granted British subjects <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Extraterritoriality\">extraterritorial</span> immunity from Chinese law and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Most_favoured_nation\">most-favoured-nation</span> treatment that automatically passed any new concession to Britain as well. Rival powers swiftly secured parallel privileges, the United States through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Wanghia\">Treaty of Wanghia</span> and France <b>through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Whampoa\">Treaty of Whampoa</span> in 1844</b>, weaving a web of foreign rights across China's coast. Notably, the treaty did not legalise the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"History_of_opium_in_China\">opium trade</span> that had sparked the war, which remained formally banned until the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Opium_War\">Second Opium War</span> and <b>the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Tientsin\">Treaty of Tianjin</span> of 1858</b> forced its toleration. By breaching the old order of restricted trade and imposing Western legal norms through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gunboat_diplomacy\">gunboat diplomacy</span>, the agreement inaugurated what Chinese nationalists would later call the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Century_of_humiliation\">century of humiliation</span> and opened the way for a <b>spreading network of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Concessions_in_China\">foreign concessions</span></b>. The cession of Hong Kong proved especially enduring, as later agreements added <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kowloon\">Kowloon</span> under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Convention_of_Peking\">Convention of Peking</span> in 1860 and leased the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Territories\">New Territories</span> for 99 years in 1898, so that the colony established at Nanjing endured until its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Handover_of_Hong_Kong\">return to Chinese sovereignty</span> in 1997.","citation":"","answerText":"Treaty of Nanking"},{"id":"em-014","num":"十四","category":"Foreign Imperialism · The Treaty System","question":"A term coined later by Chinese nationalists for the one-sided agreements imposed after military defeats, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> granted foreigners privileges such as fixed low tariffs, extraterritoriality and concessions while giving China little in return, beginning in 1842.","answer":"unequal treaties","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">First imposed</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1842 · Treaty of Nanking</span></div>","traditional":"不平等條約","hanzi":"不平等条约","pinyin":"bùpíngděng tiáoyuē","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">bùpíngděng tiáoyuē</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>unequal treaties</b> is the collective name for the series of agreements that foreign powers imposed on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> empire, and later the Chinese republic, in the wake of repeated military defeats during the 19th and early 20th centuries. Drafted overwhelmingly in the interests of the victors, such accords typically capped Chinese import duties at roughly 5%, eliminated the country's <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tariff\">tariff</span></b> autonomy, granted foreigners extraterritorial immunity from Chinese courts, opened a widening network of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_ports\">treaty ports</span>, and entrenched the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Most_favoured_nation\">most-favoured-nation</span> principle whereby any privilege won by one power passed automatically to the others. The sequence opened with the Treaty of <b>Nanking of 1842</b>, which ended the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Opium_War\">First Opium War</span>, and was extended almost at once by supplementary pacts such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_the_Bogue\">Treaty of the Bogue</span> and the American and French treaties of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Wanghia\">Wanghia</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Whampoa\">Whampoa</span> in 1843</b> and 1844. Defeat in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Opium_War\">Second Opium War</span> produced the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Tientsin\">Treaty of Tientsin</span> of 1858 and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Convention_of_Peking\">Convention of Peking</span> of 1860, while the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russian_Empire\">Russian Empire</span> exploited the same crisis—through the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Aigun\">Treaty of Aigun</span></b> and that very convention—to annex roughly 1 million square kilometres (390,000 square miles) of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Outer_Manchuria\">Outer Manchuria</span>. The humiliations deepened after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Sino-Japanese_War\">First Sino-Japanese War</span>, when <b>the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Shimonoseki\">Treaty of Shimonoseki</span> of 1895</b> forced China to surrender <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span> and pay an indemnity of 200 million <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tael\">taels</span> of silver, even as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Triple_Intervention\">Triple Intervention</span> compelled Japan to disgorge the Liaodong Peninsula it had also seized.<br> <br>Japan's victory exposed Qing weakness so starkly that it touched off a \"scramble for concessions\" in the late 1890s, as the powers partitioned the empire into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sphere_of_influence\">spheres of influence</span> and extracted leased territories—among <b>them Germany's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiaozhou_Bay_Leased_Territory\">Kiautschou Bay</span></b>, Britain's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Weihaiwei_under_British_rule\">Weihaiwei</span>, and the 99-year lease of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Territories\">New Territories</span>—alongside foreign-run urban districts like the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_International_Settlement\">Shanghai International Settlement</span>. Suppression of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boxer_Rebellion\">Boxer Rebellion</span> by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight-Nation_Alliance\">Eight-Nation Alliance</span> brought the punitive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boxer_Protocol\">Boxer Protocol</span> of 1901, whose indemnity of 450 million taels swelled to nearly 1 billion once interest was spread across 39 years, while Japanese ambitions resurfaced in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Twenty-One_Demands\">Twenty-One Demands</span></b> of 1915. It was only in the early 1920s that the label \"unequal treaty\" itself gained wide currency, popularised by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Yat-sen\">Sun Yat-sen</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span>, whose 1924 manifesto made abrogation of the accords a central demand of resurgent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_nationalism\">Chinese nationalism</span>. The dismantling came piecemeal, as the Nationalist government regained tariff autonomy around 1930 during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing_decade\">Nanjing decade</span>, the United States and Britain renounced extraterritoriality in 1943, and the last colonial vestiges vanished only with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Handover_of_Hong_Kong\">return of Hong Kong</span> in 1997 and of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Macau\">Macau</span> in 1999. Invoked across both Nationalist and Communist historiography as the defining emblem of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Century_of_humiliation\">century of humiliation</span>, the unequal treaties endure as a touchstone of modern Chinese political memory, repeatedly summoned to justify an uncompromising defence of sovereignty and a lasting suspicion of foreign designs.","citation":"","answerText":"unequal treaties"},{"id":"em-015","num":"十五","category":"Foreign Imperialism · The Treaty System","question":"Opened to foreign residence and commerce under the agreements that followed the Opium Wars, a <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> — places like Shanghai and Amoy — became a hub of trade where Western merchants lived beyond the reach of Chinese law.","answer":"Treaty port","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Origin</span><span class=\"dt-v\">English term for a port opened by treaty; system began 1842</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"通商口岸","pinyin":"tōngshāng kǒuʼàn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">tōngshāng kǒuʼàn</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Treaty port</b> was the designation given to a city or harbour that the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> empire, and later other East Asian states, was compelled to open to foreign residence and commerce under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Unequal_treaty\">unequal treaties</span> imposed by the Western powers during the 19th century. The system originated with the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Nanking\">Treaty of Nanking</span> of 1842</b>, which ended the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Opium_War\">First Opium War</span> and threw open five coastal ports — <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou\">Canton</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiamen\">Amoy</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fuzhou\">Foochow</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ningbo\">Ningpo</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span> — to British merchants and consuls who could for the first time reside and trade there year-round with their families. Subsequent agreements multiplied these privileges, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Opium_War\">Second Opium War</span>, concluded <b>by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Tientsin\">Treaties of Tientsin</span> of 1858</b> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Convention_of_Peking\">Convention of Peking</span> of 1860, prised open some ten further harbours together with inland river ports along the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span> such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hankou\">Hankow</span> and the great northern entrepôt of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tianjin\">Tientsin</span>. Foreign residents enjoyed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Extraterritoriality\">extraterritoriality</span>, answering only to their own <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Consular_jurisdiction\">consular courts</span></b> rather than to Chinese law, while a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Most_favoured_nation\">most-favoured-nation</span> clause automatically extended any concession won by one power to all the rest, and a treaty <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tariff\">tariff</span> pegged at roughly 5% stripped China of control over its own customs. Collection of those duties fell to the foreign-administered <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Maritime_Customs_Service\">Chinese Maritime Customs Service</span>, directed <b>from 1863</b> to 1911 by the Ulsterman <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Robert_Hart_(diplomat)\">Robert Hart</span>, whose meticulous bureau eventually handled tens of millions of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tael\">taels</span> a year and became one of the most dependable revenue sources of the cash-strapped imperial government. <br> <br> Within many ports the foreigners carved out self-governing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Concession_(territory)\">concessions</span> and settlements, the most celebrated being the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_International_Settlement\">Shanghai International Settlement</span>, created in 1863 by merging the British and American enclaves and policed by its own volunteer corps, and the neighbouring <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_French_Concession\">French Concession</span>, each governed entirely apart from Chinese authority. Administered by a foreign-dominated <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_Municipal_Council\">Municipal Council</span></b>, Shanghai swelled into the busiest treaty port and a great cosmopolitan metropolis whose riverfront <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Bund\">Bund</span> was lined with the offices of trading houses such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jardine_Matheson\">Jardine Matheson</span> and banks like the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Hongkong_and_Shanghai_Banking_Corporation\">Hongkong and Shanghai Banking Corporation</span></b>, founded in 1865 to finance the booming China trade. By the 1930s the city had become one of the largest urban centres on earth, its population exceeding three million, among whom the foreigners — though numbering only several tens of thousands — wielded influence wholly out of proportion to their numbers, even as missionaries fanning out into the interior carried <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Christianity_in_China\">Christianity</span></b> far beyond the ports. The model spread across the region after similar treaties forced open harbours in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japan\">Japan</span>, among them <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yokohama\">Yokohama</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nagasaki\">Nagasaki</span>, and later in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Korea\">Korea</span> at sites like <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Incheon\">Incheon</span>, while in China alone the number of treaty ports grew from the original five to several dozen by 1900 and to more than eighty by the 1910s. The privileges that defined these enclaves eroded only gradually, enduring the anti-foreign fury of the 1900 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boxer_Rebellion\">Boxer Rebellion</span> and decades of subsequent nationalist agitation, until the right of extraterritoriality in China was at last renounced by Britain and the United States in 1943, bringing the long era of the foreign-dominated treaty port to its end.","citation":"","answerText":"Treaty port"},{"id":"em-019","num":"十九","category":"Mid-Qing Crisis · Civil War","question":"Raging from 1850 to 1864 and among the deadliest conflicts in human history, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was led by a failed examination candidate who proclaimed a heavenly kingdom with its capital at Nanjing, and was finally crushed by provincial armies under officials such as Zeng Guofan.","answer":"Taiping Rebellion","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Began</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1850 · Jintian Uprising</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Ended</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1864 · fall of Nanjing</span></div>","traditional":"太平天國","hanzi":"太平天国","pinyin":"Tàipíng Tiānguó","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Tàipíng Tiānguó</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Heavenly Kingdom of Great Peace”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Taiping Rebellion</b> was a massive civil war fought across southern China <b>from 1850</b> to <b>1864</b>, and ranks among the deadliest conflicts in human history, with most estimates placing the death toll at 20 to 30 million and some far higher. It was led by <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Xiuquan\">Hong Xiuquan</span></b>, a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hakka_people\">Hakka</span> villager from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangdong\">Guangdong</span> who had failed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examination</span> 4 times, and who after a feverish illness became convinced that he was the younger brother of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jesus\">Jesus</span>, sent by God to overthrow the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_people\">Manchu</span> rulers and sweep away the old <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> order. Drawing on Protestant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Christianity\">Christian</span> tracts circulated by the convert <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liang_Fa\">Liang Fa</span></b>, he and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Feng_Yunshan\">Feng Yunshan</span> built a fervent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Millenarianism\">millenarian</span> following, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"God_Worshipping_Society\">God Worshipping Society</span>, among the impoverished peasants and miners of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangxi\">Guangxi</span>. Open revolt erupted with the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jintian_Uprising\">Jintian Uprising</span> of 1851</b>, and within 2 years the rebels had swept down the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span> and seized <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span> in 1853, renaming it Tianjing, the Heavenly Capital, and making it the seat of their new state. The Taiping regime enforced a puritanical and revolutionary programme that pooled property in a common treasury, promised a utopian redistribution of land, segregated the sexes, and outlawed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Opium\">opium</span>, gambling, and the practice of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foot_binding\">foot binding</span>. <br> <br> Authority was shared among a hierarchy of self-styled kings, but the movement was gravely weakened by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tianjing_Incident\">Tianjing Incident</span> of 1856, a murderous power struggle in which the powerful <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yang_Xiuqing\">Yang Xiuqing</span> was killed by <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wei_Changhui\">Wei Changhui</span></b>, who was in turn executed, prompting the talented general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shi_Dakai\">Shi Dakai</span> to march off with his own army. In its later years the kingdom relied on commanders such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Xiucheng\">Loyal King Li Xiucheng</span> and on the reformer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Rengan\">Hong Rengan</span>, a cousin of the leader who drafted an ambitious but largely unrealised blueprint for Westernising modernisation. Because the dynasty's hereditary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight_Banners\">Eight Banners</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Green_Standard_Army\">Green Standard</span> troops proved incapable, the war was ultimately won by new provincial armies raised by Han Chinese officials loyal to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span>, above all the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiang_Army\">Xiang Army</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zeng_Guofan\">Zeng Guofan</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huai_Army\">Huai Army</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Hongzhang\">Li Hongzhang</span>, supported by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zuo_Zongtang\">Zuo Zongtang</span>. They were aided near Shanghai by the foreign-officered <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ever_Victorious_Army\">Ever Victorious Army</span>, commanded successively by the American <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Frederick_Townsend_Ward\">Frederick Townsend Ward</span></b> and the British officer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Charles_George_Gordon\">Charles Gordon</span>, and the war ended when imperial forces stormed Nanjing in 1864, shortly after Hong Xiuquan's death, amid a slaughter that consumed much of the city. The conflict laid waste to the wealthy lower-Yangtze provinces and, by entrusting military power to regional officials, accelerated the drift towards provincial autonomy that would later feed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warlord_Era\">warlord era</span>, even as the survivors of the crisis launched the reformist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Self-Strengthening_Movement\">Self-Strengthening Movement</span> against a backdrop of simultaneous upheavals such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nian_Rebellion\">Nian Rebellion</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Panthay_Rebellion\">Panthay Rebellion</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Taiping Rebellion"},{"id":"em-021","num":"二十一","category":"Mid-Qing Crisis · The Rebel State","question":"Proclaimed by the rebels with its capital at Nanjing, renamed the \"Heavenly Capital\", the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> banned opium, foot-binding and private property in a radical mix of Christian and utopian ideas before its bloody fall in 1864.","answer":"Taiping Heavenly Kingdom","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Founded</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1851 · at Jintian</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Fell</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1864 · capture of Nanjing</span></div>","traditional":"太平天國","hanzi":"太平天国","pinyin":"Tàipíng Tiānguó","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Tàipíng Tiānguó</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Taiping Heavenly Kingdom</b> was a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Theocracy\">theocratic</span></b> rebel state that controlled much of southern China <b>from 1851</b> to <b>1864</b> during one of the bloodiest civil wars in all of human history. It was founded by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Xiuquan\">Hong Xiuquan</span>, a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hakka_people\">Hakka</span> villager from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangdong\">Guangdong</span> who, after failing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examinations</span> four times and poring over <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Christianity\">Christian</span> missionary tracts, became convinced through a series of visions that he was the younger brother of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jesus\">Jesus</span>, sent to destroy the demons he identified with the ruling <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_people\">Manchus</span>. Gathering converts into a militant <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"God_Worshipping_Society\">God Worshipping Society</span></b> in the hills of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangxi\">Guangxi</span>, he launched open revolt with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jintian_Uprising\">Jintian Uprising</span> of 1851 and proclaimed himself the Heavenly King of a new dynasty sworn to sweep away the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span>. His swelling armies, hundreds of thousands strong, surged northward through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span> valley, and <b>in 1853</b> they stormed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span>, then among the greatest cities of the empire, which the rebels renamed Tianjing, the \"Heavenly Capital\", and made the seat of their realm. At its height the kingdom ruled territory inhabited by tens of millions and fused a heterodox form of Christianity with Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Millenarianism\">millenarian</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Utopian_socialism\">utopian</span> ideas into a militant creed aimed against the alien Manchu rulers and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> order they upheld. <br> <br> The Taiping regime pursued a sweeping programme of social transformation, outlawing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Opium\">opium</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foot_binding\">foot-binding</span>, prostitution, and gambling, abolishing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Private_property\">private property</span> in favour of communal treasuries and an egalitarian land scheme, and raising the status of women to a degree unheard of in imperial China while smashing the idols and <b>temples of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Iconoclasm\">established religion</span></b>. Power was divided among a hierarchy of subordinate \"kings\", foremost among them the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yang_Xiuqing\">East King Yang Xiuqing</span>, whose claims to speak with the voice of God and whose swelling ambition bred murderous rivalry at the very heart of the movement. That rivalry erupted in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tianjing_Incident\">Tianjing Incident</span> of 1856, a frenzied purge that slaughtered Yang along with tens of thousands of his adherents, drove the gifted <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shi_Dakai\">Shi Dakai</span> into a doomed western campaign, and gravely weakened the kingdom even as the reformer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Rengan\">Hong Rengan</span> later strove to modernise its government. With the hereditary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight_Banners\">Banner</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Green_Standard_Army\">Green Standard</span> forces proving all but useless, the Qing entrusted the war to gentry-led provincial armies — above all the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiang_Army\">Xiang Army</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zeng_Guofan\">Zeng Guofan</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huai_Army\">Huai Army</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Hongzhang\">Li Hongzhang</span> — aided near Shanghai by the foreign-officered <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ever_Victorious_Army\">Ever Victorious Army</span> under <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Frederick_Townsend_Ward\">Frederick Townsend Ward</span></b> and afterwards <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Charles_George_Gordon\">Charles Gordon</span>. After Hong Xiuquan died in June 1864, Tianjing fell the next month to Zeng's besieging troops amid a horrific massacre, ending a conflict that, through battle, famine, and disease, is reckoned to have claimed at least 20 million lives — by some counts as many as 30 million or more — and that, by entrenching powerful regional armies of Han Chinese, shifted lasting authority away from the Manchu court towards the provincial reformers who would soon launch the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Self-Strengthening_Movement\">Self-Strengthening Movement</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Taiping Heavenly Kingdom"},{"id":"em-028","num":"二十八","category":"Mid-Qing Crisis · Rebellions","question":"Overlapping with the Taiping upheaval in the north China plain, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> used mobile cavalry raids and fortified earth-walled villages to defy Qing armies from the 1850s into the 1860s.","answer":"Nian Rebellion","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Began</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1851 · north-China uprising</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Ended</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1868 · suppressed</span></div>","traditional":"捻軍起義","hanzi":"捻军起义","pinyin":"Niǎn jūn qǐyì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Niǎn jūn qǐyì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Nian Rebellion</b> was a large armed uprising that convulsed the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"North_China_Plain\">North China Plain</span></b> <b>from roughly 1851</b> to <b>1868</b>, overlapping with and partly reinforcing the contemporaneous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiping_Rebellion\">Taiping Rebellion</span> to the south. It took its name from the roving bands, or nian, of impoverished peasants, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Banditry\">bandits</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Salt_in_Chinese_history\">salt smugglers</span> who had long flourished in the destitute borderlands of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anhui\">Anhui</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Henan\">Henan</span>, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shandong\">Shandong</span></b>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiangsu\">Jiangsu</span> around the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huai_River\">Huai River</span>, regions with deep ties to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"White_Lotus\">White Lotus</span> tradition. The movement exploded into open insurrection after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_River\">Yellow River</span> catastrophically changed its course in 1855, abandoning its old channel south of Shandong and flooding vast tracts of farmland, ruining millions of livelihoods and swelling the rebel ranks with displaced and starving peasants. Under <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Lexing\">Zhang Lexing</span></b>, acclaimed leader of the alliance in 1856 under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xianfeng_Emperor\">Xianfeng Emperor</span>, the scattered bands were welded into a confederation organised beneath 5 coloured banners, though they never founded a state or seized great cities as the Taiping had. Their strength lay in fast-moving <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cavalry\">cavalry</span> raids and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guerrilla_warfare\">guerrilla</span> mobility that ranged across as many as 8 provinces, combined with networks of fortified villages ringed by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rammed_earth\">rammed-earth</span> walls that served as refuges and supply bases against the slower imperial forces. <br> <br> The Qing dynasty's regular <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight_Banners\">Eight Banners</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Green_Standard_Army\">Green Standard</span> armies proved unable to pin down the elusive horsemen, and the celebrated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongols\">Mongol</span> prince and general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Senggelinqin\">Senggelinqin</span> was lured into an ambush and <b>killed in 1865</b>, a stunning blow to the court of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tongzhi_Emperor\">Tongzhi Emperor</span>. The insurgency grew more formidable after it absorbed survivors and tactics from the collapsing Taiping movement, having earlier coordinated with Taiping commanders such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Yucheng\">Chen Yucheng</span> on the north bank of the Yangtze before that alliance unraveled. Suppression ultimately fell to the same Han Chinese officials who had broken the Taiping, as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zeng_Guofan\">Zeng Guofan</span> with his <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiang_Army\">Xiang Army</span> and then <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Hongzhang\">Li Hongzhang</span>, with his <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huai_Army\">Huai Army</span>, abandoned futile pursuit for a strategy of blockade, fortifying river and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Grand_Canal_(China)\">canal</span> lines to hem the cavalry into shrinking pockets. Zhang Lexing had already been captured and executed in 1863, and after the rebellion fractured into eastern and western wings it was finally annihilated in 1868, the eastern force destroyed in Shandong and the western remnant run down in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhili\">Zhili</span> with the help of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zuo_Zongtang\">Zuo Zongtang</span></b>. Together with the Taiping and the contemporaneous Muslim revolts, the Nian wars hastened the eclipse of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_people\">Manchu</span> military power and the rise of regional Han armies, even as the dynasty's brief recovery in these years became known as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tongzhi_Restoration\">Tongzhi Restoration</span> and spurred the reformist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Self-Strengthening_Movement\">Self-Strengthening Movement</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Nian Rebellion"},{"id":"em-037","num":"三十七","category":"Foreign Imperialism · Institutions","question":"Run for decades by the Irishman Robert Hart and staffed by foreigners, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> collected tariffs at the treaty ports, provided the cash-strapped Qing with a reliable revenue stream, and even ran lighthouses and a postal service.","answer":"Chinese Maritime Customs Service","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Established</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1854 · foreign-run customs</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Until</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1949</span></div>","traditional":"海關總稅務司","hanzi":"海关总税务司","pinyin":"Hǎiguān Zǒngshuìwùsī","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Hǎiguān Zǒngshuìwùsī</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Chinese Maritime Customs Service</b>, also known historically as the <b>Imperial Maritime Customs Service</b> (Simplified: 大清海关总税务司; Traditional: 大清海關總稅務司), was a foreign-administered tax-collection and information agency of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> empire that operated from its founding in the 1850s until 1949. It arose in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span> after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Small_Swords_Society\">Small Swords Society</span> uprising and the wider upheaval of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiping_Rebellion\">Taiping Rebellion</span> paralysed the city's <b>native customs house in 1853</b>, prompting the foreign consuls to establish a <b>provisional foreign inspectorate in 1854</b> to assess duties at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_port\">treaty ports</span>, an arrangement soon given permanent legal footing by the treaties that closed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Opium_War\">Second Opium War</span>. After the abrasive first Inspector-General <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Horatio_Nelson_Lay\">Horatio Nelson Lay</span> was dismissed in 1863 over the fiasco of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lay-Osborn_Flotilla\">Lay–Osborn Flotilla</span></b>, the post passed to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ulster\">Ulster</span>-born <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Robert_Hart,_1st_Baronet\">Robert Hart</span>, who directed the service for nearly half a century until 1911 and forged it into the most efficient organ of the Chinese state. Levying a moderate <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ad_valorem_tax\">ad valorem</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tariff\">tariff</span> on the empire's expanding foreign commerce, the service furnished the chronically insolvent dynasty with its most dependable income, its annual receipts climbing from roughly 8 million <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tael\">taels</span> in the 1860s to more than 35 million by the close of the dynasty. Because this stream was both reliable and centrally controlled, it was pledged <b>as collateral for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"External_debt\">foreign loans</span></b> and for the punishing indemnities of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Shimonoseki\">Treaty of Shimonoseki</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boxer_Protocol\">Boxer Protocol</span>, deepening foreign leverage over Chinese finances even as customs funds helped underwrite the reform projects of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Self-Strengthening_Movement\">Self-Strengthening Movement</span>. <br> <br> Reporting initially to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zongli_Yamen\">Zongli Yamen</span> and headquartered from 1865 at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>, the agency, though nominally a Chinese bureau, was staffed by a multinational corps numbering in the thousands, with subjects of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"British_Empire\">British Empire</span> predominating in its senior ranks. It compiled meticulous statistics and reports that became a principal window onto Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"International_trade\">international trade</span> and the wider economy, and it acquired a reputation for honesty and discipline that contrasted sharply with the surrounding imperial <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mandarin_(bureaucrat)\">mandarinate</span>. Its remit reached well beyond <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Customs\">customs</span> collection, for under Hart it founded the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Imperial_Post\">Imperial Postal Service</span></b> in 1896, maintained scores of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lighthouse\">lighthouses</span> and other aids to coastal navigation, and undertook harbour conservancy, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Quarantine\">quarantine</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Meteorology\">meteorological</span> work. Following the fall of the dynasty in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinhai_Revolution\">Xinhai Revolution</span> of 1911, the service persisted under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)\">Republic of China</span> through successive Inspectors-General such as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Francis_Aglen\">Francis Aglen</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Frederick_Maze\">Frederick Maze</span>, even as its autonomy eroded amid nationalist pressure to overturn the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Unequal_treaty\">unequal treaties</span> and reclaim tariff control during the 1920s and 1930s. The last foreign Inspector-General, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lester_Knox_Little\">Lester Knox Little</span>, oversaw its closing years before the institution was partitioned amid the founding <b>of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Republic_of_China\">People's Republic of China</span> in 1949</b>, ending a remarkable near-century in which a body run by foreigners had become one of the most modern and effective arms of the Chinese state.","citation":"","answerText":"Chinese Maritime Customs Service"},{"id":"em-023","num":"二十三","category":"Opium Wars · The Second War","question":"Sparked partly by the Arrow incident and waged from 1856 by Britain and France, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> forced open more ports and culminated in the occupation of the capital and the looting of an imperial palace.","answer":"Second Opium War","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Began</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1856 · the Arrow Incident</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Ended</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1860 · Convention of Peking</span></div>","traditional":"第二次鴉片戰爭","hanzi":"第二次鸦片战争","pinyin":"Dì-èr cì Yāpiàn Zhànzhēng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Dì-èr cì Yāpiàn Zhànzhēng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Second Opium War</b> was an armed conflict fought <b>from 1856</b> to <b>1860</b> in which <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"British_Empire\">Britain</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"France\">France</span> compelled the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> empire to grant sweeping new privileges, extending the system of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Unequal_treaty\">unequal treaties</span> first imposed after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Opium_War\">First Opium War</span>. The Western powers, frustrated that the earlier settlement had failed to open China fully, sought to legalise the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Opium\">opium</span> trade, station permanent legations in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>, and unlock the interior, and they found their pretexts in the 1856 boarding of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span>-registered <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lorcha_(boat)\">lorcha</span> Arrow and the execution in Guangxi of the French missionary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Auguste_Chapdelaine\">Auguste Chapdelaine</span>. Anglo-French forces bombarded and <b>captured <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou\">Canton</span> in late 1857</b>, seizing and deporting the obstinate viceroy <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ye_Mingchen\">Ye Mingchen</span>, then sailed north to storm the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taku_Forts\">Taku Forts</span> guarding the approaches to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tianjin\">Tianjin</span>. The resulting <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Tientsin\">Treaty of Tientsin</span> of 1858 opened 10 additional <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_ports\">treaty ports</span>, sanctioned foreign diplomats and missionaries throughout the country, and regularised the opium trade, while the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russian_Empire\">Russian Empire</span> seized the moment to extract the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Aigun\">Treaty of Aigun</span></b> and vast tracts north of the Amur. When the court of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xianfeng_Emperor\">Xianfeng Emperor</span> balked at ratification, hostilities resumed, and a Chinese garrison inflicted a humiliating repulse on a British squadron at the Taku Forts in 1859, bloodying the supposedly invincible attackers and hardening Western resolve to march on the capital itself.<br> <br>In 1860 a far larger expedition led by the British envoy <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"James_Bruce,_8th_Earl_of_Elgin\">Lord Elgin</span> stormed the forts and drove inland, prompting the emperor to flee north to his hunting retreat at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chengde_Mountain_Resort\">Chengde</span> and leaving his half-brother <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yixin,_Prince_Gong\">Prince Gong</span> to sue for peace. After allied troops entered Beijing, Elgin retaliated for the torture and killing of captured envoys by ordering the systematic plunder and burning of the magnificent <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Old_Summer_Palace\">Old Summer Palace</span></b> in October 1860, an act of cultural destruction still bitterly remembered in China. The ensuing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Convention_of_Peking\">Convention of Peking</span> confirmed the Tientsin terms, ceded the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kowloon\">Kowloon</span> Peninsula to Britain, opened Tianjin to foreign trade, imposed fresh indemnities of 8 million <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tael\">taels</span> on each of the victors, and permitted the recruitment of Chinese labourers for work overseas. Russia, posing as a disinterested mediator, exacted its own reward through the same convention, annexing the maritime territory of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Outer_Manchuria\">Outer Manchuria</span>—roughly 400,000 square kilometres (150,000 square miles)—even as the dynasty remained locked in its desperate struggle against the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiping_Rebellion\">Taiping Rebellion</span>. The débâcle spurred the Qing to create the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zongli_Yamen\">Zongli Yamen</span> for foreign affairs in 1861 and, amid the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tongzhi_Restoration\">Tongzhi Restoration</span></b>, to launch the modernising <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Self-Strengthening_Movement\">Self-Strengthening Movement</span>, yet the sacking of the imperial gardens endured as one of the most searing emblems of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Century_of_humiliation\">century of humiliation</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Second Opium War"},{"id":"em-024","num":"二十四","category":"Foreign Imperialism · Treaties","question":"A set of 1858 agreements that the court at first refused to ratify, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> legalised the opium trade, opened further treaty ports, and permitted foreign legations in the capital and missionaries to travel the interior.","answer":"Treaty of Tientsin","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Signed</span><span class=\"dt-v\">June 1858 · Tianjin</span></div>","traditional":"天津條約","hanzi":"天津条约","pinyin":"Tiānjīn Tiáoyuē","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Tiānjīn Tiáoyuē</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Treaty of Tientsin</b> was a cluster of four agreements <b>signed in 1858</b> that the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> court was forced to conclude during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Opium_War\">Second Opium War</span>, marking a sweeping extension of foreign privilege in China. That conflict had grown out of the boarding of the lorcha <i>Arrow</i> <b>by Chinese officials in 1856</b> and the execution of the French <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Christian_mission\">missionary</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Auguste_Chapdelaine\">Auguste Chapdelaine</span>, incidents that handed Britain and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_French_Empire\">France</span> a pretext to renew their assault on the empire. After <b>seizing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou\">Canton</span> in 1857</b> and carrying off its captured viceroy, an Anglo-French fleet sailed north, stormed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taku_Forts\">Taku Forts</span> guarding the river approaches to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tianjin\">Tientsin</span>, and threatened to march on the capital itself. Confronted with this danger, the negotiators of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xianfeng_Emperor\">Xianfeng Emperor</span> put their names to four separate treaties in June 1858 — with Britain, whose plenipotentiary was the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"James_Bruce,_8th_Earl_of_Elgin\">Earl of Elgin</span></b>, and with France, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russian_Empire\">Russian Empire</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States\">United States</span>. Among the harshest of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Unequal_treaty\">unequal treaties</span>, the settlement struck directly at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tributary_system_of_China\">tributary</span> framework the dynasty had long maintained, treating the Western states for the first time as diplomatic equals and even forbidding the use of the contemptuous word for \"barbarian\" in official correspondence about them. <br> <br> Its terms opened some ten further <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_port\">treaty ports</span></b>, among them river marts along the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span> such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hankou\">Hankow</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiujiang\">Kiukiang</span>, threw open that waterway to foreign navigation, and for the first time sanctioned the resident foreign legations in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Peking</span> that the court had always refused. A supplementary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tariff\">tariff</span> agreement legalised the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Opium\">opium</span> trade at a fixed duty of about 30 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tael\">taels</span> per chest, while the treaties granted missionaries and other foreigners the right to travel and proselytise throughout the Chinese interior under passport and obliged the authorities to protect Christian converts and their churches. China was further bound to pay indemnities of four million taels to Britain and two million to France, and in parallel the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Aigun\">Treaty of Aigun</span></b> and the Tientsin settlement let Russia press the claims that would soon strip the empire of the more than one million square kilometres of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Outer_Manchuria\">Outer Manchuria</span>. The court at first balked at ratifying so humiliating a settlement, and when an Anglo-French squadron tried to force its way upriver to Peking in 1859 to exchange ratifications, the <b>Mongol commander <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sengge_Rinchen\">Sengge Rinchen</span></b> repulsed it — sinking several gunboats and inflicting hundreds of casualties — at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Battle_of_Taku_Forts\">second battle of the Taku Forts</span>. That reverse provoked a far larger Anglo-French expedition in 1860, which routed the imperial army at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Palikao\">Battle of Palikao</span>, occupied the capital, and burned the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Old_Summer_Palace\">Old Summer Palace</span> in reprisal, finally compelling the fugitive emperor's brother, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yixin,_Prince_Gong\">Prince Gong</span>, to ratify the treaty through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Convention_of_Peking\">Convention of Peking</span>, which threw in the cession of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kowloon\">Kowloon</span>, the legalisation of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Coolie\">coolie</span> trade, and a doubling of the indemnities.","citation":"","answerText":"Treaty of Tientsin"},{"id":"em-025","num":"二十五","category":"Foreign Imperialism · Russia &amp; the Frontier","question":"Imposed in 1858 by the Russian Empire while the Qing were distracted by war and rebellion, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> transferred a vast swathe of territory north of the Amur River to Russia, part of the empire's huge territorial losses in the period.","answer":"Treaty of Aigun","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Signed</span><span class=\"dt-v\">28 May 1858 · with Russia</span></div>","traditional":"璦琿條約","hanzi":"瑷珲条约","pinyin":"Àihún Tiáoyuē","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Àihún Tiáoyuē</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Treaty of Aigun</b> was an 1858 agreement between the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russian_Empire\">Russian Empire</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> that redrew the far-eastern boundary between the two empires sharply in Russia's favour. It was <b>signed on May 28, 1858</b>, in the river town of Aigun on the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Amur_River\">Amur</span></b>, where the expansionist governor-general of eastern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Siberia\">Siberia</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nikolay_Muravyov-Amursky\">Nikolay Muravyov</span>, pressed the terms upon the reluctant Manchu general Yishan amid a show of Russian naval force on the river. Russia exploited a moment when the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xianfeng_Emperor\">Xianfeng</span> court was paralysed by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiping_Rebellion\">Taiping Rebellion</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Opium_War\">Second Opium War</span>, having spent the previous years pushing settlers, gunboats, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cossacks\">Cossacks</span> down the Amur as it turned eastward after its defeat in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Crimean_War\">Crimean War</span></b>. The treaty transferred to Russia the entire left bank of the Amur from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Argun_River_(Asia)\">Argun</span> to the sea, a territory of roughly 600,000 square kilometres (230,000 square miles), and overturned the long-standing frontier that had held <b>since the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Nerchinsk\">Treaty of Nerchinsk</span> of 1689</b> fixed the border far to the north along the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stanovoy_Range\">Stanovoy Range</span>. The lands between the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ussuri_River\">Ussuri</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sea_of_Japan\">Sea of Japan</span> were placed under joint administration pending a final settlement, the Amur, Ussuri, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Songhua_River\">Sungari</span> were opened to the vessels of both states, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_people\">Manchu</span> residents of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sixty-Four_Villages_East_of_the_River\">Sixty-Four Villages East of the River</span></b> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heilongjiang\">Heilongjiang</span> were allowed to remain under Chinese jurisdiction. <br> <br> The Qing court at first refused to ratify the agreement and stripped the hapless Yishan of his rank for having yielded without authorisation, denouncing the surrender of ancestral <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchuria\">Manchurian</span> homeland as illegitimate and beyond his power to grant. The arrangement was nonetheless confirmed and enlarged 2 years later, under Tsar <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Alexander_II_of_Russia\">Alexander II</span></b>, by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Convention_of_Peking\">Convention of Peking</span>, which handed Russia the previously shared Ussuri region, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Primorsky_Krai\">Maritime Province</span>, outright. Together the two settlements stripped the empire of about 1 million square kilometres (390,000 square miles) of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Outer_Manchuria\">Outer Manchuria</span>, an area exceeding that of present-day France and Germany combined and among the greatest territorial losses in Chinese history. Russia swiftly consolidated its prize by founding <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Blagoveshchensk\">Blagoveshchensk</span> opposite the Aigun district of present-day <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heihe\">Heihe</span> in 1858 and the Pacific <b>port of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vladivostok\">Vladivostok</span> in 1860</b>, laying the foundations of the modern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russian_Far_East\">Russian Far East</span>. Reckoned in China among the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Unequal_treaty\">unequal treaties</span> of its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Century_of_humiliation\">century of humiliation</span>, alongside the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Tientsin\">Treaty of Tientsin</span> concluded that same year, the loss long shadowed relations between the two powers and was only formally laid to rest by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China–Russia_border\">China–Russia border</span> agreements of the late 20th and early 21st centuries.","citation":"","answerText":"Treaty of Aigun"},{"id":"em-047","num":"四十七","category":"Reform &amp; Revolution · 1898 Reformers","question":"A classically trained scholar who reinterpreted Confucius as a reformer, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> won the ear of the young emperor and became the intellectual driving force behind a sweeping but short-lived attempt to modernise the state in 1898, fleeing abroad when it collapsed.","answer":"Kang Youwei","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">19 March 1858 · Nanhai, Guangdong</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">31 March 1927 (age 69) · Qingdao, Shandong</span></div>","traditional":"康有為","hanzi":"康有为","pinyin":"Kāng Yǒuwéi","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Kāng Yǒuwéi</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Kang Youwei</b> (1858–1927) was a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangdong\">Guangdong</span>-born scholar, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_calligraphy\">calligrapher</span>, and political theorist of the late <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> whose radical reinterpretation of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucianism</span> furnished the intellectual scaffolding for the reform movement of the 1890s. Steeped in the classical canon yet impatient with orthodoxy, he embraced the New Text school of exegesis and contended, <b>in his 1891 treatise</b> <i>A Study of the Forged Classics</i>, that many of the venerated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_classics\">Confucian classics</span> were forgeries fabricated by the Han-era scholar <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Xin_(scholar)\">Liu Xin</span> to lend legitimacy to the usurpation of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Mang\">Wang Mang</span>. His scholarship turned to activism after the Qing defeat in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Sino-Japanese_War\">First Sino-Japanese War</span>, for the <b>humiliating <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Shimonoseki\">Treaty of Shimonoseki</span> of 1895</b> moved the newly successful <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jinshi\">jinshi</span> to rally more than 1,200 fellow examination candidates in a celebrated mass memorial to the throne and, alongside his foremost disciple <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liang_Qichao\">Liang Qichao</span>, to found study societies agitating for national renewal. Two years later he pressed his case further in <i>Confucius as a Reformer</i> (<b>1897</b>), invoking the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gongyang_Zhuan\">Gongyang Commentary</span> to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Spring_and_Autumn_Annals\">Spring and Autumn Annals</span> and a progressive \"Three Ages\" theory of history to depict Confucius not as a guardian of antiquity but as a bold advocate of institutional change. Across these same years he also elaborated his most utopian work, the <i>Datong Shu</i> (\"Book of Great Unity\"), which spun the ancient ideal of cosmic harmony preserved in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Book_of_Rites\">Book of Rites</span> into a sweeping vision of a future <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Utopia\">utopia</span></b> stripped of nations, social classes, and the family.<br> <br>These efforts won him the confidence of the young emperor, who in the summer of 1898 launched a breathless 103-day programme of modernisation that, amid a flood of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examination</span> reforms, abolished the formulaic <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight-legged_essay\">eight-legged essay</span></b>, established the institution that became <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peking_University\">Peking University</span>, and decreed wholesale changes to the army, schools, and administration. The reform collapsed on 21 September 1898 when the conservative <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empress_Dowager_Cixi\">Empress Dowager Cixi</span> mounted a palace coup—reportedly abetted by the general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_Shikai\">Yuan Shikai</span>, who betrayed the reformers' plans—confining the emperor under house arrest and ordering the execution of six leading reformers, among them the celebrated martyr <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tan_Sitong\">Tan Sitong</span>. Kang himself escaped the purge by fleeing through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span> to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empire_of_Japan\">Japan</span>, narrowly evading the fate of his younger brother, who was among those put to death. From exile he founded the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Empire_Reform_Association\">Protect the Emperor Society</span></b> and travelled the globe campaigning for a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitutional_monarchy\">constitutional monarchy</span> under the restored emperor, a programme that set him increasingly at odds with the republican revolutionaries gathering around <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Yat-sen\">Sun Yat-sen</span>. Increasingly out of step with the times, he opposed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)\">republic</span> born of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinhai_Revolution\">Xinhai Revolution</span> of 1911 and gravely discredited himself in 1917 by <b>backing the warlord <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Xun\">Zhang Xun</span></b> in the futile twelve-day <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_Restoration\">Manchu Restoration</span> of the deposed boy-emperor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Puyi\">Puyi</span>, dying at last in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qingdao\">Qingdao</span> in 1927 as a figure remembered both as a pioneering modern reformer and as a stubborn champion of a vanished imperial order.","citation":"","answerText":"Kang Youwei"},{"id":"em-064","num":"六十四","category":"Early Republic · Yuan Shikai","question":"A powerful general who commanded the modern Beiyang Army and brokered the Qing abdication, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> took over from Sun Yat-sen as president of the new republic, only to discredit himself by trying to make himself emperor before dying in 1916.","answer":"Yuan Shikai","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">16 September 1859 · Xiangcheng, Henan</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">6 June 1916 (age 56) · Beijing</span></div>","traditional":"袁世凱","hanzi":"袁世凯","pinyin":"Yuán Shìkǎi","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Yuán Shìkǎi</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Yuan Shikai</b> (September 16, 1859 – June 6, 1916) was a Chinese military and political leader who rose from a landed family in <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Henan\">Henan</span></b> province to become the most powerful figure in the final years of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> and the first president of the Chinese republic that supplanted it. Having twice failed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examinations</span>, he pursued a military career and won early distinction as the Qing resident in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joseon\">Korea</span> during the 1880s, where he suppressed <b>the pro-Japanese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gapsin_Coup\">Gapsin Coup</span> of 1884</b> and managed Chinese interests until the outbreak of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Sino-Japanese_War\">First Sino-Japanese War</span>. Following China's humiliating defeat in 1895, he was entrusted with training a Western-style <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Army\">New Army</span> at Xiaozhan near <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tianjin\">Tianjin</span>, a force of roughly 7,000 men that he forged into the elite, personally loyal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beiyang_Army\">Beiyang Army</span> and eventually expanded into 6 divisions totaling some 70,000 troops. His reputation for ruthlessness grew when he reportedly betrayed the reformers <b>behind the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hundred_Days'_Reform\">Hundred Days' Reform</span> of 1898</b>—siding with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empress_Dowager_Cixi\">Empress Dowager Cixi</span> against the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangxu_Emperor\">Guangxu Emperor</span> and his ally <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tan_Sitong\">Tan Sitong</span>—and he later governed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shandong\">Shandong</span>, where he kept his province largely clear of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boxer_Rebellion\">Boxer Rebellion</span> before rising to the powerful post of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Viceroy_of_Zhili\">Viceroy of Zhili</span>. <b>Forced into retirement in 1909</b> by the regent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zaifeng,_Prince_Chun\">Prince Chun</span> after the deaths of Cixi and the Guangxu Emperor, he was recalled when the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuchang_Uprising\">Wuchang Uprising</span> ignited the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinhai_Revolution\">Xinhai Revolution</span> in 1911, and—commanding the only army the dynasty could rely upon—he negotiated the February 12, 1912 abdication of the child emperor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Puyi\">Puyi</span> in exchange for the presidency, which the revolutionary leader <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Yat-sen\">Sun Yat-sen</span> ceded to him. <br> <br> As provisional and then official president of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)\">Republic of China</span>, he relocated the seat of government from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span> to his stronghold of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> and steadily dismantled the country's nascent parliamentary institutions, marginalising the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span> founded by Sun Yat-sen. The 1913 assassination of the Nationalist parliamentary leader <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_Jiaoren\">Song Jiaoren</span>, widely attributed to his agents, provoked the abortive <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Revolution_(Republic_of_China)\">Second Revolution</span></b>, which he swiftly crushed before outlawing the Kuomintang, dissolving parliament, and assuming near-dictatorial authority. In 1915 he accepted, in modified form, Japan's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Twenty-One_Demands\">Twenty-One Demands</span>, a sweeping bid for economic and political privileges that inflamed nationalist sentiment and badly eroded his popular standing. Persuaded that only a restored throne could stabilise the nation, in December 1915 he proclaimed the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empire_of_China_(1915–1916)\">Empire of China</span></b> and styled himself the Hongxian Emperor, but the move triggered the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Protection_War\">National Protection War</span> led by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cai_E\">Cai E</span>, as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yunnan\">Yunnan</span> and other provinces declared their independence in revolt. Abandoning the imperial venture after just 83 days, he <b>died of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Uremia\">uremia</span></b> on June 6, 1916, a broken and isolated figure, and the fragmentation of his military following into rival cliques plunged China into the fractious <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warlord_Era\">Warlord Era</span> that endured until the late 1920s.","citation":"","answerText":"Yuan Shikai"},{"id":"em-026","num":"二十六","category":"Foreign Imperialism · Treaties","question":"Signed in 1860 after Anglo-French forces entered the capital, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> ratified the earlier treaties, ceded the Kowloon peninsula to Britain, and granted Russia further lands in the far east.","answer":"Convention of Peking","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Signed</span><span class=\"dt-v\">24 October 1860 · Beijing</span></div>","traditional":"北京條約","hanzi":"北京条约","pinyin":"Běijīng Tiáoyuē","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Běijīng Tiáoyuē</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Convention of Peking</b> was the collective name for the agreements that the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> empire concluded separately with <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"British_Empire\">Britain</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_French_Empire\">France</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russian_Empire\">Russia</span> in <b>the Chinese capital in late 1860</b>, ending the Anglo-French phase of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Opium_War\">Second Opium War</span> and <b>ratifying the treaties of 1858</b> that the court had earlier refused to honour. They were extracted after an Anglo-French expedition occupied <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> and burned the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Old_Summer_Palace\">Old Summer Palace</span> in October 1860, by which point the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xianfeng_Emperor\">Xianfeng Emperor</span> had fled to his retreat at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chengde_Mountain_Resort\">Chengde</span>, leaving his half-brother <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yixin,_Prince_Gong\">Prince Gong</span> to conduct the negotiations. The convention with Britain, signed by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"James_Bruce,_8th_Earl_of_Elgin\">Lord Elgin</span>, ceded the tip of the Kowloon peninsula south of Boundary Street to the colony of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"British_Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span></b>, opened <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tianjin\">Tianjin</span> as a treaty port, raised the British indemnity to 8 million <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tael\">taels</span>, and confirmed the legalisation of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Opium\">opium</span> trade. The parallel convention with France imposed an identical indemnity and, through a contested clause inserted into the Chinese text, restored confiscated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Catholic_Church\">Catholic</span> properties and granted missionaries the right to acquire land and build churches throughout the interior. Together with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Unequal_treaty\">unequal treaties</span> they confirmed, the agreements legalised the emigration of Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Coolie\">indentured labourers</span> aboard foreign ships, permitted permanent foreign legations in the capital, and opened a fresh wave of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_ports\">treaty ports</span> to commerce.<br> <br>The most far-reaching gains went to Russia, whose envoy <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nikolay_Ignatyev\">Nikolay Ignatyev</span></b> had posed as a mediator and now secured, in a separate convention of November 1860, the cession of the entire region east of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ussuri_River\">Ussuri River</span>. This transfer of some 400,000 square kilometres (150,000 square miles) of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Outer_Manchuria\">Outer Manchuria</span> completed the dismemberment begun in 1858 by the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Aigun\">Treaty of Aigun</span></b> along the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Amur\">Amur</span>, gave Russia a long-coveted <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pacific_Ocean\">Pacific</span> frontier, and was promptly consolidated by the founding of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vladivostok\">Vladivostok</span> in 1860. In the immediate aftermath the shaken dynasty established the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zongli_Yamen\">Zongli Yamen</span> to <b>manage foreign relations in 1861</b> and embarked on the reformist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Self-Strengthening_Movement\">Self-Strengthening Movement</span>, even as the conventions cemented an entrenched framework of foreign privilege across China. Over the longer term the ceded Kowloon was absorbed into British Hong Kong and later enlarged by the 1898 lease of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Territories\">New Territories</span>, while Tianjin matured into one of the country's foremost cities of foreign <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Concessions_in_China\">concessions</span>. Among the most consequential of all the unequal settlements, the agreements left enduring scars: Outer Manchuria was lost to Russia for good, Kowloon remained British until the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Handover_of_Hong_Kong\">return of Hong Kong</span> in 1997, and the whole episode persists in national memory as a defining chapter of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Century_of_humiliation\">century of humiliation</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Convention of Peking"},{"id":"em-027","num":"二十七","category":"Opium Wars · The Second War","question":"An exquisite imperial pleasure garden of palaces and fountains outside the capital, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> — known as Yuanmingyuan — was thoroughly looted and burned by British and French troops in 1860, an act long remembered as a national wound.","answer":"Old Summer Palace","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Destroyed</span><span class=\"dt-v\">18 October 1860 · by Anglo-French forces</span></div>","traditional":"圓明園","hanzi":"圆明园","pinyin":"Yuánmíngyuán","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Yuánmíngyuán</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Garden of Perfect Brightness”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Old Summer Palace</b> was a vast imperial garden-palace complex lying some eight kilometres northwest of the walls of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>, which for much of two centuries served as the principal residence and seat of government of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> emperors. <b>Begun in 1707</b> under the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kangxi_Emperor\">Kangxi Emperor</span></b> and lavishly enlarged by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yongzheng_Emperor\">Yongzheng</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qianlong_Emperor\">Qianlong</span> emperors across the 18th century, it eventually sprawled over some 350 hectares (860 acres) — about five times the area of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Forbidden_City\">Forbidden City</span> — and comprised three adjoining gardens studded with hundreds of halls, pavilions, temples, and artificial lakes. Hailed as the crowning achievement of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_garden\">Chinese garden</span></b> and nicknamed the \"Garden of Gardens\", the complex held an immense imperial collection of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_painting\">paintings</span>, porcelain, bronzes, silks, and rare books amassed over generations, perhaps the richest store of art in the empire. Among its marvels rose the European-style <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Baroque\">Baroque</span> palaces and waterworks known as the Western Mansions, designed in the 1750s and 1760s by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jesuit_China_missions\">Jesuit</span> missionaries at the Qianlong court such <b>as the painter <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Giuseppe_Castiglione_(Jesuit_painter)\">Giuseppe Castiglione</span></b> and the hydraulic engineer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Michel_Benoist\">Michel Benoist</span>. The grandest of these was a great fountain whose jets spouted from twelve bronze animal heads of the Chinese zodiac, part of a pleasure ground of serpentine lakes, marble bridges, and miniature reproductions of famous landscapes from across China, so sumptuous that European visitors likened it to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Palace_of_Versailles\">Versailles</span> and reckoned it larger and finer than the nearby <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Summer_Palace\">Summer Palace</span> that survives today. <br> <br> <b>In 1860</b>, during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Opium_War\">Second Opium War</span>, an expedition of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"British_Empire\">British</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_French_Empire\">French</span> troops routed the imperial army at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Palikao\">Battle of Palikao</span> and pushed on to occupy the capital, from which the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xianfeng_Emperor\">Xianfeng Emperor</span> had already fled to his hunting retreat at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chengde\">Chengde</span>. The campaign had been embittered by the seizure under a flag of truce of a party of European and Indian envoys, among them <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Harry_Parkes_(diplomat)\">Harry Parkes</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Henry_Loch,_1st_Baron_Loch\">Henry Loch</span>, about twenty of whose thirty-nine captives died from torture and neglect in Qing hands, an atrocity the allied commanders were determined to avenge. In reprisal, the British high commissioner <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"James_Bruce,_8th_Earl_of_Elgin\">Lord Elgin</span> chose to spare the inhabited Forbidden City and ordered the emperor's beloved garden instead put to the torch, and on 18 October 1860 some 3,500 British soldiers set the sprawling complex ablaze in a conflagration that smouldered for days, just before the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Convention_of_Peking\">Convention of Peking</span> ended the war. Both armies had first stripped the grounds of their portable treasures, scattering countless artworks — including the bronze zodiac heads — into private and museum collections across Europe, with celebrated pieces ending up in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"British_Museum\">British Museum</span> and the imperial collections at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Palace_of_Fontainebleau\">Fontainebleau</span>. Never rebuilt — the funds nominally earmarked for its restoration were diverted by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empress_Dowager_Cixi\">Empress Dowager Cixi</span> to raise the new Summer Palace — and pillaged anew during the <b>1900 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boxer_Rebellion\">Boxer Rebellion</span></b>, the gaunt stone ruins of the Western Mansions endure today as a park and a searing emblem of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Century_of_humiliation\">century of humiliation</span>, their plunder still echoing in the modern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Repatriation_(cultural_property)\">repatriation</span> disputes that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Victor_Hugo\">Victor Hugo</span> had foreshadowed when he condemned the deed as the work of two bandits.","citation":"","answerText":"Old Summer Palace"},{"id":"em-031","num":"三十一","category":"Self-Strengthening · Dynastic Revival","question":"Named for a boy emperor and led by capable officials in the 1860s, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> sought to shore up the dynasty by restoring Confucian government, suppressing rebellion and cautiously adopting some Western technology, a partial recovery after the Taiping devastation.","answer":"Tongzhi Restoration","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Began</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1860 · post-rebellion revival</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Ended</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1874 · death of the Tongzhi Emperor</span></div>","traditional":"同治中興","hanzi":"同治中兴","pinyin":"Tóngzhì Zhōngxīng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Tóngzhì Zhōngxīng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Tongzhi Restoration</b> was a conservative revival of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> during the 1860s and early 1870s, named for the reign of the boy <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tongzhi_Emperor\">Tongzhi Emperor</span></b> although real authority lay with a regency. That regency was dominated by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empress_Dowager_Cixi\">Empress Dowager Cixi</span> alongside the senior dowager <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empress_Dowager_Ci'an\">Ci'an</span> and the emperor's capable uncle <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Prince_Gong\">Prince Gong</span>, who together had seized control of the court <b>in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinyou_Coup\">palace coup</span> of 1861</b>. Conceived as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Scholar-official\">scholar-officials</span>' effort to rescue the dynasty after its near-collapse, the programme sought to restore orderly <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> government, revive the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">examination</span>-based bureaucracy and agrarian economy, and crush the rebellions that had ravaged the empire. To these traditional ends it cautiously grafted Western <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Technology\">technology</span> through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Self-Strengthening_Movement\">Self-Strengthening Movement</span>, founding the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zongli_Yamen\">Zongli Yamen</span> to handle foreign affairs in 1861, the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tongwen_Guan\">Tongwen Guan</span> language college in 1862</b>, and modern arsenals such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiangnan_Arsenal\">Jiangnan Arsenal</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fuzhou_Arsenal\">Fuzhou Navy Yard</span>. The work was carried forward by the great provincial officials who had defeated the rebels, above all <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zeng_Guofan\">Zeng Guofan</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Hongzhang\">Li Hongzhang</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zuo_Zongtang\">Zuo Zongtang</span>, and it drew on the ideas of reformers such as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Feng_Guifen\">Feng Guifen</span></b>, who argued that China must master Western methods in order to resist the West. <br> <br> Its most tangible successes were military, as imperial and provincial forces destroyed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiping_Rebellion\">Taiping</span> in 1864, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nian_Rebellion\">Nian Rebellion</span> in 1868, and eventually the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dungan_Revolt_(1862–1877)\">Dungan</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Panthay_Rebellion\">Panthay</span> Muslim revolts, with Zuo Zongtang reconquering <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinjiang\">Xinjiang</span> by the late 1870s. In foreign relations the period favoured conciliation, underwritten by the dependable revenue of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Maritime_Customs_Service\">Maritime Customs Service</span> run by the Briton <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Robert_Hart_(diplomat)\">Robert Hart</span>, and dramatised by the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Burlingame_Treaty\">Burlingame Treaty</span></b> of 1868, negotiated by the American envoy <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anson_Burlingame\">Anson Burlingame</span> on China's behalf. Contemporaries cast the revival as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_people\">Manchu</span>-led <i>zhongxing</i>, a dynastic resurgence in the manner of earlier mid-dynasty recoveries, and it briefly restored a measure of fiscal stability and bureaucratic competence after decades of devastation. Yet the restoration remained fundamentally conservative, aiming to preserve rather than transform the old order, and <b>the historian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mary_C._Wright\">Mary Clabaugh Wright</span></b>, in her classic study <i>The Last Stand of Chinese Conservatism</i>, judged it a serious but ultimately doomed effort to reconcile Confucian governance with the demands of the modern world. The shallow foundations of these reforms were laid bare a generation later by humiliating defeats in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-French_War\">Sino-French War</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Sino-Japanese_War\">First Sino-Japanese War</span>, long after the Tongzhi <b>Emperor's early death in 1875</b> had passed the throne to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangxu_Emperor\">Guangxu Emperor</span> under Cixi's continuing grip.","citation":"","answerText":"Tongzhi Restoration"},{"id":"em-032","num":"三十二","category":"Self-Strengthening · Institutions","question":"Established in 1861 as the empire's first dedicated office for handling relations with foreign powers, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> broke with the old refusal to treat outsiders as equals and managed diplomacy, the customs service and modernisation until it was replaced by a foreign ministry.","answer":"Zongli Yamen","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Established</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1861 · foreign-affairs office</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Abolished</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1901 · replaced by the Waiwubu</span></div>","traditional":"總理衙門","hanzi":"总理衙门","pinyin":"Zǒnglǐ Yámén","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zǒnglǐ Yámén</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Zongli Yamen</b> was the office <b>established in 1861</b> to manage the foreign relations of the late <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span>, the earliest body in Chinese history dedicated to dealing with Western powers and the effective forerunner of a modern foreign ministry. It was created in the wake of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Opium_War\">Second Opium War</span>, whose <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Convention_of_Peking\">Convention of Peking</span></b> compelled the court to admit permanent foreign legations to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>, and was proposed by the reform-minded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yixin,_Prince_Gong\">Prince Gong</span>, who became its founding controlling minister. Its very creation broke with a centuries-old order in which \"barbarian\" affairs had been relegated to the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lifan_Yuan\">Lifan Yuan</span></b> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ministry_of_Rites\">Board of Rites</span> under the assumptions of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tributary_system_of_China\">tributary system</span>, which had refused to recognise outside states as equals. Loosely modelled on the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Grand_Council_(Qing_dynasty)\">Grand Council</span></b>, it conducted negotiations with the treaty powers and supervised the foreign-staffed maritime customs administration—long directed by the Ulster-born inspector-general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Robert_Hart,_1st_Baronet\">Robert Hart</span>—whose <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tariff\">tariff</span> receipts became one of the throne's most dependable sources of revenue. Charged also with promoting modernisation, it founded the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tongwen_Guan\">Tongwen Guan</span> college <b>of foreign languages in 1862</b> and oversaw a range of self-strengthening enterprises, from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiangnan_Arsenal\">Jiangnan Arsenal</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foochow_Arsenal\">Foochow Arsenal</span> to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Educational_Mission\">Chinese Educational Mission</span> and the country's earliest telegraph and railway lines.<br> <br>In practice the office was headed by a controlling prince and staffed by ministers who often doubled as grand councillors under the watchful eye of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empress_Dowager_Cixi\">Empress Dowager Cixi</span>, with the diplomacy of figures like <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Hongzhang\">Li Hongzhang</span> carrying much of its real weight, yet it remained an improvised institution that never acquired the full standing of a regular ministry. Through it the Qing steered its foreign policy across a series of disasters, <b>including the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-French_War\">Sino-French War</span> of 1884–1885</b> and the catastrophic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Sino-Japanese_War\">First Sino-Japanese War</span> of 1894–1895, sealed by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Shimonoseki\">Treaty of Shimonoseki</span>, all conducted within the constraints of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Extraterritoriality\">extraterritoriality</span> and the wider system of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Unequal_treaty\">unequal treaties</span>. Critics judged its authority weak and its structure makeshift, faulting it for overlapping jurisdictions and for a seeming inability to defend the empire's interests as one tributary after another—from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vietnam\">Vietnam</span> to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Korea\">Korea</span>—slipped from Chinese suzerainty. After the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boxer_Rebellion\">Boxer Rebellion</span> and the punitive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boxer_Protocol\">Boxer Protocol</span> imposed by the victorious <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight-Nation_Alliance\">Eight-Nation Alliance</span>, the office was at last reorganised in 1901 into a full-fledged Ministry of Foreign Affairs, the Waiwubu, ranked ahead of the other boards of government. Spanning the 40 years from 1861 to 1901, the body had marked China's reluctant entry into the <b>Western-dominated order of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Westphalian_sovereignty\">sovereign states</span></b> and stood as one of the central institutional innovations of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tongzhi_Restoration\">Tongzhi Restoration</span>, a halting early step in the empire's long and troubled adaptation amid the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Century_of_humiliation\">century of humiliation</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Zongli Yamen"},{"id":"em-033","num":"三十三","category":"Self-Strengthening · Reform","question":"Driven from the 1860s by officials who concluded that China must adopt Western arms and industry to survive, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> built arsenals, shipyards and a modern fleet under leaders such as Li Hongzhang, but was discredited by defeat in the war with Japan.","answer":"Self-Strengthening Movement","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Began</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1861 · post-Taiping reforms</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Ended</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1895 · defeat by Japan</span></div>","traditional":"自強運動","hanzi":"自强运动","pinyin":"Zìqiáng Yùndòng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zìqiáng Yùndòng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Self-Strengthening Movement</b> (<b>c. 1861–1895</b>), also known as the <b>Westernisation Movement (Simplified: 洋务运动; Traditional: 洋務運動; Hanyu Pinyin: <i>Yángwù Yùndòng</i>)</b>, was a period of institutional and technological reform in the late <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> aimed at preserving the empire by adopting Western military technology and industry. It arose in the aftermath of the twin shocks of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiping_Rebellion\">Taiping Rebellion</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Opium_War\">Second Opium War</span>, as a circle of officials concluded that China could survive the encroaching powers only by mastering their weapons and methods, a philosophy later distilled in the maxim of \"Chinese learning as the foundation, Western learning for practical use.\" Its leadership combined court figures such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yixin,_Prince_Gong\">Prince Gong</span>, who in 1861 helped establish the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zongli_Yamen\">Zongli Yamen</span></b> to manage foreign affairs, with powerful provincial governors-general including <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zeng_Guofan\">Zeng Guofan</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Hongzhang\">Li Hongzhang</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zuo_Zongtang\">Zuo Zongtang</span>, and the later advocate <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Zhidong\">Zhang Zhidong</span>. These men founded the empire's first modern arms works, among them the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiangnan_Arsenal\">Jiangnan Arsenal</span> at Shanghai in 1865</b> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foochow_Arsenal\">Fuzhou Arsenal</span> with its naval dockyard in 1866, while also building <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ironclad_warship\">ironclad</span>-equipped fleets, most famously the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beiyang_Fleet\">Beiyang Fleet</span> anchored by the German-built battleships <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_ironclad_Dingyuan\">Dingyuan</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_ironclad_Zhenyuan\">Zhenyuan</span>. The reformers extended their efforts into civilian enterprise and education, <b>launching the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Merchants_Steam_Navigation_Company\">China Merchants Steam Navigation Company</span> in 1872</b>, stringing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Electrical_telegraph\">telegraph</span> lines across the country, and founding translation schools such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tongwen_Guan\">Tongwen Guan</span> alongside the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Educational_Mission\">Chinese Educational Mission</span> that dispatched 120 boys to study in the United States between 1872 and 1881 under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yung_Wing\">Yung Wing</span>. <br> <br> Much of this activity was financed through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Maritime_Customs_Service\">Imperial Maritime Customs Service</span>, the foreign-staffed revenue agency directed by its long-serving inspector-general <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Robert_Hart_(diplomat)\">Robert Hart</span></b>, whose customs receipts helped underwrite the arsenals and warship purchases. Critics have long stressed the movement's structural weaknesses, observing that it remained piecemeal and regionally fragmented, confined modernisation to military and industrial techniques while leaving <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> political institutions untouched, and suffered from factional rivalry and the misappropriation of funds, including the notorious diversion of naval money by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empress_Dowager_Cixi\">Empress Dowager Cixi</span> to rebuild the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Summer_Palace\">Summer Palace</span>. The programme's limitations were exposed on the battlefield, first when the French annihilated the southern Fujian fleet at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Fuzhou\">Battle of Fuzhou</span></b> during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-French_War\">Sino-French War</span> of 1884–1885, and then decisively when the Beiyang Fleet lost five warships at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_the_Yalu_River_(1894)\">Battle of the Yalu River</span> before being annihilated at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Weihaiwei\">Weihaiwei</span> in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Sino-Japanese_War\">First Sino-Japanese War</span> of 1894–1895. The crushing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Shimonoseki\">Treaty of Shimonoseki</span> that ended the war laid bare how far China had fallen behind a Japan transformed by the more thoroughgoing <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Meiji_Restoration\">Meiji Restoration</span></b>, despite the two countries having begun their modernisation drives at roughly the same moment. Its perceived failure shattered confidence in mere technical borrowing and galvanised demands for deeper transformation, feeding directly into the radical <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hundred_Days'_Reform\">Hundred Days' Reform</span> of 1898 and, ultimately, the revolutionary currents that would topple the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_people\">Manchu</span> dynasty itself.","citation":"","answerText":"Self-Strengthening Movement"},{"id":"em-036","num":"三十六","category":"Mid-Qing Crisis · Frontier Rebellions","question":"A series of uprisings by Hui and other Muslim communities across the north-west, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> killed millions from the 1860s into the 1870s and was eventually put down by the armies of Zuo Zongtang.","answer":"Dungan Revolt","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Began</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1862 · Muslim revolt in the northwest</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Ended</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1877 · Qing reconquest</span></div>","traditional":"同治回變","hanzi":"同治回变","pinyin":"Tóngzhì Huí Biàn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Tóngzhì Huí Biàn</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Dungan Revolt</b> (1862–1877) was a protracted and bloody upheaval among the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hui_people\">Hui</span> and other <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Islam_in_China\">Muslim</span></b> peoples of north-western China that convulsed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> empire during the 1860s and 1870s. Centred on the provinces of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shaanxi\">Shaanxi</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gansu\">Gansu</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ningxia\">Ningxia</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qinghai\">Qinghai</span>, with a related conflagration spreading into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinjiang\">Xinjiang</span>, the violence also drew in Turkic-speaking communities and smaller Muslim groups such as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Salar_people\">Salar</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dongxiang_people\">Dongxiang</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bonan_people\">Bonan</span> peoples. Rather than a single coordinated rebellion, it was a sprawling series of largely disconnected uprisings, <b>ignited in 1862</b> amid escalating communal friction between Muslim and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Chinese\">Han</span> populations—touched off by one traditional account in a trivial market quarrel in Shaanxi—and inflamed by long-running sectarian rivalry between the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jahriyya\">Jahriyya</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khufiyya\">Khufiyya</span> orders of Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sufism\">Sufism</span>. The timing proved decisive, for the revolt erupted while the dynasty was already exhausted by the simultaneous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiping_Rebellion\">Taiping Rebellion</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nian_Rebellion\">Nian Rebellion</span> in the empire's heartland, leaving the north-west only lightly garrisoned and allowing the disorder to spread almost unchecked. Its human cost was staggering yet remains difficult to quantify, with scholarly estimates of the region's total population loss—through killing, starvation, disease, and flight—ranging from several million to as many as 20 million, and the Hui population of Shaanxi in particular collapsing from several hundred thousand before the war to only a small remnant afterward. <br> <br> Amid the turmoil a military adventurer from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Khanate_of_Kokand\">Khanate of Kokand</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yaqub_Beg\">Yaqub Beg</span>, carved out an independent Islamic state known as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yettishar\">Yettishar</span> across much of Xinjiang <b>from 1865</b>, a regime briefly courted by both Britain and Russia before its fall. The Qing response was eventually entrusted to the general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zuo_Zongtang\">Zuo Zongtang</span>, who from 1867 prosecuted a methodical campaign summed up in his maxim of advancing slowly but striking decisively, establishing agricultural colonies to provision his troops and underwriting the enormous expense with foreign loans arranged through the banker <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Xueyan\">Hu Xueyan</span>. His forces crushed the Jahriyya leader <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ma_Hualong\">Ma Hualong</span>, who was executed in 1871, pacified Gansu by 1873, and in the subsequent <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_reconquest_of_Xinjiang\">reconquest of Xinjiang</span></b> overthrew Yaqub Beg, whose <b>death in 1877</b> paved the way for the territory to be organised as a province in 1884. As Qing armies advanced, the Shaanxi leader <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bai_Yanhu\">Bai Yanhu</span> led thousands of surviving Hui across the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tian_Shan\">Tian Shan</span> into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russian_Turkestan\">Russian Turkestan</span>, where their descendants form the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dungan_people\">Dungan</span> communities of present-day <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kyrgyzstan\">Kyrgyzstan</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kazakhstan\">Kazakhstan</span>. Often studied alongside the contemporaneous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Panthay_Rebellion\">Panthay Rebellion</span> waged by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Du_Wenxiu\">Du Wenxiu</span> in far-off <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yunnan\">Yunnan</span>, the revolt left the north-west demographically shattered for a generation and ranks among the deadliest conflicts of the entire 19th century, its enduring legacy visible in the scattered Muslim communities that took root across Central Asia.","citation":"","answerText":"Dungan Revolt"},{"id":"em-038","num":"三十八","category":"Self-Strengthening · Institutions","question":"Founded in 1862 to train interpreters and diplomats now that China had to deal with foreign powers as equals, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> taught Western languages, mathematics and science in the capital, an early experiment of the self-strengthening reformers.","answer":"Tongwen Guan","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Founded</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1862 · foreign-language school</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Merged</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1902 · into the Imperial University</span></div>","traditional":"同文館","hanzi":"同文馆","pinyin":"Tóngwén Guǎn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Tóngwén Guǎn</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Tongwen Guan</b> was a government college founded in <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> in 1862</b> to train interpreters, translators, and diplomats for the late <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span>, established under the auspices of the recently created <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zongli_Yamen\">Zongli Yamen</span></b>. It answered a pressing need created by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Unequal_treaty\">unequal treaties</span> imposed after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Opium_War\">Second Opium War</span>, since a court compelled to deal with foreign states as nominal equals could no longer leave the reading of its own treaties to foreign interpreters, and so the reform-minded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yixin,_Prince_Gong\">Prince Gong</span> championed the school as part of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tongzhi_Restoration\">Tongzhi Restoration</span>. It opened with a class in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"English_language\">English</span> and within a year added departments of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"French_language\">French</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russian_language\">Russian</span> in 1863</b> to meet the court's most urgent diplomatic needs. Its intellectual reach was broadened by the American Presbyterian missionary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"W._A._P._Martin\">William Alexander Parsons Martin</span>, who in 1864 had introduced Western <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"International_law\">international law</span> to China through his translation of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Henry_Wheaton\">Henry Wheaton</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Elements_of_International_Law\"><i>Elements of International Law</i></span>. <b>A proposal in 1867</b> to establish departments of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Astronomy\">astronomy</span> and mathematics and to enrol established degree-holders provoked a fierce conservative backlash, led by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongols\">Mongol</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Grand_Secretariat\">Grand Secretary</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Woren\">Woren</span>, who insisted that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> virtue, not the techniques of foreigners, was the true foundation of the state.<br> <br>Martin nonetheless went on to serve as the college's president from 1869 to 1894, its running costs met largely from the revenues of the foreign-run <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Maritime_Customs_Service\">maritime customs</span> administered by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Robert_Hart,_1st_Baronet\">Robert Hart</span>, while an attached bureau translated further Western works into Chinese. Over time the curriculum widened to embrace <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chemistry\">chemistry</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Physics\">physics</span>, medicine, and geography, and new language departments were added, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"German_language\">German</span> in 1871 and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japanese_language\">Japanese</span> in 1896. Even so the school stayed small, its enrolment rarely exceeding roughly 100 students, and it carried little prestige among a gentry that still prized the classical <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">examination</span> path to office, so that its influence fell far short of the empire's enormous need for modern expertise. The <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_University_of_Peking\">Imperial University of Peking</span></b>, founded in 1898 during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hundred_Days'_Reform\">Hundred Days' Reform</span>, absorbed the Tongwen Guan in 1902 in the aftermath of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boxer_Rebellion\">Boxer Rebellion</span>, carrying its mission into the institution that would later become <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peking_University\">Peking University</span>. Spanning the 40 years from 1862 to 1902, the college had served as a pioneering experiment in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Westernization\">Westernisation</span></b> of Chinese education, producing an early generation of trained diplomats and translators and standing, for all its limits, as a telling emblem of the contested ambitions of the self-strengthening reformers.","citation":"","answerText":"Tongwen Guan"},{"id":"em-018","num":"十八","category":"Foreign Imperialism · Treaty Ports","question":"Formed in 1863 by merging the British and American zones in the country's greatest port, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> grew into a cosmopolitan centre of finance and vice along the Bund, run by a council of taipans beyond the authority of the Qing.","answer":"Shanghai International Settlement","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Formed</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1863 · British–American merger</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Ended</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1943 · wartime rendition</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"上海公共租界","pinyin":"Shànghǎi Gōnggòng Zūjiè","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Shànghǎi Gōnggòng Zūjiè</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Shanghai International Settlement</b> was a self-governing foreign enclave in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span> that <b>came into being in 1863</b> through the amalgamation of the separate British and American settlements established in the city after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Opium_War\">First Opium War</span>. Both had grown out of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Nanking\">Treaty of Nanking</span> and the land regulations that opened Shanghai <b>as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_port\">treaty port</span> in 1843</b>, and although the adjoining <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_French_Concession\">French Concession</span> declined to join the union, the combined Anglo-American zone — anchored on the former American quarter of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hongkou_District\">Hongkew</span> and the British waterfront — coalesced into a single international district. Authority over it rested with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_Municipal_Council\">Shanghai Municipal Council</span>, an elected body chosen by the foreign ratepayers and long dominated by the British <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taipan_(business)\">taipans</span> who headed its great commercial firms, backed by its own <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_Municipal_Police\">Municipal Police</span> and a part-time <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_Volunteer_Corps\">Volunteer Corps</span></b>. Its inhabitants lived under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Extraterritoriality\">extraterritoriality</span>, exempt from the laws of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> and answerable to their own consular tribunals such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"British_Supreme_Court_for_China\">British Supreme Court for China</span>, while cases involving Chinese subjects were tried in the foreign-influenced <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_Mixed_Court\">Mixed Court</span>. Greatly enlarged by a major extension in 1899 that brought it to some 22.6 square kilometres (8.73 square miles), the Settlement housed a population that was overwhelmingly Chinese — well over a million by the 1930s against only a few tens of thousands of foreigners — yet no Chinese were admitted to its governing council until 1928, when three were at last granted seats. <br> <br> Through the late 19th and early 20th centuries the Settlement blossomed into the commercial and financial heart of East Asia, handling a vast share of the nation's foreign trade, its monumental <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Bund\">Bund</span> lined with the headquarters of banks such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Hongkong_and_Shanghai_Banking_Corporation\">Hongkong and Shanghai Banking Corporation</span> and trading houses like <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jardine_Matheson\">Jardine Matheson</span>, while the department stores of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing_Road\">Nanjing Road</span></b> drew shoppers from across the region. Alongside this affluence flourished a notorious underworld of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Opium_den\">opium dens</span>, gambling houses, brothels, and cabarets — many of their rackets run by the criminal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Green_Gang\">Green Gang</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Du_Yuesheng\">Du Yuesheng</span> — that won the city its reputation for glamour and sin, even as property magnates like <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Victor_Sassoon\">Victor Sassoon</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silas_Hardoon\">Silas Hardoon</span></b> amassed colossal fortunes from its soaring real estate. Its polyglot crowd embraced Britons, Americans, and a large community of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"White_émigré\">White Russian</span> émigrés who had fled the revolution, but the most numerous foreign nationality by the 1930s was the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empire_of_Japan\">Japanese</span> clustered in Hongkew, a district that in the same years also gave shelter to some 20,000 Jewish refugees in what became known as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_Ghetto\">Shanghai Ghetto</span>. The enclave likewise served as a flashpoint for rising <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_nationalism\">Chinese nationalism</span>, most violently in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"May_Thirtieth_Movement\">May Thirtieth Incident</span></b> of 1925, when Settlement police shot demonstrators on Nanjing Road and ignited nationwide protest, and after the eruption of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Sino-Japanese_War\">Second Sino-Japanese War</span> it survived as an isolated island of neutrality once the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Shanghai\">Battle of Shanghai</span> in 1937 surrounded it with Japanese troops. That precarious autonomy collapsed after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Attack_on_Pearl_Harbor\">attack on Pearl Harbor</span> in December 1941, when Japanese forces seized the foreign quarters outright, and within two years Britain and the United States surrendered their treaty rights and the district was made over to the Japanese-sponsored <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Reorganized_National_Government_of_the_Republic_of_China\">Reorganised National Government</span>, so that <b>in 1943</b> the Shanghai International Settlement passed permanently out of foreign hands after eight decades.","citation":"","answerText":"Shanghai International Settlement"},{"id":"em-039","num":"三十九","category":"Self-Strengthening · Industry","question":"Set up in 1865 near Shanghai as one of the country's largest modern factories, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> manufactured guns, ships and ammunition and translated foreign technical books, a flagship enterprise of the self-strengthening drive.","answer":"Jiangnan Arsenal","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Founded</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1865 · Shanghai (weapons works)</span></div>","traditional":"江南機器製造總局","hanzi":"江南机器制造总局","pinyin":"Jiāngnán Jīqì Zhìzào Zǒngjú","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Jiāngnán Jīqì Zhìzào Zǒngjú</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Jiangnan Arsenal</b> (established <b>1865</b>) was a vast government armaments and manufacturing complex in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span> that, founded in the wake of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiping_Rebellion\">Taiping Rebellion</span>, became the largest and most ambitious industrial enterprise of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Self-Strengthening_Movement\">Self-Strengthening Movement</span> in the late <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span>. It was founded by the reformist statesman <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Hongzhang\">Li Hongzhang</span>, with the backing of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zeng_Guofan\">Zeng Guofan</span>, by consolidating existing workshops with imported equipment, including a set of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Machine_tool\">machine tools</span> that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yung_Wing\">Yung Wing</span> had purchased in the United States for some 68,000 dollars from a firm in <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fitchburg,_Massachusetts\">Fitchburg, Massachusetts</span></b>. Situated beside the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huangpu_River\">Huangpu River</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiangsu\">Jiangsu</span> province south of the city, the works were administered as an official-supervised undertaking financed largely by a fixed share of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Maritime_Customs_Service\">Shanghai customs</span> revenue, and grew to employ several thousand workers, ranking among the largest industrial establishments in East Asia. Its foundries and assembly shops turned out <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Firearm\">firearms</span> such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rifle\">rifles</span>—including locally produced copies of the American <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Remington_Rolling_Block_rifle\">Remington rolling-block</span></b> pattern—along with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Artillery\">artillery</span> pieces, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gunpowder\">gunpowder</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ammunition\">ammunition</span> for the modernising imperial forces. An attached shipyard built some of China's first modern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Steamship\">steam</span> warships, launching the wooden-hulled vessel <i>Tianji</i> <b>in 1868</b>, and over the following years produced a succession of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gunboat\">gunboats</span> for the fledgling navy. <br> <br> Beyond weaponry, the arsenal housed an influential Translation Department established in 1868 that became one of the foremost conduits for Western science entering 19th-century China, where the English translator <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"John_Fryer_(sinologist)\">John Fryer</span> worked for nearly three decades alongside Chinese scholars such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xu_Shou\">Xu Shou</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hua_Hengfang\">Hua Hengfang</span></b> to render foreign technical knowledge into Chinese. Over its lifetime the bureau translated and published more than 150 Western scientific and technical titles spanning mathematics, chemistry, engineering, and military science, work that introduced new bodies of knowledge to Chinese readers and helped fix the standard Chinese terminology for many <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chemical_element\">chemical elements</span></b> that remains in use. For all its scale, the enterprise drew persistent criticism for its heavy reliance on foreign machinery and advisers, its high costs, and the uneven quality of its output, shortcomings widely cited when China's armaments proved inadequate <b>in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Sino-Japanese_War\">First Sino-Japanese War</span> of 1894–1895</b>. It nonetheless ranked alongside the contemporaneous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foochow_Arsenal\">Fuzhou Arsenal</span> as a cornerstone of the self-strengthening programme and continued operating after the dynasty's fall, passing into the hands of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)\">Republic of China</span>. Its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shipbuilding\">shipbuilding</span> division survives to this day as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiangnan_Shipyard\">Jiangnan Shipyard</span>, now a major subsidiary of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_State_Shipbuilding_Corporation\">China State Shipbuilding Corporation</span> relocated to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Changxing_Island,_Shanghai\">Changxing Island</span>, while the original riverside grounds were repurposed for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Expo_2010\">Shanghai World Expo of 2010</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Jiangnan Arsenal"},{"id":"em-058","num":"五十八","category":"1911 Revolution · Revolutionaries","question":"A Western-educated physician turned revolutionary who spent years raising funds in exile, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is revered by both Nationalists and Communists as the father of the republic, briefly served as its provisional president in 1912, and devised an influential three-part political doctrine.","answer":"Sun Yat-sen","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">12 November 1866 · Cuiheng, Guangdong</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">12 March 1925 (age 58) · Beijing</span></div>","traditional":"孫逸仙","hanzi":"孙逸仙","pinyin":"Sūn Yìxiān","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Sūn Yìxiān</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Sun Yat-sen</b> (commonly known in Chinese as <b>Sun Zhongshan</b>, 孫中山; November 12, 1866 – March 12, 1925) was a Chinese revolutionary and statesman widely regarded as the founding father of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)\">Republic of China</span></b>. Born to a peasant family in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangdong\">Guangdong</span> and educated partly in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Honolulu\">Honolulu</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span>, he qualified as a physician <b>at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_College_of_Medicine_for_Chinese\">Hong Kong College of Medicine for Chinese</span> in 1892</b> before abandoning medicine to devote himself to overthrowing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span>. He founded the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Revive_China_Society\">Revive China Society</span> among <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Overseas_Chinese\">overseas Chinese</span> in 1894, and after his first attempted uprising <b>failed in 1895</b> he began roughly 16 years of exile, narrowly escaping detention at the Qing legation in London in 1896 in an episode that brought him international notice. In <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tokyo\">Tokyo</span> in 1905 he merged rival revolutionary factions into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tongmenghui\">Tongmenghui</span>, for which he articulated his celebrated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Principles_of_the_People\">Three Principles of the People</span>—nationalism, democracy, and the people's livelihood—as the ideological foundation of the coming republic. Funded largely by donations he tirelessly solicited from Chinese communities abroad, the alliance mounted a series of failed risings, including the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huanghuagang_Uprising\">Second Guangzhou Uprising</span> of 1911 whose</b> 72 fallen rebels became celebrated martyrs, until the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuchang_Uprising\">Wuchang Uprising</span> of October 1911 ignited the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinhai_Revolution\">Xinhai Revolution</span>. <br> <br> Hastening back from a fundraising tour abroad, Sun was elected provisional <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"President_of_the_Republic_of_China\">president</span> of the newly declared republic and was inaugurated at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span> on January 1, 1912. To unify the country and secure the abdication of the child emperor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Puyi\">Puyi</span>, he ceded the presidency after only weeks to the powerful general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_Shikai\">Yuan Shikai</span>, and later in 1912 reorganised the Tongmenghui into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span>. After Yuan suppressed the party and sought to crown himself emperor, China splintered into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warlord_Era\">Warlord Era</span>, during which Sun repeatedly tried to establish a rival nationalist government in the south. Frustrated by the absence of Western backing, he accepted aid from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Communist_International\">Comintern</span> and its agent <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mikhail_Borodin\">Mikhail Borodin</span></b>, forging in 1923–1924 the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_United_Front\">First United Front</span> with the fledgling <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> and founding the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Whampoa_Military_Academy\">Whampoa Military Academy</span> under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span>. He died of cancer in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> on March 12, 1925, before his goal of national reunification was realised through the ensuing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Expedition\">Northern Expedition</span>; his widow <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soong_Ching-ling\">Soong Ching-ling</span> would later become a vice-chair of the People's Republic, and Sun himself remains uniquely venerated by both the Nationalists, who entombed him in a monumental <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Yat-sen_Mausoleum\">mausoleum</span> and honour him as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Father_of_the_Nation\">father of the nation</span></b>, and the Communists, who hail him as a forerunner of their own revolution.","citation":"","answerText":"Sun Yat-sen"},{"id":"em-049","num":"四十九","category":"Reform &amp; Revolution · The Court","question":"Eager to save his realm after the shock of defeat by Japan, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> backed the reformers' programme in 1898, only to be placed under effective house arrest by Empress Dowager Cixi after a conservative counter-coup, dying mysteriously a day before her in 1908.","answer":"Guangxu Emperor","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">14 August 1871 · Beijing</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">14 November 1908 (age 37) · Beijing</span></div>","traditional":"光緒帝","hanzi":"光绪帝","pinyin":"Guāngxù Dì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Guāngxù Dì</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Emperor of Glorious Succession”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Guangxu Emperor</b> (born <b>Zaitian</b>; August 14, 1871 – November 14, 1908) was the 11th emperor of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> and the 9th to rule over <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_proper\">China proper</span>, reigning in name <b>from 1875</b> until his death in 1908. A nephew of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empress_Dowager_Cixi\">Empress Dowager Cixi</span> and a son of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_people\">Manchu</span> prince <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yixuan,_Prince_Chun\">Yixuan</span> of the ruling <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Aisin-Gioro\">Aisin-Gioro</span> house, he was raised to the throne at the age of 3 following the death of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tongzhi_Emperor\">Tongzhi Emperor</span></b> in 1875, a selection that conveniently permitted Cixi to extend her <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Regent\">regency</span> in defiance of established succession custom. He remained under the tutelage of Cixi and the co-regent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empress_Dowager_Ci'an\">Ci'an</span> throughout his minority, and though he formally <b>assumed personal rule around 1889</b> after an arranged marriage to Cixi's niece, the future <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empress_Dowager_Longyu\">Empress Longyu</span>, genuine power continued to reside with his formidable aunt. The catastrophic defeat in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Sino-Japanese_War\">First Sino-Japanese War</span> and the <b>humiliating <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Shimonoseki\">Treaty of Shimonoseki</span> of 1895</b> persuaded the young emperor that the cautious modernisation of the earlier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Self-Strengthening_Movement\">Self-Strengthening Movement</span> had failed, drawing him towards the sweeping proposals of the scholar-reformers <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kang_Youwei\">Kang Youwei</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liang_Qichao\">Liang Qichao</span>, and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tan_Sitong\">Tan Sitong</span></b>. Between June and September 1898 he issued a torrent of decrees over a frenetic 103 days known as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hundred_Days'_Reform\">Hundred Days' Reform</span>, attempting to streamline the bureaucracy and army, modernise the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examination</span> by abolishing the rigid <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight-legged_essay\">eight-legged essay</span>, and found new institutions including the precursor of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peking_University\">Peking University</span>. <br> <br> Alarmed conservatives rallied around Cixi, who seized power in a counter-coup in September 1898 and confined the emperor under effective house arrest on the islet of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yingtai\">Yingtai</span> amid the lake palaces of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhongnanhai\">Zhongnanhai</span> beside the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Forbidden_City\">Forbidden City</span>. Later that month the so-called Six Gentlemen, among them Tan Sitong, were executed in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>, while Kang Youwei and Liang Qichao fled into exile abroad and Cixi resumed an ascendancy that stripped the powerless sovereign of any meaningful authority. During the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boxer_Rebellion\">Boxer Rebellion</span> of 1900 he was compelled to flee the capital with the court to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi'an\">Xi'an</span> as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight-Nation_Alliance\">Eight-Nation Alliance</span> occupied Beijing, and his favoured <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Consort_Zhen\">Consort Zhen</span></b> was reportedly drowned in a palace well on Cixi's orders shortly before the flight. He died on November 14, 1908, a single day before Cixi herself, and long-standing suspicions of foul play were substantially corroborated by a forensic investigation completed in 2008, which measured arsenic in his remains at roughly 2,000 times the normal level and concluded that he had succumbed to acute <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Arsenic_poisoning\">arsenic poisoning</span></b>. Having left no surviving children, he was succeeded by his 2-year-old nephew <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Puyi\">Puyi</span> under the regency of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zaifeng,_Prince_Chun\">Zaifeng</span>, and although the court belatedly adopted many comparable measures through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Policies\">New Policies</span>, his thwarted reign came to epitomise the failure of top-down imperial reform and the gathering momentum towards the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinhai_Revolution\">Xinhai Revolution</span> that toppled the dynasty only 3 years after his death.","citation":"","answerText":"Guangxu Emperor"},{"id":"em-048","num":"四十八","category":"Reform &amp; Revolution · 1898 Reformers","question":"A brilliant student of Kang Youwei and a pioneering journalist, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> fled into exile after 1898 and, through influential essays written abroad, did much to spread ideas of nationalism, constitutional government and modern citizenship among educated Chinese.","answer":"Liang Qichao","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">23 February 1873 · Xinhui, Guangdong</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">19 January 1929 (age 55) · Beijing</span></div>","traditional":"梁啟超","hanzi":"梁启超","pinyin":"Liáng Qǐchāo","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Liáng Qǐchāo</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Liang Qichao</b> (1873–1929) was a Chinese scholar, journalist, and reformer whose voluminous writings made him perhaps the single most influential shaper of modern Chinese political thought in the late <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> and the early Republic. <b>Born in 1873</b> into a scholarly family in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinhui_District\">Xinhui</span> in coastal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangdong\">Guangdong</span>, he proved a precocious talent within the rigorous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examination</span> system, attaining the <b>rank of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Juren\">juren</span> in 1889</b> at the age of 16, yet he soon grew disillusioned with the sterile classicism that conventional success demanded. Around 1890 he entered the renowned Cantonese academy of the radical Confucian thinker <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kang_Youwei\">Kang Youwei</span>, becoming his foremost disciple and absorbing a bold programme of institutional reform inspired partly by the constitutional monarchies of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empire_of_Japan\">Japan</span> and the modernising states of the West. The pair first rose <b>to national prominence in 1895</b>, when they helped rally over 1,000 examination candidates to petition the throne against the humiliating <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Shimonoseki\">Treaty of Shimonoseki</span>, and in 1898 they became leading advisers to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangxu_Emperor\">Guangxu Emperor</span> during the abortive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hundred_Days'_Reform\">Hundred Days' Reform</span>. When the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empress_Dowager_Cixi\">Empress Dowager Cixi</span> crushed the movement in a palace coup that sent his close friend <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tan_Sitong\">Tan Sitong</span> to the execution ground along with other leading reformers, Liang narrowly escaped abroad and settled among the Chinese émigré community of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yokohama\">Yokohama</span></b>. <br> <br> It was from this exile that Liang exerted his deepest influence, founding and editing a succession of reformist journals whose accessible, emotionally charged \"new prose\" style helped popularise <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Written_vernacular_Chinese\">vernacular</span> expression and a flood of new political vocabulary among educated readers. Drawing on thinkers such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jean-Jacques_Rousseau\">Rousseau</span>, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"John_Stuart_Mill\">John Stuart Mill</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Montesquieu\">Montesquieu</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Social_Darwinism\">social Darwinism</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Herbert_Spencer\">Herbert Spencer</span>, he disseminated ideas of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nationalism\">nationalism</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Citizenship\">citizenship</span>, and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitutionalism\">constitutional government</span></b>, calling for the creation of a \"new citizen\" to regenerate the nation. He is widely credited with coining or popularising the term <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhonghua_minzu\">Zhonghua minzu</span>, the notion of a single Chinese nation, even as he championed gradual <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitutional_monarchy\">constitutional monarchy</span> and waged a celebrated polemical contest against the republican revolutionaries of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Yat-sen\">Sun Yat-sen</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tongmenghui\">Tongmenghui</span>. After the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinhai_Revolution\">Xinhai Revolution</span> of 1911 toppled the dynasty, Liang returned home to serve the new <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)\">Republic of China</span> in ministerial posts under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Duan_Qirui\">Duan Qirui</span>, and he helped rally opposition to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_Shikai\">Yuan Shikai</span>'s self-coronation through a famous essay that lent moral force to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Protection_War\">National Protection War</span> of 1915–1916. Having broken decisively with his old teacher over the failed <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_Restoration\">Manchu Restoration</span></b> of 1917, Liang withdrew from politics into prolific scholarship and teaching at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tsinghua_University\">Tsinghua University</span>, and by the time of his death in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> in 1929 his vast output—amounting to well over 10 million characters—had decisively shaped the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Culture_Movement\">New Culture</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"May_Fourth_Movement\">May Fourth</span> generations who would carry his project of national renewal far beyond his own gradualist creed.","citation":"","answerText":"Liang Qichao"},{"id":"em-069","num":"六十九","category":"Warlord Era · The Warlords","question":"Rising from a bandit to become the \"Old Marshal\" who dominated Manchuria and at times the Beijing government, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was killed in 1928 when Japanese officers blew up his train, an assassination that pushed his son towards the Nationalists.","answer":"Zhang Zuolin","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">19 March 1875 · Haicheng, Fengtian</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">4 June 1928 (age 53) · near Shenyang (Huanggutun)</span></div>","traditional":"張作霖","hanzi":"张作霖","pinyin":"Zhāng Zuòlín","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhāng Zuòlín</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Zhang Zuolin</b> (19 March 1875 – 4 June 1928) was a Chinese warlord who, rising from impoverished and lawless beginnings, came to dominate the vast northeastern region of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchuria\">Manchuria</span></b> and for a time the internationally recognised government seated in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>. Born into a poor family in what is now <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liaoning\">Liaoning</span> during the twilight of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span>, he turned in his youth to banditry as one <b>of the mounted <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Honghuzi\">honghuzi</span></b> who roamed the frontier, before the upheavals of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Sino-Japanese_War\">First Sino-Japanese War</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russo-Japanese_War\">Russo-Japanese War</span> enabled him to convert his irregulars into a recognised militia. After the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1911_Revolution\"><b>1911 Revolution</span> swept</b> away the monarchy and inaugurated the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)\">Republic of China</span>, Zhang manoeuvred his way to the military governorship of Fengtian and steadily extended his authority over the three northeastern provinces of Fengtian, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jilin\">Jilin</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heilongjiang\">Heilongjiang</span>. As the leader of the powerful <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fengtian_clique\">Fengtian clique</span> during the chaotic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warlord_Era\">Warlord Era</span>, the commander popularly known as the \"Old Marshal\" assembled one of the largest private armies in the country, a force that at its height numbered several hundred thousand men and was sustained by its own arsenals and a nascent air arm. His ambitions drew him into a protracted rivalry with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhili_clique\">Zhili clique</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Peifu\">Wu Peifu</span>, and after suffering defeat <b>in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Zhili–Fengtian_War\">First Zhili–Fengtian War</span> of 1922</b> he prevailed in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Zhili–Fengtian_War\">Second Zhili–Fengtian War</span> of 1924, a triumph clinched when the so-called \"Christian general\" <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Feng_Yuxiang\">Feng Yuxiang</span> abruptly defected in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing_Coup\">Beijing Coup</span>. <br> <br> With his rivals scattered, Zhang occupied the <b>capital and in June 1927</b> proclaimed himself <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Generalissimo\">Generalissimo</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beiyang_government\">Beiyang government</span>, becoming the last man to head the internationally recognised regime that had governed China since the founding of the republic. His grip on power was soon imperilled by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Expedition\">Northern Expedition</span>, the sweeping campaign through which the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span> and its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Revolutionary_Army\">National Revolutionary Army</span>, commanded by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span>, sought to reunify the country and uproot the northern warlords. Throughout his career Zhang had been cultivated as a client by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empire_of_Japan\">Japanese</span>, whose <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kwantung_Army\">Kwantung Army</span></b> guarded the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South_Manchuria_Railway\">South Manchuria Railway</span> and its attendant concessions, yet his mounting independence and his refusal to surrender Manchurian interests increasingly exasperated his erstwhile patrons. As the Nationalist armies closed on Beijing in 1928, Zhang resolved to withdraw to his Manchurian base, but on 4 June his train was destroyed by a bomb planted at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huanggutun_incident\">Huanggutun</span> on the outskirts of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shenyang\">Mukden</span>, an assassination engineered by the Kwantung Army colonel <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Daisaku_Kōmoto\">Kōmoto Daisaku</span></b> without the sanction of the cabinet of Prime Minister <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tanaka_Giichi\">Tanaka Giichi</span>. The killing failed to secure the pliant Manchuria its plotters had envisioned, for Zhang's son and successor, the \"Young Marshal\" <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Xueliang\">Zhang Xueliang</span>, responded within months by pledging allegiance to the Nationalist government in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northeast_Flag_Replacement\">Northeast Flag Replacement</span> of December 1928, a nominal reunification that Japan would shatter three years later through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mukden_Incident\">Mukden Incident</span> and the ensuing creation of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchukuo\">Manchukuo</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Zhang Zuolin"},{"id":"cnh-027","num":"二十七","category":"China · History","question":"A vast network of overland trade routes opened in the era after the journeys of Zhang Qian, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> carried silk, ideas and religions such as Buddhism between China and the West for centuries.","answer":"Silk Road","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Coined</span><span class=\"dt-v\">German 'Seidenstraße', coined by geographer Ferdinand von Richthofen, 1877</span></div>","traditional":"絲綢之路","hanzi":"丝绸之路","pinyin":"Sīchóu zhī Lù","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Sīchóu zhī Lù</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Silk Road</b> was a vast network of overland and maritime trade routes that linked <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> with <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Asia\">Central Asia</span></b>, Persia, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mediterranean_Sea\">Mediterranean</span> world, remaining active from the 2nd century BCE until the mid-15th century. The routes were opened in the wake of the Han envoy Zhang Qian's expeditions, <b>beginning in 138 BCE</b> and undertaken for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_Wu_of_Han\">Emperor Wu</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span>, after which Chinese control of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hexi_Corridor\">Hexi Corridor</span></b> and the oasis states of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tarim_Basin\">Tarim Basin</span> secured passage into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Western_Regions\">Western Regions</span>. From the capital <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chang'an\">Chang'an</span> the main artery ran west through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dunhuang\">Dunhuang</span>, split to skirt the forbidding <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taklamakan_Desert\">Taklamakan Desert</span>, and reconnected near <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kashgar\">Kashgar</span> before climbing through the mountains to the great emporium of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Samarkand\">Samarkand</span> and on toward Persia and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Roman_Empire\">Roman world</span>. Its most coveted commodity was Chinese silk—so prized in Rome, whose people knew the distant producers only as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Seres\">Seres</span>, that the resulting drain of gold alarmed Roman moralists—though the caravans also bore <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Spice_trade\">spices</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paper\">paper</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Porcelain\">porcelain</span>, jade, glassware, and the prized \"heavenly\" <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ferghana_horse\">Ferghana horses</span> coveted by Emperor Wu. The long-distance traffic was handled largely by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sogdians\">Sogdian</span> merchants and threaded through a succession of intervening empires—the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kushan_Empire\">Kushan Empire</span></b> of the northwest and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Parthian_Empire\">Parthian</span> and later <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sasanian_Empire\">Sasanian</span> realms of Persia—each of which profited as a middleman.<br> <br>Along these arteries travelled ideas and faiths, above all Buddhism, which spread from India into China during the 1st century CE and inspired such monuments as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mogao_Caves\">Mogao Caves</span>, propagated by translators like <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kumārajīva\">Kumārajīva</span> and by pilgrim-monks <b>such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Faxian\">Faxian</span> around 400 CE</b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xuanzang\">Xuanzang</span> between 629 and 645, while <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manichaeism\">Manichaeism</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zoroastrianism\">Zoroastrianism</span>, and Nestorian Christianity travelled the same roads. Overland exchange reached its zenith under the cosmopolitan <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang dynasty</span> between the 7th and 9th centuries, and after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Talas\">Battle of Talas</span> in 751 the techniques of papermaking, together with the new religion of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Islam\">Islam</span>, spread steadily westward into the lands beyond the frontier. The routes, having waned amid later turmoil, were dramatically revived under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongol_Empire\">Mongol Empire</span>, whose 13th-century <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pax_Mongolica\">Pax Mongolica</span> made long-distance travel safe enough for the Venetian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marco_Polo\">Marco Polo</span>, who journeyed to the court of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kublai_Khan\">Kublai Khan</span> between 1271 and 1295. This final efflorescence faded <b>across the 14th and 15th centuries</b> as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Black_Death\">Black Death</span> spread along the caravan tracks, the Mongol realm fragmented, the rising <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ottoman_Empire\">Ottoman Empire</span></b> taxed the western termini, and the European maritime ventures of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Age_of_Discovery\">Age of Discovery</span> diverted commerce to the sea. The term itself was not ancient but was coined in 1877 by the German geographer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ferdinand_von_Richthofen\">Ferdinand von Richthofen</span>, and the evocative idea of a transcontinental bridge of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eurasia\">Eurasian</span> commerce and culture has since been consciously revived, most prominently in China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Belt_and_Road_Initiative\">Belt and Road Initiative</span> of 2013.","citation":"","answerText":"Silk Road"},{"id":"em-072","num":"七十二","category":"New Culture · Intellectuals","question":"Dean at Peking University and founder of an influential reformist magazine, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> went on from the New Culture Movement to become the founding general secretary of the Chinese Communist Party before being expelled from it.","answer":"Chen Duxiu","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">8 October 1879 · Anqing, Anhui</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">27 May 1942 (age 62) · Jiangjin, Sichuan</span></div>","traditional":"陳獨秀","hanzi":"陈独秀","pinyin":"Chén Dúxiù","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Chén Dúxiù</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Chen Duxiu</b> (8 October 1879 – 27 May 1942) was a Chinese revolutionary, educator, and writer who ranks among the principal architects of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Culture_Movement\">New Culture Movement</span></b> and served as the founding leader of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span>. Born in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anqing\">Anqing</span> in the province of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anhui\">Anhui</span>, he received a classical education and passed the lowest tier of the imperial <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">civil service examinations</span>, yet he grew disillusioned with the decaying <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> and travelled repeatedly to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empire_of_Japan\">Japan</span>, where he absorbed the reformist and revolutionary currents then circulating among Chinese students abroad. <b>In 1915</b> he founded in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span> the reformist magazine <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Youth\"><i>New Youth</i></span>, which under his editorship became the foremost organ of intellectual ferment, attaining a reported peak circulation of around 16,000 copies and championing the era's twin rallying cries of science and democracy. Through its pages he launched fierce assaults on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucianism</span> and the old <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Classical_Chinese\">classical language</span>, promoting in their place a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Written_vernacular_Chinese\">vernacular written Chinese</span> accessible to ordinary readers alongside Western notions of progress, individual liberty, and social emancipation. Appointed dean of the School of <b>Letters at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peking_University\">Peking University</span> in 1917</b> by the chancellor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cai_Yuanpei\">Cai Yuanpei</span>, he gathered around him a brilliant circle that included <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Shih\">Hu Shih</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Dazhao\">Li Dazhao</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lu_Xun\">Lu Xun</span>, and his writings helped galvanise the student demonstrations <b>of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"May_Fourth_Movement\">May Fourth Movement</span> in 1919</b>. <br> <br> The political ferment of those years and the example of Russia's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"October_Revolution\">October Revolution</span> drew Chen towards <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marxism\">Marxism</span>, and together with Li Dazhao and under the guidance of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Communist_International\">Communist International</span> he began organising the scattered communist circles that would coalesce into a national party. <b>At the party's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1st_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">First National Congress</span></b> in 1921 he was chosen, though absent, as its founding <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"General_Secretary_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">general secretary</span>, an office he would hold for six turbulent years as the fledgling organisation grew from a few dozen members into a force of national consequence. Bound by Comintern policy to a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_United_Front\">First United Front</span> with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span>, Chen presided over the alliance until it disintegrated amid the bloodshed of the 1927 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_massacre\">Shanghai massacre</span>, after which the debacle was blamed on his alleged \"right opportunism\" and he was removed from the leadership at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"August_7th_Conference\">August 7th Conference</span></b> in favour of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qu_Qiubai\">Qu Qiubai</span>. Increasingly critical of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joseph_Stalin\">Stalin</span> and the Comintern's direction of the Chinese revolution, he embraced the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Trotskyism\">Trotskyist</span> opposition associated with <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Leon_Trotsky\">Leon Trotsky</span></b> and was formally expelled from the very party he had founded in November 1929. Arrested by the Nationalist authorities in 1932 and sentenced to a long prison term, Chen was released in 1937 amid the outbreak of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Sino-Japanese_War\">Second Sino-Japanese War</span>, and he passed his final years in poverty and political isolation in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan\">Sichuan</span>, dying in 1942 a figure estranged from nearly every camp he had once helped to shape.","citation":"","answerText":"Chen Duxiu"},{"id":"cnc-101","num":"一百零一","category":"China · Culture","question":"Widely hailed as the father of modern Chinese literature, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> abandoned medicine for the pen and skewered the failings of old society in vernacular stories such as <i>The True Story of Ah Q</i> and <i>A Madman's Diary</i>.","answer":"Lu Xun","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">25 September 1881</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">19 October 1936</span></div>","traditional":"魯迅","hanzi":"鲁迅","pinyin":"Lǔ Xùn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Lǔ Xùn</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Lu Xun</b>, pen name of Zhou Shuren, is widely hailed as the father of modern <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_literature\">Chinese literature</span></b>, the sharpest pen of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Culture_Movement\">New Culture Movement</span>, who abandoned medicine to dissect the spirit of old China in vernacular fiction. Born to a declining gentry family in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shaoxing\">Shaoxing</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhejiang\">Zhejiang</span>, his childhood shadowed by a grandfather jailed for examination bribery and a father dosed to death by quack prescriptions, he <b>went to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japan\">Japan</span> in 1902</b> and entered medical school at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sendai\">Sendai</span>. There, in 1906, a lecture slide showing Chinese onlookers placidly watching a countryman beheaded as a spy convinced him that bodies were not the problem, and he quit medicine to heal minds with literature. The cure <b>arrived in 1918</b>, when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"A_Madman's_Diary\"><i>A Madman's Diary</i></span>, published in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Youth\"><i>New Youth</i></span> as the first great story in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Written_vernacular_Chinese\">written vernacular Chinese</span> and borrowing its title from <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nikolai_Gogol\">Gogol</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Diary_of_a_Madman\"><i>Diary of a Madman</i></span></b>, read 4,000 years of Confucian morality as a history of cannibalism and closed with the plea \"save the children.\" The stories <b>collected in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Call_to_Arms_(short_story_collection)\"><i>Call to Arms</i></span> in 1923</b>—among them <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kong_Yiji\">\"Kong Yiji\"</span> and the serialized <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_True_Story_of_Ah_Q\"><i>True Story of Ah Q</i></span> of 1921–1922, whose hero converts every humiliation into a \"spiritual victory\"—gave the nation a mirror, while the prose poems of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wild_Grass\"><i>Wild Grass</i></span> showed his darker lyric genius. <br> <br> Teaching at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peking_University\">Peking University</span> and elsewhere alongside reformers like <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Shih\">Hu Shih</span> amid the ferment after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"May_Fourth_Movement\">May Fourth Movement</span>, he memorialized a student killed in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"March_18_Massacre\">March 18 Massacre</span></b> of 1926, fled official displeasure south, and settled in 1927 in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span>, where his last decade produced over 600 barbed <i>zawen</i> essays against the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span> censorship and every species of cant. Drawn left, he headed the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"League_of_Left-Wing_Writers\">League of Left-Wing Writers</span></b> from 1930 yet never joined the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span>, quarreling with commissars even as he sheltered young radicals. He was also a pathbreaking scholar in his <i>Brief History of Chinese Fiction</i>, a prolific translator, and the patron who introduced the German printmaker <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Käthe_Kollwitz\">Käthe Kollwitz</span> and launched China's modern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Woodcut\">woodcut</span> movement. Dead of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tuberculosis\">tuberculosis</span> in 1936 at 55, he was buried under a banner reading \"Soul of the Nation,\" then canonized by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> in 1940 as the bravest standard-bearer of the cultural revolution, though Mao reportedly conceded in 1957 that a living Lu Xun would have fallen silent or gone to jail. His tomb presides over Shanghai's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lu_Xun_Park\">Lu Xun Park</span>, the state's top fiction award is the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lu_Xun_Literary_Prize\">Lu Xun Literary Prize</span>, schoolchildren still memorize Ah Q, and admirers from Tokyo to Stockholm, among them <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kenzaburō_Ōe\">Kenzaburō Ōe</span>, keep him modern Asia's most piercing conscience.","citation":"","answerText":"Lu Xun"},{"id":"em-098","num":"九十八","category":"War with Japan · Collaboration","question":"Once a close associate of Sun Yat-sen and a rival of Chiang Kai-shek within the Kuomintang, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> defected during the war to head a Japanese-sponsored collaborationist government in occupied Nanjing.","answer":"Wang Jingwei","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">4 May 1883 · Sanshui, Guangdong</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">10 November 1944 (age 61) · Nagoya, Japan</span></div>","traditional":"汪精衛","hanzi":"汪精卫","pinyin":"Wāng Jīngwèi","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Wāng Jīngwèi</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Wang Jingwei</b> (4 May 1883 – 10 November 1944), born <b>Wang Zhaoming</b>, was a Chinese revolutionary and politician who rose to the highest ranks of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)\">Republic of China</span></b> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span> as a leading interpreter of Sun Yat-sen's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Principles_of_the_People\">Three Principles of the People</span> before his wartime collaboration with Japan made his name a byword for treason. <b>Born in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangdong\">Guangdong</span> in 1883</b>, he won a government scholarship to study law in Japan at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hosei_University\">Hosei University</span>, where in 1905 he joined Sun's newly founded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tongmenghui\">Tongmenghui</span> and quickly became its foremost essayist and propagandist. In 1910 he gained nationwide fame by plotting to assassinate the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> prince regent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zaifeng,_Prince_Chun\">Zaifeng</span>, father of the boy emperor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Puyi\">Puyi</span>, for which he was sentenced to life imprisonment, only to be freed as a celebrated hero after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1911_Revolution\"><b>1911</b> Revolution</span>. Entrusted with drafting Sun's political testament upon the latter's death in 1925, he chaired the Nationalist government at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou\">Guangzhou</span> and led the party's left wing, but during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Expedition\">Northern Expedition</span> his rivalry with Chiang Kai-shek tore the movement apart, and <b>in 1927</b> he headed a competing leftist regime at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuhan\">Wuhan</span> that briefly sustained the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_United_Front\">First United Front</span> with the communists until Chiang's bloody <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_massacre\">Shanghai massacre</span> shattered it. Thereafter he alternated between opposing and serving Chiang—whose authority rested on the officers he had trained at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Whampoa_Military_Academy\">Whampoa Military Academy</span>—and held the premiership as president of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Executive_Yuan\">Executive Yuan</span></b> from 1932 to 1935, until a 1935 assassination attempt left a bullet lodged in his body that was never removed and that would gravely undermine his health.<br> <br>Following the outbreak of full-scale war with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empire_of_Japan\">Empire of Japan</span> in 1937, Wang grew convinced that China could not prevail militarily and emerged as the foremost advocate of a negotiated settlement, leading a defeatist \"peace faction\" within the Nationalist camp during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Sino-Japanese_War\">Second Sino-Japanese War</span>. In December 1938 he fled the wartime capital of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chongqing\">Chongqing</span> for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hanoi\">Hanoi</span> and publicly endorsed the conciliatory terms offered by the Japanese <b>prime minister <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fumimaro_Konoe\">Fumimaro Konoe</span></b>, an open break that severed him from Chiang's government for good. On 30 March 1940 he proclaimed in occupied Nanjing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Reorganized_National_Government_of_the_Republic_of_China\">Reorganised National Government of the Republic of China</span>, a Japanese-sponsored <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Puppet_state\">puppet state</span> staffed by associates such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Fohai\">Zhou Fohai</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Gongbo\">Chen Gongbo</span> and bolstered by his formidable wife <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Bijun\">Chen Bijun</span>, which claimed to be the legitimate heir of Sun's revolution while serving the aims of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Greater_East_Asia_Co-Prosperity_Sphere\">Greater East Asia Co-Prosperity Sphere</span></b>. Wang died on 10 November 1944 in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nagoya\">Nagoya</span>, Japan, at the age of 61, his end hastened by the unextracted bullet of 1935, and his regime collapsed the following year with the close of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_War_II\">World War II</span>. Vilified ever since as the archetypal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hanjian\">hanjian</span>, or traitor to the Chinese nation, he was so reviled that in 1946 the victorious Nationalists demolished his tomb near the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Yat-sen_Mausoleum\">Mausoleum of Sun Yat-sen</span>, though later historians have debated whether his <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Collaborationism\">collaborationism</span> sprang from cynical ambition or a misguided conviction that accommodation might spare his country greater devastation.","citation":"","answerText":"Wang Jingwei"},{"id":"em-042","num":"四十二","category":"Foreign Imperialism · Wars","question":"Fought from 1884 to 1885 over control of Vietnam and its status as a Chinese tributary, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> saw the French destroy a southern fleet at Fuzhou and end Chinese suzerainty over its southern neighbour despite some Chinese successes on land.","answer":"Sino-French War","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Began</span><span class=\"dt-v\">August 1884 · clash over Vietnam</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Ended</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1885 · Treaty of Tientsin</span></div>","traditional":"中法戰爭","hanzi":"中法战争","pinyin":"Zhōngfǎ Zhànzhēng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōngfǎ Zhànzhēng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Sino-French War</b> was an undeclared conflict fought <b>from 1884</b> to <b>1885</b> between the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"French_Third_Republic\">French Third Republic</span></b> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> over control of northern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vietnam\">Vietnam</span> and the centuries-old <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Suzerainty\">suzerainty</span> that China claimed over its southern neighbour through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tributary_system_of_China\">tributary system</span>. The roots of the war lay in France's steady colonial expansion in Indochina, which had begun with the seizure of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cochinchina\">Cochinchina</span> under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Saigon\">Treaty of Saigon</span> of 1862 and continued into <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tonkin\">Tonkin</span></b> against the resistance of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nguyễn_dynasty\">Nguyễn dynasty</span> and the irregular <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Black_Flag_Army\">Black Flag Army</span> commanded by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Yongfu\">Liu Yongfu</span>. Open hostilities erupted after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bắc_Lệ_ambush\">Bắc Lệ ambush</span> of June 1884, in which a French column advancing to occupy agreed frontier posts was attacked by Qing forces with the loss of dozens of men, an incident that shattered a fragile preliminary accord and prompted Paris to demand a heavy indemnity and authorise punitive reprisals during the wider <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tonkin_campaign\">Tonkin campaign</span></b>. On 23 August 1884 the French squadron under Admiral <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Amédée_Courbet\">Amédée Courbet</span> launched a surprise assault at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Fuzhou\">Battle of Fuzhou</span>, annihilating the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fujian_Fleet\">Fujian Fleet</span> in roughly an hour by sinking nine warships and killing an estimated 2,000 to 3,000 Chinese sailors for negligible losses of its own. The same campaign also devastated the modern dockyards and shipbuilding facilities of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foochow_Arsenal\">Foochow Arsenal</span> at Mawei, a flagship project of the reformist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Self-Strengthening_Movement\">Self-Strengthening Movement</span> that had ironically been constructed with French engineering and technical assistance only a generation earlier. <br> <br> Unable to force a decision on the Chinese mainland, Courbet carried the naval war to the sea approaches of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span>, occupying the northern port of Keelung during the prolonged <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Keelung_Campaign\">Keelung Campaign</span></b> and seizing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Penghu\">Pescadores</span> islands in a swift operation, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pescadores_campaign\">Pescadores campaign</span> of March 1885. On land, however, Qing fortunes improved markedly when the aged general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Feng_Zicai\">Feng Zicai</span>, then in his late sixties, rallied his troops to repel a French advance at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Bang_Bo\">Battle of Bang Bo</span></b> near the Zhennan Pass in March 1885, triggering a disorderly <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Retreat_from_Lạng_Sơn\">retreat from Lạng Sơn</span> that stunned French commanders and electrified opinion across the Qing empire. News of this reverse ignited a furious political crisis in France that toppled the cabinet of Prime Minister <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jules_Ferry\">Jules Ferry</span> over the costly Tonkin venture on 30 March 1885, even though the underlying military balance had in fact remained overwhelmingly in France's favour. The two sides nonetheless moved swiftly towards a settlement, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Tientsin_(1885)\">Treaty of Tientsin</span>, negotiated for China by the senior statesman <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Hongzhang\">Li Hongzhang</span> and signed on 9 June 1885, compelled the Qing to abandon its historic claims and recognise the French <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Protectorate\">protectorate</span> over <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Annam_(French_protectorate)\">Annam</span> and Tonkin. The outcome confirmed the absorption of Vietnam into the new colonial federation of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"French_Indochina\">French Indochina</span> and laid bare the limits of Qing naval modernisation, a strategic humiliation that, together with mounting fiscal strain, foreshadowed the far graver defeat China would suffer a decade later in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Sino-Japanese_War\">First Sino-Japanese War</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Sino-French War"},{"id":"em-046","num":"四十六","category":"Foreign Imperialism · Scramble for China","question":"In the scramble that followed the defeat by Japan, a <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was a zone where one power — Russia, Germany or Japan — claimed exclusive rights to railways, mines and loans, raising fears that China would be \"carved up like a melon\".","answer":"sphere of influence","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Origin</span><span class=\"dt-v\">diplomatic term from the late 19th c. (Berlin Conference, 1884–85)</span></div>","traditional":"勢力範圍","hanzi":"势力范围","pinyin":"shìlì fànwéi","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">shìlì fànwéi</span></div>","abstract":"A <b>sphere of influence</b>, in the <b>field of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"International_relations\">international relations</span></b>, denotes a region or state in which a single outside power claims exclusive or preponderant rights over economic concessions, railways, mining, and political affairs while stopping short of the formal annexation associated with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Colonialism\">colonial</span> rule. The arrangement became most closely associated with the threatened partition of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> China, whose military weakness was starkly exposed by its defeat <b>in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Sino-Japanese_War\">First Sino-Japanese War</span> of 1894–1895</b> and the punitive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Shimonoseki\">Treaty of Shimonoseki</span> that followed. When that treaty awarded the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liaodong_Peninsula\">Liaodong Peninsula</span> to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empire_of_Japan\">Empire of Japan</span>, the so-called <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Triple_Intervention\">Triple Intervention</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russian_Empire\">Russia</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"French_Third_Republic\">France</span>, and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"German_Empire\">German Empire</span></b> forced Tokyo to surrender the peninsula in return for a larger indemnity, demonstrating the readiness of the major powers to dictate terms in the region. Over the next few years these states converted longstanding privileges won through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Unequal_treaty\">unequal treaties</span>, including <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Extraterritoriality\">extraterritoriality</span> and access to designated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_port\">treaty ports</span>, into demands for exclusive territorial leases and monopolies over railway construction and government loans across entire provinces. The resulting <b>scramble for concessions in 1897–1898 fed</b> widespread fears, captured in the contemporary metaphor of China being \"carved up like a melon,\" that the empire would be dismembered amid the broader wave of European <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperialism\">imperialism</span> then reshaping much of Africa and Asia. <br> <br> In 1898 the German Empire secured a 99-year lease of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiaozhou_Bay_Leased_Territory\">Jiaozhou Bay</span> together with a sphere over the province of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shandong\">Shandong</span>, after which Russia obtained a 25-year lease of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kwantung_Leased_Territory\">Port Arthur</span> and predominance throughout <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchuria\">Manchuria</span>, anchored by the newly built <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Eastern_Railway\">Chinese Eastern Railway</span>. France took a 99-year lease of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhouwan\">Guangzhouwan</span> and a sphere over the southern provinces adjoining <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yunnan\">Yunnan</span>, while Britain leased <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Weihaiwei_under_British_rule\">Weihaiwei</span> and, through the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Convention_for_the_Extension_of_Hong_Kong_Territory\">Convention for the Extension of Hong Kong Territory</span></b>, acquired the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Territories\">New Territories</span> for 99 years while claiming the densely populated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span> valley as its commercial preserve. The Empire of Japan, for its part, extracted <b>a non-alienation pledge in 1898</b> barring the cession of the coastal province of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fujian\">Fujian</span> to any rival, consolidating its foothold across the strait from the island of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span>, which it had annexed at Shimonoseki. Inside China the crisis helped spur the reformist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hundred_Days'_Reform\">Hundred Days' Reform</span> of 1898, while the United States, fearing the exclusion of its merchants, issued the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Open_Door_Policy\">Open Door Policy</span></b> notes of 1899–1900 under Secretary of State <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"John_Hay\">John Hay</span> to press for equal commercial access and Chinese territorial integrity, before anti-foreign violence erupted in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boxer_Rebellion\">Boxer Rebellion</span> of 1899–1901. Japan's victory in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russo-Japanese_War\">Russo-Japanese War</span> of 1904–1905 transferred Russia's southern Manchurian leases and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South_Manchuria_Railway\">South Manchuria Railway</span> to Tokyo, and although the spheres never produced outright partition and most leased territories were eventually returned, the episode endured as a central grievance of the so-called <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Century_of_humiliation\">century of humiliation</span> that still informs modern Chinese conceptions of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sovereignty\">sovereignty</span> and territorial integrity.","citation":"","answerText":"sphere of influence"},{"id":"em-081","num":"八十一","category":"Nationalist Revolution · Leadership","question":"Succeeding Sun Yat-sen as leader of the Nationalists, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> unified much of China by force, purged his Communist allies, led the resistance against Japan, and ultimately lost the mainland, withdrawing to Taiwan.","answer":"Chiang Kai-shek","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">31 October 1887 · Fenghua, Zhejiang</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">5 April 1975 (age 87) · Taipei, Taiwan</span></div>","traditional":"蔣介石","hanzi":"蒋介石","pinyin":"Jiǎng Jièshí","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Jiǎng Jièshí</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Chiang Kai-shek</b> (October 31, 1887 – April 5, 1975) was a Chinese Nationalist military and political leader who rose from a salt-merchant family in <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fenghua\">Fenghua</span></b>, in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhejiang\">Zhejiang</span> province, during the final years of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span>. After military training in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empire_of_Japan\">Empire of Japan</span> and early revolutionary activity in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tongmenghui\">Tongmenghui</span> alongside <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Yat-sen\">Sun Yat-sen</span>, he was <b>named in 1924</b> as founding commandant of the Soviet-assisted <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Whampoa_Military_Academy\">Whampoa Military Academy</span>, a post that gave him command of a loyal officer corps within the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span>. Following Sun's death in 1925 he consolidated his standing and <b>launched the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Expedition\">Northern Expedition</span> of 1926–1928</b>, a campaign that defeated the regional militarists of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warlord_Era\">Warlord Era</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beiyang_government\">Beiyang government</span> to bring much of China under a single Nationalist authority centred on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span>. In the midst of that advance he abruptly turned on his former allies in <b>the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_massacre\">Shanghai massacre</span> of April 1927</b>, shattering the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_United_Front\">First United Front</span> with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> and igniting a protracted civil struggle against forces increasingly led by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>. During the ensuing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing_decade\">Nanjing decade</span> he headed an authoritarian Nationalist state, promoted the conservative <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Life_Movement\">New Life Movement</span></b> that blended Confucian and modernising ideals, and waged repeated military campaigns against the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Soviet_Republic\">Chinese Soviet Republic</span> that ultimately forced his rivals into the epic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Long_March\">Long March</span> of 1934–1935. <br> <br> Reluctant to confront Japan while he pursued the communists, he was seized by his own subordinate <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Xueliang\">Zhang Xueliang</span> in the 1936 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi'an_Incident\">Xi'an Incident</span> and pressed into a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_United_Front\">Second United Front</span> that committed him to leading national resistance once the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Sino-Japanese_War\">Second Sino-Japanese War</span> broke out in 1937. As supreme commander he moved his capital inland to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chongqing\">Chongqing</span> after atrocities such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing_Massacre\">Nanjing Massacre</span>, in which an estimated 200,000 to 300,000 civilians and disarmed soldiers were killed, and sustained an 8-year war effort in which Chinese military and civilian deaths are commonly estimated at 14 to 20 million. Honoured as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Generalissimo\">Generalissimo</span> and supported by his influential wife <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soong_Mei-ling\">Soong Mei-ling</span>, he represented China among the major Allied leaders at the 1943 <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cairo_Conference\">Cairo Conference</span></b> with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Franklin_D._Roosevelt\">Franklin D. Roosevelt</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Winston_Churchill\">Winston Churchill</span>, even as bitter friction with the American chief of staff <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joseph_Stilwell\">Joseph Stilwell</span> strained the wartime partnership. After Japan's defeat the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">Chinese Civil War</span> resumed, and rampant hyperinflation, mass defections, and entrenched corruption steadily eroded his armies until the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army\">People's Liberation Army</span> overran the mainland in 1949. He retreated to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span> with roughly 2 million soldiers, officials, and refugees, together with much of the national gold reserve, an exodus that re-established the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Retreat_of_the_government_of_the_Republic_of_China_to_Taiwan\">Republic of China</span></b> with its seat at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taipei\">Taipei</span>, where he governed as president under decades of martial law and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"White_Terror_(Taiwan)\">White Terror</span>, held the contested Chinese seat at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_Nations\">United Nations</span> until 1971, and on his death in 1975 left a mantle that eventually passed to his son <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Ching-kuo\">Chiang Ching-kuo</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Chiang Kai-shek"},{"id":"em-041","num":"四十一","category":"Self-Strengthening · The Navy","question":"The largest and most modern of the empire's regional navies, built up by Li Hongzhang with imported warships, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was annihilated by the Japanese at the Yalu River and Weihaiwei in the war of 1894–1895.","answer":"Beiyang Fleet","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Established</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1888 · China’s modern navy</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Destroyed</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1895 · by Japan</span></div>","traditional":"北洋水師","hanzi":"北洋水师","pinyin":"Běiyáng Shuǐshī","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Běiyáng Shuǐshī</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Northern Seas Fleet”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Beiyang Fleet</b> was the largest and most modern of the four regional navies of the late <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span>, built up by Li Hongzhang in his role as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Viceroy_of_Zhili\">Viceroy of Zhili</span></b> as the naval centrepiece of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Self-Strengthening_Movement\">Self-Strengthening Movement</span> <b>inaugurated in 1861</b>. Under that programme of importing Western arms and industry, the empire also maintained the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanyang_Fleet\">Nanyang Fleet</span> and smaller provincial squadrons in Fujian and Guangdong, one of which France largely destroyed at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Fuzhou\">Battle of Fuzhou</span> <b>during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-French_War\">Sino-French War</span> of 1884–1885</b>. Its striking power rested on two German-built <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ironclad_warship\">ironclad</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battleship\">battleships</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_ironclad_Dingyuan\">Dingyuan</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_ironclad_Zhenyuan\">Zhenyuan</span>, each displacing more than 7,000 tons and mounting four 305-millimetre <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Krupp\">Krupp</span> guns when they entered service <b>from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"AG_Vulcan_Stettin\">Stettin shipyard</span> in 1885</b>, supported by faster <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Protected_cruiser\">protected cruisers</span> ordered from the British armaments firm <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Armstrong_Whitworth\">Armstrong</span>. Formally constituted in 1888 and operating from the fortified harbours of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lüshunkou_District\">Lüshunkou (Port Arthur)</span> and Weihaiwei on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shandong\">Shandong</span> coast, the fleet was widely reckoned the strongest in Asia and counted among the ten largest navies in the world, its warships <b>placed under Admiral <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ding_Ruchang\">Ding Ruchang</span></b>, a former cavalry officer drawn from Li Hongzhang's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huai_Army\">Huai Army</span>. Yet the force stagnated after 1888, taking delivery of no new capital ships as money intended for the navy was siphoned elsewhere—most notoriously towards the lavish reconstruction of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Summer_Palace\">Summer Palace</span> and its ornamental <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marble_Boat\">Marble Boat</span> commissioned for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empress_Dowager_Cixi\">Empress Dowager Cixi</span>—while corruption and chronic shortages of modern ammunition steadily eroded its readiness.<br> <br>When the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Sino-Japanese_War\">First Sino-Japanese War</span> broke out in 1894 over rival ambitions in Korea, the fleet found itself pitted against the thoroughly modern <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_Japanese_Navy\">Imperial Japanese Navy</span></b> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empire_of_Japan\">Empire of Japan</span>, whose <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Combined_Fleet\">Combined Fleet</span> was commanded by Admiral <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Itō_Sukeyuki\">Itō Sukeyuki</span>. At the climactic engagement fought in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_Sea\">Yellow Sea</span> near the mouth of the Yalu River on 17 September 1894—the largest naval battle of the war—the Beiyang squadron lost five cruisers without sinking a single Japanese warship, among them the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_cruiser_Zhiyuan\">Zhiyuan</span>, whose captain <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Shichang\">Deng Shichang</span></b> perished with his crew after reportedly trying to ram an enemy vessel. The surviving warships fell back on Weihaiwei, where they were blockaded and overwhelmed in a combined land-and-sea assault between January and February 1895, the resulting <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Weihaiwei\">Battle of Weihaiwei</span> ending in the surrender of the base, the suicide of Ding Ruchang by opium on 12 February 1895, and the capture of the crippled Zhenyuan, which was promptly taken into Japanese service. The war was closed by the punitive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Shimonoseki\">Treaty of Shimonoseki</span> in April 1895, by which the Qing ceded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Penghu\">Penghu</span> islands, surrendered the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liaodong_Peninsula\">Liaodong Peninsula</span>, and undertook to pay an indemnity of 200 million <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tael\">taels</span> of silver, although the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Triple_Intervention\">Triple Intervention</span> of Russia, Germany, and France shortly forced Japan to relinquish the Liaodong gain. The destruction of the empire's premier fleet shattered faith in the Self-Strengthening project, laid bare the futility of purchasing foreign warships without comparable institutional and political reform, and fed the reformist ferment that erupted in the abortive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hundred_Days'_Reform\">Hundred Days' Reform</span> of 1898, leaving the fleet's name a lasting emblem in China of modernisation undone by neglect and graft.","citation":"","answerText":"Beiyang Fleet"},{"id":"em-073","num":"七十三","category":"New Culture · Intellectuals","question":"A librarian and professor at Peking University who became one of China's earliest converts to Marxism after the Russian Revolution, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> co-founded the Communist Party and was executed in 1927 on the orders of the warlord Zhang Zuolin.","answer":"Li Dazhao","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">29 October 1889 · Leting, Hebei</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">28 April 1927 (age 37) · Beijing (executed)</span></div>","traditional":"李大釗","hanzi":"李大钊","pinyin":"Lǐ Dàzhāo","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Lǐ Dàzhāo</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Li Dazhao</b> (October 29, 1889 – April 28, 1927) was a Chinese intellectual, librarian, and revolutionary who became one of the principal founders of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> and the first major thinker to promote <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marxism\">Marxism</span></b> in China. Born into a rural family in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hebei\">Hebei</span> province during the closing years of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span>, he came of age as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinhai_Revolution\">Xinhai Revolution</span> toppled the empire, and he then studied political economy at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Waseda_University\">Waseda University</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empire_of_Japan\">Japan</span> <b>from 1913</b> to 1916 before returning to a China riven by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warlord_Era\">warlord politics</span>. In 1918 he was appointed chief librarian of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peking_University\">Peking University</span> and soon held professorships in history, economics, and political science, transforming the library into a gathering place for radical youth and becoming a central figure of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Culture_Movement\">New Culture Movement</span></b> and a frequent contributor to the influential journal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Youth\"><i>New Youth</i></span>. It was in the university library that he employed the young <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> as an assistant on a meagre salary of 8 silver dollars a month—a fraction of the 200 to 300 dollars paid to senior professors—exposing the future leader to radical ideas during a formative period that Mao would later openly acknowledge. As one of the intellectual leaders <b>behind the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"May_Fourth_Movement\">May Fourth Movement</span> of 1919</b>, he helped channel surging student nationalism towards a broader programme of social and political transformation, and his prestige among China's young radicals grew rapidly as he argued that only fundamental change could rescue the nation. <br> <br> The Russian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"October_Revolution\">October Revolution</span> inspired his decisive turn to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marxism–Leninism\">Marxism–Leninism</span>, which he proclaimed in landmark essays such as <i>The Victory of Bolshevism</i> and <i>The Victory of the Common People</i>, hailing the triumph of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bolsheviks\">Bolsheviks</span> as the dawn of a new era for humanity. He organised a pioneering Marxist study society <b>at the university in 1920</b> and, together with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Duxiu\">Chen Duxiu</span>, laid the groundwork for the Communist Party that was founded in 1921 with backing from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Communist_International\">Comintern</span>, a partnership immortalised in the phrase \"Chen in the south, Li in the north,\" even though neither man attended the founding congress that represented roughly 50 members nationwide. During the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_United_Front\">First United Front</span> he also joined the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span>, helping to reorganise it under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Yat-sen\">Sun Yat-sen</span> and winning election to its Central Executive Committee at the party's national congress in 1924, all while directing the communist movement across northern China. As the alliance disintegrated and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span> turned violently against the communists in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_massacre\">purge</span> of April 1927, Li took refuge in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Soviet</span> diplomatic compound within the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing_Legation_Quarter\">Beijing Legation Quarter</span></b>, only for the forces of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fengtian_clique\">Fengtian</span> warlord <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Zuolin\">Zhang Zuolin</span> to raid the premises and seize him. On April 28, 1927, he was executed by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Strangling\">strangulation</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> alongside 19 others at the age of 37, and in subsequent communist historiography he was venerated as a foundational <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Martyr\">martyr</span></b> whose distinctive fusion of revolutionary theory with a faith in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peasant\">peasantry</span> and in the dynamism of youth left a deep imprint on the young Mao Zedong and on the party he had helped create.","citation":"","answerText":"Li Dazhao"},{"id":"em-074","num":"七十四","category":"New Culture · Intellectuals","question":"A philosopher educated in the United States under John Dewey, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> became a leading voice of the New Culture Movement by championing writing in the everyday vernacular in place of classical Chinese.","answer":"Hu Shih","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">17 December 1891 · Shanghai</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">24 February 1962 (age 70) · Taipei, Taiwan</span></div>","traditional":"胡適","hanzi":"胡适","pinyin":"Hú Shì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Hú Shì</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Hu Shih</b> (17 December 1891 – 24 February 1962) was a Chinese philosopher, essayist, and diplomat who became one of the most influential intellectuals of the early <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)\">Republic of China</span></b> and a foremost champion of writing in the everyday spoken language. Born in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span> to a family from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anhui\">Anhui</span>, he <b>won a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boxer_Indemnity_Scholarship_Program\">Boxer Indemnity Scholarship</span> in 1910</b> to study in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States\">United States</span>, attending <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cornell_University\">Cornell University</span> before completing a doctorate at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Columbia_University\">Columbia University</span>, where the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pragmatism\">pragmatist</span> philosophy of his teacher Dewey shaped his lifelong outlook. While still abroad, <b>his 1917 essay</b> in the magazine <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Youth\"><i>New Youth</i></span> ignited a literary revolution by calling for prose written in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Written_vernacular_Chinese\">everyday vernacular</span> rather than the difficult classical literary language. Returning to China in 1917, he joined the faculty of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peking_University\">Peking University</span> under chancellor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cai_Yuanpei\">Cai Yuanpei</span> and quickly became, alongside <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Duxiu\">Chen Duxiu</span> and the writer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lu_Xun\">Lu Xun</span>, a leading voice of the New Culture Movement and the broader <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"May_Fourth_Movement\">May Fourth Movement</span>. He gave the new written style its early models, <b>publishing in 1919 his</b> <i>Outline of the History of Chinese Philosophy</i>, a pioneering application of modern method to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_philosophy\">Chinese philosophy</span>, and in 1920 his <i>Experiments</i>, the first collection of poetry composed entirely in the vernacular, much of it in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Free_verse\">free verse</span>.<br> <br>A <b>committed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liberalism\">liberal</span></b> and gradualist, he clashed with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Dazhao\">Li Dazhao</span> in the 1919 \"problems and isms\" debate, urging his countrymen to study concrete problems rather than embrace sweeping ideologies such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marxism\">Marxism</span>. Beyond politics he was a prolific scholar, applying rigorous <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Textual_criticism\">textual criticism</span></b> to classic novels such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dream_of_the_Red_Chamber\"><i>Dream of the Red Chamber</i></span> and writing extensively on vernacular literature, work that brought him a nomination for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nobel_Prize_in_Literature\">Nobel Prize in Literature</span>. As a public intellectual he co-founded the literary <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Crescent_Moon_Society\">Crescent Moon Society</span></b> and edited influential journals, defending <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Human_rights\">individual rights</span> while keeping his distance from both the authoritarian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Nationalists</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Communists</span>. During the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Sino-Japanese_War\">Second Sino-Japanese War</span> he served as China's ambassador to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Washington,_D.C.\">Washington</span> from 1938 to 1942, and after the conflict he returned to lead Peking University as its chancellor from 1946 to 1948. After the Communist victory of 1949 he left the mainland—where his pragmatic liberalism would soon be condemned in a sweeping denunciation campaign of the mid-1950s—and settled first in the United States and then in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span>, where he presided over the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Academia_Sinica\">Academia Sinica</span> until his death in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taipei\">Taipei</span> in 1962.","citation":"","answerText":"Hu Shih"},{"id":"cnp-002","num":"二","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Born in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> in Hunan and emerging as the dominant figure of the Communist Party during the Long March, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> served as the Party's chairman, proclaimed the founding of the People's Republic in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>, and shaped its politics until his death in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>.","answer":"Mao Zedong","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">December 26, 1893</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">September 9, 1976</span></div>","traditional":"毛澤東","hanzi":"毛泽东","pinyin":"Máo Zédōng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Máo Zédōng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Mao Zedong</b> was a Chinese revolutionary, military strategist, and political theorist who was born into a moderately prosperous peasant household in the village of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shaoshan\">Shaoshan</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hunan\">Hunan</span></b> province during the twilight of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span>. After briefly serving as a soldier during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinhai_Revolution\">Xinhai Revolution</span> of 1911 that ended more than 2,000 years of imperial rule, he took work as a library assistant at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peking_University\">Peking University</span>, where the intellectual ferment of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"May_Fourth_Movement\">May Fourth Movement</span> and the mentorship of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Dazhao\">Li Dazhao</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Duxiu\">Chen Duxiu</span> drew him toward <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marxism\">Marxism</span>. He was one of the 13 delegates who attended the 1921 <b>founding congress of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span></b>, an organization then representing roughly 50 members nationwide, and after the rupture of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_United_Front\">First United Front</span> with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span> during <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span>'s bloody <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_massacre\">anti-communist purge</span> of 1927, he turned to rural revolt by leading the failed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Autumn_Harvest_Uprising\">Autumn Harvest Uprising</span>. Withdrawing into the mountainous countryside, he helped establish the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Soviet_Republic\">Jiangxi Soviet</span> and refined a doctrine of peasant-based <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guerrilla_warfare\">guerrilla warfare</span> that broke with Soviet orthodoxy, but Nationalist encirclement campaigns drove the communists into the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Long_March\">Long March</span> of 1934–1935</b>, a grueling retreat traditionally reckoned at 25,000 li (about 12,500 kilometers (7,770 mi)) that only some 8,000 of the more than 80,000 who set out are believed to have survived. His authority was decisively consolidated at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zunyi_Conference\">Zunyi Conference</span> during that march, and from the wartime base at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yan'an\">Yan'an</span>—where he produced influential treatises such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"On_Protracted_War\"><i>On Protracted War</i></span>—he guided the Party through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Sino-Japanese_War\">war against Japan</span> and the renewed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">civil war</span>, culminating in his proclamation of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Republic_of_China\">People's Republic of China</span> from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tiananmen\">Tiananmen</span> on October 1, 1949. <br> <br> As chairman of the new state, which then <b>governed some 540 million people</b>, he oversaw sweeping <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Land_reform_movement\">land reform</span> that redistributed property from landlords to poorer peasants, committed Chinese \"volunteers\" to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Korean_War\">Korean War</span> in 1950, and launched a Soviet-modeled drive for heavy industrialization under the country's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five-Year_Plans_of_China\">Five-Year Plans</span>. His short-lived encouragement of open criticism during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hundred_Flowers_Campaign\">Hundred Flowers Campaign</span> of 1956–1957 gave way to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anti-Rightist_Campaign\">Anti-Rightist Campaign</span>, in which hundreds of thousands of intellectuals were branded \"rightists\" and persecuted. In 1958 he set in motion the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Leap_Forward\">Great Leap Forward</span>, a radical attempt to overtake Western output through mass mobilization and the creation of vast rural <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_commune\">people's communes</span>, yet its coercive quotas and inflated production figures helped trigger the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Chinese_Famine\">Great Chinese Famine</span>, which scholarly estimates place at between <b>15 and 45 million deaths</b> from 1959 to 1961. Politically eclipsed after that catastrophe by pragmatic administrators such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Shaoqi\">Liu Shaoqi</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>, he reclaimed the initiative by <b>launching the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span> in 1966</b>, mobilizing fervent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Red_Guards\">Red Guards</span> who brandished the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Quotations_from_Chairman_Mao_Tse-tung\"><i>Quotations from Chairman Mao Tse-tung</i></span> and plunging the nation into a decade of purges and factional violence that claimed hundreds of thousands of lives. In his final years he presided over the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-Soviet_split\">Sino-Soviet split</span> and a surprising opening to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States\">United States</span> marked by President <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Richard_Nixon\">Richard Nixon</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1972_Nixon_visit_to_China\">historic visit</span> in 1972, and after his death in 1976 the Party under Deng issued a verdict that judged his record \"70 percent correct and 30 percent wrong\" even as it enshrined his ideology, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maoism\">Maoism</span>, as a guiding doctrine</b> and one of the most consequential political forces of the 20th century.","citation":"","answerText":"Mao Zedong"},{"id":"em-043","num":"四十三","category":"Foreign Imperialism · Wars","question":"Fought in 1894–1895 mainly over influence in Korea, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> shocked the world by revealing how far a rapidly modernising Japan had overtaken China, sinking the Beiyang Fleet and shattering faith in self-strengthening.","answer":"First Sino-Japanese War","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Began</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1894 · war over Korea</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Ended</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1895 · Treaty of Shimonoseki</span></div>","traditional":"甲午戰爭","hanzi":"甲午战争","pinyin":"Jiǎwǔ Zhànzhēng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Jiǎwǔ Zhànzhēng</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Japanese</span><span class=\"tr-ov\">日清戦争</span> <span class=\"tr-rom\">Nisshin Sensō</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>First Sino-Japanese War</b> was a conflict fought <b>from 1894</b> to <b>1895</b> between the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> empire and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empire_of_Japan\">Empire of Japan</span>, principally for mastery over <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joseon\">Korea</span></b>. For centuries Korea had been a tributary of China within the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tributary_system_of_China\">Sinocentric order</span>, but the swift modernisation of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Meiji_era\">Meiji</span> Japan brought the two powers into direct rivalry over the peninsula, even as China's own <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Self-Strengthening_Movement\">Self-Strengthening Movement</span> faltered—its navy reportedly starved of funds after <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empress_Dowager_Cixi\">Empress Dowager Cixi</span> diverted appropriations towards rebuilding the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Summer_Palace\">Summer Palace</span>. The crisis erupted in 1894 when the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Donghak_Peasant_Revolution\">Donghak Peasant Revolution</span></b> drew troops from both empires into Korea, whereupon Japanese forces seized the royal palace in Seoul, installed a compliant government, and brought the antagonists to a formal declaration of war on August 1, 1894. Japan's modernised army and navy then won a rapid string of victories, routing Qing forces at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Pyongyang_(1894)\">Battle of Pyongyang</span> and crippling the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beiyang_Fleet\">Beiyang Fleet</span></b>—the costly armada that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Hongzhang\">Li Hongzhang</span> had built around the German ironclads <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_ironclad_Dingyuan\">Dingyuan</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_ironclad_Zhenyuan\">Zhenyuan</span>—at the decisive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_the_Yalu_River_(1894)\">Battle of the Yalu River</span> on September 17, 1894. The Japanese then stormed the fortress of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Lushunkou\">Port Arthur</span>, where their troops perpetrated a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Port_Arthur_massacre_(China)\">notorious massacre</span> of the city's inhabitants, and they destroyed the trapped remnants of the Beiyang Fleet at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Weihaiwei\">Battle of Weihaiwei</span> in early 1895, driving the fleet's commander, Admiral <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ding_Ruchang\">Ding Ruchang</span>, to take his own life. <br> <br> The war was concluded by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Shimonoseki\">Treaty of Shimonoseki</span>, negotiated by Li Hongzhang and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Itō_Hirobumi\">Itō Hirobumi</span> and signed in April 1895, under which a humiliated China recognised Korean independence, ceded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Penghu\">Penghu Islands</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liaodong_Peninsula\">Liaodong Peninsula</span>, and agreed to pay an indemnity of 200 million <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tael\">taels</span> of silver. That sum amounted to several times the annual revenue of the Japanese government and helped finance its further armament, while the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Triple_Intervention\">Triple Intervention</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russian_Empire\">Russia</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"France\">France</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"German_Empire\">German Empire</span> compelled Japan to relinquish the Liaodong Peninsula in return for an additional 30 million taels. Although China's nominal forces were far larger, its poorly coordinated armies were repeatedly outmatched by the roughly 240,000 troops Japan mobilised, and Chinese military deaths reached an estimated 35,000 in a debacle that exposed the rot beneath the dynasty's modernising façade and shattered confidence in self-strengthening. The defeat triggered a scramble among the foreign powers to carve China into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sphere_of_influence\">spheres of influence</span>, spurred <b>the abortive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hundred_Days'_Reform\">Hundred Days' Reform</span> of 1898</b> under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangxu_Emperor\">Guangxu Emperor</span>, and fed a rising tide of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_nationalism\">Chinese nationalism</span> that would eventually consume the Qing. For Japan the victory announced its arrival as the preeminent power in East Asia, inaugurating <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan_under_Japanese_rule\">half a century of colonial rule over Taiwan</span>, setting the stage for its triumph over Russia in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russo-Japanese_War\">Russo-Japanese War</span> a decade later, and hastening <b>its annexation of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Korea_under_Japanese_rule\">the Korean peninsula</span></b> in 1910.","citation":"","answerText":"First Sino-Japanese War"},{"id":"em-044","num":"四十四","category":"Foreign Imperialism · Treaties","question":"Ending the war with Japan in 1895, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> recognised the independence of Korea, ceded Taiwan and the Liaodong Peninsula, and imposed a crushing indemnity, negotiated for China by Li Hongzhang.","answer":"Treaty of Shimonoseki","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Signed</span><span class=\"dt-v\">17 April 1895 · Shimonoseki, Japan</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"馬關條約","pinyin":"Mǎguān Tiáoyuē","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Mǎguān Tiáoyuē</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Japanese</span><span class=\"tr-ov\">下関条約</span> <span class=\"tr-rom\">Shimonoseki Jōyaku</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Treaty of Shimonoseki</b> was the peace settlement that <b>ended the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Sino-Japanese_War\">First Sino-Japanese War</span> of 1894–1895</b>, a punitive and bitterly resented agreement that confirmed the ascendancy of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empire_of_Japan\">Empire of Japan</span> over a faltering <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span>. The negotiations were conducted at the Japanese port of Shimonoseki in the <b>spring of 1895</b>, where the veteran Qing statesman Li Hongzhang, assisted by his adopted son <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Jingfang\">Li Jingfang</span>, confronted the Japanese prime minister <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Itō_Hirobumi\">Itō Hirobumi</span> and his foreign minister <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mutsu_Munemitsu\">Mutsu Munemitsu</span>. The talks were jolted on 24 March 1895 when a Japanese ultranationalist shot Li in the face, an assault that so embarrassed the host government that it hastened an armistice and induced Japan to scale back its financial demands. Signed on 17 April 1895, the treaty compelled China to recognise the full independence of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joseon\">Korea</span>—severing the centuries-old <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_Chinese_tributary_system\">tributary relationship</span></b> and the Qing claim to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Suzerainty\">suzerainty</span>—and to cede in perpetuity the island of Taiwan, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Penghu\">Penghu</span> archipelago, and the strategically vital Liaodong Peninsula with its naval base at <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lüshunkou_District\">Port Arthur</span></b>. It further imposed a war indemnity of 200 million <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tael\">taels</span> of silver, opened four additional <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_ports\">treaty ports</span>—among them <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chongqing\">Chongqing</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Suzhou\">Suzhou</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hangzhou\">Hangzhou</span>—to Japanese commerce and navigation along the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span>, and granted Japan <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Most_favoured_nation\">most-favoured-nation</span> status together with the right to operate factories on Chinese soil.<br> <br>Barely a week later, on 23 April 1895, the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Triple_Intervention\">Triple Intervention</span></b> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russian_Empire\">Russian Empire</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"German_Empire\">German Empire</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"French_Third_Republic\">French Third Republic</span> pressured Tokyo into restoring the Liaodong Peninsula to China in return for a supplementary indemnity of 30 million taels. On Taiwan the cession provoked the proclamation of a short-lived <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_Formosa\">Republic of Formosa</span>, whose resistance Japanese forces crushed within months, inaugurating a half-century of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan_under_Japanese_rule\">colonial rule</span> that lasted <b>until 1945</b>. The vast indemnity, equivalent to several times Japan's annual government revenue, was overwhelmingly funnelled into military expansion and helped finance the country's adoption of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gold_standard\">gold standard</span> in 1897, accelerating its emergence as an industrial and naval power. For China the débâcle discredited the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Self-Strengthening_Movement\">Self-Strengthening Movement</span> and galvanised reformers led by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kang_Youwei\">Kang Youwei</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liang_Qichao\">Liang Qichao</span></b>, whose agitation culminated in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hundred_Days'_Reform\">Hundred Days' Reform</span> of 1898, even as the empire's evident weakness invited a scramble among the great powers for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sphere_of_influence\">spheres of influence</span>. In a final irony, Russia's own seizure of the very Liaodong territory Japan had been forced to surrender set the two empires on a collision course towards the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russo-Japanese_War\">Russo-Japanese War</span> of 1904–1905, and the accord endured in Chinese memory as one of the most galling of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Unequal_treaty\">unequal treaties</span> imposed upon the dynasty in its twilight.","citation":"","answerText":"Treaty of Shimonoseki"},{"id":"em-045","num":"四十五","category":"Foreign Imperialism · Diplomacy","question":"Occurring days after the 1895 peace, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> saw Russia, Germany and France pressure Japan into returning the Liaodong Peninsula to China — only for the powers to then demand their own leases and railway rights as reward.","answer":"Triple Intervention","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">23 April 1895 · Russia, Germany, France</span></div>","traditional":"三國干涉","hanzi":"三国干涉","pinyin":"Sānguó Gānshè","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Sānguó Gānshè</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Japanese</span><span class=\"tr-ov\">三国干渉</span> <span class=\"tr-rom\">Sangoku Kanshō</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Triple Intervention</b> was a <b>coordinated diplomatic démarche of 23 April 1895</b> in which the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russian_Empire\">Russian Empire</span></b>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"German_Empire\">German Empire</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"French_Third_Republic\">French Third Republic</span> pressed a victorious <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empire_of_Japan\">Japan</span> to surrender the gains it had just secured from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> at the close of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Sino-Japanese_War\">First Sino-Japanese War</span>. The intervention came only six days after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Shimonoseki\">Treaty of Shimonoseki</span>, signed on 17 April 1895 by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Hongzhang\">Li Hongzhang</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Itō_Hirobumi\">Itō Hirobumi</span></b>, under which China had recognised the independence of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joseon\">Korea</span> and ceded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Penghu\">Pescadores</span>, and the strategically vital <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liaodong_Peninsula\">Liaodong Peninsula</span> while agreeing to pay an indemnity of 200 million <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tael\">taels</span> of silver. Russia was the prime mover behind the intervention, alarmed that Japanese possession of the peninsula and its commanding harbour at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lüshunkou_District\">Port Arthur</span> would frustrate its own long-cherished designs on an ice-free Pacific port and on commercial dominance in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchuria\">Manchuria</span>, a forward policy energetically promoted by the <b>finance minister <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sergei_Witte\">Sergei Witte</span></b>. Germany, whose Kaiser <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wilhelm_II,_German_Emperor\">Wilhelm II</span> hoped both to deflect Russian energies away from Europe and to win goodwill in St Petersburg, lent its weight to the démarche, while France acted chiefly to honour its recent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Franco-Russian_Alliance\">alliance</span> with Russia. Militarily incapable of resisting three European empires at once, Japan reluctantly relinquished the peninsula in a retrocession convention of 8 November 1895, extracting in compensation a further indemnity of 30 million taels but nursing a bitter resolve later distilled in the slogan of perseverance through hardship. <br> <br> The episode proved a watershed in China's so-called <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Century_of_humiliation\">century of humiliation</span>, for within three years the very powers that had posed as China's disinterested protectors compelled the enfeebled Qing to grant them sweeping leaseholds, railway concessions, and exclusive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sphere_of_influence\">spheres of influence</span> across the empire. Russia secured a secret defensive alliance <b>through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li–Lobanov_Treaty\">Li–Lobanov Treaty</span> of 1896</b> and the right to drive the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Eastern_Railway\">Chinese Eastern Railway</span> across Manchuria, then in 1898 leased the southern Liaodong, including Port Arthur, as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kwantung_Leased_Territory\">Kwantung Leased Territory</span> and added the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South_Manchuria_Railway\">South Manchuria Railway</span>. Germany, seizing on the murder of two of its missionaries <b>in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Juye_Incident\">Juye Incident</span> of 1897</b>, occupied and then leased <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kiautschou_Bay_Leased_Territory\">Jiaozhou Bay</span> on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shandong\">Shandong</span> coast for 99 years, transforming the fishing town of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qingdao\">Qingdao</span> into a fortified naval base and treaty port that anchored its new East Asian presence. France obtained a 99-year lease over <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhouwan\">Guangzhouwan</span> in the far south together with mining and railway privileges adjoining its colony of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"French_Indochina\">French Indochina</span></b>, and even Britain, which had abstained from the intervention, joined the scramble by leasing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Weihaiwei_under_British_rule\">Weihaiwei</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Territories\">New Territories</span> of Hong Kong. By exposing the dynasty's helplessness before foreign coercion, the affair accelerated the reformist ferment of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hundred_Days'_Reform\">Hundred Days' Reform</span> and the anti-foreign fury of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boxer_Rebellion\">Boxer Rebellion</span>, while Russia's seizure of the prize Japan had been denied set the two empires on the collision course that erupted in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russo-Japanese_War\">Russo-Japanese War</span> of 1904–1905.","citation":"","answerText":"Triple Intervention"},{"id":"em-050","num":"五十","category":"Reform &amp; Revolution · 1898","question":"A whirlwind of edicts issued over about 100 days in 1898 to overhaul education, the bureaucracy, the military and the economy, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was abruptly crushed by a coup, sending Kang Youwei and Liang Qichao into exile.","answer":"Hundred Days' Reform","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Began</span><span class=\"dt-v\">11 June 1898 · Guangxu’s edicts</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Ended</span><span class=\"dt-v\">21 September 1898 · Cixi’s coup</span></div>","traditional":"百日維新","hanzi":"百日维新","pinyin":"Bǎirì Wéixīn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Bǎirì Wéixīn</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Wùxū (1898) Reform”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Hundred Days' Reform</b> was a sweeping but abortive programme of institutional renewal undertaken over roughly 103 days <b>in the summer of 1898</b>, in which the young Guangxu Emperor and a circle of reform-minded advisers sought to modernise the ailing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> along constitutional and Western-influenced lines. The reform sprang from a deepening sense of national crisis, for China's crushing defeat in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Sino-Japanese_War\">First Sino-Japanese War</span> and <b>the punitive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Shimonoseki\">Treaty of Shimonoseki</span> of 1895</b> had laid bare the inadequacy of the earlier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Self-Strengthening_Movement\">Self-Strengthening Movement</span> and emboldened the foreign powers to carve out <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sphere_of_influence\">spheres of influence</span> across the empire. It opened on 11 June 1898 with an imperial edict proclaiming reform as state policy—issued only days before the engineered dismissal of the emperor's longtime tutor <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Weng_Tonghe\">Weng Tonghe</span></b>—and over the following weeks the throne poured out more than 40 decrees, an outpouring that lent the episode its alternative name, the Wuxu Reform, after the year's place in the traditional <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sexagenary_cycle\">sexagenary cycle</span>, while inviting officials and commoners alike to <b>submit proposals by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Memorial_to_the_throne\">memorial to the throne</span></b>. In education and administration the decrees abolished the formulaic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight-legged_essay\">eight-legged essay</span> that had long dominated the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examination</span>, founded the modern academy that survives today as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peking_University\">Peking University</span>, and sought to prune the swollen ranks of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Scholar-official\">scholar-official</span> bureaucracy. Further edicts aimed to remodel the armed forces on Western lines and to invigorate the economy by promoting industry, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rail_transport_in_China\">railways</span>, mining, and modern banking, even as the breakneck pace and sheer breadth of the changes alarmed entrenched interests throughout the court.<br> <br>Opposition coalesced around conservative <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_people\">Manchu</span> grandees and, above all, the formidable <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empress_Dowager_Cixi\">Empress Dowager Cixi</span>, whose alarm sharpened when the visiting <b>Japanese statesman <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Itō_Hirobumi\">Itō Hirobumi</span></b> was rumoured to be courted as an adviser and the reformers reportedly schemed to neutralise her by enlisting the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Army\">New Army</span> of the ambitious general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_Shikai\">Yuan Shikai</span>. The gambit failed catastrophically when Yuan instead disclosed the plot to the <b>powerful viceroy <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ronglu\">Ronglu</span></b>, and on 21 September 1898 Cixi struck back in a swift palace coup, resuming her regency and confining the emperor to the lakeside Yingtai pavilion within <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhongnanhai\">Zhongnanhai</span> for the remaining decade of his life. A merciless purge ensued, culminating on 28 September in the summary execution of six prominent reformers—the so-called Six Gentlemen, among them the defiant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tan_Sitong\">Tan Sitong</span>—while Kang Youwei and Liang Qichao escaped respectively through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span> and a Japanese legation into exile in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empire_of_Japan\">Japan</span>, and almost all the reform edicts were swiftly rescinded. The reactionary triumph proved hollow, for Cixi's subsequent indulgence of anti-foreign militancy helped precipitate <b>the disastrous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boxer_Rebellion\">Boxer Rebellion</span> of 1899–1901</b>, after which, humbled by the punitive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boxer_Protocol\">Boxer Protocol</span>, the court itself enacted the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Late_Qing_reforms\">New Policies</span>, a programme that quietly carried out many of the very measures it had crushed, including the abolition of the imperial examinations in 1905. Yet the abrupt failure of reform from above also discredited the cause of gradual <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitutional_monarchy\">constitutional monarchy</span> and lent fresh impetus to the republican revolutionaries rallying behind <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Yat-sen\">Sun Yat-sen</span>, helping to set the dynasty on the path to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinhai_Revolution\">Xinhai Revolution</span> of 1911 and to the founding of a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)\">republic</span> that swept away both the throne and its last occupant, the child emperor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Puyi\">Puyi</span>, in 1912.","citation":"","answerText":"Hundred Days' Reform"},{"id":"em-075","num":"七十五","category":"New Culture · Institutions","question":"Reformed under the liberal chancellor Cai Yuanpei into a hotbed of new ideas, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> employed Chen Duxiu and Li Dazhao and became the cradle of the protests that erupted on 4 May 1919.","answer":"Peking University","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Founded</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1898 · Beijing</span></div>","traditional":"北京大學","hanzi":"北京大学","pinyin":"Běijīng Dàxué","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Běijīng Dàxué</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Peking University</b> is a major public research university in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> and one of the oldest and most prestigious institutions of higher learning in China, <b>founded in 1898</b> as the Imperial University of Peking. Its creation formed part of the abortive <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hundred_Days'_Reform\">Hundred Days' Reform</span></b> sponsored by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangxu_Emperor\">Guangxu Emperor</span>, and it was almost the only one of those measures to endure after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empress_Dowager_Cixi\">Empress Dowager Cixi</span> seized power and reversed the reform programme of the late <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span>. Following the establishment <b>of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)\">Republic of China</span> in 1912</b>, the institution was renamed and reorganised under its first republican-era head, the translator and reformer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yan_Fu\">Yan Fu</span>, before entering its most celebrated period under a new chancellor appointed a few years later. That chancellor, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cai_Yuanpei\">Cai Yuanpei</span>, took office in 1917 and transformed the university by <b>enshrining principles of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Academic_freedom\">academic freedom</span></b> and intellectual inclusiveness, encapsulated in his celebrated maxim of \"freedom of thought and all-embracing tolerance.\" Under his patronage the faculty came to include the radical editor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Duxiu\">Chen Duxiu</span>, the librarian and early Marxist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Dazhao\">Li Dazhao</span>, the vernacular advocate <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Shih\">Hu Shih</span>, and the writer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lu_Xun\">Lu Xun</span>, while a young <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> worked briefly as an assistant <b>in its library around 1918</b>. <br> <br> The campus rapidly became the epicentre of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Culture_Movement\">New Culture Movement</span>, hosting the influential magazine <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Youth\"><i>New Youth</i></span> after it relocated to Beijing and nurturing the study circles through which Li Dazhao introduced <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marxism\">Marxism</span> to a rising generation of students. On 4 May 1919 its students took the lead in the demonstrations of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"May_Fourth_Movement\">May Fourth Movement</span>, when roughly 3,000 protesters from the university and other Beijing colleges gathered before <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tiananmen_Square\">Tiananmen</span> to denounce the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Versailles\">Treaty of Versailles</span></b> and the so-called <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shandong_Problem\">Shandong Problem</span>, which transferred former German concessions to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empire_of_Japan\">Japan</span>. From this milieu emerged several of the founders of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span>, cementing the university's lasting reputation as a crucible of modern Chinese political radicalism. During the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Sino-Japanese_War\">Second Sino-Japanese War</span> it fled the Japanese occupation and merged with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tsinghua_University\">Tsinghua</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nankai_University\">Nankai</span> universities to form the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Southwestern_Associated_University\">National Southwestern Associated University</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kunming\">Kunming</span>, and after 1949 it absorbed the American-founded <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yenching_University\">Yenching University</span></b> and relocated to that institution's lakeside campus. Today situated in Beijing's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Haidian_District\">Haidian District</span> and enrolling tens of thousands of students, it consistently ranks among China's two leading universities, even as its long tradition of student activism resurfaced when the campus became a focal point of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1989_Tiananmen_Square_protests_and_massacre\">1989 Tiananmen Square protests</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Peking University"},{"id":"cnp-028","num":"二十八","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"A celebrated marshal who had commanded Chinese forces in the Korean War, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was disgraced in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> after criticising the Great Leap Forward and was later persecuted to death during the Cultural Revolution.","answer":"Peng Dehuai","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">24 October 1898</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">29 November 1974</span></div>","traditional":"彭德懷","hanzi":"彭德怀","pinyin":"Péng Déhuái","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Péng Déhuái</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Peng Dehuai</b> was one of the foremost military commanders of the Chinese communist movement, born into an impoverished <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peasant\">peasant</span> family in <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiangtan\">Xiangtan</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hunan\">Hunan</span>, who first took up soldiering in the provincial armies of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warlord_Era\">Warlord Era</span> and rose to regimental command during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Expedition\">Northern Expedition</span>. Having <b>joined the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> in 1928</b>, he led the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pingjiang_Uprising\">Pingjiang Uprising</span> that July and brought his troops into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Red_Army\">Red Army</span>, marching them to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jinggang_Mountains\">Jinggang Mountains</span> base held by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_De\">Zhu De</span>. He became one of the most dependable commanders of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Soviet_Republic\">Jiangxi Soviet</span>, <b>endured the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Long_March\">Long March</span> of 1934–1935</b>, and during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Sino-Japanese_War\">Second Sino-Japanese War</span> served as deputy commander of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eighth_Route_Army\">Eighth Route Army</span>, <b>directing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hundred_Regiments_Offensive\">Hundred Regiments Offensive</span> of 1940</b> with more than 100 regiments and some 400,000 troops. After commanding a major front in the closing campaigns of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">Chinese Civil War</span>, he was chosen in 1950 to lead the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Volunteer_Army\">People's Volunteer Army</span> that intervened in Korea on the side of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kim_Il_Sung\">Kim Il Sung</span>, a force exceeding a million men that fought the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_Nations_Command\">United Nations Command</span> to the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Korean_Armistice_Agreement\">Korean Armistice Agreement</span></b> of 1953. The campaign cemented his standing, and in 1954 he was appointed Minister of National Defence, named one of the ten <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marshal_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">Marshals of the People's Republic of China</span> the following year, and entrusted with modernizing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army\">People's Liberation Army</span> as a senior member of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo</span>.<br> <br>His professionalizing, partly Soviet-influenced military reforms increasingly clashed with Mao's vision, and at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lushan_Conference\">Lushan Conference</span></b> of 1959 he submitted a candid private letter decrying the excesses of the Great Leap Forward, only to be condemned as the ringleader of an \"anti-Party clique\" alongside figures such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Wentian\">Zhang Wentian</span> and replaced as defence minister by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lin_Biao\">Lin Biao</span>. Stripped of his offices and effective influence, he lived in enforced obscurity until 1965, when he was sent to help administer the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Third_Front_(China)\">Third Front</span></b> military-industrial program in China's mountainous southwest. That brief reprieve collapsed with the onset of the Cultural Revolution, when he was seized and dragged back to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> in 1966, paraded before <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Red_Guards\">Red Guards</span> in dozens of violent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Struggle_session\">struggle sessions</span>, and repeatedly beaten and interrogated. Held in detention and repeatedly denied adequate treatment for the cancer that was killing him, the disgraced marshal died in 1974, some 15 years after his fall at Lushan. Posthumously rehabilitated in 1978 under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> during the sweeping reversal of Maoist verdicts known as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boluan_Fanzheng\">Boluan Fanzheng</span>, he is remembered today as a blunt and incorruptible soldier whose warnings about the Great Leap Forward, though they cost him everything, proved tragically prescient.","citation":"","answerText":"Peng Dehuai"},{"id":"cnp-044","num":"四十四","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Serving as the sole Premier from <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> until his death and helping arrange the opening to the United States, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> tried to shield some targets of the Cultural Revolution and was widely mourned when he died in January <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>.","answer":"Zhou Enlai","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">March 5, 1898</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">January 8, 1976</span></div>","traditional":"周恩來","hanzi":"周恩来","pinyin":"Zhōu Ēnlái","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōu Ēnlái</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Zhou Enlai</b> was a Chinese revolutionary and statesman who served as the inaugural <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Premier_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">Premier</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Republic_of_China\">People's Republic of China</span> from its <b>founding in 1949</b> until his death some 27 years later—the sole occupant of the office throughout that period—and concurrently as the country's foreign minister from 1949 to 1958. Born into a declining gentry family in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huai'an\">Huai'an</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiangsu\">Jiangsu</span> province, he studied in Japan and later in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"France\">France</span> on a work-study program, where he embraced <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marxism\">Marxism</span> and helped organize an overseas branch of the fledgling <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span>. Returning to China, he became a leading party organizer, serving in the political department of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Whampoa_Military_Academy\">Whampoa Military Academy</span> during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_United_Front\">First United Front</span> with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span> and helping to launch the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanchang_uprising\">Nanchang Uprising</span> of 1927</b> that is celebrated as the founding of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Workers'_and_Peasants'_Red_Army\">Red Army</span>. Initially senior to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> in the party hierarchy, he threw his support behind Mao at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zunyi_Conference\">Zunyi Conference</span> <b>during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Long_March\">Long March</span> of 1934–1935</b> and thereafter served loyally as Mao's chief administrator and right-hand man for the rest of his life. His diplomatic skill came to the fore in negotiating the release of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span> after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi'an_Incident\">Xi'an Incident</span> of 1936, which helped forge the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_United_Front\">Second United Front</span> against the Japanese invasion in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Sino-Japanese_War\">Second Sino-Japanese War</span>. <br> <br> As premier and chief diplomat he led Chinese delegations to the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1954_Geneva_Conference\">Geneva Conference</span></b> of 1954 and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bandung_Conference\">Bandung Conference</span> of 1955, where he promoted the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five_Principles_of_Peaceful_Coexistence\">Five Principles of Peaceful Coexistence</span> as a framework for relations among newly independent states. He was a principal architect of the rapprochement with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States\">United States</span>, secretly receiving <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Henry_Kissinger\">Henry Kissinger</span> in 1971 and helping to orchestrate <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Richard_Nixon\">President Richard Nixon</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1972_visit_by_Richard_Nixon_to_China\">historic visit</span> in 1972 and the resulting <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_Communiqué\">Shanghai Communiqué</span></b>. During the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span> he worked to keep the state functioning and quietly sheltered numerous veteran cadres, intellectuals, and cultural treasures from the violence of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Red_Guards\">Red Guards</span>, maneuvering delicately between Mao, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lin_Biao\">Lin Biao</span>, and the radical <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gang_of_Four\">Gang of Four</span>. He engineered the rehabilitation of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> and, in failing health, used his report to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_People's_Congress\">National People's Congress</span> in January 1975 to call for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Modernizations\">Four Modernizations</span> of agriculture, industry, national defense, and science, a program later carried forward by Deng. <b>His death from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bladder_cancer\">bladder cancer</span></b> in January 1976 unleashed an immense outpouring of popular grief that, during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qingming_Festival\">Qingming Festival</span> that April, swelled into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1976_Tiananmen_Incident\">Tiananmen Incident</span> of mass mourning and veiled protest at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Monument_to_the_People's_Heroes\">Monument to the People's Heroes</span></b>, an episode the authorities suppressed and blamed on Deng even as the moderate premier's reputation for pragmatism and humane restraint endured.","citation":"","answerText":"Zhou Enlai"},{"id":"em-051","num":"五十一","category":"Foreign Imperialism · Diplomacy","question":"Announced from 1899 in notes circulated by US Secretary of State John Hay, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> called on the powers to keep China open to the trade of all nations on equal terms, partly to check the rush to carve out spheres of influence and protect American commercial interests.","answer":"Open Door Policy","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Proposed</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1899 · Hay’s first note</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Reaffirmed</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1900 · second note</span></div>","traditional":"門戶開放政策","hanzi":"门户开放政策","pinyin":"Ménhù Kāifàng Zhèngcè","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Ménhù Kāifàng Zhèngcè</span></div>","abstract":"The&nbsp;<b>Open Door Policy</b> was a foreign-policy doctrine, originally set out by the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States\">United States</span></b> in 1899, that urged the great powers to preserve equal commercial access to China and to refrain from partitioning the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> empire into exclusive economic preserves. Its immediate backdrop was the frantic scramble for concessions that followed China's defeat <b>in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Sino-Japanese_War\">First Sino-Japanese War</span> of 1895</b>, as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russian_Empire\">Russian Empire</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"German_Empire\">German Empire</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empire_of_Japan\">Japan</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"British_Empire\">British Empire</span> each carved out leaseholds and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sphere_of_influence\">spheres of influence</span> that threatened to close foreign markets. Having just emerged as a Pacific power through victory in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Spanish–American_War\">Spanish–American War</span> and the acquisition of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Philippines\">Philippines</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guam\">Guam</span> <b>under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Paris_(1898)\">Treaty of Paris</span> of 1898</b>, the United States possessed no sphere of its own and feared exclusion from the lucrative China trade. Acting under President <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"William_McKinley\">William McKinley</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States_Secretary_of_State\">Secretary of State</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"John_Hay\">John Hay</span>—advised by the China specialist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"William_Woodville_Rockhill\">William Woodville Rockhill</span>—dispatched a series of <b>diplomatic notes in September 1899</b> asking the powers to respect existing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_port\">treaty ports</span>, apply uniform Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tariff\">tariffs</span>, and levy no discriminatory harbour or railway charges within their zones. Although the replies were evasive and non-committal, with each capital making its assent conditional on that of the others, Hay simply proclaimed in March 1900 that the powers had granted their \"final and definitive\" acceptance, and during the upheaval of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boxer_Rebellion\">Boxer Rebellion</span> he issued a further note in July 1900 broadening the principle to uphold China's <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Territorial_integrity\">territorial and administrative integrity</span></b>. <br> <br> In reality the doctrine rested on no treaty and carried little binding force, depending instead on the mutual jealousies of the powers and on a self-interested American preference for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Free_trade\">open commerce</span> over formal colonies. Washington nonetheless invoked it repeatedly over the following decades, securing its reaffirmation in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Root–Takahira_Agreement\">Root–Takahira Agreement</span></b> of 1908 under President <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Theodore_Roosevelt\">Theodore Roosevelt</span> and again, more ambiguously, in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lansing–Ishii_Agreement\">Lansing–Ishii Agreement</span> of 1917, which conceded Japan's \"special interests\" even while restating the open-door formula. The principle was most fully codified in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nine-Power_Treaty\">Nine-Power Treaty</span></b> of 1922, concluded at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Washington_Naval_Conference\">Washington Naval Conference</span>, by which the signatories pledged to respect Chinese sovereignty and equal commercial opportunity, a commitment that nevertheless did nothing to roll back earlier encroachments such as Japan's wartime <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Twenty-One_Demands\">Twenty-One Demands</span> of 1915. The policy was effectively shattered when the Japanese army seized <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchuria\">Manchuria</span> after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mukden_Incident\">Mukden Incident</span> of 1931 and erected the puppet state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchukuo\">Manchukuo</span>, prompting the United States to respond only with the toothless non-recognition of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stimson_Doctrine\">Stimson Doctrine</span>. By the outbreak of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Sino-Japanese_War\">Second Sino-Japanese War</span> in 1937 the open door had ceased to exist in practice, yet historians have continued to regard it as the classic expression of an American <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Informal_empire\">informal empire</span>, projecting <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"American_imperialism\">commercial dominance</span> across the globe without the burdens of territorial conquest.","citation":"","answerText":"Open Door Policy"},{"id":"em-053","num":"五十三","category":"Reform &amp; Revolution · The Boxer Uprising","question":"An anti-foreign, anti-Christian uprising of 1899–1901 by a secret society of martial artists who believed rituals made them invulnerable to bullets, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> besieged the foreign legations in Beijing with the backing of Empress Dowager Cixi and killed many Christian converts.","answer":"Boxer Rebellion","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Began</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1899 · anti-foreign uprising</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Ended</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1901 · Boxer Protocol</span></div>","traditional":"義和團運動","hanzi":"义和团运动","pinyin":"Yìhétuán Yùndòng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Yìhétuán Yùndòng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Boxer Rebellion</b> was a violent anti-foreign and anti-Christian uprising that convulsed northern China <b>between 1899</b> and 1901, waged by a clandestine society of peasant militiamen who <b>practised <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_martial_arts\">martial arts</span></b> and spirit-possession rituals they believed rendered them impervious to swords and bullets. The rebels called themselves the Yihequan, or \"Righteous and Harmonious Fists,\" a name whose pugilistic connotations led foreign observers to dub them \"Boxers,\" and they emerged in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shandong\">Shandong</span> out of older folk-religious and secret-society traditions such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Big_Sword_Society\">Big Sword Society</span>. Their fury was fed by mounting <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anti-imperialism\">anti-imperialist</span></b> resentment after the carve-up of China into foreign <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sphere_of_influence\">spheres of influence</span>, by hostility towards <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Catholic_Church\">Catholic</span> and Protestant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Missionary\">missionaries</span> and their converts, and by severe drought and economic dislocation, all distilled into the rallying cry \"Support the Qing, exterminate the foreigners.\" Sweeping out of Shandong into the neighbouring province of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhili\">Zhili</span> through 1899 and 1900</b>, Boxer bands burned churches and railways and killed tens of thousands of Chinese Christians along with more than 200 foreigners, most notoriously in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiyuan_Massacre\">Taiyuan Massacre</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanxi\">Shanxi</span> in July 1900. As the violence reached the capital, the court of the Empress Dowager Cixi threw its weight behind the movement and on 21 June 1900 declared war on the foreign powers, whereupon the Boxers and imperial troops laid a 55-day siege to the foreign <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Legation_Quarter\">Legation Quarter</span></b> in Beijing, in the course of which the German minister <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Clemens_von_Ketteler\">Clemens von Ketteler</span> was murdered in the streets.<br> <br>Crucially, several powerful southern viceroys, among them <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Hongzhang\">Li Hongzhang</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Zhidong\">Zhang Zhidong</span>, refused to obey the war declaration and concluded the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mutual_Protection_of_Southeast_China\">Mutual Protection of Southeast China</span>, keeping the prosperous south at peace, even as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russian_Empire\">Russia</span> exploited the turmoil to pour troops into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchuria\">Manchuria</span>. The assault on the legations meanwhile provoked a punitive expedition by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight-Nation_Alliance\">Eight-Nation Alliance</span>—Britain, Japan, Russia, France, the United States, Germany, Italy, and Austria-Hungary—whose first relief <b>attempt under Admiral <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Edward_Hobart_Seymour\">Edward Seymour</span></b> was thrown back before its forces stormed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_the_Taku_Forts_(1900)\">Taku Forts</span> and fought their way inland through the bloody <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Tientsin\">Battle of Tientsin</span>. A relief column of some 20,000 troops under the British general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Alfred_Gaselee\">Alfred Gaselee</span> finally lifted the siege on 14 August 1900, prompting Cixi and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangxu_Emperor\">Guangxu Emperor</span> to flee the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Forbidden_City\">Forbidden City</span> in disguise for distant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi'an\">Xi'an</span>, as allied soldiers—their ferocity notoriously encouraged by the German Kaiser <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wilhelm_II,_German_Emperor\">Wilhelm II</span>—subjected the capital to weeks of looting and reprisal. The crisis was settled by the <b>humiliating <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boxer_Protocol\">Boxer Protocol</span> of 7 September 1901</b>, negotiated for the dying dynasty by Li Hongzhang, which exacted a staggering indemnity of 450 million <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tael\">taels</span> of silver—one for every subject of the empire—payable over 39 years, demanded the punishment of pro-Boxer officials, and authorised foreign garrisons to be stationed between Beijing and the sea. The debacle gutted what survived of the dynasty's prestige, spurring it into the belated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Late_Qing_reforms\">New Policies</span> even as Russia's lingering grip on Manchuria propelled the region towards the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russo-Japanese_War\">Russo-Japanese War</span>, and the cumulative disgrace—softened only slightly when the United States redirected part of its indemnity share into scholarships that helped found <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tsinghua_University\">Tsinghua University</span>—did much to hasten the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinhai_Revolution\">Xinhai Revolution</span> that toppled the Qing a decade later.","citation":"","answerText":"Boxer Rebellion"},{"id":"em-054","num":"五十四","category":"Reform &amp; Revolution · The Boxer Uprising","question":"Formed in 1900 to relieve the besieged legations and crush the Boxers, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> — including Britain, Japan, Russia and the United States — marched on Beijing, looted the city, and forced the imperial court to flee.","answer":"Eight-Nation Alliance","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Formed</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1900 · to relieve the Beijing legations</span></div>","traditional":"八國聯軍","hanzi":"八国联军","pinyin":"Bāguó Liánjūn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Bāguó Liánjūn</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Eight-Nation Alliance</b> was the international military coalition <b>assembled in 1900</b> by <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empire_of_Japan\">Japan</span></b>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russian_Empire\">Russian Empire</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"British_Empire\">British Empire</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"French_Third_Republic\">French Third Republic</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States\">United States</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"German_Empire\">German Empire</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kingdom_of_Italy\">Kingdom of Italy</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Austria-Hungary\">Austria-Hungary</span> to suppress the anti-foreign uprising convulsing northern China. The intervention was precipitated by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boxer_Rebellion\">Boxer Rebellion</span>, a violent movement of peasant militias who, with the increasing connivance of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> court under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empress_Dowager_Cixi\">Empress Dowager Cixi</span>, slaughtered Chinese Christians and foreign <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Missionary\">missionaries</span> and converged on the capital in the summer of 1900. After the murder of the German minister <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Clemens_von_Ketteler\">Clemens von Ketteler</span>, the court declared war on the powers and the Boxers laid the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Siege_of_the_International_Legations\">siege of the International Legations</span> in the diplomatic quarter, an ordeal that trapped several hundred guards and around 3,000 Chinese converts behind improvised barricades for 55 days. An initial relief column, the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Seymour_Expedition\">Seymour Expedition</span></b> of some 2,000 men led by Admiral <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Edward_Hobart_Seymour\">Edward Seymour</span>, was beaten back short of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> by Boxer and imperial forces, but allied warships soon stormed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_the_Taku_Forts_(1900)\">Taku Forts</span> guarding the coast and captured the treaty city of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tianjin\">Tianjin</span> after several days of heavy fighting. In August a far larger force of roughly 20,000 troops, the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gaselee_Expedition\">Gaselee Expedition</span></b> under the British general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Alfred_Gaselee\">Alfred Gaselee</span> and including a substantial contingent of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"British_Indian_Army\">British Indian Army</span> alongside the largest Japanese and Russian detachments, fought its way up from the coast and lifted the siege on 14 August 1900. <br> <br> In the wake of the relief the victorious soldiers, soon joined by the German <b>field marshal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Alfred_von_Waldersee\">Alfred von Waldersee</span></b> as overall commander, subjected Beijing to weeks of systematic looting that stripped the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Forbidden_City\">Forbidden City</span> and countless homes of their treasures. Cixi and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangxu_Emperor\">Guangxu Emperor</span> had already fled the capital in disguise for the distant city of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi'an\">Xi'an</span>, while punitive expeditions ravaged the surrounding countryside in a spirit notoriously encouraged by Kaiser <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wilhelm_II,_German_Emperor\">Wilhelm II</span> in his bloodthirsty <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hun_speech\">Hun speech</span>. Russia exploited the chaos to pour well over 100,000 troops into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchuria\">Manchuria</span> in a sweeping <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russian_invasion_of_Manchuria\">occupation</span> that it proved reluctant to relinquish, sowing the bitter rivalry with Japan that would erupt in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russo-Japanese_War\">Russo-Japanese War</span> only a few years later. The conflict was formally closed by the <b>punitive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boxer_Protocol\">Boxer Protocol</span> of September 1901</b>, which compelled China to execute or punish pro-Boxer officials, permit foreign garrisons along the route to the capital, and pay a colossal indemnity of 450 million <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tael\">taels</span> of silver—a sum symbolically matched to the empire's population—spread with interest across 39 years. Though the dynasty survived and even launched a programme of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Late_Qing_reforms\">New Policies</span> in its aftermath, the humiliation hastened the collapse of imperial legitimacy that culminated <b>in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinhai_Revolution\">Xinhai Revolution</span> of 1911</b>, even as a portion of the American share of the indemnity was later remitted to fund Chinese students and helped endow the future <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tsinghua_University\">Tsinghua University</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Eight-Nation Alliance"},{"id":"em-055","num":"五十五","category":"Reform &amp; Revolution · The Boxer Uprising","question":"Signed in 1901 to end the uprising, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> imposed a colossal indemnity payable over 39 years, allowed foreign troops to be stationed in the capital, and ordered the punishment of officials who had backed the Boxers.","answer":"Boxer Protocol","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Signed</span><span class=\"dt-v\">7 September 1901 · Beijing</span></div>","traditional":"辛丑條約","hanzi":"辛丑条约","pinyin":"Xīnchǒu Tiáoyuē","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Xīnchǒu Tiáoyuē</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Treaty of the Xinchou Year”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Boxer Protocol</b> (signed <b>September 7, 1901</b>) was the punitive peace settlement that formally ended the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boxer_Rebellion\">Boxer Rebellion</span> and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Siege_of_the_International_Legations\">siege of the foreign legations</span></b> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>. Negotiated after the city's occupation by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight-Nation_Alliance\">Eight-Nation Alliance</span>, it was concluded between the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> court, represented by the elder statesman <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Hongzhang\">Li Hongzhang</span> and the <b>imperial prince <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yikuang\">Yikuang</span></b>, and 11 foreign powers in all, comprising the members of the victorious alliance—among them the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"British_Empire\">British</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"French_Third_Republic\">French</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russian_Empire\">Russian</span> empires—together with Belgium, Spain, and the Netherlands. Its most crushing provision was an indemnity of 450 million <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tael\">taels</span> of silver, a sum equal to roughly one tael for every subject of the empire, to be repaid over 39 years at 4% annual interest. With interest the obligation swelled to nearly 982 million taels, equivalent at the time to some 67 million pounds sterling, and was secured against the empire's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Maritime_Customs_Service\">maritime customs</span> revenues then administered by the foreign-led service of Inspector-General <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Robert_Hart,_1st_Baronet\">Robert Hart</span></b>. Although the protocol ceded no further territory, the scale of the indemnity and the conditions attached made it among the harshest of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Unequal_treaty\">unequal treaties</span> and a defining episode in what later became known as China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Century_of_humiliation\">century of humiliation</span>. <br> <br> Beyond the financial burden, the powers demanded the punishment of officials who had backed the uprising—though they pointedly spared <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empress_Dowager_Cixi\">Empress Dowager Cixi</span>, the true power behind the nominal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangxu_Emperor\">Guangxu Emperor</span>—producing the execution or forced suicide of about 10 senior figures, the banishment of the Boxer-aligned prince <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zaiyi\">Zaiyi</span>, and the suspension of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examinations</span> for 5 years in the 45 cities where the worst violence had occurred. The treaty turned the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing_Legation_Quarter\">Legation Quarter</span></b> into a fortified enclave closed to Chinese residents and permanently garrisoned by foreign soldiers, ordered the demolition of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taku_Forts\">Dagu Forts</span> guarding the sea approach to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tianjin\">Tianjin</span>, and authorised the stationing of troops at 12 points along the railway linking the capital to the coast. China was further compelled to send formal missions of apology to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"German_Empire\">German Empire</span> for the murder of <b>its minister <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Clemens_von_Ketteler\">Clemens von Ketteler</span></b> and to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empire_of_Japan\">Empire of Japan</span> for the killing of a legation official, and to raise a commemorative arch on the spot where Ketteler had been slain. It abolished the antiquated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zongli_Yamen\">Zongli Yamen</span> in favour of a modern foreign ministry ranked above the other boards of government, prohibited the importation of arms for 2 years, and bound provincial officials to suppress anti-foreign agitation on pain of dismissal. The fiscal strain hastened the late-Qing reforms known as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Policies\">New Policies</span>, while several governments later remitted portions of the indemnity, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States\">United States</span> channeling much of its share into the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boxer_Indemnity_Scholarship_Program\">Boxer Indemnity Scholarship Programme</span></b> that helped establish <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tsinghua_University\">Tsinghua University</span>, yet the dynasty's prestige never recovered and it fell in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinhai_Revolution\">Xinhai Revolution</span> a decade later.","citation":"","answerText":"Boxer Protocol"},{"id":"em-056","num":"五十六","category":"Late Qing Reform · The Xinzheng Reforms","question":"A belated burst of reform launched by the Qing court after 1901, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> abolished the ancient civil-service examinations, built modern schools and a New Army, and promised a constitution — changes that came too late to save the dynasty.","answer":"New Policies","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Began</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1901 · post-Boxer reforms</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Ended</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1911 · fall of the Qing</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"新政","pinyin":"Xīnzhèng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Xīnzhèng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>New Policies</b> was the sweeping, belated programme of reform—also known as the <b>Late Qing Reforms (Chinese: 清末新政; Hanyu Pinyin: <i>Qīngmò Xīnzhèng</i>)</b>—through which the imperial court sought to modernise the Chinese state during the dynasty's final decade <b>between 1901</b> and <b>1911</b>. Initiated by the Empress Dowager <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empress_Dowager_Cixi\">Cixi</span></b> from her wartime refuge at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi'an\">Xi'an</span> soon after the catastrophic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boxer_Rebellion\">Boxer Rebellion</span> and the punitive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boxer_Protocol\">Boxer Protocol</span> of 1901, the programme drew on reform memorials by provincial grandees such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Zhidong\">Zhang Zhidong</span>, reached well beyond the cautious <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Self-Strengthening_Movement\">Self-Strengthening Movement</span> of earlier decades, and amounted, paradoxically, to the belated enactment of much of the very <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hundred_Days'_Reform\">Hundred Days' Reform</span> that Cixi had <b>crushed in 1898</b>. In the realm of education the court abolished in 1905 the civil-service examination system—an institution roughly 1,300 years old that reached back to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sui_dynasty\">Sui dynasty</span>—replacing it with a network of modern Western-style schools and dispatching thousands of young Chinese to study in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empire_of_Japan\">Japan</span>. Its military reforms aimed to forge a modern conscript force on Western and Japanese models, the most formidable component of which was the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beiyang_Army\">Beiyang Army</span> trained by the rising general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_Shikai\">Yuan Shikai</span>, while a new officer corps was drilled at institutions such as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Baoding_Military_Academy\">Baoding Military Academy</span></b>. Parallel measures reformed the penal code under the jurist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shen_Jiaben\">Shen Jiaben</span>—abolishing such cruelties as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lingchi\">death by slow slicing</span>—encouraged industry, commerce, and railway construction, and launched campaigns against <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Opium\">opium</span> and the practice of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foot_binding\">foot binding</span>.<br> <br>The decisive turn towards political reform came after Japan's startling triumph in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russo-Japanese_War\">Russo-Japanese War</span> of 1904–1905, widely construed as the victory of a constitutional state over an autocracy, prompting the throne to send a fact-finding mission abroad and, in 1908, to promulgate an outline constitution explicitly modelled on the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Meiji_Constitution\">Meiji Constitution</span></b> and to commit, on paper, to a nine-year transition to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitutional_monarchy\">constitutional monarchy</span>. That same November of 1908 saw the deaths, a day apart, of both Cixi and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangxu_Emperor\">Guangxu Emperor</span>, bringing to the throne the infant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Puyi\">Puyi</span> under the regency of his father <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zaifeng,_Prince_Chun\">Zaifeng, Prince Chun</span>, even as elected provincial assemblies convened in 1909 and a national consultative assembly met in 1910. Hopes for genuine constitutionalism curdled in May 1911, however, when the court unveiled a so-called \"responsible cabinet\" packed with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_people\">Manchu</span> imperial princes, a move that bitterly alienated the reform-minded gentry and the constitutional monarchists led from exile by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liang_Qichao\">Liang Qichao</span>. The breaking point came that summer, when a scheme to nationalise the trunk railways ignited the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Railway_Protection_Movement\">Railway Protection Movement</span></b> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan\">Sichuan</span>, and the diversion of troops to suppress it opened the way for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuchang_Uprising\">Wuchang Uprising</span> of 10 October 1911, in which newly modernised army units mutinied and touched off the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinhai_Revolution\">Xinhai Revolution</span>. In the end the reforms hastened the very collapse they were meant to avert, for the abolition of the examinations had cut the ancient bond between the throne and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Scholar-official\">scholar-gentry</span>, the new army had become a seedbed of sedition stoked by the revolutionary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tongmenghui\">Tongmenghui</span>, and the returned students flocked to the republican cause of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Yat-sen\">Sun Yat-sen</span>, so that the abdication of the boy emperor on 12 February 1912 swept away not merely the dynasty but more than two millennia of imperial rule and ushered in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)\">Republic of China</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"New Policies"},{"id":"cnp-049","num":"四十九","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Twice purged and twice rehabilitated, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> emerged at the end of the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>s to drive China's reform and opening up, while never holding the post of head of state or Party general secretary.","answer":"Deng Xiaoping","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">22 August 1904</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">19 February 1997</span></div>","traditional":"鄧小平","hanzi":"邓小平","pinyin":"Dèng Xiǎopíng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Dèng Xiǎopíng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Deng Xiaoping</b> was a Chinese revolutionary and statesman who served as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paramount_leader\">paramount leader</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span> <b>from 1978</b> until his retirement, presiding over the sweeping programme of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">reform and opening up</span> that transformed the nation's economy. Born into a moderately prosperous landowning family in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guang'an\">Guang'an</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan\">Sichuan</span>, in 1904, he travelled to France at the age of 16 under the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Diligent_Work-Frugal_Study_Movement\">work-study movement</span></b>, where labouring in factories radicalised him and he embraced communism alongside the future premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span>. After a brief sojourn <b>studying at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Moscow_Sun_Yat-sen_University\">Moscow Sun Yat-sen University</span> in 1926</b>, he returned to organise armed uprisings and rose as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Political_commissar\">political commissar</span>, enduring the epic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Long_March\">Long March</span> of 1934–1935 and later directing communist forces to decisive victory in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huaihai_Campaign\">Huaihai Campaign</span> during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">Chinese Civil War</span>. Following <b>the communist victory in 1949</b> he ascended rapidly within the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span>, becoming general secretary of its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Secretariat_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Secretariat</span> in the 1950s, though this administrative office was distinct from the supreme leadership titles he would pointedly never hold. His pragmatic instincts twice made him a target of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>: he was purged and exiled to manual labour in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiangxi\">Jiangxi</span> during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span>, an ordeal in which his son <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Pufang\">Deng Pufang</span></b> was left paralysed, and after a brief rehabilitation he was toppled a second time by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gang_of_Four\">Gang of Four</span> following the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1976_Tiananmen_Incident\">Tiananmen Incident</span> of 1976. <br> <br> Rehabilitated once more after Mao's death, he outmanoeuvred the designated heir <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hua_Guofeng\">Hua Guofeng</span> at the pivotal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"3rd_Plenary_Session_of_the_11th_Central_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Third Plenary Session of the 11th Central Committee</span> in December 1978, consolidating power not through formal supremacy but through the chairmanship of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Military_Commission_(China)\">Central Military Commission</span> and an unrivalled personal authority. Rejecting Maoist orthodoxy with the maxim that the colour of a cat mattered less than its ability to catch mice, he dismantled collective agriculture through the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Household-responsibility_system\">household responsibility system</span></b> and opened the country to foreign capital by establishing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Special_economic_zones_of_China\">special economic zones</span> in 1980, transforming the fishing town of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shenzhen\">Shenzhen</span> into a booming metropolis. Branding his market-oriented framework <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialism_with_Chinese_characteristics\">\"socialism with Chinese characteristics,\"</span> he oversaw economic expansion that the World Bank credits with lifting some 800 million people out of poverty, even as the accompanying <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"One-child_policy\">one-child policy</span></b> imposed sweeping demographic controls on the population. On the world stage he negotiated the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-British_Joint_Declaration\">Sino-British Joint Declaration</span> of 1984 to return <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span> under his formula of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"One_country,_two_systems\">\"one country, two systems,\"</span> yet his legacy was indelibly stained by his decision to authorise the military suppression of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1989_Tiananmen_Square_protests_and_massacre\">Tiananmen Square protests</span> in June 1989. Having never held the office of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"President_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">head of state</span> or party <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"General_Secretary_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">general secretary</span>, he reasserted his reformist vision during a celebrated 1992 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Southern_Tour\">southern tour</span> before passing the reins to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Zemin\">Jiang Zemin</span>, and he died in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> in 1997 at the age of 92, months before the Hong Kong handover he had helped engineer.","citation":"","answerText":"Deng Xiaoping"},{"id":"em-057","num":"五十七","category":"1911 Revolution · Revolutionaries","question":"Founded in 1905 in Tokyo by merging several revolutionary groups under Sun Yat-sen, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> worked to overthrow the Manchu dynasty and was the forerunner of the later Nationalist Party.","answer":"Tongmenghui","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Founded</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1905 · Tokyo, by Sun Yat-sen</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Merged</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1912 · into the Kuomintang</span></div>","traditional":"同盟會","hanzi":"同盟会","pinyin":"Tóngménghuì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Tóngménghuì</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“United League”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Tongmenghui</b> was a revolutionary alliance <b>founded in 1905</b> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tokyo\">Tokyo</span>, then a gathering place for Chinese radicals in exile across <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empire_of_Japan\">Japan</span>, that became the principal organisational vehicle of the movement to overthrow the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> and establish a Chinese <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republicanism\">republic</span></b>. It was created in August 1905 through the merger of several existing revolutionary societies, chiefly <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Yat-sen\">Sun Yat-sen</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Revive_China_Society\">Revive China Society</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huaxinghui\">Huaxinghui</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huang_Xing\">Huang Xing</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_Jiaoren\">Song Jiaoren</span></b>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Restoration_Society\">Restoration Society</span> associated with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cai_Yuanpei\">Cai Yuanpei</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Binglin\">Zhang Binglin</span>, with Sun installed as its director and propagandists such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Hanmin\">Hu Hanmin</span> rising to prominence. Its programme was distilled into a concise revolutionary oath—to expel the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_people\">Manchus</span>, restore Chinese rule, found a republic, and equalise land rights—a platform that Sun soon elaborated into his celebrated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Principles_of_the_People\">Three Principles of the People</span> of nationalism, democracy, and the people's livelihood. The alliance propagated its ideas through the Tokyo-based journal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Min_Bao\"><i>Min Bao</i></span>, whose contributors—including the fiery polemicist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Jingwei\">Wang Jingwei</span>—waged a fierce ideological war against the gradualist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitutional_monarchy\">constitutional monarchism</span> championed by the exiled reformer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liang_Qichao\">Liang Qichao</span>. Drawing financial and human support from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Overseas_Chinese\">overseas Chinese</span> communities and a growing student membership that swelled into the thousands—among them the celebrated woman revolutionary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qiu_Jin\">Qiu Jin</span>—the Tongmenghui organised and bankrolled a series of roughly 10 armed uprisings across southern China <b>between 1906</b> and 1911. <br> <br> Almost all of these revolts were swiftly and bloodily crushed, the most famous being the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huanghuagang_Uprising\">Second Guangzhou Uprising</span> of April 1911, whose fallen revolutionaries were enshrined in nationalist memory thereafter as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"72_Martyrs_of_Huanghuagang\">72 Martyrs of Huanghuagang</span>. The decisive breakthrough came unexpectedly with the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuchang_Uprising\">Wuchang Uprising</span> of 10 October 1911</b>, a mutiny by revolutionary soldiers in the central Yangtze city that, though launched while Sun himself was raising funds abroad, triggered the cascading province-by-province secession known as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinhai_Revolution\">Xinhai Revolution</span>. Sun hurried back to be elected provisional president of the new <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)\">Republic of China</span>, whose <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Provisional_Government_of_the_Republic_of_China_(1912)\">provisional government</span></b> was proclaimed at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span> on 1 January 1912, and the abdication of the boy emperor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Puyi\">Puyi</span> the following month brought more than 2,000 years of imperial rule to an end. Later in 1912 Song Jiaoren reorganised the Tongmenghui and several minor parties into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span>, the Nationalist Party, in order to contest the republic's inaugural parliamentary elections, in which it emerged as the dominant force. Song's assassination in 1913, widely blamed on the strongman president <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_Shikai\">Yuan Shikai</span>, provoked the abortive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Revolution_(China)\">Second Revolution</span> and drove Sun back into exile, where he rebuilt his followers as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Revolutionary_Party\">Chinese Revolutionary Party</span></b>, ensuring that the short-lived alliance would be remembered as the direct ancestor of the party that dominated Republican China.","citation":"","answerText":"Tongmenghui"},{"id":"em-059","num":"五十九","category":"1911 Revolution · Ideology","question":"Set out by Sun Yat-sen as the guiding doctrine of his movement, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> rested on the pillars of nationalism, democracy and the people's livelihood, and became the official creed of the Kuomintang and the Nationalist government.","answer":"Three Principles of the People","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Origin</span><span class=\"dt-v\">formulated by Sun Yat-sen; first set out 1905, expanded 1924</span></div>","traditional":"三民主義","hanzi":"三民主义","pinyin":"Sānmín Zhǔyì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Sānmín Zhǔyì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Three Principles of the People</b> is the political philosophy formulated by the revolutionary Sun Yat-sen to guide the transformation of China into a free, prosperous, and modern republic. Resting on the <b>pillars of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nationalism\">nationalism</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Democracy\">democracy</span>, and the people's livelihood, the doctrine was explicitly modelled on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Abraham_Lincoln\">Abraham Lincoln</span>'s description of government \"of the people, by the people, and for the people,\" which Sun adapted from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gettysburg_Address\">Gettysburg Address</span>. Sun first <b>articulated the programme around 1905</b> through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tongmenghui\">Tongmenghui</span>, the revolutionary alliance he founded in Tokyo to overthrow the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span>, and its principle of nationalism initially carried a strongly anti-<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_people\">Manchu</span> and anti-<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperialism\">imperialist</span> charge. The overthrow of the monarchy <b>in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1911_Revolution\">Xinhai Revolution</span> of 1911</b> produced the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)\">Republic of China</span> the following year, after which Sun broadened nationalism into a vision of unity among the country's ethnic groups, of whom the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Chinese\">Han</span> formed more than 90%, summarised in the slogan of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five_Races_Under_One_Union\">Five Races Under One Union</span>. He elaborated the mature theory in a celebrated series of 16 lectures <b>delivered at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou\">Guangzhou</span> in 1924</b>—6 on nationalism, 6 on democracy, and 4 on livelihood—which were transcribed and published as his most influential work.<br> <br>The principle of democracy envisaged a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five-Power_Constitution\">Five-Power Constitution</span> that supplemented the Western <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Separation_of_powers\">separation of powers</span> with branches drawn from imperial Chinese practice, an <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Examination_Yuan\">Examination Yuan</span></b> rooted in the old <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examination</span> and a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Control_Yuan\">Control Yuan</span> descended from the traditional <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Censorate\">censorate</span>. The principle of livelihood, frequently characterised as a moderate form of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialism\">socialism</span>, called for the equalisation of land rights and the regulation of capital, borrowing from the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Land_value_tax\">land value tax</span></b> championed by the American economist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Henry_George\">Henry George</span>. In 1924 Sun reorganised his party along Leninist lines with Soviet assistance, founded the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Whampoa_Military_Academy\">Whampoa Military Academy</span>, and entered the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_United_Front\">First United Front</span> with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span>, reinterpreting his doctrine through the Three Great Policies of alliance with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Soviet Union</span>, admission of Communists, and support for workers and peasants. After Sun's death in 1925 and the reunification of much of the country in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Expedition\">Northern Expedition</span> of 1926–1928, the doctrine was canonised as the official creed of the ruling party and the national government, enshrined in the opening article of the 1947 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitution_of_the_Republic_of_China\">Constitution of the Republic of China</span> and proclaimed in the opening lines of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Anthem_of_the_Republic_of_China\">national anthem</span></b>. Championed thereafter by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span> and carried to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span> after the Nationalists lost the mainland in 1949, the doctrine also supplied rhetorical raw material for the victorious Communists, whose programme of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Democracy\">New Democracy</span> laid claim to Sun's revolutionary legacy even while repudiating the party he had built.","citation":"","answerText":"Three Principles of the People"},{"id":"em-062","num":"六十二","category":"1911 Revolution · The Last Emperor","question":"Enthroned as a toddler in 1908 and forced to abdicate in 1912, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> later became the puppet ruler installed by Japan over Manchukuo, and ended his days as an ordinary citizen of the People's Republic.","answer":"Puyi","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">7 February 1906 · Beijing</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">17 October 1967 (age 61) · Beijing</span></div>","traditional":"溥儀","hanzi":"溥仪","pinyin":"Pǔyí","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Pǔyí</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Puyi</b> (7 February 1906 – 17 October 1967) was the final monarch of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> and the last man to reign as emperor in China, born in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Aisin-Gioro\">Aisin-Gioro</span> clan, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_people\">Manchu</span> house that had ruled China for nearly 270 years. Chosen as heir on the deathbed of the formidable <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empress_Dowager_Cixi\">Empress Dowager Cixi</span>, he was <b>enthroned in 1908</b> at the age of 2 as the Xuantong Emperor, succeeding his uncle the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangxu_Emperor\">Guangxu Emperor</span>, with his father <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zaifeng,_Prince_Chun\">Zaifeng</span> serving as prince-regent. His reign proved brief, for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1911_Revolution\">Xinhai Revolution</span> forced his <b>abdication on 12 February 1912</b>, an act proclaimed in his name by the regent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empress_Dowager_Longyu\">Empress Dowager Longyu</span> that dissolved the Qing and ended the imperial system, established long before by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_Shi_Huang\">Qin Shi Huang</span>, which had endured for more than 2,000 years. Under generous abdication terms he kept his imperial title and went on living in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Forbidden_City\">Forbidden City</span> with a substantial annual subsidy, received a Western education from his Scottish tutor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Reginald_Fleming_Johnston\">Reginald Johnston</span>, and was briefly returned to the throne for just 12 days during <b>the abortive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_Restoration\">Manchu Restoration</span> of 1917</b>. This sheltered existence collapsed in 1924, when, amid the turmoil of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warlord_Era\">Warlord Era</span>, the warlord <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Feng_Yuxiang\">Feng Yuxiang</span> seized the capital and expelled the former emperor, who fled first to the Japanese legation and then to the foreign concessions of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tianjin\">Tianjin</span>.<br> <br>Following the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mukden_Incident\">Mukden Incident</span> of 1931 and the ensuing <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japanese_invasion_of_Manchuria\">Japanese invasion of Manchuria</span></b>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kwantung_Army\">Kwantung Army</span> installed him in 1932 as chief executive of the puppet state of Manchukuo and elevated him in 1934 to the hollow dignity of emperor under the era name Kangde. Wielding no genuine authority over a regime directed from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tokyo\">Tokyo</span>, he presided over <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchuria\">Manchuria</span> until the state disintegrated in August 1945 amid the lightning <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_invasion_of_Manchuria\">Soviet invasion of Manchuria</span>. Captured by the advancing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Red_Army\">Red Army</span> as he tried to flee to Japan, he was detained in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Soviet Union</span> for some 5 years and in 1946 gave testimony before the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"International_Military_Tribunal_for_the_Far_East\">International Military Tribunal for the Far East</span> in Tokyo. Handed over to the Chinese authorities in 1950, he spent nearly a decade in political re-education at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fushun_War_Criminals_Management_Centre\">Fushun War Criminals Management Centre</span></b> before a special amnesty in 1959 freed him as an ordinary citizen, who afterward tended plants at a Beijing botanical garden and worked for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_People's_Political_Consultative_Conference\">Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference</span>, recounting his transformation in the 1964 memoir <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"From_Emperor_to_Citizen\"><i>From Emperor to Citizen</i></span></b>. He died of cancer in 1967 as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span> convulsed the nation, and his extraordinary passage from the dragon throne to a prison cell to obscurity was later immortalised in <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bernardo_Bertolucci\">Bernardo Bertolucci</span></b>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Last_Emperor\"><i>The Last Emperor</i></span>, which swept the 1988 ceremony with 9 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Academy_Awards\">Academy Awards</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Puyi"},{"id":"cnp-015","num":"十五","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Derived from the organisational thinking of Lenin and central to how the Communist Party reaches decisions, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> holds that policy is debated freely but, once decided, binds all members and lower bodies to the leadership.","answer":"Democratic centralism","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Coined</span><span class=\"dt-v\">V. I. Lenin, as the Bolshevik organizing principle, c. 1906</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"民主集中制","pinyin":"Mínzhǔ jízhōng zhì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Mínzhǔ jízhōng zhì</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Democratic centralism</b> is the organizing principle of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Communism\">communist</span> parties, prescribing that policy may be debated openly within the party but that, once a decision has been reached, all members and subordinate bodies are bound to carry it out. The principle was developed by Lenin in his writings on party organization, notably the <b>1904 polemic</b> <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"One_Step_Forward,_Two_Steps_Back\"><i>One Step Forward, Two Steps Back</i></span></b>, as the structural basis of the disciplined <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vanguardism\">vanguard party</span>, and it was formally adopted by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russian_Social_Democratic_Labour_Party\">Russian Social Democratic Labour Party</span> around 1906. Encapsulated in the maxim \"freedom of discussion, unity of action,\" it became a defining tenet of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Leninism\">Leninism</span> and, <b>after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"October_Revolution\">October Revolution</span> of 1917</b>, of the ruling <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bolsheviks\">Bolshevik</span> party that became the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Communist_Party_of_the_Soviet_Union\">Communist Party of the Soviet Union</span>. Codified more rigidly under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joseph_Stalin\">Joseph Stalin</span> in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Soviet Union</span> and propagated worldwide through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Communist_International\">Communist International</span>, it was prescribed as a condition of membership for every party in the global communist movement. Within the doctrine of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marxism–Leninism\">Marxism–Leninism</span>, the principle was held to reconcile mass participation with the iron unity thought necessary to wield the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dictatorship_of_the_proletariat\">dictatorship of the proletariat</span></b>, a synthesis that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Karl_Marx\">Karl Marx</span> and classical <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marxism\">Marxism</span> had never explicitly systematized.<br> <br>The Chinese Communist Party adopted the principle from its founding and gave it canonical Chinese expression when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> formulated <b>the \"Four Subordinations\" in 1938</b>—the individual subordinate to the organization, the minority to the majority, the lower level to the higher, and the whole party to its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Central Committee</span>. Mao tied it to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mass_line\">mass line</span> of \"from the masses, to the masses,\" and the party theorist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Shaoqi\">Liu Shaoqi</span> spelled out the duties of discipline binding every <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cadre_(politics)\">cadre</span>. The principle is enshrined both in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitution_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">party constitution</span></b> and in the state <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitution_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">constitution</span>, whose Article 3 prescribes that the organs of state power operate on its basis, structuring within a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"One-party_state\">one-party state</span> the hierarchy that runs from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_People's_Congress\">National People's Congress</span> down to local government. In practice the \"centralist\" element has generally prevailed over the \"democratic\" one, with the party's strict prohibition of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Political_faction\">factional</span> activity narrowing genuine debate, just as critics from <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rosa_Luxemburg\">Rosa Luxemburg</span></b> to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Leon_Trotsky\">Leon Trotsky</span> had warned that such concentration tends toward bureaucratic dictatorship—a danger realized when normal party procedures dissolved into personal rule during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span>. <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> subsequently reaffirmed the principle while cautioning against the over-centralization of the Mao years, and it endures today as the organizing axiom of both party and state, vesting decisive authority in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_Standing_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo Standing Committee</span> and its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"General_Secretary_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">general secretary</span> under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialism_with_Chinese_characteristics\">socialism with Chinese characteristics</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Democratic centralism"},{"id":"cnp-038","num":"三十八","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Named in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> as Mao Zedong's designated successor and a chief promoter of the <i>Little Red Book</i>, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> died in a <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> plane crash while reportedly fleeing toward the Soviet Union.","answer":"Lin Biao","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">5 December 1907</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">13 September 1971</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"林彪","pinyin":"Lín Biāo","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Lín Biāo</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Lin Biao</b> was a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marshal_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">marshal</span></b> and politician of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span> who rose to become defence minister and the constitutionally designated successor to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> before perishing in mysterious circumstances at the height of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span>. Born into a modest family in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huanggang\">Huanggang</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hubei\">Hubei</span> province, he trained at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Whampoa_Military_Academy\">Whampoa Military Academy</span> and <b>joined the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> in 1925</b>, taking part in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanchang_uprising\">Nanchang Uprising</span> of 1927 after the bloody collapse of the alliance with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span>. He earned a formidable reputation as a tactician during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Long_March\">Long March</span> of 1934–1935, in which he commanded the elite First Army Corps of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Red_Army\">Red Army</span>, and his standing grew further when his <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eighth_Route_Army\">Eighth Route Army</span> forces won the <b>celebrated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Pingxingguan\">Battle of Pingxingguan</span> in 1937</b>, an early morale-boosting clash of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Sino-Japanese_War\">Second Sino-Japanese War</span>. After recovering from a serious wound that took him to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Soviet Union</span> for several years of convalescence, he returned to lead communist armies in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchuria\">Manchuria</span> during the resumed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">Chinese Civil War</span>, masterminding the decisive <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liaoshen_campaign\">Liaoshen Campaign</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pingjin_campaign\">Pingjin Campaign</span> of 1948–1949</b> that shattered Nationalist power across the north. Appointed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Minister_of_National_Defense_(China)\">Minister of National Defence</span> in 1959 after <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peng_Dehuai\">Peng Dehuai</span> was purged at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lushan_Conference_(1959)\">Lushan Conference</span>, he set about reshaping the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army\">People's Liberation Army</span> into an instrument of ideological devotion to Mao. <br> <br> It was Lin who in 1964 directed the army to compile and study <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Quotations_from_Chairman_Mao_Zedong\"><i>Quotations from Chairman Mao Zedong</i></span></b>, the pocket-sized volume better known as the <i>Little Red Book</i>, a work ultimately printed in more than a billion copies that made him the foremost promoter of Mao's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cult_of_personality\">cult of personality</span>. As the Cultural Revolution unfolded he aligned himself with the radicals and encouraged the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Red_Guards\">Red Guards</span>, rising to sole vice-chairman of the party, and at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"9th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Ninth National Congress</span></b> in 1969 he was formally enshrined in the Party constitution as Mao's chosen heir. Relations with Mao soured rapidly thereafter, in part over a contentious dispute about restoring the abolished post of state chairman, and the 1970 plenum that brought down Lin's close ally <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Boda\">Chen Boda</span> signalled the unravelling of his position. According to the official account, his family responded by hatching an abortive coup plot code-named <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Project_571\">Project 571</span>, and when it failed Lin, his wife <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ye_Qun\">Ye Qun</span> and son <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lin_Liguo\">Lin Liguo</span> fled aboard a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hawker_Siddeley_Trident\">Hawker Siddeley Trident</span></b> that crashed near <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Öndörkhaan\">Öndörkhaan</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongolia\">Mongolia</span>, killing everyone aboard. Branded a traitor after the so-called 9-13 Incident, he was posthumously vilified in the nationwide <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Criticize_Lin,_Criticize_Confucius\">Criticize Lin, Criticize Confucius</span> campaign that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Qing\">Jiang Qing</span> and her allies soon redirected against premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span>, leaving Lin Biao one of the most enigmatic and bitterly contested figures in the entire history of the People's Republic.","citation":"","answerText":"Lin Biao"},{"id":"em-060","num":"六十","category":"1911 Revolution · The Revolution","question":"Touched off in October 1911 by an accidental bomb explosion that exposed a revolutionary cell within the New Army, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> spread rapidly as province after province declared independence from the Qing.","answer":"Wuchang Uprising","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">10 October 1911 · Wuchang (triggered the revolution)</span></div>","traditional":"武昌起義","hanzi":"武昌起义","pinyin":"Wǔchāng Qǐyì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Wǔchāng Qǐyì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Wuchang Uprising</b> was <b>the military mutiny of October 1911</b> that ignited the revolution overthrowing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> and ending more than 2,000 years of imperial rule in China. It erupted in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuchang_District\">Wuchang</span>, the capital of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hubei\">Hubei</span></b> province and one of the trio of riverside towns that together compose the great <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span> metropolis of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuhan\">Wuhan</span>, at a moment when the dynasty was already reeling from a fiscal and political crisis under the regency of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zaifeng,_Prince_Chun\">Prince Chun</span>. The immediate spark was the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Railway_Protection_Movement\">Railway Protection Movement</span></b>, a wave of mass agitation against the Qing scheme to nationalise the trunk railways with foreign loans, whose violent outbreak in neighbouring <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan\">Sichuan</span> drew away the very <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Army\">New Army</span> units that might otherwise have garrisoned the city and overawed its restless soldiery. Within the modernised garrison, a pair of revolutionary cells—the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Literary_Society_(Wuhan)\">Literary Society</span></b> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Progressive_Association\">Progressive Association</span>, both loosely tied to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Yat-sen\">Sun Yat-sen</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tongmenghui\">Tongmenghui</span>—had quietly enrolled hundreds of soldiers, so that by the autumn of 1911 a substantial part of the New Army at Wuchang was committed to the revolutionary cause. Their hand was forced on 9 October 1911 when a bomb being assembled in the Russian concession at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hankou\">Hankou</span> exploded by accident, prompting a police raid that seized the membership rolls, exposed the entire network, and sent several captured plotters swiftly to the execution ground. <br> <br> Facing imminent arrest, the revolutionary soldiers of an engineering battalion rose in mutiny on the night of 10 October 1911—a soldier named <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiong_Bingkun\">Xiong Bingkun</span></b> is traditionally credited with firing the opening shot—seizing the arsenal and storming the yamen of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Viceroy_of_Huguang\">Viceroy of Huguang</span>, who fled across the river as the rebels took control of Wuchang by dawn. Because the movement's senior leaders were absent or in hiding, the mutineers compelled a reluctant Qing brigade commander, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Yuanhong\">Li Yuanhong</span>, to head the new <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hubei_Military_Government\">Hubei Military Government</span></b>, joined by local <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitutionalism\">constitutionalist</span> gentry, which proclaimed the overthrow of Manchu rule in Hubei the following day. News of the success spread like wildfire along the telegraph lines, and within weeks 15 of the 18 provinces of China proper had declared their independence in the cascade of secessions known as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinhai_Revolution\">Xinhai Revolution</span>, so named for the year of 1911 in the traditional <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sexagenary_cycle\">sexagenary cycle</span>. The court hastily recalled <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_Shikai\">Yuan Shikai</span> and his formidable <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beiyang_Army\">Beiyang Army</span>, which under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Feng_Guozhang\">Feng Guozhang</span> recaptured Hankou and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hanyang_District\">Hanyang</span> from the revolutionary forces marshalled by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huang_Xing\">Huang Xing</span> in the bloody <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Yangxia\">Battle of Yangxia</span>, yet Wuchang held out long enough for the revolution to become irreversible. Rather than crush the revolt outright, Yuan instead manoeuvred to broker the abdication of the child <b>emperor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Puyi\">Puyi</span> in February 1912</b>, by which time Sun Yat-sen had returned from abroad to be inaugurated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"President_of_the_Republic_of_China\">provisional president</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)\">Republic of China</span> at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span>, and the date of the original mutiny endures today as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Double_Ten_Day\">Double Ten</span> national holiday of the Chinese republic.","citation":"","answerText":"Wuchang Uprising"},{"id":"em-061","num":"六十一","category":"1911 Revolution · The Revolution","question":"Named for the year 1911 in the traditional calendar cycle, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> swept away more than 2,000 years of imperial rule, toppling the Qing and leading to the proclamation of a republic the following year.","answer":"Xinhai Revolution","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Began</span><span class=\"dt-v\">10 October 1911 · Wuchang Uprising</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Ended</span><span class=\"dt-v\">February 1912 · Qing abdication</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"辛亥革命","pinyin":"Xīnhài Gémìng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Xīnhài Gémìng</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Revolution of the Xinhai Year”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Xinhai Revolution</b> was the uprising that overthrew the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span>, China's last imperial dynasty, and ended more than 2,000 years of monarchical rule reaching back to the unification of China <b>under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_dynasty\">Qin dynasty</span> in 221 BCE</b>. Its name derives from the designation of 1911 as a xinhai year in the traditional <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sexagenary_cycle\">sexagenary cycle</span>, and it is widely regarded as the culmination of decades of crisis that followed humiliating defeats such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Sino-Japanese_War\">First Sino-Japanese War</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boxer_Rebellion\">Boxer Rebellion</span>. The belated reforms of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Policies\">New Policies</span></b> failed to quell a rising tide of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Chinese\">Han</span> nationalist resentment against the ruling <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_people\">Manchu</span> minority, and revolutionary cells tied to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Yat-sen\">Sun Yat-sen</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tongmenghui\">Tongmenghui</span> had quietly infiltrated the modernised <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Army\">New Army</span>. When the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Railway_Protection_Movement\">Railway Protection Movement</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan\">Sichuan</span> drew Qing troops away from the central provinces, mutinous soldiers launched the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuchang_Uprising\">Wuchang Uprising</span> on October 10, 1911</b>—now commemorated as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Double_Ten_Day\">Double Ten Day</span></b>—and installed the reluctant officer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Yuanhong\">Li Yuanhong</span> at the head of a new military government in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hubei\">Hubei</span>. Within roughly 6 weeks 15 of the empire's 18 provinces had declared independence in a largely swift and, in many regions, comparatively bloodless collapse, leaving the court clinging to little more than the capital at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>. <br> <br> Sun Yat-sen, who had been travelling abroad when the rising began, hurried home and was chosen provisional <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"President_of_the_Republic_of_China\">president</span> by delegates of the seceded provinces, proclaiming the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)\">Republic of China</span> at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span> on January 1, 1912. Desperate, the Qing court recalled the powerful general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_Shikai\">Yuan Shikai</span>, whose loyal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beiyang_Army\">Beiyang Army</span> was the only force capable of crushing the revolt, but he instead brokered a settlement that promised him the presidency in exchange for the emperor's abdication. <b>On February 12, 1912</b> the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empress_Dowager_Longyu\">Empress Dowager Longyu</span> issued the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_Edict_of_the_Abdication_of_the_Qing_Emperor\">abdication edict</span></b> on behalf of the 6-year-old <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Puyi\">Puyi</span>, abolishing the office of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_of_China\">emperor of China</span> and the dynastic order long legitimated by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mandate_of_Heaven\">Mandate of Heaven</span>. True to the bargain, Sun stepped aside for Yuan, but the revolution proved incomplete, as Yuan soon ruled dictatorially, sought to enthrone himself as emperor, and upon his death in 1916 left the country to splinter in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warlord_Era\">Warlord Era</span>. Although it replaced the throne with a republic governed <b>by a short-lived <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Provisional_Constitution_of_the_Republic_of_China\">provisional constitution</span></b>, the revolution left Sun's broader aims unfulfilled and provoked his abortive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Revolution_(China)\">Second Revolution</span> of 1913, yet it endures as a foundational event honoured alike by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Nationalists</span> and the Communists as the decisive break with more than 21 centuries of dynastic monarchy.","citation":"","answerText":"Xinhai Revolution"},{"id":"em-063","num":"六十三","category":"Early Republic · Founding","question":"Proclaimed in 1912 after the fall of the monarchy, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> endured warlordism, civil war and the war with Japan under the Nationalists before its government retreated to Taiwan in 1949.","answer":"Republic of China","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Founded</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1912 · by Sun Yat-sen</span><span class=\"dt-k\">To Taiwan</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1949</span></div>","traditional":"中華民國","hanzi":"中华民国","pinyin":"Zhōnghuá Mínguó","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōnghuá Mínguó</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Republic of China</b> was the state established on the Chinese mainland in 1912 following the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinhai_Revolution\">Xinhai Revolution</span></b> and the abdication of the last <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> emperor, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Puyi\">Puyi</span>, which brought to a close more than 2,000 years of imperial dynastic rule. Proclaimed at <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span> on 1 January 1912</b> with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Yat-sen\">Sun Yat-sen</span> as its provisional president, it was almost immediately handed over to the northern strongman <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_Shikai\">Yuan Shikai</span>, who had secured the emperor's abdication and now moved the capital to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> to govern through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beiyang_government\">Beiyang government</span>. Yuan's brief attempt to crown himself emperor of a new <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empire_of_China_(1915–1916)\">Empire of China</span> collapsed amid the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Protection_War\">National Protection War</span>, and <b>his death in 1916</b> plunged the country into the fractured <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warlord_Era\">Warlord Era</span>, in which rival militarists carved up the provinces while the Beijing regime commanded little real authority. Against this backdrop of disunity the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"May_Fourth_Movement\">May Fourth Movement</span> of 1919, ignited by the humiliating transfer of former German rights in Shandong to Japan under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Versailles\">Treaty of Versailles</span>, galvanised a whole generation of nationalist and radical intellectuals and helped spawn both a renewed revolutionary politics and <b>the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> in 1921</b>. Sun meanwhile rebuilt the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span> with Soviet assistance and forged a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_United_Front\">First United Front</span> with the communists, a partnership that, after his death in 1925, enabled his successor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span> to launch the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Expedition\">Northern Expedition</span> and nominally reunify the nation by 1928. <br> <br> Chiang established a Nationalist government at Nanjing, inaugurating the relatively stable <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing_decade\">Nanjing decade</span>, but he had already turned violently on his allies in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_massacre\">Shanghai massacre</span> of 1927, opening a bitter <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">civil war</span> that drove the communists into rural bases and ultimately onto the epic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Long_March\">Long March</span>. Foreign aggression compounded the internal strife, as Japan seized resource-rich Manchuria after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mukden_Incident\">Mukden Incident</span> of 1931 and installed the puppet state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchukuo\">Manchukuo</span> under the deposed emperor Puyi, before escalating to full-scale invasion at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marco_Polo_Bridge_Incident\">Marco Polo Bridge</span></b> near Beijing in 1937. The ensuing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Sino-Japanese_War\">war with Japan</span> proved catastrophic, claiming an estimated 15 to 20 million Chinese lives and including the notorious <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing_Massacre\">Nanjing Massacre</span>, in which perhaps 200,000 to 300,000 people were killed, and forcing the government to retreat upriver to a wartime capital at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chongqing\">Chongqing</span>. Fighting on as a principal <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Allies_of_World_War_II\">Allied power</span></b> through years of occupation until Japan's surrender in 1945, the republic emerged nominally victorious but economically shattered and politically exhausted, only to see its uneasy wartime <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_United_Front\">truce</span> with the communists dissolve into a renewed civil war that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>'s peasant armies decisively won. With the proclamation of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span> in 1949, Chiang's defeated government, party, and army withdrew across the strait to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span>, establishing a provisional capital at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taipei\">Taipei</span> and continuing to hold China's seat at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_Nations\">United Nations</span></b> until it was transferred to Beijing in 1971.","citation":"","answerText":"Republic of China"},{"id":"em-067","num":"六十七","category":"Early Republic · The State","question":"The internationally recognised administration based in Beijing from 1912, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> — dominated after Yuan Shikai's death by a succession of militarists and their cliques — held formal sovereignty even as real power fragmented among regional warlords.","answer":"Beiyang government","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Began</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1912 · Yuan Shikai’s republic</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Ended</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1928 · Northern Expedition</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"北洋政府","pinyin":"Běiyáng zhèngfǔ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Běiyáng zhèngfǔ</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Beiyang government</b> was the internationally recognised government of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)\">Republic of China</span></b> that ruled from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> <b>between 1912</b> and <b>1928</b>, taking its name from the northern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beiyang_Army\">Beiyang Army</span> from which its leading figures emerged. It arose out of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinhai_Revolution\">Xinhai Revolution</span> that toppled the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> and was initially consolidated under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_Shikai\">Yuan Shikai</span>, whose authoritarian presidency and short-lived attempt to found the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empire_of_China_(1915–1916)\">Empire of China</span> ended only <b>with his death in 1916</b>. Yuan's death removed the one strongman capable of holding the Beiyang military together, and the army splintered into rival factions—principally the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anhui_clique\">Anhui clique</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhili_clique\">Zhili clique</span>, and the Manchuria-based <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fengtian_clique\">Fengtian clique</span>—that competed to control the capital and its institutions. Real authority therefore shifted with each turn of military fortune, passing among figures such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Duan_Qirui\">Duan Qirui</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Feng_Guozhang\">Feng Guozhang</span>, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cao_Kun\">Cao Kun</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Peifu\">Wu Peifu</span>, and the Fengtian leader <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Zuolin\">Zhang Zuolin</span>, while the formal presidency rotated rapidly among men like <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Yuanhong\">Li Yuanhong</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xu_Shichang\">Xu Shichang</span>. This volatility produced extraordinary instability, the regime briefly collapsing as early as July 1917 when the loyalist general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Xun\">Zhang Xun</span> staged the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_Restoration\">Manchu Restoration</span> that returned the deposed emperor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Puyi\">Puyi</span> to the throne for some 12 days, while over the period the office of head of state passed among at least 7 different men and the cabinet was reshuffled dozens of times—Cao Kun infamously bribing legislators to win the presidency in 1923. <br> <br> On the international stage the government maintained China's diplomatic recognition and its seat among the powers, declaring war on Germany in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_War_I\">World War I</span> in 1917 and dispatching the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Labour_Corps\">Chinese Labour Corps</span></b> of some 140,000 men to support the Allied war effort. Its failure to reclaim the former German concessions in Shandong—rights handed instead to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empire_of_Japan\">Japan</span> at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paris_Peace_Conference_(1919–1920)\">Paris Peace Conference</span> in a humiliation remembered as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shandong_Problem\">Shandong Problem</span>—ignited the nationalist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"May_Fourth_Movement\">May Fourth Movement</span> of 1919 and led the Chinese delegation to refuse to sign the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Versailles\">Treaty of Versailles</span>. The cliques nonetheless waged ruinous wars among themselves, beginning with the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhili–Anhui_War\">Zhili–Anhui War</span></b> of 1920, while the government meanwhile recovered many of its Shandong rights at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Washington_Naval_Conference\">Washington Naval Conference</span> of 1921–1922, before factional conflict flared again in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Zhili–Fengtian_War\">First Zhili–Fengtian War</span> of 1922 and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Zhili–Fengtian_War\">Second Zhili–Fengtian War</span> of 1924. Throughout these years its legitimacy was contested by a rival <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span>-led government in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou\">Guangzhou</span>, organised by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Yat-sen\">Sun Yat-sen</span> under the banner of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitutional_Protection_Movement\">Constitutional Protection Movement</span>, which rejected the Beiyang regime as illegitimate. The government was finally swept away by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Expedition\">Northern Expedition</span>, the Nationalist military campaign led by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span> that captured Beijing in 1928, and after Zhang Zuolin was killed in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huanggutun_incident\">Huanggutun incident</span> that June, authority passed to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nationalist_government\">Nationalist government</span> seated in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Beiyang government"},{"id":"em-079","num":"七十九","category":"Nationalist Revolution · The Party","question":"Reorganised by Sun Yat-sen along Leninist lines and later led by Chiang Kai-shek, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> governed much of China from 1928, fought both the Japanese and the Communists, and remains a major party on Taiwan today.","answer":"Kuomintang","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Founded</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1919 · by Sun Yat-sen (predecessor 1912)</span></div>","traditional":"中國國民黨","hanzi":"中国国民党","pinyin":"Zhōngguó Guómíndǎng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōngguó Guómíndǎng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Kuomintang</b>, commonly abbreviated <b>KMT</b> and known in English as the<b> Chinese Nationalist Party</b>, is one of the most consequential political parties in modern Chinese history, having governed the mainland for two decades before relocating to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span>, where it endures as a major party today. It was <b>founded in 1912</b> by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Yat-sen\">Sun Yat-sen</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_Jiaoren\">Song Jiaoren</span> out of the revolutionary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tongmenghui\">Tongmenghui</span> to contest the first parliamentary elections of the new <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)\">Republic of China</span>, but its electoral triumph was cut short when Song was <b>assassinated in 1913</b> and the party was soon banned by President <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_Shikai\">Yuan Shikai</span>. Rebuilt in exile and then reorganised in 1924 along <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Leninism\">Leninist</span> lines of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Democratic_centralism\">democratic centralism</span> with the guidance of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Soviet</span> advisers such as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mikhail_Borodin\">Mikhail Borodin</span></b>, the party embraced Sun's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Principles_of_the_People\">Three Principles of the People</span> and entered a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_United_Front\">First United Front</span> with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span>. To furnish itself with a reliable army it founded the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Whampoa_Military_Academy\">Whampoa Military Academy</span> near Canton, and <b>after Sun's death in 1925 leadership</b> of its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Revolutionary_Army\">National Revolutionary Army</span> passed to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span>. Chiang's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Expedition\">Northern Expedition</span> of 1926–1928 subdued the regional warlords and reunified much of the country, allowing the party to establish a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nationalist_government\">Nationalist government</span> seated at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span>. <br> <br> Even before that victory was complete the party violently purged its Communist allies in the 1927 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_massacre\">Shanghai massacre</span>, inaugurating the protracted <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">Chinese Civil War</span> and a decade of one-party \"political tutelage\" remembered as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing_decade\">Nanjing decade</span>. When full-scale war erupted with Japan in 1937, the Kuomintang led China's resistance during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Sino-Japanese_War\">Second Sino-Japanese War</span>, forming an uneasy <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_United_Front\">Second United Front</span> with the Communists and removing its wartime capital to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chongqing\">Chongqing</span>. The resumption of the civil war after 1945 ended in catastrophe, however, and in 1949 the defeated party and its government fled to Taiwan along with well over a million soldiers and refugees, surrendering the mainland to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> and the newly proclaimed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span>. On the island the party governed as an authoritarian one-party state under one of the world's <b>longest periods of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Martial_law_in_Taiwan\">martial law</span></b>, lasting from 1949 until 1987 and accompanied by the political repression of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"White_Terror_(Taiwan)\">White Terror</span>, before liberalisation began under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Ching-kuo\">Chiang Ching-kuo</span> and his successor <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lee_Teng-hui\">Lee Teng-hui</span></b>. Following democratisation in the 1990s, the Kuomintang remains one of Taiwan's two principal parties alongside the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Democratic_Progressive_Party\">Democratic Progressive Party</span>, generally favouring closer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cross-Strait_relations\">cross-strait ties</span> with the mainland on the basis of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1992_Consensus\">1992 Consensus</span></b>, and it returned most prominently to the presidency under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ma_Ying-jeou\">Ma Ying-jeou</span> from 2008 to 2016.","citation":"","answerText":"Kuomintang"},{"id":"cne-003","num":"三","category":"China · Economics","question":"Tracing its roots to <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> and long the country's specialist in foreign exchange and trade finance, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> issues banknotes in Hong Kong and was among the first mainland lenders to list overseas, regulated by the central bank.","answer":"Bank of China","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">founded 1912</span></div>","traditional":"中國銀行","hanzi":"中国银行","pinyin":"Zhōngguó Yínháng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōngguó Yínháng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Bank of China</b> is one of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Big_Four_(banking)\">Big Four</span></b> state-owned <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Commercial_bank\">commercial banks</span> of China—alongside the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Industrial_and_Commercial_Bank_of_China\">Industrial and Commercial Bank of China</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Construction_Bank\">China Construction Bank</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Agricultural_Bank_of_China\">Agricultural Bank of China</span>—and ranks among the oldest and largest <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Financial_institution\">financial institutions</span></b> in the world. It <b>traces its origins to 1912</b>, when the new <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)\">Republic of China</span> reorganized the imperial bank of the fallen <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span>—the Da Qing Bank—in the wake <b>of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinhai_Revolution\">Xinhai Revolution</span> of 1911</b>, the institution having been approved under the provisional government of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Yat-sen\">Sun Yat-sen</span>. In the early Republican era it functioned at times as the country's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_bank\">central bank</span>, issuing currency and managing government finances, before being reorganized in 1928 into a specialized bank for international exchange and a major issuer of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Banknote\">banknotes</span>. After the founding of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Republic_of_China\">People's Republic</span> it became, under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Planned_economy\">planned economy</span>, the state's sole designated specialist in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foreign_exchange_market\">foreign exchange</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Trade_finance\">trade finance</span></b>, handling the bulk of China's international settlements and overseas remittances for decades, when private foreign-currency dealing was prohibited. Headquartered in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> and restructured into a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joint-stock_company\">joint-stock</span> commercial bank during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">economic reforms</span>, it grew into the most internationally oriented of China's large lenders, with the widest overseas branch network of any of them. <br> <br> Through its subsidiary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bank_of_China_(Hong_Kong)\">Bank of China (Hong Kong)</span>, it is one of the banks authorized to issue <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_dollar\">Hong Kong dollar</span> banknotes, alongside <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"HSBC\">HSBC</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Standard_Chartered\">Standard Chartered</span>, a role it has held <b>since 1994</b>, and it issues the pataca in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Macau\">Macau</span> as well. Its presence in the territory is symbolized by the landmark <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bank_of_China_Tower_(Hong_Kong)\">Bank of China Tower</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span>, an angular skyscraper designed by the architect <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"I._M._Pei\">I. M. Pei</span> that has become one of the city's most recognizable buildings and a symbol of mainland financial power. It was among the first mainland lenders to list overseas, a milestone in the modernization of China's banking system, with its Hong Kong unit floated in 2002 and the parent bank raising about 11 billion dollars through an <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Initial_public_offering\">initial public offering</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"H_share\">H-shares</span> on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_Stock_Exchange\">Hong Kong Stock Exchange</span> in 2006, paired with a listing in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_Stock_Exchange\">Shanghai</span>. Today it operates a sprawling global network across more than 60 countries and regions and has become a leading player in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Internationalization_of_the_renminbi\">internationalization of the renminbi</span>, serving as an officially appointed offshore clearing bank for the Chinese currency in financial centres from Hong Kong to London and Frankfurt. With total assets exceeding 4 trillion dollars—placing it among the largest banks on earth—it consistently ranks near the top of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fortune_Global_500\">Fortune Global 500</span>, is designated a globally <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Systemically_important_financial_institution\">systemically important</span></b> bank by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Financial_Stability_Board\">Financial Stability Board</span>, and operates under the supervision of China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Bank_of_China\">central bank</span> and banking regulators.","citation":"","answerText":"Bank of China"},{"id":"cne-052","num":"五十二","category":"China · Economics","question":"A single number between 0 and 1 measuring how unequally income is distributed, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> rose sharply in China as reform created new wealth, prompting leaders to stress a harmonious society and, later, common prosperity.","answer":"Gini coefficient","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Coined</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Corrado Gini, Italian statistician, 1912</span></div>","traditional":"基尼係數","hanzi":"基尼系数","pinyin":"Jīní xìshù","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Jīní xìshù</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>gini coefficient</b> is a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Statistics\">statistical</span> measure of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economic_inequality\">inequality</span></b>, most often used to summarize how unequally income is distributed, expressed as a single number between 0 and 1 and sometimes scaled from 0 to 100 as a percentage known as the Gini index. A value of 0 represents perfect equality, in which everyone earns the same, while a value approaching 1 represents maximal inequality, in which a single household receives nearly all <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Income_distribution\">income</span></b>, so that higher readings denote a more skewed distribution. The measure was <b>devised in 1912</b> by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Italy\">Italian</span> statistician <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Corrado_Gini\">Corrado Gini</span>, in a paper titled <i>Variabilità e mutabilità</i>, as an index of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Statistical_dispersion\">statistical dispersion</span> derived geometrically from the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lorenz_curve\">Lorenz curve</span></b>, the coefficient equalling twice the area between that curve and the line of perfect equality. Calculated on either pre-tax market income or post-tax, post-transfer disposable <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Household_income\">household income</span>, it ranges from roughly 0.25 in the egalitarian economies of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nordic_model\">Nordic model</span> to about 0.4 in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States\">United States</span> and above 0.5 in highly unequal nations such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South_Africa\">South Africa</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Brazil\">Brazil</span>. A reading above 0.4 is widely cited as a threshold beyond which inequality may fuel <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Civil_disorder\">social unrest</span></b>, making the statistic a closely watched gauge for governments worldwide, though economists caution that it captures only relative inequality and is sensitive to how income is measured. <br> <br> In China the coefficient was low under the egalitarian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Planned_economy\">planned economy</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>, when wages were compressed and private fortunes all but abolished, but it rose sharply after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">economic reforms</span> launched by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>, whose maxim that some should \"get rich first\" unleashed rapid but uneven <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wealth\">wealth</span> creation. Official figures from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Bureau_of_Statistics_of_China\">National Bureau of Statistics</span> show the index climbing from around 0.3 in the early 1980s to a peak <b>of about 0.49 in 2008</b>—well above the 0.4 mark—and easing only slightly to roughly 0.47 thereafter, while some independent surveys, including a 2012 academic study, have estimated figures above 0.6. The widening gap reflected a deep divide between the prosperous coastal provinces and the poorer inland interior and between urban and rural residents—whose average incomes diverged by a ratio of roughly 3 to 1—the latter reinforced by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hukou\">household-registration system</span> and unequal returns to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capital_(economics)\">capital</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Distribution_of_wealth\">property</span>. Alarmed by the trend, the leadership of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Jintao\">Hu Jintao</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wen_Jiabao\">Wen Jiabao</span> promoted a \"<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Harmonious_Society\">harmonious society</span>\" and a \"<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Scientific_Outlook_on_Development\">scientific outlook on development</span>\" stressing balanced growth and expanded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Welfare\">welfare</span>, and the state mounted a vast <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Poverty_reduction\">poverty-alleviation</span> campaign that it declared had ended <b>extreme rural <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Poverty_in_China\">poverty</span> by 2021</b>, having lifted some 800 million people out of destitution over four decades. Under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span> the emphasis shifted to \"<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Common_prosperity\">common prosperity</span>,\" a renewed drive from 2021 to narrow the divide through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Redistribution_of_income_and_wealth\">redistribution</span>, tighter regulation of the wealthy and large technology firms, and encouragement of voluntary corporate <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Philanthropy\">philanthropy</span>, though analysts debated how far it would genuinely reduce inequality.","citation":"","answerText":"Gini coefficient"},{"id":"em-065","num":"六十五","category":"Early Republic · Japanese Pressure","question":"Presented secretly in 1915 by Japan to Yuan Shikai, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> sought to turn China into a virtual protectorate, and their partial acceptance provoked national outrage that fed later nationalist protest.","answer":"Twenty-One Demands","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Presented</span><span class=\"dt-v\">18 January 1915 · by Japan to Yuan Shikai</span></div>","traditional":"二十一條","hanzi":"二十一条","pinyin":"Èrshíyī Tiáo","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Èrshíyī Tiáo</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Twenty-One Articles”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Twenty-One Demands</b> were a set of secret demands issued by Japan to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beiyang_government\">Beiyang government</span> of China during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_War_I\">First World War</span>, intended to extend Japanese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperialism\">imperial</span> dominance over its weakened neighbour. With the European great powers <b>consumed by war in 1914</b>, Japan declared war on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"German_Empire\">German Empire</span>, captured the port of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qingdao\">Qingdao</span> in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Siege_of_Tsingtao\">Siege of Tsingtao</span>, and seized the German leasehold in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shandong\">Shandong</span>, gaining a base from which to press wider claims. <b>On 18 January 1915</b> the cabinet of <b>Prime Minister <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ōkuma_Shigenobu\">Ōkuma Shigenobu</span></b> and Foreign Minister <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Katō_Takaaki\">Katō Takaaki</span> presented the demands directly to President Yuan Shikai of the fledgling <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)\">Republic of China</span>, insisting that their contents remain strictly confidential. Set out in 5 groups comprising 21 separate articles, the demands sought to enlarge Japan's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sphere_of_influence\">sphere of influence</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchuria\">South Manchuria</span> and eastern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Inner_Mongolia\">Inner Mongolia</span>, to confirm its inheritance of the German <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Concessions_in_China\">concessions</span> in Shandong, and to forbid China from leasing any further coastal territory, including the province of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fujian\">Fujian</span>, to a third power. The notorious 5th group went furthest of all, requiring China to employ Japanese political, financial, and military advisers, to accept a jointly administered police force, and to buy the bulk of its munitions from Japan—terms that would have reduced the republic to a virtual <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Protectorate\">protectorate</span> and overturned the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Open_Door_Policy\">Open Door Policy</span></b> upheld by other powers.<br> <br>Among the specific terms, Japan sought to prolong its leases on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kwantung_Leased_Territory\">Kwantung Leased Territory</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South_Manchuria_Railway\">South Manchuria Railway</span> to 99 years and to acquire joint control of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hanyeping_Company\">Hanyeping Company</span></b>, the largest iron-and-steel enterprise in central China. Yuan's negotiators stalled for months and deliberately leaked the terms to foreign diplomats, prompting the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States\">United States</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_Kingdom\">United Kingdom</span> to protest that the demands breached existing treaty rights and the wider system of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Unequal_treaty\">foreign privileges</span> in China. Faced with mounting opposition, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tokyo\">Tokyo</span> dropped most of the 5th group and on 7 May 1915 delivered an <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ultimatum\">ultimatum</span> giving China 48 hours to comply. Yuan capitulated on 9 May, accepting a reduced package of 13 demands that was sealed in the Sino-Japanese treaties signed later that month, a humiliation so keenly felt that 9 May was long marked in China as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Humiliation_Day\">National Humiliation Day</span></b>. The episode shattered Yuan's standing on the eve of his abortive attempt to crown himself ruler of a new <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empire_of_China_(1915–1916)\">Empire of China</span>, and the indignation it aroused later swelled, by way of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Culture_Movement\">New Culture Movement</span>, into <b>the patriotic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"May_Fourth_Movement\">May Fourth Movement</span> of 1919</b>, which erupted when the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paris_Peace_Conference_(1919–1920)\">Paris Peace Conference</span> and the resulting <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Versailles\">Treaty of Versailles</span> awarded the former German holdings in Shandong to Japan, perpetuating the contentious <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shandong_Problem\">Shandong Problem</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Twenty-One Demands"},{"id":"em-066","num":"六十六","category":"Early Republic · Yuan's Monarchy","question":"Lasting barely 83 days before being abandoned in the face of revolt, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was the creation of Yuan Shikai, who had himself declared emperor, provoking the uprising of southern provinces and the warlords.","answer":"Empire of China","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Proclaimed</span><span class=\"dt-v\">December 1915 · Yuan Shikai’s monarchy</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Abandoned</span><span class=\"dt-v\">March 1916</span></div>","traditional":"中華帝國","hanzi":"中华帝国","pinyin":"Zhōnghuá Dìguó","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōnghuá Dìguó</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Empire of China</b> was a short-lived attempt to restore monarchical rule over China, proclaimed in late 1915 by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_Shikai\">Yuan Shikai</span>, the military strongman who had dominated the young republic since the collapse of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span>. Following the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1911_Revolution\"><b>1911</b> Revolution</span> that toppled the imperial system, Yuan had leveraged his command of the formidable <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beiyang_Army\">Beiyang Army</span> to secure the abdication of the boy-emperor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Puyi\">Puyi</span> and to supplant the Nanjing provisional government of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Yat-sen\">Sun Yat-sen</span>, taking office as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"President_of_the_Republic_of_China\">President of the Republic of China</span> in 1912. In the years that followed he steadily dismantled the constitutional order of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)\">Republic of China</span>, crushing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span> in the abortive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Revolution_(China)\">Second Revolution</span> of 1913, dissolving parliament, and ruling by decree, even as his standing eroded after he conceded most of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empire_of_Japan\">Japanese</span> government's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Twenty-One_Demands\">Twenty-One Demands</span> in 1915. A carefully orchestrated monarchist campaign, encouraged by the American constitutional adviser <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Frank_Johnson_Goodnow\">Frank Johnson Goodnow</span></b>, who argued that a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitutional_monarchy\">constitutional monarchy</span> better suited Chinese conditions, and promoted by the Peace Planning Society of the scholar <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yang_Du\">Yang Du</span>, lent a veneer of popular demand to the proposed restoration. Having already revived the imperial sacrifice to Heaven at <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Temple_of_Heaven\">Temple of Heaven</span></b> and patronised a revival of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucianism</span>, Yuan <b>accepted the throne on 12 December 1915</b> after a stage-managed assembly of 1,993 delegates voted unanimously to make him emperor and confer upon him the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mandate_of_Heaven\">Mandate of Heaven</span>. <br> <br> Ruling from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhongnanhai\">Zhongnanhai</span> in the capital rather than from the old imperial palace, Yuan adopted the reign-era title Hongxian, loosely rendered as \"Constitutional Abundance,\" and scheduled his enthronement as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emperor_of_China\">Emperor of China</span> for the opening of 1916, although the formal coronation ceremony was repeatedly postponed and never actually held. The declaration ignited immediate and widespread resistance, as the southwestern province of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yunnan\">Yunnan</span> declared its independence on 25 December 1915 and launched the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Protection_War\">National Protection War</span>, fielding a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Protection_Army\">National Protection Army</span></b> under the celebrated general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cai_E\">Cai E</span> and his mentor, the reformist intellectual <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liang_Qichao\">Liang Qichao</span>. The revolt spread rapidly as the neighbouring provinces of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guizhou\">Guizhou</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangxi\">Guangxi</span> proclaimed their own secession under figures such as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_Jiyao\">Tang Jiyao</span></b>, while crucial commanders of Yuan's own <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beiyang_government\">Beiyang</span> faction, among them <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Duan_Qirui\">Duan Qirui</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Feng_Guozhang\">Feng Guozhang</span>, conspicuously withheld their support. Isolated diplomatically as Japan and the Western powers withdrew their backing, and abandoned by the very army upon which his authority rested, Yuan formally <b>renounced the monarchy on 22 March 1916</b>, ending a reign-era that had lasted barely 83 days, and reverted to the title of president of the republic. Yuan died of uremia on 6 June 1916, only weeks after relinquishing the imperial title, and his death removed the one man capable of holding the Beiyang military together, thereby plunging China into the fragmentary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warlord_Era\">Warlord Era</span> that would convulse the country for more than a decade.","citation":"","answerText":"Empire of China"},{"id":"em-070","num":"七十","category":"New Culture · Intellectual Ferment","question":"Erupting in the mid-1910s among intellectuals disillusioned with the failures of the republic, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> attacked Confucian tradition, championed science and democracy, and promoted writing in the vernacular through journals such as New Youth.","answer":"New Culture Movement","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Began</span><span class=\"dt-v\">c. 1915 · New Youth founded</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Waned</span><span class=\"dt-v\">mid-1920s</span></div>","traditional":"新文化運動","hanzi":"新文化运动","pinyin":"Xīn Wénhuà Yùndòng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Xīn Wénhuà Yùndòng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>New Culture Movement</b> was an intellectual and cultural upheaval that swept educated Chinese society <b>from roughly 1915</b> to the <b>mid-1920s</b>, born of profound disillusionment with the weakness and corruption of the early <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)\">Republic of China</span>. Its proponents argued that <b>the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinhai_Revolution\">Xinhai Revolution</span> of 1911</b> had toppled the monarchy without transforming Chinese thought, and that the failures of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_Shikai\">Yuan Shikai</span>'s rule and the ensuing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warlord_Era\">warlordism</span> proved that political revolution alone could not regenerate the nation. Centred at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peking_University\">Peking University</span> under the liberal chancellor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cai_Yuanpei\">Cai Yuanpei</span>, the movement found its principal organ in the journal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Youth\"><i>New Youth</i></span>, founded by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Duxiu\">Chen Duxiu</span> in 1915, whose circulation reportedly climbed from about 1,000 copies to some 16,000 at its height. Around it gathered a constellation of reform-minded intellectuals—among them <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Shih\">Hu Shih</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Dazhao\">Li Dazhao</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lu_Xun\">Lu Xun</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qian_Xuantong\">Qian Xuantong</span>—who rallied beneath the twin banners of Mr Science and Mr Democracy, shorthand for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Science\">science</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Democracy\">democracy</span> they believed would modernise the country. They launched a sweeping iconoclastic assault on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucianism</span> and the traditional ethics it underpinned, condemning the cult of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Filial_piety\">filial piety</span>, the subjugation of women, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Arranged_marriage\">arranged marriage</span></b>, and the practice of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foot_binding\">foot binding</span> as relics that shackled the individual to a moribund past. <br> <br> At the heart of the movement lay a literary revolution that promoted <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vernacular_Chinese\">vernacular Chinese</span> in place of the difficult <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Classical_Chinese\">Classical Chinese</span> that had dominated writing for two millennia, a cause crystallised by Hu Shih's 1917 essay <i>A Preliminary Discussion of Literary Reform</i>. This programme produced the first masterpieces of modern Chinese fiction, most famously <b>Lu Xun's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"A_Madman's_Diary\"><i>A Madman's Diary</i></span></b> of 1918, a vernacular short story that depicted Confucian society as literally cannibalistic and helped make plain prose the standard for a new national literature. The movement also opened China to a flood of Western thought, translating and debating <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liberalism\">liberalism</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pragmatism\">pragmatism</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anarchism\">anarchism</span>, and—after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"October_Revolution\">October Revolution</span> drew Li Dazhao towards <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marxism\">Marxism</span>—a range of socialist ideas, while visiting philosophers such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"John_Dewey\">John Dewey</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bertrand_Russell\">Bertrand Russell</span></b> lectured across the country between 1919 and 1921. Its energies converged in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"May_Fourth_Movement\">May Fourth Movement</span> of 1919, a wave of student-led nationalist protest sparked by the decision at the Paris peace talks to award Germany's former holdings in Shandong to Japan, an episode known as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shandong_Problem\">Shandong Problem</span> that prompted China's refusal to sign the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Versailles\">Treaty of Versailles</span>. After 1919 the movement fractured between liberal gradualists led by Hu Shih and revolutionaries who founded the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> in 1921, but its deeper legacy endured in the triumph of vernacular education, the birth of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_literature\">modern Chinese literature</span>, and a lasting reorientation of national life that also helped reshape the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"New Culture Movement"},{"id":"em-071","num":"七十一","category":"New Culture · Print Culture","question":"Founded in 1915 by Chen Duxiu and a rallying point for the New Culture Movement, the magazine <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> published essays attacking old customs and, after 1919, helped spread Marxist ideas among Chinese students.","answer":"New Youth","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Founded</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1915 · by Chen Duxiu (journal)</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Ran to</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1926</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"新青年","pinyin":"Xīn Qīngnián","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Xīn Qīngnián</span></div>","abstract":"<b><i>New Youth</i></b> was a pioneering Chinese intellectual magazine, issued under the French cover title <b><i>La Jeunesse</i></b>, that served as the flagship of the New Culture Movement and a forum for radical debate in the early <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)\">Republic of China</span></b>. It was <b>founded in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span> in 1915</b> by Chen Duxiu under the title <i>Youth Magazine</i>, took its enduring name the following year, and rapidly gathered an influential circle of progressive writers around its editor. Championing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Written_vernacular_Chinese\">vernacular Chinese</span> in place of the difficult <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Classical_Chinese\">classical</span> written language, it urged readers to embrace \"Mr. <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Science\">Science</span>\" and \"Mr. <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Democracy\">Democracy</span>\" while assailing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> ethics, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Arranged_marriage\">arranged marriages</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foot_binding\">foot-binding</span> that defined the old order. After Chen joined <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peking_University\">Peking University</span> in <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> in 1917</b>, where the liberal chancellor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cai_Yuanpei\">Cai Yuanpei</span> had assembled the nation's foremost scholars, the magazine became the hub of a brilliant editorial circle. Its contributors transformed Chinese letters: the vernacular champion <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Shih\">Hu Shi</span> issued a celebrated 1917 call for literary reform, the linguist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qian_Xuantong\">Qian Xuantong</span> pressed for script modernisation, the essayist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Zuoren\">Zhou Zuoren</span> introduced new forms of criticism, and the writer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lu_Xun\">Lu Xun</span> <b>published in 1918 his</b> story <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"A_Madman's_Diary\"><i>A Madman's Diary</i></span>, widely held to be the first major work of fiction in the modern vernacular.<br> <br>The triumph of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bolsheviks\">Bolsheviks</span> under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vladimir_Lenin\">Lenin</span> in the Russian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"October_Revolution\">October Revolution</span> of 1917 turned the journal towards radical politics, and the university librarian <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Dazhao\">Li Dazhao</span></b> used its pages to introduce Chinese readers to the doctrines of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Karl_Marx\">Karl Marx</span>. In 1919 the magazine published a special issue on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialism\">socialist</span> thought and became a leading voice of the patriotic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"May_Fourth_Movement\">May Fourth Movement</span>, which erupted over the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shandong_Problem\">Shandong Problem</span> and whose student protesters it had helped to inspire. This radical turn fractured the editorial group, as the liberal reformers around the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pragmatism\">pragmatist</span> Hu Shi, a disciple of the American philosopher <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"John_Dewey\">John Dewey</span> who urged piecemeal solutions to concrete problems, parted company with the revolutionary circle forming around Chen Duxiu and Li Dazhao. By the early 1920s the magazine had become, in effect, the organ of an emerging <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Communism\">communist</span> movement then drawing support from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Communist_International\">Comintern</span>, and both Chen Duxiu and Li Dazhao went on to co-found the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> in 1921. Increasingly factional and politically hemmed in, the publication ceased to appear in 1926, yet its decade-long assault on tradition had permanently reshaped Chinese intellectual life, advancing the <b>cause of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Women's_rights\">women's emancipation</span></b>, securing the vernacular as the medium of literature, and shaping the outlook of young radicals such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>, who first encountered its arguments as a student.","citation":"","answerText":"New Youth"},{"id":"cnp-062","num":"六十二","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"A reform-minded protégé of Deng Xiaoping who served as general secretary until forced out in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> for tolerating student protests, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> helped trigger the mass demonstrations in Tiananmen Square.","answer":"Hu Yaobang","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">November 20, 1915</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">April 15, 1989</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"胡耀邦","pinyin":"Hú Yàobāng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Hú Yàobāng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Hu Yaobang</b> was a Chinese politician and reformer who rose to become the most senior figure in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> during the early 1980s and a leading liberal voice within its post-revolutionary leadership. Born into a poor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peasant\">peasant</span> family in <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liuyang\">Liuyang</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hunan\">Hunan</span> province, he joined the communist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Red_Army\">Red Army</span> as a teenager and was among the youngest participants <b>in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Long_March\">Long March</span> of 1934–1935</b>, later building his career largely through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Communist_Youth_League_of_China\">Communist Youth League</span>. Purged like many officials during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span> launched by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>, he <b>re-emerged after 1976</b> as a close ally of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>, by then China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paramount_leader\">paramount leader</span>, and a central architect of the campaign of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boluan_Fanzheng\">\"bringing order out of chaos\"</span> that reversed the political verdicts of the Maoist era. As head of <b>the party's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Organization_Department_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Organization Department</span></b>, he oversaw the rehabilitation of an estimated 3 million cadres and citizens who had been wrongly persecuted, an extraordinary administrative effort that restored careers, reputations, and party memberships on a vast scale. He also <b>helped promote the influential 1978 debate</b> sparked by the essay <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Practice_Is_the_Sole_Criterion_for_Testing_Truth\"><i>Practice Is the Sole Criterion for Testing Truth</i></span>, which discredited the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Two_Whatevers\">\"Two Whatevers\"</span> defended by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hua_Guofeng\">Hua Guofeng</span> and cleared the ideological path for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">economic reform</span>, propelling Hu into the party's highest councils. <br> <br> Hu became <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chairman_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">chairman of the party</span> in 1981 and, when that post was abolished the following year, served as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"General_Secretary_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">general secretary</span> from 1982 until 1987, using his authority to encourage intellectual openness, administrative reform, and a more tolerant political atmosphere. His relatively liberal instincts and willingness to question orthodox dogma increasingly alarmed conservative <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight_Elders\">party elders</span></b> such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Yun\">Chen Yun</span>, who regarded his leniency toward dissent and so-called bourgeois liberalization as a threat to one-party discipline. When nationwide <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1986_Chinese_student_demonstrations\">student demonstrations</span> erupted at the end of 1986, Hu was blamed for failing to suppress them and was compelled to resign in January 1987, retaining only a seat on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo</span> while <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhao_Ziyang\">Zhao Ziyang</span> took over as general secretary. His sudden death from a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Myocardial_infarction\">heart attack</span></b> on April 15, 1989, prompted an outpouring of public mourning in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>, as students gathering in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tiananmen_Square\">Tiananmen Square</span> to honour him transformed their grief into demands for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_democracy_movement\">political reform</span> and against corruption. Those gatherings swelled into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1989_Tiananmen_Square_protests_and_massacre\">Tiananmen Square protests</span> of 1989, which ended in the bloody military crackdown of June that year amid the dominance of hardliners such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Peng\">Li Peng</span> and the subsequent rise of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Zemin\">Jiang Zemin</span>, leaving Hu a politically sensitive symbol of reform whose memory was only partially rehabilitated when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Jintao\">Hu Jintao</span> presided over an official commemoration in 2005.","citation":"","answerText":"Hu Yaobang"},{"id":"em-068","num":"六十八","category":"Warlord Era · Fragmentation","question":"Lasting roughly from 1916 to 1928, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> saw the country fracture into territories ruled by rival strongmen who fought shifting wars and taxed the peasantry, until largely reunified by the Northern Expedition.","answer":"Warlord Era","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Began</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1916 · death of Yuan Shikai</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Ended</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1928 · nominal reunification</span></div>","traditional":"軍閥時代","hanzi":"军阀时代","pinyin":"Jūnfá Shídài","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Jūnfá Shídài</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Warlord Era</b> was the turbulent period in the history of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)\">Republic of China</span>, lasting roughly <b>from 1916</b> to 1928, during which political power fragmented among regional military commanders known as warlords. The disintegration followed the death of President <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_Shikai\">Yuan Shikai</span> in 1916, whose failed bid to restore the monarchy had shattered his authority and left the powerful <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beiyang_Army\">Beiyang Army</span> without a unifying figure. Although the internationally recognised <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beiyang_government\">Beiyang government</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> remained the nominal centre of the state, real control passed to rival cliques that contested the capital, foremost among them the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anhui_clique\">Anhui clique</span></b> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Duan_Qirui\">Duan Qirui</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhili_clique\">Zhili clique</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Peifu\">Wu Peifu</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fengtian_clique\">Fengtian clique</span> of Zhang Zuolin in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchuria\">Manchuria</span>. Beyond these northern contenders, semi-independent strongmen entrenched themselves in the provinces, including the Christian general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Feng_Yuxiang\">Feng Yuxiang</span> and his <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guominjun\">Guominjun</span>, the long-ruling <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yan_Xishan\">Yan Xishan</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanxi\">Shanxi</span>, and the brutal <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Zongchang\">Zhang Zongchang</span></b> of Shandong. In the south a rival authority took shape when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Yat-sen\">Sun Yat-sen</span> established a base at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou\">Guangzhou</span> and launched the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitutional_Protection_Movement\">Constitutional Protection Movement</span> against the warlord-dominated Beijing regime.<br> <br>The cliques fought a succession of destructive conflicts for mastery of Beijing, among <b>them the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhili–Anhui_War\">Zhili–Anhui War</span> of 1920</b> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Zhili–Fengtian_War\">First</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Zhili–Fengtian_War\">Second Zhili–Fengtian Wars</span> of 1922 and 1924, the latter decided by Feng Yuxiang's sudden <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing_Coup_(1924)\">Beijing Coup</span>. These campaigns ravaged the countryside, as commanders financed huge <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Conscription\">conscript</span></b> armies by imposing crushing land taxes—collected in some provinces such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan\">Sichuan</span> years in advance—alongside levies on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Opium\">opium</span> and the inland transit duty known as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Likin_(taxation)\">likin</span>. The mounting chaos prompted the Nationalists, allied with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Communists</span> in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_United_Front\">First United Front</span>, to send their <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Revolutionary_Army\">National Revolutionary Army</span> north under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span> on <b>the Northern Expedition of 1926</b>, which within 2 years subdued or co-opted the warlord regimes of the Yangtze valley and the north. The decisive blow in the north fell in 1928, when Zhang Zuolin, retreating from Beijing towards his Manchurian stronghold, was killed by a bomb planted by the Japanese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kwantung_Army\">Kwantung Army</span> in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huanggutun_incident\">Huanggutun Incident</span>. His son <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Xueliang\">Zhang Xueliang</span> soon pledged allegiance to the Nanjing-based <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nationalist_government\">Nationalist government</span> in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northeast_Flag_Replacement\">Northeast Flag Replacement</span></b> of December 1928, an act that brought nominal reunification, though entrenched militarism endured and soon erupted again in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Plains_War\">Central Plains War</span> of 1930.","citation":"","answerText":"Warlord Era"},{"id":"cne-074","num":"七十四","category":"China · Economics","question":"A method of comparing economies by adjusting for differences in local prices rather than market exchange rates, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the measure by which China overtook the United States around <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> to become the world's largest economy, even while remaining smaller in nominal GDP.","answer":"Purchasing power parity","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Coined</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Gustav Cassel, who named the doctrine, c. 1918</span></div>","traditional":"購買力平價","hanzi":"购买力平价","pinyin":"gòumǎilì píngjià","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">gòumǎilì píngjià</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Purchasing power parity</b> is a method in economics for comparing the size and living standards of different economies by adjusting for differences in local price levels rather than using market <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Exchange_rate\">exchange rates</span></b>. It defines the rate at which one <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Currency\">currency</span> would have to be converted into another to buy the same <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Market_basket\">basket</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Goods_and_services\">goods and services</span> in both countries, thereby equalising what a given sum of money can actually buy and stripping out the distortions of volatile financial markets. The idea rests on the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Law_of_one_price\">law of one price</span></b>, which holds that identical goods should cost the same everywhere once expressed in a common currency, while its relative version links persistent differences in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Inflation\">inflation</span> between countries to gradual movements in their exchange rates over time. In practice market exchange rates diverge widely from this benchmark because non-traded services and labour are far cheaper in poorer countries—a pattern captured by the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Balassa–Samuelson_effect\">Balassa–Samuelson effect</span></b> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Penn_effect\">Penn effect</span>—so that conversions at market rates understate the real output of a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Developing_country\">developing country</span>. The concept traces back to the 16th-century <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"School_of_Salamanca\">School of Salamanca</span></b> and was named by the Swedish economist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gustav_Cassel\">Gustav Cassel</span> after the First World War, and today it is estimated through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Bank\">World Bank</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"International_Comparison_Program\">International Comparison Program</span> and bodies such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"OECD\">OECD</span>, and popularised in light-hearted form by <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Economist\">The Economist</span></b>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Big_Mac_Index\">Big Mac Index</span>. <br> <br> Applied to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>, the measure produces a strikingly different picture from one based on market rates: at current exchange rates China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gross_domestic_product\">gross domestic product</span> remains well below that of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States\">United States</span>, leaving it second in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"List_of_countries_by_GDP_(nominal)\">nominal</span> terms. On a purchasing-power basis, however, China overtook the <b>United States around 2014</b> to become the world's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"List_of_countries_by_GDP_(PPP)\">largest economy</span>, with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"International_Monetary_Fund\">International Monetary Fund</span> then estimating its output at roughly $17.6 trillion against about $17.4 trillion for the Americans. The gap arises because the much lower <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cost_of_living\">cost of living</span> in China—especially for housing, services, and labour—means the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Renminbi\">renminbi</span> buys far more goods domestically than its market value suggests, so adjusting for those local prices reveals a substantially <b>larger volume of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Real_versus_nominal_value_(economics)\">real</span></b> economic activity. Yet because China's population is more than four times that of the United States, its income and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Standard_of_living\">standard of living</span> per person remain far lower even on this measure—a few times below American levels—leaving it ranked well down the global table of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"List_of_countries_by_GDP_(PPP)_per_capita\">GDP per capita</span>. Economists therefore disagree over which yardstick best captures economic weight—purchasing-power figures better reflect real production and account for a larger share of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gross_world_product\">world output</span>, while market-rate figures matter more for finance and trade on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foreign_exchange_market\">foreign-exchange market</span>—a debate with real stakes for how the relative <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_power\">power</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">Chinese</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_the_United_States\">American economies</span> is judged.","citation":"","answerText":"Purchasing power parity"},{"id":"em-076","num":"七十六","category":"May Fourth · 1919","question":"Touched off in 1919 by fury at the Versailles decision to hand former German holdings in Shandong to Japan, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> — a wave of student demonstrations and boycotts — marked a surge of modern nationalism and is seen as a turning point in China's intellectual history.","answer":"May Fourth Movement","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">4 May 1919 · student protest in Beijing</span></div>","traditional":"五四運動","hanzi":"五四运动","pinyin":"Wǔsì Yùndòng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Wǔsì Yùndòng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>May Fourth Movement</b> was an <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anti-imperialism\">anti-imperialist</span>, cultural, and political movement that grew out of a <b>student demonstration in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> on 4 May 1919</b>, when several thousand students from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peking_University\">Peking University</span> and a dozen other colleges massed before <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tiananmen\">Tiananmen</span> to denounce the decision of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paris_Peace_Conference_(1919–1920)\">Paris Peace Conference</span> to award the former German leasehold in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shandong_Problem\">Shandong</span> to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empire_of_Japan\">Empire of Japan</span> rather than restore it to China. Outrage at this betrayal—compounded by resentment of the secret <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Twenty-One_Demands\">Twenty-One Demands</span> and the warlord <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beiyang_government\">Beiyang government</span> that had acquiesced in them—boiled over into the burning of a pro-Japanese minister’s house and a wave of arrests. The protest swiftly broadened into a nationwide campaign of <b>student strikes, merchant shutdowns, and a boycott of Japanese goods</b>, and the government ultimately released the detained students, dismissed three pro-Japanese officials, and <b>refused to sign the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Versailles\">Treaty of Versailles</span></b>. <br> <br> The demonstrations are usually understood as the political climax of the broader <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Culture_Movement\">New Culture Movement</span>, whose iconoclastic intellectuals—among them <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Duxiu\">Chen Duxiu</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Shih\">Hu Shih</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Dazhao\">Li Dazhao</span>—had been attacking <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> tradition through journals such as <i><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Youth\">New Youth</span></i> and championing the twin ideals nicknamed <b>“Mr. Science” and “Mr. Democracy”</b> along with writing in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Written_vernacular_Chinese\">vernacular</span>. In its wake a surge of modern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_nationalism\">nationalism</span> drove many young Chinese towards radical politics, accelerating the spread of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marxism\">Marxism</span> and helping to prepare the ground for the founding of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> in 1921 and the reorganisation of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span>. Both the Nationalists and the Communists would later claim the legacy of <b>4 May 1919</b>, and the movement is conventionally treated as a watershed marking the birth of modern Chinese intellectual and political life.","citation":"","answerText":"May Fourth Movement"},{"id":"cnp-065","num":"六十五","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Architect of rural reform as premier and later Party chief, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was stripped of power after the crackdown, and spent his last 15 years under house arrest, having opposed the decision of Deng Xiaoping to impose martial law.","answer":"Zhao Ziyang","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">October 17, 1919</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">January 17, 2005</span></div>","traditional":"趙紫陽","hanzi":"赵紫阳","pinyin":"Zhào Zǐyáng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhào Zǐyáng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Zhao Ziyang</b> was a Chinese statesman who served as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Premier_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">Premier</span> <b>from 1980</b> to 1987 and as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"General_Secretary_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">General Secretary of the Chinese Communist Party</span> from 1987 to 1989, becoming one of the foremost architects of the country's market-oriented reforms before his abrupt political downfall. Born into a landlord family in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hua_County,_Henan\">Hua County</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Henan\">Henan</span> province—his father reportedly killed during the postwar <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Land_reform_movement\">land reform</span> campaigns—he <b>joined the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Communist_Youth_League_of_China\">Communist Youth League</span> in 1932</b> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> in 1938, advancing through local administrative posts during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Sino-Japanese_War\">war against Japan</span> and the ensuing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">Chinese Civil War</span>. He rose to become first party secretary of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangdong\">Guangdong</span>, but at the onset of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span> he was denounced as a \"capitalist roader,\" paraded through the streets by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Red_Guards\">Red Guards</span>, and consigned to roughly 4 years of manual labor before his rehabilitation in the early 1970s. Appointed party <b>chief of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan\">Sichuan</span> in 1975</b>, he pioneered an early form of agricultural decollectivization later generalized as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Household_responsibility_system\">household responsibility system</span>, reforms credited with sharply raising the province's grain and industrial output and inspiring a popular rhyme that urged hungry peasants to \"look for Ziyang\" for food. His success attracted the patronage of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>, who promoted him to succeed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hua_Guofeng\">Hua Guofeng</span> as premier in 1980, a post from which he became a driving force behind <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">economic reform</span>, the expansion of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Special_economic_zones_of_China\">special economic zones</span>, experiments with dual-track pricing, and greater managerial autonomy for state-owned enterprises. <br> <br> Elevated to General Secretary at the 13th <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"13th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Party Congress</span></b> in 1987—having held the acting post since January of that year following the forced resignation of the reform-minded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Yaobang\">Hu Yaobang</span>—he promoted the doctrine of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Primary_stage_of_socialism\">primary stage of socialism</span> to legitimize continued liberalization, even as he clashed repeatedly with hardliners such as Premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Peng\">Li Peng</span>. When Hu's death in April 1989 ignited the mass <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1989_Tiananmen_Square_protests_and_massacre\">Tiananmen Square protests</span>, he urged dialogue and a conciliatory response toward the student demonstrators, whose movement drew worldwide attention during the mid-May state visit of <b>Soviet leader <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mikhail_Gorbachev\">Mikhail Gorbachev</span></b>—the first Sino-Soviet summit in some 30 years—to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tiananmen_Square\">Tiananmen Square</span>. In the early hours of May 19, 1989, accompanied by his aide <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wen_Jiabao\">Wen Jiabao</span>, he made a tearful personal appeal to the hunger strikers, and his refusal to support Deng's decision to declare <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Martial_law\">martial law</span> the next day set him irrevocably against the party's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight_Elders_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Eight Elders</span>. Following the violent crackdown of June 3–4, 1989, he was stripped of every position on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_Standing_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo Standing Committee</span> and replaced as General Secretary by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Zemin\">Jiang Zemin</span>, while his closest political adviser, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bao_Tong\">Bao Tong</span></b>, was sentenced to 7 years in prison. He passed the final 15 years of his life under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"House_arrest\">house arrest</span> at his courtyard home in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>, where he covertly recorded some 30 hours of reminiscences that were later smuggled abroad and published in 2009 as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Prisoner_of_the_State\"><i>Prisoner of the State</i></span></b>, and after his death in January 2005 at the age of 85 he endured as a sensitive subject whose official rehabilitation the leadership has steadfastly withheld.","citation":"","answerText":"Zhao Ziyang"},{"id":"cnp-001","num":"一","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Founded in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> in Shanghai by figures including Chen Duxiu and Li Dazhao, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> grew out of early Chinese Marxism to become the sole ruling party of the People's Republic.","answer":"Chinese Communist Party","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1921</span></div>","traditional":"中國共產黨","hanzi":"中国共产党","pinyin":"Zhōngguó Gòngchǎndǎng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōngguó Gòngchǎndǎng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Chinese Communist Party</b> is the founding and sole ruling party of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span>, an organisation that grew out of the radical intellectual ferment of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Culture_Movement\">New Culture Movement</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"May_Fourth_Movement\">May Fourth Movement</span> during the fractured early years of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)\">Republic of China</span>. It was formally constituted at its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1st_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">First National Congress</span>, convened on&nbsp;<b>July 23, 1921</b> within the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_French_Concession\">French Concession</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span> before the delegates relocated to a pleasure boat on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South_Lake_(Jiaxing)\">South Lake</span> in nearby <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiaxing\">Jiaxing</span>, a clandestine meeting attended by 13 delegates representing an <b>estimated 50 to 57 members nationwide</b>. Its earliest leadership coalesced around the university intellectuals <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Duxiu\">Chen Duxiu</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Dazhao\">Li Dazhao</span>, who had embraced <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marxism\">Marxism</span> in the wake of Russia's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"October_Revolution\">October Revolution</span> of 1917, and the nascent party drew financial subsidies and organisational direction from the Moscow-based <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Communist_International\">Communist International</span>. Acting on Comintern instructions, it entered a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_United_Front\">First United Front</span></b> with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span> in 1924 and joined the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Expedition\">Northern Expedition</span> to reunify the warlord-divided country, a fragile alliance that collapsed when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span> turned on his communist allies in the bloody <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_massacre\">Shanghai massacre</span> of April 1927. The ensuing rupture opened a protracted <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">Chinese Civil War</span>, in the course of which the encircled communists undertook the legendary <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Long_March\">Long March</span></b> of 1934–1935, a fighting retreat of roughly 9,000 kilometres (5,600 mi) that decimated their ranks yet cemented the ascendancy of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> after the decisive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zunyi_Conference\">Zunyi Conference</span>. <br> <br> A <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_United_Front\">Second United Front</span> formed against Japanese aggression during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Sino-Japanese_War\">Second Sino-Japanese War</span> allowed the party to expand its rural base and guerrilla forces dramatically, and following its triumph in the resumed civil war it proclaimed the People's Republic from atop <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tiananmen\">Tiananmen</span> in <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> on 1 October 1949</b>. Governing thereafter as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"One-party_state\">one-party state</span>, it pursued sweeping socialist transformation through mass campaigns such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Leap_Forward\">Great Leap Forward</span> of 1958–1962, whose attendant famine is estimated by scholars to have produced between 15 and 45 million excess deaths, and the convulsive decade of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span> begun in 1966. After Mao's death in 1976, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> redirected the party toward the market-oriented programme of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">reform and opening up</span> <b>from 1978</b>, a shift that the World Bank credits with lifting roughly 800 million people out of poverty and propelling China into the world's second-largest economy. Organised on the principle of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Democratic_centralism\">democratic centralism</span> inherited from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Leninism\">Leninism</span>, its formal authority ascends from the quinquennial <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">National Congress</span> through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Central Committee</span> to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo</span> and its apex <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_Standing_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo Standing Committee</span>, which presides over party organs embedded throughout the state, the economy, and the armed forces. By the mid-2020s its <b>membership had grown to nearly 100 million</b>, ranking it among the largest political organisations in the world, while its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"General_Secretary_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">General Secretary</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span>, has concentrated power as China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paramount_leader\">paramount leader</span> and seen his eponymous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping_Thought\">Xi Jinping Thought</span> enshrined in both the party constitution and the state constitution.","citation":"","answerText":"Chinese Communist Party"},{"id":"cnp-046","num":"四十六","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Anointed by Mao Zedong with the reported words \"with you in charge, I am at ease\", the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> briefly led Party and state after <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>, oversaw the arrest of the Gang of Four, but was soon eclipsed by Deng Xiaoping.","answer":"Hua Guofeng","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">16 February 1921</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">20 August 2008</span></div>","traditional":"華國鋒","hanzi":"华国锋","pinyin":"Huà Guófēng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Huà Guófēng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Hua Guofeng</b> was a Chinese politician who briefly served as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paramount_leader\">paramount leader</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span></b> in the two years following the death of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>. Born Su Zhu into a peasant family in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiaocheng_County\">Jiaocheng County</span> in northern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanxi\">Shanxi</span> province, he adopted his revolutionary alias from a slogan of the anti-Japanese resistance and <b>joined the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> in 1938</b>, serving as a guerrilla organiser during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Sino-Japanese_War\">Second Sino-Japanese War</span>. After 1949 he built his career in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hunan\">Hunan</span>, the province of Mao's birth, where his diligent administration of the leader's home district around <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shaoshan\">Shaoshan</span> in <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiangtan\">Xiangtan</span></b> won him the chairman's personal favour and steady promotion through the provincial hierarchy. Surviving the upheaval of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span> with his reputation intact, he was elevated to the national stage as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vice_Premier_of_China\">vice premier</span> and <b>minister of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ministry_of_Public_Security_(China)\">public security</span> in 1975</b>, and the death of premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span> in January 1976 left him acting <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Premier_of_China\">premier</span> ahead of the twice-purged <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>. Anointed by an ailing Mao with the reportedly handwritten endorsement \"with you in charge, I am at ease,\" he succeeded to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chairman_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">chairmanship of the party</span>, the premiership of the government, and the leadership of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Military_Commission_(China)\">Central Military Commission</span> after Mao's <b>death on 9 September 1976</b>, becoming the only figure ever to hold all three supreme offices simultaneously. <br> <br> Barely a month later, on 6 October 1976, he joined the elder marshal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ye_Jianying\">Ye Jianying</span> and the security chief <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Dongxing\">Wang Dongxing</span> in orchestrating the dramatic arrest of the radical <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gang_of_Four\">Gang of Four</span>, including Mao's widow <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Qing\">Jiang Qing</span>, an act that effectively brought the Cultural Revolution to a close. To legitimise his authority he promulgated the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Two_Whatevers\">\"Two Whatevers,\"</span> a doctrine pledging to uphold whatever policies and instructions Mao had issued, and he reinforced the late chairman's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cult_of_personality\">cult of personality</span> by commissioning the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chairman_Mao_Memorial_Hall\">Chairman Mao Memorial Hall</span></b> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tiananmen_Square\">Tiananmen Square</span>. His ambitious ten-year economic plan launched in 1978, an investment-heavy programme derided by critics as a \"Foreign Leap Forward\" that echoed the disastrous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Leap_Forward\">Great Leap Forward</span>, soon strained state finances and undercut his standing among reform-minded cadres. Rehabilitated and politically resurgent, Deng Xiaoping repudiated the Two Whatevers and outmanoeuvred Hua at the watershed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"3rd_Plenary_Session_of_the_11th_Central_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Third Plenary Session of the 11th Central Committee</span> in December 1978, which inaugurated the era of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">reform and opening up</span> and the broader rectification known as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boluan_Fanzheng\">Boluan Fanzheng</span>. Stripped of the premiership in favour of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhao_Ziyang\">Zhao Ziyang</span> in 1980 and of the party chairmanship in favour of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Yaobang\">Hu Yaobang</span> in 1981, he faded into a ceremonial role on the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Central Committee</span></b> that he retained until 2002, dying in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> in 2008 at the age of 87, a transitional figure remembered chiefly for ending the Maoist era he had sworn to perpetuate.","citation":"","answerText":"Hua Guofeng"},{"id":"cnp-004","num":"四","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Founded in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> as the Party's organisation for young people and a springboard for officials such as Hu Yaobang and Hu Jintao, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> lends its name to a faction, the <i>tuanpai</i>, sometimes set against the Shanghai clique.","answer":"Communist Youth League of China","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1922</span></div>","traditional":"中國共產主義青年團","hanzi":"中国共产主义青年团","pinyin":"Zhōngguó Gòngchǎnzhǔyì Qīngnián Tuán","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōngguó Gòngchǎnzhǔyì Qīngnián Tuán</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Communist Youth League of China</b> is the youth wing of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span>, a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mass_organization\">mass organisation</span></b> charged with cultivating young people in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Leninism\">Leninist</span> ideology and grooming them for eventual party membership. <b>Established in May 1922</b> at a congress in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou\">Guangzhou</span> and modelled on the Soviet <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Komsomol\">Komsomol</span>, the league has served throughout its history as a transmission belt linking the party to the nation's youth, before being suspended amid the turmoil of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span> and <b>revived in 1978</b>. Open to those aged 14 to 28, it grew into one of the largest youth organisations in the world, numbering more than 73 million members by the early 2020s, with its national leadership answering to the party's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Central Committee</span> and its committees paralleling the state at every administrative level. It also directs an array of subordinate bodies that shepherd young Chinese from childhood into adulthood, most prominently the roughly 130-million-strong <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Young_Pioneers_of_China\">Young Pioneers</span></b> for children aged 6 to 14, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"All-China_Youth_Federation\">All-China Youth Federation</span>, and the influential newspaper <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Youth_Daily\"><i>China Youth Daily</i></span>. The league has long functioned as a springboard for ambitious cadres promoted under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>, propelling figures such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Yaobang\">Hu Yaobang</span>, the reform-minded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"General_Secretary_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">General Secretary</span> of the 1980s, the future <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paramount_leader\">paramount leader</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Jintao\">Hu Jintao</span>, who headed its Central Committee in the mid-1980s, the later premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Keqiang\">Li Keqiang</span>, and the jurist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Qiang\">Zhou Qiang</span> into the upper reaches of national politics. <br> <br> Officials who ascended through its ranks came to constitute an informal political <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Factions_in_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">faction</span></b> known as the <i>tuanpai</i>, or Youth League clique, generally identified with the patronage network of Hu Jintao and the consensus-driven model of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Collective_leadership\">collective leadership</span> that prevailed in the post-Deng era. The <i>tuanpai</i> was frequently contrasted with rival groupings, above all the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_clique\">Shanghai clique</span> built around <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Zemin\">Jiang Zemin</span> and the so-called <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Princelings\">princelings</span> descended from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight_Elders_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">veteran revolutionaries</span>, in analyses of the factional balance within the leadership. Its fortunes waned sharply after <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span> took power, and <b>in 2016</b> the league was publicly rebuked by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Commission_for_Discipline_Inspection\">Central Commission for Discipline Inspection</span> as bureaucratic and detached from ordinary youth, prompting a forced overhaul and reported cuts to its budget and staff that signalled Xi's distrust of the organisation. The faction's marginalisation became unmistakable at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"20th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">20th Party Congress</span> in 2022, when Li Keqiang and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Yang_(politician)\">Wang Yang</span> left the leadership and the prominent protégé <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Chunhua\">Hu Chunhua</span></b> — once touted as a candidate of the next leadership <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Generations_of_Chinese_leadership\">generation</span> — was unexpectedly dropped from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo</span> altogether. That eclipse was symbolised by the startling scene at the congress's closing session, when a visibly reluctant Hu Jintao was escorted from the hall in front of the assembled delegates, an episode widely read as the definitive end of the Youth League's once-formidable sway over the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_Standing_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo Standing Committee</span> and the succession process.","citation":"","answerText":"Communist Youth League of China"},{"id":"em-077","num":"七十七","category":"Nationalist Revolution · The United Front","question":"Brokered with help from the Comintern and lasting from 1923, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> saw members of the fledgling Communist Party join the Nationalists to fight the warlords together, before it collapsed in bloody betrayal in 1927 under Chiang Kai-shek.","answer":"First United Front","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Began</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1924 · KMT–CCP alliance</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Ended</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1927 · Shanghai massacre</span></div>","traditional":"第一次國共合作","hanzi":"第一次国共合作","pinyin":"Dìyīcì Guógòng Hézuò","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Dìyīcì Guógòng Hézuò</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>First United Front</b> was the alliance formed <b>between 1923</b> and <b>1924</b> that joined the newly founded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> to the much larger Nationalist Party in a common effort to overthrow the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warlord_Era\">warlords</span> and reunify China. Frustrated by the refusal of the Western powers to support him, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Yat-sen\">Sun Yat-sen</span> turned to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Soviet</span> Russia, and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun–Joffe_Manifesto\">Sun–Joffe Manifesto</span></b> of 1923 opened the way to cooperation, soon guided on the ground by the Comintern agent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mikhail_Borodin\">Mikhail Borodin</span>. On instructions from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Moscow\">Moscow</span>, the Communists entered the front not as a separate party but as individuals enrolling within the Nationalist organisation, a \"bloc within\" arrangement that the party's own leader <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Duxiu\">Chen Duxiu</span> accepted only with misgivings. The partnership was sealed at the Nationalists' First National Congress in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou\">Guangzhou</span> in 1924, where the party was restructured along <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Leninism\">Leninist</span> lines and embraced the Three Great Policies of alliance with the Soviet Union, admission of Communists, and support for workers and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peasant\">peasants</span>. To furnish the alliance with a loyal army, the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Whampoa_Military_Academy\">Whampoa Military Academy</span></b> was founded in 1924 with Soviet weapons and advisers, training the officer corps of a new <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Revolutionary_Army\">National Revolutionary Army</span> under the young commandant Chiang Kai-shek, with the Communist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span> heading its political department.<br> <br>The front survived the death <b>of Sun Yat-sen in 1925</b> and was galvanised by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anti-imperialism\">anti-imperialist</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"May_Thirtieth_Movement\">May Thirtieth Movement</span> of that year, and over the life of the alliance the Communists' ranks swelled from roughly 1,000 members to nearly 58,000. As the partnership pressed forward, mutual suspicion festered, and in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhongshan_Warship_Incident\">Zhongshan Warship Incident</span> of early 1926 Chiang moved to curb <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Communism\">Communist</span></b> influence and tighten his command over the movement. That summer the allies launched the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Expedition\">Northern Expedition</span> from the south, with Chiang directing the armies while Communist organisers such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> roused the peasantry, and within a year the campaign had carried the front across the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span> valley. The breach turned bloody in April 1927, when Chiang unleashed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_massacre\">Shanghai Massacre</span>, slaughtering thousands of Communists and labour activists, and set up a rival <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nationalist_government\">Nationalist government</span> at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span> against the left-wing regime at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuhan\">Wuhan</span> under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Jingwei\">Wang Jingwei</span>, which itself expelled the Communists that July. Shattered within 4 years of its founding, the alliance left the Communists nearly annihilated, driving the survivors into armed revolts—the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanchang_uprising\">Nanchang</span>, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Autumn_Harvest_Uprising\">Autumn Harvest</span></b>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou_Uprising\">Guangzhou</span> uprisings of 1927—that gave birth to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Red_Army\">Red Army</span> and opened the long <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">Chinese Civil War</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"First United Front"},{"id":"em-078","num":"七十八","category":"Nationalist Revolution · The Military","question":"Established near Canton in 1924 with Soviet advice and funding to train a loyal officer corps, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was headed by Chiang Kai-shek and produced commanders for both the Nationalist and Communist armies.","answer":"Whampoa Military Academy","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Founded</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1924 · Guangzhou</span></div>","traditional":"黄埔軍校","hanzi":"黄埔军校","pinyin":"Huángpǔ Jūnxiào","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Huángpǔ Jūnxiào</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Whampoa Military Academy</b> was an officer-training school <b>established in 1924</b> on an island in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pearl_River_(China)\">Pearl River</span></b> near <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou\">Canton</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangdong\">Guangdong</span> province, created by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span> to forge a politically reliable army capable of reunifying a China fragmented among rival <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warlord_Era\">warlords</span>. It was founded by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Yat-sen\">Sun Yat-sen</span> during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_United_Front\">First United Front</span> between the Nationalists and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span>, and it depended heavily on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Soviet Union</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Communist_International\">Comintern</span> for funding, weapons, and organisational expertise. Soviet advisers such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mikhail_Borodin\">Mikhail Borodin</span> and the <b>military strategist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vasily_Blyukher\">Vasily Blyukher</span></b>, who operated in China under the alias Galen, helped shape its organisation, curriculum, and Leninist party-army structure, while shipments of Soviet rifles and money equipped its cadets in a country where the Nationalists had previously commanded no dependable fighting force of their own. Its commandant was <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span>, who had recently returned from a study mission to the Soviet Union examining its military and party organisation, an appointment that placed him at the centre of a rising generation of officers. The academy fused rigorous military instruction with intensive political indoctrination in Sun Yat-sen's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Principles_of_the_People\">Three Principles of the People</span>, its political department directed by the communist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span> and its party affairs overseen by the Nationalist <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liao_Zhongkai\">Liao Zhongkai</span></b>. <br> <br> Its inaugural class of roughly 500 cadets graduated within months of the 1924 opening, and Whampoa-trained officers quickly formed the disciplined core of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Revolutionary_Army\">National Revolutionary Army</span> that <b>launched the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Expedition\">Northern Expedition</span> of 1926</b> to defeat the warlords and reunify the country under Nationalist rule. Remarkably, the academy trained commanders who would later lead both warring camps, counting among its early cadets future Communist marshals such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lin_Biao\">Lin Biao</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xu_Xiangqian\">Xu Xiangqian</span> and the senior general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Geng\">Chen Geng</span>, alongside Nationalist generals like <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Zongnan\">Hu Zongnan</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Du_Yuming\">Du Yuming</span>, with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ye_Jianying\">Ye Jianying</span> among its instructors. Those who studied or taught there came to form the powerful <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Whampoa_clique\">Whampoa clique</span>, a tightly knit network of officers personally loyal to Chiang Kai-shek that would dominate the upper ranks of the Nationalist military for the next several decades. When the United Front <b>collapsed in 1927</b> and Chiang turned against his communist allies, the academy's alumni were divided between the warring sides of the ensuing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">Chinese Civil War</span>—the Nationalist army on one side and the communist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Red_Army\">Red Army</span> on the other—former classmates now leading troops against one another in a struggle that would last more than two decades. The original Whampoa campus did not survive the upheavals of the period, as the institution was moved to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span> and later to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chengdu\">Chengdu</span> during the war with Japan, before the Nationalist defeat in the civil war carried its lineage across the strait to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span>, where the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_Military_Academy\">Republic of China Military Academy</span></b> still traces its descent directly from the original Whampoa.","citation":"","answerText":"Whampoa Military Academy"},{"id":"em-084","num":"八十四","category":"Nationalist China · The State","question":"Headquartered at Nanjing from 1927 and led by the Kuomintang, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> claimed authority over all China and built ministries, roads and a new currency, but struggled with warlord autonomy, Communist insurgency and Japanese aggression.","answer":"nationalist government","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Established</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1925 · Guangzhou, then Nanjing</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Reorganized</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1948</span></div>","traditional":"國民政府","hanzi":"国民政府","pinyin":"Guómín Zhèngfǔ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Guómín Zhèngfǔ</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>nationalist government</b> was the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span>-led government of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)\">Republic of China</span></b> that was first <b>proclaimed at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou\">Guangzhou</span> on July 1, 1925</b> and asserted itself as the sole legitimate authority over the whole of China. Its ideological foundation lay in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Principles_of_the_People\">Three Principles of the People</span> formulated by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Yat-sen\">Sun Yat-sen</span>, whose blueprint envisioned a transitional phase of party-led <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Political_tutelage\">political tutelage</span> preceding eventual constitutional democracy. After <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Expedition\">Northern Expedition</span> nominally reunified the country, the capital was fixed at <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span> in 1927</b>, opening the comparatively stable interval of 1927 to 1937 remembered as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing_decade\">Nanjing decade</span>. The state was organised under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five-Power_Constitution\">Five-Power Constitution</span> into Executive, Legislative, Judicial, Examination, and Control Yuan branches, and it pursued ambitious modernisation through new ministries, thousands of kilometres of new highways and railways, scientific institutions such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Academia_Sinica\">Academia Sinica</span>, and the moralising <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Life_Movement\">New Life Movement</span>. Among its most consequential reforms was the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fabi\">fabi</span> currency introduced in 1935, which abandoned the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silver_standard\">silver standard</span> amid a destabilising outflow of silver and replaced it with a unified, government-managed paper money shaped by powerful finance ministers such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"T._V._Soong\">T. V. Soong</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"H._H._Kung\">H. H. Kung</span></b>. <br> <br> Despite these claims, the government's effective control was largely confined to the lower <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span> provinces, while much of the interior remained under semi-autonomous militarists inherited from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warlord_Era\">Warlord Era</span>, tensions that exploded in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Plains_War\">Central Plains War</span> of 1930, a conflict that mobilised more than 1 million troops. It simultaneously fought a spreading Communist insurgency, launching 5 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Encirclement_Campaigns\">Encirclement Campaigns</span> between 1930 and 1934, the last of them assisted by German advisers under a programme of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-German_cooperation_(1926–1941)\">Sino-German cooperation</span></b>, which dislodged the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Soviet_Republic\">Chinese Soviet Republic</span> and drove the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Long_March\">Long March</span>. Mounting pressure from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empire_of_Japan\">Empire of Japan</span> followed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mukden_Incident\">Mukden Incident</span> of 1931, which brought the loss of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchuria\">Manchuria</span> and the establishment of the puppet state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchukuo\">Manchukuo</span>, before erupting into all-out war with the onset of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Sino-Japanese_War\">Second Sino-Japanese War</span> in 1937. Forced to relocate its capital to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chongqing\">Chongqing</span>, the government endured 8 years of devastating conflict that cost China an estimated 14 to 20 million lives, yet it emerged among the victorious Allies as a founding member of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_Nations\">United Nations</span> and a permanent seat-holder on its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_Nations_Security_Council\">Security Council</span>. <b>In 1948</b> it was formally reorganised under a <b>newly adopted <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitution_of_the_Republic_of_China\">constitution</span></b> into the constitutional <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Government_of_the_Republic_of_China\">Government of the Republic of China</span>, but catastrophic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hyperinflation\">hyperinflation</span> and military collapse in the renewed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">Chinese Civil War</span> led to the loss of the mainland to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army\">People's Liberation Army</span> and the retreat of the surviving administration to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span> in 1949.","citation":"","answerText":"nationalist government"},{"id":"em-080","num":"八十","category":"Nationalist Revolution · Reunification","question":"A military campaign launched in 1926 from the south under Chiang Kai-shek, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> defeated or co-opted the northern warlords and brought most of the country under nominal Nationalist rule by 1928.","answer":"Northern Expedition","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Began</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1926 · launched from Guangzhou</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Ended</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1928 · capture of Beijing</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"北伐","pinyin":"Běifá","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Běifá</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Northern Expedition</b> was the military campaign by which the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Nationalists</span></b> sought to destroy the regional warlords, overthrow the Beijing-based government, and reunify China under a single authority. In the wake of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Yat-sen\">Sun Yat-sen</span>'s death in 1925</b>, the party—then allied with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Communists</span> in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_United_Front\">First United Front</span>—built up a disciplined <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Revolutionary_Army\">National Revolutionary Army</span> at its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou\">Guangzhou</span> base with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Soviet</span> weapons and advisers. The offensive set out from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangdong\">Guangdong</span> in July 1926, pitting an army of roughly 100,000 ideologically motivated troops against the far larger but disunited forces of warlords such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Peifu\">Wu Peifu</span>, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Chuanfang\">Sun Chuanfang</span></b>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Zuolin\">Zhang Zuolin</span>. Driving north through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hunan\">Hunan</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hubei\">Hubei</span>, where Communist agitators had primed the peasantry, it shattered the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhili_clique\">Zhili clique</span> and seized the city <b>of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuhan\">Wuhan</span> by October 1926</b>. Wheeling eastward against Sun Chuanfang, the army captured <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span> and the great commercial port of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span> in March 1927.<br> <br>At the peak of its advance the campaign was thrown into crisis by the violent split between the Nationalists and Communists, when Chiang's <b>bloody <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_massacre\">Shanghai purge</span> of April 1927 set</b> his Nanjing regime against a rival leftist government under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Jingwei\">Wang Jingwei</span>. After the warring Nationalist factions reconciled, Chiang resumed the drive in 1928 at the head of a broader coalition that now included the former warlords <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Feng_Yuxiang\">Feng Yuxiang</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yan_Xishan\">Yan Xishan</span>, and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Guangxi_clique\">Guangxi clique</span></b>. As the armies neared the north, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empire_of_Japan\">Japan</span> sought to obstruct them, clashing with the Nationalist forces at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jinan_incident\">Jinan</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shandong\">Shandong</span> in May 1928. The decisive moment came when the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fengtian_clique\">Fengtian</span> leader, retreating from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> towards <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchuria\">Manchuria</span>, was assassinated by the Japanese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kwantung_Army\">Kwantung Army</span> in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huanggutun_incident\">Huanggutun Incident</span> of June 1928. The Nationalist army entered Beijing soon afterward, and the allegiance pledged that December by Zhang Zuolin's son <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Xueliang\">Zhang Xueliang</span> in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northeast_Flag_Replacement\">Northeast Flag Replacement</span></b> brought nominal reunification, inaugurating the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing_decade\">Nanjing decade</span>, though the regime's authority remained so shallow that fresh warlord conflict erupted in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Plains_War\">Central Plains War</span> of 1930.","citation":"","answerText":"Northern Expedition"},{"id":"cnp-068","num":"六十八","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Elevated to general secretary in the aftermath of the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> crisis, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> presided over rapid growth, the return of Hong Kong, and entry into the world trading system before handing most posts to Hu Jintao.","answer":"Jiang Zemin","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">17 August 1926</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">30 November 2022</span></div>","traditional":"江澤民","hanzi":"江泽民","pinyin":"Jiāng Zémín","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Jiāng Zémín</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Jiang Zemin</b> was a Chinese politician who led the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span> as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"General_Secretary_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">general secretary</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> <b>from 1989</b> to 2002, becoming the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paramount_leader\">paramount leader</span> regarded as the core of the country's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Generations_of_Chinese_leadership\">third generation</span> of leadership. Born in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangzhou\">Yangzhou</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiangsu\">Jiangsu</span>, he was raised in part as the adoptive son of his uncle <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Shangqing\">Jiang Shangqing</span></b>, a revolutionary martyr whose status burnished the young man's credentials, and he trained as an <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Electrical_engineering\">electrical engineer</span> at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_Jiao_Tong_University\">Jiao Tong University</span> in the 1940s. After a period training at an automobile works in <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Moscow\">Moscow</span></b> during the 1950s, he advanced through the machinery and electronics industries as a quintessential <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Technocracy\">technocrat</span>, eventually serving as minister of the electronics industry before becoming mayor and then party chief of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span>. His comparatively restrained handling of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1989_Tiananmen_Square_protests_and_massacre\">1989 unrest</span> in Shanghai, where he defused the demonstrations without bloodshed, commended him to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> and the party elders, who plucked him from relative obscurity to replace the purged reformer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhao_Ziyang\">Zhao Ziyang</span>. Installed as general secretary in June 1989 and as chairman of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Military_Commission_(China)\">Central Military Commission</span> later that year, he was initially dismissed as a transitional figurehead, yet he steadily accumulated genuine authority, particularly <b>after Deng's death in 1997</b>, and also took on the state <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"President_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">presidency</span> in 1993. <br> <br> Embracing the market direction of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">reform and opening up</span> reaffirmed by Deng's 1992 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Southern_Tour\">southern tour</span>, he presided over the formal adoption of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialist_market_economy\">socialist market economy</span> at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"14th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">14th Party Congress</span></b> and a decade of breakneck growth, overseeing a painful restructuring of the bloated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_enterprise\">state-owned enterprise</span> sector under his premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_Rongji\">Zhu Rongji</span>. His tenure was punctuated by a series of historic milestones, including the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Handover_of_Hong_Kong\">return of Hong Kong</span> in 1997 and <b>of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Transfer_of_sovereignty_over_Macau\">Macau</span> in 1999</b>, followed by China's long-sought accession to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Trade_Organization\">World Trade Organization</span> in 2001 that bound the nation ever more tightly to the global economy. His signature ideological contribution, the theory of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Represents\">Three Represents</span>, was unveiled in 2000 and subsequently enshrined in the party constitution, controversially broadening the communist movement to welcome private entrepreneurs and the rising capitalist class. His rule also encompassed a severe <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Persecution_of_Falun_Gong\">campaign against the Falun Gong</span></b> spiritual movement, outlawed in 1999, as well as the cultivation of a powerful network of protégés known as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_clique\">Shanghai clique</span>, prominent among them his close ally <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zeng_Qinghong\">Zeng Qinghong</span>. He relinquished the general secretaryship to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Jintao\">Hu Jintao</span> at the 16th Party Congress in 2002 and the presidency the following year, though he clung to the military chairmanship until 2004, and when he died in 2022 at the age of 96—as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zero-COVID\">zero-COVID</span> restrictions were stirring public discontent—many citizens recalled his comparatively freewheeling era with unexpected nostalgia.","citation":"","answerText":"Jiang Zemin"},{"id":"em-001","num":"一","category":"Republican China · Civil War","question":"Fought intermittently from 1927 to 1949 between the Kuomintang under Chiang Kai-shek and the Communists, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> ended with the Communist victory on the mainland and the Nationalist retreat to Taiwan.","answer":"Chinese Civil War","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Began</span><span class=\"dt-v\">August 1927 · Nationalist–Communist split</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Ended</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1949 · Communist victory, PRC founded</span></div>","traditional":"國共內戰","hanzi":"国共内战","pinyin":"Guó-Gòng Nèizhàn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Guó-Gòng Nèizhàn</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Nationalist–Communist War”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Chinese Civil War</b> was the protracted struggle for control of China fought intermittently between 1927 and 1949 by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span>-led government of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)\">Republic of China</span> and the forces of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Communist Party</span>, a contest that ultimately reshaped the political geography of East Asia. The conflict <b>erupted in 1927</b> when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span> abruptly purged his erstwhile Communist allies during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_massacre\">Shanghai massacre</span>, shattering the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_United_Front\">First United Front</span> that the two parties had maintained through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Expedition\">Northern Expedition</span> and prompting the Communists to launch armed risings such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanchang_uprising\">Nanchang Uprising</span> of August that year. Driven into the countryside, the Communists established the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Soviet_Republic\">Chinese Soviet Republic</span> at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ruijin\">Ruijin</span> in 1931, but a series of Nationalist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Encirclement_Campaigns\">Encirclement Campaigns</span> culminated in a fifth offensive in 1934 that forced the survivors onto the epic <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Long_March\">Long March</span></b>, during which <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> rose to dominance at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zunyi_Conference\">Zunyi Conference</span>. The battered Red Army regrouped around <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yan'an\">Yan'an</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shaanxi\">Shaanxi</span>, and the dramatic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi'an_Incident\">Xi'an Incident</span> of December 1936, in which Chiang was briefly kidnapped by his own generals, pressured the rival camps into a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_United_Front\">Second United Front</span> against the looming threat of Japanese aggression. Full-scale civil war was consequently <b>suspended for eight years of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Sino-Japanese_War\">Second Sino-Japanese War</span></b>, during which both parties nominally cooperated against the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empire_of_Japan\">Empire of Japan</span> while quietly husbanding their strength, leaving the Communists with a vastly enlarged territorial and military base by the Japanese surrender in 1945. <br> <br> Negotiations brokered by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States\">United States</span>, including the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chongqing_Negotiations\">Chongqing Negotiations</span> of 1945 and the subsequent mediation of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marshall_Mission\">Marshall Mission</span> led by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"George_Marshall\">George Marshall</span>, failed to avert a return to open warfare, and full hostilities resumed across <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchuria\">Manchuria</span> and northern China in 1946. Although the Nationalists initially <b>fielded roughly 4.3 million troops</b> against about 1.2 million Communist regulars, rampant corruption, ruinous <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gold_yuan\">hyperinflation</span></b>, and flagging morale steadily eroded their advantage, while the renamed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army\">People's Liberation Army</span> won growing peasant support through land redistribution in the territories it held. The strategic balance tipped decisively during the three great campaigns of 1948–1949 — the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liaoshen_Campaign\">Liaoshen</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huaihai_Campaign\">Huaihai</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pingjin_Campaign\">Pingjin</span> Campaigns — which together destroyed or captured an estimated 1.5 million Nationalist soldiers and laid open the route to the Yangtze. Communist armies crossed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze_River_Crossing_campaign\"><b>Yangtze</b> River</span> in April 1949 and seized the Nationalist capital of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span>, and on 1 October 1949 Mao stood atop the Gate of Heavenly Peace in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> to proclaim the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span>. The defeated government of Chiang Kai-shek, accompanied by an estimated two million soldiers, officials, and civilians, withdrew to the island of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span> in December 1949, where it relocated its capital to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taipei\">Taipei</span>; because no peace treaty was ever concluded, the war is sometimes regarded as merely <b>dormant</b>, and the unresolved division remains the crux of contemporary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cross-Strait_relations\">cross-Strait relations</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Chinese Civil War"},{"id":"em-082","num":"八十二","category":"Nationalist Revolution · KMT–CCP Split","question":"Carried out in April 1927 when Chiang Kai-shek turned on his erstwhile allies with the help of the Green Gang, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> slaughtered Communists and labour organisers in the city, shattering the united front.","answer":"Shanghai massacre","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">12 April 1927 · purge of Communists, Shanghai</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"四一二事件","pinyin":"Sìyī'èr Shìjiàn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Sìyī'èr Shìjiàn</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“April 12 Incident”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Shanghai massacre</b> was a violent suppression of the Communist movement carried <b>out in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span> on 12 April 1927</b> by the right wing of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span> under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span>. It occurred during the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Expedition\">Northern Expedition</span></b>, as Chiang's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Revolutionary_Army\">National Revolutionary Army</span> approached a metropolis whose factories and streets had already been seized in an armed workers' uprising organised by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Soviet</span>- and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Communist_International\">Comintern</span>-backed cadres of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span>, then still bound to the Nationalists in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_United_Front\">First United Front</span> that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Yat-sen\">Sun Yat-sen</span> had forged. Distrustful of the radical labour movement and courted by Shanghai's bankers, its industrialists, and the foreign powers of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_International_Settlement\">International Settlement</span>, Chiang secretly allied with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Green_Gang\">Green Gang</span> crime syndicate, whose bosses <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Du_Yuesheng\">Du Yuesheng</span>, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huang_Jinrong\">Huang Jinrong</span></b>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Xiaolin\">Zhang Xiaolin</span> furnished gunmen who were armed and uniformed for the assault. In the early hours of 12 April the gangsters, acting in concert with the garrison troops of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bai_Chongxi\">Bai Chongxi</span>, fell upon the armed pickets of the General Labour Union across the city, having first lured the union's leader Wang Shouhua to his murder the night before. When tens of thousands of workers gathered the next day to protest, troops opened fire on the demonstration along Baoshan Road, and in the immediate bloodletting several hundred people were killed or went missing while many more were summarily arrested. <br> <br> The killings in Shanghai opened a far broader <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anti-communism\">anti-Communist</span></b> purge across Nationalist-held territory, the so-called \"party purification,\" in which thousands more leftists and labour activists were hunted down and executed over the following weeks. Its impact on the Communist movement was devastating, for a party that had counted roughly 58,000 members in early 1927 was reduced to perhaps 10,000 by the end of that year, and its surviving cadres were driven underground or into the countryside. The purge also tore apart the Nationalist movement itself, as Chiang set up a rival <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nationalist_government\">Nationalist government</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)\">Republic of China</span> at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span> in defiance of the left-leaning regime at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuhan\">Wuhan</span> under <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Jingwei\">Wang Jingwei</span></b>, which nonetheless turned on its own Communist partners only months afterward. Stripped of its urban base and abandoned by its erstwhile partners, the party took up arms, launching the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanchang_uprising\">Nanchang uprising</span> of August 1927 — conventionally regarded as the birth of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army\">Red Army</span> — together with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Autumn_Harvest_Uprising\">Autumn Harvest Uprising</span> and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou_Uprising\">Guangzhou Uprising</span></b>, whose failures pushed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> towards a peasant-based revolution that would later coalesce in the rural <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Soviet_Republic\">Chinese Soviet Republic</span>. Marking the definitive rupture of the United Front and the opening of the armed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">Chinese Civil War</span> and its subsequent <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Encirclement_Campaigns\">encirclement campaigns</span></b>, the events of 1927 — narrowly survived by the young organiser <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span> — bred a mutual distrust that would shape the lethal contest between Nationalists and Communists for the next two decades.","citation":"","answerText":"Shanghai massacre"},{"id":"em-083","num":"八十三","category":"Nationalist China · The Nanjing Decade","question":"Spanning roughly 1927 to 1937 with the capital moved to a city on the Yangtze, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was a relatively stable period of Nationalist rule whose modernisation and state-building were cut short by the full-scale invasion by Japan.","answer":"Nanjing decade","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Began</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1927 · capital fixed at Nanjing</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Ended</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1937 · Japanese invasion</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"南京十年","pinyin":"Nánjīng Shínián","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Nánjīng Shínián</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Nanjing decade</b> was the period of comparative stability and ambitious modernisation under the rule of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span>, sometimes called the \"Golden Decade (Simplified: 黄金十年; Traditional: 黃金十年; Hanyu Pinyin: <i>Huángjīn Shínián</i>),\" that lasted from the <b>late 1920s</b> until the outbreak of full-scale <b>war with Japan in 1937</b>. It began after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Expedition\">Northern Expedition</span> nominally <b>reunified the country in 1928</b>, when the government of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span> established its capital at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span>, a city on the lower Yangtze, in place of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>. Pursuing the state-building programme outlined in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Yat-sen\">Sun Yat-sen</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Principles_of_the_People\">Three Principles of the People</span>, the regime promulgated modern legal codes, regained the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Unequal_treaty\">tariff autonomy</span> lost under earlier treaties, and founded scholarly bodies such as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Academia_Sinica\">Academia Sinica</span></b> in 1928. A drive for social discipline culminated in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Life_Movement\">New Life Movement</span> of 1934, a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span>-tinged moral campaign promoted by Chiang and his wife <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soong_Mei-ling\">Soong Mei-ling</span>. The decade also brought modest industrial growth, thousands of kilometres of new roads and railways, and a sweeping <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fabi\">currency reform</span></b> in 1935 that replaced the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silver_standard\">silver standard</span> with a managed paper money.<br> <br>For all its achievements, the regime was an authoritarian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"One-party_state\">one-party state</span> that justified its monopoly of power as a transitional \"political tutelage,\" and it never controlled the whole country. Residual <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warlord_Era\">warlord</span> power erupted in the massive <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Plains_War\">Central Plains War</span></b> of 1930, and the following year <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empire_of_Japan\">Japan</span> seized <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchuria\">Manchuria</span> after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mukden_Incident\">Mukden Incident</span> of 1931, detaching the region as the puppet state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchukuo\">Manchukuo</span>. Meanwhile the government waged a series of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Encirclement_Campaigns\">Encirclement Campaigns</span> against the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Communists</span> entrenched in their <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Soviet_Republic\">Jiangxi base</span>, finally dislodging them and driving the survivors onto the epic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Long_March\">Long March</span> of 1934. Mounting popular demand to resist the invaders culminated in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi'an_Incident\">Xi'an Incident</span> of December 1936, when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Xueliang\">Zhang Xueliang</span> detained Chiang and forced him into a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_United_Front\">Second United Front</span> with the Communists. The decade ended abruptly when the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marco_Polo_Bridge_Incident\">Marco Polo Bridge Incident</span></b> of July 1937 ignited all-out war, and after fierce fighting at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Shanghai\">Shanghai</span> the capital fell that December amid the atrocities of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing_Massacre\">Nanjing Massacre</span>, forcing the government to flee far up the Yangtze to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chongqing\">Chongqing</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Nanjing decade"},{"id":"cnp-005","num":"五","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Tracing its origin to the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> Nanchang uprising and historically subordinate to the Communist Party rather than the state, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is commanded through the Central Military Commission.","answer":"People's Liberation Army","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1927</span></div>","traditional":"中國人民解放軍","hanzi":"中国人民解放军","pinyin":"Zhōngguó Rénmín Jiěfàngjūn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōngguó Rénmín Jiěfàngjūn</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>People's Liberation Army</b> is the principal armed force of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Republic_of_China\">People's Republic of China</span> and the <b>military wing of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span></b>, distinctive among the world's major militaries in that it answers constitutionally to the Party rather than to the state. It traces its founding to the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanchang_uprising\">Nanchang uprising</span> of August 1,</b> 1927, when commanders including <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_De\">Zhu De</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"He_Long\">He Long</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ye_Ting\">Ye Ting</span> led more than 20,000 troops in a revolt against <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Nationalist</span> forces, a date still observed each year as the army's founding anniversary. In its early years it was known as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Red_Army\">Chinese Workers' and Peasants' Red Army</span></b>, building rural base areas alongside <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jinggang_Mountains\">Jinggang Mountains</span> from 1927 onward before enduring the punishing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Long_March\">Long March</span> of 1934–1935. During the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Sino-Japanese_War\">war against Japan</span> its principal formations, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eighth_Route_Army\">Eighth Route Army</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Fourth_Army\">New Fourth Army</span>, operated nominally under Nationalist authority within the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_United_Front\">Second United Front</span>, and the force took its current name during the <b>renewed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">Chinese Civil War</span> around 1946–1947</b>. Decisive victories in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liaoshen_campaign\">Liaoshen</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huaihai_campaign\">Huaihai</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pingjin_campaign\">Pingjin</span> campaigns of 1948–1949 secured communist control of the mainland, after which it dispatched hundreds of thousands of troops to fight United Nations forces in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Korean_War\">Korean War</span> under the nominally separate banner of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Volunteer_Army\">People's Volunteer Army</span>. <br> <br> Command of the force runs not through the government but through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Military_Commission_(China)\">Central Military Commission</span>, chaired by the country's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paramount_leader\">paramount leader</span>—a post held since 2012 by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span>—who from 2023 onward has waged a sweeping anti-corruption purge that has removed dozens of senior officers, among them two defense ministers and several sitting members of the commission. The PLA is organized into separate service branches, principally the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army_Ground_Force\">Ground Force</span>, the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army_Navy\">Navy</span></b>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army_Air_Force\">Air Force</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army_Rocket_Force\">Rocket Force</span> that oversees the country's land-based nuclear and conventional missiles. A far-reaching restructuring launched in 2015 replaced the former 7 military regions with 5 joint <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Theater_command_(People's_Liberation_Army)\">theater commands</span> and cut roughly 300,000 troops from a force of some 2.3 million, leaving an <b>active strength of about 2 million</b> that remains the world's largest <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Standing_army\">standing army</span>. Sustained by an official defense budget exceeding 200 billion dollars—second only to that of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States\">United States</span>—the force has pressed an ambitious modernization that has produced the <b>largest navy in the world</b> by number of hulls, multiple domestically built <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_aircraft_carrier_programme\">aircraft carriers</span>, and dedicated space and cyber units once grouped under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army_Strategic_Support_Force\">Strategic Support Force</span>. Beyond external defense it has periodically been turned inward, most controversially in suppressing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tiananmen_Square_protests\">Tiananmen Square protests</span> of 1989, and it now sits at the center of regional flashpoints over <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South_China_Sea\">South China Sea</span> as the chief instrument of an increasingly assertive China.","citation":"","answerText":"People's Liberation Army"},{"id":"cnp-067","num":"六十七","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Nicknamed the \"Butcher of Beijing\" by critics for his hardline stance, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was widely associated with the suppression ordered against the demonstrators in Tiananmen Square.","answer":"Li Peng","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Born</span><span class=\"dt-v\">20 October 1928</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Died</span><span class=\"dt-v\">22 July 2019</span></div>","traditional":"李鵬","hanzi":"李鹏","pinyin":"Lǐ Péng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Lǐ Péng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Li Peng</b> was a Chinese politician who <b>served as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Premier_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">premier</span></b> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span> from 1987 to 1998 and is most widely remembered for his hardline role during the suppression of the 1989 pro-democracy demonstrations. Born in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chengdu\">Chengdu</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan\">Sichuan</span>, he was the son of the early communist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Shuoxun\">Li Shuoxun</span>, a participant in the <b>1927 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanchang_uprising\">Nanchang Uprising</span></b> who was executed by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span> in 1931, after which the orphaned boy was reportedly taken under the wing of premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span> and his wife <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Yingchao\">Deng Yingchao</span>. Educated in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Soviet Union</span> at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Moscow_Power_Engineering_Institute\">Moscow Power Engineering Institute</span></b> in the early 1950s, he returned home to build a career in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hydroelectricity\">hydroelectric</span> power industry, emerging as one of a generation of Soviet-trained <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Technocracy\">technocrats</span> who climbed through the state's industrial bureaucracy. Advancing <b>to vice premier in 1983</b> and onto the powerful <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_Standing_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo Standing Committee</span>, he succeeded the reform-minded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhao_Ziyang\">Zhao Ziyang</span> as head <b>of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_Council_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">State Council</span> in 1987</b>, aligning himself with the cautious <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Planned_economy\">central-planning</span> instincts of party elders such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Yun\">Chen Yun</span>. A staunch advocate of large-scale state engineering, he became the foremost political champion of the colossal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Gorges_Dam\">Three Gorges Dam</span>, whose construction the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_People's_Congress\">National People's Congress</span> approved in 1992 amid an unusually large bloc of dissenting and abstaining votes. <br> <br> When mass protests erupted in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> following the death of the ousted reformer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Yaobang\">Hu Yaobang</span> in April 1989, Li adopted an uncompromising posture, clashing sharply with Zhao Ziyang, who favoured conciliation with the student demonstrators massing in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tiananmen_Square\">Tiananmen Square</span>. With the backing of the paramount leader <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"President_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">president</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yang_Shangkun\">Yang Shangkun</span>, he appeared on national television to declare <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Martial_law\">martial law</span> in the capital on 20 May 1989, a step that cleared the way for armed intervention. In the early hours of 4 June, units of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army\">People's Liberation Army</span> moved into the centre of the city and violently cleared the area in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1989_Tiananmen_Square_protests_and_massacre\">Tiananmen Square massacre</span>, killing an undetermined number of civilians and provoking condemnation from governments across the world. As the most visible official associated with the order he was derided as the 'Butcher of Beijing' by his detractors, even though ultimate authority for the suppression rested with Deng and the party elders—a contention Li pressed in personal diaries he later sought to publish—while leaked leadership records assembled in <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Tiananmen_Papers\"><i>The Tiananmen Papers</i></span></b> further exposed the secret deliberations behind the decision. Surviving the crisis politically unscathed, he completed a second term as premier until 1998 before chairing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Standing_Committee_of_the_National_People's_Congress\">Standing Committee of the National People's Congress</span> until 2003, while his children <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Xiaopeng_(politician)\">Li Xiaopeng</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Xiaolin\">Li Xiaolin</span> ascended to powerful positions in the state energy industry, and his death in 2019 at the age of 90 was marked by a state funeral and an official eulogy that praised his record in terms sharply at odds with his reputation abroad.","citation":"","answerText":"Li Peng"},{"id":"cne-044","num":"四十四","category":"China · Economics","question":"Serving as premier from <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> and earlier as central bank governor, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> negotiated entry into the World Trade Organization.","answer":"Zhu Rongji","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">born 23 October 1928</span></div>","traditional":"朱鎔基","hanzi":"朱镕基","pinyin":"Zhū Róngjī","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhū Róngjī</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Zhu Rongji</b> is a retired Chinese politician and economic reformer, born in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Changsha\">Changsha</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hunan\">Hunan</span>, who is widely regarded as the principal architect of his country's market transformation during the 1990s. After <b>joining the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Communist Party</span> in 1949</b> and graduating in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Electrical_engineering\">electrical engineering</span> from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tsinghua_University\">Tsinghua University</span> in 1951, he was branded a rightist <b>in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anti-Rightist_Campaign\">Anti-Rightist Campaign</span> of 1957</b> and endured years of internal exile before his fortunes recovered. Winning the patronage of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>, he served as mayor and party chief of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span> from 1988, championing the opening of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pudong\">Pudong</span> district before rising to <b>become a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vice_Premier_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">vice premier</span> in 1991</b>. Taking personal charge of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Bank_of_China\">People's Bank of China</span> in 1993 under Premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Peng\">Li Peng</span>, he imposed stern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Austerity\">austerity</span> that tamed an <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Inflation\">inflation</span> rate which had peaked near 24 percent, engineering a celebrated economic \"soft landing.\" He also pushed through a sweeping <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taxation_in_China\">tax-sharing reform</span></b> in 1994 that redirected revenue to the centre, strengthening Beijing's fiscal grip over the wider <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">Chinese economy</span>.<br> <br>As the leading economic official during the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1997_Asian_financial_crisis\">Asian financial crisis</span></b> of 1997–98, he won international praise by holding the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Renminbi\">renminbi</span> steady rather than resorting to a competitive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Devaluation\">devaluation</span> that might have deepened the regional turmoil. Appointed premier in 1998 under President <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Zemin\">Jiang Zemin</span>, he made the restructuring of loss-making <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_enterprise\">state-owned enterprises</span> a central mission, pressing the policy of \"<b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Grasp_the_large,_let_go_of_the_small\">grasp the large, let go of the small</span></b>\" that threw tens of millions of workers off the payroll through mass <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Layoff\">layoffs</span>. He confronted a fragile banking system weighed down by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Non-performing_loan\">non-performing loans</span>, shifting enormous quantities of bad debt in 1999 to <b>four newly created <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Asset_management_company\">asset management companies</span></b> in a campaign to clean up and recapitalize <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Banking_in_China\">China's banks</span>. A committed reformer, he slashed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bureaucracy\">bureaucracy</span> by merging government ministries and personally drove the marathon talks that brought China into the World Trade Organization in 2001, the capstone of his market-opening <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">reforms</span>. Blunt-spoken and incorruptible—he once vowed to prepare coffins for corrupt officials—he relinquished his seat on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_Standing_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo Standing Committee</span> and in 2003 handed the premiership to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wen_Jiabao\">Wen Jiabao</span>, retiring into a private life even as his record of fighting <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Corruption_in_China\">corruption</span> and driving decisive marketization came to be seen as a foundation of China's later rise.","citation":"","answerText":"Zhu Rongji"},{"id":"em-087","num":"八十七","category":"Chinese Communism · Suppression Campaigns","question":"A series of offensives mounted from 1930 by Chiang Kai-shek, advised by German officers, to wipe out the Communist base areas, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> used blockhouses and economic blockade to squeeze the Jiangxi Soviet, finally forcing the Red Army into a desperate retreat.","answer":"Encirclement Campaigns","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Began</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1930 · KMT drives on the Soviet bases</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Ended</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1934 · fifth campaign</span></div>","traditional":"圍剿","hanzi":"围剿","pinyin":"wéijiǎo","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">wéijiǎo</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“encircle and suppress”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Encirclement Campaigns</b> were a series of 5 large military offensives launched <b>between 1930</b> and <b>1934</b> by the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nationalist_government\">Nationalist government</span></b> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span> to eradicate the rural base areas held by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span>. Their principal objective was the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Soviet_Republic\">Jiangxi Soviet</span>, the communist republic centred on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ruijin\">Ruijin</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiangxi\">Jiangxi</span> province, whose survival depended on the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Red_Army\">Red Army</span></b> led by commanders such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_De\">Zhu De</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peng_Dehuai\">Peng Dehuai</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lin_Biao\">Lin Biao</span>. Directed from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanchang\">Nanchang</span> and entrusted largely to officers of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Whampoa_Military_Academy\">Whampoa Military Academy</span>, the 1st campaign of late 1930 committed roughly 100,000 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Revolutionary_Army\">National Revolutionary Army</span> troops but collapsed when the outnumbered defenders practiced a doctrine of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mobile_warfare\">mobile warfare</span> that lured the attackers deep before destroying isolated units. A further 3 offensives followed <b>between 1931</b> and 1933, each marshaling larger forces, with the 3rd directed in person by Chiang at the head of some 300,000 troops, yet all were thrown back by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guerrilla_warfare\">guerrilla warfare</span> perfected by Mao, while distractions such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Plains_War\">Central Plains War</span>, the Japanese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mukden_Incident\">Mukden Incident</span> of 1931, and the breakaway <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fujian_Rebellion\">Fujian Rebellion</span> of 1933 repeatedly sapped Nationalist momentum. Determined to break the pattern, Chiang adopted a methodical new approach shaped by German military advisers serving under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-German_cooperation_(1926–1941)\">Sino-German cooperation</span>, above all the former army commander <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hans_von_Seeckt\">Hans von Seeckt</span> and his successor <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Alexander_von_Falkenhausen\">Alexander von Falkenhausen</span></b>, who together championed a strategy of gradual advance, dense fortification, and economic strangulation. <br> <br> The decisive 5th campaign, begun in 1933, replaced reckless assaults with a slowly advancing cordon of thousands of fortified <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Blockhouse\">blockhouses</span> connected by military roads, reinforced by a tight economic blockade designed to deprive the soviet of salt, grain, and ammunition. Massing an estimated 500,000 to 1 million <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span> troops, the Nationalists steadily compressed the base area behind a network said to comprise some 14,000 blockhouses, strangling its trade and squeezing a defending Red Army that numbered only around 130,000. Communist strategy worsened the crisis, for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Comintern\">Comintern</span> military adviser <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Otto_Braun_(communist)\">Otto Braun</span> and the Soviet-trained leadership around <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bo_Gu\">Bo Gu</span> and the <b>so-called <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"28_Bolsheviks\">28 Bolsheviks</span></b> insisted on rigid positional defence against a far stronger foe. By October 1934 the besieged and depleted defenders could no longer hold, and roughly 86,000 troops and officials broke through the blockade, abandoning the soviet they had defended for years, to begin the grueling retreat that became the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Long_March\">Long March</span>. Although the campaigns achieved their immediate goal of clearing the southern soviets, the breakout ultimately preserved the Communist movement and produced the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zunyi_Conference\">Zunyi Conference</span>, where Mao seized the leadership and set the Party on the path that would win the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">Chinese Civil War</span> and establish the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Republic_of_China\">People's Republic of China</span> in 1949.","citation":"","answerText":"Encirclement Campaigns"},{"id":"em-086","num":"八十六","category":"Chinese Communism · The Jiangxi Soviet","question":"Proclaimed in 1931 with its capital at Ruijin in the mountains of Jiangxi, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> controlled scattered base areas, redistributed land, and was chaired by Mao Zedong before being overrun by Nationalist forces.","answer":"Chinese Soviet Republic","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Proclaimed</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1931 · at Ruijin</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Dissolved</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1937 · United Front</span></div>","traditional":"中華蘇維埃共和國","hanzi":"中华苏维埃共和国","pinyin":"Zhōnghuá Sūwéi'āi Gònghéguó","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōnghuá Sūwéi'āi Gònghéguó</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Chinese Soviet Republic</b> was a short-lived rural state <b>proclaimed on 7 November 1931</b>, the 14th anniversary of Russia's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"October_Revolution\">October Revolution</span>, by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> with its capital at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ruijin\">Ruijin</span> in the mountainous south of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiangxi\">Jiangxi</span> province. It arose from a patchwork of scattered rural base areas that the party had carved out after the <b>failed insurrections of 1927</b>, notably the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Autumn_Harvest_Uprising\">Autumn Harvest Uprising</span>, the largest being the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Soviet\">Central Revolutionary Base</span> straddling Jiangxi and neighbouring <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fujian\">Fujian</span>, which had grown out of the guerrilla stronghold of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jinggang_Mountains\">Jinggangshan</span> founded by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_De\">Zhu De</span></b> in 1927–1928. Other soviet zones lay scattered across central China, among them the Hubei–Henan–Anhui base commanded by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Guotao\">Zhang Guotao</span>, and the entire structure was modelled explicitly on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Soviet Union</span>, the very word \"soviet\" being a transliteration of the Russian term for a workers' council. At its First All-China Congress of Soviets the republic adopted a constitution and named Mao chairman of its central executive committee, while its government drove a radical campaign of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Land_reform\">land redistribution</span> that confiscated the estates of landlords and wealthier peasants for parcelling out to the rural poor. Defended by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Red_Army\">Chinese Workers' and Peasants' Red Army</span> under commanders including Zhu De and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span>, the central base governed an estimated 3 million people and printed its own currency through a state bank run by Mao's brother <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zemin\">Mao Zemin</span>, even as the regime was convulsed by brutal internal purges such as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Futian_incident\">Futian incident</span></b> of late 1930, in which thousands of suspected counter-revolutionaries were executed. <br> <br> From 1930 the Nationalist leader <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span> launched a succession of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Encirclement_Campaigns\">Encirclement Campaigns</span> against the Communist bases, the first several of which the Red Army turned back through the mobile <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guerrilla_warfare\">guerrilla tactics</span> championed by Mao and Zhu De. The decisive blow came with the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fifth_Encirclement_Campaign\">Fifth Encirclement Campaign</span></b> of 1933–1934, in which Chiang committed as many as 1 million troops of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Revolutionary_Army\">National Revolutionary Army</span> and, guided by the German general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hans_von_Seeckt\">Hans von Seeckt</span>, tightened a slow-moving noose of thousands of fortified blockhouses around the shrinking soviet. By then Mao had been pushed aside in military affairs by the Moscow-aligned faction of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"28_Bolsheviks\">28 Bolsheviks</span> under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bo_Gu\">Bo Gu</span> and by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Communist_International\">Comintern</span> military adviser <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Otto_Braun_(communist)\">Otto Braun</span>, whose insistence on conventional positional warfare against a far stronger enemy proved catastrophic. Unable to break the encirclement, the Communist leadership abandoned the Jiangxi base in October 1934 and embarked on the epic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Long_March\">Long March</span>, withdrawing roughly 86,000 troops westward, while Ruijin itself fell to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span> the following month. Though its government nominally outlasted the march after relocating to northern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shaanxi\">Shaanxi</span>, the republic was formally <b>dissolved in 1937</b> when, under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_United_Front\">Second United Front</span> against Japan, its surviving territory was reconstituted as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shaanxi–Gansu–Ningxia_Border_Region\">Shaanxi–Gansu–Ningxia Border Region</span></b>, yet the experiment had bequeathed the party a tested corps of cadres, a battle-hardened army, and a model of rural revolution that would ultimately carry it to power in 1949.","citation":"","answerText":"Chinese Soviet Republic"},{"id":"em-091","num":"九十一","category":"War with Japan · Manchuria","question":"Staged in 1931 when officers of Japan's Kwantung Army blew up a stretch of their own railway and blamed Chinese troops, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> served as a manufactured pretext to seize all of Manchuria.","answer":"Mukden Incident","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">18 September 1931 · near Mukden (Shenyang)</span></div>","traditional":"九一八事變","hanzi":"九一八事变","pinyin":"Jiǔyībā Shìbiàn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Jiǔyībā Shìbiàn</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“September 18 Incident”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Mukden Incident</b> was a staged <b>act of sabotage on 18 September 1931</b> that the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kwantung_Army\">Kwantung Army</span></b> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empire_of_Japan\">Empire of Japan</span> used as a pretext to invade and occupy all of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchuria\">Manchuria</span>. On that night Japanese officers detonated a small charge beside the tracks of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South_Manchuria_Railway\">South Manchuria Railway</span> near <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shenyang\">Mukden</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liaoning\">Liaoning</span>, inflicting damage so slight that a train passed over the spot minutes later, yet they promptly blamed Chinese soldiers for the blast in a plot devised chiefly by the staff officers <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kanji_Ishiwara\">Kanji Ishiwara</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Seishirō_Itagaki\">Seishirō Itagaki</span>. Within hours the army assaulted the Chinese garrison at Mukden and seized the city, and over the following five months it overran the three northeastern provinces, completing <b>the conquest by February 1932</b>. The vast Northeastern Army of the warlord <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Xueliang\">Zhang Xueliang</span>, heir to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fengtian_clique\">Fengtian clique</span>, offered almost no resistance and withdrew south of the Great Wall, in part because <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span> had favoured a policy of non-resistance while concentrating against the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> during the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing_decade\">Nanjing decade</span></b> and its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Encirclement_Campaigns\">encirclement campaigns</span>. The operation was launched largely on the initiative of the Kwantung Army's field officers, an act of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gekokujō\">gekokujō</span> insubordination that confronted the civilian cabinet of <b>Prime Minister <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Reijirō_Wakatsuki\">Reijirō Wakatsuki</span></b> in Tokyo with a fait accompli it proved powerless to reverse. <br> <br> In March 1932 Japan transformed the seized territory into the puppet state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchukuo\">Manchukuo</span>, installing the deposed last emperor of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Puyi\">Puyi</span>, as its nominal ruler. The aggression drew international condemnation when the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"League_of_Nations\">League of Nations</span> commissioned the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lytton_Report\">Lytton Report</span>, which in 1932 branded Japan the aggressor and refused to recognise Manchukuo, prompting Japan to storm out <b>of the League in 1933</b>. At home the incident discredited Japan's parliamentary government under Emperor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hirohito\">Hirohito</span> and emboldened the militarists, while abroad it is widely regarded as the opening move of Japanese expansion that would lead through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"January_28_incident\">Shanghai fighting</span> of 1932 to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Sino-Japanese_War\">Second Sino-Japanese War</span> and ultimately the wider <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pacific_War\">Pacific War</span>. In China the loss of the northeast ignited furious <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anti-Japanese_sentiment_in_China\">anti-Japanese sentiment</span></b> and boycotts, and Zhang Xueliang's bitterness at being made to abandon his homeland would later help drive him to kidnap Chiang in the 1936 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi'an_Incident\">Xi'an Incident</span> to force a united front against the invaders. Following by only three years the Kwantung Army's earlier assassination of Zhang's father <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Zuolin\">Zhang Zuolin</span> at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huanggutun_incident\">Huanggutun incident</span>, the seizure of Manchuria is often dated by historians as the true beginning of the so-called Fifteen Years' War and, by some accounts, of the global conflict that became the Asian theatre of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_War_II\">World War II</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Mukden Incident"},{"id":"em-092","num":"九十二","category":"War with Japan · Manchuria","question":"Set up by Japan in 1932 in the territory it had seized in the north-east, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was a puppet state nominally headed by the deposed last emperor Puyi and was condemned by the League of Nations, prompting Japan to walk out.","answer":"Manchukuo","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Established</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1932 · Japanese puppet state</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Dissolved</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1945 · Soviet invasion</span></div>","traditional":"滿洲國","hanzi":"满洲国","pinyin":"Mǎnzhōuguó","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Mǎnzhōuguó</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Manchukuo</b> was the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Puppet_state\">puppet state</span></b> that Japan established across <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchuria\">Manchuria</span>, the vast region of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northeast_China\">north-eastern China</span>, and ruled through compliant local figureheads for over a decade. Its creation followed <b>the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mukden_Incident\">Mukden Incident</span> of September 1931</b>, a sabotage attack staged by Japan's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kwantung_Army\">Kwantung Army</span> as a pretext for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japanese_invasion_of_Manchuria\">conquest of Manchuria</span>. The new state was <b>proclaimed in 1932</b> with its capital at Hsinking, the present-day city of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Changchun\">Changchun</span>, and it eventually governed a population of more than 30 million. To lend it a veneer of legitimacy, Japan installed Puyi, the deposed last emperor of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> and head of the imperial <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Aisin-Gioro\">Aisin-Gioro</span> house, first as chief executive in 1932 and then as emperor in 1934, although real power rested entirely with the Kwantung Army and its Japanese advisers. The regime cloaked Japanese control in slogans of harmony among its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Chinese\">Han</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_people\">Manchu</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongols\">Mongol</span>, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Koreans\">Korean</span></b>, and Japanese peoples, yet it functioned as a tightly controlled colony serving the interests of the home islands.<br> <br>The colony was developed as a base of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heavy_industry\">heavy industry</span> and resource extraction, its coal, iron, and soybeans funnelled to Japan and its economy organised around the powerful <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South_Manchuria_Railway\">South Manchuria Railway</span> and giant Japanese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zaibatsu\">conglomerates</span>. Its rule was harsh and exploitative, <b>marked by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Unfree_labour\">forced labour</span></b>, a state-sponsored <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Opium\">opium</span> trade, and the notorious biological-warfare experiments of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Unit_731\">Unit 731</span> near <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Harbin\">Harbin</span>, while a stubborn guerrilla resistance, including the Communist-led <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northeast_Anti-Japanese_United_Army\">Northeast Anti-Japanese United Army</span>, was met with brutal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pacification_of_Manchukuo\">pacification</span>. The international community refused to accept the conquest, for the League of Nations dispatched a commission of inquiry led by the British <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Victor_Bulwer-Lytton,_2nd_Earl_of_Lytton\">Earl of Lytton</span></b> whose <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lytton_Report\">Lytton Report</span> branded Japan the aggressor and declined to recognise the new state. When the League endorsed that verdict in 1933, Japan responded by withdrawing from the organisation altogether, and only a handful of states—mostly its future <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Axis_powers\">Axis</span> partners such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nazi_Germany\">Germany</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kingdom_of_Italy\">Italy</span>—ever extended recognition. Surviving as the cornerstone of Japan's continental empire throughout the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Sino-Japanese_War\">war with China</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_War_II\">Second World War</span>, the state was <b>swept away in August 1945</b> by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_invasion_of_Manchuria\">Soviet invasion of Manchuria</span>, its captured emperor was handed to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Soviets</span>, and the region was restored to China.","citation":"","answerText":"Manchukuo"},{"id":"em-085","num":"八十五","category":"Nationalist China · Ideology","question":"Launched by Chiang Kai-shek and his wife Soong Mei-ling in 1934, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> blended revived Confucian virtues with militarised discipline and hygiene rules, urging citizens towards a moral, orderly life as an antidote to Communist appeal.","answer":"New Life Movement","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Launched</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1934 · by Chiang Kai-shek</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Faded</span><span class=\"dt-v\">by 1949</span></div>","traditional":"新生活運動","hanzi":"新生活运动","pinyin":"Xīn Shēnghuó Yùndòng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Xīn Shēnghuó Yùndòng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>New Life Movement</b> was a government-led campaign of moral and civic renewal launched in 1934 by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span> and his wife <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soong_Mei-ling\">Soong Mei-ling</span></b> to discipline and revitalise Chinese society. Proclaimed in February 1934 in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanchang\">Nanchang</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiangxi\">Jiangxi</span> headquarters of Chiang's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Encirclement_Campaigns\">encirclement campaigns</span> against the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Soviet_Republic\">Chinese Soviet Republic</span>, the movement was conceived in part as a spiritual counterweight to the appeal of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> and as a tool of nation-building during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing_decade\">Nanjing decade</span>. Its ideology rested on a revival of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> ethics, above all the four cardinal virtues drawn from the ancient <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guanzi_(text)\"><i>Guanzi</i></span> — propriety or <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_(Confucianism)\">li</span>, righteousness or <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yi_(Confucianism)\">yi</span>, integrity, and the sense of shame — supplemented by such traditional values as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Filial_piety\">filial piety</span> and frugality. These abstract principles were translated into a detailed code of roughly 96 rules governing everyday conduct, prescribing <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hygiene\">hygiene</span></b>, punctuality, cleanliness, and orderliness while forbidding such behaviours as spitting, littering, smoking in public, and leaving one's clothing unbuttoned. The campaign fused these <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span> objectives, framed within <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Yat-sen\">Sun Yat-sen</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Principles_of_the_People\">Three Principles of the People</span>, with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Methodism\">Methodist</span> Christianity of Soong Mei-ling and the militarised, regimented ethos championed by the fascist-inspired <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Blue_Shirts_Society\">Blue Shirts Society</span></b>. <br> <br> Administered through a New Life Movement Promotion Association and energetically promoted by Soong Mei-ling, who lent it a Christian and social-service character drawing on missionary bodies such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"YMCA\">YMCA</span>, the movement sought to mobilise officials, students, and ordinary citizens behind a vision of disciplined national strength. Many scholars have noted the imprint of contemporary European <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fascism\">fascism</span> on the project, as Chiang openly admired the regimented mass mobilisation of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Benito_Mussolini\">Benito Mussolini</span></b>'s Italy and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nazi_Germany\">Nazi Germany</span>, lending the campaign a distinctly <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Authoritarianism\">authoritarian</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_nationalism\">nationalist</span> cast. Historians have interpreted it in varied ways, with <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Frederic_Wakeman\">Frederic Wakeman</span></b> emphasising its fascist dimensions and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Arif_Dirlik\">Arif Dirlik</span> characterising it as a conservative counterrevolution aimed at containing radical social change. In practice the movement achieved only modest results, for its top-down moralising, its preoccupation with trivial matters of etiquette, and the persistent gap between official exhortation and daily reality left it widely ridiculed and largely ineffectual. After the outbreak <b>of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Sino-Japanese_War\">Second Sino-Japanese War</span> in 1937</b> it was redirected towards wartime relief and mobilisation from the Nationalist capital of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chongqing\">Chongqing</span>, and although the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nationalist_government\">Nationalist government</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)\">Republic of China</span> did not formally abandon it <b>until 1949</b>, the New Life Movement had long since faded as a meaningful force in Chinese public life.","citation":"","answerText":"New Life Movement"},{"id":"em-088","num":"八十八","category":"Chinese Communism · The Long March","question":"An epic and gruelling retreat of 1934–1935 covering thousands of kilometres, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> saw the Communist Red Army break out of encirclement in the south and trek to the remote north-west, an ordeal that confirmed the leadership of Mao Zedong and became a founding legend of the Party.","answer":"Long March","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Began</span><span class=\"dt-v\">October 1934 · retreat from Jiangxi</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Ended</span><span class=\"dt-v\">October 1935 · arrival in Shaanxi</span></div>","traditional":"長征","hanzi":"长征","pinyin":"Chángzhēng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Chángzhēng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Long March</b> was an arduous military retreat undertaken in 1934–1935 by the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Red_Army\">Red Army</span></b> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span>, which broke out of encirclement in the south and trekked thousands of kilometres to a new base in the remote north-west. It was forced by the fifth of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Encirclement_Campaigns\">encirclement campaigns</span> that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span> waged against the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Soviet_Republic\">Chinese Soviet Republic</span>, a methodical blockhouse strategy advised by the <b>German general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hans_von_Seeckt\">Hans von Seeckt</span></b> that slowly strangled the Communist base around <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ruijin\">Ruijin</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiangxi\">Jiangxi</span>. With their cause directed by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Communist_International\">Comintern</span> adviser <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Otto_Braun_(communist)\">Otto Braun</span> and the Moscow-trained faction of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"28_Bolsheviks\">28 Bolsheviks</span> under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bo_Gu\">Bo Gu</span>, whose costly positional warfare had failed, roughly 86,000 troops of the First Front Army broke through <b>the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Nationalist</span> lines in October 1934</b>. The early months proved disastrous, and after suffering catastrophic losses at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiang_River\">Xiang River</span> the column was reduced from its original strength to barely 30,000 survivors within weeks of setting out. At the pivotal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zunyi_Conference\">Zunyi Conference</span> <b>held in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guizhou\">Guizhou</span> in January 1935</b>, the discredited military leadership was overturned and effective command passed to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>, an event long celebrated as the moment that confirmed his ascendancy within the party. <br> <br> Under Mao's more fluid strategy the army crossed the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chishui_River\">Chishui River</span></b> four times to evade pursuit, forded the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jinsha_River\">Jinsha</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dadu_River\">Dadu</span> rivers, seized the chain-cable span in the celebrated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Luding_Bridge\">Battle of Luding Bridge</span>, and struggled across snow-capped mountains and the treacherous high grasslands of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan\">Sichuan</span> borderlands. The First Front Army's journey lasted some 370 days and is traditionally said to have covered 25,000 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_(unit)\">li</span>, or roughly 12,500 kilometres (7,770 miles), though modern researchers regard that figure as inflated and place the true distance considerably lower. Along the way Mao prevailed in a bitter power struggle with <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Guotao\">Zhang Guotao</span></b>, whose larger Fourth Front Army briefly contested his authority before marching south on a course that ended in ruin. The exhausted vanguard finally reached northern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shaanxi\">Shaanxi</span> in October 1935, where it established a new headquarters that would centre on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yan'an\">Yan'an</span>, though only around 8,000 of the men who had set out from Jiangxi completed the entire march. Although a military defeat that cost the movement most of its strength, the march preserved a hardened core of future leaders — among them <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_De\">Zhu De</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lin_Biao\">Lin Biao</span>, and a young <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> — and, popularised abroad by <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Edgar_Snow\">Edgar Snow</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Red_Star_Over_China\"><i>Red Star Over China</i></span></b>, it became an enduring founding legend of Chinese Communism.","citation":"","answerText":"Long March"},{"id":"em-089","num":"八十九","category":"Chinese Communism · The Long March","question":"Held in a Guizhou town in January 1935 during the Long March, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> sidelined the Soviet-backed commanders blamed for the loss of the base areas and marked the decisive rise of Mao Zedong within the Party.","answer":"Zunyi Conference","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">15–17 January 1935 · Zunyi (Mao’s ascent)</span></div>","traditional":"遵義會議","hanzi":"遵义会议","pinyin":"Zūnyì Huìyì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zūnyì Huìyì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Zunyi Conference</b> was an enlarged meeting of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo</span></b> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> held <b>from 15</b> to <b>17 January 1935</b> in the town of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zunyi\">Zunyi</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guizhou\">Guizhou</span> province, convened in the midst of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Long_March\">Long March</span> as a crisis of leadership engulfed the retreating Communists. The gathering came in the wake of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Red_Army\">Red Army</span>'s abandonment of its <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiangxi\">Jiangxi</span> base in October 1934</b>, a withdrawal forced by defeat in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fifth_Encirclement_Campaign\">Fifth Encirclement Campaign</span>, and it followed the catastrophic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Xiang_River\">Battle of the Xiang River</span>, in which the main force had been slashed from roughly 86,000 troops to barely 30,000. Mounting losses fuelled bitter recriminations against the military leadership of the Moscow-trained <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bo_Gu\">Bo Gu</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Communist_International\">Comintern</span> adviser <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Otto_Braun_(communist)\">Otto Braun</span></b>, who together with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span> had formed the all-powerful \"three-man group\" that directed the army's rigidly conventional and ultimately disastrous strategy. Some 20 senior figures took part, including <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> himself, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_De\">Zhu De</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Wentian\">Zhang Wentian</span>, and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Jiaxiang\">Wang Jiaxiang</span></b>, alongside front commanders such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peng_Dehuai\">Peng Dehuai</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lin_Biao\">Lin Biao</span>, with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> reportedly keeping the minutes. Crucially, the army's radio contact with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Moscow</span> had been severed during the retreat, freeing the assembled leaders to take momentous decisions without awaiting approval from the foreign patrons of the dominant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"28_Bolsheviks\">28 Bolsheviks</span> faction. <br> <br> The conference issued a sweeping indictment of the prevailing military line, stripped Bo Gu and Braun of their command, and elected Mao to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_Standing_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo Standing Committee</span>, restoring the mobile <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guerrilla_warfare\">guerrilla warfare</span> he had long favoured over the positional tactics that had cost the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Soviet_Republic\">Chinese Soviet Republic</span> its homeland. In the weeks that followed, Zhang Wentian replaced Bo Gu as the figure carrying overall responsibility on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Central Committee</span>, and a fresh three-man military command of Mao, Zhou Enlai, and Wang Jiaxiang was constituted, consolidating his authority over strategy. Mao's restored ascendancy was soon vindicated in the field by the celebrated <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Crossing_of_the_Chishui_River\">crossings of the Chishui River</span></b>, a sequence of feints and forced marches that bewildered the pursuing armies of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span> and allowed the Red Army to slip the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span> encirclement. The fragile new consensus would soon be tested by a bruising power struggle with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Guotao\">Zhang Guotao</span> as the columns pushed west and north, but Mao prevailed, leading the survivors to a refuge in northern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shaanxi\">Shaanxi</span> by the end of 1935 and, before long, to their famous headquarters at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yan'an\">Yan'an</span>. Long enshrined in official Communist historiography as a \"life-and-death turning point,\" the conference is conventionally regarded as the moment the Chinese revolution passed decisively into Mao's hands and the party began to chart a course of its own, foreshadowing the eventual codification of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maoism\">Mao Zedong Thought</span> as its guiding ideology.","citation":"","answerText":"Zunyi Conference"},{"id":"em-093","num":"九十三","category":"War with Japan · Toward United Front","question":"Occurring in December 1936 when the \"Young Marshal\" Zhang Xueliang kidnapped Chiang Kai-shek to force him to stop fighting the Communists, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> led to an agreement to unite against Japan.","answer":"Xi'an Incident","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">12 December 1936 · Chiang detained at Xi’an</span></div>","traditional":"西安事變","hanzi":"西安事变","pinyin":"Xī'ān Shìbiàn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Xī'ān Shìbiàn</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Xi'an Incident</b> was a political and <b>military crisis of December 1936</b> in which senior commanders detained the <b>Nationalist leader <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span></b> in the city of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi'an\">Xi'an</span>, the capital of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shaanxi\">Shaanxi</span> province, to force him to abandon civil war and resist Japanese aggression. Its chief author was <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Xueliang\">Zhang Xueliang</span>, the so-called Young Marshal, who had inherited control of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchuria\">Manchuria</span> from his father <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Zuolin\">Zhang Zuolin</span>, assassinated <b>by Japanese officers in 1928</b>, only to lose that homeland after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mukden_Incident\">Mukden Incident</span> of 1931 and the founding of the puppet state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchukuo\">Manchukuo</span>, which left him commanding a large but displaced and demoralised force far from home. By the mid-1930s patriotic agitation, exemplified by the <b>student-led <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"December_9th_Movement\">December 9th Movement</span> of 1935</b>, was demanding national resistance rather than the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Encirclement_Campaigns\">campaigns</span> being waged against the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span>, whose surviving forces had regrouped at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yan'an\">Yan'an</span> after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Long_March\">Long March</span>. <b>Zhang's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northeastern_Army\">Northeastern Army</span></b>, embittered at being sent against fellow Chinese, joined with the local commander <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yang_Hucheng\">Yang Hucheng</span> to seize Chiang at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huaqing_Pool\">Huaqing</span> hot-spring retreat outside Xi'an on December 12, 1936, capturing him on the surrounding hillside after he fled the gunfire in his nightclothes. The captors demanded an immediate end to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">civil war</span> and the formation of a united front against the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empire_of_Japan\">Empire of Japan</span>, plunging the nation into a tense fortnight of uncertainty over the captured leader's fate. <br> <br> The arrest set off a fraught fortnight of bargaining that drew in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span> for the communists, Chiang's wife <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soong_Mei-ling\">Soong Mei-ling</span> and her brother <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"T._V._Soong\">T. V. Soong</span>, and the Australian adviser <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"William_Henry_Donald\">W. H. Donald</span></b>. In <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span> hardliners such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"He_Yingqin\">He Yingqin</span> urged a punitive assault on the city, whereas <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joseph_Stalin\">Joseph Stalin</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Comintern\">Comintern</span> unexpectedly pressed the communists to secure Chiang's release rather than his execution. After Chiang gave verbal assurances to suspend the anti-communist offensives and confront Japan—a course the Communist leadership under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> had come to favour—he was freed on December 25, 1936, having signed no formal document yet having tacitly accepted the new policy. The settlement opened the way for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_United_Front\">Second United Front</span>, reviving the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span>-Communist cooperation that had collapsed in 1927 and helping prepare the country for the full-scale <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Sino-Japanese_War\">Second Sino-Japanese War</span> that erupted the following year. The conspirators' fates diverged sharply, for Zhang escorted Chiang back to the capital and was <b>kept under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"House_arrest\">house arrest</span></b> for more than 50 years, much of it on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span> before his final years in Hawaii, whereas Yang was eventually imprisoned and executed in 1949, and the episode is still widely commemorated in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Republic_of_China\">People's Republic of China</span> as a patriotic turning point.","citation":"","answerText":"Xi'an Incident"},{"id":"em-002","num":"二","category":"Chinese Communism · Political Thought","question":"Written by Mao Zedong in 1937 and paired with the essay On Practice, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> applies the dialectical-materialist idea that contradiction is universal and identifies a principal contradiction within every complex process.","answer":"On Contradiction","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Written</span><span class=\"dt-v\">August 1937 · by Mao Zedong, Yan’an</span></div>","traditional":"矛盾論","hanzi":"矛盾论","pinyin":"Máodùn lùn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Máodùn lùn</span></div>","abstract":"<b><i>On Contradiction</i></b> is a philosophical essay written <b>by Mao Zedong in 1937</b> that ranks, alongside its companion work <i>On Practice</i>, among the foundational texts of Chinese <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marxist_philosophy\">Marxist philosophy</span></b>. Composed in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yan'an\">Yan'an</span> not long after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Long_March\">Long March</span>, during the opening months of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Sino-Japanese_War\">Second Sino-Japanese War</span>, and reportedly drawn from lectures Mao delivered to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Communist Party</span> cadres, the essay was framed as a weapon against the \"dogmatism\" of rivals such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Ming\">Wang Ming</span> and the Moscow-trained <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"28_Bolsheviks\">28 Bolsheviks</span>, who mechanically applied <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Communist_International\">Comintern</span> directives to Chinese realities. Drawing on the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dialectic\">dialectical</span></b> tradition of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Karl_Marx\">Karl Marx</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Friedrich_Engels\">Friedrich Engels</span>, on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vladimir_Lenin\">Vladimir Lenin</span>'s notes on the subject, and ultimately on the idealist dialectics of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Georg_Wilhelm_Friedrich_Hegel\">Hegel</span>, the work recast the law of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Unity_of_opposites\">unity and struggle of opposites</span></b> as the core of a thoroughly <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Materialism\">materialist</span> worldview. Its central argument holds that contradiction is universal and absolute, present in every process and at every stage of development, while in each case taking a particular and relative form, so that the analyst's task is to identify within any complex process the single \"principal contradiction\" whose movement governs the rest. It further set the principal aspect of a contradiction against its secondary aspect and affirmed the broader <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marxism\">Marxist</span> thesis that internal contradiction, not external cause, is the fundamental engine of all change, an emphasis that in later Maoist thought elevated the law of contradiction above classical principles such as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Negation_of_the_negation\">negation of the negation</span></b>.<br> <br>A culminating section drew the politically loaded distinction between antagonistic contradictions, to be settled by force, and non-antagonistic ones, to be resolved peacefully among the people, tying the abstract dialectic to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Class_conflict\">class struggle</span> central to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Historical_materialism\">historical materialism</span>. Paired with <i>On Practice</i>, which treated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Epistemology\">epistemology</span> and the bond between knowledge and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Praxis_(process)\">practice</span>, the essay became a pillar of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maoism\">Mao Zedong Thought</span> and furnished the conceptual language of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yan'an_Rectification_Movement\">Yan'an Rectification Movement</span> of the early 1940s. Substantially revised <b>before its publication in 1952</b>, and though firmly anchored in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marxism–Leninism\">Marxism–Leninism</span> and indebted to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Soviet</span> textbooks of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stalinism\">Stalinist</span> period, the work's stress on the particularity of contradiction underpinned Mao's drive to adapt theory to Chinese conditions, from the programme of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Democracy\">New Democracy</span> to the declaration <b>at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"8th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">8th National Congress</span> of 1956</b> that the country's principal contradiction had shifted. Outside China the essay drew notable philosophical engagement, above all from the French Marxist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Louis_Althusser\">Louis Althusser</span>, whose 1962 essay reworked Mao's principal contradiction into the influential notion of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Overdetermination\">overdetermination</span>. Required reading for cadres and masses alike during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span> of 1966–1976, and still discussed by later theorists such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Slavoj_Žižek\">Slavoj Žižek</span>, the slender essay endures as one of the most widely read statements of dialectical thought ever produced.","citation":"","answerText":"On Contradiction"},{"id":"em-090","num":"九十","category":"Chinese Communism · The Yan'an Era","question":"A remote town in Shaanxi that became the Communist headquarters at the end of the Long March, <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> gave its name to the years in which Mao Zedong consolidated his ideology and rectified the Party before the final contest for China.","answer":"Yan'an","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">CCP base</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1937 · after the Long March</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Until</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1947 · evacuation</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"延安","pinyin":"Yán'ān","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Yán'ān</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Yan'an</b> is a city in northern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shaanxi\">Shaanxi</span> province that served as the principal base and de facto capital of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> for roughly a decade after the mid-1930s. Set amid the deeply eroded ravines of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Loess_Plateau\">Loess Plateau</span></b>, the remote and impoverished district offered natural protection from attack, and its soft hillsides were honeycombed with the cave dwellings, or <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yaodong\">yaodong</span>, in which the Party's soldiers, students, and cadres lived and worked. The communists reached this corner <b>of Shaanxi in October 1935</b> at the end of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Long_March\">Long March</span>, a retreat during which the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zunyi_Conference\">Zunyi Conference</span> had already launched <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>'s rise, and after a brief interlude at the town of Bao'an they moved the leadership <b>to Yan'an in late 1936</b> and established the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shaan-Gan-Ning_Border_Region\">Shaan-Gan-Ning Border Region</span> as their governing base. Through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Sino-Japanese_War\">Second Sino-Japanese War</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_United_Front\">Second United Front</span> with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span>, an alliance cemented after the 1936 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi'an_Incident\">Xi'an Incident</span>, the base became the nerve centre of a fast-growing movement whose <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eighth_Route_Army\">Eighth Route Army</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Fourth_Army\">New Fourth Army</span>, the renamed remnants of the old <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Red_Army\">Red Army</span>, waged guerrilla resistance behind Japanese lines. Party membership swelled <b>from around 40,000 in 1937</b> to an estimated 1.2 million by 1945, and the leadership gathered figures such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_De\">Zhu De</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Shaoqi\">Liu Shaoqi</span> around the steadily ascendant Mao. <br> <br> The years there, commonly remembered as the Yan'an period, saw Mao consolidate both his political authority and a distinctive body of doctrine that adapted <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marxism\">Marxism</span> to Chinese peasant conditions, set out in influential writings such as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"On_Protracted_War\"><i>On Protracted War</i></span></b>. Between 1942 and 1945 he tightened his control through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yan'an_Rectification_Movement\">Rectification Movement</span>, a sweeping campaign of compulsory study, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Self-criticism\">self-criticism</span>, and purges that disciplined the membership, sidelined Soviet-aligned rivals such as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Ming\">Wang Ming</span></b>, and entrenched the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mass_line\">mass line</span> as a doctrine of leadership. Cultural and intellectual life was reshaped to serve the revolution, most famously at the 1942 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yan'an_Forum_on_Literature_and_Art\">Yan'an Forum on Literature and Art</span>, where Mao decreed that art and literature must serve the masses and the political aims of the Party. The base also attracted outside attention, as the American journalist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Edgar_Snow\">Edgar Snow</span> publicised the movement in his widely read <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Red_Star_Over_China\"><i>Red Star Over China</i></span>, and the United States dispatched the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dixie_Mission\">Dixie Mission</span></b> in 1944 to open the earliest official contacts with the communists. By the time the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"7th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">7th Party Congress</span> of 1945 enshrined <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maoism\">Mao Zedong Thought</span> in the Party's constitution, the town had become the spiritual home of the revolution, and although <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span>'s armies seized the deliberately abandoned settlement in 1947, the strength amassed there propelled the renamed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army\">People's Liberation Army</span> through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">Chinese Civil War</span> to the founding of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Republic_of_China\">People's Republic of China</span> in 1949.","citation":"","answerText":"Yan'an"},{"id":"em-094","num":"九十四","category":"War with Japan · Outbreak","question":"A clash between Chinese and Japanese troops near Beijing in July 1937, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> escalated into full-scale war and is generally taken as the start of the conflict that merged into the Second World War.","answer":"Marco Polo Bridge Incident","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">7 July 1937 · near Beiping</span></div>","traditional":"盧溝橋事變","hanzi":"卢沟桥事变","pinyin":"Lúgōuqiáo Shìbiàn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Lúgōuqiáo Shìbiàn</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Lugou Bridge Incident”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Marco Polo Bridge Incident</b>, also known in China as the <b>Double-Seven Incident</b> for its date, was a battle between Chinese and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empire_of_Japan\">Japanese</span> forces in July 1937 that is generally regarded as the opening of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Sino-Japanese_War\">Second Sino-Japanese War</span>. It took its Western name from the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lugou_Bridge\">Lugou Bridge</span></b> near <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>, a 12th-century stone arch bridge over the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yongding_River\">Yongding River</span> built under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jin_dynasty_(1115–1234)\">Jin dynasty</span> and famously described during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan dynasty</span> by the Venetian traveller <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marco_Polo\">Marco Polo</span> in his <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Travels_of_Marco_Polo\"><i>Travels</i></span>. Under the terms of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boxer_Protocol\">Boxer Protocol</span> imposed after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boxer_Rebellion\">Boxer Rebellion</span>, the Japanese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Garrison_Army\">China Garrison Army</span> maintained troops in the region, and tensions had been mounting steadily <b>since the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mukden_Incident\">Mukden Incident</span> of 1931</b> and the creation of the puppet state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchukuo\">Manchukuo</span>. <b>On the night of 7 July 1937</b>, after a Japanese soldier briefly went missing during night manoeuvres, the Japanese demanded entry to the walled town of Wanping in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hebei\">Hebei</span> to search for him, and when the Chinese garrison of the 29th Army under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_Zheyuan\">Song Zheyuan</span> refused, shots were exchanged and fighting erupted around the bridge. Although the missing soldier soon rejoined his unit and a fragile truce was patched together, the clash rapidly spiralled out of control as both sides rushed in reinforcements, and by the end of July 1937 the Japanese had captured the old northern capital and the great port of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tianjin\">Tianjin</span>. <br> <br> Unlike the deliberately staged Mukden Incident, the confrontation at the bridge appears to have begun as a more spontaneous skirmish, yet it ignited the all-out <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_Japanese_Army\">Imperial Japanese Army</span></b> invasion that engulfed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"North_China\">North China</span> and rapidly spread across the country. It marked the moment at which the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nationalist_government\">Nationalist government</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)\">Republic of China</span> abandoned its policy of avoidance, as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span> declared at <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mount_Lu\">Mount Lu</span></b> that the nation had reached its final juncture and must resist. The crisis also drove the rival <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> into a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_United_Front\">Second United Front</span>, nominally uniting their forces, including a reorganised <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Revolutionary_Army\">National Revolutionary Army</span>, against the common enemy. Within months the war exploded into the ferocious <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Shanghai\">Battle of Shanghai</span></b> and then the atrocities of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing_Massacre\">Nanjing Massacre</span> of December 1937, opening a conflict that would rage for eight years and claim many millions of lives. By drawing China into a total war that would eventually merge with the Allied struggle against Japan in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pacific_War\">Pacific War</span>, the incident is widely treated as the true start of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_War_II\">World War II</span> in Asia, the point at which a regional confrontation became part of a global conflagration.","citation":"","answerText":"Marco Polo Bridge Incident"},{"id":"em-095","num":"九十五","category":"War with Japan · The War","question":"Raging from 1937 to 1945 and merging into the wider Second World War, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> saw Japan occupy the coast and major cities while Nationalist and Communist forces resisted, at a cost of millions of Chinese lives.","answer":"Second Sino-Japanese War","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Began</span><span class=\"dt-v\">7 July 1937 · Marco Polo Bridge Incident</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Ended</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1945 · Japanese surrender</span></div>","traditional":"抗日戰爭","hanzi":"抗日战争","pinyin":"Kàngrì Zhànzhēng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Kàngrì Zhànzhēng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Second Sino-Japanese War</b> was a large-scale military conflict between the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)\">Republic of China</span></b> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empire_of_Japan\">Empire of Japan</span> that raged from 1937 to 1945, known in China as the War of Resistance against Japanese Aggression and remembered as one of the deadliest theatres of the global war that engulfed Asia. Its roots lay in decades of Japanese expansionism on the Asian mainland, beginning with the seizure of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchuria\">Manchuria</span> <b>after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mukden_Incident\">Mukden Incident</span> of 1931</b> and the creation of the puppet state of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchukuo\">Manchukuo</span>, which has led some historians to date the conflict's true beginning to that earlier invasion. Full-scale hostilities <b>erupted on July 7, 1937</b>, when a confrontation at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marco_Polo_Bridge_Incident\">Marco Polo Bridge</span> escalated into open war and prompted an uneasy <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_United_Front\">Second United Front</span> in which the ruling <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span> under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> led by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> suspended their own civil war to resist the invaders. After months of fierce fighting at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Shanghai\">Battle of Shanghai</span>, Japanese forces captured the Nationalist capital of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span> in December 1937 and perpetrated the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing_Massacre\">Nanjing Massacre</span>, an atrocity in which Chinese sources estimate that some 300,000 civilians and disarmed soldiers were killed over roughly 6 weeks. The government relocated inland to a new wartime capital at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chongqing\">Chongqing</span>, which endured years of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bombing_of_Chongqing\">sustained aerial bombardment</span>, while Japanese measures such as the scorched-earth <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Alls_policy\">Three Alls policy</span></b> and the lethal human experimentation of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Unit_731\">Unit 731</span> compounded the suffering of the civilian population. <br> <br> As the front lines stabilised, Communist units organised as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eighth_Route_Army\">Eighth Route Army</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Fourth_Army\">New Fourth Army</span> waged guerrilla warfare behind enemy lines, most prominently in the 1940 <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hundred_Regiments_Offensive\">Hundred Regiments Offensive</span></b>, dramatically enlarging their rural base areas and membership during the war. Japan in turn sponsored a collaborationist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Jingwei_regime\">Reorganised National Government</span> led by the defector <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Jingwei\">Wang Jingwei</span>, even as the fighting uprooted civilians on a colossal scale, with estimates of up to 80 to 100 million refugees displaced across the country. The struggle merged into the global <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pacific_War\">Pacific War</span> following the Japanese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Attack_on_Pearl_Harbor\">attack on Pearl Harbor</span> in December 1941, after which China formally joined the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Allies_of_World_War_II\">Allies</span> and received supplies along the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Burma_Road\">Burma Road</span> and guidance from American advisers such as General <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joseph_Stilwell\">Joseph Stilwell</span>. Japan mounted its largest land offensive, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Operation_Ichi-Go\">Operation Ichi-Go</span></b>, in 1944, yet the war in China was finally brought to a close by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_invasion_of_Manchuria\">Soviet invasion of Manchuria</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Atomic_bombings_of_Hiroshima_and_Nagasaki\">atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Surrender_of_Japan\">surrender of Japan</span> declared <b>by Emperor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hirohito\">Hirohito</span> in August 1945</b>. By its conclusion the war had pinned down more than 1 million Japanese troops on the mainland and ravaged China, with widely cited estimates putting total Chinese military and civilian deaths at between 14 and 20 million, and within months the wartime alliance disintegrated as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">Chinese Civil War</span> resumed and carried the Communists towards their triumph in 1949.","citation":"","answerText":"Second Sino-Japanese War"},{"id":"em-096","num":"九十六","category":"War with Japan · Atrocity","question":"Following the fall of the Nationalist capital in December 1937, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> saw Japanese troops kill vast numbers of civilians and disarmed soldiers and commit widespread sexual violence over several weeks, a war crime that remains a grievous source of tension with Japan.","answer":"Nanjing Massacre","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">From</span><span class=\"dt-v\">13 December 1937 · Nanjing</span></div>","traditional":"南京大屠殺","hanzi":"南京大屠杀","pinyin":"Nánjīng Dàtúshā","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Nánjīng Dàtúshā</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Nanjing Massacre</b>, also widely known as the Rape of Nanking, was a period of mass murder and mass rape committed by the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_Japanese_Army\">Imperial Japanese Army</span></b> against the residents of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span>, then the capital of the Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nationalist_government\">Nationalist government</span>, during the opening months of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Sino-Japanese_War\">Second Sino-Japanese War</span>. The atrocity began after Japanese forces <b>captured the city on December 13, 1937</b>, following the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Nanking\">Battle of Nanking</span></b>, from which <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span> had already ordered the withdrawal of the main <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Revolutionary_Army\">National Revolutionary Army</span> units, leaving a poorly coordinated rearguard and tens of thousands of trapped soldiers and civilians. Over <b>a span of roughly 6 weeks</b>, Japanese troops under the overall <b>command of General <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Iwane_Matsui\">Iwane Matsui</span></b> and the field leadership of Prince <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Prince_Yasuhiko_Asaka\">Yasuhiko Asaka</span> systematically executed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Prisoner_of_war\">prisoners of war</span> and disarmed combatants, carried out mass shootings and bayonet killings along the banks of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze River</span>, and engaged in widespread looting and arson. Estimates of the death toll vary enormously, ranging from fewer than 50,000 in some Japanese accounts to the 300,000 figure maintained by the Chinese government, while the postwar <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"International_Military_Tribunal_for_the_Far_East\">International Military Tribunal for the Far East</span> concluded that more than 200,000 people were killed and that between 20,000 and 80,000 women and girls were raped. Amid the violence, a small group of Western expatriates established the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing_Safety_Zone\">Nanjing Safety Zone</span></b>, a demilitarised district led by the German businessman and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nazi_Party\">Nazi Party</span> member <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"John_Rabe\">John Rabe</span> alongside the American educator <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Minnie_Vautrin\">Minnie Vautrin</span>, which is credited with sheltering as many as 250,000 civilians. <br> <br> In the years <b>after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Surrender_of_Japan\">surrender of Japan</span> in 1945</b>, several commanders were prosecuted for the killings, with Matsui and the field general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tani_Hisao\">Tani Hisao</span> convicted and executed, the former before the Tokyo tribunal and the latter by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing_War_Crimes_Tribunal\">Nanjing War Crimes Tribunal</span>, which classified the events as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"War_crime\">war crimes</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Crimes_against_humanity\">crimes against humanity</span>. The scale and even the occurrence of the massacre have since become the focus of persistent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing_Massacre_denial\">historical denial</span> by some Japanese nationalists, fueling recurring <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japanese_history_textbook_controversies\">textbook controversies</span> and diplomatic friction over how the war is remembered. Contemporaneous evidence preserved by foreign witnesses, including diaries, the documentary footage shot by the missionary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"John_Magee_(missionary)\">John Magee</span>, and dispatches filed by correspondents of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_New_York_Times\">The New York Times</span>, has been central to historians' reconstruction of the events. Public awareness in the English-speaking world was greatly amplified by the 1997 bestseller <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Rape_of_Nanking_(book)\"><i>The Rape of Nanking</i></span> by the Chinese-American writer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Iris_Chang\">Iris Chang</span>, and in 2015 documentary records of the atrocity were inscribed on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"UNESCO\">UNESCO</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Memory_of_the_World\">Memory of the World</span> register over Japanese objections. Today the killings are commemorated at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing_Massacre_Memorial_Hall\">Nanjing Massacre Memorial Hall</span> and through a national day of remembrance, and they endure as one of the most contentious issues in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China–Japan_relations\">China–Japan relations</span>, periodically inflamed by official visits to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yasukuni_Shrine\">Yasukuni Shrine</span> where convicted war criminals are among those enshrined.","citation":"","answerText":"Nanjing Massacre"},{"id":"em-097","num":"九十七","category":"War with Japan · The United Front","question":"Formed in 1937 after the Xi'an Incident, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> again paired the Nationalists and the Communists, this time against Japan, though it was strained by clashes such as the New Fourth Army incident.","answer":"Second United Front","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Began</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1937 · KMT–CCP against Japan</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Ended</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1945 · end of the war</span></div>","traditional":"第二次國共合作","hanzi":"第二次国共合作","pinyin":"Dì-èr-cì Guó-Gòng Hézuò","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Dì-èr-cì Guó-Gòng Hézuò</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Second KMT–CCP Cooperation”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Second United Front</b> was the wartime alliance formed in 1937 between the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> to resist the Japanese invasion of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Sino-Japanese_War\">Second Sino-Japanese War</span>. It revived a partnership that had ended a decade earlier when the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_United_Front\">First United Front</span> collapsed in the <b>1927 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_massacre\">Shanghai massacre</span></b>, after which the two parties had fought a bitter <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">civil war</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Encirclement_Campaigns\">encirclement campaigns</span> that drove the Communists onto the epic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Long_March\">Long March</span>. The reconciliation was forced by the dramatic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi'an_Incident\">Xi'an Incident</span> of December 1936, when the generals <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Xueliang\">Zhang Xueliang</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yang_Hucheng\">Yang Hucheng</span> kidnapped <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span> to compel him to halt the anti-Communist war, a resolution brokered partly by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span> and aligned with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Communist_International\">Comintern</span>'s contemporary <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Popular_front\">popular front</span></b> against fascism. Cooperation was hastily <b>formalised in September 1937</b>, two months after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marco_Polo_Bridge_Incident\">Marco Polo Bridge Incident</span> had ignited full-scale war, with the Communists pledging to abandon their armed overthrow of the government and to dissolve the rural <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Soviet_Republic\">Chinese Soviet Republic</span>. In return the Communist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Red_Army\">Red Army</span> was nominally absorbed into the Nationalist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Revolutionary_Army\">National Revolutionary Army</span>, its main force becoming the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eighth_Route_Army\">Eighth Route Army</span> under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_De\">Zhu De</span> while its southern guerrillas were reorganised as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Fourth_Army\">New Fourth Army</span></b> under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ye_Ting\">Ye Ting</span>. <br> <br> The alliance was always a fragile marriage of convenience, for both sides continued to manoeuvre for postwar advantage, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> reportedly directed his followers to devote the bulk of their energy to expanding Communist power rather than to fighting the Japanese. The deepest rupture came with the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Fourth_Army_incident\">New Fourth Army incident</span></b> of January 1941, when Nationalist troops ambushed and destroyed the headquarters column of roughly 9,000 New Fourth Army soldiers in southern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anhui\">Anhui</span>, capturing its commander Ye Ting and leaving his deputy <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiang_Ying\">Xiang Ying</span> dead. Despite such clashes the front endured in name, and under its cover the Communist movement expanded enormously from its base around <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yan'an\">Yan'an</span>, its membership swelling from roughly 40,000 in 1937 to around 1.2 million by 1945 and its armies to some 900,000 regular troops. While the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nationalist_government\">Nationalist government</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)\">Republic of China</span> bore the brunt of conventional resistance from its wartime capital at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chongqing\">Chongqing</span>, this rural growth left the Communists far stronger at the war's end than they had been at its beginning. Holding together precariously until <b>the Japanese surrender in 1945</b> brought the wider <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_War_II\">Second World War</span> to a close, the front swiftly disintegrated as the two former partners plunged back into the civil war that would end in Communist victory four years later.","citation":"","answerText":"Second United Front"},{"id":"em-099","num":"九十九","category":"War with Japan · Allied Aid","question":"A group of American volunteer pilots flying shark-mouthed fighters under Claire Chennault, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> defended Chinese skies and the supply route against Japan in the early 1940s, becoming a celebrated symbol of American aid.","answer":"Flying Tigers","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Formed</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1941 · American volunteer pilots</span><span class=\"dt-k\">Disbanded</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1942 · absorbed into the USAAF</span></div>","traditional":"飛虎隊","hanzi":"飞虎队","pinyin":"Fēihǔduì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Fēihǔduì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Flying Tigers</b> was the popular nickname of the <b>First American Volunteer Group</b> (Simplified: 美国志愿航空队; Traditional: 美國志願航空隊) (<b>AVG</b>), a force of American fighter pilots and ground crew recruited in 1941, with covert backing from Washington, to defend the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)\">Republic of China</span> against <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Empire_of_Japan\">Japan</span> during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Sino-Japanese_War\">Second Sino-Japanese War</span>. Organised by the retired Army aviator <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Claire_Lee_Chennault\">Claire Lee Chennault</span></b> at the urging of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span> and his wife <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soong_Mei-ling\">Soong Mei-ling</span>, the group was quietly sanctioned <b>by President <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Franklin_D._Roosevelt\">Franklin Roosevelt</span> in early 1941</b>, which allowed serving members of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States_Army_Air_Forces\">Army Air Forces</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States_Navy\">Navy</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States_Marine_Corps\">Marine Corps</span> to resign and enlist as civilians through the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Aircraft_Manufacturing_Company\">Central Aircraft Manufacturing Company</span></b>. Roughly 100 pilots and some 200 support staff were equipped with about 100 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Curtiss_P-40_Warhawk\">Curtiss P-40</span> fighters, contracted at $600 a month plus a $500 bounty for every Japanese aircraft confirmed destroyed, and divided into 3 squadrons nicknamed the Adam and Eves, the Panda Bears, and Hell's Angels. The aircraft became instantly recognisable for the fierce <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shark_mouth\">shark-mouth</span> nose art borrowed from <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Royal_Air_Force\">Royal Air Force</span></b> machines in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"North_African_campaign\">North Africa</span>, complemented by a winged-tiger emblem reportedly designed by artists at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Walt_Disney_Productions\">Walt Disney Productions</span>. Training from a base at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Toungoo\">Toungoo</span> in British <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"British_rule_in_Burma\">Burma</span>, the pilots embraced Chennault's hit-and-run tactics of diving on enemy formations rather than dogfighting, and they first saw combat on December 20, 1941, less than 2 weeks after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Attack_on_Pearl_Harbor\">attack on Pearl Harbor</span>. <br> <br> Operating from bases at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kunming\">Kunming</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yunnan\">Yunnan</span> and at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangon\">Rangoon</span>, the group fought to shield Chinese cities and the vital <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Burma_Road\">Burma Road</span>, the overland lifeline through which Allied war supplies reached the Nationalist interior after Japan had seized the country's coastal ports. During roughly 7 months of combat the unit was officially credited with destroying some 296 enemy aircraft while losing only about 14 of its own pilots, a lopsided record that turned it into a propaganda sensation in the United States during the bleak months of repeated Allied defeats across the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pacific_War\">Pacific</span>. <b>On July 4, 1942</b>, the group was disbanded and folded into the regular American military as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"23rd_Fighter_Group\">23rd Fighter Group</span></b> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Air_Task_Force\">China Air Task Force</span>, whose lineage Chennault would later command as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fourteenth_Air_Force\">Fourteenth Air Force</span>. The Flying Tigers name and shark-toothed imagery proved so popular at home that they were swiftly commemorated in the 1942 film <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Flying_Tigers_(film)\"><i>Flying Tigers</i></span> starring <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"John_Wayne\">John Wayne</span>, while veteran airmen such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gregory_Boyington\">Gregory Boyington</span> went on to wider renown in their own right. Although postwar study showed that the group's victory claims, like those of all combatant air forces, were inflated, the Flying Tigers endured as one of the most celebrated symbols of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lend-Lease\">Lend-Lease</span> aid to China, as a model for later volunteer air units, and as a lasting emblem of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Allies_of_World_War_II\">Allied</span></b> cooperation during <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_War_II\">World War II</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Flying Tigers"},{"id":"cnp-077","num":"七十七","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Rising through the Communist Youth League and serving as top leader from <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> governed in a more collective style alongside premier Wen Jiabao, promoting slogans about development and social harmony before yielding to Xi Jinping.","answer":"Hu Jintao","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">born December 21, 1942</span></div>","traditional":"胡錦濤","hanzi":"胡锦涛","pinyin":"Hú Jǐntāo","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Hú Jǐntāo</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Hu Jintao</b> is a retired Chinese engineer and statesman who served as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"General_Secretary_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">General Secretary of the Chinese Communist Party</span> <b>from 2002</b> to 2012 and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"President_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">President</span> of China from 2003 to 2013, presiding as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paramount_leader\">paramount leader</span> over a decade of breakneck economic growth. Born into a family of tea merchants in Taizhou, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiangsu\">Jiangsu</span> province, he earned a degree in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hydraulic_engineering\">hydraulic engineering</span> <b>from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tsinghua_University\">Tsinghua University</span> in 1965</b> and spent his early career as a technocrat in remote <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gansu\">Gansu</span> province, where he gained the patronage of the party elder <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_Ping\">Song Ping</span>. He rose rapidly through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Communist_Youth_League_of_China\">Communist Youth League</span>, becoming its national leader in the mid-1980s and the nucleus of the political network later known as the tuanpai, before being dispatched to govern the impoverished provinces of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guizhou\">Guizhou</span> and then <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibet_Autonomous_Region\">Tibet</span>. As party secretary in Tibet he imposed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Martial_law\">martial law</span> in <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lhasa\">Lhasa</span> amid unrest in 1989</b>, and in 1992 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> elevated the 49-year-old to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_Standing_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo Standing Committee</span>, marking him out as an eventual successor to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Zemin\">Jiang Zemin</span>. After serving as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vice_President_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">Vice President</span> from 1998, he took over as general secretary at the 16th <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"16th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Party Congress</span></b> in 2002, though Jiang and his <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_clique\">Shanghai clique</span> retained considerable influence and Jiang clung to the chairmanship of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Military_Commission_(China)\">Central Military Commission</span> until 2004. <br> <br> Governing in a comparatively <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Collective_leadership\">collective</span> and consensus-driven style alongside Premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wen_Jiabao\">Wen Jiabao</span>, the cautious \"Hu–Wen\" leadership emphasized stability and incremental policy over the personalized rule of his predecessors. His administration promoted the guiding ideology of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Scientific_Outlook_on_Development\">Scientific Outlook on Development</span>, written into the party constitution at the 17th <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"17th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Party Congress</span> in 2007, together with the goal of building a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Harmonious_Society\">harmonious society</span></b> to address the widening inequality produced by rapid growth. Under his rule China abolished its agricultural tax in 2006, ending a levy that had endured for more than 2,000 years, hosted the 2008 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2008_Summer_Olympics\">Beijing Olympics</span>, and overtook Japan to become the world's second-largest <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">economy</span> in 2010, with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gross_domestic_product\">gross domestic product</span> expanding by roughly 10% a year. The decade was punctuated by crises, including the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2002–2004_SARS_outbreak\">SARS epidemic</span></b> of 2003, the devastating <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2008_Sichuan_earthquake\">Sichuan earthquake</span> of 2008 that killed some 87,000 people, ethnic unrest in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2008_Tibetan_unrest\">Tibet</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"July_2009_Ürümqi_riots\">Xinjiang</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Recession\">global financial crisis</span>, which Beijing countered with a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_stimulus_program\">stimulus package</span> of about 4 trillion</b> yuan. Hu handed the party and military leadership to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span> at the 18th <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"18th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Party Congress</span> in 2012 in what was hailed as an orderly transfer of power—his protégé <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Keqiang\">Li Keqiang</span> becoming premier the next year—yet he returned to global headlines in October 2022 when he was abruptly escorted from the closing session of the 20th <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"20th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Party Congress</span> before the cameras, an episode widely read as emblematic of the eclipse of his more consultative style of rule.","citation":"","answerText":"Hu Jintao"},{"id":"cnp-078","num":"七十八","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Known for a folksy public image and frequent appearances at disaster sites, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> managed the economy alongside Hu Jintao and oversaw the response to the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> Sichuan earthquake.","answer":"Wen Jiabao","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">born 15 September 1942</span></div>","traditional":"溫家寶","hanzi":"温家宝","pinyin":"Wēn Jiābǎo","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Wēn Jiābǎo</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Wen Jiabao</b> is a retired Chinese politician who served as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Premier_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">Premier</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_Council_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">State Council</span> <b>from 2003</b> to 2013, functioning as the head of government and chief economic manager of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span>. Born in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tianjin\">Tianjin</span> to a family of teachers, he trained as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Geology\">geologist</span> at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_University_of_Geosciences\">Beijing Institute of Geology</span> and spent more than a decade conducting surveys in the remote northwestern province of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gansu\">Gansu</span> before transferring into party administration in the early 1980s. As director of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Communist Party</span>'s General Office he served reformist leaders <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Yaobang\">Hu Yaobang</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhao_Ziyang\">Zhao Ziyang</span>, and he famously accompanied Zhao to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tiananmen_Square\">Tiananmen Square</span> to address student demonstrators during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1989_Tiananmen_Square_protests_and_massacre\"><b>1989</b> protests</span>, yet survived the ensuing purge to continue his ascent. He served as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vice_Premier_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">vice premier</span> overseeing agriculture and finance under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_Rongji\">Zhu Rongji</span>, ascended to <b>the supreme <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_Standing_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo Standing Committee</span> in 2002</b>, and succeeded Zhu as premier when the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_People's_Congress\">National People's Congress</span> confirmed the new cabinet in March 2003. Together with President <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Jintao\">Hu Jintao</span> he formed the so-called 4th <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Generations_of_Chinese_leadership\">generation of leadership</span>, and he cultivated a folksy, accessible persona, earning the affectionate nickname \"Grandpa Wen\" through a brand of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Populism\">populism</span> rarely associated with senior Chinese officials. <br> <br> This common touch was reinforced by frequent, highly publicised visits to disaster zones and impoverished villages, beginning with the government's belated but ultimately more transparent handling of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2002–2004_SARS_outbreak\">SARS epidemic</span></b> shortly after he took office in 2003. On the domestic front his administration abolished the centuries-old <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taxation_in_China\">agricultural tax</span> in 2006, ending a levy on farmers that had endured in various forms for more than 2,000 years, while expanding rural healthcare and waiving compulsory schooling fees. His most iconic moment came after the catastrophic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2008_Sichuan_earthquake\">Sichuan earthquake</span> of 12 May 2008, a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Moment_magnitude_scale\">magnitude</span></b>-7.9 disaster in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan\">Sichuan</span> province that left roughly 87,000 people dead or missing, when he flew to the devastated region within hours to direct rescue operations before the cameras. Confronting the global <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2008_financial_crisis\">financial crisis</span> later that year, his government unveiled a stimulus package of 4 trillion <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Renminbi\">yuan</span>, roughly 586 billion US dollars, that helped sustain growth of around 10 percent and propelled the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">economy</span> past that of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japan\">Japan</span> to become the world's 2nd largest by 2010. His final year was clouded by a 2012 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_New_York_Times\">New York Times</span> investigation, which won a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pulitzer_Prize\">Pulitzer Prize</span></b> for reporter <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"David_Barboza\">David Barboza</span> and alleged that his relatives had amassed assets worth at least 2.7 billion US dollars, and after handing the premiership to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Keqiang\">Li Keqiang</span> in 2013 he largely withdrew from public life, resurfacing in 2021 with a wistful tribute to his late mother that censors blocked from circulating widely on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"WeChat\">WeChat</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Wen Jiabao"},{"id":"cne-030","num":"三十","category":"China · Economics","question":"A former army engineer who started a telecoms firm with little capital in Shenzhen in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> built one of China's most successful private companies and is the father of an executive arrested in Canada in a high-profile sanctions case.","answer":"Ren Zhengfei","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">born 25 October 1944</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"任正非","pinyin":"Rén Zhèngfēi","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Rén Zhèngfēi</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Ren Zhengfei</b> is the founder and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chief_executive_officer\">chief executive</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huawei\">Huawei</span></b>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Privately_held_company\">privately held</span> enterprise that grew into the world's largest manufacturer of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Telecommunications_equipment\">telecommunications equipment</span> and one of the most celebrated commercial successes of the post-Mao era. Born into a schoolteacher's family in the southwestern province of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guizhou\">Guizhou</span>, he trained as an engineer and spent years in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Military_engineering\">military engineering</span> corps of the national army before being demobilised in the early 1980s amid sweeping reductions to China's armed forces. <b>In 1987</b>, with reported registered capital of just 21,000 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Renminbi\">yuan</span>—roughly 5,000 US dollars—he founded the company in Shenzhen, then a fledgling <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Special_economic_zones_of_China\">special economic zone</span> at the forefront of China's market <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">economic reforms</span>. Initially reselling imported telephone <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Telephone_exchange\">switches</span> before developing its own technology, Huawei expanded into a <b>global leader in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Telecommunications\">telecommunications</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"5G\">5G</span> networking, a major maker of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Smartphone\">smartphones</span> and other <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Consumer_electronics\">consumer electronics</span>, and an employer of more than 190,000 people in over 170 countries. The firm is distinguished by an <b>unusual model of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Employee_stock_ownership\">employee stock ownership</span></b>, under which Ren is reported to retain only about 1 percent of the shares, while he himself long cultivated a reputation for reclusiveness, rarely granting interviews and tightly guarding details of his life.<br> <br>International attention turned sharply to <b>the family in December 2018</b>, when Ren's daughter <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Meng_Wanzhou\">Meng Wanzhou</span>, Huawei's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chief_financial_officer\">chief financial officer</span>, was detained at the airport in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vancouver\">Vancouver</span> at the request of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States\">United States</span>. The <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States_Department_of_Justice\">Department of Justice</span></b> accused her of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fraud\">fraud</span> bound up with violations of American <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economic_sanctions\">sanctions</span> on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Iran\">Iran</span>, alleging that she had misled the bank <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"HSBC\">HSBC</span> about Huawei's business through a subsidiary, and pressed for her <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Extradition\">extradition</span>. The episode unfolded against a wider contest over technology between <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> and Washington, in which Huawei was placed on <b>the American <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Entity_List\">Entity List</span> in 2019</b> over <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_security\">national security</span> concerns and became a central front in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China–United_States_trade_war\">China–United States trade war</span>. Meng remained confined in Canada until September 2021, when a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deferred_prosecution_agreement\">deferred prosecution agreement</span> secured her return home, an outcome that coincided with the release of two Canadian citizens whom China had detained shortly after her arrest. A member of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Communist Party</span> who has nonetheless been hailed as an emblem of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Entrepreneurship\">entrepreneurial</span> transformation, Ren has come to personify both the global ascent of the country's private technology firms and the geopolitical frictions that ascent has provoked.","citation":"","answerText":"Ren Zhengfei"},{"id":"em-100","num":"一百","category":"Civil War · Postwar Politics","question":"Held for weeks in 1945 just after Japan's surrender, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> brought Mao Zedong to the wartime capital to meet Chiang Kai-shek, producing agreements that quickly broke down as the two sides slid towards all-out civil war.","answer":"Chongqing Negotiations","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Held</span><span class=\"dt-v\">August–October 1945 · Chongqing (Mao & Chiang)</span></div>","traditional":"重慶談判","hanzi":"重庆谈判","pinyin":"Chóngqìng Tánpàn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Chóngqìng Tánpàn</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Chongqing Negotiations</b> were a series of high-level talks held <b>from 28 August</b> to <b>10 October 1945</b> between the ruling <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chongqing\">Chongqing</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nationalist_government\">Nationalist government</span>'s wartime capital, in the immediate aftermath of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Surrender_of_Japan\">surrender of Japan</span>. Coming at the close of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Sino-Japanese_War\">Second Sino-Japanese War</span>, which had raged <b>since 1937</b>, the talks unfolded against a chaotic scramble in which both parties raced to accept Japanese surrenders and seize the cities, weapons, and territory vacated by the occupiers, with the industrial northeast of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchuria\">Manchuria</span> looming especially large after the recent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_invasion_of_Manchuria\">Soviet invasion of Manchuria</span>. <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span> had pressed his rival to attend by sending him 3 telegrams in mid- and late August 1945, and a wary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> flew from the Communist base at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yan'an\">Yan'an</span> only after the American ambassador <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Patrick_J._Hurley\">Patrick J. Hurley</span></b> personally guaranteed his safety and escorted him aboard the aircraft. Both the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Soviet Union</span> under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joseph_Stalin\">Joseph Stalin</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States\">United States</span> pressed for a negotiated settlement, Stalin fearing that renewed warfare might draw in American forces even as his government, having just signed the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-Soviet_Treaty_of_Friendship_and_Alliance\">Sino-Soviet Treaty of Friendship and Alliance</span></b>, had extended formal recognition to Chiang's regime rather than to the Communists. By this juncture the Communists had grown into a formidable rival, having claimed at their <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"7th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Seventh National Congress</span> of April 1945 a regular army of roughly 900,000 soldiers, a militia exceeding 2 million, and \"liberated areas\" inhabited by nearly 100 million people, numbers that stiffened their resolve at the bargaining table. <br> <br> The Communist case was argued on the ground by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Ruofei\">Wang Ruofei</span>, who sought legal recognition of the party, a democratic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Coalition_government\">coalition government</span>, and continued command of its forces, among them the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eighth_Route_Army\">Eighth Route Army</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Fourth_Army\">New Fourth Army</span>. Even as the delegates conferred, fighting erupted in the field, most conspicuously in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shangdang_Campaign\">Shangdang Campaign</span></b> of September and October 1945, in which the Communist commanders <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Bocheng\">Liu Bocheng</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> routed Nationalist troops in southeastern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanxi\">Shanxi</span> and strengthened Mao's position. The talks closed on 10 October 1945 with the signing of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Double_Tenth_Agreement\">Double Tenth Agreement</span>, formally a summary of the conversations, in which the two sides endorsed the principles of peace, national reconstruction, and political democratisation while pledging to avert a renewed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">civil war</span>. The accord nonetheless skirted the most intractable disputes, leaving unresolved the future size and command of the Communist armies that would soon be consolidated into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army\">People's Liberation Army</span>, as well as the governance of the contested liberated zones, and deferring constitutional questions to a promised <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Political_Consultative_Conference\">Political Consultative Conference</span></b>. Although that conference duly convened in January 1946 with 38 delegates and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marshall_Mission\">Marshall Mission</span> headed by the American envoy <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"George_Marshall\">George Marshall</span> laboured for more than a year to broker a durable truce, the fragile understandings swiftly disintegrated amid deepening distrust, plunging the country by mid-1946 into the all-out conflict that would end with the Communist triumph of 1949 and the founding of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Chongqing Negotiations"},{"id":"em-101","num":"一百零一","category":"Civil War · American Mediation","question":"Dispatched by US President Harry Truman in late 1945, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was a year-long effort by the American general George Marshall that tried and failed to broker a lasting peace and coalition between the Nationalists and the Communists.","answer":"Marshall Mission","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Active</span><span class=\"dt-v\">December 1945 – January 1947 · US mediation</span></div>","traditional":"馬歇爾使華","hanzi":"马歇尔使华","pinyin":"Mǎxiēʼěr shǐ Huá","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Mǎxiēʼěr shǐ Huá</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Marshall Mission</b> was a year-long American diplomatic effort, lasting <b>from December 1945</b> to <b>January 1947</b>, in which the recently <b>retired general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"George_Marshall\">George Marshall</span></b> sought to halt the resurgent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">Chinese Civil War</span> and forge a unified <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Coalition_government\">coalition government</span> between the ruling <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Nationalists</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Communists</span>. The initiative arose in the aftermath of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_War_II\">World War II</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Surrender_of_Japan\">surrender of Japan</span> in August 1945, when the abrupt resignation of the previous ambassador <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Patrick_J._Hurley\">Patrick J. Hurley</span> <b>prompted President <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Harry_S._Truman\">Harry Truman</span></b> to dispatch Marshall, his former wartime <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chief_of_Staff_of_the_United_States_Army\">Army Chief of Staff</span>, as special envoy. Earlier talks at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chongqing_Negotiations\">Chongqing Negotiations</span> had produced the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Double_Tenth_Agreement\">Double Tenth Agreement</span> of October 1945 between <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>, yet that accord proved hollow as both sides raced to seize territory and matériel left by the defeated Japanese, especially in resource-rich <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchuria\">Manchuria</span>. Arriving in late December 1945, Marshall swiftly negotiated a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ceasefire\">ceasefire</span> that took <b>effect on 10 January 1946</b> and helped convene the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Political_Consultative_Conference\">Political Consultative Conference</span>, a 38-delegate assembly of rival parties, while a tripartite Committee of Three pairing him with the Nationalist envoy <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Qun\">Zhang Qun</span> and the Communist negotiator <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span> was charged with supervising the truce. A reorganisation plan agreed in February 1946 envisaged merging the Nationalist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Revolutionary_Army\">National Revolutionary Army</span> and the Communist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eighth_Route_Army\">Eighth Route Army</span> into a single national force of 60 divisions, of which only 10 would be Communist, and an Executive Headquarters staffed by mixed truce teams was set up at Beiping, the city now known as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>, to police the fragile peace. <br> <br> The settlement disintegrated within months as full-scale combat resumed across Manchuria, where the withdrawal of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joseph_Stalin\">Joseph Stalin</span>'s occupation troops, which had seized the region during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_invasion_of_Manchuria\">Soviet invasion of Manchuria</span>, left a power vacuum bitterly contested by both armies. In an effort to pressure Chiang's government towards compromise, Marshall imposed an American <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Arms_embargo\">arms embargo</span> that ran from the summer of 1946 until May 1947, even though the United States had already funnelled more than two billion dollars in aid to the Nationalist government since the Japanese surrender. The appointment of the missionary-educator <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"John_Leighton_Stuart\">John Leighton Stuart</span></b> as ambassador in mid-1946 failed to revive the foundering talks, and after a succession of broken truces Marshall concluded in his farewell statement that irreconcilable hardliners on both sides — reactionaries within the Kuomintang and dogmatic elements among the Communists — had doomed any prospect of compromise. Recalled to Washington in January 1947, Marshall was promptly named <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States_Secretary_of_State\">Secretary of State</span> and soon devised the European recovery programme remembered as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marshall_Plan\">Marshall Plan</span></b>, while the abandoned mediation hastened the slide into open civil war and the deepening <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cold_War\">Cold War</span> in Asia. Its failure foreshadowed the Communist military triumph and the founding of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span> in 1949, an outcome that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dean_Acheson\">Dean Acheson</span> later sought to justify in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_White_Paper\">China White Paper</span> and that fuelled the bitter recriminations of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"McCarthyism\">McCarthy era</span> over the question of who had lost China.","citation":"","answerText":"Marshall Mission"},{"id":"cnp-003","num":"三","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Adopted as a guiding ideology of the Communist Party at its 7th National Congress in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> adapts Marxism–Leninism to the conditions of a largely peasant society.","answer":"Mao Zedong Thought","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Origin</span><span class=\"dt-v\">CCP doctrine, enshrined at the 7th Party Congress, 1945</span></div>","traditional":"毛澤東思想","hanzi":"毛泽东思想","pinyin":"Máo Zédōng sīxiǎng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Máo Zédōng sīxiǎng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Mao Zedong Thought</b> denotes the body of political, military, and philosophical doctrine credited to the revolutionary leader <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> and his associates, developed across decades of armed struggle to adapt European <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Communism\">communism</span> to the overwhelmingly rural and pre-industrial conditions of early-20th-century China. Breaking with the orthodox assumption that revolution would be led by an urban <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Proletariat\">proletariat</span>, it identified the <b>impoverished <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peasant\">peasantry</span></b>, who then made up more than 80% of the population, as the decisive revolutionary force, a thesis Mao had first advanced in his 1927 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Report_on_an_Investigation_of_the_Peasant_Movement_in_Hunan\"><i>Report on an Investigation of the Peasant Movement in Hunan</i></span>. These ideas were tempered by the protracted <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">Chinese Civil War</span> and the arduous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Long_March\">Long March</span> of 1934–1935, traditionally said to have covered some 12,500 kilometres (7,770 mi), after which the Communists consolidated a base at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yan'an\">Yan'an</span> and refined the practices of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mass_line\">mass line</span>, the inter-class program of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Democracy\">New Democracy</span>, and a broad <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_front\">united front</span>. It was at Yan'an that Mao composed his principal philosophical essays, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"On_Practice\"><i>On Practice</i></span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"On_Contradiction\"><i>On Contradiction</i></span> of 1937, which recast <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dialectical_materialism\">dialectical materialism</span> in accessible terms, while <b>his 1938 treatise</b> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"On_Protracted_War\"><i>On Protracted War</i></span> set out a three-stage doctrine of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guerrilla_warfare\">guerrilla warfare</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_war\">people's war</span>. The doctrine was formally adopted as a guiding <b>ideology at the party's 7th National Congress</b> in 1945, an assembly of 547 voting delegates and 208 alternate delegates representing roughly 1.21 million members, at which <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Shaoqi\">Liu Shaoqi</span> championed the formula—coined two years earlier, in 1943, by the theoretician <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Jiaxiang\">Wang Jiaxiang</span>—while presenting his report on the revised party constitution.<br> <br>Following the establishment of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span> in 1949, the thought furnished the ideological warrant for sweeping campaigns of land reform and agricultural collectivization that reordered the lives of more than 400 million rural inhabitants. A reference to it was <b>briefly removed</b> from the party constitution at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"8th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">8th National Congress</span> in 1956—a caution prompted in part by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nikita_Khrushchev\">Nikita Khrushchev</span>'s secret denunciation of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joseph_Stalin\">Joseph Stalin</span> that year—yet Mao's authority was scarcely diminished, and the catastrophic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Leap_Forward\">Great Leap Forward</span> of 1958–1962 soon followed, its attendant famine estimated by historians to have caused between 15 and 45 million excess deaths. The associated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cult_of_personality\">cult of personality</span> reached its <b>zenith</b> during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span> of 1966–1976, when Defence Minister <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lin_Biao\">Lin Biao</span> promoted the pocket-sized <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Quotations_from_Chairman_Mao_Tse-tung\"><i>Quotations from Chairman Mao Zedong</i></span>, the so-called \"Little Red Book,\" which was printed in well over a billion copies and became a near-universal emblem of loyalty. After Mao's death in 1976, the interim leadership of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hua_Guofeng\">Hua Guofeng</span> clung to the rigid \"<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Two_Whatevers\">Two Whatevers</span>\" of 1977, but the reformist resurgence of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> reframed the legacy through the <b>1981 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Resolution_on_Certain_Questions_in_the_History_of_Our_Party_Since_the_Founding_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">Resolution on Party History</span></b>, which judged the late chairman to have been 70% correct and 30% wrong. Reconceived as the collective wisdom of the party rather than the infallible word of a single man, the thought endures as the <b>second pillar of official ideology</b> in both the state and party constitutions, ranked beside the later doctrines of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping_Theory\">Deng Xiaoping Theory</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping_Thought\">Xi Jinping Thought</span> and still invoked to underwrite the continuing project of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialism_with_Chinese_characteristics\">socialism with Chinese characteristics</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Mao Zedong Thought"},{"id":"em-102","num":"一百零二","category":"Taiwan · February 28","question":"Erupting in 1947 when the heavy-handed conduct of Nationalist authorities sparked an island-wide uprising, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was violently suppressed, killed thousands on Taiwan, and cast a long shadow over relations between the islanders and the mainlanders who arrived with Chiang Kai-shek.","answer":"February 28 incident","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">28 February 1947 · Taiwan</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"二二八事件","pinyin":"Èr'èrbā shìjiàn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Èr'èrbā shìjiàn</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>February 28 incident</b> was an anti-government <b>uprising on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span> in 1947</b> and the bloody crackdown that followed, carried out by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span>-led government of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)\">Republic of China</span> against the island's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwanese_people\">native population</span>. Taiwan had been <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan_under_Japanese_rule\">ruled by Japan</span> since its cession under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Shimonoseki\">Treaty of Shimonoseki</span> that <b>ended the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Sino-Japanese_War\">First Sino-Japanese War</span> in 1895</b>, and after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Surrender_of_Japan\">Japanese surrender</span> in 1945 its administration passed to a provincial government headed by the mainland official <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Yi_(Kuomintang)\">Chen Yi</span>, whose regime soon became notorious for corruption, mismanagement, runaway <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hyperinflation\">inflation</span>, and profitable state monopolies. Resentment <b>between the established <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Benshengren\">islander population</span></b>, most of them <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hoklo_people\">Hoklo</span> who spoke <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwanese_Hokkien\">Taiwanese</span> and had grown up under Japanese rule, and the incoming <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Waishengren\">mainlanders</span> who dominated the new bureaucracy boiled over on February 27, 1947, when agents of the state tobacco monopoly in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taipei\">Taipei</span> beat a widow caught selling untaxed cigarettes and a bystander was shot dead in the ensuing scuffle. The following day large crowds gathered in protest, government troops fired on demonstrators outside the governor's office, and within days the unrest had spread across the entire island, prompting local elites to form settlement committees that demanded political reform and greater autonomy. Rather than negotiate, Chen Yi appealed to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span>—then preoccupied with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">civil war</span> on the mainland—who dispatched <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Revolutionary_Army\">National Revolutionary Army</span> reinforcements that landed in early March and carried out a sweeping reprisal, with modern estimates of the death toll ranging from roughly 5,000 to 28,000 and a marked targeting of teachers, students, lawyers, and other community leaders. <br> <br> The massacre inaugurated a prolonged era of authoritarian repression known as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"White_Terror_(Taiwan)\">White Terror</span>, reinforced by the <b>imposition of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Martial_law_in_Taiwan\">martial law</span> in 1949</b> that remained in force for 38 years until it was lifted by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Ching-kuo\">Chiang Ching-kuo</span> in 1987, among the longest such periods anywhere in the 20th century. Under the surveillance of bodies such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan_Garrison_Command\">Taiwan Garrison Command</span>, public discussion of the killings became a strict taboo, and for decades the subject was effectively erased from official history and the school curriculum. Only with the island's gradual democratisation in the late 1980s and 1990s, advanced by the opposition <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Democratic_Progressive_Party\">Democratic Progressive Party</span>, could the episode be openly mourned, culminating in a formal state apology by President <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lee_Teng-hui\">Lee Teng-hui</span> in 1995 and the designation of February 28 as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peace_Memorial_Day\">Peace Memorial Day</span></b>. The government subsequently established a compensation foundation and erected sites of memory, among them the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"228_Peace_Memorial_Park\">228 Peace Memorial Park</span> in central Taipei and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_228_Memorial_Museum\">National 228 Memorial Museum</span>, while the event became a central reference point for the <b>broader pursuit of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Transitional_justice\">transitional justice</span></b>. More than any other episode, the incident shaped the emergence of a distinct <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwanese_nationalism\">Taiwanese identity</span> and lent enduring impetus to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan_independence_movement\">Taiwan independence movement</span>, remaining a sensitive touchstone in debates over the island's history and its <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cross-strait_relations\">relationship</span></b> with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mainland_China\">mainland China</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"February 28 incident"},{"id":"cne-038","num":"三十八","category":"China · Economics","question":"A core principle of trade law requiring a country to extend to all partners the best terms it grants any one of them, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was the subject of fraught annual reviews in the US Congress during the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>s before being made permanent ahead of China's entry into the WTO under Bill Clinton.","answer":"Most favoured nation","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Origin</span><span class=\"dt-v\">A trade-treaty principle, codified in the GATT, 1947</span></div>","traditional":"最惠國待遇","hanzi":"最惠国待遇","pinyin":"zuìhuìguó dàiyù","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">zuìhuìguó dàiyù</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Most favoured nation</b> is a <b>core principle of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"International_trade\">international trade</span></b> law requiring a country to extend to all its trading partners the most favourable terms—such as the lowest <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tariff\">tariffs</span>—that it grants to any single one of them. Together with the principle of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_treatment\">national treatment</span>, it forms the bedrock of non-discrimination in the multilateral trading system, enshrined in Article I <b>of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"General_Agreement_on_Tariffs_and_Trade\">General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade</span> of 1947</b> and carried into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Trade_Organization\">World Trade Organization</span> created by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Uruguay_Round\">Uruguay Round</span>. The obligation applies not only to trade in goods under the GATT but also to services under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"General_Agreement_on_Trade_in_Services\">General Agreement on Trade in Services</span> and to intellectual property under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"TRIPS_Agreement\">TRIPS Agreement</span>, making non-discriminatory <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Free_trade\">trade</span></b> a near-universal default that binds the great majority of the world's economies. Long embodied in bilateral <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty\">treaties</span> stretching back centuries, sometimes in conditional and sometimes in unconditional forms, the rule nonetheless admits important exceptions for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Free_trade_agreement\">free-trade agreements</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Customs_union\">customs unions</span> and for the preferential access granted to developing countries under schemes such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Generalized_System_of_Preferences\">Generalized System of Preferences</span>. In the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States\">United States</span> the term was officially renamed <b>\"normal trade relations\" in 1998</b> to signal that such treatment, rather than being a special favour, is the ordinary baseline from which higher <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Trade_barrier\">trade barriers</span> are the exception, leaving <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Multilateralism\">multilateral</span> non-discrimination the rule. <br> <br> For <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>, the status became politically fraught after the two countries normalised relations and signed a trade agreement granting it <b>most-favoured-nation treatment in 1979</b>, treatment made conditional under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jackson–Vanik_amendment\">Jackson–Vanik amendment</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Trade_Act_of_1974\">Trade Act of 1974</span>. Originally aimed at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Soviet Union</span> and other communist states, that amendment tied trade privileges for non-market economies to freedom of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emigration\">emigration</span>, so China's status was not automatic but required an annual presidential waiver that was in turn subject to contentious review by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States_Congress\">United States Congress</span>. After the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1989_Tiananmen_Square_protests_and_massacre\">Tiananmen Square crackdown</span> of 1989, these annual renewals became a bitter battleground in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China–United_States_relations\">Sino-American relations</span>, as critics invoked <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Human_rights_in_China\">human rights in China</span> and the growing bilateral <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Balance_of_trade\">trade deficit</span>. Presidents <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"George_H._W._Bush\">George H. W. Bush</span></b> and then <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bill_Clinton\">Bill Clinton</span> nonetheless renewed the status each year despite intense opposition, with Clinton briefly linking its renewal to human-rights conditions by executive order in 1993 before reversing course and formally delinking trade from human rights in 1994. The annual ritual finally ended when Congress granted permanent normal trade relations through the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States–China_Relations_Act_of_2000\">United States–China Relations Act of 2000</span></b>, clearing the way for China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_and_the_World_Trade_Organization\">entry into the World Trade Organization</span> in 2001 and a surge in trade that reshaped the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">Chinese economy</span>, even as the relationship later soured into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China–United_States_trade_war\">trade war</span> of the 2010s.","citation":"","answerText":"Most favoured nation"},{"id":"cne-001","num":"一","category":"China · Economics","question":"Established in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> on the eve of the founding of the People's Republic and serving for decades as nearly the only bank under a planned economy, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> today sets monetary policy and issues the national currency.","answer":"People's Bank of China","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">established 1 December 1948</span></div>","traditional":"中國人民銀行","hanzi":"中国人民银行","pinyin":"Zhōngguó Rénmín Yínháng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōngguó Rénmín Yínháng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>People's Bank of China</b> is the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_bank\">central bank</span> of the People's Republic of China, <b>established on 1 December 1948</b> in the city of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shijiazhuang\">Shijiazhuang</span> through the amalgamation of three Communist-controlled regional banks during the closing phase of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">Chinese Civil War</span>. For roughly the first three decades of the republic it operated as a <b>\"monobank,\"</b> serving at once as the central bank and as nearly the sole commercial, savings, and lending institution while directing credit to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_enterprise\">state-owned enterprises</span> in accordance with the national plan. From the outset it held the exclusive right to issue the national currency, denominated in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_(currency)\">yuan</span>, whose first series of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Banknote\">banknotes</span> entered circulation on the very day the bank was created. Its autonomy was sharply curtailed amid the upheavals of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Leap_Forward\">Great Leap Forward</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span>, and <b>from 1969 it was absorbed</b> into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ministry_of_Finance_(China)\">Ministry of Finance</span>, regaining a <b>separate existence only in 1978</b>. The sweeping <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">economic reforms</span> launched under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> redefined its mission, and a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_Council_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">State Council</span> decision of 1983 directed it to act exclusively as a central bank from the <b>beginning of 1984</b>, transferring its commercial functions to a new tier of specialized lenders—the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Industrial_and_Commercial_Bank_of_China\">Industrial and Commercial Bank of China</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bank_of_China\">Bank of China</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Agricultural_Bank_of_China\">Agricultural Bank of China</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Construction_Bank\">China Construction Bank</span>.<br> <br>The bank's legal status was codified by the Law on the People's Bank of China, promulgated in 1995, which designated it the formulator and executor of national <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Monetary_policy\">monetary policy</span> while expressly prohibiting it from financing government budget deficits directly. Unlike many of its Western counterparts it possesses little formal independence and remains subordinate to the State Council, relying on instruments such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Reserve_requirement\">reserve requirement ratio</span>, benchmark <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Interest_rate\">interest rates</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Open_market_operation\">open market operations</span> to regulate credit and restrain <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Inflation\">inflation</span>. Long directed by the reform-minded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Xiaochuan\">Zhou Xiaochuan</span>, who served as governor from 2002 to 2018, and thereafter by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yi_Gang\">Yi Gang</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pan_Gongsheng\">Pan Gongsheng</span>, it has pursued the gradual liberalization of interest rates and the cautious internationalization of the currency. Through its affiliated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_Administration_of_Foreign_Exchange\">State Administration of Foreign Exchange</span> it manages the <b>world's largest stockpile of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foreign-exchange_reserves_of_China\">foreign-exchange reserves</span></b>, a holding that has <b>exceeded $3 trillion</b>, and it oversees a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Managed_float_regime\">managed floating</span> currency that in 2016 became the first unit from an emerging market admitted to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"International_Monetary_Fund\">International Monetary Fund</span>'s basket of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Special_drawing_rights\">special drawing rights</span>. In the 21st century it has positioned itself at the frontier of monetary innovation, piloting a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_bank_digital_currency\">central bank digital currency</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Digital_renminbi\">digital yuan</span>, from 2020 and assuming broader <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Macroprudential_regulation\">macroprudential</span> duties after the 2023 founding of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Financial_Regulatory_Administration\">National Financial Regulatory Administration</span>, even though ultimate authority over the financial system continues to rest with the ruling <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Communist Party</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"People's Bank of China"},{"id":"cne-002","num":"二","category":"China · Economics","question":"First issued in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> by the newly formed central bank and counted in units called the yuan, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was for years pegged tightly to the US dollar before moving to a managed float, and is now pushed for cross-border trade under recent initiatives.","answer":"Renminbi","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">first issued 1948</span></div>","traditional":"人民幣","hanzi":"人民币","pinyin":"Rénmínbì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Rénmínbì</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“people's currency”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>renminbi</b> is the official currency of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span>, first <b>issued on 1 December 1948</b> by the newly founded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Bank_of_China\">People's Bank of China</span> as the Communist forces neared victory in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">Chinese Civil War</span>. While the term renminbi denotes the currency as a whole, its base unit is the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_(currency)\">yuan</span></b>—subdivided into ten <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiao_(currency)\">jiao</span> and one hundred fen—a distinction broadly analogous to that between sterling and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pound_sterling\">pound</span>, with the unit assigned the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"ISO_4217\">ISO 4217</span> code CNY and represented by the symbol ¥. The first series, spanning 12 denominations and 62 distinct designs, circulated amid the rampant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hyperinflation\">hyperinflation</span> of the late 1940s and reached values as high as 50,000 yuan, prompting a <b>sweeping revaluation in 1955</b> when a second series replaced the old notes at a rate of 10,000 to one. Successive redesigns followed across third, fourth, and fifth series, and the current fifth series of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Banknotes_of_the_renminbi\">banknotes</span>, first introduced in 1999, bears a uniform portrait of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> across its denominations, which run from 1 to 100 yuan. For decades under the centrally <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Planned_economy\">planned economy</span> the currency remained strictly <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Convertibility\">non-convertible</span> and administratively valued, a posture that began to loosen only with the market liberalisation of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">reform era</span> launched by <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> after 1978</b>. <br> <br> From 1994, following the unification of its dual exchange-rate system, the currency was pegged tightly to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States_dollar\">US dollar</span> at roughly 8.28 yuan per dollar, a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fixed_exchange_rate_system\">fixed-rate</span> arrangement that lent stability to China's export-driven growth but drew persistent foreign criticism that the unit was being held deliberately undervalued. On 21 July 2005 the authorities abandoned the hard peg in favour of a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Managed_float_regime\">managed float</span></b> referenced to a basket of currencies, with the central bank and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_Administration_of_Foreign_Exchange\">State Administration of Foreign Exchange</span> permitting the unit to trade within a daily <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Exchange_rate\">exchange-rate</span> band that was progressively widened from 0.3 percent to 2 percent by 2014. Beijing subsequently promoted the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Internationalization_of_the_renminbi\">internationalisation</span> of the currency, establishing an offshore market in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span> in 2010, signing bilateral <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Currency_swap\">currency swap</span></b> lines with dozens of central banks, and launching the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cross-Border_Interbank_Payment_System\">Cross-Border Interbank Payment System</span> in 2015 to settle transactions outside dollar-centred networks such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"SWIFT\">SWIFT</span>. A landmark came on 1 October 2016 when the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"International_Monetary_Fund\">International Monetary Fund</span> admitted the unit to its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Special_drawing_rights\">Special Drawing Rights</span> basket with an initial weighting of about 10.92 percent, ranking it third behind the dollar and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Euro\">euro</span>, a share later raised to 12.28 percent in the 2022 review. More recently the central bank has piloted a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Digital_renminbi\">digital version of the currency</span></b>, among the first major <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_bank_digital_currency\">central bank digital currencies</span> issued by a large economy, and has pressed cross-border settlement through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Belt_and_Road_Initiative\">Belt and Road Initiative</span>, though it still makes up only a few percent of global <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foreign_exchange_reserves\">foreign exchange reserves</span> and falls far short of the dollar's standing as the world's premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Reserve_currency\">reserve currency</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Renminbi"},{"id":"cnp-006","num":"六","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"First convened in September <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> and continuing today as a united front advisory body that includes the 8 legally permitted minor parties, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> served as an interim constitution.","answer":"Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1949</span></div>","traditional":"中國人民政治協商會議","hanzi":"中国人民政治协商会议","pinyin":"Zhōngguó Rénmín Zhèngzhì Xiéshāng Huìyì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōngguó Rénmín Zhèngzhì Xiéshāng Huìyì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference</b>, commonly abbreviated <b>CPPCC</b>, is the foremost institution of the patriotic united front directed by the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span></b> and the principal forum through which the party engages non-Communist constituencies in advisory consultation. It was first <b>convened in September 1949</b> in Beiping—soon renamed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>—as the Communists completed their victory over the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span> in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">Chinese Civil War</span>, gathering more than 600 delegates from the party, allied groups, ethnic minorities, and prominent independents to act as a provisional national assembly. This inaugural plenary session adopted the Common Program, a provisional constitution grounded in the principles of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Democracy\">New Democracy</span>, and enacted the founding measures of the newly proclaimed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span>. Among those measures, it confirmed Beijing as the national capital, approved the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Flag_of_China\">Flag of China</span> and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Emblem_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">National Emblem</span></b>, adopted <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"March_of_the_Volunteers\"><i>March of the Volunteers</i></span> as the provisional national anthem, and elected a Central People's Government chaired by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>. Mao also served as the conference's inaugural chairman, sharing its leadership with non-Communist vice-chairs such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soong_Ching-ling\">Soong Ching-ling</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Jishen\">Li Jishen</span>, before <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span> <b>assumed the chairmanship in 1954</b>, the same year in which the first <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_People's_Congress\">National People's Congress</span> took over the legislative function and a new <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitution_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">state constitution</span> superseded the Common Program.<br> <br>Once its quasi-legislative powers passed to the National People's Congress, the conference was reconstituted as a purely consultative organ within what is effectively a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"One-party_state\">one-party state</span>, institutionalizing the doctrine of multi-party cooperation under Communist leadership. Its membership unites the 8 legally sanctioned \"democratic parties\"—prominent among them the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Revolutionary_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Kuomintang\">Revolutionary Committee of the Chinese Kuomintang</span></b>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Democratic_League\">China Democratic League</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiusan_Society\">Jiusan Society</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Zhi_Gong_Party\">China Zhi Gong Party</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan_Democratic_Self-Government_League\">Taiwan Democratic Self-Government League</span>—together with the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"All-China_Federation_of_Industry_and_Commerce\">All-China Federation of Industry and Commerce</span></b> and delegates representing ethnic minorities, religious communities, and mass organizations. Coordinated through the party's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_Front_Work_Department\">United Front Work Department</span>, these allied organizations accept the Communist Party's leading role and possess no means of contesting for power, a subordinate position that left many of their members exposed during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hundred_Flowers_Campaign\">Hundred Flowers Campaign</span> and the <b>sweeping <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anti-Rightist_Campaign\">Anti-Rightist Campaign</span> of 1957</b>. The body ceased to meet altogether during the turmoil of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span> and was revived only in 1978, during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boluan_Fanzheng\">Boluan Fanzheng</span> period of rectification and the early <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">economic reforms</span> championed by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>. Today its National Committee of more than 2,000 members convenes each spring in concurrence with the legislature in the joint gatherings popularly known as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Two_sessions\">Two Sessions</span>, where it advances non-binding proposals on national policy while affirming the Communist Party's leadership in the era of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialism_with_Chinese_characteristics\">socialism with Chinese characteristics</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference"},{"id":"cnp-007","num":"七","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Serving as the interim constitution of the new state until the first constitution of <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was drafted under the guidance of Zhou Enlai.","answer":"Common Program","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">29 September 1949</span></div>","traditional":"共同綱領","hanzi":"共同纲领","pinyin":"Gòngtóng Gānglǐng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Gòngtóng Gānglǐng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Common Program</b> was the provisional constitution of the newly founded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span>, formally titled the Common Program of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_People's_Political_Consultative_Conference\">Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference</span></b>, and it furnished the legal and ideological foundation of the new state during its first five years. It was adopted on 29 September 1949 by the first plenary session of that conference, a gathering of some 662 delegates assembled in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beiping</span> — soon renamed Beijing — as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">Chinese Civil War</span> drew to a close, and it took effect just two days before the formal <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Proclamation_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">proclamation of the People's Republic</span> on 1 October 1949</b>. Drafted under the close guidance of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span>, the document comprised 60 articles arranged in 7 chapters covering political organisation, military affairs, economic policy, culture and education, ethnic relations, and foreign affairs. Its general principles defined the country not yet as socialist but as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Democracy\">New Democratic</span> state exercising a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_democratic_dictatorship\">people's democratic dictatorship</span>, a formula derived <b>from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>'s 1940 essay</b> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"On_New_Democracy\"><i>On New Democracy</i></span> that envisaged a transitional coalition led by the working class. This coalition rested on a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Worker-peasant_alliance\">worker-peasant alliance</span> while also embracing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Petite_bourgeoisie\">petite bourgeoisie</span> and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_bourgeoisie\">national bourgeoisie</span></b> — the four classes symbolised by the smaller stars on the new <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Flag_of_China\">national flag</span> — and it pointedly excluded landlords and the defeated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span> reactionaries from political rights. <br> <br> On the institutional side the document vested supreme state authority, pending the future convocation of a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_People's_Congress\">National People's Congress</span>, in the conference itself and in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_People's_Government\">Central People's Government</span></b> Council, the body that elected Mao as the new republic's head of state. Reflecting its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_Front_(China)\">united front</span> character, the framework reserved a substantial role for the recognised <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Minor_parties_in_China\">minor democratic parties</span> and for eminent non-Communist figures such as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soong_Ching-ling\">Soong Ching-ling</span></b>, who was named one of the central government's vice-chairs. In economic and social policy it sanctioned a mixed economy of state, cooperative, private, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_capitalism\">state-capitalist</span> sectors, mandated sweeping <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Land_reform\">land reform</span> to dismantle the old landlord system, and guaranteed expanded rights to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Women_in_China\">women</span> while promising <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Autonomous_regions_of_China\">regional autonomy</span> to the country's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ethnic_minorities_in_China\">ethnic minorities</span>. Its foreign-policy clauses bound the new government to oppose <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperialism\">imperialism</span> and to align closely with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Soviet Union</span> and the other socialist states, a tilt that Mao publicly summarised as a policy of \"leaning to one side\" in the deepening <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cold_War\">Cold War</span>. Although conceived from the outset as a temporary charter, the Common Program governed the republic for nearly five years until it was <b>superseded in 1954</b> by the country's first formal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1954_Constitution_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">Constitution</span>, a transition that marked the official passage from the New Democratic phase toward the construction of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialism\">socialism</span> under an increasingly consolidated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"One-party_state\">one-party state</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Common Program"},{"id":"cnp-008","num":"八","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Marking the formal establishment of a new state at the close of the Civil War, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> saw Mao Zedong declare the founding of the republic from the Tiananmen rostrum on 1 October <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>.","answer":"Proclamation of the People's Republic of China","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1 October 1949</span></div>","traditional":"開國大典","hanzi":"开国大典","pinyin":"Kāiguó Dàdiǎn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Kāiguó Dàdiǎn</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“grand ceremony of the founding of the state”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Proclamation of the People's Republic of China</b> was the <b>founding ceremony held on October 1</b>,<b> 1949</b>, at which <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> formally announced the birth of a new Chinese state and brought the long <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">Chinese Civil War</span> on the mainland to its effective close. Standing on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tiananmen\">Tiananmen</span> rostrum above the vast <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tiananmen_Square\">Tiananmen Square</span>, where a crowd estimated at some 300,000 had assembled, he proclaimed in the capital of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> the establishment of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_People's_Government\">Central People's Government</span></b> as the executive organ of the new republic. The proceedings featured the first public raising of the five-starred red <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Flag_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">national flag</span>, the playing of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"March_of_the_Volunteers\"><i>March of the Volunteers</i></span> as the provisional anthem, a salute of 54 guns fired in 28 volleys representing each year of the Party's struggle since its founding, and a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army\">People's Liberation Army</span> parade commanded by <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nie_Rongzhen\">Nie Rongzhen</span></b>. The newly constituted government installed Mao as chairman alongside 6 vice chairmen—namely <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_De\">Zhu De</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Shaoqi\">Liu Shaoqi</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soong_Ching-ling\">Soong Ching-ling</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Jishen\">Li Jishen</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Lan\">Zhang Lan</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gao_Gang\">Gao Gang</span>—with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span> appointed the first premier and foreign minister. The event marked the culmination of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Revolution\">communist revolution</span></b> led by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span>, whose forces had decisively defeated the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span> after more than 20 years of intermittent conflict. <br> <br> The proclamation had been prepared days earlier by the first <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_People's_Political_Consultative_Conference\">Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference</span>, which convened in September 1949, adopted the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Common_Program\">Common Program</span> as a provisional constitution, and chose the new state's flag, anthem, capital, and calendar. Within a day the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Soviet Union</span> became the first power to extend formal <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Diplomatic_recognition\">diplomatic recognition</span></b>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joseph_Stalin\">Joseph Stalin</span>'s government soon anchored the young republic's foreign alignment in the early <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cold_War\">Cold War</span>. Although the ceremony signaled communist victory, remnants of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)\">Republic of China</span> government retreated to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span> in December 1949, producing a divided sovereignty across the Taiwan Strait that has persisted ever since. The founding placed a nation of roughly 540 million people—then nearly a quarter of humanity—under a single revolutionary government, ending decades of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warlord_Era\">warlord</span> fragmentation, foreign invasion during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Sino-Japanese_War\">war against Japan</span>, and civil strife reaching back through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Long_March\">Long March</span> and beyond. October 1 is commemorated each year as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Day_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">National Day</span>, and the scene was later fixed in national memory through works such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dong_Xiwen\">Dong Xiwen</span>'s <b>celebrated 1953 oil</b> painting <i>The Founding Ceremony of the Nation</i>, a canvas repeatedly altered over the following decades to erase figures who had fallen from political favor.","citation":"","answerText":"Proclamation of the People's Republic of China"},{"id":"cnp-009","num":"九","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Theorised by Mao Zedong in a <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> essay and enshrined in the state constitution, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> describes a state led by the working class and based on an alliance of workers and peasants that exercises dictatorship over class enemies.","answer":"People's democratic dictatorship","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Coined</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Mao Zedong, in his 1949 essay of the same name</span></div>","traditional":"人民民主專政","hanzi":"人民民主专政","pinyin":"Rénmín mínzhǔ zhuānzhèng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Rénmín mínzhǔ zhuānzhèng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>people's democratic dictatorship</b> is the official characterization of state power in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span>, designating a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialist_state\">socialist state</span></b> led by the working class and resting on an alliance of workers and peasants that lies at the heart of the country's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Communism\">communist</span> constitutional order. The concept was a deliberate adaptation of the orthodox <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marxism\">Marxist</span> doctrine of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dictatorship_of_the_proletariat\">dictatorship of the proletariat</span></b>, drawing on the writings of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Karl_Marx\">Karl Marx</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Friedrich_Engels\">Friedrich Engels</span> and on the theory of the state elaborated by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vladimir_Lenin\">Vladimir Lenin</span> in works such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_State_and_Revolution\"><i>The State and Revolution</i></span>. Mao Zedong gave it canonical form in his essay <i>On the People's Democratic Dictatorship</i>, <b>issued on 30 June 1949</b> to mark the 28th anniversary of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span>, building on his earlier theory of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Democracy\">New Democracy</span>, the strategy of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_war\">people's war</span>, and the Marxist premise of unceasing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Class_conflict\">class struggle</span>. Distinguishing \"democracy among the people\" from \"dictatorship over the enemies,\" it conferred political rights on a broad bloc—the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Proletariat\">proletariat</span></b>, the peasantry, the urban <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Petite_bourgeoisie\">petite bourgeoisie</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_bourgeoisie\">national bourgeoisie</span>—while sanctioning coercion against landlords, bureaucratic capitalists, and other designated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Counter-revolutionary\">counter-revolutionaries</span>. This composition of allied classes found symbolic expression in the 4 smaller stars of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Flag_of_China\">Flag of China</span> arranged around the larger star of the Communist Party, and the principle—closely tied to Maoist practices such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mass_line\">mass line</span>—was inscribed in the state constitution as the defining character of the republic.<br> <br>In the same 1949 essay Mao paired the doctrine with the foreign-policy stance of \"leaning to one side,\" committing the new state to alignment with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Soviet Union</span> under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joseph_Stalin\">Joseph Stalin</span>, an orientation soon formalized by the <b>1950 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-Soviet_Treaty_of_Friendship,_Alliance_and_Mutual_Assistance\">Sino-Soviet Treaty of Friendship</span></b>. As the practical machinery of \"dictatorship over the enemies,\" it underwrote a succession of coercive mass campaigns, among them the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Campaign_to_Suppress_Counterrevolutionaries\">Campaign to Suppress Counterrevolutionaries</span> of the early 1950s, the urban <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three-anti_and_Five-anti_Campaigns\">Three-anti and Five-anti Campaigns</span></b>, and—following the brief opening of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hundred_Flowers_Campaign\">Hundred Flowers Campaign</span>—the sweeping <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anti-Rightist_Campaign\">Anti-Rightist Campaign</span>. <b>The constitution of 1954</b> had described the country as a \"people's democratic state,\" but those promulgated in 1975 and 1978, amid the radical climate of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span> and its immediate aftermath, recast it as a \"dictatorship of the proletariat.\" As the reform leadership of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> consolidated power, the formula was rehabilitated, enshrined in 1979 as the 2nd of his <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Cardinal_Principles\">Four Cardinal Principles</span> and restored by the 1982 constitution as the official definition of the state. Official doctrine holds it to be essentially identical to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marxism–Leninism\">Marxist-Leninist</span> dictatorship of the proletariat, and it remains the opening definition of the state under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialism_with_Chinese_characteristics\">socialism with Chinese characteristics</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"People's democratic dictatorship"},{"id":"cnp-019","num":"十九","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Summarised by Mao Zedong in the formula \"from the masses, to the masses\", the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> holds that correct policy is gathered from the scattered ideas of the people and returned to them as systematic guidance.","answer":"Mass line","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Origin</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Developed by Mao Zedong in the Yan'an period, 1940s</span></div>","traditional":"群眾路線","hanzi":"群众路线","pinyin":"Qúnzhòng Lùxiàn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Qúnzhòng Lùxiàn</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>mass line</b> is the principal political and organisational method of leadership in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maoism\">Maoism</span>, by which the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> is enjoined to gather the scattered views of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Proletariat\">masses</span></b>, refine them into coherent policy, and carry that policy back to the people as systematic guidance. <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> distilled this cyclical process into the slogan \"from the masses, to the masses\" and gave it <b>canonical form in his 1943 directive</b> <i>Some Questions Concerning Methods of Leadership</i>, which described how unsystematic popular ideas were to be concentrated through study and then propagated until the masses adopted them as their own. Theoretically the method rested on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marxism–Leninism\">Marxist–Leninist</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Epistemology\">theory of knowledge</span> that Mao had <b>set out in his 1937 essay</b> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"On_Practice\"><i>On Practice</i></span>, applying the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dialectical_materialism\">dialectical-materialist</span> movement from concrete experience to abstract theory and back again to the sphere of political leadership. Although the phrase had circulated in party discourse since the late 1920s, the doctrine matured during the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yan'an_Rectification_Movement\">Yan'an Rectification Movement</span></b> of the early 1940s, when it became a defining feature of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marxism\">Marxist</span> revolutionary practice in China. As a leadership method it was meant to keep the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vanguardism\">vanguard</span> party neither lagging behind nor running ahead of popular consciousness, complementing the organisational principle of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Democratic_centralism\">democratic centralism</span> that the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Leninism\">Leninist</span> party had inherited from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vladimir_Lenin\">Vladimir Lenin</span>. <br> <br> In the revolutionary years the mass line underpinned the CCP's reliance on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peasant\">peasantry</span> and <b>its strategy of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_war\">people's war</span></b>, in which the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guerrilla_warfare\">guerrilla</span> forces of the future <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army\">People's Liberation Army</span> depended on close bonds with the rural population to survive and prevail during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">Chinese Civil War</span>. <b>After 1949</b> the same logic of mobilising the masses was invoked to justify successive campaigns, from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Land_reform_movement\">Land Reform Movement</span> to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Leap_Forward\">Great Leap Forward</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span>, each presented as an expression of the people's own initiative. The mass line was, alongside the integration of theory with practice and the practice of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Self-criticism\">criticism and self-criticism</span>, counted among the three working styles that the party prized, and it was bound up with the related maxim of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Seeking_truth_from_facts\">seeking truth from facts</span> and the <b>cultivation of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Class_consciousness\">class consciousness</span></b> among ordinary people. Critics have long argued that the doctrine in practice inverted its own ideal, since it was the leadership that decided which popular ideas counted as \"correct,\" allowing a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"One-party_state\">one-party</span> apparatus to cloak top-down direction in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Populism\">populist</span> language while doing little to curb the very <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bureaucracy\">bureaucratism</span> it claimed to oppose. Though sidelined during the market reforms that followed Mao's death, the mass line was revived as official rhetoric under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span>, whose 2013 Mass Line Education and Practice Campaign paired an emphasis on humble service to the people with an intensifying <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anti-corruption_campaign_under_Xi_Jinping\">anti-corruption drive</span> and a renewed insistence, amplified through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Propaganda_in_China\">state propaganda</span>, that cadres remain answerable to those they govern.","citation":"","answerText":"Mass line"},{"id":"cnp-029","num":"二十九","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Driven by disputes over de-Stalinisation and peaceful coexistence and by rivalry for leadership of the world communist movement, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> between Mao Zedong's China and the Soviet Union deepened through the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>s.","answer":"Sino-Soviet split","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1960s</span></div>","traditional":"中蘇交惡","hanzi":"中苏交恶","pinyin":"Zhōng-Sū Jiāoʼè","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōng-Sū Jiāoʼè</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Sino-Soviet split</b> was the progressive breakdown of political and ideological relations between the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span> and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Soviet Union</span></b> during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cold_War\">Cold War</span>, a rupture that turned the world's two foremost communist powers from close allies into embittered adversaries across the 1950s and 1960s. Its ideological roots lay in the reforms of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nikita_Khrushchev\">Nikita Khrushchev</span>, whose <b>1956 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"On_the_Cult_of_Personality_and_Its_Consequences\">secret speech</span></b> denouncing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joseph_Stalin\">Joseph Stalin</span> launched a programme of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"De-Stalinization\">de-Stalinisation</span> at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"20th_Congress_of_the_Communist_Party_of_the_Soviet_Union\">20th Congress</span> of the Soviet party, and in <b>his doctrine of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peaceful_coexistence\">peaceful coexistence</span></b> with the capitalist West, both of which <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> condemned as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Revisionism_(Marxism)\">revisionist</span> betrayal of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marxism–Leninism\">Marxism–Leninism</span>. Beneath the doctrinal quarrels ran a contest of national interests, evident in Soviet proposals for joint military facilities that Mao rejected as affronts to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sovereignty\">sovereignty</span>, in Moscow's refusal to back Beijing <b>during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_Taiwan_Strait_Crisis\">Second Taiwan Strait Crisis</span> of 1958</b>, in the abrupt Soviet withdrawal of promised <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_and_weapons_of_mass_destruction\">nuclear assistance</span> in 1959, and in Soviet neutrality during the deepening <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-Indian_War\">Sino-Indian</span> border dispute. These tensions erupted into the open at a succession of international communist conferences in 1960, and that July the leadership of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Communist_Party_of_the_Soviet_Union\">Communist Party of the Soviet Union</span> abruptly recalled some 1,390 advisers and technicians and annulled hundreds of cooperation agreements, dealing a crippling blow to Chinese industry just as the country reeled from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Chinese_Famine\">Great Chinese Famine</span> precipitated by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Leap_Forward\">Great Leap Forward</span>. In the resulting realignment of the communist world, Beijing drew close to the hardline <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Albania\">Albania</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Enver_Hoxha\">Enver Hoxha</span> while denouncing the Soviet embrace of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Josip_Broz_Tito\">Josip Broz Tito</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yugoslavia\">Yugoslavia</span>, and the rift was dramatised when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span> walked out of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"22nd_Congress_of_the_Communist_Party_of_the_Soviet_Union\">22nd Congress</span></b> in 1961. <br> <br> The quarrel hardened into a public ideological war, the so-called Great Polemic of 1963–1964, during which the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> published a series of open letters denouncing Soviet <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Communism\">communism</span> as a capitulation to imperialism, while the contest for leadership of the movement was further inflamed by their opposing reactions to the 1962 <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cuban_Missile_Crisis\">Cuban Missile Crisis</span></b> and the concurrent Sino-Indian War. Determined to secure an independent deterrent, China detonated its first <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"596_(nuclear_test)\">atomic bomb</span> in October 1964, and once the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span> erupted in 1966 its propaganda escalated still further, branding the post-Khrushchev Soviet Union a bastion of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Social_imperialism\">social-imperialism</span>. The antagonism reached its most dangerous point in 1969, when the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-Soviet_border_conflict\">Sino-Soviet border conflict</span> flared into deadly clashes around <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhenbao_Island\">Zhenbao Island</span> on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ussuri_River\">Ussuri River</span> and along the frontier in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinjiang\">Xinjiang</span>, bringing the two nuclear-armed neighbours to the very brink of full-scale war. Fear of a Soviet attack drove a momentous strategic reversal, as Mao opened secret channels to Washington that culminated in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1972_visit_by_Richard_Nixon_to_China\">Richard Nixon's 1972 visit</span> and a tacit anti-Soviet partnership that recast the global balance of the Cold War. Normalisation came only haltingly over the following decades, and the long estrangement was finally <b>laid to rest in May 1989</b>, when the Soviet leader <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mikhail_Gorbachev\">Mikhail Gorbachev</span> travelled to Beijing to restore party-to-party ties on the eve of the upheavals soon to engulf the communist world.","citation":"","answerText":"Sino-Soviet split"},{"id":"cnp-059","num":"五十九","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Re-established by the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> constitution after years of abolition and long a largely ceremonial post until combined with the top Party and military offices, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the formal head of state, elected by the National People's Congress.","answer":"President of the PRC","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">国家主席 (Guójiā Zhǔxí, 'state chairman')</span></div>","traditional":"中華人民共和國主席","hanzi":"中华人民共和国主席","pinyin":"Zhōnghuá Rénmín Gònghéguó Zhǔxí","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōnghuá Rénmín Gònghéguó Zhǔxí</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>President of the PRC</b> is the formal <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Head_of_state\">head of state</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span></b>, an office whose Chinese title literally means 'chairman' and which is defined and tightly circumscribed by the country's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitution_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">constitution</span>. The post was first created as the chairmanship of the state under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1954_Constitution_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">the country's first constitution</span>, with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> serving as its inaugural holder <b>from 1954</b> to <b>1959</b> before he passed it to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Shaoqi\">Liu Shaoqi</span>. Liu's persecution and death amid the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span> left the office effectively vacant, its duties carried out by veteran figures such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dong_Biwu\">Dong Biwu</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soong_Ching-ling\">Soong Ching-ling</span>, until the head-of-state position was formally <b>abolished altogether in 1975</b>. It was re-established by the constitution of 1982, this time rendered in English as 'president' and deliberately designed as a largely ceremonial <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Figurehead\">figurehead</span> role, reflecting a post-Mao determination to guard against any recurrence of the unchecked personal power that had scarred the previous decades. Under the current charter the president must be a citizen aged 45 or older, is elected and removable by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_People's_Congress\">National People's Congress</span>, and serves a term of 5 years coterminous with that legislature, the first occupants under the revived system being <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Xiannian\">Li Xiannian</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yang_Shangkun\">Yang Shangkun</span>. <br> <br> On paper the president promulgates laws, appoints the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Premier_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">premier</span> and other members of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_Council_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">State Council</span>, confers state honours, and receives foreign <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ambassador\">envoys</span></b>, yet most of these acts are carried out in pursuance of decisions taken by the National People's Congress and its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Standing_Committee_of_the_National_People's_Congress\">Standing Committee</span>, leaving the office with little independent authority of its own. The presidency acquired real weight only when it came to be held concurrently with the 2 genuinely powerful posts in the Chinese system, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"General_Secretary_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">general secretaryship</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Communist Party</span> and the chairmanship of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Military_Commission_(China)\">Central Military Commission</span> that commands the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army\">People's Liberation Army</span>. The concentration of these 3 roles in a single leader, first fully realized by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Zemin\">Jiang Zemin</span> and continued by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Jintao\">Hu Jintao</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span> across successive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Generations_of_Chinese_leadership\">generations of leadership</span>, became the institutional hallmark of China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paramount_leader\">paramount leader</span> within a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"One-party_state\">one-party state</span> shaped by the reforms of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>. The 1982 constitution originally barred the president from serving more than 2 consecutive 5-year terms, a maximum of 10 years in office, but in 2018 the National <b>People's Congress approved <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2018_Chinese_constitutional_amendments\">constitutional amendments</span></b> that abolished this <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Term_limit\">term limit</span>, a change widely read as enabling Xi Jinping to remain in office indefinitely. A <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vice_President_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">vice president</span> assists the head of state and may be delegated specific duties, and although the office remains constitutionally subordinate to the legislature within the wider machinery of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politics_of_China\">Chinese politics</span>, its fusion with party and military command has made it the most internationally recognizable expression of supreme leadership in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Government_of_China\">government of China</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"President of the PRC"},{"id":"cnp-060","num":"六十","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Revived in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> as the Party's highest leadership position in place of the abolished post of chairman, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is selected by the Central Committee and has been the principal seat of power for leaders from Hu Yaobang to Xi Jinping.","answer":"General Secretary of the CCP","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">总书记 (zǒngshūjì, 'general secretary')</span></div>","traditional":"中國共產黨中央委員會總書記","hanzi":"中国共产党中央委员会总书记","pinyin":"Zhōngguó Gòngchǎndǎng Zhōngyāng Wěiyuánhuì Zǒngshūjì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōngguó Gòngchǎndǎng Zhōngyāng Wěiyuánhuì Zǒngshūjì</span></div>","abstract":"<b>General Secretary of the CCP</b> is the highest office of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> and, by extension, the most powerful position in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politics_of_China\">Chinese political system</span></b>. Although the title had been borne by early leaders such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Duxiu\">Chen Duxiu</span> in the 1920s, the supreme leadership position throughout the Maoist era was instead the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chairman_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">party chairmanship</span>, <b>established for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> in 1945</b> and inherited on his death in 1976 by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hua_Guofeng\">Hua Guofeng</span>, while the general secretaryship remained a subordinate office overseeing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Secretariat_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Secretariat</span> that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> himself had filled between 1956 and 1966. The office was revived as the party's paramount post at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"12th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">12th National Congress</span></b> <b>in 1982</b>, when the chairmanship was abolished altogether as part of a deliberate effort by Deng to dismantle the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cult_of_personality\">cult of personality</span> and one-man rule that had culminated in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span> and to restore a measure of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Collective_leadership\">collective leadership</span>. Chosen formally by the Central Committee that emerges from each party <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">national congress</span></b> but in practice by the inner circle of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_Standing_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo Standing Committee</span>, from whose members the holder must come, the general secretary convenes the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo</span> and directs the work of the Secretariat and the central party apparatus. The post reflects the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Leninism\">Leninist</span> design of a centralised <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vanguardism\">vanguard</span> party, modelled on the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Communist_Party_of_the_Soviet_Union\">Communist Party of the Soviet Union</span></b>, whose own general secretaryship had been the seat of supreme authority under figures such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joseph_Stalin\">Joseph Stalin</span>, and its powers are defined in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitution_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">party constitution</span>.<br> <br>Hu Yaobang served as the first general secretary under the new arrangement, but he was <b>forced out in 1987</b>, and his successor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhao_Ziyang\">Zhao Ziyang</span> was removed in 1989 for siding with the protesters during that year's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1989_Tiananmen_Square_protests_and_massacre\">Tiananmen Square protests</span>. Stability returned under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Zemin\">Jiang Zemin</span> and then <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Jintao\">Hu Jintao</span>, during whose tenures the general secretaryship was fused with the state <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"President_of_China\">presidency</span> and the chairmanship of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Military_Commission_(China)\">Central Military Commission</span> into a single \"trinity\" of party, state, and military command. Although no formal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Term_limit\">term limit</span> ever bound the office, a convention of two consecutive five-year terms came to regulate the orderly transfer of power from Jiang to Hu and on to Xi Jinping, reinforcing the image of a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paramount_leader\">paramount leader</span> constrained by collective norms rather than personal whim. That convention was broken at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"20th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">20th National Congress</span> in 2022, when Xi secured an unprecedented third term and further entrenched his own <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping_Thought\">political doctrine</span>, concentrating authority in the office to a degree unmatched since the days of Mao. As leader of a party of roughly 99 million members that controls the state, the armed forces, and the courts, the general secretary stands at the apex of power in the People's Republic of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>, outranking both the ceremonial head of state and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Premier_of_China\">premier</span> who heads the government.","citation":"","answerText":"General Secretary of the CCP"},{"id":"cnp-061","num":"六十一","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Devised under Deng Xiaoping in the early <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>s as a framework for reunification, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> keep their capitalist systems and a high degree of autonomy for 50 years.","answer":"One Country, Two Systems","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Coined</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Deng Xiaoping, early 1980s, for Hong Kong and Taiwan</span></div>","traditional":"一國兩制","hanzi":"一国两制","pinyin":"yī guó liǎng zhì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">yī guó liǎng zhì</span></div>","abstract":"<b>One Country, Two Systems</b> is a constitutional principle of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span> under which certain regions may retain their own <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capitalism\">capitalist</span></b> economic and legal systems and a high degree of autonomy, even as the mainland maintains its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialism\">socialist</span> order within a single sovereign state. The concept was formulated by the paramount leader <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> in the <b>early 1980s</b> and was originally conceived as a formula for the peaceful <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_unification\">reunification</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span> with the mainland, building upon a nine-point proposal advanced by the marshal <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ye_Jianying\">Ye Jianying</span> in 1981</b> that offered the island broad self-government. In practice it was first applied not to Taiwan but to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span>, whose return was negotiated in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-British_Joint_Declaration\">Sino-British Joint Declaration</span> of 1984 signed by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Margaret_Thatcher\">Margaret Thatcher</span> and premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhao_Ziyang\">Zhao Ziyang</span>, ending more than 150 years of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"British_Hong_Kong\">British colonial rule</span>. A parallel arrangement for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Macau\">Macau</span> was reached <b>in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-Portuguese_Joint_Declaration\">Sino-Portuguese Joint Declaration</span> of 1987</b>, providing for the orderly end of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Portuguese_Macau\">Portuguese administration</span> of the territory that had been a European trading foothold in Asia since the 16th century. The framework was given a domestic legal foundation by Article 31 of the country's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitution_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">constitution</span>, which authorised the creation of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Special_administrative_regions_of_China\">special administrative regions</span>, and both declarations pledged that the existing capitalist systems and ways of life of the two territories would remain unchanged for 50 years. <br> <br> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Handover_of_Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong was transferred</span> to Chinese sovereignty on 1 July 1997 and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Transfer_of_sovereignty_over_Macau\">Macau followed</span></b> on 20 December 1999, each becoming a special administrative region governed by its own constitutional <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_Basic_Law\">Basic Law</span> (a separate instrument also enacted for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Macau_Basic_Law\">Macau</span>), promulgated to entrench the autonomy promised under the principle. Under these arrangements the regions retained their own currencies such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_dollar\">Hong Kong dollar</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Macanese_pataca\">Macanese pataca</span>, their separate legal traditions including the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Common_law\">common law</span> inherited in Hong Kong, and their own borders and customs, while <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foreign_relations_of_China\">foreign affairs</span></b> and defence remained the prerogative of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>. Each region is headed by an appointed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chief_Executive_of_Hong_Kong\">chief executive</span> and possesses its own legislature, exemplified by Hong Kong's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Legislative_Council_of_Hong_Kong\">Legislative Council</span>, though the eligibility of candidates and the methods of election remain subject to close oversight from the central authorities. The model has been consistently and emphatically rejected by the government in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taipei\">Taipei</span>, where successive administrations and the major parties including the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Kuomintang</span> and the pro-independence <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Democratic_Progressive_Party\">Democratic Progressive Party</span> have refused to accept a formula they regard as incompatible with the island's de facto independence and democratic system. In Hong Kong the principle has grown increasingly contentious, as pro-democracy movements such as the 2014 <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Umbrella_Movement\">Umbrella Movement</span> and the mass <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2019–2020_Hong_Kong_protests\">protests of 2019</span></b> were met by Beijing's imposition of a sweeping <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_national_security_law\">national security law</span> in 2020, leading many observers to conclude that the territory's autonomy has been substantially curtailed well before the framework's scheduled expiry.","citation":"","answerText":"One Country, Two Systems"},{"id":"cnp-071","num":"七十一","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Centred on protégés that Jiang Zemin promoted from his power base in China's largest city, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> dominated the upper ranks of the Party in the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>s and rivalled groups linked to Hu Jintao.","answer":"Shanghai clique","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">上海帮 ('Shanghai gang'), the faction around Jiang Zemin</span></div>","traditional":"上海幫","hanzi":"上海帮","pinyin":"Shànghǎi bāng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Shànghǎi bāng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Shanghai clique</b> is the informal label for a network of senior Chinese officials whose careers were advanced by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Zemin\">Jiang Zemin</span> and who came to dominate the leadership of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> from the <b>early 1990s</b> into the <b>2000s</b>. The faction took its name from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span>, China's most populous city, where Jiang had served as mayor and party secretary before he was unexpectedly elevated <b>to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"General_Secretary_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">General Secretary</span> in June 1989</b> following the purge of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhao_Ziyang\">Zhao Ziyang</span> in the wake of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1989_Tiananmen_Square_protests_and_massacre\">Tiananmen Square crackdown</span>. After <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> anointed him as the \"core\" of the leadership and especially after Deng's death in 1997, Jiang—who had also assumed the state <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"President_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">presidency</span> in 1993—became <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paramount_leader\">paramount leader</span> and transplanted a cohort of trusted lieutenants from the city's administration into the central government in Beijing. Its most prominent figures included <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zeng_Qinghong\">Zeng Qinghong</span>, Jiang's powerful political fixer who became <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vice_President_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">Vice President</span>, the future <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_People's_Congress\">National People's Congress</span> chairman <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Bangguo\">Wu Bangguo</span></b>, Vice Premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huang_Ju\">Huang Ju</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Premier_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">premier</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_Rongji\">Zhu Rongji</span>, an architect of the market <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">reforms</span> who had overseen the development of Shanghai's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pudong\">Pudong</span> district. The grouping also drew on intellectual talent such as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fudan_University\">Fudan University</span></b> theorist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Huning\">Wang Huning</span>, who helped formulate Jiang's signature doctrine of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Represents\">Three Represents</span>, a formula opening the party to private entrepreneurs that was written into its constitution in 2002 alongside <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong_Thought\">Mao Zedong Thought</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping_Theory\">Deng Xiaoping Theory</span>. <br> <br> Throughout the 1990s and 2000s the clique competed for influence with rival camps, most notably the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Communist_Youth_League_of_China\">Communist Youth League</span> faction associated with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Jintao\">Hu Jintao</span> and the so-called <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Princelings\">princelings</span> descended from veteran revolutionaries. When Hu succeeded Jiang as General Secretary at the 16th <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"16th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Party Congress</span> in 2002, Jiang nonetheless retained the chairmanship of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Military_Commission_(China)\">Central Military Commission</span> until 2004 and stacked the new 9-member <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_Standing_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo Standing Committee</span>, 6 of whose members were widely seen as his allies. The faction's grip was severely weakened in 2006 when <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Liangyu\">Chen Liangyu</span></b>, the Shanghai party secretary and a leading clique member, was dismissed amid a major social security fund scandal and later sentenced to 18 years in prison for corruption, a move widely interpreted as Hu reasserting central authority. Its remaining clout eroded further after <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span> took power in 2012 and launched a sweeping <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anti-corruption_campaign_under_Xi_Jinping\">anti-corruption campaign</span> that ensnared a number of Jiang-era figures, including the security chief <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Yongkang\">Zhou Yongkang</span></b> and the disgraced princeling <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bo_Xilai\">Bo Xilai</span>. By the time Jiang died in 2022 at the age of 96, the Shanghai clique had largely been eclipsed as a force in elite politics, yet its rise and fall remained a textbook illustration of the informal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Factions_in_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">factional</span> bargaining that shaped the party's opaque succession struggles at the turn of the 21st century.","citation":"","answerText":"Shanghai clique"},{"id":"cnp-076","num":"七十六","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"An informal title rather than a constitutional office, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> describes the single most powerful figure in Chinese politics, applied to Mao Zedong, then Deng Xiaoping despite his holding few formal posts, and later to Xi Jinping.","answer":"Paramount leader","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">最高领导人 ('highest leader'), an informal title for the top figure</span></div>","traditional":"最高領導人","hanzi":"最高领导人","pinyin":"zuìgāo lǐngdǎorén","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">zuìgāo lǐngdǎorén</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>paramount leader</b> is an informal designation used by scholars and journalists for the single most powerful figure in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politics_of_China\">politics</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span>, denoting the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"De_facto\">de facto</span></b> ruler whose real authority within the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> far exceeds whatever formal offices that individual happens to hold. The concept first attached to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>, who ruled from the founding <b>of the republic in 1949</b> until his death in 1976 as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chairman_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chairman</span> of the party, the architect of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maoism\">Mao Zedong Thought</span>, and the object of an extensive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cult_of_personality\">cult of personality</span> whose excesses culminated in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Leap_Forward\">Great Leap Forward</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span>. Following Mao's death the formal succession passed to his anointed heir <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hua_Guofeng\">Hua Guofeng</span>, yet within a few years Hua was politically outmaneuvered despite holding the top party, state, and military titles, demonstrating that the substance of paramount authority could diverge sharply from official rank. The figure who best embodied the term was <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>, who steered China through its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">economic reforms</span> <b>from 1978 onward</b> while never serving as head of state, party general secretary, or <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Premier_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">premier</span>, exercising decisive influence chiefly through his chairmanship of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Military_Commission_(China)\">Central Military Commission</span> and his immense personal prestige. His sway rested on seniority, impeccable revolutionary credentials, and a network of veteran cadres often dubbed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight_Elders\">Eight Elders</span>, together with his grip on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army\">People's Liberation Army</span>, which allowed him to remain the decisive arbiter of policy even after surrendering his <b>final formal title in 1989</b>. <br> <br> To curb the instability of unchecked personal rule, Deng promoted a system of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Collective_leadership_in_China\">collective leadership</span> exercised through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_Standing_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo Standing Committee</span>, in which the paramount leader would simultaneously occupy the offices of party <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"General_Secretary_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">general secretary</span></b>, state <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"President_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">president</span>, and chairman of the Central Military Commission, a configuration first fully realised by his chosen successor. That successor, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Zemin\">Jiang Zemin</span>, and his own successor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Jintao\">Hu Jintao</span> presided over an increasingly orderly transfer of power between distinct <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Generations_of_Chinese_leadership\">generations of leadership</span>, reinforced by a constitutional cap of 2 consecutive presidential terms introduced into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitution_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">state constitution</span> in 1982. Each dominant figure was also distinguished by the honorific of \"<b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Leadership_core\">core</span></b>\" of his respective generation, a label notably withheld from the consensus-minded Hu but conferred upon <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span> in 2016, signalling a pronounced recentralisation of authority in a single individual. Having become party general secretary in 2012 and head of state the following year, Xi oversaw the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_People's_Congress\">National People's Congress</span> abolish the presidential <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Term_limit\">term limit</span> in March 2018 by a vote of 2,958 to 2, clearing the way for him to govern without a fixed end to his tenure. At the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"20th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">20th Party Congress</span> in 2022 he secured an unprecedented 3rd term, and with his eponymous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping_Thought\">political doctrine</span> inscribed in both the party and state constitutions, many observers came to regard him as the most dominant Chinese <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Strongman_(politics)\">strongman</span></b> since Mao, even as the very informality of the role leaves its outer limits perpetually undefined.","citation":"","answerText":"Paramount leader"},{"id":"cnp-079","num":"七十九","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Heading the State Council and responsible chiefly for the economy and administration, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> has been held by figures from Zhou Enlai to Li Peng, ranking 2nd in the Party hierarchy below the general secretary.","answer":"Premier of the PRC","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">国务院总理 (Guówùyuàn Zǒnglǐ, 'premier of the State Council')</span></div>","traditional":"中華人民共和國國務院總理","hanzi":"中华人民共和国国务院总理","pinyin":"Zhōnghuá Rénmín Gònghéguó Guówùyuàn Zǒnglǐ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōnghuá Rénmín Gònghéguó Guówùyuàn Zǒnglǐ</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Premier of the PRC</b> is the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Head_of_government\">head of government</span> of the People's Republic</b> of China and the leader of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_Council_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">State Council</span>, the country's chief administrative body. As the nation's senior administrative official, the premier directs the central bureaucracy, manages economic policy and the state budget, and oversees the dozens of ministries that make up the government with the help of several <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vice_Premier_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">vice premiers</span>, while ranking beneath the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"President_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">president</span>, who serves as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Head_of_state\">head of state</span>, and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"General_Secretary_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">general secretary</span></b>, who leads the ruling party. The post is nominated by the president, confirmed by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_People's_Congress\">National People's Congress</span>, and limited to 2 consecutive 5-year terms, a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Term_limit\">term limit</span> that survived even the <b>2018 abolition</b> of similar restrictions on the presidency. The premier is almost always a member of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_Standing_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo Standing Committee</span>, customarily ranking near the very top of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Communist Party</span> hierarchy and frequently second only to the general secretary on a standing committee that currently numbers 7 members. Established at the founding <b>of the republic in 1949</b>, the post was originally styled premier of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Government_Administration_Council\">Government Administration Council</span> before being renamed under the 1954 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitution_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">constitution</span>, and to date it has been occupied by 8 individuals. <br> <br> The inaugural premier, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span>, served continuously from 1949 <b>until his death in 1976</b>, managing diplomacy and administration under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> for some 27 years, surviving the upheavals of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span>, and lending the office enormous early prestige. He was succeeded by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hua_Guofeng\">Hua Guofeng</span> and then by the reformist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhao_Ziyang\">Zhao Ziyang</span>, who later rose to become party leader, after which <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Peng\">Li Peng</span> held the premiership from 1987 to 1998 and became closely identified with the imposition of martial law during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1989_Tiananmen_Square_protests_and_massacre\">Tiananmen Square protests</span> of 1989. His successor, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_Rongji\">Zhu Rongji</span>, working under general secretary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Zemin\">Jiang Zemin</span>, drove an ambitious agenda of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">economic reform</span> between 1998 and 2003, restructuring <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_enterprises_of_China\">state-owned enterprises</span> and steering China into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Trade_Organization\">World Trade Organization</span>. <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wen_Jiabao\">Wen Jiabao</span> presided over the booming <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Jintao\">Hu Jintao</span> decade, delivering the annual <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Government_Work_Report\">Government Work Report</span></b> and overseeing successive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five-Year_Plans_of_China\">Five-Year Plans</span>, before the office passed to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Keqiang\">Li Keqiang</span> and, in 2023, to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Qiang\">Li Qiang</span>. Under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span>, however, the premiership's traditional authority over the economy has visibly contracted, as decision-making has migrated to party organs such as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Financial_and_Economic_Affairs_Commission\">Central Financial and Economic Affairs Commission</span></b>, leaving the once-dominant office increasingly overshadowed by the general secretary's concentration of power and exemplified by the markedly diminished profile of Li Keqiang before his death in 2023.","citation":"","answerText":"Premier of the PRC"},{"id":"cnp-083","num":"八十三","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Comprising in recent years 7 members who meet in secret and rank at the very apex of power, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> embodies the principle of collective leadership and is headed by the general secretary.","answer":"Politburo Standing Committee","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">the standing committee of the 政治局 (Politburo)</span></div>","traditional":"中央政治局常務委員會","hanzi":"中央政治局常务委员会","pinyin":"Zhōngyāng Zhèngzhìjú Chángwù Wěiyuánhuì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōngyāng Zhèngzhìjú Chángwù Wěiyuánhuì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Politburo Standing Committee</b> is the supreme decision-making body of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> and, by extension, the most powerful political institution in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span>, a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"One-party_state\">one-party state</span></b> in which the party commands the government, armed forces, and courts. Sitting at the apex of a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Leninism\">Leninist</span> hierarchy organized on the principle of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Democratic_centralism\">democratic centralism</span>, it forms the innermost tier of a steep pyramid that narrows from a party of more than 98 million members, through the roughly 2,300 delegates to the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">National Congress</span></b> convened every 5 years and a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Central Committee</span> of around 200 full members, up to the 24-member Politburo and finally to its 7-member standing core. Its 7 members are formally elected by the Central Committee at the 1st plenary session convened after each National Congress, and they concurrently hold the state's commanding offices, including the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Premier_of_China\">premiership</span>, the chairmanship of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_People's_Congress\">National People's Congress</span>, and the leadership of the party's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Secretariat_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Secretariat</span>. The committee's size has fluctuated considerably, expanding to 9 members <b>between 2002</b> and 2012 before contracting to 7 at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"18th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">18th National Congress</span>, a figure retained at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"20th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">20th National Congress</span> of 2022, with each member assigned a fixed rank in the published protocol order. Although it is widely understood to deliberate in secret and to favour <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Consensus_decision-making\">consensus</span></b>, the committee publishes no record of the proceedings it conducts within the walled leadership compound of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhongnanhai\">Zhongnanhai</span>, and it has come to embody a doctrine of shared rule designed to prevent the concentration of authority in any single leader.<br> <br>The body originated at <b>the party's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"5th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">5th National Congress</span> in 1927</b>, when an inner standing organ was first carved out of the newly created leadership to direct daily affairs under the founding general secretary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Duxiu\">Chen Duxiu</span>. Under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>, who dominated the party as its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chairman_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">chairman</span>, the collegial character of the committee eroded into a pronounced <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cult_of_personality\">cult of personality</span>, and the upheavals of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span> left the institution sidelined and its ranks repeatedly purged. The chaos of those years, and the brief interregnum of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hua_Guofeng\">Hua Guofeng</span>, prompted <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> and his successors to institutionalize the committee during the era of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">economic reform</span>, abolishing <b>the party chairmanship in 1982</b> and gradually entrenching norms of fixed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Term_limit\">terms</span>, orderly succession, and an informal retirement convention that bars officials aged 68 or older from new appointments. At its head stands the general secretary, an office that became the country's paramount post after 1982 and whose holder customarily also chairs the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Military_Commission_(China)\">Central Military Commission</span> and <b>serves as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"President_of_China\">state president</span></b>, making that individual the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paramount_leader\">paramount leader</span> of China. Successive general secretaries—<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Zemin\">Jiang Zemin</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Jintao\">Hu Jintao</span>, and since 2012 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span>—have presided over its deliberations, yet many analysts judge the collective model to have weakened markedly under Xi, whose far-reaching <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anti-corruption_campaign_under_Xi_Jinping\">anti-corruption campaign</span>, 2018 abolition of the presidential term limit, and elevation of close allies such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Qiang\">Li Qiang</span> have marked a pronounced recentralization of personal power.","citation":"","answerText":"Politburo Standing Committee"},{"id":"cnp-084","num":"八十四","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"A charismatic princeling and party boss of Chongqing known for a populist \"red culture\" revival, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> fell in a dramatic <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> scandal involving his wife's murder of a Briton and the flight of his police chief, ending his bid for the Politburo Standing Committee.","answer":"Bo Xilai","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">born 1949</span></div>","traditional":"薄熙來","hanzi":"薄熙来","pinyin":"Bó Xīlái","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Bó Xīlái</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Bo Xilai</b> is a former Chinese politician whose meteoric career within the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> ended in one of the most sensational political scandals of the post-<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao</span> era, as the son of the revolutionary veteran <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bo_Yibo\">Bo Yibo</span></b>, one of the so-called <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight_Elders_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Eight Elders</span> who wielded decisive influence over the party in the 1980s and 1990s. As a prominent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Princelings\">princeling</span>, he rose rapidly through a series of senior posts, serving as mayor of the port city of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dalian\">Dalian</span>, governor of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liaoning\">Liaoning</span> province, and national <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ministry_of_Commerce_(China)\">Minister of Commerce</span> before being <b>dispatched in 2007</b> to lead the sprawling southwestern municipality of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chongqing\">Chongqing</span>, home to more than 30 million residents. In Chongqing he cultivated an unusually high public profile through the populist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chongqing_model\">Chongqing model</span>, pairing a nostalgic \"red culture\" revival of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maoism\">Maoist</span>-era revolutionary songs and slogans, propagated through mass public sing-alongs and red text-message campaigns, with heavy state spending on public housing, welfare, and infrastructure. The campaign's harsher prong was a sweeping anti-mafia drive popularly known as \"strike black,\" which through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chongqing_gang_trials\">Chongqing gang trials</span> overseen by his police chief <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Lijun_(police_officer)\">Wang Lijun</span></b> produced thousands of arrests of alleged gangsters, businessmen, and officials, sometimes amid allegations of torture and confiscated assets. Charismatic, telegenic, and unusually willing to court publicity, he came to be widely regarded as a leading contender for elevation to the elite <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_Standing_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo Standing Committee</span> at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"18th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">18th Party Congress</span>, even as his showmanship and Maoist nostalgia unsettled many of his colleagues in the leadership. <br> <br> The entire edifice <b>collapsed in early 2012</b> after the murder of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_Kingdom\">British</span> businessman <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Neil_Heywood\">Neil Heywood</span>, who had been poisoned with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cyanide_poisoning\">cyanide</span> in a Chongqing hotel in November 2011 by Bo's wife, the lawyer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gu_Kailai\">Gu Kailai</span>, amid a soured business and financial dispute that prosecutors later said had turned threatening. When Wang Lijun, fearing for his own safety after confronting Bo with evidence of the killing, fled in February 2012 to the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Consulate_General_of_the_United_States,_Chengdu\">United States consulate</span></b> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chengdu\">Chengdu</span> and sought protection, the affair erupted into an international incident that the party could no longer suppress. Within weeks Bo was stripped of his Chongqing post and his seat on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo</span>, expelled from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Central Committee</span> and ultimately from the party itself, abruptly ending a political ascent that had once seemed all but assured and triggering the gravest leadership crisis the party had faced in years. Gu Kailai received a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Death_sentence_with_reprieve\">suspended death sentence</span> in August 2012, while Bo himself was tried the following year in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jinan\">Jinan</span>, the capital of the eastern province of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shandong\">Shandong</span>, and <b>convicted in September 2013</b> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bribery\">bribery</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Embezzlement\">embezzlement</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Abuse_of_power\">abuse of power</span> involving more than 20 million <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Renminbi\">yuan</span>. Sentenced to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Life_imprisonment\">life imprisonment</span> and confined thereafter at the high-security <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qincheng_Prison\">Qincheng Prison</span></b>, Bo became the most senior official purged in a generation, his downfall clearing a formidable rival from the path of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span>, whose far-reaching <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anti-corruption_campaign_under_Xi_Jinping\">anti-corruption campaign</span> would soon ensnare many more powerful cadres.","citation":"","answerText":"Bo Xilai"},{"id":"cnp-085","num":"八十五","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"A term for the descendants of senior revolutionary veterans who have leveraged family ties into power and wealth, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> includes Xi Jinping, son of a comrade of Mao Zedong, and the disgraced Bo Xilai.","answer":"Princelings","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">太子党 ('Crown Prince Party'), for descendants of party elders</span></div>","traditional":"太子黨","hanzi":"太子党","pinyin":"Tàizǐ dǎng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Tàizǐ dǎng</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Crown Prince Party”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Princelings</b> is an informal and often pejorative term for the descendants of prominent senior officials of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span>, particularly the founding revolutionary generation, who have parlayed their family lineage into political power and commercial wealth. The grouping has no formal organization but is rooted in the families of the veteran leaders—most notably the so-called <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight_Elders_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Eight Elders</span></b>—whose children inherited extensive networks of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guanxi\">guanxi</span>, or personal connections, that critics liken to a hereditary red aristocracy or <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nomenklatura\">nomenklatura</span>. Its best-known member is <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span>, the son of the revolutionary elder and reformist <b>vice premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Zhongxun\">Xi Zhongxun</span></b>, a comrade of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> who was purged and persecuted for some 16 years before being rehabilitated and pioneering China's special economic zone in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shenzhen\">Shenzhen</span>. Xi himself was sent to labour in the countryside during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span> under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Down_to_the_Countryside_Movement\">Down to the Countryside Movement</span>, yet he ultimately rose <b>to become <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"General_Secretary_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">General Secretary</span> in 2012</b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"President_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">President</span> the following year. A starkly contrasting fate befell <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bo_Xilai\">Bo Xilai</span>, son of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bo_Yibo\">Bo Yibo</span>, one of the Eight Elders, and a charismatic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chongqing\">Chongqing</span> party chief and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo</span> member once tipped for the top leadership, whose career collapsed in 2012 amid a sensational scandal. <br> <br> The affair erupted when Bo's police chief <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Lijun\">Wang Lijun</span></b> fled to the United States consulate in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chengdu\">Chengdu</span>, exposing the murder of the British businessman <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Neil_Heywood\">Neil Heywood</span> by Bo's wife, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gu_Kailai\">Gu Kailai</span>, who received a suspended death sentence in 2012. Bo was himself expelled from the party and sentenced <b>to life imprisonment in 2013</b> on charges of bribery, embezzlement, and abuse of power, in one of the most dramatic political downfalls in modern Chinese history. Other figures associated with the group include the banker <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Yuan_(banker)\">Chen Yuan</span>, son of the economic planner <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Yun\">Chen Yun</span> and longtime head of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Development_Bank\">China Development Bank</span></b>, the general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Yuan_(general)\">Liu Yuan</span>, son of the former head of state <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Shaoqi\">Liu Shaoqi</span>, and the influential party organizer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zeng_Qinghong\">Zeng Qinghong</span>. Foreign investigations have documented the enormous fortunes amassed by such political families, with <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_New_York_Times\">The New York Times</span></b> reporting in 2012 that relatives of Premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wen_Jiabao\">Wen Jiabao</span> controlled assets worth at least $2.7 billion, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bloomberg_News\">Bloomberg</span> tracing some $376 million in holdings linked to Xi's extended family, fuelling charges of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Crony_capitalism\">crony capitalism</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nepotism\">nepotism</span>. Although Xi launched a sweeping <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anti-corruption_campaign_under_Xi_Jinping\">anti-corruption campaign</span> that toppled many rivals, the princelings as a class have remained deeply embedded in the upper reaches of the state and the economy, embodying the fusion of political privilege and private fortune that many observers regard as a defining feature of elite <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Corruption_in_China\">corruption in China</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Princelings"},{"id":"cnp-090","num":"九十","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Serving as the Party's chief internal watchdog and the main engine of the campaign against graft, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> investigates members for misconduct and could impose the secretive detention system once known as <i>shuanggui</i>, reporting to the Central Committee under figures aligned with Xi Jinping.","answer":"Central Commission for Discipline Inspection","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">中央纪律检查委员会 ('central discipline-inspection commission')</span></div>","traditional":"中央紀律檢查委員會","hanzi":"中央纪律检查委员会","pinyin":"Zhōngyāng Jìlǜ Jiǎnchá Wěiyuánhuì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōngyāng Jìlǜ Jiǎnchá Wěiyuánhuì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Central Commission for Discipline Inspection</b> is the highest internal-control and anti-corruption body of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span>, charged with enforcing party discipline and <b>investigating members for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Corruption_in_China\">corruption</span></b> and other misconduct. Formally elected by and reporting to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Central Committee</span>, it is led by a secretary who customarily sits on the elite <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_Standing_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo Standing Committee</span> and oversees a vast hierarchy of discipline-inspection commissions embedded at every level of the party and the state. The commission traces its origins to a control body <b>founded in 1927</b> at the party's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"5th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">5th national congress</span>, but the modern organisation was re-established in December 1978, under the reformist leadership of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>, at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"3rd_Plenary_Session_of_the_11th_Central_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">3rd plenary session of the 11th Central Committee</span> with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Yun\">Chen Yun</span> as its inaugural secretary, having been dismantled during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span> launched by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>. Among its most controversial instruments was <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shuanggui\"><i>shuanggui</i></span>, a secretive form of extralegal detention in which a member under investigation could be held incommunicado at a designated time and place, outside the protections of the ordinary legal system, while interrogators pressed for confessions. <b>In 2018 this</b> practice was formally abolished and replaced by a successor mechanism known as <i>liuzhi</i>, administered jointly with the newly created <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Supervisory_Commission\">National Supervisory Commission</span>, a state organ established by amendment to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitution_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">national constitution</span> that extended anti-graft oversight to all who exercise public power, not party members alone. <br> <br> The body assumed <b>unprecedented prominence after 2012</b>, when it became the principal engine of the sweeping <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anti-corruption_campaign_under_Xi_Jinping\">anti-corruption campaign</span> launched by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span> soon after he became <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"General_Secretary_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">General Secretary</span> and driven during its opening phase by the formidable commission secretary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Qishan\">Wang Qishan</span>. Pledging to catch both powerful \"tigers\" and lowly \"flies,\" the campaign disciplined more than 1.5 million officials during Xi's initial term alone, enforcing frugality rules such as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight-point_Regulation\">Eight-point Regulation</span></b> and punishing officials from village cadres up to dozens at the vice-ministerial level and above. Its most prominent targets included the former security chief <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Yongkang\">Zhou Yongkang</span>, the first retired member of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo</span> Standing Committee to face criminal prosecution, alongside the disgraced Chongqing boss and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Princelings\">princeling</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bo_Xilai\">Bo Xilai</span> and the senior generals <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xu_Caihou\">Xu Caihou</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guo_Boxiong\">Guo Boxiong</span>, both former vice-chairmen of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Military_Commission_(China)\">Central Military Commission</span> overseeing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army\">People's Liberation Army</span>. Other high-profile cases swept up <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Zhengcai\">Sun Zhengcai</span></b>, a one-time contender for top leadership, and the political fixer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ling_Jihua\">Ling Jihua</span>, though critics and outside analysts have argued that the commission also functions as an instrument of factional struggle and political purges directed from the top. Subsequently headed by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhao_Leji\">Zhao Leji</span> and then, from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"20th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">20th Party Congress</span> in 2022, by <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Xi_(politician)\">Li Xi</span></b>, the commission has entrenched itself as one of the most powerful organs in Chinese politics, its disciplinary reach reinforcing the centralisation of authority around Xi as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paramount_leader\">paramount leader</span> and a defining feature of his rule.","citation":"","answerText":"Central Commission for Discipline Inspection"},{"id":"cnp-094","num":"九十四","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Chairing this body has been the true source of supreme authority for leaders from Deng Xiaoping to Xi Jinping; the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> commands the People's Liberation Army, existing in parallel Party and state forms with identical membership.","answer":"Central Military Commission","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">中央军事委员会 ('central military commission')</span></div>","traditional":"中央軍事委員會","hanzi":"中央军事委员会","pinyin":"Zhōngyāng Jūnshì Wěiyuánhuì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōngyāng Jūnshì Wěiyuánhuì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Central Military Commission</b> is the supreme military leadership body of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span>, exercising command over the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army\">People's Liberation Army</span>, the paramilitary <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Armed_Police\">People's Armed Police</span></b>, and the national militia. It exists in two parallel forms—one a body of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Central Committee</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> and the other a state organ created <b>by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitution_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">state constitution</span> in 1982</b> and nominally accountable to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_People's_Congress\">National People's Congress</span>—yet the two share identical membership and operate as a single institution under two names. This arrangement embodies the foundational principle that the Party, rather than the state, commands the armed forces, a tenet <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> distilled in his dictum that <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Political_power_grows_out_of_the_barrel_of_a_gun\">political power grows out of the barrel of a gun</span></b>, and it sets China apart from systems built on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Civilian_control_of_the_military\">civilian control of the military</span>. Its lineage runs back to the Party's earliest armed units, beginning with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanchang_uprising\">Nanchang uprising</span> of 1927 that produced the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Red_Army\">Red Army</span> during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">Chinese Civil War</span>, the forerunner of what is today among the world's largest <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Standing_army\">standing armies</span>. Because effective command of the military flows through its <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Commander-in-chief\">chairman</span></b> rather than through the formal head of state, the chairmanship has functioned as the true seat of supreme power, overshadowing even the offices of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"General_Secretary_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">general secretary</span> and state <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"President_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">president</span>. <br> <br> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> demonstrated this most vividly by retaining the chairmanship as paramount leader even after relinquishing his seat <b>on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_Standing_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo Standing Committee</span> in 1987</b>, holding the party post until 1989 and thereby keeping ultimate authority over policy and succession. <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Zemin\">Jiang Zemin</span> followed a similar course, clinging to the chairmanship for roughly two years after surrendering the party leadership in 2002, whereas <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Jintao\">Hu Jintao</span> broke with that pattern by handing the post directly to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span> <b>at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"18th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">18th National Congress</span> in 2012</b>. Under Xi, who assumed the party chairmanship in November 2012 and the state chairmanship the following March, the so-called CMC chairman responsibility system has been reinforced to concentrate final military authority in his hands, ensuring that no major operational or personnel decision is taken without his approval. Beginning in 2015 he launched the most sweeping reorganization of the armed forces in decades, abolishing the 4 general departments—among them the powerful <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army_General_Staff_Department\">General Staff Department</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army_General_Political_Department\">General Political Department</span></b>—in favor of 15 functional organs answering directly to the commission, regrouping the 7 military regions into 5 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Theater_command_(China)\">theater commands</span>, and establishing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army_Rocket_Force\">Rocket Force</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army_Strategic_Support_Force\">Strategic Support Force</span> alongside the existing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army_Ground_Force\">ground</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army_Navy\">naval</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army_Air_Force\">air</span> branches while cutting troop strength by 300,000 to roughly 2 million. Typically chaired by the top leader and rounded out by 2 vice-chairmen—a role held in recent years by figures such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Youxia\">Zhang Youxia</span>—and a small number of members, including the heads of the joint staff and political-work organs and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ministry_of_National_Defense_(China)\">minister of national defense</span>, an office devoted to military diplomacy rather than operational command, the commission has remained a focal point of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anti-corruption_campaign_under_Xi_Jinping\">Xi's anti-corruption campaign</span>, which has toppled senior officers including the defense minister <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Shangfu\">Li Shangfu</span> in 2023.","citation":"","answerText":"Central Military Commission"},{"id":"cnp-098","num":"九十八","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Held together each spring in Beijing, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> brings together the National People's Congress and the consultative conference to approve budgets, laws and personnel, marking the high point of the political calendar.","answer":"Two Sessions","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">两会 ('two meetings'), the annual NPC and CPPCC sessions</span></div>","traditional":"兩會","hanzi":"两会","pinyin":"liǎnghuì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">liǎnghuì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Two Sessions</b> is the collective name for the concurrent annual plenary meetings of China's two foremost national political bodies, convened in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> each spring and widely regarded as the high point of the country's political calendar. The two gatherings comprise the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_People's_Congress\">National People's Congress</span></b>, the constitutionally supreme state <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Legislature\">legislature</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_People's_Political_Consultative_Conference\">Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference</span>, an advisory body that serves as the chief platform of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span>'s broad <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_Front_(China)\">united front</span></b>. Alongside the ruling party's own delegates, the consultative conference draws in representatives from eight legally sanctioned minor parties, among them the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Democratic_League\">China Democratic League</span>, and bodies such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"All-China_Federation_of_Industry_and_Commerce\">All-China Federation of Industry and Commerce</span>, lending the proceedings a veneer of pluralistic consultation within what remains a firmly <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"One-party_state\">one-party system</span>. Each session typically opens in early March, the conference convening a day or so before the congress, and gathers nearly 3,000 NPC deputies and more than 2,000 conference members in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Hall_of_the_People\">Great Hall of the People</span></b> on the western flank of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tiananmen_Square\">Tiananmen Square</span>. Running for roughly one to two weeks, the meetings assemble deputies drawn from every province, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army\">People's Liberation Army</span>, and the special administrative regions of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Macau\">Macau</span>, while thousands of accredited journalists and intense coverage by the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Media_of_China\">state media</span></b> turn the event into a national spectacle. <br> <br> The centrepiece of the congress is the government work report on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_Council_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">State Council</span>'s performance, delivered by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Premier_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">Premier</span> — a duty discharged in recent years by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Qiang\">Li Qiang</span> — which reviews the past year and announces the headline annual <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gross_domestic_product\">GDP</span> growth target along with deficit, inflation, and employment goals. Delegates also vote to approve the state <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Government_budget\">budget</span></b>, ratify economic blueprints such as the country's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five-year_plans_of_China\">five-year plans</span>, and enact major legislation, with day-to-day legislative work between the brief annual sittings left to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Standing_Committee_of_the_National_People's_Congress\">NPC Standing Committee</span>. At the opening session of each new term the congress fills the state's top posts, formally electing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"President_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">President</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vice_President_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">Vice President</span> and confirming the premier and other senior officials, with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span> re-elected to the presidency at the <b>2023</b> sitting of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"14th_National_People's_Congress\">14th National People's Congress</span>. Because the assemblies almost never reject proposals advanced by the leadership, the congress in particular is frequently characterised abroad as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rubber_stamp_(politics)\">rubber-stamp</span> body that lends formal legitimacy to decisions already taken within the party's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_Standing_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo Standing Committee</span>, its votes routinely passing by overwhelming margins. Nonetheless the sessions have served as the stage for consequential measures, including the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitution_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">constitutional</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2018_amendment_to_the_Constitution_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">amendment</span> abolishing <b>presidential term limits in 2018</b>, the adoption of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Civil_Code_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">Civil Code</span> in 2020, and the decision the same year to impose a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_national_security_law\">national security law</span> on Hong Kong, each unveiled amid the tightly choreographed proceedings.","citation":"","answerText":"Two Sessions"},{"id":"cng-029","num":"二十九","category":"China · Geography","question":"Following a mountain range and a river across the land, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is taken to divide China into north and south, separating wheat country from rice country and roughly marking where winter central heating historically stopped, near the 0 °C (32 °F) January isotherm.","answer":"Qinling–Huaihe Line","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">秦岭–淮河线, the Qinling–Huai River dividing line</span></div>","traditional":"秦嶺–淮河線","hanzi":"秦岭–淮河线","pinyin":"Qínlǐng–Huáihé Xiàn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Qínlǐng–Huáihé Xiàn</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Qinling–Huaihe Line</b> is the conventional boundary dividing China into North and South, running near the 33rd parallel along the crest of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qinling\">Qinling Mountains</span></b> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shaanxi\">Shaanxi</span> and then eastward down the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huai_River\">Huai River</span> through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Henan\">Henan</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anhui\">Anhui</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiangsu\">Jiangsu</span>, a divide first articulated by <b>the geographer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Xiangwen\">Zhang Xiangwen</span> in 1908</b>. The line closely tracks the 0 °C (32 °F) January isotherm and the 800-millimeter annual rainfall contour, separating the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Humid_subtropical_climate\">humid subtropical</span> south from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Humid_continental_climate\">humid continental</span> north within the regime of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"East_Asian_Monsoon\">East Asian monsoon</span>. Agriculturally it marks where irrigated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rice\">rice</span> paddies and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Multiple_cropping\">double cropping</span> give way to dryland <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wheat\">wheat</span>, and where citrus reaches its limit, a contrast proverbial since the statesman <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yan_Ying\">Yan Ying</span> observed in the 6th century BCE that orange trees planted north of the Huai yield only bitter <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Trifoliate_orange\">trifoliate orange</span>. The Qinling barrier itself, crowned by 3,767-meter (12,360 ft) <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mount_Taibai\">Mount Taibai</span>, the highest peak in eastern China, blocks frigid winter winds and forms the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Drainage_divide\">drainage divide</span></b> between the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wei_River\">Wei</span>, flowing to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_River\">Yellow River</span>, and the Han, flowing to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span>. The boundary even acquired administrative force in the 1950s, when a decision associated with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span> extended state-subsidized winter <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"District_heating\">district heating</span></b> only to cities north of the line, leaving hundreds of millions of southerners to unheated winters and to a debate that resurfaces with every cold snap. <br> <br> The Qinling section shelters extraordinary biodiversity, including roughly 345 wild <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qinling_panda\">Qinling pandas</span></b>, a distinct subspecies of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Giant_panda\">giant panda</span>, alongside the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Golden_snub-nosed_monkey\">golden snub-nosed monkey</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Takin\">takin</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Crested_ibis\">crested ibis</span>, <b>rediscovered in 1981</b> as a final population of just 7 birds that conservation has since multiplied into the thousands. The Huai section has a darker hydrological history, for after the Yellow River usurped its outlet in 1194 the roughly 1,000-kilometer (620 mi) stream was left to drain awkwardly through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hongze_Lake\">Hongze Lake</span>, breeding chronic floods that <b>contributed to the catastrophic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1931_China_floods\">1931 deluge</span></b>. Taming this river became the new People's Republic's first great water campaign in 1950, mobilizing millions of laborers under the slogan that the Huai must be harnessed. Modern engineering now pierces and exploits the divide, from the 18-kilometer (11 mi) <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhongnanshan_Tunnel\">Zhongnanshan Tunnel</span> opened in 2007 to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Danjiangkou_Dam\">Danjiangkou reservoir</span>, which since 2014 has sent southern water north to Beijing through the middle route of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South–North_Water_Transfer_Project\">South–North Water Transfer Project</span>. In everyday culture the line endures as shorthand for a civilizational contrast, noodles against rice and kangs against braziers, that no railway tunnel has yet erased.","citation":"","answerText":"Qinling–Huaihe Line"},{"id":"cng-034","num":"三十四","category":"China · Geography","question":"A spectacular stretch of steep limestone canyons on the Yangtze, comprising the Qutang, Wu and Xiling gorges, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is now partly submerged behind the world's largest hydroelectric dam in Hubei.","answer":"Three Gorges","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">三峡 (Sānxiá, 'three gorges')</span></div>","traditional":"三峽","hanzi":"三峡","pinyin":"Sānxiá","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Sānxiá</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Three Gorges</b> is a roughly 193-kilometer (120 mi) stretch of canyons where the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span> saws through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Limestone\">limestone</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Karst\">karst</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Mountains\">Wu Mountains</span>, running from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Baidicheng\">Baidicheng</span> near <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fengjie_County\">Fengjie</span></b> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chongqing\">Chongqing</span> downstream to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yichang\">Yichang</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hubei\">Hubei</span>. First comes <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qutang_Gorge\">Qutang Gorge</span>, the shortest at about 8 kilometers (5 mi) yet the most dramatic, whose cliff-flanked Kuimen gate, towering over 1,000 meters (3,300 ft) above the water, adorns the 10-yuan note of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Renminbi\">renminbi</span>. Next the 45-kilometer (28 mi) <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Gorge\">Wu Gorge</span> threads beneath the Twelve Peaks, among them Goddess Peak, identified in legend with a daughter of heaven who guides boatmen below. Longest is the 66-kilometer (41 mi) <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiling_Gorge\">Xiling Gorge</span></b>, once the deadliest reach of the river, where shoals and whirlpools forced gangs of trackers to haul junks upstream by bamboo hawsers along galleries chiseled into the rock. For most of history this funnel was the only water route between the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan_Basin\">Sichuan Basin</span> and the plains of central China, a strategic chokepoint as much as a scenic wonder. <br> <br> Human traces in the gorges reach back to the ancient <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ba_(state)\">Ba</span> people, whose <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hanging_coffins\">hanging coffins</span></b> still cling to crevices, while <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zigui_County\">Zigui</span> on the Xiling reach claims the poet <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qu_Yuan\">Qu Yuan</span> of the 4th–3rd centuries BCE, honored in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dragon_Boat_Festival\">Dragon Boat Festival</span>, and nearby villages claim the Han beauty <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Zhaojun\">Wang Zhaojun</span>. At Baidicheng the warlord <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Bei\">Liu Bei</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Kingdoms\">Three Kingdoms</span> <b>died in 223 CE</b> entrusting his heir to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuge_Liang\">Zhuge Liang</span>, in 280 a Jin fleet burned through iron chains strung across Qutang during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Conquest_of_Wu_by_Jin\">conquest of Wu</span>, and the canyons echo through verse from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Bai\">Li Bai</span>'s famous dawn departure from Baidi to the roughly 430 poems <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Du_Fu\">Du Fu</span> wrote beside Qutang. <b>In 1938</b> the shipping magnate <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lu_Zuofu\">Lu Zuofu</span> ran a \"Chinese Dunkirk\" through the rapids, ferrying refugees and over 100,000 tonnes (110,000 tons) of dismantled factories upstream ahead of the Japanese advance. Since the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Gorges_Dam\">Three Gorges Dam</span> rose at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sandouping\">Sandouping</span> inside Xiling Gorge, impounding water to 175 meters (574 ft) <b>by around 2010</b>, the river has drowned old Fengjie together with some 13 cities, 140 towns, and over 1,000 archaeological sites, prompting salvage feats such as relocating the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhangfei_Temple\">Zhangfei Temple</span>, diking the pagoda of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shibaozhai\">Shibaozhai</span>, and enclosing the 1,200 years of low-water inscriptions on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Baiheliang\">Baiheliang</span> ridge in an underwater museum opened in 2009. Yet the cliffs rise so high that the spectacle endures, and cruise ships now glide on slack water past side canyons like the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lesser_Three_Gorges\">Lesser Three Gorges</span> of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Daning_River\">Daning River</span></b>, where the age of the trackers survives only in memory.","citation":"","answerText":"Three Gorges"},{"id":"cng-045","num":"四十五","category":"China · Geography","question":"A seasonal reversal of winds that brings hot, rainy summers and cold, dry winters to most of eastern China, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> drives the plum rains of early summer, governs the farming calendar, and can cause both floods and droughts.","answer":"East Asian Monsoon","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">东亚季风 ('East Asian seasonal wind')</span></div>","traditional":"東亞季風","hanzi":"东亚季风","pinyin":"Dōngyà Jìfēng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Dōngyà Jìfēng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>East Asian Monsoon</b> is the seasonal reversal of winds, born of the differential heating of the Asian landmass and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pacific_Ocean\">Pacific Ocean</span>, that governs the climate of eastern China together with Korea and Japan. In summer, moist southerlies drawn off the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South_China_Sea\">South China Sea</span> and the Pacific, steered around the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Subtropical_ridge\">subtropical ridge</span></b>, deliver 60–80 percent of the year's rain, while in winter the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Siberian_High\">Siberian High</span> reverses the flow into dry northerlies that bring <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cold_wave\">cold waves</span> and the dust that built the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Loess\">loess</span> lands. The summer rain band marches north on a strict schedule, soaking South China in May, stalling as a quasi-<b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stationary_front\">stationary front</span></b> over the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span> from mid-June to mid-July in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Meiyu_(season)\">plum rains</span>, known in Korea as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Changma\">changma</span>, then leaping to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"North_China_Plain\">North China Plain</span> in late July as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jet_stream\">jet stream</span></b> shifts past the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_Plateau\">Tibetan Plateau</span>. The system stretches annual rainfall from above 1,600 millimeters (63 in) on the southeast coast to under 400 in the northwest, fixing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qinling–Huaihe_Line\">Qinling–Huaihe</span> divide between <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rice\">rice</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wheat\">wheat</span>, the limits of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Multiple_cropping\">multiple cropping</span>, and the rhythm of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Agriculture_in_China\">Chinese farming</span> codified in the 24 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Solar_term\">solar terms</span>. Because modest shifts in timing or strength, modulated by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"El_Niño–Southern_Oscillation\">El Niño–Southern Oscillation</span>, can park the rain band too long in one place or withhold it entirely, the same engine manufactures both <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Flood\">floods</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Drought\">droughts</span>. <br> <br> Monsoon failure has written some of history's darkest pages, including the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northern_Chinese_Famine_of_1876–1879\">Northern Chinese Famine of <b>1876–1879</b></span> that killed perhaps 9–13 million people, while overabundance produced the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1931_China_floods\">1931 floods</span>, among the deadliest disasters ever, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1998_China_floods\">1998 inundation</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2021_Henan_floods\"><b>2021</b> Henan floods</span>, when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhengzhou\">Zhengzhou</span> recorded 201.9 millimeters (7.95 in) of rain in a single hour. The monsoon's deep past is read from cave <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Speleothem\">speleothems</span>, whose oxygen isotopes have extended <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paleoclimatology\">paleoclimate</span> records across 640,000 years and revealed weak-monsoon decades coinciding with the collapse of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span> dynasties, as a <b>celebrated 2008 cave</b> study argued. Geologists add that the winter limb of the system, blowing for over 2 million years, stacked the dust of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Loess_Plateau\">Loess Plateau</span> into the thickest such archive on earth. In recent decades observers traced a \"south flood, north drought\" pattern partly to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Aerosol\">aerosol</span> pollution dimming the land, and warming seas are now loading the summer winds with heavier extremes even as reservoirs, dikes, and forecasting blunt their edge. For 4 millennia of recorded history, this atmospheric metronome has set the tempo of sowing, harvest, famine, and abundance across the most populous farmland in the world.","citation":"","answerText":"East Asian Monsoon"},{"id":"cng-050","num":"五十","category":"China · Geography","question":"A diagonal line drawn across the map in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> by the geographer Hu Huanyong, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> famously splits the country into a crowded eastern half holding the great majority of people and a sparsely settled western half covering most of the land.","answer":"Heihe–Tengchong Line","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">named for the cities Heihe and Tengchong (the Hu Line)</span></div>","traditional":"黑河－騰衝線","hanzi":"黑河－腾冲线","pinyin":"Hēihé–Téngchōng Xiàn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Hēihé–Téngchōng Xiàn</span></div>","abstract":"The&nbsp;<b>Heihe–Tengchong Line</b>, also known internationally as the Hu Line, is an imaginary diagonal running from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heihe\">Heihe</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heilongjiang\">Heilongjiang</span>, the border town facing Russian <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Blagoveshchensk\">Blagoveshchensk</span></b>, southwest to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tengchong\">Tengchong</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yunnan\">Yunnan</span> near the border with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Myanmar\">Myanmar</span>, first drawn in 1935 by <b>the geographer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Huanyong\">Hu Huanyong</span></b> as the Aigun–Tengchong line after the old town of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Aigun\">Aigun</span>. Plotting county populations dot by dot, Hu found that the southeastern half contained 96 percent of China's people on only 36 percent of its territory, leaving 4 percent of the population scattered across the remaining 64 percent. The pattern has proved astonishingly durable, for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2020_Chinese_census\"><b>2020 census</span> still</b> placed about 94 percent of the population east of the line on roughly 44 percent of the land, yielding <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Population_density\">densities</span> near 300 people per square kilometer in the east against around 15 in the west. The explanation lies in nature, since the line shadows the 400-millimeter <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Precipitation\">precipitation</span></b> frontier where the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"East_Asian_Monsoon\">East Asian monsoon</span> fails, beyond which stretch the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Arid\">arid</span> wastes of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gobi_Desert\">Gobi</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taklamakan_Desert\">Taklamakan</span> and the frozen heights of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_Plateau\">Tibetan Plateau</span>. The divide therefore separates far more than headcounts, splitting the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Chinese\">Han</span> agricultural heartland from the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ethnic_minorities_in_China\">minority</span> homelands of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Western_China\">western China</span></b> such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinjiang\">Xinjiang</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibet\">Tibet</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qinghai\">Qinghai</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Inner_Mongolia\">Inner Mongolia</span>, and tracking everything from 90-plus percent of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gross_domestic_product\">GDP</span> to the glow of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Satellite_imagery\">satellite</span> night-light maps, the density of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"WeChat\">WeChat</span> activity, and the lattice of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"High-speed_rail_in_China\">high-speed rail</span>. <br> <br> Hu Huanyong, who lived <b>from 1901</b> to 1998 and founded the study of population geography in China, produced the line from painstaking compilation of registration data in an era before computing, publishing it in the country's first modern population dot map. Through war, revolution, famine, and 4 decades of breakneck growth in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Demographics_of_China\">demography</span> of the People's Republic, the proportions he measured have shifted by barely 2 percentage points, leading geographers to speak of the line almost as a natural law. Its grip became a matter of state when Premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Keqiang\">Li Keqiang</span> publicly <b>asked in 2014 how</b> the Hu Line might be \"broken\" so that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Urbanization_in_China\">urbanization</span> could spread modern prosperity westward. Beijing had already launched the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Western_Development\">Western Development</span> program in 2000, channeling trillions of yuan into railways, highways, and energy projects, yet the western share of population has crept up only marginally because scarce water and fragile ecosystems cap the region's carrying capacity. Many scholars now argue the line should be respected rather than erased, and the 90-year-old pencil stroke endures in every geography classroom as the single most eloquent summary of how nature has apportioned the Chinese people.","citation":"","answerText":"Heihe–Tengchong Line"},{"id":"cng-051","num":"五十一","category":"China · Geography","question":"Organised into a multi-tier hierarchy beneath the central government, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> sorts the territory into provincial-level units — including ordinary provinces, autonomous regions and municipalities — that are further split into prefectures, counties and townships.","answer":"Administrative divisions of China","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">中国行政区划 ('administrative divisions of China')</span></div>","traditional":"中國行政區劃","hanzi":"中国行政区划","pinyin":"Zhōngguó xíngzhèng qūhuà","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōngguó xíngzhèng qūhuà</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>administrative divisions of China</b> form the multi-tiered hierarchy through which the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People’s Republic of China</span> organises its territory beneath the central <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Government_of_China\">government</span></b>. Although the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitution_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">constitution</span> formally recognises three levels — province, county, and township — the modern state in practice operates through as many as five tiers, inserting a prefecture level between province and county and a village level below the township. At the top stand 34 provincial-level units, comprising 23 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Provinces_of_China\">provinces</span>, 5 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Autonomous_regions_of_China\">autonomous regions</span> such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibet_Autonomous_Region\">Tibet</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinjiang\">Xinjiang</span>, 4 <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Direct-administered_municipalities_of_China\">directly governed municipalities</span></b> led by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chongqing\">Chongqing</span>, and the 2 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Special_administrative_regions_of_China\">special administrative regions</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Macau\">Macau</span>. Below them the territory is subdivided into roughly 333 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Prefectures_of_China\">prefecture-level</span> divisions, about 2,800 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Counties_of_China\">county-level</span> divisions such as counties and urban <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"District_(China)\">districts</span></b>, and tens of thousands of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Township_(China)\">township-level</span> units of towns, townships, and urban <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Subdistrict_(China)\">subdistricts</span>, beneath which villagers’ and residents’ committees govern the village level. Many divisions take autonomous forms — <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Autonomous_prefecture\">autonomous prefectures</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Autonomous_county\">autonomous counties</span>, and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ethnic_township\">ethnic townships</span></b> — created to accommodate the country’s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ethnic_minorities_in_China\">ethnic minorities</span>, while <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Inner_Mongolia\">Inner Mongolia</span> preserves the distinctive Mongol <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"League_(administrative_division)\">leagues</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Banners_of_Inner_Mongolia\">banners</span>, and the special regions enjoy wide self-rule under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"One_country,_two_systems\">one country, two systems</span>. <br> <br> The roots of the <b>system reach back to 221 BCE</b>, when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_Shi_Huang\">Qin Shi Huang</span> unified China and abolished <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fengjian\">feudal</span> fiefs in favour of the centralised <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Commandery_(China)\">commandery</span>-and-county system administered by appointed officials rather than hereditary lords. Subsequent dynasties elaborated this template, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han</span> blending commanderies with restored kingdoms before the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span> grouped the realm into large supervisory <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Circuit_(administrative_division)\">circuits</span> known as dao. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song</span> reorganised the realm into circuits called lu, but the modern province was born under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan</span>, whose Mongol rulers <b>governed through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Branch_Secretariat\">branch secretariats</span></b>, the xing sheng from which the Chinese word for province derives. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> consolidated the framework into a recognisable set of provinces, several of whose names and boundaries — among them <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shandong\">Shandong</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanxi\">Shanxi</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan\">Sichuan</span> — have endured with little change to the present day. After the People’s Republic was <b>founded in 1949</b> the divisions were repeatedly redrawn, with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hainan\">Hainan</span> split from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangdong\">Guangdong</span> to form a new province in 1988 and Chongqing elevated to a municipality in 1997, while the establishment of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sansha\">Sansha</span> in 2012 extended the hierarchy to administer the country’s contested claims in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South_China_Sea\">South China Sea</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Administrative divisions of China"},{"id":"cng-052","num":"五十二","category":"China · Geography","question":"Numbering 22 (or 23 by Beijing's count, which adds Taiwan), the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> includes populous units such as Sichuan and Guangdong, each run by a governor under a Communist Party secretary.","answer":"Provinces of China","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">省 (shěng), originally a term for an imperial secretariat</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"省","pinyin":"shěng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">shěng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Provinces of China</b> are the most numerous type of provincial-level division in the People's Republic, numbering 22 under actual administration but 23 in Beijing's official count, which includes <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span></b>, and standing alongside the 5 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Autonomous_regions_of_China\">autonomous regions</span>, 4 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Direct-administered_municipalities_of_China\">direct-administered municipalities</span>, and 2 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Special_administrative_regions_of_China\">special administrative regions</span> in a claimed total of 34 first-level units. The word <i>sheng</i> originally denoted a department of the imperial palace bureaucracy such as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhongshu_Sheng\">Central Secretariat</span></b>, and it became territorial in the 13th century when the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_dynasty\">Yuan dynasty</span> planted \"branch secretariats\" across the realm, displacing the older circuits of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span> and routes of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song</span>. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span> consolidated 13 provinces plus 2 metropolitan regions, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> ruled 18 \"inner\" provinces before <b>expanding to 22 by 1907</b> through the promotion of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinjiang\">Xinjiang</span> in 1884, Taiwan in 1885, lost a decade later under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Shimonoseki\">Treaty of Shimonoseki</span>, and the 3 Manchurian provinces. The People's Republic has kept the roster remarkably stable, carving <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hainan\">Hainan</span> <b>from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangdong\">Guangdong</span> in 1988</b> as the newest province and detaching <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chongqing\">Chongqing</span> from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan\">Sichuan</span> in 1997, while its listed Taiwan Province remains a matter of the unresolved <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Political_status_of_Taiwan\">political status of Taiwan</span>. The units are of national scale in themselves, for Guangdong counted 126 million residents in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2020_Chinese_census\"><b>2020</b> census</span> with an economy rivaling <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South_Korea\">South Korea</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shandong\">Shandong</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Henan\">Henan</span> each approach 100 million, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qinghai\">Qinghai</span> spreads over 720,000 square kilometers (280,000 sq mi), with each province bearing a single-character abbreviation displayed on its <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vehicle_registration_plates_of_China\">vehicle plates</span></b>. <br> <br> Every province is run on the dual party-state model, headed nominally by a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Governor_(China)\">governor</span> who leads the provincial people's government but in practice subordinated to the provincial <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Party_Committee_Secretary\">Party Committee Secretary</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span>, who holds the real first rank. Both posts are filled from Beijing through a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nomenklatura\">nomenklatura</span> system that rotates leaders across regions to prevent local power bases, and governing a major province has long served as the proving ground for national leadership. Below the province the <b>hierarchy descends through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Prefecture-level_city\">prefecture-level cities</span></b> to roughly 2,800 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Counties_of_China\">counties</span> and tens of thousands of townships, giving a single governor administrative reach over populations larger than most countries. Provinces implement national law, draft their own budgets, and answer to local people's congresses, yet the 1994 fiscal recentralization clawed back revenue, and the temptation to inflate performance surfaced when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liaoning\">Liaoning</span> admitted in 2017 to years of padded economic statistics. For all the centralism, the province remains the deepest frame of everyday identity, expressed in cuisines, dialects, and affectionate stereotypes that have outlived every dynasty that drew the boundaries.","citation":"","answerText":"Provinces of China"},{"id":"cng-053","num":"五十三","category":"China · Geography","question":"Established in areas with large concentrations of ethnic minorities and nominally granting them extra self-government, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> include Inner Mongolia and the homeland of the Uyghurs in the far west.","answer":"Autonomous regions of China","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">自治区 (zìzhìqū, 'self-governing region')</span></div>","traditional":"自治區","hanzi":"自治区","pinyin":"zìzhìqū","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">zìzhìqū</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>autonomous regions of China</b> are the highest-ranked of the country’s <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Autonomous_administrative_divisions_of_China\">autonomous areas</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Administrative_divisions_of_China\">provincial-level</span> units of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People’s Republic of China</span> created in territories home to large populations of non-<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Chinese\">Han</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ethnic_minorities_in_China\">ethnic minorities</span>. In principle each region wields broader <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Autonomy\">autonomy</span></b> than an ordinary province — the right to use local languages, adapt national laws, and install a chairman drawn from the titular minority — yet effective power rests with the regional secretary of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span>, who is almost always an ethnic Han. The five regions are <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Inner_Mongolia\">Inner Mongolia</span></b>, homeland of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongols\">Mongols</span> with its capital at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hohhot\">Hohhot</span>; the vast <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinjiang\">Xinjiang</span> in the far northwest, named for its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Uyghurs\">Uyghur</span> population and centred on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ürümqi\">Ürümqi</span>; <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangxi\">Guangxi</span></b> in the south, established for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuang_people\">Zhuang</span>; <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ningxia\">Ningxia</span>, created for the Muslim <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hui_people\">Hui</span>; and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibet_Autonomous_Region\">Tibet</span>, the high plateau home of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_people\">Tibetans</span> governed from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lhasa\">Lhasa</span>. Inner Mongolia was the first, <b>founded in 1947 even</b> before the People’s Republic, followed by Xinjiang in 1955, Guangxi and Ningxia in 1958, and finally Tibet in 1965, each conversion replacing or reorganising an existing province or frontier territory. Together the five sprawl across roughly 45 percent of China’s land area yet hold only a small fraction of its people, and in several the titular minority is now outnumbered by Han migrants, the Zhuang forming under a third of Guangxi’s population and Mongols barely a sixth of Inner Mongolia’s. <br> <br> The framework drew on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Soviet</span> model of managing nationalities, sorting the population into the Han and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"List_of_ethnic_groups_in_China\">55 recognised minorities</span>, yet unlike the Soviet union republics the Chinese regions hold no right of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Secession\">secession</span>. Most of these lands had been knit to the Chinese empire only gradually, the northwest secured as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> conquered the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dzungar_Khanate\">Dzungar Khanate</span> and renamed the region the “New Frontier” in the 18th century, while the Mongol autonomous government proclaimed in 1947 during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">Chinese Civil War</span> became the prototype for all that followed. Tibet was incorporated after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army\">People’s Liberation Army</span> <b>entered in 1950–1951</b>, and following the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1959_Tibetan_uprising\">1959 Tibetan uprising</span> that drove the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"14th_Dalai_Lama\">14th Dalai Lama</span> into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_diaspora\">exile</span>, the autonomous region was formally constituted in 1965. The northwestern region has since become the most contentious, drawing international condemnation from the late 2010s over the mass <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinjiang_internment_camps\">internment of Uyghurs</span> and other Muslims, while in the south Guangxi borders <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vietnam\">Vietnam</span> and the small Hui region of Ningxia is strung along the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_River\">Yellow River</span>. The same principle extends downward to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Autonomous_prefecture\">autonomous prefectures</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Autonomous_county\">autonomous counties</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ethnic_township\">ethnic townships</span> elsewhere in the country, codified in a <b>national autonomy law of 1984</b>, though critics contend that the Party’s centralised control and large-scale Han migration have left the regions’ self-rule more nominal than real.","citation":"","answerText":"Autonomous regions of China"},{"id":"cng-054","num":"五十四","category":"China · Geography","question":"Ranking equal to provinces and reporting straight to the central government, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> — among them the capital Beijing and the financial hub Shanghai — are each governed as their own top-level units.","answer":"Direct-administered municipalities of China","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">直辖市 (zhíxiáshì, 'directly-governed city')</span></div>","traditional":"直轄市","hanzi":"直辖市","pinyin":"zhíxiáshì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">zhíxiáshì</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“directly governed city”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>direct-administered municipalities of China</b> are the 4 great cities that rank equal to the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Provinces_of_China\">provinces</span></b> and answer directly to the central <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Government_of_China\">government</span>: <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tianjin\">Tianjin</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chongqing\">Chongqing</span>. The category descends from the special municipalities created <b>under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)\">Republic of China</span> after 1927</b>, a dozen of which, headed by the capital <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span>, existed by 1948, and the young People's Republic likewise began with around a dozen before pruning the list in 1954 to Beijing, Tianjin, and Shanghai, with Tianjin even folded into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hebei\">Hebei</span> <b>between 1958</b> and 1967. The 4th member arrived in 1997, when Chongqing was detached from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan\">Sichuan</span> to oversee the resettlement of more than a million people displaced by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Gorges_Dam\">Three Gorges Dam</span> and to anchor the coming <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Western_Development\">Western Development</span> drive. The result is a giant in disguise, for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2020_Chinese_census\"><b>2020</b> census</span> counted 32.05 million people in Chongqing across 82,400 square kilometers (31,800 sq mi), an area comparable to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Austria\">Austria</span>, against 24.9 million in Shanghai, 21.9 million in Beijing, and 13.9 million in Tianjin. Administratively the municipalities skip the prefecture tier, dividing straight into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"District_(China)\">districts</span> and counties, and each is run by a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mayor\">mayor</span> subordinate to a municipal <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Party_Committee_Secretary\">Party Committee Secretary</span></b> who customarily holds a seat on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo</span>, giving these cities political weight beyond ordinary provinces. <br> <br> Each plays a distinct national role, with Beijing serving as the seat of the party-state, the cultural capital, and headquarters for most central <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_enterprises_of_China\">state-owned enterprises</span>. Shanghai at the mouth of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span> is the financial hub, home to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_Stock_Exchange\">Shanghai Stock Exchange</span> and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Port_of_Shanghai\">Port of Shanghai</span></b>, the world's busiest container harbor, which moved roughly 49 million <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Twenty-foot_equivalent_unit\">TEU</span> in a recent year. Tianjin, grown from a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Grand_Canal_(China)\">Grand Canal</span> garrison through the 9 foreign <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Concessions_in_Tianjin\">concessions</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_ports\">treaty-port</span> era, now pairs that architectural inheritance with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Binhai\">Binhai</span> industrial seafront as the maritime gateway of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jing-Jin-Ji\">Jing-Jin-Ji</span></b> megaregion. Chongqing, the mountain city of the upper Yangtze, has meanwhile become one of the planet's largest producers of laptop computers and the urban engine of the southwest. Residence in these cities is so prized that their <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hukou\">hukou</span> are rationed through points systems, with planners capping Beijing near 23 million and Shanghai near 25 million by 2035, while the capital decants its non-capital functions to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tongzhou_District,_Beijing\">Tongzhou</span> sub-center and the new city of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiong'an\">Xiong'an</span>, founded in 2017, so that 4 city-states continue to steer the fortunes of the nation.","citation":"","answerText":"Direct-administered municipalities of China"},{"id":"cng-085","num":"八十五","category":"China · Geography","question":"A low-lying maze of channels where the Pearl River meets the sea, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> — taking in Guangzhou, Shenzhen and Hong Kong — forms one of the world's largest manufacturing and megacity clusters.","answer":"Pearl River Delta","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">珠江三角洲 ('Pearl River delta')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"珠江三角洲","pinyin":"Zhūjiāng Sānjiǎozhōu","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhūjiāng Sānjiǎozhōu</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Pearl River Delta</b> is a low-lying <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"River_delta\">river delta</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangdong\">Guangdong</span> province where the combined waters of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_River\">West</span>, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bei_River\">North</span></b>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dong_River\">East</span> rivers braid through a maze of channels and empty into the South China Sea by 8 principal mouths. Its alluvial flats, long farmed through an ingenious dike-and-pond system pairing mulberry and sugarcane embankments with fish <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Aquaculture\">aquaculture</span>, enjoy a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Humid_subtropical_climate\">humid subtropical climate</span> raked by summer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Typhoon\">typhoons</span>, while the estuary shelters the threatened <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_white_dolphin\">Chinese white dolphin</span></b> and ranks among the urban regions most exposed to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sea_level_rise\">sea level rise</span>. Since the 1980s the delta has become the “factory of the world,” its export workshops in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou\">Guangzhou</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shenzhen\">Shenzhen</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dongguan\">Dongguan</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foshan\">Foshan</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuhai\">Zhuhai</span>, and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhongshan\">Zhongshan</span></b> at times generating over a third of China’s exports and a commanding share of the planet’s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Electronics_industry\">electronics</span>, toys, garments, and appliances. Relentless urbanisation fused these cities into a single conurbation that <b>the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Bank\">World Bank</span> in 2015</b> pronounced the largest urban area on Earth, having overtaken <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Greater_Tokyo_Area\">Greater Tokyo</span>, and with Hong Kong and Macau it now forms the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangdong–Hong_Kong–Macau_Greater_Bay_Area\">Greater Bay Area</span> of some 86 million people whose economy approaches 2 trillion US dollars, comparable to a major industrial nation. Engineering ties the estuary ever tighter, from the 55-kilometre (34 mi) <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong–Zhuhai–Macau_Bridge\">Hong Kong–Zhuhai–Macau Bridge</span> of 2018</b> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shenzhen–Zhongshan_Link\">Shenzhen–Zhongshan Link</span> opened in 2024 to the cross-border <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou–Shenzhen–Hong_Kong_Express_Rail_Link\">Express Rail Link</span>, alongside container ports and airports that rank among the world’s busiest. <br> <br> The delta was the land of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Baiyue\">Yue</span> peoples until the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_dynasty\">Qin</span> conquest, after which the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanyue\">Nanyue</span> kingdom ruled from the site of Guangzhou <b>from 204 BCE</b>, beginning 2 millennia in which the estuary served as China’s great southern gate on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maritime_Silk_Road\">Maritime Silk Road</span>. Under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Canton_System\">Canton System</span> from 1757 all Western trade funnelled past the forts of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bocca_Tigris\">Bocca Tigris</span> to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Whampoa_anchorage\">Whampoa anchorage</span>, and the commissioner <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lin_Zexu\">Lin Zexu</span>’s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Destruction_of_opium_at_Humen\">destruction of opium at Humen</span> in 1839 ignited the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Opium_War\">First Opium War</span> that planted the colonies of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span> and, beside the older Portuguese enclave of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Macau\">Macau</span>, fixed foreign powers at the delta’s flanks. The crowded waterscape of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sericulture\">silk</span> dikes and paddies also became the principal homeland of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Overseas_Chinese\">overseas Chinese</span>, as emigrants from delta counties such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taishan,_Guangdong\">Taishan</span> built the Chinatowns of the Americas, Australia, and Southeast Asia and sustained their villages with remittances. After 1978 the delta led the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">reform and opening</span> of the entire country, its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Special_economic_zones_of_China\">special economic zones</span> at Shenzhen and Zhuhai pioneering a “front shop, back factory” partnership with Hong Kong that drew an outsized share of national <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foreign_direct_investment\">foreign direct investment</span> and tens of millions of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Migrant_workers_in_China\">migrant workers</span>, a course sealed by <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping's_southern_tour\">Deng Xiaoping’s southern tour</span></b> of 1992. The 2019 Greater Bay Area blueprint now seeks to weld the 9 mainland cities with the 2 special administrative regions into an innovation cluster rivalling the bay areas of San Francisco and Tokyo, even as rising costs, automation, and trade tensions push the old workshop economy up the value chain.","citation":"","answerText":"Pearl River Delta"},{"id":"cng-086","num":"八十六","category":"China · Geography","question":"A prosperous, densely populated region where the country's longest river reaches the sea, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> centred on Shanghai and the cities of Jiangsu and Zhejiang generates a huge share of national output.","answer":"Yangtze Delta","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">长江三角洲 ('Yangtze delta')</span></div>","traditional":"長江三角洲","hanzi":"长江三角洲","pinyin":"Cháng Jiāng Sānjiǎozhōu","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Cháng Jiāng Sānjiǎozhōu</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Yangtze Delta</b> is both the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"River_delta\">river delta</span></b> where the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span> meets the sea and the surrounding megaregion of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiangsu\">Jiangsu</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhejiang\">Zhejiang</span>, joined under a <b>2019 national</b> plan by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anhui\">Anhui</span>, which on under 4 percent of China's land holds some 235 million people and produces roughly 24 percent of national output, on the order of 4 trillion dollars. The land itself is alluvium laid down over the past 6,000–7,000 years, a plain mostly below 10 meters (33 ft) laced with canals around <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lake_Tai\">Lake Tai</span></b> and capped at the river mouth by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chongming_Island\">Chongming Island</span>, at 1,267 square kilometers (489 sq mi) the world's largest alluvial island, though 20th-century groundwater pumping sank Shanghai by about 2.6 meters (8.5 ft) and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Subsidence\">subsidence</span>, salt intrusion, and typhoons still stalk the lowland. Civilization here is ancient, from the 5,000-year jade city of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liangzhu_culture\">Liangzhu culture</span> to the medieval flowering of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiangnan\">Jiangnan</span>, when the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Grand_Canal_(China)\">Grand Canal</span> and the southward shift of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song dynasty</span> made the delta the empire's granary and treasury, proverbially heaven on earth. Under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span> and Qing its cotton and silk towns ran a proto-industrial economy whose wealth schooled a wildly disproportionate share of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Imperial_examination\">imperial examination</span> graduates. The modern relay began when treaty-port Shanghai <b>opened in 1843</b>, resumed in the 1980s with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Township_and_village_enterprises\">township and village enterprises</span> of southern Jiangsu and the private bootstrapping of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wenzhou\">Wenzhou</span>, and accelerated when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pudong\">Pudong</span> rose <b>from paddies after 1990</b>. <br> <br> Today the delta is a constellation of specialized giants, with Shanghai anchoring finance through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_Stock_Exchange\">Shanghai Stock Exchange</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Suzhou\">Suzhou</span> running the largest prefecture-level economy at around 2.5 trillion yuan, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hangzhou\">Hangzhou</span> hosting <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Alibaba_Group\">Alibaba</span> while Shanghai bred <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pinduoduo\">Pinduoduo</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanjing\">Nanjing</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ningbo\">Ningbo</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuxi\">Wuxi</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hefei\">Hefei</span>, home of the quantum laboratories of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"University_of_Science_and_Technology_of_China\">University of Science and Technology of China</span></b>, filling out the bench. Its factories span chips from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"SMIC\">SMIC</span> and the Wuxi fabs to the Shanghai gigafactory that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tesla,_Inc.\">Tesla</span> opened in 2019 as China's first wholly foreign-owned car plant, now turning out hundreds of thousands of vehicles a year. Twin port lungs breathe for the region, as the offshore terminals of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangshan_Port\">Yangshan</span> keep Shanghai the world's busiest container harbor while the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Port_of_Ningbo-Zhoushan\">Port of Ningbo-Zhoushan</span></b> leads the planet in cargo tonnage at roughly 1.3 billion tonnes (1400 million tons). Integration has become state strategy, knitting the cities into commuting circles with the country's densest mesh of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"High-speed_rail_in_China\">high-speed rail</span>, the 36-kilometer (22 mi) <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hangzhou_Bay_Bridge\">Hangzhou Bay Bridge</span> opened in 2008, and a cross-border ecological demonstration zone around Lake Tai. Aging populations, rising costs, and the lake's algal scars temper the triumph, yet the delta remains the place where China concentrates its bet that a quarter of its economy can keep inventing the next one.","citation":"","answerText":"Yangtze Delta"},{"id":"cng-088","num":"八十八","category":"China · Geography","question":"Officially numbering 55 recognised groups alongside the dominant majority, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> — together about a tenth of the population — include the Zhuang, Uyghurs and Tibetans, and are concentrated largely in the border regions.","answer":"Ethnic minorities","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">少数民族 (shǎoshù mínzú, 'minority nationalities')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"","pinyin":"","translations":"","abstract":"<b>Ethnic minorities</b> in China are the 55 officially recognized peoples who, alongside the dominant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Chinese\">Han</span>, make up the state's 56-group ethnic framework, counting 125.5 million people or 8.9 percent of the population in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2020_Chinese_census\"><b>2020 census</span></b> against the Han's 91.1 percent. The roster emerged from the 1950s classification project, which sifted over 400 self-declared groups using criteria adapted from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joseph_Stalin\">Joseph Stalin</span>'s nationality theory before the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"List_of_ethnic_groups_in_China\">official list</span> closed <b>with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jino_people\">Jino</span> in 1979</b>, leaving hundreds of thousands in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Unrecognized_ethnic_groups_in_China\">unrecognized groups</span> and folding all <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwanese_indigenous_peoples\">Taiwanese indigenous peoples</span> into a single category. The groups span a vast size spectrum, from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuang_people\">Zhuang</span> at 19.6 million, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Uyghurs\">Uyghurs</span> at 11.8 million, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hui_people\">Hui</span> at 11.4 million, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Miao_people\">Miao</span> at 11.1 million, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manchu_people\">Manchu</span> at 10.4 million, through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yi_people\">Yi</span>, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tujia_people\">Tujia</span></b>, 7.1 million <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_people\">Tibetans</span>, and 6.3 million <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongols_in_China\">Mongols</span>, down to the roughly 4,000 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lhoba_people\">Lhoba</span>. Though only a 10th of the population, minorities predominate across great stretches of the strategic frontier, administered through a pyramid of 5 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Autonomous_regions_of_China\">autonomous regions</span>, 30 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Autonomous_prefecture\">autonomous prefectures</span>, and some 120 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Autonomous_county\">autonomous counties</span> under the <b>1984 autonomy</b> law. Their hundred-plus languages range across the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-Tibetan_languages\">Sino-Tibetan</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Turkic_languages\">Turkic</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kra–Dai_languages\">Kra–Dai</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hmong–Mien_languages\">Hmong–Mien</span> families and even Indo-European <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sarikoli_language\">Sarikoli</span>, with 4 minority scripts printed on every note of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Renminbi\">renminbi</span>. <br> <br> State policy long mixed control with preference, granting an <b>early form of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Affirmative_action_in_China\">affirmative action</span></b> through partial exemption from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"One-child_policy\">one-child policy</span>, bonus points on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gaokao\">gaokao</span>, and guaranteed seats in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_People's_Congress\">National People's Congress</span>. The framework descends from the multiethnic Qing empire through the republic's 1912 flag of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five_Races_Under_One_Union\">Five Races Under One Union</span> to the communists' Soviet-inspired regional autonomy, adopted in place of federation after 1949. Officially the diversity is celebrated, with the Dai <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Water-Splashing_Festival\">Water-Splashing Festival</span></b>, the Yi <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Torch_Festival\">Torch Festival</span>, and dozens of epics and crafts honored as national heritage and paraded as the unity of one family. Since the 2010s, however, scholars describe an assimilationist turn, visible in Mandarin-first schooling that sparked the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2020_Inner_Mongolia_protests\">2020 Inner Mongolia protests</span></b>, campaigns for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sinicization\">Sinicization</span> of religion, and above all the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinjiang_internment_camps\">Xinjiang internment camps</span> and the roughly halved Uyghur birthrate of 2017–2019, policies Beijing defends as development and counter-extremism. Because the minority homelands hold the headwaters, pastures, and borders of the state, the standing of these 55 peoples within the officially promoted \"Chinese nation\" remains one of the country's most consequential questions.","citation":"","answerText":"Ethnic minorities"},{"id":"cng-089","num":"八十九","category":"China · Geography","question":"The most numerous of the country's ethnic minorities, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> are concentrated in the southern autonomous region of Guangxi and neighbouring Yunnan, having a script of their own based on Chinese characters.","answer":"Zhuang people","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">壮族 (Zhuàngzú)</span></div>","traditional":"壯族","hanzi":"壮族","pinyin":"Zhuàngzú","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhuàngzú</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Zhuang people</b> are the most numerous of China’s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ethnic_minorities_in_China\">ethnic minorities</span>, counting about 19.6 million people in the 2020 census, the great majority living in <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangxi\">Guangxi</span></b>, where they form roughly a third of the population, with further communities in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wenshan_Zhuang_and_Miao_Autonomous_Prefecture\">Wenshan prefecture</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yunnan\">Yunnan</span> and in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangdong\">Guangdong</span>. Their <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuang_languages\">Zhuang languages</span></b>, split into divergent northern and southern groups, belong to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tai_languages\">Tai branch</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kra–Dai_languages\">Kra–Dai family</span> and are thus kin to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Thai_language\">Thai</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lao_language\">Lao</span> rather than to Chinese, though most Zhuang today are bilingual. For over a millennium, since at least the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang dynasty</span>, literate Zhuang have written their tongue in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sawndip\">Sawndip</span>, a folk script of borrowed and invented <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_characters\">Chinese characters</span> used for song texts and ritual manuscripts, supplemented <b>since 1957</b> by an official alphabet, purged of its Cyrillic-style letters in 1982, whose word “Cuengh” appears among the minority scripts printed on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Renminbi\">renminbi</span> banknotes. Zhuang culture is famed for antiphonal singing at open-air song fairs, above all on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Double_Third_Festival\">3rd day of the 3rd lunar month</span>, now a public holiday throughout Guangxi, a tradition personified by the legendary songstress <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Sanjie\">Liu Sanjie</span>, alongside celebrated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Brocade\">brocade</span> weaving and ancient <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bronze_drum\">bronze drums</span></b>. Traditional belief centres on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mo_(religion)\">Mo religion</span> with its creator-ancestor Buluotuo and on rain-bringing frog veneration, imagery that dances across the ochre cliffs of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zuojiang_Huashan_Rock_Art\">Zuojiang Huashan rock art</span>, painted by Zhuang ancestors some 2,000 years ago and inscribed <b>as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Heritage_Site\">World Heritage Site</span> in 2016</b>. <br> <br> The Zhuang descend from the Xi’ou and Luoyue branches of the ancient <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Baiyue\">Baiyue</span>, who fiercely resisted the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_dynasty\">Qin</span> invasion of 214 BCE before their lands were knit to the empire by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lingqu_Canal\">Lingqu Canal</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanyue\">Nanyue</span> kingdom. Through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song</span> era the uplands remained under native lords, one of whom, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nong_Zhigao\">Nong Zhigao</span>, proclaimed <b>an independent state in 1052</b> and besieged Guangzhou before falling to the general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Di_Qing\">Di Qing</span>, after which the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span> governed through hereditary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tusi\">tusi</span> chieftains only gradually replaced by regular officials. Zhuang villagers were deeply entangled in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiping_Rebellion\">Taiping Rebellion</span>, supplying many of the earliest soldiers and several commanders of the movement that erupted from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jintian_Uprising\">Jintian Uprising</span> in Guangxi in 1851. In 1929 the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Baise_Uprising\">Baise Uprising</span></b>, organised by the young <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> with the Zhuang peasant leader <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wei_Baqun\">Wei Baqun</span>, planted a revolutionary base among Zhuang communities along the Right River, and after 1949 the province was reconstituted in 1958 as the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span> endorsing the 1965 change of the group’s name-character from one meaning “servant” to one meaning “strong.” Comparatively integrated through schooling, intermarriage, and labour migration to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pearl_River_Delta\">Pearl River Delta</span>, the Zhuang anchor a regional economy built on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sugarcane\">sugarcane</span> that yields most of China’s sugar, even as advocates work to revive song fairs, Buluotuo rites, and a language increasingly yielding ground to Mandarin.","citation":"","answerText":"Zhuang people"},{"id":"cng-090","num":"九十","category":"China · Geography","question":"A Turkic-speaking, mostly Muslim people who are the largest indigenous group of Xinjiang, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> traditionally farmed the oases ringing the Tarim Basin along the old Silk Road.","answer":"Uyghurs","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">维吾尔 (Wéiwú'ěr); the name is linked to a sense of 'union'</span></div>","traditional":"維吾爾","hanzi":"维吾尔","pinyin":"Wéiwú'ěr","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Wéiwú'ěr</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Uyghurs</b> are a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Turkic_peoples\">Turkic</span></b> people numbering 11.77 million in China at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2020_Chinese_census\">2020 census</span>, plus a diaspora in Central Asia and beyond, forming the largest group of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinjiang\">Xinjiang</span> at roughly 45 percent and the overwhelming majority in the oasis belt around the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tarim_Basin\">Tarim Basin</span>, anchored by <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kashgar\">Kashgar</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hotan\">Hotan</span> on the old <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk_Road\">Silk Road</span>. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Uyghur_language\">Uyghur language</span> belongs to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Karluk_languages\">Karluk branch</span> closest to Uzbek and is written in an Arabic-derived script, while the faith is <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sunni_Islam\">Sunni Islam</span> threaded with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sufism\">Sufism</span>, adopted after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kara-Khanid_Khanate\">Kara-Khanid</span> conversion began in the 10th century and completed as the Buddhist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kingdom_of_Qocho\">Kingdom of Qocho</span> faded by the 15th. The ethnonym descends from the steppe <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Uyghur_Khaganate\">Uyghur Khaganate</span> of 744–840, whose refugees settled the Turpan oases and mingled with indigenous farmers partly descended from the ancient stock of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tarim_mummies\">Tarim mummies</span>, though the modern collective name was fixed only at a <b>1921</b> émigré conference. Karakhanid Kashgar produced a golden age of letters, when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mahmud_al-Kashgari\">Mahmud al-Kashgari</span> compiled his great dictionary of the Turkic tongues in the 1070s and Yusuf Khass Hajib finished the verse mirror-for-princes <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kutadgu_Bilig\"><i>Kutadgu Bilig</i></span> in 1069. The living culture centers on the 12 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Muqam\">muqam</span> song suites, codified under the 16th-century queen <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Amannisa_Khan\">Amannisa Khan</span> and <b>proclaimed UNESCO heritage in 2005</b>, on communal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Meshrep\">meshrep</span> gatherings listed in 2010, and on a world of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Doppa\">doppa</span> caps, karez-watered melons and grapes, and tables of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lagman\">laghman</span> and polo. <br> <br> In the 20th century Uyghur nationalists twice proclaimed independence, in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_East_Turkestan_Republic\">First East Turkestan Republic</span> at Kashgar in 1933–1934</b> and the Soviet-backed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Second_East_Turkestan_Republic\">Second East Turkestan Republic</span> of 1944–1949, before incorporation into the People's Republic, autonomous-region status in 1955, and settlement driven by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinjiang_Production_and_Construction_Corps\">Xinjiang Production and Construction Corps</span> that cut the Uyghur share of Xinjiang from about 76 percent in 1953 to 45 percent today. Cycles of unrest and crackdown ran from the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ghulja_incident\">Ghulja incident</span></b> of 1997 to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"July_2009_Ürümqi_riots\">2009 Ürümqi riots</span> that officially killed 197 people. After <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Quanguo\">Chen Quanguo</span> took over the region in 2016, researchers and leaks such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinjiang_Police_Files\">Xinjiang Police Files</span> documented the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinjiang_internment_camps\">internment camps</span> holding an estimated million or more, blanket surveillance, mosque demolitions, and birth-control measures under which Uyghur birthrates roughly halved between 2017 and 2019, findings the UN human-rights office <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Office_of_the_United_Nations_High_Commissioner_for_Human_Rights\">OHCHR</span> said in 2022 may constitute crimes against humanity and several parliaments label a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Uyghur_genocide\">Uyghur genocide</span></b>, while Beijing insists the facilities were vocational counter-extremism centers. The economic arm of the dispute produced the 2021 American <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Uyghur_Forced_Labor_Prevention_Act\">Uyghur Forced Labor Prevention Act</span>, presumptively banning Xinjiang cotton, tomatoes, and polysilicon over forced-labor findings. Voices for the community persist against heavy odds, from the imprisoned economist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ilham_Tohti\">Ilham Tohti</span>, awarded the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sakharov_Prize\">Sakharov Prize</span> in 2019 while serving a life sentence, to the exile <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Uyghur_Congress\">World Uyghur Congress</span> long associated with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rebiya_Kadeer\">Rebiya Kadeer</span>, keeping the fate of the oasis people at the center of world attention.","citation":"","answerText":"Uyghurs"},{"id":"cng-091","num":"九十一","category":"China · Geography","question":"An ethnic group native to the high Tibetan Plateau who traditionally herd yaks and follow Tibetan Buddhism, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> live mainly in the Tibet Autonomous Region and parts of the surrounding provinces.","answer":"Tibetan people","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">藏族 (Zàngzú), from Tsang in central Tibet</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"藏族","pinyin":"Zàngzú","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zàngzú</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Tibetan people</b> are an ethnic group native to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_Plateau\">Tibetan Plateau</span>, numbering roughly 7 million within <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> and several hundred <b>thousand more in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_diaspora\">exile</span></b> and the neighbouring Himalaya. Beyond the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibet_Autonomous_Region\">Tibet Autonomous Region</span> they inhabit the historic provinces of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Amdo\">Amdo</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kham\">Kham</span>, now divided among <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qinghai\">Qinghai</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gansu\">Gansu</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan\">Sichuan</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yunnan\">Yunnan</span>, and they speak the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetic_languages\">Tibetic languages</span></b> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-Tibetan_languages\">Sino-Tibetan</span> family, written since the 7th century in a script derived from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Brahmi_script\">Brahmi</span>. Their adaptation to altitudes above 4,000 metres (13,000 ft) is partly genetic, for most carry a variant of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"EPAS1\">EPAS1</span> gene, inherited from the archaic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Denisovan\">Denisovans</span>, that lets them thrive on scarce oxygen without the thickened blood seen in lowlanders. Pastoral life on the plateau revolves around the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Domestic_yak\">yak</span>, whose milk, meat, dung, and wool sustain the nomadic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Drokpa\">drokpa</span> herders, complemented in the valleys by farming of cold-hardy <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Barley\">barley</span>, the staple roasted as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tsampa\">tsampa</span> and drunk with salty <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Butter_tea\">butter tea</span>. Their culture is suffused with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_Buddhism\">Tibetan Buddhism</span>, expressed in the great <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Monastery\">monasteries</span>, the <b>spinning of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Prayer_wheel\">prayer wheels</span></b> and fluttering of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Prayer_flag\">prayer flags</span>, the painting of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Thangka\">thangkas</span>, and the practice of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sky_burial\">sky burial</span>, though some, especially in Amdo, follow the older <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bon\">Bon</span> tradition. <br> <br> The Tibetans entered recorded history when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Songtsen_Gampo\">Songtsen Gampo</span> forged the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_Empire\">Tibetan Empire</span> in the 7th century, a Central Asian power that warred and intermarried with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang</span> China, briefly seized its capital <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chang'an\">Chang’an</span> in 763, and adopted Buddhism under <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Trisong_Detsen\">Trisong Detsen</span></b>, who invited the tantric master <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Padmasambhava\">Padmasambhava</span> to found the monastery of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Samye\">Samye</span>. After the empire fragmented in the 9th century, religious authority rose to the fore, and from the 17th century the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gelug\">Gelug</span> school’s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dalai_Lama\">Dalai Lamas</span> governed much of the plateau from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lhasa\">Lhasa</span> through the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ganden_Phodrang\">Ganden Phodrang</span></b>, under the increasingly formal overlordship of the Mongols and then the Manchu <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span>. Following the Qing collapse Tibet functioned with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibet_(1912–1951)\">de facto independence</span> until the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army\">People’s Liberation Army</span> <b>entered in 1950</b> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Seventeen_Point_Agreement\">Seventeen Point Agreement</span> of 1951 affirmed Chinese sovereignty, but mounting tensions exploded in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1959_Tibetan_uprising\">1959 uprising</span>, after which the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"14th_Dalai_Lama\">14th Dalai Lama</span> fled to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dharamshala\">India</span> and established a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Tibetan_Administration\">government in exile</span>. Monasteries suffered grievously during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span>, and the decades since have brought waves of protest, a contested <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sinicization\">assimilation</span> debate, and a bitter dispute over the reincarnation of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Panchen_Lama\">Panchen Lama</span>, even as state investment, railways, and tourism have reshaped a homeland whose people remain bound to their <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_culture\">distinctive faith and language</span></b>.","citation":"","answerText":"Tibetan people"},{"id":"cng-094","num":"九十四","category":"China · Geography","question":"Based on the Beijing dialect and promoted as the national common tongue under the name <i>Putonghua</i>, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is taught in schools nationwide and written with Chinese characters, unifying speakers of many mutually unintelligible varieties.","answer":"Standard Chinese","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">普通话 (Pǔtōnghuà, 'common speech')</span></div>","traditional":"普通話","hanzi":"普通话","pinyin":"Pǔtōnghuà","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Pǔtōnghuà</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“common speech”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Standard Chinese</b> is the official spoken language of the People's Republic, defined as taking its sounds from the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing_dialect\">Beijing dialect</span></b>, its core vocabulary from northern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mandarin_Chinese\">Mandarin</span>, and its grammar from exemplary modern prose. Its ancestor was the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mandarin_(late_imperial_lingua_franca)\">guanhua</span> koiné that imperial officials spoke across provincial lines for centuries, a standard whose base shifted from Nanjing toward Beijing speech by the 19th century. Republican language planners <b>convened the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Commission_on_the_Unification_of_Pronunciation\">Commission on the Unification of Pronunciation</span> in 1913</b>, whose artificial compromise pronunciation collapsed within a decade in favor of pure Beijing phonology, and the People's Republic rechristened the standard <i>Putonghua</i> in the mid-1950s. The written side was revolutionized when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Shih\">Hu Shih</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"May_Fourth_Movement\">May Fourth</span> generation <b>dethroned <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Classical_Chinese\">Classical Chinese</span> after 1917</b> in favor of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Written_vernacular_Chinese\">written vernacular</span>, after which the mainland adopted <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Simplified_Chinese_characters\">simplified characters</span> in 1956 and 1964 while Taiwan and Hong Kong kept <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Traditional_Chinese_characters\">traditional</span> forms of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_characters\">Chinese characters</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pinyin\">pinyin</span> romanization <b>devised under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Youguang\">Zhou Youguang</span> in 1958</b> joined the older <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bopomofo\">bopomofo</span> as a pronunciation key. Phonologically the standard distinguishes 4 contour <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tone_(linguistics)\">tones</span> plus a neutral tone over only about 400 base syllables, and since 1982 Article 19 of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitution_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">constitution</span> has mandated its nationwide promotion, codified by a 2001 language law. <br> <br> The campaign has been strikingly effective, lifting the share of citizens able to speak the standard from about 53 percent in 2000 to over 80 percent by 2020, with an official target of 85 percent by 2025, enforced through schooling, broadcasting, and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Putonghua_Proficiency_Test\">Putonghua Proficiency Test</span></b> required of teachers and announcers. The result is a vast <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Diglossia\">diglossia</span>, since speakers of the mutually unintelligible <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Varieties_of_Chinese\">varieties of Chinese</span>, from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yue_Chinese\">Yue</span> and its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cantonese\">Cantonese</span> standard to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Chinese\">Wu</span> with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghainese\">Shanghainese</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Min_Chinese\">Min</span> group, switch to Putonghua in public life, fueling worries about dialect erosion among younger generations. In minority regions Mandarin-first schooling has displaced instruction in Tibetan, Uyghur, and Mongolian, igniting the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2020_Inner_Mongolia_protests\">2020 Inner Mongolia protests</span> and sharpening the tension between linguistic unification and diversity. Beyond the mainland the standard lives in variants, from <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwanese_Mandarin\">Taiwanese Mandarin</span></b> with its softer retroflexes to the <i>Huayu</i> promoted in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Singapore\">Singapore</span> by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Speak_Mandarin_Campaign\">Speak Mandarin Campaign</span> launched in 1979. Globally it ranks among the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Official_languages_of_the_United_Nations\">official languages of the United Nations</span></b>, is examined through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hanyu_Shuiping_Kaoshi\">HSK</span> taken by millions of learners and once taught through some 500 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucius_Institute\">Confucius Institutes</span>, and crowns the most natively spoken language family on earth, a deliberately built common tongue for a fifth of humanity.","citation":"","answerText":"Standard Chinese"},{"id":"cng-095","num":"九十五","category":"China · Geography","question":"A major variety of Chinese with a distinctive sound and many tones, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is spoken across Guangdong, in Hong Kong and Macau, and among many overseas Chinese communities.","answer":"Cantonese","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">广东话 (Guǎngdōnghuà, 'Guangdong speech')</span></div>","traditional":"廣東話","hanzi":"广东话","pinyin":"Guǎngdōnghuà","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Guǎngdōnghuà</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Cantonese</b> is the prestige form of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yue_Chinese\">Yue Chinese</span></b>, spoken by on the order of 85 million people across <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangdong\">Guangdong</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pearl_River_Delta\">Pearl River Delta</span>, by roughly 9 in 10 households in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span>, in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Macau\">Macau</span> and eastern Guangxi, making it among the most vigorous of all <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Varieties_of_Chinese\">varieties of Chinese</span></b>. Its sound system distinguishes 6 contour <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tone_(linguistics)\">tones</span> plus 3 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Checked_tone\">checked-tone</span> variants, the traditional \"9 tones,\" and preserves the final consonants -p, -t, -k, and -m of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Middle_Chinese\">Middle Chinese</span></b> that Mandarin has lost. This conservatism means much <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_poetry\">Tang poetry</span> still rhymes and scans when read in Cantonese, fitting for speakers who have called themselves \"people of Tang\" since the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tang_dynasty\">Tang dynasty</span> and whose <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinatown\">Chinatowns</span> worldwide are literally \"Tang people's streets.\" Mutually unintelligible with <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mandarin_Chinese\">Mandarin</span></b> in pronouns, negatives, and core vocabulary, the language takes its standard from the speech of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou\">Guangzhou</span>, was first systematically recorded for Westerners by <b>the missionary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Robert_Morrison_(missionary)\">Robert Morrison</span> in 1828</b>, and is romanized today chiefly through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yale_romanization_of_Cantonese\">Yale system</span> of 1958 and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jyutping\">Jyutping</span> of 1993. Formal documents are composed in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Standard_Chinese\">Standard Chinese</span> and read aloud with Cantonese sounds, but a flourishing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Written_Cantonese\">Written Cantonese</span> with its own characters fills Hong Kong's advertisements, comics, subtitles, and text messages. <br> <br> In Hong Kong and Macau the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_Basic_Law\">Basic Law</span> names only \"Chinese\" as official, which in practice means Cantonese in courtrooms, the legislature, and the studios of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"TVB\">TVB</span>, making it the sole Sinitic variety besides Mandarin with a complete modern media ecosystem. That ecosystem conquered the world in the golden ages of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cantopop\">Cantopop</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cinema_of_Hong_Kong\">cinema of Hong Kong</span>, while the older art of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cantonese_opera\">Cantonese opera</span> was recognized <b>as UNESCO <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Intangible_cultural_heritage\">intangible cultural heritage</span> in 2009</b>. The 19th-century emigration from the delta, including cousins speaking the related <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taishanese\">Taishanese</span>, made Cantonese the lingua franca of overseas communities from San Francisco to Sydney and seeded English with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dim_sum\">dim sum</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wok\">wok</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bok_choy\">bok choy</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kumquat\">kumquat</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chop_suey\">chop suey</span>. On the mainland the variety lives under the pressure of Putonghua schooling, which provoked thousands to rally in the <b>2010 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou_Television_Cantonese_controversy\">Guangzhou Television Cantonese controversy</span></b>, and surveys find Guangzhou youth shifting toward Mandarin even as Hong Kong holds firm within the integrating <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Greater_Bay_Area\">Greater Bay Area</span>. For over a millennium the language has carried the wit, commerce, and song of the south, and whether its 9 tones keep sounding in the megacities of the delta is now one of the liveliest questions in the Chinese-speaking world.","citation":"","answerText":"Cantonese"},{"id":"cng-096","num":"九十六","category":"China · Geography","question":"One of the largest engineering schemes ever attempted, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> diverts water from the wetter Yangtze basin in the south to the parched North China Plain and thirsty Beijing.","answer":"South–North Water Transfer Project","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">南水北调 ('divert southern water to the north')</span></div>","traditional":"南水北調工程","hanzi":"南水北调工程","pinyin":"Nánshuǐ Běidiào Gōngchéng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Nánshuǐ Běidiào Gōngchéng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>South–North Water Transfer Project</b> is the largest <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Interbasin_transfer\">interbasin transfer</span></b> ever built and among the most expensive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Megaproject\">megaprojects</span> in history, conceived to cure the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Water_scarcity\">water scarcity</span> of the north with the abundance of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span> basin, an idea <b>voiced by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> in 1952</b>, approved only in 2002 after 5 decades of study, and costing well over 60 billion dollars. The Eastern Route, opened in 2013, upgrades the ancient <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Grand_Canal_(China)\">Grand Canal</span> from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangzhou\">Yangzhou</span> into a 1,156-kilometer (718 mi) conduit whose 13-stage cascade of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pumping_station\">pumping stations</span>, the mightiest on earth, lifts water some 65 meters (210 ft) on its way to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shandong\">Shandong</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tianjin\">Tianjin</span>. The Middle Route, flowing <b>since December 2014</b>, raised the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Danjiangkou_Dam\">Danjiangkou Dam</span> on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_River_(Yangtze_River_tributary)\">Han River</span> to 176.6 meters (579 ft), displacing about 345,000 people, and sends water 1,432 kilometers (890 mi) by gravity across <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Henan\">Henan</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hebei\">Hebei</span>, diving beneath the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_River\">Yellow River</span> near <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhengzhou\">Zhengzhou</span> through twin 4-kilometer (2.5 mi) tunnels and riding immense <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Aqueduct_(water_supply)\">aqueducts</span> to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Miyun_Reservoir\">Miyun Reservoir</span></b>. A Western Route, which would carry headwaters of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jinsha_River\">Jinsha</span> across the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_Plateau\">Tibetan Plateau</span> into the Yellow River, remains unbuilt amid seismic and ecological doubts. Designed ultimately to move around 45 billion cubic meters a year, the system had delivered a cumulative 70-plus billion cubic meters to more than 40 cities and some <b>185 million people by 2024</b>, and the capital now draws roughly 3 quarters of its tap water from the canal. <br> <br> The northern dividends are measurable, for decades of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Overdrafting\">overdrafting</span> had drained the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"North_China_Plain\">North China Plain</span>'s great <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Aquifer\">aquifer</span>, whose <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Groundwater\">groundwater</span> levels began rebounding after 2018, while long-dead streams like the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yongding_River\">Yongding River</span> flowed full-length in 2021 for the first time in a quarter century and the replenished marshes of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Baiyangdian\">Baiyangdian</span> now anchor the new city of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiong'an\">Xiong'an</span>. The south pays the bill in kind, since diversion takes roughly a 3rd of the Han's flow, straining navigation and ecology downstream in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hubei\">Hubei</span>, while resettled farmers nurse lasting grievances. The Eastern Route demanded a <b>parallel war on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Water_pollution\">water pollution</span></b>, with hundreds of treatment plants built so that the once <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eutrophication\">eutrophic</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nansi_Lake\">Nansi Lake</span> could pass drinkable water north. Critics object that the transferred water costs several times local supplies, that pumping devours energy, and that demand-side fixes from <b>pricing to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sponge_city\">sponge cities</span></b> deserved priority, while planners reply that no conservation could close the capital region's structural deficit. The replumbing continues regardless, as work began in 2022 on the 194.8-kilometer (121 mi) Yinjiangbuhan tunnel, the longest water tunnel ever attempted, to refill Danjiangkou from the reservoir of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Gorges_Dam\">Three Gorges Dam</span> by the early 2030s, extending humanity's boldest attempt to rearrange a continent's rivers.","citation":"","answerText":"South–North Water Transfer Project"},{"id":"cng-097","num":"九十七","category":"China · Geography","question":"Reaching over 5,000 m (16,000 ft) at its highest pass — the highest railway in the world — the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> carries trains with extra oxygen across the permafrost of the high plateau to connect Lhasa with the rest of the country.","answer":"Qinghai–Tibet railway","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">青藏铁路 ('Qinghai–Tibet railway')</span></div>","traditional":"青藏鐵路","hanzi":"青藏铁路","pinyin":"Qīngzàng Tiělù","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Qīngzàng Tiělù</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Qinghai–Tibet railway</b> is the 1,956-kilometer (1,215 mi) line from <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xining\">Xining</span></b> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qinghai\">Qinghai</span> to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lhasa\">Lhasa</span>, whose first stage reached <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Golmud\">Golmud</span> <b>across the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qaidam_Basin\">Qaidam Basin</span> in 1984</b> and whose 1,142-kilometer (710 mi) second stage, built from 2001 to 2006 for some 33 billion yuan, opened on 1 July 2006 as the first railway ever to enter the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibet_Autonomous_Region\">Tibet Autonomous Region</span>. Climbing past the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kunlun_Mountain_Pass\">Kunlun Mountain Pass</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kunlun_Mountains\">Kunlun Mountains</span>, the track crests the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tanggula_Pass\">Tanggula Pass</span></b> at 5,072 meters (16,640 ft), the highest rails on earth, served by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tanggula_railway_station\">Tanggula station</span> at 5,068 meters (16,630 ft) and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fenghuoshan_Tunnel\">Fenghuoshan Tunnel</span> at 4,905 meters (16,090 ft), with about 960 kilometers (600 mi) of line above 4,000 meters (13,000 ft). Roughly 550 kilometers (340 mi) ride on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Permafrost\">permafrost</span>, kept frozen by elevated viaducts, crushed-rock embankments, and thousands of ammonia-filled <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Thermosyphon\">thermosyphons</span> that wick summer heat out of the ground against a warming climate. Passengers are <b>shielded from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Altitude_sickness\">altitude sickness</span></b> by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Oxygen\">oxygen</span>-enriched carriages developed with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bombardier_Transportation\">Bombardier</span>, complete with per-seat outlets, onboard medics, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ultraviolet\">ultraviolet</span>-filtering windows, while <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"General_Electric\">General Electric</span></b>-built <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Railways_NJ2\">NJ2 diesels</span> haul the high section. Even the wildlife was engineered for, with 33 passages beneath the line through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hoh_Xil\">Hoh Xil</span> that let migrating <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tibetan_antelope\">Tibetan antelope</span> herds, since rebounded, cross to their calving grounds. <br> <br> The building itself became legend, for surveys begun in the 1950s had stalled at Golmud before the frozen ground, until the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Western_Development\">Western Development</span> drive <b>revived the project in 2001</b> and some 100,000 workers, supported by 17 oxygen-generating stations and roadside clinics, completed it with officials reporting not a single death from altitude sickness. The effects were immediate, as freight costs to Lhasa fell by roughly two-thirds, through trains linked the capital 40 hours away in Beijing, and annual visitors to Tibet multiplied from <b>under 2 million in 2005</b> to tens of millions, forcing timed tickets at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Potala_Palace\">Potala Palace</span>. Critics led by the exile <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Tibetan_Administration\">Central Tibetan Administration</span> warned the line would accelerate migration and military logistics in what some called a second invasion, while Beijing hailed it as development and integration made steel. The network has since grown, with a branch to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shigatse\">Shigatse</span> in 2014, the electrified <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lhasa–Nyingchi_railway\">Lhasa–Nyingchi railway</span> of 2021 carrying <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fuxing_(train)\">Fuxing</span> trainsets to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nyingchi\">Nyingchi</span> at 160 kilometers per hour (99 mph), and the vastly harder <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan–Tibet_railway\">Sichuan–Tibet railway</span> tunneling toward completion in the 2030s. The singer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Hong_(singer)\">Han Hong</span> fixed the line in popular memory with her anthem <i>Tianlu</i>, celebrating a heavenly road where antelope, oxygen masks, and prayer flags now share a single horizon.","citation":"","answerText":"Qinghai–Tibet railway"},{"id":"cng-098","num":"九十八","category":"China · Geography","question":"Long the most populous country on Earth before being overtaken by India, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> covers a population now ageing and beginning to shrink after decades of the one-child policy, with people heavily concentrated in the east.","answer":"Demographics of China","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">中国人口 ('population of China')</span></div>","traditional":"中國人口","hanzi":"中国人口","pinyin":"Zhōngguó rénkǒu","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōngguó rénkǒu</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>demographics of China</b> concern the population that was long the largest on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Earth\">Earth</span>, counted at 1.412 billion in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2020_Chinese_census\"><b>2020</b> census</span>, until <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"India\">India</span> overtook it in 2023, with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Bureau_of_Statistics_of_China\">National Bureau of Statistics</span> confirming that outright <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Population_decline\">population decline</span> <b>began in 2022</b> and had trimmed the total to about 1.408 billion by the end of 2024. Annual births collapsed from 17.9 million in 2016 to 9.0 million in 2023, recovering only to 9.5 million in the auspicious dragon year of 2024, as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Total_fertility_rate\">total fertility rate</span> sank toward 1.0–1.2 children per woman, among the lowest <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Birth_rate\">birth rates</span> recorded anywhere. The mirror image is the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Aging_of_China\">aging of China</span>, with 310 million people aged 60 or above, some 22 percent, <b>by 2024</b>, a median age near 40 against India's 28, and projections of roughly 500 million elderly by 2050, while <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_Nations\">United Nations</span> medium scenarios see the population near 630 million by 2100. The working-age population peaked around 2012, closing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Demographic_dividend\">demographic dividend</span> that powered the boom decades, pushing up the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dependency_ratio\">dependency ratio</span></b> and straining <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pension\">pension</span> finances enough that retirement ages began rising in 2025. The modern trajectory started from 583 million at the 1953 count, surged under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> despite the tens of millions lost to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Chinese_Famine\">Great Chinese Famine</span>, and had already seen fertility fall from 6 to 2.7 under the 1970s later-longer-fewer campaign before stricter limits arrived. <br> <br> The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"One-child_policy\">one-child policy</span> of 1980–2015, enforced with fines, sterilizations, and abortions, officially claimed 400 million averted births, a figure scholars dispute, and left deep scars, <b>since <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sex-selective_abortion\">sex-selective abortion</span></b> drove the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Human_sex_ratio\">sex ratio</span> at birth to about 121 boys per 100 girls in the mid-2000s, creating tens of millions of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Missing_women\">missing women</span> and surplus bachelors, <b>alongside the pampered <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Little_Emperor_Syndrome\">little emperor</span></b> generation, unregistered <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heihaizi\">heihaizi</span> children, and inverted 4-2-1 family trees. Reversal came too late to matter, as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Two-child_policy\">two-child policy</span> of 2016 and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three-child_policy\">three-child policy</span> of 2021 gave way to cash allowances and a 2025 national childcare subsidy of 3,600 yuan per young child, even as marriage registrations crashed from 13.5 million in 2013 to a record-low 6.1 million in 2024. Geographically the people remain spectacularly lopsided, with about 94 percent living east of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heihe–Tengchong_Line\">Heihe–Tengchong Line</span></b>, urbanization risen from 19 percent in 1980 to 67 percent in 2024, and a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Floating_population\">floating population</span> of some 376 million <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Migrant_workers_in_China\">migrant workers</span> still sorted by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hukou\">hukou</span> registration system. In composition the nation is 91.1 percent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Chinese\">Han</span> alongside the 8.9 percent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ethnic_minorities_in_China\">ethnic minorities</span>, with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Life_expectancy\">life expectancy</span> approaching 79 years. The defining question is whether productivity and automation can outrun an inverting age pyramid, for a country that grew rich on abundant youth must now learn to prosper while growing old.","citation":"","answerText":"Demographics of China"},{"id":"cng-099","num":"九十九","category":"China · Geography","question":"Marking much of the border between China and North Korea, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was crossed by Chinese troops entering the Korean War in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>.","answer":"Yalu River","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">鸭绿江 (Yālù Jiāng, 'duck-green river')</span></div>","traditional":"鴨綠江","hanzi":"鸭绿江","pinyin":"Yālù Jiāng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Yālù Jiāng</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“duck-green river”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Yalu River</b> flows about 795 kilometers (494 mi) from the crater lake of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heaven_Lake\">Heaven Lake</span></b> on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paektu_Mountain\">Paektu Mountain</span> in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Changbai_Mountains\">Changbai range</span>, sweeping southwest between <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jilin\">Jilin</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liaoning\">Liaoning</span> on one bank and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"North_Korea\">North Korea</span></b> on the other to enter <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Korea_Bay\">Korea Bay</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yellow_Sea\">Yellow Sea</span> between <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dandong\">Dandong</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sinuiju\">Sinuiju</span>, forming with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tumen_River\">Tumen</span> nearly the whole <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China–North_Korea_border\">China–North Korea border</span></b>. Its middle valley cradled the kingdom of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Goguryeo\">Goguryeo</span>, whose early capitals near <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ji'an,_Jilin\">Ji'an</span> survive in the walls and painted tombs <b>inscribed by UNESCO in 2004</b> as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capital_Cities_and_Tombs_of_the_Ancient_Koguryo_Kingdom\">Capital Cities and Tombs of the Ancient Koguryo Kingdom</span>, while a 1962 treaty assigned most of the river's 200-odd islands to Pyongyang. The name rang through modern military history twice before 1950, in <b>the naval <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_the_Yalu_River_(1894)\">Battle of the Yalu River</span> of 1894</b> that decided the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Sino-Japanese_War\">First Sino-Japanese War</span> at sea, and in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Yalu_River_(1904)\">Battle of Yalu River</span> of 1904, the first major land clash of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russo-Japanese_War\">Russo-Japanese War</span>. Colonial engineers then harnessed the stream <b>with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sup'ung_Dam\">Sup'ung Dam</span> of 1937–1943</b>, a 106-meter (348 ft) wall that was Asia's largest hydroelectric work of its day and still anchors a cascade whose power both banks share. Cutting gorges through dense Changbai forest and freezing solid in winter, the river has served armies as both moat and highway for 2 millennia. <br> <br> Its fateful hour came in October 1950, when, as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Douglas_MacArthur\">Douglas MacArthur</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_Nations_Command\">United Nations Command</span> raced toward the river, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Volunteer_Army\">People's Volunteer Army</span> under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peng_Dehuai\">Peng Dehuai</span> began slipping across on the night of 19 October, an initial force of some 260,000 that grew over the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Korean_War\">Korean War</span> to nearly 3 million who served, transforming the conflict at the cost of hundreds of thousands of Chinese lives. American pilots were ordered in November 1950 to bomb only the Korean halves of the bridges, and the skies upstream became <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"MiG_Alley\">MiG Alley</span>, where the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mikoyan-Gurevich_MiG-15\">MiG-15</span> dueled the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"North_American_F-86_Sabre\">F-86 Sabre</span> in history's first great jet-against-jet arena. At Dandong the amputated half of the 1911 \"Broken Bridge\" still ends mid-river beside the functioning <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-Korean_Friendship_Bridge\">Sino-Korean Friendship Bridge</span></b> of 1943, which carries the great bulk, roughly 70 percent, of North Korea's foreign trade. A 4-lane <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Yalu_River_Bridge\">New Yalu River Bridge</span> completed in 2014 stood unopened for a decade with no roads built on the far side, an emblem of stalled opening in the age of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sanctions_against_North_Korea\">sanctions against North Korea</span>, even as nighttime smuggling plies the channel. Along the upper reaches a trickle of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"North_Korean_defectors\">North Korean defectors</span> still braves the current or the winter ice, while tourist boats from Dandong glide within meters of the opposite shore, making the duck-green river at once a frontier, a lifeline, and an open-air museum of the 20th century.","citation":"","answerText":"Yalu River"},{"id":"cng-100","num":"一百","category":"China · Geography","question":"Remarkably for so wide a country, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> keeps the entire nation — from the Pamirs in the west to the Pacific coast — on a single standard set to Beijing, so that the sun can rise hours \"late\" by the clock in the far west of Xinjiang.","answer":"Timezones in China","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">中国时区 ('time zones of China')</span></div>","traditional":"中國時區","hanzi":"中国时区","pinyin":"Zhōngguó shíqū","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōngguó shíqū</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Timezones in China</b> present a striking anomaly, for a territory spanning some <b>62 degrees of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Longitude\">longitude</span></b> from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pamir_Mountains\">Pamirs</span> near 73°E to the Pacific near 135°E, naturally covering 5 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Time_zone\">time zones</span>, has since 1949 run on a single standard, Beijing Time at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"UTC+08:00\">UTC+08:00</span>, making it the most populous time zone on earth, shared by 1.4 billion clocks referenced to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Coordinated_Universal_Time\">Coordinated Universal Time</span>. The standard descends from the \"coast time\" that the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Maritime_Customs_Service\">Chinese Maritime Customs Service</span> <b>adopted in 1902</b>, pegged 8 hours ahead of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Greenwich_Mean_Time\">Greenwich</span> on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"120th_meridian_east\">120th meridian east</span> for treaty ports like <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span>. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Republic_of_China_(1912–1949)\">Republic of China</span> <b>formalized 5 zones in 1918</b>, running from a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kunlun_Mountains\">Kunlun</span> zone at UTC+5:30 through Xinjiang–Tibet, Gansu–Sichuan, and Central zones to Changbai time at UTC+8:30 in the far northeast. The People's Republic swept these away in favor of one national hour as a symbol of unity, with the mild irony that the reference meridian lies east of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> itself, whose own <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Solar_time\">solar time</span> runs about 14 minutes behind the clock. The arrangement admits no seasonal tinkering either, since a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Daylight_saving_time\">daylight saving</span> experiment of 1986–1991</b> was abandoned, while <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Macau\">Macau</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span> all happen to keep the same offset, placing the whole Chinese world on one hour. <br> <br> The consequences are most theatrical in the far west, where <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kashgar\">Kashgar</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinjiang\">Xinjiang</span> sees solar noon near 3 in the afternoon, winter <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sunrise\">sunrise</span></b> after 10:00, and summer daylight lingering past 22:30, so that offices open at 10:00 and the region runs official \"work-rest\" schedules shifted 2 hours. Many residents, particularly <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Uyghurs\">Uyghurs</span>, keep unofficial <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinjiang_Time\">Xinjiang Time</span> at UTC+6 while <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_Chinese\">Han</span> neighbors favor Beijing time, an ethnically inflected double-clock life in which every appointment in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ürümqi\">Ürümqi</span> requires asking which time is meant. The opposite extreme lies in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heilongjiang\">Heilongjiang</span>, where the \"east pole\" town of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fuyuan,_Heilongjiang\">Fuyuan</span> greets summer sunrises before 4:00 and winter dusk by mid-afternoon. Defenders prize the coordination, for the 19:00 <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinwen_Lianbo\">Xinwen Lianbo</span></b> newscast airs simultaneously nationwide and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Railway\">China Railway</span> runs a single timetable, a simplicity that contrasts with the 4 zones described under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Time_in_the_United_States\">time in the United States</span> and the <b>11 under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Time_in_Russia\">time in Russia</span></b>, while India similarly binds its breadth to one <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Indian_Standard_Time\">Indian Standard Time</span>. Researchers counter that westerners' <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Circadian_rhythm\">circadian rhythms</span> drift hours behind the official day at measurable cost in sleep, a quiet reminder that however firmly the state fixes the hour, the sun keeps its own time.","citation":"","answerText":"Timezones in China"},{"id":"cne-004","num":"四","category":"China · Economics","question":"Descended from the old State Planning Commission that drafted the early five-year plans, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> approves major projects, sets many prices, and steers industrial policy in the era of the socialist market economy.","answer":"National Development and Reform Commission","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">国家发展和改革委员会 ('national development and reform commission')</span></div>","traditional":"國家發展和改革委員會","hanzi":"国家发展和改革委员会","pinyin":"Guójiā Fāzhǎn hé Gǎigé Wěiyuánhuì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Guójiā Fāzhǎn hé Gǎigé Wěiyuánhuì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>National Development and Reform Commission</b> is a cabinet-level macroeconomic management agency of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span> that operates under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_Council_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">State Council</span> and ranks among the most powerful organs of the central government. It traces its institutional descent to the <b>State Planning Commission</b>, <b>founded in 1952</b> and modelled directly on the Soviet <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gosplan\">Gosplan</span>, the central agency that imported the apparatus of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Planned_economy\">planned economy</span> into China during the early years of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>'s rule. That predecessor drafted <b>China's first <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five-year_plans_of_China\">Five-Year Plan</span> for 1953–1957</b>, a programme of state-directed industrialisation patterned on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five-year_plans_of_the_Soviet_Union\">five-year plans of the Soviet Union</span> and emphasising <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heavy_industry\">heavy industry</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_enterprises_of_China\">state-owned enterprises</span>. As the rigid command system gradually gave way to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">reform and opening-up</span> initiated by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> after 1978, the commission's mandate shifted from comprehensive central allocation toward indicative <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Macroeconomics\">macroeconomic</span> guidance, and <b>in 1998</b> it was renamed the <b>State Development Planning Commission</b>. The body assumed its present name and greatly enlarged remit in March 2003, when a restructuring approved by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_People's_Congress\">National People's Congress</span> merged the planning commission with the former State Economic and Trade Commission and parts of the office overseeing economic restructuring, consolidating sweeping authority over the emerging <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialist_market_economy\">socialist market economy</span>. <br> <br> Often nicknamed the \"mini State Council\" for the breadth of its jurisdiction, it approves large-scale investment projects, exercises residual <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Price_controls\">price controls</span> over goods and services such as utilities and transport, and directs <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Industrial_policy\">industrial policy</span> across broad swathes of the economy. It remains the principal drafter of the recurring five-year plans and of national development strategies, setting headline targets for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gross_domestic_product\">economic growth</span> and structural transformation, whereas <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Inflation\">inflation</span>, interest rates, and monetary policy fall instead to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Bank_of_China\">People's Bank of China</span>. Numerous major programmes and agencies operate under its umbrella, among them the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Energy_Administration\">National Energy Administration</span></b> that shapes <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Energy_policy_of_China\">energy policy</span>, the regional <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Western_Development\">Western Development</span> strategy, and coordination of the cross-border <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Belt_and_Road_Initiative\">Belt and Road Initiative</span>. A sweeping institutional reform in 2018 pared back its portfolio, transferring climate-change responsibilities to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ministry_of_Ecology_and_Environment\">Ministry of Ecology and Environment</span>, price-related antitrust enforcement under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anti-Monopoly_Law_of_China\">Anti-Monopoly Law</span> to the newly created <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_Administration_for_Market_Regulation\">State Administration for Market Regulation</span>, and drug-pricing powers to the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Healthcare_Security_Administration\">National Healthcare Security Administration</span></b>. Even after decades of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Market_economy\">market</span> liberalisation that left well over 90 percent of prices determined by supply and demand, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>-headquartered commission—answerable to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Premier_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">Premier</span>—continues to set corporate <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bond_(finance)\">bond</span> quotas, regulate strategic sectors, and serve as the chief architect of China's long-term economic planning.","citation":"","answerText":"National Development and Reform Commission"},{"id":"cne-005","num":"五","category":"China · Economics","question":"Modelled on the Soviet system during the five-year plans of the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>s, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was largely dismantled after the reforms of Deng Xiaoping.","answer":"Planned economy","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Origin</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Modelled on Soviet central planning (Gosplan), from the 1920s</span></div>","traditional":"計劃經濟","hanzi":"计划经济","pinyin":"jìhuà jīngjì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">jìhuà jīngjì</span></div>","abstract":"A <b>planned economy</b> is a <b>type of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economic_system\">economic system</span></b> in which decisions about production, investment, and the allocation of resources are made through centralized state directives and quantitative output targets rather than through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Price_signal\">price signals</span> of a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Market_economy\">market economy</span>. Its intellectual foundations lie in the 19th-century critique of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capitalism\">capitalism</span> advanced by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Karl_Marx\">Karl Marx</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Friedrich_Engels\">Friedrich Engels</span>, who envisioned that <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialism\">socialist</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Communism\">communist</span> societies would supersede the disorder of private markets by bringing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Means_of_production\">means of production</span> under conscious collective control. Whether such an economy could function efficiently became the subject of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialist_calculation_debate\">socialist calculation debate</span>, <b>opened in 1920</b> by the Austrian economist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ludwig_von_Mises\">Ludwig von Mises</span> in his essay <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economic_Calculation_in_the_Socialist_Commonwealth\"><i>Economic Calculation in the Socialist Commonwealth</i></span>, who contended that without market prices rational allocation was impossible, a position later sharpened by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Friedrich_Hayek\">Friedrich Hayek</span> and challenged by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Market_socialism\">market-socialist</span> model of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Oskar_Lange\">Oskar Lange</span>. The first large-scale application came in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Soviet Union</span>, where after the <b>improvisations of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"War_communism\">war communism</span></b> and the partial market revival of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Economic_Policy\">New Economic Policy</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joseph_Stalin\">Joseph Stalin</span> launched a sweeping program of forced industrialization and agricultural <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Collectivization_in_the_Soviet_Union\">collectivization</span> through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five-year_plans_of_the_Soviet_Union\">five-year plans</span> <b>beginning in 1928</b>. Coordination fell to the central planning agency <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gosplan\">Gosplan</span>, which relied on a technique of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Material_balance_planning\">material balance planning</span> to match the supply and demand of key commodities, a task of staggering complexity in an economy that by the 1980s encompassed an estimated 12 million or more distinct products, of which planners could realistically set physical targets for only a few thousand. <br> <br> <b>After 1945</b> the model was extended across the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eastern_Bloc\">Eastern Bloc</span> and coordinated through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Comecon\">Comecon</span>, and it was adopted in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Republic_of_China\">People's Republic of China</span>, whose <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five-year_plans_of_China\">First Five-Year Plan</span> of 1953–1957 centered on the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"156_Projects\">156 major industrial projects</span> built</b> with Soviet assistance. Under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> the Chinese command economy was pushed to radical extremes during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Leap_Forward\">Great Leap Forward</span>, and at their height centrally planned economies are estimated to have governed roughly a third of the world's population. Critics drew attention to chronic inefficiency, distorted incentives, and persistent scarcities, most influentially the Hungarian economist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"János_Kornai\">János Kornai</span>, who in works such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economics_of_Shortage\"><i>Economics of Shortage</i></span> characterized socialist states as a perpetual <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shortage_economy\">shortage economy</span> sustained by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soft_budget_constraint\">soft budget constraint</span> facing state enterprises. Such directive planning was distinguished from the looser <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Indicative_planning\">indicative planning</span> practiced under French <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dirigisme\">dirigisme</span>, which set broad targets while leaving allocation largely to the market, and from the mere <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nationalization\">nationalization</span> of industry that did not by itself displace the price system. The model was largely abandoned in the closing decades of the 20th century, dismantled in China by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">market reforms</span> launched under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> from 1978 that produced a hybrid <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialist_market_economy\">socialist market economy</span>, and swept away across the Eastern Bloc by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dissolution_of_the_Soviet_Union\">dissolution of the Soviet Union</span> in 1991, after which the resulting <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Transition_economy\">transition economies</span> turned to the market, frequently through abrupt programs of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shock_therapy_(economics)\">shock therapy</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Planned economy"},{"id":"cne-006","num":"六","category":"China · Economics","question":"Forming the backbone of industry under central planning and long providing workers with lifetime jobs and an iron rice bowl, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> were partly reformed in the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>s, with many small ones sold off while large ones in strategic sectors stayed under the State Council and the Communist Party.","answer":"State-owned enterprises","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">国有企业 (guóyǒu qǐyè, 'state-owned enterprises')</span></div>","traditional":"國有企業","hanzi":"国有企业","pinyin":"guóyǒu qǐyè","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">guóyǒu qǐyè</span></div>","abstract":"<b>State-owned enterprises</b>&nbsp;(<b>SOEs</b>) are commercial entities owned and ultimately controlled by the Chinese state, which under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Planned_economy\">centrally planned economy</span> formed the structural backbone of industry and the chief instrument through which the government mobilized capital, fixed output quotas, and employed the urban workforce. Their dominance was <b>constructed after 1949</b> through the wholesale <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nationalization\">nationalization</span> of private firms and the launch of the First <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five-year_plans_of_China\">Five-Year Plan</span> of 1953–1957, which, with extensive aid from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Soviet Union</span> and some 156 turnkey projects, erected a <b>vast base of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heavy_industry\">heavy industry</span></b> under the leadership of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>. Far more than economic units, these firms operated as the cellular <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Danwei\">work units</span> of urban society, binding workers to a single employer for life while furnishing housing, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Health_care\">health care</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pension\">pensions</span>, and schooling in the cradle-to-grave arrangement popularly known as the \"iron rice bowl.\" By the <b>eve of reform in 1978</b> the state sector produced roughly 78 percent of the country's gross <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Industrial_production\">industrial output</span> and absorbed almost the entire formal urban labor force, yet chronic overstaffing, soft budget constraints, and weak incentives left many enterprises persistently unprofitable. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">economic reforms</span> initiated under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> gradually exposed them to market forces as the country moved toward what officials termed a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialist_market_economy\">socialist market economy</span>, setting the stage for a painful structural overhaul.<br> <br>During the 1980s a sequence of incremental reforms granted enterprise managers greater autonomy and the right to retain a share of profits, even as the <b>explosive growth of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Township_and_village_enterprises\">township and village enterprises</span></b> and private businesses steadily eroded the state sector's commanding position. A far more decisive turn followed the policy of \"<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Grasp_the_large,_let_go_of_the_small\">grasp the large, let go of the small</span>,\" endorsed <b>at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"15th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">15th Party Congress</span> in 1997</b> under Premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_Rongji\">Zhu Rongji</span> and sharpened by China's 2001 accession to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Trade_Organization\">World Trade Organization</span>, whereby thousands of smaller firms were sold, merged, or shut through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Privatization\">privatization</span> while large enterprises in strategic sectors were deliberately retained. The ensuing restructuring shrank the urban state payroll from a peak above 110 million to about 64 million by 2002, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Layoff\">laying off</span></b> tens of millions of workers in one of the largest contractions of formal employment in modern history. Surviving enterprises were progressively reorganized through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Corporatization\">corporatization</span> into shareholding companies, many of them floated in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Initial_public_offering\">public offerings</span> on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_Stock_Exchange\">Shanghai</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shenzhen_Stock_Exchange\">Shenzhen</span> stock exchanges, while supervision of the largest central groups was vested in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_Assets_Supervision_and_Administration_Commission\">State-owned Assets Supervision and Administration Commission</span>, created in 2003 and steadily consolidated from 196 firms at its founding to fewer than 100. Today the surviving giants dominate the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Commanding_heights_of_the_economy\">commanding heights</span> of finance, energy, telecommunications, and transport—<b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_Grid_Corporation_of_China\">State Grid</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_National_Petroleum_Corporation\">China National Petroleum</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sinopec\">Sinopec</span> consistently rank among the largest corporations on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fortune_Global_500\">Fortune Global 500</span>—and although the sector accounts for an estimated 25 to 30 percent of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gross_domestic_product\">gross domestic product</span>, the administration of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span> has tightened the role of internal party committees and entrenched a distinctive model of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_capitalism\">state capitalism</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"State-owned enterprises"},{"id":"cne-008","num":"八","category":"China · Economics","question":"Acting as the basic cell of urban society under Mao Zedong, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was the state enterprise or office that not only employed a person but also provided housing, healthcare and permission to marry or travel, binding workers tightly to a single employer.","answer":"Danwei","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">单位 (dānwèi, 'work unit')</span></div>","traditional":"單位","hanzi":"单位","pinyin":"dānwèi","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">dānwèi</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“work unit”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>danwei</b> was the basic-level social and economic institution of urban <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Republic_of_China\">China</span> under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>, denoting the state-owned factory, government office, school, or other organization to which nearly every city resident was permanently assigned. Far more than an <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Employment\">employer</span></b>, it functioned as the principal provider of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Public_housing\">housing</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Healthcare_in_China\">medical care</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Education_in_China\">schooling</span>, childcare, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pension\">pensions</span>, and it administered the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rationing\">ration coupons</span> required to obtain grain, cloth, and other necessities under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Planned_economy\">planned economy</span>. Because it issued the official permissions needed to marry, divorce, travel, change jobs, or later to bear a child under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"One-child_policy\">one-child policy</span>, the unit bound its members tightly to a single workplace and served as a <b>powerful instrument of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Social_control\">social control</span></b> and political mobilization. Day-to-day authority rested with resident Party <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cadre_(politics)\">cadres</span>, who organized the compulsory political study that intensified during campaigns like the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span>, maintained the personal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dang'an\">dang'an</span> dossier kept on each worker, and exercised the pervasive <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Surveillance\">surveillance</span></b> that made the workplace the chief point of contact between the individual and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span>. The system took shape in the 1950s as the new state pressed forward with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nationalization\">nationalization</span> of industry along <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Soviet</span> lines, and it came to <b>embody the so-called <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Iron_rice_bowl\">iron rice bowl</span></b>, a guarantee of lifetime employment and cradle-to-grave welfare that became a defining feature of Maoist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_socialism\">state socialism</span>. <br> <br> The urban unit had a rural counterpart in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_commune\">people's commune</span>, and both were locked into place by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hukou\">hukou</span> household-registration system <b>established in 1958</b>, which tied welfare entitlements to a fixed locality and sharply restricted <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Internal_migration\">internal migration</span>. At its peak the institution dominated urban life almost completely, so that by the late 1970s nearly all of China's roughly 95 million city employees were attached to a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_enterprises_of_China\">state-owned enterprise</span> or collective unit, with private business all but eliminated. This arrangement began to unravel after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">market reforms</span> initiated by <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> in 1978</b>, which gradually exposed the inefficiency of bundling production with comprehensive welfare and pushed the country toward a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialist_market_economy\">socialist market economy</span>. Under Premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_Rongji\">Zhu Rongji</span> the restructuring of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Privatization\">state enterprises</span> shattered the iron rice bowl between 1995 and 2002, when tens of millions of redundant employees—by some estimates more than 30 million—were laid off in the wave of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiagang\">xiagang</span>, while the abolition of welfare <b>housing allocation in 1998</b> stripped the unit of one of its central functions. As employment shifted to a competitive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Labour_economics\">labour market</span> and a growing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Floating_population\">floating population</span> of migrant workers filled the cities, the comprehensive unit faded into a residual role, leaving its legacy chiefly in the social welfare gaps, residential compounds, and patterns of urban governance it bequeathed to contemporary China.","citation":"","answerText":"Danwei"},{"id":"cne-009","num":"九","category":"China · Economics","question":"A vivid metaphor for the system of guaranteed lifetime employment, housing and welfare offered by state enterprises, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was steadily broken in the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>s as layoffs spread and the labour market opened under reformers such as Zhu Rongji and Deng Xiaoping.","answer":"Iron rice bowl","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">铁饭碗 ('iron rice bowl'), a metaphor for secure lifetime employment</span></div>","traditional":"鐵飯碗","hanzi":"铁饭碗","pinyin":"tiě fànwǎn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">tiě fànwǎn</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>iron rice bowl</b> is a Chinese metaphor for an occupation offering near-absolute <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Job_security\">job security</span></b>, a guaranteed and unchanging wage, and comprehensive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Welfare\">welfare</span>, the \"bowl\" representing one's livelihood and the \"iron\" signifying that it could not be broken. The arrangement was an artifact of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Planned_economy\">planned economy</span> built after the <b>1949 founding</b> of the People's Republic of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>, under which urban workers were assigned for life to a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Danwei\">work unit</span> that doubled as employer and welfare provider, dispensing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Public_housing\">housing</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Health_care\">medical care</span>, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pension\">pensions</span></b>, and subsidized necessities. Such security was overwhelmingly an urban privilege bound up with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hukou_system\">household-registration system</span>, since the rural majority laboured instead within the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_commune\">people's communes</span>, earning work-points rather than fixed salaries and enjoying no comparable guarantees of housing, pensions, or tenure. Consolidated across the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao</span> era and maintained through the disruptions of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Leap_Forward\">Great Leap Forward</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span>, the system operated within the framework of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_enterprise\">state-owned enterprises</span> and government organs and embodied a deliberately egalitarian ethos colloquially called \"eating from one big pot.\" Critics across the reform period charged that this <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Egalitarianism\">egalitarian</span> distribution bred chronic overstaffing, absenteeism, and stagnant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Productivity\">productivity</span>, defects that successive leaders would target as a central impediment to raising the national <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Standard_of_living\">standard of living</span>.<br> <br>The dismantling of the iron rice bowl <b>began in earnest in 1986</b>, when the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_Council_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">State Council</span> introduced a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Employment_contract\">labour contract system</span> that replaced permanent, inheritable tenure with renewable fixed-term agreements for newly recruited workers. A national Labour Law that <b>took effect in 1995</b> extended contract-based employment across the entire economy, formalizing the shift from job assignment to a competitive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Market_economy\">labour market</span> as part of the broader <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">economic reforms</span> guiding the transition to a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialist_market_economy\">socialist market economy</span>. The decisive blow came after 1997, when the restructuring of the state sector under the slogan \"<b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Grasp_the_large,_let_go_of_the_small\">grasp the large, let go of the small</span></b>\" drove successive waves of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Privatization\">privatization</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Layoff\">layoffs</span> that left tens of millions of once-secure workers <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Unemployment\">unemployed</span>, even as a burgeoning private sector and rural <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Township_and_village_enterprises\">township and village enterprises</span> absorbed only a portion of the displaced. The accompanying retreat from cradle-to-grave provision saw welfare <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Subsidy\">subsidies</span> curtailed and the work-unit housing system abolished in 1998, obliging urban residents to buy homes on the open market and pushing the government to assemble a contributory <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Social_safety_net\">social safety net</span> of pooled pensions and medical insurance. Although the classic guarantee has largely vanished from the private economy, the metaphor endures in popular speech, attached above all to coveted posts in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Civil_Service_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">civil service</span> and the broader <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Public_sector\">public sector</span></b>, whose stability under the ruling <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Communist Party</span> has drawn more than three million candidates in recent cycles of the national examination, competing for only tens of thousands of advertised positions.","citation":"","answerText":"Iron rice bowl"},{"id":"cne-010","num":"十","category":"China · Economics","question":"Carried out in the mid-<span class=\"blank\">_____</span>s as households were merged first into mutual-aid teams and then into cooperatives, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> pooled land and labour, culminating in the giant communes of the Great Leap Forward before being reversed by the household responsibility system.","answer":"Collective farming","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1950s</span></div>","traditional":"集體農業","hanzi":"集体农业","pinyin":"jítǐ nóngyè","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">jítǐ nóngyè</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Collective farming</b> is an agrarian system in which land, implements, and labour are pooled so that the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Means_of_production\">means of production</span></b> are held in common, a model standing between <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Private_property\">private</span> smallholding and the state-owned <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_farm\">state farm</span> that was adopted across the communist world and pursued in China from the early 1950s as the rural pillar of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marxism–Leninism\">Marxist–Leninist</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialism\">socialism</span>. In <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> the process <b>followed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Land_reform_movement\">land reform</span> of 1950–1953</b>, which had stripped the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Landlord\">landlord</span> class of its holdings and distributed roughly 43 percent of cultivated land to some 300 million <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peasant\">peasants</span> who briefly held it as private smallholdings. Beginning in the mid-1950s these newly independent farmers were merged in graduated stages, first into mutual-aid teams of 4 to 10 households, then into lower-stage <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Agricultural_cooperative\">agricultural cooperatives</span> of 20 to 40</b> families in which members were still paid partly according to the land they contributed, and finally into higher-stage cooperatives of 100 or more households where ownership passed wholly to the collective. The campaign drew explicitly on the <b>Soviet precedent of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Collectivization_in_the_Soviet_Union\">collectivization</span></b> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kolkhoz\">kolkhoz</span> farms imposed under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joseph_Stalin\">Joseph Stalin</span>, reflecting the close <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-Soviet_relations\">Sino-Soviet</span> alignment of the era, and it accelerated sharply after <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> demanded a faster \"socialist high tide <b>in the countryside\" in 1955</b>. Under pressure from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span>, which had abandoned the gradualism of the earlier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Democracy\">New Democracy</span> period in favour of rapid socialist transformation aligned with the first <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five-year_plans_of_China\">Five-Year Plan</span>, roughly 96 percent of peasant households had joined cooperatives <b>by the end of 1956</b>, with about 88 percent enrolled in the fully collective higher-stage form. <br> <br> In 1958 the cooperatives were amalgamated into vast <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_commune\">people's communes</span> during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Leap_Forward\">Great Leap Forward</span>, sprawling units averaging some 5,000 households that absorbed nearly the entire rural population into roughly 26,000 communes within months. This headlong communalisation disrupted incentives and grain production so severely that it helped precipitate the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Chinese_Famine\">Great Chinese Famine</span> of 1959–1961, in which an estimated 15 to 45 million people died. After the catastrophe the communes were restructured into a three-tier hierarchy whose basic accounting unit became the production team of 20 to 30 households, distributing income through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Egalitarianism\">egalitarian</span> work points within the framework of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Planned_economy\">planned economy</span> and compulsory state grain procurement. The collective structure endured through the upheavals of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span> and shaped <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Agriculture_in_China\">Chinese agriculture</span> for nearly 30 years, fixing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Land_tenure\">land tenure</span> in the hands of the collective and binding peasants to their <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rural_area\">rural</span></b> production teams. The entire edifice was dismantled only with the market reforms of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">reform and opening-up</span>, after farmers in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anhui\">Anhui</span> secretly contracted collective land to individual families in 1978 and the resulting <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Household_responsibility_system\">household responsibility system</span>, championed by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>, spread nationwide to cover nearly all rural households and led to the formal abolition of the communes by the mid-1980s.","citation":"","answerText":"Collective farming"},{"id":"cne-012","num":"十二","category":"China · Economics","question":"A poor mountain village in Shanxi hailed for raising output through sheer collective effort, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> became the agricultural counterpart to an industrial model under a <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>s campaign promoted by Mao Zedong that urged peasants nationwide to emulate it during the Cultural Revolution.","answer":"Dazhai","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">大寨 (Dàzhài), a model production brigade in Shanxi</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"大寨","pinyin":"Dàzhài","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Dàzhài</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Dazhai</b> is a mountain village and former production brigade in <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiyang_County\">Xiyang County</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jinzhong\">Jinzhong</span>, set amid the rugged <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taihang_Mountains\">Taihang Mountains</span> of Shanxi on the eastern rim of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Loess_Plateau\">Loess Plateau</span>, where thin, erosion-prone soils long rendered farming precarious. In the early 1960s its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peasant\">peasant</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Collective_farming\">collective</span>, organized as a brigade within the surrounding <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_commune\">people's commune</span> and led by the local Party secretary <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Yonggui\">Chen Yonggui</span></b>, won renown for carving barren hillsides into productive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Terrace_(agriculture)\">terraced fields</span> and steadily lifting its grain yields through sheer collective labour. The brigade's legend was <b>sealed in 1963</b>, when, after a devastating flood ravaged its fields, it pointedly refused state grain, money, and materials, rebuilt entirely by its own effort, and still delivered its full quota in a feat hailed as the supreme parable of self-reliant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Agriculture_in_China\">Chinese agriculture</span>. <b>In 1964</b>, as the countryside was still recovering from the famine of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Leap_Forward\">Great Leap Forward</span>, Mao Zedong personally elevated the village into a national exemplar through the directive \"In agriculture, learn from Dazhai,\" deliberately pairing the agrarian model with its industrial counterpart, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Daqing_Oil_Field\">Daqing oil field</span>. Propagated relentlessly across <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> as the embodiment of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maoism\">Maoist</span> ideals of austerity, self-sacrifice, and collective struggle, the model spread through a nationwide <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mass_line\">mass</span> campaign whose <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Propaganda_in_China\">propaganda</span> and attendant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cult_of_personality\">personality cult</span> intensified during the Cultural Revolution, when officials exhorted localities to \"make every county a Dazhai county.\"<br> <br>Chen Yonggui's stardom carried him to the apex of national politics, where he <b>entered the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo</span> in 1973</b> and served from 1975 as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vice_Premier_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">Vice Premier</span> within the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_Council_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">State Council</span>, an almost unheard-of ascent for a working peasant. Endorsed by Premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span> and showcased at the first National Conference on Learning from Dazhai in Agriculture, convened in 1975 under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hua_Guofeng\">Hua Guofeng</span> and echoed in sessions of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_People's_Congress\">National People's Congress</span>, the village drew a tide of pilgrims that by some accounts approached ten million over the campaign's lifespan, including foreign delegations from scores of countries. After Mao's death in 1976, official investigations exposed the model as substantially fraudulent, revealing that Dazhai's vaunted output figures had been inflated and that the ostensibly self-reliant brigade had in fact received covert state subsidies and the labour of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army\">army</span> units. Under the reforms of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>, the campaign was condemned around 1980 as a leftist excess associated with the disgraced <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gang_of_Four\">Gang of Four</span>, Chen Yonggui was stripped of his offices, and decollectivized family farming under the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Household_responsibility_system\">household responsibility system</span></b> dismantled the collective <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialism\">socialist</span> order that Dazhai had personified. In the decades since, the village has refashioned itself within the country's wider <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">market reforms</span>, the returning \"Iron Girl\" <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guo_Fenglian\">Guo Fenglian</span></b> steering it into tourism and private enterprise, so that the onetime shrine of collectivism now sustains itself through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Red_tourism\">red tourism</span> and branded commerce under the continuing rule of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Communist Party</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Dazhai"},{"id":"cne-014","num":"十四","category":"China · Economics","question":"A development strategy under which a country builds domestic industry behind tariff walls to replace imported manufactures, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> broadly characterised the inward-looking, planned economy of the Mao Zedong era before policy shifted toward exporting under Deng Xiaoping.","answer":"Import substitution industrialization","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Coined</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Structuralist economics (Raúl Prebisch, ECLA), 1950s</span></div>","traditional":"進口替代工業化","hanzi":"进口替代工业化","pinyin":"jìnkǒu tìdài gōngyèhuà","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">jìnkǒu tìdài gōngyèhuà</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Import substitution industrialization</b> is a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Trade_policy\">trade</span></b> and development strategy under which a country fosters domestic manufacturing to replace imported goods, typically by shielding nascent producers behind <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tariff\">tariffs</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Import_quota\">import quotas</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Subsidy\">subsidies</span>, and overvalued <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Exchange_rate\">exchange rates</span>. The strategy drew on mid-20th-century <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Development_economics\">development economics</span></b> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Structuralist_economics\">structuralist</span> school associated with the Argentine economist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Raúl_Prebisch\">Raúl Prebisch</span> and the German-British economist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hans_Singer\">Hans Singer</span> at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_Nations_Economic_Commission_for_Latin_America_and_the_Caribbean\">UN Economic Commission for Latin America</span>, <b>founded in 1948</b>, whose <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Prebisch–Singer_hypothesis\">Prebisch–Singer hypothesis</span> held that the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Terms_of_trade\">terms of trade</span> for primary commodities tended to deteriorate over the long run. By building manufacturing at home rather than exporting raw materials, advocates such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Albert_O._Hirschman\">Albert Hirschman</span> argued, a nation could generate domestic industrial linkages, escape the subordination described by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dependency_theory\">dependency theory</span>, and justify temporary protection through the classic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Infant_industry_argument\">infant industry argument</span>. The approach became the dominant development paradigm across <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Latin_America\">Latin America</span></b> after the collapse of export markets in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Depression\">Great Depression</span>, shaping the economies of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Brazil\">Brazil</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Argentina\">Argentina</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mexico\">Mexico</span> from the 1930s through the 1970s behind average effective rates of protection that in some economies exceeded 100 percent. It was adopted more widely by post-colonial and socialist states, from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"License_Raj\">License Raj</span> of newly independent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"India\">India</span> to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Autarky\">autarkic</span> development model of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>'s China, where national self-sufficiency was elevated into a central tenet of policy. <br> <br> In the Chinese case the principle merged with a highly inward-looking <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Planned_economy\">planned economy</span> built on the doctrine of self-reliance, in which the state channelled investment toward heavy industry on a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Soviet</span> model while foreign trade was minimized and tightly controlled. This orientation was reversed by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">economic reforms</span> launched under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> <b>from 1978</b>, which opened the country to foreign capital, established the first <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Special_economic_zones_of_China\">special economic zones</span> in 1980 beginning with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shenzhen\">Shenzhen</span>, and pivoted decisively toward <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Export-oriented_industrialization\">export-oriented industrialization</span>. The success of the export-led <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Asian_Tigers\">Four Asian Tigers</span>, including <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South_Korea\">South Korea</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span>, which posted near double-digit annual growth and transformed themselves from agrarian societies into advanced industrial economies within a generation, contrasted sharply with the stagnation of many import-substituting economies and helped discredit the strategy among policymakers. Critics charged that prolonged protection bred inefficiency, fostered <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rent-seeking\">rent-seeking</span>, and produced chronic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Balance_of_payments\">balance-of-payments</span> strains, weaknesses laid bare when the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Latin_American_debt_crisis\">Latin American debt crisis</span> <b>erupted in 1982</b> amid regional external debt exceeding 300 billion dollars, ushering in a \"lost decade\" of contraction. In its aftermath the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Washington_Consensus\">Washington Consensus</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Structural_adjustment\">structural adjustment</span> programmes of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"International_Monetary_Fund\">International Monetary Fund</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Bank\">World Bank</span> pressed <b>developing countries toward <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Trade_liberalization\">trade liberalization</span></b>, and following India's sweeping reforms in 1991 import substitution had, by the close of the 20th century, largely given way to globally integrated, market-oriented growth.","citation":"","answerText":"Import substitution industrialization"},{"id":"cne-015","num":"十五","category":"China · Economics","question":"A family of models in which the means of production are publicly or collectively owned but goods and labour are allocated through markets, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is often invoked to describe China's hybrid system, distinguishing it from both a pure command economy and Western capitalism.","answer":"Market socialism","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Origin</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Theorized by Oskar Lange, 1930s</span></div>","traditional":"市場社會主義","hanzi":"市场社会主义","pinyin":"shìchǎng shèhuìzhǔyì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">shìchǎng shèhuìzhǔyì</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Market socialism</b> denotes a family of economic models in which the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Means_of_production\">means of production</span></b> are held in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Social_ownership\">social</span>, public, or <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cooperative\">cooperative</span> ownership, yet the allocation of goods and labour is governed not by central planning but by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Supply_and_demand\">supply and demand</span> of a functioning <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Market_economy\">market economy</span>. As a distinct branch of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialism\">socialist</span> thought it occupies a middle ground between a centrally administered command system and private capitalism, an arrangement whose intellectual lineage reaches back to the 19th-century <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mutualism_(economic_theory)\">mutualism</span> of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pierre-Joseph_Proudhon\">Pierre-Joseph Proudhon</span></b> and the wider search for an <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economic_system\">economic system</span> uniting common ownership with decentralized exchange. The theory acquired analytical rigour during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialist_calculation_debate\">socialist calculation debate</span> of the 1920s, when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ludwig_von_Mises\">Ludwig von Mises</span> and later <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Friedrich_Hayek\">Friedrich Hayek</span> argued that a socialist economy, lacking genuine prices for capital goods, could never rationally compute the value of resources. In reply, the economists <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Oskar_Lange\">Oskar Lange</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Abba_Lerner\">Abba Lerner</span> devised in the 1930s the celebrated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lange_model\">Lange model</span>, a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Neoclassical_economics\">neoclassical</span> scheme in which a planning board would adjust prices by trial and error while publicly owned firms produced up to the point at which <b>price equalled <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marginal_cost\">marginal cost</span></b>. Later contributors—among them <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"John_Roemer\">John Roemer</span>, who proposed distributing corporate ownership through tradable coupons, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"David_Schweickart\">David Schweickart</span>, an advocate of worker-run firms—refined these ideas, several of their designs featuring a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Social_dividend\">social dividend</span></b> that would return enterprise profits to the citizenry rather than to private shareholders.<br> <br>The most ambitious real-world experiment unfolded in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialist_Federal_Republic_of_Yugoslavia\">Yugoslavia</span>, where from the early 1950s the regime of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Josip_Broz_Tito\">Josip Broz Tito</span>, guided by the theorist <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Edvard_Kardelj\">Edvard Kardelj</span></b>, built an economy of socially owned enterprises run through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Workers'_self-management\">workers' self-management</span> and competing in the market. That system delivered brisk growth in its first decades but later succumbed to chronic inflation and unemployment, while Hungary pursued a gentler variant known as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Goulash_Communism\">Goulash Communism</span>, whose market-oriented New Economic Mechanism was <b>launched in 1968</b> under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"János_Kádár\">János Kádár</span>. The label is today most often applied to the reforming economies of East Asia, beginning with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>, where the changes set in motion by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> after 1978, and the parallel <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Đổi_Mới\">Đổi Mới</span> reforms <b>adopted by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vietnam\">Vietnam</span> in 1986</b>, wedded expanding markets to enduring public and party control. China formalized the model as a \"socialist market economy\" at its 14th National Congress in 1992, embedding it within the doctrine of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialism_with_Chinese_characteristics\">socialism with Chinese characteristics</span>, even as many economists dispute whether such hybrids represent authentic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialist_market_economy\">socialist markets</span> or a variety of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_capitalism\">state capitalism</span> dominated by party-directed firms. A flexible and contested category rather than a single blueprint, market socialism endures as both a theoretical vocabulary for analysing such <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mixed_economy\">mixed economies</span> and a rallying point for those who would harness the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Price_mechanism\">price mechanism</span> to egalitarian ends, keeping the means of production in common hands while leaving exchange to the market.","citation":"","answerText":"Market socialism"},{"id":"cne-016","num":"十六","category":"China · Economics","question":"Legalised for cooperation with foreign partners by a landmark <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> law early in reform and opening up, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> let overseas companies pair with local firms to gain market access while transferring technology, a model heavily used in special economic zones.","answer":"Joint venture","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">合资企业 (hézī qǐyè, 'jointly-funded enterprise')</span></div>","traditional":"合資企業","hanzi":"合资企业","pinyin":"hézī qǐyè","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">hézī qǐyè</span></div>","abstract":"A <b>joint venture</b> is a business arrangement in which two or more parties pool capital, assets, and expertise into a shared enterprise while dividing its control, profits, and risks, a form that became central to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>'s strategy for attracting foreign capital as it began loosening its rigid <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Planned_economy\">planned economy</span> at the outset of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">reform and opening up</span>. The model was formally legalised by the Law on Chinese-Foreign Equity Joint Ventures, adopted by the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_People's_Congress\">National People's Congress</span> on 1 July 1979</b> as the first foreign-investment statute of the People's Republic and an early signal of the reforms championed by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>. It permitted <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Multinational_corporation\">overseas companies</span> to take an <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Equity_(finance)\">equity</span> stake of at least 25 percent in a jointly owned company, typically paired with a Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_enterprises_of_China\">state-owned enterprise</span>, giving the foreign partner a foothold in a market otherwise largely closed to outsiders. Two further vehicles soon supplemented it—the contractual joint venture and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wholly_Foreign-Owned_Enterprise\">wholly foreign-owned enterprise</span></b>—yet throughout the 1980s the equity joint venture predominated because Beijing initially restricted fully foreign-owned firms and preferred shared ventures it could oversee within its emerging <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialist_market_economy\">socialist market economy</span>. Authorities promoted the arrangement as a <b>conduit for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Technology_transfer\">technology transfer</span></b> under a \"market for technology\" policy, channelling much of the resulting <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foreign_direct_investment\">foreign direct investment</span> into the new <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Special_economic_zones_of_China\">special economic zones</span> opened <b>from 1980</b> at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shenzhen\">Shenzhen</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuhai\">Zhuhai</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shantou\">Shantou</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiamen\">Xiamen</span>, with a large share routed through neighbouring <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span>. <br> <br> Among the earliest landmark ventures were <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing_Jeep\">Beijing Jeep</span>, <b>established in 1983</b> between Beijing's main car plant and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"American_Motors_Corporation\">American Motors</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"SAIC_Volkswagen\">Shanghai Volkswagen</span>, a 1984 tie-up that brought <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Volkswagen\">Volkswagen</span> together with the state group later known as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"SAIC_Motor\">SAIC Motor</span>. In the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Automotive_industry_in_China\">automotive industry</span> in particular, foreign manufacturers were long capped at 50 percent ownership and limited to two local partners, rules deliberately designed to force the diffusion of engineering know-how to domestic firms. The policy helped transform China into one of the world's largest recipients of inbound capital, with annual foreign investment climbing from negligible sums in 1979 to tens of billions of dollars by the 1990s, as multinationals accepted shared control <b>in exchange for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Market_access\">market access</span></b>. China's accession to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Trade_Organization\">World Trade Organization</span> on 11 December 2001 obliged it to open many protected sectors, and over subsequent years it relaxed numerous requirements that had compelled foreign entrants to operate through local partners, as set out in its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_and_the_World_Trade_Organization\">WTO commitments</span>. Persistent foreign complaints that the system amounted to coerced surrender of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Intellectual_property\">intellectual property</span> fed directly into the American <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Section_301_of_the_Trade_Act_of_1974\">Section 301</span> investigation and the ensuing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China–United_States_trade_war\">trade war</span>, and although a 2019 law consolidating China's foreign-investment rules formally barred forced technology transfer, the loosening of ownership caps was most vividly symbolised by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tesla,_Inc.\">Tesla</span>'s wholly owned <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gigafactory_Shanghai\">Gigafactory Shanghai</span></b>, the first foreign carmaker permitted to operate without a local partner.","citation":"","answerText":"Joint venture"},{"id":"cne-018","num":"十八","category":"China · Economics","question":"Rural collectively-owned firms that boomed in the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>s outside the state plan, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> absorbed surplus farm labour, drove early industrial growth, and were hailed by Deng Xiaoping as an unexpected success of reform beyond the state sector.","answer":"Township and village enterprises","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">乡镇企业 (xiāngzhèn qǐyè, 'township and village enterprises'), 1980s</span></div>","traditional":"鄉鎮企業","hanzi":"乡镇企业","pinyin":"xiāngzhèn qǐyè","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">xiāngzhèn qǐyè</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Township and village enterprises</b> were rural, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Collective_ownership\">collectively-owned</span></b> firms that operated outside the central <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Planned_economy\">state plan</span> and became one of the most dynamic forces of China's early <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">economic reform</span>, sponsored by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Townships_of_China\">township</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Administrative_village\">village</span> governments rather than by the central state or private owners. They evolved from the commune and brigade enterprises that had sprung up under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Leap_Forward\">Great Leap Forward</span> and expanded under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span>, when the rural <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_commune\">people's communes</span> first established small workshops to serve local agriculture. Their <b>explosive growth came after 1978</b>, when the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Household_responsibility_system\">household responsibility system</span> dismantled <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Collective_farming\">collective farming</span>, sharply raised <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Agricultural_productivity\">agricultural productivity</span>—with grain output climbing by roughly a third <b>between 1978 and 1984</b>—and released a vast pool of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Underemployment\">underemployed</span> rural labour from the land. Because the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hukou\">hukou</span> system still restricted permanent migration to the cities, these enterprises allowed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peasant\">peasants</span> to \"leave the land without leaving the countryside,\" absorbing surplus farm workers into local <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Industrialisation\">industry</span> and driving a wave of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economic_growth\">economic growth</span> across rural China. <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>, <b>reflecting in 1987</b>, famously described their rise as a development the central leadership had never anticipated, hailing the enterprises as one of the great unexpected gains of reform beyond the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_enterprises_of_China\">state sector</span>. <br> <br> The sector expanded at an extraordinary pace, growing from around 1.5 million firms in 1978 to roughly 25 million by the mid-1990s and posting annual output growth that often exceeded 20 percent, by which time they employed some 135 million workers and accounted for roughly a quarter of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gross_domestic_product\">gross domestic product</span> and more than a third of national industrial output. Their hybrid ownership fascinated economists, since firms resembling vaguely defined <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cooperative\">cooperatives</span> with such ambiguous <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Property_rights_(economics)\">property rights</span></b> seemed to defy conventional theory yet thrived, and they came to be seen as a distinctive feature of China's emerging <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialist_market_economy\">socialist market economy</span> and a practical experiment in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Market_socialism\">market socialism</span>. A wave of fiscal <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Decentralization\">decentralization</span></b> gave local governments strong incentives to nurture industry within their jurisdictions, even though the enterprises frequently operated under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soft_budget_constraint\">soft budget constraints</span> and lacked the secure financing available to state firms. Regional patterns diverged, with the collectively run \"Sunan model\" of southern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiangsu\">Jiangsu</span> contrasting with the more <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Entrepreneurship\">entrepreneurial</span> private firms of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wenzhou\">Wenzhou</span>, and many ostensibly collective enterprises were in fact privately run businesses wearing a \"red hat\" of collective registration to secure political protection and access to credit. From the mid-1990s the model faded as restructuring under Premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_Rongji\">Zhu Rongji</span> led most surviving enterprises to be <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Privatization\">privatized</span> or <b>converted into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joint-stock_company\">shareholding companies</span></b>, leaving a lasting legacy as the principal engine of rural industrialization and a major source of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Export\">exports</span> during the 1980s and early 1990s, the formative phase of China's reforms.","citation":"","answerText":"Township and village enterprises"},{"id":"cne-023","num":"二十三","category":"China · Economics","question":"A transitional mechanism of the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>s under which the same good carried both a low state-plan price and a higher market price, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> eased the shift from the planned economy but bred arbitrage and corruption, fuelling discontent before the protests of <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> under Zhao Ziyang.","answer":"Dual-track price system","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">mid-1980s</span></div>","traditional":"價格雙軌制","hanzi":"价格双轨制","pinyin":"jiàgé shuāngguǐ zhì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">jiàgé shuāngguǐ zhì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>dual-track price system</b> was a transitional pricing mechanism of China's 1980s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">economic reform</span> under which a single commodity simultaneously carried two prices: a low, fixed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Price_controls\">state-controlled price</span> for output traded within the mandatory <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economic_planning\">plan</span></b>, and a higher, fluctuating price set by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Supply_and_demand\">supply and demand</span> on the open <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Market_economy\">market</span>. <b>Introduced for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capital_good\">producer goods</span> after 1984</b> and formally sanctioned by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_Council_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">State Council</span> in 1985, the device permitted <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_enterprise\">state-owned enterprises</span> to sell their planned quota to the government at the old administered rate—an implicit <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Subsidy\">subsidy</span>—while disposing of any surplus at market prices. As reform deepened, an ever-larger share of industrial inputs and other <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Means_of_production\">means of production</span> flowed through the market track, allowing the two prices to converge gradually rather than through a single wrenching liberalization and marking China out among the era's <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Transition_economy\">transition economies</span></b>. This gradualist design—later analysed by economists as a strategy of \"reform without losers\"—shielded entrenched interests by preserving their cheap plan-track allocations while creating fresh incentives at the margin, in pointed contrast to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shock_therapy_(economics)\">shock therapy</span> soon applied across the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Soviet Union</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eastern_Bloc\">Eastern Bloc</span>. Yet the coexistence of two <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Price\">prices</span></b> for the same good created an enormous and irresistible gap that invited <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Arbitrage\">arbitrage</span>, as commodities diverted from the plan could be resold on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Black_market\">black market</span> for windfall gains.<br> <br>Connected officials and the politically favoured exploited this differential through rampant <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Profiteering\">profiteering</span></b>, buying scarce goods at the plan price and reselling them at the market price in a form of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rent-seeking\">rent-seeking</span> that enriched well-placed cadres and their children, the so-called <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Princelings\">princelings</span>, and made official <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Corruption_in_China\">corruption</span> a defining grievance of the reform era. <b>An attempt in 1988</b> to abolish the two-tier structure and free prices outright backfired badly, igniting waves of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Panic_buying\">panic buying</span> and hoarding that helped push <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Inflation\">inflation</span> to nearly 19 percent, its highest level in decades. Mounting fury over profiteering and the soaring <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cost_of_living\">cost of living</span> swelled the popular discontent behind the <b>1989 protests</b>, deepening the rift between hardliners such as Premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Peng\">Li Peng</span> and the veteran planner <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Yun\">Chen Yun</span> on one side and the reformist general secretary Zhao Ziyang, architect of the market program ratified at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"13th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">13th Party Congress</span>, on the other. After the upheaval and the conservative retrenchment that followed, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>'s 1992 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Southern_Tour\">Southern Tour</span> revived liberalization, and over the next few years the plan track was largely abolished as prices were unified under the emerging <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialist_market_economy\">socialist market economy</span>. The dual-track approach is now widely cited as a textbook case of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Communist Party</span>-led gradualism, credited with easing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>'s passage from plan to market even as its corrosive side effects left an enduring lesson in the political hazards of partial reform.","citation":"","answerText":"Dual-track price system"},{"id":"cne-024","num":"二十四","category":"China · Economics","question":"Named for an entrepreneurial city in Zhejiang, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> relied on private family workshops, informal credit and small-scale manufacturing, contrasting with approaches built more on collective township enterprises and state firms.","answer":"Wenzhou model","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">温州模式, named for Wenzhou's private-enterprise model</span></div>","traditional":"溫州模式","hanzi":"温州模式","pinyin":"Wēnzhōu móshì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Wēnzhōu móshì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Wenzhou model</b> is a development pattern of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">reform era</span> that built rapid growth on private family enterprise, small-scale <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Light_industry\">light industry</span></b>, and informal finance rather than on public ownership. It takes its name from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wenzhou\">Wenzhou</span>, a mountainous coastal city of some 9 million people in southeastern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhejiang\">Zhejiang</span> with little arable land and a long mercantile and seafaring tradition, conditions that had pushed its inhabitants toward petty trade, handicrafts, and emigration well before the term itself was popularised in the mid-1980s. From the early 1980s the city's economy came to rest on hundreds of thousands of household workshops and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Private_sector\">private</span></b> firms run by family <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Entrepreneurship\">entrepreneurs</span> operating with minimal capital, a sharp departure from the collective and state-led ownership that dominated most of the country and that local officials quietly tolerated despite its ambiguous legal status. These businesses organised into dense specialised <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Business_cluster\">clusters</span>, each town or village concentrating on a single product, so that Wenzhou and its county of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yueqing\">Yueqing</span> came to supply around 70 percent of the world's metal <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lighter\">cigarette lighters</span></b> along with vast quantities of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Button\">buttons</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shoe\">shoes</span>, and low-voltage electrical equipment. Lacking access to the state banking system, these private producers financed themselves through an <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Informal_economy\">informal economy</span> of family savings</b>, trade credit, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rotating_savings_and_credit_association\">rotating credit associations</span>, an early form of the curb finance later described as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shadow_banking_system\">shadow banking</span>. <br> <br> The pattern was frequently contrasted with two rival paths: the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sunan_model\">Sunan model</span></b> of southern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiangsu\">Jiangsu</span>, which relied on collectively owned <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Township_and_village_enterprises\">township and village enterprises</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pearl_River_Delta\">Pearl River Delta</span> model of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangdong\">Guangdong</span>, driven by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foreign_direct_investment\">foreign direct investment</span> in its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Special_economic_zones_of_China\">special economic zones</span>. Because it leaned so heavily on private capital and household initiative rather than on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_enterprises_of_China\">state-owned enterprises</span>, the model was politically contentious throughout the 1980s, when the legitimacy of a largely <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capitalism\">capitalist</span> private sector remained ideologically fraught and its defenders risked accusations of abandoning socialism. The sociologist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fei_Xiaotong\">Fei Xiaotong</span> helped legitimise the phenomenon through influential field studies, and acceptance broadened after <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>'s 1992 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Southern_Tour\">Southern Tour</span></b> reaffirmed market reform and the goal of a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialist_market_economy\">socialist market economy</span>. Wenzhou's merchants became famous for their far-flung commercial and financial networks, forming large communities of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Overseas_Chinese\">overseas Chinese</span> across Europe—most conspicuously in the Italian textile town of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Prato\">Prato</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Italy\">Italy</span>—and for the pooled wealth that later financed waves of property speculation across Chinese cities. The same dependence on private lending eventually produced a <b>severe credit crisis in 2011</b>, when a wave of defaults and the flight of indebted business owners prompted the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_Council_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">State Council</span> to designate the city a financial-reform pilot zone the following year, an episode that underscored both the dynamism and the fragility of an economy built largely outside the formal state system.","citation":"","answerText":"Wenzhou model"},{"id":"cne-025","num":"二十五","category":"China · Economics","question":"Centred on the prosperous southern part of Jiangsu province, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> emphasised collectively-owned township and village enterprises under local-government guidance, in contrast to the private-firm path associated with the city of Wenzhou.","answer":"Sunan model","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">苏南模式 ('southern Jiangsu model'), built on collective enterprises</span></div>","traditional":"蘇南模式","hanzi":"苏南模式","pinyin":"Sūnán móshì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Sūnán móshì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Sunan model</b> is a regional development pattern that emerged in the 1980s in the prosperous southern part of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiangsu\">Jiangsu</span></b> province, built on rural <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Industrialisation\">industrialization</span> led by collectively-owned <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Township_and_village_enterprises\">township and village enterprises</span> operating under the close guidance of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Local_government\">local government</span>. Centred on the wealthy cities of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Suzhou\">Suzhou</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuxi\">Wuxi</span>, and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Changzhou\">Changzhou</span></b> in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze_Delta\">Yangtze Delta</span>, the region capitalized on its closeness to nearby <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span>, drawing technical and managerial expertise that included the so-called \"Sunday engineers\" who moonlighted in rural factories on their days off. The term was popularized in the early 1980s by the sociologist <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fei_Xiaotong\">Fei Xiaotong</span></b>, a pioneer of Chinese rural <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sociology\">sociology</span> since the 1930s, who studied the country's varied paths of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economic_development\">economic development</span> and distinguished the collective Sunan pattern from other regional models then emerging. Its defining feature was <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Collective_ownership\">collective ownership</span></b>, with township and village governments acting as de facto entrepreneurs whose <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cadre_(politics)\">cadres</span> founded, financed, and managed enterprises and ploughed their profits back into industry and infrastructure, producing a relatively egalitarian, community-based form of industrialization in which enterprise revenues underwrote local schools, roads, and rural welfare. This approach stood in deliberate contrast to the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wenzhou_model\">Wenzhou model</span></b> of neighbouring <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhejiang\">Zhejiang</span>, where growth was driven by private family firms and bustling commodity markets centred on the city of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wenzhou\">Wenzhou</span>, and to the foreign-investment-led model of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pearl_River_Delta\">Pearl River Delta</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangdong\">Guangdong</span>. <br> <br> During the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">reforms</span> launched under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>, the Sunan pattern became a celebrated example of gradual, bottom-up growth within China's emerging <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialist_market_economy\">socialist market economy</span> and a frequent reference point in scholarly debates over property rights and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Market_socialism\">market socialism</span>. By the late 1980s and early 1990s southern Jiangsu had become one of the most heavily industrialized and prosperous rural areas in the country, its three core cities ranking among China's wealthiest, with collective enterprises generating well over half of the region's industrial <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gross_domestic_product\">output</span> and absorbing millions of former farm workers. From the mid-1990s, however, the model encountered mounting difficulties, <b>as the blurred <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Property_rights_(economics)\">property rights</span></b> of collective firms, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soft_budget_constraint\">soft budget constraints</span> that encouraged over-borrowing, and rising <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Competition_(economics)\">competition</span> from private and foreign-funded rivals left many enterprises burdened with debt. In response, the bulk of the region's collective enterprises were <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Privatization\">privatized</span> or restructured into shareholding companies around the turn of the millennium, dismantling the original collective basis of the model. Even as this occurred, southern Jiangsu was reinventing itself through a \"New Sunan model\" oriented toward <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foreign_direct_investment\">foreign direct investment</span> and export <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manufacturing\">manufacturing</span>, anchored by industrial parks such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Suzhou_Industrial_Park\">Suzhou Industrial Park</span>, a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joint_venture\">joint venture</span> <b>launched with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Singapore\">Singapore</span> in 1994</b> that drew billions of dollars in foreign investment and turned the area into a hub of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Globalization\">globalized</span> production.","citation":"","answerText":"Sunan model"},{"id":"cne-026","num":"二十六","category":"China · Economics","question":"Referring to the webs of personal relationships and reciprocal obligation that grease business and politics, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is widely seen as essential to navigating deals, bureaucracy and the state sector, sometimes blurring into the corruption targeted by campaigns of the Communist Party.","answer":"Guanxi","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">关系 (guānxì, 'relationships')</span></div>","traditional":"關係","hanzi":"关系","pinyin":"guānxì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">guānxì</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“relationships”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Guanxi</b> is a foundational concept of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_culture\">Chinese culture</span></b> denoting the dense webs of personal relationship and reciprocal obligation that bind individuals together and lubricate the conduct of business and politics. At its heart lie the linked principles of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Reciprocity_(cultural_anthropology)\">reciprocity</span>, the careful management of social <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Face_(sociological_concept)\">face</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Social_status\">prestige</span>, and a long-running ledger of favours cultivated over years through banquets, gifts, and mutual aid within an enduring <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gift_economy\">gift economy</span></b>. The concept is commonly traced to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> ethics, with their emphasis on hierarchy, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kinship\">kinship</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Filial_piety\">filial piety</span>, and the graded duties of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five_Bonds\">five cardinal relationships</span></b> codified in the teachings of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucius\">Confucius</span>. In a celebrated analysis, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sociology\">sociologist</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fei_Xiaotong\">Fei Xiaotong</span> described <b>Chinese society in his 1947 study</b> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"From_the_Soil\"><i>From the Soil</i></span> as organized into concentric rings of obligation radiating outward from the self, a \"differential mode of association\" he set against the more rule-bound associations of the West. Functioning as a potent form of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Social_capital\">social capital</span> and a flexible <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Social_network\">social network</span>, guanxi has long supplied the trust and access that formal <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Institution\">institutions</span></b> and a robust <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rule_of_law\">rule of law</span> furnish elsewhere, a role echoed in comparable systems such as the Russian practice of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Blat_(favors)\">blat</span>.<br> <br>In contemporary China it is widely regarded as indispensable to closing deals, threading the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bureaucracy\">bureaucracy</span>, and securing contracts or licences within the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_enterprise\">state-owned</span> sector, where well-tended connections can open doors that merit or regulation alone would not. Foreign companies and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Overseas_Chinese\">overseas Chinese</span> entrepreneurs alike have treated the cultivation of guanxi as a prerequisite for entering Chinese markets, though scholars <b>influenced by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Modernization_theory\">modernization theory</span></b> debate whether its sway recedes as legal and market institutions mature. The practice shades uneasily into illegality, since the trading of favours can slide into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bribery\">bribery</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nepotism\">nepotism</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cronyism\">cronyism</span>, and the patron-client <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Clientelism\">clientelism</span> that critics decry as a wellspring of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Corruption_in_China\">corruption in China</span>. The blurring of these lines has made guanxi networks a recurrent target of the ruling party's anti-graft drives, above all the sweeping <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anti-corruption_campaign_under_Xi_Jinping\">anti-corruption campaign</span> launched by <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span> after 2012</b>, which has disciplined millions of officials across <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>. Yet such drives have done little to dislodge a deeply rooted social institution, and guanxi endures as both an everyday lubricant of Chinese life and, at its extreme, a conduit for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Crony_capitalism\">crony capitalism</span> that reformers continue to combat.","citation":"","answerText":"Guanxi"},{"id":"cne-027","num":"二十七","category":"China · Economics","question":"Surging after coastal areas and special economic zones were opened, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> — often through joint ventures and much of it routed via Hong Kong — financed factories and made the country a manufacturing hub.","answer":"Foreign direct investment","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">外商直接投资 ('foreign direct investment')</span></div>","traditional":"外商直接投資","hanzi":"外商直接投资","pinyin":"wàishāng zhíjiē tóuzī","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">wàishāng zhíjiē tóuzī</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Foreign direct investment</b>&nbsp;(<b>FDI</b>) is cross-border investment in which an enterprise or individual acquires a lasting management interest—conventionally a stake of at least 10 percent under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"International_Monetary_Fund\">IMF</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"OECD\">OECD</span></b> definitions—in a business located in another economy, distinguishing it from passive portfolio holdings. In <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> such inflows were negligible under central planning but began to climb after <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">reform and opening up</span>, accelerating once the first <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Special_economic_zones_of_China\">special economic zones</span> were <b>established in 1980</b> at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shenzhen\">Shenzhen</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuhai\">Zhuhai</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shantou\">Shantou</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiamen\">Xiamen</span>, followed by 14 open coastal cities in 1984 and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pudong\">Pudong</span> <b>zone of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span> in 1990</b>. Most early capital arrived through Sino-foreign <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joint_venture\">joint ventures</span> in which <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Multinational_corporation\">multinational corporations</span> partnered with local firms, while fully owned ventures, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wholly_Foreign-Owned_Enterprise\">wholly foreign-owned enterprise</span>, grew more common only later, especially after market access widened. A striking feature was its routing, with the bulk of inflows channelled through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span> and offshore <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tax_haven\">tax havens</span> such as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"British_Virgin_Islands\">British Virgin Islands</span></b>, a substantial portion of which was \"round-tripped\" mainland money returning home to claim the incentives reserved for foreign investors. Those incentives included preferential <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Corporate_tax\">corporate income tax</span> rates and multi-year <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tax_holiday\">tax holidays</span></b> for foreign-invested enterprises, and the state encouraged the arrangements as a vehicle for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Technology_transfer\">technology transfer</span> and the importation of modern management. <br> <br> Inflows surged after <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>'s 1992 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Southern_Tour\">Southern Tour</span></b> reaffirmed the reform programme, with annual realised investment jumping from roughly $4 billion in 1991 to about $27 billion in 1993 and some $37 billion by the mid-1990s as foreign firms rushed to secure a foothold. Membership in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Trade_Organization\">World Trade Organization</span> from 2001 triggered another surge, set out in China's <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_and_the_World_Trade_Organization\">accession commitments</span></b>, and by 2002–2003 the country had briefly overtaken the United States as the world's largest recipient, drawing over $50 billion a year. The capital concentrated overwhelmingly in the coastal manufacturing belts of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pearl_River_Delta\">Pearl River Delta</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangdong\">Guangdong</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze_Delta\">Yangtze Delta</span> around <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiangsu\">Jiangsu</span> and Shanghai, financing the labour-intensive export-processing factories assembling goods for foreign brands that underpinned China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Export-oriented_industrialization\">export-oriented industrialisation</span>. This investment helped turn the country into the world's pre-eminent manufacturing hub and a pillar of the wider <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">Chinese economy</span>, and it swelled the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foreign_exchange_reserves\">foreign-exchange reserves</span> recorded in the national <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Balance_of_payments\">balance of payments</span>, with annual utilised inflows surpassing $100 billion by 2010 and peaking near $160 billion in 2020, when, by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_Nations_Conference_on_Trade_and_Development\">UNCTAD</span> figures, China became the single largest destination worldwide. Although a 2008 corporate-tax reform unified rates and stripped away the old privileges that had favoured foreign-invested firms, China remained a magnet for global capital until the mid-2020s, when inflows fell sharply amid slowing growth, geopolitical tension, and rising competition for investment elsewhere.","citation":"","answerText":"Foreign direct investment"},{"id":"cne-028","num":"二十八","category":"China · Economics","question":"A growth strategy of producing manufactured goods for sale abroad to earn foreign exchange, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> — pioneered earlier by the Four Asian Tigers — turned China into the workshop of the world after it joined the WTO, building vast currency reserves.","answer":"Export-oriented industrialization","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Origin</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Development economics, from the East Asian model of the 1960s–70s</span></div>","traditional":"出口導向型工業化","hanzi":"出口导向型工业化","pinyin":"chūkǒu dǎoxiàng xíng gōngyèhuà","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">chūkǒu dǎoxiàng xíng gōngyèhuà</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Export-oriented industrialization</b>&nbsp;(<b>EOI</b>) is a development strategy that seeks to accelerate a country's industrial growth by producing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manufacturing\">manufactured</span> goods for sale on world markets, earning <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foreign_exchange_reserves\">foreign exchange</span> by exploiting a nation's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Comparative_advantage\">comparative advantage</span> in low-cost, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Labor_intensity\">labour-intensive</span></b> production. Standing in direct opposition to inward-looking <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Import_substitution_industrialization\">import substitution</span>, it typically relies on competitive or undervalued <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Exchange_rate\">exchange rates</span>, openness to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foreign_direct_investment\">foreign direct investment</span>, high domestic savings, and the <b>creation of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Export_processing_zone\">export processing zones</span></b> to draw in manufacturers. The strategy was pioneered in post-war <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japan\">Japan</span> and then adopted with spectacular results from the 1960s by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Asian_Tigers\">Four Asian Tigers</span>—<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Singapore\">Singapore</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South_Korea\">South Korea</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span>—which sustained growth of 7 to 10 percent a year and transformed themselves into advanced economies within a single generation. Their success, often attributed to a strong <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Developmental_state\">developmental state</span> that combined market openness with active <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Industrial_policy\">industrial policy</span>, was <b>analysed in the influential 1993 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Bank\">World Bank</span></b> report <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_East_Asian_Miracle\"><i>The East Asian Miracle</i></span>, which praised the region for combining rapid expansion with relatively equitable growth. The pattern spread across the region in a sequence sometimes likened to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Flying_geese_paradigm\">flying geese paradigm</span> first described by <b>the economist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kaname_Akamatsu\">Kaname Akamatsu</span></b>, in which industries migrated from more advanced economies to lower-wage neighbours as costs rose, setting the stage for adoption on a far larger scale by China. <br> <br> China embraced the strategy following the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">economic reforms</span> begun under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>, opening <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Special_economic_zones_of_China\">special economic zones</span> such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shenzhen\">Shenzhen</span> <b>from 1980</b>, courting foreign investors, and adopting a coastal development strategy that channelled labour-intensive manufacturing toward export markets. The strategy reached full force after China joined the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Trade_Organization\">World Trade Organization</span> in December 2001 as its 143rd member, an accession that slashed trade barriers and unleashed a manufacturing boom that earned the country a reputation as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Workshop_of_the_world\">workshop of the world</span>. Within a decade China had become the world's largest exporter, <b>overtaking <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Germany\">Germany</span> in 2009</b>, and the world's largest manufacturing power by around 2010, its share of world merchandise exports climbing from under 4 percent in 2000 to roughly 13 percent by the mid-2010s while its factories came to account for close to 30 percent of global industrial output. The resulting export surge produced large <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Balance_of_trade\">trade surpluses</span> and a soaring <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Current_account\">current account</span>, allowing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Bank_of_China\">central bank</span> to amass the world's <b>largest holdings of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foreign_exchange_reserves_of_China\">foreign exchange reserves</span></b>, which surpassed 1 trillion dollars in 2006 and peaked at nearly 4 trillion in 2014. This deep dependence on foreign demand left the economy vulnerable to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Protectionism\">protectionism</span> and to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Balance_of_payments\">global imbalances</span> exposed by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Recession\">global financial crisis</span>, and in subsequent years, as wages rose and trade tensions intensified, Beijing increasingly sought to rebalance growth toward domestic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Consumption_(economics)\">consumption</span> and higher-value production.","citation":"","answerText":"Export-oriented industrialization"},{"id":"cne-031","num":"三十一","category":"China · Economics","question":"Designated in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> for intensive development on the east bank of the Huangpu River, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> grew from farmland into a forest of skyscrapers and a global finance hub, symbolising the deepening of reform and opening up.","answer":"Pudong","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">浦东 (Pǔdōng, 'east of the Huangpu')</span></div>","traditional":"浦東","hanzi":"浦东","pinyin":"Pǔdōng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Pǔdōng</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“east of the Huangpu”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Pudong</b> is a district of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span></b> occupying the low-lying east bank of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huangpu_River\">Huangpu River</span> near the mouth of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span>, directly across the water from the historic riverfront of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Bund\">the Bund</span> in older <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Puxi\">Puxi</span></b>. Long an expanse of farmland, warehouses, and rundown housing—captured in a local saying that a bed in Puxi was preferable to a home in Pudong—the eastern bank lay neglected while wealth and commerce concentrated in the old treaty-port districts of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_International_Settlement\">International Settlement</span> across the river. <b>In April 1990</b> the central government designated Pudong for intensive development as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-level_new_area\">state-level new area</span>, an early flagship initiative championed by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> to signal that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">reform and opening up</span> would continue after the upheaval of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tiananmen_Square_protests_of_1989\"><b>1989</b> Tiananmen protests</span>. The project gained decisive momentum after Deng's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1992_southern_tour\">1992 southern tour</span> reaffirmed the reform agenda, and over the following decades the district was transformed from rice <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paddy_field\">paddies</span> and reed marshes into a dense <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_business_district\">central business district</span> bristling with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Skyscraper\">skyscrapers</span> and broad boulevards. Its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lujiazui\">Lujiazui</span> financial zone became a showcase of the new skyline, crowned by landmarks such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Oriental_Pearl_Tower\">Oriental Pearl Tower</span> <b>completed in 1994</b>, the 421-metre (1,380 ft) <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jin_Mao_Tower\">Jin Mao Tower</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_World_Financial_Center\">Shanghai World Financial Center</span>, and the 632-metre (2,070 ft) <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_Tower\">Shanghai Tower</span> of 2015, China's tallest building and among the tallest in the world. <br> <br> Pudong developed into one of Asia's principal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Financial_centre\">financial centres</span>, hosting the relocated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_Stock_Exchange\">Shanghai Stock Exchange</span>—among the world's largest by market value—and the regional headquarters of numerous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bank\">banks</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Multinational_corporation\">multinational corporations</span>. Major infrastructure followed, with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_Pudong_International_Airport\">Shanghai Pudong International Airport</span> opening in 1999 and a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_maglev_train\">maglev train</span>—the world's first commercial high-speed magnetic-levitation line—linking it to the city from 2004, while waves of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foreign_direct_investment\">foreign direct investment</span> poured into the district. The new area also pioneered trade and technology hubs, from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Waigaoqiao\">Waigaoqiao</span> <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Free-trade_zone\">free-trade zone</span></b> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhangjiang_Hi-Tech_Park\">Zhangjiang Hi-Tech Park</span> to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_(Shanghai)_Pilot_Free-Trade_Zone\">China (Shanghai) Pilot Free-Trade Zone</span> launched in 2013, the first such zone on the Chinese mainland, which experimented with looser controls on investment, trade, and capital flows. Encompassing roughly 1,210 square kilometres (467 sq mi) after absorbing the neighbouring district of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nanhui_District\">Nanhui</span>, Pudong is today among China's most populous and prosperous <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Districts_of_China\">districts</span></b>, with around 5.7 million residents and an annual economic output exceeding 1 trillion <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Renminbi\">yuan</span>, over 150 billion dollars. Its rise from farmland to a forest of towers within a single generation has made Pudong an enduring symbol of China's rapid <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economic_growth\">economic growth</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Urbanization\">urbanization</span>, frequently invoked alongside <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shenzhen\">Shenzhen</span> as a showcase of the nation's modernization under reform.","citation":"","answerText":"Pudong"},{"id":"cne-036","num":"三十六","category":"China · Economics","question":"Denominated in renminbi and traded on the Shanghai and Shenzhen exchanges, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was historically restricted to domestic investors, in contrast to the foreign-currency shares once reserved for overseas buyers.","answer":"A-share","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">A股 ('A shares'), renminbi shares for domestic investors</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"A股","pinyin":"A gǔ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">A gǔ</span></div>","abstract":"An <b>A-share</b> is a class of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Share_(finance)\">share</span> issued by companies incorporated in mainland <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>, denominated and traded in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Renminbi\">renminbi</span> on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_Stock_Exchange\">Shanghai</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shenzhen_Stock_Exchange\">Shenzhen</span>, and later <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing_Stock_Exchange\">Beijing</span></b> stock exchanges, and it constitutes by far the largest of the several share classes through which Chinese firms raise equity. From the emergence of these <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stock_market\">markets</span> in the early 1990s such shares were, with limited exceptions, restricted to domestic Chinese investors, a barrier rooted in the country's tight <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capital_control\">capital controls</span></b> and largely closed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capital_account\">capital account</span>. They were distinguished from B-shares, the foreign-currency counterpart quoted in US dollars in Shanghai and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span> dollars in Shenzhen, which were <b>introduced in 1992</b> and originally reserved for overseas buyers. A further category, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"H_share\">H-share</span>, covered mainland firms listed on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_Stock_Exchange\">Hong Kong Stock Exchange</span> and denominated in Hong Kong dollars, so that a single state enterprise such as a large bank might issue both A-shares at home and H-shares abroad to reach entirely different pools of investors. The whole market is overseen by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Securities_Regulatory_Commission\">China Securities Regulatory Commission</span>, and an early structural overhaul <b>between 2005</b> and 2006 converted the large blocks of non-tradable shares held by the state in listed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_enterprises_of_China\">state-owned enterprises</span> into freely tradable stock. <br> <br> Access for foreign investors was opened only gradually, beginning with <b>the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qualified_Foreign_Institutional_Investor\">Qualified Foreign Institutional Investor</span> scheme of 2002</b> and broadening sharply through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stock_Connect\">Stock Connect</span> programmes that linked the mainland bourses to Hong Kong in 2014 and 2016. International index providers followed, with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"MSCI\">MSCI</span> beginning to add A-shares to its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emerging_market\">emerging-market</span> benchmarks in 2018 at a small initial weighting that was steadily raised, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"FTSE_Russell\">FTSE Russell</span> doing likewise, developments that drew successive waves of foreign institutional money into a market long dominated by local participants. The market remained overwhelmingly retail-driven, with individual <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Investor\">investors</span></b>—more than 200 million of them by the 2020s—accounting for the bulk of turnover and contributing to dramatic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stock_market_bubble\">bubbles</span>, including the boom and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2015–2016_Chinese_stock_market_turbulence\">crash</span> of 2015 that prompted heavy state intervention. To curb the resulting swings the exchanges impose a daily <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Trading_curb\">price limit</span> of 10 percent on most A-shares, with tighter and looser bands on some boards, while benchmark gauges such as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"SSE_Composite_Index\">SSE Composite Index</span> and the broader <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"CSI_300_Index\">CSI 300</span></b>, which spans the 300 largest stocks across both exchanges, track their performance. By the mid-2020s the combined A-share market listed more than 5,000 companies, swelled by a steady stream of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Initial_public_offering\">initial public offerings</span>—from giant state banks to the high-growth technology firms on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"STAR_Market\">STAR Market</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"ChiNext\">ChiNext</span> growth boards—and carried a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Market_capitalization\">market capitalisation</span> of around $10 trillion, or some 70 trillion <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_(currency)\">yuan</span>, ranking it second only to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States\">United States</span> and making it a central pillar of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">Chinese economy</span> and its ongoing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">financial reforms</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"A-share"},{"id":"cne-037","num":"三十七","category":"China · Economics","question":"Issued by mainland companies but listed and traded in Hong Kong in the local dollar, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> let international investors buy into big state-owned enterprises from the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>s, often trading at prices different from the equivalent mainland-listed shares.","answer":"H-share","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">H股 ('H shares'), 'H' for Hong Kong-listed mainland firms</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"H股","pinyin":"H gǔ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">H gǔ</span></div>","abstract":"<b>H-share</b> refers to a <b>class of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Share_(finance)\">shares</span></b> issued by companies incorporated in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mainland_China\">mainland China</span> but listed and traded on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_Stock_Exchange\">Hong Kong Stock Exchange</span> and denominated in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_dollar\">Hong Kong dollar</span>, the letter \"H\" standing for Hong Kong. Because <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span> operates a separate financial system under the principle of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"One_country,_two_systems\">one country, two systems</span>, these shares were freely open to international <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Institutional_investor\">institutional investors</span></b> at a time when foreigners faced tight restrictions on the mainland's own exchanges. Introduced in the early 1990s as part of the market reforms under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>, the mechanism gave large <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_enterprises_of_China\">state-owned enterprises</span> a channel to raise foreign capital on international <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capital_market\">capital markets</span> while requiring them to undergo <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Corporatization\">corporatization</span> and adopt Western standards of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Corporate_governance\">corporate governance</span>, accounting, and disclosure that exposed previously opaque firms to global scrutiny. The first such listing was the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Initial_public_offering\">initial public offering</span> <b>of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tsingtao_Brewery\">Tsingtao Brewery</span> in July 1993</b>, an offering that raised some 115 million dollars and was made possible by a regulatory framework agreed between Hong Kong and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Securities_Regulatory_Commission\">China Securities Regulatory Commission</span>, created the previous year. A wave of flagship enterprises soon followed, among them the oil majors <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"PetroChina\">PetroChina</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sinopec\">Sinopec</span>, the insurer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Life_Insurance_Company\">China Life</span>, and the big state lenders <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bank_of_China\">Bank of China</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Construction_Bank\">China Construction Bank</span>, turning the Hong Kong market into the principal venue for Chinese corporate fundraising abroad. <br> <br> H-shares form part of an alphabet of Chinese equity classes that also includes the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"A_share_(mainland_China)\">A-shares</span> traded in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Renminbi\">renminbi</span> on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_Stock_Exchange\">Shanghai</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shenzhen_Stock_Exchange\">Shenzhen</span> exchanges, the foreign-currency <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"B_share_(mainland_China)\">B-shares</span>, the <b>Hong Kong-incorporated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Red_chip\">red chips</span></b>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"American_depositary_receipt\">American depositary receipts</span> of mainland firms listed in New York. Because China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capital_control\">capital controls</span> kept the two markets segmented and limited <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Arbitrage\">arbitrage</span>, a company's H-shares—grouped in the benchmark <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hang_Seng_China_Enterprises_Index\">Hang Seng China Enterprises Index</span></b>—often traded at a markedly different price from its mainland A-shares, with the latter frequently commanding a premium that at times exceeded 30 percent. Many giants pursued <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dual-listed_company\">dual listings</span> in both cities, most spectacularly the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Industrial_and_Commercial_Bank_of_China\">Industrial and Commercial Bank of China</span>, then among the world's largest banks, whose simultaneous Shanghai and <b>Hong Kong flotation in 2006</b> raised about 22 billion dollars, then the largest IPO in history—a deal that underscored how such listings imposed international disclosure standards on Chinese state lenders. Cross-border access widened in 2014 with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai–Hong_Kong_Stock_Connect\">Shanghai–Hong Kong Stock Connect</span>, followed by a Shenzhen link in 2016, which for the first time allowed mainland and international investors to trade directly across the boundary and gradually eroded the segmentation that had long sustained the price gaps. Over three decades H-shares and related instruments transformed Hong Kong into the chief gateway between Chinese enterprises and global finance, reinforcing its standing as a global <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Financial_centre\">financial centre</span> in which mainland companies came to account for a majority of stock-market capitalization and the bulk of daily turnover, a cornerstone of China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">reform and opening up</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"H-share"},{"id":"cne-040","num":"四十","category":"China · Economics","question":"Begun in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> on the Yangtze and completed in the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>s, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> became the world's largest hydroelectric power station, displacing well over 1 million people in a controversial scheme championed by premier Li Peng.","answer":"Three Gorges Dam","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">三峡 ('Three Gorges'): the Qutang, Wu and Xiling gorges</span></div>","traditional":"三峽大壩","hanzi":"三峡大坝","pinyin":"Sānxiá Dàbà","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Sānxiá Dàbà</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Three Gorges Dam</b> is a colossal <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gravity_dam\">gravity dam</span></b> spanning the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze\">Yangtze</span> River at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sandouping\">Sandouping</span> near <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yichang\">Yichang</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hubei\">Hubei</span> province, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>, and the world's largest <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hydroelectricity\">hydroelectric</span> power station. A dam across the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Gorges\">Three Gorges</span> had been <b>envisioned as early as 1919</b> by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Yat-sen\">Sun Yat-sen</span> and was later celebrated in verse by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>, who imagined \"walls of stone\" rising in the gorges, but the scheme remained mired in technical, financial, and political debate for much of the 20th century. It was finally approved <b>by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_People's_Congress\">National People's Congress</span> in 1992</b> in an unusually divided vote, with roughly a third of delegates declining to endorse it, and was driven forward by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Premier_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">Premier</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Peng\">Li Peng</span>, a hydroelectric engineer by training. Construction <b>began in 1994</b> under the state-owned <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Three_Gorges_Corporation\">China Three Gorges Corporation</span>, the river was blocked in 1997, reservoir filling commenced in 2003, the main <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dam\">dam</span> wall was completed in 2006, and the last of the 32 generators came online in 2012, making it one of the longest and most expensive infrastructure undertakings in history at an official cost of around 200 billion yuan. The completed structure stretches roughly 2,300 metres (7,500 ft) across the river and rises about 185 metres (607 ft) high, impounding a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Reservoir\">reservoir</span></b> some 600 kilometres (370 mi) long whose normal water level sits 175 metres (574 ft) above the sea and which can store enormous volumes of floodwater. <br> <br> Its 32 main turbines give it an installed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nameplate_capacity\">capacity</span> of 22,500 megawatts, making it by far the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"List_of_largest_power_stations\">largest power station</span> on earth, well ahead of Brazil's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Itaipu_Dam\">Itaipu Dam</span>, and in 2020 it set a world record by generating about 112 billion <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kilowatt-hour\">kilowatt-hours</span> of electricity. As one of the world's largest sources of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Renewable_energy\">renewable energy</span>, the station displaces tens of millions of tonnes of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Coal\">coal</span> each year and substantially reduces <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Greenhouse_gas\">greenhouse-gas</span> emissions compared with the thermal power it replaces, a benefit its supporters weigh against its costs. Beyond power, the dam was justified by <b>its role in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Flood_control\">flood control</span></b> on a river prone to catastrophic deluges such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1998_China_floods\">1998 floods</span>, and by the giant ship <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lock_(water_navigation)\">locks</span> and a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boat_lift\">ship lift</span> that allow large vessels to reach <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chongqing\">Chongqing</span> far upstream. The project was deeply controversial from the outset, requiring the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Forced_displacement\">forced resettlement</span> of an estimated 1.3</b> million people as the rising reservoir submerged 13 cities, some 140 towns, and over 1,000 villages along with irreplaceable archaeological and scenic sites of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_heritage\">cultural heritage</span>. Critics also blamed it for grave environmental harm, including the decline of endangered species such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Baiji\">baiji</span> river dolphin and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_sturgeon\">Chinese sturgeon</span>, the build-up of sediment behind the wall, and an increase in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Landslide\">landslides</span> and concerns over <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Induced_seismicity\">reservoir-induced seismicity</span>, leaving the dam an enduring symbol of both China's engineering ambition and the human and ecological costs of its mega-projects.","citation":"","answerText":"Three Gorges Dam"},{"id":"cne-042","num":"四十二","category":"China · Economics","question":"Swelling to become the largest hoard in the world and exceeding 3 trillion US dollars, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> accumulated from huge trade surpluses and was long managed partly by buying American government bonds, overseen by the central bank.","answer":"Foreign exchange reserves","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">外汇储备 (wàihuì chǔbèi, 'foreign-exchange reserves')</span></div>","traditional":"外匯儲備","hanzi":"外汇储备","pinyin":"wàihuì chǔbèi","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">wàihuì chǔbèi</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Foreign exchange reserves</b> are assets held by a country's <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_bank\">central bank</span></b> or <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Monetary_policy\">monetary</span> authority in foreign currencies, used to back the national currency, manage the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Exchange_rate\">exchange rate</span>, meet external obligations, and stabilize the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Balance_of_payments\">balance of payments</span>. Such reserves are usually concentrated in major <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Reserve_currency\">reserve currencies</span></b>—above all the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States_dollar\">US dollar</span>, with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Euro\">euro</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japanese_yen\">Japanese yen</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pound_sterling\">pound sterling</span> playing lesser roles—and are typically <b>supplemented by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gold_reserve\">gold</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Special_drawing_rights\">special drawing rights</span>, and reserve positions at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"International_Monetary_Fund\">International Monetary Fund</span>. To preserve safety and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Market_liquidity\">liquidity</span>, much of the money is invested in low-risk instruments such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Government_bond\">government bonds</span>—most prominently <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States_Treasury_security\">US Treasury securities</span></b>—alongside the sovereign debt of other advanced economies, bank deposits, and gold. Beyond backing a currency, reserves allow a central bank to intervene in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Currency_intervention\">currency markets</span> and serve as a buffer against <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capital_flight\">capital flight</span> and a sudden loss of financing, a motive that intensified across Asia <b>after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1997_Asian_financial_crisis\">Asian financial crisis</span> of 1997</b> forced several economies into emergency bailouts. Worldwide reserves total well over 12 trillion dollars, the bulk of it amassed by emerging economies since the 1990s, of which the dollar's share—a reflection of its role in global trade and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dollar_hegemony\">dollar hegemony</span>—has long hovered near 60 percent, even as central banks have slowly trimmed it in favour of the euro, the renminbi, and other assets. <br> <br> China holds by far the largest such hoard, exceeding 3 trillion dollars—more than twice the holdings of any other country—a stockpile built up over two decades of rapid <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Export-oriented_industrialization\">export-oriented</span> growth and tight management of the currency. The reserves accumulated from persistent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Balance_of_trade\">trade surpluses</span> and a soaring <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Current_account\">current account</span>—which at its height ran near 10 percent of output—swollen further by inflows of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foreign_direct_investment\">foreign direct investment</span>, as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Bank_of_China\">People's Bank of China</span> bought up foreign currency and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sterilization_(economics)\">sterilized</span> the inflows to restrain appreciation of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Renminbi\">renminbi</span> and preserve the competitiveness of exports. Having surpassed <b>1 trillion dollars in 2006</b>, they grew so rapidly that the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Investment_Corporation\">China Investment Corporation</span> was established in 2007 as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sovereign_wealth_fund\">sovereign wealth fund</span> to pursue higher returns on a portion of them—the corporation later managing well over 1 trillion dollars—and the total pile peaked at nearly 4 <b>trillion dollars in June 2014</b>. Managed by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_Administration_of_Foreign_Exchange\">State Administration of Foreign Exchange</span> under the central bank, the reserves were long invested heavily in American government debt—at times more than 1 trillion dollars of it, making China one of the largest foreign holders of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_debt_of_the_United_States\">United States national debt</span>—before sliding back toward 3 trillion dollars, a drawdown approaching 1 trillion from its peak, as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capital_control\">capital controls</span> came under strain and the bank spent reserves to support the currency within its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Managed_float_regime\">managed float</span>. The sheer scale of the holdings has fueled debate over a so-called dollar trap and the wisdom of financing American deficits, prompting gradual diversification into other currencies and gold and renewed efforts to advance the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Internationalization_of_the_renminbi\">internationalization of the renminbi</span>, even as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japan\">Japan</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Switzerland\">Switzerland</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"India\">India</span> hold the next-largest reserves, each only a fraction of China's.","citation":"","answerText":"Foreign exchange reserves"},{"id":"cne-045","num":"四十五","category":"China · Economics","question":"The <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was a late-<span class=\"blank\">_____</span>s slogan for the policy of keeping the biggest state-owned enterprises in strategic sectors under control while privatising, merging or closing thousands of smaller ones, a restructuring driven by Zhu Rongji under Jiang Zemin.","answer":"Grasping the large, letting go of the small","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Origin</span><span class=\"dt-v\">SOE-reform slogan under Jiang Zemin and Zhu Rongji, 1990s</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"抓大放小","pinyin":"zhuā dà fàng xiǎo","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">zhuā dà fàng xiǎo</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Grasping the large, letting go of the small</b> was a guiding slogan of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>'s <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_enterprises_of_China\">state-owned enterprise</span></b> reform in the late 1990s, summarising a strategy of retaining the largest firms while shedding the rest. Under the policy the state would \"grasp\" a core of giant enterprises in strategic sectors such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Banking_in_China\">banking</span>, energy, telecommunications, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Public_utility\">utilities</span>, and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Arms_industry\">defence industry</span></b>, while \"letting go\" of tens of thousands of smaller and loss-making firms through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Privatization\">privatisation</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mergers_and_acquisitions\">merger</span>, or outright <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bankruptcy\">bankruptcy</span>. The approach was formally endorsed <b>at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"15th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">15th National Congress of the Chinese Communist Party</span> in 1997</b> under General Secretary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Zemin\">Jiang Zemin</span> and pursued with notable resolve by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Premier_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">Premier</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_Rongji\">Zhu Rongji</span>, who set a target of lifting most large and medium loss-making enterprises out of difficulty within three years. By the mid-1990s the bloated state sector inherited from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Planned_economy\">planned economy</span> had become a chronic burden, with a large share of enterprises operating at a loss and weighed down by debt and overstaffing, even as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>'s earlier reforms had unleashed competition from private and collective rivals. The surviving giants were reorganised as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joint-stock_company\">joint-stock companies</span> and groomed into globally competitive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_champions\">national champions</span>, an approach partly inspired by the South Korean <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chaebol\">chaebol</span>, within China's emerging <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialist_market_economy\">socialist market economy</span>. <br> <br> Implementation was sweeping: the number of industrial state firms fell from well over 100,000 in the mid-1990s to a few tens of thousands within a decade, while many of the retained enterprises were <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Corporatization\">corporatised</span> and partially floated on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_Stock_Exchange\">Shanghai Stock Exchange</span> and other markets through major <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Initial_public_offering\">public offerings</span>. The restructuring shattered the \"<b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Iron_rice_bowl\">iron rice bowl</span></b>\" of guaranteed lifetime employment provided through the urban <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Danwei\">work-unit</span> system, and tens of millions of workers—by many estimates around 30 million or more between the late 1990s and the mid-2000s—were laid off, a wrenching social phenomenon known as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiagang\">xiagang</span>. This produced a steep rise in urban <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Unemployment\">unemployment</span></b>, officially understated but widely felt, and forced the government to dismantle cradle-to-grave welfare and build a rudimentary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Social_safety_net\">social safety net</span> of pensions, unemployment insurance, and reemployment programmes to cushion the mass <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Layoff\">layoffs</span>. The reforms also exposed mountains of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Non-performing_loan\">non-performing loans</span> that the state banks had extended to ailing enterprises under the old system, <b>prompting the creation in 1999</b> of four dedicated asset-management companies to absorb the soured debt and clean up bank balance sheets ahead of their own later listings. The process culminated in the establishment <b>of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_Assets_Supervision_and_Administration_Commission\">State-owned Assets Supervision and Administration Commission</span> in 2003</b> to manage roughly 196 surviving central enterprises, leaving a leaner but still dominant state sector that helped prepare China for entry into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Trade_Organization\">World Trade Organization</span> and remains a defining feature of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">Chinese economy</span> alongside the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">broader reform programme</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Grasping the large, letting go of the small"},{"id":"cne-047","num":"四十七","category":"China · Economics","question":"A system in which the state owns or dominates major firms and uses them to pursue national goals while still engaging in markets and profit-seeking, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is frequently applied to China's mix of giant state enterprises and a thriving private sector under the Communist Party.","answer":"State capitalism","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Origin</span><span class=\"dt-v\">A term from 19th-century socialist thought, later used by Lenin</span></div>","traditional":"國家資本主義","hanzi":"国家资本主义","pinyin":"guójiā zīběnzhǔyì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">guójiā zīběnzhǔyì</span></div>","abstract":"<b>State capitalism</b> is an economic system in which the state owns or dominates the largest firms and deploys them to advance national and strategic objectives, while still <b>operating through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Market_(economics)\">markets</span></b>, private enterprise, and the pursuit of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Profit_(economics)\">profit</span> characteristic of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capitalism\">capitalism</span>. Occupying a middle ground between a centrally <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Planned_economy\">planned economy</span> and a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Free_market\">free market</span>, it is a <b>form of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mixed_economy\">mixed economy</span></b> in which the government retains control of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Commanding_heights_of_the_economy\">commanding heights</span>—typically energy, banking, and telecommunications—while leaving room for private firms and competition in the wider economy. The term has a long history in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marxism\">Marxist</span> thought, where <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Friedrich_Engels\">Friedrich Engels</span> argued that state ownership alone did not abolish capitalism, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vladimir_Lenin\">Vladimir Lenin</span> used it to describe the mixed economy of his <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Economic_Policy\">New Economic Policy</span> in the 1920s, and later critics such as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tony_Cliff\">Tony Cliff</span></b> applied it pejoratively to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Soviet Union</span>, which they regarded as capitalist rather than socialist. In its modern political-economy sense, popularized by the political scientist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ian_Bremmer\">Ian Bremmer</span> in <b>works such as his 2010 study</b> <i>The End of the Free Market</i>, the model relies on state-owned firms, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sovereign_wealth_fund\">sovereign wealth funds</span>, directed lending, and active <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Industrial_policy\">industrial policy</span> to build <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_champions\">national champions</span>. Beyond China, the label is commonly applied to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russia\">Russia</span>, the petro-states of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Persian_Gulf\">Persian Gulf</span></b>, and the state-holding model of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Singapore\">Singapore</span>, whose sovereign investor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Temasek_Holdings\">Temasek Holdings</span> manages a vast portfolio of strategic assets. <br> <br> China is the most prominent contemporary example, though its government describes its own system as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialist_market_economy\">socialist market economy</span> rather than state capitalism, insisting that public ownership remains the mainstay of an order that took shape through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">economic reforms</span> launched under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> <b>from 1978</b>. The state retains ownership of giant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_enterprises_of_China\">state-owned enterprises</span> overseen by the powerful <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_Assets_Supervision_and_Administration_Commission\">State-owned Assets Supervision and Administration Commission</span>, channels credit through the state-controlled <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Big_Four_(banking)\">big four banks</span>, and embeds <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Communist Party</span> committees within major companies to keep even commercially run firms responsive to political direction. Although the roughly 100 centrally controlled conglomerates account for only a portion of output, state-linked firms still generate a large share of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gross_domestic_product\">gross domestic product</span>—by some estimates between a quarter and a third—and command the bulk of bank lending and industrial assets, dominating the Chinese entries on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fortune_Global_500\">Fortune Global 500</span>, while the sovereign fund <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Investment_Corporation\">China Investment Corporation</span> invests more than 1 trillion dollars abroad. This state core coexists with a thriving <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Private_sector\">private sector</span>—epitomized by technology firms such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Alibaba_Group\">Alibaba</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tencent\">Tencent</span>—which by official accounts contributes around 60 percent of output, 70 percent of innovation, 80 percent of urban employment, and 90 percent of new jobs. The balance has tilted back toward the state under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span>, whose emphasis on national strategy and <b>programmes such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Made_in_China_2025\">Made in China 2025</span></b>—part of a trend often summarized as \"the state advances, the private sector retreats\"—has intensified debate over whether the model represents a durable <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Developmental_state\">developmental state</span> or breeds inefficiency and distortion.","citation":"","answerText":"State capitalism"},{"id":"cne-048","num":"四十八","category":"China · Economics","question":"Numbering in the hundreds of millions and often barred by their household registration from full urban benefits, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> left the countryside to staff coastal factories and building sites, powering the export boom while remaining a vulnerable, low-paid workforce.","answer":"Migrant workers","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">农民工 (nóngmíngōng, 'peasant workers')</span></div>","traditional":"農民工","hanzi":"农民工","pinyin":"nóngmíngōng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">nóngmíngōng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Migrant workers</b> are people who leave their home region in search of employment, and in China the term refers above all to the vast population of rural residents who move to the cities for work while keeping a countryside <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hukou\">household registration</span></b> that sets them apart from established urban dwellers. Known in Chinese as \"peasant workers,\" they number in the hundreds of millions—around 290 million by official counts of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Bureau_of_Statistics_of_China\">National Bureau of Statistics</span>, of whom some 170 million work outside their home province—and constitute the largest <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Internal_migration\">internal migration</span></b> in human history. The flow began in the 1980s after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">economic reforms</span> dismantled <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Collective_farming\">collective farming</span> and freed hundreds of millions of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Underemployment\">underemployed</span> rural labourers, accelerating into a <b>tide of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rural_flight\">rural flight</span></b> as the coastal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Special_economic_zones_of_China\">special economic zones</span> opened and demand for cheap labour surged. They came to staff the export <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manufacturing\">factories</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Construction\">building sites</span> of booming regions such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pearl_River_Delta\">Pearl River Delta</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangdong\">Guangdong</span> around <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shenzhen\">Shenzhen</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze_Delta\">Yangtze Delta</span>, where some factory complexes employed hundreds of thousands of workers each, as well as the service trades of the cities. This abundant, low-cost workforce powered China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Export-oriented_industrialization\">export boom</span> and turned the country into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Workshop_of_the_world\">workshop of the world</span>, underpinning decades of rapid <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economic_growth\">economic growth</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Urbanization\">urbanization</span> while making up roughly a third of the entire Chinese workforce. <br> <br> Because welfare entitlements remain tied to one's registered locality, migrants in the cities are largely barred from full urban benefits, including <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Social_security\">social security</span></b>, pensions, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Public_housing\">subsidized housing</span>, and access to urban public <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Education_in_China\">schooling</span> for their children. This division has produced a large, semi-permanent urban underclass and forced many to leave their families behind, swelling the ranks of the rural <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Left-behind_children_in_China\">left-behind children</span>—estimated at the peak to exceed 60 million—and forming much of the country's mobile <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Floating_population\">floating population</span>, counted at over 370 million in the <b>2020 census</b>. They have long endured low wages, long hours, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Occupational_safety_and_health\">hazardous conditions</span>, and chronic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wage_theft\">wage arrears</span>, abuses dramatized by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foxconn_suicides\">Foxconn suicides</span> of 2010 and only partly addressed by the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Labor_Contract_Law_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">Labour Contract Law</span></b> and tightening <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Labor_rights\">labour-rights</span> rules, even as independent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Trade_union\">unions</span> remained banned. Each year vast numbers return to their villages during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chunyun\">Spring Festival travel rush</span>, the largest seasonal human migration on the planet, generating billions of trips—around 3 billion across all travellers in peak years—over the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rail_transport_in_China\">rail</span> and road network. As labour shortages pushed up wages above the rising <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Minimum_wage\">minimum wage</span></b> and a more assertive new generation came of age, the government began a gradual relaxation of household-registration rules in smaller cities, though the largest metropolises stayed tightly rationed, leaving migrant workers a vulnerable group at the centre of debates over <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Income_inequality_in_China\">inequality</span> and the future of China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peasant\">peasantry</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Migrant workers"},{"id":"cne-049","num":"四十九","category":"China · Economics","question":"Describing the growth boost a country enjoys when a bulge of working-age people supports relatively few children and elderly, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> helped power China's rise but is now fading as the effects of the one-child policy and an ageing population shrink the labour force.","answer":"Demographic dividend","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Origin</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Coined in development economics, 1990s–2000s</span></div>","traditional":"人口紅利","hanzi":"人口红利","pinyin":"rénkǒu hónglì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">rénkǒu hónglì</span></div>","abstract":"A <b>demographic dividend</b> is a surge in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economic_growth\">economic growth</span> that a country can enjoy when a <b>large bulge of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Working_age\">working-age</span></b> people supports comparatively few dependent children and elderly. The phenomenon arises during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Demographic_transition\">demographic transition</span>, the historical shift from high to low <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Birth_rate\">birth</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mortality_rate\">death rates</span>, when falling fertility temporarily produces a swollen labour cohort and a low <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dependency_ratio\">dependency ratio</span></b>. This advantage works through several channels—an expanded labour <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Labour_economics\">supply</span>, higher rates of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capital_accumulation\">capital accumulation</span> as prime-age earners save, greater investment in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Human_capital\">human capital</span> as families shrink, and <b>rising participation by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Women_in_the_workforce\">women in the workforce</span></b>. Crucially the benefit is transitory, opening only a finite <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Demographic_window\">demographic window</span> before the same cohort ages and a top-heavy <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Population_pyramid\">population pyramid</span> reverses the gains. Economists have credited the dividend with a large share of the postwar <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economic_miracle\">economic miracles</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Asian_Tigers\">Four Asian Tigers</span> and Japan, by some estimates as much as a third of East Asia's growth <b>between 1965</b> and 1990.<br> <br><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> reaped an exceptionally large dividend, as the sharp decline in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Total_fertility_rate\">fertility</span> driven by the birth-control campaigns of the 1970s and the one-child policy imposed <b>from 1979</b> reshaped the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Demographics_of_China\">country's population</span> and pushed its dependency ratio to remarkably low levels. An abundance of cheap young labour underpinned the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manufacturing\">manufacturing</span> boom of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">reform</span> era, helping drive decades of double-digit growth until the country approached the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dual-sector_model\">Lewis turning point</span> at which surplus rural workers run short. That window is now closing, for China's working-age population <b>peaked around 2013</b> and has since contracted, swelling the ranks of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Old_age\">elderly</span> and weighing on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Productivity\">productivity</span> across the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">economy</span>. In response Beijing has scrambled to lift the birth rate, relaxing the rule to permit <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Two-child_policy\">two children</span> in 2016 and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three-child_policy\">three</span> in 2021, embracing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pronatalism\">pronatalist</span> incentives, and moving to raise the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Retirement_age\">retirement age</span></b>. Yet fertility has slumped to around 1, far beneath the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sub-replacement_fertility\">replacement level</span> of about 2.1, and the total population began to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Population_decline\">shrink</span> in 2022, leaving China to confront the prospect of \"getting old before getting rich\" with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Per_capita_income\">per-capita incomes</span> still well below those of advanced economies, even as a younger <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"India\">India</span> and much of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Africa\">Africa</span> stand to inherit dividends of their own.","citation":"","answerText":"Demographic dividend"},{"id":"cne-050","num":"五十","category":"China · Economics","question":"Referring to people living and working away from the place where they hold official residence registration, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> consists mostly of rural migrants in the cities, lacking local access to schools and welfare across the People's Republic.","answer":"Floating population","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">流动人口 (liúdòng rénkǒu, 'floating population')</span></div>","traditional":"流動人口","hanzi":"流动人口","pinyin":"liúdòng rénkǒu","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">liúdòng rénkǒu</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>floating population</b> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>&nbsp;refers to people who live and work in a place other than where they hold official <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hukou_system\">household registration</span></b>, the great majority of them rural <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Migrant_workers_in_China\">migrants</span> drawn by one of the largest streams of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Human_migration\">human migration</span> in history. The category arises from the household registration system <b>institutionalised in 1958</b>, which classified every citizen as either agricultural or non-agricultural, bound them to a specific locality, and tightly restricted <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Internal_migration\">internal migration</span> throughout the era of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>, when the state allocated grain, jobs, and housing through one's place of registration. As <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">reform and opening up</span> <b>from 1978</b> relaxed those controls and the demand for cheap labour in coastal industry exploded, tens of millions of people left the countryside in a vast wave of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rural_flight\">rural-to-urban migration</span>, swelling the ranks of those living and working far outside their place of registration. From only a few million in the early 1980s, the group climbed to well <b>over 100 million by 2000</b> and roughly 220 million by 2010, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2020_Chinese_census\">2020 census</span> recorded a far larger figure of about 376 million as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Urbanization_in_China\">urbanisation</span> accelerated. Migrants concentrated above all in the booming coastal cities of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"East_China\">eastern China</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pearl_River_Delta\">Pearl River Delta</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yangtze_Delta\">Yangtze Delta</span>, including <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Special_economic_zones_of_China\">special economic zone</span> hubs like <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shenzhen\">Shenzhen</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangdong\">Guangdong</span>, where they supplied the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Workforce\">labour</span></b> for factories, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Construction\">construction</span> sites, and services. <br> <br> Because access to public <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Welfare\">welfare</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Healthcare_in_China\">health care</span>, subsidised housing, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pension\">pensions</span> is tied to local registration, members of the floating population are largely excluded from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Social_safety_net\">social safety net</span> in the cities where they actually live. Their children face particular hardship, often barred from enrolling in local public schools and from sitting the high-stakes <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gaokao\">college entrance examination</span> in the city where their parents work, a structural gap that has profoundly shaped <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Education_in_China\">education in China</span> and entrenched rural-urban inequality. Many migrant parents consequently leave their offspring behind in rural villages, creating a population of tens of millions of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Left-behind_children_in_China\">left-behind children</span> raised by grandparents or other relatives. The migrants powered a historic rise in the country's urban share of the population, from under a fifth in 1978 to well over half today, prompting partial reforms such as a national <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Residence_permit\">residence permit</span></b> scheme, even as megacities like <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span> kept tight, points-based limits on granting local hukou. Numbering close to 300 million migrant workers by the 2020s, the floating population has been the engine of the country's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Labour_economics\">labour market</span> and the wider <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">Chinese economy</span>, yet its <b>members long endured <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Discrimination\">discrimination</span></b> and second-class status within a divided urban society, making the gradual dismantling of registration barriers a central question for the country's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Demographics_of_China\">demographic</span> and social future.","citation":"","answerText":"Floating population"},{"id":"cne-061","num":"六十一","category":"China · Economics","question":"Expanding explosively after <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> into by far the world's longest such network, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> links most major cities with trains running over 300 km/h (190 mph), built rapidly with heavy borrowing and financed in part by policy banks as a form of industrial policy by the state railway.","answer":"High-speed rail","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">高速铁路 (gāosù tiělù, 'high-speed railway')</span></div>","traditional":"高速鐵路","hanzi":"高速铁路","pinyin":"gāosù tiělù","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">gāosù tiělù</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>high-speed rail</b> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> is by a wide margin the largest such network on earth, a <b>centrepiece of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Transport_in_China\">transport in China</span></b> that links most of the country's major cities with services routinely operating at more than 300 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kilometres_per_hour\">kilometres per hour</span> (190 mph). The system grew explosively after 2008, the year the inaugural <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing–Tianjin_intercity_railway\">Beijing–Tianjin intercity railway</span> opened on the eve of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2008_Summer_Olympics\">Beijing Olympics</span>, and its construction was powerfully accelerated by the 4-trillion-<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Renminbi\">yuan</span> <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_stimulus_program\">stimulus package</span></b> that the government launched during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Recession\">global financial crisis</span>. The country's flagship line, the 1,318-kilometre (819 mi) <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing–Shanghai_high-speed_railway\">Beijing–Shanghai high-speed railway</span>, <b>entered service in 2011</b>, and the newest <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Electric_multiple_unit\">electric multiple units</span> of the domestically developed Fuxing family cruise at up to 350 kilometres per hour (220 mph), faster than most networks abroad if still slower than the German-built <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maglev\">maglev</span> line in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span>. By the 2020s the network, a central component of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rail_transport_in_China\">rail transport in China</span>, had grown to roughly 45,000 kilometres (28,000 mi)—about two-thirds of the world's total high-speed mileage—with official plans to reach 50,000 kilometres (31,000 mi) <b>by 2025</b> and around 70,000 kilometres (43,000 mi) by 2035. Its rolling stock initially drew on technology supplied by foreign firms such as Germany's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Siemens\">Siemens</span>, France's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Alstom\">Alstom</span>, Canada's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bombardier_Transportation\">Bombardier</span>, and <b>Japan's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kawasaki_Heavy_Industries\">Kawasaki Heavy Industries</span></b>, but through extensive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Technology_transfer\">technology transfer</span> the trains came to be manufactured domestically by the state conglomerate <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"CRRC\">CRRC</span>.<br> <br>The network, an immense work of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Infrastructure\">infrastructure</span>, was built at extraordinary speed and largely on credit, financed through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bond_(finance)\">bond</span> issues and loans from state policy banks as a deliberate instrument of industrial policy, leaving the railway authorities burdened with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Government_debt\">debts</span> running into trillions of yuan. Much of this breakneck growth was driven by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Zhijun\">Liu Zhijun</span>, the powerful railways minister dismissed in 2011 in a sweeping <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Corruption_in_China\">corruption</span> investigation and later handed a suspended death sentence. Public confidence was badly shaken in July 2011 by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wenzhou_train_collision\">Wenzhou train collision</span>, traced to a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Railway_signalling\">signalling</span> failure, which killed about 40 people and prompted a temporary freeze on new approvals together with reductions in operating speeds. <b>In 2013</b> the scandal-tarnished <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ministry_of_Railways_(China)\">Ministry of Railways</span> was abolished, its commercial operations passing to a new state railway corporation and its regulatory functions to a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Railway_Administration\">National Railway Administration</span> under the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ministry_of_Transport_(China)\">Ministry of Transport</span></b>. The finished network now carries billions of passenger journeys each year and has transformed domestic travel and the development of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">Chinese economy</span>'s regions, even as doubts linger over its debt, while Chinese firms increasingly export the technology abroad through projects such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jakarta–Bandung_high-speed_railway\">Jakarta–Bandung high-speed railway</span> and the wider <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Belt_and_Road_Initiative\">Belt and Road Initiative</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"High-speed rail"},{"id":"cne-063","num":"六十三","category":"China · Economics","question":"Companies created by city and provincial authorities to borrow for projects kept off their official books, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> ballooned after the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> stimulus, funding infrastructure and property and fuelling worries about hidden government debt.","answer":"Local government financing vehicle","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">地方政府融资平台 ('local-government financing platform')</span></div>","traditional":"地方政府融資平臺","hanzi":"地方政府融资平台","pinyin":"dìfāng zhèngfǔ róngzī píngtái","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">dìfāng zhèngfǔ róngzī píngtái</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“local government financing platform”</span></div>","abstract":"A <b>local government financing vehicle</b> is a type of company set up by city and provincial authorities in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> to borrow money for projects kept off their official books. Such vehicles arose because Chinese <b>law long barred <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Local_government\">local governments</span></b> across the country's many <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Administrative_divisions_of_China\">administrative divisions</span> from borrowing or running deficits directly, while a 1994 reform had shifted much tax revenue to the centre, leaving localities chronically short of funds yet responsible for vast spending. <b>Structured as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Special-purpose_entity\">special-purpose</span></b> investment companies and ultimately controlled by the state, they raise capital through bank <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Loan\">loans</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bond_(finance)\">bonds</span>, often pledging government-injected land as collateral, so that the resulting <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Off-balance-sheet\">off-balance-sheet</span></b> debt carries only an implicit official guarantee. Although they predated the global financial crisis, their numbers and borrowing exploded after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Recession\">Great Recession</span>, when the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_Council_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">State Council</span> launched a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_stimulus_program\">stimulus programme</span> of 4 trillion <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_(currency)\">yuan</span><b>—about $586 billion—in late 2008</b> and pushed localities to co-finance the spending. The vehicles poured the borrowed funds into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Infrastructure\">infrastructure</span> such as roads, railways, and water systems, into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Public_works\">public works</span> and property, becoming central to an investment-led development model that leaned heavily on selling <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Land_tenure\">land-use rights</span> and on credit from the broader <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Banking_in_China\">banking system</span>. <br> <br> As a result, their liabilities ballooned into one of the largest sources of hidden <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Government_debt\">government debt</span> in the world, with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"International_Monetary_Fund\">International Monetary Fund</span> and analysts estimating the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Debt\">debt</span> of these vehicles</b> at tens of trillions of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Renminbi\">renminbi</span>, equivalent to a large share of national <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gross_domestic_product\">output</span>. Because much of this borrowing sat outside official budgets and was often routed through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shadow_banking_system\">shadow banking</span>, it obscured the true scale of public liabilities and fuelled <b>persistent worries about <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Financial_risk\">financial risk</span></b> and the solvency of local <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Public_finance\">public finances</span>. Those fears intensified during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2020–2023_Chinese_property_sector_crisis\">property sector crisis</span> of the early 2020s, when the collapse of developers such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Evergrande_Group\">Evergrande</span> and the deflation of a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Real_estate_bubble\">real-estate bubble</span> slashed the land-sale revenues that vehicles depended on, raising the spectre of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Default_(finance)\">default</span> and wider <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Credit_risk\">credit risk</span>. Beijing repeatedly tried to rein them in—amending <b>the budget law in 2014</b> to let provinces issue <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Municipal_bond\">municipal bonds</span> directly and launching programmes to swap opaque vehicle debt for cheaper government bonds—yet their borrowing kept climbing despite each round of new <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fiscal_policy\">fiscal</span> rules. Closely tied to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_enterprises_of_China\">state-owned enterprises</span> and the wider financial system overseen by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Bank_of_China\">People's Bank of China</span>, these vehicles came to embody both the infrastructure-driven dynamism and the mounting debt risks of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">Chinese economy</span>, leaving policymakers to grapple with how to defuse a hidden liability of extraordinary size.","citation":"","answerText":"Local government financing vehicle"},{"id":"cne-067","num":"六十七","category":"China · Economics","question":"A term for the vast, largely empty new districts and apartment blocks thrown up during the building boom, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> — exemplified by Ordos in Inner Mongolia — reflected speculative real estate investment and overcapacity.","answer":"Ghost cities","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">鬼城 (guǐchéng, 'ghost city')</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"鬼城","pinyin":"Guǐchéng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Guǐchéng</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“ghost city”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Ghost cities</b> is a term for the vast, largely uninhabited new districts, apartment blocks, and even entire towns thrown up across <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> during its decades-long <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Construction\">construction</span></b> boom. The phenomenon arose from a building frenzy propelled by breakneck <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Urbanization_in_China\">urbanization</span>, ambitious targets for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economic_growth\">economic growth</span>, and the <b>heavy dependence of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Local_government_in_China\">local governments</span></b> on revenue from selling land to developers. Because housing functioned as the principal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Store_of_value\">store of value</span> for Chinese households, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Speculation\">speculative</span> buyers acquired large numbers of units they never intended to occupy, inflating a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_property_bubble\">property bubble</span></b> and a glut of unsold <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Real_estate_development\">real-estate development</span>. The most celebrated example was the Kangbashi district of Ordos, in Inner Mongolia, a gleaming new <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"City\">urban centre</span> financed by the region's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Coal\">coal</span> wealth and planned for hundreds of thousands of residents yet for years left almost deserted. Comparable developments proliferated elsewhere, among them <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tianducheng\">Tianducheng</span>, a replica of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paris\">Paris</span> complete with an imitation <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eiffel_Tower\">Eiffel Tower</span></b> outside <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hangzhou\">Hangzhou</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yujiapu_Financial_District\">Yujiapu Financial District</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tianjin\">Tianjin</span> modelled on <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manhattan\">Manhattan</span></b>, and the sprawling new eastern districts of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhengzhou\">Zhengzhou</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Henan\">Henan</span>.<br> <br>The scale of the surplus was immense, with independent surveys estimating that around 20 percent of urban <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Housing\">homes</span> stood empty and that tens of millions of finished <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Apartment\">apartments</span> had no occupants, a striking measure of the country's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Overproduction\">overcapacity</span>. Whether such places represented a dangerous <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economic_bubble\">bubble</span></b> or merely <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fixed_investment\">investment</span> running ahead of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Supply_and_demand\">demand</span> was much debated, and several—Kangbashi among them—did slowly fill with residents over the following decade. Ultimately, however, the reliance on debt-fuelled property construction proved unsustainable, contributing to a <b>severe sectoral crisis after 2021</b> in which giant developers such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Evergrande_Group\">Evergrande Group</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Country_Garden\">Country Garden</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Default_(finance)\">defaulted</span> on enormous obligations. With <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Real_estate_in_China\">real estate in China</span> accounting at its height for as much as 25 to 30 percent of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gross_domestic_product\">gross domestic product</span>, the ghost cities laid bare the distortions of a growth model dependent on construction and rising land values. They became an enduring emblem of the imbalances within the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">Chinese economy</span>, illustrating how local incentives, abundant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Credit_(finance)\">credit</span>, and speculative demand could conjure entire cities for which there were, at least for a time, almost no people.","citation":"","answerText":"Ghost cities"},{"id":"cne-070","num":"七十","category":"China · Economics","question":"Government efforts to favour particular industries through subsidies, cheap credit, tariffs and procurement, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is central to China's strategy of nurturing champions in semiconductors, electric vehicles and renewables, often clashing with the free-trade rules of the WTO.","answer":"Industrial policy","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">产业政策 (chǎnyè zhèngcè, 'industrial policy')</span></div>","traditional":"產業政策","hanzi":"产业政策","pinyin":"chǎnyè zhèngcè","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">chǎnyè zhèngcè</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Industrial policy</b> refers to deliberate government <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economic_interventionism\">intervention</span></b> to favour and develop particular industries judged to be of strategic importance, rather than leaving their fortunes wholly to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Market_(economics)\">market</span>. Its characteristic instruments include direct <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Subsidy\">subsidies</span>, cheap and directed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Credit_(finance)\">credit</span>, protective <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tariff\">tariffs</span>, preferential <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Government_procurement\">government procurement</span>, support for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Research_and_development\">research and development</span>, and at times outright state ownership of favoured enterprises. Advocates justify such measures <b>by appeal to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Market_failure\">market failures</span></b> and to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Infant_industry_argument\">infant-industry argument</span>, a doctrine traced to <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Alexander_Hamilton\">Alexander Hamilton</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Report_on_Manufactures\">Report on Manufactures</span> of 1791</b> and elaborated by the economist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Friedrich_List\">Friedrich List</span>. The approach became closely associated with the East Asian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Developmental_state\">developmental state</span>, exemplified in the decades after 1945 by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japan\">Japan</span>'s <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ministry_of_International_Trade_and_Industry\">Ministry of International Trade and Industry</span></b> and by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chaebol\">chaebol</span>-driven industrialisation of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South_Korea\">South Korea</span>. Critics counter that governments are poorly placed to \"pick winners\" and that intervention invites <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Government_failure\">government failure</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rent-seeking\">rent-seeking</span>, contending that resources are better allocated according to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Comparative_advantage\">comparative advantage</span> under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Free_trade\">free trade</span>.<br> <br>Industrial policy lies at the heart of China's economic strategy, pursued through successive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five-year_plans_of_China\">Five-Year Plans</span> and crystallised in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Made_in_China_2025\">Made in China <b>2025</span> initiative</b> of 2015, which set targets for domestic dominance across a range of advanced manufacturing sectors. In <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Integrated_circuit\">semiconductors</span>, the state channelled tens of billions of dollars through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Integrated_Circuit_Industry_Investment_Fund\">National Integrated Circuit Industry Investment Fund</span>, <b>created in 2014</b>, to build champions such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Semiconductor_Manufacturing_International_Corporation\">Semiconductor Manufacturing International Corporation</span> and to reduce dependence on imports amid tightening American export controls and the rival <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"CHIPS_and_Science_Act\">CHIPS and Science Act</span>. Sustained support over more than a decade likewise propelled China to global leadership in electric vehicles and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lithium-ion_battery\">lithium-ion batteries</span> that power them, dominated by national champions such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"BYD_Company\">BYD</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"CATL\">Contemporary Amperex Technology</span>. In <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Renewable_energy\">renewable energy</span> the strategy proved equally transformative, leaving Chinese firms responsible for roughly 80 percent of the world's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Photovoltaics\">solar photovoltaic</span> manufacturing alongside a commanding share of global <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wind_power\">wind power</span> production. Because these measures rely on subsidies, cheap finance, and local-content requirements, they have repeatedly collided with the free-trade rules of the World Trade Organization, fuelling accusations of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Overproduction\">overcapacity</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dumping_(pricing_policy)\">dumping</span> and prompting the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"European_Union\">European Union</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States\">United States</span> to impose steep tariffs on Chinese electric vehicles and solar panels in 2024.","citation":"","answerText":"Industrial policy"},{"id":"cne-072","num":"七十二","category":"China · Economics","question":"A long-term project to widen the global use of the Chinese currency in trade, lending and reserves, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> included offshore markets in Hong Kong, swap lines with foreign central banks, and a push to settle Belt and Road deals outside the US dollar.","answer":"Internationalization of the renminbi","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">人民币国际化 ('internationalization of the renminbi')</span></div>","traditional":"人民幣國際化","hanzi":"人民币国际化","pinyin":"rénmínbì guójìhuà","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">rénmínbì guójìhuà</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>internationalization of the renminbi</b> is <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>'s long-term policy effort to widen the global use of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Renminbi\">renminbi</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"International_trade\">trade</span></b>, lending, and official <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foreign_exchange_reserves\">reserves</span>, reducing reliance on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States_dollar\">US dollar</span>. The effort <b>began in earnest around 2009</b> with a pilot scheme allowing exporters and importers to settle cross-border trade in the currency, followed by the rapid rise of an offshore <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_(currency)\">yuan</span> market in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span>—the largest <b>such hub—where so-called <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dim_sum_bond\">dim sum bonds</span></b> and other renminbi-denominated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bond_(finance)\">bonds</span> were issued to international investors. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Bank_of_China\">People's Bank of China</span> signed bilateral <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Currency_swap\">currency swap</span> lines worth trillions of yuan with dozens of foreign <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_bank\">central banks</span>, while official clearing arrangements and offshore trading spread to financial centres such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"London\">London</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Singapore\">Singapore</span>. A <b>symbolic milestone came in 2016</b>, when the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"International_Monetary_Fund\">International Monetary Fund</span> admitted the renminbi to its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Special_drawing_rights\">Special Drawing Rights</span> basket—with a weighting of about 11 percent, the third-largest after the dollar and the euro—formally recognising it as a global <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Reserve_currency\">reserve currency</span>. Beijing also <b>built the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cross-Border_Interbank_Payment_System\">Cross-Border Interbank Payment System</span> in 2015</b> as an alternative to the dollar-centred <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"SWIFT\">SWIFT</span> network, pushed to settle <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Belt_and_Road_Initiative\">Belt and Road</span> deals in yuan, and developed a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Digital_renminbi\">digital renminbi</span> with potential cross-border uses. <br> <br> Despite these efforts, the renminbi remains a modest player, making up only a few percent of global payments and central-bank reserves and around 7 percent of turnover on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foreign_exchange_market\">foreign-exchange market</span> measured by the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bank_for_International_Settlements\">Bank for International Settlements</span></b>, far behind the dominant dollar and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Euro\">euro</span>. Its global ambitions are constrained above all by China's tight <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capital_control\">capital controls</span> and the limited <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Convertibility\">convertibility</span> of the currency on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capital_account\">capital account</span>, which deter foreign investors wary of being unable to move money in and out freely and sit in fundamental tension with the goal of internationalisation itself. Reserve currencies also depend on deep, open financial markets and strong legal protections for foreign holders, areas where the renminbi still trails the established Western currencies despite the sheer size of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">Chinese economy</span>. Interest in the currency nonetheless revived after sweeping Western sanctions on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russia\">Russia</span> in 2022—including the freezing of its dollar reserves—spurred wider talk of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dedollarisation\">de-dollarisation</span>, with <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China–Russia_relations\">China–Russia trade</span></b> increasingly invoiced in renminbi and some oil and commodity deals priced in the currency. Ultimately the project embodies an enduring tension at the heart of Chinese policy—between the desire to project financial power abroad and the determination to keep firm control over the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Exchange_rate\">exchange rate</span> and capital flows at home—so that even as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span> is groomed as a global financial centre, the renminbi's rise has remained gradual and tightly managed.","citation":"","answerText":"Internationalization of the renminbi"},{"id":"cne-083","num":"八十三","category":"China · Economics","question":"A tax imposed on imported goods, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was deployed in waves by President Donald Trump on hundreds of billions of dollars of Chinese products from <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>, met by retaliation from Beijing in a dispute over the trade deficit and technology.","answer":"Tariff","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Arabic taʿrīf ('notification'), via Italian tariffa</span></div>","traditional":"關稅","hanzi":"关税","pinyin":"guānshuì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">guānshuì</span></div>","abstract":"A <b>tariff</b> is a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tax\">tax</span> levied by a government on goods crossing its borders, <b>most commonly on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Import\">imports</span></b>, and it ranks among the oldest instruments of economic statecraft, historically supplying the bulk of public <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Government_revenue\">revenue</span> — in the United States, most federal income <b>before the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sixteenth_Amendment_to_the_United_States_Constitution\">income tax</span> of 1913</b> — while also serving to shield domestic producers and exert diplomatic pressure. Such duties are typically structured either as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ad_valorem_tax\">ad valorem</span> charges set as a percentage of a good's value or as specific levies fixed per unit, and economists conventionally distinguish revenue tariffs, designed chiefly to fund the state, from protective tariffs meant to blunt foreign competition through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Protectionism\">protectionism</span>. Mainstream economic analysis, rooted in the theory of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Comparative_advantage\">comparative advantage</span> articulated by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"David_Ricardo\">David Ricardo</span>, generally holds that tariffs reduce aggregate welfare by raising consumer prices and generating a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deadweight_loss\">deadweight loss</span></b>, even as they benefit protected industries and the treasury. Advocates of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Free_trade\">free trade</span> have nonetheless long contended with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Infant_industry_argument\">infant-industry argument</span> championed by figures such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Alexander_Hamilton\">Alexander Hamilton</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Friedrich_List\">Friedrich List</span></b>, who maintained that temporary protection could nurture nascent manufacturing, a logic central to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mercantilism\">mercantilist</span> doctrines of early modern Europe. Over the modern era tariff policy oscillated dramatically, from the repeal of <b>Britain's protectionist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Corn_Laws\">Corn Laws</span> in 1846</b> to the United States' notorious <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Smoot–Hawley_Tariff_Act\">Smoot–Hawley Tariff Act</span> of 1930, which revised duties on more than 20,000 imported items and is widely blamed for deepening the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Depression\">Great Depression</span>, before the postwar <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"General_Agreement_on_Tariffs_and_Trade\">General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade</span> and its successor the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Trade_Organization\">World Trade Organization</span> drove average industrial-country rates down to low single digits. <br> <br> The instrument returned to global prominence <b>from 2018</b>, when President <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Donald_Trump\">Donald Trump</span> launched the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China–United_States_trade_war\">China–United States trade war</span>, invoking national-security and unfair-practice statutes to impose duties on Chinese goods over the bilateral <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Balance_of_trade\">trade deficit</span> and allegations of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Intellectual_property\">intellectual-property</span> theft and forced technology transfer. Beginning with a 25 percent levy on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Steel\">steel</span> and 10 percent on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Aluminium\">aluminium</span> in March 2018, Washington escalated through successive tranches that by 2019 covered roughly US$360 billion of Chinese imports — including 25 percent duties on US$250 billion of goods — to which <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> retaliated with tariffs on about US$110 billion of American products, notably <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soybean\">soybeans</span> and other farm exports. A partial truce arrived with the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China–United_States_Phase_One_trade_deal\">Phase One agreement</span></b> signed in January 2020, under which China pledged to purchase an additional US$200 billion of American goods over two years and Washington halved one tranche of duties, though the bulk of the tariffs remained in force and the purchase targets ultimately went unmet. Empirical studies of the episode found that the economic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tax_incidence\">incidence</span> of the levies fell overwhelmingly on American importers and consumers through near-complete pass-through to domestic prices, with researchers estimating aggregate real-income losses of around US$1.4 billion per month by late 2018 and a burden of several hundred dollars on the average household each year. Rather than reverse this turn, the administration of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joe_Biden\">Joe Biden</span> retained most of the inherited duties and in 2024 sharply raised tariffs on strategic Chinese products, lifting the rate on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Electric_vehicle\">electric vehicles</span> to 100 percent, a trajectory that left the once-dominant postwar consensus favouring ever-lower <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Trade_barrier\">trade barriers</span> looking increasingly fragile.","citation":"","answerText":"Tariff"},{"id":"cne-086","num":"八十六","category":"China · Economics","question":"Producing the bulk of the world's supply of 17 metallic elements vital to magnets, electronics and electric vehicles, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> has given Beijing powerful leverage, wielded through export controls against Japan and the United States.","answer":"Rare earth industry","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">稀土 (xītǔ, 'rare earth')</span></div>","traditional":"稀土產業","hanzi":"稀土产业","pinyin":"xītǔ chǎnyè","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">xītǔ chǎnyè</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>rare earth industry</b> encompasses the mining, refining, and processing of a group of 17 metallic <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rare-earth_element\">elements</span></b> — the 15 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lanthanide\">lanthanides</span> together with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Scandium\">scandium</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yttrium\">yttrium</span> — whose strategic weight far exceeds their modest share of global mining revenue. These metals underpin the powerful <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Neodymium_magnet\">neodymium permanent magnets</span> used in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Electric_vehicle\">electric vehicles</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wind_turbine\">wind turbines</span>, as well as in smartphones, lasers, refining catalysts, and an <b>array of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Strategic_material\">strategic</span></b> military systems ranging from precision-guided missiles to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lockheed_Martin_F-35_Lightning_II\">F-35</span> fighter. Despite their name the elements are relatively abundant in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Crust_(geology)\">Earth's crust</span>, but they seldom occur in concentrated deposits and their <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mining\">extraction</span> and separation are technically demanding and notoriously polluting, generating toxic and mildly radioactive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Thorium\">thorium</span>-laden tailings that have scarred regions such as Baotou. <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> overwhelmingly dominates the sector, accounting for roughly 60 percent of the world's mined output — on the order of 240,000 tonnes (260,000 tons) a year — and around 90 percent of refining and magnet-manufacturing capacity, anchored by the vast Bayan Obo deposit in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Inner_Mongolia\">Inner Mongolia</span>. This pre-eminence prompted <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> to remark in 1992</b> that \"the Middle East has oil, China has rare earths,\" and in 2021 the government merged several producers into the single giant China Rare Earth Group, a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_enterprises_of_China\">state-owned enterprise</span> created to consolidate control over supply, pricing, and strategic stockpiling. <br> <br> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>'s control has handed it potent geopolitical leverage, <b>most dramatically in 2010</b> when, amid the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Senkaku_Islands_dispute\">Senkaku Islands dispute</span> following a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2010_Senkaku_boat_collision_incident\">collision near the contested islands</span>, China curtailed rare-earth shipments to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japan\">Japan</span> in an unofficial embargo that jolted Japanese manufacturers and triggered a global scramble for alternatives. The episode, compounded by sharp cuts to Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Export_restriction\">export quotas</span>, sent prices of some rare earths soaring <b>several-fold in 2010 and 2011</b> — with certain oxides briefly rising roughly tenfold — alarming governments dependent on a single supplier. In response the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States\">United States</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"European_Union\">European Union</span>, and Japan lodged a complaint with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Trade_Organization\">World Trade Organization</span> in 2012, and the body ruled against the quotas in 2014, leading Beijing to scrap them the following year, though its underlying dominance of the processing <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Supply_chain\">supply chains</span></b> remained intact as few countries possessed the capacity to challenge it. The leverage resurfaced forcefully during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China–United_States_trade_war\">trade war</span> with Washington, as China imposed export controls on the related minor metals <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gallium\">gallium</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Germanium\">germanium</span> in 2023, restricted <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Graphite\">graphite</span> and the technology for processing rare earths, and from 2025 required licences for the export of several heavy rare earths such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dysprosium\">dysprosium</span> and the finished magnets on which electric motors and weapons depend. These measures spurred frantic efforts abroad to rebuild alternative supply chains, reviving the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mountain_Pass_rare_earth_mine\">Mountain Pass mine</span></b> in California operated by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"MP_Materials\">MP Materials</span> and expanding output by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Australia\">Australia's</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lynas\">Lynas</span>, yet by the mid-2020s the West still relied on Chinese plants to refine the overwhelming majority of separated rare earths for the magnets at the heart of the green and digital economies.","citation":"","answerText":"Rare earth industry"},{"id":"cne-096","num":"九十六","category":"China · Economics","question":"The difference between the value of a country's exports and imports, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> has run a large and persistent surplus for China, becoming a flashpoint with trading partners and a driver of its accumulation of foreign reserves and accusations of mercantilism from the United States.","answer":"Balance of trade","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">贸易差额 (màoyì chā'é, 'trade balance')</span></div>","traditional":"貿易差額","hanzi":"贸易差额","pinyin":"màoyì chāʼé","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">màoyì chāʼé</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>balance of trade</b>, also termed the trade balance or net exports, is the difference between the monetary value of a nation's <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Export\">exports</span></b> and its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Import\">imports</span> of goods and services in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"International_trade\">international trade</span>, yielding a surplus when exports exceed imports and a deficit when the reverse holds. As the largest component of the broader <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Current_account\">current account</span> within a country's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Balance_of_payments\">balance of payments</span>, it feeds directly into the expenditure measure of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gross_domestic_product\">gross domestic product</span>, where net exports are added to consumption, investment, and government spending. The concept lay at the heart of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mercantilism\">mercantilist</span> doctrine, which dominated European economic thinking from the 16th to the 18th century and held that a favourable balance enabled the accumulation of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bullion\">bullion</span>, a view articulated by writers such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Thomas_Mun\">Thomas Mun</span>, whose <b>1664 treatise</b> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"England's_Treasure_by_Forraign_Trade\"><i>England's Treasure by Forraign Trade</i></span> treated a trade surplus as the surest source of national wealth. This preoccupation with hoarding precious metals was famously challenged by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Adam_Smith\">Adam Smith</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Wealth_of_Nations\"><i>The Wealth of Nations</i></span> and by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"David_Hume\">David Hume</span>, whose <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Price–specie_flow_mechanism\">price–specie flow mechanism</span></b> demonstrated that trade surpluses tend to correct themselves automatically through subsequent price adjustments. Later classical thinkers, notably <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"David_Ricardo\">David Ricardo</span>, advanced the theory of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Comparative_advantage\">comparative advantage</span> to argue that the mutual gains from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Free_trade\">free trade</span> mattered far more than the pursuit of a perpetual surplus, laying the intellectual groundwork for the open trading order of the 20th century. <br> <br> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> has run a large and persistent merchandise surplus for decades, <b>particularly after its 2001 accession</b> to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Trade_Organization\">World Trade Organization</span> transformed it into the world's foremost <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manufacturing\">manufacturing</span> exporter, accounting in time for over a tenth of global goods exports by value. Its current-account surplus peaked at nearly 10 percent of <b>gross domestic product around 2007</b>, when it exceeded US$350 billion, and although that ratio later fell to low single digits, the surplus in absolute terms swelled to record levels, with the goods trade balance approaching US$1 trillion in 2024 even as a widening deficit in services and investment income held the overall current account far below its earlier peak. This export machine drove a <b>vast accumulation of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foreign_exchange_reserves_of_China\">foreign-exchange reserves</span></b>, which climbed to a peak of just under US$4 trillion in 2014 — by far the largest such holdings of any country — before easing to around US$3.2 trillion thereafter, as the authorities intervened to restrain appreciation of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Renminbi\">renminbi</span>. The scale of the surplus and the managed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Exchange_rate\">exchange rate</span> provoked recurring accusations of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Currency_intervention\">currency manipulation</span> and mercantilism from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States\">United States</span>, culminating when the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States_Department_of_the_Treasury\">Treasury</span> formally labelled China a currency manipulator in August 2019, a designation it rescinded the following January amid trade negotiations. The persistent imbalance became a central flashpoint in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China–United_States_trade_war\">trade war</span> waged by President <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Donald_Trump\">Donald Trump</span>, who cited the bilateral United States deficit with China — roughly US$300 billion by the mid-2020s — to justify sweeping <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tariff\">tariffs</span>, even as economists such as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ben_Bernanke\">Ben Bernanke</span></b> attributed the wider pattern of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Global_saving_glut\">global imbalances</span> partly to a worldwide glut of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Saving\">savings</span> rather than to trade policy alone.","citation":"","answerText":"Balance of trade"},{"id":"cne-099","num":"九十九","category":"China · Economics","question":"Nurtured by years of generous subsidies, charging-network rollouts and industrial policy, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> became the world's largest, producing more than half of global output and home to brands such as BYD and battery maker CATL.","answer":"Electric vehicle industry","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">电动汽车产业 ('electric-vehicle industry')</span></div>","traditional":"電動汽車產業","hanzi":"电动汽车产业","pinyin":"diàndòng qìchē chǎnyè","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">diàndòng qìchē chǎnyè</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>electric vehicle industry</b> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> is the world's largest, encompassing the <b>manufacture of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_energy_vehicle\">new energy vehicles</span></b>—the official category covering <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battery_electric_vehicle\">battery-electric</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Plug-in_hybrid\">plug-in hybrid</span> cars—and by the mid-2020s it accounted for well over half of global output. The sector was deliberately cultivated through sustained <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Industrial_policy\">industrial policy</span>, including generous purchase <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Subsidy\">subsidies</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sales_tax\">tax</span> exemptions, and a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Charging_station\">charging</span> network that grew to 12.82 million points by the end of 2024, with <b>national programs such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Made_in_China_2025\">Made in China 2025</span></b> setting aggressive targets. An analysis by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Center_for_Strategic_and_International_Studies\">Center for Strategic and International Studies</span> estimated cumulative government support for the sector at roughly $230 billion between 2009 and 2023, and although direct consumer purchase subsidies were largely phased out <b>by the end of 2022</b>, that backing had already met the official sales-penetration target years ahead of schedule. New-energy-vehicle penetration rose from just 6.3% of new-car sales in 2020 to nearly half by 2024, when sales reached about 12.9 million units—roughly 41% of total vehicle output—and in 2025 such vehicles outsold <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Internal_combustion_engine\">internal-combustion</span> cars in China for the first time. China's factories turned out close to 70% of the world's electric vehicles, a dominance underpinned by the country's command of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lithium-ion_battery\">lithium-ion battery</span> manufacturing, led by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Contemporary_Amperex_Technology\">CATL</span>—which alone produces close to 40% of the world's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Electric_vehicle_battery\">electric-vehicle batteries</span>—and its low-cost <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lithium_iron_phosphate_battery\">lithium iron phosphate</span> chemistry. <br> <br> The industry is intensely competitive, led by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"BYD_Company\">BYD</span>, which sold roughly 4.6 million new-energy vehicles in 2025 and overtook <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tesla,_Inc.\">Tesla</span> as the world's largest seller of battery-electric cars while building its lead through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vertical_integration\">vertical integration</span> and in-house batteries, alongside <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"SAIC_Motor\">SAIC Motor</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Geely\">Geely</span>, smartphone maker <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiaomi\">Xiaomi</span>, and startups such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"XPeng\">XPeng</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Auto\">Li Auto</span>. Bolstered by this scale, China became the world's <b>largest <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Automotive_industry\">automobile</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Export\">exporter</span> in 2023</b>, and its electric-car exports reached roughly 1.28 million units in 2024—about 40% of the global total, after climbing to some $42 billion in value by 2023—as Chinese brands pushed into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Europe\">Europe</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Brazil\">Brazil</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mexico\">Mexico</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Southeast_Asia\">Southeast Asia</span>. This rapid expansion alarmed foreign rivals and triggered trade barriers, as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States\">United States</span> quadrupled its tariff on Chinese electric cars to 100% in May 2024, the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"European_Commission\">European Commission</span></b> imposed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Countervailing_duties\">countervailing duties</span> of up to about 35% in October 2024 after finding subsidies across the supply chain, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Canada\">Canada</span> matched the United States with a 100% levy. Western governments accused Beijing of fostering <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Overcapacity\">overcapacity</span> that flooded export markets, even as a brutal domestic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Price_war\">price war</span> battered profits and pushed regulators to curb cut-throat discounting, while they advanced rival subsidies of their own through measures like the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Inflation_Reduction_Act\">Inflation Reduction Act</span></b>. By 2025 China was producing more new-energy vehicles than the rest of the world combined and was on track to become the largest car market and exporter overall, cementing the sector as a centerpiece of the country's ambitions in advanced manufacturing and the global shift to clean energy.","citation":"","answerText":"Electric vehicle industry"},{"id":"cnp-010","num":"十","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Carried out across the countryside in the early <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>s and redistributing holdings from the landlord class to poorer peasants, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was directed by the new Communist Party authorities and caused the deaths of large numbers of people labelled class enemies.","answer":"Land Reform Movement","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1950–1953</span></div>","traditional":"土地改革運動","hanzi":"土地改革运动","pinyin":"Tǔdì Gǎigé Yùndòng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Tǔdì Gǎigé Yùndòng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Land Reform Movement</b> was the sweeping agrarian campaign through which the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> overturned the <b>existing system of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Land_tenure\">land tenure</span></b> across rural China during the first years of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic</span>. Although the party had experimented with confiscating and redistributing land in its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">civil war</span> base areas since the 1940s, drawing on a tradition of rural radicalism that <b>reached back to Mao's 1927 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Report_on_an_Investigation_of_the_Peasant_Movement_in_Hunan\"><i>Report on an Investigation of the Peasant Movement in Hunan</i></span></b>, the drive went nationwide only after the new regime, whose <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Common_Program\">Common Program</span> had endorsed the old nationalist ideal of \"land to the tiller\" once espoused by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Yat-sen\">Sun Yat-sen</span>, extended its authority over the countryside after 1949. The campaign's legal basis was the Agrarian Reform Law promulgated in June 1950 and introduced to the leadership by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Shaoqi\">Liu Shaoqi</span>, which sanctioned the uncompensated confiscation of land, draft animals, implements, and surplus grain held by the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Landlord\">landlord</span></b> class and rented out to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tenant_farmer\">tenant farmers</span>, all to be reallocated among the village poor. Work teams of party cadres sent into each village sorted rural households into rigid classes — landlords, rich <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peasant\">peasants</span>, middle peasants, poor peasants, and hired labourers — and these class labels, rooted in a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marxism\">Marxist</span> reading of rural society, came to determine each family's political fate for decades. Redistribution was carried out less by administrative fiat than by orchestrated mass mobilisation, as villagers were assembled into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Speaking_bitterness\">speak-bitterness</span> meetings and violent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Struggle_session\">struggle sessions</span> where accused landlords were publicly humiliated, beaten, and frequently sentenced to death by hastily convened people's tribunals, turning the reform into a deliberate exercise in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Class_conflict\">class struggle</span>. <br> <br> By the time it was <b>largely complete in 1953</b>, the campaign had transferred roughly 700 million <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mu_(unit)\">mu</span>, or about 47 million hectares (120 million acres), of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Arable_land\">arable land</span> — close to 43 percent of the national total — to an estimated 300 million land-poor and landless peasants, dramatically flattening the distribution of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Agriculture_in_China\">agricultural</span> wealth. The human toll was heavy, since the deaths of landlords and <b>others branded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Enemy_of_the_people\">class enemies</span></b> through execution, beating, or suicide are commonly estimated at between 1 and 2 million and by some accounts considerably more, a wave of killing closely entwined with the concurrent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Campaign_to_Suppress_Counterrevolutionaries\">Campaign to Suppress Counterrevolutionaries</span>. Coming alongside <b>the urban <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three-anti_and_five-anti_campaigns\">Three-anti and Five-anti Campaigns</span> of 1951–1952</b>, the rural purges meant that the early <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> period witnessed the systematic elimination of entire social strata that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maoism\">Maoist</span> ideology condemned as exploiters of the labouring masses. Beyond the redistribution of property, the movement broke the landed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Landed_gentry\">gentry</span> as a social and economic force, eroded the lineage and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Clan\">clan</span> networks that had organised village life for centuries, and implanted party authority at the grassroots, extending the reach of the central state into the village to a degree without precedent in Chinese history. Yet the individual peasant ownership the campaign conferred lasted only briefly, for within a few years the leadership herded the new smallholders first into mutual-aid teams and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Agricultural_cooperative\">agricultural cooperatives</span> and then into large <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Collective_farming\">collective farms</span>, a programme of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Soviet</span>-inspired collectivisation — distantly echoing the earlier liquidation of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kulak\">kulaks</span> — tied to the first <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five-year_plans_of_China\">Five-Year Plan</span> that would soon give rise to the calamitous <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_commune\">people's communes</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Leap_Forward\">Great Leap Forward</span></b>.","citation":"","answerText":"Land Reform Movement"},{"id":"cnp-011","num":"十一","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Sent across the Yalu River in October <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> to fight United Nations forces during the Korean War, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was commanded in the field by Peng Dehuai.","answer":"Chinese People's Volunteer Army","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1950</span></div>","traditional":"中國人民志願軍","hanzi":"中国人民志愿军","pinyin":"Zhōngguó Rénmín Zhìyuànjūn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōngguó Rénmín Zhìyuànjūn</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Chinese People's Volunteer Army</b> was the expeditionary force, drawn largely from regular <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army\">People's Liberation Army</span> units, that the newly founded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Republic_of_China\">People's Republic of China</span> committed to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Korean_War\">Korean War</span> under the deliberate fiction of \"volunteers\" so as to avoid a formal declaration of war against the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States\">United States</span>. After the <b>amphibious <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Inchon\">landing at Inchon</span> in September 1950</b> reversed a war that had begun with the North's invasion of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South_Korea\">South Korea</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_Nations_Command\">United Nations Command</span> forces under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Douglas_MacArthur\">Douglas MacArthur</span> drove north across the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"38th_parallel_north\">38th parallel</span></b> toward the Chinese frontier, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> resolved to intervene on behalf of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kim_Il_Sung\">Kim Il Sung</span>'s reeling <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"North_Korea\">North Korea</span>. Command of the force fell to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peng_Dehuai\">Peng Dehuai</span> after <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lin_Biao\">Lin Biao</span> reportedly declined on grounds of ill health, and beginning on the night of October 19, 1950, several hundred thousand troops slipped across the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yalu_River\">Yalu River</span> under cover of darkness. Composed of hardened veterans of the recently concluded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">Chinese Civil War</span>, the army opened its first offensive on October 25, 1950, catching United Nations forces by surprise, and weeks later shattered the American advance in the frigid <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Chosin_Reservoir\">Battle of the Chosin Reservoir</span></b>. Fighting alongside the battered <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Korean_People's_Army\">Korean People's Army</span>, successive offensives recaptured <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pyongyang\">Pyongyang</span> and <b>seized <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Seoul\">Seoul</span> in January 1951</b>, pushing the front roughly back to the prewar boundary before the advance stalled against superior firepower and overstretched supply lines. <br> <br> Lacking armor, artillery, and air power to match its adversaries, the force leaned on night marches, infiltration, and massed close-quarters assaults often labeled in the <b>West as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Human_wave_attack\">human wave attacks</span></b>, while the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Soviet Union</span>, with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joseph_Stalin\">Joseph Stalin</span>'s covert approval, supplied <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mikoyan-Gurevich_MiG-15\">MiG-15</span> jets and pilots who contested the skies over <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"MiG_Alley\">MiG Alley</span>. By the middle of 1951 the conflict had hardened into a grinding stalemate near the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_the_Imjin_River\">Imjin River</span> and a string of contested ridgelines, where attritional clashes such as the <b>1952 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battle_of_Triangle_Hill\">Battle of Triangle Hill</span></b> exacted heavy casualties for negligible territorial change. Estimates of Chinese losses diverge sharply, ranging from official figures of roughly 180,000 dead to Western tallies exceeding 400,000, among them <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Anying\">Mao Anying</span>, the eldest son of Mao Zedong, killed by a United States airstrike in November 1950. The fighting ended with the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Korean_Armistice_Agreement\">Korean Armistice Agreement</span></b> signed at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Panmunjom\">Panmunjom</span> on July 27, 1953—Peng putting his signature to the document on behalf of the Chinese—yet no peace treaty was ever concluded, leaving the peninsula divided to the present day. The last units withdrew from Korea by 1958, and the campaign—glorified in China as the \"War to Resist America and Aid Korea\"—is remembered there as a costly but defining proof that the young republic could stand toe to toe with the world's leading power at the height of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cold_War\">Cold War</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Chinese People's Volunteer Army"},{"id":"cnp-012","num":"十二","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Launched in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> against former Kuomintang officials, secret-society members and other alleged enemies of the new People's Republic, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> led to large numbers of executions in the early <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>s.","answer":"Campaign to Suppress Counterrevolutionaries","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1950–1951</span></div>","traditional":"鎮壓反革命運動","hanzi":"镇压反革命运动","pinyin":"Zhènyā fǎngémìng yùndòng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhènyā fǎngémìng yùndòng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Campaign to Suppress Counterrevolutionaries</b> was a nationwide political campaign waged by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> during the first years of the People's Republic to consolidate its rule and eliminate perceived enemies of the new <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maoism\">Maoist</span> state in its early phase of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Democracy\">New Democracy</span>. Initiated by a Communist Party directive <b>issued in October 1950</b> and given statutory form by the Regulations for the Punishment of Counter-Revolutionaries promulgated under <b>Premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span> in February 1951</b>, it unfolded against the backdrop of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Korean_War\">Korean War</span>—in which the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Volunteer_Army\">People's Volunteer Army</span> was then engaged—and the parallel <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Resist_America,_Aid_Korea_campaign\">Resist America, Aid Korea</span> mobilization, which together sharpened official fears of internal subversion. Its principal targets were former Nationalist officials and soldiers loyal to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span>, whose government had withdrawn to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span> after losing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">Chinese Civil War</span>, all of whom the new authorities branded as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Counter-revolutionary\">counter-revolutionaries</span>. The dragnet also swept up members of clandestine religious sects such as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yiguandao\">Yiguandao</span></b>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Triad_(organized_crime)\">triad</span> brotherhoods, bandits, and alleged <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Espionage\">spies</span>, with operations directed by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ministry_of_Public_Security_(China)\">Ministry of Public Security</span> under <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luo_Ruiqing\">Luo Ruiqing</span></b> and backed by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army\">People's Liberation Army</span>. Conducted as a classic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mass_line\">mass-line</span> mobilization, the campaign relied on public denunciation and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Struggle_session\">struggle sessions</span>, with mass sentencing rallies staged in cities such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span> to publicize verdicts and intimidate the wider population.<br> <br><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> personally pressed for execution quotas, proposing in early 1951 that roughly 1 in 1,000 of the population—some 0.1 percent—be put to death, a target that local cadres frequently exceeded. Sentences were <b>carried out through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capital_punishment_in_China\">public executions</span></b>, while many of those spared the death penalty were imprisoned or consigned to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Laogai\">laogai</span> system of reform-through-labour camps. Internal Communist Party statistics later cited by the senior official <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bo_Yibo\">Bo Yibo</span> recorded roughly 712,000 people executed, <b>whereas the historian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yang_Kuisong\">Yang Kuisong</span></b>, working from archival sources, has placed the death toll closer to 2 million. The campaign entrenched \"counter-revolutionary\" as a hereditary political stigma, foreshadowing the later system of \"<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five_black_categories\">five black categories</span>,\" and proceeded alongside the contemporaneous programmes of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Land_reform\">land reform</span> and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three-anti_and_Five-anti_Campaigns\">Three-anti and Five-anti Campaigns</span></b>. Together these movements translated the doctrine of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_democratic_dictatorship\">people's democratic dictatorship</span> into practice and set the template for the coercive mass campaigns that would recur in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anti-Rightist_Campaign\">Anti-Rightist Campaign</span> and, most destructively, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Campaign to Suppress Counterrevolutionaries"},{"id":"cnp-013","num":"十三","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Aimed in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>–<span class=\"blank\">_____</span> at corruption among officials and at alleged crimes by the bourgeoisie such as bribery and tax evasion, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> followed the consolidation of Communist Party rule.","answer":"Three-anti and Five-anti Campaigns","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">三反五反 ('three antis, five antis'), for the targets of the 1951–52 drives</span></div>","traditional":"三反五反運動","hanzi":"三反五反运动","pinyin":"Sānfǎn Wǔfǎn Yùndòng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Sānfǎn Wǔfǎn Yùndòng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Three-anti and Five-anti Campaigns</b> were two linked mass movements waged <b>by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> in 1951</b> and <b>1952</b> to discipline its own ranks and to bring the urban <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capitalism\">capitalist</span> class to heel during the consolidation of the new <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic</span>. Following hard upon the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Land_reform_movement\">Land Reform Movement</span> and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Campaign_to_Suppress_Counterrevolutionaries\">Campaign to Suppress Counterrevolutionaries</span></b>, the drives unfolded amid the fiscal strain and patriotic fervour of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Korean_War\">Korean War</span>, which lent urgency to demands for austerity, probity, and ideological conformity. The Three-anti Campaign, which grew out of an anti-waste drive in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northeast_China\">Northeast China</span> championed by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gao_Gang\">Gao Gang</span> and was launched nationwide late in 1951, <b>targeted <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Corruption\">corruption</span></b>, waste, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bureaucracy\">bureaucratism</span> among officials in the party, government, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army\">army</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_enterprise\">state enterprises</span>, employing confessions, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Self-criticism\">self-criticism</span>, and public \"tiger-hunting\" sessions to expose embezzlers great and small. Hundreds of thousands of cadres were investigated under the supervision of figures such as the finance minister <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bo_Yibo\">Bo Yibo</span>, and the campaign produced exemplary punishments, most famously the 1952 execution of two senior officials in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tianjin\">Tianjin</span> region, Liu Qingshan and Zhang Zishan, convicted of large-scale <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Embezzlement\">embezzlement</span>, a case publicised to signal the leadership's resolve. The Five-anti Campaign, opened early in 1952, was aimed instead at the private <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bourgeoisie\">bourgeoisie</span> and enumerated five economic crimes — <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bribery\">bribery</span>, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tax_evasion\">tax evasion</span></b>, theft of state property, cheating on government contracts through shoddy work and materials, and the stealing of state economic intelligence — that drew on a wider rhetoric of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Class_conflict\">class struggle</span>. <br> <br> Carried out through neighbourhood committees, mutual denunciation, and intimidating <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Struggle_session\">struggle sessions</span>, the Five-anti drive classified urban firms along a spectrum from fully law-abiding to wholly criminal, with the great majority found to have transgressed in some way and made to pay heavy fines and years of back taxes. The pressure proved unbearable for many of the accused, and a wave of suicides swept the commercial cities, with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span> in particular reporting numerous businessmen taking their own lives at the height of the terror, though the total death toll across both campaigns remains difficult to establish and is estimated only loosely. Economically the Five-anti shifted large sums into state coffers through fines and recovered taxes while leaving the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_bourgeoisie\">national bourgeoisie</span></b> demoralised, indebted, and dependent on the government, decisively tilting the balance between the public and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Private_sector\">private sectors</span> in the state's favour. By breaking the political and economic confidence of private business, the campaigns smoothed the way for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nationalization\">nationalisation</span> of industry and commerce that followed within a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Planned_economy\">planned economy</span> under the first <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five-year_plans_of_China\">Five-Year Plan</span>, even as the parallel Three-anti tightened <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>'s grip on a rapidly expanding party-state apparatus. More than a passing purge, the two campaigns refined a distinctively <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maoism\">Maoist</span> method of governance — mass mobilisation, quotas, public denunciation, and enforced confession descended from the wartime <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yan'an_Rectification_Movement\">Yan'an Rectification Movement</span></b> — that the regime would deploy repeatedly in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anti-Rightist_Campaign\">Anti-Rightist Campaign</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Leap_Forward\">Great Leap Forward</span>, and ultimately the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Three-anti and Five-anti Campaigns"},{"id":"cne-064","num":"六十四","category":"China · Economics","question":"Tasked above all with serving the countryside, farmers and rural credit cooperatives, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> carried heavy burdens of bad loans from state enterprises before a clean-up and a record <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> listing on the Shanghai and Hong Kong exchanges.","answer":"Agricultural Bank of China","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">founded 1951</span></div>","traditional":"中國農業銀行","hanzi":"中国农业银行","pinyin":"Zhōngguó Nóngyè Yínháng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōngguó Nóngyè Yínháng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Agricultural Bank of China</b> is one of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>'s \"Big Four\" state <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Commercial_bank\">commercial banks</span> and among the largest <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bank\">banks</span></b> in the world, charged above all with financing the rural economy. With roots reaching back to a rural cooperative bank <b>founded in 1951</b>, the institution was repeatedly merged into and split from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Bank_of_China\">People's Bank of China</span> before being definitively re-established in 1979 as a specialised lender at the start of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">reform and opening up</span>. Its core mission was to serve the \"<b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Rural_Issues\">three rural issues</span></b>\" of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Agriculture_in_China\">agriculture</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rural_area\">countryside</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Farmer\">farmers</span>, channelling credit to grain procurement, irrigation, and village enterprises, and for many years it also administered the sprawling network of rural credit <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cooperative_banking\">cooperatives</span></b> that reached the most remote villages until they were separated from it in the 1990s. It took its place alongside the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bank_of_China\">Bank of China</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Construction_Bank\">China Construction Bank</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Industrial_and_Commercial_Bank_of_China\">Industrial and Commercial Bank of China</span> as one of the four giant state banks that have long dominated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Banking_in_China\">Chinese banking</span>. Headquartered in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> and operating within the two-tier banking system overseen by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_bank\">central bank</span>, it remained a majority state institution serving both commercial and policy ends across a countryside that was home to the majority of the country's population for much of its history. <br> <br> Because its borrowers were concentrated in agriculture and weaker rural enterprises, the bank long carried the worst asset quality of the four, with a ratio of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Non-performing_loan\">non-performing loans</span>—many inherited from lending to ailing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_enterprises_of_China\">state-owned enterprises</span>—that at one point exceeded 20 percent. This left it the last of the Big Four to be overhauled, and only after a roughly $19 billion capital injection <b>from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Huijin_Investment\">Central Huijin Investment</span> in 2008</b> and a wholesale transfer of bad debt to asset-management vehicles was it cleaned up and reorganised into a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joint-stock_company\">joint-stock company</span> in 2009. In July 2010 it conducted a simultaneous dual <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Initial_public_offering\">listing</span> on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_Stock_Exchange\">Shanghai</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_Stock_Exchange\">Hong Kong</span> exchanges that raised about $22 billion, narrowly surpassing the earlier record set by its sister bank to become briefly the largest initial public offering in history and the final step in floating all four big state banks. That record was later eclipsed by the <b>flotations of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Alibaba_Group\">Alibaba</span> in 2014</b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Saudi_Aramco\">Saudi Aramco</span> in 2019, yet control of the bank stayed with the state through Central Huijin, a unit of the sovereign-wealth fund <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Investment_Corporation\">China Investment Corporation</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ministry_of_Finance_(China)\">Ministry of Finance</span>. With total <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Asset\">assets</span> exceeding $5 trillion, one of the world's largest customer bases of more than 800 million account-holders, and a workforce of around 450,000, it ranks among the very <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"List_of_largest_banks\">largest banks</span></b> on earth, is classed a globally <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Systemically_important_financial_institution\">systemically important</span> institution by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Financial_Stability_Board\">Financial Stability Board</span>, and remains—through its tens of trillions of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Renminbi\">renminbi</span> in assets—a pillar of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">Chinese economy</span> and its rural credit system.","citation":"","answerText":"Agricultural Bank of China"},{"id":"cne-085","num":"八十五","category":"China · Economics","question":"A Harvard-trained economist and trusted confidant of Xi Jinping, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> served as the country's chief negotiator in the trade talks with Washington and as the leading official steering macroeconomic and financial policy in the late <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>s.","answer":"Liu He","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">born 25 January 1952</span></div>","traditional":"劉鶴","hanzi":"刘鹤","pinyin":"Liú Hè","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Liú Hè</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Liu He</b> is a Chinese <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economist\">economist</span></b> and politician who became one of the country's most influential architects of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Macroeconomics\">macroeconomic</span> and financial policy during the second half of the 2010s, widely regarded as the chief economic strategist of the Xi Jinping era. Born in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>, he studied industrial economics at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Renmin_University_of_China\">Renmin University of China</span> before earning a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Master_of_Public_Administration\">Master of Public Administration</span> <b>from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Harvard_Kennedy_School\">Harvard Kennedy School</span> in 1995</b>, an education that lent him a fluency with Western economic thinking unusual among senior Chinese officials and a reputation as a market-minded reformer. Over subsequent decades he rose through the apparatus of economic planning, holding posts at the former State Planning Commission, the Development Research Center of the State Council, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Development_and_Reform_Commission\">National Development and Reform Commission</span>, before directing the powerful office of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Financial_and_Economic_Affairs_Commission\">Central Financial and Economic Affairs Commission</span>, the party's top body for steering the economy. <b>At the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"19th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">19th Party Congress</span> in 2017</b> he was elevated to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span>, a striking ascent for a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Technocracy\">technocrat</span> who had built his authority on expertise and proximity to the leadership rather than on any regional or factional power base. The following year he was appointed a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vice_Premier_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">Vice Premier</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_Council_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">State Council</span> under Premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Keqiang\">Li Keqiang</span>, ranking as the senior official responsible for the sprawling portfolios that governed industry, finance, technology, and foreign trade. <br> <br> His international prominence stemmed above all from his role as China's chief negotiator in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China–United_States_trade_war\">trade war</span> launched by President <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Donald_Trump\">Donald Trump</span>, in which he sparred across more than a dozen rounds of talks <b>between 2018</b> and 2020 with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Office_of_the_United_States_Trade_Representative\">United States Trade Representative</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Robert_Lighthizer\">Robert Lighthizer</span> and Treasury Secretary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Steven_Mnuchin\">Steven Mnuchin</span>. These exchanges culminated in his signing of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China–United_States_Phase_One_trade_deal\">Phase One agreement</span> at the White House on 15 January 2020, under which Beijing pledged to buy an additional US$200 billion of American goods over two years, though most existing tariffs stayed in place and the purchase targets went largely unmet amid the disruptions of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"COVID-19_pandemic\">COVID-19 pandemic</span> that erupted within weeks of the signing. At home he was the leading figure behind a sweeping campaign to curb <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Financial_regulation\">financial</span></b> risk, chairing the Financial Stability and Development Committee created in 2017 and pressing a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deleveraging\">deleveraging</span> drive aimed at reining in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shadow_banking_in_China\">shadow banking</span> and a total debt burden that had swelled to well over 250 percent of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gross_domestic_product\">gross domestic product</span>. Long regarded as a trusted confidant of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span> — whom he had known since their schooldays and who reportedly described him as \"very important to me\" — he was also a respected scholar whose 2012 study <i>Comparative Study of Two Global Crises</i>, juxtaposing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Depression\">Great Depression</span> with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2008_financial_crisis\">2008 financial crisis</span>, won the prestigious <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Yefang\">Sun Yefang</span></b> economics prize. He relinquished his Politburo seat at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"20th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">20th Party Congress</span> of 2022 and stepped down as vice premier in March 2023 as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_People's_Congress\">National People's Congress</span> seated a new cabinet under Premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Qiang\">Li Qiang</span>, though he had already made a notable valedictory appearance at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Economic_Forum\">World Economic Forum</span></b> in Davos that January, where he sought to reassure global investors that China remained open for business.","citation":"","answerText":"Liu He"},{"id":"cnp-014","num":"十四","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Modelled on Soviet practice and running from <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> to <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> with an emphasis on heavy industry, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> inaugurated the system of multi-year plans that guided China's command economy.","answer":"First Five-Year Plan","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1953–1957</span></div>","traditional":"第一個五年計劃","hanzi":"第一个五年计划","pinyin":"Dì-yī gè Wǔnián Jìhuà","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Dì-yī gè Wǔnián Jìhuà</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>First Five-Year Plan</b> was the inaugural medium-term economic program of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Republic_of_China\">People's Republic of China</span>, <b>covering 1953</b> to <b>1957</b> and launching the system of centralized <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Planned_economy\">command-economy</span> planning that would structure Chinese development for decades under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span>. Closely modeled on the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five-year_plans_of_the_Soviet_Union\">Soviet five-year plans</span></b> pioneered under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joseph_Stalin\">Joseph Stalin</span> and administered through planning methods akin to those of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gosplan\">Gosplan</span>, the program depended heavily on financial credits, blueprints, and thousands of technical advisers supplied by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Soviet Union</span>. Its central priority was the rapid <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Industrialisation\">industrialization</span> of a largely agrarian</b> country through concentrated investment in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heavy_industry\">heavy industry</span>—steel, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Coal\">coal</span>, electricity, and machinery—at the deliberate expense of consumer goods and agriculture. Drafting and supervision were entrusted to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Development_and_Reform_Commission\">State Planning Commission</span> and economic managers such as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Fuchun\">Li Fuchun</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Yun\">Chen Yun</span>, working under Premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span> and the broader strategic direction of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>. Much of the new capacity was sited in the resource-rich <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northeast_China\">Northeast</span>, the country's established industrial heartland, where the bulk of a celebrated package of major Soviet-aided plants—popularly remembered as the \"156 Projects\"—was concentrated. <br> <br> The plan delivered tangible results, raising annual <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Steel\">steel</span> output from roughly <b>1.3 million tons in 1952</b> to about 5.3 million tons by 1957 and expanding the great <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ansteel_Group\">Anshan Iron and Steel Works</span> while founding new complexes such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuhan_Iron_and_Steel_Corporation\">Wuhan Iron and Steel</span> company. Flagship achievements included the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"FAW_Group\">First Automobile Works</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Changchun\">Changchun</span>, which produced the country's first domestically built trucks in 1956, a pioneering tractor plant at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luoyang\">Luoyang</span>, new <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Machine_tool\">machine-tool</span> and aircraft industries, and the completion in 1957 of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuhan_Yangtze_River_Bridge\">Wuhan Yangtze River Bridge</span></b>. Running in parallel was a sweeping socialist transformation of ownership, as private farms were absorbed into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Collective_farming\">agricultural collectives</span> and private firms were folded into joint state-private enterprises through near-total <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nationalization\">nationalization</span> by 1956. Generally judged the most successful of China's plans, it lifted industrial production at double-digit annual rates and laid the foundations of the modern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">Chinese economy</span>, even as the lopsided emphasis on heavy industry left agriculture and living standards lagging. Its apparent triumph emboldened Mao to abandon cautious planning for the radical mass mobilization of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Leap_Forward\">Great Leap Forward</span> and its rural <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_commune\">people's communes</span> from 1958, while the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-Soviet_split\">Sino-Soviet split</span> under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nikita_Khrushchev\">Nikita Khrushchev</span> soon stripped away the Soviet support on which the first plan had so heavily relied.","citation":"","answerText":"First Five-Year Plan"},{"id":"cnp-086","num":"八十六","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Becoming general secretary in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> and soon recognised as the most powerful leader since Mao Zedong, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> launched a sweeping drive against corruption, and engineered the removal of presidential term limits.","answer":"Xi Jinping","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">born 15 June 1953</span></div>","traditional":"習近平","hanzi":"习近平","pinyin":"Xí Jìnpíng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Xí Jìnpíng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Xi Jinping</b> is a Chinese politician who has served as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"General_Secretary_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">General Secretary</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paramount_leader\">paramount leader</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span> <b>since 2012</b>, widely regarded as the most powerful Chinese ruler since <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>. Born in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> as the son of the veteran revolutionary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Zhongxun\">Xi Zhongxun</span>, a former vice premier, he belonged to the so-called <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Crown_Prince_Party\">princeling</span> class of children of senior party officials, though his privileged upbringing was abruptly upended when his father was purged in the early 1960s. During the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span> he was sent down to the countryside under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Down_to_the_Countryside_Movement\">Down to the Countryside Movement</span>, spending roughly 7 years <b>from 1969</b> in a poor village in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shaanxi\">Shaanxi</span> province where he laboured in a production brigade before gaining admission to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tsinghua_University\">Tsinghua University</span> to study chemical engineering. After joining the party in 1974, he advanced through a methodical provincial career spanning more than 3 decades, holding senior posts in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fujian\">Fujian</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhejiang\">Zhejiang</span> before a brief tenure as party <b>chief of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span> in 2007</b> propelled him onto the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_Standing_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo Standing Committee</span>. Designated the presumptive successor to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Jintao\">Hu Jintao</span>, he became <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vice_President_of_China\">Vice President</span> in 2008 and then assumed the party's top office at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"18th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">18th National Congress</span> in November 2012, concurrently taking the chairmanship of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Military_Commission_(China)\">Central Military Commission</span> in a notably swift and complete transfer of military authority. <br> <br> He was formally installed as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"President_of_China\">President</span></b> of China in March 2013 and moved rapidly to centralise decision-making in his own hands, chairing a proliferating array of leading small groups and being elevated to the status of \"core\" leader by the party in 2016. His signature <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anti-corruption_campaign_under_Xi_Jinping\">anti-corruption campaign</span>, prosecuted through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Commission_for_Discipline_Inspection\">Central Commission for Discipline Inspection</span> under his ally <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Qishan\">Wang Qishan</span>, disciplined more than 1.5 million officials in its first 5 years and felled high-ranking \"tigers\" including the former security chief <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Yongkang\">Zhou Yongkang</span></b> and the populist rival <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bo_Xilai\">Bo Xilai</span>. In March 2018 the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_People's_Congress\">National People's Congress</span> amended the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitution_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">state constitution</span> to abolish presidential term limits by a vote of 2,958 to 2, a change widely interpreted as clearing the path for him to rule indefinitely. His guiding ideology, codified as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping_Thought\">Xi Jinping Thought</span> and inscribed in the party charter at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"19th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">19th National Congress</span> in 2017, has underpinned signature initiatives such as the globe-spanning <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Belt_and_Road_Initiative\">Belt and Road Initiative</span>, the nationalist rhetoric of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Dream\">Chinese Dream</span></b>, and the redistributive agenda of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Common_prosperity\">common prosperity</span>. Breaking with the post-Deng convention of orderly succession, he secured an unprecedented 3rd term as party leader at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"20th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">20th National Congress</span> in October 2022, capping a decade marked by stringent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zero-COVID\">zero-COVID</span> controls, the imposition of a sweeping <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2020_Hong_Kong_national_security_law\">national security law</span> on Hong Kong, and the publication of his collected speeches in the multi-volume <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Governance_of_China\"><i>The Governance of China</i></span></b>.","citation":"","answerText":"Xi Jinping"},{"id":"cnp-016","num":"十六","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Adopted by the National People's Congress and replacing the earlier Common Program, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> established the formal governmental structure of the state, with Mao Zedong as head of state.","answer":"1954 Constitution","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">20 September 1954</span></div>","traditional":"五四憲法","hanzi":"五四宪法","pinyin":"Wǔsì Xiànfǎ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Wǔsì Xiànfǎ</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>1954 Constitution</b> was the first formal constitution of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span>, <b>adopted on 20 September 1954</b> by the inaugural session of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_People's_Congress\">National People's Congress</span></b> and superseding the provisional <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Common_Program\">Common Program</span> that had governed the state since 1949. Its drafting had been overseen by a committee chaired by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>, who worked on successive <b>drafts at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hangzhou\">Hangzhou</span> in 1953</b> and 1954, and the resulting text borrowed heavily from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1936_Soviet_Constitution\">1936 Soviet Constitution</span> promulgated under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joseph_Stalin\">Joseph Stalin</span>. Approved by the roughly 1,226 deputies of the First National People's Congress, the document comprised 106 articles in 4 chapters and designated the Congress, chosen through tiered <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Elections_in_China\">elections</span>, as the highest organ of state power, operating between its sessions through a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Standing_Committee_of_the_National_People's_Congress\">Standing Committee</span>. At the apex of the state it created the office of Chairman, or <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"President_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">head of state</span></b>, to which Mao Zedong was duly elected with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_De\">Zhu De</span> as his deputy, a presidency endowed with the power to command the armed forces and to represent the republic at home and abroad. Executive authority was vested in a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_Council_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">State Council</span>, the central government headed by a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Premier_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">Premier</span> — an office first held by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span> — while judicial functions were entrusted to the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Supreme_People's_Court\">Supreme People's Court</span></b> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Supreme_People's_Procuratorate\">Supreme People's Procuratorate</span>. <br> <br> Ideologically the constitution defined the country as a people's democratic state led by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Working_class\">working class</span> and resting on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Worker-peasant_alliance\">alliance of workers and peasants</span>, and it formally proclaimed the nation to be in a period of transition from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Democracy\">New Democracy</span> toward the construction of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialism\">socialism</span>. It recognised several coexisting forms of ownership of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Means_of_production\">means of production</span> while privileging the <b>growth of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_ownership\">state ownership</span></b>, organised the state on the principle of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Democratic_centralism\">democratic centralism</span>, and described the republic as a unified multi-national state in which compactly settled minorities could enjoy <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Autonomous_regions_of_China\">regional autonomy</span>. A lengthy chapter enumerated the fundamental rights and duties of citizens — equality before the law, the vote, and freedoms of speech, assembly, and religious belief among them — though in practice these <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Human_rights_in_China\">guarantees</span> carried little weight against the overriding authority of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span>. Indeed the constitution proved more aspirational than binding, for within a few years its provisions were effectively eclipsed by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anti-Rightist_Campaign\">Anti-Rightist Campaign</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Leap_Forward\">Great Leap Forward</span>, and above all the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span>, during which legal institutions collapsed and the head of state <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Shaoqi\">Liu Shaoqi</span> was himself persecuted to death. Never formally repealed but long disregarded, it was eventually <b>replaced by the radical <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1975_Constitution_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">1975 Constitution</span></b> of the Cultural Revolution era and, after a further revision, by the current <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitution_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">constitution</span> of 1982, yet it remains historically significant as the founding charter that first gave the People's Republic a settled governmental form.","citation":"","answerText":"1954 Constitution"},{"id":"cnp-017","num":"十七","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Described in the constitution as the highest organ of state power and meeting in full session each spring in the Great Hall of the People, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> formally elects the State Council.","answer":"National People's Congress","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">from 1954</span></div>","traditional":"全國人民代表大會","hanzi":"全国人民代表大会","pinyin":"Quánguó Rénmín Dàibiǎo Dàhuì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Quánguó Rénmín Dàibiǎo Dàhuì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>National People's Congress</b> is the national <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Legislature\">legislature</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Republic_of_China\">People's Republic of China</span></b>, designated by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitution_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">constitution</span> as the highest organ of state power. First <b>convened in September 1954</b>, when it adopted the country's first constitution, it is a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Unicameralism\">unicameral</span> assembly whose nearly 3,000 deputies—a figure capped by law at 3,000—make it the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"List_of_legislatures_by_number_of_members\">largest parliament in the world</span></b>. Its deputies serve five-year terms and are chosen not by direct popular vote but through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Indirect_election\">indirect election</span> by the people's congresses of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Provinces_of_China\">provinces</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Autonomous_regions_of_China\">autonomous regions</span>, and municipalities, together with delegations from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Macau\">Macau</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army\">People's Liberation Army</span>. The full congress meets in plenary session for only about a week or two each spring in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Hall_of_the_People\">Great Hall of the People</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>, gathering alongside the advisory <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_People's_Political_Consultative_Conference\">Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference</span></b> in the yearly spectacle known as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Two_Sessions\">Two Sessions</span>. On paper its powers are sweeping, encompassing amendment of the constitution, enactment of basic national legislation, approval of the state budget and the country's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five-year_plans_of_China\">Five-Year Plans</span>, and the election or confirmation of the highest officeholders in the land. <br> <br> Because the plenary gathers so briefly, day-to-day legislative authority rests with its 175-member <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Standing_Committee_of_the_National_People's_Congress\">Standing Committee</span>, a permanent body first chaired in 1954 by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Shaoqi\">Liu Shaoqi</span> and led <b>since 2023</b> by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhao_Leji\">Zhao Leji</span>, the third-ranking member of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_Standing_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo Standing Committee</span>. Among the officials it formally selects are the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"President_of_China\">President</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Premier_of_China\">Premier</span> who heads the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_Council_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">State Council</span>, the chairman of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Military_Commission_(China)\">Central Military Commission</span>, and the heads of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Supreme_People's_Court\">Supreme People's Court</span></b> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Supervisory_Commission\">National Supervisory Commission</span>. In practice, however, the congress is widely characterized as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rubber_stamp_(politics)\">rubber stamp</span>, ratifying by near-unanimous margins decisions already taken by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> within what remains a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"One-party_state\">one-party state</span>. Its most consequential <b>modern act came in 2018</b>, when it amended the constitution to abolish presidential term limits—clearing the way for the indefinite rule of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span>—and to write his guiding ideology, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping_Thought\">Xi Jinping Thought</span>, into the nation's basic law. Now sitting as the 14th National People's Congress elected in 2023, it has continued to give legal form to the leadership's agenda, its spring 2026 session adopting the 15th Five-Year Plan for 2026 to 2030 along with a wave of new statutes.","citation":"","answerText":"National People's Congress"},{"id":"cnp-018","num":"十八","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Headed by the Premier and overseeing the ministries and commissions of the central government, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is the state's cabinet, formally answerable to the National People's Congress.","answer":"State Council","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1954</span></div>","traditional":"國務院","hanzi":"国务院","pinyin":"Guówùyuàn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Guówùyuàn</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>State Council</b>, formally the Central People's Government, is the chief administrative authority of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span> and serves as the country's cabinet. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitution_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">constitution</span> defines it as the executive organ of the highest organ of state power and the highest organ of state administration, rendering it formally accountable to the National People's Congress and, while that assembly is in recess, to its <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Standing_Committee_of_the_National_People's_Congress\">Standing Committee</span></b>. Headed by the Premier, it comprises several <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vice_Premier_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">vice-premiers</span>, a number of state councillors, the ministers who lead its component ministries and commissions, and a secretary-general who manages its routine business. It directs more than 20 ministries and commissions—among them the ministries of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ministry_of_Foreign_Affairs_(China)\">Foreign Affairs</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ministry_of_Finance_(China)\">Finance</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ministry_of_Public_Security_(China)\">Public Security</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Development_and_Reform_Commission\">National Development and Reform Commission</span>, and the central bank, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Bank_of_China\">People's Bank of China</span>. Beyond day-to-day administration, it drafts the national budget and <b>the country's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five-year_plans_of_China\">Five-Year Plans</span></b>, issues binding administrative regulations, and supervises the provincial and local governments of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Unitary_state\">unitary state</span>.<br> <br>The body was <b>established in 1954</b> under the country's first constitution, succeeding the Government Administration Council that had directed the central government <b>from 1949</b> under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Common_Program\">Common Program</span>. Its inaugural premier was <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span>, who had also chaired the predecessor council and held the post until his death in 1976, having steered the government through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Leap_Forward\">Great Leap Forward</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span> before the office passed to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hua_Guofeng\">Hua Guofeng</span>. Under the reforms launched by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>, the premiership passed in turn to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhao_Ziyang\">Zhao Ziyang</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Peng\">Li Peng</span>—who as premier proclaimed the martial law that preceded the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1989_Tiananmen_Square_protests_and_massacre\"><b>1989</b> Tiananmen Square crackdown</span>—and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_Rongji\">Zhu Rongji</span>. Zhu and his successor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wen_Jiabao\">Wen Jiabao</span> presided over far-reaching <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">economic reform</span>, including the restructuring of loss-making <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_enterprise\">state-owned enterprises</span> and China's 2001 accession to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Trade_Organization\">World Trade Organization</span>, before <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Keqiang\">Li Keqiang</span> took the office in 2013. Although constitutionally answerable to the legislature, the body operates under the direction of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span>, with its premier ranking inside the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_Standing_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo Standing Committee</span> beneath the party's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"General_Secretary_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">general secretary</span>, so that the <b>doctrine of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Democratic_centralism\">democratic centralism</span></b> keeps the cabinet subordinate to the party leadership in the era of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialism_with_Chinese_characteristics\">socialism with Chinese characteristics</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"State Council"},{"id":"cne-007","num":"七","category":"China · Economics","question":"Originally set up in the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>s to finance state building projects under the planned economy, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> now serves mortgages and infrastructure, took a strategic investment from Bank of America, and listed in Hong Kong in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>.","answer":"China Construction Bank","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">founded 1954</span></div>","traditional":"中國建設銀行","hanzi":"中国建设银行","pinyin":"Zhōngguó Jiànshè Yínháng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōngguó Jiànshè Yínháng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>China Construction Bank</b> is one of the \"Big Four\" <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_enterprise\">state-owned</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Commercial_bank\">commercial banks</span> of China, ranking alongside the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Industrial_and_Commercial_Bank_of_China\">Industrial and Commercial Bank of China</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Agricultural_Bank_of_China\">Agricultural Bank of China</span>, and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bank_of_China\">Bank of China</span></b>. <b>Established in 1954</b> as the People's Construction Bank of China, it was originally not a bank in the Western sense but a fiscal agent of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ministry_of_Finance_(China)\">Ministry of Finance</span>, disbursing state budget appropriations for capital <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Public_works\">construction projects</span> under the planned economy. As the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">economic reforms</span> unfolded it shed this role, separating from the budget in the 1980s, becoming a <b>full commercial <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bank\">lender</span> in 1994</b>, and adopting its present name in 1996. Today it operates as a universal bank, prominent in residential <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mortgage_loan\">mortgage</span> lending and the financing of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Infrastructure\">infrastructure</span>—a legacy of its construction origins—while also serving corporate clients and a vast <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Retail_banking\">retail</span> base across the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">Chinese economy</span>. Headquartered in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>, it serves hundreds of millions of customers and stands as one of the principal lenders behind the surging <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Real_estate_in_China\">real-estate market</span></b> that has underpinned much of the country's recent growth.<br> <br>As part of a sweeping clean-up of China's debt-laden banks, it was purged of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Non-performing_loan\">non-performing loans</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Recapitalization\">recapitalized</span> with an injection from the country's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foreign-exchange_reserves_of_China\">foreign-exchange reserves</span>, and reorganized <b>into a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joint-stock_company\">joint-stock company</span> in 2004</b>. Its controlling shareholder became <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Huijin_Investment\">Central Huijin Investment</span>, the domestic arm of the sovereign-wealth fund <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Investment_Corporation\">China Investment Corporation</span>, through which the state retained firm control. In 2005 it attracted a strategic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foreign_direct_investment\">foreign investment</span> from Bank of America and the Singapore state fund <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Temasek_Holdings\">Temasek Holdings</span></b>, and in October that year it became the first of the Big Four to go public, raising roughly $8 billion through an <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Initial_public_offering\">initial public offering</span> on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_Stock_Exchange\">Hong Kong Stock Exchange</span> that ranked as the world's largest in years. It added a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_Stock_Exchange\">Shanghai</span> share listing in 2007, and under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_Council_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">State Council</span> the bank is supervised by the central bank, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Bank_of_China\">People's Bank of China</span>, together with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Financial_Regulatory_Administration\">National Financial Regulatory Administration</span>. With a balance sheet that places it among the largest banks in the world by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Market_capitalization\">market capitalization</span> and assets, it ranks near the top of global league tables such as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Forbes_Global_2000\">Forbes Global 2000</span></b>, a pillar of the state-controlled financial system of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"China Construction Bank"},{"id":"cnp-020","num":"二十","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Encouraging citizens in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> to voice criticism under a slogan inviting many schools of thought to contend, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> preceded a sharp Party crackdown on outspoken intellectuals directed by Mao Zedong.","answer":"Hundred Flowers Campaign","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1956–1957</span></div>","traditional":"百花運動","hanzi":"百花运动","pinyin":"Bǎihuā Yùndòng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Bǎihuā Yùndòng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Hundred Flowers Campaign</b> was a brief period of relative intellectual openness in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Republic_of_China\">People's Republic of China</span></b> <b>during 1956</b> and <b>1957</b> when, in the wake of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five-year_plans_of_China\">First Five-Year Plan</span> and the socialist transformation of the economy, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> invited citizens to voice open criticism of its conduct. Its name derived from the slogan \"let a hundred flowers bloom, let a hundred schools of thought contend,\" an evocation of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hundred_Schools_of_Thought\">Hundred Schools of Thought</span> that had flourished during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warring_States_period\">Warring States period</span> more than 2,000 years earlier. The initiative unfolded against the backdrop of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"De-Stalinization\">de-Stalinization</span> following <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nikita_Khrushchev\">Nikita Khrushchev</span>'s 1956 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"On_the_Cult_of_Personality_and_Its_Consequences\">secret speech</span> and the upheavals of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hungarian_Revolution_of_1956\">Hungarian Revolution</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Polish_October\">Polish October</span>, which convinced <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> that suppressed grievances might prove more dangerous than open debate. Encouraged by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span>'s call to value the nation's experts and by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lu_Dingyi\">Lu Dingyi</span>, head of the Party's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Publicity_Department_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">propaganda department</span>, intellectuals responded warily at first, mindful of recent persecutions such as the <b>1955 campaign</b> against the writer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Feng\">Hu Feng</span>, condemned as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Counter-revolutionary\">counter-revolutionary</span>. After Mao amplified the appeal in his February 1957 address <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"On_the_Correct_Handling_of_Contradictions_Among_the_People\"><i>On the Correct Handling of Contradictions Among the People</i></span>, a torrent of criticism erupted that spring, with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Big-character_poster\">big-character posters</span> at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peking_University\">Peking University</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> assailing bureaucratic privilege, official corruption, and the absence of democratic checks. <br> <br> The opening proved short-lived, for, alarmed by the ferocity of the attacks, Mao reversed course in June 1957 and unleashed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anti-Rightist_Campaign\">Anti-Rightist Campaign</span>, a purge directed in large part by the Party's general secretary, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>. Critics who had spoken out were branded \"rightists,\" and by official counts later acknowledged during their rehabilitation, roughly 550,000 people were so labeled, many stripped of their posts and dispatched to rural exile, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Laogai\">labor camps</span>, or <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Re-education_through_labor\">re-education through labor</span></b>. Historians continue to debate whether the episode was a genuine experiment in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liberalization\">liberalization</span> that Mao abandoned once it spun out of control, or a calculated ploy—later described by Mao himself as \"enticing the snakes out of their lairs\"—to expose and eliminate <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dissent\">dissent</span>. Continuing a pattern set by the earlier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yan'an_Rectification_Movement\">Yan'an Rectification Movement</span>, the crackdown silenced independent criticism for a generation and helped clear the political ground for the radical <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Leap_Forward\">Great Leap Forward</span> launched in 1958. Most of those condemned were not rehabilitated until the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boluan_Fanzheng\">reversal of verdicts</span> carried out under Deng after 1978, by which point many had also been persecuted afresh in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span>, leaving a deep and lasting wariness of political candor among China's <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Intellectual\">intellectuals</span></b>.","citation":"","answerText":"Hundred Flowers Campaign"},{"id":"cnp-021","num":"二十一","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Held in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> and notably declaring that large-scale class struggle had largely ended, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> briefly removed Mao Zedong Thought from the Party charter before the radicalism of the Great Leap Forward.","answer":"8th National Congress of the CCP","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1956</span></div>","traditional":"中國共產黨第八次全國代表大會","hanzi":"中国共产党第八次全国代表大会","pinyin":"Zhōngguó Gòngchǎndǎng dì-bā cì quánguó dàibiǎo dàhuì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōngguó Gòngchǎndǎng dì-bā cì quánguó dàibiǎo dàhuì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>8th National Congress of the CCP</b> was the first national congress the Chinese communist movement had convened <b>since its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"7th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">7th National Congress</span></b> of 1945, and the first held after the establishment of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span> in 1949, meeting in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> from 15 to 27 September 1956. It was attended by 1,026 voting delegates and 107 alternate delegates representing a party membership that had swelled to roughly 10.73 million, and it gathered amid the recently completed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Collective_farming\">collectivization</span> of agriculture and the broader transition to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialism\">socialism</span> that accompanied the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five-Year_plans_of_China\">First Five-Year Plan</span></b>. Convening only months after <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nikita_Khrushchev\">Nikita Khrushchev</span> had delivered his <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"On_the_Cult_of_Personality_and_Its_Consequences\">secret speech</span> denouncing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joseph_Stalin\">Joseph Stalin</span> at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"20th_Congress_of_the_Communist_Party_of_the_Soviet_Union\">20th Congress</span> of <b>the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Communist_Party_of_the_Soviet_Union\">Communist Party of the Soviet Union</span> in February 1956</b>, the gathering was deeply marked by the climate of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"De-Stalinization\">de-Stalinization</span> then sweeping the socialist world. In that spirit the delegates approved a revised party <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitution_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">constitution</span> that quietly deleted the reference to Mao Zedong Thought as a guiding ideology, explicitly warned against the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cult_of_personality\">cult of the individual</span>, and elevated the <b>principle of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Collective_leadership\">collective leadership</span></b>. Its most consequential resolution, advanced in the political report of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Shaoqi\">Liu Shaoqi</span>, declared that the large-scale <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Class_conflict\">class struggle</span> between the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Proletariat\">proletariat</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bourgeoisie\">bourgeoisie</span> had been essentially settled, so that the principal contradiction now lay <b>between an advanced <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialist_mode_of_production\">socialist system</span></b> and the country's still-backward <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Productive_forces\">productive forces</span>.<br> <br>Acting on that judgment, the congress redefined the party's central task as economic construction, elected a new <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Central Committee</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo</span> that kept <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> as chairman, and—on a report delivered by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>—made him <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"General_Secretary_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">General Secretary</span> of a strengthened secretariat, while <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span> reported on the forthcoming Second Five-Year Plan. The conciliatory line of the congress briefly animated policy <b>through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hundred_Flowers_Campaign\">Hundred Flowers Campaign</span> of 1956–1957</b>, which invited open criticism of the party. That opening was sharply reversed by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anti-Rightist_Campaign\">Anti-Rightist Campaign</span> of 1957, during which more than half a million people were branded \"rightists,\" as Mao grew convinced that acute class struggle had not in fact disappeared. At the congress's <b>second session in May 1958</b> the moderate verdict of 1956 was formally repudiated, and Mao launched the Great Leap Forward, whose hastily organized <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_commune\">people's communes</span> and inflated output targets helped bring on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Chinese_Famine\">Great Chinese Famine</span>, which killed tens of millions. Only after Mao's death and the repudiation of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span> was the congress retrospectively praised, its founding documents commending the sober pursuit of development and the grounding of party legitimacy in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marxism–Leninism\">Marxism–Leninism</span> rather than the infallibility of a single leader, even though its moderate program had been overturned within two years of its close.","citation":"","answerText":"8th National Congress of the CCP"},{"id":"cnp-035","num":"三十五","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Criticised within classical Marxist thought yet vividly displayed in the Mao Zedong worship of the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>s and earlier in Stalin's Soviet Union, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> arises when a leader uses propaganda to build an idealised, heroic public image.","answer":"Cult of personality","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Coined</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Phrase popularized by Khrushchev's 'Secret Speech', 1956</span></div>","traditional":"個人崇拜","hanzi":"个人崇拜","pinyin":"gèrén chóngbài","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">gèrén chóngbài</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>cult of personality</b> is a political phenomenon in which a regime uses <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Propaganda\">propaganda</span>, <b>tightly controlled <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mass_media\">mass media</span></b>, public spectacle, and state-sponsored art and iconography to construct an idealized, heroic, and often quasi-divine public image of a single leader. The idea is bound up with the related notion of the \"cult of the individual,\" a phrase <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Karl_Marx\">Karl Marx</span> used with evident distaste in an <b>1877 letter</b>, insisting that he and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Friedrich_Engels\">Friedrich Engels</span> had entered the workers' movement out of conviction and cared nothing for popularity or personal adulation. Within classical <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marxism\">Marxist</span> theory the glorification of an individual fits awkwardly with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Historical_materialism\">historical materialism</span>, which locates the driving force of history in class struggle and collective social forces rather than in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_man_theory\">great-man theory</span> of decisive heroic leaders</b>. The term gained wide international currency after <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nikita_Khrushchev\">Nikita Khrushchev</span> delivered his so-called <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"On_the_Cult_of_Personality_and_Its_Consequences\">Secret Speech</span> to a closed session of <b>the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"20th_Congress_of_the_Communist_Party_of_the_Soviet_Union\">Communist Party congress</span> in February 1956</b>, a sweeping denunciation lasting some 4 hours that opened a broad campaign of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"De-Stalinization\">de-Stalinization</span>. Political scientists often analyze such cults through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Max_Weber\">Max Weber</span>'s concept of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Charismatic_authority\">charismatic authority</span>, and the phenomenon is most strongly associated with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Totalitarianism\">totalitarian</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Authoritarianism\">authoritarian</span> regimes that monopolize information and suppress rival sources of legitimacy. <br> <br> The archetypal modern case is the cult that surrounded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joseph_Stalin\">Joseph Stalin</span> in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Soviet Union</span>, where <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stalinism\">Stalinism</span> saturated public life with omnipresent portraits, monumental statues, and adulatory verse and renamed numerous cities and landmarks in his honor. A comparable reverence had earlier been fostered around <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vladimir_Lenin\">Vladimir Lenin</span>, whose embalmed body was placed on permanent public display in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lenin's_Mausoleum\">Lenin's Mausoleum</span>, while in China the veneration of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> reached its height <b>during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span> of 1966–1976</b>, when his <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Quotations_from_Chairman_Mao_Tse-tung\"><i>Quotations from Chairman Mao Tse-tung</i></span> was printed in over 1 billion copies and became one of the most widely distributed books in history. Fascist movements developed their own variants, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Führerprinzip\">Führer principle</span> exalting <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Adolf_Hitler\">Adolf Hitler</span></b> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nazi_Germany\">Nazi Germany</span> and the honorific \"Il Duce\" glorifying <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Benito_Mussolini\">Benito Mussolini</span> under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Italian_Fascism\">Italian Fascism</span>. The most elaborate and durable example is that of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kim_dynasty_(North_Korea)\">ruling Kim family</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"North_Korea\">North Korea</span>, where the cults of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kim_Il-sung\">Kim Il-sung</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kim_Jong-il\">Kim Jong-il</span> are fused with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Juche\">Juche</span> ideology and even with the national calendar, whose year 1 corresponds to Kim Il-sung's birth in 1912. Further instances include the extravagant self-glorification of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Saparmurat_Niyazov\">Saparmurat Niyazov</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Turkmenistan\">Turkmenistan</span>, who renamed the months of the year and made his quasi-spiritual text the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ruhnama\"><i>Ruhnama</i></span> compulsory study, and the grandiose cult of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nicolae_Ceaușescu\">Nicolae Ceaușescu</span> in communist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialist_Republic_of_Romania\">Romania</span>, demonstrating how the deliberate manufacture of a heroic public image recurred across ideologically diverse regimes throughout the 20th century.","citation":"","answerText":"Cult of personality"},{"id":"cnp-022","num":"二十二","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Following the criticisms aired during the liberalisation of <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>–<span class=\"blank\">_____</span>, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> organised in part by Deng Xiaoping persecuted hundreds of thousands of alleged \"rightists\" among intellectuals and the minor democratic parties.","answer":"Anti-Rightist Campaign","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1957</span></div>","traditional":"反右派運動","hanzi":"反右派运动","pinyin":"Fǎn Yòupài Yùndòng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Fǎn Yòupài Yùndòng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Anti-Rightist Campaign</b> was a sweeping political purge <b>launched in mid-1957</b> by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> against citizens, and especially <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Intellectual\">intellectuals</span></b> and members of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"List_of_political_parties_in_China\">minor democratic parties</span>, who had aired criticism of the regime during the preceding <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hundred_Flowers_Campaign\">Hundred Flowers Campaign</span> in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span>. The campaign grew directly out of <b>the brief liberalisation of 1956–1957</b>, when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>, invoking the classical slogan to let a hundred flowers bloom and a hundred schools of thought contend, encouraged open commentary on party governance amid the unsettling repercussions of Soviet <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"De-Stalinization\">de-Stalinization</span> that followed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nikita_Khrushchev\">Nikita Khrushchev</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"On_the_Cult_of_Personality_and_Its_Consequences\">secret speech</span>, alongside the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Polish_October\">Polish October</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hungarian_Revolution_of_1956\">Hungarian Revolution of <b>1956</b></span>. As the invited criticism swelled into pointed attacks—students erecting <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Big-character_poster\">big-character posters</span> and outspoken voices such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lin_Xiling\">Lin Xiling</span> drawing crowds at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peking_University\">Peking University</span> while others demanded genuine oversight of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"One-party_state\">one-party state</span>—the leadership abruptly reversed course, and many historians contend that Mao had deliberately lured his critics into the open, a manoeuvre he later likened to enticing the snakes out of their holes. The reversal was signalled by a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Daily\">People's Daily</span> editorial of 8 June 1957, after which an anti-rightist leading group headed by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>, who had become the party's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"General_Secretary_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">General Secretary</span> at its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"8th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Eighth National Congress</span> in 1956, directed the prosecution of the campaign through party committees nationwide. Official tallies eventually classified some 552,877 people as \"rightists,\" a cohort that included leading members of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Democratic_League\">China Democratic League</span>, though later scholarship has suggested that the true number of those persecuted may have exceeded a million once informal victims and dismissed family members are taken into account. <br> <br> Those branded as rightists faced public denunciation, dismissal from their posts, and in many cases banishment to the countryside or <b>confinement in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Re-education_through_labor\">re-education through labour</span></b> camps and the wider <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Laogai\">laogai</span> penal system, with notable victims including the politicians <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Bojun\">Zhang Bojun</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luo_Longji\">Luo Longji</span>, the editor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chu_Anping\">Chu Anping</span>, and <b>the writer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ding_Ling\">Ding Ling</span></b>. The sociologist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fei_Xiaotong\">Fei Xiaotong</span> and the journalist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Binyan\">Liu Binyan</span> were condemned alongside them, and the silencing of so large a part of the educated elite deprived the state of independent expertise just as it embarked on the calamitous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Leap_Forward\">Great Leap Forward</span> of 1958. By cowing dissent and exposing the dangers of candid speech, the campaign entrenched a culture of conformity that scholars regard as a decisive milestone in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maoism\">Maoist</span> radicalisation, and many of the same individuals would be persecuted afresh during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span> launched in 1966. Most of the surviving rightists were finally rehabilitated during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boluan_Fanzheng\">Boluan Fanzheng</span> reversals overseen by Deng from 1978, when the verdicts against all but a small handful of designated rightists were formally annulled and the victims were restored to their positions or otherwise compensated. The party has nonetheless continued to insist that the campaign was correct in its original purpose yet broadened far beyond reasonable bounds, a carefully hedged verdict that preserves the legitimacy of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_Front_Work_Department\">United Front</span></b> system while leaving largely unspoken the enduring harm the purge did to intellectual and political life in China.","citation":"","answerText":"Anti-Rightist Campaign"},{"id":"cne-100","num":"一百","category":"China · Economics","question":"Capturing the part of economic growth not explained by adding more labour or capital, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> has slowed in China, central to debates over whether it can keep growing fast or will sink into the middle-income trap.","answer":"Total factor productivity","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Coined</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Robert Solow, as the 'Solow residual', 1957</span></div>","traditional":"全要素生產率","hanzi":"全要素生产率","pinyin":"quán yàosù shēngchǎnlǜ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">quán yàosù shēngchǎnlǜ</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Total factor productivity</b>, also known as the <b>Solow residual</b> or <b>multifactor productivity</b>, is the portion of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economic_growth\">economic growth</span> in output that cannot be explained by increases in measured inputs of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Labour_economics\">labour</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capital_(economics)\">capital</span></b>, and is read as a gauge of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Productivity\">productivity</span>, technology, and organisation with which those inputs are combined. It is derived as a residual within the framework of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Growth_accounting\">growth accounting</span> rooted in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Solow–Swan_model\">Solow–Swan model</span> and typically anchored in a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cobb–Douglas_production_function\">Cobb–Douglas production function</span>, where the growth of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gross_domestic_product\">gross domestic product</span> is decomposed into contributions from capital, from labour, and from this unexplained remainder. The concept was formalised by the economist <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Robert_Solow\">Robert Solow</span> in a landmark 1957 study</b> that attributed roughly 87 percent of the growth in American output per worker-hour between 1909 and 1949 to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Technological_change\">technical change</span> rather than to capital accumulation, work that helped earn him the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nobel_Memorial_Prize_in_Economic_Sciences\">Nobel Memorial Prize</span> in 1987. Because it captures everything affecting output beyond the quantity of inputs — from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Innovation\">innovation</span> and managerial skill to institutional quality — <b>the economist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Moses_Abramovitz\">Moses Abramovitz</span></b> famously described the residual as \"a measure of our ignorance\" about the true sources of growth. Later theorists, notably <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paul_Romer\">Paul Romer</span>, sought to explain the residual through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Endogenous_growth_theory\">endogenous growth theory</span>, treating ideas and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Research_and_development\">research and development</span> as the engines of long-run productivity rather than leaving technology an unexplained gift, work for which Romer shared <b>the Nobel award in 2018</b>. <br> <br> In <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>, decades of breakneck expansion after the launch of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">market reforms</span> in 1978 rested heavily on prodigious <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capital_accumulation\">capital accumulation</span> and a labour supply swelled by a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Demographic_dividend\">demographic dividend</span>, yet substantial productivity gains also flowed from the reallocation of workers out of agriculture into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Industrialisation\">industry</span> and from opening to foreign technology. Economists estimate that these gains contributed on the order of a third of the country's output growth during the reform era, with productivity rising by roughly 3 to 4 percent a year at its peak, even as an <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Investment\">investment</span> rate approaching half of the national <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">economy</span> drove much of the rest, though influential studies of resource misallocation suggested that inefficiency depressed Chinese manufacturing productivity by 30 to 50 percent relative to an efficient allocation. This pattern fed a long-running debate, <b>sharpened by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paul_Krugman\">Paul Krugman</span>'s 1994 essay</b> <i>The Myth of Asia's Miracle</i>, over whether East Asian growth was driven by perspiration rather than inspiration and therefore vulnerable to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Middle_income_trap\">middle-income trap</span> that ensnares economies unable to graduate from factor accumulation to genuine innovation and movement up the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Value_chain\">value chain</span>. China's productivity growth slowed markedly after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2008_financial_crisis\">global financial crisis</span> of 2008, with several estimates showing it falling close to zero or even turning negative in the mid-2010s, as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Diminishing_returns\">diminishing returns</span> to investment — reflected in a steadily rising amount of capital needed to generate each unit of output — the misallocation of credit toward inefficient <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_enterprises_of_China\">state-owned enterprises</span>, and a mounting debt burden eroded the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economic_efficiency\">efficiency</span> of new spending. The slowdown placed productivity at the heart of policy debate, prompting the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Bank\">World Bank</span> in its 2012 \"China 2030\" report to urge a shift from input-driven to innovation-led growth, and underpinning Beijing's subsequent rhetoric of \"high-quality development\" as the country, with per-capita <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gross_national_income\">income</span> of roughly US$13,000 hovering</b> near the World Bank's high-income threshold, weighed whether it could keep expanding rapidly or stagnate short of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Developed_country\">advanced-economy</span> status.","citation":"","answerText":"Total factor productivity"},{"id":"cnp-023","num":"二十三","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Launched in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> with utopian targets for steel produced in backyard furnaces and the mass creation of rural communes, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> contributed to a catastrophic famine.","answer":"Great Leap Forward","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1958–1962</span></div>","traditional":"大躍進","hanzi":"大跃进","pinyin":"Dàyuèjìn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Dàyuèjìn</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Great Leap Forward</b> was a sweeping economic and social campaign <b>launched by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> in 1958</b> to transform the largely agrarian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Republic_of_China\">People's Republic of China</span> into a socialist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Industrialisation\">industrial</span> power almost overnight. Coinciding with the country's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five-year_plans_of_China\">Second Five-Year Plan</span> and propelled by the slogan to overtake the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_Kingdom\">United Kingdom</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Steel\">steel</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heavy_industry\">heavy industry</span> within 15 years, it discarded cautious Soviet-style planning in favor of the utopian mass mobilization of the peasantry. The rural population was herded by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> into roughly 25,000 enormous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_commune\">people's communes</span>, each averaging some 5,000 households, in which private plots were abolished and families took their meals in communal mess halls. Tens of millions of peasants were set to smelting metal in primitive <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Backyard_furnace\">backyard furnaces</span></b>, melting down their own pots and tools to meet quotas that yielded mostly brittle, unusable <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pig_iron\">pig iron</span> while diverting labor from the harvest. Agriculture was simultaneously thrown into disarray by pseudoscientific methods inspired by Soviet <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lysenkoism\">Lysenkoism</span>, including dense planting and deep plowing, and by the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Pests_Campaign\">Four Pests Campaign</span></b>, whose extermination of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eurasian_tree_sparrow\">tree sparrow</span> unleashed crop-devouring insects. <br> <br> Local cadres, fearful after the recent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anti-Rightist_Campaign\">Anti-Rightist Campaign</span>, reported wildly inflated grain yields, prompting the state to seize quotas based on fictional figures and even to export grain as the countryside began to starve. When Defense Minister <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peng_Dehuai\">Peng Dehuai</span> privately criticized the program at the <b>1959 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lushan_Conference_(1959)\">Lushan Conference</span></b>, Mao denounced him as the head of an anti-Party clique, replaced him with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lin_Biao\">Lin Biao</span>, and drove the campaign onward rather than correcting course. The result was the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Chinese_Famine\">Great Chinese Famine</span> of 1959 to 1961</b>, the deadliest <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Famine\">famine</span> in recorded history, whose toll is estimated at between 15 and 55 million in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Excess_mortality\">excess deaths</span>, with many scholars settling near 30 million. As the disaster deepened, the withdrawal of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Soviet</span> advisers amid the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-Soviet_split\">Sino-Soviet split</span> compounded the strain, and pragmatists such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Shaoqi\">Liu Shaoqi</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Yun\">Chen Yun</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> moved to dismantle the worst policies, a retreat formalized at the 1962 <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Seven_Thousand_Cadres_Conference\">Seven Thousand Cadres Conference</span></b>. Liu reportedly judged the catastrophe \"70 percent man-made,\" and the erosion of Mao's authority that followed helped drive him to launch the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span> in 1966, while later accounts such as the journalist <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yang_Jisheng_(journalist)\">Yang Jisheng</span></b>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tombstone_(book)\"><i>Tombstone</i></span> have cemented the Leap's standing as one of the gravest man-made calamities in human history.","citation":"","answerText":"Great Leap Forward"},{"id":"cnp-024","num":"二十四","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Rooted in a registration system formalised in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> and still shaping access to schooling, housing and welfare, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> ties citizens to a registered place of residence, creating a deep divide between urban residents and rural migrant workers in the People's Republic under the Communist Party.","answer":"Hukou system","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">户口 (hùkǒu, 'households and mouths'); system formalized 1958</span></div>","traditional":"戶口","hanzi":"户口","pinyin":"hùkǒu","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">hùkǒu</span></div>","abstract":"The <b><i>Hukou</i> system</b> is the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Household_registration\">household-registration</span></b> system of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span>, administered by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ministry_of_Public_Security_(China)\">Ministry of Public Security</span>, that records every citizen in a household ledger tied to a specific place of residence and to either an agricultural or a non-agricultural status. Because access to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Education_in_China\">schooling</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Healthcare_in_China\">healthcare</span>, public housing, pensions, and other <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Social_security_in_China\">social welfare</span></b> has long been linked to the locality and category in which a person is registered, the document has effectively functioned as a kind of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Internal_passport\">internal passport</span> governing where citizens may settle and what benefits they may claim. Although household registration in China reaches back to ancient antecedents—from the population ledgers instituted by the Legalist statesman <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shang_Yang\">Shang Yang</span> in the 4th century BCE to the later <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Baojia_system\">baojia</span> mutual-surveillance system—the modern apparatus was <b>formalized in 1958</b> through landmark regulations issued amid the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Leap_Forward\">Great Leap Forward</span> under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>, partly to curb rural-to-urban <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Internal_migration\">internal migration</span></b>. Within the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Planned_economy\">planned economy</span>, the system anchored the allocation of grain <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rationing\">rations</span> and guaranteed urban employment through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Danwei\">danwei</span> work-unit, channeling resources toward state-led <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Industrialisation\">industrialization</span> while binding the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peasant\">peasantry</span> to the land. In design it resembled the Soviet <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Propiska_in_the_Soviet_Union\">propiska</span></b> residence-permit regime, and over the decades it hardened into a structural feature of governance under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span>, dividing the population into two sharply unequal classes of citizenship. <br> <br> Its most visible consequence is a deep divide between city and countryside, embodied by the roughly 290 million rural <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Migrant_workers_in_China\">migrant workers</span> who power urban economies yet, retaining rural registration, are largely shut out of local schools, clinics, and housing, part of a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Floating_population\">floating population</span> that the <b>2020 census</b> put at about 376 million. A further toll falls on the country's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Left-behind_children_in_China\">left-behind children</span>, tens of millions of whom grow up in rural villages while their parents work in distant cities they cannot bring them to. Scholars and critics have likened the resulting two-tier citizenship to a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Caste\">caste</span>-like order or even a system of internal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Apartheid\">apartheid</span>, and it is widely regarded as a major driver of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Income_inequality_in_China\">income inequality</span> between urban and rural China. Successive reforms since the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Reform_and_opening_up\">reform and opening up</span> launched by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> have loosened controls, and a <b>2014 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_Council_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">State Council</span></b> urbanization plan moved to merge the agricultural and non-agricultural categories into a single resident registration and to grant urban hukou to around 100 million migrants, yet China's headline <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Urbanization_in_China\">urbanization</span> rate of roughly 64 percent still far outpaced the share of the population holding urban registration, near 46 percent. Major cities such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span> nonetheless retained tight, points-based admission to local registration, so that despite pledges of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Common_prosperity\">common prosperity</span> the system continued into the 2020s to shape opportunity, mobility, and welfare for hundreds of millions of people.","citation":"","answerText":"Hukou system"},{"id":"cnp-025","num":"二十五","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Established from <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> as the largest collective units in the countryside, combining agriculture, local industry, schooling and militia under one administration, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> pooled peasant land and labour during the Great Leap Forward.","answer":"People's commune","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1958</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"人民公社","pinyin":"rénmín gōngshè","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">rénmín gōngshè</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>people's commune</b> was the largest unit in the three-tier system of rural collective organization in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span>, conceived as a comprehensive body that fused economic production, local government, and social life in the drive to build <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialism\">socialism</span> across the countryside. Pioneered in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Henan\">Henan</span> province in the <b>spring of 1958</b> through the amalgamation of smaller <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Agricultural_cooperative\">agricultural cooperatives</span></b> that had themselves grown out of earlier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Land_reform_movement\">land reform</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Collective_farming\">collectivization</span>, the communes were embraced by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> as a shortcut toward full <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Communism\">communism</span> and a decisive break with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Private_property\">private property</span>. Endorsed soon after the second session of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"8th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">8th National Congress</span></b> by a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo</span> directive of August 1958 and ratified by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Central Committee</span>, the movement spread with extraordinary speed, so that by the end of that year roughly 26,000 communes embraced about 99 percent of China's peasant households, each averaging some 5,000 families. A single commune typically integrated farming, local industry, schooling, commerce, and a people's militia under one administration, and was subdivided into production brigades and production teams that directed the daily labour of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peasant\">peasant</span></b> population. In their most radical phase the communes abolished private plots, brought even tools and draught animals into the collective <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Means_of_production\">means of production</span>, and ran communal mess halls in which, at the peak, close to 90 percent of villagers took their meals, while a \"free supply\" system promised <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Egalitarianism\">egalitarian</span> distribution akin to a rural <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Iron_rice_bowl\">iron rice bowl</span>.<br> <br>The communes also served as the chief vehicle for the Great Leap Forward's frenzied industrial targets, set amid the launch of the Second <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five-Year_plans_of_China\">Five-Year Plan</span></b>, most notoriously the drive to smelt <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Steel\">steel</span> in improvised <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Backyard_furnace\">backyard furnaces</span>, a campaign that pulled tens of millions of peasants away from the harvest and yielded mostly unusable metal. When Defence Minister <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peng_Dehuai\">Peng Dehuai</span> criticized the campaign's excesses <b>at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lushan_Conference\">Lushan Conference</span> of 1959</b> he was abruptly purged, and the leadership pressed the policy forward even as Soviet ridicule of the communes deepened the widening <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-Soviet_split\">Sino-Soviet split</span>. Compounded by wildly inflated harvest reports and punishing state grain procurement, the upheaval culminated in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Chinese_Famine\">Great Chinese Famine</span> of 1959–1961, in which tens of millions perished, before pragmatic leaders such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Shaoqi\">Liu Shaoqi</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Yun\">Chen Yun</span> scaled the system back, dismantling the communal mess halls and shifting the basic accounting unit down to the production team. In a diminished and less utopian form the commune nonetheless endured as the standard unit of rural administration <b>throughout the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span> of 1966–1976</b>, functioning as the agrarian counterpart to the urban <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Danwei\">work unit</span> and helping to bind peasants to the land under the household-registration, or <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hukou\">hukou</span>, system. With the launch of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">market-oriented reforms</span> under Deng, the communes were dismantled between 1982 and 1985, their economic functions superseded by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Household_responsibility_system\">household responsibility system</span> and their governmental role returned to revived <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Townships_of_China\">township</span> authorities under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitution_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">state constitution</span> of 1982.","citation":"","answerText":"People's commune"},{"id":"cnp-026","num":"二十六","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Resulting from the policies of the Great Leap Forward, exaggerated grain reports and the diversion of labour, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> caused tens of millions of deaths and damaged Mao Zedong's standing within the Party.","answer":"Great Chinese Famine","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1959–1961</span></div>","traditional":"三年大饑荒","hanzi":"三年大饥荒","pinyin":"Sānnián Dà Jīhuāng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Sānnián Dà Jīhuāng</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Three-Year Great Famine”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Great Chinese Famine</b> was a catastrophic period of mass starvation across the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span> <b>between 1959</b> and 1961 that is widely regarded as the deadliest <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Famine\">famine</span> in recorded history and that flowed directly from the utopian policies of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Leap_Forward\">Great Leap Forward</span>. Its proximate causes lay in the forced amalgamation of peasants into giant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_commune\">people's communes</span>, the diversion of <b>agricultural labour toward <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Backyard_furnace\">backyard furnaces</span></b> and grandiose irrigation works, and a cascade of falsified output reports that prompted ruinous state grain procurement, all aggravated by the pseudoscientific agronomy of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lysenkoism\">Lysenkoism</span> and by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Pests_campaign\">Four Pests campaign</span>, whose extermination of sparrows unleashed devastating insect plagues. National grain output collapsed from roughly 200 million tonnes (220 million tons) <b>in 1958</b> to about 143 million tonnes (158 million tons) in 1960, yet the authorities continued to requisition and even export grain, and the worst-affected regions—above all <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Henan\">Henan</span>, where the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinyang_Incident\">Xinyang Incident</span> alone claimed around a million lives, together with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anhui\">Anhui</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan\">Sichuan</span> under <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Jingquan\">Li Jingquan</span></b>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gansu\">Gansu</span>—endured staggering mortality. The catastrophe was deepened by politics, for at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lushan_Conference_(1959)\">Lushan Conference</span> of 1959 the defence minister <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peng_Dehuai\">Peng Dehuai</span> was purged after he dared to criticise the Leap, a warning that discouraged cadres from reporting shortfalls, while the deepening <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-Soviet_split\">Sino-Soviet split</span> and the abrupt withdrawal <b>of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Soviet</span> advisers in 1960</b> stripped away vital technical assistance. Estimates of the death toll range from about 15 million to more than 55 million, with the journalist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yang_Jisheng_(journalist)\">Yang Jisheng</span> reckoning some 36 million excess deaths in his study <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tombstone_(book)\"><i>Tombstone</i></span> and <b>the historian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Frank_Dikötter\">Frank Dikötter</span></b> proposing at least 45 million in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao's_Great_Famine\"><i>Mao's Great Famine</i></span>, while the nation's recorded population fell by roughly 10 million during 1960. <br> <br> On the ground the disaster manifested in mass <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Starvation\">starvation</span>, widespread oedema, and, in the most desperate localities, documented instances of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cannibalism\">cannibalism</span>, while collapsing birth rates carved out a demographic trough that left a lasting imprint on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Demographics_of_China\">population structure</span> of the country. Recovery came only as more pragmatic leaders such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Shaoqi\">Liu Shaoqi</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Yun\">Chen Yun</span> rolled back the most extreme measures from 1961 onward, and at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Seven_Thousand_Cadres_Conference\">Seven Thousand Cadres Conference</span></b> of 1962 Liu publicly ascribed the calamity to thirty per cent natural causes and seventy per cent human error. The episode badly eroded the authority of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> within the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span>, prompting him to withdraw from frontline economic management and cede the initiative to his colleagues, a reversal that nourished the resentments he would later unleash in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span>. For decades the official narrative euphemistically blamed the deaths on the so-called Three Years of Natural Disasters and minimised the role of policy, and frank discussion of the famine has remained tightly circumscribed under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Censorship_in_China\">Chinese censorship</span>. Although its precise scale continues to be contested by demographers and historians, the famine endures in scholarship as one of the deadliest <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"List_of_famines\">famines</span> ever recorded and as a sobering indictment of the coercive utopianism that gave rise to it.","citation":"","answerText":"Great Chinese Famine"},{"id":"cnp-027","num":"二十七","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Convened in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> at a mountain resort, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> became infamous when a letter criticising the Great Leap Forward led Mao Zedong to purge his defence minister as head of an \"anti-Party clique\" within the Politburo.","answer":"Lushan Conference (1959)","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">&lt;b&gt;July–August 1959&lt;/b&gt;</span></div>","traditional":"廬山會議","hanzi":"庐山会议","pinyin":"Lúshān Huìyì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Lúshān Huìyì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Lushan Conference</b> was a pivotal series of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> leadership meetings held at a cool mountain retreat in the midst of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Leap_Forward\">Great Leap Forward</span>. It took place on <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mount_Lu\">Mount Lu</span></b>, a scenic resort in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiangxi\">Jiangxi</span> province, and combined an enlarged session of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo</span> with the 8th plenum of the party's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Central Committee</span>. Convened ostensibly to assess and gently correct the Leap's mounting failures, the gathering opened in a comparatively relaxed atmosphere as senior leaders began to admit that output figures across the new <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_commune\">people's communes</span> had been wildly overstated. Into this setting stepped <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peng_Dehuai\">Peng Dehuai</span>, the defense minister and a revered <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marshal_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">Marshal</span></b> who had risen through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">Chinese Civil War</span>, commanded Chinese forces in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Korean_War\">Korean War</span>, and recently toured rural districts ravaged by the campaign. On July 14, 1959, he handed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> a private \"letter of opinion\" candidly faulting the waste of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Backyard_furnace\">backyard steel furnaces</span> that produced near-worthless <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pig_iron\">pig iron</span></b>, the exaggeration he likened to \"petty-bourgeois fanaticism,\" and the hardship the policies had inflicted on the peasantry. <br> <br> Rather than accept the critique, Mao circulated the letter to all delegates, recast it as a frontal assault on his leadership of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Republic_of_China\">People's Republic of China</span> and on his swelling <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cult_of_personality\">cult of personality</span>, and rallied the conference—even figures such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Shaoqi\">Liu Shaoqi</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span>—to condemn its author and extract from him a humiliating <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Self-criticism\">self-criticism</span>. Peng was branded the ringleader of an \"anti-Party clique\" that also implicated the army chief of staff <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huang_Kecheng\">Huang Kecheng</span></b> and the senior official <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Wentian\">Zhang Wentian</span>, along with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hunan\">Hunan</span> party chief Zhou Xiaozhou, and was suspected of harboring sympathies tied to the deepening <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-Soviet_split\">Sino-Soviet split</span>. Stripped of his command, Peng was succeeded as defense minister by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lin_Biao\">Lin Biao</span>, whose ascent would militarize the politics of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army\">People's Liberation Army</span> over the coming decade. Most consequentially, the conference reversed the tentative moderation of the Leap and launched a fresh purge of officials accused of \"right deviation,\" echoing the earlier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anti-Rightist_Campaign\">Anti-Rightist Campaign</span>, a chilling of dissent that emboldened the ruinous policies and deepened the unfolding <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Chinese_Famine\">Great Chinese Famine</span>. Peng himself was hounded <b>to his death in 1974</b> during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span> and only posthumously rehabilitated through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boluan_Fanzheng\">reversal of verdicts</span> under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> in 1978, while Lushan itself would host a <b>second bitter clash in 1970</b>, when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Boda\">Chen Boda</span> and Lin Biao fell out with Mao.","citation":"","answerText":"Lushan Conference (1959)"},{"id":"cne-011","num":"十一","category":"China · Economics","question":"Discovered in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> in the north-east and developed into the country's largest source of crude, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> gave rise to a Maoist slogan urging the nation to emulate its self-reliant workers, exemplified by the model labourer Wang Jinxi during the era of Mao Zedong and the Cultural Revolution.","answer":"Daqing Oil Field","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">大庆 (Dàqìng, 'great celebration'), named on the PRC's 10th anniversary, 1959</span></div>","traditional":"大慶油田","hanzi":"大庆油田","pinyin":"Dàqìng Yóutián","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Dàqìng Yóutián</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Daqing Oil Field</b> is a vast oil field in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Songliao_Basin\">Songliao Basin</span></b> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heilongjiang\">Heilongjiang</span> province in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northeast_China\">northeast China</span>, <b>discovered in 1959</b> and given a name meaning \"great celebration\" in honour of the 10th <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Day_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">National Day</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Republic_of_China\">People's Republic of China</span>. Struck near the end of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Leap_Forward\">Great Leap Forward</span>, the field confirmed major petroleum <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Oil_reserves\">reserves</span> in the continental sediments of the basin and, by reducing reliance on imports from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Soviet Union</span> amid the worsening <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-Soviet_split\">Sino-Soviet split</span>, enabled China to declare <b>self-sufficiency in oil by 1963</b>. It rapidly became the country's largest source of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Petroleum\">crude oil</span> and the backbone of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Petroleum_industry_in_China\">Chinese petroleum industry</span>, sustaining an annual output of more than 50 million tonnes (55 million tons)—around a million <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Barrel_(unit)\">barrels</span> per day—for 27 consecutive years <b>from 1976</b> and supplying close to half of the nation's crude for decades. Developed across successive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five-year_plans_of_China\">five-year plans</span> as a flagship <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_enterprises_of_China\">state-owned enterprise</span>, the field anchored a boomtown that grew into the prefecture-level city of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Daqing\">Daqing</span>, a major centre of refining and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Petrochemical\">petrochemicals</span>. Operated within the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Planned_economy\">planned economy</span>, it furnished the young republic with a strategic resource that underpinned its <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Energy_security\">energy security</span></b> at a time of acute international isolation, and with cumulative output eventually surpassing 2 billion tonnes (2.2 billion tons) it remains the most productive oil field in China's history. <br> <br> Beyond its economic role, the field became a centrepiece of Maoist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Propaganda_in_China\">propaganda</span> when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> in 1964 launched the campaign \"In Industry, Learn from Daqing,\" holding up its workforce as a national model of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Self-sufficiency\">self-reliance</span> and arduous struggle. The campaign's human embodiment was the oil driller <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Jinxi\">Wang Jinxi</span>, celebrated as the \"Iron Man\" for his feats at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Drilling_rig\">drilling rig</span></b>—including the storied episode in which he is said to have leapt into a pit to mix the drilling mud with his own body—and his mythologized devotion to hard labour made him one of the most famous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Model_worker\">model workers</span> in the history of the People's Republic. Daqing was paired in official rhetoric with the agricultural model village of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dazhai\">Dazhai</span></b>, and the twin slogans were promoted with particular intensity throughout the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span>, when the \"Daqing spirit\" was woven into films, posters, and mass campaigns. Following the economic reforms begun under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">Deng Xiaoping</span>'s leadership, the operation was folded into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_National_Petroleum_Corporation\">China National Petroleum Corporation</span> and its listed arm <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"PetroChina\">PetroChina</span>, shifting from a symbol of revolutionary self-sacrifice toward a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Corporatization\">corporatized</span>, profit-driven enterprise. After its prolonged plateau the field entered a gradual decline as its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Petroleum_reservoir\">reservoirs</span> matured, annual output slipping from the 50-million-tonne peak toward roughly 30 million tonnes (33 million tons) a year by the 2010s, yet Daqing has endured in Chinese political culture as the archetypal emblem of industrial self-reliance and the worker-hero ideal cultivated during the Mao era.","citation":"","answerText":"Daqing Oil Field"},{"id":"cnp-030","num":"三十","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Initiated by Mao Zedong in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> to cleanse politics and ideology in the countryside, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> — sometimes called the Four Cleanups — targeted alleged corruption and revisionism among rural cadres.","answer":"Socialist Education Movement","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1963–1966</span></div>","traditional":"社會主義教育運動","hanzi":"社会主义教育运动","pinyin":"Shèhuìzhǔyì Jiàoyù Yùndòng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Shèhuìzhǔyì Jiàoyù Yùndòng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Socialist Education Movement</b> was a mass political campaign in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Republic_of_China\">People's Republic of China</span></b>, <b>launched by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> in 1963</b> to reassert <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialism\">socialist</span> values and tighten <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> discipline in the countryside. It arose in the aftermath of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Leap_Forward\">Great Leap Forward</span> and the ensuing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Chinese_Famine\">famine</span>, after Mao—put on the defensive at the <b>1962 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Seven_Thousand_Cadres_Conference\">Seven Thousand Cadres Conference</span></b>—grew alarmed that recovery measures championed by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Shaoqi\">Liu Shaoqi</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>, including the revival of private plots and rural markets, were allowing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capitalism\">capitalist</span> tendencies to creep back into the villages. Mao framed the danger as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Revisionism_(Marxism)\">revisionism</span>, equating domestic backsliding with the course taken by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nikita_Khrushchev\">Nikita Khrushchev</span> in the Soviet Union amid the deepening <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-Soviet_split\">Sino-Soviet split</span>, and called for a <b>renewed emphasis on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Class_struggle\">class struggle</span></b>. The drive became popularly known as the \"Four Cleanups,\" at first targeting <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Political_corruption\">corruption</span> in village accounts, granaries, property, and work points, with investigations carried out by work teams of cadres and students sent down into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_commune\">people's communes</span>. The campaign unfolded alongside a wider ideological revival—the 1963 \"Learn from <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lei_Feng\">Lei Feng</span></b>\" drive and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lin_Biao\">Lin Biao</span>'s elevation of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maoism\">Mao Zedong Thought</span> within the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army\">People's Liberation Army</span>, where he compiled the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Quotations_from_Chairman_Mao_Tse-tung\"><i>Quotations from Chairman Mao Tse-tung</i></span>—which re-centered public life on the Maoist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mass_line\">mass line</span> and Mao's swelling cult. <br> <br> A succession of competing directives steered the campaign, and Liu Shaoqi took an increasingly hard line—amplified by the influential \"Taoyuan Experience\" of his wife <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Guangmei\">Wang Guangmei</span>, who led a model work team—subjecting suspect cadres to investigation and humiliating <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Struggle_session\">struggle sessions</span> reminiscent of the earlier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anti-Rightist_Campaign\">Anti-Rightist Campaign</span>. <b>In January 1965 Mao</b> issued the \"Twenty-Three Articles,\" redirecting the campaign away from petty village graft and toward \"people in power taking the capitalist road,\" the so-called <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capitalist_roader\">capitalist roaders</span> he believed had infiltrated the Party and even the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo</span> itself. This redefinition implicitly rebuked Liu's handling of the movement and widened a bitter rift between the two men, transforming a rural rectification drive into a contest over the future of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Revolution\">Chinese revolution</span></b> itself. By the time it wound down, work teams had investigated millions of rural <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Collective_farming\">collective</span> officials, large numbers of whom were dismissed, punished, or driven to despair, hardening an atmosphere of suspicion across the countryside. Before it could be completed, the movement was overtaken in 1966 by the far more sweeping <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span> and its radicalized <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Red_Guards\">Red Guards</span>, in which the very charge of \"capitalist roader\" was turned against Liu Shaoqi himself—purged, imprisoned, and dead by 1969—marking the earlier campaign as a crucial rehearsal for the upheaval to come.","citation":"","answerText":"Socialist Education Movement"},{"id":"cnp-052","num":"五十二","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Originally proposed by Zhou Enlai and made a centrepiece of policy under Deng Xiaoping, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> targeted agriculture, industry, national defence, and science and technology.","answer":"Four Modernizations","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Coined</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Proposed by Zhou Enlai, 1963; championed by Deng Xiaoping</span></div>","traditional":"四個現代化","hanzi":"四个现代化","pinyin":"sì gè xiàndàihuà","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">sì gè xiàndàihuà</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Four Modernizations</b> were a set of strategic development goals adopted by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> to transform the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span> into a modern industrial power by strengthening <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Agriculture\">agriculture</span>, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Industry\">industry</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army\">national defence</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Science_and_technology_in_China\">science and technology</span>. The concept was first articulated by premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span>, who sketched an early version embracing industry, agriculture, transport, and defence during the 1950s before refining the formulation and presenting it in his <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Government_Work_Report\">Government Work Report</span></b> <b>to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_People's_Congress\">National People's Congress</span> in late 1964</b>. Addressing the Fourth <b>National People's Congress in January 1975</b>, the terminally ill Zhou revived the slogan and set the ambitious aim of achieving comprehensive modernization in two stages before the end of the 20th century, a vision meant to rescue the country from the economic devastation wrought by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Leap_Forward\">Great Leap Forward</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span>. Its implementation was obstructed by the radical <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gang_of_Four\">Gang of Four</span>, who denounced such pragmatic priorities as a betrayal of revolution, and only after the deaths of <b>Zhou and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> in 1976 did</b> the programme regain momentum under the transitional leadership of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hua_Guofeng\">Hua Guofeng</span>. It was <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>, however, who elevated the goals to the centrepiece of national policy at the landmark <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"3rd_Plenary_Session_of_the_11th_Central_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Third Plenary Session of the 11th Central Committee</span> in December 1978, redirecting the party's overriding focus away from Maoist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Class_struggle\">class struggle</span> and the dogmatic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Two_Whatevers\">\"Two Whatevers\"</span> toward economic construction. <br> <br> Serving as the guiding rationale for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">reform and opening up</span>, the four goals justified the gradual dismantling of the rigid <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Planned_economy\">planned economy</span> through innovations such as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Household-responsibility_system\">household responsibility system</span></b> in farming and the creation of export-oriented <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Special_economic_zones_of_China\">special economic zones</span> like <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shenzhen\">Shenzhen</span> to attract <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foreign_direct_investment\">foreign investment</span>. The strictly economic and technical thrust of the agenda drew sharp criticism from the dissident <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wei_Jingsheng\">Wei Jingsheng</span></b>, who in a famous 1978 essay posted on Beijing's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Democracy_Wall\">Democracy Wall</span> demanded a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Fifth_Modernization\">\"Fifth Modernization\"</span> of democracy, an appeal for political liberalisation that earned him a lengthy imprisonment. Deng firmly rebuffed such demands by enunciating the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Cardinal_Principles\">Four Cardinal Principles</span> in 1979, insisting that modernization proceed strictly within the bounds of socialist rule and the unchallenged leadership of the party. Embedded thereafter in successive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five-year_plans_of_China\">five-year plans</span> and the maturing doctrine of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialism_with_Chinese_characteristics\">socialism with Chinese characteristics</span>, the modernizations underpinned several decades of near double-digit growth that propelled China toward becoming the world's second-largest economy. Although the original deadline of the year 2000 elapsed with its targets only partially fulfilled, the four-sector formula endured as a foundational reference point for national development, complementing the broader rehabilitative campaign of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boluan_Fanzheng\">Boluan Fanzheng</span> and crystallising within the body of ideas eventually codified as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping_Theory\">Deng Xiaoping Theory</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Four Modernizations"},{"id":"cnp-031","num":"三十一","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Compiled within the People's Liberation Army under Lin Biao and waved by Red Guards across the country, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> became the most printed book of the Cultural Revolution era.","answer":"Quotations from Chairman Mao Zedong","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1964</span></div>","traditional":"毛主席語錄","hanzi":"毛主席语录","pinyin":"Máo Zhǔxí yǔlù","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Máo Zhǔxí yǔlù</span></div>","abstract":"<b><i>Quotations from Chairman Mao Zedong</i></b> is a compendium of statements excerpted from the speeches and writings of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>, the founding leader of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span> and a veteran of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Long_March\">Long March</span></b>, known in the West as the \"<b>Little Red Book</b>.\" Organized into 33 thematic chapters and comprising some 427 short <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Quotation\">quotations</span>, the book distilled <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maoism\">Mao Zedong Thought</span> into memorable <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Aphorism\">aphorisms</span> drawn from such writings as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"On_Practice\"><i>On Practice</i></span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"On_Contradiction\"><i>On Contradiction</i></span>, and the much-recited essays <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Serve_the_People\"><i>Serve the People</i></span></b> and <i>In Memory of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Norman_Bethune\">Norman Bethune</span></i>. The work grew out of a campaign, intensified within the army from the early 1960s, to study Mao's words as a corrective after the disastrous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Leap_Forward\">Great Leap Forward</span> and amid the deepening <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-Soviet_split\">Sino-Soviet split</span></b>, and it was first <b>issued in 1964</b> under defence minister Lin Biao, whose calligraphic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_calligraphy\">inscription</span> exhorting soldiers to follow the Chairman prefaced its early editions. The anthology swiftly became the central instrument of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cult_of_personality\">cult of personality</span> built around Mao, casting the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Communist Party</span> chairman as an infallible <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paramount_leader\">paramount leader</span> whose every utterance carried doctrinal authority. Its pages condensed <b>Mao's doctrines of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Class_conflict\">class struggle</span></b>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mass_line\">mass line</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_war\">people's war</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Democracy\">New Democracy</span> into slogans simple enough to be memorized and chanted by hundreds of millions.<br> <br>During the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span> <b>launched in 1966</b> it was printed in well over a billion copies and made a centrepiece of state <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Propaganda_in_China\">propaganda</span>, the small red-vinyl volume becoming a quasi-sacred object that the Chinese press hailed as the \"red treasured book.\" Citizens were expected to carry, wave, and recite from it at mass rallies, in the ritualized <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Loyalty_dance\">loyalty dance</span>, and amid the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Struggle_session\">struggle sessions</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Big-character_poster\">big-character poster</span> campaigns through which the movement enforced ideological conformity. A laudatory foreword by Lin Biao prefaced most editions until <b>his abrupt downfall in 1971</b>, when—accused of mounting the abortive coup plot known as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Project_571\">Project 571</span>—he died in a plane crash over <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongolia\">Mongolia</span> and his preface was hastily excised from the book. The cult it sustained outlived Lin and was carried on by radicals such as Mao's wife <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Qing\">Jiang Qing</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gang_of_Four\">Gang of Four</span>, but after Mao's death in 1976 and the brief interregnum under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hua_Guofeng\">Hua Guofeng</span>, official enthusiasm for the volume rapidly faded. Under the reforms of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> its printing was halted around 1979 and the book was largely withdrawn during the broad reassessment of Maoism known as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boluan_Fanzheng\">Boluan Fanzheng</span>, yet with cumulative printings estimated in the billions it endures as one of the most widely produced books in human history.","citation":"","answerText":"Quotations from Chairman Mao Zedong"},{"id":"cne-013","num":"十三","category":"China · Economics","question":"Launched in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> amid fears of war with the Soviet Union and the United States, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> relocated heavy industry and defence plants to remote interior provinces such as Sichuan, at great economic cost.","answer":"Third Front","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">from 1964</span></div>","traditional":"三線建設","hanzi":"三线建设","pinyin":"Sānxiàn Jiànshè","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Sānxiàn Jiànshè</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“third-line construction”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Third Front</b> was a vast programme of military-industrial relocation <b>launched by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> in 1964</b> under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> to build a self-sufficient strategic rear in the mountainous interior. The initiative arose from acute <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cold_War\">Cold War</span></b> insecurity, as the deepening <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-Soviet_split\">Sino-Soviet split</span> raised the spectre of attack from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Soviet Union</span> while escalating American intervention in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vietnam_War\">Vietnam War</span>, dramatised by the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gulf_of_Tonkin_incident\">Gulf of Tonkin incident</span></b> of August 1964, stoked equal fear of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States\">United States</span>. These anxieties were sharpened by China's own detonation of its first atomic bomb in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"596_(nuclear_test)\">596 test</span> of October 1964 and would appear vindicated by the <b>armed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-Soviet_border_conflict\">Sino-Soviet border conflict</span> of 1969</b>, which brought the two communist powers close to full-scale war. Strategic planners divided the country into three zones—a vulnerable coastal \"first front,\" a transitional \"second front,\" and a defensible \"third front\" comprising the remote provinces of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Southwest_China\">southwestern</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Northwest_China\">northwestern</span> China such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan\">Sichuan</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guizhou\">Guizhou</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yunnan\">Yunnan</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shaanxi\">Shaanxi</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gansu\">Gansu</span>. Following Mao's directive that new plants be \"dispersed, close to the mountains, and hidden,\" the campaign sought to transplant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heavy_industry\">heavy industry</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Arms_industry\">defence industry</span> away from exposed cities into rugged, easily concealed terrain, even at the price of enormous logistical difficulty. <br> <br> Sustained across successive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five-year_plans_of_China\">five-year plans</span> from 1964, the effort consumed over <b>200 billion yuan by 1980</b>—close to 40 percent of national capital-construction investment in the period—and produced more than 1,100 large and medium-sized factories, mines, and research institutes. Millions of workers, engineers, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army\">People's Liberation Army</span> soldiers were mobilised under harsh and secretive conditions, with the labour force reaching perhaps 4 million at its height as crews carved factories and rail lines out of isolated valleys far from existing roads, power, or housing. Among its flagship achievements were the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Panzhihua\">Panzhihua</span> iron-and-steel complex built from nothing in the Sichuan highlands, the 1,100-kilometre (680 mi) <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chengdu–Kunming_railway\">Chengdu–Kunming railway</span></b> completed in 1970 at the cost of thousands of lives, and the Second Automobile Works at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shiyan\">Shiyan</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hubei\">Hubei</span> that grew into the carmaker <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dongfeng_Motor_Corporation\">Dongfeng Motor</span>. Sprawling defence installations, including underground nuclear and weapons facilities tied to China's <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_and_weapons_of_mass_destruction\">nuclear-weapons programme</span></b> and concentrated in cave complexes around <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chongqing\">Chongqing</span>, were erected across the interior even as the simultaneous turmoil of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span> repeatedly disrupted planning, transport, and supply. Although the programme seeded modern industry in long-neglected regions, its remote and dispersed siting proved chronically inefficient under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Planned_economy\">planned economy</span>, and after the launch of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">reform and opening-up</span> under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> many of its enterprises were relocated to accessible cities, merged, or abandoned outright as commercially unviable.","citation":"","answerText":"Third Front"},{"id":"cne-090","num":"九十","category":"China · Economics","question":"A former English teacher from Hangzhou who became China's richest man, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> largely vanished from public life after a <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> speech criticising regulators helped scupper the giant Ant Group listing under Xi Jinping.","answer":"Jack Ma","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">born 10 September 1964</span></div>","traditional":"馬雲","hanzi":"马云","pinyin":"Mǎ Yún","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Mǎ Yún</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Jack Ma</b> is the principal co-founder and former executive chairman of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Alibaba_Group\">Alibaba Group</span></b>, the sprawling <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"E-commerce\">e-commerce</span> conglomerate whose rise made him for a time the wealthiest person in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>. Raised in the eastern province of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhejiang\">Zhejiang</span>, he failed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gaokao\">national college entrance examination</span> twice before graduating <b>from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hangzhou_Normal_University\">Hangzhou Normal University</span> in 1988</b> and taking up work as an <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"English_language\">English</span> instructor. In 1999 he and a group of 17 colleagues launched Alibaba from his apartment with about 60,000 US dollars in pooled savings, building a marketplace that would come to encompass the consumer platforms <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taobao\">Taobao</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tmall\">Tmall</span> and the payments service <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Alipay\">Alipay</span> while decisively outcompeting <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"EBay\">eBay</span> in the Chinese market. <b>The group's 2014 listing</b> on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_York_Stock_Exchange\">New York Stock Exchange</span>—backed by early investors such as Japan's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"SoftBank\">SoftBank</span> under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Masayoshi_Son\">Masayoshi Son</span>—raised roughly 25 billion US dollars in what was then the largest <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Initial_public_offering\">initial public offering</span> in history, cementing Ma's standing as one of Asia's foremost <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Billionaire\">billionaires</span>. Famed for a flamboyant public persona—performing in costume at company gatherings and casting himself as a champion of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Small_business\">small businesses</span>—Ma relinquished the <b>chairmanship of Alibaba in 2019</b> and turned increasingly toward <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Philanthropy\">philanthropy</span>.<br> <br>The reversal of his fortunes centred on the financial affiliate Ant Group, the operator of Alipay, which in late 2020 was preparing a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Financial_technology\">financial technology</span> flotation widely expected to become the largest in the world, with simultaneous listings planned on Shanghai's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"STAR_Market\">STAR Market</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_Stock_Exchange\">Hong Kong Stock Exchange</span>. On 24 October 2020, addressing a finance summit on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Bund\">Bund</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span>, Ma delivered a provocative speech denouncing China's <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Financial_regulation\">financial regulators</span></b> and likening its state-dominated banks to pawnshops, remarks that swiftly drew the displeasure of the authorities. Within days the regulators summoned Ma and his deputies, and on 3 November 2020 the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Bank_of_China\">People's Bank of China</span> and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Securities_Regulatory_Commission\">securities regulator</span></b> abruptly suspended the offering, ultimately compelling Ant Group to restructure itself as a tightly regulated financial holding company. The episode triggered a wider regulatory assault on the country's technology sector, culminating in a record <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Competition_law\">antitrust</span> penalty of 18.2 billion <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Renminbi\">yuan</span>—about 2.8 billion US dollars—imposed on Alibaba by the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_Administration_for_Market_Regulation\">market regulator</span></b> in April 2021 amid the drive for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Common_prosperity\">common prosperity</span> promoted under Xi Jinping. Having retreated almost entirely from public view—reappearing only occasionally and reportedly spending long stretches abroad—Ma came to embody the precarious position of even the most prominent private entrepreneurs within the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Communist Party</span>'s vision of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">Chinese economy</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Jack Ma"},{"id":"cnp-032","num":"三十二","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Launched by Mao Zedong in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> to reassert his authority and combat alleged bourgeois elements within the Party, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> mobilised youth and persecuted officials and intellectuals until <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>.","answer":"Cultural Revolution","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1966–1976</span></div>","traditional":"無產階級文化大革命","hanzi":"无产阶级文化大革命","pinyin":"Wúchǎn Jiējí Wénhuà Dà Gémìng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Wúchǎn Jiējí Wénhuà Dà Gémìng</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“Great Proletarian Cultural Revolution”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Cultural Revolution</b> was a sweeping sociopolitical upheaval <b>launched by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> in 1966</b> to reassert his authority over the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> and <b>to purge purported <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bourgeoisie\">bourgeois</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Revisionism_(Marxism)\">revisionist</span> elements, convulsing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span> for a full decade <b>until 1976</b>. Mao had been politically sidelined after the calamity of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Leap_Forward\">Great Leap Forward</span>, during which <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Shaoqi\">Liu Shaoqi</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> had assumed day-to-day management of the economy, and he conceived the movement to dislodge such pragmatic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capitalist_roader\">capitalist-roaders</span> and restore an uncompromising revolutionary orthodoxy. The campaign was <b>ignited by a November 1965 polemic</b> against <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Han_(historian)\">Wu Han</span>'s historical drama <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hai_Rui_Dismissed_from_Office\"><i>Hai Rui Dismissed from Office</i></span>, sanctioned by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"May_16_Notification\">May 16 Notification</span> of 1966, and carried into the streets after <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nie_Yuanzi\">Nie Yuanzi</span> posted an inflammatory big-character poster at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peking_University\">Peking University</span> and Mao himself published the manifesto <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bombard_the_Headquarters\">Bombard the Headquarters</span></b> against Liu. Millions of students were mobilised into fanatical <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Red_Guards\">Red Guards</span> who set out to smash the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Olds\">Four Olds</span> of old ideas, culture, customs, and habits, humiliating teachers and officials in violent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Struggle_session\">struggle sessions</span> and destroying countless cultural relics, while a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Cultural_Revolution_Group\">Central Cultural Revolution Group</span> dominated by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Boda\">Chen Boda</span> and the security chief <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kang_Sheng\">Kang Sheng</span> usurped the functions of the regular party apparatus. The most radical leadership coalesced in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gang_of_Four\">Gang of Four</span>—Mao's wife <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Qing\">Jiang Qing</span> together with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Chunqiao\">Zhang Chunqiao</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yao_Wenyuan\">Yao Wenyuan</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Hongwen\">Wang Hongwen</span>—while the defence minister and anointed successor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lin_Biao\">Lin Biao</span> orchestrated an extravagant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cult_of_personality\">cult of personality</span>, propagating the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Quotations_from_Chairman_Mao_Zedong\"><i>Little Red Book</i></span> in well over a billion copies. <br> <br> Rival factions soon turned their weapons on one another, and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Revolutionary_committee_(China)\">power seizures</span> of early 1967 pitched</b> the country toward civil war until the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army\">People's Liberation Army</span> intervened to impose order, while from 1968 the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Down_to_the_Countryside_Movement\">Down to the Countryside Movement</span> dispersed the Red Guards by rusticating some 17 million urban youth. Lin Biao, formally enshrined as Mao's heir at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"9th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Ninth Party Congress</span> of 1969, fell abruptly from grace and perished in a 1971 plane crash over <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongolia\">Mongolia</span> while reportedly fleeing after a failed coup, an episode that badly shook popular faith in the movement. As <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span> and a briefly rehabilitated Deng sought to stabilise the country, the radicals pressed on with ideological drives such as the campaign to criticise Lin Biao and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucius\">Confucius</span>, and the spontaneous <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tiananmen_Incident\">Tiananmen Incident</span></b> of April 1976, mourning the recently deceased Zhou, furnished the pretext for Deng's second purge. The human and institutional costs were immense, as schools and universities shut their doors and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gaokao\">national college entrance examination</span> was suspended for over a decade, while estimates of those killed range from roughly 500,000 to as many as 2 million and tens of millions more were persecuted, among them Liu Shaoqi, who died in detention in 1969. The decade of turmoil finally ended with Mao's death in September 1976 and the arrest of the Gang of Four a month later, after which <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hua_Guofeng\">Hua Guofeng</span> and then Deng presided over the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boluan_Fanzheng\">Boluan Fanzheng</span> reversals that dismantled its policies, and in 1981 the party formally condemned the movement as the gravest setback the People's Republic had endured since its founding.","citation":"","answerText":"Cultural Revolution"},{"id":"cnp-033","num":"三十三","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Issued in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> as a circular drafted under Mao Zedong's direction, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is generally regarded as the formal opening salvo of the Cultural Revolution and established the Central Cultural Revolution Group.","answer":"May 16 Notification","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">16 May 1966</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"五一六通知","pinyin":"Wǔyīliù Tōngzhī","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Wǔyīliù Tōngzhī</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>May 16 Notification</b> was a circular adopted by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo</span> <b>of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> on 16 May 1966</b>, a document widely regarded by historians as the formal opening salvo of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span> that would convulse China for the following decade. Drafted and repeatedly revised under the close personal supervision of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>, with substantial input from his ideological allies <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kang_Sheng\">Kang Sheng</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Boda\">Chen Boda</span>, the text was circulated as a confidential Party communication and would not be published openly until exactly one year later in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Daily\">People's Daily</span>. At its core the circular repudiated the conciliatory <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"February_Outline\">February Outline</span> issued only months earlier by a five-member group headed by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> mayor <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peng_Zhen\">Peng Zhen</span></b>, condemning that body for having sought to confine a sharpening <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Class_struggle\">class struggle</span> within the bounds of mere academic debate. Echoing fears stoked by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"De-Stalinization\">de-Stalinization</span> pursued in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Soviet Union</span> under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nikita_Khrushchev\">Nikita Khrushchev</span>, the document warned that representatives of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bourgeoisie\">bourgeoisie</span> had infiltrated the party, the government, the army and cultural circles, branding such hidden enemies <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Revisionism_(Marxism)\">revisionists</span> who had to be exposed and overthrown. Crucially, it dissolved Peng Zhen's group and created in its place the Central <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution_Group\">Cultural Revolution Group</span></b>, an extraordinary body that bypassed the regular Party apparatus and soon became a principal engine of the upheaval under figures including <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Qing\">Jiang Qing</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Chunqiao\">Zhang Chunqiao</span>. <br> <br> The Notification's roots lay in the literary controversy <b>ignited in November 1965</b>, when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yao_Wenyuan\">Yao Wenyuan</span> published a scathing critique of the historical play <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hai_Rui_Dismissed_from_Office\"><i>Hai Rui Dismissed from Office</i></span> by the historian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_Han_(historian)\">Wu Han</span>, an attack that Mao interpreted as a veiled defence of recently purged officials. Within weeks of the circular's adoption the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Central Committee</span> sanctioned the mobilisation of radicalised youth into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Red_Guards\">Red Guards</span>, and that August Mao further escalated the campaign with his own <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Big-character_poster\">big-character poster</span> <b>urging followers to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bombard_the_Headquarters\">bombard the headquarters</span></b>. The vaguely defined enemies named in the Notification supplied the ideological licence for purging senior leaders denounced as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capitalist_roader\">capitalist roaders</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Counter-revolutionary\">counter-revolutionaries</span>, most prominently <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Shaoqi\">Liu Shaoqi</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>, as the country slid into factional violence and institutional paralysis. In a striking irony, the date itself later lent its name to the alleged May Sixteenth conspiracy, an ostensibly ultra-leftist plot whose investigation became a sprawling <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Purge\">purge</span> that ensnared hundreds of thousands of cadres during the early 1970s. Formally rescinded only after the deaths of Mao and his designated successor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lin_Biao\">Lin Biao</span> and the <b>1976 arrest</b> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gang_of_Four\">Gang of Four</span>, the Notification is today characterised by the Chinese Communist Party itself as a grievous error that helped unleash a decade-long catastrophe whose death toll modern scholars estimate at anywhere from several hundred thousand to as many as 2 million.","citation":"","answerText":"May 16 Notification"},{"id":"cnp-034","num":"三十四","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Drawn largely from students and emerging in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> attacked the so-called Four Olds and persecuted teachers and officials in the early phase of the Cultural Revolution.","answer":"Red Guards","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1966–1968</span></div>","traditional":"紅衛兵","hanzi":"红卫兵","pinyin":"Hóngwèibīng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Hóngwèibīng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Red Guards</b> were a mass movement of radicalized young people, overwhelmingly secondary-school and university <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Student\">students</span></b>, who became the shock troops of the early <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span> in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Republic_of_China\">People's Republic of China</span>. The first groups <b>coalesced in mid-1966</b> at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> schools—among them a middle school attached to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tsinghua_University\">Tsinghua University</span>—and were galvanized when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> praised a militant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Big-character_poster\">big-character poster</span> by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nie_Yuanzi\">Nie Yuanzi</span> at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peking_University\">Peking University</span>. Encouraged by Mao's own August 1966 poster \"<b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bombard_the_Headquarters\">Bombard the Headquarters</span></b>\" and the cult cultivated by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lin_Biao\">Lin Biao</span>, the youths brandished the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Quotations_from_Chairman_Mao_Tse-tung\"><i>Quotations from Chairman Mao Tse-tung</i></span> and answered his call to wage <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Class_struggle\">class struggle</span> against established authority. Their first great target was the so-called <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Olds\">Four Olds</span></b>—old ideas, culture, customs, and habits—prompting them to ransack temples, burn books, smash relics, and even assail the ancestral home of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucius\">Confucius</span>, destroying an incalculable portion of China's cultural heritage. They also turned on teachers, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Intellectual\">intellectuals</span>, and officials condemned as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capitalist_roader\">capitalist roaders</span> or members of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five_Black_Categories\">Five Black Categories</span></b>, parading victims in brutal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Struggle_session\">struggle sessions</span>, as Mao reviewed roughly 12 million of them at 8 massive rallies in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tiananmen_Square\">Tiananmen Square</span> in late 1966. <br> <br> The violence peaked during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Red_August\">Red August</span> of 1966 in Beijing, when Red Guards beat and killed thousands of perceived class enemies and drove many others to suicide. Egged on by the radical <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution_Group\">Central Cultural Revolution Group</span> and Mao's wife <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Qing\">Jiang Qing</span>, later a leader of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gang_of_Four\">Gang of Four</span>, they helped topple Mao's rivals at the apex of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span>, above all <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Shaoqi\">Liu Shaoqi</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>. As the movement spread nationwide through free railway travel to \"exchange revolutionary experience,\" the Red Guards splintered into rival factions whose feuds escalated into pitched armed battles, culminating in episodes such as the <b>1967 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuhan_Incident\">Wuhan Incident</span></b>. <b>By 1968</b>, with the country sliding toward anarchy, Mao curbed his own creation, deploying the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army\">People's Liberation Army</span> to restore order and dispersing millions of former Red Guards to the villages under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Down_to_the_Countryside_Movement\">Down to the Countryside Movement</span>. The episode left a generation with interrupted educations and a legacy of trauma, and its frenzy of destruction and persecution—part of a Cultural Revolution that ultimately claimed hundreds of thousands to perhaps millions of lives—remains among the most cautionary chapters of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maoism\">Maoist</span> rule.","citation":"","answerText":"Red Guards"},{"id":"cnp-036","num":"三十六","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Intensifying from <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> as Mao Zedong sought to disperse the increasingly unruly Red Guards, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> sent millions of urban \"educated youth\" to live and labour among the peasantry in remote rural areas.","answer":"Down to the Countryside Movement","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1968–1980</span></div>","traditional":"上山下鄉運動","hanzi":"上山下乡运动","pinyin":"Shàngshān xiàxiāng yùndòng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Shàngshān xiàxiāng yùndòng</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“up to the mountains and down to the countryside”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Down to the Countryside Movement</b> was a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mass_mobilization\">mass mobilization</span></b> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> that relocated urban \"educated youth\" to rural and frontier areas to live and labour alongside the rural poor. Although smaller, voluntary resettlement schemes had existed since the mid-1950s, the campaign became a sweeping and compulsory program <b>from 1968</b>, when the factional violence of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span> had thrown the cities into chaos and Mao, relying on the army under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lin_Biao\">Lin Biao</span>, moved to disband the increasingly unmanageable Red Guards. The turning point came in December 1968, when a directive from Mao published in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Daily\">People's Daily</span></b> declared it necessary for educated youth to be re-educated by the poor peasants, a policy that at once cleared restless students from the cities, eased urban unemployment, and, in the name of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maoism\">Mao Zedong Thought</span> and the surrounding <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cult_of_personality\">cult of personality</span>, sought to temper a privileged generation through manual labour. Over the following decade the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Communist Party</span>, working through bodies such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Communist_Youth_League_of_China\">Communist Youth League</span>, dispatched an estimated 16 to 17 million young people to the villages, the largest peacetime transfer of urban population in modern Chinese history. Most were settled on rural <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_commune\">people's communes</span> or <b>on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_farm\">state farms</span></b> run by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army\">army</span>, including remote frontier postings in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heilongjiang\">Heilongjiang</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Inner_Mongolia\">Inner Mongolia</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yunnan\">Yunnan</span> and under paramilitary bodies such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinjiang_Production_and_Construction_Corps\">Xinjiang Production and Construction Corps</span>.<br> <br>On arrival the youths' urban household registration, or <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hukou\">hukou</span>, was transferred to the countryside, often stranding them for years amid harsh conditions, interrupted schooling, and the demanded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Class_conflict\">class</span> re-education that fed a wider current of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anti-intellectualism\">anti-intellectualism</span>. Among the millions sent down were future national leaders, including <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span>, who lived <b>from 1969</b> to 1975 in a village in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shaanxi\">Shaanxi</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Keqiang\">Li Keqiang</span>, for whom the rural years became a defining episode of youth. State <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Propaganda_in_China\">propaganda</span> celebrated the program as a fusion of intellectual and peasant life, and although many youths did bring teaching and basic health care to isolated villages—an aim echoed in the contemporaneous spread of rural <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Barefoot_doctor\">barefoot doctors</span>—most endured hardship, boredom, and squandered opportunity. The program faltered <b>after Mao's death in 1976</b> and the fall of the radical <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gang_of_Four\">Gang of Four</span> led by his widow <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Qing\">Jiang Qing</span>, and under the transitional leadership of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hua_Guofeng\">Hua Guofeng</span> the reinstated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_College_Entrance_Examination\">national college entrance examination</span> of 1977 opened a route back to the cities, soon followed by mass petitions demanding the right to return. Effectively ended around 1980 amid the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">economic reforms</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> and the broad repudiation of Maoist policy known as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boluan_Fanzheng\">Boluan Fanzheng</span>, the campaign left a generation with disrupted educations and a lasting sense of grievance that found voice in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Scar_literature\">scar literature</span> of the early reform</b> era.","citation":"","answerText":"Down to the Countryside Movement"},{"id":"cnp-037","num":"三十七","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Convened in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> at the height of the Cultural Revolution, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> fall.","answer":"9th National Congress of the CCP","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1969</span></div>","traditional":"中國共產黨第九次全國代表大會","hanzi":"中国共产党第九次全国代表大会","pinyin":"Zhōngguó Gòngchǎndǎng Dìjiǔ Cì Quánguó Dàibiǎo Dàhuì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōngguó Gòngchǎndǎng Dìjiǔ Cì Quánguó Dàibiǎo Dàhuì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>9th National Congress of the CCP</b> was a national congress of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> held in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> <b>from April 1 </b>to<b> 24, 1969</b>, at the height of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span>. Meeting roughly 13 years <b>after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"8th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">8th National Congress</span> of 1956</b>, in a party whose machinery had been shattered by mobilized <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Red_Guards\">Red Guards</span>, the gathering assembled about 1,512 delegates said to represent some 22 million members, the overwhelming majority chosen amid the turmoil rather than by regular procedures. Its central aim was to proclaim the violent opening phase of the Cultural Revolution a triumph and to re-enshrine <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong_Thought\">Mao Zedong Thought</span>, alongside <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marxism–Leninism\">Marxism–Leninism</span>, as the Party's guiding ideology, reversing the more collective and moderate line of the preceding congress. The keynote political report, delivered by <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lin_Biao\">Lin Biao</span></b> and drafted largely by the radical theorist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Boda\">Chen Boda</span>, propounded the doctrine of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Continuous_Revolution_Theory\">continuing revolution</span> under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dictatorship_of_the_proletariat\">dictatorship of the proletariat</span> and branded the deposed head of state <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Shaoqi\">Liu Shaoqi</span> the foremost <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capitalist_roader\">capitalist-roader</span>. Reflecting the collapse of the civilian apparatus, the proceedings were dominated by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army\">People's Liberation Army</span> and by Cultural Revolution radicals, elevating figures such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Qing\">Jiang Qing</span>, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kang_Sheng\">Kang Sheng</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Chunqiao\">Zhang Chunqiao</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yao_Wenyuan\">Yao Wenyuan</span> while sidelining surviving veterans such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>. <br> <br> The new <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitution_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Party Constitution</span> adopted at the congress took the extraordinary step of naming <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>'s \"close comrade-in-arms\" Lin Biao as his designated successor, an explicit codification of a succession that had no precedent in the Party's history. It further elected a new <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Central Committee</span> of some 170 full members weighted heavily toward the army and the beneficiaries of the purges, and rebuilt the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_Standing_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo Standing Committee</span> around Mao, Lin Biao, the premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span>, Chen Boda, and Kang Sheng, while raising Lin Biao's wife <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ye_Qun\">Ye Qun</span> to the wider Politburo. Lin Biao's pre-eminence proved fleeting, for in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lin_Biao_incident\">Lin Biao incident</span></b> of 1971 he died in a plane crash over the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongolian_People's_Republic\">Mongolian People's Republic</span> while allegedly fleeing the failure of a coup plot, devised with his son <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lin_Liguo\">Lin Liguo</span>, that became known as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Project_571_Outline\">Project 571</span> scheme. After his death the leadership branded him a traitor, and the clause designating him as successor was excised from the charter when the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"10th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">10th National Congress</span></b> convened in 1973 and advanced the rising radical <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Hongwen\">Wang Hongwen</span> in his stead. Historians regard the congress as the institutional high-water mark of the Cultural Revolution and of the Maoist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cult_of_personality\">personality cult</span>, soon to be carried on by the radical clique later condemned as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gang_of_Four\">Gang of Four</span>, yet the rapid collapse of its centerpiece succession plan laid bare the profound instability at the summit of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maoism\">Maoist</span> state.","citation":"","answerText":"9th National Congress of the CCP"},{"id":"cne-082","num":"八十二","category":"China · Economics","question":"An international reserve asset created by the IMF, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> has an elite currency basket into which the renminbi was admitted in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> alongside the dollar, euro, yen and pound, a milestone for China's financial standing.","answer":"Special drawing rights","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">created 1969</span></div>","traditional":"特別提款權","hanzi":"特别提款权","pinyin":"tèbié tíkuǎnquán","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">tèbié tíkuǎnquán</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Special drawing rights</b> are an international reserve asset created <b>by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"International_Monetary_Fund\">International Monetary Fund</span> in 1969</b> to supplement the official <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foreign_exchange_reserves\">foreign-exchange reserves</span> of its member states, and although the instrument is frequently described as a currency, it is more accurately a potential claim on the freely usable currencies held by those members. Identified by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"ISO_4217\">ISO 4217</span> currency code XDR, the asset serves chiefly as a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Unit_of_account\">unit of account</span></b> for the Fund and a handful of other international bodies rather than as money used in ordinary commerce. Its creation arose from the strains of the post-war <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bretton_Woods_system\">Bretton Woods system</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fixed_exchange_rate_system\">fixed exchange rates</span>, when anxieties that the <b>world's supply of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gold\">gold</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States_dollar\">United States dollars</span> might prove insufficient to finance expanding <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"International_trade\">international trade</span> — a concern famously crystallised in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Triffin_dilemma\">Triffin dilemma</span> — drove the search for a new source of global reserves. Under the prevailing <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gold_standard\">gold-based monetary order</span></b> a single unit was initially defined as 0.888671 grams of fine gold, an amount then exactly equal to one US dollar, but this anchor dissolved following the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nixon_shock\">end of dollar–gold convertibility</span> and the general shift to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Floating_exchange_rate\">floating exchange rates</span> in the early 1970s. The asset was thereafter redefined as a weighted basket of currencies, <b>encompassing 16 in 1974</b> before being trimmed to five in 1981 — the dollar, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deutsche_Mark\">Deutsche Mark</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"French_franc\">French franc</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japanese_yen\">Japanese yen</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pound_sterling\">pound sterling</span> — with the German and French components later absorbed into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Euro\">euro</span> <b>after its launch in 1999</b>. <br> <br> The basket's composition is reviewed roughly every five years, and in a decision reached in November 2015 and brought into effect on 1 October 2016 the Fund admitted the Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Renminbi\">renminbi</span> as a fifth member, assigning it an opening weight of 10.92 percent behind the dollar at 41.73 percent and the euro at 30.93 percent. This step represented the first enlargement of the basket since the euro's introduction and was broadly read as formal acknowledgement of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China's</span> rising economic stature, even though the renminbi still lacked the full <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Convertibility\">convertibility</span></b> that characterised the other constituent currencies. A later review that took effect in August 2022 lifted the renminbi's share to 12.28 percent and the dollar's to 43.38 percent, while the associated interest rate on the asset continued to be calculated weekly from a weighted average of representative <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Money_market\">money-market</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Interest_rate\">interest rates</span> in the five economies. Allocations are distributed to members in proportion to their Fund quotas to help meet <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Balance_of_payments\">balance-of-payments</span> needs, and beyond the modest issuances of the 1970s the Fund authorised roughly SDR 161 billion during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2008_financial_crisis\">global financial crisis</span> of 2009 and an unprecedented SDR 456 billion — about US$650 billion — in August 2021 to reinforce global <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Market_liquidity\">liquidity</span> amid the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"COVID-19_pandemic\">COVID-19 pandemic</span>. Though small in scale beside the trillions of dollars held in conventional <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Reserve_currency\">reserve currencies</span>, the asset has repeatedly drawn proposals for a grander role, most prominently in 2009 when the governor of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Bank_of_China\">People's Bank of China</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Xiaochuan\">Zhou Xiaochuan</span>, urged that it be developed into a supranational reserve currency to ease the world's reliance on any single <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_bank\">central bank</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Special drawing rights"},{"id":"cnp-039","num":"三十九","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Symbolised by the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> visit of an American table tennis team, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> helped pave the way for improved relations between the People's Republic and the United States amid the deepening Sino-Soviet split.","answer":"Ping-pong diplomacy","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Origin</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Coined for the US table-tennis team's visit to China, 1971</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"乒乓外交","pinyin":"pīngpāng wàijiāo","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">pīngpāng wàijiāo</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Ping-pong diplomacy</b> refers to the exchange of table-tennis players between the United States and the People's Republic of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> in the <b>early 1970s</b>, an episode that signalled a dramatic thaw in <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China–United_States_relations\">Sino-American relations</span></b> after more than two decades of mutual hostility. The opening unfolded against the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cold_War\">Cold War</span> rivalries of the era, as the deepening rift with Moscow—which had erupted into armed clashes along the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhenbao_Island\">Zhenbao Island</span> frontier <b>during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-Soviet_border_conflict\">Sino-Soviet border conflict</span> of 1969</b>—drove China to seek a counterweight to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Soviet Union</span>, while in Washington <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Richard_Nixon\">Richard Nixon</span> and his adviser <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Henry_Kissinger\">Henry Kissinger</span> pursued a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Realpolitik\">realpolitik</span> of exploiting that split. The catalyst came at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1971_World_Table_Tennis_Championships\"><b>1971</b> World Table Tennis Championships</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nagoya\">Nagoya</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japan\">Japan</span>, where a chance encounter between the American player <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Glenn_Cowan\">Glenn Cowan</span> and the Chinese champion <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuang_Zedong\">Zhuang Zedong</span>, who presented Cowan with a gift, drew worldwide notice at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"International_Table_Tennis_Federation\">International Table Tennis Federation</span></b> tournament. Seizing the moment, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> personally approved an invitation for the United States squad to tour China, and from 10 to 17 April 1971 the players became the first American delegation officially welcomed since the founding of the People's Republic in 1949. Remarkably, the gesture came in the midst of the radical <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span> and over the reservations of figures such as Mao's heir apparent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lin_Biao\">Lin Biao</span>, and Chinese officials captured its logic in the saying that \"the small ball moved the big ball\" of global politics.<br> <br>Within months a secret mission to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> in July 1971 saw Kissinger meet Premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span> to prepare a presidential trip, even as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_Nations\">United Nations</span> voted that October, <b>through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_Nations_General_Assembly_Resolution_2758\">Resolution 2758</span></b>, to seat the People's Republic in place of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span>. The process culminated in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1972_visit_by_Richard_Nixon_to_China\">Nixon's visit to China</span> in February 1972, during which he met Mao and Zhou and the two governments issued the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_Communiqué\">Shanghai Communiqué</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span>, pledging to work toward normalization while finessing the disputed status of Taiwan. That rapprochement rested on a deliberately ambiguous understanding of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"One-China_policy\">One-China policy</span></b>, and it served broader aims for both parties, offering Nixon leverage in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vietnam_War\">Vietnam War</span> and against Moscow while easing China's strategic isolation. Part of the wider <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Détente\">détente</span> of the 1970s, the table-tennis exchange was reciprocated by a Chinese team's tour of the United States in 1972 and signalled a historic strategic realignment by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Communist Party</span> leadership. Although full diplomatic relations were not established until 1979 under President <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jimmy_Carter\">Jimmy Carter</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>, the modest sporting overture of 1971 endures as the textbook illustration of how informal cultural contact can open a path through entrenched geopolitical hostility.","citation":"","answerText":"Ping-pong diplomacy"},{"id":"cnp-040","num":"四十","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Arranged through secret diplomacy by Henry Kissinger and including a meeting with Mao Zedong, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> ended decades of estrangement and produced a joint communiqué in Shanghai.","answer":"1972 Nixon visit to China","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1972</span></div>","traditional":"尼克松訪華","hanzi":"尼克松访华","pinyin":"Níkèsōng fǎng Huá","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Níkèsōng fǎng Huá</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>1972 Nixon visit to China</b> was a pivotal week-long diplomatic mission undertaken by <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"President_of_the_United_States\">United States president</span></b> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Richard_Nixon\">Richard Nixon</span> <b>from 21</b> to <b>28 February 1972</b>, the first time a sitting <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States\">American</span> head of state had set foot in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span>. The journey had been prepared through more than a year of clandestine manoeuvring, most <b>notably the secret July 1971 flight</b> to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> by national security adviser <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Henry_Kissinger\">Henry Kissinger</span>, itself foreshadowed by the unexpected thaw of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ping-pong_diplomacy\">ping-pong diplomacy</span> in the spring of that year. Shortly after his arrival Nixon was received for roughly an hour by the ageing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> at his residence in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhongnanhai\">Zhongnanhai</span>, a brief but symbolically momentous encounter, while the substantive bargaining was carried out with premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span>. Extensively televised to audiences back home, the carefully choreographed trip featured state banquets in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Hall_of_the_People\">Great Hall of the People</span> and widely broadcast excursions to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Wall_of_China\">Great Wall</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Forbidden_City\">Forbidden City</span>, scenes that Nixon himself dubbed \"the week that changed the world.\" The visit culminated on 27 February in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_Communiqué\">Shanghai Communiqué</span></b>, a joint statement issued in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span> in which the two governments frankly acknowledged their differences yet pledged to work toward the normalisation of relations and to oppose any nation's bid for hegemony in the Asia-Pacific. <br> <br> For more than two decades the two countries had been bitter adversaries, having fought on opposite sides of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Korean_War\">Korean War</span> and remained locked in mutual hostility ever since the communist triumph in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Civil_War\">Chinese Civil War</span> of 1949, a freeze that constituted one front of the wider <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cold_War\">Cold War</span>. What made the rapprochement possible was the deepening <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-Soviet_split\">Sino-Soviet split</span>, which by the late 1960s had erupted into a deadly <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-Soviet_border_conflict\">border conflict</span> and left Beijing eager for a counterweight against the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Soviet Union</span>, while Washington hoped Chinese leverage might ease its extraction from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vietnam_War\">Vietnam War</span>. That a fervent anti-communist like Nixon, long a champion of the policy of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Containment\">containment</span> against <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Communism\">communism</span>, should be the one to reach out to Beijing even as the country remained convulsed by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span> gave rise to the enduring political adage that \"only Nixon could go to China.\" The thorniest matter addressed was the status of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span>, on which the American side acknowledged that Chinese on both sides of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan_Strait\">Taiwan Strait</span> held there to be but one China, a deliberately ambiguous formulation that became a cornerstone of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"One_China_policy\">One China policy</span></b>. Although full diplomatic relations would not be established until 1979 under president <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jimmy_Carter\">Jimmy Carter</span>, the breakthrough fundamentally realigned the global <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Balance_of_power_(international_relations)\">balance of power</span>, advanced the broader pursuit of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Détente\">détente</span>, and endures as a defining episode in the long and turbulent story of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China–United_States_relations\">China–United States relations</span></b>.","citation":"","answerText":"1972 Nixon visit to China"},{"id":"cnp-041","num":"四十一","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Issued at the close of the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> Nixon visit, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> saw the United States acknowledge the One-China position and set the basis for eventual diplomatic recognition between the two governments.","answer":"Shanghai Communiqué","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Origin</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Issued jointly at Shanghai during Nixon's visit, Feb 1972</span></div>","traditional":"上海公報","hanzi":"上海公报","pinyin":"Shànghǎi Gōngbào","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Shànghǎi Gōngbào</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Shanghai Communiqué</b>, formally the <b>Joint Communiqué of the United States of America and the People's Republic of China</b>, was a diplomatic statement issued in the <b>city of Shanghai on February 27, 1972</b>, at the <b>close of President <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Richard_Nixon\">Richard Nixon</span></b>'s groundbreaking <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1972_visit_by_Richard_Nixon_to_China\">visit to China</span>. Its issuance marked a dramatic realignment in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cold_War\">Cold War</span>, as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States\">United States</span> sought to exploit the deepening <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-Soviet_split\">Sino-Soviet split</span> by drawing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Republic_of_China\">People's Republic of China</span> closer as a counterweight to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Soviet Union</span>, recasting the long-standing American doctrine of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Containment\">containment</span> within Nixon's wider policy of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Détente\">détente</span>. The visit had been prepared by a cautious thaw that <b>included the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ping-pong_diplomacy\">ping-pong diplomacy</span> of 1971</b> and a secret July 1971 mission to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> by national security adviser <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Henry_Kissinger\">Henry Kissinger</span>, and it came only months after the October 1971 vote under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_Nations_General_Assembly_Resolution_2758\">Resolution 2758</span> that transferred China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_Nations\">United Nations</span> seat from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kuomintang\">Nationalists</span> to the communist government. On the Chinese side the talks, conducted partly in the resort city of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hangzhou\">Hangzhou</span>, were led by premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span> and vice <b>foreign minister <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qiao_Guanhua\">Qiao Guanhua</span></b>, while Nixon's reception by an ailing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> furnished the symbolic centerpiece of a trip the president himself called \"the week that changed the world.\" Unusually, the document candidly set out the contrasting positions of both governments on a range of international questions before identifying their areas of agreement, a format the Chinese had insisted upon so as not to paper over the genuine ideological gulf between <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Communism\">communism</span> and the American-led order. <br> <br> At the heart of the communiqué lay its carefully worded passage on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span>, in which the United States acknowledged that Chinese on both sides of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan_Strait\">Taiwan Strait</span> maintained there was but one China and declared that it did not challenge that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"One_China\">One-China</span> position. Washington further affirmed its interest in a peaceful settlement of the Taiwan question and its ultimate objective of withdrawing American forces from the island, while both sides pledged to broaden cultural and trade contacts and to work toward full <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Diplomatic_recognition\">diplomatic recognition</span> and the eventual normalization of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China–United_States_relations\">Sino-American relations</span>. Progress was slowed by <b>the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Watergate_scandal\">Watergate scandal</span> and Nixon's 1974 resignation</b>, but liaison offices opened in 1973 and full diplomatic relations were finally established on January 1, 1979, under President <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jimmy_Carter\">Jimmy Carter</span> and the Chinese leader <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>. Normalization required Washington to switch recognition away from the Nationalist government of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Kai-shek\">Chiang Kai-shek</span>'s successors, to terminate the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-American_Mutual_Defense_Treaty\">Sino-American Mutual Defense Treaty</span></b>, and to leave unofficial ties with the island to be governed by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan_Relations_Act\">Taiwan Relations Act</span> passed by Congress that same year. As the first of the three joint communiqués that, together with the 1979 normalization accord and the 1982 statement on arms sales, continue to frame the relationship, the document is widely regarded as one of the pivotal turning points of 20th-century diplomacy and the cornerstone of subsequent engagement between Washington and Beijing.","citation":"","answerText":"Shanghai Communiqué"},{"id":"cnp-043","num":"四十三","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Running in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>–<span class=\"blank\">_____</span> and directing public attacks at both a disgraced defence minister and the ancient sage Confucius, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is widely read as a veiled assault by the radical faction on the rehabilitated Zhou Enlai.","answer":"Criticize Lin, Criticize Confucius Campaign","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1973–1974</span></div>","traditional":"批林批孔運動","hanzi":"批林批孔运动","pinyin":"Pī Lín Pī Kǒng Yùndòng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Pī Lín Pī Kǒng Yùndòng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Criticize Lin, Criticize Confucius Campaign</b> was a nationwide mass political movement <b>waged across <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> in 1973</b> and <b>1974</b> during the final years of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span>. Orchestrated by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gang_of_Four\">radical faction</span> later condemned as the Gang of Four, it yoked together two seemingly incongruous targets: the disgraced former defence minister <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lin_Biao\">Lin Biao</span>, who had died <b>fleeing toward <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mongolia\">Mongolia</span> in 1971</b>, and the ancient sage <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucius\">Confucius</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Spring_and_Autumn_period\">Spring and Autumn period</span> teacher whose thought underpinned the venerable tradition of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucianism</span>. The radicals constructed an elaborate historical analogy in which Confucianism was branded a reactionary creed and set against the centralising <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Legalism_(Chinese_philosophy)\">Legalist</span> statecraft that had flourished in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warring_States_period\">Warring States period</span> and was embodied by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_Shi_Huang\">Qin Shi Huang</span>, the ruler who forged the unified <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qin_dynasty\">Qin dynasty</span> in 221 BCE. Within this framework <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>, who personally disdained Confucius and admired the First Emperor, sanctioned <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Propaganda\">propaganda</span> recasting Lin Biao as a covert Confucian and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Counter-revolutionary\">counter-revolutionary</span> who had schemed to restore a defunct aristocratic order and turn back the revolutionary clock. It was prosecuted through the now-familiar machinery of the era, <b>including waves of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Big-character_poster\">big-character posters</span></b>, compulsory study sessions, and a torrent of theoretical articles in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Daily\">People's Daily</span>, many of them ghost-written by anonymous teams attached to universities such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peking_University\">Peking University</span>. <br> <br> Beneath its antiquarian veneer the movement is widely read by historians as a thinly disguised assault on premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span>, for the barbed attacks on the venerated <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Duke_of_Zhou\">Duke of Zhou</span></b> of the early <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_dynasty\">Zhou dynasty</span> were understood as coded strikes against the premier, who shared the same surname. After Lin Biao's death the pragmatic Zhou had steadily restored order and rehabilitated veteran cadres of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> purged earlier in the upheaval, most consequentially returning <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> to high office in 1973, a \"rightist\" drift that deeply alarmed the radicals. The faction's leading figures, several of them risen from radical <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span>—<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Qing\">Jiang Qing</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Chunqiao\">Zhang Chunqiao</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yao_Wenyuan\">Yao Wenyuan</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Hongwen\">Wang Hongwen</span></b>—sought to discredit the moderates and to defend the radical legacy of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maoism\">Maoism</span> against any creeping restoration of pre-1966 policies. Mao himself, however, grew wary of the radicals' ambition, reportedly admonishing the four in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo</span> meetings for operating as a factional clique, and by the latter half of 1974 the intensity of the campaign was deliberately allowed to subside. Though it failed to dislodge Zhou, who served as premier until his death in early 1976, the campaign foreshadowed the bitter factional warfare—soon redirected into a further drive to study the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dictatorship_of_the_proletariat\">dictatorship of the proletariat</span></b>—that convulsed Chinese politics until the radicals were arrested by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hua_Guofeng\">Hua Guofeng</span> only weeks after Mao's death, and it endures in retrospect as a striking example of the weaponisation of historical analogy for partisan ends.","citation":"","answerText":"Criticize Lin, Criticize Confucius Campaign"},{"id":"cne-041","num":"四十一","category":"China · Economics","question":"A set of policies — caps on interest rates, captive savers and tight capital controls — that quietly transfers wealth from households to borrowers, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is widely said to have channelled cheap Chinese savings into state firms and infrastructure.","answer":"Financial repression","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Coined</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Ronald McKinnon and Edward Shaw, 1973</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"金融抑制","pinyin":"jīnróng yìzhì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">jīnróng yìzhì</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Financial repression</b> is a set of government policies that channel cheap funds to the state and favoured borrowers by holding down the returns available to savers, functioning in effect as a hidden <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tax\">tax</span> that <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Redistribution_of_income_and_wealth\">transfers wealth</span></b> from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Household\">households</span> and depositors to debtors—chiefly governments, state enterprises, and other privileged borrowers—without the visibility or political cost of an ordinary levy. Its characteristic tools include caps on deposit and lending <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Interest_rate\">interest rates</span>, high <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Reserve_requirement\">reserve requirements</span></b>, a captive domestic audience of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bank\">banks</span>, insurers, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pension_fund\">pension funds</span> obliged to hold government debt at low yields, and tight <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capital_control\">capital controls</span> that prevent savers from seeking better returns abroad. The concept was <b>introduced in 1973</b> by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stanford_University\">Stanford</span> economists Edward Shaw and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ronald_McKinnon\">Ronald McKinnon</span>, who argued that such restrictions, then common across the developing world, stunted <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Financial_development\">financial development</span> and slowed growth in poorer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economic_development\">developing economies</span> by starving them of efficiently allocated credit. By combining interest-rate ceilings with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Inflation\">inflation</span>, the policy can push the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Real_interest_rate\">real interest rate</span></b> earned by depositors toward zero or below, so that savers are in effect taxed without legislation, eroding the value of their <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deposit_account\">deposits</span> while holding the cost of borrowing for the favoured sector far below what a free market would charge. The idea was revived after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Recession\">global financial crisis</span> by economists including <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Carmen_Reinhart\">Carmen Reinhart</span></b>, who showed how advanced economies such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States\">United States</span> and Britain had used financial repression and negative real rates to liquidate the enormous public <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Government_debt\">government debt</span> accumulated after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_War_II\">Second World War</span>. <br> <br> China became the textbook modern example of the practice, where a state-dominated banking system and a long-closed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capital_account\">capital account</span> left hundreds of millions of households as captive savers earning meagre, often negative real returns on their <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Saving\">savings</span>, which they could neither move offshore nor invest freely in alternatives. Under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Bank_of_China\">People's Bank of China</span>, regulated deposit ceilings and guided lending funnelled this cheap money to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_enterprises_of_China\">state-owned enterprises</span> and vast <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Infrastructure\">infrastructure</span> projects—roads, railways, ports, and property—at artificially low cost, subsidizing investment on a colossal scale and underpinning the country's rapid but lopsided growth. This subsidy to borrowers came at the expense of household income, holding down <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Consumption_(economics)\">consumption</span> to little more than a third of output—among the lowest shares in the world—while pushing the gross national saving rate above 45 percent of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gross_domestic_product\">gross domestic product</span> and tilting the <b>economy heavily toward <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Investment\">investment</span></b> and exports rather than domestic spending. Economists such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nicholas_Lardy\">Nicholas Lardy</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Michael_Pettis\">Michael Pettis</span> argued that this repression of household returns was a central engine of China's high-saving, investment-led model and a major contributor to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Current_account\">current-account</span> surpluses and accumulated reserves behind global imbalances. Beijing gradually loosened the controls during its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">economic reforms</span>, removing the floor on <b>lending rates in 2013</b> and the ceiling on deposit rates in October 2015, yet guided <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Credit_(finance)\">credit</span>, a closed capital account, and dominant state banks endured, leaving financial repression a defining and much-debated feature of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Renminbi\">renminbi</span> economy and of its long-promised rebalancing toward household consumption.","citation":"","answerText":"Financial repression"},{"id":"cnp-042","num":"四十二","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Comprising Jiang Qing and 3 radical allies based in Shanghai, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> wielded great power late in the Cultural Revolution before being arrested in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>.","answer":"Gang of Four","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">arrested 1976</span></div>","traditional":"四人幫","hanzi":"四人帮","pinyin":"Sì rén bāng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Sì rén bāng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Gang of Four</b> was a radical faction of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> that dominated much of the cultural and propaganda apparatus of the People's Republic of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> during the later years of the Cultural Revolution. It comprised <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>'s wife Jiang Qing alongside the chief theorist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Chunqiao\">Zhang Chunqiao</span>, the literary polemicist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yao_Wenyuan\">Yao Wenyuan</span>, and the young worker-rebel <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Hongwen\">Wang Hongwen</span>, all of whom had risen rapidly during the Cultural Revolution. The faction's roots lay in Shanghai, where <b>Yao's 1965 assault</b> on the historical play <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hai_Rui_Dismissed_from_Office\"><i>Hai Rui Dismissed from Office</i></span> helped ignite the Cultural Revolution and where its members later seized power in the <b>1967</b> \"January Storm\" that briefly produced the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_People's_Commune\">Shanghai People's Commune</span>, after which they operated through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution_Group\">Cultural Revolution Group</span>. From their commanding positions in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo</span> the radicals controlled much of the national press, including the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Daily\">People's Daily</span>, and wielded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Propaganda_in_China\">propaganda</span> to promote a militant doctrine of permanent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Class_conflict\">class struggle</span>. Fervent champions of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maoism\">Mao Zedong Thought</span> and of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cult_of_personality\">cult of personality</span> that had mobilized the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Red_Guards\">Red Guards</span>, they were nonetheless reproached by Mao himself, who is said to have warned Jiang Qing around 1974 against operating as a \"gang of four.\"<br> <br>Through the mid-1970s the group reached the height of its power, driving mass campaigns such as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Criticize_Lin,_Criticize_Confucius\">Criticize Lin, Criticize Confucius</span></b>—nominally aimed at the disgraced <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lin_Biao\">Lin Biao</span> but widely seen as a covert attack on the moderate premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span>—while fiercely opposing the rehabilitation of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>. The decisive year was 1976: after Zhou's death in January, mass mourning erupted into the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tiananmen_Incident\">Tiananmen Incident</span></b> of April, which the radicals exploited to oust Deng once again, and in September their patron Mao died. Less than a month later, <b>on 6 October 1976</b>, they were arrested in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> in a swift operation led by Mao's chosen successor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hua_Guofeng\">Hua Guofeng</span> together with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army\">army</span> marshal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ye_Jianying\">Ye Jianying</span> and the security chief <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Dongxing\">Wang Dongxing</span></b>, a coup widely regarded as marking the end of the Cultural Revolution. Put on trial in 1980–1981 before a special court of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Supreme_People's_Court\">Supreme People's Court</span> as a \"<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Counter-revolutionary\">counter-revolutionary</span> clique,\" they were convicted, with Jiang Qing and Zhang <b>receiving suspended <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capital_punishment_in_China\">death sentences</span></b> and Yao and Wang given long prison terms. Their downfall opened the way for the return of Deng and the dismantling of Maoist orthodoxy—against the lingering \"<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Two_Whatevers\">Two Whatevers</span>\"—during the rectification known as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boluan_Fanzheng\">Boluan Fanzheng</span>, and official histories thereafter laid the catastrophes of the Cultural Revolution at the group's door as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">economic reform</span> began.","citation":"","answerText":"Gang of Four"},{"id":"cnp-045","num":"四十五","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Erupting in April <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> when crowds gathered in Tiananmen Square to mourn the recently deceased Zhou Enlai, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was suppressed and blamed on Deng Xiaoping, leading to his temporary second purge.","answer":"1976 Tiananmen Incident","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1976</span></div>","traditional":"四五運動","hanzi":"四五运动","pinyin":"Sìwǔ yùndòng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Sìwǔ yùndòng</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“April Fifth Movement”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>1976 Tiananmen Incident</b> was a mass outpouring of public grief and political protest in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>, capital of the People's Republic of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>, during the final year of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span>. It was triggered <b>by the death in January 1976</b> of the moderate <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Premier_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">premier</span> Zhou Enlai, whose passing left the radical <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gang_of_Four\">Gang of Four</span></b> ascendant while the aged <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> declined. During the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qingming_Festival\">Qingming Festival</span> in early April, hundreds of thousands of people converged on Tiananmen Square to lay wreaths and post <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_poetry\">poems</span> at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Monument_to_the_People's_Heroes\">Monument to the People's Heroes</span></b>, the granite obelisk at the heart of the vast plaza bordered by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Hall_of_the_People\">Great Hall of the People</span>. Much of the mourning carried a sharp political edge, as verses and speeches obliquely denounced the radicals—above all Mao's wife <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Qing\">Jiang Qing</span> and her allies <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Chunqiao\">Zhang Chunqiao</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yao_Wenyuan\">Yao Wenyuan</span>, and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Hongwen\">Wang Hongwen</span></b>—and implicitly defended the moderate, reformist line. When the authorities removed the wreaths overnight, angry crowds returned on 5 April and clashed with officials, whereupon the urban <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Militia\">militia</span>, backed by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army\">army</span> units, cleared the square by force and arrested hundreds.<br> <br>The leadership swiftly branded the episode a \"<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Counter-revolutionary\">counter-revolutionary</span>\" riot in the pages of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Daily\">People's Daily</span>, with the Beijing boss <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_De\">Wu De</span></b> condemning it over loudspeakers, and laid the blame on Deng Xiaoping. On 7 April 1976 the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo</span>, meeting in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhongnanhai\">Zhongnanhai</span> leadership compound with Mao's approval, stripped Deng of all his official posts—his second purge—and named <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hua_Guofeng\">Hua Guofeng</span> premier and first vice-chairman of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Communist Party</span>. The radical triumph proved brief, for after Mao's death in September the Gang of Four were arrested in October 1976 by Hua together with the marshal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ye_Jianying\">Ye Jianying</span> and the security chief <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Dongxing\">Wang Dongxing</span>. <b>In November 1978</b>, as Deng returned to power and dismantled <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maoism\">Maoist</span> orthodoxy against the lingering \"<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Two_Whatevers\">Two Whatevers</span>,\" the verdict was formally reversed and the protest hailed as a patriotic act during the rectification known as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boluan_Fanzheng\">Boluan Fanzheng</span>. Coming as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">economic reform</span> began and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cult_of_personality\">cult</span> surrounding Mao receded, the incident is remembered as an early assertion of popular political voice that foreshadowed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Democracy_Wall\">Democracy Wall</span> movement and, more distantly, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1989_Tiananmen_Square_protests_and_massacre\"><b>1989</b> protests</span> in the same square.","citation":"","answerText":"1976 Tiananmen Incident"},{"id":"cnp-047","num":"四十七","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Articulated in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> as a defence of orthodoxy by supporters of Hua Guofeng, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> had made, and was challenged by the pragmatic line of Deng Xiaoping.","answer":"Two Whatevers","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Coined</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Hua Guofeng, 1977 (the two 'whatevers' on Mao's decisions)</span></div>","traditional":"兩個凡是","hanzi":"两个凡是","pinyin":"liǎng gè fánshì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">liǎng gè fánshì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Two Whatevers</b> was the popular name for a doctrinal slogan <b>promulgated in early 1977</b> holding that the Party would resolutely uphold whatever policy decisions <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span></b> had made and unswervingly follow whatever instructions he had given. The formulation first appeared in a joint editorial published on February 7, 1977, in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Daily\"><i>People's Daily</i></span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army_Daily\"><i>People's Liberation Army Daily</i></span>, only months <b>after <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Death_and_state_funeral_of_Mao_Zedong\">Mao's death</span> in September 1976</b> and the arrest of the radical <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gang_of_Four\">Gang of Four</span> that October. It was advanced by supporters of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hua_Guofeng\">Hua Guofeng</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chairman_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Party Chairman</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Premier_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">Premier</span> whose authority rested almost entirely on Mao's personal blessing, and it served both to legitimize his succession and to preserve <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maoism\">Maoist</span> orthodoxy intact. The line became the rallying point of the so-called Whatever Faction, which included the security chief <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Dongxing\">Wang Dongxing</span> and the <b>Beijing leader <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wu_De\">Wu De</span></b>, men who had risen during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span> and feared any reversal of its verdicts. By insisting on the literal infallibility of Mao's words, the doctrine implicitly upheld the purge of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1976_Tiananmen_Incident\">Tiananmen Incident</span> of 1976 and reinforced the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cult_of_personality\">personality cult</span> that the late chairman had inspired. <br> <br> The slogan was directly challenged by Deng Xiaoping, who upon his rehabilitation in July 1977 argued that <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong_Thought\">Mao Zedong Thought</span></b>, the Chinese adaptation of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marxism–Leninism\">Marxism–Leninism</span>, had to be applied as an integrated whole rather than as literal dogma, reviving the older maxim of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Seeking_truth_from_facts\">seeking truth from facts</span>. This pragmatic position was <b>reinforced by the influential 1978 essay</b> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Practice_Is_the_Sole_Criterion_for_Testing_Truth\"><i>Practice Is the Sole Criterion for Testing Truth</i></span>, which appeared in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangming_Daily\"><i>Guangming Daily</i></span> and was championed by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Yaobang\">Hu Yaobang</span> through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Party_School_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Central Party School</span>, igniting a nationwide debate that steadily eroded the Whateverists' standing. Deng's faction prevailed at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"3rd_Plenary_Session_of_the_11th_Central_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">3rd Plenary Session of the 11th Central Committee</span></b> in December 1978, the gathering conventionally regarded as the launch of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">Reform and Opening Up</span> era and of Deng's program of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Modernizations\">Four Modernizations</span>. Backed by elder statesmen such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Yun\">Chen Yun</span>—newly restored to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_Standing_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo Standing Committee</span>—and the marshal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ye_Jianying\">Ye Jianying</span>, the reformers pressed ahead with the sweeping <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boluan_Fanzheng\">Boluan Fanzheng</span> reversal of Cultural Revolution policies, and Hua Guofeng was progressively stripped of his posts and eased from power by 1981. The repudiation of the doctrine thus marked a decisive ideological break, shifting the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> away from rigid devotion to the dead leader's pronouncements and toward the experimental pragmatism of what would become <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialism_with_Chinese_characteristics\">socialism with Chinese characteristics</span> in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Republic_of_China\">People's Republic of China</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Two Whatevers"},{"id":"cnp-048","num":"四十八","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Designating the effort led by Deng Xiaoping from the late <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>s to reverse the verdicts of the Cultural Revolution and sideline the \"two whatevers\" line, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is named with a phrase meaning to eliminate chaos and return to normal.","answer":"Boluan Fanzheng","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">from 1977</span></div>","traditional":"撥亂反正","hanzi":"拨乱反正","pinyin":"Bōluàn fǎnzhèng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Bōluàn fǎnzhèng</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“eliminating chaos and returning to normal”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Boluan Fanzheng</b> designates the wide-ranging program of political and ideological correction pursued by Deng Xiaoping and his allies in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> from the <b>late 1970s</b>, an effort aimed at dismantling the radical legacy of the Cultural Revolution and discrediting the orthodox \"two whatevers\" upheld by Mao's designated successor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hua_Guofeng\">Hua Guofeng</span>. The phrase is a classical idiom drawn from the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gongyang_Zhuan\"><i>Gongyang Commentary</i></span></b> on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Spring_and_Autumn_Annals\"><i>Spring and Autumn Annals</i></span>, a Confucian classic traditionally associated with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucius\">Confucius</span>, in which it evoked the restoration of moral and political order to an age of turmoil. The disorder the slogan addressed was that of the decade-long upheaval set in motion by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>, an episode whose death toll modern scholarship estimates at between several hundred thousand and some 2 million, and which Marshal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ye_Jianying\">Ye Jianying</span> later suggested had ensnared as many as 100 million people. The death of Mao and the arrest of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gang_of_Four\">Gang of Four</span>—the radical clique that included <b>his widow <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Qing\">Jiang Qing</span>—in 1976</b> opened the way for change, and one of the earliest reversals was the 1977 restoration of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gaokao\">national college entrance examination</span>, which some 5.7 million candidates sat that winter and from which roughly 273,000 were admitted. The decisive ideological breakthrough arrived with the 1978 essay <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Practice_Is_the_Sole_Criterion_for_Testing_Truth\"><i>Practice Is the Sole Criterion for Testing Truth</i></span>, which furnished reformers with a weapon against Hua's dogmatism, and that December the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"3rd_Plenary_Session_of_the_11th_Central_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">3rd Plenary Session of the 11th Central Committee</span> confirmed Deng's ascendancy amid a brief flowering of public <b>debate at Beijing's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Democracy_Wall\">Democracy Wall</span></b>.<br> <br>Central to the practical work was <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Yaobang\">Hu Yaobang</span>, who as head of the party's Organization Department drove the systematic redress of \"unjust, false, and wrongful cases\" with the backing of the veteran planner <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Yun\">Chen Yun</span>, an undertaking that by the early 1980s had rehabilitated roughly 3 million cadres alongside countless ordinary citizens. The roughly 550,000 intellectuals branded as \"rightists\" in the <b>1957 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anti-Rightist_Campaign\">Anti-Rightist Campaign</span></b> had their labels lifted, the official verdict on the 1976 protests at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tiananmen_Square\">Tiananmen Square</span>—a mass mourning for the late premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Enlai\">Zhou Enlai</span>—was reversed in 1978, and the disgraced former head of state <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Shaoqi\">Liu Shaoqi</span> together with the general <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peng_Dehuai\">Peng Dehuai</span>, long condemned for criticizing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Leap_Forward\">Great Leap Forward</span>, were posthumously rehabilitated. The vast <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Down_to_the_Countryside_Movement\">Down to the Countryside Movement</span>, which had dispatched some 17 million urban youths to the countryside, was wound down, while the televised <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Trial_of_the_Gang_of_Four\">trial of the Gang of Four</span></b> over the winter of 1980–1981 fixed formal responsibility for the preceding decade of turmoil. The campaign culminated in the 1981 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Resolution_on_Certain_Questions_in_the_History_of_Our_Party_Since_the_Founding_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">Resolution on Party History</span>, which formally condemned the Cultural Revolution as a grave error while judging Mao to have been 70 percent correct and 30 percent wrong, and its conclusions were embedded the following year in the new <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitution_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">Constitution of 1982</span>. Beyond merely settling accounts, the effort reaffirmed the party's commitment to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marxism–Leninism\">Marxism–Leninism</span> while clearing the ground for the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Modernizations\">Four Modernizations</span></b> and the sweeping <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">reform and opening up</span>—soon embodied in the first <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Special_economic_zones_of_China\">special economic zones</span>—that, steered thereafter by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping_Theory\">Deng Xiaoping Theory</span>, would transform <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> into the proving ground of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialism_with_Chinese_characteristics\">socialism with Chinese characteristics</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Boluan Fanzheng"},{"id":"cnp-050","num":"五十","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Held in December <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> and widely regarded as the turning point that launched reform and opening up, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> marked the decisive ascendancy of Deng Xiaoping over Hua Guofeng.","answer":"3rd Plenary Session of the 11th Central Committee","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">December 1978</span></div>","traditional":"中國共產黨第十一屆中央委員會第三次全體會議","hanzi":"中国共产党第十一届中央委员会第三次全体会议","pinyin":"Zhōngguó Gòngchǎndǎng Dìshíyī Jiè Zhōngyāng Wěiyuánhuì Dìsān Cì Quántǐ Huìyì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōngguó Gòngchǎndǎng Dìshíyī Jiè Zhōngyāng Wěiyuánhuì Dìsān Cì Quántǐ Huìyì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>3rd Plenary Session of the 11th Central Committee</b> was a meeting of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Central Committee</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> held in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> <b>from December 18</b> to <b>22, 1978</b>. It is almost universally regarded as the pivotal turning point in the history of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Republic_of_China\">People's Republic of China</span>, marking the start of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">Reform and Opening Up</span> era and the effective beginning of the period of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>'s leadership. The session sealed the decisive ascendancy of Deng over the nominal party chairman <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hua_Guofeng\">Hua Guofeng</span>, whose <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Two_Whatevers\">Two Whatevers</span> had been discredited by the campaign affirming that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Practice_Is_the_Sole_Criterion_for_Testing_Truth\"><i>Practice Is the Sole Criterion for Testing Truth</i></span>. It was preceded by a lengthy central work conference, at whose close on December 13 Deng delivered his celebrated speech urging the party to emancipate the mind and to practice <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Seeking_truth_from_facts\">seeking truth from facts</span></b>, a clarion call widely treated as the true keynote of the reform program. Most fundamentally, the plenum repudiated the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maoism\">Maoist</span> insistence on perpetual <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Class_conflict\">class struggle</span> that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> had made the Party's central task, redirecting national energy toward economic construction and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Modernizations\">Four Modernizations</span>. <br> <br> Among its concrete decisions, the plenum launched the broad <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boluan_Fanzheng\">Boluan Fanzheng</span> process of reversing the verdicts of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span>, overturning the official condemnation <b>of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1976_Tiananmen_Incident\">Tiananmen Incident</span> of 1976</b> and opening the way for the rehabilitation of disgraced figures such as the late marshal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peng_Dehuai\">Peng Dehuai</span>. It substantially reshaped the leadership by elevating <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Yun\">Chen Yun</span> to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_Standing_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo Standing Committee</span>, adding <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Yaobang\">Hu Yaobang</span>, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Zhen_(general)\">Wang Zhen</span></b>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Yingchao\">Deng Yingchao</span> to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo</span>, and creating the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Commission_for_Discipline_Inspection\">Central Commission for Discipline Inspection</span> to rebuild party discipline. In economics the plenum set in motion changes that soon produced the rural <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Household-responsibility_system\">household responsibility system</span></b>—advanced by provincial reformers such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhao_Ziyang\">Zhao Ziyang</span>—and, within a few years, the earliest <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Special_economic_zones_of_China\">Special Economic Zones</span> created to attract foreign trade and investment. Although Hua Guofeng formally retained the chairmanship for a time, real authority now lay with Deng, who emerged as China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paramount_leader\">paramount leader</span> and saw the body that had been elected at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"11th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">11th National Congress</span></b> in 1977 reoriented decisively behind his program. The decisions taken over those December days are conventionally treated as the foundation of decades of rapid growth and of the doctrine later codified as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialism_with_Chinese_characteristics\">socialism with Chinese characteristics</span>, making the session one of the most consequential gatherings in modern Chinese history.","citation":"","answerText":"3rd Plenary Session of the 11th Central Committee"},{"id":"cnp-051","num":"五十一","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Inaugurated at a pivotal <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> Party plenum and associated above all with Deng Xiaoping, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> dismantled much of the planned economy, welcomed foreign investment, and transformed the country while preserving rule by the Communist Party.","answer":"Reform and Opening Up","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1978</span></div>","traditional":"改革開放","hanzi":"改革开放","pinyin":"Gǎigé kāifàng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Gǎigé kāifàng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Reform and Opening Up</b> was the sweeping programme of economic transformation inaugurated by Deng Xiaoping <b>at the close of 1978</b>, which gradually dismantled China's Soviet-style command system in favour <b>of a market-oriented <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialist_market_economy\">socialist market economy</span></b> while leaving the political monopoly of the Communist Party firmly intact. Conceived as a decisive break with the economic devastation and ideological rigidity bequeathed by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Leap_Forward\">Great Leap Forward</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span>, the new line prevailed over the orthodoxy of Mao's chosen heir <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hua_Guofeng\">Hua Guofeng</span> at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"3rd_Plenary_Session_of_the_11th_Central_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">3rd Plenary Session of the 11th Central Committee</span> in December 1978, and was justified by Deng's pragmatic maxim that the colour of a cat mattered less than its ability to catch mice. Reform began in the countryside, where the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Household_responsibility_system\">household responsibility system</span></b>—pioneered when 18 farmers in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anhui\">Anhui</span> village of Xiaogang secretly divided their land in 1978—allowed families to farm individually and sell their surplus instead of pooling labour in the collective <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_commune\">people's communes</span>, helping to raise grain output by roughly a third within six years. A second pillar was <b>the establishment in 1980</b> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Special_economic_zones_of_China\">special economic zones</span> at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shenzhen\">Shenzhen</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuhai\">Zhuhai</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shantou\">Shantou</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangdong\">Guangdong</span>, together with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiamen\">Xiamen</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fujian\">Fujian</span>, where foreign capital and export manufacturing were welcomed and which turned Shenzhen from a border town of some 30,000 people into a metropolis of well over 10 million. Inward <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foreign_direct_investment\">foreign direct investment</span> and a rapid proliferation of rural <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Township_and_village_enterprises\">township and village enterprises</span></b> propelled growth through the 1980s under reform-minded leaders such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Yaobang\">Hu Yaobang</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhao_Ziyang\">Zhao Ziyang</span>, even as the cautious elder <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Yun\">Chen Yun</span> warned that the market ought to be confined like a bird within the cage of state planning.<br> <br>Momentum <b>stalled in 1989</b>, when the violent suppression of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1989_Tiananmen_Square_protests_and_massacre\">Tiananmen Square protests</span> brought down Zhao Ziyang and emboldened conservatives who blamed liberalisation for the unrest. The ensuing retrenchment was reversed by Deng's celebrated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Southern_Tour\">Southern Tour</span> of early 1992, during which the 87-year-old leader visited Shenzhen and other zones to demand bolder change, and that autumn the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"14th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">14th National Congress</span> formally</b> adopted the goal of a socialist market economy. Under Deng's successor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Zemin\">Jiang Zemin</span> and the reforming premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_Rongji\">Zhu Rongji</span>, the state overhauled loss-making public enterprises and steered the country into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Trade_Organization\">World Trade Organization</span> in 2001, binding its economy ever more tightly to global markets. Over roughly three decades, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gross_domestic_product\">gross domestic product</span> expanded at an average rate approaching 10 percent a year, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Bank\">World Bank</span> credited the reforms with lifting more than 800 million people out of extreme poverty, and by 2010 the country had overtaken Japan to become the world's second-largest <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">economy</span>. Codified within the party's canon as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping_Theory\">Deng Xiaoping Theory</span> and the wider doctrine of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialism_with_Chinese_characteristics\">socialism with Chinese characteristics</span>, the policy fulfilled the long-deferred promise of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Modernizations\">Four Modernizations</span> and has remained the cornerstone of national strategy even as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span> has tempered its market liberalism with a renewed insistence on state and party control.","citation":"","answerText":"Reform and Opening Up"},{"id":"cnp-053","num":"五十三","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Appearing in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>–<span class=\"blank\">_____</span> as a brick wall in Beijing where citizens posted big-character posters demanding reform, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was suppressed after activists such as Wei Jingsheng called for democracy as a \"fifth modernisation\" under the new policies of Deng Xiaoping.","answer":"Democracy Wall","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Origin</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Named for the wall at Xidan, Beijing, where notices were posted, 1978–79</span></div>","traditional":"民主牆","hanzi":"民主墙","pinyin":"Mínzhǔ Qiáng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Mínzhǔ Qiáng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Democracy Wall</b> was a long brick wall on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xidan\">Xidan</span> Street in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xicheng_District\">Xicheng District</span></b> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> that, <b>from late 1978</b>, became the focal point of an unprecedented outpouring of public political expression. Ordinary citizens covered it with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Big-character_poster\">big-character posters</span>, poems, and essays that criticized the recent past and demanded democracy, legal rights, and the redress of grievances, repurposing a propaganda form made ubiquitous during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span>. The phenomenon flourished amid the political thaw that accompanied the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"3rd_Plenary_Session_of_the_11th_Central_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">3rd Plenum</span> of December 1978 and the launch of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">reform and opening up</span>, and was at first tolerated by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> because many posters attacked the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gang_of_Four\">Gang of Four</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Two_Whatevers\">Two Whatevers</span>, and his rival <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hua_Guofeng\">Hua Guofeng</span>. Together with samizdat journals and the wider ferment known as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing_Spring\">Beijing Spring</span>, it nurtured a literary revival led by the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Misty_Poets\">Misty Poets</span></b> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bei_Dao\">Bei Dao</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mang_Ke\">Mang Ke</span>, whose magazine helped define a generation of unofficial culture. Among the activists drawn to the wall were the human-rights campaigner <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ren_Wanding\">Ren Wanding</span>, founder of an early rights league, the editor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xu_Wenli\">Xu Wenli</span>, and above all the young Beijing Zoo electrician <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wei_Jingsheng\">Wei Jingsheng</span></b>, who would become the movement's most famous and most enduring voice. <br> <br> On December 5, 1978, Wei posted his celebrated essay <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Fifth_Modernization\"><i>The Fifth Modernization</i></span>, contending that democracy was the indispensable fifth goal without which the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Modernizations\">Four Modernizations</span> of agriculture, industry, defense, and science promoted by the leadership could never truly succeed. As the posters grew bolder—Wei went so far as to warn that Deng, by now the nation's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paramount_leader\">paramount leader</span>, might become a new dictator—the authorities moved to curb a movement that had begun to challenge the rule of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> itself. <b>In March 1979 Deng</b> enunciated the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Cardinal_Principles\">Four Cardinal Principles</span>, demanding adherence to the socialist road, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_democratic_dictatorship\">people's democratic dictatorship</span>, the leadership of the party, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marxism–Leninism\">Marxism–Leninism</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong_Thought\">Mao Zedong Thought</span>, thereby fixing the boundaries beyond which dissent would not be permitted. Wei was arrested that same month and sentenced to 15 years' imprisonment on charges of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Counter-revolutionary\">counter-revolutionary</span> activity, including the alleged leaking of intelligence about the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-Vietnamese_War\">Sino-Vietnamese War</span>, and by the end of 1979 the wall's postings were relocated to an obscure, tightly controlled park before the right to display such posters was struck from the constitution <b>of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Republic_of_China\">People's Republic of China</span> in 1980</b>. Though short-lived, the episode stands as one of the earliest organized expressions of the post-Mao <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_democracy_movement\">Chinese democracy movement</span> and a clear forerunner of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1989_Tiananmen_Square_protests_and_massacre\">Tiananmen Square protests</span> a decade later, while Wei Jingsheng, who endured many further years in prison before his exile, came to embody the <b>struggle for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Human_rights_in_China\">human rights in China</span></b>.","citation":"","answerText":"Democracy Wall"},{"id":"cnp-056","num":"五十六","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Spreading through the countryside in the early <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>s and effectively dismantling the collective communes, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> let farming families contract land, meet a state quota, and sell any surplus, sharply raising agricultural output under Deng Xiaoping.","answer":"Household responsibility system","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Origin</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Emerged among rural households in Anhui and Sichuan, c. 1978–81</span></div>","traditional":"家庭聯產承包責任制","hanzi":"家庭联产承包责任制","pinyin":"jiātíng liánchǎn chéngbāo zérènzhì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">jiātíng liánchǎn chéngbāo zérènzhì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>household responsibility system</b> was a framework of agricultural organization adopted across rural China at the start of the 1980s that decisively dismantled the collective <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_commune\">people's communes</span></b> created during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Leap_Forward\">Great Leap Forward</span> under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>. Under the arrangement, farmland remained the property of the village <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Collective_farming\">collective</span>, but individual <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peasant\">peasant</span> families received contracted <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Usufruct\">use rights</span> over specific plots, pledged to deliver a fixed quota of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Grain\">grain</span> to the state, and were free to keep or sell on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Market_economy\">market</span> whatever surplus they grew beyond that obligation. The model is widely traced to a clandestine pact signed in late 1978 by 18 families in the village of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiaogang,_Anhui\">Xiaogang</span>, in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fengyang_County\">Fengyang County</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anhui\">Anhui</span> province, who secretly divided communal fields among themselves at the risk of severe punishment. Provincial leaders such as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wan_Li\">Wan Li</span></b> in Anhui and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhao_Ziyang\">Zhao Ziyang</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sichuan\">Sichuan</span> tolerated and then championed such experiments, and after <b>the landmark <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"3rd_Plenary_Session_of_the_11th_Central_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Third Plenum</span> of December 1978 set</b> the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Communist Party</span> on a reformist course, the leadership of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>—prevailing over the more cautious <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hua_Guofeng\">Hua Guofeng</span> and orthodox planners like <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Yun\">Chen Yun</span>—endorsed the practice as a centerpiece of national policy. What began as a local deviation spread with remarkable speed, so that the share of households operating under family contracting rose from <b>a negligible fraction in 1979</b> to roughly 98 percent of <b>the rural population by 1984</b>, when the commune system was formally replaced by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Townships_of_China\">township</span> governments. <br> <br> The reform produced an immediate and dramatic surge in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Agriculture_in_China\">Chinese agriculture</span>, as national grain output climbed from about 305 million tonnes (336 million tons) in 1978 to roughly 407 million tonnes (449 million tons) in 1984 and rural per-capita income more than doubled, sharply reducing the deprivation that had culminated in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Chinese_Famine\">Great Chinese Famine</span> of the commune era. Economists have attributed much of this gain to the restoration of work incentives, and an influential study by <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Justin_Yifu_Lin\">Justin Yifu Lin</span></b> estimated that decollectivization accounted for roughly half of the growth in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Total_factor_productivity\">total factor productivity</span> in farming between 1978 and 1984. The system formed the agricultural pillar of the broader program of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">economic reform</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Modernizations\">Four Modernizations</span>, complementing urban initiatives such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Special_economic_zones_of_China\">special economic zones</span> and signaling a decisive turn away from the rigid <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Planned_economy\">command economy</span> inherited from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span>. Freed from collective labor obligations and able to profit from their own effort, hundreds of millions of rural workers were gradually released into off-farm activity, fueling the explosive growth of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Township_and_village_enterprises\">township and village enterprises</span> and accelerating the wider <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Decollectivization\">decollectivization</span> of the countryside</b>. Land contracts initially granted for short terms were later extended to 15 and then 30 years to encourage investment, and although debates over fragmented plots and insecure tenure persisted, the household responsibility system is widely regarded as the opening act of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialism_with_Chinese_characteristics\">socialism with Chinese characteristics</span> and one of the most consequential rural reforms in the modern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">economic history of China</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Household responsibility system"},{"id":"cnp-054","num":"五十四","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Set out by Deng Xiaoping in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> as non-negotiable limits on liberalisation, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> demanded adherence to the socialist road, the people's democratic dictatorship, the leadership of the Communist Party, and Marxism–Leninism–Mao Zedong Thought.","answer":"Four Cardinal Principles","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1979</span></div>","traditional":"四項基本原則","hanzi":"四项基本原则","pinyin":"Sì xiàng jīběn yuánzé","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Sì xiàng jīběn yuánzé</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Four Cardinal Principles</b> were the ideological boundaries laid down by Deng <b>Xiaoping in 1979</b> to mark the outer limits of permissible liberalisation as China embarked on its sweeping <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">economic reforms</span>. The doctrine demanded unwavering fidelity to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialism\">socialist</span> road, the people's democratic dictatorship—the Chinese variant of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dictatorship_of_the_proletariat\">dictatorship of the proletariat</span></b>—the leadership of the Communist Party, and the ideological canon of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marxism–Leninism\">Marxism–Leninism</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maoism\">Mao Zedong Thought</span>, each of them placed beyond the reach of public challenge. Deng first enunciated them in a speech of 30 March 1979 to a party conference on theoretical work, intending them as a conservative counterweight both to the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boluan_Fanzheng\">unwinding of past verdicts</span></b> after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span> and to the market opening that he was himself driving as he eclipsed the more orthodox <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hua_Guofeng\">Hua Guofeng</span>. Their immediate target was the political ferment of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Democracy_Wall\">Democracy Wall</span> movement, part of a brief liberal interlude known as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing_Spring\">Beijing Spring</span>, during which the activist <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wei_Jingsheng\">Wei Jingsheng</span></b> had demanded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liberal_democracy\">democracy</span> as a \"<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Fifth_Modernization\"><i>fifth modernisation</i></span>\" beyond the regime's official <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Modernizations\">Four Modernizations</span> before his arrest and 15-year sentence later that year. Framed as the bedrock separating acceptable change from \"bourgeois liberalisation,\" the principles drew their authority from the revolutionary tradition of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Karl_Marx\">Karl Marx</span>, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vladimir_Lenin\">Vladimir Lenin</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>, and from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Leninism\">Leninist</span> insistence on the party as the sole <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vanguardism\">vanguard</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Proletariat\">working class</span>.<br> <br>The doctrine was written into the preamble of the <b>revised state <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitution_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">Constitution</span> in 1982</b>, lending it a permanence that the era's economic experiments conspicuously lacked. At the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"13th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">13th National Congress</span> of 1987 the principles were fused with reform into the party's \"basic line\" for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Primary_stage_of_socialism\">primary stage of socialism</span>, a formula summarised as \"one centre, two basic points\" in which economic construction formed the centre, flanked by the principles on one side and the open-door reforms on the other. They furnished the rationale for recurrent campaigns against ideological deviation, <b>from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anti-Spiritual_Pollution_Campaign\">Anti-Spiritual Pollution Campaign</span> of 1983</b> to the drive against \"bourgeois liberalisation\" that, after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1986_Chinese_student_demonstrations\">student demonstrations of 1986</span>, forced the resignation of the reformist general secretary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Yaobang\">Hu Yaobang</span> in 1987. They were invoked again to justify the crushing of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1989_Tiananmen_Square_protests_and_massacre\">Tiananmen Square protests</span> in 1989, a turn that ended the career of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhao_Ziyang\">Zhao Ziyang</span> and was vigorously reaffirmed by his successor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Zemin\">Jiang Zemin</span>. Still embedded in the constitution and the party's guiding canon alongside <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping_Theory\">Deng Xiaoping Theory</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialism_with_Chinese_characteristics\">socialism with Chinese characteristics</span>, the principles have been reasserted with particular vigour under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span>, for whom the unchallengeable primacy of the party remains the organising axiom of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>'s politics.","citation":"","answerText":"Four Cardinal Principles"},{"id":"cnp-055","num":"五十五","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"First established in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> in places such as Shenzhen near Hong Kong, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> offered tax incentives and market freedoms to attract foreign capital as a laboratory for economic reform.","answer":"Special Economic Zone","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">from 1980</span></div>","traditional":"經濟特區","hanzi":"经济特区","pinyin":"jīngjì tèqū","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">jīngjì tèqū</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Special Economic Zones</b> were designated coastal districts in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span> granted exceptional autonomy, tax concessions, and market freedoms in order to attract <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foreign_direct_investment\">foreign direct investment</span></b> and serve as controlled laboratories for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">economic reform</span>. Championed by the paramount leader <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>, the first four zones were <b>inaugurated in 1980</b> at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shenzhen\">Shenzhen</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuhai\">Zhuhai</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shantou\">Shantou</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangdong\">Guangdong</span> province and at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiamen\">Xiamen</span> in neighbouring <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fujian\">Fujian</span>, their coastal locations chosen to harness capital from nearby <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Macau\">Macau</span>, and the wider <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Overseas_Chinese\">overseas Chinese</span> diaspora. Their legal basis was codified when the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Standing_Committee_of_the_National_People's_Congress\">Standing Committee of the National People's Congress</span> approved special regulations for Guangdong in August 1980, a reform vigorously advocated by the provincial party chief <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Zhongxun\">Xi Zhongxun</span></b>, who pressed Beijing for the latitude to experiment. Within the zones the rigid mechanisms of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Planned_economy\">planned economy</span> were relaxed in favour of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Market_economy\">market</span> principles, with enterprises enjoying preferential corporate tax rates of 15 percent, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tariff\">duty-free imports</span>, flexible labour and land arrangements, and <b>streamlined approval for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joint_venture\">joint ventures</span></b> with foreign firms. Conceived as windows onto the global economy and engines of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Export-oriented_industrialization\">export-oriented industrialisation</span>, the zones allowed the leadership to test <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capitalism\">capitalist</span> methods on a confined scale while shielding the broader socialist system from their disruptive effects. <br> <br> The most spectacular transformation occurred in Shenzhen, a modest border settlement of roughly 30,000 inhabitants that mushroomed within four decades into a megacity of more than 17 million and a global technology hub home to corporate giants such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tencent\">Tencent</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huawei\">Huawei</span>, whose output came to surpass that <b>of Hong Kong around 2018</b>. Encouraged by these results, the government extended the experiment by opening <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Open_Coastal_Cities\">fourteen coastal cities</span> to foreign investment in 1984, designating the entire island province of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hainan\">Hainan</span> as the largest such zone in 1988, and later developing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pudong\">Pudong</span> district of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span> along similar lines. These zones were administratively distinct from the later <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Special_administrative_regions_of_China\">special administrative regions</span> of Hong Kong</b> and Macau, yet together they formed the leading edge of a strategy that progressively integrated the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">Chinese economy</span> into global commerce. By concentrating infrastructure, foreign expertise, and capital, the zones came to account for a disproportionate share of the nation's exports and inbound investment, attracting tens of billions of dollars in foreign capital and accelerating the rise of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pearl_River_Delta\">Pearl River Delta</span> as the world's preeminent manufacturing region. Widely emulated by developing economies seeking to replicate China's growth, the special economic zone became one of the most influential policy instruments of the late 20th century and a defining emblem of the pragmatic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialism_with_Chinese_characteristics\">socialism with Chinese characteristics</span> that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping_Theory\">Deng's reforms</span> bequeathed to the nation.","citation":"","answerText":"Special Economic Zone"},{"id":"cng-073","num":"七十三","category":"China · Geography","question":"A fishing town transformed into a tech metropolis after being made the flagship special economic zone in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is now a global hub of electronics and innovation.","answer":"Shenzhen","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">SEZ from 1980</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"深圳","pinyin":"Shēnzhèn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Shēnzhèn</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“deep drainage ditch,”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Shenzhen</b> is a metropolis in southern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangdong\">Guangdong</span> province directly bordering <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span>, celebrated as the flagship of China’s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">reform era</span> <b>after its designation in 1980</b> as the first <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Special_economic_zones_of_China\">special economic zone</span>. Chosen by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> precisely for its position across the border from capitalist Hong Kong, the area then held perhaps 300,000 people in fishing and farming communities around the old market town near the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Luohu_District\">Luohu</span></b> crossing, a frontier so stark that thousands had risked the swim to Hong Kong in earlier decades to escape poverty. In little more than 40 years it exploded into a city of roughly 17.5 million, often called the fastest urbanisation in history, its growth embodied by skyscrapers such as the 599-metre (1,970 ft) <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ping_An_International_Finance_Centre\">Ping An International Finance Centre</span></b> and by an economy whose output now rivals or exceeds Hong Kong’s. Anchoring the eastern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pearl_River_Delta\">Pearl River Delta</span>, the city is the world’s electronics workshop, home to the sprawling <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huaqiangbei\">Huaqiangbei</span> component markets and to the headquarters of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huawei\">Huawei</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tencent\">Tencent</span>, the drone maker <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"DJI\">DJI</span>, the electric-vehicle and battery giant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"BYD\">BYD</span>, and the insurer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ping_An_Insurance\">Ping An</span>, alongside the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shenzhen_Stock_Exchange\">Shenzhen Stock Exchange</span> <b>founded in 1990</b>. Its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Port_of_Shenzhen\">port</span> ranks among the world’s busiest container harbours, its bus and taxi fleets became the first in any major city to go fully <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Electric_vehicle\">electric</span>, and its research spending, patent filings, and maker culture have earned it the nickname of China’s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silicon_Valley\">Silicon Valley</span>. <br> <br> The region’s deeper past belies the “instant city” legend, for the walled town of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nantou_(historic_town)\">Nantou</span> administered the area for some 1,700 years and the coast is dotted with fortified <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hakka_walled_village\">Hakka walled villages</span> such as those of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hakka_people\">Hakka</span> settlers who arrived under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing</span>. The frontier itself dates <b>from 1898</b>, when Britain’s lease of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Territories\">New Territories</span> drew the boundary along the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sham_Chun_River\">Sham Chun River</span> from which the city takes its name, and the railway station on that line made Shenzhen the gateway between Hong Kong and the mainland. After 1980 the zone pioneered practices then radical in socialist China, from land auctions and labour markets to foreign joint ventures, proclaimed by the local slogan that “time is money, efficiency is life,” and its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shekou\">Shekou</span> industrial district <b>under the reformer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_Geng\">Yuan Geng</span></b> became a national symbol of opening. Migrants from every province built the boom, first in toy, garment, and electronics plants typified by the giant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foxconn\">Foxconn</span> complex at Longhua that assembles much of the world’s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"IPhone\">iPhones</span>, making Shenzhen a city of newcomers where <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mandarin_Chinese\">Mandarin</span> rather than the local <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cantonese\">Cantonese</span> dominates. Deng defended the experiment during his <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping's_southern_tour\">1992 southern tour</span>, propelling a second boom that shifted the city from cheap assembly toward research and finance, and in 2019 the central government anointed it a “pilot demonstration area” of socialist modernisation at the heart of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangdong–Hong_Kong–Macau_Greater_Bay_Area\">Greater Bay Area</span>, even as soaring housing costs and its role in <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Science_and_technology_in_China\">China’s technology rise</span></b> placed it at the centre of global trade and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China–United_States_trade_war\">tech tensions</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Shenzhen"},{"id":"cne-017","num":"十七","category":"China · Economics","question":"Introduced around <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> and enforced for over 3 decades through fines, sterilisations and abortions, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> curbed births but accelerated an ageing society and a skewed sex ratio, weighing on the labour force.","answer":"One-child policy","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1980–2015</span></div>","traditional":"獨生子女政策","hanzi":"独生子女政策","pinyin":"dúshēng zǐnǚ zhèngcè","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">dúshēng zǐnǚ zhèngcè</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>one-child policy</b> was a sweeping <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Human_population_planning\">population-control</span></b> programme implemented across <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> <b>from around 1979</b>, under the leadership of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>, restricting the majority of couples to a single child as the centrepiece of the country's broader <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Family_planning\">family-planning</span> system. It emerged from official anxiety that rapid demographic expansion — the population had surged from roughly 540 million in 1949 to nearly 970 million by the late 1970s after <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> had earlier discouraged birth control — would overwhelm <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">economic development</span> and the country's scarce resources. The programme's technocratic design drew on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cybernetics\">cybernetic</span> population modelling advanced by the missile scientist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_Jian\">Song Jian</span>, who was influenced by the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Club_of_Rome\">Club of Rome's</span></b> 1972 report <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Limits_to_Growth\"><i>The Limits to Growth</i></span>, and it built upon the earlier \"Later, Longer, Fewer\" campaign that had already cut fertility sharply in the 1970s. Indeed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Total_fertility_rate\">total fertility rate</span> had already fallen from about 5.8 children per woman in 1970 to roughly 2.7 by 1979, leading many demographers to argue that the decline preceding the policy owed more to that prior campaign and to rising development than to the one-child rules themselves. Enforcement relied on a system of birth quotas administered by local cadres of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Population_and_Family_Planning_Commission\">family-planning bureaucracy</span></b> and backed by punitive fines, the denial of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hukou\">household registration</span> that left some children undocumented as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heihaizi\">heihaizi</span>, and, in numerous documented cases, coercive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sterilization_(medicine)\">sterilisations</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Forced_abortion\">forced abortions</span> that drew sustained criticism on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Human_rights_in_China\">human-rights</span> grounds, though rural households and recognised <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ethnic_minorities_in_China\">ethnic minorities</span> were frequently permitted a second child. <br> <br> Among its most striking consequences was a severely skewed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sex_ratio\">sex ratio</span> at birth, which a deep-rooted preference for sons combined with the spread of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Medical_ultrasound\">ultrasound</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sex-selective_abortion\">sex-selective abortion</span> pushed to around 118 boys per 100 girls by the mid-2000s, well above the natural norm of about 105. This imbalance produced what scholars have termed tens of millions of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Missing_women\">missing women</span> — <b>partly through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Female_infanticide\">female infanticide</span></b> and abandonment — and a surplus of more than 30 million young men sometimes called <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guanggun\">bare branches</span>, fuelling concerns about marriage markets and social instability. The collapse in births simultaneously accelerated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Population_ageing\">population ageing</span> and the erosion of China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Demographic_dividend\">demographic dividend</span>, as the working-age <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Workforce\">labour force</span> peaked around 2013 and a \"4-2-1\" family structure left single children responsible for two parents and four grandparents. Chinese authorities long claimed the policy had prevented some 400 million births, a figure widely disputed by independent demographers, and as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sub-replacement_fertility\">sub-replacement fertility</span> took hold — the fertility rate sinking toward 1.5 and later close to 1.0 — the government relaxed the rules in 2013 before replacing them with a universal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Two-child_policy\">two-child policy</span> <b>announced in 2015</b> and effective the following year. When even these measures failed to lift birth rates, a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three-child_policy\">three-child policy</span> <b>followed in 2021</b>, yet the long demographic shadow persisted as China's total population began to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Demographics_of_China\">decline</span> in 2022 for the first time in six decades and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"India\">India</span> overtook it as the world's most populous nation the following year.","citation":"","answerText":"One-child policy"},{"id":"cnp-057","num":"五十七","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Coined in the early <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>s and serving as the umbrella phrase for the Party's ideology ever since, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> justifies market mechanisms and private enterprise as compatible with socialism under the leadership of the Communist Party, as theorised by Deng Xiaoping.","answer":"Socialism with Chinese characteristics","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Coined</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Deng Xiaoping, opening the 12th Party Congress, 1982</span></div>","traditional":"中國特色社會主義","hanzi":"中国特色社会主义","pinyin":"Zhōngguó tèsè shèhuìzhǔyì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōngguó tèsè shèhuìzhǔyì</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Socialism with Chinese characteristics</b> has served since the early 1980s as the official umbrella term for the ideology of the Communist Party, reconciling market mechanisms and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Private_sector\">private enterprise</span> with continued one-party rule in the name of socialism. The phrase was coined by Deng Xiaoping in his address <b>opening the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"12th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">12th National Congress</span> in September 1982</b>, and it was <b>anchored in 1987</b> in the theory of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Primary_stage_of_socialism\">primary stage of socialism</span>, elaborated under General Secretary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhao_Ziyang\">Zhao Ziyang</span>, which held that a still-underdeveloped China would remain at an initial stage of socialism for around 100 years. Its economic substance crystallised in the \"<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialist_market_economy\">socialist market economy</span>\" <b>adopted in 1992</b>, a hybrid order in which a competitive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Market_economy\">market</span> and a thriving private sector operate alongside dominant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_enterprise\">state-owned enterprises</span> and pervasive party direction of the economy. Presented as a creative adaptation of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marxism\">Marxism</span> to national conditions rather than a repudiation of it, the formulation discarded the rigid <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Soviet</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Planned_economy\">planned economy</span> and has often been compared by scholars to <b>Lenin's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Economic_Policy\">New Economic Policy</span></b> and to other variants of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Market_socialism\">market socialism</span>. Its proponents drew a sharp contrast with the economic ruin of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Leap_Forward\">Great Leap Forward</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span>, and after <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Communism\">communism</span> fell across Eastern Europe in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Revolutions_of_1989\">revolutions of 1989</span></b> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dissolution_of_the_Soviet_Union\">Soviet Union was dissolved</span>, the model was credited with allowing the party to survive where its fraternal counterparts had perished.<br> <br>The doctrine was formally codified as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping_Theory\">Deng Xiaoping Theory</span>, and it has since functioned as an elastic banner beneath which each successive leader has been permitted to inscribe his own contribution. <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Zemin\">Jiang Zemin</span> added the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Represents\">Three Represents</span>, which opened party membership to private entrepreneurs, while <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Jintao\">Hu Jintao</span> contributed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Scientific_Outlook_on_Development\">Scientific Outlook on Development</span> and the goal of a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Harmonious_Society\">harmonious society</span></b>. Under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"19th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">19th National Congress</span> of 2017 proclaimed that socialism with Chinese characteristics had entered a \"new era,\" enshrining <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping_Thought\">Xi Jinping Thought</span> in the party's constitution beside the doctrines of his predecessors. By the 2010s the private sector that the doctrine had legitimised was generating more than 60 percent of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gross_domestic_product\">gross domestic product</span> and over 80 percent of urban employment, helping to make China the world's second-largest <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">economy</span> while the ruling party itself swelled to some 99 million members. Western analysts frequently characterise the resulting system as a <b>form of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_capitalism\">state capitalism</span></b> in which <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capitalism\">capitalist</span> methods serve authoritarian ends, whereas its official exponents present it as the only viable path to national rejuvenation, and the phrase endures as the ideological keystone of the People's Republic of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Socialism with Chinese characteristics"},{"id":"cnp-058","num":"五十八","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Promulgated in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> and remaining the basic law in force today, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> restored the office of head of state, strengthened the National People's Congress, and reflected the priorities of the reform era launched by Deng Xiaoping.","answer":"1982 Constitution","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">4 December 1982</span></div>","traditional":"中華人民共和國憲法","hanzi":"中华人民共和国宪法","pinyin":"Zhōnghuá Rénmín Gònghéguó Xiànfǎ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōnghuá Rénmín Gònghéguó Xiànfǎ</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>1982 Constitution</b> is the fourth and current fundamental law of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span>, adopted by <b>the Fifth <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_People's_Congress\">National People's Congress</span> on 4 December 1982</b> and remaining in force, with amendments, to the present day. It superseded the <b>three earlier charters of 1954</b>, 1975, and 1978, the radical 1975 version having been thoroughly shaped by the upheaval of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span>, and its drafting—overseen by a revision committee chaired by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ye_Jianying\">Ye Jianying</span> with the veteran jurist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peng_Zhen\">Peng Zhen</span> directing the practical work—marked a decisive break with that turbulent past. Among its most consequential reforms was the restoration of the ceremonial office of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"President_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">head of state</span>, a post that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> had left vacant after the persecution of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Shaoqi\">Liu Shaoqi</span> and that the <b>1975 constitution</b> had abolished altogether. The new text substantially strengthened the legislature, expanding the powers of the National People's Congress and its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Standing_Committee_of_the_National_People's_Congress\">Standing Committee</span> and reinforcing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_Council_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">State Council</span> headed by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Premier_of_China\">premier</span>, while also establishing a state <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Military_Commission_(China)\">Central Military Commission</span> to oversee the armed forces. Reflecting the priorities of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">reform era</span> launched by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>, it foregrounded a chapter on the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fundamental_rights\">fundamental rights</span></b> and duties of citizens, emphasised <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rule_of_law\">socialist legality</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Modernizations\">Four Modernizations</span>, and affirmed in its preamble both the leadership of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Cardinal_Principles\">Four Cardinal Principles</span></b>. <br> <br> Structured around a lengthy preamble and four chapters covering general principles, citizens' rights, the organisation of state organs, and national symbols such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Flag_of_China\">national flag</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"March_of_the_Volunteers\">anthem</span>, the document comprises 138 articles in its original form. It has been formally amended on five occasions, in 1988, 1993, 1999, 2004, and 2018, a <b>process of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitutional_amendment\">constitutional amendment</span></b> that progressively constitutionalised the market reforms by recognising the private economy, enshrining the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialist_market_economy\">socialist market economy</span> in 1993, and incorporating <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping_Theory\">Deng Xiaoping Theory</span> in 1999. The fourth revision of 2004 added landmark clauses declaring that the state respects and protects <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Human_rights\">human rights</span></b> and guarantees lawful <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Private_property\">private property</span>, while also writing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Represents\">Three Represents</span> doctrine of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Zemin\">Jiang Zemin</span> into the preamble. The far-reaching 2018 amendment proved especially contentious, abolishing the two-consecutive-<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Term_limit\">term limit</span> on the presidency and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vice_President_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">vice presidency</span>, elevating <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping_Thought\">Xi Jinping Thought</span> to constitutional status, and creating a powerful new <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Supervisory_Commission\">National Supervisory Commission</span> to combat corruption. Although critics note that its guarantees coexist with the unchallengeable supremacy of the party and that it lacks robust mechanisms of judicial review, the charter under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span> remains the formal cornerstone of the Chinese state, its enduring authority symbolically affirmed each year on the National Constitution Day observed since 2014.","citation":"","answerText":"1982 Constitution"},{"id":"cne-055","num":"五十五","category":"China · Economics","question":"One of the giant oil-and-gas groups carved out of the state ministries and listed in the early <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>s, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> ranks among the world's largest companies by revenue and competes with rivals such as PetroChina under the supervision of state asset managers in the energy sector.","answer":"Sinopec","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">founded 1983</span></div>","traditional":"中國石油化工集團","hanzi":"中国石油化工集团","pinyin":"Zhōngguó Shíyóu Huàgōng Jítuán","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōngguó Shíyóu Huàgōng Jítuán</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Sinopec</b>, officially the <b>China Petroleum &amp; Chemical Corporation</b>, is a <b>giant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_enterprises_of_China\">state-owned</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Petroleum_industry\">oil, gas, and petrochemical</span></b> group in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> and one of the largest companies in the world. It traces its origins to the China Petrochemical Corporation founded in 1983 to consolidate the country's scattered refining and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Petrochemical\">petrochemical</span> assets, which had previously been administered directly by industrial ministries such as the petroleum ministry under the old planned economy. In a sweeping reorganisation <b>of the sector in 1998</b>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_Council_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">State Council</span> swapped assets to create two vertically integrated majors—Sinopec and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_National_Petroleum_Corporation\">China National Petroleum Corporation</span>—divided roughly along north–south lines, alongside the offshore specialist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"CNOOC_Group\">CNOOC</span>. Through this <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vertical_integration\">vertical integration</span> Sinopec leaned toward the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Downstream_(petroleum_industry)\">downstream</span> end of the business—<b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Oil_refinery\">refining</span></b> crude into fuels, manufacturing chemicals, and marketing finished products—while its principal rival concentrated more heavily on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Upstream_(petroleum_industry)\">upstream</span> exploration and production, though both groups operate across the whole chain. As a central enterprise overseen by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_Assets_Supervision_and_Administration_Commission\">State-owned Assets Supervision and Administration Commission</span> in the era of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">reform and opening up</span>, it became the country's dominant refiner and fuel retailer, operating tens of thousands of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Filling_station\">service stations</span> selling <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gasoline\">petrol</span> and diesel. <br> <br> Its main subsidiary, China Petroleum &amp; Chemical Corporation, was <b>floated in 2000</b> with simultaneous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Initial_public_offering\">listings</span> on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_Stock_Exchange\">Hong Kong</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_York_Stock_Exchange\">New York</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"London_Stock_Exchange\">London</span> exchanges in one of the era's larger share sales, followed by a domestic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"A-share_(mainland_China)\">A-share</span> <b>listing in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_Stock_Exchange\">Shanghai</span> in 2001</b>, even as the state retained a controlling majority. The company consistently ranks among the very <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"List_of_largest_companies_by_revenue\">largest firms in the world by revenue</span>, climbing as high as second on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fortune_Global_500\">Fortune Global 500</span>, and is the world's largest oil refiner by processing capacity. In the domestic market it competes chiefly with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"PetroChina\">PetroChina</span>, the listed arm of its main rival, and with the offshore producer CNOOC in a tightly controlled <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Oligopoly\">oligopoly</span> of state-owned energy champions. Its sprawling operations span <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Petroleum\">crude oil</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Natural_gas\">natural gas</span> production, a vast refining and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chemical_industry\">chemical</span></b> manufacturing base, and pipeline and distribution networks that make it a linchpin of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Energy_in_China\">China's energy sector</span>. Headquartered in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> and employing several hundred thousand people, it stands alongside global giants such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Saudi_Aramco\">Saudi Aramco</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"ExxonMobil\">ExxonMobil</span> as one of the world's foremost energy corporations, embodying the rise of the state-controlled national champions that anchor the modern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">Chinese economy</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Sinopec"},{"id":"cne-019","num":"十九","category":"China · Economics","question":"Spun off in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> to handle urban commercial lending, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> grew into the largest of the \"Big Four\" banks and, by assets, one of the biggest in the world, listing shares in Hong Kong and Shanghai while remaining majority state-owned.","answer":"Industrial and Commercial Bank of China","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">founded 1984</span></div>","traditional":"中國工商銀行","hanzi":"中国工商银行","pinyin":"Zhōngguó Gōngshāng Yínháng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōngguó Gōngshāng Yínháng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Industrial and Commercial Bank of China</b> is the largest <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Commercial_bank\">commercial bank</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> and, by total <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Asset\">assets</span></b>, among the largest <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bank\">banks</span> in the world. It was <b>created on 1 January 1984</b> when the urban industrial and commercial lending and deposit business of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Bank_of_China\">People's Bank of China</span> was spun off into a separate institution, allowing the People's Bank to function purely as a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_bank\">central bank</span></b> within a new two-tier banking system established during <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">reform and opening up</span>. Alongside the older <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bank_of_China\">Bank of China</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Construction_Bank\">China Construction Bank</span>, and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Agricultural_Bank_of_China\">Agricultural Bank of China</span></b>, it became one of the \"Big Four\" specialised state lenders—each originally assigned its own sphere of the economy—that together came to dominate <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Banking_in_China\">Chinese banking</span> and channel credit on behalf of the state. Headquartered in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>, it concentrated initially on financing urban industrial and commercial enterprises and the savings of city households, and over the following decades it expanded into a sprawling retail and corporate network spanning tens of thousands of domestic branches and operations in dozens of countries. Although later partly listed, it has always remained a majority <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_enterprises_of_China\">state-owned enterprise</span>, an instrument of policy as much as a profit-seeking lender and a central pillar of the wider <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">Chinese economy</span>. <br> <br> Like its peers, the bank was saddled in the late 1990s with enormous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Non-performing_loan\">non-performing loans</span> accumulated from years of directed policy lending to ailing state firms, and the government cleaned up its balance sheet through transfers of bad debt to asset-management companies and large injections of capital before it was reorganised <b>as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joint-stock_company\">joint-stock company</span> in 2005</b>. In October 2006 it staged a simultaneous dual <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Initial_public_offering\">listing</span> on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_Stock_Exchange\">Hong Kong</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_Stock_Exchange\">Shanghai</span> exchanges that raised roughly $22 billion, the largest initial public offering in the world at the time, after foreign strategic investors including <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Goldman_Sachs\">Goldman Sachs</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Allianz\">Allianz</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"American_Express\">American Express</span> had taken pre-flotation stakes. Control nonetheless stayed firmly with the state, exercised through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Huijin_Investment\">Central Huijin Investment</span>, a unit of the sovereign-wealth fund <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Investment_Corporation\">China Investment Corporation</span>, together with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ministry_of_Finance_(China)\">Ministry of Finance</span>, which between them retain a clear controlling majority of the shares even after the public flotation. By the 2010s it ranked as the world's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"List_of_largest_banks\">largest bank</span> by assets and by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tier_1_capital\">tier-1 capital</span>, holding the top spot in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Banker\">The Banker</span>'s global rankings for over a decade and repeatedly heading the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Forbes_Global_2000\">Forbes Global <b>2000</span> list</b> of the world's biggest public companies. With total assets exceeding $6 trillion, more than 700 million personal customers, and a workforce of over 400,000, the bank is designated a globally <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Systemically_important_financial_institution\">systemically important</span> institution by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Financial_Stability_Board\">Financial Stability Board</span>, its sheer scale—measured in tens of trillions of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Renminbi\">renminbi</span>—making it a cornerstone of China's state-dominated financial system.","citation":"","answerText":"Industrial and Commercial Bank of China"},{"id":"cne-020","num":"二十","category":"China · Economics","question":"Founded in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> in the coastal city of Qingdao and famously turning around a failing refrigerator plant, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> grew into one of the world's largest makers of home appliances and acquired the appliance arm of America's General Electric.","answer":"Haier","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">founded 1984</span></div>","traditional":"海爾","hanzi":"海尔","pinyin":"Hǎi'ěr","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Hǎi'ěr</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Haier</b> is a Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Multinational_corporation\">multinational</span> manufacturer of home appliances and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Consumer_electronics\">consumer electronics</span></b>, headquartered in the coastal city of Qingdao in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shandong\">Shandong</span> province. It was <b>founded in 1984</b>, in the early years of China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">economic reform</span>, out of a debt-ridden and nearly bankrupt collective <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Refrigerator\">refrigerator</span></b> factory whose fortunes were transformed by its new director, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Ruimin\">Zhang Ruimin</span>. That same year the plant licensed technology from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Germany\">German</span> firm <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liebherr_Group\">Liebherr</span>—from whose Chinese transliteration the brand name was later coined—as it set out to modernize its primitive production. Its reputation was forged in a <b>celebrated 1985 episode</b> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Quality_control\">quality control</span>, when Zhang ordered workers to destroy 76 defective refrigerators with sledgehammers—smashing the first himself—to drive home an uncompromising standard of workmanship. From this base it expanded far beyond refrigerators into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Washing_machine\">washing machines</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Air_conditioning\">air conditioners</span>, and a full line of household goods, building a reputation as a quality-driven <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Brand\">brand</span></b> across the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">Chinese economy</span>.<br> <br>Embracing the government's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Go_Out_policy\">\"go out\" strategy</span>, Haier expanded abroad early, opening a manufacturing <b>plant in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South_Carolina\">South Carolina</span> in 1999</b> and building its own brand in foreign markets rather than merely producing for others. A wave of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mergers_and_acquisitions\">acquisitions</span> followed, beginning with the appliance business of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japan\">Japan</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sanyo\">Sanyo</span> in 2011 and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Zealand\">New Zealand</span> maker <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fisher_&amp;_Paykel\">Fisher &amp; Paykel</span></b> in 2012. In 2016 it made its most prominent purchase, acquiring the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"GE_Appliances\">appliance arm</span> of America's General Electric for about $5.6 billion, and in 2019 it added the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Italy\">Italian</span> maker <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Candy_(company)\">Candy</span>. Such expansion helped make it one of the world's largest appliance manufacturers—ranked the top-selling major-appliance brand globally for more than a decade—and a fixture on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fortune_Global_500\">Fortune Global 500</span>, with its flagship listed as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Public_company\">public company</span> on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_Stock_Exchange\">Shanghai</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_Stock_Exchange\">Hong Kong</span> exchanges. Under Zhang Ruimin it became renowned for a distinctive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Business_model\">business model</span> dubbed \"rendanheyi,\" which dissolved the firm into thousands of self-managed micro-units accountable directly to customers and drew the attention of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Harvard_Business_School\">Harvard Business School</span>, while in recent years it has pushed into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Internet_of_things\">internet-of-things</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Home_automation\">smart-home</span> technologies.","citation":"","answerText":"Haier"},{"id":"cne-022","num":"二十二","category":"China · Economics","question":"Spun out of the Chinese Academy of Sciences in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> and originally named Legend, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> became the world's biggest seller of personal computers after buying the PC division of IBM in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>, a landmark in the \"going out\" drive to build global multinationals.","answer":"Lenovo","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">founded 1984</span></div>","traditional":"聯想","hanzi":"联想","pinyin":"Liánxiǎng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Liánxiǎng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Lenovo</b> is a Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Multinational_corporation\">multinational</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Technology_company\">technology company</span> best known as the world's <b>largest maker of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Personal_computer\">personal computers</span></b> and a major producer of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tablet_computer\">tablets</span>, smartphones, and servers, with annual revenue of around 60 billion dollars. It was <b>founded in 1984</b> when a group of 11 researchers led by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Chuanzhi\">Liu Chuanzhi</span> spun a venture out of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Academy_of_Sciences\">Chinese Academy of Sciences</span></b> in Beijing's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhongguancun\">Zhongguancun</span> district, starting in a cramped guardhouse with roughly 200,000 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Renminbi\">yuan</span>—about 25,000 dollars—of state-provided capital under the original English name Legend. Initially importing and distributing foreign machines and add-on Chinese-language cards before manufacturing its own computers, it grew into China's dominant home-computer brand and floated in an <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Initial_public_offering\">initial public offering</span> <b>on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_Stock_Exchange\">Hong Kong Stock Exchange</span> in 1994</b>. In 2003 it retired the Legend name in favour of \"Lenovo,\" a coined <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Brand\">brand</span> fusing the \"Le\" of Legend with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Latin\">Latin</span> novo, meaning new, in preparation for an international expansion the domestic name could not easily carry abroad. Its controlling shareholder is the partly state-linked <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Legend_Holdings\">Legend Holdings</span>, a legacy of its origins inside the state research system that gives the firm a hybrid public-and-private ownership structure, with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yang_Yuanqing\">Yang Yuanqing</span> serving for decades as its chairman and chief executive. <br> <br> Lenovo <b>gained global prominence in 2005</b> when it acquired the personal-computer division of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"IBM\">IBM</span> for about 1.25 billion dollars, a deal that brought it the prestigious <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"ThinkPad\">ThinkPad</span> line and a worldwide sales network, propelling it overnight into the front rank of global PC makers. The purchase was a landmark of China's \"<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Go_Out_policy\">going out</span>\" strategy, a state campaign launched around the turn of the century to encourage domestic firms to undertake outbound <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foreign_direct_investment\">foreign investment</span> and build globally competitive multinationals through cross-border <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mergers_and_acquisitions\">acquisitions</span>, at a time when few Chinese brands were known internationally. By around 2013 it had overtaken <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hewlett-Packard\">Hewlett-Packard</span> to become the world's biggest seller of personal computers, commanding around 25 percent of the global <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Market_share\">market</span> and shipping tens of millions of machines a year while holding the top spot for much of the following decade. It expanded beyond PCs through two further purchases in 2014, buying <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Motorola_Mobility\">Motorola Mobility</span></b> from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Google\">Google</span> for about 2.9 billion dollars to enter the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Smartphone\">smartphone</span> business and acquiring IBM's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"X86\">x86</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Server_(computing)\">server</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Data_center\">data-centre</span> operations for some 2.1 billion dollars. Today it employs well over 70,000 people, operates in some 180 countries from twin headquarters in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Morrisville,_North_Carolina\">Morrisville, North Carolina</span></b>, ranks on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fortune_Global_500\">Fortune Global 500</span>, and stands as a leading symbol of Chinese corporate <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Globalization\">globalization</span> under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">reform</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Lenovo"},{"id":"cnp-063","num":"六十三","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Held in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> under the brief leadership of Zhao Ziyang, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> endorsed bolder political and economic reform and formally advanced the theory that China remained at an early stage of building socialism.","answer":"13th National Congress of the CCP","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1987</span></div>","traditional":"中國共產黨第十三次全國代表大會","hanzi":"中国共产党第十三次全国代表大会","pinyin":"Zhōngguó Gòngchǎndǎng Dìshísān Cì Quánguó Dàibiǎo Dàhuì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōngguó Gòngchǎndǎng Dìshísān Cì Quánguó Dàibiǎo Dàhuì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>13th National Congress of the CCP</b> was a landmark assembly of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> held in 1987, widely regarded as the most reform-minded and politically liberal of the congresses convened since the death of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>, and the one that carried furthest the reform agenda begun <b>at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"12th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">12th National Congress</span> of 1982</b>. It convened in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> from late <b>October</b> <b>to early November 1987</b>, bringing together some 1,936 delegates who represented a party of around 46 million members, and it confirmed Zhao Ziyang—newly risen to the top after the fall of his predecessor—as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"General_Secretary_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">general secretary</span>, the office from which he delivered the central political report. After the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1986_Chinese_student_demonstrations\">student demonstrations of <b>1986</b></span> provoked a conservative campaign against \"bourgeois liberalisation,\" the reformist general secretary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Yaobang\">Hu Yaobang</span> was forced to resign in January 1987, clearing the path for Zhao's rise to the leadership. The congress is remembered above all for its systematic formulation of the theory of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Primary_stage_of_socialism\">primary stage of socialism</span>, an adaptation of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marxism\">Marxist</span> stage theory which held that China, still economically backward in the aftermath of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span>, would occupy an initial phase of socialism lasting roughly 100 years and must therefore concentrate on developing its <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Productive_forces\">productive forces</span></b> through market-oriented reform and diversified ownership. From this premise it derived the party's \"basic line\" for the era, summarised as \"one centre, two basic points,\" in which economic construction formed the centre, flanked by adherence to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Cardinal_Principles\">Four Cardinal Principles</span> on one side and to reform and opening up on the other.<br> <br>On the economic front the congress endorsed a bolder opening of the economy, advocating a \"planned commodity economy\" that widened the role of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Market_economy\">market</span></b> well beyond the bounds of the orthodox <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Planned_economy\">planned economy</span>, a step on the road toward the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialist_market_economy\">socialist market economy</span> proclaimed at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"14th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">14th National Congress</span> in 1992. Zhao went further still in the political sphere, making the congress the high-water mark of 1980s liberalisation by championing a programme of political structural reform that aimed at separating the party from the day-to-day organs of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politics_of_China\">government</span>, trimming the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bureaucracy\">bureaucracy</span>, and widening consultation within the party itself. A sweeping generational change accompanied these ideas: the veteran <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> stepped down from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Central Committee</span> while keeping the decisive chairmanship of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Military_Commission_(China)\">Central Military Commission</span>, the elder economist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Yun\">Chen Yun</span> took over the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Advisory_Commission\">Central Advisory Commission</span></b>, and a compact five-member <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_Standing_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo Standing Committee</span> formed around Zhao, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Peng\">Li Peng</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qiao_Shi\">Qiao Shi</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Qili\">Hu Qili</span>, with Li soon installed as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Premier_of_China\">premier</span>. This brief season of reform was abruptly foreclosed by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1989_Tiananmen_Square_protests_and_massacre\">Tiananmen Square protests</span> of 1989, after which Zhao was placed under house arrest for opposing the crackdown, the political reform agenda was shelved, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Zemin\">Jiang Zemin</span> was installed in his place. Its political experiments were thus buried within two years, yet the doctrine it had proclaimed endured, becoming a permanent foundation of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping_Theory\">Deng Xiaoping Theory</span> and the wider edifice of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialism_with_Chinese_characteristics\">socialism with Chinese characteristics</span> by which the party would continue to govern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"13th National Congress of the CCP"},{"id":"cnp-064","num":"六十四","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Formalised as theory at the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> Party congress to justify market reforms over a long horizon, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> holds that an economically underdeveloped China must spend a prolonged era building the productive forces before advanced socialism or communism can be reached under the Communist Party.","answer":"Primary stage of socialism","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Coined</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Formalized at the 13th Party Congress, 1987</span></div>","traditional":"社會主義初級階段","hanzi":"社会主义初级阶段","pinyin":"shèhuì zhǔyì chūjí jiēduàn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">shèhuì zhǔyì chūjí jiēduàn</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>primary stage of socialism</b> is a theoretical concept in the ideology of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> which holds that the economically underdeveloped <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span> must pass through a prolonged historical phase of building its <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Productive_forces\">productive forces</span></b> before a more advanced <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialism\">socialism</span> and ultimately <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Communism\">communism</span> can be attained. Rooted in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marxism\">Marxist</span> theory of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Historical_materialism\">historical materialism</span>, the doctrine adapts the developmental schema of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Karl_Marx\">Karl Marx</span> by contending that a country which had not completed capitalist industrialisation could not leap directly into developed socialism, but must first expand its <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Means_of_production\">means of production</span></b> and transform its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Relations_of_production\">relations of production</span> over the course of many decades. Although the phrase had surfaced <b>earlier in the party's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Resolution_on_Certain_Questions_in_the_History_of_Our_Party_Since_the_Founding_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">1981 resolution on its own history</span></b> and in reports to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"12th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">12th Congress</span> of 1982, the theory was systematically formalised at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"13th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">13th National Congress</span> in 1987, where the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"General_Secretary_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">general secretary</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhao_Ziyang\">Zhao Ziyang</span> expounded it as the ideological cornerstone of the entire reform programme. According to that congress, the primary stage would last for at least 100 years, dating from the completion of the socialist <b>transformation of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Private_property\">private ownership</span> around 1956</b> to the basic attainment of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Modernizations\">socialist modernisation</span> projected for the middle of the 21st century. By defining China as still developmentally immature, the doctrine furnished a powerful rationale for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>'s embrace of markets, foreign capital, and private enterprise, while implicitly condemning the utopian attempts to force-march the nation toward communism during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Leap_Forward\">Great Leap Forward</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span>. <br> <br> Central to the formulation was a redefinition of the principal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"On_Contradiction\">contradiction</span> facing Chinese society, recast as the tension between the people's ever-growing material and cultural needs and the country's backward social production, a shift that elevated economic construction above <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Class_struggle\">class struggle</span></b> as the party's overriding task. This priority was enshrined in what the party termed its basic line, summarised in the slogan 'one centre and two basic points'—treating economic development as the centre while simultaneously upholding the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Cardinal_Principles\">Four Cardinal Principles</span> and the policy of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">reform and opening up</span>. The theory thereby legitimised the gradual construction of a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialist_market_economy\">socialist market economy</span></b> in place of rigid central <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Planned_economy\">planning</span>, and it became tightly interwoven with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping_Theory\">Deng Xiaoping Theory</span> and the wider banner of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialism_with_Chinese_characteristics\">socialism with Chinese characteristics</span>. It likewise represented a sober retreat from the more triumphal <b>Soviet rhetoric of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Developed_socialism\">developed socialism</span></b>, returning to a cautious reading of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marxism–Leninism\">Marxism–Leninism</span> that earlier leaders such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> had at times overlooked in their impatience for an egalitarian future. Far from being discarded as the economy boomed, the concept was reaffirmed by the successive leaderships of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Zemin\">Jiang Zemin</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Jintao\">Hu Jintao</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span> has continued to insist that the country remains in the primary stage even while proclaiming a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping_Thought\">'new era'</span> of socialism, leaving the theory among the most durable ideological pillars of the modern Chinese state.","citation":"","answerText":"Primary stage of socialism"},{"id":"cne-029","num":"二十九","category":"China · Economics","question":"Founded in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> in Shenzhen and growing into a global leader in telecoms equipment and 5G, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> became a flashpoint in the tech rivalry with the United States, facing sanctions over security fears.","answer":"Huawei","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">founded 1987</span></div>","traditional":"華為","hanzi":"华为","pinyin":"Huáwéi","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Huáwéi</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Huawei</b> is a Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Multinational_corporation\">multinational</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Technology_company\">technology company</span> and one of the world's <b>largest makers of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Telecommunications_equipment\">telecommunications equipment</span></b>, as well as a major producer of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Smartphone\">smartphones</span>, a provider of cloud services, and a leader in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"5G\">5G</span> technology that has at times been the world's largest seller of handsets. It was <b>founded in 1987</b> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shenzhen\">Shenzhen</span> by <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ren_Zhengfei\">Ren Zhengfei</span></b>, a former engineer in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army\">People's Liberation Army</span>, with about 21,000 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Renminbi\">yuan</span> of capital, initially reselling imported <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Telephone_exchange\">telephone switches</span> before developing its own and winning contracts in China's underserved rural telecom market. Riding China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Go_Out_policy\">going-out</span> drive, it expanded first across Africa, the Middle East, and other developing regions and then worldwide, growing into the planet's <b>largest supplier of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cellular_network\">mobile-network</span></b> gear, ahead of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ericsson\">Ericsson</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nokia\">Nokia</span>, and a leading force in 5G standards and patents. Unusually for a firm of its size, it is privately held and unlisted, describing itself as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Employee_stock_ownership\">employee-owned</span> through a shareholding scheme in which Ren retains only about 1 percent, an opaque structure that critics in the West suspect could mask state influence, a charge the company strenuously denies. <b>By 2020 its</b> revenue approached 140 billion dollars, making it one of China's largest companies, and it employed nearly 200,000 people, more than half of them in research, ranking among the world's heaviest spenders on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Research_and_development\">research and development</span>—over 20 billion dollars a year—while operating in more than 170 countries. <br> <br> Huawei became the central flashpoint in the technology <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China–United_States_trade_war\">rivalry between China and the United States</span>, as Washington and other governments warned that its network equipment could serve as a channel for state <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Espionage\">espionage</span> or contain hidden <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Backdoor_(computing)\">backdoors</span> threatening critical infrastructure, charges the company has consistently denied. These fears, amplified by Ren's military background and a Chinese <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Intelligence_Law_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">national intelligence law</span></b> obliging companies to cooperate with state security, led the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States\">United States</span> to press its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five_Eyes\">Five Eyes</span> allies, including the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_Kingdom\">United Kingdom</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Australia\">Australia</span>, to bar Huawei from their 5G networks, fracturing the global telecom-equipment market along geopolitical lines. Tensions <b>sharpened in December 2018</b> with the arrest in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Canada\">Canada</span> of the company's chief financial officer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Meng_Wanzhou\">Meng Wanzhou</span>, the founder's daughter, on a US <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Extradition\">extradition</span> request alleging that Huawei had violated American sanctions on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Iran\">Iran</span>, a case that escalated into a diplomatic crisis. Months later, in 2019, the administration of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Donald_Trump\">Donald Trump</span> placed Huawei on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Entity_List\">Entity List</span>, a trade blacklist, imposing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economic_sanctions\">sanctions</span> that cut it off from American technology, stripping its handsets of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Google\">Google</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Android_(operating_system)\">Android</span> services and, through later rules, barring it from buying advanced <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Semiconductor\">semiconductors</span> made anywhere with American equipment. With foundries such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"TSMC\">TSMC</span> forced to halt production of its chips, Huawei's consumer business slumped, prompting it to sell its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Honor_(brand)\">Honor</span> sub-brand in 2020 and build its own <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"HarmonyOS\">HarmonyOS</span> operating system; although Meng was freed in 2021, the firm's resilience was underlined by a 2023 smartphone powered by a domestically fabricated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Semiconductor_Manufacturing_International_Corporation\">SMIC</span> chip that suggested it could weather the deepening tech war.","citation":"","answerText":"Huawei"},{"id":"cne-056","num":"五十六","category":"China · Economics","question":"The state-owned parent group that floated its main subsidiary as PetroChina, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is one of the country's largest state-owned enterprises and a leading developer of overseas oilfields tied to the drive for energy security.","answer":"China National Petroleum Corporation","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">founded 1988</span></div>","traditional":"中國石油天然氣集團有限公司","hanzi":"中国石油天然气集团有限公司","pinyin":"Zhōngguó Shíyóu Tiānránqì Jítuán Yǒuxiàn Gōngsī","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōngguó Shíyóu Tiānránqì Jítuán Yǒuxiàn Gōngsī</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“China Petroleum and Natural Gas Group”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>China National Petroleum Corporation</b>, widely known as <b>CNPC</b>, is the foremost producer of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Petroleum\">petroleum</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Natural_gas\">natural gas</span> in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span> and one of the country's most powerful state-owned enterprises. Its domestic resource base centres on long-developed deposits such as the oil fields of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Daqing\">Daqing</span>, <b>discovered in 1959</b> and for decades the largest in the nation, and it stands alongside <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sinopec\">Sinopec</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_National_Offshore_Oil_Corporation\">China National Offshore Oil Corporation</span> as one of the three dominant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_oil_company\">national oil companies</span> that organise the Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Energy_industry\">energy industry</span>. The corporation was <b>established in 1988</b> upon the dissolution of the former Ministry of Petroleum Industry, answers ultimately to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_Council_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">State Council</span> through the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_Assets_Supervision_and_Administration_Commission\">State-owned Assets Supervision and Administration Commission</span></b>, carries the administrative rank of a government ministry, and maintains its headquarters in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>. A perennial fixture among the five largest companies in the world by revenue on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fortune_Global_500\">Fortune Global 500</span> and a pillar of the wider <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">Chinese economy</span>, it employs roughly 1.4 million people and accounts for the bulk of the country's domestic crude-oil production. <b>In 2000</b> the group floated most of its core assets in an <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Initial_public_offering\">initial public offering</span> of the subsidiary PetroChina, whose shares debuted on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_Stock_Exchange\">Hong Kong Stock Exchange</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_York_Stock_Exchange\">New York Stock Exchange</span> while the parent retained roughly 86 percent of the equity, and a further listing on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_Stock_Exchange\">Shanghai Stock Exchange</span> in 2007 briefly lifted PetroChina's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Market_capitalization\">market capitalisation</span> above one trillion dollars.<br> <br>The corporation's expansion abroad was driven by a pivotal shift in 1993, when China became a net importer of crude oil for the first time, and reinforced by the state's subsequent <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Go_Out_policy\">\"Go Out\" policy</span></b> urging national champions to invest overseas. Functioning as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Multinational_corporation\">multinational</span> instrument of national energy policy, CNPC acquired or developed oilfields across <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kazakhstan\">Kazakhstan</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Turkmenistan\">Turkmenistan</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Iraq\">Iraq</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Venezuela\">Venezuela</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Iran\">Iran</span>, frequently entering markets that Western majors avoided. Its most prominent and most criticised venture unfolded in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sudan\">Sudan</span>, where it spearheaded the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Greater_Nile_Petroleum_Operating_Company\">Greater Nile Petroleum Operating Company</span></b> amid prolonged civil war, an involvement that drew international censure and grew more tangled after the secession of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South_Sudan\">South Sudan</span> in 2011. To deliver these supplies homeward, the firm constructed or co-owns major arteries including the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kazakhstan–China_oil_pipeline\">Kazakhstan–China oil pipeline</span> and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Asia–China_gas_pipeline\">Central Asia–China gas pipeline</span></b>, infrastructure progressively folded into the sprawling <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Belt_and_Road_Initiative\">Belt and Road Initiative</span>. Commanding upstream <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hydrocarbon_exploration\">exploration</span>, refining at numerous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Oil_refinery\">refineries</span>, and an extensive grid of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pipeline_transport\">pipelines</span>, the enterprise endures as a cornerstone of Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_capitalism\">state capitalism</span> and a principal instrument through which the leadership pursues the long-term security of the nation's energy supply.","citation":"","answerText":"China National Petroleum Corporation"},{"id":"cnp-066","num":"六十六","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Sparked by the death of Hu Yaobang and growing into mass calls for reform, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> centred on a square in Beijing ended when the army cleared the demonstrators with deadly force on 4 June.","answer":"1989 Tiananmen Square protests and massacre","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1989</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"六四事件","pinyin":"Liùsì shìjiàn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Liùsì shìjiàn</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“June Fourth Incident”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>1989 Tiananmen Square protests and massacre</b> was a student-led pro-democracy movement that occupied <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tiananmen_Square\">Tiananmen Square</span> at the heart of the Chinese capital for some seven weeks in the <b>spring of 1989</b> before being crushed by the military in one of the most consequential episodes in the modern history of China. The unrest was ignited by the death on 15 April 1989 of Hu Yaobang, the reformist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"General_Secretary_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">general secretary</span> who had been forced from office two years earlier after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1986_Chinese_student_demonstrations\">student protests of <b>1986</b></span>, as mourners gathered in the square to honour him and to voice the grievances his fall had come to symbolise. Within weeks the mourning swelled into mass demonstrations—led by student activists such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuer_Kaixi\">Wuer Kaixi</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Dan_(dissident)\">Wang Dan</span>—that demanded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Democracy\">democracy</span>, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Freedom_of_the_press\">freedom of the press</span></b>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rule_of_law\">rule of law</span>, and an end to official <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Corruption_in_China\">corruption</span>, spread to some 400 cities, and were inflamed by a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Daily\">People's Daily</span> editorial of 26 April that condemned the unrest as \"turmoil\" directed against the party. A <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hunger_strike\">hunger strike</span></b> begun on 13 May coincided with a state visit by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soviet_Union\">Soviet</span> leader <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mikhail_Gorbachev\">Mikhail Gorbachev</span>—the first such summit since the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-Soviet_split\">Sino-Soviet split</span>—which drew the world's media to the capital just as the crowds swelled to perhaps a million, and art students soon raised a \"<b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Goddess_of_Democracy\">Goddess of Democracy</span></b>\" before the assembled throng. The crisis laid bare a fissure at the top: <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhao_Ziyang\">Zhao Ziyang</span>, the sympathetic general secretary, opposed the use of force and made a tearful final appearance among the demonstrators, only to be overruled by the hardline premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Peng\">Li Peng</span>, the president <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yang_Shangkun\">Yang Shangkun</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paramount_leader\">paramount leader</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>, who with the party <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight_Elders_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">elders</span> imposed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Martial_law\">martial law</span> on 20 May.<br> <br>On the night of 3–4 June, columns of tanks and infantry advanced into central Beijing, firing on civilians along <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chang'an_Avenue\">Chang'an Avenue</span></b> as they forced their way to the square and expelled the last protesters before dawn. The number of dead has never been established and remains fiercely contested, with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Government_of_China\">Chinese government</span> acknowledging some 200 to 300 fatalities while independent estimates have ranged from several hundred to several thousand. The episode produced one of the 20th century's defining images, that of the lone \"<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tank_Man\">Tank Man</span>\" who halted a column of armour on the avenue the following day. In the purge that followed, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Zemin\">Jiang Zemin</span> was raised to lead the party, Western governments imposed lasting <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Arms_embargo\">arms embargoes</span>, and a conservative chill descended that was dispelled only <b>by Deng's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Southern_Tour\">Southern Tour</span> of 1992</b> and the revival of the stalled <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">economic reforms</span>, while Zhao remained under house arrest until his death in 2005. Inside China the massacre became one of the most rigorously <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Censorship_in_China\">censored</span> subjects in public life, its memory kept alive instead by exiles and imprisoned dissidents such as the future Nobel laureate <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Xiaobo\">Liu Xiaobo</span> and by an annual candlelight vigil in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span> that was itself suppressed under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_national_security_law\">national security law</span> imposed after 2020, leaving the event an enduring emblem of the limits the ruling party places on dissent in the People's Republic of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"1989 Tiananmen Square protests and massacre"},{"id":"cne-032","num":"三十二","category":"China · Economics","question":"Reopened in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> after being shut for 4 decades under the planned economy, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> — based in the financial capital and home to many large state-owned enterprises — became one of the world's largest by value, overseen by the securities regulator.","answer":"Shanghai Stock Exchange","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">founded 1990</span></div>","traditional":"上海證券交易所","hanzi":"上海证券交易所","pinyin":"Shànghǎi Zhèngquàn Jiāoyìsuǒ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Shànghǎi Zhèngquàn Jiāoyìsuǒ</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Shanghai Stock Exchange</b> is the principal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stock_exchange\">stock exchange</span> of mainland <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>, a non-profit institution in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span> on which <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Security_(finance)\">securities</span></b> in many of the country's largest companies are traded. Shanghai had been East Asia's foremost financial centre before 1949, with a stock exchange operating from the late 19th century, but its securities markets were abolished after the Communist victory and lay dormant for some 40 years under the centrally <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Planned_economy\">planned economy</span> that treated share trading as incompatible with socialism. The modern exchange was <b>founded on 26 November 1990</b> and began trading that December with just 8 listed companies, a milestone of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">reform era</span> that coincided with the parallel creation of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shenzhen_Stock_Exchange\">Shenzhen Stock Exchange</span>. Oversight passed to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Securities_Regulatory_Commission\">China Securities Regulatory Commission</span> <b>after its establishment in 1992</b>, the same year that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Southern_Tour\">Southern Tour</span> reaffirmed market reform and lent political legitimacy to the nascent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capital_market\">capital markets</span>. Trading was divided between <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"A-share_(mainland_China)\">A-shares</span> denominated in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Renminbi\">renminbi</span> and originally reserved for domestic investors and foreign-currency B-shares introduced for overseas buyers in 1992, a segmentation that long insulated the mainland market from global capital and left it dominated by retail rather than institutional investors. <br> <br> As China privatised and partially floated its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_enterprises_of_China\">state-owned enterprises</span>, the exchange hosted the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Initial_public_offering\">initial public offerings</span> of giants including <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"PetroChina\">PetroChina</span></b>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Industrial_and_Commercial_Bank_of_China\">Industrial and Commercial Bank of China</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sinopec\">Sinopec</span>, alongside the liquor maker <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kweichow_Moutai\">Kweichow Moutai</span>, which became one of its most valuable listings. <b>PetroChina's 2007 listing</b> was especially dramatic, briefly making it on paper the world's first company valued at roughly $1 trillion before its shares slumped over the following years, illustrating both the scale and the speculative excess of the young market. By the 2020s the exchange listed more than 2,000 companies and carried a combined <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Market_capitalization\">market capitalisation</span> of several trillion US dollars, placing it among the three or four largest in the world alongside the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_York_Stock_Exchange\">New York Stock Exchange</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nasdaq\">Nasdaq</span> and far exceeding most European venues. Its benchmark <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"SSE_Composite_Index\">SSE Composite Index</span></b>, set at a base value of 100 on its opening day in 1990, charted the market's extreme volatility through successive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stock_market_bubble\">bubbles</span>, peaking near 6,124 in October 2007 and again above 5,000 in mid-2015 before the violent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2015–2016_Chinese_stock_market_turbulence\">crash</span> of that year erased trillions in value. Gradual liberalisation followed, from the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qualified_Foreign_Institutional_Investor\">Qualified Foreign Institutional Investor</span></b> programme of 2002 to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stock_Connect\">Shanghai–Hong Kong Stock Connect</span> launched with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_Stock_Exchange\">Hong Kong exchange</span> in 2014 and the inclusion of A-shares in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"MSCI\">MSCI</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emerging_market\">emerging-market</span> indices from 2018, while the technology-focused <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"STAR_Market\">STAR Market</span> opened in 2019 within the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lujiazui\">Lujiazui</span> financial district of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pudong\">Pudong</span>, cementing the bourse's place at the heart of Chinese finance.","citation":"","answerText":"Shanghai Stock Exchange"},{"id":"cne-033","num":"三十三","category":"China · Economics","question":"Opened in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> in a city next to Hong Kong that had been a flagship special economic zone, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is policed by the securities watchdog.","answer":"Shenzhen Stock Exchange","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">founded 1990</span></div>","traditional":"深圳證券交易所","hanzi":"深圳证券交易所","pinyin":"Shēnzhèn Zhèngquàn Jiāoyìsuǒ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Shēnzhèn Zhèngquàn Jiāoyìsuǒ</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Shenzhen Stock Exchange</b> is one of mainland China's two principal <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stock_exchange\">stock exchanges</span></b>, situated in the southern city of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shenzhen\">Shenzhen</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangdong\">Guangdong</span> province, just across the boundary from Hong Kong. Shenzhen had been designated China's first and most celebrated <b>special economic zone in 1980</b>, a laboratory of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">economic reforms</span> whose torrent of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foreign_direct_investment\">foreign investment</span> transformed a cluster of fishing villages on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pearl_River_Delta\">Pearl River Delta</span> into a teeming <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Megacity\">megacity</span>. Against this backdrop the exchange began trading on <b>a trial basis in 1990</b> and was formally established in 1991, emerging alongside the larger <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_Stock_Exchange\">Shanghai Stock Exchange</span> as the second pillar of a reviving <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stock_market\">stock market</span> within the broader <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">Chinese economy</span>. Whereas Shanghai came to host many of the country's largest <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_enterprise\">state-owned</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Blue_chip_(stock_market)\">blue-chip</span></b> giants, the Shenzhen bourse developed a reputation for listing smaller, private, and fast-growing firms, a contrast that shaped the character of China's twin <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capital_market\">capital markets</span>. Its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Security_(finance)\">securities</span> are issued chiefly as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Renminbi\">renminbi</span>-denominated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"A-share_(mainland_China)\">A-shares</span> traded by domestic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Investor\">investors</span>, supplemented by foreign-currency B-shares, with prices tracked by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stock_market_index\">indices</span> such as the SZSE Component Index.<br> <br>The exchange has progressively widened its menu of markets, opening a <b>board for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Small_and_medium-sized_enterprises\">small and medium-sized enterprises</span> in 2004</b> and, in 2009, the technology-oriented <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"ChiNext\">ChiNext</span> board, frequently likened to the American <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nasdaq\">Nasdaq</span>. Cross-border access widened in 2016 with the launch of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stock_Connect\">Stock Connect</span> programme linking Shenzhen to the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_Exchanges_and_Clearing\">Hong Kong exchange</span></b> and admitting a measure of foreign capital to its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yuan_(currency)\">yuan</span>-denominated shares. ChiNext meanwhile became a magnet for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Startup_company\">start-ups</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Venture_capital\">venture-capital</span>-backed growth companies, hosting a wave of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Initial_public_offering\">initial public offerings</span> and adopting a <b>more market-based <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Listing_(finance)\">listing</span></b> regime in 2020. As a non-profit <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Self-regulatory_organization\">self-regulatory</span> institution, the bourse operates under the oversight of the national securities watchdog and, above it, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_Council_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">State Council</span>, which together set the rules governing listings and trading. Today it lists roughly 2,800 companies and ranks among the largest exchanges in the world by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Market_capitalization\">market capitalization</span>, cementing its place beside Shanghai at the heart of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>'s rapidly expanding financial system.","citation":"","answerText":"Shenzhen Stock Exchange"},{"id":"cnp-069","num":"六十九","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Undertaken in early <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> by a semi-retired Deng Xiaoping through cities including Shenzhen, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> revived stalled market reforms after the conservative retrenchment that followed <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>.","answer":"Southern Tour","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1992</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"南巡","pinyin":"nánxún","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">nánxún</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Southern Tour</b> refers to the series of inspection visits and informal speeches made by the 87-year-old <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paramount_leader\">paramount leader</span></b> <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> in early 1992</b>, an intervention widely regarded as the decisive act that rescued China's market <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">reforms</span> from political paralysis. In the aftermath of <b>the bloody <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1989_Tiananmen_Square_protests_and_massacre\">Tiananmen Square crackdown</span> of 1989</b> and the fall of reformist leaders such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhao_Ziyang\">Zhao Ziyang</span>, conservative <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eight_Elders_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">party elders</span> led by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Yun\">Chen Yun</span> and Premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Peng\">Li Peng</span> had imposed an austerity program and an ideological campaign, steeped in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maoism\">Maoist</span> orthodoxy, questioning whether the reforms were \"socialist\" or \"capitalist.\" Although he had relinquished his last formal post, the chairmanship of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Military_Commission_(China)\">Central Military Commission</span>, in 1989 and held no official government title, Deng retained immense personal authority within the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> and warned that the chief danger to China now lay on the political left rather than the right, fearing that the retreat from reform imperiled the project he had <b>launched in 1978</b>. Between January 18 and February 21, 1992, he undertook a 5-week journey through the south, traveling from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuhan\">Wuhan</span> to the boomtown of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shenzhen\">Shenzhen</span>—the pioneering <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Special_economic_zones_of_China\">special economic zone</span>, established in 1980 beside <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span>—and onward to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhuhai\">Zhuhai</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou\">Guangzhou</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span>. At every stop he pressed local officials to quicken the pace of liberalization, declaring that \"development is the only hard truth\" and brushing aside doctrinal disputes over whether a given policy was <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialism\">socialist</span> or <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capitalism\">capitalist</span>, since he held that both central <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Planned_economy\">planning</span> and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Market_economy\">market</span></b> were merely economic tools. <br> <br> The initiative was at first met with near silence from the central party press, including the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Daily\">People's Daily</span>, and only after reform-minded newspapers in the south publicized his remarks did General Secretary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Zemin\">Jiang Zemin</span> and the rest of the leadership, with the public <b>backing of President <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yang_Shangkun\">Yang Shangkun</span></b>, swing decisively behind him. His campaign culminated at the 14th <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"14th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Party Congress</span> in October 1992, which formally adopted the goal of building a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialist_market_economy\">socialist market economy</span> and enshrined the principles later codified as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping_Theory\">Deng Xiaoping Theory</span>. The tour unleashed an extraordinary surge of growth and investment, as China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gross_domestic_product\">gross domestic product</span> expanded by more than 14% in 1992 while annual <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foreign_direct_investment\">foreign direct investment</span> leapt from roughly $4 billion in 1991 to over $11 billion in 1992 and some $27 billion the following year. It accelerated the development of coastal hubs such as Shanghai's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pudong\">Pudong</span> district and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pearl_River_Delta\">Pearl River Delta</span>, fueled the rapid expansion of private firms and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Township_and_village_enterprises\">township and village enterprises</span></b>, and drew millions of rural migrants into the booming manufacturing economy. Historians generally regard the journey as the moment that locked China onto an irreversible path of rapid marketization and as Deng's final and most consequential political act, one that sustained years of double-digit growth, cemented his standing as the chief architect of the reform era, and is remembered as among the pivotal turning points of late-20th-century Chinese history.","citation":"","answerText":"Southern Tour"},{"id":"cnp-070","num":"七十","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Adopted as the official goal at the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> Party congress, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> — embraced after the southern tour of Deng Xiaoping — combines extensive markets and private firms with continued state ownership of strategic sectors and Party control, distinguishing it from a pure planned economy.","answer":"Socialist market economy","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Coined</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Adopted as official policy at the 14th Party Congress, 1992</span></div>","traditional":"社會主義市場經濟","hanzi":"社会主义市场经济","pinyin":"shèhuìzhǔyì shìchǎng jīngjì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">shèhuìzhǔyì shìchǎng jīngjì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>socialist market economy</b> is the official designation for the economic system of the People's Republic of China, in which an extensive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Market_economy\">market</span> and a large private sector coexist with predominant public ownership and the overarching control of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span>. It was proclaimed the goal of reform at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"14th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">14th National Congress</span></b> <b>in October 1992</b>, only months after Deng Xiaoping's southern tour of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shenzhen\">Shenzhen</span> and the other coastal <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Special_economic_zones_of_China\">special economic zones</span> had shattered the conservative paralysis that had gripped the leadership <b>since the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1989_Tiananmen_Square_protests_and_massacre\">Tiananmen Square crackdown</span> of 1989</b>. The formulation marked a decisive break with the earlier notion of a merely \"planned commodity economy\" and the boldest stride yet in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">reform and opening</span> launched in 1978, embracing the market as the principal mechanism for allocating resources on the strength of Deng's contention that planning and market forces were mere instruments rather than the essence dividing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialism\">socialism</span> from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capitalism\">capitalism</span>. While allowing <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Private_sector\">private</span></b> and foreign enterprise to flourish in competitive industries, the system preserved public ownership as its mainstay, with vast <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_enterprise\">state-owned enterprises</span> retaining the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Commanding_heights_of_the_economy\">commanding heights</span> of finance, energy, and the other sectors deemed strategic. Conceived as the economic core of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialism_with_Chinese_characteristics\">socialism with Chinese characteristics</span> and of the doctrine that the country remained at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Primary_stage_of_socialism\">primary stage of socialism</span></b>, it was enshrined within <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping_Theory\">Deng Xiaoping Theory</span> and has often been likened by economists to earlier experiments in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Market_socialism\">market socialism</span> and to Lenin's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Economic_Policy\">New Economic Policy</span>.<br> <br>The system was built through a wave of reforms in the 1990s under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Zemin\">Jiang Zemin</span> and his economic strategist, Premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_Rongji\">Zhu Rongji</span>, including a <b>sweeping 1993 blueprint</b>, the 1994 tax-sharing reform that introduced a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Value-added_tax\">value-added tax</span> and reapportioned revenue between Beijing and the provinces, and a strengthening of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Bank_of_China\">People's Bank of China</span> as a central bank. Zhu's restructuring of the state sector, summed up in the slogan \"grasp the large, let go of the small,\" <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Privatization\">privatised</span> or closed tens of thousands of smaller enterprises and threw an estimated 30 million employees out of work, while the surviving giants were later marshalled under a powerful <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_Assets_Supervision_and_Administration_Commission\">state-asset regulator</span>. Integration into the global economy followed with China's accession to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Trade_Organization\">World Trade Organization</span> in 2001, and the rising weight of the private economy was acknowledged in a 2004 amendment to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitution_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">constitution</span> that declared lawful <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Private_property\">private property</span> inviolable. A further turn came in 2013, when the leadership under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span> declared that the market should play a \"decisive role\" in allocating resources, by which time the model had helped propel China past Japan to become the world's second-largest <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">economy</span>, with a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gross_domestic_product\">gross domestic product</span> exceeded only by that of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States\">United States</span>. Widely characterised abroad as a variety of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_capitalism\">state capitalism</span> or a hybrid <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mixed_economy\">mixed economy</span></b>, yet defended by its architects as a genuine adaptation of socialism to a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Developing_country\">developing nation</span>, the model remains the constitutionally mandated economic order of the People's Republic of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Socialist market economy"},{"id":"cne-035","num":"三十五","category":"China · Economics","question":"Created in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> after the reopening of the Shanghai and Shenzhen exchanges, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> approves listings and polices the country's stock and futures markets.","answer":"China Securities Regulatory Commission","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">founded 1992</span></div>","traditional":"中國證券監督管理委員會","hanzi":"中国证券监督管理委员会","pinyin":"Zhōngguó Zhèngquàn Jiāndū Guǎnlǐ Wěiyuánhuì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōngguó Zhèngquàn Jiāndū Guǎnlǐ Wěiyuánhuì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>China Securities Regulatory Commission</b> is the ministerial-level <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Regulatory_agency\">regulatory agency</span></b>, based in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>, that oversees <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Security_(finance)\">securities</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Futures_exchange\">futures</span> markets throughout mainland China. It was <b>created in 1992</b>, soon after the reopening of the Shanghai and Shenzhen <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stock_exchange\">stock exchanges</span></b> and amid the turbulence of a stock market reborn under China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">economic reforms</span>, and was consciously modelled on the American <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"U.S._Securities_and_Exchange_Commission\">Securities and Exchange Commission</span>. <b>In 1998</b> the separate State Council Securities Commission was folded into it, creating a single unified regulator with authority anchored in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Financial_regulation\">securities law</span> enacted that year. Operating under the State Council, the commission licenses securities firms and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stockbroker\">brokers</span>, vets and approves new <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Listing_(finance)\">listings</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Initial_public_offering\">initial public offerings</span>, and supervises the exchanges, listed companies—many of them <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_enterprise\">state-owned</span>—and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mutual_fund\">mutual funds</span></b> across the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">Chinese economy</span>. Its enforcement arm polices abuses such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Insider_trading\">insider trading</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Market_manipulation\">market manipulation</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Securities_fraud\">securities fraud</span>, a mandate grown more demanding as China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capital_market\">capital markets</span> have swelled into some of the world's largest.<br> <br>Beyond equities the commission regulates the country's futures bourses—among them the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_Futures_Exchange\">Shanghai Futures Exchange</span></b> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Financial_Futures_Exchange\">China Financial Futures Exchange</span>—and governs the channels through which foreigners may reach its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Renminbi\">renminbi</span>-denominated shares, including the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qualified_Foreign_Institutional_Investor\">qualified foreign institutional investor</span> scheme and the cross-border <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stock_Connect\">Stock Connect</span>. A defining challenge is the predominance of small <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Investor\">retail investors</span>, who hold more than 200 million trading accounts and lend the market to violent swings, most dramatically in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2015–2016_Chinese_stock_market_turbulence\"><b>2015</b> stock market crash</span>, when the regulator suspended new listings and orchestrated state-backed share buying to arrest the rout. For most of its history the body wielded an approval-based system that closely rationed the timing and pricing of new offerings, but it has since moved toward a disclosure-driven, registration-based model, trialled on Shanghai's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"STAR_Market\">STAR Market</span> in 2019 and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"ChiNext\">ChiNext</span> board in 2020 before being extended market-wide in 2023. That same 2023 reorganization of financial oversight, which also created the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Financial_Regulatory_Administration\">National Financial Regulatory Administration</span>, recast the commission as an institution reporting directly to the State Council and working in concert with the central bank, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Bank_of_China\">People's Bank of China</span>. Among its former chairmen was <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Xiaochuan\">Zhou Xiaochuan</span>, later the long-serving governor of the central bank, and through successive reforms the commission has remained the chief guardian of investor confidence in markets now indispensable to the financing of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>'s economy.","citation":"","answerText":"China Securities Regulatory Commission"},{"id":"cne-039","num":"三十九","category":"China · Economics","question":"Founded in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> as a policy lender rather than a commercial bank, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> funds infrastructure, urban projects and overseas ventures tied to schemes such as the Belt and Road, channelling state credit at the direction of the State Council and the planning agency.","answer":"China Development Bank","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">founded 1994</span></div>","traditional":"國家開發銀行","hanzi":"国家开发银行","pinyin":"Guójiā Kāifā Yínháng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Guójiā Kāifā Yínháng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>China Development Bank</b> is the largest of China's three policy banks, a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Development_finance_institution\">development finance institution</span></b> charged with funding government priorities rather than operating as an ordinary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Commercial_bank\">commercial bank</span>. It was <b>founded in 1994</b> amid a wave of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">financial reform</span> that hived off policy lending from commercial banking, alongside the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Export–Import_Bank_of_China\">Export–Import Bank of China</span> and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Agricultural_Development_Bank_of_China\">Agricultural Development Bank of China</span></b>. Headquartered in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>, it channels long-term credit into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Infrastructure\">infrastructure</span> such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"High-speed_rail_in_China\">high-speed railways</span> and power grids, as well as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Urbanization_in_China\">urban development</span> and other strategic sectors of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">Chinese economy</span>. Unlike a deposit-taking lender, it raises most of its funds by issuing quasi-sovereign <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Government_bond\">bonds</span> in the interbank <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Money_market\">money</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bond_market\">bond markets</span></b>, which it then deploys through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Project_finance\">project finance</span> and large policy <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Loan\">loans</span>. It operates at the direction of the State Council and the national planning agency, its lending aligned with the country's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five-year_plans_of_China\">five-year plans</span> and supervised within the financial system overseen by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Bank_of_China\">People's Bank of China</span>.<br> <br><b>From 1998</b> the bank was built into a formidable institution under the long-serving chairman <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Yuan_(banker)\">Chen Yuan</span>, son of the veteran economic planner <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chen_Yun\">Chen Yun</span>, who turned it into a pillar of state-directed finance. In 2008 it was converted into a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joint-stock_company\">joint-stock company</span> as part of a push toward commercialization, becoming a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_enterprise\">state-owned</span> corporation that nonetheless retained its developmental mission. Abroad it has grown into one of the world's <b>largest sources of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Development_aid\">development finance</span></b>, lending hundreds of billions of dollars to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Developing_country\">developing countries</span>—often for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Port\">ports</span>, railways, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Power_station\">power stations</span> linked to the Belt and Road Initiative <b>launched in 2013</b>—on a scale that has rivalled the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Bank\">World Bank</span> and drawn accusations of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Debt-trap_diplomacy\">debt-trap diplomacy</span>. Reaffirmed in 2015 as a dedicated development finance institution, it has also worked alongside the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk_Road_Fund\">Silk Road Fund</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Asian_Infrastructure_Investment_Bank\">Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank</span> while remaining the chief domestic financier of local-government projects, fuelling growth but also swelling concerns over <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Government_debt\">public debt</span>. Supervised since a 2023 overhaul of financial regulation by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Financial_Regulatory_Administration\">National Financial Regulatory Administration</span> and holding assets exceeding $2 trillion, it ranks among the largest development banks on earth, embodying the way <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> mobilizes state credit to advance both domestic construction and its ambitions overseas.","citation":"","answerText":"China Development Bank"},{"id":"cne-098","num":"九十八","category":"China · Economics","question":"Starting as a maker of rechargeable batteries and backed early by Warren Buffett, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> grew into one of the world's biggest producers of electric and plug-in hybrid cars, overtaking Western rivals in volume.","answer":"BYD Company","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">founded 1995</span></div>","traditional":"比亞迪","hanzi":"比亚迪","pinyin":"Bǐyàdí","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Bǐyàdí</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>BYD Company</b> is a publicly listed Chinese <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Conglomerate_(company)\">conglomerate</span></b> headquartered in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shenzhen\">Shenzhen</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangdong\">Guangdong</span>, that has grown from an obscure battery workshop into one of the world's foremost producers of electric vehicles. The firm was <b>established in February 1995</b> by the chemist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Chuanfu\">Wang Chuanfu</span>, who began by manufacturing rechargeable <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nickel–cadmium_battery\">nickel-cadmium</span></b> and later <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lithium-ion_battery\">lithium-ion</span> cells, and within a few years it had become one of the world's largest suppliers of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mobile_phone\">mobile-phone</span> batteries, counting handset makers such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Motorola\">Motorola</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nokia\">Nokia</span> among its customers. It diversified <b>into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Automotive_industry\">automotive industry</span> in 2003</b> through the acquisition of a struggling state-owned carmaker in Xi'an, a move initially met with scepticism but which positioned the company to exploit <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China's</span> later embrace of electrified transport. International credibility followed in 2008 when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warren_Buffett\">Warren Buffett</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Berkshire_Hathaway\">Berkshire Hathaway</span>, at the urging of his partner <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Charlie_Munger\">Charlie Munger</span></b>, paid roughly US$230 million for about 225 million shares, a stake of nearly 10 percent that proved enormously profitable as the company's value subsequently soared. Beyond passenger cars the firm operates across a sprawling range of activities, producing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Electric_bus\">electric buses</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Energy_storage\">energy-storage</span> systems, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Solar_panel\">solar panels</span></b>, consumer electronics, and even a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Monorail\">monorail</span> transit system, while its shares trade on both the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_Stock_Exchange\">Hong Kong</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shenzhen_Stock_Exchange\">Shenzhen</span> exchanges. <br> <br> A decisive strategic <b>pivot came in March 2022</b>, when the company became the first major carmaker to halt production of pure <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Internal_combustion_engine\">internal-combustion</span> vehicles, concentrating entirely on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battery_electric_vehicle\">battery-electric</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Plug-in_hybrid\">plug-in hybrid</span> models. Its in-house battery expertise underpinned the 2020 launch of the Blade Battery, a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lithium_iron_phosphate_battery\">lithium iron phosphate</span> design marketed for its safety after passing a stringent nail-penetration test, which the company now supplies both to its own vehicles and to external manufacturers. Sales expanded with remarkable speed, as the firm sold roughly 1.86 million <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_energy_vehicles_in_China\">new energy vehicles</span> in 2022 to surpass <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tesla,_Inc.\">Tesla</span> in combined electric and hybrid sales, before delivering about 3 million in 2023 and some 4.27 million in 2024, the year its revenue exceeded US$100 billion and overtook that of its American rival. To sustain this momentum it pushed aggressively into overseas markets across Southeast Asia, Latin America, and Europe, opening assembly plants in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Thailand\">Thailand</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Brazil\">Brazil</span> and breaking ground on its first European car factory in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Szeged\">Szeged</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hungary\">Hungary</span>, even as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"European_Union\">European Union</span> imposed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Countervailing_duties\">countervailing duties</span> on Chinese-made electric cars in 2024. Employing a workforce of more than 700,000 and ranked among the most valuable automakers on earth, with a market value at times exceeding US$100 billion, the company came to symbolise China's rapid ascent in the global <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Electric_vehicle\">electric-vehicle</span> industry, having transformed in three decades from a maker of cheap handset cells into a formidable challenger to long-established Western manufacturers.","citation":"","answerText":"BYD Company"},{"id":"cne-094","num":"九十四","category":"China · Economics","question":"Once among the country's biggest property developers, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> became the emblem of the housing slump when it defaulted in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> on more than 300 billion dollars of liabilities, before a Hong Kong court ordered its liquidation.","answer":"Evergrande Group","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">founded 1996</span></div>","traditional":"恆大集團","hanzi":"恒大集团","pinyin":"Héngdà Jítuán","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Héngdà Jítuán</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Evergrande Group</b>, formally the <b>China Evergrande Group</b>, was once one of China's largest <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Real_estate_development\">property developers</span></b>, <b>founded in 1996</b> by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Billionaire\">billionaire</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hui_Ka_Yan\">Hui Ka Yan</span>—known in Mandarin as Xu Jiayin—in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou\">Guangzhou</span> and later based in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shenzhen\">Shenzhen</span>. After <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Initial_public_offering\">listing</span> <b>on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stock_Exchange_of_Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong Stock Exchange</span> in 2009</b> as the Evergrande Real Estate Group, it grew explosively across more than 280 Chinese cities and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Diversification_(finance)\">diversified</span> far beyond housing into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Electric_vehicle\">electric vehicles</span>, bottled water, theme parks, and the football club <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangzhou_F.C.\">Guangzhou Evergrande</span>. Its expansion was financed by enormous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Leverage_(finance)\">leverage</span>, off-balance-sheet <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shadow_banking_system\">shadow financing</span>, and the widespread practice of selling <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Off-plan_property\">apartments before they were built</span></b>, a model that came under acute strain after Beijing imposed its 2020 \"three red lines\" caps on developer debt. In December 2021 the company <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Default_(finance)\">defaulted</span> on its offshore <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bond_(finance)\">bonds</span>, having amassed around $300 billion in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liability_(financial_accounting)\">liabilities</span> against roughly $240 billion in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Asset\">assets</span>, a debt load that made it the world's most indebted property developer. Because much of that debt was denominated in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States_dollar\">United States dollars</span> and owed to international <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Creditor\">creditors</span></b>, the default reverberated through global financial markets and came to symbolize the unraveling of China's decades-long, debt-fueled <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Real_estate_bubble\">property boom</span>. <br> <br> Evergrande's collapse triggered <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Financial_contagion\">financial contagion</span> across a sector central to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">Chinese economy</span>—by some estimates nearly a third of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gross_domestic_product\">gross domestic product</span>—pushing rivals such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Country_Garden\">Country Garden</span> into distress and leaving millions of pre-sold homes unfinished as frustrated buyers staged <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mortgage\">mortgage</span> boycotts. A liquidation petition was filed in June 2022 by the investor Top Shine over a soured share-repurchase agreement, even as the company spent some two years trying to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Debt_restructuring\">restructure</span> roughly $23 billion of offshore debt and to resume work on hundreds of stalled projects. Those efforts unraveled after its auditor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"PricewaterhouseCoopers\">PricewaterhouseCoopers</span> resigned in early 2023 over disagreements about its accounts and Hui was detained in September 2023 on suspicion of crimes, derailing negotiations with creditors. On January 29, 2024, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"High_Court_of_Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong High Court</span> issued a winding-up order, placing Evergrande into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liquidation\">liquidation</span> and suspending its shares at HK$0.16, although with more than 90% of its assets located in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mainland_China\">mainland China</span>—largely beyond the court's reach—recovery for creditors looked likely to be slow and partial. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Securities_Regulatory_Commission\">China Securities Regulatory Commission</span> subsequently fined its onshore subsidiary, Hengda Real Estate Group, 4.2 billion yuan (about $584 million) for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Securities_fraud\">falsifying financial records</span>, verified creditor claims swelled to roughly $45 billion, and <b>on August 25, 2025</b>, Evergrande was delisted from the Hong Kong exchange, ending the public life of a company whose downfall became the defining emblem of China's property crisis.","citation":"","answerText":"Evergrande Group"},{"id":"cnp-072","num":"七十二","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Occurring at midnight on 1 July <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> and ending more than 150 years of British rule, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> placed a major financial centre under Chinese sovereignty as a special administrative region governed under the \"one country, two systems\" formula.","answer":"Handover of Hong Kong","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1 July 1997</span></div>","traditional":"香港主權移交","hanzi":"香港主权移交","pinyin":"Xiānggǎng zhǔquán yíjiāo","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Xiānggǎng zhǔquán yíjiāo</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“transfer of sovereignty over Hong Kong”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>handover of Hong Kong</b> was the transfer of sovereignty over <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span> from the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_Kingdom\">United Kingdom</span></b> to the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span> at midnight on 1 July 1997</b>, an event widely framed in mainland China as the territory's \"return\" to the motherland. British control had been acquired piecemeal during the 19th century through a sequence of so-called <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Unequal_treaty\">unequal treaties</span>: the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Nanking\">Treaty of Nanking</span> of 1842</b>, which followed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Opium_War\">First Opium War</span> and ceded <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_Island\">Hong Kong Island</span> in perpetuity; the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Convention_of_Peking\">Convention of Peking</span> of 1860, which added the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kowloon\">Kowloon</span> Peninsula; and <b>the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Convention_for_the_Extension_of_Hong_Kong_Territory\">Convention for the Extension of Hong Kong Territory</span> of 1898</b>, which leased the adjacent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Territories\">New Territories</span> for 99 years. Because that lease was due to expire on 30 June 1997 and the colony could not function without the New Territories, protracted negotiations between the two governments produced the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-British_Joint_Declaration\">Sino-British Joint Declaration</span>, signed in Beijing on 19 December 1984 by Prime Ministers <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Margaret_Thatcher\">Margaret Thatcher</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhao_Ziyang\">Zhao Ziyang</span>. Under the formula of \"one country, two systems\"—originally devised by paramount leader <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>—the declaration guaranteed that Hong Kong would retain its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capitalism\">capitalist</span> economy, separate legal system, and a high degree of autonomy for 50 years, commitments later codified in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_Basic_Law\">Hong Kong Basic Law</span> promulgated in 1990. The transfer was solemnized in a formal ceremony at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_Convention_and_Exhibition_Centre\">Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition Centre</span></b>, where <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Charles_III\">Charles, Prince of Wales</span> represented <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Elizabeth_II\">Queen Elizabeth II</span> alongside the departing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Governor_of_Hong_Kong\">Governor</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chris_Patten\">Chris Patten</span>, while President <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Zemin\">Jiang Zemin</span> and Premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Peng\">Li Peng</span> oversaw the inauguration of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tung_Chee-hwa\">Tung Chee-hwa</span></b> as the first <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chief_Executive_of_Hong_Kong\">Chief Executive</span>.<br> <br>At the time of the handover the territory was home to roughly 6.5 million people and ranked among the world's foremost <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Financial_centre\">financial centres</span>, its economy then equivalent to almost 18 percent of mainland China's total output. The political transition proved contentious, as late electoral reforms introduced by Patten prompted Beijing to abolish the sitting <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Legislative_Council_of_Hong_Kong\">Legislative Council</span></b> and install an appointed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Provisional_Legislative_Council\">Provisional Legislative Council</span> in its place, while a garrison of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army\">People's Liberation Army</span> took up positions across the city. A closely comparable transfer followed just over two years later, in 1999, when the neighbouring territory of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Macau\">Macau</span> reverted from Portuguese to Chinese administration under an almost identical arrangement. In the decades after 1997, recurring disputes over the pace of democratization and the limits of the promised autonomy fuelled large-scale demonstrations, most prominently the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Umbrella_Movement\">Umbrella Movement</span> of 2014 and the far larger anti-government <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2019–2020_Hong_Kong_protests\">protests</span> of 2019 and 2020. The central government's imposition of a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_national_security_law\">national security law</span> in 2020 sharply curtailed those freedoms, leaving the durability of the city's guaranteed autonomy—nominally assured until 2047—a subject of intense international scrutiny.","citation":"","answerText":"Handover of Hong Kong"},{"id":"cng-055","num":"五十五","category":"China · Geography","question":"Created under the \"one country, two systems\" formula, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> — the former British and Portuguese colonies — keep their own legal and economic systems and currencies.","answer":"Special administrative regions of China","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">from 1997</span></div>","traditional":"特別行政區","hanzi":"特别行政区","pinyin":"tèbié xíngzhèngqū","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">tèbié xíngzhèngqū</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>special administrative regions of China</b> are <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Administrative_divisions_of_China\">provincial-level</span></b> divisions of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People’s Republic of China</span> that enjoy a high degree of autonomy under the principle of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"One_country,_two_systems\">“one country, two systems”</span>. There are two such regions, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span>, handed back by the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_Kingdom\">United Kingdom</span> on 1 July 1997</b>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Macau\">Macau</span>, returned by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Portugal\">Portugal</span> on 20 December 1999, each having been a European colony before its transfer to Chinese sovereignty. Under their respective <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_Basic_Law\">Basic Laws</span>, the regions keep capitalist economies and legal systems wholly distinct from the mainland — Hong Kong preserving English <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Common_law\">common law</span> and <b>Macau a Portuguese-derived <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Civil_law_(legal_system)\">civil law</span></b> — together with separate currencies, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_dollar\">Hong Kong dollar</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Macanese_pataca\">Macanese pataca</span>, their own <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Customs_territory\">customs</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Border_control\">immigration</span> controls, and free-port status. Foreign affairs and defence remain the responsibility of the central government, which stations <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army_Hong_Kong_Garrison\">garrisons</span> in both, but each region runs its own <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Government_of_Hong_Kong\">government</span></b> under a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chief_Executive_of_Hong_Kong\">Chief Executive</span>, maintains its own police and travel documents, and participates separately in international bodies such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Trade_Organization\">World Trade Organization</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Asia-Pacific_Economic_Cooperation\">APEC</span>, Hong Kong even fielding its own <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_at_the_Olympics\">Olympic team</span></b>. These arrangements were promised to remain unchanged for 50 years after each handover, until 2047 for Hong Kong and 2049 for Macau, a guarantee enshrined in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-British_Joint_Declaration\">Sino-British Joint Declaration</span> and the parallel <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-Portuguese_Joint_Declaration\">Sino-Portuguese Joint Declaration</span> registered as international treaties. <br> <br> The formula was devised in the early 1980s by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>, originally as a model for the eventual reunification of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span>, but it was first applied to the question of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"British_Hong_Kong\">British Hong Kong</span>. Britain had taken Hong Kong from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> in stages — <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_Island\">Hong Kong Island</span> by the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty_of_Nanking\">Treaty of Nanking</span> of 1842</b>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kowloon\">Kowloon</span> peninsula in 1860, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Territories\">New Territories</span> on a 99-year lease in 1898 — and it was the looming expiry of that lease in 1997 that forced negotiations over the colony’s future. Macau, by contrast, had been a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Portuguese_Macau\">Portuguese settlement</span> <b>since 1557</b>, the oldest European outpost in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"East_Asia\">East Asia</span>, and its return a few years after Hong Kong’s made it the last European colony in Asia to be relinquished. Today the two thrive on very different foundations, one of the world’s leading <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Financial_centre\">financial centres</span> anchored by its stock exchange and free flow of capital, the other the planet’s largest <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gambling\">gambling</span> hub, whose casino <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gambling_in_Macau\">gaming revenue</span> long eclipsed that of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Las_Vegas\">Las Vegas</span>. The Hong Kong model has come under strain in recent years, as mass <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2019–2020_Hong_Kong_protests\">protests</span> in 2019 were followed by a sweeping <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_national_security_law\">national security law</span> imposed by Beijing in 2020 and an overhaul of the electoral system in 2021, changes that supporters cast as restoring order but that critics and several foreign governments view as eroding the promised autonomy.","citation":"","answerText":"Special administrative regions of China"},{"id":"cne-043","num":"四十三","category":"China · Economics","question":"Triggered by currency collapses in Thailand, Indonesia and South Korea, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> saw China win praise for holding its currency steady rather than devaluing, even as growth slowed and the episode shaped its later caution on opening its capital account.","answer":"1997 Asian financial crisis","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">1997</span></div>","traditional":"亞洲金融危機","hanzi":"亚洲金融危机","pinyin":"Yàzhōu jīnróng wēijī","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Yàzhōu jīnróng wēijī</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>1997 Asian financial crisis</b> was a <b>severe wave of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Financial_contagion\">financial contagion</span></b> that swept across much of East and Southeast Asia from mid-1997, toppling currencies, stock markets, and banks and raising fears of a global economic meltdown. It was <b>touched off on 2 July 1997</b> when Thailand abandoned the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fixed_exchange_rate_system\">fixed peg</span> of its <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Thai_baht\">baht</span></b> to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States_dollar\">US dollar</span>, allowing the currency to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Floating_exchange_rate\">float</span> and collapse after the government exhausted its reserves defending it. The disaster exposed deep vulnerabilities across the region—heavy short-term foreign borrowing, yawning <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Current_account\">current-account</span> deficits, speculative <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economic_bubble\">asset bubbles</span></b>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Crony_capitalism\">crony capitalism</span>—that had been masked by a flood of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hot_money\">hot money</span> which abruptly reversed into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capital_flight\">capital flight</span>. Contagion spread rapidly to Indonesia, whose <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Indonesian_rupiah\">rupiah</span> lost roughly 80 percent of its value, to South Korea's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South_Korean_won\">won</span>, and to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Malaysia\">Malaysia</span>, plunging much of the region into a deep <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Recession\">recession</span>. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"International_Monetary_Fund\">International Monetary Fund</span> assembled enormous rescue packages—including some $58 billion for South Korea—whose stern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Austerity\">austerity</span> conditions proved deeply controversial, while collapsing economies fed unrest that helped topple <b>Indonesia's President <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Suharto\">Suharto</span> in 1998</b> after more than 30 years in power.<br> <br>Throughout the turmoil China won wide international praise for holding its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Renminbi\">renminbi</span> steady rather than joining a ruinous round of competitive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Devaluation\">devaluation</span>, a stance eased by the strict <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capital_control\">capital controls</span> that insulated its still-inconvertible currency from speculative attack. Hong Kong likewise defended the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Linked_exchange_rate_system\">linked exchange rate</span> of its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_dollar\">dollar</span></b>, with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_Monetary_Authority\">Hong Kong Monetary Authority</span> spending some HK$118 billion in August 1998 to buy up <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hang_Seng_Index\">Hang Seng Index</span> shares and beat back speculators. China's own <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gross_domestic_product\">growth</span> slackened, yet it held near 8 percent in 1998 as Premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_Rongji\">Zhu Rongji</span> launched a programme of deficit-financed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Infrastructure\">infrastructure</span> spending to cushion the slowdown. The shock rippled far beyond Asia, helping to trigger the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1998_Russian_financial_crisis\">Russian financial crisis</span> and the collapse of the hedge fund <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Long-Term_Capital_Management\">Long-Term Capital Management</span>, and it left a lasting imprint on Chinese policy, hardening Beijing's caution about opening its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capital_account\">capital account</span> and spurring it to amass vast <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foreign-exchange_reserves_of_China\">foreign-exchange reserves</span> as a buffer. It also galvanized regional cooperation, <b>producing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chiang_Mai_Initiative\">Chiang Mai Initiative</span> of 2000</b> among the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"ASEAN_Plus_Three\">ASEAN Plus Three</span> economies, and although most of the stricken nations had recovered by the turn of the century, the crisis durably reshaped the financial strategy of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> and its neighbours.","citation":"","answerText":"1997 Asian financial crisis"},{"id":"cne-058","num":"五十八","category":"China · Economics","question":"Carved out of the telecoms ministry and serving the world's largest base of subscribers, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was delisted from New York amid US restrictions before relisting on the Shanghai market.","answer":"China Mobile","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">founded 1997</span></div>","traditional":"中國移動","hanzi":"中国移动","pinyin":"Zhōngguó Yídòng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōngguó Yídòng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>China Mobile</b> is a <b>state-controlled <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mobile_network_operator\">mobile network operator</span></b> and the largest of its kind in the world by number of subscribers, the dominant force in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Telecommunications_in_China\">telecommunications in China</span> and one of the country's most valuable enterprises. It was carved out of the mobile <b>operations of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Telecom\">China Telecom</span> around 2000</b> as the country's monopolistic <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Telecommunication\">telecommunications</span></b> sector was broken up and reorganised, ultimately leaving the market to three large state carriers—China Mobile, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Unicom\">China Unicom</span>, and China Telecom—under the regulation of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ministry_of_Industry_and_Information_Technology\">Ministry of Industry and Information Technology</span>. A central enterprise overseen by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_Assets_Supervision_and_Administration_Commission\">State-owned Assets Supervision and Administration Commission</span> and headquartered in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>, its listed arm had floated shares on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_Stock_Exchange\">Hong Kong</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_York_Stock_Exchange\">New York</span> exchanges back in 1997</b>. Serving the world's largest base of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mobile_phone\">mobile</span> subscribers—a figure that climbed past a billion customers—it rolled out successive generations of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cellular_network\">cellular networks</span>, beginning with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"GSM\">2G</span> and adding a homegrown <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"3G\">3G</span> standard, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"TD-SCDMA\">TD-SCDMA</span>, before deploying vast <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"4G\">4G</span> systems. It went on to operate the world's largest <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"5G\">5G</span> network, with more <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Base_station\">base stations</span></b> than any other operator, and expanded well beyond mobile into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Broadband\">broadband</span> internet, digital services, and cloud computing, making it one of the most important and profitable <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_enterprises_of_China\">state-owned enterprises</span> in the country. <br> <br> Amid escalating <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China–United_States_trade_war\">US–China tensions</span>, an executive order signed <b>by President <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Donald_Trump\">Donald Trump</span> in 2020</b> barred American investment in firms deemed linked to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army\">People's Liberation Army</span>, a designation applied to China Mobile and its peers. As a result, its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"American_depositary_receipt\">American depositary receipts</span> were stripped from the New York exchange in early 2021, together with those of the other two Chinese carriers, ending a presence on Wall Street that stretched back more than two decades. It responded by relisting at home, raising the equivalent of roughly $8 billion in an <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Initial_public_offering\">initial public offering</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"A-share_(mainland_China)\">A-shares</span> on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_Stock_Exchange\">Shanghai Stock Exchange</span> in early 2022, one of the largest mainland flotations in a decade and a sign of capital being repatriated from foreign markets. With annual revenue running to well over $100 billion, it ranks among the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"List_of_largest_companies_by_revenue\">largest companies in the world</span></b> on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fortune_Global_500\">Fortune Global 500</span> and commands a vast <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Market_capitalization\">market capitalisation</span>, even as its reliance on 5G equipment from suppliers such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huawei\">Huawei</span> drew it deeper into the technology dispute between the two powers. From those early 2G networks to its world-leading 5G rollout, China Mobile has grown into a central pillar of the country's digital infrastructure and a flagship of the state-led <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">Chinese economy</span>, its commercial fortunes now increasingly entangled with the geopolitical rivalry between Beijing and Washington over technology.","citation":"","answerText":"China Mobile"},{"id":"cne-046","num":"四十六","category":"China · Economics","question":"Launched in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> and best known for the ubiquitous super-app WeChat, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> became one of the world's most valuable companies before regulators tightened control over the sector.","answer":"Tencent","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">founded 1998</span></div>","traditional":"騰訊","hanzi":"腾讯","pinyin":"Téngxùn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Téngxùn</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Tencent</b> is a Chinese technology and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Video_game\">video-game</span></b> conglomerate based in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shenzhen\">Shenzhen</span>, best known internationally for the ubiquitous super-app <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"WeChat\">WeChat</span>. It was <b>founded in November 1998</b> in Shenzhen by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ma_Huateng\">Ma Huateng</span>, known as Pony Ma, together with several partners, and its first major success was an <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Instant_messaging\">instant-messaging</span> service <b>launched in 1999</b> and modelled on the pioneering <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"ICQ\">ICQ</span>, soon renamed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tencent_QQ\">QQ</span>, which grew to hundreds of millions of users and made the company a fixture of the early Chinese internet. The company listed on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_Stock_Exchange\">Hong Kong Stock Exchange</span> in 2004, by which time the South African group <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Naspers\">Naspers</span>—later through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Prosus\">Prosus</span>—had taken a large early stake that became one of the most lucrative venture investments in history. Its defining product, WeChat, <b>launched in 2011</b> and rapidly evolved from a simple messaging app into an all-encompassing platform that fused chat, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Social_media\">social media</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mobile_payment\">mobile payments</span>, and embedded mini-programs, eventually serving well over a billion monthly active users and becoming nearly indispensable to daily life in China. Tencent also became the world's largest <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Video_game_industry\">video-game company</span></b> by revenue, owning <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Riot_Games\">Riot Games</span>, maker of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"League_of_Legends\">League of Legends</span>, a majority of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Supercell_(video_game_company)\">Supercell</span>, and a large stake in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Epic_Games\">Epic Games</span>, while publishing blockbusters such as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Honor_of_Kings\">Honor of Kings</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"PUBG_Mobile\">PUBG Mobile</span>. <br> <br> Beyond games and social media, it built large businesses in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cloud_computing\">cloud computing</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Financial_technology\">financial technology</span>, online advertising, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tencent_Music\">music-streaming</span>, amassed one of the world's largest corporate investment portfolios, and stood with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Alibaba_Group\">Alibaba</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Baidu\">Baidu</span> as one of the \"BAT\" trio of Chinese internet champions. At its height around early 2021 its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Market_capitalization\">market capitalisation</span> approached $1 trillion, having earlier become the first Asian company to surpass $500 billion in value, which ranked it among the most valuable corporations in the world and the single most valuable listed in Hong Kong. From 2020 it was caught up in a sweeping crackdown on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Big_Tech\">Big Tech</span>, as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_Administration_for_Market_Regulation\">State Administration for Market Regulation</span> wielded the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anti-Monopoly_Law_of_China\">Anti-Monopoly Law</span> to fine the firm, block a planned game-streaming merger, and force it to give up exclusive music-licensing rights. Gaming faced especially harsh measures, with regulators limiting players under 18 to roughly 3 hours of play a week in 2021 amid <b>official campaigns against <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Video_game_addiction\">video-game addiction</span></b>, a freeze on new game approvals, and state media branding online games \"spiritual opium,\" remarks that erased tens of billions of dollars in market value in a single day. Echoing the halted listing of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ant_Group\">Ant Group</span>, the campaign—framed by Beijing's drive for \"<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Common_prosperity\">common prosperity</span>\"—wiped hundreds of billions of dollars from the company's value, illustrating both the extraordinary scale Chinese technology firms had reached and the state's determination to keep them within the bounds of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">Chinese economy</span> and political order.","citation":"","answerText":"Tencent"},{"id":"cne-073","num":"七十三","category":"China · Economics","question":"A major rival to Alibaba in online retail, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> sell electronics and goods directly to consumers.","answer":"JD.com","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">founded 1998</span></div>","traditional":"京東","hanzi":"京东","pinyin":"Jīngdōng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Jīngdōng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>JD.com</b> is a Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"E-commerce\">e-commerce</span> giant, also known as Jingdong, headquartered in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> and one of the principal rivals to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Alibaba_Group\">Alibaba Group</span> in the country's vast online-retail market. The business traces its origins to a small <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Retail\">retail</span></b> counter <b>opened in 1998</b> by the entrepreneur <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Qiangdong\">Liu Qiangdong</span> in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhongguancun\">Zhongguancun</span> technology district, where it sold <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Magneto-optical_drive\">magneto-optical</span> products and other <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Consumer_electronics\">consumer electronics</span> under a name fusing a character from Liu's own given name with one from that of a former girlfriend. When <b>the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2002–2004_SARS_outbreak\">SARS epidemic</span> of 2003 made</b> physical commerce hazardous, the firm shifted decisively onto the internet, launching online sales the following year under the domain 360buy, a pivot that proved prescient as Chinese online shopping expanded explosively over the following decade, before it rebranded to the shorter jd.com in 2013. Unlike the asset-light <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Online_marketplace\">marketplace</span> model of Alibaba's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taobao\">Taobao</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tmall\">Tmall</span>, the company embraced a heavily <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vertical_integration\">vertically integrated</span></b> approach, purchasing inventory directly and selling it to consumers in a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Business-to-consumer\">business-to-consumer</span> arrangement reminiscent of Amazon's first-party retailing. Central to this strategy was the construction of a sprawling proprietary network of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warehouse\">warehouses</span> and delivery infrastructure staffed by hundreds of thousands of couriers, giving it direct control over <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Logistics\">logistics</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Order_fulfillment\">order fulfilment</span></b> in a manner that set it sharply apart from its platform-only competitors and became its defining advantage. <br> <br> Through its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"JD_Logistics\">JD Logistics</span> arm the company came to operate more than 1,500 warehouses spanning some 30 million square metres across <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>, enabling same- and next-day <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Delivery_(commerce)\">delivery</span> to much of the population and pioneering experiments with rural <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Delivery_drone\">delivery drones</span>. Major investors propelled its expansion, as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tencent\">Tencent</span> took a roughly <b>15 percent stake in 2014</b> and opened access to its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"WeChat\">WeChat</span> platform, the same year the firm raised about US$1.78 billion in a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nasdaq\">Nasdaq</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Initial_public_offering\">listing</span>, while the American retailer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Walmart\">Walmart</span> acquired its own holding ahead of a 2020 secondary flotation on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_Stock_Exchange\">Hong Kong</span> exchange. By the mid-2020s it had become one of China's largest companies by revenue, recording sales of about 1.08 trillion yuan in 2023, ranking among the top tier of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fortune_Global_500\">Fortune Global 500</span>, employing more than 500,000 people, and serving in the region of 580 million annual active customers, a scale that long ranked it as China's second-largest e-commerce platform by transaction volume behind Alibaba. Beyond its core marketplace the group branched into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"JD_Health\">healthcare</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Financial_technology\">financial technology</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cloud_computing\">cloud computing</span>, spinning several of these units off in their own listings, and it popularised the annual 618 shopping festival as a midyear counterpart to <b>Alibaba's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Singles'_Day\">Singles' Day</span></b>. Its founder Liu Qiangdong stepped back from day-to-day management, ceding the chief-executive role to a successor in 2022, after a 2018 arrest in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Minnesota\">Minnesota</span> on an allegation that prosecutors ultimately declined to charge, yet the firm continued to grow even as fierce competition from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pinduoduo\">Pinduoduo</span> and recurrent price wars squeezed margins across China's crowded retail landscape.","citation":"","answerText":"JD.com"},{"id":"cnp-073","num":"七十三","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Completed on 20 December <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> and ending centuries of Portuguese administration, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> made a former colony the 2nd Chinese special administrative region under the same autonomy framework applied earlier to Hong Kong.","answer":"Transfer of sovereignty over Macau","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">20 December 1999</span></div>","traditional":"澳門回歸","hanzi":"澳门回归","pinyin":"Àomén huíguī","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Àomén huíguī</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>transfer of sovereignty over Macau</b> refers to the handover of the territory of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Macau\">Macau</span> from <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Portugal\">Portugal</span></b> to the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span> at midnight on 20 December 1999</b>, an event that ended more than 400 years of European administration and created the country's 2nd <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Special_administrative_regions_of_China\">special administrative region</span>. Traders of the seaborne <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Portuguese_Empire\">Portuguese Empire</span> had established a permanent settlement <b>on the peninsula around 1557</b> with the tolerance of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ming_dynasty\">Ming dynasty</span>, and the enclave on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pearl_River_Delta\">Pearl River Delta</span> flourished as a vital <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Entrepôt\">entrepôt</span> linking Chinese, Japanese, Indian, and European commerce well into the modern era. Although the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> conceded perpetual Portuguese occupation under the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-Portuguese_Treaty_of_Peking\">Sino-Portuguese Treaty of Peking</span> in 1887</b>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Carnation_Revolution\">Carnation Revolution</span> of 1974 prompted a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Decolonization\">decolonising</span> Portugal to redesignate Macau as Chinese territory merely under Portuguese administration. After Beijing declined an early Portuguese offer to relinquish the territory, formal negotiations produced the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-Portuguese_Joint_Declaration\">Sino-Portuguese Joint Declaration</span>, signed on 13 April 1987, which fixed the retrocession date and committed both governments to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"One_country,_two_systems\">\"one country, two systems\"</span> formula earlier devised by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>. This arrangement closely mirrored the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Handover_of_Hong_Kong\">handover of Hong Kong</span> from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_Kingdom\">United Kingdom</span> on 1 July 1997, which had served as the template for reintegrating the last vestiges of foreign control along China's southern coast. <br> <br> The handover ceremony, held in the small hours of 20 December 1999, was witnessed by Chinese President <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Zemin\">Jiang Zemin</span> and <b>Portuguese President <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jorge_Sampaio\">Jorge Sampaio</span></b> as the territory's last <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Governor_of_Macau\">governor</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vasco_Rocha_Vieira\">Vasco Rocha Vieira</span>, departed and units of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army_Macau_Garrison\">People's Liberation Army Macau Garrison</span> crossed the border. Governance passed to a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chief_Executive_of_Macau\">Chief Executive</span></b>, the businessman <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Edmund_Ho\">Edmund Ho</span>, under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Basic_Law_of_Macau\">Macau Basic Law</span> promulgated by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_People's_Congress\">National People's Congress</span> in 1993, a constitutional instrument guaranteeing a high degree of autonomy and the preservation of the existing social and economic system for 50 years until 2049. The region retained its own currency, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Macanese_pataca\">pataca</span>, a separate customs territory, and a legal order rooted in Portuguese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Civil_law_(legal_system)\">civil law</span>, alongside a distinctive heritage embodied by the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Macanese_people\">Macanese people</span></b> and their creole <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Macanese_Patois\">Patois</span>, with Beijing assuming responsibility only for defence and foreign affairs. In the decades following the handover the territory's liberalised <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gambling_in_Macau\">gaming industry</span> expanded explosively, overtaking the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Las_Vegas_Strip\">Las Vegas Strip</span> in gambling revenue by 2006 and at its peak generating roughly 7 times that rival's takings, which underwrote one of the highest levels of GDP per capita on earth. Home to fewer than 450,000 residents at the time of the transfer, this predominantly <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cantonese\">Cantonese</span>-speaking enclave has since seen its population climb past 680,000 within an area of barely 33 square kilometres (13 sq mi), ranking it among the most densely populated places on earth even as debate over the long-term durability of its promised autonomy has sharpened.","citation":"","answerText":"Transfer of sovereignty over Macau"},{"id":"cne-051","num":"五十一","category":"China · Economics","question":"Built around the Taobao and Tmall online marketplaces and founded in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> in Hangzhou, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> fell from public favour.","answer":"Alibaba Group","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">founded 1999</span></div>","traditional":"阿里巴巴集團","hanzi":"阿里巴巴集团","pinyin":"Ālǐbābā Jítuán","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Ālǐbābā Jítuán</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Alibaba Group</b> is a Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Multinational_corporation\">multinational</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Technology_company\">technology</span> conglomerate and one of the world's largest <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"E-commerce\">e-commerce</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cloud_computing\">cloud-computing</span>, and digital-payments companies, built around the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taobao\">Taobao</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tmall\">Tmall</span> online marketplaces that together handle the bulk of Chinese online shopping. It was <b>founded in 1999</b> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hangzhou\">Hangzhou</span> by the former English teacher <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jack_Ma\">Jack Ma</span> and 18 associates working from his apartment, with about 60,000 dollars pooled among them, beginning with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Alibaba.com\">Alibaba.com</span>, a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Business-to-business\">business-to-business</span> portal linking Chinese manufacturers and exporters with overseas buyers. Its consumer platforms—the auction-style Taobao, <b>launched in 2003</b>, and the brand-oriented Tmall—soon eclipsed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"EBay\">eBay</span> in the Chinese market, and it expanded abroad through the cross-border <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"AliExpress\">AliExpress</span> service to dominate online <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Retail\">retail</span>, eventually serving close to a billion annual users. Beyond shopping, it built a sprawling ecosystem including the payment service <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Alipay\">Alipay</span> and its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fintech\">fintech</span> affiliate <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ant_Group\">Ant Group</span></b>, the market-leading <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Alibaba_Cloud\">Alibaba Cloud</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cainiao\">Cainiao</span> logistics network, and holdings in media, entertainment, and food delivery. Backed early by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japan\">Japan</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"SoftBank_Group\">SoftBank</span>, whose <b>roughly 20-million-dollar investment in 2000</b> ballooned into one of the most profitable venture bets in history, and by the American firm <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yahoo!\">Yahoo!</span>, the company turned the November shopping festival <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Singles'_Day\">Singles' Day</span> into the world's biggest retail event, with single-day sales eventually exceeding 70 billion dollars. <br> <br> In 2014 Alibaba staged a landmark <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Initial_public_offering\">initial public offering</span> on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_York_Stock_Exchange\">New York Stock Exchange</span>, raising about 25 billion dollars in what was then the largest flotation in history and giving the company a valuation of around 230 billion dollars. Like many Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Internet_in_China\">internet</span> firms, it listed through a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Variable_interest_entity\">variable interest entity</span></b>—a contractual structure used to skirt restrictions on foreign ownership of sensitive sectors—and at its height the group was worth more than 800 billion dollars and accounted for a large share of China's online <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gross_merchandise_volume\">gross merchandise volume</span>. Its founder became one of China's most celebrated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Entrepreneurship\">entrepreneurs</span> and a global business celebrity before stepping down as executive chairman in 2019 in favour of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Daniel_Zhang\">Daniel Zhang</span></b>, the same year the group took a secondary listing on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_Stock_Exchange\">Hong Kong Stock Exchange</span> to hedge against rising US-China tensions. The reversal came in late 2020, when a speech by Ma at a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span> forum criticizing China's financial regulators as overly conservative was followed within days by the abrupt suspension of Ant Group's planned listing, which at some 34 billion dollars would have been the largest in the world. An <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Competition_law\">antitrust</span> crackdown followed under the banner of \"<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Common_prosperity\">common prosperity</span>\" championed by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span>, with regulators imposing a record fine of about 2.8 billion dollars in 2021 for monopolistic conduct, after which Ma withdrew almost entirely from public life and the once-dominant empire was reined in and later split into separate business groups.","citation":"","answerText":"Alibaba Group"},{"id":"cne-053","num":"五十三","category":"China · Economics","question":"Encouraged from around <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> to push domestic firms to invest abroad, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> promoted overseas acquisitions and resource deals, helping create global champions and later dovetailing with the Belt and Road ambitions of Xi Jinping, backed by the policy banks.","answer":"Go Out policy","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">走出去 ('going out'), an outbound-investment policy from 1999</span></div>","traditional":"走出去戰略","hanzi":"走出去战略","pinyin":"Zǒu chūqù zhànlüè","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zǒu chūqù zhànlüè</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“going out strategy”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Go Out policy</b> is the strategy by which the People's Republic of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> encouraged its enterprises—above all its <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_enterprises_of_China\">state-owned enterprises</span></b>—to invest beyond the country's borders. Promoted <b>from around 1999</b> under the leadership of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Zemin\">Jiang Zemin</span> and the government of premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_Rongji\">Zhu Rongji</span>, it was formalised in the country's 10th <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five-year_plans_of_China\">Five-Year Plan</span> and gathered momentum alongside China's accession <b>to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Trade_Organization\">World Trade Organization</span> in 2001</b>. Conceived as the outward counterpart to the inbound investment of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">reform era</span>, the strategy sought to secure <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Natural_resource\">natural resources</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Energy_security\">energy security</span>, acquire foreign technology and brands, diversify the nation's swelling <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foreign_exchange_reserves\">foreign exchange reserves</span>, and forge globally competitive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_champions\">national champions</span>. It channelled outward <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foreign_direct_investment\">foreign direct investment</span> through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mergers_and_acquisitions\">mergers and acquisitions</span>, underwritten by state policy banks such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Export–Import_Bank_of_China\">Export–Import Bank of China</span> and, <b>from 2007</b>, by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sovereign_wealth_fund\">sovereign wealth fund</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Investment_Corporation\">China Investment Corporation</span>, with central firms supervised by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_Assets_Supervision_and_Administration_Commission\">State-owned Assets Supervision and Administration Commission</span>. Chinese outbound investment grew explosively as a result, climbing from only a few billion dollars at the policy's inception to a peak of roughly 196 billion dollars in 2016, by which point China ranked among the world's largest sources of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Multinational_corporation\">multinational</span> capital.<br> <br>The policy's earliest and most strategic thrust lay in energy and minerals, as state oil firms including the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_National_Petroleum_Corporation\">China National Petroleum Corporation</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sinopec\">Sinopec</span> and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_National_Offshore_Oil_Corporation\">China National Offshore Oil Corporation</span></b> pursued oilfields across <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kazakhstan\">Kazakhstan</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Africa\">Africa</span>, though CNOOC's 2005 bid for the American producer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Unocal_Corporation\">Unocal</span> collapsed under political opposition vetted by the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Committee_on_Foreign_Investment_in_the_United_States\">Committee on Foreign Investment in the United States</span></b>. Chinese companies likewise advanced into technology and consumer brands, a trend epitomised by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lenovo\">Lenovo</span>'s 2005 purchase of the personal-computer division of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"IBM\">IBM</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Geely\">Geely</span>'s 2010 acquisition of the Swedish carmaker <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Volvo_Cars\">Volvo</span>. From 2013 the strategy increasingly merged with the Belt and Road Initiative championed by Xi Jinping, an immense program of overseas infrastructure lending that critics abroad came to portray as a form of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Debt-trap_diplomacy\">debt-trap diplomacy</span>. Even as record transactions such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"ChemChina\">ChemChina</span>'s roughly 43-billion-dollar takeover of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Syngenta\">Syngenta</span> drove Chinese outbound deals to new heights, mounting alarm over capital flight led Beijing from around 2016 to restrain \"irrational\" foreign spending by conglomerates such as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"HNA_Group\">HNA Group</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anbang\">Anbang</span> and to tighten <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capital_control\">capital controls</span>. Despite this retrenchment, the policy durably reshaped patterns of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"International_trade\">global commerce</span>, transforming once-insular firms into leading cross-border investors and embedding outward expansion at the heart of the modern <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">Chinese economy</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Go Out policy"},{"id":"cne-057","num":"五十七","category":"China · Economics","question":"Listed in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> as the main subsidiary of a state oil group, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> briefly became the world's most valuable firm after its <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> Shanghai debut, counted Warren Buffett among its past investors, and operates as a major state-owned enterprise.","answer":"PetroChina","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">founded 1999</span></div>","traditional":"中國石油","hanzi":"中国石油","pinyin":"Zhōngguó Shíyóu","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōngguó Shíyóu</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“China Petroleum”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>PetroChina</b> is a Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Petroleum\">oil</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Natural_gas\">natural gas</span> company and the publicly listed arm of the state-owned <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_National_Petroleum_Corporation\">China National Petroleum Corporation</span>, ranking among the country's and the world's <b>largest producers of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Energy_industry\">energy</span></b> by output and revenue. It was <b>incorporated in 1999</b> as the main operating subsidiary spun out of its parent's reorganization under China's broader <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">economic reforms</span>, and held an <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Initial_public_offering\">initial public offering</span> in 2000 that raised about 2.9 billion dollars, listing on the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_Stock_Exchange\">Hong Kong</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_York_Stock_Exchange\">New York</span> exchanges while the parent retained roughly 86 percent of its shares. Its operations span <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Upstream_(petroleum_industry)\">upstream</span> exploration and production at giant fields such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Daqing_Oil_Field\">Daqing</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tarim_Basin\">Tarim Basin</span>, which make it China's biggest producer of crude oil and natural gas, as well as downstream <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Oil_refinery\">refining</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Petrochemical\">petrochemicals</span>, and a vast <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pipeline_transport\">pipeline</span> network carrying gas from western fields to the populous east. It markets fuel through tens <b>of thousands of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Filling_station\">filling stations</span></b> and stands alongside <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sinopec\">Sinopec</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"CNOOC\">CNOOC</span> among China's dominant state-owned oil majors, focusing more heavily on oil and gas extraction than its refining-oriented peers. Consistently ranked among the world's largest corporations on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fortune_Global_500\">Fortune Global 500</span>, with annual revenue in the hundreds of billions of dollars, the company is central to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Energy_in_China\">China's energy</span> sector and to the nation's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Energy_security\">energy security</span>, investing heavily in overseas oil and gas projects across Asia, Africa, and the Middle East. <br> <br> <b>In November 2007 PetroChina</b> made its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"A_share_(mainland_China)\">A-share</span> debut on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_Stock_Exchange\">Shanghai Stock Exchange</span>, where the stock nearly tripled on its opening day amid a frenzied domestic market that had roughly doubled that year. The surge briefly pushed its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Market_capitalization\">market capitalization</span> above 1 trillion dollars on paper—a level no company had reached before—making it for a moment the world's most valuable listed firm, ahead of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"ExxonMobil\">ExxonMobil</span>, though analysts widely dismissed the figure as a product of a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Speculation\">speculative</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stock_market_bubble\">bubble</span>. The valuation rested on a small <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Public_float\">free float</span> of A-shares trading</b> at several times the price of the firm's Hong Kong-listed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"H_share\">H-shares</span> held by foreign investors, and the stock then collapsed over the following years as the broader Chinese market deflated, erasing most of the paper wealth created on its opening day. The American investor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Warren_Buffett\">Warren Buffett</span>, through his firm <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Berkshire_Hathaway\">Berkshire Hathaway</span>, had bought about 488 million dollars of those <b>Hong Kong shares around 2002</b> and 2003 and sold the entire stake in 2007 for roughly 4 billion dollars, an eightfold gain realized just before the Shanghai listing. Buffett had faced <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Divestment\">divestment</span> pressure from activists over the parent group's oil operations in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sudan\">Sudan</span> during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"War_in_Darfur\">Darfur conflict</span>, a campaign he resisted before ultimately exiting, and PetroChina remains a state-controlled <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_enterprises_of_China\">national champion</span> overseen through China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_Assets_Supervision_and_Administration_Commission\">state asset regulators</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"PetroChina"},{"id":"cnp-074","num":"七十四","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Introduced around <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> by Jiang Zemin and written into the Party constitution, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> represent advanced productive forces, advanced culture, and the interests of the majority, opening membership to private entrepreneurs.","answer":"Three Represents","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Coined</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Jiang Zemin, 2000</span></div>","traditional":"三個代表","hanzi":"三个代表","pinyin":"sān gè dàibiǎo","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">sān gè dàibiǎo</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Three Represents</b> is a guiding ideology of Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Communism\">communism</span>, formally titled the \"Important Thought of Three Represents\" and credited to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paramount_leader\">paramount leader</span> Jiang Zemin, which asserts that the ruling party must perpetually represent the development demands <b>of China's advanced <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Productive_forces\">productive forces</span></b>, the progressive orientation of its advanced culture, and the fundamental interests of the overwhelming majority of its people. Jiang first set out the formulation during a <b>February 2000 inspection</b> tour of the southern province of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guangdong\">Guangdong</span>, where two decades of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">market reform</span> initiated by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> had produced a flourishing private economy and a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialist_market_economy\">socialist market economy</span> increasingly at odds with the party's traditional self-image. The theory's most far-reaching and politically sensitive consequence was the justification it furnished for admitting private entrepreneurs—long regarded with suspicion in a party of workers and peasants—into its ranks, a move Jiang publicly endorsed in his keynote <b>speech of 1 July 2001</b> marking the 80th anniversary of the party's founding. That decision represented a striking departure from the party's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marxism\">Marxist</span> self-conception as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vanguardism\">vanguard</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Proletariat\">proletariat</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peasant\">peasantry</span>, effectively reorienting it toward the model <b>of a broad-based <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Catch-all_party\">catch-all party</span></b> representative of society as a whole. Orthodox leftists steeped in the doctrines of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Karl_Marx\">Karl Marx</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vladimir_Lenin\">Vladimir Lenin</span> condemned the embrace of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capitalism\">capitalist</span> class as a betrayal of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Class_conflict\">class struggle</span>, even as later surveys by political scientists indicated that roughly a third of private entrepreneurs had themselves joined the party.<br> <br>The Three Represents was written into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitution_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">party constitution</span> at <b>the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"16th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">16th National Congress</span> in November 2002</b>, the same gathering at which Jiang surrendered the post of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"General_Secretary_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">general secretary</span> to his designated successor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Jintao\">Hu Jintao</span>, before also vacating the state <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"President_of_China\">presidency</span> the following year. Two years later it was incorporated into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitution_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">state constitution</span> through a 2004 amendment, formally elevating Jiang's contribution to a canon that already comprised <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marxism–Leninism\">Marxism–Leninism</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maoism\">Mao Zedong Thought</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping_Theory\">Deng Xiaoping Theory</span>. The reform was a pragmatic response to the surging weight of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Private_sector\">private sector</span></b> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>'s rapidly expanding economy, a transformation accelerated by the country's accession to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Trade_Organization\">World Trade Organization</span> in December 2001 and the steady erosion of the once-dominant state sector. Detractors on the political left warned that the doctrine legitimized widening income inequality and a retreat from core <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialism\">socialist</span> commitments, whereas its proponents defended it as a necessary adaptation of party theory to the realities of a modernizing, market-oriented economy. Within the official ideological canon the Three Represents was soon joined by <b>Hu Jintao's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Scientific_Outlook_on_Development\">Scientific Outlook on Development</span></b> and, after 2017, by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping_Thought\">Xi Jinping Thought</span>, a sequence that marks it as a pivotal stage in the party's continual effort to reconcile <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialism_with_Chinese_characteristics\">socialism with Chinese characteristics</span> with the pressures of a globalized economy.","citation":"","answerText":"Three Represents"},{"id":"cne-054","num":"五十四","category":"China · Economics","question":"Founded in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> and dominating Chinese-language web search after rivals such as Google withdrew from the mainland, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> later poured resources into artificial intelligence and self-driving cars.","answer":"Baidu","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">founded 2000</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"百度","pinyin":"Bǎidù","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Bǎidù</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Baidu</b> is a Chinese multinational technology company, headquartered in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>, that for two decades dominated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_language\">Chinese-language</span> <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Web_search_engine\">web search</span></b> within <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>. It was <b>founded in January 2000</b> by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Robin_Li\">Robin Li</span> and a co-founder, building on Li's earlier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"RankDex\">RankDex</span> system for ranking web pages by the number and quality of incoming hyperlinks, a technique conceptually similar to the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"PageRank\">PageRank</span></b> algorithm developed at <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Google\">Google</span>. Its distinctive name derives from a line in a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ci_(poetry)\">ci</span> lyric poem by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Song_dynasty\">Song dynasty</span> poet <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xin_Qiji\">Xin Qiji</span>, in which a lover searches a thousand times through a festival crowd, an allusion to the persistent quest for information. Baidu came to control the overwhelming majority of the Chinese search market—at times more than 70 percent of <b>it—after <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Google_China\">Google's mainland operation</span> withdrew in 2010</b> amid a dispute over <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Internet_censorship_in_China\">internet censorship</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Operation_Aurora\">Operation Aurora</span> cyber-attacks. Listed on the American <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nasdaq\">Nasdaq</span> exchange in a spectacular 2005 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Initial_public_offering\">flotation</span>, and later granted a secondary listing on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_Stock_Exchange\">Hong Kong Stock Exchange</span>, it earned most of its revenue from search <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Online_advertising\">advertising</span>, until a <b>2016 scandal</b> over a student's death linked to paid medical ads prompted the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cyberspace_Administration_of_China\">Cyberspace Administration of China</span> to tighten regulation. <br> <br> Facing intensifying competition and the maturing of search, the company poured resources into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Artificial_intelligence\">artificial intelligence</span> from the mid-2010s, recruiting the prominent researcher <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Andrew_Ng\">Andrew Ng</span> to lead its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deep_learning\">deep-learning</span> work and building the open-source <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"PaddlePaddle\">PaddlePaddle</span> framework alongside its own cloud services. It became a <b>national leader in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Self-driving_car\">self-driving cars</span></b> through its Apollo platform, launched in 2017, which came to underpin a commercial <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Robotaxi\">robotaxi</span> fleet operating in Chinese cities such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuhan\">Wuhan</span> and Beijing. When the global generative-AI boom erupted, Baidu launched <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ernie_Bot\">Ernie Bot</span> in 2023, one of China's first <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Large_language_model\">large language models</span> and consumer <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Generative_artificial_intelligence\">generative-AI</span></b> chatbots, explicitly positioned as a domestic answer to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"ChatGPT\">ChatGPT</span>. Baidu had long been grouped with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Alibaba_Group\">Alibaba</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tencent\">Tencent</span> as one of the \"BAT\" trio of Chinese internet giants, although by the 2020s it had fallen well behind the other two in market value as the country's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Big_Tech\">Big Tech</span> sector grew and diversified. Having reinvented itself from a pure search engine into a self-styled artificial-intelligence champion, Baidu came to embody both the rise of China's internet industry and Beijing's drive for leadership in advanced technology as a strategic pillar of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">Chinese economy</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Baidu"},{"id":"cne-087","num":"八十七","category":"China · Economics","question":"The country's largest contract chipmaker, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> sits at the centre of efforts to achieve semiconductor self-sufficiency, but was placed on a US blacklist that cut its access to advanced lithography machines during the tech war.","answer":"Semiconductor Manufacturing International Corporation","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">founded 2000</span></div>","traditional":"中芯國際","hanzi":"中芯国际","pinyin":"Zhōngxīn Guójì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōngxīn Guójì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Semiconductor Manufacturing International Corporation</b>, known as <b>SMIC</b>, is <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>'s largest contract chipmaker and a leading pure-play <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foundry_model\">foundry</span></b>, headquartered in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span> and ranked among the world's biggest manufacturers of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Integrated_circuit\">integrated circuits</span> as well as the only mainland foundry able to produce chips near the technological frontier. It was <b>established in 2000</b> by the Taiwanese-American engineer Richard Chang, a veteran of Texas Instruments who recruited hundreds of overseas Chinese and Taiwanese specialists to build advanced fabrication lines on the mainland, positioning the firm to manufacture chips for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fabless_manufacturing\">fabless</span> designers much as Taiwan's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"TSMC\">TSMC</span> and South Korea's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Samsung_Electronics\">Samsung</span> did. The company <b>listed in 2004</b> on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_Stock_Exchange\">Hong Kong</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_York_Stock_Exchange\">New York</span> exchanges, withdrew its American listing in 2019 amid rising tensions, and raised roughly US$7.5 billion in a 2020 flotation on Shanghai's Nasdaq-style <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"STAR_Market\">STAR Market</span>, underscoring official determination to fund a homegrown chip champion. It sits at the centre of China's drive for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Self-sufficiency\">self-sufficiency</span> in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Semiconductor_industry\">semiconductor industry</span> — a priority of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Made_in_China_2025\">Made in China <b>2025</span> programme</b>, which targeted meeting 70 percent of domestic chip demand locally — backed by the state-run <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Integrated_Circuit_Industry_Investment_Fund\">Big Fund</span>, since imported chips long ranked as the country's single largest import by value, exceeding even crude oil at well over US$300 billion a year. Despite heavy investment the foundry trailed industry leaders by several process generations, <b>reaching <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Semiconductor_device_fabrication\">14-nanometre production</span> around</b> 2019, and it was unable to obtain the cutting-edge <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Extreme_ultraviolet_lithography\">extreme-ultraviolet lithography</span> machines, made solely by the Dutch firm <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"ASML_Holding\">ASML</span> and essential for the most advanced nodes. <br> <br> In December 2020 the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States_Department_of_Commerce\">United States Department of Commerce</span></b>, through its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bureau_of_Industry_and_Security\">Bureau of Industry and Security</span>, added the company to its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Entity_List\">Entity List</span>, requiring licences for American technology and effectively cutting its access to the equipment needed for the most advanced nodes, generally those at 10 nanometres and below. Barred from buying ASML's extreme-ultraviolet tools, which the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Netherlands\">Netherlands</span> had blocked from export under American pressure, SMIC was confined to older deep-ultraviolet <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Photolithography\">lithography</span></b>, restrictions later tightened as the Netherlands and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japan\">Japan</span> joined sweeping export curbs in the intensifying <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China–United_States_trade_war\">technology war</span>. Even so, in 2023 the firm stunned observers by fabricating an advanced <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"7_nm_process\">7-nanometre</span> processor — the Kirin 9000S — for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huawei\">Huawei</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huawei_Mate_60\">Mate 60 Pro</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Smartphone\">smartphone</span> through painstaking <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Multiple_patterning\">multiple-patterning</span> that compensated for the missing EUV machines. The chip was designed by Huawei's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"HiSilicon\">HiSilicon</span> arm, which had earlier been severed from TSMC by American sanctions, and the apparent breakthrough prompted Washington to tighten its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Export_restriction\">export controls</span> still further, notably through sweeping rules in October 2022 targeting chipmaking tools and artificial-intelligence processors bound for China. Buoyed nonetheless by surging domestic demand, the firm's revenue climbed toward US$8 billion and it grew into one of the world's three largest contract chipmakers by sales — commanding around 5 percent of the global foundry market and overtaking long-established rivals such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"GlobalFoundries\">GlobalFoundries</span> — even as it remained several process generations behind the global leaders and dependent on foreign equipment, leaving it at once a symbol of China's technological ambition and a central prize in the rivalry over advanced chipmaking.","citation":"","answerText":"Semiconductor Manufacturing International Corporation"},{"id":"cnp-075","num":"七十五","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Finalised in December <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> after 15 years of negotiations, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> integrated the country into the global trading order, accelerated reform, and bound it to the rules of an organisation based in Geneva under leaders including Jiang Zemin.","answer":"China's accession to the WTO","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">2001</span></div>","traditional":"中國加入世界貿易組織","hanzi":"中国加入世界贸易组织","pinyin":"Zhōngguó jiārù Shìjiè Màoyì Zǔzhī","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōngguó jiārù Shìjiè Màoyì Zǔzhī</span></div>","abstract":"<b>China's accession to the WTO</b> was the culmination of a protracted process by which the People's Republic of China joined the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Trade_Organization\">World Trade Organization</span>, the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Geneva\">Geneva</span></b>-based organization that administers the rules of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"International_trade\">international trade</span>, becoming <b>its 143rd member on December 11, 2001</b>. China had been one of the 23 founding contracting parties <b>of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"General_Agreement_on_Tariffs_and_Trade\">General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade</span> in 1948</b> but withdrew in 1950 following the Communist revolution, and its bid to rejoin the trading system began in earnest with a formal application in July 1986, opening 15 years of arduous negotiations. The decisive breakthroughs came when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Premier_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">Premier</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhu_Rongji\">Zhu Rongji</span> concluded a landmark bilateral agreement with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States\">United States</span>—whose negotiators were led by trade <b>representative <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Charlene_Barshefsky\">Charlene Barshefsky</span>—in November 1999</b>, followed by a parallel accord with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"European_Union\">European Union</span> in May 2000. In 2000 the administration of President <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bill_Clinton\">Bill Clinton</span> secured congressional approval to grant China permanent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Most_favoured_nation\">most-favoured-nation</span> trade status, removing the annual review that had long politicized China's commercial ties with Washington. Under the terms negotiated by its chief representative <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Long_Yongtu\">Long Yongtu</span> and approved at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Doha\">Doha</span> ministerial overseen by Director-General <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mike_Moore_(New_Zealand_politician)\">Mike Moore</span>, China agreed to slash average <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tariff\">tariffs</span> from roughly 15% to under 10%, dismantle many <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Non-tariff_barriers_to_trade\">non-tariff barriers</span></b>, open sectors such as banking and telecommunications, and strengthen protection of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Agreement_on_Trade-Related_Aspects_of_Intellectual_Property_Rights\">intellectual property</span>. <br> <br> Championed by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Communist Party</span> leaders including <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Zemin\">Jiang Zemin</span>, who held the posts of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"General_Secretary_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">general secretary</span> and state <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"President_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">president</span>, accession was used to lock in and accelerate domestic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">economic reform</span>, including the painful restructuring of bloated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_enterprises_of_China\">state-owned enterprises</span>. Its economic impact was profound, as China's annual merchandise <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Export\">exports</span></b> soared from about $266 billion in 2001 to more than $2 trillion within little over a decade, lifting its share of world merchandise exports from roughly 4% to above 10% and propelling the country past Germany to become the world's largest exporter by 2009. A flood of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foreign_direct_investment\">foreign direct investment</span> accompanied the boom, cementing China's role as the \"workshop of the world\" and helping the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">economy</span> overtake Japan to rank as the world's second-largest by 2010, with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gross_domestic_product\">gross domestic product</span> growth averaging close to 10% a year through the decade. The surge also generated friction abroad, as economists later attributed the loss of as many as 2.4 million American manufacturing jobs between 2000 and 2011 to the so-called <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_shock\">China shock</span></b>, while a clause permitting trading partners to treat China as a non-market economy in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dumping_(pricing_policy)\">anti-dumping</span> cases for up to 15 years became a lasting source of dispute as the country's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Balance_of_trade\">trade surplus</span> with Western economies widened. By the time leadership passed to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Jintao\">Hu Jintao</span>, membership had bound China ever more tightly to the institutions of economic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Globalization\">globalization</span> and exposed its industries to fiercer competition, and the accession is now widely regarded as a pivotal turning point that reshaped both the Chinese economy and the structure of global commerce in the early 21st century.","citation":"","answerText":"China's accession to the WTO"},{"id":"cnp-080","num":"八十","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Associated with Hu Jintao and added to the Party constitution in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> called for balanced, sustainable, people-centred growth as a corrective to the environmental and social costs of breakneck economic reform.","answer":"Scientific Outlook on Development","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Coined</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Hu Jintao, advanced from 2003 and written into the charter, 2007</span></div>","traditional":"科學發展觀","hanzi":"科学发展观","pinyin":"kēxué fāzhǎn guān","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">kēxué fāzhǎn guān</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Scientific Outlook on Development</b> is a guiding socio-economic doctrine of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> closely associated with the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Jintao\">Hu Jintao</span></b> era and conceived as a corrective to the social and environmental costs of China's headlong <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">economic reform</span>. First <b>advanced by Hu in 2003</b> and elaborated alongside his premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wen_Jiabao\">Wen Jiabao</span>, the doctrine called for development that was \"people-centred\" (以人为本) as well as comprehensive, coordinated, and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sustainable_development\">sustainable</span></b>, departing from the single-minded pursuit of growth that had defined the preceding decades. Its programmatic core was a set of \"five balances,\" which sought to harmonise urban and rural development long divided by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hukou\">household-registration</span> system, coordinate the prosperous coast with the lagging interior, reconcile economic expansion with social welfare and the protection of the natural environment, and integrate domestic growth with engagement abroad. These priorities responded to mounting strains of the reform era, including a soaring <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gini_coefficient\">Gini coefficient</span> that <b>approached 0.49 by 2008</b>, widening <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economic_inequality\">inequality</span> between city and countryside, and severe <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pollution_in_China\">pollution</span> that saw China overtake the United States around 2006 as the world's largest emitter of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Greenhouse_gas_emissions_by_China\">greenhouse gases</span>. The doctrine was paired with the parallel goal of building a \"<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Harmonious_Society\">harmonious society</span>\" and was operationalised <b>through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five-year_plans_of_China\">11th Five-Year Plan</span> of 2006–2010</b>, which introduced binding national targets to cut <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Energy_intensity\">energy intensity</span> per unit of economic output. <br> <br> In the official canon of party theory, the Scientific Outlook on Development takes its place in a succession of doctrines running from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marxism–Leninism\">Marxism–Leninism</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maoism\">Mao Zedong Thought</span> through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping_Theory\">Deng Xiaoping Theory</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Zemin\">Jiang Zemin</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Represents\">Three Represents</span> to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping_Thought\">Xi Jinping Thought</span>. It was written into the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitution_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">party constitution</span> at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"17th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">17th National Congress</span></b> in October 2007, having first been set out by Hu in 2003 at a plenary session of the Central Committee elected by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"16th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">16th National Congress</span>. At the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"18th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">18th National Congress</span> in 2012 it was elevated to a formal \"guide to action\" on a par with the earlier theories, and in 2018 it was additionally inscribed in the state <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitution_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">constitution</span> of the People's Republic. Regarded as the signature theoretical contribution of Hu — who rose through the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Communist_Youth_League_of_China\">Communist Youth League</span></b> to become <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"General_Secretary_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">General Secretary</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"President_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">President</span> and a leading figure of the so-called 4th <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Generations_of_Chinese_leadership\">generation</span> — the doctrine framed its objectives within the longer project of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialism_with_Chinese_characteristics\">socialism with Chinese characteristics</span> and the drive to complete a \"moderately prosperous society,\" or <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiaokang\">xiaokang</span>. Although it remains formally embedded in the party's ideological framework, the concept has been substantially overshadowed since 2012 by the rise of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span> as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paramount_leader\">paramount leader</span>, whose own enshrined thought now dominates official discourse and has relegated Hu's once-prominent formula to a comparatively minor place in the pantheon of guiding doctrines.","citation":"","answerText":"Scientific Outlook on Development"},{"id":"cne-059","num":"五十九","category":"China · Economics","question":"Set up in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> to act as the controlling shareholder of the central government's biggest companies, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> manages the giant state-owned enterprises and appoints their bosses in coordination with the Communist Party.","answer":"State-owned Assets Supervision and Administration Commission","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">founded 2003</span></div>","traditional":"國有資產監督管理委員會","hanzi":"国有资产监督管理委员会","pinyin":"Guóyǒu Zīchǎn Jiāndū Guǎnlǐ Wěiyuánhuì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Guóyǒu Zīchǎn Jiāndū Guǎnlǐ Wěiyuánhuì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>State-owned Assets Supervision and Administration Commission</b>, commonly abbreviated SASAC, is a special commission directly under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_Council_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">State Council</span>, China's central <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Government_of_China\">government</span></b>, that acts as the controlling <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shareholder\">shareholder</span> of the country's biggest non-financial <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_enterprises_of_China\">state enterprises</span> and ranks among the most powerful economic bodies in the world. It was <b>established in 2003</b>, during the era of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">economic reform</span>, to consolidate the state's previously fragmented ownership rights, replace supervision by a patchwork of competing ministries, and preserve and grow the value of public <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Asset\">assets</span> held by the central <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cabinet_(government)\">cabinet</span>. Its creation embodied the policy of \"grasping the large and letting go of the small,\" under which thousands of smaller and loss-making firms were closed, merged, or subjected to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Privatization\">privatization</span> during the 1990s and after, while the state retained, recapitalized, and consolidated its biggest <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_champions\">national champions</span>. Acting as an owner rather than a regulator, the commission appoints and dismisses top executives, approves major <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mergers_and_acquisitions\">mergers</span> and restructurings, sets profit and investment targets, and shapes the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Corporate_governance\">corporate governance</span> of the firms it</b> supervises, increasingly delegating ownership to state capital investment and operation companies. The enterprises it controls dominate the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Commanding_heights_of_the_economy\">commanding heights</span> of the economy—energy, telecommunications, defense, transport, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Heavy_industry\">heavy industry</span>—and the system is mirrored by hundreds of local commissions overseeing state firms owned by governments in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Provinces_of_China\">provinces</span> and cities. <br> <br> Among the giant <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Conglomerate_(company)\">conglomerates</span></b> under its supervision are the oil group <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_National_Petroleum_Corporation\">China National Petroleum</span>, parent of the listed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"PetroChina\">PetroChina</span>, alongside the refiner <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sinopec\">Sinopec</span>, the power giant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_Grid_Corporation_of_China\">State Grid</span>, the mobile carrier <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Mobile\">China Mobile</span></b>, and the aerospace and defense maker <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Aviation_Industry_Corporation_of_China\">AVIC</span>, among roughly a hundred such groups. The number of these central enterprises has fallen from nearly 200 at the commission's founding in 2003 to under 100 in recent years through state-engineered consolidation, yet together they hold assets worth tens of trillions of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Renminbi\">yuan</span> and employ tens of millions of workers across strategic sectors. By the combined value of the firms it ultimately owns, the commission is frequently described as the world's largest <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Controlling_interest\">controlling shareholder</span></b> and a defining instrument of Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_capitalism\">state capitalism</span>, an arrangement with no close equivalent in major market economies. Crucially, it does not appoint enterprise leaders alone: senior personnel are selected in coordination with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Communist Party</span>'s powerful <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Organization_Department_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Organization Department</span></b> through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nomenklatura\">nomenklatura</span> system of political appointments, with many chief executives ranking as senior <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cadre_(politics)\">cadres</span> of vice-ministerial status and the Party's role within state firms markedly strengthened under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span>. Notably, China's large state-owned banks and insurers fall outside its remit, their shares instead held by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ministry_of_Finance_(China)\">Ministry of Finance</span> and by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Huijin_Investment\">Central Huijin</span>, an arm of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sovereign_wealth_fund\">sovereign wealth fund</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Investment_Corporation\">China Investment Corporation</span>, leaving the commission focused on the industrial, energy, and commercial core of the state sector.","citation":"","answerText":"State-owned Assets Supervision and Administration Commission"},{"id":"cnp-081","num":"八十一","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Promoted from around <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> under Hu Jintao and Wen Jiabao, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> sought to ease the inequality and unrest produced by rapid growth, drawing on Confucian ideals of balance.","answer":"Harmonious Society","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Coined</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Hu Jintao, c. 2004–05</span></div>","traditional":"和諧社會","hanzi":"和谐社会","pinyin":"héxié shèhuì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">héxié shèhuì</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Harmonious Society</b> was a guiding socioeconomic vision promoted by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> leadership of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Jintao\">Hu Jintao</span> and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wen_Jiabao\">Wen Jiabao</span></b> in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span> <b>from around 2004</b>. The slogan of building a \"socialist harmonious society\" was advanced at the 4th plenum of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"16th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">16th Party Congress</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Central Committee</span> in 2004, elaborated by Hu in <b>a major address in 2005</b>, and given doctrinal weight by a dedicated resolution at the 6th plenum in 2006. It represented a deliberate corrective to the side effects of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">market reforms</span> launched by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>, whose breakneck <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economic_growth\">growth</span> had generated severe <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economic_inequality\">inequality</span>, environmental degradation, and rising social tension across the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialist_market_economy\">socialist market economy</span>. By the late <b>2000s the country's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gini_coefficient\">Gini coefficient</span></b> had climbed to roughly 0.49, well above the 0.4 threshold often regarded as a marker of destabilising disparity, while officially tallied \"mass incidents\" of protest had multiplied to around 87,000 in 2005 alone. Conceptually it was paired with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Scientific_Outlook_on_Development\">Scientific Outlook on Development</span>, Hu's signature contribution to the party's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ideology_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">ideology</span> emphasising people-centred, balanced, and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sustainable_development\">sustainable development</span></b>, succeeding the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Represents\">Three Represents</span> theory associated with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Zemin\">Jiang Zemin</span>. <br> <br> The vision consciously drew on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucianism\">Confucian</span> ideals of social harmony, invoking the reverence for balance attributed to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Confucius\">Confucius</span> in texts such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Analects\">Analects</span>, with its maxim that harmony is to be prized, and the utopian ideal of \"great unity\" found in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Book_of_Rites\">Book of Rites</span>. In practice the agenda translated into a raft of redistributive measures, including the <b>2006 abolition</b> of the centuries-old agricultural <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taxation_in_China\">tax</span>, the extension of subsidised rural <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Healthcare_in_China\">healthcare</span>, the waiving of rural school fees, and a campaign to build a \"new socialist countryside.\" Further initiatives such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Labour_Contract_Law_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">Labour Contract Law</span> of 2008 and the ongoing <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Western_Development\">Western Development</span></b> programme sought to protect workers and narrow the yawning gap between the prosperous coast and the lagging interior. Critics charged that the rhetoric of harmony masked an expanding apparatus of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Censorship_in_China\">censorship</span> and \"stability maintenance,\" and Chinese netizens turned the term into bitter satire, coining \"to be harmonised\" as a euphemism for being silenced and adopting the homophonous \"river crab\" as a mascot of online <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Internet_censorship_in_China\">repression</span>. The associated Scientific Outlook was written into the party's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitution_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">constitution</span> in 2007, anchoring the goal within the rhetoric of the so-called 4th <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Generations_of_Chinese_leadership\">generation of leadership</span>, yet after 2012 its prominence faded as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span> reframed national aspirations around the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Dream\">Chinese Dream</span> and the later drive for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Common_prosperity\">common prosperity</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Harmonious Society"},{"id":"cne-060","num":"六十","category":"China · Economics","question":"Founded in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> to earn better returns on part of the country's vast foreign exchange reserves, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> became one of the world's largest sovereign wealth funds, investing globally on behalf of the state.","answer":"China Investment Corporation","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">founded 2007</span></div>","traditional":"中國投資有限責任公司","hanzi":"中国投资有限责任公司","pinyin":"Zhōngguó Tóuzī Yǒuxiàn Zérèn Gōngsī","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōngguó Tóuzī Yǒuxiàn Zérèn Gōngsī</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“China Investment Limited Liability Company”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>China Investment Corporation</b>, commonly abbreviated CIC, is the principal sovereign wealth fund of the People's Republic of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> and one of the largest such institutions in the world. It was <b>created in 2007</b> to obtain higher returns on a portion of the country's enormous foreign exchange reserves, which by then exceeded 1.4 trillion US dollars and had been invested heavily in low-yielding <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States_Treasury_security\">United States Treasury securities</span></b>. The fund was endowed with an initial 200 billion US dollars, raised when the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ministry_of_Finance_(China)\">Ministry of Finance</span> issued roughly 1.55 trillion <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Renminbi\">yuan</span> in special <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Government_bond\">government bonds</span> to purchase foreign currency from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Bank_of_China\">People's Bank of China</span>, and it answers ultimately to the State Council from its headquarters in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>. A substantial share of its assets is held through the subsidiary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Huijin_Investment\">Central Huijin Investment</span>, which manages the government's controlling stakes in the leading state banks of the country's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Banking_in_China\">banking system</span>, among them the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Industrial_and_Commercial_Bank_of_China\">Industrial and Commercial Bank of China</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Construction_Bank\">China Construction Bank</span>, the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bank_of_China\">Bank of China</span></b>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Agricultural_Bank_of_China\">Agricultural Bank of China</span>. Its first chairman, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lou_Jiwei\">Lou Jiwei</span>, who would go on to serve as China's finance minister, was charged with deploying the fund's overseas capital to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Diversification_(finance)\">diversify</span> the nation's holdings and to pursue stronger long-term <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rate_of_return\">returns</span></b> than reserve assets had previously earned.<br> <br>Among its earliest and most conspicuous moves, both made in 2007 on the eve of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Recession\">global financial crisis</span>, were a 3-billion-dollar stake in the American private-equity firm <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Blackstone_Group\">Blackstone</span> and a 5-billion-dollar investment in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Investment_banking\">investment bank</span></b> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Morgan_Stanley\">Morgan Stanley</span>, transactions that soon incurred heavy paper losses and provoked criticism at home. Over time the corporation assembled a broadly diversified global <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Portfolio_(finance)\">portfolio</span> spanning publicly listed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stock\">equities</span>, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Private_equity\">private equity</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hedge_fund\">hedge funds</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Real_estate\">real estate</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Infrastructure\">infrastructure</span>, managed in large part through its international investment arm. Its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Assets_under_management\">assets under management</span> climbed past 1 trillion dollars within little more than a decade, placing it among the very largest sovereign funds in the world, on a scale comparable to <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Government_Pension_Fund_of_Norway\">Norway's government pension fund</span></b> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Abu_Dhabi_Investment_Authority\">Abu Dhabi Investment Authority</span>. As a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_capitalism\">state-controlled</span> investor, it has at times attracted scrutiny abroad, with several of its bids reviewed by bodies such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Committee_on_Foreign_Investment_in_the_United_States\">Committee on Foreign Investment in the United States</span> over concerns about strategic motives, even as the fund stressed its purely commercial objectives. Together with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_Administration_of_Foreign_Exchange\">State Administration of Foreign Exchange</span>, the corporation forms a central pillar of the way the state manages its external wealth, and it remains a prominent instrument of the broader <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">Chinese economy</span>'s engagement with global <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capital_market\">capital markets</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"China Investment Corporation"},{"id":"cne-066","num":"六十六","category":"China · Economics","question":"Encompassing wealth-management products, trust loans and other credit outside the formal banking system, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> grew rapidly as savers sought higher returns than the central bank allowed on deposits, prompting repeated crackdowns over systemic risk.","answer":"Shadow banking","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Coined</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Paul McCulley, 2007</span></div>","traditional":"影子銀行","hanzi":"影子银行","pinyin":"yǐngzi yínháng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">yǐngzi yínháng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Shadow banking</b> <b>refers to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Credit_(finance)\">credit</span></b> intermediation carried out by non-bank <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Financial_intermediary\">financial intermediaries</span> or off the balance sheets of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bank\">banks</span>, outside the deposit insurance, capital rules, and supervisory oversight that govern conventional lenders. The term was coined by the <b>American economist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paul_McCulley\">Paul McCulley</span> in 2007</b> and gained worldwide prominence during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2007–2008_financial_crisis\">global financial crisis</span>, when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Securitization\">securitization</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Money_market_fund\">money market funds</span>, and other off-balance-sheet vehicles spread risk in ways monitored ever since by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Financial_Stability_Board\">Financial Stability Board</span>. In China the sector grew especially large <b>from around 2010</b>, encompassing high-yielding <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wealth_management\">wealth-management products</span> sold by banks to ordinary savers, loans extended by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Trust_company\">trust companies</span>, interbank and entrusted credit, online money funds such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yu'e_Bao\">Yu'e Bao</span>, and a <b>sprawling wave of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peer-to-peer_lending\">peer-to-peer lending</span></b> platforms numbering in the thousands at their peak. Much of this activity moved lending <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Off-balance-sheet\">off banks' balance sheets</span> to evade loan quotas, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capital_requirement\">capital requirements</span>, and restrictions on lending to certain sectors, channeling funds to borrowers such as private firms and developers that struggled to obtain ordinary bank loans. It expanded rapidly through the 2010s until broad estimates of its assets ran into the tens of trillions of yuan—by some measures equivalent to most of a year's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gross_domestic_product\">gross domestic product</span>—making it one of the largest sources of credit in China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">economy</span> outside the official loan books. <br> <br> Its growth was <b>driven by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Financial_repression\">financial repression</span></b>: the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Bank_of_China\">central bank</span> long capped the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Interest_rate\">interest rates</span> that banks could pay on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deposit_account\">deposits</span>, often leaving real returns below inflation and pushing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Saving\">savers</span> toward products promising markedly higher <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yield_(finance)\">yields</span>. On the borrowing side, strong demand came from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Real_estate_development\">property developers</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Local_government_financing_vehicle\">local government financing vehicles</span> that regulators were periodically trying to prevent banks from funding directly, leaving shadow channels to fill the gap at higher cost. The resulting web <b>posed dangers through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maturity_transformation\">maturity transformation</span></b>, in which short-term funds backed longer-term loans, pervasive opacity, and implicit guarantees that bred <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Moral_hazard\">moral hazard</span>, while its deep entanglement with the formal banks that distributed many products and with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Interbank_lending_market\">interbank market</span> raised the threat of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Systemic_risk\">systemic risk</span>. Beijing mounted repeated crackdowns <b>from around 2017</b>, alarmed by surging risk, including a sweeping <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deleveraging\">deleveraging</span> campaign and a set of unified <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Asset_management\">asset-management</span> rules issued in 2018 and enforced by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Banking_and_Insurance_Regulatory_Commission\">banking regulator</span>, tightening <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bank_regulation\">bank regulation</span> to break implicit guarantees and curb opaque channel business. The peer-to-peer boom collapsed in a wave of defaults and fraud, epitomized by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ponzi_scheme\">Ponzi scheme</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ezubao\">Ezubao</span>, which cheated hundreds of thousands of investors, and authorities shut down almost the entire industry by 2020, part of a broader effort that shrank shadow credit even as it remained central to financing parts of the economy that banks underserved.","citation":"","answerText":"Shadow banking"},{"id":"cne-068","num":"六十八","category":"China · Economics","question":"A situation in which a fast-growing economy stalls after reaching moderate prosperity, unable to compete with low-wage rivals or rich innovators, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is a danger that China hopes to escape by climbing the value chain through schemes like Made in China <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> rather than relying on cheap manufacturing and exports.","answer":"Middle income trap","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Coined</span><span class=\"dt-v\">World Bank economists Gill and Kharas, 2007</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"中等收入陷阱","pinyin":"zhōngděng shōurù xiànjǐng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">zhōngděng shōurù xiànjǐng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>middle income trap</b> is a <b>concept in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Development_economics\">development economics</span></b> describing a situation in which a fast-growing economy stalls after reaching moderate prosperity, caught between low-wage rivals it can no longer undercut and rich innovators it cannot yet match. The term was <b>popularised in 2007</b> by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Bank\">World Bank</span> economists, notably <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Indermit_Gill\">Indermit Gill</span> and Homi Kharas, to describe middle-income countries that climb to a comfortable <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Per_capita_income\">income per head</span></b> but then stagnate, never crossing the line into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Bank_high-income_economy\">high-income</span> status as the rich world's economies have. As <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wage\">wages</span> rise during rapid catch-up, such economies lose the cheap-labour edge that drove their early <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economic_growth\">growth</span>, yet they frequently lack the rising <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Total_factor_productivity\">productivity</span></b>, skilled <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Human_capital\">human capital</span>, sound institutions, and capacity for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Innovation\">innovation</span> needed to compete with advanced economies in higher-value industries. Relatively few <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Developing_country\">developing economies</span> have escaped: the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Asian_Tigers\">Four Asian Tigers</span>, among them <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South_Korea\">South Korea</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span>, broke through to wealth, whereas many in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Latin_America\">Latin America</span>, such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Brazil\">Brazil</span>, languished at middle income for decades. Escaping the trap is generally thought to require moving up the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Value_chain\">value chain</span> through sustained investment in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Research_and_development\">research and development</span>, education, and technological upgrading, a challenge the World Bank made the <b>central theme of its 2024 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Development_Report\">World Development Report</span></b>, which noted how few economies had managed the transition since 1990. <br> <br> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> became an upper-middle-income country around 2010 and by the 2020s had pushed its income per head close to the high-income threshold, making the question of whether it can avoid the trap central to the future of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">Chinese economy</span>. To escape it, Beijing has pursued an aggressive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Industrial_policy\">industrial policy</span> <b>epitomised by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Made_in_China_2025\">Made in China 2025</span></b>, a plan unveiled in 2015 to upgrade the country's vast <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manufacturing\">manufacturing</span> base away from cheap, labour-intensive assembly and toward technologically sophisticated, higher-margin sectors. The strategy targets high-value industries such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Semiconductor_industry\">semiconductors</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Electric_vehicle\">electric vehicles</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Robotics\">robotics</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Artificial_intelligence\">artificial intelligence</span>, seeking to replace dependence on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Export-oriented_industrialization\">export-led</span> low-cost production with domestic innovation. It has also tried to rebalance growth toward domestic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Consumption_(economics)\">consumption</span> under the banner of \"<b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dual_circulation\">dual circulation</span></b>\" and has lifted research spending to among the highest levels in the world in absolute terms. Yet the country faces formidable headwinds, as climbing labour costs drive low-end factories to cheaper rivals such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vietnam\">Vietnam</span>, a rapidly ageing population strains its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Demographics_of_China\">demographics</span>, and slowing productivity growth tests whether even a state as powerful as China's can engineer the rare transition from middle income to fully <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Developed_country\">developed</span> status.","citation":"","answerText":"Middle income trap"},{"id":"cnp-082","num":"八十二","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Released in December <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> and modelled on a Czechoslovak dissident document, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> called for democratic reform, rule of law, and human rights, leading to the imprisonment of its co-author Liu Xiaobo by authorities of the Communist Party under Hu Jintao.","answer":"Charter 08","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">2008</span></div>","traditional":"零八憲章","hanzi":"零八宪章","pinyin":"Língbā Xiànzhāng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Língbā Xiànzhāng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Charter 08</b> was a manifesto and citizens' <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Petition\">petition</span></b> calling for sweeping democratic and legal reform in the People's Republic of China, <b>released on December 10, 2008</b>. Consciously modelled on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Charter_77\">Charter 77</span>, the celebrated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dissident\">dissident</span> declaration <b>drafted in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Czechoslovakia\">Czechoslovakia</span> in 1977</b> by figures such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Václav_Havel\">Václav Havel</span>, the document was deliberately timed to coincide with the 60th anniversary of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Universal_Declaration_of_Human_Rights\">Universal Declaration of Human Rights</span> and the 30th anniversary of China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Democracy_Wall\">Democracy Wall</span> movement. Its 19 recommendations urged the establishment of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liberal_democracy\">constitutional democracy</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Separation_of_powers\">separation of powers</span>, an <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Judicial_independence\">independent judiciary</span> upholding the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rule_of_law\">rule of law</span>, and <b>robust guarantees of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Human_rights\">human rights</span></b>, including <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Freedom_of_speech\">freedom of expression</span>, assembly, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Freedom_of_religion\">religion</span>. The charter further called for an end to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"One-party_state\">one-party rule</span>, the introduction of a genuine <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Multi-party_system\">multi-party system</span>, the protection of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Private_property\">private property</span>, and a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Federalism\">federated</span> republic, demands that struck directly at the foundations of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Communist Party</span> control under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Jintao\">Hu Jintao</span>. Originally signed by 303 intellectuals, lawyers, and activists—among them its principal drafters, the literary critic <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Xiaobo\">Liu Xiaobo</span></b> and the political scientist <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Zuhua\">Zhang Zuhua</span>—it drew thousands of additional signatures across the country in the months that followed. <br> <br> The authorities responded with swift repression, detaining Liu Xiaobo on December 8, 2008, 2 days before the text appeared, and subjecting many signatories to interrogation and surveillance while scrubbing the charter from the country's heavily <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Internet_censorship_in_China\">censored internet</span>. <b>In December 2009</b>, after more than a year in detention, Liu was convicted of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Inciting_subversion_of_state_power\">inciting subversion of state power</span>—partly on the basis of Charter 08 and his essays—and sentenced to 11 years in prison, a punishment that drew widespread international condemnation. While imprisoned, he was awarded the 2010 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nobel_Peace_Prize\">Nobel Peace Prize</span> by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Norwegian_Nobel_Committee\">Norwegian Nobel Committee</span>, which had cited his long, non-violent struggle for human rights and honoured him in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Oslo\">Oslo</span> with an empty chair on the stage because neither he nor his family could attend. Liu died of liver cancer in custody on July 13, 2017, becoming the first Nobel laureate to die under state detention since <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Carl_von_Ossietzky\">Carl von Ossietzky</span> in Nazi Germany, while his widow, <b>the poet <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_Xia_(poet)\">Liu Xia</span></b>, endured years of effective house arrest. Although its immediate political demands went unrealized, Charter 08 became a landmark text of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_democracy_movement\">Chinese democracy movement</span> and a pointed reminder that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> had signed but never ratified the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"International_Covenant_on_Civil_and_Political_Rights\">International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights</span>, securing its place as one of the most consequential dissident statements of post-<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1989_Tiananmen_Square_protests_and_massacre\">Tiananmen</span> China.","citation":"","answerText":"Charter 08"},{"id":"cne-062","num":"六十二","category":"China · Economics","question":"Unveiled in late <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> as the global financial crisis hit exports, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> poured money into infrastructure, railways and construction, sustaining growth under Hu Jintao and Wen Jiabao but leaving a legacy of local debt.","answer":"Chinese economic stimulus program","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">2008</span></div>","traditional":"四萬億計劃","hanzi":"四万亿计划","pinyin":"sì wàn yì jìhuà","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">sì wàn yì jìhuà</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Chinese economic stimulus program</b> refers to the roughly 4-trillion-<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Renminbi\">yuan</span> fiscal package — equivalent to about US$586 billion — that the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_Council_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">State Council</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> <b>announced on 9 November 2008</b> to cushion the economy against the unfolding <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2008_financial_crisis\">global financial crisis</span>. Devised under the administration of President <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Jintao\">Hu Jintao</span> and Premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wen_Jiabao\">Wen Jiabao</span>, the measure responded to a sharp contraction in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Export\">exports</span> as demand in the United States and Europe evaporated during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Recession\">Great Recession</span>, which threatened the millions of manufacturing jobs concentrated in China's coastal provinces. In conception it amounted to a vast exercise in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Keynesian_economics\">Keynesian</span> demand management implemented through aggressive <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fiscal_policy\">fiscal policy</span></b>, channelling state-directed investment into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Infrastructure\">infrastructure</span> rather than relying on tax cuts or direct transfers to households. The single largest tranche, on the order of 1.5 trillion yuan, was earmarked for transport and power projects spanning <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rail_transport_in_China\">railways</span>, highways, airports, and the electricity grid, while a further trillion was directed toward reconstruction following the devastating <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2008_Sichuan_earthquake\">Sichuan earthquake</span> of May 2008. Smaller allocations supported rural development, affordable housing, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Environmental_protection\">environmental protection</span></b>, and technological upgrading, yet only about 1.18 trillion yuan came directly from the central treasury, with the remainder expected to be mobilised by local governments, state banks, and enterprises under the coordination of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Development_and_Reform_Commission\">National Development and Reform Commission</span>. <br> <br> To finance this effort the authorities unleashed an extraordinary monetary expansion, as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Bank_of_China\">People's Bank of China</span> relaxed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Monetary_policy\">monetary policy</span>, expanded the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Money_supply\">money supply</span>, and state banks extended a record 9.6 trillion yuan in new <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Loan\">loans</span> <b>during 2009</b>, nearly double the level of the previous year. The programme is widely credited with sustaining rapid expansion of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gross_domestic_product\">gross domestic product</span> — by roughly 9.4 percent in 2009 and 10.6 percent in 2010 — even as much of the developed world slid into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Recession\">recession</span>, and the country was frequently portrayed as an engine helping to pull the broader <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_economy\">world economy</span></b> back toward recovery. Among the most visible beneficiaries was the country's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"High-speed_rail_in_China\">high-speed rail</span> network, whose breakneck construction over the following decade produced the largest such system in the world, exceeding 40,000 kilometres (25,000 mi) of track by the early 2020s and carrying billions of passenger journeys each year. The spending nonetheless bequeathed a durable legacy of indebtedness, since local administrations skirted borrowing limits by establishing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Local_government_financing_vehicle\">local government financing vehicles</span> that fuelled the rise of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shadow_banking_in_China\">shadow banking</span> and swelled the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_debt_of_China\">national debt</span></b> in the years that followed. Critics further charged that the flood of cheap credit entrenched industrial <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Overcapacity\">overcapacity</span> in sectors such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Steel\">steel</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cement\">cement</span>, inflated a speculative <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Real_estate_bubble\">property bubble</span> that later spawned numerous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Under-occupied_developments_in_China\">under-occupied developments</span>, and stoked the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Inflation\">inflation</span> that policymakers <b>struggled to contain in 2010</b> and 2011.","citation":"","answerText":"Chinese economic stimulus program"},{"id":"cne-065","num":"六十五","category":"China · Economics","question":"Founded in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> and rising fast by selling feature-packed smartphones at thin margins largely through online sales, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> built a wide ecosystem of connected gadgets and later moved into electric cars.","answer":"Xiaomi","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">founded 2010</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"小米","pinyin":"Xiǎomǐ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Xiǎomǐ</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“millet”</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Xiaomi</b> is a Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Multinational_corporation\">multinational</span> <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Consumer_electronics\">consumer electronics</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Technology_company\">technology company</span> headquartered in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> and ranked among the world's largest makers of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Smartphone\">smartphones</span> and connected devices. It was <b>founded in 2010</b> by <b>the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Entrepreneurship\">entrepreneur</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lei_Jun\">Lei Jun</span></b>, previously the chairman of the software firm <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kingsoft\">Kingsoft</span> and an early internet investor, together with a group of co-founders, and grew with extraordinary speed into a global brand within a few years. Xiaomi rose quickly by selling feature-packed phones at razor-thin <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Profit_margin\">profit margins</span>, with Lei Jun publicly pledging to cap hardware net margins at around 5 percent, and by selling largely through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"E-commerce\">online channels</span> and flash sales that bypassed costly <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Retail\">retail</span> markups, a strategy that drew frequent comparisons to Apple. A cornerstone of its early success was <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"MIUI\">MIUI</span>, a heavily customized version of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Android_(operating_system)\">Android</span> first released in 2010 that cultivated a devoted base of \"Mi fans\" and let the company earn growing revenue from internet services, app stores, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Advertising\">advertising</span> layered on top of its low-cost hardware. Competing with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Samsung_Electronics\">Samsung</span>, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Apple_Inc.\">Apple</span></b>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huawei\">Huawei</span>, it became one of the leading global smartphone vendors, shipping well over 100 million handsets a year and ranking as a market leader in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"India\">India</span>, and entered the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fortune_Global_500\">Fortune Global 500</span> as one of the youngest firms ever to qualify. <br> <br> Beyond phones, Xiaomi built one of the world's largest consumer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Internet_of_things\">Internet-of-things</span> platforms, a sprawling ecosystem of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Smart_home\">smart-home</span> and lifestyle gadgets spanning <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Smart_TV\">televisions</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Router_(computing)\">routers</span>, fitness <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Activity_tracker\">trackers</span>, electric scooters, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Air_purifier\">air purifiers</span></b>, and even rice cookers, many priced to undercut established rivals. Many of these products were made by a network of invested partner companies, such as the robot-vacuum maker <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Roborock\">Roborock</span>, and sold under Xiaomi's own Mijia label and affiliated brands, extending its reach into millions of homes in China and abroad. The company held an <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Initial_public_offering\">initial public offering</span> <b>on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_Stock_Exchange\">Hong Kong Stock Exchange</span> in 2018</b>, raising about 4.7 billion dollars at a valuation near 54 billion dollars, as the first firm to list under the bourse's new <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dual-class_stock\">dual-class share</span> rules giving founders outsized voting control. In early 2021 the United States <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States_Department_of_Defense\">Department of Defense</span> briefly designated Xiaomi a company with alleged ties to China's military amid the broader <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China–United_States_trade_war\">technology rivalry</span> with Beijing, a move that restricted American investment in its shares, but the firm sued and a US court led the designation to be lifted later that year. Also <b>in 2021</b> it announced a multibillion-dollar move into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Electric_vehicle\">electric vehicles</span>, with Lei Jun pledging some 10 billion dollars over a decade, and in 2024 it launched its first car, the Xiaomi <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiaomi_SU7\">SU7</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sedan_(automobile)\">sedan</span>, which drew strong demand and marked an ambitious diversification well beyond consumer electronics into a crowded, capital-intensive industry.","citation":"","answerText":"Xiaomi"},{"id":"cne-093","num":"九十三","category":"China · Economics","question":"Dominating food delivery and local services through an army of scooter-riding couriers, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was hit with a record antitrust fine during the regulatory crackdown on big technology firms under Xi Jinping.","answer":"Meituan","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">founded 2010</span></div>","traditional":"美團","hanzi":"美团","pinyin":"Měituán","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Měituán</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Meituan</b> is a Chinese <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Super-app\">super-app</span></b> for everyday consumption, headquartered in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> and dominant in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Food_delivery\">food delivery</span> and a sprawling range of on-demand local services from dining and groceries to travel and entertainment. The company was <b>founded in 2010</b> by the serial entrepreneur <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Xing_(entrepreneur)\">Wang Xing</span>, who had earlier created Chinese imitations of Facebook and Twitter, as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Group_buying\">group-buying</span> website modelled on the American daily-deals pioneer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Groupon\">Groupon</span>, emerging victorious from a brutal shakeout among thousands of similar Chinese start-ups. <b>In 2015</b> it merged with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dianping\">Dianping</span>, a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yelp\">Yelp</span>-style reviews and listings platform founded in 2003, combining discounted group purchases with crowd-sourced restaurant ratings and later building an <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Online_travel_agency\">online travel</span> business whose hotel-booking volumes came to rival the country's largest agencies. Its operations grew to span restaurant delivery, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Restaurant\">restaurant</span> reviews, grocery and community group buying, ride-hailing, movie ticketing, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bicycle-sharing_system\">bike-sharing</span> service <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mobike\">Mobike</span>, which it <b>acquired in 2018</b> for some US$2.7 billion, knitting these into a single platform that processes the bulk of China's online food orders. The business rests on an army of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Motorized_scooter\">scooter</span>-riding <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Courier\">couriers</span> — more than seven million of whom earned income on the platform in a single year — directed by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Artificial_intelligence\">artificial-intelligence</span> dispatch <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Algorithm\">algorithms</span></b> that, at peak, route tens of millions of food orders a day to some 690 million annual users. <br> <br> Backed by the technology giant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tencent\">Tencent</span>, the company raised about US$4.2 billion in a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_Stock_Exchange\">Hong Kong</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Initial_public_offering\">listing</span> in 2018, becoming one of the first firms to float under the exchange's new <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dual-class_stock\">dual-class share</span></b> rules and growing into one of China's most valuable internet companies. It long battled <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Alibaba_Group\">Alibaba</span>'s rival delivery platform <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ele.me\">Ele.me</span> for the market, holding well over half of it, before facing fresh incursions in the mid-2020s from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"ByteDance\">ByteDance</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"JD.com\">JD.com</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pinduoduo\">Pinduoduo</span> that ignited a costly subsidy war in 2025. In October 2021 the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_Administration_for_Market_Regulation\">State Administration for Market Regulation</span> fined the company 3.44 billion yuan — about US$534 million, equal to roughly 3 percent of its prior-year domestic revenue — for abusing its dominance by forcing merchants into exclusive arrangements known as \"pick one of two.\" The penalty formed part of a sweeping <b>regulatory crackdown on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Big_Tech\">big technology</span></b> firms under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span>, which had begun with the abrupt suspension of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ant_Group\">Ant Group</span>'s record US$34 billion stock-market debut in late 2020 and a far larger 18.2-billion-yuan antitrust penalty against Alibaba, whose founder <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jack_Ma\">Jack Ma</span> had retreated from public view, all set against Beijing's drive for \"<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Common_prosperity\">common prosperity</span>.\" Meituan also drew scrutiny over the welfare of its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gig_economy\">gig-economy</span> riders, whose relentless algorithm-set deadlines were exposed in widely read reporting, prompting pledges of better pay and social insurance, yet the firm remained <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>'s pre-eminent platform for local commerce, with revenue surpassing 270 billion yuan and roughly 700 million annual transacting users by the mid-2020s even as new rivals pressed in.","citation":"","answerText":"Meituan"},{"id":"cne-069","num":"六十九","category":"China · Economics","question":"Founded in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> in Fujian and now the world's largest maker of lithium-ion batteries for cars, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> supplies automakers globally and anchors China's dominance of the electric-vehicle battery supply chain.","answer":"Contemporary Amperex Technology","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">founded 2011</span></div>","traditional":"寧德時代","hanzi":"宁德时代","pinyin":"Níngdé Shídài","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Níngdé Shídài</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Contemporary Amperex Technology</b>, commonly known by the acronym <b>CATL</b>, is a Chinese <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Electric_battery\">battery</span></b> manufacturer founded in 2011 by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Robin_Zeng\">Robin Zeng</span> and headquartered in the city of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ningde\">Ningde</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fujian\">Fujian</span> province. The company specializes in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lithium-ion_battery\">lithium-ion batteries</span> and battery systems for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Electric_vehicle\">electric vehicles</span>, and <b>since 2017</b> it has been the world's largest producer of automotive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Electric_vehicle_battery\">traction batteries</span>, a rank it held for the 9th consecutive year in 2025. Industry data placed its share of global power-battery installations at 39.2% in 2025, up 1.2 percentage points and well ahead of domestic rival <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"BYD_Company\">BYD</span>, <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South_Korea\">South Korea</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"LG_Energy_Solution\">LG Energy Solution</span></b>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japan\">Japan</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Panasonic\">Panasonic</span>, while its share outside China climbed to roughly 30%. That year CATL reported revenue of about 423.7 billion <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Renminbi\">yuan</span> (around $61 billion), <b>a 17% rise over 2024</b>, and net profit of 72.2 billion yuan (about $10.4 billion), a 42% increase, on lithium-battery sales of 661 gigawatt-hours. Installed in more than 24 million vehicles worldwide, its batteries power close to 40% of new electric cars and have made it a leading supplier to global <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Automotive_industry\">automakers</span> including <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tesla,_Inc.\">Tesla</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Volkswagen\">Volkswagen</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"BMW\">BMW</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Toyota\">Toyota</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ford_Motor_Company\">Ford</span>. <br> <br> Much of the company's competitiveness rests on its early, large-scale adoption of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lithium_iron_phosphate_battery\">lithium iron phosphate</span> chemistry, which sacrifices some <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Energy_density\">energy density</span> in exchange for lower cost, improved safety, and reduced reliance on scarce <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cobalt\">cobalt</span>. CATL has expanded far beyond passenger cars into grid-scale <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Grid_energy_storage\">energy storage</span>, where it held a <b>30.4% global share in 2025</b>, as well as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battery_recycling\">battery recycling</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Battery_swapping\">battery-swapping</span> networks, and emerging <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sodium-ion_battery\">sodium-ion batteries</span> designed to cut dependence on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lithium\">lithium</span>. After its 2018 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Initial_public_offering\">initial public offering</span> on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shenzhen_Stock_Exchange\">Shenzhen Stock Exchange</span>, the firm raised about $4.6 billion in a 2025 secondary listing on the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stock_Exchange_of_Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong Stock Exchange</span></b>, among the largest share sales of the year, helping to finance an aggressive build-out of overseas factories. Its dominance has nonetheless attracted scrutiny in Western markets over <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Supply_chain\">supply-chain</span> concentration and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Technology_transfer\">technology transfer</span>, prompting some automakers to license its technology for locally built plants rather than import cells, while the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States_Department_of_Defense\">United States Department of Defense</span> added the company to a list of firms it alleges are linked to China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army\">military</span>, a designation CATL has rejected. Backed by some 23,000 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Research_and_development\">research</span> personnel and manufacturing capacity of roughly 770 gigawatt-hours across 13 production bases and a presence in more than 60 countries, CATL stands at the center of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>'s commanding position in the global battery industry and the worldwide shift toward electrified transport.","citation":"","answerText":"Contemporary Amperex Technology"},{"id":"cnp-087","num":"八十七","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Unveiled by Xi Jinping shortly after he took power, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> ties personal aspiration to a \"great rejuvenation of the Chinese nation\", a revival meant to be realised by the centenaries of the Communist Party and the People's Republic.","answer":"Chinese Dream","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">2012</span></div>","traditional":"中國夢","hanzi":"中国梦","pinyin":"Zhōngguó mèng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōngguó mèng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Chinese Dream</b> is a political slogan and guiding ideological concept associated with <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span></b>, who unveiled it shortly after becoming <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"General_Secretary_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">General Secretary</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> <b>at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"18th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">18th Party Congress</span> in November 2012.</b> He first articulated the phrase on 29 November 2012 during a visit to the \"Road to Rejuvenation\" exhibition at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Museum_of_China\">National Museum of China</span></b>, a display tracing the nation's modern trajectory, where he tied it explicitly to the \"great rejuvenation of the Chinese nation\" after what the party portrays as a long era of national weakness and decline. Although the slogan binds individual aspiration and personal success to the collective fortunes of the nation, commentators have frequently contrasted it with the more individualistic <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"American_Dream\">American Dream</span></b>, emphasising that the Chinese formulation subordinates private ambition to a state-defined vision of national strength and growing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soft_power\">soft power</span> abroad. The concept draws heavily on the narrative of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Century_of_humiliation\">Century of Humiliation</span>, the era of foreign domination, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Unequal_treaty\">unequal treaties</span>, and internal weakness stretching from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Opium_War\">First Opium War</span> and the decline of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qing_dynasty\">Qing dynasty</span> to the founding <b>of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic</span> in 1949</b>. In this respect it serves as Xi's signature contribution to a lineage of leadership doctrines extending from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>'s reform era through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Zemin\">Jiang Zemin</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Represents\">Three Represents</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Jintao\">Hu Jintao</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Scientific_Outlook_on_Development\">Scientific Outlook on Development</span> and vision of a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Harmonious_Society\">harmonious society</span>. <br> <br> The realisation of the Chinese Dream is pegged to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Two_Centenaries\">Two Centenaries</span>, a pair of benchmark anniversaries comprising the 100th year of the party's <b>founding in 1921</b> and the centenary of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Proclamation_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">republic's founding</span> in 1949, twin deadlines that lend the vision a concrete temporal horizon. By the first of these milestones, reached in 2021, China was to have completed the building of a \"moderately prosperous society,\" or <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiaokang\">xiaokang</span>, a goal the leadership formally declared accomplished alongside the elimination of extreme rural <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Poverty_in_China\">poverty</span></b>, which official figures credited with lifting nearly 100 million people above the poverty line. By the second milestone in 2049, the nation is meant to have become a \"great modern socialist country\" that is prosperous, strong, democratic, culturally advanced, and harmonious, an ambition closely bound up with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialism_with_Chinese_characteristics\">socialism with Chinese characteristics</span> and the rapid military modernisation of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army\">People's Liberation Army</span>. Promoted relentlessly through state <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Propaganda_in_China\">propaganda</span>, the slogan swiftly saturated billboards, school curricula, and official media, becoming a central vehicle for the cultivation of patriotic sentiment and resurgent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_nationalism\">Chinese nationalism</span>. Enshrined in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitution_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">party constitution</span> as part of the broader framework of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping_Thought\">Xi Jinping Thought</span>, the Chinese Dream has since underpinned signature initiatives ranging from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Belt_and_Road_Initiative\">Belt and Road Initiative</span> to the industrial strategy <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Made_in_China_2025\">Made in China 2025</span>, framing Xi's tenure as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paramount_leader\">paramount leader</span> around the restoration of national greatness.","citation":"","answerText":"Chinese Dream"},{"id":"cnp-088","num":"八十八","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Pledging to catch both \"tigers and flies\", the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> drive launched in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> by Xi Jinping investigated and purged vast numbers of officials, including the former security chief Zhou Yongkang, and was run largely through the Party's discipline inspectors.","answer":"Anti-corruption campaign under Xi Jinping","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Origin</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Launched by Xi Jinping on taking power, 2012–13</span></div>","traditional":"反腐運動","hanzi":"反腐运动","pinyin":"fǎnfǔ yùndòng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">fǎnfǔ yùndòng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>anti-corruption campaign under Xi Jinping</b> is the sweeping and sustained drive against official graft that <b>began in late 2012</b>, immediately after Xi Jinping took over as the party's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"General_Secretary_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">general secretary</span> at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"18th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">18th National Congress</span></b> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span>. Framed by Xi's pledge to strike at both powerful \"tigers\" and lowly \"flies,\" it became the most extensive campaign against <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Corruption_in_China\">corruption</span> in the history of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic</span>, targeting graft long ranked as endemic by bodies such as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Transparency_International\">Transparency International</span></b> in its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Corruption_Perceptions_Index\">Corruption Perceptions Index</span>. Operational authority rested largely with the party's discipline inspectors, then led by Xi's close ally <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Qishan\">Wang Qishan</span>, who wielded the extralegal detention system known as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shuanggui\">shuanggui</span> to interrogate suspected cadres outside the ordinary courts. Within just 5 years the apparatus had punished more than 1.5 million officials, ranging from village cadres to ministers and generals, a tally announced <b>at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"19th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">19th National Congress</span> in 2017</b>, after which the inspection chiefs <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhao_Leji\">Zhao Leji</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Xi\">Li Xi</span> carried the drive onward. Its most spectacular target was the former security chief Zhou Yongkang, who in 2015 was sentenced to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Life_imprisonment\">life imprisonment</span>, becoming the most senior figure ever prosecuted and breaking an unwritten taboo that no member of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_Standing_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo Standing Committee</span>, serving or retired, would face criminal trial.<br> <br>The drive's most prominent \"tigers\" included <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bo_Xilai\">Bo Xilai</span>, the charismatic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Princelings\">princeling</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo</span> member who governed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chongqing\">Chongqing</span> before his dramatic fall culminated in <b>a life sentence in 2013</b>. The former vice-chairmen of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Military_Commission_(China)\">Central Military Commission</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xu_Caihou\">Xu Caihou</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Guo_Boxiong\">Guo Boxiong</span>, were brought down for selling military promotions, laying bare the extent of graft within the armed forces. Other felled grandees included <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ling_Jihua\">Ling Jihua</span></b>, the powerful former aide to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Jintao\">Hu Jintao</span> and a figure linked to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Communist_Youth_League_of_China\">Communist Youth League</span> faction, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sun_Zhengcai\">Sun Zhengcai</span>, once tipped as a future supreme leader, whose downfalls many analysts read as strikes against rival <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Factions_in_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">factions</span>. Zhou Yongkang's case in particular dismantled an entrenched web reaching from the domestic-security organs of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Political_and_Legal_Affairs_Commission\">Central Political and Legal Affairs Commission</span></b> to the oil interests of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_National_Petroleum_Corporation\">China National Petroleum Corporation</span>, prompting commentators to liken the accused clique to a latter-day <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gang_of_Four\">Gang of Four</span>. To institutionalize the purge, the campaign's reach was widened in 2018 through the creation of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Supervisory_Commission\">National Supervisory Commission</span>, which placed all public employees under its scrutiny, even as critics contended that the drive served as much to bolster Xi's standing as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paramount_leader\">paramount leader</span> and to remove his rivals as to advance the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rule_of_law\">rule of law</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Anti-corruption campaign under Xi Jinping"},{"id":"cne-071","num":"七十一","category":"China · Economics","question":"Founded in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> and powering the short-video apps Douyin and TikTok, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> built its success on recommendation algorithms and became a target of security concerns and forced-sale threats in the United States.","answer":"ByteDance","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">founded 2012</span></div>","traditional":"字節跳動","hanzi":"字节跳动","pinyin":"Zìjié Tiàodòng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zìjié Tiàodòng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>ByteDance</b> is a Chinese internet <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Technology_company\">technology company</span></b> headquartered in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> and one of the world's most valuable <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Privately_held_company\">privately held</span> firms, a major force in global digital media and short-form video. It was <b>founded in 2012</b> by the entrepreneur <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Yiming\">Zhang Yiming</span>, who led it until stepping down <b>as chief executive in 2021</b>, and it grew into one of the world's largest <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Startup_company\">startups</span>, a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Unicorn_(finance)\">unicorn</span> incorporated in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cayman_Islands\">Cayman Islands</span> and valued in the hundreds of billions of dollars. Its breakthrough product was <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Toutiao\">Toutiao</span>, launched in 2012 as a personalized news feed <b>built on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Recommender_system\">recommendation algorithms</span></b> powered by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Machine_learning\">machine learning</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Artificial_intelligence\">artificial intelligence</span>, a data-driven capability that became the company's defining strength. The same engine drove its short-video <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mobile_app\">apps</span>, Douyin in China, launched in 2016, and the international <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"TikTok\">TikTok</span></b>, released the following year and greatly expanded by the 2017 acquisition of the lip-syncing app <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Musical.ly\">Musical.ly</span> for about a billion dollars. TikTok became a global <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Social_media\">social-media</span> phenomenon with more than a billion monthly users, and ByteDance expanded into video editing with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"CapCut\">CapCut</span>, workplace software, gaming, and booming <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"E-commerce\">e-commerce</span>, becoming one of the highest-earning internet companies in the world, with revenue rivalling the largest US technology firms in scale. <br> <br> In the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States\">United States</span>, TikTok became a focus of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Information_privacy\">data-privacy</span> and national-security concerns, with officials fearing that a Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Intelligence_Law_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">national intelligence law</span> could compel ByteDance to hand over the data of millions of users or covertly manipulate its feed to spread propaganda, anxieties heightened by the broader <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China–United_States_trade_war\">technology rivalry</span> between the two countries. <b>In 2020</b> the administration of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Donald_Trump\">Donald Trump</span> issued <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Executive_order\">executive orders</span> seeking to ban the app or force its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Divestment\">divestiture</span>, and a review by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Committee_on_Foreign_Investment_in_the_United_States\">Committee on Foreign Investment</span> spurred a stalled proposal for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Oracle_Corporation\">Oracle</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Walmart\">Walmart</span> to take stakes in a new American entity sometimes called TikTok Global. President <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joe_Biden\">Joe Biden</span> rescinded those orders in 2021 but ordered fresh security scrutiny, and in 2024 the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States_Congress\">United States Congress</span> passed the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Protecting_Americans_from_Foreign_Adversary_Controlled_Applications_Act\">Protecting Americans from Foreign Adversary Controlled Applications Act</span></b>, signed into law that April, requiring ByteDance to sell TikTok's American operations or see the app banned outright across the country. ByteDance and TikTok challenged the law on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"First_Amendment_to_the_United_States_Constitution\">First Amendment</span> free-speech grounds, but the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Supreme_Court_of_the_United_States\">Supreme Court</span> upheld it in early 2025, and the service briefly went dark for its roughly 170 million American users before being restored within a day under political pressure. Earlier state-level efforts, such as a ban attempted by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Montana\">Montana</span>, had been blocked by the courts, and after returning to office Trump repeatedly postponed enforcement while a sale or restructuring of TikTok's US business was negotiated, leaving the company's long-term position in the country unresolved.","citation":"","answerText":"ByteDance"},{"id":"cnp-089","num":"八十九","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Announced by Xi Jinping in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> finances ports, railways and other infrastructure across Asia, Africa and Europe, reviving the imagery of the ancient Silk Road to extend Chinese influence.","answer":"Belt and Road Initiative","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">2013</span></div>","traditional":"一帶一路","hanzi":"一带一路","pinyin":"Yīdài Yīlù","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Yīdài Yīlù</span></div><div class=\"tr-oth tr-litrow\"><span class=\"tr-k\">Lit.</span><span class=\"tr-lit\">“One Belt, One Road”</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Belt and Road Initiative</b> is a sweeping global infrastructure and economic-development strategy adopted by the government of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Republic_of_China\">People's Republic of China</span> to finance ports, railways, highways, pipelines, and power plants stretching across <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eurasia\">Eurasia</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Africa\">Africa</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Latin_America\">Latin America</span>, and beyond. <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span> introduced the concept <b>in a pair of 2013 speeches</b>, unveiling the land-based Silk Road Economic Belt at <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nazarbayev_University\">Nazarbayev University</span></b> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kazakhstan\">Kazakhstan</span> in September and the 21st Century <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maritime_Silk_Road\">Maritime Silk Road</span> before the parliament of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Indonesia\">Indonesia</span> the following month. The name deliberately evokes the ancient <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk_Road\">Silk Road</span>, the network of overland and maritime trade routes that connected China to the Mediterranean and flourished after the westward missions of the imperial envoy <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhang_Qian\">Zhang Qian</span> during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Han_dynasty\">Han dynasty</span> in the 2nd century BCE. To bankroll the undertaking, China endowed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Silk_Road_Fund\">Silk Road Fund</span> <b>with $40 billion in 2014</b> and helped launch the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Asian_Infrastructure_Investment_Bank\">Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank</span> in 2015 with an authorized capital of $100 billion, while the bulk of project lending has flowed through state policy banks such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Development_Bank\">China Development Bank</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Export–Import_Bank_of_China\">Export–Import Bank of China</span>. By the early 2020s more than 140 countries and over 30 international organizations had signed cooperation agreements under its banner, and cumulative Chinese investment and lending across the program has been estimated by various analysts at between $1 trillion and $1.3 trillion, ranking it among the most ambitious <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Infrastructure\">infrastructure</span> efforts in modern history. <br> <br> Its flagship venture, the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China–Pakistan_Economic_Corridor\">China–Pakistan Economic Corridor</span></b>, has directed an initially announced $46 billion—later expanded toward $62 billion—into energy and transport links joining western China to the deep-water <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Port_of_Gwadar\">port of Gwadar</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pakistan\">Pakistan</span> on the Arabian Sea. Other prominent works include the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mombasa–Nairobi_Standard_Gauge_Railway\">Mombasa–Nairobi Standard Gauge Railway</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Kenya\">Kenya</span>, the roughly $6 billion <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boten–Vientiane_railway\">China–Laos Railway</span> <b>opened in 2021</b>, the approximately $7 billion <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jakarta–Bandung_high-speed_railway\">Jakarta–Bandung high-speed railway</span> inaugurated in 2023, and the purchase by the shipping giant <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"COSCO\">COSCO</span> of a controlling stake in the Greek <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Port_of_Piraeus\">port of Piraeus</span>. The initiative has attracted sustained criticism over debt sustainability, environmental impact, labor practices, and opaque contracting, with skeptics invoking the contested notion of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Debt-trap_diplomacy\">debt-trap diplomacy</span> after <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sri_Lanka\">Sri Lanka</span> granted a 99-year lease over <b>its strategically located <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Port_of_Hambantota\">port of Hambantota</span></b> to a Chinese state enterprise in 2017. Partly in response, Beijing convened the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Belt_and_Road_Forum\">Belt and Road Forum</span> in 2017, 2019, and 2023 and recast its messaging around smaller, greener, and higher-quality projects, even as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Italy\">Italy</span>—the only member of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Group_of_Seven\">Group of Seven</span> to formally join, in 2019—announced its withdrawal in late 2023. Widely interpreted as a vehicle for extending Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Geopolitics\">geopolitical</span> reach and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soft_power\">soft power</span>, the program has spurred rival Western responses such as the European Union's €300 billion <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Global_Gateway\">Global Gateway</span></b> and the G7-backed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Partnership_for_Global_Infrastructure_and_Investment\">Partnership for Global Infrastructure and Investment</span>, leaving it a central and hotly debated feature of 21st-century international relations.","citation":"","answerText":"Belt and Road Initiative"},{"id":"cne-075","num":"七十五","category":"China · Economics","question":"Launched in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> to link the Shanghai and later Shenzhen markets with Hong Kong, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> let international investors trade mainland shares and mainland investors buy Hong Kong stocks within set quotas, partially opening the capital account.","answer":"Stock Connect","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">互联互通 ('interconnection'), the HK–mainland trading link, 2014</span></div>","traditional":"互聯互通機制","hanzi":"互联互通机制","pinyin":"hùlián hùtōng jīzhì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">hùlián hùtōng jīzhì</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Stock Connect</b> is a cross-boundary trading link that joins the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mainland_China\">mainland Chinese</span></b> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stock_exchange\">stock exchanges</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_Stock_Exchange\">Shanghai</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shenzhen_Stock_Exchange\">Shenzhen</span> with the market in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span>, allowing investors in each to trade eligible shares listed on the other within set limits. The Shanghai leg <b>launched in November 2014</b> and a parallel Shenzhen link <b>followed in December 2016</b>, each operated jointly by the relevant mainland exchanges and clearing houses together with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_Exchanges_and_Clearing\">Hong Kong Exchanges and Clearing</span>. Through \"northbound\" trading, international investors gained access to eligible mainland <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"A_share_(mainland_China)\">A-shares</span> previously hard for outsiders to reach, while \"southbound\" trading lets mainland investors purchase Hong Kong-listed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stock\">stocks</span> tracked by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hang_Seng_Index\">Hang Seng Index</span>, including many <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"H_share\">H-shares</span> of Chinese firms. Investors trade through their own local exchange and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Clearing_(finance)\">clearing</span></b> system rather than opening accounts abroad, with orders routed across the boundary, held in nominee form, and settled in local currency. Overseen jointly by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Securities_Regulatory_Commission\">China Securities Regulatory Commission</span> and Hong Kong's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Securities_and_Futures_Commission\">Securities and Futures Commission</span>, the scheme operated within daily and aggregate <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Security_(finance)\">securities</span> quotas, the overall cap being abolished when the Shenzhen link opened in 2016 and the daily quota <b>quadrupled in 2018</b> as cross-boundary flows grew. <br> <br> Stock Connect marked a significant step in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liberalization\">liberalizing</span> foreign access to Chinese equities and partially opening the country's tightly managed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capital_account\">capital account</span>, doing so without fully lifting <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capital_control\">capital controls</span> or removing restrictions on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Renminbi\">renminbi</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Convertibility\">convertibility</span>. Its closed-loop design—funnelling money through designated channels that must eventually flow back—was meant to limit <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capital_flight\">capital flight</span> and preserve oversight, with cross-boundary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foreign_exchange_market\">currency conversion</span> handled offshore under the watch of China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Bank_of_China\">central bank</span>. It built on earlier arrangements such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Qualified_Foreign_Institutional_Investor\">Qualified Foreign Institutional Investor</span> scheme and its renminbi variant, but proved far more flexible, requiring no individual licenses or pre-assigned quotas for the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Institutional_investor\">institutional investors</span></b> using it. By giving foreign funds reliable, scalable access, it helped persuade major index providers like <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"MSCI\">MSCI</span> to add mainland A-shares to their global <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stock_market_index\">indices</span> from 2018, drawing in waves of passive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Index_fund\">index-fund</span> money and lifting foreign ownership of Chinese shares into the trillions of yuan within a few years. It became the template for a wider family of cross-boundary links, including <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bond_Connect\">Bond Connect</span></b> and later wealth-management and swap connects, and stands as a landmark in integrating Hong Kong, a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Special_administrative_regions_of_China\">special administrative region</span>, as a gateway to China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Financial_market\">financial markets</span> under the framework of \"<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"One_country,_two_systems\">one country, two systems</span>,\" reshaping the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">Chinese economy</span>'s ties to global capital.","citation":"","answerText":"Stock Connect"},{"id":"cne-089","num":"八十九","category":"China · Economics","question":"An affiliate of a giant e-commerce firm that runs the Alipay payment platform, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> had its record-breaking <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> stock listing abruptly halted by regulators, triggering a wider crackdown on fintech and the empire of Jack Ma.","answer":"Ant Group","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">founded 2014</span></div>","traditional":"螞蟻集團","hanzi":"蚂蚁集团","pinyin":"Mǎyǐ jítuán","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Mǎyǐ jítuán</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Ant Group</b> is a Chinese financial-technology company headquartered in <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hangzhou\">Hangzhou</span></b>, an affiliate of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Alibaba_Group\">Alibaba Group</span> and the operator of Alipay, the dominant online and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mobile_payment\">mobile payment</span> platform in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>. Alipay <b>originated in 2004</b> as an <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Escrow\">escrow</span> service for transactions on Alibaba's marketplaces and grew into a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Digital_wallet\">digital wallet</span> used by more than a billion people, while the parent business, known until 2020 as Ant Financial, adopted its present name that year. Beyond payments the group built a sprawling financial empire encompassing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yu'e_Bao\">Yu'ebao</span>, once the world's largest <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Money_market_fund\">money market fund</span>, the consumer-<b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Consumer_debt\">lending</span></b> services Huabei and Jiebei, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Online_banking\">online bank</span> MYbank, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Credit_score\">credit-scoring</span> system Sesame Credit. Although Alibaba retained roughly a third of its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Equity_(finance)\">equity</span>, effective control rested with the company's founder, Jack Ma, and its reach <b>extended into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wealth_management\">wealth management</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Insurance\">insurance</span>. In the realm of payments it commanded roughly half of a vast Chinese market, its principal competitor being the rival service operated by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tencent\">Tencent</span>, and the two together rendered cash all but obsolete in the near-<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cashless_society\">cashless society</span> of the country's cities.<br> <br><b>In 2020 Ant</b> prepared a simultaneous stock listing on Shanghai's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"STAR_Market\">STAR Market</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_Stock_Exchange\">Hong Kong Stock Exchange</span> that was set to raise some 34 billion US dollars, an <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Initial_public_offering\">initial public offering</span> that would have been the largest in history and valued the firm, by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Market_capitalization\">market capitalisation</span>, at more than 300 billion dollars. Days after Jack Ma used a speech on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Bund\">Bund</span> in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span> to lambast the country's <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Financial_regulation\">financial regulators</span></b>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Bank_of_China\">People's Bank of China</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Securities_Regulatory_Commission\">securities regulator</span> abruptly suspended the offering on 3 November 2020, only days before its scheduled debut. The episode set off a sweeping <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Competition_law\">antitrust</span> and regulatory assault on China's technology and finance sectors, which saw Alibaba fined a record 18.2 billion <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Renminbi\">yuan</span> by <b>the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_Administration_for_Market_Regulation\">market regulator</span> in April 2021</b> as part of a broader campaign for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Common_prosperity\">common prosperity</span>. Ant itself was compelled to restructure as a tightly regulated financial <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Holding_company\">holding company</span> supervised much like a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bank\">bank</span>, its lucrative lending operations reined in, and in 2023 it was fined a further 7.1 billion yuan to conclude the rectification. In the same year Jack Ma relinquished control of the company, a denouement widely read as marking the end of a freewheeling era for Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"E-commerce\">e-commerce</span> and finance and a reassertion of the state's authority over the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">Chinese economy</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Ant Group"},{"id":"cne-076","num":"七十六","category":"China · Economics","question":"Announced in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> as a 10-year blueprint to make the country a leader in high-tech sectors such as robotics, aerospace and semiconductors, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> fed into the trade war, prompting Beijing to talk about it less publicly.","answer":"Made in China 2025","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Origin</span><span class=\"dt-v\">A State Council industrial strategy, announced 2015</span></div>","traditional":"中國製造2025","hanzi":"中国制造2025","pinyin":"Zhōngguó zhìzào 2025","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōngguó zhìzào 2025</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Made in China 2025</b> is a state-led <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Industrial_policy\">industrial policy</span> intended to transform <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> from a producer of low-cost goods into a global leader in advanced <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manufacturing\">manufacturing</span>. <b>Unveiled in 2015</b> by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_Council_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">State Council</span> under premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Keqiang\">Li Keqiang</span> and modelled in part on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Germany\">Germany</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Industry_4.0\">Industry 4.0</span> concept, the programme set out a 10-year blueprint <b>running to 2025</b>. Its central ambition was to reduce China's reliance on imported technology and to achieve <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Self-sufficiency\">self-sufficiency</span> in the components and know-how underpinning the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"High_tech\">high-technology</span> industries of the future. The plan identified 10 priority sectors, among them <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Semiconductor_industry\">semiconductors</span>, industrial robotics, aerospace and aviation equipment embodied by the aircraft maker <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Comac\">Comac</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Electric_vehicle\">new-energy vehicles</span>, <b>advanced <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rolling_stock\">rail equipment</span></b>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Materials_science\">new materials</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Biotechnology\">biotechnology</span>. To these ends it set explicit targets—domestic content of core materials and components <b>reaching 40 percent by 2020</b> and 70 percent by 2025—pursued through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Subsidy\">subsidies</span>, state investment funds, preferential <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Government_procurement\">procurement</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Research_and_development\">research support</span>, and the work of the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ministry_of_Industry_and_Information_Technology\">Ministry of Industry and Information Technology</span></b>.<br> <br>The strategy alarmed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States\">United States</span> and other advanced economies, which saw it as a bid to build <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_champions\">national champions</span> and displace their technological leadership and objected to the forced <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Technology_transfer\">technology transfer</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Intellectual_property\">intellectual property</span> appropriation, and market-distorting state support associated with it. Washington's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Office_of_the_United_States_Trade_Representative\">trade representative</span> launched a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Section_301_of_the_Trade_Act_of_1974\">Section 301</span> investigation into these practices, and the punitive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tariff\">tariffs</span> imposed by President <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Donald_Trump\">Donald Trump</span> from 2018 fell heavily on the very sectors the plan had singled out. As the dispute escalated into a full-blown trade war, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> grew noticeably reticent about the initiative, all but ceasing to invoke its name in official pronouncements after around 2019 even as the underlying policies continued unabated. The objectives nonetheless endured, folded into a broader campaign for technological self-reliance and the <b>strategy of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dual_circulation\">dual circulation</span></b>, with intensified efforts—channelled through bodies such as the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Integrated_Circuit_Industry_Investment_Fund\">National Integrated Circuit Industry Investment Fund</span>—to build a domestic chip industry. Whether judged a <b>visionary act of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economic_planning\">economic planning</span></b> or a provocation that hardened the technological rivalry at the centre of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China–United_States_relations\">China–United States relations</span>, the initiative remains a defining statement of the ambitions of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">Chinese economy</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Made in China 2025"},{"id":"cne-077","num":"七十七","category":"China · Economics","question":"Following a frenzied, debt-fuelled rally that then collapsed, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> wiped trillions from share values, prompted clumsy state rescue efforts and trading halts, and rattled global markets amid a surprise weakening of the currency overseen by the central bank and the securities regulator.","answer":"2015–2016 Chinese stock market turbulence","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">2015–2016</span></div>","traditional":"中國股災","hanzi":"中国股灾","pinyin":"Zhōngguó gǔzāi","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōngguó gǔzāi</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>2015–2016 Chinese stock market turbulence</b> was a period of severe <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Volatility_(finance)\">volatility</span></b> on China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stock_market\">stock markets</span>, beginning in mid-2015 after a frenzied, debt-fuelled rally and extending into early 2016, one of the most dramatic boom-and-bust cycles in the country's short market history. In the preceding year the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"SSE_Composite_Index\">Shanghai Composite</span></b> roughly doubled, peaking above 5,000 points in June 2015, as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Market_trend\">bull market</span> on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai_Stock_Exchange\">Shanghai</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shenzhen_Stock_Exchange\">Shenzhen</span> exchanges was driven by a <b>surge of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Margin_(finance)\">margin</span></b> borrowing by small investors that pushed margin debt to record highs. The surge was a classic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stock_market_bubble\">bubble</span>, inflated by record levels of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Leverage_(finance)\">leverage</span> and feverish retail <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Speculation\">speculation</span> that state media had openly cheered on, leaving share prices far above the fundamental value of the underlying <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stock\">stocks</span>. <b>From mid-June 2015</b> the market reversed violently, the Shanghai index shedding roughly a third of its value within weeks as margin calls forced heavily leveraged investors to dump holdings and set off a self-reinforcing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deleveraging\">deleveraging</span> spiral that overwhelmed buyers. The rout erased trillions of dollars in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Market_capitalization\">market value</span> from mainland <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"A_share_(mainland_China)\">A-shares</span>—by some estimates more than 3 trillion—with further sharp plunges through the summer of 2015 and <b>again in January 2016</b>, when fresh falls reverberated worldwide. <br> <br> The authorities responded with a sweeping but widely criticized rescue, hastily assembled as losses mounted: a state-backed \"national team\" of funds was directed to buy shares in a massive <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bailout\">bailout</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Initial_public_offering\">initial public offerings</span> were frozen, large shareholders were barred from selling for months, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Bank_of_China\">central bank</span> cut <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Interest_rate\">interest rates</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Reserve_requirement\">reserve requirements</span> while <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Brokerage_firm\">brokerages</span> were pressed to prop up prices. Anxiety deepened in August 2015 when the central bank engineered a surprise <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Devaluation\">devaluation</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Renminbi\">renminbi</span> by overhauling its daily <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Exchange_rate\">exchange-rate</span> fixing, the steepest one-day fall in decades, a move that—though officially framed as a market reform—rattled <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Financial_market\">global markets</span>, contributed to the worldwide \"<b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Black_Monday_(2015)\">Black Monday</span></b>\" sell-off, and stoked fears of a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Currency_war\">currency war</span> and a sharper-than-expected slowdown in the world's second-largest economy. As <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Capital_flight\">capital fled</span> the country and pressure spread to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span>, China spent heavily from its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Foreign_exchange_reserves\">foreign exchange reserves</span>—then the world's largest, near 4 trillion dollars—to defend the yuan, drawing them down by hundreds of billions over the following year and fuelling worries about a hard landing. Regulators led by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China_Securities_Regulatory_Commission\">China Securities Regulatory Commission</span> cracked down on what officials called malicious <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Short_(finance)\">short selling</span></b> and launched investigations into alleged manipulation, while hundreds of listed firms suspended trading in their own shares and a market-wide <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Trading_curb\">circuit breaker</span> introduced in January 2016 was scrapped within days after it repeatedly worsened the panic. Markets stabilized later in 2016, but the episode cost the securities regulator's chairman, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiao_Gang\">Xiao Gang</span>, his job and badly dented confidence in Beijing's competence at managing markets and in the health of the wider <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">Chinese economy</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"2015–2016 Chinese stock market turbulence"},{"id":"cne-078","num":"七十八","category":"China · Economics","question":"Established in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> and headquartered in Shanghai, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was set up by the BRICS group of major emerging economies to fund infrastructure and development as an alternative to Western-dominated bodies like the IMF.","answer":"New Development Bank","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">founded 2015</span></div>","traditional":"新開發銀行","hanzi":"新开发银行","pinyin":"Xīn Kāifā Yínháng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Xīn Kāifā Yínháng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>New Development Bank</b>, formerly referred to as the <b>BRICS Development Bank</b>, is a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Multilateral_development_bank\">multilateral development bank</span> <b>established in 2015</b> by the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"BRICS\">BRICS</span></b> grouping of major <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Emerging_market\">emerging economies</span> — <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Brazil\">Brazil</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russia\">Russia</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"India\">India</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South_Africa\">South Africa</span> — and headquartered in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span>. The institution was conceived as a counterweight to the Western-dominated <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bretton_Woods_system\">Bretton Woods</span> order embodied by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"International_Monetary_Fund\">International Monetary Fund</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Bank\">World Bank</span>, and its founding agreement was signed at the 6th BRICS summit in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fortaleza\">Fortaleza</span>, Brazil, on 15 July 2014 before entering into force on 3 July 2015. It launched <b>with an authorised <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Authorised_capital\">capital</span></b> of US$100 billion and an initial subscribed capital of US$50 billion divided equally among the five founders at US$10 billion apiece, an arrangement that, unlike the weighted voting of older lenders, granted no single member a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Veto\">veto</span>. Created in tandem with the bank was the US$100 billion <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"BRICS_Contingent_Reserve_Arrangement\">Contingent Reserve Arrangement</span>, a currency-swap framework intended to provide members with short-term liquidity support and further reduce their dependence on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States_dollar\">United States dollar</span>. The bank's presidency, designed to rotate among the founding members, was inaugurated by the veteran Indian banker and former <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"ICICI_Bank\">ICICI Bank</span> chairman K. V. Kamath <b>from 2015 to 2020</b>, passed to Brazil's economist Marcos Troyjo from 2020 to 2023, and has since been held by the former Brazilian president <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dilma_Rousseff\">Dilma Rousseff</span>. <br> <br> Operationally, the bank concentrates on financing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Infrastructure\">infrastructure</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sustainable_development\">sustainable development</span> across transport, clean water and sanitation, urban projects, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Renewable_energy\">renewable energy</span>, and by the early 2020s it had approved roughly 100 projects with a combined value of about US$33 billion, the bulk of them in its founding member states. A distinctive ambition has been to fund a substantial share of its lending in the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Local_currency\">local currencies</span> of borrowing members rather</b> than in hard currency, with the bank setting an early target of roughly 30 percent to shield projects from exchange-rate volatility and to deepen domestic capital markets. During the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"COVID-19_pandemic\">COVID-19 pandemic</span> the lender pivoted rapidly toward crisis support, approving an emergency assistance programme of up to US$10 billion in 2020 to help member governments finance health systems and cushion the severe economic shock. Seeking to broaden its reach beyond the original BRICS core, the bank admitted <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bangladesh\">Bangladesh</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_Arab_Emirates\">United Arab Emirates</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Egypt\">Egypt</span> <b>as new members in 2021 while</b> approving the accession of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Uruguay\">Uruguay</span>, and it has established regional offices including an Africa Regional Centre in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Johannesburg\">Johannesburg</span> and an Americas hub in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"São_Paulo\">São Paulo</span>. Having secured an AA+ <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Credit_rating\">credit rating</span> from agencies such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"S&amp;P_Global_Ratings\">S&amp;P Global</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fitch_Ratings\">Fitch</span>, the bank has been widely portrayed as part of a broader push to reshape the global financial architecture, yet it confronted a serious test after the 2022 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Russian_invasion_of_Ukraine\">Russian invasion of Ukraine</span>, when it suspended new transactions in Russia to preserve its access to international capital markets amid sweeping Western <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"International_sanctions_during_the_Russian_invasion_of_Ukraine\">sanctions</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"New Development Bank"},{"id":"cne-079","num":"七十九","category":"China · Economics","question":"Rising quickly by offering steep discounts for group buying among bargain-hunters in smaller cities and the countryside, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> later launched the overseas budget app Temu.","answer":"Pinduoduo","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">拼多多 (Pīnduōduō), from 拼 'to team up'; e-commerce firm founded 2015</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"拼多多","pinyin":"Pīnduōduō","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Pīnduōduō</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Pinduoduo</b> is a Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"E-commerce\">e-commerce</span> platform <b>founded in 2015</b> by the former <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Google\">Google</span> engineer <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Colin_Huang\">Colin Huang</span></b>, which grew explosively at a moment when <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Alibaba_Group\">Alibaba</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"JD.com\">JD.com</span> were widely thought to have all but saturated the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"E-commerce_in_China\">Chinese online retail market</span>. Its defining innovation was <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Group_buying\">group buying</span></b>, in which shoppers teamed up—frequently by sharing links on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"WeChat\">WeChat</span>, the messaging platform run by early backer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tencent\">Tencent</span>—to unlock steep discounts on goods sourced directly from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manufacturing\">manufacturers</span>, a formula its founder likened to \"<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Costco\">Costco</span> plus <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"The_Walt_Disney_Company\">Disney</span>\" for its mix of low prices and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gamification\">gamification</span>. By targeting price-conscious consumers in smaller cities and the countryside and through an early emphasis on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Agriculture_in_China\">agricultural produce</span>, the company seized market share with remarkable speed while running an asset-light <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Online_marketplace\">online marketplace</span> that held little inventory of its own. It carried out an <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Initial_public_offering\">initial public offering</span> of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"American_depositary_receipt\">depositary shares</span> <b>on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Nasdaq\">Nasdaq</span> in 2018</b>, and in 2023 its parent reorganized as PDD Holdings, a group registered in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cayman_Islands\">Cayman Islands</span> and headquartered in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dublin\">Dublin</span> while operating largely from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span>. By 2024 the company reported revenue of roughly $54 billion and net income of about $15.4 billion, carried a stock-market value of around $135 billion, and yet employed only some 17,000 people, a reflection of its lean, platform-based model. <br> <br> In September 2022 PDD Holdings launched <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Temu\">Temu</span></b>, an overseas budget-shopping app first introduced in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boston\">Boston</span> that applied the same low-price playbook to Western consumers and expanded to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Oceania\">Oceania</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Europe\">Europe</span> in 2023 before reaching dozens of countries. Temu's extraordinarily cheap goods leaned heavily on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States\">United States</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"De_minimis\">de minimis</span> exemption, which let parcels worth under $800 enter duty-free; such shipments had ballooned to about 1.36 billion <b>packages a year by 2023</b>, with Temu and rival <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shein\">Shein</span> together making up more than 30% of them. The app spread with striking speed, reaching an estimated 290 million monthly active users worldwide, ranking as the most-downloaded application among young adults in the United States for much of 2024, and pushing its quarterly global <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gross_merchandise_volume\">merchandise volume</span> above $20 billion. That model was upended in 2025 when the administration of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Donald_Trump\">Donald Trump</span> abolished the de minimis exemption for Chinese goods and levied <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tariff\">tariffs</span> of up to 145%, forcing Temu to suspend direct shipments from China, shift to a \"local fulfillment\" model staffed by United States-based sellers, and watch its American daily users drop by more than 50%. Confronting further scrutiny abroad—including investigations under the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"European_Union\">European Union</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Digital_Services_Act\">Digital Services Act</span></b> over non-compliant and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Counterfeit\">counterfeit</span> products—the group nonetheless stayed firmly profitable on the back of Pinduoduo's lucrative Chinese operations, capping a swift ascent from scrappy discounter to one of the world's most valuable retailers.","citation":"","answerText":"Pinduoduo"},{"id":"cne-080","num":"八十","category":"China · Economics","question":"Proposed by Xi Jinping and beginning operations in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> over US objections, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> finances roads, ports and power, widely seen as a complement to the Belt and Road and a rival to the World Bank.","answer":"Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">from 2016</span></div>","traditional":"亞洲基礎設施投資銀行","hanzi":"亚洲基础设施投资银行","pinyin":"Yàzhōu Jīchǔ Shèshī Tóuzī Yínháng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Yàzhōu Jīchǔ Shèshī Tóuzī Yínháng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank</b>, commonly abbreviated <b>AIIB</b>, is a <b>Beijing-based <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Multilateral_development_bank\">multilateral development bank</span></b> that finances <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Infrastructure\">infrastructure</span> across Asia and, increasingly, the wider world. It was proposed by Xi Jinping in 2013, and as it took shape the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States\">United States</span> under the administration of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Barack_Obama\">Barack Obama</span></b> lobbied its allies not to join, regarding the venture as a challenge to the established <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bretton_Woods_system\">Bretton Woods</span> order of the World Bank and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"International_Monetary_Fund\">International Monetary Fund</span>. Britain's <b>decision to join in 2015 broke</b> the Western front, prompting the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_Kingdom\">United Kingdom</span>'s partners in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Germany\">Germany</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"France\">France</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Australia\">Australia</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South_Korea\">South Korea</span> to follow, although the United States and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japan\">Japan</span> conspicuously stayed out. Having gathered 57 founding members behind its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Treaty\">Articles of Agreement</span>, the bank <b>opened for business in January 2016</b> from its headquarters in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> under its inaugural president, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jin_Liqun\">Jin Liqun</span>. Capitalised at an initial 100 billion US dollars, it counts <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> as its largest <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shareholder\">shareholder</span>, a stake that confers an effective <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Veto\">veto</span> over the institution's most important decisions.<br> <br>Membership subsequently expanded to more than 100 economies, making the bank the second-largest <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Multilateralism\">multilateral</span></b> lender in the world by membership, behind only the World Bank itself. Its lending concentrates on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Road\">roads</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rail_transport\">railways</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Port\">ports</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Electric_power\">power</span> generation and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Telecommunications\">telecommunications</span>, frequently in partnership with established institutions such as the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Asian_Development_Bank\">Asian Development Bank</span></b>, and it has financed scores of projects across dozens of countries. The bank is widely regarded as a complement to the Belt and Road Initiative, even as it insists on its independence and adherence to international standards, lending well beyond the initiative's footprint and alongside the BRICS-sponsored <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Development_Bank\">New Development Bank</span></b>. For its critics the bank embodies a vehicle of Chinese <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soft_power\">soft power</span> and a deliberate challenge to the Western-led order, a fresh assertion of Beijing's ambitions within the architecture of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Global_governance\">global governance</span>. Counting major borrowers such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"India\">India</span> among its clients and holding a top-tier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Credit_rating\">credit rating</span> from the leading agencies, the bank has come to occupy a significant place in the financing of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economic_development\">economic development</span> across <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Asia\">Asia</span> and beyond.","citation":"","answerText":"Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank"},{"id":"cne-081","num":"八十一","category":"China · Economics","question":"Adopted in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> to address a shrinking workforce and rapid ageing, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was soon loosened further to allow three children.","answer":"Two-child policy","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Origin</span><span class=\"dt-v\">PRC population policy, replacing the one-child rule, 2016</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"二孩政策","pinyin":"èrhái zhèngcè","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">èrhái zhèngcè</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>two-child policy</b> was the relaxation of birth restrictions through which <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> permitted couples to have a second child, formally superseding the longstanding <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"One-child_policy\">one-child policy</span></b> as the central instrument of the nation's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Family_planning\">family-planning</span> regime. It was introduced in two stages, beginning with a \"selective\" version approved at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"3rd_Plenary_Session_of_the_18th_Central_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">third plenum</span> of the <b>ruling <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Communist Party</span> in late 2013</b>, which allowed a second child only where one parent was an only child, before a universal two-child policy <b>announced in October 2015</b>, under the leadership of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span>, <b>took effect on 1 January 2016</b> and extended the entitlement to all married couples. The shift responded to mounting demographic strains, including a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Workforce\">workforce</span> that had begun to contract around 2012, accelerating <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Population_ageing\">population ageing</span> with a rising old-age <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Dependency_ratio\">dependency burden</span>, the looming \"4-2-1\" problem of one child supporting two parents and four grandparents, and the impending exhaustion of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Demographic_dividend\">demographic dividend</span> that had powered decades of rapid growth in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">Chinese economy</span>. The reform initially appeared to bear fruit, as the <b>number of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Birth_rate\">births</span></b> rose to about 17.9 million in 2016 — the highest annual total since 2000 — with second children accounting for close to half of all births, a brief uptick within China's broader <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Demographic_transition\">demographic transition</span>. Yet even the earlier selective phase had drawn a tepid response, with only about 1.5 million of the roughly 11 million eligible couples applying for a second child by 2015, a muted reaction that, according to figures from the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Bureau_of_Statistics_of_China\">national statistics bureau</span>, foreshadowed the broader policy's eventual disappointment. <br> <br> The hoped-for rebound proved fleeting, as annual births resumed their decline almost immediately, falling from about 17.2 million in 2017 to roughly 9.6 million in 2022 and about 9.0 million in 2023, the first years in which the figure dropped below 10 million. The <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Total_fertility_rate\">total fertility rate</span> likewise stayed far beneath the replacement level of 2.1, sliding from roughly 1.6 around 2017 into deep <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sub-replacement_fertility\">sub-replacement</span> territory near 1.0 by the early 2020s — among the lowest figures recorded anywhere in the world for human <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fertility\">fertility</span></b>. Analysts attributed the failure to lift fertility to the soaring cost of raising children amid an intense <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Education_in_China\">educational</span> arms race and high urban housing prices, to shifting attitudes among <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Women_in_China\">women</span> and falling <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marriage_in_China\">marriage</span> rates, and to a steadily shrinking pool of women of childbearing age, itself a legacy of the skewed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sex_ratio\">sex ratio</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Urbanization_in_China\">urbanisation</span> of recent decades. In response, and prompted by the sobering results of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2020_Chinese_census\">2020 census</span>, the authorities — acting through the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Health_Commission\">National Health Commission</span></b> — loosened the limits again in 2021 with a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three-child_policy\">three-child policy</span>, abolishing the punitive \"social maintenance\" birth fines and rolling out <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pronatalism\">pro-natalist</span> incentives such as extended <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Parental_leave\">parental leave</span>, childcare subsidies, and tax deductions. These successive relaxations nonetheless failed to reverse the trend, and China's total population began to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Demographics_of_China\">contract</span> in 2022 for the first time since the early 1960s, with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"India\">India</span> surpassing it as the world's most populous country in 2023, leaving Beijing to confront the kind of entrenched low fertility — with its implications for pensions and long-term growth — already afflicting neighbouring <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"East_Asia\">East Asian</span> societies such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japan\">Japan</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South_Korea\">South Korea</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Two-child policy"},{"id":"cnp-091","num":"九十一","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Enshrined in the Party constitution at the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> congress and in the state constitution the next year, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> — titled for a \"new era\" of socialism with Chinese characteristics — placed its author alongside Mao Zedong in ideological status.","answer":"Xi Jinping Thought","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Coined</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Enshrined at the 19th Party Congress, 2017</span></div>","traditional":"習近平新時代中國特色社會主義思想","hanzi":"习近平新时代中国特色社会主义思想","pinyin":"Xí Jìnpíng Xīn Shídài Zhōngguó Tèsè Shèhuìzhǔyì Sīxiǎng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Xí Jìnpíng Xīn Shídài Zhōngguó Tèsè Shèhuìzhǔyì Sīxiǎng</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Xi Jinping Thought</b> is the official guiding ideology of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span>, known in full as Xi Jinping Thought on Socialism with Chinese Characteristics for a New Era and bound to the leadership of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span>. Building on the lineage of <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marxism–Leninism\">Marxism–Leninism</span></b> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialism_with_Chinese_characteristics\">socialism with Chinese characteristics</span>, it is condensed by the Party into a 14-point basic policy and a wider programme encompassing the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Dream\">Chinese Dream</span> of national rejuvenation, the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Four_Comprehensives\">Four Comprehensives</span></b>, the pursuit of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Common_prosperity\">common prosperity</span>, and the building of an <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ecological_civilization\">ecological civilization</span>. The doctrine recast the country's principal social contradiction as one between unbalanced and inadequate development and the people's ever-growing aspirations for a better life, and it codified the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Two_Centenaries\">Two Centenary Goals</span> of completing a moderately <b>prosperous <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiaokang\">xiaokang</span> society by 2021</b> and building a fully modern socialist nation by 2049. It was inscribed in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitution_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Party constitution</span> at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"19th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">19th National Congress</span> in October 2017 and incorporated into the state <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitution_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">Constitution of the People's Republic of China</span> by <b>the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_People's_Congress\">National People's Congress</span> in March 2018</b>, within the same package of amendments that abolished the two-term limit on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"President_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">state presidency</span>. This codification placed Xi in the company of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>, whose <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Maoism\">Mao Zedong Thought</span> had guided the Party since its founding generation, and made him the first sitting leader since Mao to attach his name to an enshrined ideology, a rank widely read as standing above the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping_Theory\">Deng Xiaoping Theory</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Three_Represents\">Three Represents</span> credited to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Zemin\">Jiang Zemin</span>, and the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Scientific_Outlook_on_Development\">Scientific Outlook on Development</span></b> credited to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Jintao\">Hu Jintao</span>. <br> <br> Many analysts view the doctrine as the ideological scaffolding for a sweeping concentration of power, noting that the national legislature approved the 2018 amendment by 2,958 votes to 2, with 3 abstentions, and that it dismantled the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Term_limit\">term limits</span> written into the <b>1982 constitution</b> under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> to forestall a return to one-man rule. Xi had already been recognized in 2016 as the Party's core and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paramount_leader\">paramount leader</span>, and a landmark 2021 Party resolution—only the third such historical resolution after those issued under Mao and Deng—further affirmed the guiding role of his Thought, a trajectory widely seen as eroding the norm of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Collective_leadership\">collective leadership</span> that had prevailed throughout the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Reform_and_opening_up\">reform and opening up</span> era. To propagate the ideology, the Party made it a compulsory subject from primary schools through universities, issued dedicated student textbooks in 2021, and launched the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xuexi_Qiangguo\">Xuexi Qiangguo</span></b> study application in 2019, which rapidly amassed more than 100 million registered users and became the most-downloaded app in the country that year. The broader doctrine has since branched into specialized strands governing the rule of law, the economy, diplomacy, ecological policy, and military modernization, and at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"20th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">20th National Congress</span> in 2022 it underpinned Xi's norm-breaking elevation to a third term as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"General_Secretary_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">General Secretary</span>. Official theorists hail it as a 21st-century development of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Marxism\">Marxism</span> adapted to Chinese conditions, tying it to signature initiatives such as the sweeping <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anti-corruption_campaign_under_Xi_Jinping\">anti-corruption campaign</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Belt_and_Road_Initiative\">Belt and Road Initiative</span>, while many outside observers instead describe it as the centerpiece of an intensifying <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cult_of_personality\">cult of personality</span> around the leader who took the Party's helm at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"18th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">18th National Congress</span> in 2012.","citation":"","answerText":"Xi Jinping Thought"},{"id":"cnp-092","num":"九十二","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Created in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> to extend anti-graft oversight beyond Party members to all public employees, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> ranks alongside the State Council and the courts, works in tandem with the discipline commission, and answers to the National People's Congress.","answer":"National Supervisory Commission","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Origin</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Established by constitutional amendment, 2018</span></div>","traditional":"國家監察委員會","hanzi":"国家监察委员会","pinyin":"Guójiā Jiānchá Wěiyuánhuì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Guójiā Jiānchá Wěiyuánhuì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>National Supervisory Commission</b> is the highest <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Corruption_in_China\">anti-corruption</span></b> and supervisory agency of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span>, a constitutional state organ <b>created in 2018</b> to police the integrity of everyone who exercises public power on behalf of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> and the state. It was established in March 2018 by the 1st session of the 13th <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_People's_Congress\">National People's Congress</span>, which amended the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitution_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">state constitution</span> to insert an entire chapter on supervisory organs and enacted a new Supervision Law, formalising a reform the Party had set in motion <b>at its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"19th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">19th National Congress</span> in 2017</b>. Within China's state architecture it stands as a distinct branch alongside the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State_Council_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">State Council</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Supreme_People's_Court\">Supreme People's Court</span>, and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Supreme_People's_Procuratorate\">Supreme People's Procuratorate</span>, each of which is constituted by and accountable to the legislature, marking the most significant addition to the country's constitutional structure of state organs in decades. The commission was assembled by merging the former <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ministry_of_Supervision_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">Ministry of Supervision</span></b> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Bureau_of_Corruption_Prevention\">National Bureau of Corruption Prevention</span> with the anti-graft and anti-malfeasance units of the procuratorate, consolidating previously scattered investigative functions into a single hierarchy. In practice it operates in a fused arrangement with the Party's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Commission_for_Discipline_Inspection\">Central Commission for Discipline Inspection</span>, sharing offices, personnel, and a single chain of command, so that the inaugural director <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Yang_Xiaodu\">Yang Xiaodu</span></b> simultaneously held senior rank in the discipline commission then led by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhao_Leji\">Zhao Leji</span>, a member of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_Standing_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo Standing Committee</span> and successor to the campaign's early architect <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Qishan\">Wang Qishan</span>. <br> <br> The body's defining innovation was to extend anti-corruption oversight beyond the roughly 90 million members of the Chinese Communist Party to every official wielding public authority, drawing in non-Party <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Civil_Service_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">civil servants</span>, managers of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"State-owned_enterprise\">state-owned enterprises</span>, and the staff of public schools and hospitals, and thereby enlarging the supervised population to a figure estimated in the hundreds of millions. To pursue its investigations it wields a coercive detention power known as liuzhi, which permits holding a suspect in a designated facility for up to 3 months, a term that may be extended by a further 3 months, replacing the Party's earlier and extralegal practice of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shuanggui\">shuanggui</span>. Critics, among them <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Human_Rights_Watch\">Human Rights Watch</span></b> and numerous legal scholars, contend that the system weakens <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Due_process\">due process</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Presumption_of_innocence\">presumption of innocence</span>, since detainees under liuzhi may be held incommunicado for months without access to a lawyer, sharpening wider concerns about <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Human_rights_in_China\">human rights in China</span> and the limits of the country's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rule_of_law\">rule of law</span>. Mirroring the national body, parallel supervisory commissions were instituted at the provincial, prefecture, and county levels throughout all of China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Provinces_of_China\">provinces</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Counties_of_China\">counties</span>, building on a <b>2016 pilot</b> that had been trialled in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> and the provinces of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanxi\">Shanxi</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhejiang\">Zhejiang</span> before the nationwide rollout. Conceived as the institutional capstone of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Anti-corruption_campaign_under_Xi_Jinping\">anti-corruption campaign</span> that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span> launched after becoming <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paramount_leader\">paramount leader</span> in 2012, the commission has entrenched the centralisation of disciplinary power under the Party leadership, even as it continues to fuel debate over whether so sweeping an organ can be reconciled with any meaningful <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Separation_of_powers\">separation of powers</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"National Supervisory Commission"},{"id":"cnp-093","num":"九十三","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Approved by the National People's Congress in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> deleted the 2-term cap on the head of state, clearing the way for Xi Jinping to rule indefinitely.","answer":"2018 removal of presidential term limits","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Origin</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Enacted by the National People's Congress, March 2018</span></div>","traditional":"取消國家主席任期限制","hanzi":"取消国家主席任期限制","pinyin":"qǔxiāo guójiā zhǔxí rènqī xiànzhì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">qǔxiāo guójiā zhǔxí rènqī xiànzhì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>2018 removal of presidential term limits</b> was a constitutional change in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">People's Republic of China</span> that deleted the long-standing two-term cap on the office of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"President_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">President</span>, the nation's formal <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Head_of_state\">head of state</span></b>, thereby clearing the way for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span> to remain in office indefinitely. The change formed the headline element of a package of amendments to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitution_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">national constitution</span> <b>approved on 11 March 2018</b> by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_People's_Congress\">National People's Congress</span>, China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rubber_stamp_(politics)\">rubber-stamp</span> legislature, during the annual <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Two_Sessions\">Two Sessions</span>, which endorsed it by a vote of 2,958 in favour, 2 against, and 3 abstentions at the opening session of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"13th_National_People's_Congress\">13th National People's Congress</span>. The abolished restriction had been written into the <b>1982 constitution</b> adopted under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> during his era of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">reform and opening up</span>, a leader who had championed fixed terms as part of the post-<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao</span> drive to prevent any recurrence of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cult_of_personality\">personality cult</span> and lifelong, unchecked rule that had culminated in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cultural_Revolution\">Cultural Revolution</span>. Crucially, the presidency itself is a largely ceremonial post, with real authority residing in Xi's concurrent positions as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"General_Secretary_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">General Secretary</span> of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> and chairman of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Military_Commission_(China)\">Central Military Commission</span>, neither of which carried any formal term limit. By scrapping the lone term limit attached to any of his three core offices, the revision harmonised the presidency with his other two posts, while the same amendment package also enshrined <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping_Thought\">Xi Jinping Thought</span> on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialism_with_Chinese_characteristics\">socialism with Chinese characteristics</span> in the constitution and granted constitutional status to the newly established <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Supervisory_Commission\">National Supervisory Commission</span></b>. <br> <br> The move marked a decisive break with the norm of orderly, term-limited succession and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Collective_leadership\">collective leadership</span> exercised through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_Standing_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo Standing Committee</span>, a system entrenched after Deng's death under which <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jiang_Zemin\">Jiang Zemin</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Jintao\">Hu Jintao</span> had each stepped down after roughly a decade in power. Domestically the announcement triggered an <b>intense bout of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Censorship_in_China\">internet censorship</span></b>, with platforms scrubbing terms ranging from \"emperor\" and \"lifelong\" to satirical references mocking the leader, while many foreign observers warned of a slide toward indefinite one-man rule reminiscent of an imperial restoration. The reform was widely interpreted as the capstone of Xi's steady concentration of power, prompting comparisons to the era of personalised dominance under Mao and raising fears about the erosion of institutional checks within the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"One-party_state\">one-party state</span> and a <b>drift toward <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Authoritarianism\">authoritarian</span></b> personal rule. At the same 2018 session <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Qishan\">Wang Qishan</span> was installed as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vice_President_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">vice president</span> and Xi was reappointed head of state, and Xi went on to secure an unprecedented 3rd term as party leader at <b>the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"20th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">20th Party Congress</span> in October 2022</b>, having already locked in his grip on the party and the military. Re-elected to a 3rd presidential term in March 2023 by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"14th_National_People's_Congress\">14th National People's Congress</span> — again by a unanimous tally — Xi thereby cemented his standing as China's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paramount_leader\">paramount leader</span> for the foreseeable future, leaving the country without any clear successor or fixed limit on his tenure.","citation":"","answerText":"2018 removal of presidential term limits"},{"id":"cne-084","num":"八十四","category":"China · Economics","question":"Beginning in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> with tit-for-tat tariffs and export bans, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> targeted firms like Huawei, disrupted global supply chains, and led to a limited \"phase one\" deal before broadening into a contest over semiconductors.","answer":"China–United States trade war","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">from 2018</span></div>","traditional":"中美貿易戰","hanzi":"中美贸易战","pinyin":"Zhōng-Měi Màoyìzhàn","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōng-Měi Màoyìzhàn</span></div>","abstract":"Th e<b>China–United States trade war</b> is an ongoing economic conflict between the world's two largest economies, which together account for roughly 40% of global economic output, that <b>began in 2018</b> when the administration of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Donald_Trump\">Donald Trump</span>—citing a large bilateral <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Balance_of_trade\">trade deficit</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Intellectual_property\">intellectual property</span> theft, and the forced <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Technology_transfer\">technology transfer</span> <b>linked to Beijing's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Made_in_China_2025\">Made in China 2025</span> industrial</b> strategy—moved to penalize Chinese imports. After an investigation by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Office_of_the_United_States_Trade_Representative\">United States Trade Representative</span> under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Section_301_of_the_Trade_Act_of_1974\">Section 301</span> of the Trade Act of 1974, Washington imposed a 25% <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tariff\">tariff</span> on $34 billion of Chinese goods on July 6, 2018, the opening tranche of <b>a program that by 2019</b> affected roughly $360 billion of imports and drew retaliatory duties from Beijing on American <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Soybean\">soybeans</span> and other exports. The dispute quickly broadened from commerce into a technology rivalry, with the United States crippling the telecom-equipment maker <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"ZTE\">ZTE</span> through a component ban in 2018, adding its larger rival <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Huawei\">Huawei</span> to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Entity_List\">Entity List</span> in 2019, and blacklisting the chipmaker <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Semiconductor_Manufacturing_International_Corporation\">SMIC</span> in 2020, while volatile tariffs and uncertainty disrupted global <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Supply_chain\">supply chains</span> and pushed firms to diversify production toward <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vietnam\">Vietnam</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"India\">India</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mexico\">Mexico</span>. A partial de-escalation arrived with the \"phase one\" agreement signed on January 15, 2020, by Trump and <b>Vice Premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liu_He_(politician)\">Liu He</span></b>, under which China pledged to buy an additional $200 billion of American goods and services—spanning manufactured goods, energy, agriculture, and services—above 2017 levels during 2020 and 2021. That commitment, hampered partly by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"COVID-19_pandemic\">COVID-19 pandemic</span> and a collapse in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Boeing\">Boeing</span> aircraft sales, fell badly short, as China ultimately purchased only about 58% of the promised total and effectively none of the additional $200 billion. <br> <br> Under President <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joe_Biden\">Joe Biden</span> the rivalry sharpened into a contest over advanced <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Semiconductor_industry\">semiconductors</span>, as Washington enacted the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"CHIPS_and_Science_Act\">CHIPS and Science Act</span> in 2022—appropriating about $52.7 billion for domestic chip manufacturing—and on October 7, 2022, imposed sweeping <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Export_Administration_Regulations\">export controls</span></b> to deny China access to cutting-edge <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Integrated_circuit\">chips</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Extreme_ultraviolet_lithography\">lithography</span> equipment required to produce them. These restrictions, tightened in 2023 and joined by allied producers in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Netherlands\">Netherlands</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japan\">Japan</span>, marked a sharp deterioration in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China–United_States_relations\">China–United States relations</span>, even as Beijing retained leverage through <b>its dominance over <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rare_earth_element\">rare earth elements</span></b> and other critical minerals. The conflict reached new extremes after Trump's return to office in 2025, when so-called <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tariffs_in_the_second_Trump_administration\">reciprocal tariffs</span> imposed under the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"International_Emergency_Economic_Powers_Act\">International Emergency Economic Powers Act</span> pushed American duties on Chinese goods as high as 145% and Chinese duties on American goods to 125%, before a truce negotiated in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Geneva\">Geneva</span> in May 2025 temporarily cut them to 30% and 10% respectively. Independent analyses found that the cumulative tariffs constituted the largest United States tax increase as a share of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gross_domestic_product\">gross domestic product</span> since 1993, that the government had collected roughly $72 billion under the emergency duties by mid-2025, and that the measures imposed a cost of about $1,500 per household in 2026. The legal foundation of many of these duties collapsed when the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Supreme_Court_of_the_United_States\">Supreme Court</span></b> struck them down in February 2026, and despite a new bilateral agreement and continued contacts between Trump and Chinese leader <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span>, the broader struggle over trade, technology, and the future of the multilateral <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Trade_Organization\">World Trade Organization</span> trading system remained unresolved.","citation":"","answerText":"China–United States trade war"},{"id":"cnp-095","num":"九十五","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Imposed directly by Beijing in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> after months of mass protests, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> was widely seen as eroding the autonomy promised under \"one country, two systems\".","answer":"Hong Kong national security law","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">2020</span></div>","traditional":"香港國安法","hanzi":"香港国安法","pinyin":"Xiānggǎng Guó'ān Fǎ","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Xiānggǎng Guó'ān Fǎ</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Hong Kong national security law</b> is a sweeping piece of legislation, formally the <b>Law of the People's Republic of China on Safeguarding National Security in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Special_administrative_regions_of_China\">Hong Kong Special Administrative Region</span></b>, enacted <b>by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Standing_Committee_of_the_National_People's_Congress\">Standing Committee of the National People's Congress</span> on June 30, 2020</b>. Rather than being passed by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span>'s own <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Legislative_Council_of_Hong_Kong\">Legislative Council</span></b>, it was inserted into Annex III of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_Basic_Law\">Basic Law</span> and promulgated directly by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span>, taking effect just before the 23rd anniversary of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Handover_of_Hong_Kong\">handover</span> on July 1. The law followed months <b>of mass <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2019–2020_Hong_Kong_protests\">protests</span> in 2019</b> against a proposed extradition bill, and it filled the gap left when an earlier effort to pass local security legislation under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Article_23_of_the_Hong_Kong_Basic_Law\">Article 23</span> of the Basic Law was abandoned in 2003 after some 500,000 people marched against it. It criminalizes 4 broadly defined offenses—<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Secession\">secession</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Subversion\">subversion</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Terrorism\">terrorism</span>, and collusion with foreign or external forces—carrying penalties up to life imprisonment, and it asserts <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Extraterritorial_jurisdiction\">extraterritorial jurisdiction</span></b> over acts committed anywhere by anyone. To enforce it, the statute created a mainland-run <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Office_for_Safeguarding_National_Security_of_the_CPG_in_the_HKSAR\">Office for Safeguarding National Security</span> operating beyond local jurisdiction and a security committee chaired by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chief_Executive_of_Hong_Kong\">Chief Executive</span>, then <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Carrie_Lam\">Carrie Lam</span>, while departing from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Common_law\">common-law</span> norms by allowing handpicked judges, restricting <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jury_trial\">jury trials</span>, and reversing the presumption in favor of bail. <br> <br> Critics at home and abroad argued that the law gutted the \"<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"One_country,_two_systems\">one country, two systems</span>\" framework and the high degree of autonomy that <b>the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sino-British_Joint_Declaration\">Sino-British Joint Declaration</span> of 1984</b> had promised to preserve until 2047. In its wake hundreds of people were arrested, the authorities forced the closure of outlets including <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jimmy_Lai\">Jimmy Lai</span>'s <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Apple_Daily\"><i>Apple Daily</i></span> in 2021 and the news outlet <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Stand_News\"><i>Stand News</i></span>, and numerous civil-society groups disbanded as the annual vigil for the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1989_Tiananmen_Square_protests_and_massacre\">Tiananmen crackdown</span> of 1989 was banned. Alongside a sweeping <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2021_Hong_Kong_electoral_changes\">overhaul of the electoral system</span></b> that slashed directly elected seats under the slogan of \"patriots\" governing Hong Kong, much of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Pro-democracy_camp_(Hong_Kong)\">pro-democracy camp</span> was jailed, disqualified, or driven into exile. The law's reach was epitomized by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong_47\">Hong Kong 47</span>, a group of activists charged with subversion over an unofficial primary election, of whom 45 were convicted in 2024 in the territory's largest national-security trial, with the legal scholar <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Benny_Tai\">Benny Tai</span> receiving the heaviest sentence of about 10 years and younger figures such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Joshua_Wong\">Joshua Wong</span> also imprisoned. Foreign governments condemned the measure as a breach of the Joint Declaration—the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_Kingdom\">United Kingdom</span> opening a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"British_National_(Overseas)\">British National (Overseas)</span> immigration route for Hong Kongers—and in 2024 the local Legislative Council unanimously passed a complementary <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Safeguarding_National_Security_Ordinance\">Safeguarding National Security Ordinance</span> under Article 23, further widening the scope of national-security offenses in the city.","citation":"","answerText":"Hong Kong national security law"},{"id":"cne-088","num":"八十八","category":"China · Economics","question":"Promoted from <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> as a development strategy stressing self-reliant domestic demand and supply chains as the main engine while keeping external trade as a secondary loop, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> responded to rising tensions with the United States and disruptions during the pandemic.","answer":"Dual circulation","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Coined</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Xi Jinping and the CCP leadership, 2020</span></div>","traditional":"雙循環","hanzi":"双循环","pinyin":"shuāng xúnhuán","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">shuāng xúnhuán</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Dual circulation</b> is a Chinese economic development strategy, first articulated by <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span> in May 2020</b>, that aims to make the domestic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">economy</span> the principal engine of growth while treating external trade and investment as a secondary, complementary loop. Xi unveiled the concept at a meeting of the Communist Party's <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_Standing_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo Standing Committee</span> convened to manage the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"COVID-19_pandemic\">COVID-19 pandemic</span>, describing a \"new development pattern\" in which a large internal circulation of production, distribution, and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Consumption_(economics)\">consumption</span></b> would form the mainstay. It emerged as a direct response to deteriorating relations with the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States\">United States</span>, the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China–United_States_trade_war\">trade war</span> and foreign curbs on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Technology_transfer\">technology transfer</span>, and the pandemic's exposure of fragile global <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Supply_chain\">supply chains</span></b>, developments that Beijing interpreted as signs of rising <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Protectionism\">protectionism</span> and a retreat from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Globalization\">globalization</span> in the West. Its central aim was greater economic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Self-sufficiency\">self-sufficiency</span>—securing strategic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Industrial_policy\">industrial</span> and technological supply chains and reducing reliance on imports—an objective Xi had foreshadowed in April 2020 when he called for independent, controllable, and reliable supply chains. The approach consciously inverted the export-led \"great international circulation\" that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> had championed in the 1980s, a phase of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Export-oriented_industrialization\">export-oriented growth</span> whose fragility had been exposed by the <b>2008 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Recession\">global financial crisis</span></b>, yet it stopped well short of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Autarky\">autarky</span>. <br> <br> Dual circulation was elevated to the heart of national planning at a Communist Party <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Central Committee</span> plenum in October 2020 and then enshrined <b>in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fourteenth_five-year_plan\">14th Five-Year Plan</span> for 2021</b> to 2025, which was formally approved by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_People's_Congress\">National People's Congress</span> during the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Two_Sessions\">Two Sessions</span> in March 2021. A full chapter of that <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Five-year_plans_of_China\">five-year plan</span> was devoted to the strategy, which complemented earlier initiatives such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Made_in_China_2025\">Made in China 2025</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Belt_and_Road_Initiative\">Belt and Road Initiative</span> and was carried out through agencies like the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"National_Development_and_Reform_Commission\">National Development and Reform Commission</span>, with targets including annual <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Research_and_development\">research and development</span> spending growth above 7% and the digital economy reaching 10% of output by 2025. In practice the internal loop proved hard to energize, as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Household_income\">household</span> demand stayed weak and consumption hovered around 40% of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gross_domestic_product\">gross domestic product</span> in 2024, far below the global average of roughly 60%. Critics described the resulting framework as a supply-driven program that tried to manufacture <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Aggregate_demand\">demand</span> by expanding production, thereby worsening industrial <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Overcapacity\">overcapacity</span> and leaving <b>China's quest for <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economic_security\">economic security</span></b> still tied to the export markets the policy was meant to de-emphasize. By the time the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"15th_Five-Year_Plan\">15th Five-Year Plan</span> for 2026 to 2030 was outlined at a Party plenum in October 2025 and approved by the legislature in March 2026, the phrase \"dual circulation\" had largely faded from official rhetoric, even as its core emphasis on self-reliance, technological upgrading, and a stronger <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Social_safety_net\">social safety net</span></b> to unleash consumer spending remained central to Beijing's economic vision.","citation":"","answerText":"Dual circulation"},{"id":"cne-091","num":"九十一","category":"China · Economics","question":"Signed in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> and binding China with Japan, South Korea and ASEAN, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> created the world's largest free-trade bloc by population, cutting tariffs across much of the Asia-Pacific.","answer":"Regional Comprehensive Economic Partnership","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Origin</span><span class=\"dt-v\">A 15-nation Asia-Pacific trade pact, signed 2020</span></div>","traditional":"區域全面經濟夥伴關係協定","hanzi":"区域全面经济伙伴关系协定","pinyin":"Qūyù Quánmiàn Jīngjì Huǒbàn Guānxì Xiédìng","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Qūyù Quánmiàn Jīngjì Huǒbàn Guānxì Xiédìng</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Regional Comprehensive Economic Partnership</b>, commonly abbreviated <b>RCEP</b>, is a sweeping <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Free_trade_agreement\">free-trade agreement</span></b> linking 15 <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Asia-Pacific\">Asia-Pacific</span> economies — the ten members of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"ASEAN\">ASEAN</span> together with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japan\">Japan</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"South_Korea\">South Korea</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Australia\">Australia</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Zealand\">New Zealand</span> — that together span much of the region's economy. <b>Signed on 15 November 2020</b> at a virtual <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"ASEAN_Summit\">ASEAN summit</span></b> hosted by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vietnam\">Vietnam</span> after roughly eight years of negotiation, the pact entered into force on 1 January 2022 and constitutes the largest <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Free_trade_area\">free-trade bloc</span> in the world as measured by population. Its members together encompass roughly 30 percent of the global population — some 2.3 billion people — and a comparable share of world <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gross_domestic_product\">gross domestic product</span> worth around US$26 trillion, as well as close to a third of international <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"International_trade\">trade</span></b>, surpassing both the European Union and the North American bloc on each of these measures. The agreement aims to eliminate <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tariff\">tariffs</span> on around 90 percent of goods traded among its parties over roughly 20 years and, more importantly, establishes a single set of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Rules_of_origin\">rules of origin</span> that lets inputs sourced from any member count toward preferential treatment, a provision expected to knit together the region's manufacturing <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Value_chain\">value chains</span>. Beyond goods it contains chapters on services, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Investment\">investment</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"E-commerce\">e-commerce</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Intellectual_property\">intellectual property</span>, yet analysts generally regard it as a shallower accord than the rival <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Comprehensive_and_Progressive_Agreement_for_Trans-Pacific_Partnership\">Comprehensive and Progressive Agreement for Trans-Pacific Partnership</span>, with weaker provisions on labour, the environment, and state-owned enterprises. <br> <br> The initiative grew out of negotiations <b>launched in 2012</b> at an ASEAN summit in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Phnom_Penh\">Phnom Penh</span>, conceived as a means of consolidating the five separate agreements the bloc already held with its partners into a single framework of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Free_trade\">free trade</span> and deeper <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economic_integration\">economic integration</span>. <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"India\">India</span> participated in the talks for several <b>years but withdrew in 2019</b>, citing fears that lower tariffs would widen its already large trade deficit with China and flood its markets with cheap imports capable of harming domestic <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Manufacturing\">manufacturing</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Agriculture\">agriculture</span>, though the remaining members left the door open for it to rejoin. The deal was widely interpreted as enhancing China's regional economic influence, particularly after the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States\">United States</span> abandoned the rival <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Trans-Pacific_Partnership\">Trans-Pacific Partnership</span></b> under President <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Donald_Trump\">Donald Trump</span> in 2017, a withdrawal that left the world's largest economy outside both of the major Asia-Pacific trade pacts and ceding economic ground to Beijing. It also became the first free-trade arrangement to bind China, Japan, and South Korea together within a single treaty, and economists at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Peterson_Institute_for_International_Economics\">Peterson Institute</span> estimated that it could add nearly US$200 billion a year to global income and roughly US$500 billion to world trade by 2030, with the gains concentrated among the Northeast Asian economies. Although its tariff cuts are phased in gradually and its commitments are far less demanding than those of a full <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Customs_union\">customs union</span>, the partnership stands as a landmark of Asian <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Regional_integration\">regional integration</span> and a centrepiece of the increasingly multipolar trading order taking shape across the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_economy\">world economy</span>.","citation":"","answerText":"Regional Comprehensive Economic Partnership"},{"id":"cne-092","num":"九十二","category":"China · Economics","question":"Piloted in cities from <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> and among the most advanced projects of its kind among major economies, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> is run by the central bank as a digital form of cash, potentially aiding state oversight of payments.","answer":"Digital renminbi","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Origin</span><span class=\"dt-v\">Issued by the People's Bank of China, piloted from 2020</span></div>","traditional":"數字人民幣","hanzi":"数字人民币","pinyin":"Shùzì Rénmínbì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Shùzì Rénmínbì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>digital renminbi</b>, <b>officially designated e-CNY</b> and developed under the project name <b>Digital Currency Electronic Payment</b>, is the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_bank_digital_currency\">central bank digital currency</span></b> issued by the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Bank_of_China\">People's Bank of China</span> as a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Legal_tender\">legal-tender</span> digital counterpart to physical cash. Functioning as a state-backed equivalent of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Banknote\">banknotes</span> and coins, it forms part of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Money_supply\">M0 money supply</span>, carries the full backing of the sovereign as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Fiat_money\">fiat money</span>, and bears no interest, distinguishing it sharply from interest-bearing commercial bank deposits and privately issued stablecoins. Research into the project <b>began around 2014</b> under the then governor <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhou_Xiaochuan\">Zhou Xiaochuan</span>, and a dedicated Digital Currency Research Institute was established in 2016, making China one of the first major economies to develop such a currency at scale and distinguishing the effort from decentralised <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cryptocurrency\">cryptocurrencies</span> such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bitcoin\">Bitcoin</span>, which <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> later banned outright. Public pilots <b>commenced in April 2020</b> across four locations — <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shenzhen\">Shenzhen</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Suzhou\">Suzhou</span>, the planned city of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiong'an_New_Area\">Xiong'an</span>, and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chengdu\">Chengdu</span> — before steadily expanding to more than 20 cities across 17 provinces and regions by the mid-2020s. The currency operates on a two-tier model in which the central bank issues e-CNY to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Commercial_bank\">commercial banks</span> that then distribute it to the public through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Digital_wallet\">digital wallets</span>, and it incorporates features such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Near-field_communication\">near-field</span> offline payments — operating without relying primarily on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Blockchain\">blockchain</span> technology that underpins cryptocurrencies — alongside a principle of \"controllable anonymity\" under which small transfers remain private while larger ones stay traceable by the authorities. <br> <br> To spur adoption, local governments distributed the currency through lottery-style giveaways, including a Shenzhen scheme in October 2020 that handed 10 million yuan to 50,000 residents in 200-yuan digital red packets, while the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2022_Winter_Olympics\"><b>2022</b> Winter Olympics</span> in Beijing offered e-CNY to international visitors as a high-profile showcase. Usage grew steadily thereafter, with roughly 261 million personal wallets opened and cumulative transactions of about 87.6 billion <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Renminbi\">yuan</span> by the end of 2021, a figure the central bank reported had climbed to some 1.8 trillion yuan by mid-2023 and around 7 trillion yuan, roughly US$1 trillion, by mid-2024. Despite these milestones the digital yuan remained a minuscule fraction of total spending, amounting to only about 0.1 percent of cash in circulation and trailing far behind the entrenched private <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mobile_payment\">mobile-payment</span> platforms <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Alipay\">Alipay</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"WeChat\">WeChat Pay</span>, which together dominate Chinese retail transactions. Observers noted that, unlike anonymous cash, the system grants the state <b>unprecedented visibility into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Payment\">payment</span></b> flows, raising concerns about <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mass_surveillance_in_China\">state surveillance</span> and the prospect of programmable money, even as proponents argued it could sharpen <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Monetary_policy\">monetary policy</span> and advance <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Financial_inclusion\">financial inclusion</span>. Beyond domestic use, the project was widely interpreted as part of a broader Chinese ambition to promote the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Internationalization_of_the_renminbi\">internationalisation of the renminbi</span> and to reduce reliance on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"United_States_dollar\">United States dollar</span> and the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"SWIFT\">SWIFT</span> messaging network, especially in the context of Western <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economic_sanctions\">economic sanctions</span>, with cross-border experiments such as the multi-currency mBridge platform pursued through the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bank_for_International_Settlements\">Bank for International Settlements</span>, leaving it among the most advanced sovereign digital-currency efforts undertaken by any major economy.","citation":"","answerText":"Digital renminbi"},{"id":"cne-097","num":"九十七","category":"China · Economics","question":"A strategy of stamping out infections through mass testing, snap lockdowns and quarantines, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> kept deaths low early in the pandemic but battered the economy with shutdowns of cities like Shanghai in <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>, before being abruptly abandoned after rare public protests.","answer":"Zero-COVID","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Etymology</span><span class=\"dt-v\">清零 ('clear to zero'), the pandemic-suppression policy of 2020–22</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"清零政策","pinyin":"qīnglíng zhèngcè","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">qīnglíng zhèngcè</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Zero-COVID</b> was a <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Public_health\">public-health</span></b> strategy, branded by Chinese authorities as \"dynamic zero-COVID,\" that sought to eliminate community transmission of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"SARS-CoV-2\">SARS-CoV-2</span> entirely rather than merely mitigate its spread, relying on mass <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"COVID-19_testing\">testing</span>, snap <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lockdown\">lockdowns</span>, and centralised <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Quarantine\">quarantine</span>. The approach took shape with the unprecedented <b>lockdown of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wuhan\">Wuhan</span> in January 2020</b>, when some 11 million residents were sealed off, and it was sustained by pervasive <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Contact_tracing\">contact tracing</span></b>, ubiquitous digital health codes scanned to enter public spaces, and some of the world's strictest border quarantines for nearly three years. During the first two years the policy kept reported infections and deaths remarkably low — <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span> recorded only a few thousand official fatalities while many countries counted hundreds of thousands — and it echoed the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Eradication_of_infectious_diseases\">elimination</span> efforts briefly pursued by <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Zealand\">New Zealand</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Australia\">Australia</span> before they changed course. <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span> upheld the strategy as proof of the superiority of China's governance, yet the highly transmissible <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"SARS-CoV-2_Omicron_variant\">Omicron</span></b> variant made suppression vastly harder and triggered a cascade of city-wide shutdowns in 2022 affecting tens of millions, from <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi'an\">Xi'an</span> to Chengdu and Jilin. The most punishing was the roughly two-month lockdown of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Shanghai\">Shanghai</span> and its 25 million inhabitants from April 2022, an ordeal marked by food shortages that, alongside other shutdowns that snarled global <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Supply_chain\">supply chains</span>, helped slow growth in the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">Chinese economy</span> to about 3 percent that year — far short of the official 5.5 percent target — and pushed urban <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Youth_unemployment\">youth unemployment</span></b> toward 20 percent. <br> <br> Mounting frustration erupted into open dissent in November 2022 after a deadly apartment fire in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2022_Ürümqi_fire\">Ürümqi</span>, the capital of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinjiang\">Xinjiang</span>, which killed 10 people and which many blamed on lockdown barriers that hampered escape and rescue. The tragedy sparked the so-called \"white paper\" <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2022_COVID-19_protests_in_China\">protests</span>, in which demonstrators held up blank sheets to symbolise censorship, across cities including <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> and numerous university campuses, with some making the extraordinary demand that Xi Jinping step down in the boldest display of public defiance since the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"1989_Tiananmen_Square_protests_and_massacre\"><b>1989</b> Tiananmen protests</span>. Within days the government abruptly reversed course, announcing <b>\"ten new measures\" in December 2022</b> that dismantled the mass <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Polymerase_chain_reaction\">PCR</span> testing regime, scrapped the digital health codes, and lifted most travel and isolation requirements almost overnight, abandoning a policy that had governed daily life for nearly three years. The sudden reopening unleashed an enormous wave of infection over the winter of 2022 and 2023 that overwhelmed hospitals and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Crematory\">crematoria</span>; while officials acknowledged only about 60,000 hospital deaths in the five weeks to mid-January 2023, independent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Excess_mortality\">excess-mortality</span> estimates placed the true toll between one and two million, far beyond official tallies that the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"World_Health_Organization\">World Health Organization</span> publicly cautioned were underreported. The catastrophe was aggravated by reliance on domestically produced <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Inactivated_vaccine\">inactivated vaccines</span> such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"CoronaVac\">CoronaVac</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sinopharm_BIBP_COVID-19_vaccine\">Sinopharm</span>, which proved less effective against Omicron, and by low <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Vaccination\">booster</span> coverage among the elderly — a large share of those over 80 remaining unprotected — after Beijing declined to approve foreign <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"MRNA_vaccine\">mRNA vaccines</span>, bringing one of the world's most stringent pandemic regimes to a deadly close.","citation":"","answerText":"Zero-COVID"},{"id":"cnp-096","num":"九十六","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Revived as a guiding slogan by Xi Jinping around <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> marked earlier reform.","answer":"Common prosperity","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Origin</span><span class=\"dt-v\">A Mao-era phrase revived as a slogan by Xi Jinping, 2021</span></div>","traditional":"","hanzi":"共同富裕","pinyin":"gòngtóng fùyù","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">gòngtóng fùyù</span></div>","abstract":"<b>Common prosperity</b> is a political and economic slogan of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> that calls for narrowing the yawning gap between rich and poor and ensuring that the fruits of growth are more broadly shared across society. Though the phrase dates back to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span> era of the 1950s, it acquired its enduring meaning under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span>, who reconciled it with market reform through the maxim that some regions and people should be \"allowed to get rich first\" in order ultimately to help the rest catch up. That formula licensed decades of soaring <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economic_inequality\">inequality</span></b> during the era of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_economic_reform\">reform and opening up</span>, leaving China with an official <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gini_coefficient\">Gini coefficient</span> of roughly 0.47, among the highest of the world's major economies and a politically sensitive marker of the era's lopsided gains. <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span> revived the slogan <b>with new force in 2021</b>, declaring at a meeting of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Financial_and_Economic_Affairs_Commission\">Central Financial and Economic Affairs Commission</span> in August that common prosperity was an essential requirement of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Socialism_with_Chinese_characteristics\">socialism</span> and calling for the \"reasonable adjustment of excessive incomes.\" The push was framed as the next national objective after the 2021 declaration that a \"moderately prosperous society,\" or <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xiaokang\">xiaokang</span>, had been achieved and absolute <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Poverty_in_China\">poverty</span> eliminated, with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zhejiang\">Zhejiang</span> province designated as a demonstration zone for the policy. <br> <br> Common prosperity coincided with a sweeping regulatory crackdown on the country's largest <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Big_Tech\">technology firms</span>, beginning with the <b>abrupt suspension in late 2020</b> of the record initial public offering of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ant_Group\">Ant Group</span>, after its founder <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Jack_Ma\">Jack Ma</span> publicly criticised regulators, and continuing with a record <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Competition_law\">antitrust</span> fine of 18.2 billion yuan imposed on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Alibaba_Group\">Alibaba</span> in April 2021. The campaign widened to other sectors, effectively banning for-profit private tutoring in core school subjects in a blow to firms such as <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"New_Oriental\">New Oriental</span></b>, sharply restricting the hours minors could spend on <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Video_gaming_in_China\">video games</span>, and unfolding against the backdrop of a deepening property crisis epitomised by the debt-laden developer <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Evergrande_Group\">Evergrande</span>. Central to the agenda was the idea of a \"tertiary distribution,\" under which <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Redistribution_of_income_and_wealth\">redistribution</span></b> through <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Philanthropy\">philanthropy</span> would supplement market wages and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taxation_in_China\">taxation</span>, prompting <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Tencent\">Tencent</span> and Alibaba to pledge 100 billion yuan each toward common-prosperity initiatives. The regulatory onslaught erased trillions of yuan in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Market_capitalization\">market value</span> from Chinese shares, and officials moved to reassure investors that the goal was to expand the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Middle_class\">middle class</span></b> into an \"olive-shaped\" structure rather than to impose radical <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Egalitarianism\">egalitarianism</span> or simply \"rob the rich,\" even as pilot schemes for a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Property_tax\">property tax</span> on real estate were authorised but soon delayed. After dominating policy rhetoric in 2021, the slogan grew noticeably quieter amid the economic slowdown and <b>pandemic disruptions of 2022</b>, yet it remains woven into Xi's longer-term vision — linked to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Dream\">Chinese Dream</span> and the 2049 milestone of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Two_Centenaries\">Two Centenaries</span> — and was reaffirmed at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"20th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">20th Party Congress</span> as a defining ambition of his rule.","citation":"","answerText":"Common prosperity"},{"id":"cne-095","num":"九十五","category":"China · Economics","question":"Unfolding from around <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> after curbs on developer borrowing, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> saw defaults, stalled projects, mortgage boycotts and falling prices spread across an industry that had driven much of national growth, dragging on local-government finances tied to land sales under Xi Jinping.","answer":"Chinese property sector crisis","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">from 2021</span></div>","traditional":"中國房地產危機","hanzi":"中国房地产危机","pinyin":"Zhōngguó fángdìchǎn wēijī","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōngguó fángdìchǎn wēijī</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>Chinese property sector crisis</b> was a prolonged downturn in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"China\">China</span>'s vast <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Real_estate_in_China\">real-estate industry</span></b> that unfolded from around 2020, marked by developer defaults, stalled construction, and falling prices across a sector that had long served as a principal engine of national growth. At its height the property sector and its related activities accounted for roughly a quarter to nearly 30 percent of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Gross_domestic_product\">gross domestic product</span>, while real estate represented around 70 percent of household <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wealth\">wealth</span></b>, making the industry both a pillar of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Economy_of_China\">economy</span> and a critical store of savings in which tens of millions of units were held as investments. Decades of rapid <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Urbanization_in_China\">urbanisation</span> had fuelled a building boom financed by heavily <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Leverage_(finance)\">leveraged</span> <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Real_estate_development\">developers</span> who routinely pre-sold apartments before completion, accumulating off-balance-sheet <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Debt\">debt</span></b> running into the trillions of dollars and inflating a speculative <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Real_estate_bubble\">property bubble</span>. The crisis was <b>precipitated in August 2020</b> when authorities imposed the \"three red lines,\" strict caps on developers' debt ratios intended to force <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deleveraging\">deleveraging</span> after years of warnings, a clampdown aligned with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span>'s dictum that \"houses are for living in, not for speculation.\" The squeeze quickly engulfed <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Evergrande_Group\">Evergrande</span>, the world's most indebted developer with liabilities exceeding US$300 billion, which began missing payments on <b>its <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Bond_(finance)\">bonds</span> in late 2021</b> and was eventually ordered into <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Liquidation\">liquidation</span> by a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hong_Kong\">Hong Kong</span> court in early 2024, an event some had feared might become a Chinese \"<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Lehman_Brothers\">Lehman moment</span>.\" <br> <br> The distress spread rapidly through the industry, with major builders including <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Country_Garden\">Country Garden</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Sunac\">Sunac</span> succumbing to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Default_(finance)\">default</span> alongside Kaisa, Shimao, and others, so that firms responsible for roughly 40 percent of Chinese home sales had <b>defaulted by 2023</b>, wiping out vast sums of bondholder value at home and abroad. Across the country pre-sold but unfinished apartments left buyers in limbo, prompting a wave of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"2022_China_mortgage_boycotts\">mortgage boycotts</span> in mid-2022 as homeowners on more than 300 stalled projects across over 100 cities refused to keep paying <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mortgage_loan\">mortgages</span>. New-home sales by value fell by around a quarter and prices slid in many cities, with <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Construction\">construction</span> starts plunging by some 40 percent in 2022, eroding the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Consumer_confidence\">confidence</span> of households whose savings were locked in apartments and adding to broader <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deflation\">deflationary</span> pressure as property-related wealth evaporated. The collapse also battered the finances of local governments, which had long depended on selling <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Land_use\">land-use rights</span></b> to developers for 30 to 40 percent of their revenue, income that tumbled by roughly a fifth in 2022 and deepened the strains on the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Local_government_financing_vehicle\">local-government financing vehicles</span> that had borrowed heavily against expected <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Real_estate\">land</span> proceeds. The downturn became a heavy drag on growth, prompting comparisons to <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Japanese_asset_price_bubble\">Japan's asset-price collapse</span> of the 1990s, and although the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Bank_of_China\">central bank</span> cut <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Interest_rate\">interest rates</span> and eased mortgage rules, the authorities resisted a sweeping bailout, leaving an oversupply estimated in the tens of millions of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Under-occupied_developments_in_China\">vacant homes</span> and a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Demographics_of_China\">population</span> that began shrinking in 2022 to weigh on the sector's recovery well into the mid-2020s.","citation":"","answerText":"Chinese property sector crisis"},{"id":"cnp-097","num":"九十七","category":"China · Politics & Government","question":"Convened in October <span class=\"blank\">_____</span>, the <span class=\"blank\">_____</span> broke recent convention by handing Xi Jinping a 3rd term as general secretary and featured the abrupt, televised escorting of his predecessor Hu Jintao from the closing session.","answer":"20th National Congress of the CCP","answerDate":"<div class=\"dt\"><span class=\"dt-k\">Date</span><span class=\"dt-v\">2022</span></div>","traditional":"中國共產黨第二十次全國代表大會","hanzi":"中国共产党第二十次全国代表大会","pinyin":"Zhōngguó Gòngchǎndǎng Dì-Èrshí Cì Quánguó Dàibiǎo Dàhuì","translations":"<div class=\"tr-pinline\"><span class=\"tr-pin\">Zhōngguó Gòngchǎndǎng Dì-Èrshí Cì Quánguó Dàibiǎo Dàhuì</span></div>","abstract":"The <b>20th National Congress of the CCP</b> was the quinquennial congress of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Chinese_Communist_Party\">Chinese Communist Party</span> held in <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Beijing\">Beijing</span> <b>from October 16</b> to <b>22, 2022</b>, at the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Great_Hall_of_the_People\">Great Hall of the People</span></b>. Bringing together some 2,296 delegates said to represent more than 96 million party members, it broke with the retirement conventions of the post-<span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Deng_Xiaoping\">Deng Xiaoping</span> era by awarding <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping\">Xi Jinping</span> a third term as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"General_Secretary_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">general secretary</span> and chairman of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Military_Commission_(China)\">Central Military Commission</span>. The reshuffled 7-member <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_Standing_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo Standing Committee</span> was packed with Xi allies such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Qiang\">Li Qiang</span>, <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cai_Qi\">Cai Qi</span>, and <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Ding_Xuexiang\">Ding Xuexiang</span></b>, while figures linked to the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Communist_Youth_League_of_China\">Communist Youth League</span>, among them the outgoing premier <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Li_Keqiang\">Li Keqiang</span> and <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Wang_Yang_(politician)\">Wang Yang</span>, were dropped though young enough to remain under prior norms. Alongside a newly elected <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Central_Committee_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Central Committee</span> of 205 full members, delegates amended the <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Constitution_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">party constitution</span></b> to enshrine the \"Two Establishes\" affirming Xi's status as the leadership core and the guiding role of <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xi_Jinping_Thought\">Xi Jinping Thought</span>, further cementing his standing as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Paramount_leader\">paramount leader</span>. The proceedings, unfolding against the backdrop of a slowing economy and the country's stringent <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Zero-COVID\">zero-COVID</span> controls, foregrounded themes such as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Common_prosperity\">common prosperity</span>, technological self-reliance, national security, and a hardened stance toward <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Taiwan\">Taiwan</span>. <br> <br> The congress became globally known for an extraordinary moment on October 22, when the 79-year-old former leader <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Hu_Jintao\">Hu Jintao</span>, seated beside Xi, was abruptly escorted from the closing session in front of assembled cameras. State outlet <b><span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Xinhua_News_Agency\">Xinhua</span></b> afterward said that Hu had felt unwell, yet the footage spread rapidly overseas even as references to it were scrubbed under <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Censorship_in_China\">censorship in China</span>, and many observers read the scene as a symbolic eclipse of the party's older generation. Together with the leadership purge, the episode was widely interpreted as marking the definitive end of the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Collective_leadership\">collective leadership</span> norm that had prevailed since Deng and the consolidation of a <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Cult_of_personality\">cult of personality</span> around Xi, who by then had concentrated more personal power than any leader since <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Mao_Zedong\">Mao Zedong</span>. The third term followed the abolition <b>of presidential <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Term_limit\">term limits</span> in 2018</b> and built on the power consolidated at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"19th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">19th National Congress</span> in 2017 and Xi's initial ascent at the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"18th_National_Congress_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">18th National Congress</span> in 2012. In the new lineup the broader <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Politburo_of_the_Chinese_Communist_Party\">Politburo</span> contained no women for the first time in 25 years, and Li Qiang was confirmed as <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"Premier_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China\">premier</span> the following March, completing a turnover that left Xi commanding the <span class=\"ttip\" data-k=\"People's_Liberation_Army\">People's Liberation Army</span> and the party with little institutional check on his authority.","citation":"","answerText":"20th National Congress of the CCP"}];
